INSERT INTO @tmpJokes (JokeId, Categories, JokeTxt, Attribution, ImageTxt) VALUES
 (2465, 'Abstract Humor, Cartoon, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Time is the image of eternity.', 'Diogenes', 'Draw a whimsical, cartoon-style scene with a large, old-fashioned hourglass prominently in the center. Inside the hourglass, instead of normal sand, depict tiny stars, planets, and cosmic elements slowly falling from the top chamber to the bottom, symbolizing ''eternity'' as a vast universe in miniature. Surrounding the hourglass, include some smaller clocks—like an alarm clock, a wristwatch, and a sundial—all looking up in amazement at the hourglass. The background should be a simple gradient suggesting deep space, with subtle sparkles to emphasize a cosmic feel. The hourglass can have a small, friendly smiley face to add charm and humor, as if it''s proud to represent both ''time'' and ''eternity.'' The overall tone is light-hearted, imaginative, and thought-provoking, in a playful cartoon format with bright colors and soft lines, ensuring it feels approachable and funny rather than serious or abstract.'),
 (2540, 'Abstract Humor, Friendship Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'What is a friend? A single soul dwelling in two bodies.', 'Aristotle', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two friends who look very similar and are closely connected in a playful way. Show them standing side by side with friendly smiles, but with their torsos merged into one shared body, illustrating the idea of ''a single soul dwelling in two bodies.'' Each friend has their own head, arms, and legs on opposite sides of the shared torso, exaggerating the connection humorously. The background can be simple and cheerful, perhaps with a sunny park setting or a cozy room to evoke warmth and friendship. Include speech bubbles or playful little hearts around them to emphasize their close bond without using any text. The overall style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish to bring out the warmth and whimsical nature of the quote.'),
 (2358, 'Abstract Humor, Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The only way to discover the limits of the possible is to go beyond them into the impossible.', 'Arthur C. Clarke', 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene depicting a curious explorer standing at the edge of a cliff labeled ''Limits of the Possible.'' The explorer looks determined and excited, stepping forward into a surreal, colorful landscape on the other side labeled ''Impossible.'' The impossible side can include exaggerated and imaginative elements like floating islands, upside-down trees, and glowing unusual creatures. The background should blend gradually from realistic mountains and sky on the ''possible'' side to fantastical and dreamlike scenery on the ''impossible'' side. The explorer wears classic hiking gear with a backpack and a map, symbolizing discovery and adventure. Include a signpost at the cliff edge with arrows pointing one way ''Possible'' and the other way ''Impossible.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and inspiring, capturing the spirit of pushing boundaries in a fun, cartoon style.'),
 (1836, 'Abstract Humor, Music Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'I see music as the augmentation of a split second of time.', 'Erin Cleary', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a whimsical clock with musical notes flying out of it. The clock is exaggerated and cartoonish, with its hands split in half, visually emphasizing a ''split second.'' Surrounding the clock are floating colorful musical notes, like treble clefs and quavers, which look like they’re bursting or expanding from the split second. A cheerful character, maybe a quirky musician or a music lover with headphones, is watching the scene in awe or contemplation. The background is simple, maybe with subtle waves or lines to suggest sound or time flowing. The overall tone is light and imaginative, emphasizing the idea that music makes a tiny moment feel bigger or enhanced. The style is playful and suitable for a general audience, no violence or other sensitive content.'),
 (1949, 'Abstract Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'In the province of the mind, what one believes to be true either is true or becomes true.', 'John Lilly', 'A whimsical, colorful cartoon scene portraying a person''s head as a large open province or map, with small buildings, trees, and winding roads inside the skull outlined like a country border. Inside the ''province of the mind,'' several cheerful stick-figure characters are painting or placing signs labeled ''Truth'' on various spots. Above the head floats a thought bubble depicting a glowing light bulb or shining star symbolizing belief and realization. The background is light and airy with soft clouds and a peaceful sky, emphasizing imagination and abstract thinking. The style is humorous and lighthearted, with playful details like tiny flags planted on the landscape that say ''Belief Zone'' and ''Reality Check.'' The overall tone is whimsical and philosophical without any aggressive or inappropriate elements.'),
 (2120, 'Abstract Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'My eye does not make the world; it only sees it.', 'from Don Quixote', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, anthropomorphic human eye standing on two legs with arms. The eye is looking thoughtfully outward, wearing round spectacles perched on its ''face'' (iris area), conveying a wise, philosophical expression. Surrounding it is a simple globe of the Earth to its side, clearly depicted as a separate object, emphasizing the idea that the eye is observing but not creating the world. The background is a minimalistic abstract space with light thought bubbles above the eye containing small images of a sun, clouds, and trees representing the world it ''sees.'' The style is lighthearted and whimsical, with curved lines and bright colors. No people, animals, or violence, just the eye and the globe as the main elements, conveying the concept of perception versus creation in a playful way.'),
 (1950, 'Abstract Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'In the world of human thought generally, and in physical science particularly, the most important and fruitful concepts are those to which it is impossible to attach a well-defined meaning.', 'H. A. Kramers', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a whimsical, cluttered scholar''s study filled with books, scientific instruments like microscopes, telescopes, and beakers bubbling with colorful liquids. In the center, a quirky professor with wild hair and thick glasses stands scratching his head, holding a giant oversized question mark as if it were a physical object. Around him, floating ghostly abstract concepts and question marks without clear forms hover ambiguously. On a chalkboard behind him, scribbles and diagrams lead nowhere, with phrases like ''Undefined Ideas'' and ''Meaningless Concepts'' written messily. A faded chart titled ''Fruitful but Vague Theories'' with scattered fruit illustrations adds subtle absurdity. The overall tone is light, playful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions highlighting the confusion and irony about important concepts being unclear or undefinable.'),
 (2042, 'Abstract Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Life is a wave, which in no two consecutive moments of its existence is composed of the same particles.', 'John Tyndall', 'Draw a lighthearted cartoon scene showing a stylized, cheerful ocean wave on a sunny beach. The wave should be semi-transparent and sparkling, with swirls and bubbles inside to suggest it’s constantly changing. To emphasize the idea that the wave is made of different particles over time, depict numerous tiny, colorful dots or particles inside the wave, each labeled with fun, tiny faces or quirky little expressions that change from front to back or top to bottom. Above the wave, have a thought bubble with a simple, whimsical clock or hourglass icon to hint at time passing. The beach can include a smiling sun wearing sunglasses, a few seashells, and a palm tree to keep the scene lively but simple. The overall tone should be playful and clever, capturing the abstract concept of change and impermanence with a humorous, visual twist appropriate for all ages.'),
 (1987, 'Abstract Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'It is true greatness to have in one the frailty of a man and the security of a god.', 'Seneca', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person split down the middle. On one side, the person is portrayed as frail and human, wearing a loose, wrinkled shirt, with a tired, worried expression, a slight slouch, and maybe a cane or crutch leaning beside them. On the other side, the person is a majestic god-like figure radiating calm and security, with broad shoulders, a glowing aura or halo, and a confident, serene smile. This godly half could wear a flowing robe and hold a small shield emblem symbolizing protection. The background should suggest a blend of ordinary human environment on the left (like a simple room with a creaky chair and clock) and a divine or celestial setting on the right (like clouds or rays of light). The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright, cheerful colors emphasizing the contrast without violence or distress. The scene visually represents the contrast between human frailty and divine security in a playful way.'),
 (2180, 'Abstract Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'One''s mind, once stretched by a new idea, never regains its original dimensions.', 'Oliver Wendell Holmes', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person with a large, exaggeratedly stretched-out head or brain, symbolizing their mind being expanded by a new idea. The person should be sitting in a cozy armchair reading a book or looking at a glowing light bulb above their head, indicating the moment of inspiration. Around their head, wavy lines or comical stretching effects emphasize the mind''s expansion, with small original-sized brain icons popping out and floating away to show that the mind can’t shrink back to its original state. The background should be simple and cheerful, with maybe a bookshelf or a lamp to create a relaxed, thoughtful atmosphere. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the humorous metaphor of mental growth and permanent change.'),
 (2501, 'Absurd Humor, Academic Humor, Education Humor, Quotes', 'University politics are vicious precisely because the stakes are so small.', 'Henry Kissinger (1923-)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a university professor''s lounge or office with exaggerated features. In the foreground, two professors, drawn with expressive faces showing exaggerated anger and intensity, are engaged in a petty argument over something trivial — such as a small coffee mug or a single chair. Around them, the setting includes typical university details: a cluttered office with bookshelves, a chalkboard with complicated formulas, a stack of papers labeled ''Committee Minutes,'' and a small trophy labeled ''Best Faculty Award.'' In the background, other professors watch worriedly or whisper to each other, some holding clipboards or academic reports. The tone is playful and exaggerated to emphasize the contrast between the fierce expressions and the trivial object or issue they fight over. The overall style is colorful and cartoonish, highlighting the irony that these supposedly serious academics are so passionately invested in something inconsequential, illustrating the punchline about university politics being vicious because the stakes are so small.'),
 (2414, 'Absurd Humor, Academic Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'There are only two kinds of scholars; those who love ideas and those who hate them.', 'Emile Chartier', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy library or study room filled with tall bookshelves overflowing with colorful books. Two scholars are seated at a wooden table in the center. The first scholar is visibly excited, with wide eyes and a big smile, surrounded by floating lightbulbs and whimsical idea symbols like gears, stars, and question marks above their head. They are eagerly holding an open book titled ''Big Ideas.'' The second scholar, in contrast, looks annoyed and frustrated, furrowing their brow while burying their face in their hands, with crumpled papers and torn-out pages scattered around. Above them, dark scribbles and broken lightbulbs indicate their frustration or disdain for ideas. The room is warmly lit with a desk lamp and has cute details such as a steaming cup of coffee, a globe, and a quirky cat calmly watching the scene, adding charm and humor. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the comic contrast between loving and hating ideas without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2278, 'Absurd Humor, Academic Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'The average Ph.D. thesis is nothing but a transference of bones from one graveyard to another.', 'J. Frank Dobie', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a scholarly-looking professor with glasses and a tweed jacket standing between two graveyards. Each graveyard has rows of simple gravestones. The professor is holding a big stack of large papers labeled ''Ph.D. Thesis.'' The professor is in the act of physically moving cartoon-style human bones—oversized femurs and skulls—from one graveyard plot to another, as if transferring them. The surrounding area is a grassy cemetery under a light blue sky with fluffy clouds. The professor has a slightly tired but amused expression, and there are a few crows watching curiously from nearby gravestones. The overall tone is light-hearted and imaginative, resembling a classic comic or editorial cartoon style with exaggerated expressions and clear, bold outlines. The scene humorously visualizes the metaphor of moving ''bones'' between graveyards to represent recycling old research without violence or negativity.'),
 (2432, 'Absurd Humor, Adventure Humor, Historical Humor, Quotes', 'There is nothing more exhilarating than to be shot at without result.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently in an old-fashioned battlefield setting, dressed in loose explorer or adventurer clothes reminiscent of colonial times. The character has a surprised but thrilled expression on their face, arms raised triumphantly as several musket balls (depicted as harmless-looking small puffs of smoke or clearly missing shots) whiz past them closely. Around this person, there are cartoon-style soldiers aiming muskets in their direction, but missing with exaggerated wide-eyed shock and disbelief. The background includes a simple open field with distant trees and a clear sky. The overall tone is lighthearted and adventurous, emphasizing excitement and the thrill of narrowly escaping danger rather than any harm. The style should be colorful, playful, and exaggerated for comedic effect.'),
 (1495, 'Absurd Humor, Adventure Humor, Life, Quotes', 'Adventure is the result of poor planning.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of two friends on a hiking trip in a forest or mountainous setting. One friend looks calm and prepared, wearing proper hiking gear, holding a map and compass, while the other looks confused or panicked, wearing mismatched clothes and carrying a messy backpack with items spilling out. Around them are exaggerated signs of ''wrong turns'' like bent or broken signposts, a winding trail that leads off a cliff or into a swamp, and a small animal watching them curiously (like a squirrel or bird). The friend with the map looks at the other with a knowing smile, and above them is a playful caption bubble or sign that reads, "Adventure is the result of poor planning." The background should be colorful and lively, drawing a lighthearted, silly atmosphere without danger or negativity, emphasizing the humor in unexpected misadventures caused by not planning well.'),
 (3073, 'Absurd Humor, Adventure Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'If at first you don''t succeed, skydiving is not for you', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a nervous person about to jump out of a small airplane mid-flight. The person is wearing a skydiving suit and helmet, looking very hesitant and anxious with wide eyes and a forced smile. The airplane is simple and cartoonish, with a door open and clouds in the background. Below the plane, a big, colorful target on the ground is visible, implying the landing zone. Nearby, a skydiving instructor inside the plane is looking worried or shaking their head. Include a speech bubble from the instructor or a sign on the plane with the phrase: ''If at first you don''t succeed, skydiving is not for you.'' The overall tone should be light, funny, and exaggerated to emphasize the joke''s meaning without any hint of danger or harm.'),
 (2388, 'Absurd Humor, Aging, Humor, Quotes', 'The surprising thing about young fools is how many survive to become old fools.', 'Doug Larson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a young person with a silly, wide-eyed expression doing something foolish—maybe attempting a wild skateboard trick and about to fall off. On the right, an older version of the same character, now with wrinkles, gray hair, and glasses, repeating a similar foolish action like tripping over something or making a funny mistake. Both should have exaggerated expressions—comically clueless and cheerful despite their mistakes. The background is a simple park or street with a few trees and a bench, subtly highlighting the passage of time. The style is bright, colorful, and cartoony, emphasizing humor and lightheartedness without any hint of harm or negativity.'),
 (2613, 'Absurd Humor, Aging, Quotes', 'You know you''re old when you notice how young the derelicts are getting.', 'Joanne Phillips', 'A humorous cartoon scene set outside a city park bench. An elderly person with glasses, a cane, and gray hair is sitting on the bench looking surprised and slightly bewildered. Around them, several very young and scruffy-looking individuals meant to represent ''derelicts'' are loitering nearby. These young derelicts have exaggerated ragged clothes, slouched postures, and mischievous or lazy expressions. The elderly person squints and leans forward, observing the young derelicts, with a thought bubble above their head showing a mental image of the usual, older derelicts to emphasize their shock at the young age. The background should be light and simple with a few trees and a trash can for context. The overall style is colorful, whimsical, and cartoonish, emphasizing the funny contrast of age and appearance without anything mean-spirited or dark.'),
 (2524, 'Absurd Humor, Aging, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'We learn from experience than men never learn anything from experience.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one is a man looking puzzled and scratching his head, standing beside a large open book labeled ''Experience.'' The book appears worn, with pages marked and notes scribbled. Behind the man, a second character, a woman with an amused expression, holds a smaller book titled ''Lessons Learned.'' The background shows a thought bubble above the man filled with repeated identical scenarios or silly mistakes, symbolizing that despite many experiences, he hasn’t gained any new insight. The setting is casual and simple, perhaps in a living room with a comfy chair, a small table holding a coffee mug, and a window showing a sunny day, emphasizing everyday life. The overall cartoon style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive facial features to enhance the humorous contrast between the man''s confusion and the woman''s knowing look.'),
 (2020, 'Absurd Humor, Aging, Quotes, Word Play', 'Just remember, when you''re over-the-hill, you begin to pick up speed.', 'Charles Schulz', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set on a steep hill with a whimsical, exaggerated slope. At the top of the hill stands an older person with gray hair, wearing casual clothes and a party hat, looking both surprised and amused. Below, the hill slopes downward dramatically, with the person shown multiple times along the hill to create a motion blur or cartoon speed effect as they ''pick up speed'' rolling or sliding down on a large, comically oversized skateboard or sled. Add small rocks, grass tufts, and a few trees along the hill to give context. The sky is bright and cheerful with a few fluffy clouds. Include a sign near the top that reads ''Over-the-Hill Hill'' to emphasize the joke. The style should be colorful and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor in aging and gaining speed going downhill.'),
 (2257, 'Absurd Humor, Agriculture, Animals, Quotes', 'Strong like tractor, smart like bull.', 'Harlan Cornell', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a cheerful bull standing confidently next to a big, red tractor. The bull should look smart and proud, perhaps wearing glasses or holding a book to emphasize intelligence. The tractor appears robust and powerful, parked on a bright green farm field with a clear blue sky above. The setting includes simple farm elements like a few hay bales, a wooden fence, and a barn in the background. The bull’s expression is clever and witty, while the tractor looks strong and sturdy. Add a playful caption near the top or bottom that says: "Strong like tractor, smart like bull." The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, with exaggerated features for the bull and tractor to enhance humor and charm.'),
 (2507, 'Absurd Humor, Agriculture, Animals, Quotes', 'Walk a straight line through a cow pasture, you are bound to step in a few cow pies, but you will get where you are going.', 'Clint (Joe Kidd) Eastwood', 'Draw a bright, humorous cartoon scene set in a sunny cow pasture. A cheerful person is confidently walking along a clearly marked straight path cutting through the field. The grass is lush and green, dotted with several cute, cartoon-style black and white cows that look calm and mildly curious. On the ground along the path are obvious cow pies, drawn as exaggerated, silly piles with flies buzzing around them to add humor. The traveler should have a slightly amused or resigned expression, maybe lifting one foot mid-step with a careful look to avoid stepping in the pies but clearly aware some are unavoidable. Surround the scene with a simple wooden fence and a blue sky with a few fluffy clouds to keep the mood light and funny. The cartoon style should be colorful, with bold outlines and expressive characters to emphasize the playful, lighthearted nature of the joke.'),
 (2830, 'Absurd Humor, Agriculture, Puns, Unknown', 'Every man reaps what he sows, except the amateur gardener.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a small backyard garden. In the center is an enthusiastic but clueless-looking amateur gardener, a man wearing oversized gardening gloves, a floppy hat, and mismatched boots. Instead of regular plants, his plots have funny, unexpected things sprouting: one spot grows random objects like socks, shoes, and a TV remote; another has weeds tangled with a smiling carrot looking confused; a third patch is barren with a tiny comic worm holding a protest sign. Nearby, a wise old farmer with a straw hat and a satisfied smile is looking on, holding a basket filled with perfect vegetables. The background shows a sunny clear day with birds chirping and a garden fence with a sign that reads “Every man reaps what he sows.” The style is colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish with expressive faces and playful details emphasizing the gardener’s lack of skill humorously.'),
 (2721, 'Absurd Humor, Alcohol Humor, Cartoon, Unknown', 'Consider: when you drink beer and get drunk, the beer is also getting drunk', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a bar stool with a frothy beer mug raised in one hand, looking pleasantly tipsy with flushed cheeks and a slight smile. The beer mug itself has a face with eyes half-closed and a silly grin, slightly leaning or swaying as if it’s also drunk. Around the bar are lively elements like a few other mugs on the counter, some with amusing expressions too, and a bartender in the background wiping a glass with a smirk. The setting is colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoonish features to emphasize the silliness of the idea that the beer can be drunk along with the person. The style should be playful and fun, with round shapes and bright colors, evoking a friendly pub atmosphere without any aggressive or adult themes.'),
 (3012, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Bad Puns, Unknown', 'I just saw a study that says humans eat more bananas than monkeys. Makes sense. I don''t remember the last time I ate a monkey.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a surprised human sitting at a kitchen table holding a peeled banana with a puzzled expression. On the wall behind them is a framed, comically exaggerated scientific study titled ''Banana Eating Habits: Humans vs. Monkeys'' with cartoon images of bananas and monkeys. Nearby, a few bananas are scattered on the table. In the background, a cheeky, cartoon monkey peeks through an open window, looking amused or mischievous. The overall style is colorful and light-hearted with exaggerated facial expressions and simple, bright details to emphasize the joke''s play on words and absurd logic.'),
 (2646, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Bar Humor, Unknown', 'A skeleton walks into a bar and says, ''give me a beer... and a mop.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy bar with wooden walls and typical bar decor like stools, a counter, and bottles on shelves. At the center, a friendly-looking skeleton stands upright at the bar, facing the bartender. The skeleton is holding out one bony hand, ordering a frothy mug of beer. Next to the beer, there is a clean mop bucket and mop leaning casually against the counter as if the skeleton has just requested it together with the beer. The bartender, an amused person wiping a glass, looks surprised but amused by the order. The overall mood is light and funny, capturing the joke’s punchline about the skeleton needing a mop, implying a mess might happen after drinking. Bright colors and exaggerated expressions on characters enhance the cartoon humor.'),
 (2424, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Classic Quotes, Quotes', 'There comes a time in the affairs of man when he must take the bull by the tail and face the situation.', 'W. C. Fields', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bewildered man who is comically holding onto the tail of a rather calm, slightly confused bull. The man looks surprised yet determined, gripping the bull’s tail firmly with both hands as if trying to control the situation. The bull stands on a grassy field with a few simple farm elements in the background like a wooden fence and a distant barn. The man wears casual clothes, like a shirt and jeans, and exaggerate a worried expression with wide eyes and raised eyebrows. The bull looks down at the man with a deadpan, slightly amused expression. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with warm colors and clean line work, emphasizing the absurdity of taking the bull by the tail rather than the horns.'),
 (1613, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Culture Humor, Quotes', 'Culture is roughly anything we do and the monkeys don''t.', 'Lord Raglan', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, show a group of diverse humans engaging in various cultural activities like painting on a canvas, playing a musical instrument, reading a book, and wearing colorful clothes. On the right side, depict a group of playful monkeys doing simple, natural monkey behaviors like swinging on tree branches, eating bananas, and grooming each other. The background should clearly separate the two sides with a clear boundary or line. Include some lighthearted expressions on both humans and monkeys, emphasizing the contrast between the complex, creative human activities versus the natural, instinctive monkey actions. The overall style should be colorful, cheerful, and cartoonish with exaggerated, expressive faces to highlight the joke’s point about culture being anything humans do but monkeys don’t.'),
 (417, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Dad, Humor, Puns', 'Why don''t cannibals eat clowns? Because they taste funny.', NULL, 'A cartoon-style humorous scene set at a dinner table with three playful cannibals sitting around it. One cannibal is holding a fork and knife, hesitating with a puzzled expression as he looks at a clown sitting on a large plate in front of him. The clown is brightly dressed in a classic colorful outfit with oversized shoes, a red nose, and a big smiling face. The table has typical dinner items like plates, utensils, and maybe a roasted turkey in the background, but the focus is on the clown-on-a-plate. The overall atmosphere is light, silly, and exaggerated with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the joke''s pun about taste and humor. No blood or anything graphic should be shown—keep it funny and playful, like a comic strip.'),
 (1544, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'Ants have a good thing going. Besides getting along pretty well with everyone in their house, they can lift 30 times their body weight, and they never even belong to health clubs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of cheerful ants inside a cozy anthill home. The anthill is shown as a cross-section so the interior rooms and tunnels are visible. Inside, a few ants are happily interacting with each other, showing a friendly, communal atmosphere. One ant is effortlessly carrying a large, heavy leaf or crumb several times its size to highlight their strength. Nearby, an anthill corridor has a small humorous sign or poster with a crossed-out health club or gym icon, hinting that ants don’t need gyms. The overall mood is light-hearted and funny, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to portray the ants as hardworking and sociable, with a touch of irony about their natural fitness routine.'),
 (2774, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Fantasy Humor, Unknown', 'Do not meddle in the affairs of dragons, ''cuz, like, you are crunchy and taste good with ketchup.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, menacing but comical dragon sitting at a picnic table in a sunny outdoor setting with rolling hills in the background. The dragon is looking down at a tiny, nervous human character who is standing nearby, sweating and holding a bottle of ketchup. The dragon is licking its lips with a mischievous grin, clearly eyeing the human as if considering them a tasty snack. On the picnic table, there is a ketchup bottle prominently displayed, along with a small plate with some cartoonishly crunchy snacks like chips or crackers shaped like humans. The human looks worried and is wearing casual clothes. The scene should be colorful, lighthearted, and clearly whimsical, emphasizing the joke that humans are crunchy and taste good with ketchup when meddling with dragons. The style should be a fun, exaggerated cartoon with expressive faces and simple backgrounds to keep focus on the characters and the joke.'),
 (1, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Food Humor', 'When a cat is dropped, it always lands on its feet, and when toast is dropped, it always lands with the buttered side facing down.  I propose to strap buttered toast to the back of a cat; the two will hover, spinning inches above the ground.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a fluffy cat mid-air, with a slice of buttered toast strapped comically to its back using a loose, quirky strap or harness. The cat''s body is slightly tilted, feet splayed as if trying to land, while the toast is oriented butter-side down. The background is simple, with a few motion lines to suggest the cat-toast combination is hovering and spinning just above a living room floor. Nearby, a surprised person with wide eyes and an open mouth watches the hovering cat-toast contraption. Include small humor details like a tipped-over butter dish or a clock on the wall showing the humorous moment, keeping the colors bright and the style lighthearted and cartoonish without any violence or distress.'),
 (593, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Food Humor, Good Question!', 'What is black and white and black and white and black and white and green? 3 penguins fighting over a pickle', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring three chubby, black-and-white penguins animatedly squabbling over a single green pickle. The setting is simple and playful, with an icy or snowy backdrop suggested by light blue and white colors. Each penguin should have exaggerated expressions showing determination and mild irritation as they tug or hover around the unusually green pickle placed on the ice between them. The pickle should be large and bright green, clearly contrasting with the penguins'' colors and the mostly monochrome black-and-white theme they represent. The style is cartoony, with rounded shapes and friendly features to emphasize humor and lightheartedness. No background details aside from subtle icy or snowy texture are needed, keeping the focus on the three penguins and the pickle they are fighting over.'),
 (1929, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Food Humor, Quotes', 'I''m not a vegetarian because I love animals; I''m a vegetarian because I hate plants.', 'A. Whitney Brown', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in a sunny garden surrounded by an exaggerated number of large, angry-looking plants with furrowed brows and glaring eyes. The person has a cheeky smirk, arms crossed, clearly not intimidated. Nearby, a few small happy animals (like a rabbit and a bird) watch the scene with puzzled expressions. The setting includes garden elements like flowers, bushes, and trees, but all the plants are comically menacing, highlighting the joke''s twist—that the person dislikes plants rather than loving animals. The style is colorful, playful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions on both the person and the plants to emphasize humor without any conflict or violence.'),
 (2973, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Food Humor, Unknown', 'I didn''t fight my way to the top of the food chain to be a vegetarian.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a confident, upright predator animal—such as a lion or a wolf—wearing a crown or standing on a small podium labeled ''Top of the Food Chain.'' The animal should have a proud and slightly smug expression, maybe crossing its arms or holding a fork and knife. Nearby, display a colorful salad bowl or plate full of vegetables with a confused or worried herbivore animal watching in the background. Emphasize the contrast between the predator’s carnivorous nature and the vegetarian food by adding little humorous details, like a thought bubble above the predator reading, "I didn’t fight my way to the top of the food chain to be a vegetarian." Include natural surroundings like grass, trees, or rocks to set a simple outdoor scene. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated cartoonish styles to keep it light and funny.'),
 (1392, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Fun Facts, Quotes', 'A duck''s quack doesn''t echo, and no one knows why.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a duck standing on the edge of a still pond at sunset. The duck looks puzzled, scratching its head with one wing while looking around suspiciously. Around the duck, faint, wavy sound lines emerge from its open beak illustrating a quack. However, unlike typical echo visuals, there are no echo repeats of the sound lines bouncing back from the trees, hills, or water surfaces nearby. The background includes softly rolling hills, a few tall trees, and a small hill in the distance where sound waves would normally reflect. Near the duck’s feet, a small sign reads “Quack Echo Not Found.” The style is cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors, emphasizing the oddity and mystery of the sound not echoing. The mood is lighthearted and whimsical, capturing the curiosity and confusion about why a duck’s quack doesn’t echo.'),
 (603, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!', 'What''s black and white and black and white and black and white? A penguin rolling down a hill!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a comical penguin rolling downhill. The penguin is colored in classic black and white, styled in a cute, exaggerated cartoon manner with big, expressive wide eyes and a goofy smile. It is in a horizontal rolling position with its flippers and feet slightly flailing in the air to show motion. The hill is gently sloped, covered in green grass with a few simple flowers and stones dotting the scenery. The background is a bright, sunny day with a clear blue sky and fluffy white clouds. To emphasize the rolling motion, several curved motion lines trail behind the penguin. The overall style is playful and lighthearted, suitable for all ages, avoiding any complex or detailed backgrounds to keep the focus on the penguin and its amusing tumble downhill.'),
 (643, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!', 'Why do you never see elephants hiding in trees? Because they''re really good at it!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set in a jungle or forest. In the foreground, a large tree with thick branches and lots of green leaves. Peeking out subtly from behind the tree trunk or blending into the leaves is a huge gray elephant, cleverly camouflaged and barely noticeable. The elephant should look sneaky and proud of its hiding skills. Nearby, a curious cartoon monkey or explorer with a confused or amazed expression is looking around but clearly cannot spot the elephant. The overall style should be lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated features for the elephant to emphasize the joke—big ears and trunk but partly hidden. The setting includes other jungle details like vines, bushes, and a blue sky, keeping a bright and silly tone without any violence or negativity.'),
 (646, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!, Lawyer Humor', 'Why experiment on animals with so many lawyers out there?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a quirky laboratory. In the center, a nervous-looking scientist wearing a white lab coat stands beside a large, detailed cage holding a group of indifferent animals—such as a calm dog, a bored cat, and a relaxed rabbit. Nearby, a group of cartoonish, well-dressed lawyers wearing suits and holding briefcases congregates, smiling slyly and looking ready to approach the scientist. The scientist looks anxiously back and forth between the animals and the approaching lawyers, scratching his head in confusion. Include lab equipment like beakers, test tubes, and a chalkboard with some scientific scribbles in the background to establish the setting. The tone is light and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the awkwardness of the situation and the underlying joke about experimenting on lawyers instead of animals.'),
 (577, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!, Pun', 'What do Eskimos get from sitting on the ice too long? Polaroids.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly Eskimo character sitting on a large, clear sheet of ice. The Eskimo is dressed in traditional winter clothing with a fur-lined hood and mittens, looking relaxed but surprised. Below the Eskimo’s bottom on the ice, there are two classic Polaroid-style photos developing, as if his sitting caused the pictures to form instantly. Around the scene, add wintry elements like snow, small icebergs, and a simple snowy landscape background with a pale blue sky. The overall style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and smooth, rounded cartoon lines to emphasize the joke''s playful tone. No other characters or props are needed besides the ice, the Eskimo, and the emerging Polaroid photos under him.'),
 (628, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!, Pun', 'Why do birds fly south in the winter? It''s faster than walking', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of birds flying in a V-formation in the sky. Below them on the ground, several birds are comically trudging along a winding path, looking tired and frustrated. The flying birds wear cheeky expressions as if they''re enjoying their faster mode of travel. The walking birds carry tiny suitcases or backpacks to add to the humor of their slow pace. The background includes a simple landscape with a few trees and a bright sun or clouds indicating winter season with some bare branches or small patches of snow. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the joke''s playful tone.'),
 (573, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!, Puns', 'What color is a chameleon sitting on a mirror?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a chameleon sitting on a large, shiny mirror placed on the ground. The chameleon should be in classic bright green with colorful patterns, looking confused or puzzled. The mirror reflects the chameleon''s image clearly, showing the same bright green colors. Around the chameleon, include a few exaggerated question marks floating above its head to emphasize its confusion about its own color. The background should be simple and bright, possibly outdoors with some grass and a clear blue sky. The style should be lighthearted and cartoony with thick outlines and vibrant colors, emphasizing the playful absurdity of a chameleon trying to blend in with a mirror rather than natural surroundings.'),
 (570, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!, Word Play', 'What animal jumps higher than a house? Any animal. Houses can''t jump.', NULL, 'Create a colorful and humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful farmyard setting. In the foreground, draw a variety of animals—such as a dog, a cat, a rabbit, and a kangaroo—all mid-jump with exaggerated motion lines to show height. Near these animals, depict a simple house with a smiling face, clearly planted firmly on the ground, with no motion or jumping lines. The house looks solid and unmoving, perhaps with arms or eyes to give it character but showing that it cannot jump. Include a bright sunny sky and green grass to keep the mood light and playful. The overall style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity of a house trying to jump and the animals effortlessly getting higher. The expressions on the animals should be joyful and fun, and the house can look slightly surprised or puzzled.'),
 (630, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Good Question!, Word Play', 'Why do flamingoes lift one leg up? If they lifted both they''d fall', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bright pink flamingo standing on one long, slender leg in a shallow pond. The flamingo wears a slightly confused or cheeky expression as it balances effortlessly. Nearby, another flamingo attempts to stand on both legs but is comically falling over sideways, wings flailing to regain balance, with a small splash in the water. The background shows a sunny blue sky, a few reeds, and lily pads. The style is cute and exaggerated, emphasizing the flamingos'' long legs and awkward fall in a playful, non-threatening way.'),
 (787, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Halloween, Puns', 'Why didn''t the skeleton cross the road? It did''t have the guts', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a skeleton standing at the edge of a crosswalk on a sunny day. The skeleton looks hesitant and comically worried, glancing nervously across the street. The crosswalk is a classic zebra-style road marking with a simple two-lane road visible. Nearby, there is a speech bubble coming from the skeleton saying, ''I don''t have the guts.'' To emphasize the pun, draw a small transparent outline of internal organs (guts) missing inside the skeleton’s ribcage area, as if they were never there. The background includes a friendly neighborhood setting with trees, a sidewalk, and a few simple buildings. Add a humorous style with bright colors, exaggerated facial expression on the skeleton, and a subtle playful tone, avoiding anything scary or grotesque.'),
 (799, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Hipsters, Word Play', 'How do you drown a hipster? In the mainstream', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon set in a river scene. In the center, a trendy hipster character with a modern beard, round glasses, a beanie, and skinny jeans is partially submerged in water that is depicted as a flowing river labeled ''Mainstream'' with a large, playful signpost reading ''Mainstream'' on the riverbank. The hipster looks surprised and slightly alarmed, struggling playfully as water surrounds him up to his chest. Nearby, a couple of hipster items like a vintage camera and a cup of artisanal coffee float beside him. In the background, to emphasize the contrast, the riverbank has symbols of ''cool'' and ''alternative'' culture like a vinyl record and an old bicycle leaned against a tree. The entire scene is colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and a lighthearted mood conveying the joke visually without any harm or danger.'),
 (2826, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Irony, Unknown', 'Even the boldest zebra fears the hungry lion.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a zebra standing wide-eyed and nervous at the edge of a grassy savanna. The zebra has exaggerated, wide-open eyes and sweat drops to show fear. Nearby, a lion with a comically large mouth wide open in a hungry grin is peeking from behind a bush, looking at the zebra with eager eyes and exaggerated, oversized teeth. The background features sparse acacia trees and a bright sunny sky. The style should be colorful, light-hearted, and exaggerated in a classic cartoon fashion, emphasizing the contrasting expressions of boldness and fear without any harm or violence depicted. The zebra could have an exaggerated, bold mane or stance to visually emphasize its usual courage clashing with the fear it feels here.'),
 (1246, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Knock Knock, Pun', 'KK/WT: Impatient Cow ? (interrupt them) Moo!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a cow standing in the middle of a green pasture under a bright blue sky with a few fluffy clouds. The cow looks impatient and slightly annoyed, with raised eyebrows and a hoof tapping its leg as if waiting. Next to the cow is a speech bubble with the word ''Moo!'' in bold letters. Nearby, a person or another animal starts to speak or approach the cow but is humorously interrupted by the cow''s loud ''Moo!'' The style should be playful and exaggerated, with the cow having expressive cartoon eyes, a big friendly snout, and small horns. Additional details can include a wooden fence or a barn in the background to set the farm theme. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny without any negativity or complexity, focusing on the idea of the impatient cow cutting someone off with a ''Moo!''.'),
 (2385, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Leadership Humor, Quotes', 'The speed of the leader determines the rate of the pack.', 'Wayne Lukas', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of animals running together as a pack, like wolves or dogs. At the front is a comically serious leader animal, maybe a confident wolf wearing sunglasses or a captain''s hat, setting the pace. Behind the leader, the pack struggles to keep up, with some animals panting or stumbling humorously, showing various reactions to the leader’s speed. The background is a simple forest or open plain to signify nature, with motion lines around the animals to emphasize movement. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to maximize humor without any violent or intense expressions.'),
 (2067, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Love Humor, Quotes', 'Love is like racing across the frozen tundra on a snowmobile which flips over, trapping you underneath. At night, the ice-weasels come.', 'Nietchze', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a vast, snowy frozen tundra under a night sky with twinkling stars and a crescent moon. In the center, a snowmobile is overturned on its side, with a surprised person wearing winter clothes (puffy jacket, scarf, and earmuffs) partially trapped underneath it, their eyes wide with a mix of shock and mild panic. Around them, small, cute but mischievous-looking cartoon ice-weasels with fluffy tails and sharp eyes are creeping closer, sniffing or peeking curiously. The background shows an endless snowy landscape with small icebergs or snow mounds, and a few bare, leafless trees dusted with snow. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright winter colors to emphasize the absurdity and humor of the metaphor about love. The scene should evoke a silly and slightly chaotic feeling without any threat or horror.'),
 (2447, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Music Humor, Quotes', 'These are bagpipes. I understand the inventor of the bagpipes was inspired when he saw a man carrying an indignant, asthmatic pig under his arm. Unfortunately, the man-made sound never equalled the purity of the sound achieved by the pig.', 'Alfred Hitchcock', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene showing a whimsical countryside background with rolling green hills and a few fluffy clouds. Centrally, a cheerful man is walking while carrying a small, round pig tucked under his arm. The pig looks asthmatic and indignant, with puffed cheeks, squinting eyes, and little puffs of air coming from its snout indicating labored breathing. Near them, a set of traditional bagpipes sits on a wooden post or the ground, with musical notes floating upwards in a wavy pattern to show sound. The bagpipes look somewhat comical, with exaggerated pipes and a slightly silly expression drawn on the bag part. The man has a curious, slightly amused facial expression as if reminiscing about the inspiration. The overall tone is humorous and playful, with bright pastel colors and cartoonish proportions. No violence or unpleasant imagery, just a funny visual connection between the pig and the bagpipes’ sound origin.'),
 (3053, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Ocean Humor, Unknown', 'I wonder how much deeper the ocean would be without sponges.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cross-section of the ocean. The water is a bright blue, with various sea creatures like fish, octopuses, and seaweed visible. Several large, exaggerated cartoon sponges are sitting on the ocean floor, puffed up and oversized, clearly taking up a lot of space. Above the water, a curious character (a person with a thinking expression, hand on chin) stands on a beach or pier, looking out at the ocean. A thought bubble from this character contains a question mark and an image of the ocean without the sponges, showing a much deeper sea bed empty and vast. The sponges appear comically inflated, emphasizing the joke that they fill up the ocean''s depth. The cartoon style is colorful, light-hearted, and playful, with simple lines and friendly expressions on the creatures.'),
 (1458, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Political Humor, Quotes', 'A politician is an animal who can sit on a fence, yet keep both ears to the ground.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a comical hybrid creature that looks part animal, part human politician. The creature has the body of a friendly, slightly exaggerated farm animal like a sheep or goat, with exaggerated human facial features such as a wide smile and slightly slick hair resembling a politician. It is sitting on top of a large wooden fence, which runs horizontally across the image. The politician-animal''s hind legs are perched on one side of the fence, while its front legs rest on the other as if balancing perfectly on the fence without falling off. Both of its large ears are exaggerated and are pressed down firmly against the ground on either side of the fence, like antennae listening carefully. Around the fence, add small tufts of grass, and a couple of cartoon-style bugs or tiny animals to emphasize the act of ''keeping ears to the ground.'' The background is a simple outdoor rural scene with a bright blue sky and a few fluffy clouds, adding to the lighthearted and non-threatening atmosphere. Make sure the style is colorful and playful, with smooth lines and exaggerated features to highlight the humor and absurdity of the image.'),
 (1622, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Political Humor, Quotes', 'Democracy is also a form of worship. It is the worship of Jackals by Jackasses.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a humorous and exaggerated depiction of a political setting. Center the image on a group of jackals dressed in formal politician suits, standing at a podium with microphones, looking smug and proud. Surrounding them is a crowd of jackasses (donkeys) wearing casual or everyday clothes, some holding voting ballots or signs, looking confused or overly enthusiastic. The background could depict elements of a voting booth or a government building stylized with funny details, like a banner reading ''Democracy'' above. The cartoon style should be playful and exaggerated with bright colors, big expressive eyes, and oversized heads to emphasize humor. Include little visual puns like caricatured campaign posters showing jackals and jackasses interacting absurdly. The focus is on the absurdity of the situation, not intended to offend but to create a lighthearted visual joke about democracy as a ''worship'' involving these animals.'),
 (2757, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Political Humor, Unknown', 'Democracy: Four wolves and a lamb voting on lunch.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing four big, fierce-looking wolves sitting around a wooden picnic table, each wearing sly, happy grins. Across from them sits a small, nervous lamb looking uncomfortable and outnumbered. Above them is a large banner or sign reading ''Democracy'' in playful letters. The setting is a sunny meadow with green grass and a few trees in the background. Each wolf has a voting ballot or hand raised, clearly marking their choice. The lamb appears confused or worried about the vote. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the mismatch between the wolves and the lamb voting together.'),
 (2215, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Pop Culture, Quotes', 'Rambo is a wimp.', 'Arnold Schwarzenegger', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Rambo, the iconic tough action hero, drawn in a playful, exaggerated style. He is dressed in his classic outfit with a red headband and combat gear but is shown sneaking timidly behind a small, cute bunny rabbit that looks completely unfazed. The setting is a jungle clearing with oversized leaves and cartoonish plants. Rambo''s expression is comically scared or nervous, with wide eyes and a slight sweat drop. The little bunny appears confident, maybe even smirking. Include a simple caption or speech bubble near the bunny saying, ''Who''s the wimp now?''. The colors are bright and playful, enhancing the joke''s lighthearted tone.'),
 (2253, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Programming Humor, Quotes', 'Sometimes you''re the windshield, sometimes you''re the bug. Dire Straits.  Sometimes you''re the program, sometimes you''re the bug.', 'Mr. Interesting', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two parts. On the left side, depict a large, shiny car windshield with a small, cartoonish bug splattered on it with exaggerated surprised eyes and antennae splayed. Above the windshield, include the text ''Sometimes you''re the windshield, sometimes you''re the bug.'' On the right side, show a computer screen displaying a simple program code window with a small, bug-shaped character crawling on it looking distressed or guilty. Above this screen, display the text ''Sometimes you''re the program, sometimes you''re the bug.'' The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and expressive, comical characters, emphasizing the irony between being in control or being the problem in different contexts. No humans or harsh details, just the bug, windshield, and computer elements in a friendly cartoon style.'),
 (2200, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Pun, Quotes', 'Pigs make lousy ninjas.', 'Hamton in Tiny Toon Adventures', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a pig dressed in a classic black ninja outfit, including a mask covering most of its face but with its pink snout sticking out. The pig is awkwardly attempting stealth by tiptoeing exaggeratedly with one hoof raised, but it has big muddy footprints behind it, showing it''s anything but stealthy. Nearby, a startled ninja master—an older human dressed in a traditional ninja robe—is watching the pig with a mix of disbelief and amusement, holding a scroll titled ''Ninja Code.'' The background shows a Japanese-style garden with bonsai trees, stone lanterns, and a bamboo fence. The pig’s tail is slightly wagging, and a nearby speech bubble reads, ''Pigs make lousy ninjas.'' The overall style is colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor, emphasizing the pig''s inherent unsuitability for ninja stealth.'),
 (2612, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Pun, Quotes', 'You know why fish are so thin? They eat fish.', 'Jerry Seinfeld', 'A humorous cartoon scene set underwater showing two skinny fish having a casual conversation. One fish looks lean and slightly surprised or amused while the other fish, looking a bit sly, is holding a tiny fish (like a snack) in its fin-muzzle area, as if about to eat it. Around them, a few other tiny fish swim by looking equally thin and somewhat funny due to their skinniness. The background shows a simple ocean floor with a few seaweed strands and bubbles rising. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the fish''s thinness and the humor of one fish eating fish. No scary or violent elements – just a playful underwater interaction between two cartoon fish characters.'),
 (2649, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Pun, Unknown', 'A three legged dog walks into a bar and says ''I''m looking for the man who shot my paw''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a typical old-fashioned bar with wooden stools and a bartender behind the counter. In the middle of the bar, prominently feature a three-legged dog standing on its remaining legs, facing the bartender. The dog should have a determined, slightly gruff expression, perhaps with a small cowboy hat tilted jauntily on its head to add character. Show a speech bubble above the dog saying, ''I''m looking for the man who shot my paw.'' The other bar patrons, a mix of various animals or humans, turn their heads to look amused or surprised by the talking dog. Include details like beer mugs on the counter, a neon sign in the background, and warm lighting to give the scene a cozy, classic bar atmosphere. The overall style should be colorful, exaggerated, and playful to emphasize the pun and absurdity of the situation.'),
 (1599, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Puns, Quotes', 'Cats are smarter than dogs. You can''t get eight cats to pull a sled through snow.', 'Jeff Valdez', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a snowy landscape with a small sled. In front of the sled, eight cats are standing in a line, each with an indifferent or mischievous expression, clearly ignoring the idea of pulling. Some cats are sitting, others are grooming themselves or looking sideways. Behind the sled, a frustrated but comical person wearing winter clothes (e.g., a hat, scarf, and mittens) tries to encourage the cats with exaggerated gestures and facial expressions. In the background, a happy dog team (about four dogs) enthusiastically pulls another sled, showing clear cooperation and effort. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoonish features on all characters. Snow is gently falling, and the scene has a bright, cheerful winter day atmosphere.'),
 (2423, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Quotes', 'There are, of course, several things in Ontario that are more dangerous than wolves. For instance, the step-ladder.', 'J. W. Curran', 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors in a Canadian wilderness environment, showing a menacing yet slightly comical wolf on the left side snarling or growling, perhaps with exaggerated sharp teeth and wild eyes. On the right side, a large, upright step-ladder looms imposingly, almost personified with a sly or mischievous face drawn on it, making it appear unexpectedly dangerous compared to the wolf. The background includes typical Ontario elements, such as pine trees, a clear blue sky, and maybe a small cabin or a rustic sign reading ''Ontario Wilderness.'' The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity of fearing a step-ladder more than a wild animal. Bright colors and friendly but exaggerated expressions should highlight the joke’s playful contrast between natural danger and an everyday household object being perceived as more threatening.'),
 (1541, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Quotes, Science Humor', 'An ostrich''s eye is bigger than its brain. (Kinda gives new meaning to the term bird brain, doesn''t it?)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, cartoonish ostrich standing in a sunny savanna setting with sparse trees and grass. The ostrich has an exaggeratedly huge eye that takes up nearly half of its small head, looking wide and comical. Its brain is humorously small and visible inside a transparent skull section or floating next to its head as a tiny cartoon brain with a puzzled expression. The ostrich has a goofy, slightly confused but innocent expression. Nearby, a small sign or speech bubble reads: ''Bird brain? Think again!'' The style is light, colorful, and playful, with rounded shapes and exaggerated features to emphasize the joke without any aggression or complexity.'),
 (1656, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Quotes, Word Play', 'Eagles may soar in the clouds, but weasels never get sucked into jet engines.', 'Jason Hutchinson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confident bald eagle soaring proudly high up in fluffy white clouds against a bright blue sky. The eagle looks majestic but nervously glances down toward a large commercial jet engine mounted on the wing of a passing airplane below. Meanwhile, on the ground beneath the sky, a small, smug-looking cartoon weasel with a sly grin stands beside a signpost pointing up with an arrow labeled ''Jet Engines: Danger!'' The weasel appears completely safe and happy, far from any flying hazards. The illustration should emphasize the contrast between the eagle dangerously flying high near the plane and the weasel confidently staying grounded, avoiding trouble. The style is light-hearted, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke''s irony and humor, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon.'),
 (1961, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Quotes, Word Play', 'Is that a rabbit in your coat, or are you just glad to see me?', 'Who Framed Roger Rabbit', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person wearing a large, fluffy winter coat that looks oversized and puffy. The person is standing with a surprised, slightly embarrassed expression while looking down at their coat pocket where a small, cute cartoon rabbit is peeking out. The rabbit should look playful and innocent with big eyes and floppy ears. The background can be a simple outdoor winter setting, maybe with snow on the ground and a few bare trees to suggest cold weather. Include a speech bubble coming from an off-screen character saying the joke line, "Is that a rabbit in your coat, or are you just glad to see me?" The style should be light and funny, emphasizing the silly absurdity of a rabbit hidden inside a coat rather than anything intense or realistic.'),
 (2269, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Quotes, Word Play', 'That duck spits out more words than a dictionary in a garbage disposal.', 'Foghorn Leghorn in Tiny Toon Adventures', 'Draw a colorful cartoon scene featuring a cartoon duck sitting next to a large, open dictionary and a kitchen garbage disposal unit. The duck has an exaggerated, wide-open beak as if it is speaking or spitting out words rapidly. Around the duck’s beak, numerous colorful, whimsical word bubbles and letters fly out in every direction, some shaped like pages or letters, emphasizing the idea of a flood of words. The dictionary should look oversized and open, with visible text and illustrations, while the garbage disposal unit should be a typical kitchen sink with a grinding chamber clearly visible. The setting is a simple kitchen countertop with a sink, faucet, and some kitchen elements in soft pastel colors to keep it lighthearted and funny. The duck’s expression is comically intense as it ''spits'' words, capturing the absurd humor of the phrase. The overall style is a cheerful, humorous cartoon with bold outlines and vibrant colors, making the scene playful and engaging without any violence, politics, or adult themes.'),
 (2700, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Cat''s urine glows under a blacklight.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room at night. In the center, a mischievous-looking cat is standing beside a glowing puddle of bright yellow urine that emits an eerie greenish glow, as if lit by a blacklight. Nearby, a curious person wearing pajamas and holding a blacklight flashlight peers down at the glowing spot with wide eyes and an exaggerated surprised expression. The room has a couch, a coffee table with a spilled drink, a potted plant slightly knocked over, and a window showing a full moon outside. The overall tone is lighthearted and comedic, with exaggerated facial expressions and a playful vibe.'),
 (2782, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Dolphins have bigger brains than humans.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a dolphin and a human facing each other. The dolphin is standing upright on its tail in shallow water near a beach, proudly showing off an oversized brain that is visibly large and shiny, almost glowing. The human, on the shore wearing casual beach clothes and sunglasses, looks surprised and slightly puzzled, scratching their head while glancing at their own much smaller brain depicted hovering above their head inside a transparent thought bubble. The background includes simple ocean waves, a bright sunny sky, and a few seashells on the sand. The style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the dolphin’s brain size contrast with the human’s, with exaggerated cartoon features and expressions to highlight the joke without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (2823, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Elephants can''t jump.  Every other mammal can.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, sunny savannah clearing. At the center, a large, friendly-looking elephant with a puzzled expression is mid-air with its legs tucked awkwardly, clearly attempting to jump but barely leaving the ground. Around the elephant, several other animals—such as a rabbit, a kangaroo, a monkey, and a dog—are shown happily leaping high into the air with big smiles, clearly enjoying their ability to jump. The background shows a few trees and a simple blue sky with fluffy clouds. A small sign or caption near the elephant says, “Elephants can’t jump.” The overall style is playful and light-hearted with exaggerated cartoon expressions and movements to emphasize the humor.'),
 (2882, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Science Humor, Unknown', 'GENETIC ENGINEERING: Tampering with chromosomes so that science might develop a new miracle cure or a rabbit that plays the banjo.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful scientist in a lab coat and goggles standing proudly next to a cartoon rabbit that is energetically playing a banjo. The lab is filled with classic scientific equipment such as test tubes, microscopes, and a double helix DNA model prominently displayed on a poster in the background. The rabbit has an exaggerated, joyful expression, large ears, and is wearing tiny glasses to add to the humor. On a nearby lab bench, there is a clipboard with the words ''Genetic Engineering Project'' written on it. The overall style is bright, colorful, and playful, emphasizing the absurdity of genetically engineering a musical rabbit in a lighthearted way, without any hints of harm or seriousness.'),
 (3196, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Steven Wright, Word Play', 'Eagles may soar, but weasels don''t get sucked into jet engines.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large majestic eagle soaring high in a clear blue sky with wings fully spread, looking proud and graceful. Below the eagle, a small, sneaky weasel is on the ground next to a runaway jet engine from an airplane that has stopped spinning, looking smug and safe. The jet engine is exaggerated in size and detail but cartoonish and harmless-looking. The background includes fluffy clouds, a distant mountain silhouette, and a bright sun. The style should be light-hearted and funny, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the eagle''s elegance and the weasel''s clever luck. The scene should avoid any violence or danger, focusing on the contrast between soaring high and staying grounded safely.'),
 (3216, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Steven Wright, Word Play', 'The early bird may get the worm, but the second mouse gets the cheese.', 'Steven Wright', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, a bright, cheerful early bird (a small, round, happy-looking bird with big eyes) eagerly pecks at a wriggly worm on the ground with the sun just rising in the background. On the right side, a sneaky, clever-looking mouse with a satisfied grin carefully approaches a classic mouse trap with a large piece of cheese inside, ready to snag it after another mouse is gone. The first mouse is shown as a shadow or ghostly outline near the trap to imply it got caught earlier. The background is a simple kitchen floor with a cupboard nearby and a soft contrast between morning light on the bird’s side and dimmer, cautious shadowy lighting on the mouse’s side. The style is playful, with exaggerated expressions on both the bird and the mouse to emphasize the joke’s contrast between getting an early start versus benefiting from others’ mistakes.'),
 (3044, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Transportation, Unknown', 'I think that we''re all bozos in this bus.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly quirky bus filled with a diverse group of amusing clown-like characters (bozos) sitting inside. The bus is mid-sized, bright yellow, with exaggerated round windows that show each clown with big red noses, oversized shoes, polka-dot costumes, and goofy hats. The bus driver is a clown wearing a conductor''s hat, looking happily bewildered. Outside the bus, a road sign reads "Welcome to Bozo Land." The background is a sunny day with fluffy clouds and playful trees. The overall style is lighthearted, fun, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions on the characters to emphasize the silliness and humor of everyone being ''bozos'' together on this bus.'),
 (2657, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown', 'As the twig is bent, the birds fall off.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors with a comically bent twig or small branch hanging from a tree. Several colorful cartoon birds, looking surprised and flapping their wings, are shown slipping and falling off the twig mid-air. The twig is exaggeratedly bent downward, almost like a diving board, adding a playful dynamic. Around the tree, a few leaves flutter and a simple blue sky with a smiling sun is visible. The birds have funny expressions—some wide-eyed, some clutching their feathers—emphasizing the unexpected nature of their fall. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated features, making the scene feel silly and whimsical rather than serious.'),
 (2703, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown', 'Certain bears can smell you from 20 miles away.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene in a forest or wilderness setting. Show a large, cartoonish bear standing upright with an exaggeratedly large nose sniffing the air with intense focus. Surround the bear with pine trees and distant mountains to suggest a vast wilderness. Include a tiny human figure far away in the background (about 20 miles away), looking startled and waving nervously, visibly trying to hide behind a small tree or rock. The bear’s nose should have cartoon-style smell lines trailing from the person''s direction to the bear’s nose to emphasize the long-distance sniffing ability. The overall tone is light and funny, with bright colors and expressive characters to make the joke clear and visually engaging. Avoid anything scary or violent — the scene should feel playful and silly, highlighting the bear’s powerful sense of smell in a comical way.'),
 (2780, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown', 'Does my dog think I''m a hypocrite because I poop in the house?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room. In the center, there is a confused-looking dog sitting on a plush rug, tilting its head as if pondering deeply. Facing the dog is a human owner with a puzzled expression, scratching their head thoughtfully. Near the owner’s feet is a small, cartoonish pile representing dog poop on the carpet. To add humor, include little thought bubbles above the dog showing images: one of the owner using the bathroom, and another of the dog looking morally conflicted. The background should show everyday home details like a couch, a small table with a plant, and a window. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the confusion and irony, keeping the tone light and funny without any negativity.'),
 (3109, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown', 'Why don''t blind people skydive? Their dogs hate it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a blind person standing on the edge of an airplane''s open door, ready to skydive. The blind person wears classic skydiving gear including goggles, helmet, and harness. Next to them is a small, grumpy-looking dog wearing tiny aviator goggles and a scarf. The dog is barking or pulling back slightly, clearly unhappy or worried. The background shows the sky and clouds, giving a clear sense of altitude and the thrill of skydiving. The scene should emphasize the dog''s protective, disapproving attitude in a funny, exaggerated manner without fear or danger, with light-hearted, playful expressions on both characters’ faces. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the joke through the dog''s comical dislike of the idea.'),
 (3103, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown, Word Play', 'The early bird may get the worm, but the second mouse gets the cheese. (Think about it some more.)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two mice in a simple kitchen setting. On the left, a bright-eyed early bird wearing a tiny alarm clock on its wing sits proudly on a branch just outside a mouse hole, with a small, realistic worm dangling from its beak. On the right, two cartoon mice are near a mousetrap set on the floor; the first mouse looks startled and is caught in the trap (but drawn in a non-violent, slapstick way like a popped spring or raised trap), while the second mouse stands confidently at a short distance, happily holding a big wedge of cheese with a sly smile, clearly safe and enjoying the prize. Around them, include a clock on the wall showing early morning time, crumbs around the cheese, and a few kitchen items like a rolling pin and a small plate to set the scene. The style should be colorful and exaggerated with expressive faces to emphasize the joke''s playful irony.'),
 (3125, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown, Word Play', 'You are familiar with ''school of fish'' and ''pride of lions'', but what about a ''knot of toads'', an ''exaltation of larks'', and  a ''murder of crows''?', NULL, 'A colorful, playful cartoon scene showing three groups of animals labeled with their humorous collective nouns. On the left, a small cluster of toads is tangled together in a loose knot shape, looking confused but friendly. Above them, a group of cheerful larks are flying upward in an elegant formation, some looking proud or regal, with a subtle glow or aura to suggest ''exaltation.'' On the right, a group of crows huddle together with mischievous expressions, some holding tiny detective hats or magnifying glasses, referencing the ''murder of crows'' phrase humorously. Each group is clearly distinct and the background is a cheerful outdoor setting with trees, grass, and a light blue sky. At the top of the image, bold text reads: "You know ''school of fish'' and ''pride of lions''... but what about these?" The whole drawing adopts a bright, lighthearted, and exaggerated cartoon style to enhance the humor and whimsy of the unusual animal group names.'),
 (3130, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown, Word Play', 'You can never lose a homing pigeon. If it doesn''t come back, it was just a pigeon.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two birds on the ground: one is a confident, smug-looking homing pigeon wearing a little messenger bag, clearly ready to fly back home. The other bird is an ordinary, clueless pigeon looking confused and standing still, maybe scratching its head with a wing. Above them, a thought bubble or a sign says: ''You can never lose a homing pigeon. If it doesn''t come back, it was just a pigeon.'' The background is a simple park with a bench and a tree, drawn in bright, cheerful colors. The homing pigeon is brightly colored or marked to stand out, while the ordinary pigeon is plain gray. Cartoon style, exaggerated expressions, light-hearted and fun.'),
 (3135, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Unknown, Word Play', 'You don''t have to hang from a tree to be a nut.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky character standing confidently on the ground next to a large tree. The tree has a few scattered nuts hanging from its branches, such as acorns and walnuts, clearly visible. The character, depicted with exaggerated features like wide eyes and a goofy smile, looks a little ''nutty''—for example, wearing a silly hat made of colorful nuts or mismatched clothes. The character is pointing at themselves or striking a proud pose as if to say they''re ''nuts'' without the typical tree-hanging context. The background is a playful outdoor setting with bright colors, a clear sky, and maybe a small squirrel looking confused or amused from a nearby branch. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with simple shapes and vibrant hues to emphasize the joke''s punchline visually without any aggressive or inappropriate elements.'),
 (3252, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Visual Humor, What do you call...', 'What do you call a dog with no legs? It doesn''t matter - it''s not going to come.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful dog with no legs sitting on the ground, looking up with a hopeful expression. The background is a simple park setting with green grass, a tree, and a bright blue sky with a few fluffy clouds. Nearby, a smiling, casually dressed person is calling out to the dog, cupping their hands around their mouth. To emphasize the joke, the dog remains stationary and the person shows some playful frustration or amusement. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated in a classic cartoon style with rounded shapes and friendly character expressions, making the scene feel silly and gentle without any tension or negative tone.'),
 (2, 'Absurd Humor, Animals, Word Play', 'When the chips are down, the buffalo is empty.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large buffalo standing next to a bowl or small basket labeled ''Chips.'' The chips bowl is completely empty. The buffalo looks puzzled or slightly sad, as if surprised by the empty chips bowl. The setting is simple, with a plain background and maybe a small picnic table holding the chips bowl beside the buffalo. The buffalo should have exaggerated features - big eyes and a gentle, friendly expression to add to the humor. Include scattered poker chips or snack chips around to imply ''chips'' in both senses, and a small sign or thought bubble near the buffalo that hints at confusion or disappointment. The style is colorful, fun, and cartoonish without any harsh lines or dark tones.'),
 (1391, 'Absurd Humor, Architecture Humor, Career Humor, Quotes', 'A doctor can bury his mistakes but an architect can only advise his clients to plant vines.', 'Frank Lloyd Wright (1868-1959)', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels side by side. On the left, a doctor in a white coat and stethoscope is standing beside an open grave in a cemetery, looking smugly at it, implying he has buried a mistake in it. The grave has a small sign labeled ''Mistake #1''. The setting is lighthearted with gravestones, green grass, and a clear sky. On the right panel, an architect dressed in a suit with rolled-up blueprints under one arm gestures nervously toward a half-built modern house surrounded by a garden. The garden is full of lush, climbing vines creeping up the walls and around the foundation, as if the architect recommended planting them to hide construction errors. The architect has a sheepish smile while a client, wearing casual clothes, looks at the vines with a mix of skepticism and amusement. The background should be bright and cheerful, with cartoonish exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke''s irony. Both panels should have a playful, light cartoon style emphasizing the contrast between the professions and their approaches to mistakes, with clear labels or small speech bubbles to hint at the joke without words.'),
 (2768, 'Absurd Humor, Art Humor, Music Humor, Unknown', 'Disco is to music what Etch-A-Sketch is to art.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two panels side-by-side. On the left panel, depict a lively 1970s disco scene with colorful lights, a disco ball hanging from the ceiling, and a group of people dressed in iconic disco fashion (bell-bottom pants, platform shoes, big hair) dancing awkwardly or striking goofy dance poses. The atmosphere should be vibrant but slightly silly. On the right panel, show a classic Etch-A-Sketch toy with a simple, childlike drawing of a stick figure or a scribble inside the screen, emphasizing the crude and limited artistic capability of the Etch-A-Sketch. Between the two panels, include a humorous caption or text bubble that reads, "Disco is to music what Etch-A-Sketch is to art," to tie the comparison together. Use bright colors and exaggerated expressions to give the cartoon a lighthearted and playful feel, without implying any negativity—just a funny analogy between the perceived simplicity or datedness of disco music and the childlike nature of Etch-A-Sketch drawings.'),
 (3, 'Absurd Humor, Art Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'What garlic is to food, insanity is to art.', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene split into two parts side-by-side. On the left, depict a steaming dish of food (like a pasta plate) with exaggerated, cartoonish garlic bulbs floating around it, emphasizing how essential garlic is to food. On the right, show a wild, eccentric artist in a messy art studio surrounded by crazy, surreal paintings, splashes of paint, and quirky art tools flying around. The artist looks delightfully ''insane'' or wildly inspired, with a playful expression and maybe wild hair. Include whimsical details like a paintbrush swirling through the air or a canvas with a bizarre image, to highlight the connection between insanity and art. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, no harsh lines or serious tones.'),
 (1834, 'Absurd Humor, Art Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'I passionately hate the idea of being with it, I think an artist has always to be out of step with his time.', 'Orson Welles', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky artist standing proudly on a small hill with a paintbrush in one hand and a palette in the other. The artist wears a traditional beret, smock, and glasses, looking slightly eccentric. Around the artist''s feet, there are clocks and calendars showing different times and dates scattered on the ground, emphasizing ''being out of step with his time.'' In the background, a modern cityscape or crowd of people dressed in fashionable clothes and carrying smartphones look puzzled or confused, glancing at the artist. The sky is bright and cheerful, with little exaggerated cartoon-style musical notes or swirls indicating the artist’s passionate mood. The overall vibe is lighthearted and clever, visually illustrating the joke about an artist purposely standing apart from current trends.'),
 (1443, 'Absurd Humor, Art Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'A man paints with his brains and not with his hands.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing in front of a large easel with a blank canvas, but instead of holding a paintbrush in his hand, his head is open at the top like a jar, and bright, colorful paint is flowing out of his brain directly onto the canvas. His hands are raised and empty, looking surprised or puzzled. Around him are typical painting tools like brushes, palettes, and cans of paint sitting unused on the floor. The background is a simple art studio with easels, paint splatters on the floor, and a stool. The overall style is exaggerated and playful with bold lines and vibrant colors to emphasize the absurdity of painting with one''s brain instead of hands.'),
 (1543, 'Absurd Humor, Art Humor, Quotes', 'Another unsettling element in modern art is that common symptom of immaturity, the dread of doing what has been done before.', 'Edith Warton', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a modern art gallery. In the foreground, a quirky art critic with exaggerated facial features (wide eyes, raised eyebrows) is standing in front of a large minimalist painting — a simple square or circle — looking both puzzled and slightly disturbed. To emphasize the ''dread of doing what has been done before,'' behind the critic there are several similar minimalist artworks on the gallery walls, all near-identical in style and simplistic shapes. One of the paintings is whimsically labeled with a sticky note saying ''Been there, done that.'' Scatter papers or a small book titled ''Art History'' on a nearby bench to suggest tradition being repeated. The atmosphere should be light and comical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, capturing the ironic discomfort the critic feels about modern art’s tendency to imitate or repeat itself. No people should appear aggressive or upset, just amused or mildly confused.'),
 (1983, 'Absurd Humor, Aviation, Quotes, Word Play', 'It is now possible for a flight attendant to get a pilot pregnant.', 'Richard J. Ferris, president of United Airlines', 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside an airplane cockpit. The cockpit is shown with typical aviation controls, buttons, and windows displaying the sky outside. Standing just outside the cockpit door is a cheerful flight attendant holding a safety demonstration card, smiling slyly. Inside the cockpit, a surprised pilot in uniform is sitting in the pilot''s seat with wide eyes and a comically flushed face. Above them, a speech bubble from an announcer or a caption at the top reads: ''It is now possible for a flight attendant to get a pilot pregnant.'' The overall tone should be lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated facial expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize the joke’s absurdity. Include small airplane interior details, like overhead bins or passenger seats visible behind the flight attendant, to establish the setting clearly. The cartoon style should be simple and bold with clean lines and a cheerful atmosphere.'),
 (606, 'Absurd Humor, Bad Puns, Good Question!', 'What''s red and bad for your teeth? A brick', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a big, bright red brick with a smiling, slightly mischievous face. The brick is positioned on a sidewalk or ground in the foreground. Nearby, a person with an exaggeratedly shocked and pained expression is holding their cheek as if they just bit into it, with cartoon-style stars or sparkles around their head indicating pain or discomfort. The person could be mid-step, caught off guard. The background is simple and clean, like a city street or a plain park setting, to keep focus on the brick and the person. The style is light-hearted, with bold outlines and playful colors to emphasize the joke''s absurdity. No other objects or characters needed.'),
 (1860, 'Absurd Humor, Bad Puns, Quotes', 'I''d rather be rich than stupid.', 'Jack Handy', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a wealthy-looking person is dressed in fancy clothes, wearing sunglasses, holding a large money bag with a dollar sign, and standing confidently with a smug smile. On the right, a character with a goofy appearance, perhaps with crossed eyes, a silly grin, mismatched clothes, and a dunce cap labeled ''Dunce,'' looks a bit confused and comical. They are both standing on a simple background with a split line dividing them, emphasizing the contrast. The expression on the wealthy character exaggerates pride, while the silly character is carefree and oblivious, highlighting the joke''s preference for wealth over stupidity. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and light-hearted with no harsh or negative imagery.'),
 (2800, 'Absurd Humor, Bad Puns, Safety Humor, Unknown', 'Don''t smoke in bed. The ash on the floor may be your own.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bedroom with a person sleeping peacefully in a bed. Next to the bed on the floor, there is a lit cigarette that has fallen and is burning into the floorboards, creating a small pile of hot ash. The person is unaware, with a relaxed expression and snoring softly. The room is cozy with a nightstand holding an alarm clock and a lamp. The floor has visible ash trails leading from the cigarette to the bed. The style is light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the absurdity of smoking in bed. The overall mood is comical, with bright colors and exaggerated, cartoonish features.'),
 (2672, 'Absurd Humor, Bar Humor, Food Humor, Unknown', 'Beerstains are hardest to remove when using bar napkins & pretzels.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene set in a lively bar with a wooden counter. On the counter are a frothy beer mug, a small bowl of pretzels, and a stack of paper bar napkins. The napkins and pretzels are oddly covered in visible, exaggerated yellowish-beer stains, making a clear mess. A puzzled bartender or customer with a comical facial expression is holding a napkin in one hand and a pretzel in the other, looking frustrated or confused about the stubborn stains. The background shows a few other cheerful patrons enjoying drinks, but the focus is on the central characters and the stained napkins and pretzels. The style is lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated cartoon, emphasizing the humor of beer stains on items not typically considered for accidental staining.'),
 (2667, 'Absurd Humor, Bathroom Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'BATHQUAKE: n. The violent quake that rattles the entire house when the water faucet is turned on to a certain point.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bathroom interior with a bathtub and a sink. A person, drawn with exaggerated surprise, is standing by the bathtub faucet turning the handle. Water is gushing out with such force that it causes the entire bathroom to visibly shake—shown by wavy lines around the walls and objects like a towel rack, shower curtain, and toilet wobbling or tilting. The room’s light fixture swings, a small picture frame on the wall slightly askew. The person''s hair and bathrobe flap dramatically from the ''quake.'' Include a comic-style sound effect reading "BATHQUAKE!" in big, bold letters above the faucet. The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the ridiculous idea of a faucet causing an earthquake inside the house, all drawn in a colorful, playful cartoon style, without any mess or damage shown.'),
 (2605, 'Absurd Humor, Beer Humor, National Stereotypes, Quotes', 'You can''t be a Real Country unless you have a BEER and an airline. It helps if you have some kind of a football team, or some nuclear weapons, but at the very least you need a BEER.', 'Frank Zappa', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a colorful, fictional country shaped like a beer bottle wearing aviator goggles and a small pilot''s hat, happily flying a tiny airplane. The foreground features a cheerful football mascot holding a football and a cartoonish cartoonish nuclear missile with a comically scared expression. The background shows a sunny blue sky with fluffy clouds, a small airport runway labeled ''Beer AirCorp,'' and a festive beer festival tent with people clinking mugs. Everything is drawn in a bright, exaggerated, and lighthearted cartoon style emphasizing the absurdity and playful stereotypes mentioned in the joke.'),
 (1200, 'Absurd Humor, Body Positivity Humor, Family, Insults', 'The problem isn''t that obesity runs in your family. It''s that nobody runs in your family.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a family living room or backyard. In the foreground, a slightly overweight character stands with hands on hips, looking exasperated or making a witty expression. Around them, several family members are lazily sitting or lounging—one on a couch, another on a recliner, and a child lying on the floor—none showing any intention of running or exercising. Perhaps a family dog nearby is looking confused or panting. To the side, there’s a framed family photo on the wall or on a side table depicting several ancestors, all similarly overweight or sedentary, suggesting the family history. Include subtle visual cues like a pair of dusty running shoes in a corner, cobwebbed and untouched, to emphasize the joke. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and simple, clean lines to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (2806, 'Absurd Humor, Body Positivity Humor, Food Humor, Unknown', 'Donuts are not forever, but just try and get rid of that spare tire.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing sideways, clearly struggling to remove a large, inflatable tire wrapped around their waist like a spare tire from a car. Their face is comically strained with exaggerated effort. Next to them on the ground is a colorful box of delicious donuts, some sprinkled and some glazed, as if tempting them. The background is simple but includes a small scale and a mirror reflecting the person''s round belly. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the tempting donuts and the stubborn spare tire that won''t go away.'),
 (1796, 'Absurd Humor, Body Positivity Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I don''t consider myself bald. I''m simply taller than my hair.', 'Thom Sharp', 'A humorous cartoon drawing of a man standing confidently with a proud smile. He has a noticeably high forehead with a small patch of hair at the very top of his head, emphasizing his balding. The man''s height is exaggerated so that his head is nearly touching the top of the frame, while his hair is drawn much lower on his scalp, creating visible space between the top of his head and his hairline. He is wearing casual clothes and stands with his hands on his hips in a light-hearted, self-assured pose. The background is simple and bright, focusing attention on the character. Include a small, playful speech bubble above his head with the phrase: "I''m simply taller than my hair." The overall style is cartoonish and whimsical, making the joke clear and funny without any sharp edges.'),
 (2293, 'Absurd Humor, Books, Comic Humor, Quotes', 'The covers of this book are too far apart.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, thick book lying closed on a table. The book is comically oversized with the front and back covers exaggeratedly spread far apart, creating a wide gap between them, with pages seemingly stretched. A puzzled character, perhaps a small person or a cartoon figure wearing reading glasses, is squinting at the book confusedly and trying to bring the covers together with both hands. The background is simple, maybe a cozy study room with a lamp and bookshelf in the distance, to emphasize the book. The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, highlighting the physical impossibility of the book’s ''covers being too far apart.'' No other characters or objects suggest violence, politics, or anything inappropriate.'),
 (1202, 'Absurd Humor, Books, Insults, Pun', 'This is not a novel to be tossed aside lightly. It should be thrown with great force.', 'Dorothy Parker', 'A humorous cartoon scene centered on a person about to throw a large book with exaggerated effort. The person, with a determined and slightly strained expression, is standing in a casual setting, such as a living room or park. The book is clearly oversized and thick, labeled simply as ''Novel'' or having a book cover with a title that looks long and complex. The person is winding up to throw the book like a baseball, with one arm pulled back and their body turned sideways for maximum throwing power. Around them, a few startled or amused onlookers—friends or pets—react to the impending book toss. The background is lighthearted, with simple furniture or park elements like a bench and trees. The style is cartoonish with bold lines and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the comic absurdity of throwing a novel with great force rather than reading it carefully. The scene conveys the dual meaning of the joke visually: books normally being treated delicately but here being used as a heavy object to be tossed.'),
 (2454, 'Absurd Humor, Books, Quotes, Word Play', 'This book fills a much-needed gap.', 'Moses Hadas (1900-1966) in a review', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, thick book standing upright on a wooden table labeled ''Essential Gaps.'' The book has a comically large hole cut right through its middle, shaped like a puzzle piece, emphasizing a literal ''gap'' in the book. Around the table, a few people with puzzled and amused expressions are looking at the gap in the book. One person holds a magnifying glass, another is scratching their head. In the background, a bookshelf is visible with other normal, solid books, highlighting how unusual this one is. The setting is a cozy study or library room with warm lighting. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with simple lines and expressive faces suitable for a lighthearted cartoon.'),
 (2015, 'Absurd Humor, Calendar Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'I''ve been on a calendar, but I''ve never been on time.', 'Marilyn Monroe', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful human character personified as a calendar page stuck on a wall. The calendar character should have a big friendly face with wide eyes and a mischievous grin, clearly looking lively. Surround the character with several comic-style clocks of various designs (some digital, some analog), all showing different times. The clocks should appear confused or frustrated, highlighting the joke about never being on time. Include a small sticky note on the calendar character that says "Never on time" as if it''s a self-caption. The style should be colorful and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the humor of being on a calendar but not on time. The background can be a simple office or home wall to imply normal calendar placement, but keep it minimal to focus on the calendar and clocks.'),
 (3099, 'Absurd Humor, Calendar Humor, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, valentine''s Day would be moved to February 29th so it would only occur in leap years.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a calendar page prominently marked ''Valentine''s Day'' with a big red heart on February 14th. Nearby, a group of cartoon men stand around a conference table looking serious and holding charts and clipboards. One man is pointing to a calendar with a giant red circle around February 29th and a label that says, ''New Valentine''s Day.'' The men have exaggerated, lighthearted expressions to emphasize the joke. In the background, a woman peeks through a door with a raised eyebrow, looking amused or skeptical. The setting is a bright, simple office with a wall clock and a motivational poster that humorously reads, ''Efficiency is key!'' The overall style is colorful, clean, and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the comedic tone without any negativity.'),
 (2792, 'Absurd Humor, Camping, Pun, Unknown', 'Don''t draw fire; it irritates the people around you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a campfire surrounded by a small group of cartoon characters sitting on logs or rocks around it. One character near the fire is nervously holding a large, comically oversized bottle of water or a giant fire extinguisher labeled ''No Fire'' as if ready to put out the fire. The fire itself looks a bit grumpy or annoyed, with a cartoon face showing irritation or frowning eyebrows. Another character nearby wrinkles their nose and waves their hand in front of their face to indicate irritation from the heat or smoke. The background is a simple outdoor setting with trees and a starry night sky. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the wordplay about fire being irritating to people around it, not literally harmful. The style is simple and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to bring out the humor.'),
 (3026, 'Absurd Humor, Camping, Puns, Unknown', 'I recently took a pole - and 100% of the people in the tent were upset with me', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a camping tent. Show a small, crowded tent interior with several cartoon-style unhappy campers inside, all looking upset or angry. The focal character, standing in the center or entrance of the tent, is holding a long pole with a confused or guilty expression. The pole is clearly exaggerated in size to emphasize the joke. Around the characters, include typical camping gear like backpacks, sleeping bags, and a lantern to clearly establish the setting. The style should be playful and exaggerated with bright colors, making the campers'' emotionally upset faces obvious and funny but not mean. The overall vibe should be lighthearted and silly, showing the idea that taking the tent pole has inconvenienced everyone inside.'),
 (1651, 'Absurd Humor, Career Humor, History Humor, Quotes', 'Drill for oil? You mean drill into the ground to try and find oil? You''re crazy. (Drillers who Edwin L. Drake tried to enlist to his project to drill for oil in 1859.)', 'Edwin L. Drake', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in 1859 at an early oil drilling site. In the foreground, a determined Edwin L. Drake, dressed in old-fashioned 19th-century explorer clothes and a top hat, energetically gestures toward a tall, wooden oil derrick rig being constructed over a patch of dirt. Next to him are two skeptical drillers dressed in vintage work clothes with suspenders and caps, looking puzzled and incredulous. One driller has his arms crossed and an exaggerated skeptical expression, while the other scratches his head as if baffled by the idea. The background shows a simple rural landscape with a few wooden crates, oil barrels, and a horse-drawn cart. Above them, a cartoon-style speech bubble from one driller reads, "Drill for oil? You mean drill into the ground to try and find oil? You''re crazy." The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial reactions and clear old-timey details to underline the historic context. The style should be cartoony and whimsical, with bright colors and playful character proportions to enhance the humor without any negativity or offense.'),
 (2419, 'Absurd Humor, Career Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'There are three roads to ruin; women, gambling and technicians. The most pleasant is with women, the quickest is with gambling, but the surest is with technicians.', 'Georges Pompidou', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing three distinct roads diverging from a single path labeled ''Road to Ruin.'' Each road has a signpost with one label: ''Women,'' ''Gambling,'' and ''Technicians.'' The ''Women'' road is illustrated as a scenic, pleasant path lined with flowers, hearts, and cheerful people chatting happily, creating a warm and inviting atmosphere. The ''Gambling'' road is shorter, cluttered with poker chips, dice, and slot machines, with a character nervously clutching a handful of money, eyes wide in excitement or worry. The ''Technicians'' road appears solid and straight but shows a stubborn, serious-looking technician holding tools and cables, with machinery sparking or tangled wires around. The setting is bright and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions for comic effect, emphasizing the contrast between each route''s feel. The overall style is playful and light-hearted, avoiding negativity or offense, focusing on visual puns and caricatures to emphasize the joke’s punchline.'),
 (2981, 'Absurd Humor, Cars Humor, Health Humor, Unknown', 'I drive way too fast to worry about cholesterol.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person driving a small, brightly colored car at an exaggeratedly high speed, with motion lines and clouds of dust behind the car to emphasize speed. The driver is smiling wildly and wearing sunglasses, clearly unconcerned. On the side of the road, a large, oversized cholesterol pill bottle is shown with a worried face and tiny arms, looking shocked or scared as the car zooms past. The background is a simple countryside road with a few trees and a clear blue sky. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the absurdity of ignoring health concerns because of driving fast.'),
 (1889, 'Absurd Humor, Cars Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'If the automobile followed the same development cycle as the PC, today a Rolls-Royce would cost $100, get a million miles to the gallon, and explode once a year, killing everyone inside.', 'Robert X. Cringley, Infoworld', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a luxury Rolls-Royce car with exaggerated features: an oversized gas gauge showing ''1,000,000 miles per gallon,'' a giant price tag dangling that reads ''$100,'' and a few small comic-style explosions popping from the hood with smoke and stars. The car is shiny and pristine, parked on a street with amazed onlookers pointing and reacting in surprise and disbelief. One or two characters inside the car look worried or frantic, emphasizing the danger. The style should be colorful and lighthearted, with playful exaggeration emphasizing the absurd performance stats and the irony of the cheap cost but disastrous explosion, capturing the joke’s satirical comparison between car and PC development cycles. Background details are minimal but suggest a typical city street or dealership to keep focus on the car.'),
 (2685, 'Absurd Humor, Cars Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Bumper sticker: I don''t care what you love, what your other car is, or what you''d rather be doing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of the back of a plain car with a large, bold bumper sticker covering the rear bumper. The bumper sticker reads: ''I don''t care what you love, what your other car is, or what you''d rather be doing.'' The car is drawn in a simple, exaggerated cartoon style, parked on a suburban street with a few trees or houses faintly in the background. The focus is on the car and its bumper sticker, with no other characters or distractions in the scene. The font on the bumper sticker should be clear, bold, and slightly playful to emphasize the blunt, humorous message.'),
 (3069, 'Absurd Humor, Cars Humor, Traffic Jokes, Unknown', 'If all the cars in the world were placed end to end, 98 per cent would change lanes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a very long line of cars stretching far into the distance, all packed bumper-to-bumper on a single narrow road. The cars are comically cluttered, each with wheels turned at various angles as if they are trying to change lanes simultaneously, causing a chaotic but funny traffic jam. Some cars have exaggerated facial expressions like confusion or frustration, anthropomorphizing them for added humor. The background includes a blue sky with light clouds and a simple roadside with a few trees. The road is a single lane but crowded with cars trying to squeeze into another lane that doesn’t exist, emphasizing the absurdity. The style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, making the scene lively and visually amusing without any aggressive elements.'),
 (2245, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Dark Humor, Quotes', 'Some people say that I must be a horrible person, but that''s not true. I have the heart of a young boy. In a jar.  On my desk.', 'Steven King', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tidy office desk with a nameplate, a lamp, a coffee mug, and some scattered papers. On the desk is a clear glass jar with a small, exaggeratedly cute, cartoonish young boy''s heart inside it, complete with a tiny face looking slightly surprised or squished. The heart is bright red and distinctly shaped, so it’s clear it’s an anatomical heart but with a comical expression. Nearby, a speech bubble from an off-screen person reads, ''Some people say I must be a horrible person, but that''s not true. I have the heart of a young boy. In a jar. On my desk.'' The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and bold outlines, evoking a playful yet slightly absurd vibe.'),
 (2595, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Dark Humor, Quotes', 'Yea, though I walk through the valley of death I will fear no evil, for I am the meanest son of a bitch in the valley.', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a rugged, tough-looking character confidently standing in a dark, spooky valley called ''Valley of Death'' (indicated by a signpost). The valley is shadowy with ominous cliffs, a few creepy twisted trees, and bats flying around. The character is snarling and flexing muscles, wearing worn-out tough clothes like a leather jacket and boots, giving off an intimidating ''mean'' vibe. Around him are startled, scared little cartoon animals or characters retreating or hiding. The overall art style is light-hearted and exaggerated with bold outlines and expressive facial features to emphasize the character''s fearless and mean attitude in a comically scary environment. A small caption bubble next to him shows the phrase, “I am the meanest son of a bitch in the valley,” to highlight the joke’s punchline without using offensive language in the drawing itself.'),
 (2425, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Education Humor, Quotes', 'There is a country is Europe where multiple-choice tests are illegal.', 'Sigfried Hulzer', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, fictional European country map on a classroom chalkboard with the label ''No Multiple-Choice Tests Allowed!'' The classroom is lively and colorful, featuring a confused teacher holding a test paper covered with large ''A'', ''B'', ''C'', and ''D'' options crossed out boldly. Sitting at desks, diverse cartoon students look surprised or puzzled, some scratching their heads, others raising their hands unsure what to do without multiple-choice answers. On the teacher''s desk, a big red ''Banned'' stamp lies next to textbooks and a single open-ended question paper. The classroom walls have posters saying ''Open-ended Questions Only!'' and ''Critical Thinking Zone.'' Outside a window, a friendly European townscape with classic architecture hints at the country’s setting. The overall style is playful and exaggerated to highlight the absurdity of banning multiple-choice tests, focusing on expressions and the unusual test environment without any tension or negativity.'),
 (1662, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Fantasy Humor, Quotes', 'Eeeney-Meeney, Chili-beanie, the spirits are about to speak!', 'Bullwinkle', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a young kid outdoors, standing in front of a small campfire at dusk. The child is holding a stick with a marshmallow over the fire and is chanting with an exaggerated, playful expression: ''Eeeney-Meeney, Chili-beanie, the spirits are about to speak!'' Around the kid, small ghost-like figures hover in the air, looking surprised or curious about the chant. The background shows a darkening forest with simple trees and twinkling stars beginning to appear in the sky. The overall mood is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright, friendly colors and cute, rounded character designs. The scene should evoke a playful mix of a childhood campfire moment and imagining spirits responding humorously to a silly rhyme.'),
 (2240, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Fantasy Humor, Quotes', 'Soitenly! Nuk, Nuk, Nuk, Nuk!', 'Curly Howard', 'A cheerful, whimsical cartoon scene featuring a quirky, colorful alien or fantasy creature with a wide grin saying the nonsense phrase ''Soitenly! Nuk, Nuk, Nuk, Nuk!''. The creature should be mid-gesture, perhaps waving or enthusiastically moving its hands to show excitement or emphasis. Surround the character with playful, floating text bubbles containing the words "Soitenly!" above and repeated "Nuk, Nuk, Nuk, Nuk!" nearby in varying sizes and fonts for comedic effect. The setting is minimal but bright, with simple stars or sparkles to add a lighthearted, silly mood. The style is exaggerated and cartoonish, focusing on fun and absurdity rather than realism. There are no humans, weapons, or complex backgrounds, only the creature, the text bubbles, and a plain background to highlight the absurd phrase humorously.'),
 (3087, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Fantasy Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, at the end of the workday a whistle would blow and you would jump out of your window and slide down the tail of a brontosaurus and right into your car like Fred Flintstone.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outside a large office building at the end of a workday. Several people wearing typical business attire (men in suits and ties) are excitedly jumping out of open windows on a high floor. In the foreground is a giant friendly-looking brontosaurus standing next to the building, its long tail angled downward like a giant slide. People are sliding joyfully down the brontosaurus’s tail, wide smiles on their faces, in playful poses with arms raised or holding briefcases. At the base of the tail, some are landing directly into vintage-style cars parked below, reminiscent of the Flintstones’ stone-age vehicles but with a modern twist (wheels included). The background shows a setting sun and a cloud with a whimsical whistle symbol coming from the building, indicating the end of the workday. The style is colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish, focusing on fun and fantasy without any realistic details or serious elements. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, capturing the absurdity of replacing a traditional fire escape with a dinosaur slide and echoing the Flintstones’ iconic prehistoric lifestyle.'),
 (2686, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Food Humor, Unknown', 'BURGACIDE (burg'' uh side) n. When a hamburger can''t take any more torture and hurls itself through the grill into the coals.', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene showing a hamburger on a grill that looks distressed and animated, with eyes wide open and a mouth open as if yelling or gasping. The hamburger bun is slightly squished, and the patty appears to be sweating. The grill bars are visible beneath it, and in front of the burger, there’s a dramatic motion line or cloud indicating it’s leaping or hurling itself forward. Below the grill, cartoon-style bright red and orange coals glow intensely, ready to ''receive'' the burger. The scene should be colorful and exaggerated, with a lighthearted tone—the burger is clearly acting as if it’s escaping torture by jumping into the fire. Maybe add small sad or shocked faces on nearby condiments, like a tomato slice or lettuce leaf, watching the burger’s leap. The setting is an outdoor barbecue with a simple background to emphasize the burger’s dramatic ''escape.'' The overall illustration should look like a humorous cartoon panel rather than realistic.'),
 (1741, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Geography Humor, Quotes', 'Hawaii is a part of the United States that is an island, and is right here.', 'Dan Quayle, while in Hawaii', 'A humorous cartoon map of the United States with exaggerated features. The mainland states are drawn with simple, bold outlines, and Hawaii is depicted as a small, tropical island with palm trees and a tiny volcano, floating comically close to the mainland (for example, near the east coast) instead of its real location in the Pacific Ocean. A large red arrow points to the island labeled ''Hawaii'' with a speech bubble above it saying, ''Right here!'' The overall style is cheerful, colorful, and playful, with smiling cartoonish state shapes and sunny skies in the background. The scene is lighthearted and clearly meant to play on the common misconception about Hawaii''s distant location by humorously relocating it on the map.'),
 (2468, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Geography Humor, Quotes', 'Tip the world over on its side and everything loose will land in Los Angeles.', 'Frank Lloyd Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a simplified globe tilted dramatically on its side so that the western coast of the United States, especially Los Angeles, is facing downward. Various everyday objects—like loose change, keys, sunglasses, small toys, papers, and other miscellaneous items—are depicted falling off the tilted globe and piling directly onto a caricatured map or iconic skyline of Los Angeles below. The globe is exaggerated in size and colorful, with a surprised facial expression looking down at the falling items. Los Angeles is illustrated with easily recognizable landmarks such as palm trees, a Hollywood sign, and sunny weather. The overall mood is playful and lighthearted, with objects comically bouncing or stacking in the pile, emphasizing the idea that everything loose naturally ends up in LA. The style is bright, cartoony, and whimsical with bold outlines and cheerful colors.'),
 (584, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Good Question!, Pun', 'What do you get when you cross the ocean with the Titanic?   Halfway', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large ocean with a comically oversized ship labeled ''Titanic'' stuck in the middle of the ocean. Half of the ship is sinking or leaning to one side while the other half is still above water. Above the ship, a playful thought bubble shows a question mark and an image of the ocean crossed with the Titanic, emphasizing the pun. The ocean should look calm except around the ship where gentle waves splash. Include a bright, sunny sky with a few fluffy clouds for a lighthearted mood. The style should be colorful and exaggerated to enhance the joke’s absurdity, with the ship having a cartoonish, friendly face or expression to make the scene funny and non-threatening.'),
 (649, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Good Question!, Word Play', 'Why is it that night falls but day breaks?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, depict a whimsical night sky with a large cartoonish crescent moon playfully tumbling or ''falling'' down from the upper corner, complete with small stars looking surprised or dizzy around it. On the right side, show a bright morning scene with a huge smiling sun smashing through a cartoon-style glass window labeled ''Day,'' with shards humorously flying to represent ''breaking.'' Both scenes are colorful and exaggerated, with friendly faces on the moon and sun adding charm and humor. The background includes simple rolling hills and a few trees to unify the setting. Make sure the tone is light, fun, and cartoonish, meant to visually illustrate the pun on ''night falling'' and ''day breaking'' in a clever, non-literal way.'),
 (763, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Halloween, Word Play', 'How can you tell when ghosts are lying? You can see right through them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two friendly-looking ghosts in a simple, slightly spooky yet charming haunted house setting. One ghost is telling a story with animated gestures, eyes wide and expressive. The other ghost has a skeptical expression, looking closely at the first ghost as if trying to catch a lie. Between them, there’s a playful visual gag: the skeptical ghost’s eyes are positioned so you can literally see right through the storytelling ghost’s transparent body, emphasizing the punchline. The background includes classic ghostly elements such as floating candles, cobwebs, and a crescent moon visible through a window, but all drawn in a lighthearted, cartoon style without any darkness or frightening details. The ghosts are simple, cute, white, slightly translucent with rounded edges and friendly faces to keep the mood fun and family-appropriate.'),
 (1976, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Military Humor, Quotes', 'It is generally inadvisable to eject directly over the area you just bombed.', 'US Air Force Manual', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, old-fashioned military airplane flying high above a brightly colored, cartoonish target area on the ground that has just been bombed, with tiny explosions and smoke puffs visible on the ground. The pilot, a comically panicked character with wide eyes and a helmet slightly askew, is dramatically pulling the handle to eject. The ejection seat is being launched upward, but there is a clear visual warning with a big red arrow curving backwards from the bombed area to the seat, humorously indicating the danger of ejecting right where you just bombed. The background includes fluffy clouds and a bright blue sky, with no threatening elements, keeping it funny and light. The style is playful and exaggerated, similar to classic war cartoons or humorous aviation comics.'),
 (2446, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Music Humor, Quotes', 'There''s nothing remarkable about it. All one has to do is hit the right keys at the right time and the instrument plays itself.', 'Johann Sebastian Bach', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a grand piano on a simple stage. The piano has a pair of cartoonish, mischievous eyes and a big, cheeky smile on its front panel. The piano lid is open, and instead of a person sitting on the bench, a small pair of mechanical hands on robotic arms is pressing the piano keys automatically. Musical notes float merrily in the air around the piano, emphasizing that music is playing. The background is plain with a spotlight highlighting the piano to keep the focus on it. The overall tone is light, playful, and funny, emphasizing the idea that the piano ''plays itself'' by hitting the right keys at the right time without human intervention.'),
 (2719, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Political Humor, Unknown', 'Congress: the only circus in the world without a balancing act.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene set in a circus tent labeled ''Congress'' on a big banner above the entrance. Inside the tent, politicians dressed in bright, exaggerated circus outfits are running around frantically. There is no tightrope or balancing beam, but several clowns (representing politicians) are juggling papers, microphones, and briefcases haphazardly. One clown stands on a pedestal looking confused, holding a large, wobbly unicycle with no seat. The audience outside the tent watches in amusement and disbelief, with some people laughing and others scratching their heads. Include circus decorations like balloons, flags, and a popcorn stand nearby for a lively atmosphere. The overall tone is humorous, cartoonish, and playful, emphasizing the chaos and lack of balance in the political circus without any hint of conflict or violence.'),
 (2636, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Puns, Unknown', 'A magician was walking down the street, then he turned into a grocery store', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bewildered magician mid-trick on a sunny city sidewalk. The magician is dressed in a classic magician''s outfit including a tall top hat, a cape, a tuxedo with tails, and a magic wand in his hand. His expression is one of surprise as the lower half of his body is turning into a storefront with a glass door and a bright, colorful grocery store sign above it that reads ''Grocery Store.'' The door is slightly open, inviting customers in, and inside you can see shelves stocked with fruits, vegetables, bread, and cans. Around the street, casual pedestrians stroll by looking at the magician/store with expressions of amusement and confusion. The background shows a simple urban environment with a few trees and lampposts. The overall style is lighthearted, cartoonish, and playful, emphasizing the visual pun of the magician literally turning into a store rather than performing a magical transformation trick.'),
 (1664, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Quotes', 'Eh-buh-dee, Eh-buh-dee, Ehhh - Thhhhthat''s all, Folks!', 'Porky Pig', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic Warner Bros. style animated character resembling a cheerful, plump little bird standing on a theater stage. The bird is mid-song, holding a tiny microphone, with musical notes floating around it as it sings the phrase ''Eh-buh-dee, Eh-buh-dee, Ehhh - Thhhhthat''s all, Folks!'' The background should resemble an old-timey cartoon theater curtain, red velvet with golden tassels, partially open as if ending a show. Include a small spotlight shining on the bird, emphasizing the performance. The bird''s expression is playful and slightly exaggerated, lips pursed to mimic singing the drawn-out, slurred phrase. To the side or bottom corner, add a classic Looney Tunes style drawn oval frame with a little tail feather poking out to hint it''s a parody. The overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, capturing the whimsical vibe of nostalgic cartoon endings but with a silly, drawn-out sound joke twist.'),
 (2572, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'When women kiss it always reminds one of prize fighters shaking hands.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'A funny cartoon scene showing two women greeting each other with a playful air of competition: they are about to kiss on the cheek, but their faces are exaggeratedly intense and serious like boxers before a match. Their cheeks are puffed up slightly as if bracing for impact, eyebrows furrowed and eyes squinting in mock determination. They are standing in a simple setting like a park or street, with a small crowd of amused onlookers in the background, some with surprised or chuckling expressions. Above them, a boxing referee humorously waves a flag or holds up a ''Fight!'' sign, while the women''s clasped hands imitate the posture of fighters shaking hands before a boxing match. The overall style is cartoonish and lighthearted, emphasizing the humorous comparison without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2678, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Black holes are where God divided by zero.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a giant, friendly-looking cosmic figure labeled ''God'' floating in space next to a large, comical black hole. God is shown scratching his head with a puzzled expression while holding a giant dividing symbol (÷) and a zero. The black hole itself looks exaggeratedly cartoonish — a swirling dark vortex with a wide goofy mouth sucking in stars, planets, and numbers. Around the black hole, floating space objects like stars and a small cartoon planet with a surprised face enhance the cosmic setting. The background is a colorful starry night sky with a few distant galaxies. The overall style is lighthearted, whimsical, and clearly cartoonish without any threatening or serious cosmic drama.'),
 (3115, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Science Humor, Unknown', 'WILY''S LAW: n. The only known exception to Newton''s Law of Gravity, Wily''s Law states that an animal or person can suspend himself in midair provided (a) he is in a cartoon, and (b) he doesn''t look down and realize he is no longer on solid ground.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a classic slapstick moment: a character (could be a silly person or an animal like a cartoon dog or cat) is frozen in midair, arms flailing and eyes wide with surprise, caught just after stepping off the edge of a cliff. The cliff is rocky and jagged, with a clear empty space below. The character is looking straight ahead and not down, with a big question mark above their head. Nearby, a whimsical signpost reads ''WILY''S LAW'' with a small caption that says ''Exception to Newton''s Law of Gravity.'' The background is a bright blue sky with fluffy white clouds. The style should be playful, colorful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the impossibility of floating in midair while comic-style motion lines illustrate the suspended fall. No violence or distress, just funny and lighthearted cartoon physics at work.'),
 (4, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Technology Humor', 'When a computer has the desire to travel somewhere by itself, we''re going to be in trouble.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk with a desktop computer that has anthropomorphic features: a happy, determined expression on its screen with cartoon eyes and a small mouth. The computer has little arms and legs, is standing up, and holding a suitcase and a travel map, ready to leave. Around the computer are typical office items like a keyboard, mouse, papers, and a coffee mug. The person looks surprised and worried, leaning back slightly in their chair. The setting is a simple, colorful home office with a window showing a sunny day outside. The vibe is light-hearted and comedic, emphasizing the absurd idea of a computer wanting to travel by itself.'),
 (3132, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Transportation, Unknown', 'You cannot tell which way the train went by looking at the track.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a railroad track that suddenly ends in a puzzling way. The train tracks start off normally from the bottom left corner and extend towards the middle of the image, but then abruptly stop with no continuation or visible train. In the middle near the track’s end, a confused cartoon character (wearing a conductor’s hat and holding a pocket watch) is scratching their head, looking puzzled. Around the character, cartoon question marks float to emphasize confusion. The background is simple with green grass on both sides of the tracks and a sunny sky with fluffy clouds. Near the track’s end, small whimsical signs point in opposite directions labeled vaguely like “This way?” and “Or that way?” to capture the joke''s idea that the direction the train went can’t be told just by looking at the track. The overall style is bright, light-hearted, and playful, enhancing the joke’s irony and absurdity without any threatening or inappropriate elements.'),
 (2868, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Unknown, Word Play', 'For someone somewhere in America, today is the last day they will wake up with 10 fingers', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of diverse people across America waking up in bed. One person, in the foreground, is looking down at their hands in surprise or slight alarm; their hands are clearly visible with all ten fingers intact. In the background, a calendar on the wall shows today''s date highlighted. Around the scene, subtle visual hints suggest something strange might happen after waking up—like a mysterious shadow or a playful cloud shaped like a pair of scissors floating nearby, implying the joke''s punchline without any violence. The style is lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the surprise and humor of the concept.'),
 (2901, 'Absurd Humor, Cartoon, Unknown, Word Play', 'Half a wit is better than none.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a simple setting like a park bench. One character looks perfectly normal but has only half a brain visible inside their head (the other half is missing or cut away). The other character looks empty-headed with a completely transparent or blank head, symbolizing ''none'' of a wit. Both characters have friendly, exaggerated cartoon expressions: the half-wit character looks proud or content, while the no-wit character is confused or clueless. Above or between them, include a speech bubble or funny sign with the words "Half a wit is better than none." The overall tone should be lighthearted and silly, with bright colors and simple backgrounds, emphasizing the wordplay on ''wit'' and its literal depiction as brain halves or absence.'),
 (1372, 'Absurd Humor, Celebrity Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A celebrity is a person who is known for well-knownness.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a celebrity standing on a red carpet at a glamorous event. The celebrity is smiling confidently, surrounded by flashing cameras and reporters holding microphones. Above the celebrity, a large, comical thought bubble reads: "I am known for being well-known!" The crowd in the background is a mix of eager fans holding autograph books and photographers snapping pictures frantically. The setting includes bright lights, velvet ropes, and a backdrop with generic sponsor logos to emphasize the celebrity status. The style is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and playful details, such as paparazzi with oversized cameras and the celebrity wearing stylish but slightly exaggerated fashionable attire. The overall tone is silly and self-referential, highlighting the joke''s humor about fame and notoriety without referencing any real person.'),
 (2343, 'Absurd Humor, Chess Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'The mistakes are all waiting to be made.  (Said about a chess game''s opening position)', 'Chessmaster Savielly Grigorievitch Tartakower (1887-1956)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a chessboard set up at the very start of a chess game. The chess pieces—pawns, rooks, knights, bishops, queen, and king—should each have small, comical eyes and expressive faces, looking eager and slightly nervous. Surrounding the board, show a few ghostly, playful cartoon characters labeled "Mistakes" in a light, whimsical font. These ''Mistakes'' are hovering just above the chessboard or sitting on the edges, some scratching their heads or giggling, ready to jump in. The chess players are off to the side, watching the scene with mixed expressions of anticipation and slight worry. The background can be simple, such as a plain table and subtle indoor setting, to keep the focus on the chessboard and its lively pieces and ''Mistakes''. The artwork should have a light-hearted, clean cartoon style emphasizing personification and humor without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2562, 'Absurd Humor, Childhood Humor, Quotes', 'When I was born, I was so surprised I couldn''t talk for a year and a half.', 'Gracie Allen', 'A cartoon-style newborn baby lying in a cozy crib with a big surprised expression—wide eyes, raised eyebrows, and a small open mouth as if gasping. The baby wears a simple diaper and is surrounded by soft pastel-colored blankets and toys. Above the crib, a thought bubble shows a humorous scene of the baby trying to say something but only emitting jumbled symbols or squiggles representing gibberish. To add humor, a calendar or clock nearby emphasizes the passage of a year and a half, perhaps with pages flying off or a clock showing a long time span. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial features and a bright, cheerful nursery background.'),
 (1762, 'Absurd Humor, Classic Quotes, Detective Humor, Quotes', 'How often have I said to you that when you heve eliminated the impossible, whatever remains, _however improbable_, must be the truth?', 'Sherlock Holmes', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a detective in classic Sherlock Holmes style, wearing a deerstalker hat and holding a magnifying glass. The detective has a thought bubble containing a chaotic board filled with clues and crossed-out impossible options, leaving one extremely improbable but highlighted, glowing clue. The detective looks both puzzled and triumphant. Around him, exaggeratedly silly impossible scenarios are crossed out with big red X marks—for example, a flying pig, a talking clock, and a dancing shoe. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bold lines and bright colors to emphasize the absurdity of eliminating the impossible. The setting is an old-fashioned study with a large window, a cluttered desk full of papers, and a bookshelf, to give it a classic detective vibe without any dark or scary elements.'),
 (1988, 'Absurd Humor, Classic Quotes, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It is unbecoming for young men to utter maxims.', 'Aristotle (384-322 B.C.)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a young man standing awkwardly at a podium or on a stage, about to give a speech. He looks nervous and out of place, holding a scroll or paper with wise sayings or maxims written on it. Behind him is an older man or a wise elder, facepalming or shaking his head with a mildly disapproving but gentle expression. The setting suggests a formal or traditional place, such as a town hall or a school auditorium, with a banner or sign that reads ''Maxim Contest'' or ''Wisdom Conference.'' The young man is dressed casually and looks unsure, while the elder wears robes or formal attire, emphasizing the contrast between youth and wisdom. The overall style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humorous tension between youthful enthusiasm and the idea that young men should not utter maxims.'),
 (2102, 'Absurd Humor, Classic Quotes, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Men fear death as children fear to go in the dark; and as that natural fear in children is increased by tales, so is the other.', 'Francis Bacon', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of men of various ages standing nervously at the entrance to a dark, ominous cave labeled ''DEATH''. Their expressions show mild fear and hesitation, similar to children reluctant to enter a dark room. Nearby, a group of small children clutch each other tightly, equally scared, with wide eyes staring into a shadowy closet labeled ''THE DARK''. Behind both groups, shadowy figures or ghostly storytellers animatedly tell scary stories, causing exaggerated fearful reactions from the men and children. The setting is bright and cartoonish, with playful exaggeration in facial expressions to highlight the shared fear and the influence of scary tales. The background could include whimsical elements like a flickering lantern near the cave and a glowing nightlight near the closet to emphasize the darkness theme. Overall, the image should humorously parallel the fears of men about death with children''s fear of the dark, as amplified by stories, in a lighthearted, family-friendly style without any violence or distress.'),
 (2201, 'Absurd Humor, Classic Quotes, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Plato was a bore.', 'Friedrich Nietzsche (1844-1900)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in ancient Greece featuring a classical philosopher, styled as Plato. Plato is sitting on a simple stone bench under an olive tree in a sunny courtyard with white marble columns in the background. He has a long beard, traditional Greek toga, and is holding a scroll but looks very dull and sleepy, with half-closed eyes and a yawn. Nearby, a small crowd of bored listeners, including young students and fellow philosophers, are slumped over or covering their faces to avoid falling asleep. One student is dramatically pretending to snore with bubbles above his head. The mood is light and exaggeratedly boring in a playful way. The scene should have bright colors and clean lines, emphasizing the humorous contrast between the serious setting and the dull atmosphere. Include subtle classical Greek elements like amphora vases and laurel wreaths to set the period, but focus on the comedic expression of boredom to convey the joke visually.'),
 (2695, 'Absurd Humor, Cleaning Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown', 'CARPERPETUATION (kar'' pur pet u a shun) n. The act, when vacuuming, of running over a string or a piece of lint at least a dozen times, reaching over and picking it up, examining it, then putting it back down to give the vacuum one more chance.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person vacuuming a living room carpet. The character is mid-action: one hand is holding a vacuum cleaner while the other hand is reaching down to pick up a tiny string or piece of lint from the carpet. Nearby, on the floor, the string is clearly visible, slightly frayed or loose. The person has a curious and slightly puzzled expression, as if examining the lint with great interest. The vacuum cleaner is sleek and modern, with a clear hose or nozzle. Around the character, subtle motion lines or circles emphasize repeated vacuuming over the same spot. The background shows a simple cozy room setting with a couch, a small coffee table, and perhaps a potted plant to add warmth without distraction. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and clear focus on the vacuum, the tiny lint, and the person’s repeated inspection process, highlighting the silliness of obsessively vacuuming the same little piece multiple times.'),
 (633, 'Absurd Humor, Clothing Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'Why do men''s and women''s shirts button opposite ways?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two dress shirts—one labeled ''Men''s'' and the other labeled ''Women''s''—hanging side by side on a clothing rack. The men''s shirt has buttons on the right side with neatly aligned buttonholes on the left, while the women''s shirt has buttons on the left side with buttonholes on the right, exaggerated for clarity. Around the shirts, include amusing little details like confused, anthropomorphized buttons and buttonholes looking puzzled at each other, as if wondering why they face opposite ways. The background should be simple, maybe a closet or a clothing store, with a playful sign overhead saying ''Button Mystery.'' The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with big eyes and expressive faces on the buttons and buttonholes to enhance the humor. No people should be in the scene, just the shirts and the interactive buttons.'),
 (2712, 'Absurd Humor, Clothing Humor, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'Clothes make the man.  Naked people have little or no influence on society.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side. One character is fully dressed in formal, stylish business attire—suit, tie, glasses, and polished shoes—looking confident and influential, with a briefcase or a newspaper in hand. The other character stands next to him completely naked but depicted in a lighthearted, comically modest way using censor bars or strategically placed objects like a large leaf or a newspaper to cover private areas. This naked character looks awkward, shy, or confused, with a speech bubble implying no influence or social presence. The background is a simple city street or office setting with subtle details like a building entrance, a bench, or street signs to hint at a societal environment. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated in a classic cartoon style to maximize humor and contrast between the two characters.'),
 (1775, 'Absurd Humor, Comedy, Psychology Humor, Quotes', 'I am a kind of paranoiac in reverse. I suspect people of plotting to make me happy.', 'J.D. Salinger', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, quirky character who looks wide-eyed and slightly suspicious but in a playful way. The character should be smiling nervously, glancing around as if expecting others to secretly arrange something nice for them. Surround the character with other people whispering and conspiring with joyful expressions, holding small gifts like balloons, a cake, or a party hat behind their backs. The setting is a casual outdoor park or living room, bright and colorful, with festive decorations subtly hinting a surprise party. The art style should be lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the ironic twist that this paranoiac''s suspicion is about happiness rather than harm or mischief—conveying a warm, funny mood without fear or threat.'),
 (1505, 'Absurd Humor, Comedy, Quotes, Word Play', 'Alex, I''ll take ''Things Only I Know'' for $200.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set in a classic TV game show studio. The main focus is on a quirky, confident contestant named Alex standing at a podium labeled ''Alex.'' Alex is smiling mischievously, looking proud and slightly smug. Across from Alex is the smiling, middle-aged male host holding a microphone and reading from a large game show card that says, ''Things Only I Know - $200.'' The host looks amused and slightly puzzled. The background shows a bright scoreboard with categories displayed, studio lights overhead, and an enthusiastic but small audience clapping and laughing. Include typical game show elements like buzzers on the podium and flashy decorations to create a lively atmosphere. The tone is light and playful, emphasizing the ironic humor that Alex is claiming his own knowledge as a *category* on the quiz show.'),
 (2849, 'Absurd Humor, Comedy, Unknown', 'Explaining a joke is like dissecting a frog. You understand it better but the frog dies.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person holding a frog that looks slightly alarmed. The person is wearing casual clothes and has one hand gently holding the frog, while the other hand is holding a large magnifying glass over the frog, as if ''analyzing'' it carefully. Nearby, there is a dissecting tray with cartoon-styled frog parts scattered, with tiny labels and a pencil lying on the tray, creating a lighthearted scientific setting. The background is simple, like a classroom or home study area, with a whiteboard behind showing a simple stick-figure joke drawing being explained with arrows and text. The overall style is playful with exaggerated expressions emphasizing both curiosity and the frog''s sadness. No violence or gore, just cartoonish frog parts and a humorous vibe of a joke being ''taken apart'' literally.'),
 (1157, 'Absurd Humor, Comic Humor, Courtroom Humor, Insults', 'Allow me to fast-forward to my final rebuttal: ''PTHBBPBT!''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon courtroom scene. In the center is a casually dressed speaker at the podium labeled ''Final Rebuttal.'' The speaker is making a silly, exaggerated sound with their lips, illustrated as a comic-style ''PTHBBPBT!'' speech bubble. The judge, looking confused and slightly amused, is sitting behind a bench with a gavel and paperwork. In the background, two lawyers on either side appear taken aback or bewildered by the unexpected sound. Include typical courtroom items like the judge''s bench, flags, and seating for spectators. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the absurdity of responding to a serious legal debate with a silly lip-blowing noise.'),
 (2242, 'Absurd Humor, Comic Humor, Inspirational, Quotes', 'Some of the world''s greatest feats were accomplished by people not smart enough to know they were impossible.', 'Doug Larson', 'A cartoon scene showing a determined, slightly goofy-looking inventor or adventurer who is confidently tackling an obviously ridiculous or impossible task. For example, the character could be trying to push a huge, oversized boulder uphill or building a quirky flying machine with mismatched parts like wheels, wings, and balloons. The character''s exaggerated facial expression is focused and cheerful, oblivious to the absurdity of their task. In the background, you can include spectators with puzzled or amazed expressions watching this over-the-top effort. The style should be bright and colorful with simple, bold lines and a playful, humorous tone, emphasizing the contrast between the task''s impossibility and the character''s innocent determination.'),
 (1643, 'Absurd Humor, Comic Humor, Quotes', 'Don''t let it end like this. Tell them I said something.', 'last words of Pancho Villa (1877-1923)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person dramatically collapsing or fainting onto a couch or the floor, looking exhausted or overwhelmed. Another character nearby looks confused or worried, as if unsure what to do. A speech bubble from the fainting person says, "Don''t let it end like this. Tell them I said something." The setting is a cozy living room with a lamp, a small table with a cup, and maybe a TV or bookshelf in the background. The exaggerated, cartoon-style expressions emphasize the comedic desperation of the fainting person trying to make their last words count before ''ending.'' No violence or distress, just a funny, exaggerated moment of someone trying to leave a lasting impression at a dramatic moment.'),
 (2509, 'Absurd Humor, Comic Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'We all agree that your theory is crazy, but is it crazy enough?', 'Niels Bohr (1885-1962)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon-style scene set in a cozy, informal meeting room with a round table. Around the table are four characters with exaggerated, quirky facial expressions showing a mix of skepticism, surprise, and amusement. One character, clearly the ''theorist,'' looks a little proud and a bit defensive, holding a large, complicated-looking blueprint or diagram labeled ''Crazy Theory.'' Another character leans forward, raising an eyebrow and gesturing toward the blueprint with a finger, as if questioning the idea. The other characters exchange glances that suggest they find the theory wild but are debating if it''s wild enough. Include small details like a coffee mug, some scattered papers, and a whiteboard in the background with half-erased scribbles and math symbols. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and playful expressions emphasizing the humor in the intellectual debate about craziness.'),
 (3221, 'Absurd Humor, Comic Humor, Steven Wright, Visual Humor', 'What happens if you get scared half to death twice?', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cartoon character experiencing two separate scary moments. The first panel shows the character wide-eyed and frightened, hair standing on end, nearly fading out with a transparent look to symbolize ''half to death.'' The second panel shows the same character, again startled in the same exaggerated way, but this time the character appears completely ghostly or as a cartoon skeleton, suggesting they''ve gone ''all the way.'' The background is simple, with exaggerated motion lines, sweat drops, and cartoonish expressions of terror. Between the two panels or above them, include a large question mark or the joke text: ''What happens if you get scared half to death twice?'' The overall style is bright, colorful, and playful with bold outlines to emphasize the comic exaggeration of fear and its consequences.'),
 (2138, 'Absurd Humor, Computer Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'Never trust a computer you can''t lift.', 'Stan Masor', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person struggling to lift a giant, bulky, old-fashioned desktop computer with a huge CRT monitor and a bulky tower. The person, looking puzzled and frustrated, is attempting to hoist the computer into the air with both hands but failing because of its obvious weight. The computer should look heavy and cumbersome with wires dangling and maybe a small puff of dust or cobwebs to emphasize its size and weight. The background is a simple home office or tech room setting with a desk, a chair, and some tech gadgets or posters on the wall. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the absurdity of trying to lift a computer to gain trust in it. The cartoon character''s expression is comedic, not angry or upset, with slightly exaggerated features for fun.'),
 (1366, 'Absurd Humor, Computer Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'A bad random number generator:  1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 4.33e+67, 1, 1, 1', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a computer desk with a large, old-fashioned monitor displaying a random number generator on the screen. The random numbers shown are: 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 4.33e+67, 1, 1, 1. Next to the monitor, a small robot or quirky computer character looks confused or frustrated, scratching its head or with a question mark above it. Around the desk, there are scattered papers with numbers and formulas, emphasizing the randomness theme. The background is a simple office or workspace setting with a coffee mug labeled “#1 Randomizer.” The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor of a malfunctioning or “bad” random number generator that almost always outputs the number 1 except for one absurdly large outlier. No violence or offensive elements.'),
 (2751, 'Absurd Humor, Computer Humor, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Death is a nonmaskable interrupt.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a computer’s internal circuitry, with colorful chips, wires, and a classic CPU chip prominently in the center. Above the CPU, illustrate a small, friendly-looking anthropomorphic figure wearing a skull mask and holding a sign that says ''Death'' declaring itself as a ''Nonmaskable Interrupt.'' The CPU looks surprised or worried, with wide eyes and sweat drops to suggest it cannot ignore this ''interrupt.'' Include computer components like circuit boards, memory chips, and blinking LEDs around, in bright, playful colors. The overall style should be lighthearted and silly, resembling a comic strip panel combining computer hardware and personified death in a fun, geeky way.'),
 (2350, 'Absurd Humor, Computers Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'The most likely way for the world to be destroyed, most experts agree, is by accident. That''s where we come in; we''re computer professionals. We cause accidents.', 'Nathaniel Borenstein', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered, slightly chaotic office filled with computers and tech gadgets. In the center, a group of computer professionals wearing casual attire (glasses, hoodies, T-shirts) are gathered around a large computer that is sparking or smoking lightly, looking both worried and clueless. One person is nervously pressing random keys on a keyboard while another nervously bites their nails. The office has posters on the wall humorously related to technology like ''Keep Calm and Reboot'' and a calendar showing a doomsday date circled. In the background, a globe or Earth image is displayed on a monitor, with a cartoon-style alarm light flashing. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the idea that these professionals jokingly admit they cause accidents, potentially leading to big problems. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish to enhance the comedic effect without threatening or alarming.'),
 (2662, 'Absurd Humor, Computers Humor, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'AUTOMAGICALLY: Automatically, but in a way which, for some reason (typically because it is too complicated, or too ugly, or perhaps even too trivial), the speaker doesn''t feel like explaining. Example: ''Temporary files are automagically deleted when you logoff.''', 'The Hacker''s Dictionary', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused office worker sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer screen showing a pop-up that says ''Temporary files are automagically deleted when you logoff.'' The worker has a puzzled expression and a small thought bubble with a tangled mess of wires, gears, and question marks symbolizing complexity and confusion. The background shows a typical office environment with filing cabinets labeled ''Important Files'' and ''Mystery Files.'' Make the text style playful and the colors bright to emphasize the lighthearted confusion over the word ''automagically.'' The scene should feel whimsical and slightly exaggerated, highlighting the absurdity of a technical process happening ''by magic'' without explanation.'),
 (2824, 'Absurd Humor, Computers, Math Humor, Unknown', 'Enter any 12-digit prime number to continue.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a computer screen with a simple dialog box that says, ''Enter any 12-digit prime number to continue.'' In front of the screen sits a puzzled cartoon character with exaggerated confused facial expression, scratching their head while staring at the keyboard. Around the character, math books, papers with prime numbers and question marks floating in the air emphasize the difficulty of the task. The setting is a bright and colorful home office or study room. The style is playful and light-hearted to highlight the absurdity of expecting someone to easily provide such a complex number on the spot.'),
 (2714, 'Absurd Humor, Computers, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'Compatible:  Gracefully accepts erroneous data from any source.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a computer or a robot sitting peacefully at a desk, surrounded by floating data streams represented as colorful, chaotic chunks of information—some obviously wrong or nonsensical, like random numbers, misspelled words, and funny icons. The computer has a cheerful, calm face on its screen with a smile indicating it happily accepts all this jumbled, wrong data without complaint. In the background, other struggling computers or frustrated humans try to make sense of the same data, looking confused and annoyed. The setting is a bright, friendly office or workspace with lighthearted, exaggerated expressions emphasizing the robot’s calm acceptance versus everyone else’s stress. The overall vibe is light, playful, and techy with a focus on the concept of being ''compatible'' with any data, no matter how wrong or messy it is.'),
 (2898, 'Absurd Humor, Cooking Humor, Food Humor, Unknown', 'Guaranteed breakfast in five minutes or you don''t eat. (The Hunger-Back Guarantee)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon kitchen scene showing a grumpy breakfast chef inside a small diner or home kitchen. The chef is wearing a tall white chef''s hat and apron, arms crossed with a stern, slightly impatient expression. Behind him is a stove with a frying pan sizzling eggs and bacon. On the wall behind the chef is a comical sign reading: ''The Hunger-Back Guarantee: Guaranteed breakfast in five minutes or you don''t eat!'' There is a small, hungry-looking customer sitting at a counter with a plate in front of them, looking confused or amused by the sign. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated in cartoon style with silly facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s absurdity.'),
 (2726, 'Absurd Humor, Country Humor, Music Humor, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: Hell Stays Open All Night Long', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a lively country bar at night. The bar is rustic with wooden walls, a few hay bales for seats, and cowboy hats hanging on pegs. Near the center, a cheerful country singer with a big hat and boots is holding a microphone, mid-performance, singing a sign that reads: ''Hell Stays Open All Night Long.'' Around him, a small crowd of amused cowboys and cowgirls laugh and tap their feet. On the wall behind the singer, several other country and western song title signs hang alongside this one, but the featured sign is prominently displayed on a glowing neon board. Include details like a jukebox in the corner and a guitar leaning against a barrel to enhance the country vibe. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright, warm colors to emphasize the humorous and absurd nature of the song title.'),
 (2519, 'Absurd Humor, Courtroom Humor, Law Humor, Quotes', 'We have a criminal jury system which is superior to any in the world; and its efficiency is only marred by the difficulty of finding twelve men every day who don''t know anything and can''t read.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous courtroom scene drawn in a lighthearted cartoon style showing a jury box with twelve seats. Each jury seat is occupied by a comically clueless-looking man. Some are scratching their heads, others are peeking at books upside down or with confused expressions, and a few have literally blank thought bubbles over their heads. The judge, depicted with an exaggerated expression of mild frustration but also amusement, is pointing toward the jury. A courtroom clerk holds a long list labeled ''Juror Qualifications.'' The background includes typical courtroom details like a raised judge''s bench, American flags, and a witness stand. The overall tone is playful and whimsical, emphasizing the absurdity of the joke without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (3131, 'Absurd Humor, Creative Humor, Motivational Humor, Unknown', 'You cannot achieve the impossible without attempting the absurd.', NULL, 'A bright, colorful cartoon scene featuring a determined, cartoonish character wearing a thinking cap and holding a blueprint labeled ''Impossible Project.'' The character stands at the base of a ridiculously absurd contraption: it looks like a mix of a flying machine made from kitchen utensils, rubber ducks, balloons, and a catapult. Above the character is a large thought bubble showing a comic depiction of achieving a wildly improbable goal, like walking on clouds or pulling stars from the sky. The background shows whimsical elements like floating question marks and light bulbs to emphasize creative thought. The overall tone is playful and imaginative, with exaggerated expressions of determination and silliness on the character''s face. The style is reminiscent of a lighthearted editorial cartoon in bright, friendly colors with clear, simple lines to emphasize humor and whimsy without any negativity.'),
 (1990, 'Absurd Humor, Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It may be that our role on this planet is not to worship God, but to create him.', 'Arthur C. Clarke', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, whimsical artist''s studio. In the center, a quirky, cheerful human character is sculpting a large, half-finished stone statue of a traditional deity figure (e.g., a haloed figure or a figure with rays of light). The artist wears a smock splattered with paint and has a concentrated but amused expression. Around the studio are whimsical creative tools like chisels, a hammer, paintbrushes, and sketches pinned on the walls showing different godly figures. There is also a small playful mythical creature (like a smiling imp or sprite) peeking from behind, watching the creation. The background includes a window showing a sunny blue sky with birds flying, emphasizing the earthly setting. The overall tone is lighthearted and imaginative, illustrating the idea of humans actively making or ''creating'' a god rather than worshiping passively.'),
 (2449, 'Absurd Humor, Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'They who dream by day are cognizant of many things which escape those who dream only by night.', 'Edgar Allen Poe', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters side by side. On the left, a person is shown lounging comfortably in a chair, eyes half-closed, with whimsical thought bubbles extending above their head depicting imaginative and surreal daytime dreams: floating clouds shaped like clocks, playful animals wearing hats, flying books, and vibrant colors. On the right, a sleepy person is curled up in bed at night with their eyes closed, surrounded by dark blues and purples representing nighttime. Around their head are dream bubbles, but these are more abstract or fuzzy shapes, suggesting less vivid or less aware dreaming. The setting should show a clear contrast between day and night in the background (sun and bright sky on the left, moon and stars on the right). The overall tone is light-hearted and whimsical rather than serious, with playful character expressions emphasizing the difference in awareness between daydreaming and sleep dreaming.'),
 (2381, 'Absurd Humor, Creativity Humor, Humor, Quotes', 'The secret to creativity is knowing how to hide your sources.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky inventor or artist sitting at a cluttered desk flooded with papers, books, and sketches. The character has a mischievous smile and is glancing over their shoulder nervously while hastily stuffing rolled-up blueprints, art references, or books into a large drawer labeled ''Secret Sources.'' The workspace should look chaotic but colorful, with creative tools like paintbrushes, pencils, lightbulbs hanging overhead, and quirky inventions or art pieces scattered around. In the background, a bulletin board displays pinned famous book covers, scientific papers, or art prints partially hidden behind sticky notes. The overall tone of the image is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the idea of cleverly concealing the origins of one’s creative work without any negative connotation or illicit behavior. The style should be a bold, bright, cartoon with exaggerated expressions and details to enhance the humor and absurdity of ‘hiding your sources.’'),
 (2473, 'Absurd Humor, Creativity Humor, Inventors, Quotes', 'To invent, you need a good imagination and a pile of junk.', 'Thomas Edison', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a cheerful inventor in a messy workshop filled with quirky piles of assorted junk. The inventor, wearing big round glasses and a lab coat, stands proudly with one hand on their hip and the other holding a lightbulb symbolizing an idea. Around them are heaps of random, mismatched objects: old gears, wires, broken clocks, empty cans, discarded gadgets, springs, and other unidentifiable parts. The background should show cluttered shelves with various tools and a blueprint pinned on the wall titled ''My Next Big Invention.'' The inventor’s expression is enthusiastic and imaginative, capturing the playful spirit of creativity emerging from chaos. Include a sign or a thought bubble near the inventor that reinforces the idea: ''To invent, you need a good imagination and a pile of junk.'' The style should be lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated cartoonish features to emphasize humor and fun invention energy.'),
 (1612, 'Absurd Humor, Criticism, Quotes', 'Critics are like eunuchs in a harem; they know how it''s done, they''ve seen it done every day, but they''re unable to do it themselves.', 'Brendan Behan', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a grand, colorful harem setting with soft cushions, lanterns, and flowing curtains. In the middle, a group of critics are dressed in typical modern attire, holding clipboards and pens, looking frustrated and puzzled. Nearby, a single eunuch character stands apart, wearing traditional historical clothing with a bemused expression, clearly unable to participate. Around them, vibrant dancers and entertainers perform gracefully, showing the skill the critics can only observe but not replicate. The background should be lighthearted and exaggerated with playful expressions highlighting the critics'' helplessness. Make sure the overall tone is funny and whimsical, avoiding any harsh or inappropriate elements, with exaggerated, cartoonish faces and gestures that emphasize the contrast between knowing how something is done and being unable to do it oneself.'),
 (1914, 'Absurd Humor, Cultural Humor, Economic Humor, Quotes', 'If you think the United States has stood still, who built the largest shopping center in the world?', 'Richard M. Nixon', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a very large, bustling shopping center labeled ''Largest Shopping Center in the World'' with an American flag waving above it. In front of the mall stands a cheerful, cartoonish builder character wearing a hard hat emblazoned with a small US flag. He holds blueprints labelled ''Biggest Mall'' and gestures proudly toward the building. Around the mall, various shoppers carry shopping bags, and exaggeratedly large store signs like ''Mega Mall,'' ''Superstores,'' and ''Food Court Galore'' appear. The background includes an old-fashioned statue or monument that looks like it hasn''t changed much to contrast the lively, vibrant mall, visually emphasizing that while the country may seem ''still,'' it built this massive shopping center. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, drawn in a bright, colorful cartoon style with clean, simple lines emphasizing the size and modernity of the shopping center compared to the static monument.'),
 (2096, 'Absurd Humor, Cultural Humor, Food Humor, Quotes', 'Mayonnaise: One of the sauces which serve the French in place of a state religion.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a quaint French café or bistro. In the foreground, a bottle of mayonnaise is anthropomorphized with a small French beret, a tiny mustache, and holding a little French flag. The mayonnaise bottle is standing atop a pedestal like a saint or religious icon. Surrounding it are various French foods, like a baguette, a croissant, and a plate of fries, all looking reverently up at the mayonnaise bottle. In the background, faint outlines of famous French symbols like the Eiffel Tower and a church or cathedral spire can be shown, subtly blending the ideas of French culture, cuisine, and religion. The sky is bright and cheerful with a few humorous angelic mayonnaise drops floating like halos. The overall tone is light-hearted and whimsical, emphasizing the joke that mayonnaise acts as a ''state religion'' for the French, in a respectful and playful way.'),
 (800, 'Absurd Humor, Cultural Humor, Hipsters, Puns', 'How many hipsters does it take to change a light bulb? the number is really obscure and you probably haven''t heard of it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of quirky hipsters attempting to change a light bulb. The setting is a cozy, trendy living room with vintage furniture and eclectic decorations like vinyl records, succulents, and string lights. One hipster stands on a chair holding a light bulb box labeled with a strange, made-up obscure number (like ''Edition #7.43''). Another hipster, sporting thick glasses, a beanie, and a scarf, looks confused and slightly pretentious, glancing sideways as if questioning the obscurity of the number. Other hipsters are casually seated on a couch, sipping craft coffee and nodding knowingly but with vague expressions. The light fixture overhead is clearly in need of a bulb change. The overall style is colorful and exaggeratedly comedic with emphasis on hipster stereotypes but in a friendly and lighthearted way. Include speech bubbles containing the punchline: "The number is really obscure and you probably haven''t heard of it." The mood is playful and whimsical, with a focus on irony and social commentary delivered through visual cues.'),
 (1923, 'Absurd Humor, Cultural Humor, Language, Quotes', 'I''ll moider da bum.  (Said when asked what he thought of William Shakespeare)', 'Heavyweight boxer Tony Galento', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing outside a simple English Tudor-style theater resembling the Globe Theatre. One character is a rough-looking person with a thick accent, wearing a flat cap and casual street clothes reminiscent of East London, angrily saying the line, "I''ll moider da bum." The other character is holding a rolled-up parchment labeled ''Shakespeare,'' looking confused and slightly shocked. Around them, playful details such as a quill, ink pot, and feathered hat lie on the ground. The theater backdrop has a sign with ''Shakespeare Play Tonight'' on it. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the accent and the humor of the misunderstanding of Shakespeare''s significance in a comedic way. No violent or graphic elements are included.'),
 (2611, 'Absurd Humor, Cultural Humor, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'You know the world is going crazy when the best rappers is a white guy, the best golfer is a black guy, and the tallest guy in the NBA is Chinese.', 'Chris Rock', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring three characters exaggerated to highlight the joke''s irony. On the left, a white man dressed as a rapper with typical hip-hop style clothing: oversized hoodie, sunglasses, a big gold chain, and a microphone in hand, confidently rapping. In the middle, a black man in golf attire holding a golf club and wearing a visor, standing posed as if about to swing on a simple green putting area with a flagstick. On the right, a very tall Chinese man in a basketball jersey with a basketball under one arm, standing noticeably taller than the other two characters. The background is a simple urban park with a few trees and a basketball hoop behind the tall man, and a golf hole nearby. All three characters have friendly, humorous facial expressions, making the cartoon feel fun and playful, without any negative or offensive tone. The style should be colorful, bright, and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing height difference and stereotypical attire lightly and respectfully.'),
 (2752, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Family, Unknown', 'Death is hereditary.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a family portrait hanging on a wall. The portrait features three generations: a great-grandparent skeleton with a bow tie, a grandparent skeleton holding a family photo album, and a child skeleton playing with a toy skull. Each skeleton is smiling in a playful, friendly way. Around the portrait, subtle ghostly images of ancestors float softly, implying a chain of inheritance. The room is cozy, decorated with framed certificates labeled ''Hereditary Death Club,'' and a calendar marked with humorous skull icons on certain dates. The overall tone is lighthearted, with bright colors, exaggerated cartoon features, and a gentle spooky vibe emphasizing the joke that death passes down genetically. No scary elements, just fun skeleton characters lounging casually as if discussing their ''family trait.'''),
 (2290, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'The bomb will never go off. I speak as an expert in explosives.', 'Admiral William Leahy, US Atomic Bomb Project.', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person dressed as a bomb technician or explosives expert standing confidently next to a large, old-fashioned cartoon bomb with a lit fuse that is visibly short and about to explode. The expert has a calm, slightly smug expression and is holding a clipboard or manual labeled ''Explosives Expert Guide.'' The bomb itself looks like a classic round black bomb with a burning wick. Around the scene, there are small comedic details like a clock showing time running out and a few puzzled or nervous bystanders in the background reacting with exaggerated worry or surprise. The setting is simple and clear, possibly a flat surface or a small open area with no danger implied, just the tension of expectation that the bomb will not explode despite appearances. The style is bright, cheerful, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions for comedic effect, emphasizing the irony of the expert’s confident statement against the obvious ticking bomb.'),
 (2847, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Life, Unknown', 'Exercise daily. Eat wisely. Die anyway.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing on a treadmill looking tired and slightly frustrated. Nearby, a table holds a balanced meal with fruits, vegetables, and a water bottle. Above the scene, a thought bubble shows a simple, smiling skull wearing a party hat, symbolizing death attending the ''party'' anyway. The background is light and colorful, with motivational posters that say ''Exercise Daily'' and ''Eat Wisely'' on the walls. The overall tone is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the irony that despite all efforts, death comes for everyone.'),
 (1499, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'After I''m dead I''d rather have people ask why I have no monument than why I have one.', 'Cato the Elder (234-149 BC, AKA Marcus Porcius Cato)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a peaceful cemetery scene with two graves side by side. On one grave, there is an extravagant, overly large, and gaudy monument with too many decorations like statues, gold lettering, and flowers, making it look absurdly showy. Nearby, a group of curious cartoon characters (wearing casual clothes) stand around this grand monument looking puzzled and whispering. On the second grave, there is just a simple, small headstone that is plain and unobtrusive; close to it, another group of cartoon characters looks relaxed and thoughtful, some with raised eyebrows but smiling gently, indicating a preference for simplicity. The sky is bright, and the overall style should be light-hearted and colorful, emphasizing the contrast between ostentation and modesty in a funny and respectful way. Include some small details like birds or trees to set the cemetery atmosphere without making it gloomy.'),
 (1654, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Dying is a very dull, dreary affair. And my advice to you is to have nothing whatever to do with it.', 'W. Somerset Maugham', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a gloomy, monochrome setting with a worried-looking skeleton dressed in a dull, gray suit reclining on a plain old-fashioned armchair. The skeleton is holding a cup of tea with one bony hand and looking bored and uninterested. Around the skeleton, softly faded ghostly figures drift lazily and yawning, emphasizing the dullness of the situation. A calendar on the wall shows many crossed-out days, underscoring the long passage of time. In the background, a simple sign reads ''Death Lounge'' to suggest a waiting room for the afterlife. The overall mood is comically bland and lethargic rather than scary or sad, with muted colors and minimal decoration. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the joke’s dry humor about the dullness of dying and the advice to avoid it.'),
 (2009, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It''s not that I''m afraid to die; I just don''t want to be there when it happens.', 'Woody Allen', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a nervous cartoon character nervously peeking around a corner, with wide eyes and a worried expression. The setting is a simple room with a door slightly ajar through which a ghostly, transparent figure or symbol representing Death (such as a classic Grim Reaper with a friendly, non-threatening look) is visible. The character is clearly trying to avoid being seen or present where ''Death'' is. Include a clock on the wall indicating time passing, and perhaps a calendar with the date circled to add a subtle hint of impending event. The overall tone should be lighthearted and comical, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor in the character’s contradictory wish to avoid being present for death.'),
 (2124, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'My philosophy of life is that the meek shall inherit nothing but debasement, frustration, and ignoble deaths . . .', 'Harlan Ellison', 'A humorous cartoon depicting a meek-looking character, slouched and timid, standing in an empty, barren landscape symbolizing ''inheriting nothing.'' Around them are exaggerated, comical symbols of debasement and frustration: a spilled cup of coffee, a broken clock, and a wilting flower. In the background, shadowy, pompous figures dressed in fine clothes stand confidently atop a small hill labeled ''Wealth and Power.'' The meek character’s facial expression conveys a mix of resignation and bewilderment. The sky is overcast with cartoonish storm clouds, subtly emphasizing the bleak outlook. The overall art style is light and playful, with exaggerated features and bright colors to keep the scene humorous and non-threatening.'),
 (2433, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'There is nothing quite so good as burial at sea. It is simple, tidy, and not very incriminating.', 'Alfred Hitchcock', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a calm, sunny ocean setting with a small boat on the water. On the boat, there is a cheerful but slightly mischievous-looking character wearing casual seaside clothing and a captain''s hat, gently dropping a simple coffin overboard into the sea. Around the boat, a few fish swim by, looking curious but unfazed. The coffin is plain and neatly closed, emphasizing tidiness. In the background, there are a few fluffy clouds and a seagull flying above, adding to the peaceful maritime vibe. The scene conveys a lighthearted and clean approach to the concept of burial at sea, with no dark or morbid tones, just simple humor and an innocent nautical setting.'),
 (1516, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Quotes', 'Although prepared for martyrdom, I preferred that it be postponed.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a calm, slightly nervous person dressed in simple historical or medieval clothing, standing with arms crossed and a polite, slightly worried smile. They are facing a group of serious, traditional executioners or stern officials holding tools like axes or scrolls labeled ''Martyrdom Decree.'' The person is subtly gesturing towards a large calendar or clock showing the current date, implying a request to delay. The background is minimal, maybe a stone wall or a government building to set the historical tone, but kept light and cartoonish. The style is exaggerated and friendly, with expressive faces highlighting the polite but firm wish to postpone martyrdom rather than confrontation or violence. No graphic elements, just comedic tension in the expressions and body language.'),
 (1854, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Quotes', 'I wouldn''t mind dying -- it''s the business of having to stay dead that scares the shit out of me.', 'R. Geis', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky skeleton sitting in an easy chair, wearing reading glasses and holding a newspaper. The skeleton looks slightly worried or contemplative. Around it are everyday objects like a cozy lamp, a small side table with a cup of coffee, and a calendar on the wall showing the date. Above the skeleton''s head is a thought bubble with the words: "I wouldn’t mind dying - it’s the business of having to stay dead that scares me." The background is simple, bright, and cheerful to contrast the morbid subject, and the overall tone is lighthearted and funny rather than dark or scary.'),
 (2487, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Quotes', 'Tragedy is when I cut my finger. Comedy is when you fall into an open sewer and die.', 'Mel Brooks', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels. On the left panel, a character lightly cuts their finger while holding a knife in a kitchen, looking mildly annoyed but harmlessly so, with a small red drop of blood. The background is a typical cozy kitchen with a cutting board, vegetables, and a sink. On the right panel, another character humorously and exaggeratedly falls headfirst into an open sewer grate on a city sidewalk. The sewer grate is comically open and large, with bubbling green sewer water inside. The falling character has wide eyes and flailing arms, expression exaggerated for comic effect but not graphic, while passersby look shocked or bewildered. Both panels have bright, simple colors and clean lines, emphasizing the contrast between a minor injury (tragedy) and a much bigger mishap (comedy) in an ironic style. The overall tone is light-hearted and cartoonish, avoiding any graphic or violent imagery.'),
 (2576, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Quotes', 'When you have to kill a man, it costs nothing to be polite.', 'Sir Winston Churchill (1874-1965)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple, nondescript office or waiting room. In the foreground, a smiling, polite-looking character in a suit is extending a handshake or tipping a hat with a big friendly grin, demonstrating politeness. Across from them stands another cartoon character looking surprised or confused. Nearby, a sign on the wall reads, ''When you have to kill a man, it costs nothing to be polite.'' The atmosphere is lighthearted and absurd, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the irony of being courteous in a dark situation. Include typical office objects like a water cooler, a clock, and a potted plant to keep the setting casual and relatable. The overall tone is a funny contrast between extreme seriousness and polite friendliness, shown clearly in exaggerated cartoon style with bright colors and clean lines.'),
 (1520, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Always go to other people''s funerals, otherwise they won''t come to yours.', 'Yogi Berra', 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a cheerful, colorful cemetery on a sunny day with a few fluffy clouds. Several cartoon characters are standing next to a simple gravestone labeled ''Here Lies Bob.'' One character, dressed as a party-goer with casual clothes and a friendly smile, waves down a path where an amusingly dressed ghost with a party hat floats nearby, looking both surprised and hopeful. Around the scene are lively flowers and a few benches. The ghost appears to be the spirit of someone who didn''t get visitors at their funeral. A sign near the path humorously reads ''Funeral Attendance Club Meeting Today.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the ironic, silly idea of going to others'' funerals to ensure they come to yours, without any sadness or gloom.'),
 (2687, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Unknown', 'But if your parachute doesn''t open - don''t worry - you have the rest of your life to figure it out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a skydiver mid-fall from a plane. The skydiver is wearing typical skydiving gear including a helmet and jumpsuit, with an obviously unopened parachute pack on their back. Their facial expression is a mix of surprise and worry, but with a comical twist like a raised eyebrow or a quirky smile. The background features blue sky with fluffy clouds, and a small airplane flying away in the distance. A funny caption or thought bubble floats beside the skydiver that reads: "But if your parachute doesn''t open - don''t worry - you have the rest of your life to figure it out." The style is a bright, colorful cartoon with exaggerated features to emphasize humor, no violence or distress, making it clearly lighthearted and funny.'),
 (2750, 'Absurd Humor, Dark Humor, Unknown', 'Death is a necessary thing. If nobody died, where would you park?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a crowded parking lot filled with rows of cars. The lot is completely full, and people are standing around looking frustrated, scratching their heads or checking their watches. In the foreground, a cheerful grim reaper character (a skeleton in a black hooded cloak) stands next to a large empty parking space, holding a giant cartoon scythe casually over one shoulder. The grim reaper smiles gently, as if saying, ''This spot is why I’m needed!'' Around the scene, include a few lighthearted details: a parking meter, some cars with exaggerated expressions of impatience (like a car with eyes and a frown), and a sign that says ''No Vacancy.'' The overall tone is playful and whimsical, emphasizing the joke that death clears space for parking. The color palette should be bright and friendly, with a clean cartoon style and exaggerated facial expressions to boost the humor and accessibility of the image.'),
 (1926, 'Absurd Humor, Drinking Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'I''m a simple man. All I want is enough sleep for two normal men, enough whiskey for three, and enough women for four.', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, slightly disheveled middle-aged man standing in a cozy living room. He wears casual clothes—an untucked shirt and jeans—and has a relaxed, satisfied expression. Surrounding him are three distinct elements: a large bed with two people sleeping soundly side-by-side (symbolizing ''enough sleep for two normal men''), a bar cart or small table stacked with three full whiskey glasses and a bottle prominently labeled ''Whiskey'' (representing ''enough whiskey for three''), and in the background, four smiling women casually chatting or engaging with the man in a friendly manner (depicting ''enough women for four''). The style is cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, emphasizing the humorous and lighthearted tone without implying anything inappropriate. The overall vibe is that of an easygoing man enjoying simple yet exaggerated desires.'),
 (3222, 'Absurd Humor, Driving Humor, Everyday Life, Humor, Life, Relatable, Steven Wright', 'When everything is coming your way, you''re in the wrong lane.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a two-lane road with a confused driver in a small car stuck in the left lane. Ahead of the car, all the traffic is coming straight at the driver in that lane (cars, trucks, bicycles, and pedestrians), clearly moving toward the driver from the front. The right lane is completely empty, with a clear path forward. The driver has a surprised and worried expression, with wide eyes and raised eyebrows, gripping the steering wheel tightly. Above the scene is a cartoon-like thought bubble or sign that says, ''When everything is coming your way, you''re in the wrong lane.'' The background is a simple sunny day with a few clouds, and there are road signs indicating the lanes. The style is colorful and exaggerated to emphasize the humor without any danger or violence.'),
 (3129, 'Absurd Humor, Driving Humor, Exaggeration, Unknown', 'You can get ANYWHERE in ten minutes if you drive fast enough.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a car speeding along a road. The car is drawn in a comically exaggerated style, with motion lines and dust clouds behind it to clearly indicate very high speed. The driver, visible through the window, looks panicked or overly determined, gripping the steering wheel tightly. Around the car, road signs show locations with distances that humorously contradict the joke—such as a sign reading ''City Center: 50 miles''. A large clock in the sky or by the roadside shows a 10-minute countdown timer. The sky is bright and cheerful to keep the tone light and funny. Overall, the scene captures the absurdity of the claim that driving fast alone can get you anywhere in just ten minutes, with exaggerated speed effects and visual irony between the long distances and short time.'),
 (1838, 'Absurd Humor, Dry Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'I think it would be a good idea.  (Said when asked what he thought of Western civilization)', 'Mahatma Ghandi (1869-1948)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene where a person is standing confidently with a thoughtful expression, perhaps stroking their chin, as if sharing a serious opinion. The setting is minimal but hints at Western civilization—include simple iconic elements subtly in the background like a classical column, a small pyramid-like structure, and maybe a modern city skyline silhouette. The speech bubble above the character should read: ''I think it would be a good idea.'' The character’s demeanor should be earnest but deadpan, creating a comedic contrast with the abstract and vague statement about a huge concept like Western civilization. The overall tone should be lighthearted and ironic, using simple lines and soft colors to emphasize the dry humor.'),
 (1531, 'Absurd Humor, Economics Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Among economists, the real world is often a special case.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom labeled ''Economics 101.'' There is a quirky, slightly disheveled professor standing at the front, pointing to a large chalkboard filled with complex economic graphs and formulas. The professor has a playful smirk, conveying a dry sense of humor. In front of the professor, a group of students sits at desks with confused and skeptical facial expressions, scratching their heads or raising eyebrows. Behind the professor, a window shows a chaotic, exaggeratedly messy outside world featuring random funny elements like a cow wearing a business hat, a person juggling dollar bills, and a clock spinning wildly. A small cartoon label above the professor says, ''In economics, the real world is often a special case.'' The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the ironic contrast between theoretical models and unpredictable reality. No violence or sensitive content is included.'),
 (1962, 'Absurd Humor, Economics Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Isn''t it strange? The same people who laugh at gypsy fortune tellers take economists seriously.', 'Cincinnati Enquirer', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a colorful, stereotypical gypsy fortune teller with a headscarf, large hoop earrings, and flowing clothes, peering mysteriously into a glowing crystal ball on a small round table cluttered with tarot cards and candles. This character is making a silly face, causing a couple of people in the background to laugh heartily. On the right, a serious-looking economist wearing a suit and glasses, holding a thick book titled ''Economics''. He stands confidently on a podium with a graph chart behind him, showing complicated economic data with an upward and downward trend. The audience listening to him appears puzzled, skeptical, or doubtful, some scratching their heads. The background can be a simple stage setting separating the two scenes. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, capturing the irony that people laugh at the fortune teller but take the economist seriously. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish with expressive faces and clear visual contrast between whimsy and seriousness.'),
 (2248, 'Absurd Humor, Education Humor, Exaggeration, Quotes', 'Sometimes a scream is better than a thesis.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson (1803-1882)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stressed-out college student sitting at a cluttered desk piled high with thick textbooks, papers, and a laptop. The student has wild hair, glasses slipping down their nose, and a frazzled expression. Instead of furiously typing or writing a thesis, the student is mid-scream with mouth wide open, hands clenched into fists on the desk, and eyes squeezed shut. Around the student, thought bubbles show a complicated thesis outline crossed out, while a large comic-style ''Aaaaah!'' bubble emphasizes the scream. The background can include motivational posters ironically stating ''Keep Calm and Write On'' and a clock showing late night. The overall tone is exaggerated and playful, capturing the humor of preferring a loud scream over the daunting task of writing a thesis. The drawing style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish with emphasis on the student’s exaggerated facial expression and chaotic study environment.'),
 (1556, 'Absurd Humor, Education Humor, Literary Humor, Quotes', 'Anyone who has passed through a classical education and not been made a fool by it has had a very narrow escape.', 'Hazlitt', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a medieval-style classroom with a stern-looking classical teacher wearing a toga and laurel wreath pointing at a large ancient scroll filled with Latin text. Several students sit on wooden benches looking bewildered and slightly silly – one scratching their head with scattered papers around, another with crossed eyes trying to read the scroll, and a third with a humorously oversized book labeled "Classical Education." In the background, a dumbfounded student narrowly dodges a large cartoonish trapdoor labeled "Fool’s Pitfall." The setting includes columns and old bookshelves filled with scrolls and ancient texts to evoke a classical education vibe. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the idea that classical education can confuse or ''fool'' students in a funny way.'),
 (1510, 'Absurd Humor, Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'All knowledge is of itself of some value. There is nothing so minute or inconsiderable, that I would not rather know it than not.', 'Samuel, Dr. Johnson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky professor in a cluttered study filled with odd and tiny objects representing various knowledge. The professor, looking enthusiastic and slightly eccentric with round glasses and wild hair, holds a magnifying glass in one hand examining a tiny insect or a small, seemingly insignificant item on his desk. The desk is covered with books, scrolls, a globe, a microscope, and small jars labeled with humorous tags like ''Invisible Dust'', ''Micro-thoughts'', and ''Atomic Ideas''. Around the professor, whimsical floating light bulbs and question marks add to the atmosphere of curiosity and learning. The room has shelves stuffed with eclectic knowledge items from a feather to a cosmic model, indicating that no detail is too small to explore. The style is bright, cartoonish, and playful, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing a joyful obsession with learning all sorts of knowledge, however trivial it may seem.'),
 (2100, 'Absurd Humor, Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Men are born ignorant, not stupid; they are make stupid by education.', 'Bertrand Russell', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classroom where several men sit at desks looking confused and silly. The teacher, perhaps a caricature with glasses and a pointer, stands at the blackboard with the phrase ''Ignorance is born, stupidity is taught'' written. The men have exaggerated, goofy expressions, some scratching their heads or staring blankly at their books. Learning materials like books, pencils, and papers are scattered around, highlighting formal education. The setting is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and cartoonish features to emphasize the joke without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (1720, 'Absurd Humor, Education Humor, Quotes', 'Go, my students, burn your books, buy yourselves stout shoes. Get away to the mountains, the deserts and the deepest recesses of the earth. In this way, and no other, will you gain a true knowledge of things and of their properties.', 'Peter Severinus, 1571 A.D.', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking, eccentric teacher or guru standing on a small elevated rock or podium. The teacher is wearing flowing robes and round glasses, with an exaggerated serious expression, gesturing dramatically with one arm raised. Surrounding the teacher are a group of funny-looking, bewildered students holding books with surprised or confused faces. Some students are tossing their books into a small, comical bonfire made of colorful books nearby. The setting is outdoors, with a backdrop of a rugged mountain range, sand dunes (representing deserts), and a large cave entrance to symbolize the ''deepest recesses of the earth.'' One student is lacing up oversized, exaggeratedly stout hiking boots, adding humor. The overall style is bright, playful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity of burning books to gain knowledge by exploring nature instead. Include subtle smiling sun and birds flying in the clear sky to keep the tone light and friendly.'),
 (1906, 'Absurd Humor, Education Humor, Quotes', 'If you have both feet planted on level ground, then the university has failed you.', 'Robert F. Goheen', 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors on a grassy, perfectly flat field under a bright blue sky. In the center stands a quirky university graduate wearing a cap and gown, looking surprised and slightly confused. Both their feet are firmly and evenly planted flat on the level ground. Nearby, a skeptical professor with glasses and a pointer in hand editorially observes the graduate, looking a bit disappointed as if the student missed the point. Around them, typical university symbols like a diploma scroll floating mid-air, a podium with a crest, and a campus building silhouette in the background add context. The mood is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke about the graduate''s overly stable and unadventurous footing, implying lack of imagination or risk-taking.'),
 (2034, 'Absurd Humor, Education Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'Learning is what most adults will do for a living in the 21st century.', 'Perelman', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of adults at a workplace that resembles a school classroom mixed with an office. Several adults of varying ages sit at desks with computers, books, and notepads, looking both confused and focused as they learn. One adult raises their hand with a puzzled expression, while another takes notes frantically. In the background, a teacher or trainer, smiling and holding a pointer, stands next to a large whiteboard with charts and diagrams labeled ''21st Century Skills.'' The room has posters on the walls with motivational slogans like ''Never Stop Learning!'' and ''Adult Education Rocks!'' The overall vibe is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing adults engaged in continuous learning as if it''s their main job, with a playful mix of school and office elements. The style is colorful and exaggerated cartoon, with friendly faces and an inviting atmosphere.'),
 (1960, 'Absurd Humor, Engineering, Inventors, Quotes', 'Inventor:  A person who makes an ingenious arrangement of wheels, levers and springs, and believes it civilization.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky inventor''s workshop filled with a chaotic but clever contraption. The contraption is a large, whimsical machine composed of various oversized wheels, levers, and springs all interconnected in a complicated and somewhat tangled design. The inventor, a slightly eccentric character wearing round goggles, a lab coat with rolled-up sleeves, and messy hair, proudly stands next to the machine with a confident, proud grin, gesturing towards it as if presenting a great achievement. The background shows scattered blueprints, tools like wrenches and screwdrivers lying around, and mechanical parts strewn across a wooden workbench. The overall art style is colorful, playful, and exaggerated with cartoonish proportions to emphasize the humor and inventiveness of the scene, but with no hint of danger or negativity.'),
 (3066, 'Absurd Humor, Engineering, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'If a system doesn''t have to be reliable, it can do anything else.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered tech workshop or engineering lab. At the center is a quirky, cartoonish robot or machine with many random gadgets, screens, and blinking lights attached chaotically. The robot looks wild and unpredictable, with arms and tools pointing in different directions, some sparking or bubbling with colorful smoke, suggesting it’s doing all sorts of crazy things. Nearby, a relaxed engineer or technician leans back in a chair with a big grin, holding a coffee cup labeled ''Not reliable, just fun!''. On the wall behind them hangs a whiteboard with a simple, funny flowchart titled ''System Requirements'' showing two paths: one labeled ''Reliable = Boring'' crossed out, and the other labeled ''Not Reliable = Can Do Anything'' circled with excitement. Around the room, add humorous details like a calendar with all dates crossed out, a wrench taped to a computer mouse, and posters saying ''Embrace Chaos'' and ''Innovation over Stability'' to emphasize the joke''s meaning. The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, using bright colors and expressive characters to highlight the irony about system reliability and creativity.'),
 (2623, 'Absurd Humor, Environmental Humor, Family, Quotes', 'Your grandchildren will likely find it incredible -- or even sinful -- that you  burned up a gallon of gasoline to fetch a pack of cigarettes!', 'Paul, Dr., Jr. MacCready', 'A humorous cartoon scene set outside a suburban house. In the foreground, an elderly person stands looking puzzled, holding a small pack of cigarettes. Behind them, a somewhat outdated car is parked with its door open and an empty gallon gas can on the ground nearby. A thought bubble above the elderly person shows a confused or shocked face, reflecting the incredulity about using so much gasoline just to get cigarettes. In the background, a group of smiling grandchildren (kids of varied ages) look on skeptically or with wide eyes, clearly amazed or judging the situation. The setting includes a driveway, a small lawn with flowers, and a clear sky to keep the tone light and cheerful. The cartoon style should be colorful and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the contrast between the small pack of cigarettes and the large gasoline used for the trip, highlighting the absurdity in a playful way.'),
 (636, 'Absurd Humor, Environmental Humor, Food Humor, Good Question!', 'Why do so many foods come packaged in plastic? It''s quite uncanny.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a bright kitchen or grocery aisle. Show a bewildered character, perhaps a cheerful shopper or a puzzled chef, standing in front of a store shelf overflowing with various foods all packaged excessively in clear plastic wrap. Include items like fruits (bananas, apples), vegetables, sandwiches, and snacks, all wrapped in exaggeratedly large or absurd amounts of plastic. The character should be scratching their head with a confused expression, maybe holding a tiny plastic-wrapped banana in one hand and a magnifying glass in the other, as if inspecting the overpackaging. The background has a sign reading ''Plastics Department'' to emphasize the irony. The overall tone is light and comical without any negativity, and the style is bright, colorful with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the silliness of packaging so many foods in plastic unnecessarily.'),
 (2435, 'Absurd Humor, Environmental Humor, Geography Humor, Quotes', 'There is nothing wrong with Southern California that a rise in the ocean level wouldn''t cure.', 'Ross MacDonald', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a coastal cityscape labeled ''Southern California.'' The city is shown with a mix of palm trees, sunny beaches, and recognizable landmarks like a pier and modern buildings. The ocean is humorously rising like a giant wave creeping toward the city, with the water halfway up some buildings and covering some streets. People on the beach are either running away in exaggerated panic or relaxing as if nothing unusual is happening, some wearing sunglasses and holding drinks. Seagulls fly overhead, some looking confused by the rising water. The sky is bright and sunny with a few fluffy clouds, reinforcing the typical SoCal vibe. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions highlighting the absurdity of the ocean supposedly ''curing'' the region by flooding it.'),
 (5, 'Absurd Humor, Environmental Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'What philosophical question will replace ''If a tree falls in the forest...'' when all the forests have been cut down?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a completely barren landscape where a dense, lush forest once stood. In the foreground, a thoughtful-looking philosopher character with a beard and glasses, wearing a classic philosopher''s robe, strokes his chin while looking at a single, small tree stump. Above his head is a whimsical thought bubble with a question mark and a fading old tree falling sound effect. The background shows dull tree stumps, some with tiny sad faces, and distant hills with no trees at all. Near the philosopher, a sign reads ''Welcome to the Forest of the Future.'' The overall mood is lighthearted and ironic, emphasizing the missing forest while humorously pondering philosophy in a world without trees. The style should be simple, colorful, and exaggerated with clean lines typical of a cartoon strip, emphasizing expression and the irony of the scenario without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2161, 'Absurd Humor, Environmental Humor, Quotes', 'Nothing is wrong with California that a rise in the ocean level wouldn''t cure.', 'Ross MacDonald (1915-1983)', 'A humorous cartoon scene of California as a large, exaggeratedly happy state-shaped island with iconic California landmarks like the Golden Gate Bridge, palm trees, and a Hollywood sign visible. Rising ocean waters, shown as playful blue waves with smiling faces, gently lap against the coast. A few cartoonish fish and sea creatures peek out of the water, adding an amusing touch. Above, a bright sun shines down with a slightly mischievous grin. The scene should feel light-hearted and funny, with the ocean''s rise personified in a friendly, non-threatening way, hinting at the subtle irony of the joke.'),
 (2883, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Fishing Humor, Unknown', 'Give a man a fish and he will eat for a day. Teach him how to fish, and he will sit in a boat and drink beer all day.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a small, comically simple fishing boat floating on a calm lake. In the boat sits a cheerful man wearing a fishing hat, sunglasses, and casual clothes. He is relaxed, leaning back with his feet up on the edge of the boat, holding a fishing rod in one hand but not actively fishing. In his other hand, he has a frosty beer can or bottle, clearly enjoying himself. The boat has a small cooler labeled ''Beer'' with the lid open, revealing more drinks inside. Nearby on the water''s surface is a single, plain fish swimming by, as if ignored. The background shows a bright, sunny day with a few fluffy clouds and some reeds on the shore to set the peaceful fishing vibe. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the man''s carefree and lazy mood, subtly poking fun at the idea of teaching someone to fish leading to more leisure than productive effort.'),
 (1196, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Food Humor, Insults', 'May your spoon always slip and sink all the way into your bowl of hot soup', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bowl of steaming hot soup on a table. A spoon is comically slipping and sinking deep into the soup, nearly disappearing, with exaggerated motion lines around it to show the slipping action. The soup looks inviting but is animated with a playful, almost mischievous expression, possibly with eyes or a smile on the surface to personify it. Around the bowl, a cheerful character with a surprised or exaggeratedly frustrated face is reaching for the spoon, trying to catch it before it sinks too far. The background is simple, kitchen-themed with a checkered tablecloth and a steam wisp rising from the bowl to emphasize the hot temperature. The overall style is bright, colorful, and lighthearted, capturing the relatable annoyance of losing a spoon in hot soup in a fun way without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (2394, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Food Humor, Quotes', 'The trouble with jogging is that the ice falls out of your glass.', 'Martin Mull', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person dressed in typical jogging gear—running shoes, shorts, a headband, and a sweatband—mid-stride on a scenic jogging path. The jogger is holding a fancy cocktail glass filled with ice cubes and a colorful drink. Several ice cubes are magically flying out of the glass, dropping to the ground behind the jogger as if the motion of jogging is causing the ice to fall out. The jogger has a slightly confused or annoyed expression, looking at the emptying glass. In the background, include a bright sunny day with a few whimsical trees and a park bench. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with cartoonish bold lines and bright colors, emphasizing the silliness of carrying a drink that loses ice while jogging. The scene should feel cheerful and playful, capturing the absurdity of the punchline without implying any danger or messiness.'),
 (2803, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Food Humor, Unknown', 'Don''t try to out-weird me - I get stranger things than you free with my breakfast cereal.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a cozy kitchen breakfast table. At the center is a quirky-looking person with a playful smirk, holding a spoon and sitting before a large bowl of cereal. Floating whimsically above the cereal bowl are several odd, surreal items appearing as if they just popped out of the cereal: a tiny purple alien wearing sunglasses, a miniature dancing robot, and a tiny circus elephant balancing on a colorful cereal ring. The kitchen around them is brightly lit, with boxes of cereal stacked on the counter labeled with exaggerated phrases like ''Strangest Things Inside!'' A family pet (cat or dog) nearby looks on baffled or amused. The overall style is colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and playful details to highlight the absurdity of getting bizarre things ''free with breakfast cereal.'' The atmosphere is lighthearted and fun, with no references to anything inappropriate or sensitive.'),
 (2237, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Funny Advice, Quotes', 'Slovotsky''s Law Number Thirty-One: Get scared right away; avoid the rush.', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a nervous person depicted in a comedic exaggerated manner – wide eyes, sweating, maybe hunched slightly in fear. The character is standing at the entrance of a door labeled ''Danger Ahead'' or ''Caution,'' and there is a long crowd behind them, depicted as impatient or pushing forward. The person is quickly recoiling or stepping back in surprise, avoiding the crowd''s rush to get scared first. In the background, a sign or floating text says ''Slovotsky''s Law Number Thirty-One: Get scared right away; avoid the rush.'' The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors, simple lines, and exaggerated expressions showing panic mixed with humor. Include subtle visual cues like zigzag lines around the scared person to indicate fear and motion lines behind to show the crowd pushing forward.'),
 (756, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Good Question!, Humor, Pun, Puns, Steven Wright', 'How do you tell when you''re out of invisible ink?', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cluttered home office or desk area. On the desk, there is a bottle labeled ''Invisible Ink'' that is completely empty. A puzzled person, drawn in a simple cartoon style with exaggerated facial expression showing confusion, is holding a blank sheet of paper up in front of them, scrutinizing it closely. The paper looks entirely blank from the viewer’s perspective. Nearby on the desk, several writing tools like regular pens, pencils, and a notebook are scattered around. In the background, a small poster or calendar on the wall humorously hints at ''Invisible Ink Week'' with a faintly drawn invisible figure, visible only by an outline or by objects seemingly floating. The overall color palette is light and bright, emphasizing a comical and light-hearted mood. Cartoon speech bubble from the character reads: “How do you tell you’re out of invisible ink?” The scene captures the irony of trying to see something that is invisible, making the joke visually clear and humorous without any violence, politics, or adult themes.'),
 (656, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Good Question!, Pun', 'Why should you never brush your teeth with your left hand?  Your toothbrush works much better.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person with a puzzled expression standing in front of a bathroom mirror. The person is holding a toothbrush awkwardly with their left hand, and the toothbrush is clearly not working well: it looks bent or confused with cartoon-style motion lines showing it struggling to brush teeth. Meanwhile, the person''s right hand, shown from behind the mirror reflection, holds another toothbrush that is sparkling clean and working perfectly with exaggerated shine and happy facial expression on the toothbrush (like eyes and a smile). The bathroom has a simple, bright background with a sink, a mirror, and typical items like toothpaste and a cup. The overall style is playful and exaggerated, with cartoonish expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke about using the wrong hand for brushing teeth.'),
 (2568, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes', 'When something goes wrong, just yell ''Plot twist!'' and move on.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in the middle of a chaotic situation at home or work. Around them, various things have obviously gone wrong: a spilled coffee cup on a laptop, papers flying in the air, maybe a broken lamp or a tipped-over chair to indicate disorder. The person is mid-shout, with their mouth wide open and one hand cupped near their mouth as if yelling. A speech bubble above them reads: ''Plot twist!'' Their facial expression is a mix of surprise and exaggerated acceptance, showing they''re choosing to move on rather than stress out. The background is simple but conveys a bit of chaos with scattered objects, tilted picture frames, and a clock slightly askew on the wall. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated features to amplify the humor.'),
 (2771, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Humor, Unknown', 'Do it today, Tomorrow it will be illegal.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a casually dressed person standing with a calendar in one hand, looking slightly stressed but determined. The calendar page is flipped to ''Today'' with a big red circle around it. In the background, there is a large, exaggerated official-looking sign that reads ''Starting Tomorrow: Procrastination is Illegal!'' The setting is a typical home office or bedroom with a desk cluttered with unfinished tasks like papers, a coffee mug, and a laptop. The character is nervously holding a pen, about to start working. The overall style is light and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the pressure of doing tasks today before the ''law'' changes tomorrow. Bright colors and playful details like a clock showing late afternoon and a small motivational poster on the wall add to the humor of forced urgency.'),
 (1183, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Insults', 'May all your troubles last as long as your New Year''s Resolutions.', 'Joey Adams', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tired, frustrated person standing by a large calendar displaying January 1st at the top, with a big bold headline that says ''New Year''s Resolutions.'' The person is surrounded by a chaotic mess of crumpled resolution lists and half-finished plans scattered around. Nearby, a mischievous clock with eyes and a smirk is speeding rapidly through the calendar pages, flipping them fast from January 1st to mid-January, while a little calendar monster labeled ''Troubles'' is lurking nearby, looking happy and stretching out like it plans to stay a long time. The background is bright and colorful to keep the mood light and funny, with exaggerated expressions on the character and the clock to emphasize the fleeting nature of resolutions versus the lingering troubles. The overall tone is playful and cartoonish without any negativity or hostility.'),
 (1178, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Insults, Irony', 'It is impossible to make anything foolproof because fools are so ingenius.', 'Edsel Murphy', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a simple workshop or kitchen setting. One character is confidently showing a product or gadget labeled ''Foolproof Device'' to another character who looks skeptical or amused. The ''Foolproof Device'' should look overly complicated with buttons, levers, or warning signs, implying it''s supposed to be easy to use but clearly isn''t. Around the characters, include scattered tools or utensils in disarray, emphasizing attempts at making something foolproof. The expression on the skeptical character''s face should convey disbelief or mild amusement, while the confident character looks proud but a bit puzzled. The background should be light and simple to keep focus on the interaction. Include a small chalkboard or note with the phrase ''Impossible because fools are so ingenious'' written humorously to reinforce the punchline. The style should be colorful, bright, and exaggerated with cartoonish proportions for comedic effect, keeping the tone light and funny without any negativity.'),
 (1199, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Insults, Parking Humor', 'Stupidity does not qualify as a handicap, park elsewhere.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a parking lot with a clear signpost prominently displaying the phrase: ''Stupidity does not qualify as a handicap, park elsewhere.'' The main focus is on a comically confused character trying to park a small, quirky-looking car in a handicapped spot. This character looks a little clueless, scratching their head with exaggerated puzzled expression. Nearby, a very obviously handicapped cartoon character in a wheelchair watches with a raised eyebrow and a smirk. The background has a few other parking spots with ordinary cars and a sunny, cheerful day ambiance. The style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions for humor and clarity. The environment should be simple and uncluttered, emphasizing the parking spots, signs, and characters involved in the joke.'),
 (1208, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'You aren''t the dumbest person in the world, but you better hope he doesn''t die', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a simple, colorful outdoor setting like a park or a bench scene. One character looks slightly confused or worried, with exaggerated cartoonish features suggesting innocence or cluelessness. Nearby, another character is clearly portrayed as very dim-witted, with a goofy expression, crossed eyes, a drooling mouth, and perhaps a dunce cap or a very silly hat to emphasize their lack of smarts. The worried character is nervously glancing at the goofy character, who is happily oblivious to everything. In the background, a small newspaper stand or poster can be seen with a headline hinting that the ''dumbest person in the world'' is alive. The style should be lighthearted, with rounded shapes and bright pastel colors, focusing on the comedic relationship between the two characters without any threats or negative vibes.'),
 (1241, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Knock Knock', 'KK/WT: Boo? Don''t cry, it''s only a joke', NULL, 'Draw a simple cartoon scene featuring two characters: one character is playfully shouting ''Boo!'' trying to scare the other. The second character looks more surprised than scared, with a half-smile or amused expression while wiping away a small, exaggerated cartoon tear. The background is minimal to keep focus on the characters. Make it lighthearted and humorous with bright, cheerful colors. Include a speech bubble from the second character saying, ''Don''t cry, it''s only a joke.'' The overall style is a clean, friendly cartoon style suitable for all ages, emphasizing playful teasing rather than genuine fear or sadness.'),
 (2194, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Life, Quotes', 'People find life entirely too time-consuming.', 'Stanislaw J. Lec', 'A humorous cartoon showing a person overwhelmed by a huge, exaggerated clock that is shaped like a giant, complex machine with lots of gears and spinning hands. The person is standing in the center looking frazzled and holding a calendar and a wristwatch, both showing different times. Around them, everyday life objects like a coffee cup, a laptop, and papers are spinning or flying around in chaotic motion to emphasize how busy and time-consuming life feels. The background is simple, with bright colors, to keep the focus on the character and the massive, overcomplicated clock-machine. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the person’s face to show confusion and mild frustration without any negativity.'),
 (3202, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Life, Steven Wright', 'Hard work pays off in the future; laziness pays off now.', 'Steven Wright', 'Draw a humorous cartoon split into two halves. On the left side, depict a person dressed in work clothes, wearing a hard hat and holding a hammer or tool, sweating as they build or laboriously stack bricks to build a house or structure labeled ''Future Success.'' The background should look bright but a bit distant and foggy, showing the effort will pay off later. On the right side, draw a relaxed person lying in a hammock tied between two palm trees, wearing sunglasses, sipping a cold drink with an umbrella in it, smiling contentedly and surrounded by snacks or leisure items. This side should look sunny, immediate, and carefree, labeled ''Laziness Pays Off Now.'' Above the scene, include a witty banner or text box with the joke: ''Hard work pays off in the future; laziness pays off now.'' Keep the style light, cheerful, and exaggerated for comedic effect to clearly contrast the hard work and relaxing attitudes.'),
 (2123, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, List Humor, Quotes', 'My loathings are simple: stupidity, oppression, crime, cruelty, soft music.', 'Vladimir Nabokov', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing with a confident, slightly annoyed expression, holding a list titled ''My Loathings'' written on a large piece of paper. The list clearly reads: stupidity, oppression, crime, cruelty, and soft music. Surrounding the person are visual representations of the first four loathings: a clueless-looking character with question marks over their head for stupidity; a stern figure symbolizing oppression; a thief sneaking away with a bag marked with a dollar sign for crime; and a mean-looking figure with crossed arms for cruelty. Nearby, a small, cute, innocuous speaker emits soft music notes that visually annoy the person, illustrated by cartoonish frustration marks (e.g., squiggly lines) around their head. The style should be colorful and exaggerated, with clear facial expressions that highlight annoyance and disdain in a lighthearted, non-threatening way. The background is simple with a neutral color so the focus remains on the characters and the list. The overall mood is playful and witty, capturing the contrast between serious societal problems and the trivial annoyance of soft music.'),
 (2764, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Mail Humor, Unknown', 'Didja ever notice:  Junk mail arrives the same day it was sent, sometimes the day before.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cluttered mailbox overflowing with colorful envelopes marked ''JUNK MAIL.'' Nearby, a cheerful mail carrier is handing an envelope to a puzzled homeowner. The envelopes have little clocks and calendar icons floating above them, with one envelope humorously stamped with a date in the future, while others have the current date and some even a ''sent today'' sign. The homeowner, standing by the mailbox with a confused and bemused expression, holds one envelope labeled ''Sent Tomorrow?'' exaggerating the idea of junk mail arriving before it was even sent. The background is a sunny suburban street with a simple house, mailbox post, and a small dog looking curious. The style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity and irony of junk mail delivery times without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (1609, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Money Humor, Quotes', 'Consequences, shmonsequences, as long as I''m rich.', 'Daffy Duck', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a carefree, wealthy-looking character sitting on a large, overflowing pile of gold coins and cash. The character wears flashy sunglasses, a big smile, and relaxed posture, with one arm casually thrown over a golden treasure chest. Surrounding the character are various objects symbolizing ''consequences'' ignored humorously: a broken calendar with torn pages flying away, bills and warning signs like ''Warning: Consequences Ahead!'' floating like balloons, and a small, harmless-looking cloud labeled ''Consequences'' drifting far off in the background without touching the character. The background is bright and cheerful, emphasizing the character''s carefree attitude with exaggerated, cartoonish expressions. Objects like a luxury car, a cocktail with a little umbrella, and a beach ball emphasize a lavish, worry-free lifestyle. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated features to emphasize humor and silly defiance toward consequences.'),
 (2146, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Motivational Humor, Quotes', 'No one ever gets far unless he accomplishes the impossible at least once a day.', 'Elbert Hubbard', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, cheerful office environment. In the center, a cheerful character (could be a cartoon human or a funny animal like a determined squirrel) stands proudly on a small podium labeled ''Impossible Achievements''. The character holds a giant, shiny gold trophy labeled ''Daily Impossible''. Around them, colleagues or friends wear amazed and impressed expressions, holding clipboards or coffee mugs. In the background, a whiteboard displays a comically exaggerated to-do list titled ''Things to Accomplish Today'' with impossible tasks like ''Juggle flamingos'', ''Find a unicorn'', or ''Make time stand still''. The overall mood should be lighthearted and motivational, emphasizing the irony and humor of doing the ''impossible'' daily, with playful cartoon exaggeration, bright colors, and whimsical expressions. Objects include office desks, computer screens, papers, and motivational posters with funny slogans like ''Keep Trying the Impossible!'' and a calendar showing every day checked off with a star.'),
 (2109, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Office Humor, Quotes', 'Miscellaneous is always the largest category.', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a giant filing cabinet with an overflowing drawer labeled ''Miscellaneous.'' Various quirky, random items spill out—like a sock, a rubber duck, a tiny potted plant, a half-eaten sandwich, a quirky gadget, and a stray shoe. A confused office worker, looking puzzled and overwhelmed, stands next to the drawer with a clipboard, scratching their head. The background is a typical office setting with desks, computers, and papers scattered around, emphasizing everyday chaos. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and comically cluttered details to highlight the joke about how ''Miscellaneous'' becomes the largest category due to miscellaneous randomness.'),
 (2280, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The basic fact about human existence is not that it is a tragedy, but that it is a bore. It is not so much a war as an endless standing in line.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'A humorous cartoon depicts a long, winding queue of diverse, exaggeratedly bored cartoon humans stretching endlessly into the distance. Each character displays classic signs of boredom: yawning, checking watches, slouching, daydreaming, or doodling on their shoes. The setting is an ordinary urban street with a subtle clock tower to emphasize the passage of time. Near the front of the line is a small sign that reads ''Life''s Waiting Line.'' The sky is a dull, monotonous grey to highlight the mood of monotony rather than excitement. A couple of characters hold small protest signs humorously reading ‘Not a War, Just a Queue’ and ‘Tragedy? Nah, Just Bored.’ The style is bright and cartoonish with playful exaggerations, focusing on facial expressions and body language to convey the joke visually without any violent or political elements.'),
 (2584, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Why torture yourself when life will do it for you?', 'Laura Walker', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk, looking overwhelmed and stressed out, with exaggerated sweat drops and frazzled hair. Their surroundings depict everyday life causing them trouble: a spilled coffee cup, a ringing phone, a messy pile of papers, a broken clock showing a late hour, and a calendar with many red circles indicating deadlines. Next to the person, a smaller cartoon version of the same person is holding a small whip labeled ''Self-Torture,'' looking unsure or hesitant. The contrast emphasizes that life itself, represented by chaotic everyday objects, is already ''torturing'' the person more than their own self-imposed pressure. The overall tone is light-hearted and funny, using expressive faces and lively, exaggerated cartoon styles with bright colors and simple lines to highlight the irony and mental exhaustion of life’s challenges without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2214, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Procrastination Humor, Quotes', 'Procrastination is the thief of time.', 'John Dos Pasos', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person lounging comfortably in a messy living room. The person is wearing pajamas, reclining on a couch with a remote control in one hand and a clock in the background showing time flying away like little winged clocks or animated clock faces with legs running off. On the coffee table, unfinished tasks like a pile of papers, a laptop with notifications, and a calendar marked with deadlines are ignored. The room has a playful, exaggerated messiness with snacks and a sleepy pet nearby. The overall vibe is lighthearted, emphasizing the idea of wasted or stolen time due to procrastination in a fun, visual way.'),
 (1996, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Public Speaking, Quotes', 'It usually takes more than three weeks to prepare a good impromptu speech.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person nervously standing at a podium in front of an audience, holding note cards with scribbles. Behind the person is a large calendar on the wall, prominently displaying three weeks marked off with big X''s and notes like ''Speech Prep Day 1'', ''Speech Prep Day 10'', and ''Speech Prep Day 20''. The audience looks expectant but slightly confused, with some scratching their heads. The speaker appears stressed yet determined, with sweat drops and a thought bubble showing chaotic swirling ideas and a clock indicating time slipping away. The scene should be colorful and exaggerated to emphasize the irony of preparing extensively for something meant to be spontaneous. Include typical conference room elements: chairs, a microphone stand, and a glass of water on the podium to complete the setup.'),
 (1652, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes', 'Duct tape is like The Force. It has a light side, a dark side, and it holds the universe together.', 'Carl Zwanzig', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a roll of duct tape personified with a friendly face and little arms, standing proudly like a Jedi knight. Half of the roll glows with a bright, shining light (the ''light side''), and the other half emits a dark, mysterious shadow with sparkles (the ''dark side''). Around the roll, depict a miniature galaxy or universe with stars, planets, and swirling cosmic dust held together by a wide strip of duct tape wrapped snugly around the whole scene, symbolizing it holding the universe together. The style should be lighthearted and colorful with simple, exaggerated cartoon features to keep it fun and non-threatening. Include a subtle hint of a Jedi-style lightsaber leaning against the duct tape roll for extra connection to ''The Force.'''),
 (2139, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes', 'Never try to walk across a river just because it has an average depth of four feet.', 'Martin Friedman', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person attempting to walk across a river. The river is labeled with a large sign that says ''Average Depth: 4 feet.'' In the river, the water varies greatly: near the front, the person is confidently stepping in shallow water about knee-deep, but soon the river suddenly plunges into a deep hole where the person is waist-deep, looking surprised and struggling to stay upright. The background features a sunny sky, green riverbank with some playful animals like ducks or fish watching in amusement. The person is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions of confusion and shock as they realize the danger hidden by the average depth sign. The style is light, colorful, and goofy, emphasizing the unexpected risk despite the reassuring sign, with humorous exaggeration of water depth changes and the person''s clumsy attempts to cross.'),
 (2723, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown', 'Contrary to popular myth, washing machines do NOT eat single socks. They save the singles in a secret pocket and eject them later, one at a time, into sockless loads.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene centered around a washing machine with a sly, mischievous face on its front panel. The washing machine door is open, and inside there is a small hidden pocket or compartment labeled ''Secret Sock Pocket,'' visibly stuffed with a pile of single socks of various colors and patterns. Nearby, a confused person stands holding a solitary sock with a puzzled expression. Around the washing machine, scattered laundry items are visible, including pairs of socks and sockless shoes. The background should be a simple laundry room with a laundry basket and detergent bottles. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features and bright colors to emphasize the silly secret hiding sock singles instead of eating them.'),
 (1800, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'I don''t know and I don''t care.', 'William Safire', 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene showing a relaxed character sitting back in a chair with a carefree expression. The character should have a shrugging pose with both hands raised palms up, eyebrows raised in a playful ''I don''t know and I don''t care'' attitude. Surround the character with a few scattered question marks floating in the air to emphasize confusion or ignorance. The background is minimalistic, keeping the focus on the character''s body language and facial expression. Use bright, inviting colors and exaggerated cartoon style to enhance the lighthearted and indifferent tone of the phrase.'),
 (1883, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'If it smells like something is burning, then something is burning.', 'B.J.', 'A simple cartoon kitchen scene featuring a person standing next to a stove with a worried or confused expression. Above the stove, a small, cartoonish cloud of smoke rises, with wavy lines indicating a burning odor. The stove has a pot or pan with something visibly smoking or charred inside. The person is holding their nose or sniffing the air, clearly reacting to the smell. The background includes common kitchen items like cabinets, a countertop with a toaster or kettle, and a window showing daytime. The overall style is light-hearted and humorous, with exaggerated expressions and clean, bright colors, emphasizing the obvious cause-and-effect of smell and burning in a non-threatening, family-friendly way.'),
 (1903, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'If you drop your keys into molten lava just let ''em go ''cause, man, they''re gone.', 'Jack Handy', 'A vibrant, humorous cartoon scene shows a person standing at the edge of a glowing lava pit, looking down with a comical expression of realization and mild disappointment. The person is casually dressed and has just dropped a shiny keyring with several keys, which is illustrated as mid-fall toward the bubbling molten lava below. The lava glows bright orange and red with little animated bubbles and steam rising. Around the scene, there are humorous details such as a small sign reading ''Lava Pit - Hot!'' and maybe a worried little cartoon bird or animal watching from a safe rock nearby. The overall mood is light and silly, emphasizing the joke’s punchline that once keys are dropped in lava, they are irretrievably lost. The art style is simple, colorful, and cartoonish, suitable for a family-friendly humor comic.'),
 (1924, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'I''ll play with it first and tell you what it is later.', 'Miles Davis', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one is holding an unusual or mysterious object, examining it with intense curiosity and a playful smile. The other character stands nearby, looking both eager and slightly impatient, waiting for an explanation. The setting is casual and simple, like a living room or workshop, with bright, cheerful colors. The mysterious object should be ambiguous or odd in shape, sparking curiosity (e.g., a strange gadget, a puzzling toy, or an odd-shaped artifact). Cartoonish expressions exaggerate the playful suspense and anticipation. The overall tone is light-hearted and fun, capturing the humor in withholding information until after ''playing'' with the object first.'),
 (1939, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'In America, an hour is about 40 minutes.', 'German saying', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a typical American setting, such as a workplace break room or a casual living room. Include a wall clock prominently showing the time, where the minute hand is humorously sped up or bent to indicate that 60 minutes actually only lasts about 40 minutes. Add a confused or exasperated character, maybe holding a coffee cup or looking at their watch, with exaggerated surprise or disbelief on their face. Incorporate a calendar or another clock in the background to emphasize the concept of time passing too quickly. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, using bright colors and simple lines to create a friendly, comic atmosphere without any violence or complex details.'),
 (2000, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'It''s easier to put on slippers than to carpet the whole world.', 'Al Franken, Stuart Saves His Family', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in a cozy living room trying to put on a pair of large, fluffy slippers. The person looks relaxed and happy, wearing casual home clothes. In the background, instead of a normal floor, there is a simplified globe or Earth carpeted with a tiny, green carpet that covers just a small area while the rest remains bald or plain floor. Around the globe are a few rolled-up carpets waiting to be laid. The whole setup exaggerates the idea of carpeting the world, with a playful vibe and bright colors emphasizing comfort and simplicity. The focus is on the contrast between the ease of putting on the slippers and the immense effort implied by trying to carpet the entire Earth. No people are struggling or upset, and the scene is lighthearted and whimsical.'),
 (2197, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'People with beards can''t suck drinking glasses to their face.', 'Mister Interesting', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man with a big, fluffy beard trying to drink from a glass. The man’s beard is so wide and puffy that it prevents the glass from sealing against his face. The man looks frustrated but comically determined. The glass is slightly tilted, and you can see a small gap between the glass rim and his beard. The setting is a simple kitchen or dining room environment with a table and a drink coaster. The overall tone is light and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and beard size to highlight the joke without any negativity or mess.'),
 (2250, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'Sometimes I guess there just aren''t enough rocks.', 'Forrest Gump', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in a barren, rocky landscape. The character looks puzzled or frustrated while holding a small empty bucket or bag labeled ''Rocks.'' Around them are scattered, sparse rocks, some with exaggerated cartoon cracks or holes as if they are running out. In the background, a signpost reads ''Rock Supply: Limited.'' Nearby, a small cart or wheelbarrow is tipped over with a few rocks spilling out. The person is scratching their head, emphasizing the idea of scarcity. The sky is clear with a few fluffy clouds, and the overall tone is light and funny, with bright colors and simple, exaggerated cartoon-style features to highlight the joke''s silliness about not having enough rocks.'),
 (2560, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'When I get rich, I''m going to buy a taxi, drive around downtown with the sign on top lit up, and wave back to all the people who wave at me. I''m sure that a lot of rich people have done the same thing ''cause I see that happen all the time. Except they don''t wave back.', 'Ken R', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, middle-aged man sitting at the wheel of a classic taxi cab driving through a bustling downtown city street. The taxi has a bright, lit-up ''TAXI'' sign on its roof. The man is smiling widely and enthusiastically waving out the window. Around the taxi, several pedestrians on the sidewalk are waving back enthusiastically, some with big grins and friendly expressions. The city street is lively with tall buildings, streetlights, crosswalks, and a few other cars in the background. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features—big eyes, expressive faces, and colorful surroundings that emphasize the man''s playful idea of pretending to be a friendly rich person in a taxi waving at others. No one else is driving taxis; just the one cartoonish taxi cab stands out in the scene.'),
 (2175, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable', 'One of the advantages of being disorderly is that one is constantly making exciting discoveries.', 'A. A. Milne', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cluttered, messy room. The room should have scattered papers, books, clothes, and random objects like a lamp, coffee mug, and a small plant all strewn about unevenly. In the center, show a cheerful person, perhaps wearing casual clothes and glasses, with an excited and surprised expression, holding up an odd or unexpected item they just found—such as a toy dinosaur, a forgotten sock, or a funny note. Around them, little sparkling lines or stars emphasize the discovery moment. The background should have an uneven bookshelf leaning slightly, and a calendar or clock on the wall tilted crookedly to accentuate disorder. The overall style should be lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial features and loose lines to enhance the playful mood of finding joy in messiness.'),
 (1515, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Almost anything is easier to get into than out of.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a variety of different objects and situations that visually represent the joke ‘Almost anything is easier to get into than out of.’ Include a person struggling to crawl out of a giant tangled ball of yarn, with a frustrated expression. Nearby, show a character trying to climb out of a small, cramped box or storage trunk looking very uncomfortable. In the background, depict a person stuck halfway inside a too-tight jacket or sweater with arms flailing. Also include a comical scene of someone slipping into quicksand easily with a surprised look but struggling to climb out, reaching up with wide eyes. Place all characters in a simple lighthearted setting, such as a park or room with a few trees or furniture pieces. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish with expressive faces to emphasize the humor and frustration of being stuck. Make sure the overall mood is playful and amusing with no scary or negative tones.'),
 (2328, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The length of a film should be directly related to the endurance of the human bladder.', 'Alfred Hitchcock', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a movie theater interior with a large screen playing a film. In the audience, several exaggerated, comical characters are nervously crossing their legs or holding their bladders, expressing discomfort. One person is glancing anxiously at a clock on the wall showing elapsed time. Nearby, a restroom sign with a running stick figure is prominently displayed, indicating a desire to leave. The theater environment is typical with popcorn buckets, soda cups, and theater seats. Above the scene, a speech bubble or banner humorously states, ''The length of a film should be directly related to the endurance of the human bladder.'' The style should be bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and body language to convey urgency and humor, but no violence or negativity.'),
 (2493, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Try to relax and enjoy the crisis.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting calmly in a lounge chair, sipping a cup of tea or coffee, with a relaxed smile on their face. Around them, chaos erupts in exaggerated, silly ways: papers flying everywhere, smoke coming out of a computer, a phone ringing off the hook, and maybe a tipped-over plant or spilled coffee nearby. The background is a cluttered office or home workspace with bright colors to enhance the comedic effect. The person''s posture and facial expression clearly contrast with the hectic environment, emphasizing their attempt to ''relax and enjoy the crisis.'' Include exaggerated facial expressions and comic-style motion lines to amplify the humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1512, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, School', 'All right everyone, line up alphabetically according to your height.', 'Casey Stengel', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a school gym or playground where a diverse group of kids stand in a loose line. The teacher or adult, standing at the front with a clipboard, is cheerfully giving instructions: ''Line up alphabetically according to your height!'' The children are confused, looking at each other puzzled. Visual humor shows that some tall kids have letters painted on their shirts, and some short kids have letters too, but the line order is jumbled because the instruction mixes ''alphabetically'' and ''height,'' creating a silly contradiction. The background includes typical school elements like a bulletin board, basketball hoop, and lockers. The style is colorful, joyful, with exaggerated expressions of confusion and surprise on the kids’ faces. Make it clear the humor comes from the mixed-up instruction combining two unrelated ordering methods in a fun way.'),
 (1397, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Science Humor', 'A flying particle will seek the nearest eye.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tiny dust particle with small wings buzzing through the air, heading straight toward a large, exaggerated human eye that looks wide open and startled. The dust particle has a goofy, determined expression, as if on a mission. In the background, a face with a comically scrunched-up nose and eyelids squinting and watering suggests impending sneezing or blinking. Around the main character, subtle motion lines illustrate the particle''s flight path. The setting is indoors, with a simple background like a living room or bedroom with a window letting in sunlight to emphasize dust in the air. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial features to convey the comedic tension between the particle and the eye it targets.'),
 (1503, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Air doesn''t weigh anything - check your local bathroom scale!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical home bathroom. The focus is on a person standing barefoot on a bathroom scale, looking down with a puzzled and slightly amused expression. The scale''s digital display shows a normal weight number. Surrounding the person are light, illustrated swirls or lines representing invisible air around them. In the background, there is a toilet, a sink with a mirror reflecting the person''s confused face, and a towel rack. The overall style should be colorful, bright, and playful, emphasizing the irony of the joke that air supposedly doesn''t weigh anything, but the scale clearly shows weight. The character can have exaggerated cartoon features for comedic effect, like big eyes and raised eyebrows, to convey disbelief mixed with humor.'),
 (1559, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Appliance of the future: a self-making bed. Could be dangerous, though, if it accidentally goes off in the middle of the night.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy bedroom at night. The focus is a large, modern bed with mechanical arms and gadgets around it, resembling a quirky futuristic machine. The bed covers are partially folded up by robotic arms, mid-action as if the bed is making itself. The room is dimly lit by a moonlight through a window with curtains slightly swaying. In the bed lies a startled person with wide eyes and messy hair, caught off guard as the bed unexpectedly starts moving on its own in the middle of the night. Nearby, a bedside table with a lamp, an alarm clock showing a late hour, and a book add to the cozy atmosphere. The overall style is cartoonish and light-hearted, emphasizing surprise and absurdity without any menace or harm. The mechanical bed can have buttons and dials labeled "Auto-Make" and humorous warning signs like "Caution: May Activate While Sleeping."'),
 (2274, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Television', 'The answers to life''s problems aren''t at the bottom of a bottle: they''re on TV!', 'Homer Simpson', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room. Center the drawing around a person sitting in a comfy armchair with a relaxed, slightly amused expression. In one hand, they hold an empty or nearly empty bottle placed on a small table nearby, symbolizing the ''bottom of a bottle.'' In front of them, a large, glowing TV screen is showing a cheerful, over-the-top infomercial or a bright daytime talk show, to emphasize the idea that answers come from TV. The room should have humorous details like empty snack bowls, scattered remote controls, and perhaps motivational posters on the wall that hint at life''s problems (e.g., ''Stay Positive!'' or ''Keep Trying!''). The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to enhance the comedic tone. No dark or heavy elements—just a funny take on seeking solutions from TV instead of drinking.'),
 (2504, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Travel Humor', 'Vacation: When you spend thousands of dollars to see what rain looks like in different parts of the world.', 'Robert Orben', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful traveler standing in the rain with an umbrella and wearing a raincoat, looking around in exaggerated surprise or mild disappointment. The traveler holds a suitcase with travel stickers from famous destinations around the world. Behind him, a map on the wall highlights multiple world landmarks (Eiffel Tower, Statue of Liberty, Pyramids, etc.), each marked with cartoon raindrops falling on them. The sky above each landmark is rainy and gray, with some clouds swirling humorously. To the side, a sign reads ''Vacation Adventures'' ironically. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to capture the joke about spending a lot of money just to see rain in different parts of the world.'),
 (1669, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Wit', 'Even if you''re on the right track, you''ll get run over if you just sit there.', 'Will Rogers', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a railroad track stretching into the distance. In the center of the track, a person is sitting cross-legged, looking calm and relaxed, maybe even checking a watch or reading a newspaper. A large, classic cartoon-style train with a big smiling face is approaching from behind, about to arrive at the person on the track. The person’s expression is peaceful and oblivious to the incoming train. The background is bright and simple, with green grass on either side of the tracks, a blue sky, and a few fluffy clouds. The overall style is colorful and lighthearted, emphasizing the absurdity of sitting on a train track while a train is coming. Cartoonish exaggeration should be used to highlight the person’s relaxed attitude and the train’s imminent arrival, without any sense of danger or severity.'),
 (2621, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Wit', 'You win some, you lose some, and then there''s that little known third category.', 'Al Gore, 2000 Presidential nominee', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing three podiums side by side labeled ''Win'', ''Lose'', and ''That Other Thing''. On the ''Win'' podium, a happy character is holding up a trophy with a big smile. On the ''Lose'' podium, a sad character looks disappointed, slumped over with a droopy expression. On the ''That Other Thing'' podium, a confused character is shrugging with a puzzled look, scratching their head, surrounded by question marks or silly symbols like stars and squiggles to emphasize uncertainty. The background is simple, with a cheering crowd and a banner overhead that says ''Life''s Competitions''. The art style is lighthearted and exaggerated, using vibrant colors and exaggerated facial expressions to make it playful and funny without any negativity.'),
 (1886, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Word Play', 'If mini-marts are open 365 days a year, 24 hours a day and 7 days a week, why do the doors have locks on them?', 'Gallagher', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the front of a mini-mart at night. The mini-mart is brightly lit with a colorful sign reading ''Mini-Mart'' above the entrance. The large glass doors have big, shiny locks clearly visible on them, despite the store looking fully open with lights on and shelves stocked inside. A puzzled cartoon character stands outside scratching their head, holding a shopping basket, looking confused about why the doors are locked when the store looks open 24/7. Around the scene, exaggerated details like a clock showing midnight and a calendar emphasizing ‘365 days a year’ add to the humor. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with expressive faces and vibrant colors to convey the joke visually without any negative or controversial elements.'),
 (2648, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Real Estate Humor, Unknown', 'A third of an acre of undeveloped land may not seem big to you, but to realtors it''s a lot', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, clearly marked plot of undeveloped land labeled "1/3 Acre". The land is modest in size with simple grass and a few wild flowers. In the foreground, a cheerful realtor wearing a suit and holding a clipboard excitedly points at the land with a big smile. Nearby, a casual-looking person (potential buyer) looks puzzled or unimpressed, with arms crossed and a questioning expression. Behind them, a minimal suburban backdrop with a few houses far away, emphasizing the small size of the lot. Add a small sign stuck into the land reading "For Sale". The style is colorful and cartoony with exaggerated expressions on the characters’ faces to emphasize the comedic contrast in perception of the land size.'),
 (2742, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Crankiness. For me it''s as natural as the morning.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person waking up in bed in the early morning light shining through a bedroom window. The person is rubbing one eye with a grumpy, cranky expression on their face, showing clear signs of morning irritability. The bed is slightly messy with pillows and a blanket half off. Nearby on the bedside table, place an alarm clock with the time showing early morning hours. Add a steaming cup of coffee or tea within reach to signify an attempt to combat crankiness. The overall scene should capture the natural and inevitable mood of crankiness upon waking, emphasizing the phrase ''as natural as the morning'' with a light-hearted and relatable vibe. Use bright, soft colors to represent morning light but juxtapose with the character''s obviously cranky demeanor for comedic effect.'),
 (2818, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'EIFFELITES (eye'' ful eyetz) n. Gangly people sitting in front of you at the movies who, no matter which direction you lean in, follow suit.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a movie theater filled with rows of people. The focus is on a lanky, gangly-looking group of three or four very tall individuals sitting directly in front of the viewer. They have exaggerated long limbs and necks, stretching awkwardly in all directions. As the viewer character (shown from behind) leans left, right, or tries to peek around, the gangly people in front are shown comically mimicking every movement simultaneously, leaning in the same directions with long, bendy arms and necks following suit. Their eyes are wide and exaggerated to emphasize their synchronized, almost spooky following. The background shows a dimly lit cinema screen with the usual movie theater seats and a few other audience members scattered about. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and lighthearted with exaggerated proportions for comic effect. No one appears annoyed, just comically stuck trying to see the screen past these ''EIFFELITES.'''),
 (2985, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'I finally got it all together, but I forgot where I put it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in the middle of a messy room filled with scattered belongings like papers, clothes, keys, and gadgets. The person looks proud and relieved, holding a neatly tied bundle representing ''getting it all together,'' but with a confused expression and a hand scratching their head, clearly trying to remember where they placed the bundle. The background includes exaggerated piles and clutter suggesting disorganization, with a thought bubble above the person''s head containing a question mark. The style is light-hearted and colorful, emphasizing the contrast between neatness and forgetfulness without any negative or stressful tone.'),
 (2720, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Sleep Humor, Unknown', 'Consciousness: that annoying time between naps.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cozy bedroom where a sleepy person is lying on a bed surrounded by fluffy pillows and a cozy blanket. The room has a bedside table with a sleeping mask and a mug of warm beverage. Above the person is a thought bubble shaped like a clock or a timeline, with two nap icons on either side and a tiny figure snoozing inside each. Between the two nap icons, in the thought bubble, is a grumpy or bored-looking cartoon representation of ''consciousness'' depicted as a small, annoying buzzing bee or a tiny character holding a sign that says ''wake up!'' The overall color scheme is soft pastels. The style is simple, lighthearted, and playful with exaggerated expressions showing the annoyance of being awake between naps.'),
 (2866, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Social Humor, Unknown', 'For every action, there is an equal and opposite criticism.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person doing a simple everyday action, such as watering a small plant in a pot on a windowsill. Nearby, another character stands with their arms crossed, looking unimpressed and ready to criticize. A speech bubble from the second character contains a negative comment about the action, like ‘You’re overwatering that plant!’ or ‘Why not use a bigger pot?’ In the background, a chalkboard or sign displays the phrase: ''For every action, there is an equal and opposite criticism.'' The setting is bright and cheerful, with exaggerated facial expressions – the first character looks slightly confused or frustrated, while the critic looks hyper-serious. The overall tone is light with clear, playful cartoon style and simple, friendly colors. The focus is on the interaction and the humorous inevitability of criticism accompanying any act.'),
 (2805, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown', 'Don''t you hate it when you wake up with an upholstery pattern on your face?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person waking up in bed with a confused and slightly annoyed expression. Their face has a colorful, patterned imprint that looks like the floral or geometric fabric pattern of the couch or armchair they were sleeping against. The setting is a cozy living room with a couch visible next to the bed or a person slouched on the couch covered in a blanket. Around them, there are typical living room items like a coffee table, a small lamp, and maybe a sleepy pet nearby. The cartoon style should exaggerate the pattern on their face to make it obvious and funny, like the exact upholstery design transferred onto their cheeks and forehead. The mood is light and playful, no harsh lines or dramatic expressions, just a funny relatable moment of accidental imprinting after dozing off on furniture.'),
 (2815, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown', 'Early to bed and early to rise and you will make your neighbours suspicious.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a simple neighborhood street with cute, colorful houses. In the foreground, a person is yawning and sleepily dragging themselves out of bed early morning in pajamas, with a sleepy, half-open eye expression. Next to the person’s house, a nearby neighbor peeks suspiciously through their window, wide-eyed, with eyebrows raised and a hand on their chin as if deeply intrigued or wondering what''s going on. The street is quiet, maybe with a rooster crowing or a rising sun in the sky to suggest early morning. The scene should emphasize the funny tension between the early riser and the curious neighbor in a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon style, focusing on their expressions and body language to convey comedic suspicion without hostility or negativity.'),
 (2878, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown', 'FRUST (frust) n. The small line of debris that refuses to be swept onto the dust pan and keeps backing a person across the room until he finally decides to give up and sweep it under the rug.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene shows a frustrated person holding a broom and standing in a messy living room. The person''s expression is exaggeratedly annoyed and defeated. Ahead of them, a tiny line of dust and debris stubbornly refuses to move onto a bright yellow dustpan on the floor. The debris is drawn with tiny, cheeky eyes and mischievous grins, clearly resisting being swept. The person is slowly being backed across the room by the dust, which creates a visible trail behind them. In the background, a cozy rug lies near a doorway, slightly rolled up, ready to hide the dust when the person finally gives up. The scene uses bright colors and bold outlines for a cartoonish, lighthearted feel, emphasizing the small scale of the dust compared to the person and highlighting the comic frustration of the situation.'),
 (3143, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown', 'You know you''re having a bad day when you see your own face on a milk carton.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in a kitchen looking shocked and confused. In front of them is an open refrigerator with a milk carton prominently displayed on the middle shelf. The milk carton has a large photo of the person''s face printed on it, framed like a missing person flyer, complete with a headline reading ''Missing! Have You Seen Me?''. The person has wide eyes and a hand on their cheek in disbelief. The kitchen background is simple, with a counter, a toaster, and a fruit bowl to set a homey atmosphere. The overall tone is light and funny, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (2982, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'I feel like I am diagonally parked in a parallel universe.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing in front of a parking spot on a city street. The parking spot is clearly marked for parallel parking, with cars neatly parked one behind another along the curb. The person stands awkwardly in a small car parked diagonally across this spot, with the car''s front wheels turned at a sharp angle. Above the person''s head is a comic-style thought bubble with the phrase, ''I feel like I am diagonally parked in a parallel universe.'' The background shows other cars perfectly parallel parked, a sidewalk, and some simple cityscape elements like buildings and street lamps. The art style should be light-hearted and exaggerated to emphasize the person''s puzzled expression and the odd angle of the car. Bright, simple colors with clear lines to keep the cartoon feel.'),
 (2983, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'I fell off my 30 foot ladder this week. Good thing I was only on the first step', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a very tall ladder labeled ''30 ft'' standing against a plain background. A person, looking surprised but uninjured, is at the bottom near the first rung of the ladder, having just fallen off. The person is lightly sprawled on the ground with minimal impact, showing relief rather than pain. The ladder is exaggeratedly tall and looming above, emphasizing the height but the small step the person was on. Include a small speech bubble from the person saying, ''Good thing I was only on the first step!'' The style should be bright, colorful, and light-hearted with simple lines, making the joke clear and visually funny without any violence or distress.'),
 (2769, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown, Word Play', 'DISCONFECT (dis kon fect'') v. To sterilize the piece of candy you dropped on the floor by blowing on it, somehow assuming this will remove all the germs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a kitchen or a brightly lit room. A child or adult is kneeling or crouching by the floor, reaching down to pick up a small colorful piece of candy. The person is exaggeratedly blowing on the candy with puffed cheeks and eyes squinted, as if performing a magical sterilizing ritual. Tiny animated germs or microbes with funny faces and sad expressions are shown scattering away from the candy to emphasize the ''disinfecting.'' Nearby, a dog or a cat watches with a puzzled or amused expression. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, using bright colors and simple lines typical of a fun comic strip. Include a small text label or comic-style caption near the character saying “DISCONFECT” with a phonetic spelling and definition written in a playful font, as if part of an imaginary dictionary entry.'),
 (2821, 'Absurd Humor, Everyday Life, Unknown, Workplace', 'ELECELLERATON (el a cel er ay'' shun) n. The mistaken notion that the more you press an elevator button the faster it will arrive.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in front of a closed elevator door in a modern building lobby. A nervous-looking character stands facing the elevator, repeatedly and frantically pressing the elevator button with exaggerated arm movements. Around the character, multiple transparent ghost-like impressions of their hand show the repeated pressing. The elevator panel shows the button lit up brightly, and there’s a small digital clock on the wall showing time passing. The character’s expression is hopeful but impatient. Nearby, a small frustrated person or maybe a bystander is watching with an amused or sarcastic smile, crossing their arms. The surroundings include a simple floor mat, some potted plants, and a wall sign labeled “Elevator” to keep the setting clear. The style is colorful and cartoony, with big expressive eyes and clear motion lines illustrating the repeated button presses, and an overall light-hearted, playful mood.'),
 (2169, 'Absurd Humor, Exaggeration, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Once a man indulges himself in murder, very soon he comes to think little of robbing; and from robbing he comes next to drinking and sabbath-breaking, and from that to incivility and procrastination.', 'Thomas de Quincey', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting comfortably in an armchair at home, initially looking solemn but gradually showing a thought bubble above his head depicting a downward spiral of bad behaviors. Inside the thought bubble, starting at the top, is a small comic-style image of the man committing ''murder'' represented by a silly, non-violent symbol like a crossed-out smiley face or an exaggerated villain mask. Below that, in the same bubble, a smaller comic panel shows him robbing, humorously illustrated by the man sneaking away with a large cartoonish bag labeled with a big dollar sign. Next, the bubble flows downward to a depiction of the man drinking from a large oversized bottle or mug, shaking his head with exaggerated cheerfulness. Then the bubble continues to show him breaking a candle-lit Sabbath dinner table with a sheepish grin, tearing papers or ignoring a calendar marked ''Sabbath.'' At the bottom of the bubble, the man looks rude and unkempt, brushing off polite gestures and procrastinating by lazily lounging with a clock indicating late time. The main scene is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and simple, rounded cartoon forms. Objects include an armchair, a clock, a calendar, and symbolic props like a robber''s bag and a drink, all drawn in a non-threatening, comical style.'),
 (2486, 'Absurd Humor, Exaggeration, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Too much of a good thing is WONDERFUL.', 'Mae West', 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring a character joyfully surrounded by an abundance of something traditionally considered good, like large piles of chocolate bars or overflowing baskets of fresh fruits. The character should have a big, delighted smile and open arms embracing the excess. The background can be simple and bright with sparkles or stars around to emphasize the feeling of joy and exaggeration. Include a playful sign or banner above the character that reads, ''Too much of a good thing is WONDERFUL.'' The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated proportions to amplify the humor, such as oversized chocolates or fruits almost comically spilling everywhere. The overall mood is celebratory and fun, showing that an excess of something nice can be delightfully overwhelming rather than negative.'),
 (2141, 'Absurd Humor, Exaggeration, Quotes', 'Ninety percent of everything is crud.', 'Theodore Sturgeon', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a large, overflowing container labeled ''Everything.'' The container is filled mostly with messy, cartoonish crud—depicted as greenish goo, scraps of trash, and miscellaneous junk—with only a small corner or portion appearing clean and shiny. The character looks bewildered and slightly disgusted, scratching their head with one hand and holding a magnifying glass in the other, inspecting a tiny clean spot in the huge pile. In the background, small thought bubbles show random items like books, gadgets, and food being covered by the massive amount of crud. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated to emphasize the overwhelming amount of crud compared to the small fraction that is clean or valuable. Bright colors and simple lines keep the tone playful and cartoonish.'),
 (1608, 'Absurd Humor, Exaggeration, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'Computers in the future may weigh no more than 1.5 tons.', 'Popular Mechanics, forecasting the relentless march of science, 1949', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a futuristic computer setup. The computer looks like an enormous, old-fashioned desktop tower but exaggerated to comically huge proportions — bigger than a car. It sits on the ground wearing a price tag or label that says ''Weight: 1.5 tons.'' Nearby, a small person or technician stands beside the computer, looking surprised or struggling to push or carry it with widened eyes and sweat drops flying. The background shows a futuristic office or home environment with sleek gadgets, floating holograms, or modern decor contrasting humorously with the gigantic computer’s outdated bulky style. The style is bright and clean, with a lighthearted and exaggerated cartoon tone emphasizing the joke that future computers could still be extremely heavy, despite the expectation they''d be light and compact.'),
 (2776, 'Absurd Humor, Family, Humor, Unknown', 'Do twins ever realize that one of them was unplanned?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two young twins, one looking slightly surprised and the other casually shrugging. They stand side by side in a simple, bright room with a baby crib off to the side filled with toys. The surprised twin has wide eyes and a speech bubble above his head saying, ''Do you ever think one of us was unplanned?'' The other twin responds with a relaxed grin and a speech bubble saying, ''I just go with the flow.'' The background includes lighthearted details like framed baby photos labeled ''planned'' and ''not so much.'' The overall art style is colorful, playful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor. No violent or controversial elements are present, aiming to evoke a light, funny family moment.'),
 (1918, 'Absurd Humor, Family, Irony, Quotes', 'If your parents never had children, chances are you won''t, either.', 'Dick Cavett', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two panels side-by-side. The left panel shows a cheerful couple (the parents) standing proudly next to an empty cradle with a question mark hovering above it, implying they never had children. They have their hands on their hips and are smiling knowingly. The right panel shows a young adult with a similar facial expression and stance, standing next to an empty cradle or baby stroller, also with a question mark floating above it. Both scenes are bright and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon-style features, friendly faces, and playful colors. The background is a simple home setting, like a living room with a couch and a lamp visible behind the characters to give context but keep the focus on the cradles and characters. The overall image captures the ironic and slightly existential humor of the joke in a visually straightforward and comic way without any negativity.'),
 (2581, 'Absurd Humor, Family, Quotes', 'Where there''s a will, there are relatives, but, where there''s no will at all, there are even more.', 'Sylvia Porter', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy but cluttered living room. In the center, a large, fancy will document lies open on a coffee table, surrounded by several eager-looking relatives—all dressed in slightly exaggerated, stereotypical styles of greedy family members (e.g., one with glasses looking sly, another whispering with a raised eyebrow, a third holding a stack of papers). To one side, another group of even more relatives is crowding around a simple, empty or nonexistent will folder, looking even more frantic and competitive—scrambling, bumping into each other, and pointing fingers. The expressions of the relatives around the real will are sly and calculating, while the relatives with no will look chaotic, panicked, and desperate. Include subtle details like a family pet watching the chaos with bemused eyes. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the comedic exaggeration of family greed and chaos over inheritance without anything violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (2914, 'Absurd Humor, Family, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'He walks as if balancing the family tree on his nose.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man walking awkwardly down a suburban sidewalk. Balanced on his nose is a large, elaborate family tree—a literal tree with thick branches spread wide and leaves, with small framed photos or caricatures of various family members hanging from the branches. The man looks comically concentrated, with his eyes crossed slightly upward to keep the tree steady. Around him, a few amused neighbors or pets watch the unusual sight with smiles or raised eyebrows. The background should include a simple house, some greenery, and a clear sky to set a pleasant suburban environment. The style should be bright and colorful, using exaggerated cartoon proportions for comic effect without any violent or inappropriate elements.'),
 (1473, 'Absurd Humor, Fantasy Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'A truly wise man never plays leapfrog with a unicorn.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking man standing hesitantly at the edge of a small grassy clearing. The man wears glasses, a thoughtful expression, and holds a walking stick. In front of him is a large, colorful unicorn with a shiny horn, looking playful but somewhat mischievous. The unicorn is mid-leap, about to jump over a group of small animals (such as frogs with exaggerated, cartoonish expressions) who are crouching or leaping around, evoking the traditional game of leapfrog. The setting is bright and whimsical with soft pastel colors, a few flowers, and a rainbow in the sky to enhance the magical atmosphere. The caption or a speech bubble near the man reads, "A truly wise man never plays leapfrog with a unicorn." The overall tone is light, fantastical, and silly, emphasizing the absurdity of the situation without any signs of danger or conflict.'),
 (1846, 'Absurd Humor, Fantasy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I used to be Snow White, but I drifted.', 'Elle West', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person dressed as Snow White but looking a bit disheveled and detached from the fairy tale world. The character stands center stage wearing a classic Snow White costume with a yellow skirt, blue bodice, red bow headband, and white collar, but their expression is tired or bemused rather than happy. Around them are several familiar fairy tale elements slightly askew: a few tired-looking dwarfs lounging nearby, a small bird looking confused, and a poisoned apple with a bite taken out of it lying on the ground. In the background, a faint, dreamy-looking mist or fog drifts around, symbolizing the idea of ''drifting away'' from the Snow White story. The style should be bright and whimsical with exaggerated cartoon features to enhance the humor but avoid anything violent or dark. The overall feeling is that this Snow White used to be part of the classic story but has now ''drifted'' away into a more relaxed, less fairy-tale-perfect version of herself.'),
 (3203, 'Absurd Humor, Fantasy Humor, Relationship Humor, Steven Wright', 'I almost had a psychic girlfriend, ..... But she left me before we met.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a young man standing alone on a city sidewalk looking puzzled and slightly disappointed. Above his head is a transparent, ghostly silhouette of a woman wearing psychic or fortune-teller style clothing (think crystal ball, headscarf, and dangling earrings) walking away in the distance before they can meet. The man holds a small heart-shaped box or bouquet awkwardly, symbolizing a missed romantic connection. There is a subtle psychic theme: a floating crystal ball on a nearby table with sparkles, tarot cards scattered around, and a ''Psychic Readings'' sign hanging crookedly on a nearby storefront. The scene combines a lighthearted romantic vibe with a playful supernatural angle, all rendered in a bright, exaggerated cartoon style with friendly, round shapes and cheerful colors.'),
 (6, 'Absurd Humor, Farmers Humor, School', 'What do they call 100 John Deeres circling a McDonald''s in Iowa? Prom night.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large group of exactly 100 green John Deere tractors forming a perfect circle around a bright, classic McDonald''s restaurant with its golden arches clearly visible. The setting is a small Iowa town with flat farmland visible in the background. The tractors are all similar, each with visible brand logos and big wheels, parked close together to form the ''circle.'' Inside the circle, a few teenagers dressed up for prom—wearing tuxedos and prom dresses—are standing awkwardly beside the diners or peeking outside. The setting is daytime with a simple blue sky, and the overall mood is light and comical, highlighting the contrast between farm equipment and a traditional high school event. The style should be cartoonish with exaggerated expressions on the teenagers’ faces showing surprise or embarrassment, and the tractors have a subtle, almost personified look to enhance humor.'),
 (2170, 'Absurd Humor, Fashion Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Once you can accept the universe as matter expanding into nothing that is something, wearing stripes with plaid comes easy.', 'Einstein on Fashion', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, slightly bewildered character standing confidently in the center. The character is wearing an obviously clashing outfit: a shirt with bold vertical black-and-white stripes and pants or a skirt with a loud plaid pattern in bright colors. Around the character, a whimsical background conveys the vastness of the universe: a starry sky with swirling galaxies and planets, drawn in a playful, exaggerated style. The cosmos subtly flows outward or expands, illustrated by stretching stars or comets fading into a blank, white space that suggests ''nothing.'' The character has a lightbulb or thought bubble above their head with a simplified atom or molecule graphic, hinting at the concept of matter and the universe expanding. The overall mood is lighthearted and clever, capturing the absurdity of grappling with complex cosmic ideas while embracing a bold fashion faux pas. The cartoon style should be colorful, exaggerated, and friendly, with no menacing or serious elements.'),
 (1888, 'Absurd Humor, Fishing Humor, Life, Quotes', 'If people concentrated on the really important things in life, there''d be a shortage of fishing poles.', 'Doug Larson', 'A humorous cartoon scene set by a calm, scenic lake on a sunny day. Multiple cartoon people are shown relaxing and fishing with fishing poles, looking peaceful and carefree. Around the lake, some individuals appear distracted or worried, holding briefcases, smartphones, or papers, representing people who aren''t focusing on the ''important things.'' The focal point is a large pile or shortage of fishing poles in the foreground, with a sign next to it that reads, ''Out of Fishing Poles!'' To emphasize the joke, a cheerful character joyfully holds up the last fishing pole, smiling broadly. The overall tone is lighthearted with exaggerated expressions and colorful, simple cartoon details like trees, ducks, and wildlife enjoying the outdoors. No violence or complex backgrounds, just a simple, funny nature setting highlighting the contrast between stress and leisure.'),
 (7, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor', 'We don''t make sense, but we do like pizza.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two whimsical characters standing side by side. One character is a quirky, abstract shape with mismatched eyes and limbs, symbolizing the idea of ''not making sense.'' The other character, more normal in shape but happily holding a large, cheesy pizza with various toppings. Both characters have big smiles and relaxed poses, emphasizing their positive attitude despite confusion. The background is simple with a casual setting, like a brightly colored kitchen or a park with a picnic blanket and a pizza box open nearby. Include playful details such as floating question marks around the quirky character and little hearts or sparkles around the pizza-loving character. The overall tone is lighthearted, cheerfully embracing silliness and the joy of pizza.'),
 (651, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'Why is lemon juice made with artificial flavor, and dishwashing liquid made with real lemons?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon kitchen scene featuring two main objects: a bright yellow bottle labeled ''Dishwashing Liquid'' with cartoonish happy lemon characters on it, and a small glass bottle labeled ''Lemon Juice'' with a similar style but showing a tiny lemon character looking frustrated or fake (maybe wearing a disguise or holding a fake mustache). The dishwashing liquid bottle should look cheerful and fresh, while the lemon juice bottle should look artificial or ''phony.'' Place these objects side by side on a kitchen counter with a sink in the background and bubbles floating near the dishwashing liquid bottle. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the irony and humor in the contrast between the ''real lemons'' for dishwashing and ''artificial flavor'' for lemon juice. No people in the scene, focus on the bottles and their expression-like features to convey the joke visually.'),
 (2858, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Health Humor, Unknown', 'FIBER: Edible wood-pulp said to aid digestion and prolong life, so that we might enjoy another six or eight years in which to consume wood-pulp.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a cheerful character sitting at a dining table with an eager expression, holding a fork and knife. On the plate is a stack of cartoonish wood pulp sheets resembling thin, flat tree bark or paper, clearly labeled ''Fiber''. Nearby, a smiling anthropomorphic tree stands beside the table, waving or offering more wood pulp. Above the character, a thought bubble shows a calendar with six to eight glowing years marked, highlighting the idea of extended life. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and playful expressions emphasizing the silliness of eating ''edible wood pulp'' as fiber for digestion and longevity. The setting is a simple kitchen or dining room with a window showing trees outside to connect the theme. No violence or controversial elements.'),
 (1911, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Logic Humor, Quotes', 'If you put a spoonful of wine in a barrel full of sewage, you get sewage. If you put a spoonful of sewage in a barrel full of wine, you get sewage.', 'Schopenhauer''s Law of Entropy', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two large wooden barrels side by side, labeled respectively ''Wine Barrel'' and ''Sewage Barrel.'' Above the first barrel, a cheerful character holding a small spoon pours a spoonful of bright red wine into a huge barrel filled with dark, dirty-looking sewage with green bubbles. The second barrel shows the same character with a slightly confused or disappointed expression, pouring a small spoonful of grimy sewage into a large barrel filled with rich red wine. The barrels visibly illustrate the difference: the wine barrel starting with sparkling red wine, and turning dark and disgusting after the sewage addition, while the sewage barrel remains unchanged regardless of wine addition. Add some humorous smell lines rising from the sewage barrel and sparkling stars around the wine in the wine barrel before contamination. The characters should be cartoonish and expressive, emphasizing the irony, with a light and playful style, no violence or negativity.'),
 (2211, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Principles have no force except when one is well fed.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing proudly with their arms crossed, dressed in slightly formal clothes looking determined. They stand beside a large, overflowing buffet table loaded with various delicious food items: a big roast turkey, bowls of salad, piles of bread rolls, cakes, fruits, and drinks. Around the person, there are faint comic-style symbols representing ''principles'' as little glowing sparks or icons floating near them, but these icons look weak or almost invisible when the buffet is empty. A thought bubble above the person shows two scenes: one where the icons are very bright and strong when the person is happily eating at the table, and another when the plates are empty and the icons vanish or are very faint. The background is simple and bright, emphasizing the contrast between hunger and fullness. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize the humor that principles gain ''force'' when someone is well-fed.'),
 (2467, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'Time''s fun when you''re having flies.', 'Kermit the Frog', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a picnic table outdoors with a cheerful person sitting and laughing joyfully. Around the picnic table and on the food, several comically large, goofy-looking flies buzz and land. The person has an amused, delighted expression despite the flies swarming around, as if enjoying their presence. Include typical picnic elements like a picnic blanket, a basket, plates with food such as sandwiches and fruit, and a sunny park or backyard background. Emphasize the pun by illustrating the flies in a playful, friendly manner rather than annoying or scary. The overall mood is lighthearted and silly, capturing the joke''s playful twist on the phrase ''Time flies when you''re having fun.'''),
 (2862, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Five Jell-O flavors that flopped:  celery, coffee, cola, apple, and chocolate.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing five small Jell-O cups arranged in a row on a table. Each cup is a different, odd flavor and color: pale green labeled ''Celery,'' dark brown labeled ''Coffee,'' caramel brown labeled ''Cola,'' light green labeled ''Apple,'' and rich brown labeled ''Chocolate.'' Each cup has a sad or disappointed face drawn on the Jell-O surface, maybe with little cartoon sweat drops or frowns, expressing their failure. Behind the table, a cartoon chef or scientist character wearing a white coat looks puzzled or embarrassed, scratching their head while holding an empty spoon. The background is a simple kitchen or lab with a Jell-O box prominently displayed with a big question mark on it. The overall style is bright and playful with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor of these unusual and undesirable flavors that didn''t succeed.'),
 (3005, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I just bought a cured ham. Wonder what it had?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a person standing in a quaint grocery store aisle labeled ''Cured Meats.'' The person is holding up a large, shiny ham with a puzzled and slightly humorous expression on their face. Above the ham, floating in a thought bubble, is a small, cute pig wearing a chef''s hat and holding a cooking spoon, implying the pig might have been cooking itself. The background should show a neatly arranged shelf with other deli meats and price tags. The style should be lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the pun about the ham being ''cured'' and the person''s funny confusion about what the ham actually ''had.'' No scary or complex elements; keep everything bright, cartoonish, and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the joke''s absurdity and wordplay on ''cured.'''),
 (8, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Puns', 'What a concept - boneless spare ribs!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene at a backyard barbecue or picnic setting. In the center, show a large plate labeled ''Boneless Spare Ribs'' piled high with ribs, but the ribs look funny—each rib is a cartoon rib bone with a cute, exaggerated meat portion that is comically missing its bone in the center. Nearby, have a surprised cartoon character (could be a cheerful grill master or a picnic guest) with wide eyes and an open mouth, holding a rib in one hand and scratching their head with the other as if puzzled and amazed by the idea of ''boneless spare ribs.'' Include a barbecue grill in the background with smoke wafting lightly, and casual picnic elements like a checkered tablecloth, condiment bottles, and a bottle of barbecue sauce labeled ''Sauce.'' The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated for humor, not realistic. No violence or inappropriate content.'),
 (9, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Puns', 'When Heinz ketchup leaves the bottle, it travels at a rate of 25 miles per year.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a nearly empty bottle of Heinz ketchup on a kitchen table. From the small opening at the bottle''s top, a thin, slow-moving red ketchup ''road'' or ''trail'' extends outward. Along this trail, small cartoon-style speed indicators appear, like a tiny road sign that reads "25 mph" but corrected humorously to "25 miles per year" in big, playful lettering. Nearby, an amused cartoon character with glasses and a measuring tape or stopwatch is observing the ketchup trail as if timing the slow movement. The background is a simple kitchen setting with a plate, fork, and other condiment bottles, emphasizing the slow drip of ketchup in a lighthearted and exaggerated way. The overall tone is gentle and funny, highlighting the joke about how slowly ketchup actually comes out of the bottle.'),
 (3217, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Puns, Relatable Humor, Steven Wright', 'The hardness of the butter is proportional to the softness of the bread.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large slice of bread sitting comfortably on a plate, looking soft and squishy, with exaggerated fluffy texture and a relaxed, smiling face. Next to the bread is a stick or block of butter with a serious, firm expression, arms crossed as if proud of its hardness. Above them, a simple scientific-looking equation or graph floats in the air, showing an arrow or line labeled ''hardness of butter'' increasing in proportion to ''softness of bread''. The background is a simple kitchen countertop with a butter knife nearby, and maybe a toaster or bread bag in the background. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features emphasizing the contrast between the hard butter and soft bread in a funny visual metaphor.'),
 (2219, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Quotes', 'Reality is still the only place to get a good steak.', 'Woody Allen', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a character standing in a surreal, exaggerated fantasy world where everything is clearly not real: floating clouds shaped like question marks, cartoonish animals wearing funny hats, and bright, unnatural colors everywhere. The character looks disappointed or skeptical while holding a fork and knife, staring at a comically tiny or completely imaginary steak on a transparent platter. To the side, a signpost points in two directions: one labeled ''Reality'' with a juicy, perfectly cooked steak on a serving platter, and the other labeled ''Fantasy'' with weird abstract shapes or fake food items like a glowing green cube or a spongy pink blob. The background should feel whimsical and clearly unreal, emphasizing the contrast. Style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with bold outlines and bright colors to enhance the humor and the idea that only in the real world can you get a real steak worth eating.'),
 (2306, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Quotes', 'The first time I saw some cheese that was white but the package said cheddar, I wondered why they dyed it white.', 'J Bird', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene focused on a person holding a block of cheese with a puzzled and curious expression. The person is looking closely at the cheese, which is pure white in color, yet the package prominently labels it as ''Cheddar.'' The cheese block should be square or rectangular with a clear label showing the word ''Cheddar'' in bold letters. Around the person, add subtle visual clues signaling confusion, like a question mark floating above their head and a small magnifying glass in their hand inspecting the cheese. The background should be a simple kitchen or grocery store shelf with other colorful cheeses to highlight the unusual white cheddar. Make the style lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the absurdity of thinking cheese might be dyed white. Avoid any people or elements that could be interpreted as violent or offensive.'),
 (1560, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'Appliance of the future: Microwave Refrigerators: a device which can cool a can of beverage in a few seconds. Haven''t you ever put a can of beverage in the freezer for just 20 minutes only to discover it the next day?', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon kitchen scene featuring a futuristic-looking appliance labeled ''Microwave Refrigerator'' with buttons and a glowing digital screen. Next to it, a surprised person holds a can of soda looking amazed as the can instantly cools down with little frost forming on it. In the background, an old-fashioned freezer is open with a clock showing a long time passed and an exploded, frozen soda can dripping messily on the floor. The setting is bright and cheerful with exaggerated expressions to show the humor of discovering a forgotten beverage turned into a frozen disaster. Include a small sign or label on the futuristic appliance that says ''Cools drinks in seconds!''. The style is cartoonish and lighthearted, with rounded shapes and vibrant colors to emphasize the joke''s playful tone.'),
 (3126, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Safety Humor, Unknown', 'You are more likely to be killed by a Champagne cork than by a poisonous spider.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a surprised person standing next to two exaggeratedly dangerous hazards. On one side, a large, over-the-top sparkling Champagne bottle with the cork shooting out like a missile toward the person, who has wide eyes and raised hands in mock fear. On the other side, a small but menacing-looking black spider with exaggerated fangs and a sly expression, sitting calmly on a spider web nearby. The setting is lighthearted with a simple background such as a kitchen or party room, with confetti and bubbles floating in the air to suggest celebration. A caption or sign above reads: "More likely to be killed by a Champagne cork than a poisonous spider!" The style is colorful, cartoonish, and silly without any threatening or violent elements.'),
 (2766, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Unknown', 'Diner''s Dilemma: A clean tie attracts the Soup of the Day.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy diner. At the center, a well-dressed man wearing a perfectly clean, spotless tie sits at a small table with a bowl of soup placed right in front of him. The soup is dramatically splashing out of the bowl, as if it’s magically attracted to the spotless tie. The man looks surprised and slightly dismayed, staring at his tie and the soup splash. The diner background includes classic elements: a booth with a retro-style checkered tablecloth, a menu board on the wall showing ''Soup of the Day,'' and a friendly waiter approaching with a spoon in hand. Make the characters and objects exaggerated and cartoonish, with wide eyes and expressive faces to emphasize the comedic effect of the tie attracting the soup. The overall tone should be lighthearted and silly, capturing the absurdity of the situation without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2892, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Unknown', 'Gourmet tip: don''t eat in restaurants where they stamp your hand!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a casual restaurant. In the foreground, a confused and slightly annoyed customer looks down at their hand, which has a large, brightly colored stamp on the back, similar to those used at amusement parks or clubs. The customer is sitting at a small table with a plate of uneaten food and a drink, clearly uncomfortable with the mark. Behind the counter, a cheerful restaurant employee is stamping other customers'' hands eagerly with a big, comical rubber stamp. The background has other diners noticing their own stamped hands with mixed reactions—some surprised, some amused. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and simple lines to emphasize the silly concept of stamping customers'' hands as a ''gourmet tip.'' No harsh expressions, just playful confusion and mild annoyance to keep the tone funny and cartoonish.'),
 (2992, 'Absurd Humor, Food Humor, Unknown', 'I got gas for $1.39 today. Unfortunately it was at Taco Bell', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing outside a Taco Bell restaurant. The person holds a receipt or a sign that says ''$1.39 gas'' with a puzzled expression on their face. Nearby, a Taco Bell drive-thru or counter is visible with typical Taco Bell branding and a menu board showing tacos and burritos. Next to the person, a classic gas pump with a nozzle, but instead of fueling a car, the gas pump is humorously connected to a Taco Bell taco or burrito. The setting is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke about confusing cheap taco gas for actual gasoline. Avoid any vehicles or people in distress, keep it light and silly.'),
 (2874, 'Absurd Humor, Friends, Humor, Unknown', 'Friends don''t let friends drive naked.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing two friends inside a car. The driver is a surprised person with wide eyes, sitting behind the steering wheel completely naked but strategically covered by the steering wheel and car seat to keep it tasteful. The passenger friend is sitting next to them, looking shocked but also playfully concerned, with one hand raised as if stopping the driver from starting the car. The background should show the interior of a typical car with windows, rearview mirror, and dashboard. Add a small humorous detail like a sign on the dashboard that says ''Friends don''t let friends drive naked'' in bold, fun letters. The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke in a friendly, cartoon style.'),
 (1947, 'Absurd Humor, Friendship Humor, Quotes', 'In the End, we will remember not the words of our enemies, but the silence of our friends.', 'Martin Luther King Jr. (1929-1968)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing dramatically on a small stage, looking sad and disappointed. Around them are several other cartoon characters who represent ''friends,'' but instead of speaking or consoling, they are all comically silent and frozen with exaggerated ''shocked'' or ''awkward'' expressions, covering their mouths or looking away. The ''enemy'' is shown far off to the side, looking angry and shouting with a visible speech bubble full of angry words, but the main focus is on the silent friends'' exaggerated muteness. The background is simple, with a spotlight on the main character and muted colors to emphasize the theme of silence versus loud words. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, avoiding any serious or dark interpretations.'),
 (2682, 'Absurd Humor, Furniture Humor, Pop Culture Humor, Unknown', 'BOOKCASE:  A piece of furniture used in America to house bowling trophies and Elvis collectibles.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cozy American living room. In the center is a large, classic wooden bookcase filled not with books, but instead overflowing with shiny bowling trophies of various sizes and colorful plaques. Interspersed among the trophies are quirky Elvis Presley collectibles, like a miniature Elvis figurine in a flashy jumpsuit, a pair of Elvis sunglasses perched on a shelf edge, and a small framed photo of Elvis. Around the bookcase, a smiling middle-aged person is proudly pointing at the display, wearing casual clothes and perhaps sneakers with a bowling logo. The background has a comfy armchair, a small side table with a lamp, and a banner or wall plaque referencing bowling or Elvis fandom. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the irony that the bookcase is not used for books but for these unrelated treasured items, making a visual pun on the joke’s meaning.'),
 (1874, 'Absurd Humor, Garden Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'If dandelions were hard to grow, they would be most welcome on any lawn.', 'Andrew V. Mason', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bright green suburban lawn sprinkled with many cheerful yellow dandelions in full bloom. The dandelions look vibrant and almost glowing with a welcoming expression, some having little smiling faces. In the foreground, a homeowner with a surprised, delighted look is kneeling down, joyfully admiring a single dandelion like a prized flower, holding a small watering can as if tending to the plant carefully. Behind him, a typical garden background features a white picket fence, a bird happily perched on it, and a few common lawn care tools like a rake and a lawnmower standing idly by, indicating a usual battle against weeds. The sky is clear and sunny, adding to the lighthearted, welcoming mood of the scene. The style should be colorful, simple, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions, emphasizing the contrast of the normally unwelcome dandelions being celebrated as precious.'),
 (1892, 'Absurd Humor, Gender Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'If the world were a logical place, men would ride sidesaddle.', 'Rita Mae Brown', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a man awkwardly trying to ride a horse sidesaddle, wearing casual modern clothes. The horse looks calm but slightly puzzled. Nearby, a confident woman happily rides another horse sidesaddle, in traditional elegant attire. The background is a sunny countryside with rolling hills and a clear blue sky. Add a small thought bubble above the man’s head showing a confused expression, as if questioning his own posture. Include a signpost nearby that reads ''Logical World'' with an arrow pointing toward the woman and her horse, hinting at irony. The style should be lighthearted and playful, focusing on exaggerated expressions and posture to emphasize the humor without anything offensive or inappropriate.'),
 (2591, 'Absurd Humor, Gender Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Women don''t want to hear what you think. Women want to hear what they think, in a deeper voice.', 'Bill Cosby', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man and a woman sitting across from each other at a small round table in a cozy cafe. The woman has a confident, knowing expression with her arms crossed, clearly stating her thoughts. The man, looking slightly puzzled but trying to be agreeable, has a thought bubble above his head displaying the same words she said, but written in a deeper, bold font with musical notes to imply a deeper voice. The setting is light and friendly with other cafe details like a coffee cup and pastries on the table, and soft pastel colors. The focus is on the interaction and the funny idea that the man is just echoing her thoughts in a deeper tone rather than sharing his own ideas. Both characters are drawn in a simple, exaggerated cartoon style with expressive faces to emphasize the joke’s playful tone.'),
 (3096, 'Absurd Humor, Gender Humor, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, telephones would cut off after 30 seconds of conversation.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a man and a woman each holding a phone to their ear, standing side by side. The man looks annoyed and impatient, glancing at a large, exaggerated stopwatch or timer next to him counting down from 30 seconds. The woman looks surprised and confused, holding her phone with a speech bubble showing several sentences or ellipses to indicate she has more to say. The background shows a simple living room or office setting with minimal furniture, emphasizing the characters and their phones. The telephone cords are slightly exaggerated and tangled, adding to the comic effect. Overall, the style is light-hearted, with bright colors and playful expressions to enhance the joke’s irony about men cutting off phone calls quickly.'),
 (3095, 'Absurd Humor, Gender Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, tanks would be far easier to rent.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cityscape with a large military tank parked in front of a rental shop with a big sign saying ''Tanks for Rent!'' The rental shop window displays price tags and rental terms with playful details like ''No experience necessary'' and ''Discounts for weekend warriors.'' Outside the shop, a man wearing a casual t-shirt and shorts with sunglasses is confidently leaning on the tank, holding a rental contract with a huge grin on his face. Nearby, an amused woman and child watch the scene with raised eyebrows and smiles. In the background, a few other tanks are lined up like cars at a dealership, some with colorful balloons tied to them, emphasizing the lighthearted tone. The overall style is bright, exaggerated, and cartoonish, with friendly character designs and simple bold lines to capture the playful absurdity of the idea that renting tanks is as easy as renting a car if men ran the world.'),
 (2179, 'Absurd Humor, Geography Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'One thing the discovery of the North Pole revealed is that there is nobody sitting on top of the world.', 'Tennessee Farm Bureau News', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a cheerful explorer standing on a small snowy peak labeled ''North Pole,'' holding a flag triumphantly planted in the ice. The peak is shown as the very top of a simplified, rounded globe, emphasizing that it’s the highest point on Earth. The explorer is looking around with a surprised expression, hands on hips, realizing there is nobody else there. The globe below shows cartoonish continents with happy faces, but the very top spot is empty except for the explorer. The sky is clear with a few light clouds and a bright shining sun. Include playful details like a small polar bear peeking from behind the snow, and maybe an old-style compass or map lying on the ground next to the explorer. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated in a lighthearted cartoon format to convey the joke that nobody is literally sitting on top of the world.'),
 (2191, 'Absurd Humor, Geography Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Parts of Los Angeles have had their area code changed to 310. New York has also had its area code changed. All of New York is now area code 911.', 'Kevin Nealon', 'A colorful cartoon map showing a humorous contrast between Los Angeles and New York. On the left side, depict Los Angeles with iconic landmarks like palm trees, Hollywood sign, and sunny skies labeled with a big, bold ''310'' area code sign placed above the city skyline. On the right side, illustrate New York City with famous landmarks such as the Statue of Liberty, yellow taxis, and tall skyscrapers—but instead of a normal area code, show a large, blinking red ''911'' emergency sign hovering above the city. Add playful, exaggerated details like a confused phone operator scratching their head near a telephone switchboard, and people around New York reacting humorously to the emergency number as their area code (e.g., a person dialing the phone with a panicked expression but then shrugging). The style should be cartoonish with bright colors, exaggerated expressions, and a lighthearted, funny tone. No violence or negative imagery—just fun urban stereotypes and a silly emergency number twist.'),
 (2835, 'Absurd Humor, Geography Humor, Unknown', 'Every year there is a race from one side of Sweden to other. They start at the Norwegian line and end at the Finnish line', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon-style map scene showing Sweden as a long vertical country between Norway and Finland. On the left, label the Norwegian border with a starting line where a group of quirky runners (various ages and funny expressions) are eagerly waiting to begin a race. On the right side of the map, show the Finnish border as a big finish line with a checkered flag. The runners are looking puzzled or confused, as if the course is unexpectedly long, poking fun at Sweden’s length between the two borders. Include simple trees and small houses along the route to emphasize the landscape. Add speech bubbles with runners making lighthearted comments about how far the race is, enhancing the humor. The overall style is bright, playful, and exaggerated for comedy, with smiling, cartoonish characters and clear country names on the map to guide the viewer.'),
 (2679, 'Absurd Humor, Geography Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Blame Saint Andreas - its all his fault.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly disheveled saint character labeled ''Saint Andreas'' standing beside a cartoon-style fault line in the earth, which is cracked and jagged. The saint is shrugging with an apologetic smile and exaggerated innocent eyes, as if to say, ''Oops, my bad!'' In front of him, a small group of surprised, puzzled townsfolk or animals stand near the crack, looking at the saint with mixed expressions of amusement and disbelief. The background can include a simple village with houses slightly tilted or cracked, indicating minor earthquake effects, but nothing serious or scary. The art style should be lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the absurdity of blaming a saint for a geological fault. The text "Blame Saint Andreas - it''s all his fault" can be written in a playful font above or below the scene to tie the joke together.'),
 (2887, 'Absurd Humor, God Humor, Time Humor, Unknown', 'God, how long is a million years?  To me, it’s about a minute. God, how much is a million dollars? To me, it’s a penny. God, may I have a penny? Sure - in a minute.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a child and God in conversation. The child is standing on the left side, looking curious and slightly impatient, hands on hips or with one hand raised asking a question. God is portrayed on the right side as a cheerful, kindly older man with a long white beard, wearing flowing robes and a glowing halo. Behind God, a large clock or hourglass emphasizes the concept of time passing slowly. Above them, speech bubbles show their dialogue: the child asking ''God, how long is a million years?'' with God replying ''To me, it’s about a minute.'' Then the child asks ''God, how much is a million dollars?'' with God answering ''To me, it’s a penny.'' Finally, the child offers the request ''God, may I have a penny?'' and God responds ''Sure - in a minute.'' The background is light, heavenly, with soft clouds and bright colors to keep the mood light and playful. The cartoon style is friendly and exaggerated, emphasizing expressions for humor and clarity of the punchline.'),
 (1725, 'Absurd Humor, Golf Humor, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'Golf is a game in which you yell ''Fore'', shoot- six, and write down five.', 'Paul Harvey', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a golf course. Show a frustrated golfer mid-swing with an exaggerated surprised expression, shouting ''Fore!'' as a golf ball flies wildly off-course. Near the golfer is a scorecard held in one hand, with a pencil in the other, showing the number five written down. In the background, depict six golf balls scattered around, clearly illustrating the golfer''s many attempts. The setting includes a green with a hole flag, some trees, and a bright sunny sky. Emphasize the comedic contrast between the golfer’s yelling, missed shots, and optimistic scoring. The style should be lighthearted, colorful, and playful, capturing the humor and irony in the joke about golf scoring and shooting.'),
 (598, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, History Humor, Pun', 'What rock group has four men, one of which is named George and another that was shot to death?  Mount Rushmore!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the famous Mount Rushmore National Memorial with the four presidential faces carved into a large granite cliff. Each face is distinctly recognizable and arranged side-by-side. To emphasize the joke, add subtle cartoon-style labels with names: George (Washington), and a ghostly or lightly shaded outline behind Abraham Lincoln’s face, referencing that he was shot to death. The setting is a bright, sunny day with a few fluffy clouds. In the foreground, a small group of four cartoon men dressed as a rock band stands comically small beside the huge mountain carving; one of them wears a band shirt with ''Mount Rushmore'' written on it. Musical instruments like a guitar, microphone, and drums can be scattered around them to highlight the ''rock group'' pun. The overall style should be light-hearted, colorful, and playful, avoiding any dark or morbid tones despite the historical reference. The focus is on the contrast between a real rock formation (the monument) and the idea of a rock music band.'),
 (637, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Mental Health Humor', 'Why do the criminally insane get to have all the fun?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful group of characters labeled ''criminally insane'' enjoying a wild, exaggerated party. The scene is set in a bright, colorful room with playful decorations like streamers and balloons. The ''criminally insane'' characters have quirky, exaggerated facial expressions and poses, wearing mismatched goofy clothing and hats. One is happily juggling objects like rubber chickens and oversized dice, another is riding a tiny tricycle wildly around, and a third is laughing uproariously while spinning in an office chair. Nearby, a more straight-laced character watches skeptically with raised eyebrows and crossed arms, highlighting the contrast. The overall mood is lighthearted and fun, capturing the idea that the ''criminally insane'' are having more fun in a carefree, silly way without any harmful or dark undertones.'),
 (621, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Objects Humor', 'Why are electrical outlets always so far away from the plug?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a living room or office. Show a frustrated person trying to plug an electrical plug into an outlet that is comically far away from them, maybe across the room. The person could be stretching awkwardly or even crawling on the floor, holding a short electrical cord that clearly can''t reach the distant outlet. Include the electrical outlet visibly mounted on a wall in the background, far from any furniture. Humorously exaggerate the distance between the person and the outlet, for example, by showing a long stretch of empty floor in between. The expression on the person''s face should be one of bewilderment or irritation. The overall style should be light-hearted and simple, with bright colors and exaggeration to emphasize the absurdity of the distance between plug and outlet.'),
 (575, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Objects Humor, Pun', 'What did the bra say to the hat? You go on ahead - I''ll give these two a lift', NULL, 'A whimsical cartoon scene featuring two characters: a bra and a hat, both anthropomorphized with cute, friendly faces and expressive eyes. The bra is positioned in the foreground, wearing white or pastel colors with straps neatly draped, smiling confidently. The bra’s straps lift up two small, humorous-sized cartoon breasts that appear cheerful as well. Next to it, the hat—a classic fedora or wide-brimmed hat—is shown taking a quick step forward, looking amused or surprised. The background is simple and light-hearted, perhaps a soft pastel gradient or a minimal park bench to suggest casual interaction. Above or nearby, a speech bubble from the bra says, “You go on ahead - I’ll give these two a lift.” The overall tone is playful and charming, rendered in a bright, bold, humorous cartoon style with clean lines and vibrant colors, capturing the joke’s pun about the bra lifting the breasts while the hat goes ahead.'),
 (597, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Ocean Humor, Puns', 'What lies at the bottom of the ocean and twitches? A nervous wreck.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an underwater ocean floor. In the center, draw a cartoon-style old shipwreck with visible cracks and barnacles. The shipwreck should have cartoon eyes wide open with a worried or nervous expression, and its hull twitches or shivers with small motion lines around it to show the twitching. Around the shipwreck, include some colorful sea creatures like fish and crabs looking surprised or curious at the twitching shipwreck. The ocean floor should have sand, some seaweed, and bubbles rising to the surface. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor, creating a lighthearted and fun underwater atmosphere.'),
 (757, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Philosophy Humor, Science Humor, Steven Wright, Word Play', 'OK, so what''s the speed of dark?', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a curious person, maybe a kid or a quirky scientist, standing in a dimly lit room. The character wears a puzzled expression, scratching their head while looking at a speedometer labeled ''Speed of Dark.'' The speedometer needle points at zero. Around them, there are playful visual elements: beams of light trying to reach the edges of darkness but stopping sharply. The room should have exaggerated shadows with dark areas depicted as thick, wavy blobs creeping towards the light source, emphasizing how darkness spreads or moves. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors for lights and deep purples or blues for shadows. Include a classic question mark above the character’s head to highlight confusion and intrigue. The overall tone should feel like a funny sci-fi or exploratory moment focused on the idea of measuring something intangible like darkness''s speed.'),
 (599, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What was the best thing *before* sliced bread?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused, friendly-looking character standing in a simple kitchen. The character is holding a large, unsliced loaf of bread with a questioning expression. Around them, exaggerated objects like a big knife hovering but not cutting and a calendar or clock on the wall emphasizing ''before sliced bread'' concept. The kitchen is bright and simple, with a countertop, a bread box, and a toaster nearby to highlight the bread theme. The style is cartoonish with light colors and an inviting, playful atmosphere emphasizing the joke about the idea of ''the best thing before sliced bread.'''),
 (607, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What''s red and looks like a bucket? A red bucket.  What''s blue and looks like a bucket? NOPE! It''s a red bucket in disguise!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two large buckets side by side on a simple ground background. The bucket on the left is bright red, plain and typical looking. The bucket on the right is painted entirely blue but is clearly the same shape and size as the red bucket. The blue bucket has a playful, exaggerated disguise: it wears goofy glasses and a fake mustache, hinting at the joke that it is trying to hide its true red color. Above the buckets are two speech bubbles; the first bubble (above the red bucket) says, ''What''s red and looks like a bucket? A red bucket.'' The second bubble (above the blue bucket) says, ''What''s blue and looks like a bucket? NOPE! It''s a red bucket in disguise!'' The style should be bright and colorful, with thick outlines typical of lighthearted cartoon humor. The setting is simple and uncluttered with no background characters, focusing entirely on the two buckets and the text for clarity and comedic effect.'),
 (644, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Pun, Science Humor', 'Why doesn''t glue stick to the inside of the bottle?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a close-up of an open glue bottle with a quirky, surprised face on it. The bottle has wide, cartoonish eyes looking inside itself as if confused. Inside the bottle, the glue appears calm and smooth with a smiling, slick expression, clearly avoiding sticking to the bottle’s inner walls. The bottle is on a simple white surface, with a small puddle of glue outside next to it, happily sticking to the surface. Include a speech bubble from the bottle that says, "Why won''t you stick to me?" The style should be bright and playful, emphasizing the irony that glue can stick to almost anything but not the inside of its own container. No background characters, just the glue bottle and the little puddle to focus on the joke visually.'),
 (583, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'What do you get when you cross a joke with a rhetorical question?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of two characters standing next to each other. One character, holding a large sign that reads ''Joke,'' is smiling and mid-sentence. The other character looks puzzled, scratching their head, while a large floating question mark hovers over them. Between them is a large, whimsical hybrid creature with exaggerated features combining symbols of a joke (like a jester’s hat or a whoopee cushion) and a giant punctuation mark shaped like a question mark. The setting is a simple, bright, and playful background, such as a sunny park or comedy club stage, with minimal props other than a microphone stand nearby to imply telling jokes or asking questions. The style is colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing the confusion and wordplay in the joke without any text other than the sign and the visual question mark.'),
 (591, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'What has 5 toes but isn''t your foot? My foot', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a single human foot with all five toes clearly visible, standing on a floor mat labeled ''My Foot''. Next to it, a comical ambiguous object resembling a giant toe with tiny little toes growing off it, indicating confusion about what has five toes but isn''t a foot. The background is simple and bright, with the foot character having a friendly face and cartoon eyes to add personality. A question mark floats above the scene to emphasize the riddle aspect of the joke. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated proportions on the toes for comedic effect.'),
 (616, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Pun, Workplace', 'Where are average things built? In the satisfactory', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set inside a cheerful factory labeled ''Satisfactory'' on a big sign over the entrance. The factory looks average and unremarkable, with smoke puffs gently coming out of a single chimney. Inside the factory, humorous little machines and conveyor belts are producing and packing medium-sized, plain-looking objects marked as ''Mediocre Widgets'' or ''Average Gadgets.'' Workers in cartoonish uniforms wear hats with a checkmark symbol (to symbolize ''satisfactory''). Nearby, a large assembly line sign reads ''Building Average Things Here.'' The overall mood is light and funny, with some cartoon characters looking proud of their ''satisfactory'' work, while others shrug humorously. Background elements include tools like hammers, wrenches, and measuring tapes, emphasizing a factory environment but without any complexity or grandeur. The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the joke''s silly pun on ''factory'' and ''satisfactory.'' No characters appear stressed or unhappy; instead, aimed to create a playful, mildly silly atmosphere.'),
 (634, 'Absurd Humor, Good Question!, Relatable', 'Why do people let the phone ring twice before answering when they are sitting right next to it?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room. Center the image on a person sitting comfortably on a couch, holding a book or remote control, looking relaxed and slightly distracted. Nearby, place a classic landline or smartphone on a small table or the floor next to the couch. The phone is clearly ringing, illustrated by exaggerated motion lines or comic sound effects like "Ring! Ring!" showing it has rung twice. The person glances toward the phone but isn''t in a hurry to pick it up, maybe with a humorous thought bubble showing a question mark or a playful grin. The room should be bright and welcoming, with simple furniture like a lamp, a coffee table with a cup of coffee, and maybe a pet or a clock on the wall indicating time passing. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the funny but relatable habit of delaying answering a nearby ringing phone just to let it ring twice first.'),
 (792, 'Absurd Humor, Halloween, Pun', 'Why don''t skeletons go trick or treating? They have no body to go with', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly skeleton standing on a suburban doorstep decorated for Halloween at night. The skeleton looks a bit sad or lonely, holding a small, empty trick-or-treat bucket. Around it are Halloween decorations like pumpkins, cobwebs, and autumn leaves. Nearby, a group of cheerful children in various costumes happily trick-or-treat in pairs or groups, emphasizing companionship. The skeleton stands apart from them, highlighting the joke’s punchline about having ''no body'' to go with. The art style should be lighthearted and playful with exaggerated expressions and bright Halloween colors to keep the mood fun and whimsical.'),
 (790, 'Absurd Humor, Halloween, Puns', 'Why don''t monsters eat ghosts? They taste like sheet', NULL, 'A colorful and playful cartoon scene featuring two friendly-looking monsters standing next to each other. One monster is holding a fork and knife, looking skeptically at a ghost floating in front of them. The ghost is a simple white sheet with eyes, shaped like a classic Halloween ghost. The monster''s face shows a mix of disgust and confusion as a speech bubble from the monster says, "They taste like sheet!" The background is light and cheerful, maybe with a hint of a spooky but fun setting like a haunted house or a misty graveyard with pumpkins and bats in the distance. The style is whimsical and exaggerated with big eyes and rounded shapes, emphasizing humor rather than fear.'),
 (1455, 'Absurd Humor, Health Humor, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'A pint of sweat saves a gallon of blood.', 'General George S. Patton (1885-1945)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a person running in the heat, visibly sweating a lot. The runner wears sporty clothes and a headband, with sweat droplets flying off their forehead and body. Nearby, show a large gallon jug labeled "Blood" sweating cartoonishly as well, looking relieved or happy while a smaller pint-sized sweat droplet with a superhero cape flies heroically toward it. The background is a sunny outdoor setting, like a park or track field, with exaggerated heat waves rising to emphasize the hot environment. The style should be lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated expressions on the characters to highlight the joke that sweating (the pint) saves the bigger amount (gallon) of blood.'),
 (2779, 'Absurd Humor, Health Humor, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Doctors at Canada''s McGill University claim you can kill the pain of a toothache by holding an ice cube to the web of skin between your thumb and index finger. Toothache intensity was reduced by 50% in subjects who iced their webs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a kitchen table with a pained expression, holding a red, throbbing cheek to indicate a toothache. Their other hand is raised and pressing an ice cube firmly between their thumb and index finger (the skin web). The ice cube is cartoonishly frosty with small snowflakes around it. On the table, there are dental items like a toothbrush and toothpaste, and a comedic oversized poster on the wall behind them that reads ''McGill University Toothache Cure!'' with a cartoon tooth giving a thumbs-up. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the discomfort and the odd remedy.'),
 (3011, 'Absurd Humor, Health Humor, Unknown', 'I just read an article on the dangers of drinking diet soda and it really scared me, so that''s it - after today - no more reading.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting comfortably in an armchair with a newspaper or tablet titled ''Health News'' or ''Dangers of Diet Soda'' prominently displayed. The person''s eyes are wide open in exaggerated shock or fear, mouth agape as they stare at the article. Around them, an empty diet soda can or bottle sits on a small table nearby, untouched. The background is a simple cozy living room setting with a lamp and bookshelf to suggest a casual reading environment. The character’s exaggerated reaction humorously contrasts with the calm setting, emphasizing their decision to stop reading altogether. The style should be bright and colorful with clear expressions, and the scene should have a lighthearted, cartoonish feel without any violence or negativity, just playful exaggeration of fear from reading the article itself.'),
 (1821, 'Absurd Humor, Historical Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'I have traveled the length and breadth of this country and talked with the best people, and I can assure you that data processing is a fad that won''t last out the year.', 'The editor in charge of business books for Prentice Hall, 1957', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a busy, vintage traveling context. Depict a confident, older man dressed as a well-traveled 1950s-style salesman or lecturer, standing on a small wooden platform or stage with an old-fashioned microphone. He is confidently addressing a small, diverse crowd of people from different local backgrounds—farmers, office workers, and homemakers—each with amused or skeptical expressions. Around them, travel-themed props such as a suitcase with travel stickers, a map marked with routes, and a classic car or bus in the background emphasize extensive travel. The speaker holds a paper titled ''Data Processing Trends'' with a big red stamp labeled ''Fad.'' The overall style is colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and lighthearted details like a calendar showing the current year and a vintage computer or punch card machine sitting ignored next to him. The tone is playful and ironic, poking fun at outdated predictions about technology trends without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2291, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The charm of history and its enigmatic lesson consist in the fact that, from age to age, nothing changes and yet everything is completely different.', 'Aldous Huxley', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two historical figures standing side by side to represent ''age to age.'' On the left, a medieval knight in shining armor with a puzzled expression, holding an old scroll with ancient symbols. On the right, a futuristic astronaut in a high-tech suit, equally puzzled, holding a glowing digital tablet displaying a very different futuristic script. Between them is a large hourglass with sand flowing, symbolizing time passing. In the background, a whimsical timeline scroll hangs with exaggerated changes: from castles to skyscrapers, horses to flying cars, while both characters scratch their heads or shrug, illustrating the contradiction that ''nothing changes and yet everything is different.'' The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize confusion and irony without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1843, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Political Humor, Quotes', 'I think this is the most extraordinary collection of talent, of human knowledge, that has ever been gathered together in the White House -- with the possible exception of when Thomas Jefferson dined alone.', 'JFK, White House dinner for Nobel Prize winners', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a grand White House dining room filled with a large, diverse group of important-looking people, all animatedly talking and showing off their talents or knowledge—professors with books, scientists with test tubes, artists painting, musicians playing instruments, and politicians debating. The opulent room is richly decorated with chandeliers and a long dining table laden with fancy dishes. In sharp contrast, in the foreground on one side, there is a tiny, simple table with just Thomas Jefferson sitting alone, looking dignified but solitary, enjoying a modest meal with a candle. Jefferson wears colonial-era clothing and holds a fork and knife. The caption or speech bubble from a character could emphasize the joke''s punchline about the extraordinary collection of talent gathered at the White House, with the playful exception noted when Jefferson dined alone. The style should be bright, colorful, and caricatured for comic effect, with exaggerated expressions and body language to highlight the humor of social gathering versus solitary greatness.'),
 (2709, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Clans of long ago that wanted to get rid of their unwanted people without killing them used to burn their houses down  -hence the expression ''to get fired.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an ancient village with a few small, simple wooden houses. In the foreground, several villagers dressed in primitive, rustic clothing (like animal skins or rough tunics) are casually standing around with amused expressions. Nearby, one house is on fire with small cartoonish flames and smoke billowing upward. The villagers are not panicked; instead, they look comically relaxed or slightly grinning while watching the burning house. One villager holds a primitive torch, symbolizing the act of ‘firing’ the house down. In the background, other houses appear intact with some villagers gossiping or shrugging in confusion. A playful sign or banner could read “Clan Meeting” or something similar to set the context. The style is lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon with bright colors and friendly faces, emphasizing the pun on the phrase ''to get fired'' rather than any danger or violence.'),
 (1680, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Quotes', 'Everything that can be invented has been invented.', 'Charles H. Duell, Commissioner, U.S. Office of Patents, 1899', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in an old-fashioned inventor''s workshop filled with quirky inventions. In the center, an exhausted, slightly frazzled inventor wearing a white lab coat and round glasses sits slumped at his cluttered wooden workbench covered with blueprints, gears, and odd gadgets. Above him, a large vintage-style thought bubble contains the phrase: ''Everything that can be invented has been invented.'' Around the room, include a few comically exaggerated contraptions like a steam-powered robot, a flying bicycle with propellers, and a suspiciously broken toaster labeled ''World''s Last Invention.'' To add humor, show a cat playfully batting at a rubber ball labeled ''Next Big Idea,'' oblivious to the inventor''s frustration. The setting should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and slightly whimsical, old-timey details to emphasize the vintage inventor vibe and the absurdity of believing everything is already invented.'),
 (1953, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Quotes', 'Indeed, history is nothing more than a tableau of crimes and misfortunes.', 'Voltaire', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a grand, old-fashioned museum gallery. In the center, a large, dramatic tableau display is shown—like a classical painted scene or diorama with various historical figures caught in comically exaggerated misfortunes and crimes. For instance, a cartoonish medieval king looks guilty holding a treasure chest, a knight accidentally knocking over a vase, and a philosopher tripping over scrolls. The backdrop is an ornate frame labeled “History: Crimes & Misfortunes.” Visitors, including a few wide-eyed adults and puzzled children, observe the tableau with a mix of amusement and confusion. Add speech bubbles from visitors with light comments like "So history is just a highlight reel of chaos?" The overall art style is lighthearted, bright, and colorful, emphasizing humor without any negativity or violence. The objects to include are old scrolls, broken artifacts, some classical costumes on figures, and museum placards with funny captions.'),
 (1530, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'America is the only country that went from barbarism to decadence without civilization in between.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a timeline-style signpost with three clearly marked stages. On the left side, a rough caveman with a club and animal skin loincloth represents barbarism, standing on a simple dirt patch with a few bones scattered around. In the middle, an empty, barren, desert-like space labeled ''Civilization'' with a single tumbleweed rolling through, emphasizing its absence humorously. On the right side, a wealthy businessman or aristocrat wearing a fancy suit, sunglasses, and holding a champagne glass is lounging decadently on a fancy throne or chaise lounge with gold decorations and jewels, surrounded by items symbolizing luxury like a fine feast, a diamond necklace, and a stack of money. Above the scene, a bold banner reads: ''America''s Unique Journey.'' The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated to highlight the joke, with exaggerated expressions: the caveman looks tough but simple, the empty middle looks comically desolate, and the aristocrat looks smug and overly pampered. The overall tone is playful and satirical, avoiding anything offensive, focusing on the absurdity of skipping an important historical step.'),
 (1751, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Heavier-than-air flying machines are impossible.', 'Lord Kelvin, president, Royal Society, 1895.', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set at the dawn of aviation. Center a frustrated, old-fashioned inventor wearing period clothing (early 1900s) with goggles pushed up on his forehead and a big bushy mustache. He stands next to a ridiculous flying machine made of wooden planks, large feathers, hot air balloons, and flapping wings, clearly absurd and impractical. The flying machine is wobbling precariously, not off the ground. Around him, birds effortlessly soar through the sky, looking down at him quizzically or amused. Add a simple countryside backdrop with a few trees, a barn, and puffy clouds. The inventor holds a clipboard labeled "Flying Machine Test Results" with bold text that reads, "Heavier-than-air flying machines are impossible." Make the overall style light-hearted, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the humor and the old misconception about flight.'),
 (2126, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'My theory of evolution is that Darwin was adopted.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Charles Darwin standing next to a family portrait on a wall. Darwin is depicted as a slightly bewildered Victorian gentleman with a bushy beard and top hat, scratching his head in confusion. The family portrait shows a typical Victorian family with a mother, father, and child, but the child has exaggerated, funny differences (such as unusual features or quirky traits) implying he’s ''different'' from the rest. In the background, a thought bubble above Darwin’s head reads, ''My theory of evolution is that Darwin was adopted.'' The setting is a cozy Victorian study with bookshelves filled with natural history and evolution-related books. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and the absurdity of the idea. The art should have bright colors and clean lines to appeal to a broad audience and enhance the comedic effect without any aggression.'),
 (1842, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'I think there is a world market for maybe five computers.', 'Thomas Watson (1874-1956), Chairman of IBM, 1943', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confident mid-20th-century businessman in a suit and hat, standing at a podium in front of an audience at a trade show or a business conference. He is holding an old-fashioned microphone and gesturing towards a small display table with exactly five vintage computers lined up neatly. The computers look bulky and outdated by modern standards. The audience is a mix of curious and skeptical people dressed in 1950s-style business attire. The backdrop features a banner reading ''World Computer Market Forecast.'' The overall style is colorful and exaggerated with expressive faces, emphasizing the humorous absurdity of the prediction.'),
 (1492, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Quotes, Time Humor', 'According to an old English time unit, a moment is 1 1/2 minutes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a medieval English setting with an old-style clock tower in the background displaying roughly 1:30 on its face. In the foreground, a confused, slightly scruffy medieval man dressed in traditional English peasant clothing holds a large, exaggerated sundial and a scroll labeled ''Old English Time Units.'' He scratches his head with one hand, looking puzzled. Next to him is a comically oversized hourglass with an exaggerated drip indicating about one and a half minutes passing slowly. Small whimsical birds or a cat nearby look equally confused. The sky is bright and cheerful to emphasize light-heartedness. The style should be colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing the archaic concept with a playful tone and exaggeration for humor without any sharp or aggressive elements.'),
 (3121, 'Absurd Humor, History Humor, Unknown', 'Would you believe...the pyramids in Egypt contain enough stone and mortar to construct a wall ten feet high and five feet wide running from New York City to Los Angeles.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a very long, enormous stone wall stretching across a simplified stylized map of the United States from New York City on the east coast all the way to Los Angeles on the west coast. The wall is exactly ten feet high and five feet wide, made of large, irregular pyramid stones with visible mortar between them. In the foreground, a small group of wide-eyed, amazed tourists or archaeologists stand near the start of the wall in New York, pointing and measuring it with oversized rulers or tape measures. The background shows iconic NYC skyscrapers on the east side, a desert with cacti in the middle, and the Hollywood sign in Los Angeles at the west end of the wall. Above, a playful sun wearing sunglasses smiles down on the scene to add a lighthearted cartoon vibe. The overall style is colorful, exaggerated, and whimsical, emphasizing the absurd size and scale of the wall made from pyramid stones. Include humorous signs along the wall like ''Pyramid Stones Wall: 3000 Years in the Making!'''),
 (1991, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'It may be that the race is not always to the swift, nor the battle to the strong - but that is the way to bet.', 'Damon Runyon', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a quaint old-timey race track and a battlefield side by side. On the left, a group of runners lined up for a race; the fastest looking runner is cocky and stretching confidently while a slower runner looks determined but uncertain. Near them, a well-dressed bookie or gambler stands with a big grin, holding a betting slip marked with a dollar sign. On the right side, there’s a battlefield with two soldiers facing off—one muscular and armored, looking strong and confident, and the other smaller but smiling slyly. The same gambler is depicted placing a bet favoring the strong soldier. The background is lighthearted with exaggerated expressions: the gambler elbows the crowd, winkingly suggesting he''s about to make money regardless of the outcome. The art style is colorful, cartoonish with goofy, exaggerated characters. No violence is shown—soldiers just stand ready as if posing for a photo rather than fighting. The setting merges ancient/medieval aesthetics with modern elements (such as the betting slip) to enhance the humor of contrasting old sayings with modern betting culture.'),
 (1690, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Life, Quotes', 'Experience is what allows us to repeat our mistakes, only with more finesse!', 'Derwood Fincher', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person confidently walking on a tightrope stretched between two platforms. The person looks calm and poised, dressed in stereotypical circus attire like a leotard and a small hat. Below the tightrope, there are several broken boards or nets indicating past failed attempts to cross, each labeled with funny signs like ''Mistake #1'', ''Mistake #2'', etc. The tightrope walker is holding a long balancing pole, and there is a small crowd of amusingly exaggerated people on the sidelines watching, some looking worried, others amused. Above the person, a playful banner reads ''Experience: Repeating Mistakes with Finesse''. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of gaining skill by repeating errors but with style.'),
 (1555, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Anyone who has begun to think places some portion of the world in jeopardy.', 'John Dewey', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cartoonish globe personified with wide, worried eyes and a sweating forehead, maybe perched on a stand like a classroom globe. Around the globe, scattered thought bubbles float containing silly, random icons and symbols, like question marks, light bulbs, and confused emojis to represent thinking. Nearby, a simple cartoon character (a generic person with a puzzled expression) taps their chin, looking as if they''ve just started to think deeply. The background is minimal but playful, maybe with a lightbulb over the character’s head flickering on. The overall style should be light and friendly with exaggerated expressions for comic effect, emphasizing the globe''s comedic fear of being ''jeopardized'' by someone thinking.'),
 (1978, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It is human nature to think wisely and act foolishly.', 'Anatole France', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing at a crossroads with two signs. One sign says ''Wise Path,'' and the other says ''Foolish Path.'' The person looks thoughtfully at a large, oversized brain floating above their head, symbolizing ''thinking wisely.'' Meanwhile, their feet are stepping awkwardly and comically onto the ''Foolish Path.'' Around them, silly elements like slipping on a banana peel, a goofy expression on their face, or tripping over a rocking horse emphasize acting foolishly despite the serious thinking. The background is light and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the contrast between wisdom and folly.'),
 (2172, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'One can dream of something more terrible than a hell where one suffers; it''s a hell where one would get bored.', 'Victor Hugo', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person stuck in a dull, endless waiting room as their version of hell. The room is plain and bland, with outdated floral wallpaper, flickering fluorescent lights, and uncomfortable plastic chairs lined up against the walls. The person, looking bored and restless, is sitting slouched with a tired expression, tapping their fingers or yawning. A clock on the wall shows time moving slowly, with exaggeratedly large minute and second hands. A small, uninteresting magazine lies closed and untouched on a side table. Nearby, there''s a calendar with all the days marked ''Boredom.'' To accentuate the humor, a tiny red devil is peeking in through a window, looking surprised or confused that there’s no suffering, just boredom. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and simple lines to emphasize the monotony and tedium of this comedic ''hell.'' No violence or negativity, just a funny take on boredom as a punishment.'),
 (3223, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Psychology Humor, Steven Wright', 'Why do psychics have to ask you for your name', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon showing a psychic sitting at a small foldable table covered with a purple velvet cloth decorated with stars and moons. The psychic is wearing a turban and colorful robes, looking confused and holding a crystal ball that is glowing. In front of the psychic stands a puzzled customer with a skeptical expression, holding out an ID card. Speech bubbles show the psychic saying, ''What''s your name again?'' The background includes typical psychic props like tarot cards, candles, and a hanging crescent moon. The setting is light-hearted and colorful, emphasizing the irony of a psychic needing basic personal information.'),
 (3218, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Puns, Science, Science Humor, Steven Wright', 'The problem with the gene pool is that there is no lifeguard.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a shallow pool labeled ''Gene Pool'' filled with various cartoonish DNA strands shaped like double helices lounging around, some floating on inflatable tubes, others playing or splashing in the water. At the edge of the pool, there is a lifeguard chair with a very bored or missing lifeguard—either an empty chair with the lifeguard whistle hanging unused or a comical character distractedly looking away. Around the pool are playful signs that say ''No Lifeguard on Duty'' and ''Swim at Your Own Risk.'' The background can include an outdoor setting with bright colors and a few trees or bushes, emphasizing a typical pool environment but maintaining the absurdity of DNA strands as pool guests. The style is lighthearted cartoon, with exaggerated expressions on the DNA to give a silly, fun vibe.'),
 (1691, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Quotes', 'Expressing anger is a form of public littering.', 'Willard Gaylin', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a city park with a few people walking by. In the center is a person with an exaggerated angry expression, bright red face, furrowed eyebrows, and steam comically puffing out of their ears. Instead of litter like bottles or wrappers, they are angrily shouting words or symbols (like comic-style speech bubbles with jagged edges, exclamation marks, and cartoonish symbols representing yelling) that litter the air. Nearby, a park trash can has a sign that says ''No Public Littering,'' and a couple of bystanders look on confused or amused. To emphasize the joke, some silly pieces of trash have little faces, reacting to the angry words as if they were real litter. The overall art style should be vibrant, exaggerated, and lighthearted, emphasizing the metaphor of anger as litter without any harsh or violent imagery.'),
 (2366, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Quotes', 'The place where optimism most flourishes is the lunatic asylum.', 'Havelock Ellis', 'A colorful cartoon scene set outside a classic lunatic asylum building with a sign reading ''Lunatic Asylum'' above the door. The building looks welcoming and quirky rather than frightening, with large windows and a few whimsical bushes shaped like smiley faces around it. In the foreground, several cheerful cartoon characters wearing bright, mismatched clothing are happily planting flowers and watering a garden labelled ''Optimism''. Some characters have exaggerated, joyful expressions and playful poses, like giving thumbs up or skipping. Nearby, a shiny bright sunshine with a big smiling face beams down on everyone. The overall tone is lighthearted and humorous, portraying the asylum as a surprisingly upbeat and hopeful place. The style is bright, clean, and exaggerated in a classic humorous cartoon manner.'),
 (1774, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'I always wanted to be the last guy on earth, just to see if all those women were lying to me.', 'Ronnie Shakes', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a lone man standing on a deserted Earth-like landscape, looking puzzled and slightly amused. The man is simple and cartoonish, with exaggerated wide eyes and a hand on his chin, as if thinking. Around him, there are empty city streets, deserted parks, and empty benches, emphasizing the solitude. The sky is clear with a bright sun. In the background, shadowy, ghost-like outlines of many women are floating or fading away, symbolizing the man''s suspicion that they might not have been truthful about something. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions. No violence or offensive content.'),
 (2152, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'Nobody can be exactly like me. Even I have trouble doing it.', 'Tallulah Bankhead', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, cartoonish character looking at their own reflection in a tall, full-length mirror. The character has a slightly puzzled or bemused expression, scratching their head or shrugging, conveying mild confusion and amusement. The reflection in the mirror is identical but subtly exaggerated for comic effect—perhaps the reflection is attempting to mimic the character''s pose but slightly out of sync or awkward. The setting is a simple bedroom or living room with minimal background details, such as a small plant, a picture frame on the wall, and a rug, keeping the focus on the character and their reflection. The overall style is bright, colorful, and lighthearted, with rounded shapes and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the playful nature of the joke without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2462, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Those who flee temptation generally leave a forwarding address.', 'Lane Olinghouse', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person mid-escape from a large, colorful, exaggerated temptation character (like a playful, mischievous figure holding tempting objects such as a giant chocolate bar, shopping bags, or a big slice of cake). The person looks surprised and hurried, glancing back nervously while holding a small suitcase labeled ''Forwarding Address.'' Behind the temptation, a whimsical mailbox stands with the label ''Temptation''s Address'' and a little envelope popping out of it with the words ''Forwarded to...'' The background is simple and bright, with fun, exaggerated expressions on both characters’ faces highlighting the playful tone. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features and vivid colors to emphasize humor rather than realism.'),
 (2592, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Words are, of course, the most powerful drug used by mankind.', 'Rudyard Kipling', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting on a couch with a big, open book in their hands, looking utterly blissed out and relaxed, as if they are getting high. Around their head are classic comic-style wavy lines and little sparkles to suggest a euphoric or dreamy state. The room around them is cozy, with a steaming cup of coffee on a small table nearby and scattered papers with words and letters floating gently in the air. A thought bubble above their head shows tiny pills shaped like letters and words, emphasizing that words are like a powerful drug. The overall vibe is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to underline the joke without any references to real drugs or harmful behavior.'),
 (1870, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'If at first you don''t succeed, change the requirements and declare success', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person sitting at a desk with a big smile, confidently holding up a certificate labeled ''Success!'' In front of them is a whiteboard or flip chart showing a flowchart or checklist with the original, complicated ''Requirements'' crossed out and replaced by much simpler ones, like ''Just show up'' or ''Try once.'' Around the desk are scattered crumpled papers and a frustrated version of the same person in the background, slumped with a failed project. The setting is a casual office or home workspace, with a motivational poster humorously altered to say ''If at first you don''t succeed... just redefine your goals!'' The overall style is light and funny, with exaggerated expressions and a bright color palette to emphasize the comic and positive tone.'),
 (10, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Relatable', 'Whatever it is, I didn''t do it.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring a mischievous-looking character, who is an ordinary person — perhaps a child or a casually dressed adult — standing in the middle of a room that looks slightly chaotic. The room should have a few obvious signs of trouble: a broken vase on the floor, a spilled cup of juice, and a torn book on a table. The character has an innocent, wide-eyed expression and is shrugging their shoulders with palms up in a classic ''I didn''t do it'' pose. Around the character, perhaps a couple of other cartoon characters (like a parent or a pet) look on with skeptical or surprised expressions. The overall tone is light, playful, and non-threatening, emphasizing the humor in the denial despite obvious evidence. Use bright, simple colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (3056, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'I worry no matter how cynical you become, it''s never enough to keep up.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person who looks increasingly exhausted and frazzled. The character should have wild hair, dark circles under their eyes, and a weary expression. Surround the character with various symbolic representations of cynicism: thought bubbles containing sarcastic remarks, gloomy clouds overhead, and a growing stack of newspapers or emails filled with negative headlines. The character is trying desperately to hold onto a long, tangled chain labeled ''Cynicism,'' but the chain keeps growing and pulling them backwards. The background can be a simple cityscape or office setting to suggest everyday life stress. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the never-ending struggle to keep up with negativity in a playful, cartoonish way. Include bright but muted colors to keep it humorous not gloomy.'),
 (3051, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Self-Reflection Humor, Unknown', 'I wish I was deep instead of just macho.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a muscular, macho-looking man standing in front of a mirror. He’s flexing his big muscles proudly but has a thought bubble above his head showing a book, a philosophy symbol (like an ancient scroll or a light bulb), and a deep ocean wave, representing depth of thought. The man’s expression is a mix of confusion and longing. The background should be simple, like a bedroom or gym locker room, with typical macho items like a dumbbell, a protein shake, and a poster of a bodybuilder on the wall. The style should be light and playful, emphasizing the contrast between physical macho appearance and the desire for intellectual or emotional depth without being serious.'),
 (11, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Social Commentary', 'When a bunch of bizarre people get together, how do you think we appear to them, if at all?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of quirky, eccentric-looking people facing each other. On one side, a group of very strange, oddball characters with exaggerated features (wild hairstyles, mismatched clothes, silly expressions) looking puzzled and whispering among themselves. On the other side, another distinct group of equally bizarre and colorful characters mirroring their confusion and curiosity. Between them, a translucent, ghostly outline representing how they might see each other—faint, blurry, and hard to distinguish, as if they barely perceive one another clearly or at all. The background is simple and bright, with exaggerated facial expressions of confusion and curiosity to enhance the comic effect. Include humorous elements like question marks or thought bubbles above their heads to emphasize their mutual bewilderment and the theme of mutual perception.'),
 (3133, 'Absurd Humor, Humor, Unknown', 'You can''t kill yourself by holding your breath.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person sitting calmly with their cheeks puffed out, clearly trying to hold their breath. The person''s eyes are wide and cheeks exaggeratedly swollen, showing the struggle but no harm. Around them, a simple living room setting with a clock showing time passing and a worried friend or pet looking at them with concern. The atmosphere is light-hearted and silly, with cartoonish sweat drops or a bubble above their head showing their effort. The style is colorful and exaggerated to highlight the absurdity of the idea that holding your breath could be deadly, making it clear it''s a playful and non-threatening situation.'),
 (1180, 'Absurd Humor, Insults', 'Keep rolling your eyes. You might just find a brain back there.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person with exaggerated, large eyes rolling upward dramatically. Their eyes are almost popping out comically, and the background is simple and bright to keep focus on the character. Above their head, a small cartoon brain is peeking out from behind the eye socket as if it just appeared when the eyes rolled up. The character has a surprised, slightly confused expression, with their mouth slightly open. Optional props include a speech bubble near them with the caption: ''Keep rolling your eyes. You might just find a brain back there.'' The art style is playful, with bold outlines and bright colors, making the scene feel light, funny, and non-threatening.'),
 (1164, 'Absurd Humor, Insults, Office Humor, Spy Humor', 'As always, should you be caught or killed, the secretary will disavow any knowledge of your existence.', 'Mission Impossible', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classic office environment. In the foreground, a nervous-looking person dressed in business casual stands fumbling with papers at a cluttered desk. Behind the desk is a secretary sitting calmly, wearing glasses and smart attire, holding a phone receiver to her ear with a knowing smirk. The office should have typical objects like a computer, filing cabinets, a nameplate on the desk that reads ''Secretary,'' and a coffee mug. To add humor, include a shadowy figure visible through a slightly open door labeled ''Top Secret'' or ''Confidential,'' hinting at espionage. The overall atmosphere is playful, lighthearted, and reminiscent of spy or secret agent tropes but in a mundane office setting, emphasizing the absurdity of the secretary''s role in disavowing knowledge of the person if they get ''caught or killed.'' The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish with clear expressions to convey the joke visually without violence or serious undertones.'),
 (1211, 'Absurd Humor, Insults, Psychology Humor, Wit', 'You suffer from a deep and abiding delusion of adequacy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing confidently with a smug smile and puffed-out chest, clearly feeling self-satisfied. Opposite them, a professional-looking therapist or psychiatrist sits in an armchair with a clipboard, wearing glasses and a mildly skeptical expression. The setting is a cozy, typical therapist''s office with a potted plant, a small bookshelf filled with psychology books, and a framed diploma on the wall. The person looks completely unaware of their own flaws, radiating misplaced confidence. Include a speech bubble from the therapist saying, ''You suffer from a deep and abiding delusion of adequacy.'' The style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the irony and humor of the statement without being harsh or mean.'),
 (1207, 'Absurd Humor, Insults, Pun, Relatable Humor', 'You are the human equivalent of a participation trophy.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing proudly on a podium labeled ''Participation Only.'' The person looks slightly confused but smiling awkwardly, holding a shiny but modest participation trophy that is noticeably smaller and less impressive than typical champion trophies displayed nearby. Around the podium, there are exaggerated, large, sparkling champion trophies on higher platforms, perhaps with ribbons and stars to emphasize the difference. The background should be a simple award ceremony setting with balloons, a banner saying ''Well Done!'' and an audience clapping politely but without great enthusiasm. The style should be light-hearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the gentle humor of being just a participant rather than a winner.'),
 (1177, 'Absurd Humor, Insults, Relatable', 'Is it possible to be too dumb? I didn''t know that.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a character standing with a confused and slightly clueless expression. The character is scratching their head in puzzlement, eyebrows raised and mouth slightly open as if genuinely surprised. Around the character''s head, cartoonish question marks float to emphasize their confusion. The background is simple and colorful, perhaps a bright sky or a plain room, to keep focus on the character''s expression. Include a speech bubble above the character that reads: "Is it possible to be too dumb? I didn’t know that." Keep the style lighthearted and exaggerated, with soft lines and bright colors to emphasize the comedic and innocent tone of the joke.'),
 (3084, 'Absurd Humor, Insults, Unknown', 'If I ordered a truck load of idiots and then they only delivered you -- I''d still say I got my money''s worth!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a delivery truck parked in front of a house. The truck''s side door is open, showing it is mostly empty except for one surprised-looking person standing inside the truck bed. This person should have a goofy, clueless expression and be scratching their head or looking bewildered. Outside the truck, a cheerful, confident person—the joke''s speaker—is standing with arms crossed and a smirk, as if delivering the punchline. The background should be simple, with a clear blue sky and a suburban house facade. Add a sign on the truck side that reads ''Truckload of Idiots'' in bold, playful letters. The overall tone should be light and silly, emphasizing the comic exaggeration without harshness.'),
 (1167, 'Absurd Humor, Insults, Word Play', 'His ignorance is encyclopedic', 'Abba Eban (1915-)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person proudly holding a giant, thick encyclopedia book titled ''Ignorance'' on the cover. The person is standing in a cozy home library full of bookshelves packed with colorful books. Their facial expression is oblivious but confident, with a slight goofy smile, as if they think they are very knowledgeable. Around them, some books have absurd or humorous titles about nonsense topics, emphasizing the misunderstanding of knowledge. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and rounded shapes to keep the mood playful and silly.'),
 (1204, 'Absurd Humor, Insults, Word Play', 'Way down deep, he''s really shallow.', 'Doug Mackenzie', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a deep-looking well or cave with a small puddle of shallow water at its very bottom. Above it, a character (like a man or woman) peers down into the well with a surprised or confused expression. Around the well or cave opening, include some rocks and a sign reading “Deep Well.” Emphasize the contrast between the tall, long vertical shaft (to suggest depth) and the tiny shallow puddle below, making the joke visual. Use light-hearted, colorful cartoon style with exaggerated features to make the scene funny and clear—no dark or scary elements. Possibly add a thought bubble or caption that reads, “Way down deep, he’s really shallow.” The character could be wearing casual clothes and standing with hands on hips or scratching their head in puzzlement.'),
 (2535, 'Absurd Humor, Internet Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'We''ve all heard that a million monkeys banging on a million typewriters will eventually reproduce the entire works of Shakespeare. Now, thanks to the Internet, we know this is not true.', 'Robert Wilensky', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with a large group of monkeys sitting at typewriters in an old-fashioned office setting. The monkeys look chaotic and distracted as they randomly pound on the keys, papers flying everywhere. In the foreground, show a modern computer screen displaying a typical Internet webpage filled with silly memes, cat videos, and nonsense rather than Shakespeare’s works. Maybe one monkey looks confused while glancing at the computer screen. Include details like scattered banana peels, typewriter paper sheets with gibberish text, and a small sign that says ''Shakespeare Project.'' The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the old idea and the modern absurd reality revealed by the Internet.'),
 (2870, 'Absurd Humor, Invention Humor, Unknown, Vehicles', 'Fortunately, the wheel was invented before the car, otherwise the scraping noise would be terrible.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an old-fashioned wooden wheel lying on the ground with scratch marks beneath it, looking distressed or worried. Nearby, an early car frame without wheels is stuck, scraping along the ground, creating visible cartoon-style ''scraping'' sound lines. The background is simple, perhaps with a surprised caveman or early inventor character scratching their head, looking at the scene. The style is light and playful, with exaggerated expressions and sound effects emphasized for comedy. No violence or any political elements. Bright colors and a cheerful setting.'),
 (3219, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Life, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Steven Wright', 'The sooner you fall behind, the more time you''ll have to catch up.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person running on a race track but intentionally falling behind a group of other runners far ahead. The runner looks relaxed and slightly smug, glancing back over their shoulder at the leading pack. The track curves through a park-like setting with exaggeratedly large clocks on poles spaced along the track, symbolizing time. Near the fallen-behind runner, a large sign reads ''Catch-Up Zone'' with an arrow pointing forward. The other runners look surprised or puzzled by the slow runner’s tactic. The overall tone is lighthearted and comedic, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the irony in the joke.'),
 (2050, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Life, Quotes', 'Life: It''s just like watching T.V. without the T.V.', 'Brooks Peck', 'A cartoon scene showing a person sitting on a couch in a cozy living room, staring blankly into empty space where a TV would normally be. The TV stand is there but the TV screen is missing, replaced by an empty, glowing rectangle or just an empty frame with maybe some dust or cobwebs. The person looks puzzled and slightly bored, maybe with a cup of coffee or remote control in hand, as if expecting the TV to be there but realizing it’s not. Around them are typical living room objects: a lamp, some books on a side table, a plant, and a rug. The style is humorous and light-hearted with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the irony and silliness of "watching TV without the TV." The atmosphere captures the concept of experiencing life passively, like watching TV but having nothing to watch.'),
 (2949, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Music Humor, Unknown', 'How wonderful opera would be if there were no singers.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a grand opera house with an elegant stage set, complete with fancy red curtains, golden chandeliers, and an elaborate backdrop. The stage is completely empty except for a single grand piano or an empty microphone stand. In front of the stage, a diverse audience of cartoons with varied expressions is shown—some looking confused, some looking impressed as if listening. Maybe include a thought bubble from one audience member saying, ''It''s surprisingly wonderful!'' or a speech bubble from the conductor holding a baton looking perplexed but hopeful. The overall scene should evoke the irony and humor of an opera without any singers, focusing on the silent or instrumental-only atmosphere in a grand operatic setting. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish without any people making musical sounds, emphasizing the emptiness or silence where singers would normally be.'),
 (1717, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Give me the luxuries of life and I will willingly do without the necessities.', 'Frank Lloyd Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a well-dressed character lounging luxuriously on a plush, over-the-top velvet chaise lounge with fancy pillows and a champagne glass in hand. Around them, essential everyday items like a small plate of basic food, a glass of water, simple clothing like socks, and a bare light bulb hang forgotten and neglected, indicated by a few dust clouds or cobwebs to show they are being ignored. The character has a smug, content expression, eyes half-closed in exaggerated satisfaction, clearly enjoying the luxuries despite the lack of necessities. The background should be a cozy room with elegant decorations emphasizing luxury but showing the humor in ignoring basics, such as an empty refrigerator or a calendar hanging on the wall with the word "Necessities" crossed out humorously. Cartoon-style exaggeration of comfort and disdain for essentials adds to the comedic effect.'),
 (2398, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The truth is more important than the facts.', 'Frank Lloyd Wright (1868-1959)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a courtroom setting with a judge, jury, and a witness stand. At the witness stand, a character confidently states, "The truth is more important than the facts." The judge looks puzzled, scratching their head with a gavel in hand. The jury members whisper among themselves, some looking confused and others amused. Papers labeled ''Facts'' lie scattered and slightly disorganized on a table, while a big, shining golden trophy labeled ''Truth'' sits prominently on the judge’s bench. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the irony and humor of prioritizing ''truth'' over concrete ''facts.'''),
 (1887, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Political Humor, Quotes', 'If one morning I walked on top of the water across the Potomac River, the headline that afternoon would read: PRESIDENT CAN''T SWIM.', 'Lyndon B. Johnson', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a calm, wide river labeled ''Potomac River''. In the center, a man in a suit (suggesting a president) is confidently walking across the water’s surface, leaving gentle ripples behind him. There should be a surprised group of reporters on the riverbank, holding microphones and cameras, snapping pictures and writing notes. Behind them, a large newspaper stand or billboard displays a bold headline reading ''PRESIDENT CAN''T SWIM'' in capital letters. The setting is lighthearted with bright colors, clear skies, and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor. The style is clean and simple, with caricature-like figures to emphasize the joke’s irony without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (1754, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'Hell is paved with good samaritans.', 'William M. Holden', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a long, winding road labeled ''Hell'' made entirely of flat stones shaped like kind-hearted people wearing ''Good Samaritan'' badges. The road stretches into a fiery background with smiling devils and flames, but the devils look casually relaxed and not threatening. In the foreground, a confused and slightly worried good samaritan character, wearing simple clothes and holding a first aid kit, stands at the start of the road, scratching their head and looking unsure about stepping onto the paved path. The setting includes classic hellish elements like small fire pits and cartoon flames, but everything has a lighthearted style with bright colors and playful expressions, emphasizing the ironic twist of the phrase rather than something scary or dark.'),
 (2351, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'The nice thing about egotists is that they don''t talk about other people.', 'Lucille S. Harper', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters facing each other in a simple living room setting. One character is a large, smiling person dressed flamboyantly with an oversized crown or laurel wreath symbolizing egotism. They have an exaggeratedly large head or a literal speech bubble overflowing with their own portrait or icons representing themselves (like a mirror, a trophy, and a photo of themselves). The second character is a smaller, puzzled-looking person holding a cup of coffee, trying to get a word in but clearly ignored. Around them, no other people are depicted or mentioned, emphasizing that the egotist talks only about themselves. The speech bubbles from the egotist contain only self-related images or words like ''me,'' ''I,'' or caricatures of themselves. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish with playful expressions to highlight the joke’s irony in a lighthearted way.'),
 (1759, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Quotes, Word Play', 'Honor has been the reward for what he gave.', 'Calvin Coolidge', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a medieval knight standing proudly on a small podium labeled ''Honor Award.'' The knight is fully clad in shiny armor and holding a large, ornate treasure chest labeled ''What He Gave.'' Surrounding him are a few slightly confused townsfolk with question marks above their heads. The setting is a quaint village square with a banner overhead reading ''Honor Ceremony.'' The knight looks proud but somewhat puzzled, as if unsure why he''s being rewarded with honor just for giving the treasure chest. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the ironic twist of the joke.'),
 (2315, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Quotes, Workplace', 'The graveyards are full of indispensable men.', 'Charles de Gaulle (1890-1970)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, old-fashioned graveyard with numerous tombstones of varying shapes and sizes scattered over a gently rolling hill. In the foreground, a comically confident man dressed in formal business attire with a big title name tag labeled ''Indispensable'' stands next to a modest fresh grave marked with a tombstone that reads ''Indispensable Man - Here Lies''. Around him, other gravestones have humorous inscriptions like ''Absolutely Essential'' and ''Can''t Be Replaced,'' some with subtle cracks or cartoonish flowers growing over them, showing that even ''indispensable'' people end up here. The sky is bright and cheerful with a few cartoon birds flying by, contributing to the ironic but lighthearted tone. The overall style is colorful, exaggerated cartoon with playful expressions and details that convey the irony of the phrase ''The graveyards are full of indispensable men'' without any gloominess or sadness.'),
 (2837, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Social Humor, Unknown', 'Everybody repeat after me... We are all individuals.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or seminar room. In the center, a cheerful, slightly exaggerated teacher or motivational speaker stands on a small stage or front of the room with a big smile, holding a pointer or microphone, saying, "Everybody repeat after me... We are all individuals." The audience consists of rows of students or attendees who all appear exactly identical — same facial expressions, clothes, hairstyles, and posture — emphasizing the irony. Maybe give them blank or robotic expressions as they obediently repeat the phrase in unison. Include typical classroom elements like desks, a whiteboard behind the teacher with the phrase "We are all individuals" written on it, and posters on the wall about individuality or teamwork. The overall style should be colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated features to enhance the humor and irony of everyone looking the same while claiming to be unique.'),
 (2859, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Social Humor, Unknown', 'Fight like hell for pacifism', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a peaceful protest for pacifism. In the center, a group of cheerful protesters hold signs with messages like ''End War!'' and ''Peace Now!''. However, instead of gentle behavior, they look intensely determined, as if gearing up for a fierce battle. Their exaggerated angry facial expressions contrast comically with their peaceful cause. One person is dramatically pumping their fist in the air, another is shouting passionately, while a third clenches their teeth, all showing intense energy despite advocating nonviolence. The background shows a sunny park setting with a peaceful vibe, birds flying in the sky, and a few confused onlookers watching the ironically intense demonstration. The overall style is bright, colorful, and playful with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the contradiction of fighting hard for peace.'),
 (2917, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Unknown', 'He who dies with the most toys, is, nonetheless, still dead.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, cozy living room filled with piles of colorful toys—action figures, remote control cars, board games, and stuffed animals—scattered everywhere. In the center lies a simple, peaceful grave marked by a tombstone that reads: ''He who dies with the most toys.'' Above the tombstone is a small ghost or spirit character with a playful smile, shrugging as if saying ''But still dead.'' The background includes a window with bright daylight, indicating life goes on outside, contrasting with the grave in the room cluttered with toys. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors, highlighting the ironic humor of having many toys but the inevitable fate of death.'),
 (2932, 'Absurd Humor, Irony, Unknown', 'Honk if you love peace and quiet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a busy city street filled with many cars. Each car has a large, colorful speech bubble above it shouting ''Honk!'' The scene is lively and slightly chaotic with exaggerated expressions on drivers'' faces, all eagerly pressing their car horns. In the foreground, a calm and serene person stands on the sidewalk holding a sign that reads ''Peace and Quiet.'' This person looks confused and frustrated while surrounded by the loud honking. The background features cartoonish buildings, streetlights, and trees, emphasizing an ironic clash between the desire for silence and the noisy environment.'),
 (2645, 'Absurd Humor, Island Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'A ship sailing past a remote island spots a man who has been stranded there for several years. The captain goes ashore to rescue the man and notices three huts. ''What’s the first hut for?'' he asks. ''That’s my house,'' says the castaway. ''What’s the second hut for?'' ''That’s my church.'' ''And the third hut?'' ''Oh, that?'' sniffs the castaway. ''That’s the church I used to go to.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tropical remote island with three small, simple huts lined up along the shore. A large wooden sailing ship is anchored nearby, with the ship''s captain—a friendly-looking man in a naval uniform—standing on the beach, talking to a scruffy castaway man wearing tattered clothes and a scraggly beard. The castaway points to the three huts: the first hut looks like a humble living home with a small door and a chimney; the second hut has a simple cross on its roof, indicating a church; the third hut is dilapidated, with a faded and broken sign reading ''Church''. The castaway has a wistful, slightly sad expression as he refers to the third hut, while the captain looks curious but amused. Palm trees, a sunny sky, and some birds can be in the background to enhance the island setting. The drawing style should be colorful and cartoony, emphasizing the lighthearted and ironic tone of the joke without any harsh or dark elements.'),
 (2238, 'Absurd Humor, Kids Humor, Motivational Humor, Quotes', 'So be sure when you step, step with care and great tact, and remember that life''s a great balancing act and will you succeed? Yes! You will indeed (98 and ¾ percent guaranteed). Kid, you''ll move mountains.', 'Dr. Seuss', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful young child confidently stepping onto a large, wobbly tightrope stretched high over a lively landscape. The child is wearing bright clothes and balancing carefully with exaggeratedly wide arms. Below the tightrope, a whimsical background of rolling hills, mountains, and small cheering animals like birds and squirrels adds to the uplifting mood. A friendly old owl in spectacles stands nearby on a tree branch, holding a scroll that reads ''98 and 3/4% guaranteed!'' The scene emphasizes balance and care with a playful vibe, and a large banner overhead reads, ''Life’s a great balancing act!'' The overall tone is positive and inspiring, with cartoon-style exaggerated proportions and expressive faces to convey humor and encouragement without any violence or controversy.'),
 (2929, 'Absurd Humor, Kids Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'Hey, you kids! Keep out of that Jello tree!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a group of curious kids gathered around a peculiar tree in a backyard. The tree''s branches are covered with dripping, shiny, wobbly jello molds in various bright colors instead of leaves or fruit. One of the kids is reaching out tentatively to touch a jello blob hanging from a branch. Nearby, an older person, possibly a parent or a grandparent, is standing with arms crossed and a playful yet stern expression, pointing at the tree while saying the phrase. The setting includes a sunny day with a simple fence and a few garden items like a watering can or a flower pot in the background. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the absurdity of a ''Jello tree.'' The tree should look like an ordinary fruit tree in shape but replaced by jello lumps to create the humor.'),
 (2077, 'Absurd Humor, Language, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Man invented language to satisfy his deep need to complain.', 'Lily Tomlin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a caveman standing next to a large stone tablet with primitive drawings and early alphabet letters. The caveman looks slightly frustrated or exasperated, holding a speech bubble that says something like, ''Ugh! Too many things to complain about!'' Around him are humorous objects to symbolize complaints: a crooked spear, a small fire that''s barely lit, a crooked cave drawing, and a dinosaur with a funny annoyed expression. The setting is a prehistoric cave with simple art style, exaggerated expressions, and lighthearted tone, emphasizing the idea that language was invented as a tool to express grumbling or complaints.'),
 (1482, 'Absurd Humor, Language, Quotes, Word Play', 'AAAAA -- American Association Against Acronym Abuse.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a group of people at a conference or meeting room, with a large banner overhead reading ''AAAAA - American Association Against Acronym Abuse.'' The characters look comically overwhelmed and confused, some scratching their heads or staring at stacks of papers and documents filled with acronyms. One person is holding a giant magnifying glass trying to decipher a note filled with absurdly long and complicated acronyms. The setting should include a table with name tags, coffee cups, and a flip chart displaying various confusing acronyms. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony of an organization that itself has a lengthy acronym fighting acronym abuse, making it visually funny and ironic without any harmful or sensitive content.'),
 (2525, 'Absurd Humor, Language, Quotes, Word Play', 'We made too many wrong mistakes.', 'Yogi Berra', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two people standing in front of a large whiteboard or chalkboard filled with scribbles, crossed-out words, and arrows pointing in every direction. Both characters look confused and slightly frustrated but with exaggerated, silly expressions. One person is holding a big eraser or a marker in mid-air as if about to fix something, while the other has their hands on their head in disbelief. Around them are crumpled up papers littering the floor showing repeated failed attempts. The whiteboard has the phrase ''Too many wrong mistakes'' written prominently in a messy, almost nonsensical way to highlight the joke. The setting is a casual office or classroom with a desk, a chair pushed aside, and some humorous details like a coffee cup tipping over or a clock showing an odd time to emphasize the chaotic but lighthearted vibe. Use bright colors and exaggerated cartoon style to enhance the humor, keeping it friendly and relatable without any aggressive elements.'),
 (2664, 'Absurd Humor, Language, Unknown', 'Back when I was a kid there were only 25 letters in the alphabet (ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXZ). Nobody knew why.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene shows a nostalgic child sitting at an old-fashioned school desk, looking puzzled. On the wall behind is a large, colorful alphabet chart with letters A to Z, but the letter Y is clearly missing — instead, there''s a big question mark in its place. The child scratches their head in confusion. Around the classroom, curious kids whisper and point at the chart, casting wondering glances. A teacher stands nearby with a shrugging expression, holding a pointer stick but looking equally baffled. The classroom has classic elements: a globe, a chalkboard with scribbles, and scattered papers. The mood is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing innocent confusion about the missing letter Y in the alphabet. The art style is bright and cartoony, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight curiosity and mystification.'),
 (2925, 'Absurd Humor, Language, Unknown, Word Play', 'Help stamp out, eliminate and abolish redundancy!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly exaggerated activist or campaigner standing on a small stage with a big banner behind them. The banner reads: "Help stamp out, eliminate and abolish redundancy!" The character is holding a large red stamp labeled "REDUNDANT!" The stage is decorated with redundant posters featuring the same phrase repeated multiple times. The background has a crowd of confused yet amused people scratching their heads, with speech bubbles showing phrases like "Did they say that twice?" and "Isn''t that redundant?" The overall style is bright, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the irony of the over-the-top wording of the message. The setting is a public rally or event, with some funny details like a microphone and paperwork with additional obvious redundant phrases scattered on a table.'),
 (2376, 'Absurd Humor, Legal Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The right to swing my fist ends where the other man''s nose begins.', 'Oliver Wendell Holmes (1841-1935)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two men standing face to face. The man on the left is swinging his fist mid-air with an exaggerated motion, looking a bit oblivious and cheerful. The man on the right has his nose prominently sticking out, just at the very edge where the fist is about to make contact, with a surprised or slightly alarmed expression. Between them is a dotted line or a subtle visual marker indicating a boundary that separates the fist''s reach from the nose, emphasizing the phrase ''the right to swing my fist ends where the other man''s nose begins.'' The background is simple, maybe a park or street setting, and the characters are drawn in bright, cheerful colors with exaggerated cartoonish facial features to highlight the humor and avoid any sense of violence. The overall style is light-hearted and fun.'),
 (2044, 'Absurd Humor, Life, Metaphor Humor, Quotes', 'Life is like licking honey from a thorn.', 'M. Froese', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person trying to lick a large, golden honeycomb shaped like a dripping honey jar, but the honeycomb is mounted on a big, very visible thorny branch. The person is leaning forward with their tongue out, eyes squinting in effort and slight discomfort. The thorny branch has exaggerated, large sharp thorns. Around the person are little dripping honey drops and a few bees buzzing nearby looking amused or playful. The background is simple and cheerful, emphasizing the silliness of trying to enjoy something sweet but painful at the same time. The style should be colorful and exaggerated, with cartoonish expressions and clear focus on the contrast between the delicious honey and dangerous thorn.'),
 (2819, 'Absurd Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Either I''m going to live forever or I''m not. And either way, I''ll be very surprised.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a thoughtful person standing at a crossroads outdoors under a bright blue sky with fluffy clouds. The person is middle-aged with a puzzled but amused expression, scratching their head or stroking their chin as if deep in thought. To their left, depict a signpost pointing towards ''Live Forever,'' with a whimsical, glowing path or sparkles leading into a distant horizon. To their right, another signpost points towards ''Not Live Forever,'' leading to a normal, everyday path lined with flowers and a bench. The background shows a mix of absurd elements like a cartoon-style hourglass with sand flowing both up and down, symbolizing time uncertainty. The style should be simple, colorful, and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial features to emphasize the surprised and contemplative mood. No dark or violent elements, focusing on the paradox and humor of the statement about life expectancy and surprise no matter what.'),
 (1831, 'Absurd Humor, Life, Quotes', 'I never resist temptation, because I have found that things that are bad for me do not tempt me.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, confident person standing with arms crossed and a smile, reflecting a lighthearted ''life philosophy.'' Around the individual are floating thought bubbles containing tempting but clearly unhealthy food and objects, such as a slice of cake, a donut, a smoking cigarette, and a video game controller. However, each tempting item has a red ''X'' or a faded, ghostly look to show they do not actually lure the person. The setting is bright and simple, perhaps a park or a cozy living room to keep the mood light and relatable. The character''s body language and facial expression should convey both amusement and contentment, emphasizing the ironic humor that harmful things do not tempt them at all. The style is playful, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and simple shapes to underline the joke’s witty tone without any negativity.'),
 (2607, 'Absurd Humor, Life, Quotes', 'You got to be careful if you don''t know where you''re going, because you might not get there.', 'Yogi Berra', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused character standing at a crossroads with multiple street signs pointing in different directions. The character looks puzzled, scratching their head, and holding a map upside down. Some signs say ambiguous things like ''This Way?'', ''That Way?'', and ''Who Knows?''. In the background, a whimsical winding path leads off into a vague, cloudy horizon, implying uncertainty about the destination. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and simple shapes, emphasizing the character''s confusion and the irony of not knowing where they''re going while trying to travel.'),
 (3014, 'Absurd Humor, Life, Unknown', 'I like life. It''s something to do.', NULL, 'Draw a simple, humorous cartoon scene featuring a relaxed character sitting on a comfy armchair with a content smile, enjoying a cup of coffee or tea. The background is minimal but cheerful, maybe a window showing a sunny day outside. Around the character, place various casual leisure items like a book, a newspaper, a TV remote, and a potted plant to emphasize the ordinary, everyday nature of ''life.'' The character should appear calm and thoughtful, conveying the idea that life is just a pleasant way to pass time rather than something complicated or stressful. Use soft colors and a lighthearted style to create a feel-good vibe without any tension or drama.'),
 (3068, 'Absurd Humor, Life, Unknown', 'If all else fails, lower your standards.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing proudly with their arms crossed in front of a large wooden signpost labeled ''Standards.'' The signpost is adjustable like a height measuring stick, with multiple levels marked ''High,'' ''Medium,'' and ''Low.'' The person is happily turning a big, comically oversized lever attached to the signpost, causing the ''Standards'' marker to drop from ''High'' to ''Low.'' Nearby, a small crowd of amusingly surprised onlookers watches this action, some looking confused, others smirking. The setting is a sunny, outdoor park-like area with cartoon-style trees and bushes. Include a humorous speech bubble above the person saying, ''If all else fails...'' and a smaller bubble near the lever saying, ''Lower your standards!'' The overall style should be lighthearted and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s meaning about adjusting expectations downward as a last resort.'),
 (2296, 'Absurd Humor, Literary Humor, Quotes', 'The difference between fiction and reality? Fiction has to make sense.', 'Tom Clancy', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two contrasting panels side by side. The left panel is labeled ''Fiction'' and depicts a tidy, well-organized library or a cozy reading nook with an open book, a character sitting comfortably and enjoying the story, with a calm, logical, and neat environment. The right panel is labeled ''Reality'' and shows a chaotic everyday scene with random absurd elements – for example, a person slipping on a banana peel, a cat knocking over a plant, a spilled coffee cup, and papers flying everywhere. The reality side should look messy, confusing, and unpredictable, highlighting how reality doesn’t always ''make sense.'' Both panels have a cartoonish style with exaggerated expressions: the character in fiction is calm and happy, while the character in reality looks bewildered or overwhelmed. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated features to emphasize the humor in the contrast between fiction’s order and reality’s disorder.'),
 (1931, 'Absurd Humor, Literary Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I''m not going to get into the ring with Tolstoy.', 'Ernest Hemingway (1899-1961)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small boxing ring set up in a cozy, old-fashioned library. In the ring, a nervous-looking stick figure or simple cartoon character, dressed in casual clothes with boxing gloves, is hesitating at the ropes. Opposite them is a large, anthropomorphic book with a stern face, arms, and boxing gloves, labeled ''Tolstoy''. The background shows tall bookshelves filled with classic novels and Russian literature, and there might be a small audience of various famous literary characters watching and whispering. The overall vibe is light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the silliness of boxing a famous author or his book. The style should be colorful, clear, and exaggerated to enhance the absurdity and wit behind the pun on ''getting into the ring'' with Tolstoy, mixing literature and fighting imagery.'),
 (2361, 'Absurd Humor, Logic Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The opposite of a correct statement is a false statement. The opposite of a profound truth may well be another profound truth.', 'Niels Bohr (1885-1962)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy study filled with books and an oversized globe. At the center, a thoughtful-looking philosopher character with a large beard and round glasses sits in an armchair, stroking their chin. Above their head are two large, floating speech bubbles. The first bubble shows a simple green checkmark with the words ''Correct Statement,'' and the second bubble shows a big red X with the words ''False Statement.'' Slightly off to the side, another speech bubble depicts a sparkly star with the words ''Profound Truth,'' and next to it, another identical bubble also labeled ''Profound Truth,'' emphasizing the contradiction humorously. The philosopher looks both puzzled and amused, holding a steaming cup of tea. The room has quirky details like a cat staring curiously at the bubbles and a blackboard behind the philosopher covered with scribbles of logic symbols and paradox signs. The entire scene is drawn with exaggerated expressions and cartoonish proportions to keep it light and funny.'),
 (2601, 'Absurd Humor, Logic Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'You can only find truth with logic if you have already found truth without it.', 'G.K. Chesterton', 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters engaged in a playful debate. One character, looking thoughtful and dressed in classic philosopher attire (robes, laurel wreath), holds an ancient scroll labeled ''Truth without Logic.'' The other character, wearing a modern suit and glasses, holds a large magnifying glass inspecting a book titled ''Logic.'' They stand on opposite sides of a seesaw balanced on a large question mark. Above their heads are floating light bulbs—one dim and irregular (representing intuition), and one bright and geometric (representing logic). The background features a whimsical library with books labeled ''Philosophy,'' ''Reason,'' and ''Mystery.'' Both characters have exaggerated, cartoonish expressions of eager curiosity and mild frustration. The style should be light, playful, and not too serious, emphasizing the funny paradox of needing to have found truth before using logic to find it again.'),
 (2086, 'Absurd Humor, Marriage Humor, Quotes', 'Marriage is a lottery, but you can''t tear up your ticket if you lose.', 'F. M. Knowles', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a couple standing side by side. The man is holding a large lottery ticket labeled ''Marriage Lottery.'' He looks worried and a bit regretful, glancing at the ticket. The woman stands next to him with a calm but slightly amused expression. The background is a simple living room with a cozy couch and a small table showing a photo frame of the couple''s wedding day. On the wall behind them is a calendar marked with a heart on the wedding date. The lottery ticket is oversized and brightly colored, with no option to tear it as a ''no tearing'' icon is clearly displayed on it. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoony, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and irony of being stuck with the ''ticket.'''),
 (2090, 'Absurd Humor, Marriage Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Marriage must incessantly contend with a monster that devours everything: familiarity.', 'Honore de Balzac (1799-1850)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a married couple standing side by side in their living room looking tired but amused. Between them is a large, friendly-looking cartoon monster with big eyes and a huge mouth wide open, as if about to ''devour'' items floating in the air around them. The items include a calendar, a clock, a photo album, a coffee cup, and a couple of everyday objects like a TV remote and a pair of slippers, symbolizing the passing of time and daily routines eaten up by familiarity. The room is cozy and somewhat cluttered to suggest everyday life, with a couch, a lamp, and framed pictures on the wall. The monster should look more comical and less scary, emphasizing the metaphor rather than fear. Both characters appear to acknowledge the monster with a knowing smile, showing an affectionate but resigned acceptance of the challenge marriage faces with familiarity. The overall tone is light, warm, and witty.'),
 (1590, 'Absurd Humor, Marriage Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Bigamy is having one wife too many.  Monogamy is the same.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two wedding ceremonies side by side, sharing the same area. In the foreground, a nervous man in a tuxedo stands awkwardly between two brides, each wearing a classic white wedding dress and holding bouquets. Both brides look equally confident and slightly amused, while the man looks confused and overwhelmed, scratching his head. Behind them is a simple arch decorated with flowers and a banner that says ''Wedding Day.'' Nearby, a small, chuckling character (like a wedding officiant or guest) holds a scroll labeled ''Marriage Definitions'' with the words ''Bigamy'' and ''Monogamy'' humorously underlined. The overall tone is light-hearted and cartoonish, with vibrant colors and exaggerated facial expressions that emphasize the man’s predicament and the joke’s punchline, without any violence or negativity.'),
 (3215, 'Absurd Humor, Medical Humor, Steven Wright', 'The colder the x-ray table, the more of your body is required to be on it.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a brightly lit doctor''s office with a very cold-looking x-ray table covered in frosty ice crystals and snowflakes visibly forming on its surface. A patient, wrapped in a blanket but still shivering with exaggerated chattering teeth and goosebumps, is trying to lay on the table. The patient looks confused and uncomfortable, with arms and legs awkwardly stretched out to avoid contact. The doctor, wearing a white coat and a playful smile, is pointing at the table and holding a clipboard. A thermometer with a low temperature reading hangs nearby. Include some silly visual cues like ice cubes around the table legs and frosty breath coming from the patient’s mouth. The overall style should be colorful, cartoonish, and exaggerated to enhance the humor without any scary or serious undertones.'),
 (2283, 'Absurd Humor, Medieval Humor, Quotes, Safety Humor', 'The best armor is to keep out of range.', 'Italian Proverb', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small medieval knight in full armor standing at a safe distance away from a giant catapult that is lazily loaded with a huge rock. The knight has a confident, smug expression, arms crossed, clearly avoiding any danger by staying well outside the catapult''s throwing radius. Around them is a simple castle wall backdrop, with the catapult on one side waiting to launch and some birds taking flight in the background to add an animated feel. The knight''s speech bubble says, ''The best armor is to keep out of range,'' emphasizing the joke about avoiding combat rather than wearing heavy armor. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with rounded shapes, bright colors, and playful expressions to keep the tone fun and family-friendly.'),
 (2178, 'Absurd Humor, Mental Health Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'One of the symptoms of an approaching nervous breakdown is the belief that one''s work is terribly important.', 'Bertrand Russell (1872-1970)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stressed-out office worker at their cluttered desk. The worker has wide, frazzled eyes and messy hair, frantically typing on a computer keyboard. Papers and sticky notes are scattered everywhere, with some pinned up on a bulletin board behind them, all emphasizing urgency and importance. Above the worker’s head, a thought bubble shows a cartoonish, oversized alarm clock and a pile of work labeled "VERY IMPORTANT." In the background, a calendar with multiple deadlines circled in red is visible. The overall atmosphere conveys anxiety but in a comical, exaggerated way, highlighting the worker''s overblown sense of the importance of their work. The colors should be bright and the style cartoony and lighthearted to enhance the humor without any harsh tones or violence.'),
 (2788, 'Absurd Humor, Mental Health Humor, Unknown', 'Don''t bother walking a mile in my shoes. That would be boring. Spend 30 seconds in my head. That''ll freak you right out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a pair of ordinary shoes sitting quietly on the floor, looking calm and uninteresting with a small yawn or sleepy eyes to convey ''boring.'' Next to the shoes, a large thought bubble rises above a cartoon person’s head. Inside the thought bubble is a wild, chaotic mental scene illustrating an overwhelmed mind: swirling colorful spirals, random objects like clocks, question marks, light bulbs, and little cartoon monsters or crazed faces showing confusion or stress. The person looks wide-eyed and frazzled, with wild hair and sweat drops flying off their face to show how intense and freaky their thoughts are. The background is simple and light to keep focus on the contrast between the peaceful shoes and the hectic mind. The overall style is friendly and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon expressions for comedic effect.'),
 (2492, 'Absurd Humor, Military Humor, Quotes', 'Try to look unimportant; they may be low on ammo.', 'US Army Infantry Journal', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a playful, exaggerated war zone. In the center, a small, scruffy soldier wearing an oversized helmet and baggy uniform is crouching behind a tiny, flimsy barricade made of barrels and wooden crates. The soldier looks nervous but is deliberately trying to blend into the background by adopting a slouched, unassuming pose. Nearby, a group of tough-looking soldiers with serious expressions and lots of exaggerated ammunition belts and big guns are peeking cautiously around corners, apparently uneasy because their ammo boxes near them are almost empty, with scattered bullets and empty clips visible. In the background, cartoonish explosions and smoke clouds rise from behind more barricades, emphasizing a comical and lighthearted battle. The overall atmosphere is playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions showing both anxiety and hope. The setting should include military-themed props like sandbags, a battlefield sign, and a dusty environment to make the situation clear, but everything should be lighthearted and non-threatening.'),
 (2137, 'Absurd Humor, Military Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'Never tell the Platoon Sergeant you have nothing to do.', ' Marine Corps Recruit', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set inside a military barracks. Show a nervous-looking young soldier standing stiffly at attention in front of a stern, no-nonsense platoon sergeant. The sergeant should be much larger, wearing a uniform with a serious expression, arms crossed or pointing accusingly. Around them, show typical military details like bunk beds, lockers, and a wall clock. Include a speech bubble from the soldier saying, ''I have nothing to do,'' and an obvious thought bubble above the sergeant''s head with a mischievous or menacing grin, hinting he is about to give the soldier a difficult task. The style should be cartoonish and lighthearted, emphasizing the humorous dynamic of a soldier foolishly admitting boredom to a strict supervisor without any violence or harshness.'),
 (3145, 'Absurd Humor, Military Humor, Science Fiction Humor, Unknown', 'You know, just once, I''d like to meet an alien menace that wasn''t immune to bullets!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a sci-fi desert battleground. In the foreground, a confident human soldier wearing casual military gear is holding a smoking gun, looking frustrated but hopeful. Around him on the ground are several strange-looking, cartoonish aliens with exaggerated features—big eyes, antennae, and unusual shapes—but they all appear unharmed, some shrugging or smirking as if bullets just bounce off them. In the background, a flying saucer hovers ominously, casting a shadow. The sky is bright with a few fluffy clouds. A signpost nearby reads ''Alien Shooting Range: Immune Targets Only!'' The overall tone is lighthearted and comical, with expressive character faces emphasizing the soldier’s playful exasperation and very resilient aliens'' smug attitudes.'),
 (1894, 'Absurd Humor, Money Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'If women didn''t exist, all the money in the world would have no meaning.', 'Aristotle Onassis (1906-1975)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, overflowing treasure chest filled with coins and bills in the center of the image. The chest is surrounded by confused, cartoonish characters (both men and women), looking puzzled and scratching their heads as they stare at the money. In the background, a big question mark hovers above the treasure chest. The scene should look lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions of bewilderment and contemplation. Include a speech bubble from one character saying, ''What’s the point without women?'' The style is colorful, simple, and exaggerated, typical of a funny comic strip without violence or offense.'),
 (1699, 'Absurd Humor, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'For every one of us, living in this world means waiting for our end. Let whoever can win glory before death. When a warrior is gone, that will be his best and only bulwark.', 'Beowulf', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an ancient battlefield at sunset. In the foreground, a cartoonish, proud warrior in shiny but slightly oversized armor stands heroically on a small hill. He is holding a comically large, exaggerated shield labeled ''Bulwark,'' looking determined and somewhat smug. Behind him, a few exhausted, less glamorous warriors slump on the ground, looking tired and confused. The background shows scattered swords, shields, and a humorous ''waiting line'' made of skeletons with clocks on them, symbolizing waiting for the end. The sky is a blend of warm sunset colors, and a banner flies above with the phrase ''Win Glory Before Death!'' in playful, medieval-style lettering. The overall mood is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the concept of living life waiting for an end but striving for glory in a fun and imaginative way.'),
 (1592, 'Absurd Humor, Movie Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Boy: ''Do not try and bend the spoon. That''s impossible. Instead... only try to realize the truth.  There is no spoon.'' Neo: ''There is no spoon?''  Boy: ''Then you''ll see, that it is not the spoon that bends, it is only yourself.''', 'The Matrix', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inspired by a famous movie moment. Show two young boys sitting at a small table in a minimalist, slightly futuristic room. One boy is holding an imaginary spoon delicately with his fingers, concentrating deeply with a wise and calm expression. The other boy looks surprised and curious, leaning forward slightly with wide eyes and raised eyebrows. The table should have a simple, shiny spoon hovering in midair near the first boy’s hand, but the spoon is obviously bending in a wavy impossible way, as if it''s melting or bending like rubber. Around them, faint sparkles or shimmer lines can emphasize the magical or mental nature of the moment. The background is plain but subtle futuristic elements like soft glowing panels or a faint digital grid can be included. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and clean lines to emphasize the humor and the surreal concept of ''there is no spoon'' bending itself, only the mind perceiving it bending.'),
 (2807, 'Absurd Humor, Music Humor, Nostalgia, Unknown', 'Doo-wah-ditty-ditty-dum-ditty-doo.  They sure don''t write songs like that anymore!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an old-timey musician sitting on a wooden stool, playing a vintage guitar with exaggerated enthusiasm. Musical notes float above his head, cartoonishly styled as quirky, nonsensical squiggles and symbols representing the silly "doo-wah-ditty-ditty-dum-ditty-doo" sounds. The musician is dressed in retro clothes—perhaps suspenders and a bowler hat—to suggest a nostalgic vibe. Around him, a small audience of diverse, modern-looking people with puzzled or amused expressions watches, suggesting the old tune is unusual by today''s standards. The background can be a cozy, small-town music hall or a simple living room with a record player and some classic music posters on the wall, reinforcing the nostalgic contrast. The overall tone of the illustration should be lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the funny absurdity of the silly tune and the comment "They sure don''t write songs like that anymore!" in a speech bubble from the musician or an observer.'),
 (1908, 'Absurd Humor, Music Humor, Quotes', 'If you only had a brain - de doo de doo de dooooooo.', 'The Wizard of Oz', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, anthropomorphic brain character standing center stage, singing joyfully with musical notes floating around it. The brain should have a wide smile, eyes closed in happiness, and tiny arms holding a microphone like a singer. Surround the brain with a whimsical, colorful background that hints at a lighthearted musical performance. Add a few simple instruments like a drum set, guitar, or keyboard in the background to suggest a band. Include a musical score or lyrics floating in the air above or beside the brain that says: ''If you only had a brain - de doo de doo de dooooooo.'' The overall style should be playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated features and bright colors, emphasizing fun and silliness rather than realism or complexity.'),
 (12, 'Absurd Humor, Music Humor, Relatable', 'What happens when you play a Country & Western album backwards? Your spouse comes back, your pickup truck starts, you get out of jail and you sober up.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene centered around a vintage record player with a Country & Western album spinning backwards. Nearby, show a joyful person with a big smile reunited with their happy spouse who is arriving with open arms. Include a classic pickup truck with its headlights on and smoke coming from the exhaust, indicating it just started. In the background, add a simple jail cell door swinging open with cartoon hands waving goodbye. Also show the same person holding a clear water bottle or coffee cup, looking alert and refreshed to represent sobering up. The overall atmosphere is lighthearted and positive, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the absurdity of these unlikely good events happening simultaneously. Keep the style playful and cartoonish with clean lines and simple backgrounds so all elements stand out clearly as part of the joke''s visual punchline.'),
 (1615, 'Absurd Humor, Nature Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Death is a low chemical trick played on everybody except sequoia trees.', 'J. J. Furnas', 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene featuring a giant, ancient sequoia tree standing tall and proud in the center of a lush forest. The tree has a wise, smiling face with eyes and a mouth, giving it a lively, characterful personality. Around the sequoia, various smaller plants and flowers look lively but slightly wilted or fading, symbolizing death''s effect on most living things. Above them hovers a small, cheeky cartoon depiction of ''Death'' as a harmless, mischievous chemical flask or atom wearing a jester hat, playfully trying to reach the plants but visibly bouncing off the sequoia''s bark like a magical shield. The background should be bright and colorful to keep the tone light and humorous. Include subtle visual elements like small glowing sparkles or magic dust around the sequoia to emphasize its immunity to ''Death.'' The style should be cartoonish and funny, with exaggerated features and expressions to convey the joke''s playful take on death and eternal life in sequoia trees.'),
 (2221, 'Absurd Humor, Nature Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Remember that the most beautiful things in the world are the most useless; peacocks and lilies, for example.', 'John Ruskin', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene outdoors during a sunny day. On one side, a proud peacock stands tall, flaunting its magnificent, vibrant tail feathers fully fanned out, with exaggerated sparkle effects to emphasize its beauty. Nearby, a delicate lily with large, elegant petals blooms on a slender stem, surrounded by a few other simple flowers to provide context. In the background, a curious little person (perhaps a child or cartoon character) looks puzzled or amused, scratching their head as they gaze at these two objects. The setting is a simple garden or park with soft green grass and a few whimsical clouds in the sky. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated features to emphasize the ''useless but beautiful'' concept, like the peacock’s overly extravagant feathers and the lily’s pristine petals gleaming in the sunlight. No text bubbles needed, just the visual setup conveying the idea of beauty without practical use in a fun, animated style.'),
 (2130, 'Absurd Humor, Nature Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Nature abhors a hero. For one thing, he violates the law of conservation of energy. For another, how can it be the survival of the fittest when the fittest keeps putting himself in situations where he is most likely to be creamed?', 'Solomon Short', 'A humorous cartoon set in a lively natural environment like a forest clearing with green trees and bushes. In the center is a character portrayed as a heroic adventurer wearing a cape and a helmet, looking a bit disheveled but determined. Around him are various exaggerated traps or dangerous obstacles such as wild animals with puzzled expressions, a large rolling boulder about to chase him, and broken branches snapping under his feet. Nearby animals (a deer, a rabbit, and a bird) watch the scene with cheeky smirks or raised eyebrows, illustrating the irony. A small diagram or signpost in the background humorously reads ''Law of Conservation of Energy'' with a puzzled symbol, underlining the joke. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the hero repeatedly jumping into danger despite nature’s logic against it.'),
 (13, 'Absurd Humor, Nature Humor, Workplace', 'When you''re up to your hips in alligators, you forget the original project was to drain the swamp.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a swamp with murky water up to a man''s hips. The man looks overwhelmed and frazzled, half-submerged among a comically large number of friendly-looking alligators that surround him, some poking their heads out of the water near his arms and legs. The man wears casual outdoor clothing—shorts and a shirt—stained with mud, holding a simple, dripping bucket labeled ''Swamp Drain Project'' loosely in one hand, forgotten. In the background, the swamp is dense with exaggerated reeds, cattails, and a funny sign stuck in the mud that reads ''Drain the Swamp!'' The overall tone is light and silly, with exaggerated expressions on the man and cartoonish, slightly goofy alligators to emphasize the man''s distraction and predicament. Bright colors and clear lines define the characters and setting in a playful style suitable for family-friendly cartoons.'),
 (2811, 'Absurd Humor, Occupational Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Drilling for oil is boring.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a bored-looking worker at an oil drilling site. The setting is a simple desert-like area with a large, classic oil derrick rig in the background. The worker, wearing a hard hat and safety vest, is sitting on a crate next to the drill, yawning widely and looking at his watch. Nearby, a small oil puddle or leak is seen but not very exciting. In the sky, a few vultures or birds circle lazily to emphasize the slow pace. The worker''s facial expression should clearly convey boredom and impatience, with exaggerated cartoon features. The overall scene is bright and simple, with clear focus on the worker’s boredom and the oil rig setup, emphasizing the dullness of the activity in a lighthearted way.'),
 (2513, 'Absurd Humor, Office Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'We can lick gravity, but sometimes the paperwork is overwhelming.', 'Wernher von Braun', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky scientist or inventor standing on a small hill that looks like a tongue, licking a big, shiny apple hanging in the sky, symbolizing gravity (a playful nod to Newton''s apple). The scientist wears oversized glasses, a lab coat with pens sticking out, and has a comically large tongue extended to ''lick'' the apple. Nearby is a cluttered desk overflowing with piles of paperwork, folders, and sticky notes, some scattered on the ground. The character looks slightly frustrated or overwhelmed, glancing at the paperwork while still reaching out to the apple. The background is simple and colorful with a clear blue sky and a few cartoon-like clouds. The overall vibe is lighthearted and whimsical, highlighting the contrast between the simple act of ''licking gravity'' and the complexity of handling paperwork.'),
 (2928, 'Absurd Humor, Office Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Hey, I could be spontaneous if I wanted to. Just tell me when you want me to be spontaneous, and I''ll pencil you in. Next Tuesday at 10:30 is open.', NULL, 'A cartoon of a well-dressed, slightly nerdy-looking man standing next to a large whiteboard or calendar on an office wall. The calendar clearly shows days of the week and times in neat handwriting. The man is holding a pencil and smiling awkwardly, as if he’s trying to look enthusiastic but a bit rigid. Above him is a speech bubble saying, ''Just tell me when you want me to be spontaneous, and I''ll pencil you in.'' On the calendar, the slot for ''Next Tuesday at 10:30'' is marked with a neat little box and a pencil icon. The scene should have a lighthearted, humorous office vibe with bright colors, exaggerated expressions, and clear, playful details like a clock showing time and sticky notes around the calendar to highlight the contrast between spontaneity and scheduling. The overall mood is fun and nerdy, emphasizing the irony of scheduling spontaneity.'),
 (3204, 'Absurd Humor, Optimism Humor, Steven Wright, Wit', 'I intend to live forever ... So far, so good.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing confidently in the center of the frame. The person is smiling and giving a thumbs-up gesture. Around them, various clocks and calendars float in the background, symbolizing the passage of time. The calendar pages for many years are gently fluttering or scattered on the ground, implying a long timeline. Next to the person is a speech bubble containing the text, ''I intend to live forever ... So far, so good.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and optimistic, with bright colors and exaggerated, playful cartoon style emphasizing the absurdity and optimism of the statement. No other characters or objects are needed, focus is on the individual and time elements to highlight the joke’s theme.'),
 (3004, 'Absurd Humor, Optimism Humor, Unknown', 'I intend to live forever - so far, so good.', NULL, 'Draw a cheerful cartoon character standing confidently with arms crossed and a big smile, looking directly at the viewer. The character should be surrounded by floating clocks and calendars, all showing various dates far into the future. Nearby, a humorous tombstone with ''To Be Decided'' engraved can be visible, indicating the idea of not dying yet. The background should be bright and lighthearted with clouds and birds to emphasize the optimistic mood. Add a speech bubble above the character saying, ''I intend to live forever—so far, so good.'' The style should be simple, colorful, and cartoonish to enhance the whimsical feel of the joke.'),
 (2840, 'Absurd Humor, Paranoia Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Everyone hates me because I''m paranoid.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a lonely character standing awkwardly in the center of a room. The character is drawn with exaggerated wide eyes, looking nervously over their shoulder. Around them, faint transparent thought bubbles show caricatured people whispering, looking suspiciously, or glaring at the character, creating a sense of paranoia. The room is simple: a plain wall, a small window with closed curtains, and a clock showing time passing slowly. The character''s body language shows they''ve wrapped their arms protectively around themselves, with slightly hunched shoulders. The overall tone is light and humorous, with a slightly exaggerated cartoon style emphasizing the character''s paranoid feelings without depicting actual hostility from others. The ghostly figures are slightly exaggerated and comical, not threatening, adding to the humorous effect of the character''s paranoia.'),
 (3061, 'Absurd Humor, Parenting, Unknown', 'If a child cries in the woods and nobody is there to hear it, is it still bad parenting?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon set deep in a dense, whimsical forest with tall trees and birds perched on branches. In the center stands a small child wearing bright clothes, crying dramatically with big tears streaming down their face, mouth wide open in a classic wailing pose. Nearby, no adults are seen; instead, a confused squirrel and a rabbit are looking at the child in surprise. The forest floor is dotted with flowers, mushrooms, and a few scattered toys that look abandoned. In the background, a distant house is visible but faint, emphasizing the child’s isolation. The overall style is light-hearted and colorful, capturing the absurdity of the situation without any menace or sadness, making it clear the joke is about parenting and perception rather than actual distress.'),
 (1946, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'In the end, everything is a gag.', 'Charlie Chaplin (1889-1977)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a simple stage setup with a spotlight shining on a large, classic gag wheel (like a prank toy spring loaded to pop out) in the center. Around the gag wheel are various everyday objects whimsically transformed into gag items: a banana peel, a whoopee cushion on a chair, a joy buzzer in a handshake, and a hand buzzer disguised as a microphone. The background shows an audience of diverse cartoon characters laughing and pointing slightly exaggerated and colorful, sitting in theater seats. Above the stage, a banner reads ''The Final Show.'' The overall atmosphere is playful and lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun on the word ''gag'' as both a joke and a prank device. No violence or sensitive content, just cheerful comic exaggeration on the theme that ''everything is a gag.'''),
 (1375, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'A choice is always possible, even without any options.', NULL, 'Draw a simple, humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing at a fork in the road with no visible paths except the one they stand on. The person should have a puzzled, thoughtful expression, scratching their head or tapping their chin. The surroundings can be a plain, empty landscape with a single signpost that points to ''Options'' but with blank signs or no arrows, implying no real choices. Include subtle elements like question marks or light bulbs above their head to show contemplation. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial features and clean lines to emphasize the irony of having to make a choice despite no real options being present.'),
 (1462, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'A scholar who cherishes the love of comfort is not fit to be deemed a scholar.', 'Lao-Tzu (570?-490? BC)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a librarian or scholar in a cozy, overly comfortable setting. The scholar is sitting in an oversized, plush armchair with a cup of tea or coffee, wrapped in a thick blanket, wearing slippers and reading glasses. Around them are stacks of books, scrolls, and papers indicating serious study. Nearby, there’s a small side table with a warm lamp and perhaps a plate of cookies. The scholar looks relaxed and slightly smug, embodying comfort and intellectual seriousness at the same time. The room is lined with tall bookshelves filled with many books, but the focus is on the scholar’s comfort rather than active study or hard work. The overall style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated comfy elements to emphasize the joke about loving comfort rather than scholarly rigor.'),
 (1527, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Am I lightheaded because I''m not dead or because I''m still alive?', 'Heidi Sandige', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused man standing in the middle of a simple, bright room. The man looks dizzy with swirly eyes and a little sweat drop on his forehead, holding his head in one hand. Above his head are two thought bubbles: one with a playful ghost floating and the other with a lively heart beating strongly. The background is minimalistic with a clock ticking and a sunny window to emphasize life. The style is light-hearted and cartoony, with exaggerated facial expressions to amplify his baffled and ‘lightheaded’ state. No scary or dark elements, just a funny visual pun about being alive versus being dead, emphasizing the man''s comical internal debate.'),
 (1542, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'An unexamined life is not worth living.', 'Socrates', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person leisurely lying on a couch or hammock, looking bored or sleepy, with a thought bubble above their head containing a big book titled "Philosophy" and a glowing question mark. Nearby, there is a large sign or poster on the wall that says, "An unexamined life is not worth living." The setting is cozy and simple—a small living room with a plant, a coffee table with a cup of tea, and a window showing sunshine outside. The character’s exaggerated relaxed posture contrasts humorously with the serious philosophical quote, emphasizing their lack of reflection or deep thought in a lighthearted way.'),
 (1747, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'He who fights with monsters might take care lest he thereby become a monster. And if you gaze for long into an abyss, the abyss gazes also into you.', 'Nietchze', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a brave but slightly confused person dressed as a medieval knight, holding a small sword and shield, standing face-to-face with a large, silly-looking cartoon monster. The knight''s reflection in a nearby shiny shield morphs subtly into a mini monster version of themselves, showing the idea of ''becoming the monster.'' To the side, a dark, swirling abyss with exaggerated cartoon eyes is staring back at the knight, wide and blinking, giving the impression it''s alive and watching the knight in return. The background is a simple cave entrance or rocky cliff, with exaggerated expressions on the characters'' faces—both the monster and abyss look slightly puzzled and curious rather than scary. The overall style is lighthearted and goofy, with bright colors and exaggerated features to emphasize the humor and the metaphor in a visual, playful way.'),
 (1793, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'I don''t believe in an afterlife, so I don''t have to spend my whole life fearing hell, or fearing heaven even more. For whatever the tortures of hell, I think the boredom of heaven would be even worse.', 'Isaac Asimov', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a person sitting comfortably on a couch with a thoughtful, slightly amused expression. Above their head, depict two contrasting thought bubbles: one showing a fiery, chaotic scene labeled ''Hell'' with flames, pitchforks, and a few exaggerated tiny demons having fun in a wild party setting; the other bubble shows a dull, bland Heaven with angels sitting quietly on clouds, yawning or falling asleep, reading endless books, or staring at a monotonous sky. The person''s body language should suggest relief and contemplation as they weigh their thoughts about afterlife boredom versus hellish torture. The background should be simple, indoors, emphasizing a relaxed casual atmosphere. Use bright and cheerful colors for the cartoon, emphasizing humor and lightheartedness without any darkness or fear.'),
 (1865, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'If a man insisted always on being serious, and never allowed himself a bit of fun and relaxation, he would go mad or become unstable without knowing it.', 'Herodotus', 'Draw a cartoon scene featuring a man sitting stiffly at a desk in a small office. The man looks extremely serious and formal, wearing a suit and tie, with a tightly clenched jaw and furrowed eyebrows. Around him, the office environment is dull and gray with stacks of paperwork, a ticking clock on the wall, and a calendar showing a monotonous schedule. Above the man’s head, show a thought bubble that splits into two halves: on one side, dark, chaotic scribbles representing his growing madness; on the other side, a small, fading cartoon smiley face symbolizing the lost fun and relaxation he’s denying himself. To emphasize humor, draw the man’s chair slightly wobbling or tipping over as if symbolizing instability. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated, using simple lines and vibrant colors for contrast—make the office drab and the man overly stiff, highlighting his serious demeanor in a silly way without any menace or negativity.'),
 (1876, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'If God meant us to be naked, he would have made our skin fit better.', 'Maureen Murphy', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing awkwardly, with their skin visibly loose and sagging all over, like a poorly fitted suit. The person looks puzzled and is tugging at the excess skin around their arms and legs. Nearby is a large cartoonish figure representing God — depicted as a kindly, older artist-like character with a paintbrush and palette — inspecting the person thoughtfully, as if puzzled about the fitting. The background is simple and bright, with a fitting room mirror showing the reflection of the skin not fitting properly. Add small humorous details, such as a measuring tape hanging from God''s neck, a sign that says ''Skin Fitting Department,'' and some clothes hanging on a rack labeled ''Human Fashion.'' The overall tone is lighthearted, playful, and absurd, with exaggerated expressions and a clean, colorful cartoon style.'),
 (1885, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'If knowledge can create problems, it is not through ignorance that we can solve them.', 'Isaac Asimov', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a library table surrounded by towering piles of books labeled ‘Knowledge.’ The person looks puzzled and stressed, scratching their head with a furrowed brow. Nearby, another character lounging lazily in a cozy chair wearing pajamas, blissfully ignoring all the books and holding a pillow labeled ‘Ignorance.’ The setting is bright and cheerful, with a large window showing a sunny day outside to contrast the person overwhelmed by knowledge, while the relaxed character enjoys the calm of ignorance. Include humorous details like a chalkboard behind the table with a complicated equation and a thought bubble from the person full of question marks, while the lazy character’s thought bubble shows simple smiling faces. The art style should be exaggerated, cartoonish, and warm, emphasizing the irony between knowledge causing problems and ignorance offering a seemingly easier path but not the solution.'),
 (1935, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Imagine if there were no hypothetical situations.', 'John Mendoza', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a thinker-like character, dressed in casual clothes, sitting in a classic philosopher pose (chin resting on hand) on a comfy armchair. Around them are thought bubbles but instead of usual ideas or questions, each bubble is crossed out or has a big red ''X'' over it, symbolizing the absence of hypothetical situations. In the background, a whiteboard or chalkboard displays the phrase ''No Hypotheticals Allowed!'' written boldly. The setting is a cozy room with bookshelves filled with philosophy and logic books, some with titles partially visible like ''What If?'', ''Possibilities'', and ''Maybe''. The overall tone is light and funny, with exaggerated cartoon features: big eyes, raised eyebrow, and a perplexed expression on the thinker’s face. Include whimsical details like a mouse peeking from a corner holding a tiny sign that says ''Hypotheticals missing!''. The colors should be bright and inviting to enhance the humorous, clever vibe of the scene.'),
 (1993, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It takes a long time to understand nothing.', 'Edward Dahlberg', 'A cartoon scene showing a confused person sitting at a desk cluttered with papers, books, and a steaming cup of coffee. The person has a puzzled expression with furrowed brows, maybe scratching their head. Above their head is a thought bubble with the word ''Nothing'' inside it. The clock on the wall shows that a long time has passed (hour and minute hands apart). Around the desk are humorous hints of futile study: an open book titled ''Understanding Nothing,'' a calendar with many crossed-out days, and a dim lightbulb hanging overhead. The general mood is lightheartedly comical, illustrating the irony of spending so much time trying to grasp something that is essentially ''nothing.'' The style is exaggerated and cartoonish with bright colors and simple lines emphasizing the comic nature of the struggle.'),
 (2046, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Life is too serious to be taken seriously.', 'Mike Leonard', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person dressed in a business suit sitting at a large office desk cluttered with papers, calculators, and a big serious-looking wall clock. The person has a playful grin and is balancing a colorful party hat on their head while holding a rubber chicken instead of a pen. Around them, small whimsical objects float like balloons and confetti to contrast with the serious office setting. Behind the desk, a whiteboard reads ''Life is too serious to be taken seriously'' in bold, playful letters. The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize the irony of mixing seriousness with silliness.'),
 (2076, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Man has made use of his intelligence, he invented stupidity.', 'Remy de Gourmant', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a man sitting at a desk cluttered with inventions and blueprints. The man, looking proud and slightly goofy, holds a lightbulb above his head symbolizing intelligence. Nearby, an oversized, comically exaggerated cartoon box labeled ''Stupidity'' has spilled out silly objects like a rubber chicken, a whoopee cushion, a big floppy hat, and crossed-out math equations floating around. The man’s expression is a mix of pride and bewilderment, as if he’s just realized that his measure of intelligence created all this silliness. The background is a simple, cheerful workshop with gadgets and tools, drawn in bright, lively colors with exaggerated, cartoonish features to keep the tone light and fun.'),
 (2082, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Man''s mind, once stretched by a new idea, never regains its original dimensions.', 'Oliver Wendell, Jr. Holmes', 'A humorous cartoon-style scene featuring a man with a cartoonishly large, inflatable balloon for a head representing his stretched mind. The man stands in a simple room with a lightbulb above his head symbolizing a new idea. Around him, small objects like books, a chalkboard with a complex equation, and scattered papers emphasize learning and thinking. The man''s expression is one of surprise and amazement as his head inflates like a balloon stretching larger and larger. In the background, a deflated balloon labeled ''original mind'' lies on the floor, hinting at the idea that the mind can''t shrink back to its old size. The overall style is colorful and whimsical, emphasizing exaggeration and curiosity in a lighthearted way without anything violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (2097, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Mediocrity requires aloofness to preserve its dignity.', 'Charles G. Dawes', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bland, ordinary-looking middle-aged man sitting on a simple park bench with a neutral, slightly smug expression. He is dressed in plain, slightly dull clothes (beige pants and a gray shirt) that emphasize his mediocrity. Around him, more lively and colorful characters are enjoying various impressive or extraordinary activities—such as a person painting a vivid mural, someone juggling brightly colored balls, and another flying a kite. The background should be a cheerful park setting with trees, flowers, and a bright blue sky to contrast the man''s unimpressive presence. The man is holding a small trophy or medal labeled ''Mediocrity'' with a subtle but proud air, perhaps with a tiny cloud or halo effect above his head symbolizing his ''aloofness'' and preserved dignity. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the lively characters to highlight the humor of the man''s detached pride in being average.'),
 (2236, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Silence is the virtue of fools.', 'Francis Bacon', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters having a conversation in a simple park setting with a bench and some trees. One character is a wise-looking figure, dressed like a philosopher with a toga and laurel wreath, holding a small book labeled ''Virtues.'' This character has a calm, knowing expression. The second character is a foolish-looking person, wearing mismatched clothes and a dunce cap, sitting silently on the bench with their mouth zipped shut comically with a giant zipper. Above them floats a comic-style speech bubble from the philosopher saying, ''Silence is the virtue of fools.'' The background is bright and cheerful, emphasizing a lighthearted tone. Include exaggerated cartoon features like big eyes and expressive faces to enhance humor without any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (2270, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'That we can comprehend the little we know already is mindboggling in itself.', 'Tom Gates', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person''s head with an exaggeratedly large, classic cartoon brain visible inside a transparent skull. The person looks bewildered, scratching their head with one hand while staring at a small pile of tiny books and notes labeled ''What I Know''. Above the character''s head is a swirling, colorful thought bubble full of question marks, puzzle pieces, and tiny lightning bolts to indicate confusion and amazement. The background is simple, perhaps a classroom or study room setting, with a desk cluttered with scrolls and half-read books, emphasizing the small amount of knowledge. The style is lighthearted and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to underline the irony that even understanding a little knowledge is itself a puzzling and complex feat. No text is included in the image, just the visual elements conveying overwhelmed comprehension and mind-boggling thought.'),
 (2420, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'There are times when silence has the loudest voice.', 'Leroy Brownlow', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting face-to-face on simple chairs in a quiet room. Both characters have exaggerated surprised or shocked expressions, wide eyes, and open mouths as if they expect to hear something but there is complete silence. Between them, show little visual noise or sound lines, emphasizing the silence. One character could have a speech bubble with a faded or empty outline to indicate quietness, while the other looks confused or uncomfortable. The background should be minimal, maybe a plain wall with a clock showing time passing slowly, and a window letting in soft light. The overall style is lighthearted and funny with bright colors and simple, expressive features on the characters to capture the irony of "loud silence."'),
 (2421, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'There are two tragedies in life. One is to lose your heart''s desire. The other is to gain it.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing at a crossroad, with two signs pointing in opposite directions. One sign reads ''Lose Your Heart''s Desire'' and the other ''Gain Your Heart''s Desire.'' The person looks puzzled and stressed, scratching their head with a worried expression. Around them, there are subtle visual metaphors: a broken heart lying on the ground near the ''Lose'' sign and an overflowing treasure chest next to the ''Gain'' sign. The background is bright and simple, emphasizing the dilemma. The style is light-hearted and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions and clear, bold lines to enhance the comedic tone without any darkness or negativity.'),
 (2552, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Whatever you do will be insignificant, but it is very important that you do it.', 'Mohandas Gandhi', 'A simple, colorful cartoon scene set in a whimsical park or open field. In the center, a small, quirky character with an exaggeratedly serious expression is desperately trying to plant a single tiny flower seed. Around the character, everything else is huge and vibrant—a massive tree, an oversized boulder, a giant sun in the sky with a smiling face, and other large, lively animals or creatures looking on curiously. Despite the smallness of the task (planting the tiny seed), the character holds a large watering can and a big gardening tool, emphasizing the contrast between the insignificant action and its apparent importance. A thought bubble above the character’s head contains the words: "Whatever you do will be insignificant, but it is very important that you do it." The style should be playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and a lighthearted feel, evoking a humorous but thoughtful mood without any negativity.'),
 (2610, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'You know nothing for sure, except the fact that you know nothing for sure.', 'John F. Kennedy', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused person sitting at a desk cluttered with books, question marks floating above their head. The person is scratching their head with a puzzled expression, looking at a large open book titled ''Knowledge.'' In front of them on the desk is a thought bubble showing the words: ''You know nothing for sure.'' Behind them is a chalkboard or whiteboard with the phrase ''You know nothing for sure'' written twice, emphasizing the paradox. The background should be simple and light-colored to keep focus on the character and their bewilderment. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and whimsical details like small swirls or stars around the head to show confusion. No violent or controversial elements.'),
 (1768, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Humankind cannot bear very much reality.', 'T. S. Elliot', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of diverse people sitting comfortably on a couch in a cozy living room. They all wear casual clothes and have exaggerated expressions of shock, discomfort, or disbelief as they look at a large, old-fashioned television screen. On the screen, the phrase ''Very Much Reality'' is shown boldly in curly, dramatic letters, as if it were a heavy, unsettling documentary. Some characters attempt to shield their eyes or cover their ears, while one person holds a remote control hesitating to change the channel. The room includes typical furniture like a side table with a lamp, a houseplant, and framed family photos to emphasize the everyday setting. The cartoon style is lighthearted with bright colors and clear, expressive features, emphasizing the comedic idea that reality is almost too much for people to handle peacefully.'),
 (2292, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The conventional view serves to protect us from the painful job of thinking.', 'John Kenneth Galbraith', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of people sitting comfortably on a couch and lounge chairs in a living room, each with relaxed, sleepy, or distracted expressions on their faces. One person sits with an oversized helmet labeled ''Conventional View'' that looks like a protective helmet, acting as a shield. In front of them is a big book titled ''Thinking: Hard Work'' gathering dust on a small table, clearly untouched. In contrast, another character nearby is struggling to carry a giant brain, sweating and looking exhausted, symbolizing the ''painful job of thinking.'' The room has cozy, warm colors with simple, everyday furniture, and a poster on the wall whimsically reads ''Welcome to Easy Mode.'' The art style is playful and exaggerated with big eyes and goofy smiles, emphasizing the humor in avoiding deep thought by hiding behind conventional ideas rather than engaging in mental effort.'),
 (2546, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'What sane person could live in this world and not be crazy?', 'Ursula K. LeGuin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a bewildered, slightly frazzled person standing in the middle of a chaotic, surreal street scene symbolizing the world. Around them, depict exaggerated oddities: a clock melting over a street lamp, traffic signs pointing in contradictory directions, animals wearing human clothes engaging in strange behaviors, and people walking upside down on the sky. The person''s face shows a mix of confusion and disbelief, scratching their head or with wide eyes. The background should look colorful and busy with comically exaggerated details to emphasize absurdity and disorder, giving the feeling that everything is just a bit ''off'' or crazy. The tone is light and funny, emphasizing the absurdity of the world and the idea that sanity is hard to maintain in such an environment.'),
 (1841, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religion Humor', 'I think that God in creating man somewhat overestimated his ability.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon-style scene showing a goofy, slightly overwhelmed looking man at the center. Above him, a large, friendly caricature of God, resembling a kindly old man with a long white beard and a glowing aura, is looking down at the man with a mildly amused and surprised expression, holding a giant blueprint labeled ''Human Design.'' The man is scratching his head with one hand, while the other hand is fumbling with a complicated, oversized tool or instruction manual labeled ''Manual for Being Human.'' The background is simple with fluffy clouds to emphasize a heavenly setting. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to highlight the joke about God overestimating man''s abilities without any negativity.'),
 (1945, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religion Humor', 'In the beginning Man created God; and in the image of Man created he him.', 'Jethro Tull Aqualung', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a caveman dressed in simple animal skin clothing holding a rough wooden carving of a figure labeled ''God.'' The caveman looks proud and slightly amused, standing beside a stone pedestal with various primitive carving tools scattered around. The figure of God is designed in the caveman''s likeness, featuring exaggerated features like a big nose, messy hair, and a goofy smile, mirroring the caveman’s appearance. In the background, a simplistic prehistoric landscape with a bright sky, a few cartoon trees, and rolling hills. A speech bubble above the caveman reads, ''In the beginning, Man created God;'' while near the carving, a small sign says, ''In the image of Man he created him.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, capturing the ironic twist of the phrase in a playful prehistoric setting with bold lines and vibrant colors typical of a cartoon comic style.'),
 (1570, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'As soon as questions of will or decision or reason or choice of action arise, human science is at a loss.', 'Noam Chomsky', 'A cartoon-style illustration showing a confused, cartoon human figure with a big puzzled expression, scratching their head. Around the character''s head are colorful thought bubbles containing symbols representing ''will'' (a tiny muscle arm flexing), ''decision'' (a fork in the road sign), ''reason'' (a glowing light bulb), and ''choice of action'' (a checklist with question marks). The human figure stands in front of a large, old-fashioned book labeled ''Human Science'' that looks overwhelmed and worn out, with sweat drops and cartoon tired eyes. The background is simple, with a light-hearted, humorous atmosphere, emphasizing the comic frustration of science trying to handle subjective concepts like will, decision, and reason. No other complex details or backgrounds, keeping the focus on the humorous struggle between abstract ideas and human science.'),
 (1788, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'I could prove God statistically.', 'George Gallup', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple office or study room. In the center, a cheerful character, maybe a scientist or mathematician, confidently stands beside a large whiteboard covered with colorful, complex-looking charts, graphs, and numbers. The person is pointing excitedly at the whiteboard with a marker in hand. The whiteboard has a big equation or graph humorously labeled ''Proof of God (Statistical).'' Nearby, a small skeptical character sits at a desk with a puzzled or amused expression, holding a coffee mug. The room has typical office details, like bookshelves filled with math and science books and a framed diploma on the wall. The overall mood is light and comical, showcasing the absurdity of proving God through statistics. Draw in a cartoon style emphasizing exaggerated expressions and a playful atmosphere.'),
 (1868, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'If all else fails, immortality can always be assured by spectacular error.', 'John Kenneth Galbraith', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky scientist in a messy lab, with wild hair and oversized glasses, standing next to a giant, complicated machine with blinking lights and smoke puffing out. The scientist looks surprised but comically proud, holding up a test tube labeled ''Experiment Gone Wrong''. Around them are charts and notes with big red X marks and funny mistakes written on them. In the background, a ghostly but friendly cartoon figure floats, waving cheerfully, symbolizing accidental immortality through a spectacular error. The lab should have exaggerated cartoon elements like bubbling beakers, scattered papers, and a chalkboard with scribbles illustrating failed experiments. The overall mood is lighthearted and whimsical, highlighting the idea that big mistakes can lead to unexpected lasting fame or presence.'),
 (1890, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'If the human mind was simple enough to understand, we''d be too simple to understand it.', 'Emerson Pugh', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a simplified human brain character with big cartoon eyes and a puzzled expression, holding a large magnifying glass trying to examine itself. Around it are several tiny humans who look very simple—like stick figures with blank expressions—struggling to think or understand anything. The background is a light-hearted laboratory or library setting filled with books labeled ''Mind,'' ''Thoughts,'' and ''Consciousness.'' A big thought bubble above the brain shows complex symbols and equations dissolving into very basic shapes like circles and squares. The overall style is colorful and playful, emphasizing the irony of complexity versus simplicity in an educational but funny way.'),
 (1967, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'It has yet to be proven that intelligence has any survival value.', 'Arthur C. Clarke', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a caveman and a modern person standing on opposite sides of a small cliff or river. The caveman, looking rugged and confused, holds a club and scratches his head. The modern person stands confidently, holding a smartphone and wearing glasses, but looking uncertain or worried. In the background, various animals roam freely, including a big woolly mammoth and a saber-toothed tiger near the caveman, while a few city buildings and a park are visible behind the modern person. A thought bubble above the caveman reads, "Who needs brains anyway?" and above the modern person "Still not sure if being smart helps me survive." The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the playful tone. No violence or offensive elements included.'),
 (2155, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Not only does God play dice with the universe, but sometimes he throws them where they cannot be seen.', 'Stephen Hawking', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a large, friendly-looking God character dressed in flowing robes, sitting in outer space surrounded by stars and planets. God is holding a pair of dice in one hand and is mid-throw with the dice flying away from him. The dice are shown tumbling toward a black hole or an invisible area represented by a dark swirling void or empty space labeled "Can''t Be Seen". The scene should be lighthearted with exaggerated, playful expressions on God''s face, showing a mix of mischief and amusement. Include small cosmic elements like comets, planets with faces watching curiously, and whimsical sparkles around the dice to emphasize the space universe setting. The overall style should be colorful, cartoonish, and non-threatening, emphasizing a cosmic game vibe with a touch of irony and fun.'),
 (2156, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Not only is the Universe stranger than we think, it is stranger than we can think.', 'Werner Heisenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a bewildered scientist sitting at a cluttered desk filled with open books, scattered papers, and a glowing globe of the Universe. The scientist has wild, frazzled hair and exaggeratedly wide eyes staring at a thought bubble above their head. Inside the thought bubble, space is depicted with colorful planets, stars, and odd, surreal cosmic shapes that defy normal understanding—like swirling galaxies with question marks and abstract shapes that look impossible. The scientist’s expression conveys a mix of amazement and perplexity. In the background, a chalkboard shows a chaotic formula with random symbols and question marks, emphasizing the complexity of the Universe. The style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with playful exaggeration to highlight the theme of the Universe being beyond comprehension in a lighthearted way. No violence, politics, or anything inappropriate.'),
 (2267, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Thank God man cannot as yet fly and lay waste the sky as well as the earth.', 'Henry David Thoreau (1817-1862)', 'A humorous cartoon showing a man nervously standing on the edge of a simple wooden launching ramp for a homemade flying machine that looks quirky and unsafe. The man is wearing aviator goggles and a scarf blowing in the wind. Above him is a tiny, visibly shaky biplane or early flying contraption with patchy wings and exaggerated mechanical details like exposed gears. Below the ramp, the ground is cartoonishly damaged with cracks and uprooted trees, while in the sky above, there are scattered dark storm clouds shaped like bombs or explosions, suggesting destruction. The man looks apprehensive and uncertain, as if about to test fly this dangerous invention. The background is a clean blue sky with a few silly birds nervously flying away. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated to add humor, avoiding any violence—just exaggerated chaos caused by the man’s flying attempt.'),
 (2316, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'The great tragedy of Science -- the slaying of a beautiful hypothesis by an ugly fact.', 'Thomas Henry Huxley', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classic scientist''s laboratory. In the center, a large, whimsical hypothesis character is personified as a glowing, elegant, and beautiful figure with sparkles around it, wearing a flowing robe and holding a lightbulb symbolizing an idea. Opposite it stands a grumpy, unattractive ''ugly fact'' character drawn as a rough, scruffy monster-like figure with a frown and maybe a pair of thick glasses to look serious. The ugly fact holds a giant, comically oversized sword labeled ''Fact'' that is lightly poking or leaning against the hypothesis, symbolizing the ''slaying.'' Around them are scientific instruments such as test tubes, flasks, and chalkboards covered in equations. The background should be colorful and light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions on both characters to emphasize humor, not violence. The atmosphere reflects the phrase ''Great tragedy of science'' but in a playful cartoon style, showing the contrast between beauty and harsh reality in scientific discovery.'),
 (2426, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'There is a theory which states that if ever anyone discovers exactly what the Universe is for and why it is here, it will instantly disappear and be replaced by something even more bizarre and inexplicable. There is another theory which states that this has already happened.', 'Douglas Adams, ''Restaurant At The End Of The Universe''', 'A whimsical cartoon scene depicting a quirky, colorful cosmic setting. At center, a large, friendly-looking, slightly puzzled cartoon character resembling a cosmic explorer or scientist (with a lab coat and oversized glasses), holding a scroll labeled ''Theory'' that looks old and tattered. Surrounding them are vibrant swirling galaxies, stars, planets, and strange cosmic objects with exaggerated and bizarre shapes (e.g., a planet shaped like a rubber duck, another shaped like a teapot). Nearby, another cosmic entity—a cartoonish, mysterious, shadowy figure—waves or gestures knowingly, implying it just swapped the universe. The background is deep space with bright nebulas in pinks, blues, and purples, creating a dreamy but humorous vibe. The caption or a speech bubble near the scientist could say: ''So if we find out what the Universe is for... it''ll vanish?!'' emphasizing the joke. The overall vibe is playful, surreal and lighthearted, capturing the idea of existential mystery and cosmic absurdity without anything scary or serious.'),
 (2482, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'To those who think that the law of gravity interferes with their freedom, there is nothing to say.', 'Lionel Tiger', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on the edge of a cliff or a high building, looking frustrated with their arms crossed. Around them, little cartoon symbols like question marks and tiny angry clouds float to emphasize their annoyance. Below or behind them, a large, friendly, anthropomorphic boulder or planet Earth character is holding a giant, thick book titled ''Law of Gravity'' with a calm, knowing smile. The background is bright and simple: a clear blue sky with a few fluffy clouds. The scene should convey the idea that gravity is an unavoidable rule, somewhat personified as a firm but kind authority figure, while the person is humorously upset at how it limits their freedom. The art style is clean and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect. No violence or conflict, just a playful representation of the tension between human desire for freedom and natural laws.'),
 (2489, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Truly great madness can not be achieved without significant intelligence.', 'Henrik Tikkanen', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky mad scientist in a cluttered laboratory filled with bubbling test tubes, quirky inventions, and chalkboards covered in complex equations. The scientist has wild, crazy hair and thick glasses, looking both slightly confused and proud. Around them, show cartoonish thought bubbles combining chaotic scribbles and intellectual symbols like light bulbs, math formulas, and question marks. Nearby, a small brain character wearing a graduation cap is cheerfully holding a sign that reads, ''Madness requires brains!'' The overall art style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing both the chaotic ''madness'' and the intellectual ''intelligence'' to visually reflect the joke’s message without any alarming or inappropriate elements.'),
 (1419, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Help Humor', 'A human being''s first responsibility is to shake hands with himself.', 'Henry Winkler', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a full-length mirror, enthusiastically shaking hands with their own reflection. The person is smiling confidently, giving a thumbs-up with their free hand. The room is simple and lighthearted, with a small potted plant and a framed motivational poster in the background that reads ''Self-Motivation''. The mirror clearly shows the reflection reciprocating the handshake. Both the person and the reflection wear casual, bright clothing. The style is clean and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor and warmth of the idea of ''shaking hands with oneself.'''),
 (2114, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'Morality is the herd-instinct in the individual.', 'Nietchze', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a single person standing in a green field surrounded by a herd of sheep. The person looks puzzled and slightly conflicted, scratching their head, while the sheep are all looking at the person expectantly as if waiting for them to follow herd behavior. Give the person human traits but slightly exaggerated for comedic effect with a thought bubble showing a small group of sheep with a moral scale floating above them. The background is simple, with rolling hills and a blue sky to keep the focus on the person and the sheep. Include a small signpost stuck in the ground nearby reading ''Morality Field.'' The overall tone is lighthearted, poking fun at the idea that individuals adopt morality because of herd instinct, depicted by the person trying to decide whether to join the sheep or go against them.'),
 (1607, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'Computers are useless.  They can only give you answers.', 'Pablo Picasso', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a frustrated person sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer in front of them. The computer screen brightly displays a single line saying: ''42''. The person has an exaggerated confused expression, scratching their head and holding a question mark-shaped thought bubble above them. Surrounding the desk are stacks of books labeled ''Philosophy'', ''Life Questions'', and ''Mysteries of the Universe''. A coffee mug sits nearby with the word ''Hope'' on it. The background is a simple office or home study with a window showing a sunny day outside to contrast the person''s puzzled mood. The style is playful and exaggerated, with rounded, colorful cartoon characters and objects, emphasizing the irony that computers can only provide answers while the person is overwhelmed by questions.'),
 (2395, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Time Humor', 'The trouble with our times is that the future is not what it used to be.', 'Paul Valery', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a small town square blending a vintage and futuristic feel. In the foreground, a confused elderly man dressed in old-fashioned clothes (like from the 1950s) holds a futuristic gadget—an oddly shaped tablet with blinking lights and holograms projecting out of it. He squints at the gadget, scratching his head. Behind him is a town clock tower with its clock face showing different times on each side, symbolizing uncertainty about time. Around the man are scattered objects representing different eras—an old rotary phone lying next to a drone, a horse-drawn carriage passing by a self-driving car, and people in a mix of retro and futuristic outfits walking about. The sky has a whimsical swirl of colors, blending past and future hues. Signs in the background humorously read “Welcome to Yesterday-Tomorrow” and “Future: Not What It Used To Be.” The overall style should be playful and cartoony, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the man’s bemusement and the clash between past expectations of the future and today’s reality.'),
 (1666, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Even a fool knows you can''t touch the stars, but it doesn''t stop a wise man from trying.', 'Harry Anderson', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set at night under a star-filled sky. In the foreground, show a wise-looking man wearing glasses and a thoughtful expression, reaching upward on his tiptoes toward the distant twinkling stars. His hand is just stretching out but clearly far from touching them. Nearby, depict a simple, silly-looking fool (perhaps with a goofy grin and crossed eyes) standing back casually with arms crossed, shaking his head in disbelief or amusement. The setting can be a small hill or open field to give a sense of openness and height. Include a subtle glow around the stars to emphasize their unreachable distance, and maybe small comical sparkles or question marks near the fool’s head to show his skepticism. The overall tone should be light, wise, and funny without being dramatic or intense.'),
 (2329, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The life which is unexamined is not worth living.', 'Plato', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a thoughtful philosopher character resembling a classic Greek thinker, sitting cross-legged on a simple rock in a sunny outdoor setting. The philosopher is wearing a toga and has a laurel wreath on their head, stroking their chin as if in deep contemplation. Above their head is a large, exaggerated thought bubble containing the quote "The life which is unexamined is not worth living." Surrounding the philosopher are humorous details like a small magnifying glass and a checklist labeled ''Life Examined?'' with various silly items ticked off, such as ''Questioned Breakfast,'' ''Doubted Socks,'' and ''Analyzed Clouds.'' The background should be bright and cheerful, with simple cartoon trees and a smiling sun. The overall style is lighthearted, emphasizing the philosopher’s serious pondering contrasted with the playful, silly checklist to underscore the humor of overly examining life.'),
 (2357, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The only true wisdom is knowing you know nothing.', 'Socrates', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or ancient study room. In the center, a wise-looking old philosopher character, resembling a simplified version of Socrates or a classical thinker, stands with a long beard, wearing a toga. He holds an oversized scroll or book that says ''Wisdom'' on the cover but looks empty or blank. Around him are curious, cartoonish students or listeners with confused or skeptical expressions. Above the philosopher, a speech bubble reads, "The only true wisdom is knowing you know nothing." The background includes classic elements like Greek columns or a chalkboard with a question mark and some doodles implying deep thinking. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated with playful facial expressions, emphasizing the irony of claiming wisdom through admitting ignorance. Bright colors and simple lines should make the image comedic and approachable, without any dark or serious tone.'),
 (1413, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'A great truth is a truth whose opposite is also a great truth.', 'Thomas Mann', 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing two large speech bubbles facing each other. One bubble contains the phrase ''A great truth,'' and the other bubble contains the phrase ''The opposite of a great truth.'' Between them is a whimsical scale balancing both bubbles evenly, symbolizing equality. In the background, depict a wise-looking cartoon character, like a robe-clad philosopher with a beard, scratching his head in playful confusion or amusement. The scene should be lighthearted and metaphoric, using soft pastel colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the paradoxical idea. Include subtle details like question marks floating around the philosopher''s head and a small book titled ''Philosophy'' lying open beside him to set the thoughtful yet amusing mood. The overall style should be simple, clean, and cartoonish, inviting viewers to smile at the paradox without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (1507, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'All generalizations are false, including this one.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky professor-like character standing in front of a large blackboard filled with complicated writings and formulas. The professor wears round glasses and has wild, messy hair, holding a piece of chalk in one hand while scratching his head with the other, clearly puzzled. On the blackboard, written prominently in big, bold letters is the phrase: ''All generalizations are false, including this one.'' The classroom environment is exaggeratedly academic with books stacked haphazardly, a globe, and quirky scientific instruments around. The style should be light-hearted, colorful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the paradoxical and self-contradictory nature of the phrase, creating a playful and brain-teasing vibe.'),
 (2117, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Most people would sooner die than think; in fact, they do so.', 'Bertrand Russell (1872-1970)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of people at a party or social gathering with thought bubbles above their heads. Most of the thought bubbles are empty or show simple silly symbols like question marks or doodles to indicate lack of deep thinking. In the foreground, a person is shown dramatically fainting or collapsing in an exaggerated comedic manner with a small cloud above labeled ''thinking'' to visually represent the phrase ''sooner die than think.'' The scene should be bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions of surprise or confusion on the faces of the bystanders. Include everyday objects like chairs, a table with snacks or drinks, and a clock on the wall to give it a relatable social setting. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity and humor of avoiding thinking.'),
 (2182, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Only two things are infinite, the universe and human stupidity, and I''m not sure about the former.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking, slightly exasperated philosopher character standing in front of a blackboard under a starry night sky filled with galaxies and planets. The blackboard has two big circles drawn: one labeled ''Universe'' filled with stars and colors, and another labeled ''Human Stupidity'' that goes off the edge of the board, indicating it''s boundless. The philosopher, wearing round glasses and a robe, scratches their head with a puzzled expression looking toward the ''Universe'' circle, a thought bubble above showing a question mark mystery. Around them, comedic props like a stack of thick books titled ''Infinite Concepts'' and a spilled coffee cup add to the lighthearted feel. The style is clean, whimsical, and cartoonish, emphasizing both vastness and silliness without anything offensive.'),
 (2188, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Our proper bliss depends on what we blame.', 'Alexander Pope', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a joyful, contented person sitting cross-legged on a comfy cloud labeled ''Bliss.'' Around them float several colorful thought bubbles containing humorous blame targets like a grumpy cartoon thundercloud, a mischievous cartoon squirrel dropping acorns, and a comical frowning arrow pointing at themselves in a mirror. The background is a cheerful sky with a bright sun smiling, fluffy clouds, and birds chirping, emphasizing a lighthearted mood. The person has a calm, zen expression, with hands raised as if meditating. The overall tone is whimsical and positive, illustrating the idea that happiness depends on where we direct our blame or focus, with a subtle ironic feel. The style is simple, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions on the blame targets to add humor without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2212, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Probable impossibilities are to be preferred to improbable possibilities.', 'Aristotle', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a whimsical, slightly surreal library or study filled with quirky objects like oversized books, a large hourglass, and a chalkboard with complicated probability formulas. In the center, a comical professor or philosopher figure, wearing round glasses and a tweed jacket with elbow patches, stands confidently holding a pointer and gesturing towards two thought bubbles above his head. One bubble shows improbable possibilities represented by a tiny lottery ticket flying away, while the other bubble shows probable impossibilities depicted as a giant, improbable creature (like a friendly purple dragon with glasses) calmly reading a book. The professor has a knowing smile, emphasizing the joke''s ironic wisdom. The background includes playful details, like a cat wearing a graduation cap staring at the scene or a stack of books leaning precariously. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and clear, expressive lines to convey intellectual humor in a fun, accessible way.'),
 (2235, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Show me a sane man and I will cure him for you.', 'Carl Gustav Jung (1875-1961)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, slightly eccentric-looking man in casual clothes, standing confidently with a big grin. He holds out one hand as if offering to help or cure someone. Across from him is another character, looking confused or bewildered, perhaps rubbing their head or looking puzzled. Background elements should be simple: a plain park bench and a tree, suggesting a calm everyday setting. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with bold lines and bright colors. The emphasis is on the contrast between the ''sane'' man who appears a bit unconventional and the skeptical observer, capturing the irony and wit of the joke without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2557, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'When choosing between two evils, I always like to try the one I''ve never tried before.', 'Mae West (1892-1980)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing at a fork in a road, each path labeled with a sign reading ''Evil #1'' and ''Evil #2.'' The person, looking curious and a bit mischievous, is scratching their chin thoughtfully while looking down both paths. The paths lead toward silly, exaggerated representations of ''evil''—one with a comically wicked villain wearing a cape and holding a pitchfork, and the other with an absurd monster eating a giant ice cream cone messily. The background is bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions on both characters to keep the tone light-hearted. The person’s outfit is casual and modern, and the whole composition is cartoonish with bold outlines and vibrant colors, emphasizing a playful and fun exploration of the joke’s idea of ''trying new evils.'' Include a thought bubble above the person with the text: ''Might as well try something new!'''),
 (1399, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a small, cartoonish hobgoblin character with oversized glasses and a scholarly look, holding a large, thick book titled ''Rules of Consistency''. The hobgoblin looks stern and serious but comically tiny and somewhat foolish. Surrounding it are several little cartoon brains with expressive faces, some rolling their eyes or looking bored. The scene is set in a whimsical library filled with scattered papers and books about logic and philosophy. The background shows a chalkboard with the phrase ''Foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds'' in playful lettering. The style is light-hearted, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the silliness of being overly consistent in a foolish way, capturing the ironic tone of the quote without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (1433, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A life without cause is a life without effect.', 'Barbarella', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused character standing in the middle of a room looking puzzled. The character, drawn in a simple, exaggerated style, holds a small sign that reads ''Cause?'' above their head. Surrounding the character are floating glowing bubbles or thought clouds labeled ''Effect?'' that hover around uncertainly, as if waiting for something to happen but nothing is connected. The room is minimalistic with a desk, a chair, and a wall clock that is motionless, emphasizing inactivity. The expression on the character''s face is one of bewilderment mixed with mild frustration, and the overall color tone is light and playful. The scene visually depicts the idea of cause and effect being disconnected, making the philosophical statement amusing by showing the literal confusion of someone experiencing a ''life without cause'' and hence, a ''life without effect.'' No complex backgrounds or violence, just a simple, funny visual metaphor for the joke''s meaning.'),
 (1602, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Character is like a tree and reputation like its shadow. The shadow is what we think of it; the tree is the real thing.', 'Abraham Lincoln (1809-1865)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, sturdy tree standing proudly on a small patch of grass in the center. The tree has a confident and cheerful face drawn on its trunk to personify it as a character. On the ground beside it, a large shadow stretches out that looks completely different and exaggerated: the shadow might be wavy, distorted, or quirky, representing the idea of reputation. The shadow should be clearly distinct and comical, perhaps wearing sunglasses or making an amusing pose that contrasts with the serious and solid tree. The background is a simple sunny day with a few clouds and maybe a couple of birds to create a lighthearted atmosphere. The focus is on the contrast between the tree and its shadow, capturing the joke''s metaphor about character and reputation in a fun and visual way.'),
 (1769, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Humor is a serious thing. I like to think of it as one of our greatest earliest natural resources, which must be preserved at all cost.', 'James Thurber', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a playful, colorful natural landscape labeled as ''Humor National Park.'' The setting includes a large sign at the entrance that reads ''Welcome to the Humor Reserve - Preserve at All Costs!'' Below the sign, a group of cheerful cartoon characters (diverse humans and animals) are gathered around, some planting joke seeds into the ground, others watering smiley-face flowers. Nearby, a big treasure chest is half-buried with the label ''Natural Resource: Humor'' on it, glowing gently to emphasize its value. In the background, rolling hills and bright blue skies with fluffy clouds shaped like laughing faces add to the lighthearted tone. The entire scene looks like a conservation effort, with park ranger hats on some characters and informational posters about the importance of humor pinned on trees. The overall mood is bright, friendly, and whimsical, giving the sense that humor is an essential, precious natural resource being lovingly protected.'),
 (1817, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I have an existential map; it has ''you are here'' written all over it.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, oversized map resembling those found in tourist spots, but with a twist: the entire map is covered in many scattered, large red stickers all saying ''YOU ARE HERE.'' The map is pinned on a stand or wall, and a confused character, looking puzzled and scratching their head, stands in front of it trying to understand. The background is simple, perhaps with a few trees or benches indicating a park or public place. The character should be drawn in a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon style with expressive eyes and a slightly comedic bewildered expression. The overall tone is playful and whimsical, emphasizing the absurdity of having every part of an ''existential'' map marked as the current location.'),
 (1864, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'If a man has common sense, he has all the sense there is.', 'Sam Rayburn', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man with his head replaced by a giant, classic human brain labeled ''Common Sense''. The man is dressed in everyday casual clothes and stands confidently with his hands on his hips. Around him are floating speech bubbles or little icons representing various senses: an eye for sight, an ear for hearing, a nose for smell, a mouth for taste, and a hand for touch. All these senses are depicted as smaller and faint compared to the oversized ''Common Sense'' brain. The background is simple, maybe with a gentle gradient or a plain color to keep focus on the character. The overall style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated in a lighthearted, cartoonish way to highlight the pun on ''all the sense there is'' being equated to common sense.'),
 (2080, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Man was predestined to have free will.', 'Hal Lee Luyah', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing at a large, old-fashioned book labeled ''Destiny'' that is open on a stand. The man looks puzzled and confused, scratching his head. Behind him is a whimsical thought bubble showing a signpost with two arrows: one says ''Free Will,'' the other says ''Predestined Path,'' but both arrows point in the same direction. The background should be simple and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and playful lines to emphasize the irony and confusion inherent in the joke about predestination and free will coexisting. The overall style is cartoonish and non-threatening, with soft colors and clear, simple details. Avoid any religious symbols or complex metaphysical imagery, focusing instead on the amusing contradiction suggested by the joke.'),
 (2218, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Reality is merely an illusion, albeit a very persistent one.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene featuring a quirky, whimsical philosopher character wearing round glasses and a tweed jacket, standing in a surreal landscape where the ground is a giant checkerboard and the sky is filled with floating clocks and melting objects reminiscent of a dream. The philosopher holds a tiny, glowing orb labeled ''Reality'' that seems to shimmer and slightly distort the surroundings. Around him, various everyday objects—like a chair, a cup of coffee, and a streetlight—appear slightly fuzzy or transparent to emphasize the illusion concept. The overall mood is light and playful, with exaggerated, colorful shapes and a slightly melting, dreamlike background to humorously illustrate the idea that reality is an illusion but a very persistent one.'),
 (2497, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Uncertain of Certainty: What exists is, what isn''t doesn''t, what didn''t wasn''t. That doesn''t mean that what won''t didn''t but what might may.', 'Ken Robertson', 'A whimsical cartoon scene featuring a quirky philosopher character standing on a small cliff edge, pondering existential questions. He wears a quirky thinking cap, stroked beard, and round glasses. Around him float translucent bubbles labeled with phrases like ''What exists is,'' ''What isn''t doesn''t,'' ''What didn''t wasn''t,'' and ''What might may.'' One bubble is cracked or uncertain-looking. In the background is a whimsical night sky filled with stars and vague shapes that blend reality and imagination, symbolizing uncertainty. The philosopher gestures with one hand toward an invisible far horizon while scratching his head with the other, looking both puzzled and amused. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing thoughtfulness without heaviness. Use bright, soft colors and exaggerated, cartoonish proportions to keep it humorous and accessible.'),
 (14, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Relatable', 'What can''t affect you isn''t really there. But that doesn''t mean what isn''t really there can''t affect you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting calmly on a park bench, eyes closed, smiling peacefully. Around them, faint translucent ghost-like shapes (representing ''things that can''t affect you'' because they''re not really there) float harmlessly, looking silly and harmless. However, one of these ghostly shapes is shown momentarily casting a visible shadow or ripple that subtly causes the person to sneeze or twitch, highlighting the contradiction. The background is a simple park setting with trees and a clear sky, and the overall tone is light and whimsical rather than spooky. The characters and ghosts should be colorful and exaggerated with friendly, non-threatening expressions to emphasize humor and irony without any sense of danger or fear.'),
 (3000, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'I have seen the truth and it makes no sense.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a bewildered person standing in front of a bizarre signpost labeled ''Truth''. The signpost has arrows pointing in conflicting, nonsensical directions like a spiral, zigzags, question marks, and abstract shapes. The person has wide eyes and a confused expression, scratching their head. Around them are floating symbols representing confusion: swirling question marks, exclamation points, and abstract squiggles. The background is simple, with a clear sky and a few whimsical clouds shaped like question marks. The style is bright and playful, emphasizing humor and confusion without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (2659, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Asking whether machines can think is like asking whether submarines can swim.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sideways-view of a large, shiny, metal submarine underwater with big cartoonish eyes and a little thought bubble showing bubbles (to indicate breathing). Next to it is a large, retro-style robot with visible gears and bolts, looking puzzled, also underwater but not swimming in a graceful fish-like way – instead it awkwardly bobs in the water with its arms stiff and legs straight, clearly struggling to ''swim''. Above the robot is a comic-style text bubble saying: ''Can machines think?'' while above the submarine is a text bubble saying: ''Can submarines swim?''. The background is a simple ocean scene with a few small fish looking confused and a simple ocean floor with rocks and seaweed, drawn in bright and cheerful colors. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity of comparing thinking to swimming in machines and submarines.'),
 (2677, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Bizarreness is not a state of mind, it''s relative.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side in a surreal setting. One character is a normal-looking person with a simple puzzled expression, wearing everyday clothes. The other character is wildly bizarre, perhaps an alien or a whimsical creature with unusual shapes, bright colors, and mismatched body parts (like a clock for a head and spaghetti arms). Around them are floating objects that contrast normal and strange: a regular tree beside a melting, Dali-style tree, a typical house next to a surreal, twisted building. A small signpost between them reads ''Bizarreness: Not a state of mind, it''s relative.'' The background should be colorful but quirky, with a dream-like, abstract style to highlight the idea of relativity in bizarreness. The art style is lighthearted and playful, similar to a comic strip or cartoon, to emphasize the conceptual humor without being dark or scary.'),
 (2855, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Fate keeps on happening.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing on a winding path labeled ''Life''. Ahead, a large, comically exaggerated figure labeled ''Fate'' stands with arms crossed and a sly grin, as if casually insisting that things just ''keep on happening''. The person looks surprised and slightly bewildered, scratching their head. The background is simple with a few whimsical clouds and a signpost pointing forward that reads ''Events''. The style is lighthearted and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the inevitability and randomness of fate continuing to unfold.'),
 (15, 'Absurd Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'What you cannot avoid, Welcome.', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a big, friendly anthropomorphic obstacle with a smiling face standing firmly in the middle of a busy street. The obstacle is shaped like a large, colorful roadblock or traffic cone with exaggerated eyes and a welcoming grin. Around it, cartoon people dressed in everyday clothes are humorously trying to walk past but are gently being stopped or guided by the obstacle. One person has a confused expression, another is shrugging, while a third is cheerfully waving at the obstacle. The background shows a sunny, cheerful urban setting with simple buildings and trees. A whimsical speech bubble emerges from the obstacle, saying, ''What you cannot avoid, Welcome.'' The overall style is bright and playful with bold outlines and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humorous tone.'),
 (2754, 'Absurd Humor, Physical Comedy, Pun, Unknown', 'Deja Fu: The feeling that somehow, somewhere, you''ve been kicked in the head like this before.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing dazed with stars and little birds flying around their head, indicating they just got kicked. Behind them, a large, cartoonish foot is in mid-air, about to deliver a playful kick to their head. The person''s eyes are wide and swirly, with a confused and slightly pained expression. The background is simple, maybe a plain park or street setting, to keep focus on the action. Above them is a speech bubble saying, ''Deja Fu: The feeling that somehow, somewhere, you''ve been kicked in the head like this before.'' The overall style is exaggerated and whimsical, with bright colors and rounded outlines to emphasize the slapstick, lighthearted nature of the joke.'),
 (1671, 'Absurd Humor, Physics, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Every body continues in its state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line, except insofar as it doesn''t.', 'Sir Arthur Eddington', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a physics classroom. At the center, a quirky, slightly confused-looking physics teacher stands next to a blackboard with Newton’s First Law written on it (“Every body continues in its state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line…”). The teacher is gesturing to a simple drawing on the board: a cartoonish ball rolling straight, but just after a bend where it abruptly stops or veers off in a ridiculous direction. Nearby, a student at their desk has a puzzled expression, scratching their head. Around the classroom, playful elements include a few science posters (like a rocket ship or atoms) and a rolling toy car that has just collided with a schoolbag. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated with expressive faces, emphasizing the unexpected twist that the law doesn’t always hold exactly, making it an amusing take on physics. No realistic or technical detail is needed, just clear comic exaggeration and minimal props to keep the scientific setting obvious and funny.'),
 (3213, 'Absurd Humor, Physics, Science Humor, Steven Wright', 'If your car could travel at the speed of light, would your headlights work?', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a futuristic, sleek car with bright, exaggerated headlights, seemingly zooming at an impossible speed. The car is drawn with motion lines to emphasize extreme velocity, almost stretching across the panel. The background is a blurred starry sky or space to suggest traveling at or near the speed of light. In front of the car, a cartoon person (driver) is looking puzzled or scratching their head, glancing at the car’s headlights which are turned on but depicted as confused—one headlight has a question mark above it, the other a small cartoon light bulb flickering uncertainly. Include simple, bright colors and the overall style should be lighthearted and playful to match the joke’s absurd concept. No people or objects should appear distressed or in danger.'),
 (2888, 'Absurd Humor, Physics, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Going the speed of light is bad for your age.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful cartoon character standing beside a futuristic race car or spaceship labeled ''Light Speed Machine.'' The character is looking at a large, comically exaggerated calendar or birthday cake showing many candles, appearing shocked or dismayed. Nearby, a clock or stopwatch displays a speed approaching the speed of light with little light beams or motion lines suggesting extreme speed. The background can include stars or space elements to emphasize the light speed theme. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to convey the joke about how moving at light speed would affect aging (relativity). No violence or negative elements.'),
 (1314, 'Absurd Humor, Pirates, Word Play', 'Where can you find a pirate who has lost his wooden legs? Right where you left him.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a pirate standing still on a simple wooden plank dock beside the sea. The pirate is missing both wooden legs and instead has normal human legs, looking slightly puzzled or confused. He wears a classic pirate outfit with a striped shirt, bandana, eye patch, and a large pirate hat with a skull emblem. Around him, there are two wooden peg legs leaning unused against a barrel or the dock''s edge. The background shows a calm ocean with a small sailing pirate ship anchored nearby. The style is bright, colorful, and playful with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the joke’s silliness and the pirate’s fixed location.'),
 (2816, 'Absurd Humor, Planet Humor, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Earth is the least peaceful planet in our solar system', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the solar system with all the planets lined up like characters at a peace conference. Earth looks frazzled and chaotic, illustrated with little icons like explosions, storms, tiny angry people, and traffic jams around it. The other planets appear calm, serene, or indifferent, each with peaceful facial expressions or simple peaceful symbols like olive branches or doves above them. The background is a starry space scene with the sun nearby, and a banner overhead reads ''Interplanetary Peace Summit.'' The style is colorful and exaggerated, highlighting the contrast between the calm planets and the very stressed Earth, making the concept of Earth being the ''least peaceful'' visually obvious and funny.'),
 (1942, 'Absurd Humor, Poetry, Quotes, Science Humor', 'In science one tries to tell people, in such a way as to be understood by everyone, something that no one ever knew before. But in poetry, it''s the exact opposite.', 'Paul Dirac (1902-1984)', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, depict a friendly and enthusiastic scientist in a lab coat holding a clipboard and pointing at a large, clear, simple chart or diagram with basic shapes and labels. The scientist has a big smile, and a small group of diverse people (different ages, clothes) stand attentively, clearly engaged and understanding the explanation. On the right side, depict a whimsical, somewhat mysterious poet wearing a beret and holding a quill pen, standing before a blackboard filled with swirling, abstract, and complex scribbles, symbols, and shapes that look confusing and tangled. The poet has a knowing smirk, while a small confused audience scratches their heads or looks puzzled. The overall style is bright, playful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between clear communication in science and the complex enigmatic nature of poetry. Include a banner or caption above that reads: "Science vs. Poetry: Communication Styles" to frame the humor.'),
 (2548, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'What this country needs is a good five-cent nickel.', 'Franklin P. Adams', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set outside a U.S. government building or a Capitol-style dome building with an old-fashioned large sign that reads ''What this country needs: A good five-cent nickel.'' In the foreground, show a giant, exaggerated nickel coin with a big 5¢ symbol that looks shiny and oversized, drawing people''s attention. Around the scene, sketch a few confused or pondering citizens—diverse in age and style—scratching their heads or looking amused. The style should be light and cartoonish with bright colors and simple line work. Include a speech bubble from one character saying the joke phrase to emphasize the pun. The coin should look comically out of place as a literal gigantic nickel, highlighting the absurdity of the phrase. No violence or anything inappropriate—just a funny, silly political/social commentary imagery without any direct negativity.'),
 (1623, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Democracy is the art and science of running the circus from the monkey cage.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene depicting a circus setting. In the foreground, a large monkey cage with an excited monkey inside is shown. The monkey is holding a small megaphone and a circus ringmaster''s hat, looking both mischievous and proud. Surrounding the cage is a group of various circus performers and animals looking confused, bewildered, or comically frustrated—such as a clown juggling balls poorly, a lion yawning, and a tightrope walker tangled in their rope. Above the cage, a banner reads ''Democracy Circus'' with bright, playful lettering. The background shows a circus tent interior with colorful flags and spotlights, emphasizing the lively, chaotic atmosphere. The overall style is exaggerated and light-hearted, capturing the absurdity and humor of the phrase without any negativity. The visual should suggest that the ''monkey cage'' is the control center, humorously implying the monkey is in charge of the circus, reflecting the joke''s metaphor about democracy.'),
 (1940, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'In America, anybody can be president. That''s one of the risks you take.', 'Adlai Stevenson (1900-1965)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a typical American town hall or presidential debate stage with a large banner reading ''Presidential Candidates''. In the center stands a cartoonish, exaggeratedly goofy character wearing a suit and a big ‘Everyman’ smile, clearly out of place among serious, confident-looking candidates. The goofy character might be holding a ballot or microphone awkwardly. The audience, filled with ordinary people of diverse ages and backgrounds, appears both shocked and bemused. Some are whispering or pointing. The scene is bright, colorful, and playful, emphasizing the idea that literally anyone, including unlikely characters, can run for president in America. Avoid any political details or likenesses; keep all characters generic and cartoonish to keep humor light and universal.'),
 (1941, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'In politics stupidity is not a handicap.', 'Napoleon Bonaparte', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a traditional political setting: a podium with a microphone at center stage, where a confident, slightly cartoonish politician is giving a speech. The politician has exaggerated features like a big smile and empty, goofy eyes to suggest cluelessness. Around the podium are several puzzled or surprised audience members, scratching their heads or whispering to each other. On the side, a judge’s bench or a scoreboard reads a sarcastic note: ''Stupidity: Not a Handicap.'' The background includes a banner that says ''Politics.'' The overall style is light-hearted and silly, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to convey comedy without offense.'),
 (2204, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Politicians are the same all over. They promise to build a bridge even when there is no river.', 'Nikita Khrushchev', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of politicians standing proudly next to a brand-new, elaborate bridge. The bridge is large, impressive, and stretches across dry, cracked ground with no river or water body underneath. The politicians are dressed in formal suits with exaggerated happy and confident expressions, maybe one of them holding a blueprint or ribbon-cutting scissors. Nearby, puzzled locals wearing casual clothes look on with confused or skeptical expressions. The background is a sunny clear day with a few trees or distant hills, emphasizing the nonsensical placement of the bridge. Include a signpost next to the bridge that says ''New Bridge Project.'' The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish to emphasize the absurdity and satire of the situation.'),
 (2303, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'The first duty of a revolutionary is to get away with it.', 'Abbie Hoffman', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a sly, cartoonish revolutionary character sneaking away from a chaotic protest scene. The revolutionary is wearing a classic beret and simple revolutionary attire, tiptoeing with a mischievous grin while glancing back over their shoulder. Behind them is a blurred crowd waving signs and banners, some with flames and smoke in the background to suggest upheaval but drawn in a lighthearted, exaggerated style. The revolutionary holds a small flag or pamphlet labeled ''Revolution'' but looks clearly focused on escaping rather than fighting. The overall style is colorful, playful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the ironic idea that the revolutionary''s ''first duty'' is just to run away unscathed. The setting can be a generic city street or park plaza with humorous details like spilled coffee or startled pigeons to add comedy without violence or intensity.'),
 (1386, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'A conservative is a man with two perfectly good legs who has never learned to walk.', 'Franklin D. Roosevelt', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a well-dressed man labeled ''Conservative'' standing awkwardly still in the center. He has two perfectly healthy legs shown clearly, but instead of walking forward, he is stubbornly standing with arms crossed and a confused or stubborn expression on his face. Around him, there are visible footprints showing a path leading away from him in a forward walking motion, implying that walking is common knowledge he simply hasn''t used. The setting is a simple park or sidewalk with a couple of trees and a park bench nearby to give context. The style is lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated facial features and a bright color palette to emphasize the joke''s playful tone. No one else in the scene is present, drawing full focus on the man''s refusal to walk despite being physically able to do so.'),
 (2456, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'This is a strange country we live in. When it comes to electing a President, we get two choices. But when we have to select a Miss America, we get 50.', 'Jay Leno', 'A cartoon scene split into two panels side by side. The left panel shows a voting booth with two exaggeratedly grumpy-looking male candidates standing behind podiums labeled ''Presidential Election.'' A confused or bemused voter stands in front holding a ballot with only two options. The right panel depicts a stage brightly lit with colorful spotlights and a banner reading ''Miss America Pageant.'' Fifty glamorous women contestants line up on stage in dazzling gowns, each numbered, smiling and waving to an excited audience. The voter from the first panel now looks shocked or overwhelmed, observing the large crowd of contestants. Include humorous cartoon expressions and exaggerate the contrast between the small number of presidential candidates and the large number of pageant participants to highlight the joke. The style should be vibrant, funny, and playful without any political imagery or aggression.'),
 (2527, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'We may not imagine how our lives could be more frustrating and complex -- but Congress can.', 'Cullen Hightower', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a cluttered desk with papers and a computer, clearly overwhelmed. Behind or above them, a large, exaggerated caricature of the U.S. Capitol building looms, but instead of being just a building, it has cartoonish arms, hands, and a mischievous smirk, as if it’s intentionally complicating things. The building might be juggling or tangled in a web of red tape and complicated documents, emphasizing complexity and frustration. The setting should feel exaggerated and comical, with the person showing exaggerated expressions of confusion and annoyance, and the Congress-building character looking gleefully devious. Bright colors and simple lines keep the tone light and humorous, emphasizing the joke that Congress makes life more complex and frustrating.'),
 (2208, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Politics is not the art of the possible. It consists in choosing between the disastrous and the unpalatable.', 'John Kenneth Galbraith', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a politician standing at a podium labeled ''Politics.'' The politician looks confused and stressed, scratching their head while looking at two large doors behind them. One door has a sign saying ''Disastrous'' and is dark, cracked, and ominous with smoke puffing out. The other door says ''Unpalatable'' and appears like a giant unpleasant dish with exaggerated cartoonish bad smells wafting upwards, featuring eyeballs and odd colors. The background is a simple office or government building setting. The politician is wearing a suit and tie, with exaggerated wide eyes and a furrowed brow to emphasize the dilemma. The overall style is colorful, playful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the difficult and unappealing choices inherent in politics in a lighthearted, non-threatening way.'),
 (1852, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I would like to electrocute everyone who uses the word ''fair'' in connection with income tax policies.', 'William F. Buckley', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a colorful office environment. In the center, a frustrated character, possibly a tax inspector or a politician, stands holding a cartoonishly large lightning bolt or a vintage style electric prod labeled ''Fair Punisher.'' This character has an exaggerated angry expression, with steam coming from their ears, and looks toward an audience or a group of characters just off-screen. Surrounding the main character are several smaller cartoon figures, depicted mid-sentence with speech bubbles containing the word ''fair'' repeatedly. The setting features a large wall chart titled ''Income Tax Policies'' with graphs and dollar signs. The style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and dynamic poses, emphasizing humor without any violence—lightning bolt is clearly a gag prop, and no one is actually getting hurt. Other small details include papers labeled ''Tax reform'' flying around and a calendar on the wall showing ''Tax Day.'' The overall tone is comedic, focusing on the frustration with the overuse of the word ''fair'' in tax debates, presented as a silly cartoon scenario rather than an actual threat.'),
 (2264, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Take the diplomacy out of war and the thing would fall flat in a week.', 'Will Rogers', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a war scenario literally missing its ''diplomacy.'' Picture two groups of cartoon soldiers on opposite sides of a battlefield, but instead of traditional weapons, one side holds a large, oversized word bubble labeled ''Diplomacy'' like a tangible object—a big colorful balloon or a heavy book. The other side looks confused and concerned, with their weapons drooping and their battle gear lacking energy. The battlefield is simple and stylized, with trenches or barriers, but noticeably, without the ''Diplomacy'' object, the scene looks limp and deflated, emphasizing the pun that without diplomacy, war ''falls flat.'' Include some exasperated generals or commanders scratching their heads in bewilderment. The overall tone should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the quirky metaphor. No realistic violence or gore—just playful and imaginative personification of abstract concepts in a war setting.'),
 (2272, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'The 10 Commandments contain 297 words. The Bill of Rights is stated in 463 words. Lincon''s Gettysburg Address contains 266 words. A recent federal directive to regulate the price of cabbage contains 26,911 words.', 'Atlanta Journal', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting four separate items side by side on a simple light-colored background. On the left, a stone tablet labeled ''10 Commandments'' with roughly 10 chunky, ancient-looking lines carved in stone, showing an old, solemn style. Next to it, a parchment scroll labeled ''Bill of Rights'' with neat, dense cursive writing filling the paper, rolled slightly at the edges. Beside that, an old-fashioned typewritten letter titled ''Gettysburg Address'' with a neat block of text, about half the size of the scroll, on yellowed paper. Lastly, a huge, absurdly long stack of official-looking government documents labeled ''Federal directive to regulate cabbage prices,'' towering comically high and spilling papers everywhere, with many tiny, dense words visible on the top sheet. On the floor or table, there are a few scattered green cabbages to emphasize the topic. The style is colorful, exaggerated cartoon with simple facial expressions on the documents: the tablets look serious, the scroll dignified, the letter calm, and the big stack overwhelmed and chaotic. Lighthearted and clean, no people are needed, just the documents personified by subtle eyes or expressions. The contrast in length and complexity should be visually humorous and clear.'),
 (2606, 'Absurd Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'You couldn''t even prove the White House staff sane beyond resonable doubt.', 'Ed Meese', 'A cartoon scene of the White House lawn, drawn in a humorous style with exaggerated features. In the foreground, a group of staff members wearing typical office attire with badges stand looking quirky and eccentric—one nervously adjusting their glasses, another clutching a clipboard with wildly scribbled notes, and a third making a silly face. A judge, dressed in traditional robes and wig, holds a large oversized magnifying glass up to the group, squinting as if trying very hard to find proof. A speech bubble from the judge says, ''Not sane beyond reasonable doubt!'' The White House building is visible in the background with classic columns and the American flag waving above. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, capturing an investigative court-like scene with absurd humor about proving sanity, without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (2159, 'Absurd Humor, Politics, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Nothing is so admirable in politics as a short memory.', 'John Kenneth Galbraith', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a politician at a podium giving a speech. The politician has an exaggeratedly large head with a comically tiny brain visible through a transparent section, symbolizing forgetfulness. Around him are floating cartoon-style thought bubbles containing crossed-out images of past promises, scandals, and statements, illustrating the ''short memory.'' The background includes a crowd of diverse, cartoonish people with puzzled and amused expressions. A calendar on the wall shows multiple crossed-out dates, reinforcing the theme of forgotten events. The style is light and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and simple lines to keep it playful and non-threatening.'),
 (1349, 'Absurd Humor, Programmers, Pun', 'When your hammer is C, everything begins to look like a thumb.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a person holding a hammer, but instead of a normal hammer head, the hammer is shaped exactly like a giant thumb. The character is looking slightly confused or surprised, staring at their hand and the thumb-shaped hammer as if they can’t tell the difference anymore. Around the character, several objects that are commonly hammered — like nails or a wooden board — are visible, but exaggeratedly resemble thumbs as well. The setting is a simple workshop or garage with a workbench, toolboxes, and scattered tools. Use bright, simple colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the confusion and humor. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bold outlines and playful proportions to create a funny and absurd atmosphere without violence or negativity.'),
 (3079, 'Absurd Humor, Programming Humor, Tech Humor, Unknown', 'If God had intended Man to program, we would be born with serial I/O ports.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a newborn baby lying in a crib in a bright, cheerful nursery. Instead of a regular human body, the baby’s torso has visible computer-style serial I/O ports (the classic 9-pin D-sub connector) where its belly button would normally be. The baby looks content and curious, with wide eyes and a slight smile. Nearby, a cute stork wearing glasses holds a clipboard, glancing at the baby with a puzzled expression. The nursery includes common baby items like a mobile overhead with hanging toys shaped as little computers and circuit boards. A digital clock on the wall humorously displays ''Hello, World!'' The background is colorful and lively, drawn in a playful cartoon style emphasizing the absurd juxtaposition of technology and newborn innocence, without any hint of violence or adult themes.'),
 (3134, 'Absurd Humor, Programming Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'You can''t make a program without broken egos.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene set in a typical open office with several quirky programmers sitting at their desks filled with computers, keyboards, coffee cups, and stacks of code printouts. One programmer is proudly holding up a finished program on his screen, smiling confidently. Around him, scattered on the floor and desks, are shattered, oversized cartoonish egos depicted as cracked, anthropomorphic trophies or shiny helmets with faces showing hurt expressions. A thought bubble above the main programmer says, “You can’t make a program without broken egos,” humorously highlighting the struggle of coding teamwork. The background shows a whiteboard with flowcharts and funny motivational posters about collaboration. The cartoon style is playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize humor without any negative tone.'),
 (2538, 'Absurd Humor, Project Management, Quotes, Workplace', 'What I need is a list of specific unknown problems we will encounter.', '(Actual Dilbert Manager Quotes)', 'A humorous cartoon-style office scene with a stressed-looking person sitting at a cluttered desk covered in papers and a laptop. The person is scratching their head and looking confused. In front of them is a large, comically long scroll titled ''List of Unknown Problems,'' which is blank except for a big question mark at the top. Around the desk, small thought bubbles show absurd, exaggerated problems like a robot malfunctioning, a UFO sighting, or a giant banana slipping on a peel—implying unknown and unpredictable troubles. The background shows a whiteboard with a scattered flowchart and charts labeled ''Possible Issues'' but all ending in question marks. The overall tone is light, poking fun at the futility of planning for unknown problems. The cartoon style should be bright and exaggerated to enhance the humor and confusion.'),
 (1380, 'Absurd Humor, Psychology Humor, Quotes', 'A competent and self-confident person is incapable of jealousy in anything. Jealousy is invariably a symptom of neurotic insecurity.', 'Robert A. Heinlein', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting on a park bench. One character appears relaxed, confident, and self-assured, sitting back with a smug smile and arms crossed confidently. A glowing aura or light bulb above their head highlights their competence and calm demeanor. The other character is visibly upset and jealous, glaring sideways at the confident character with crossed arms, a furrowed brow, and steam or squiggly lines rising from their head to represent neurotic insecurity. Surrounding them are subtle visual metaphors: a small jealousy monster or green-eyed cartoonish figure whispering into the upset character''s ear. In the background, a simple park setting with trees and a path to keep the scene lighthearted and friendly. The art style should be colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing exaggerated facial expressions to convey confidence and jealousy humorously without hostility.'),
 (1589, 'Absurd Humor, Psychology Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Big egos are big shields for lots of empty space.', 'Diana Black', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, inflated ego represented as a big, shiny, exaggeratedly oversized bubble or balloon shaped like a human head or bust. The balloon is comically blocking or shielding a tiny person inside it, but the person is looking a bit sad or empty-handed, highlighting the emptiness inside. Around the ego balloon, there are small symbols representing space or emptiness, like empty shelves, open boxes, or little voids. The setting is simple, maybe with a neutral background and a floor for grounding, and the tone is light and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the huge ego and the emptiness inside rather than anything negative or threatening.'),
 (3195, 'Absurd Humor, Psychology Humor, Steven Wright', 'Depression is merely anger without enthusiasm.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. The first character represents ''Depression'' and looks gloomy, with slouched posture, droopy eyes, and a dark cloud hovering faintly over their head. They wear dull, gray clothing and have a small frown. The second character represents ''Anger without enthusiasm'' and looks visibly frustrated but tired or disinterested; their face is red with irritation, but their mouth is neutral or slightly downturned as if they don’t really care. This character is surrounded by little steam puffs but no energetic motion lines, emphasizing lack of enthusiasm. Between them is a simple, bright signpost or speech bubble with the text: "Depression is merely anger without enthusiasm." The background is minimal and lightly colored to keep focus on the characters, drawn in exaggerated cartoon styles to clearly display emotions without being dark or heavy.'),
 (1856, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'I''d give my right arm to be ambidextrous.', 'Brian W. Kernighan', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing with a comically exaggerated missing right arm, which is shown as a simple stump. The person looks cheerful and hopeful, with a big smile on their face and an expressive eye, possibly a raised eyebrow to emphasize the joke. Near them is a thought bubble showing a perfect pair of hands holding objects effortlessly, symbolizing ambidexterity. The setting is simple and clean, with a neutral background to keep the focus on the character and their condition. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, using bright colors and clear, bold outlines to give a friendly and funny vibe. Optionally, a small sign or label saying "Ambidextrous Goals" could be included nearby as a humorous touch, but the focus remains on the missing right arm and the character’s wish to be ambidextrous.'),
 (1857, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'I''d give my right arm to be ambidextrous.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in the center looking thoughtful and slightly puzzled. The person is cartoon-styled with exaggerated features, wearing casual clothes. Their right arm is humorously detached and floating next to them, held by a little string or tether, emphasizing the joke about giving their right arm away. Both hands are shown clearly, one missing the right arm but the left arm intact. Above the person is a thought bubble with a simple drawing showing a left hand and a right hand labeled ''Ambidextrous'' with a small arrow pointing to both hands. The background is plain or simple indoor setting, like a hobby room with a desk and some pens or art supplies to subtly hint at the desire to write with both hands. The overall tone is light, friendly, and silly, drawn in a colorful, exaggerated cartoon style with playful expressions and no violence or negativity.'),
 (2371, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'The quickest way to a man''s heart is through his chest.', 'Roseanne Barr', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused-looking man standing upright, chest exposed like a medical diagram, with a large target on his chest. A smiling character holding a big, exaggerated arrow labeled ''Quickest Way'' is aiming directly at the man''s chest. Surrounding them are cartoonish hearts floating around, but instead of approaching the heart area, the arrow is comically pointed at the chest/thorax area. The background is simple, bright, and cheerful to emphasize the pun. The characters have exaggerated expressions—man surprised or puzzled, arrow-holder confident and playful. Include a small sign or label near the man that reads ''Man''s Heart'' with an arrow pointing at his anatomical heart location inside the chest to underline the pun.'),
 (2574, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'When you come to a fork in the road, take it.', 'Yogi Berra', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a winding country road that literally splits into two paths. At the junction stands a large, shiny metal fork (the eating utensil) stuck upright in the ground, right where the road forks. A confused traveler, wearing casual clothes and a backpack, is standing next to the fork scratching their head with a puzzled expression. There is a simple road sign nearby that reads ''Fork in the Road''. The background features green rolling hills, a bright sunny sky with a few fluffy clouds, and distant trees. The style is light-hearted and whimsical, with exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the visual pun on the phrase ''fork in the road.'' The fork in the ground is oversized and shiny to make it obvious and funny.'),
 (2258, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Stupidity is like nuclear power; it can be used for good and evil. And, you don''t want to get any on you.', 'Dilbert', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left half, show a smiling, goofy-looking character holding a glowing, green cartoonish atomic nucleus with sparkles around it, symbolizing ''good'' use of nuclear power. On the right half, depict the same character accidentally spilling a glowing green substance labeled ''stupidity'' onto themselves, with exaggerated shocked expression, wide eyes, and a small puff of green smoke to show something bad happening. The background should be simple, bright, and colorful, emphasizing the contrast between positive and negative uses. Include a sign or small label near the spill that says ''Don''t get any on you!'' in playful lettering. The style should be cheerful and exaggerated like a light-hearted comic strip, without any threatening or serious elements.'),
 (2401, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes, Science Humor', 'The two most common things in the universe are hydrogen and stupidity.', 'Harlan Ellison', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in outer space showing a cute, oversized hydrogen atom with a big happy face floating among colorful stars and planets. Next to the atom stands a clueless-looking human character with a silly, vacant expression, scratching their head. The character is wearing a space helmet and a simple spacesuit, emphasizing the cosmic setting. Around them are whimsical labels pointing to the hydrogen atom titled ''Most common element'' and the human character titled ''Most common stupidity,'' as if they are both equally abundant in the universe. The background is filled with twinkling stars and a few distant galaxies to reinforce the vastness of space, but the focus remains on the friendly atom and the goofy astronaut. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish to keep the tone light and humorous without any negativity.'),
 (1616, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'Deep down, I''m pretty superficial.', 'Ava Gardner', 'A humorous cartoon featuring a character standing with a big grin. The character looks relaxed and confident. The background shows layers of the earth beneath their feet, like soil, rock, and minerals, but only plays a minor role to establish the idea of "deep down." The character is holding a mirror, admiring themselves, emphasizing vanity and surface-level focus. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to convey the pun on being "deep down" yet "superficial." No other characters or complex backgrounds are necessary, focusing mainly on the character, the mirror, and the subtle earth layers beneath.'),
 (1849, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'I worship the quicksand he walks in.', 'Art Buchwald', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a character who looks awestruck or mesmerized, standing near a patch of quicksand. The quicksand is personified with subtle eyes and a faint smile, giving it a playful, almost worship-worthy expression. The character is gazing at the quicksand as if it’s a divine figure, maybe with sparkling eyes or little glowing stars around their head to emphasize admiration. The setting is outdoors with a few trees, bushes, and a simple patch of sandy earth with quicksand in the center. Include a small sign next to the quicksand that says ''Quick sand'' to clarify the scene. The overall mood should be lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated, cartoonish features and bright colors, capturing the pun on the phrase ‘I worship the ground he walks on’ but replacing ground with quicksand for the comedic twist.'),
 (16, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Relatable', 'When one door closes and another door opens, you are probably in prison.', NULL, 'A cartoon-style prison hallway featuring two large metal doors. One door is shown closing with a heavy slam, complete with motion lines and a ''clang'' sound effect. Another identical door nearby is ajar, slightly open with a bright light shining through, suggesting entrance or exit. Inside the hallway, a confused prisoner wearing classic striped prison clothes and a ball-and-chain attached to his ankle looks back and forth between the doors with a puzzled expression. The walls are plain and gray, with a small barred window casting shadows. A simple bench and a water fountain near the closed door add to the setting. The overall style should be humorous and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and clean, bold lines typical of comic strips.'),
 (2953, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'I almost had a psychic girlfriend but she left me before we met.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a young man looking wistfully at a large crystal ball on a small round table. Inside the crystal ball, a whimsical, slightly transparent female figure is waving goodbye while stepping away, as if she can see the future and is already leaving. The man has a surprised and slightly sad expression. Around them, add subtle psychic or fortune teller props such as tarot cards, a flickering candle, and mystical smoke curls rising from incense. The background should be cozy with drapes, giving the impression of a small fortune teller''s room. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, capturing the irony of meeting a ''psychic girlfriend'' who left before they could meet in real life.'),
 (2711, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Clones are people two.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two identical people standing side by side. Both have surprised and playful expressions, emphasizing that they are clones of each other. One might have a finger pointing cheekily at the other as if saying "we are people two!" In the background, a simple laboratory setting with a few scientific gadgets like test tubes and a computer monitor displaying DNA helix or clone charts. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated cartoon features to accentuate the humor. The focus is on the pair and the idea that the clone is literally the ''people two,'' playing on the phrase ''people too.'' No harsh lines or complex backgrounds; keep it simple and funny.'),
 (2896, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Gravity brings me down.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a character standing on the ground looking frustrated with a small cloud or thought bubble above their head containing a literal depiction of the word ''Gravity'' as a big, heavy, invisible force pulling them downward. The character is slightly slumped over, as if weight is pushing on their shoulders, with exaggerated wavy motion lines indicating downward pull. Surrounding the character is a simple outdoor scene with a tree and grass to establish they are on Earth. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun in the phrase ''Gravity brings me down.'' There should be no violence or negativity, just a cartoonish, relatable expression of feeling weighed down physically and metaphorically by gravity.'),
 (2964, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Shopping Jokes, Unknown', 'I bought a gym membership at CostCo and now I have 36 pack abs', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a CostCo store aisle. In the foreground, a cheerful person is holding a huge, oversized pack of 36 cans or bottles labeled ''Abs'' (like an energy drink or a snack) with a proud grin. The ''36 pack abs'' are literally a bulky 36-pack container being held like a gym membership. Around them, shelves are stocked with similarly oversized items, but the focus is on this ridiculous package. The background shows a CostCo sign overhead, and maybe a few puzzled shoppers glancing at the large ''36 pack abs'' product. The style is playful with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun between gym abs and a pack of products, no actual gym or gym equipment is shown to keep the joke focused on the pun.'),
 (3208, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Sports Humor, Steven Wright', 'If at first you don''t succeed, skydiving is not for you.', 'Steven Wright', 'A cartoon scene showing a person wearing a skydiving suit and goggles, standing nervously at the edge of an open airplane door high in the sky. The person is sweating and clearly hesitant to jump. Behind them, a skydiving instructor stands with arms crossed, looking unimpressed. Below, a safe landing area with a bullseye target is visible on the ground far beneath the clouds. The airplane interior shows a few other cheerful skydivers ready to jump, conveying a humorous contrast to the hesitant person. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated, typical of a cartoon humor format.'),
 (3105, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Star Wars Humor, Unknown', 'Why did the Jedi kill his master? To get to the other side!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a Jedi character dressed in classic robes and wielding a glowing blue lightsaber. The Jedi is standing comically on a simple wooden bridge that crosses over a calm, shallow river. On the opposite side of the bridge, a surprised and slightly confused Jedi Master character wearing similar robes and holding a green lightsaber watches the younger Jedi. The younger Jedi is mid-stride, looking cheeky or mischievous, as if determined to ''get to the other side.'' The background should be light and playful, with a few simple trees and a clear blue sky to keep the tone fun and whimsical. Include a small sign next to the bridge that says ''The Other Side'' to emphasize the pun. The style is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor, no violence or harshness depicted—just a playful take on the classic joke format involving Star Wars elements and a harmless bridge crossing metaphor.'),
 (3191, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Steven Wright', 'All those who believe in psycho kinesis, raise my hand.', 'Steven Wright', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with a person standing confidently on a stage or platform, addressing an audience. The person has one hand raised and is smirking mischievously. Nearby is a disembodied hand floating mid-air, raised as if by itself, creating a magic or psychic vibe. The audience members look puzzled or confused, some scratching their heads. Background should be simple, maybe an auditorium or conference room setting. The style is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the comic effect. Include a small banner or sign behind the speaker saying ''Psycho Kinesis Meeting'' or something similar to set the context. The floating hand should be clearly distinct and cartoonishly animated to emphasize the joke about psychokinesis and the impossibility of someone else raising the speaker''s hand remotely.'),
 (3197, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Steven Wright, Word Play', 'Everyone has a photographic memory; some just don''t have film.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side. The first character looks confident and cheerful, holding a large vintage camera pointed at their own head, symbolizing their ''photographic memory.'' The second character looks puzzled and slightly frustrated, holding an empty camera film box labeled ''No Film.'' Both characters have thought bubbles: the first has a clear, bright photo developing in the bubble, while the second has a blank or faded photo. The background is simple, maybe a plain park or indoor setting, focusing attention on the characters and their cameras. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the joke about memory and film. No violent or inappropriate elements included.'),
 (2651, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'After finishing lunch, the cannibal says: a sandwich is a sandwich, but a manwich is a meal!', NULL, 'Draw a funny cartoon scene showing two cannibals sitting at a rustic wooden picnic table in a jungle clearing. One cannibal, looking satisfied and slightly mischievous, is holding a plate with a large sandwich. The other cannibal, wide-eyed and amused, is holding a big sandwich labeled ''Manwich'' that looks like a sandwich but shaped like a tiny person between the bread slices. The setting is bright and colorful with tropical plants and trees in the background. Both characters should have exaggerated cartoon features, like big round eyes and toothy grins, and wear simple tribal or jungle-inspired clothing made of leaves. Include some bones and cooking utensils around the table to imply a cannibal feast, but keep everything lighthearted and humorous without any graphic content. The speech bubble over the first cannibal says: "A sandwich is a sandwich..." and the second cannibal’s speech bubble completes: "...but a Manwich is a meal!" The overall vibe should be playful and silly, emphasizing the pun on the word ''Manwich.'''),
 (2762, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Did you hear the one about the guy with the broken hearing aid? Neither did he.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing with a confused expression, holding a broken hearing aid in his hand. The hearing aid looks visibly cracked or broken with little cartoon-style stars or zigzag lines indicating damage. Around him, sound waves or musical notes are drifting away silently, showing he cannot hear anything. The background is simple, maybe just a park or a living room to keep focus on the man. Include a speech bubble above him that says, ''Did you hear about the guy with the broken hearing aid?'' and another bubble coming from him saying, ''Neither did he.'' The style should be light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the comic misunderstanding in a bright and colorful cartoon format.'),
 (2909, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Have you ever tried to eat a clock? It''s very time consuming.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, round wall clock with exaggerated features like big eyes and a wide-open mouth. The clock is sitting on a plate at a dining table, as if it''s food. A person with a fork and knife looks puzzled and hesitant, staring at the clock ready to ''eat'' it. The table has a simple tablecloth and a few utensils scattered around. The background is a cozy kitchen or dining room setting with a clock-themed wall decoration for extra emphasis. The overall style is colorful, playful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions conveying confusion and amusement.'),
 (3027, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I recently won a ski race. Everyone else died in an avalanche. It was a landslide victory.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful skier at the bottom of a snowy mountain with arms raised in victory wearing typical ski gear (ski suit, goggles, helmet). Around him, faint, ghostly, cartoon-style outlines of other skiers are partially buried under fluffy white snow, with little puffs of snowflakes scattered about to suggest an avalanche just passed. Above the scene, a large, colorful banner reads ''Race Winner!'' In front of the skier, a podium shaped like a snowdrift with a gold medal hangs around his neck. The background shows snowy pine trees and a clear blue sky. The whole style is lighthearted and cartoonish without any dark or grim elements, emphasizing the pun ''landslide victory'' literally with snow piled like a small landslide on the slope.'),
 (3039, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I successfully figured out how to weigh a rainbow.  Turns out it was pretty light.', NULL, 'A bright, colorful cartoon scene showing a cheerful person holding an oversized weight scale that has a big, vibrant rainbow stretched across it like a ribbon. The rainbow gently rests on the scale’s platform, sagging slightly to show it’s very light. The scale’s dial is clearly visible and points to a very low weight number. The person wears a playful, surprised expression, maybe scratching their head or smiling broadly. The background is simple and sunny with a few fluffy clouds to emphasize the outdoors. The overall style is whimsical and exaggerated, emphasizing the fun and absurdity of weighing something intangible like a rainbow.'),
 (3046, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I took an IQ test and the results were negative.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a puzzled person sitting at a desk with an IQ test paper in front of them. The person looks confused, scratching their head or with a raised eyebrow. The test paper is prominently shown with big bold letters stating ''IQ Test Result: Negative'' as if it were a medical test result. Around the desk are typical office or classroom items like a pencil, eraser, and a small stack of papers. The background is simple to keep attention on the character and the test result. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to enhance the joke''s absurdity, with bright colors and comical facial expression emphasizing confusion and surprise.'),
 (3136, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'You don''t need a parachute to go skydiving. You need a parachute to go skydiving twice.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a skydiver mid-air during a jump. The skydiver is wearing a typical jumpsuit and goggles, with arms and legs spread out as if falling freely. Above the skydiver, include a large open parachute with a big smiley face on it, symbolizing safety and success. To the side, show a second parachute laying unused on the ground with a sad, deflated look, emphasizing it''s only needed if the first jump didn''t go well. The background should be a bright blue sky with a few fluffy clouds to set a light, airy mood. Add a subtle caption or sign somewhere showing the joke''s punchline: “You don''t need a parachute to go skydiving. You need a parachute to go skydiving twice.” The style should be colorful, playful, and exaggerated to enhance the comedic effect without any danger or violence depicted.'),
 (3137, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'You gotta take the lemons and throw ''em.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a small lemon tree laden with bright yellow lemons. The person is mid-action, preparing to throw a lemon with an exaggerated, playful expression on their face. Around them, several lemons are flying through the air, some already mid-toss. Nearby, a basket or bowl overflowing with lemons sits on the ground. The background is simple, bright, and cheerful, emphasizing the playful mood of ''taking lemons and throwing them'' instead of the usual phrase. Include vibrant colors and exaggerated cartoon-style features to enhance the humor and lightheartedness of the scene.'),
 (3144, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'You know, I''d give my right arm to be ambidextrous.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing with both arms visible. The person has a comically exaggerated empty right arm stump, clearly showing it has been ''given away,'' while the left arm looks normal. The person''s facial expression should be a mix of wistfulness and irony, as if regretting the phrase ''I’d give my right arm to be ambidextrous.'' Include a simple background like a park or living room to keep focus on the character. Optionally, add a speech bubble above the person containing the joke text. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and playful without any violence or discomfort.'),
 (2710, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Cliches are a dime a dozen, avoid them like the plague.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two separate panels. On the left panel, show a cheerful street vendor at a small stand with a big sign saying ''Clichés for Sale: A Dime a Dozen!'' The vendor is holding a handful of fix-me-up clichés, like ''Break a leg'', ''Better late than never'', written on slips of paper. On the right panel, depict a nervous character awkwardly stepping back, looking alarmed and clutching their chest as if avoiding a scary invisible threat labeled ''The Plague'', which is illustrated as a classic old-style microbe cartoon with eyes and a mischievous grin. Both panels are bright, colorful, and exaggerated with expressive faces to enhance the humor. The overall style should be lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the play on words about avoiding clichés ''like the plague'' while ironically presenting clichés for sale.'),
 (3255, 'Absurd Humor, Pun, What do you call...', 'What do you call a nose with no body? Nobody knows', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, standalone human nose floating in mid-air with no body attached. The nose has exaggerated nostrils and a surprised expression, perhaps with eyes and a mouth on it to add personality. Below or next to the nose, a comical, puzzled character (a person with a thought bubble containing a question mark) looks up at it, scratching their head in confusion. The background is simple, maybe a plain light color or a vague room setting to keep focus on the floating nose. The style is colorful and playful, with bold outlines and exaggerated facial features to enhance the joke''s whimsy.'),
 (17, 'Absurd Humor, Puns', 'What''s worse than a box full of snakes? A box that''s SUPPOSED to be full of snakes', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two large, open boxes placed side by side on a wooden table. The first box is overflowing with cartoonish, colorful snakes that look lively and slightly mischievous, with some slithering out of the box. The second box is also open but completely empty, with a big label on it reading ''Snakes Inside'' in bold letters. A confused character, drawn in a funny, exaggerated style—maybe a person with wide eyes and scratching their head—stands between the two boxes, clearly puzzled and disappointed that the box supposed to have snakes contains nothing. The background is simple, maybe a backyard or a warehouse setting, keeping focus on the boxes and the character. The overall style is light and playful with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the joke’s irony.'),
 (1504, 'Absurd Humor, Puns, Quotes, Road Humor', 'Alberta Highway Sign:  Pick your rut carefully. You will be in it for the next eighty miles.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a long, straight Alberta highway stretching far into the horizon with fields or prairies on both sides. In the foreground, a large, official-style highway sign reads: ''Pick your rut carefully. You will be in it for the next eighty miles.'' The road itself is depicted as having deep, comical ruts or grooves that the tires can slide into. A couple of cartoon cars can be visualized driving along—one car visible with its wheels clearly stuck in one of these exaggerated ruts, looking slightly frustrated or bemused. The sky is bright with a few fluffy clouds to keep the mood light and funny. The overall style should be colorful and playful to emphasize the pun and the idea of being ‘stuck’ in a rut for a long distance, avoiding any harsh or serious tones.'),
 (1420, 'Absurd Humor, Puns, Quotes, Science Fiction Humor', 'A hypothetical paradox: What would happen in a battle between an Enterprise security team, who always get killed soon after appearing, and a squad of Imperial Stormtroopers, who can''t hit the broad side of a planet?', 'Tom Galloway', 'A cartoon scene depicting a comical standoff between two groups on a neutral, simple background. On the left side, draw a small group of futuristic security guards dressed in sleek, Star Trek: Enterprise-style uniforms with visible worried or defeated expressions. Show a few faint, ghostly outlines behind them to suggest they often get ''killed soon after appearing.'' On the right side, depict a squad of six Imperial Stormtroopers in classic white armor holding blasters, but looking clueless or distracted with exaggeratedly wide eyes and silly expressions. Their blaster shots should comically miss everywhere, with some shots bouncing off a large cartoonish planet shaped like a target labeled "Broad side of the planet" in the background. Above the scene, include a humorous sign or thought bubble reading: "Who wins?" The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated in a lighthearted, cartoonish manner emphasizing the humor in both groups'' well-known failings: the security team’s bad luck and the stormtroopers’ poor aim.'),
 (3091, 'Absurd Humor, Puns, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, instead of a fancy, expensive engagement ring, you could present your wife-to-be with a giant foam hand that said ''You''re #1!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man nervously proposing to a woman. Instead of holding a small, elegant diamond engagement ring box, he is presenting her with an oversized, bright foam hand like those seen at sports events, with a big ''#1'' printed on the palm. The foam hand is comically huge compared to the man and woman. The woman looks surprised and amused, with raised eyebrows and a smile. They are outdoors in a park with a few trees and a bench in the background. The man is dressed casually but neatly, and the woman is wearing a simple dress. The foam hand should be colorful and exaggerated in size to emphasize the joke. The overall drawing style is playful and cartoonish with soft outlines and expressive faces to highlight the humor of replacing an expensive ring with a silly foam hand.'),
 (3258, 'Absurd Humor, Puns, Weather Humor, What do you call...', 'What do you call a very old snowman? Water', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon scene depicting a snowman that is clearly melting. The snowman should have a sad or surprised facial expression, with its eyes wide and a small frown. Instead of a full snowman body, it is partially melted into a puddle of water on the ground. Include typical snowman features like a carrot nose, coal eyes, and a scarf that is drooping and wet. The background should show a bare patch of ground with some small drips of water around the puddle. Maybe add a small sign or label near the puddle that says ''Very Old Snowman'' to emphasize the joke. The overall style should be humorous and cartoonish, with bright colors to keep it light and funny.'),
 (18, 'Absurd Humor, Puns, Workplace', 'When companies ship styrofoam, what do they pack it in?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a shipping warehouse with a puzzled-looking cartoon box character standing beside a giant shipping crate. The crate is humorously overflowing with white, puffy, cloud-like pieces of styrofoam shaped like tiny boxes, with some pieces stacked haphazardly inside and some floating outside the crate as if they were being packed. The box character has wide eyes and a comical expression of confusion. In the background, there’s a simple conveyor belt with various packaging materials (bubble wrap, tape rolls, cardboard boxes), emphasizing the shipping context. The scene has bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to keep the mood light and funny. The overall vibe is playful and cartoonish, focusing on the funny paradox of styrofoam needing packaging itself.'),
 (1715, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes', 'Give me a museum and I''ll fill it.', 'Pablo Picasso (1881-1973)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a large art museum with tall walls and classic columns. The focus is on a mischievous, cheerful character – a curator or artist type – enthusiastically carrying or juggling an exaggeratedly large pile of quirky and random objects that clearly don’t belong in a museum, such as giant rubber ducks, silly hats, colorful balloons, oversized shoes, and a random garden gnome. The background should show classic art pieces like paintings and sculptures with confused or surprised visitors looking on. The character’s expression is playful and proud, as if they are confidently promising to fill the empty museum space with these absurd items. The setting is bright and whimsical to add to the overall light-hearted and comedic tone of the scene.'),
 (2261, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Real Estate Humor', 'Surburbia is where the developer bulldozes out the trees, then names the streets after them.', 'Bill Vaugnhan', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a newly built suburban neighborhood. In the foreground, show a large bulldozer tearing down big green trees with a cloud of dust. Nearby, a cheerful, somewhat oblivious developer in a hard hat is holding a clipboard and pointing proudly at a street sign that says ''Oak Tree Lane''. Show several other street signs visible in the background with tree-related names like ''Maple Avenue,'' ''Pine Street,'' and ''Birch Boulevard.'' Include typical suburban elements such as simple houses, trimmed lawns, and a clear sky. Emphasize a contrast between the missing trees on the bulldozed lot and the street names referencing those very trees, creating an ironic and funny visual. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated expressions for a lighthearted cartoon style.'),
 (1557, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Anyone who isn''t confused here doesn''t really understand what''s going on.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of people gathered around a complicated-looking map or flowchart filled with confusing symbols, arrows pointing in all directions, question marks, and indecipherable text. One person in the center looks utterly bewildered, scratching their head with wide eyes, while another person nearby appears calm and overly confident, smiling and pointing at the map. The background is a simple office or meeting room setting, with a whiteboard or poster behind them covered in more confusing scribbles. Include exaggerated expressions and slightly chaotic elements to emphasize the confusion. Bright, colorful cartoon style with clear facial expressions to highlight the humor of misunderstanding a complex or nonsensical situation.'),
 (1851, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Religion Humor', 'I would have made a good Pope.', 'Richard M. Nixon (1913-1994)', 'A humorous cartoon featuring a man standing proudly inside the grand, ornate interior of the Vatican''s Sistine Chapel. The man is wearing a simple white shirt and pants but is trying on an oversized, slightly crooked papal tiara that comically dwarfs his head. He strikes a confident pose with one hand on his hip and the other holding a large golden crozier (the Pope''s staff). Around him are startled, wide-eyed cardinals in red robes and hats, humorously looking at him with a mix of surprise and disbelief. The background shows famous frescoes from the ceiling, including a subtle nod to Michelangelo''s Creation of Adam, but with a lighthearted twist, like a smiling cherub giving a thumbs-up. The style is bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and the man''s overconfidence about being a good Pope, despite his casual attire and obvious lack of preparation for the role.'),
 (2271, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Science Humor', 'That''s the nature of research -- you don''t know what in hell you''re doing.', '''Doc'' Edgerton', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered research laboratory filled with typical science equipment like microscopes, test tubes, books, and computers. In the center, a confused and slightly frazzled scientist with wild hair and lab coat is scratching their head while looking at a whiteboard filled with complicated, nonsensical diagrams, question marks, and random doodles symbolizing confusion. Nearby, a cat wearing tiny glasses sits on a stack of papers, looking equally perplexed. The background shows scattered notes, empty coffee cups, and a calendar that says ''Research Day 37.'' Above the scientist, cartoon-style floating text reads, ''That''s the nature of research -- you don''t know what in hell you''re doing.'' The overall tone should be light, funny, and relatable to anyone who’s ever struggled with complex tasks, drawn in a colorful and exaggerated cartoon format with expressive characters and a cluttered but cozy atmosphere.'),
 (2247, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'Some see this as a glass half empty, some see it as a glass half full. I see it as a glass twice as big as it needs to be.', 'George Carlin', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a single oversized, transparent drinking glass placed prominently on a simple table. The glass is filled halfway with water, clearly showing the liquid level in the middle. Next to the glass, include two small, stylized thought bubbles. One bubble shows a character imagining the glass as half empty, depicted with a sad or worried face. The second bubble shows the same character imagining the glass as half full, depicted with a happy or optimistic face. A third, larger thought bubble floats above the character, showing the character shrugging with a neutral or slightly amused expression, while pointing at the glass itself and imagining it as absurdly large—much bigger than a regular glass, emphasizing the idea that the glass is just too big for the amount of water inside. The overall style should be light, simple, and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions and playful lines to enhance the cartoon humor without any harsh elements. The background should be minimal to keep focus on the glass and the thought bubbles. The character can be a simple human figure with minimal detail, focusing on expression and gesture.'),
 (1476, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'A visit to a fresh place will bring strange work.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a large, unusual, freshly opened office or workplace labeled ''New Place.'' The person looks confused and overwhelmed, holding a stack of strange, mismatched papers and a bizarre-looking tool or gadget, scratching their head. Around them, odd and quirky office equipment and tools are scattered, such as a computer with wires tangled up, a coffee machine that looks like a strange contraption, and a calendar with unpredictable tasks written on it. The background has a sign that reads ''Welcome to Fresh Place - Expect the Unexpected!'' The color palette is bright and cheerful, emphasizing the absurdity and funny confusion of starting strange work in a new environment.'),
 (2411, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'There ain''t no rules around here! We''re trying to accomplish something!', 'Thomas Edison', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cluttered, chaotic workshop or office. Two characters are featured: one is a stern-looking boss or supervisor, mid-gesture with one hand raised as if making a point, wearing business casual clothes. The other is a frustrated or bewildered worker surrounded by messy desks and tools or papers scattered everywhere, with a concerned facial expression. In the background, there is a whiteboard or wall with scribbles, unfinished projects, and crumpled notes. The setting emphasis is on the disorder and lack of structure, with funny details like a tipped-over chair, a coffee cup spilled, and a clock showing odd times. The boss’s speech bubble contains the phrase, "There ain''t no rules around here! We''re trying to accomplish something!" The overall tone is light and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor in the anarchic but goal-driven atmosphere.'),
 (2151, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Word Play', 'No sane man will dance.', 'Cicero (106-43 B.C.)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man dressed in ordinary clothes, standing stiffly with a worried expression on his face. He is surrounded by a whimsical, slightly chaotic dance floor where cartoonish, silly dancers of all kinds perform exaggerated, goofy dance moves—some twirling, some flailing arms, others leaping. The man looks out of place and cautious amid this goofy crowd. The setting is colorful and playful, with musical notes floating around, disco lights, and a sign overhead that reads ''Dance Floor''. No one is serious; the overall tone is light and comical, emphasizing the contrast between the man''s refusal to dance and the joyful silliness of everyone else dancing wildly around him.'),
 (1647, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Don''t play dumb. You''re not as good at it as I am.', 'Colonel Flagg MASH', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people facing each other with playful expressions. One person looks confidently smug while the other tries to look ''dumb'' but clearly fails, showing frustration or envy. Both are standing in a simple everyday setting, such as a casual room or a park bench. Above them, a speech bubble from the smug person says, "Don''t play dumb. You''re not as good at it as I am." The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial features and body language emphasizing the playful competition between them. Include playful details like one character scratching their head awkwardly while the other has a cheeky grin, highlighting the joke’s theme of pretending to be less smart than one really is.'),
 (1958, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Instead of getting married again, I''m going to find a woman I don''t like and just give her a house.', 'Rod Stewart', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a middle-aged man with an exaggerated, cheeky expression, standing confidently with his arms crossed. Next to him is a small, simple cartoon house, maybe with a ''For You'' sign or a little gift bow on top. The man is thinking or saying the joke text in a speech bubble: ''Instead of getting married again, I''m going to find a woman I don''t like and just give her a house.'' The setting should be lighthearted with no backgrounds that imply negativity—perhaps a sunny day, with simple trees or clouds, to maintain a friendly cartoon style. No aggression or harshness; the humor is in the absurdity and irony. The woman is not depicted, leaving the focus on the man''s decision and the house as the ''gift.'' The overall tone is playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial features to emphasize the joke’s ironic twist.'),
 (2069, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Science Humor', 'Love is only the dirty trick played on us to achieve continuation of the species.', 'W. Somerset Maugham', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a devilish Cupid-like character with small horns and a mischievous grin, holding a bow and arrow aimed at a confused couple standing nearby. The couple looks bemused and slightly suspicious, as if they are realizing Cupid’s arrow is a ''dirty trick.'' Around them, DNA helix symbols float in the air subtly, hinting at the biological purpose behind love. The background is light and playful with soft pastel colors, reinforcing the humorous, non-threatening nature of the scene. The couple is dressed in casual, everyday clothes, and Cupid is drawn in a classic cherubic style but with a cheeky twist to emphasize the joke’s punchline about love being a ruse for species continuation. The overall tone is lighthearted and comical, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon.'),
 (2590, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Social Humor', 'Women are cursed, and men are the proof.', 'Roseanne Barr', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a courtroom labeled ''Fate Tribunal.'' In the center, a cheerful woman dressed as a playful witch, holding a large scroll titled ''Curse List,'' points dramatically at a group of ordinary men standing on the witness stand looking bewildered and sheepish. The men vary in appearance—some scratching their heads, some shrugging—clearly depicted as the ''proof'' of the curse. The courtroom audience consists of various funny characters like a judge with a gavel looking amused and a jury of enchanted animals. The mood is light and exaggerated, with comical expressions to keep the tone humorous and not offensive. The background includes silly banners like ''Evidence of Misbehavior'' and funny law books stacked on a table. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and playful details to emphasize the joke''s ironic and absurd nature.'),
 (2450, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Religion Humor, Social Humor', 'They''ve got dancing girls and drinking and wild parties and shows here.  This is no place for a Presbyterian, so I no longer am one', 'Hal Holbrook (in his show Mark Twain Tonight!)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a lively, colorful party room filled with dancing girls in sparkling costumes, people holding drinks and laughing wildly, and a stage with a band playing energetic music. In the foreground, a slightly bewildered man dressed in modest, old-fashioned Presbyterian-style clothing stands apart, looking out of place and nervously clutching a hymnal or Bible. The party atmosphere contrasts sharply with his reserved demeanor. The background includes decorations like streamers, disco balls, and people having fun, emphasizing the wild, carefree setting not typically associated with a Presbyterian. The overall style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated to enhance the humor of the clash between the wild party and the man''s conservative vibe.'),
 (1913, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Safety Humor', 'If you see a bomb technician running, try to keep up with him.', 'USAF Ammo Troop', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a bomb technician in full protective gear—bulky helmet with a clear face shield, heavy padded suit with visible protective layers—running hurriedly. The setting is outdoors, perhaps a park or city street, with a few startled bystanders in casual clothes watching or starting to run behind him. The technician holds a large toolbox or bomb defusal device in one hand, and his exaggerated running pose emphasizes urgency, with motion lines to show speed. Include humorous details like a shoe flying off or sweat droplets, and the expressions of the bystanders should be a mix of confusion and determination as they try to keep up. The background can have simple buildings or park elements like trees and benches to suggest an everyday public space. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and body language to emphasize the joke’s playful warning to run if you see the bomb technician running.'),
 (2375, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Humor', 'The rich will do anything for the poor but get off their backs.', 'Karl Marx', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a wealthy person and a poor person in exaggerated, comedic poses. The wealthy person is standing upright with a smug, slightly worried expression, dressed in fancy clothes like a suit with a top hat and monocle. The poor person is comically small, struggling beneath the wealthy person''s back, literally sitting or crouching on it, looking tired but determined. The wealthy person appears to be trying to push the poor person off their back with both hands, but the poor person clings stubbornly. Surround them with a simple cityscape backdrop or park setting, keeping colors vibrant and the style light-hearted and playful. Include a small pile of gold coins near the wealthy person and a tattered bag by the poor person to emphasize their social statuses. The overall tone is exaggerated and funny, emphasizing the literal interpretation of the joke without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2429, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Humor', 'There is no underestimating the intelligence of the American public.', 'H.L. Mencken', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a large crowd of diverse American people gathered in a public square. The crowd should look a bit silly and distracted, with some people doing absurd things like talking on upside-down phones, staring confusedly at simple signs, or holding exaggeratedly large question marks above their heads. In the background, include a big banner that reads ''American Public Intelligence Test Today!'' with cartoonishly low scores displayed on a scoreboard. The sky is clear, and the setting is bright and colorful to keep the tone light and playful. The focus is on capturing a funny, gentle poke at the collective intelligence in a non-offensive, lighthearted way, using exaggerated expressions of confusion, misunderstanding, and distraction throughout the crowd.'),
 (1708, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Space Humor', 'Fusion power is great as long as you have a really big fusion plant that''s at least 93 million miles away.', 'Ben Bova', 'A humorous cartoon showing a large, futuristic fusion power plant shaped like a giant glowing orb or sun, emitting bright light and energy beams. The plant is located on a small planet or asteroid, with space in the background filled with stars. In the foreground, a worried-looking scientist or engineer in a lab coat stands on Earth, holding papers or a clipboard, looking through a telescope or binoculars pointed at the giant fusion plant. A distance marker shows ''93 million miles'' between Earth and the fusion plant, emphasizing the huge space between them. The Earth should be drawn with familiar continents visible and a slightly exaggerated worried expression (like eyes and a frown) on its surface to add humor. The style should be colorful, light-hearted, and exaggerated, typical of a comic strip or editorial cartoon. No violence or scary elements, just a silly vibe that plays on the idea that fusion power is only safe if it’s very far away, like the sun itself.'),
 (2081, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Space Humor', 'Man will never reach the moon regardless of all future scientific advances.', 'Dr. Lee De Forest, inventor of the vacuum tube and father of television.', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a futuristic space center. In the foreground, a cheerful, slightly clueless-looking man wearing a casual outfit and holding a complex blueprint labeled ''Moon Mission Plan'' waves his hands confidently, as if making a bold claim. Behind him, a highly advanced spaceship is parked, ready for launch, with shiny metallic surfaces and futuristic design elements. Floating above the spaceship, a huge, detailed cartoonish moon shines brightly with a subtle smile and a playful wink, as if mocking the man''s claim. Around the scene, include various scientific instruments like telescopes, satellites, and robot assistants looking puzzled or bemused. The background shows stars and planets emphasizing outer space. The overall style is colorful, exaggerated, and goofy, emphasizing the irony and humor of the man''s confident statement despite obvious scientific progress toward moon travel, making it lighthearted and funny.'),
 (2310, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Technology Humor', 'The generation of random numbers is too important to be left to chance.', 'Robert R. Coveyou', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a serious-looking scientist in a cluttered lab filled with computers and random number generator devices. The scientist is holding a digital tablet displaying a random number sequence, with a determined expression. On the desk, scattered papers show complex math formulas and probability charts. Nearby, a large roulette wheel labeled ''Chance'' sits unused in the corner, covered with a cloth. In the background, a small robot or machine is trying to roll dice with tiny mechanical arms but failing comically. The overall vibe is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the irony that something called ''random numbers'' is treated with such seriousness, suggesting it''s too important to rely on pure luck or chance. The drawing style should be cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the humor.'),
 (2549, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Word Play', 'What was that popping sound? A paradigm shifting without a clutch.', 'Dilbert', 'A cartoon-style drawing showing a confused person standing next to a quirky, old-fashioned car or vehicle with no hands on a clutch pedal. The car is cartoonishly exaggerated with bright colors and a whimsical steam-puff or smoke explosion coming from under the hood, symbolizing the ''paradigm shifting.'' Above the car, a comic-style speech bubble or sound effect bubble contains the words ''POP!'' The person looks bewildered, scratching their head. In the background, colorful arrows and abstract shapes swirl and shift orientation, visually representing a ''paradigm shift'' in a playful, metaphorical way. The overall style is lighthearted and humorous with exaggerated expressions and motion lines to emphasize surprise and confusion, suitable for a comic panel.'),
 (1789, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Workplace', 'I didn''t think; I experimented.', 'Wilhelm Roentgen', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, slightly frazzled scientist standing in a cluttered laboratory. The scientist wears a lab coat, oversized goggles pushed up on the forehead, and messy hair. Around them are bubbling test tubes, colorful chemicals in beakers, and a chalkboard with random formulas and doodles. The scientist holds a beaker with an odd, fizzing green liquid spilling over as they look at it with a surprised, slightly confused expression. Above their head is a thought bubble that reads, ''I didn''t think; I experimented.'' In the background, various amusing experiment results are visible, such as a small explosion puff of smoke, a robot with crossed-out eyes spinning in circles, or a plant growing sideways. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing trial and error in science without any danger or negativity.'),
 (1694, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Self-Improvement Humor', 'Few people think more than two or three times a year; I have made an international reputation for myself by thinking once or twice a week.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a quirky, slightly disheveled man sitting comfortably in an oversized armchair in a cozy living room. The man is smiling proudly and appears deep in thought, with a light bulb above his head flickering on and off. Around him are a few scattered papers, books, and a calendar on the wall highlighting isolated, spaced-out days that have been circled to represent the infrequent moments he ''thinks.'' The calendar clearly shows most days blank and only two or three circles per week, exaggerated and comical to emphasize rarity. In the background, a small globe or world map on a stand hints at his ''international reputation.'' The style should be cartoonish and warm, with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor and irony, avoiding any violent or sensitive imagery.'),
 (1839, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'I think it would be totally inappropriate for me to even contemplate what I am thinking about.', 'Don Mazanowski former Candian Minister of Finance', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting in a simple armchair with a thoughtful look on their face, holding their chin in a classic ''thinking'' pose. Around their head are several comic-style thought bubbles, but each bubble is either blank or filled with scribbles, question marks, or swirling lines to represent confused or indecipherable thoughts. The person looks slightly exaggerated with wide eyes and raised eyebrows to emphasize their puzzlement over their own thoughts. The background is a cozy living room with minimal details—a small side table with a cup of coffee, a window showing a calm day outside, and a floor lamp. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, highlighting the irony of not wanting to even contemplate one''s own thoughts. The style should be bright, simple, and cartoonish, with clean lines and expressive facial features to emphasize the humor without any dark or serious connotations.'),
 (1925, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Sleep Humor', 'I''ll sleep when I''m dead.', 'Warren Zevon', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person lying awake in bed late at night, eyes wide open with an exaggerated sleepless expression. Above the person’s head is a thought bubble containing a small cartoon ghost or skeleton peacefully sleeping in a bed. The bedroom is dimly lit with a clock showing a late hour, an alarm clock on a nightstand, and pajamas tossed aside. The contrast between the restless person and the peacefully sleeping ghost emphasizes the joke''s punchline.'),
 (1753, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Hell is a half-filled auditorium.', 'Robert Frost (1874-1963)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large auditorium with many empty seats and only a small number of people scattered sparsely around. The auditorium is exaggeratedly half-full—half the chairs visibly empty, and the other half occupied by a few bored or mildly annoyed attendees. The perspective emphasizes the emptiness and the dullness of the scene. The stage is simple with a plain lectern or microphone stand, maybe a small spotlight shining down, but no performer. The lighting is slightly dim and the overall mood is one of awkwardness and quiet, capturing the irony of the phrase ''Hell is a half-filled auditorium.'' The style is clean, colorful, and lighthearted, emphasizing the irony and social discomfort rather than horror or negativity.'),
 (2597, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'You can fool too many of the people too much of the time.', 'James Thurber', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky con artist standing on a street corner with a small crowd of diverse, exaggeratedly confused people gathered around. The con artist is holding a large sign that reads, ''Too Many Folks Fooled!'' with a sly grin. The crowd looks a mix of amused, puzzled, and skeptical with raised eyebrows and tilted heads. In the background, a whimsical clock shows various times to emphasize ''too much of the time.'' The setting is colorful and lighthearted, with cartoon-style buildings and a bright sky. The overall vibe is playful and exaggerated without any aggressive or negative elements.'),
 (1772, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Wit', 'Hypocrisy is the lubricant of society.', 'David Hull', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a busy city street filled with people interacting. In the foreground, two characters are shaking hands slyly; one is clearly whispering a secret to the other with a mischievous grin. Around them, gears and machinery labeled ''Society'' are connected by a large, shining tube of lubricant labeled ''Hypocrisy'' that is visibly dripping oil onto the gears, keeping them smoothly turning. In the background, some people look shocked or annoyed, highlighting the irony. The characters are exaggerated and colorful, with playful expressions. The scene uses symbolic elements like the lubricant and gears to humorously portray hypocrisy as a necessary, if somewhat sly, smoothener of social interactions. The overall style is bright, cartoonish, and light-hearted, emphasizing irony without negativity.'),
 (2342, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'The mind of a bigot is like the pupil of the eye. The more light you shine on it, the more it will contract.', 'Oliver Wendell, Jr. Holmes', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, cartoonish human eye center stage. The pupil is exaggeratedly small and tense as a bright, comically oversized flashlight beam shines directly onto it. Nearby, a simple angry-looking character representing a ''bigot'' has a thought bubble above their head with a tiny dark shrinking pupil inside it. The setting is simple and clean, focusing on the eye and the light beam, with exaggerated facial expressions on the character to emphasize stubbornness and contraction. The style should be colorful and playful, emphasizing the contrast between light and the shrinking pupil, embodying the joke’s metaphor clearly without any harsh or negative tone.'),
 (2002, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'It''s good to know that if I behave strangely enough, society will take full responsibility for me.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky, slightly disheveled person standing in the middle of a busy city street. The person has an exaggerated confused or eccentric expression, wearing mismatched clothes and maybe a tilted hat. Around them, passersby look on with varied expressions of surprise or curiosity. In the background, a large, friendly-looking official figure dressed like a social worker or government representative, holding a clipboard and a big stamp labeled ''Responsibility,'' is stepping forward as if ready to ''claim'' the person. The scene should have bright colors, clear cartoon outlines, and a lighthearted, playful vibe to emphasize humor without any negativity. Include subtle visual cues like signs reading ''Society''s Responsibility Dept.'' or a banner overhead, enhancing the joke''s meaning.'),
 (2101, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'Men are conservatives when they are least vigorous, or when they are most luxurious. They are conservatives after dinner.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson', 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a cozy dining room table after dinner. A middle-aged man, looking slightly tired and comfortably full, reclines in a plush chair with a satisfied smirk. He wears a relaxed casual outfit, maybe slippers and a loose shirt. On the table, there are empty plates and a half-full wine glass, suggesting a heavy, luxurious meal. In the background, a clock shows a late evening hour. To emphasize the joke, a small thought bubble shows the man imagining himself as a proud, upright, and serious-looking figure dressed in formal conservative attire. Another smaller scene inset beside him shows a much younger, energetic man (same character as younger self) dressed in similar formal attire but looking lively and dynamic. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated facial expressions to show ''conservative'' seriousness contrasted with post-meal relaxation and luxury-induced sluggishness. The style is simple and cartoonish, with bold lines and bright colors to keep it cheerful and funny.'),
 (2313, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Social Humor, Technology Humor', 'The gossip of the future may not be a backbiting, nosy, tongue-wagging two face, but a supermegabyte, random-access, digital interface.', 'Ronald Zeh', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a futuristic digital environment. In the center, depict a large, goofy-looking anthropomorphic computer chip or digital interface with a smiling, expressive face on its screen. Surround this ''digital gossiper'' with floating holographic speech bubbles filled with pixelated icons like chatter bubbles, emoji, or random digital symbols representing gossip. The background should have sleek, sci-fi elements like circuit lines and glowing data streams to emphasize a high-tech setting. Nearby, show a confused or surprised human character looking at the digital interface with a raised eyebrow, as if hearing gossip from the machine. The overall vibe is playful and lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to highlight the absurdity of a ''digital gossip'' in the future. Avoid any aggressive or negative depictions; focus on the whimsy of technology replacing traditional gossip.'),
 (2378, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Space Humor, Travel Humor', 'The scientific theory I like best is that the rings of Saturn are composed entirely of lost airline luggage.', 'Mark Russell', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in outer space showing the planet Saturn prominently with its famous rings clearly visible. Instead of normal rings, the rings are made up of countless colorful suitcases and luggage pieces swirling around the planet. The suitcases vary in shape, size, and color—some have travel stickers, tags, and straps dangling. Nearby, a small spaceship with a surprised astronaut inside floats, pointing at the luggage-rings with an exaggerated expression of amazement. The background is a starry night sky with a few distant planets and twinkling stars to emphasize the cosmic setting. The scene should be lighthearted, bright, and comical, capturing the absurdity of the idea that lost airline luggage forms Saturn''s rings.'),
 (2459, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'This telephone has too many shortcomings to be seriously considered as a means of communication. The device is inherently of no value to us.', 'Western Union internal memo, 1876.', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an old-fashioned rotary telephone sitting on a small wooden table. The phone has exaggerated features to show its ''shortcomings''—one ear piece hanging loosely by its cord, a dial with numbers jumbled or missing, and a tangled cord snaking messily around the table. Nearby, a bewildered person (cartoon style) with a puzzled expression is holding the receiver awkwardly away from their ear. Surround the phone with little comic-style text bubbles showing symbols of communication failure, such as crossed-out speech bubbles and broken signal icons. The background is simple, possibly a cozy living room or study, to emphasize the vintage device being considered useless as a communication tool. The overall tone is light and playful, emphasizing the irony of the phone being ''inherently of no value.'' The style should be bright and colorful with exaggerated, friendly features for comedic effect.'),
 (1382, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'A computer scientist is someone who fixes things that aren''t broken.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a modern office or home workspace. In the center, a computer scientist (wearing glasses and a casual shirt with a pocket protector) is proudly holding a large colorful toolbox labeled ''Bug Fixes''. The computer scientist is looking at a perfectly functioning glowing computer monitor, which displays a smiling, content face or a simple ''All Systems Go'' message. Around the computer, nothing appears broken or malfunctioning, but the scientist enthusiastically waves a wrench or screwdriver towards it as if ready to ''fix'' it. A confused or slightly amused colleague watches nearby, perhaps sipping coffee and scratching their head, emphasizing the irony. The background includes typical tech paraphernalia like a keyboard, mouse, and cables neatly arranged, reinforcing the professional yet playful atmosphere. The entire scene is drawn in a lighthearted, cartoon style with exaggerated expressions for humor and clarity, using bright colors and simple, clean lines to keep it cheerful and inviting.'),
 (1869, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Theater Humor, Word Play', 'If all the world''s a stage, I want to operate the trap door.', 'Paul Beatty', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a classic theatre stage with red velvet curtains pulled back. Center stage is a large wooden trap door slightly open, with a mischievous person peeking out or leaning close to the trap door’s operating lever, smiling gleefully. Around the stage, actors dressed in various theatrical costumes (such as Shakespearean robes, a jester outfit, and a mime) are posing dramatically or delivering lines. The background includes typical stage elements like spotlight beams shining down, stage props such as a throne or a sword, and an audience in silhouette. The expressions and body language of the actors and the trap-door operator suggest playful anticipation and comic timing. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and playful to emphasize the joke’s witty and slightly cheeky tone without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1465, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Time Humor, Word Play', 'A seminar on Time Travel will be held two weeks ago.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small conference room with a banner on the wall that reads ''Time Travel Seminar.'' In the foreground, a cheerful seminar speaker stands at a podium presenting to a small audience. The speaker holds a calendar with the current date circled prominently, but behind them, a digital sign or wall clock humorously displays a date labeled ''Two Weeks Ago.'' The audience looks confused and puzzled, with some scratching their heads or glancing at their own watches. Include playful, exaggerated expressions on the faces of the characters to emphasize the absurdity of the seminar timing. The setting should be light, colorful, and cartoonish, featuring visual jokes around time confusion, like a clock with backward-moving hands or a poster titled ''Mastering Yesterday.'' Avoid any violent, political, or inappropriate elements.'),
 (1521, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Traffic Jokes', 'Always look both ways when running a red light.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a busy city intersection with traffic lights. A character, drawn in a funny, exaggerated style, is running energetically across the crosswalk while the traffic light shows red. The character''s head is turned dramatically first to one side and then to the other, wide-eyed and comically cautious, as if looking both directions for oncoming cars despite running a red light. Nearby, a few cars are stopped at the intersection, with surprised or confused expressions visible on the drivers'' faces through the windows. The background shows a typical urban street with buildings, traffic signs, and a pedestrian crosswalk painted on the road. The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the joke''s absurdity without promoting dangerous behavior. Bright colors and playful lines should be used to keep it funny and cartoonish rather than serious or realistic.'),
 (2529, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'We owe most of what we know to about one hundred men. We owe most of what we have suffered to another hundred or so.', 'R. W. Dickson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of about one hundred men each, depicted as small stick figures or caricatures to emphasize the large numbers. On the left side, one group is portrayed as inventors or thinkers with light bulbs over some heads, holding books, tools, or scientific equipment, symbolizing knowledge and discovery. They have happy, proud expressions. On the right side, another similar-sized group looks frustrated or miserable, with exaggerated worried faces, holding broken objects or symbols of troubles like thunderclouds or bandages, representing suffering. In the middle or foreground, a large scroll or banner reads: ''We owe most of what we know to about one hundred men. We owe most of what we have suffered to another hundred or so.'' The background is simple and bright to keep focus on the groups, with a lighthearted, cartoon style emphasizing the contrast between knowledge and suffering in a witty way. Avoid any violent or politically charged elements.'),
 (2451, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Wit, Words of Wisdom', 'Things are more like they are now than they ever were before.', 'Dwight D. Eisenhower', 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in the middle of a room that looks very ordinary and modern, like a typical living room or office. The person has a confused but slightly amused expression, scratching their head. Around them, everyday objects are scattered—like a smartphone on a table, a laptop, a coffee mug, and a clock showing the current time. The background shows a window with a clear sky outside, suggesting the present moment. Above the person’s head is a large, whimsical thought bubble containing the phrase: "Things are more like they are now than they ever were before." The style is lighthearted with soft, rounded lines and pastel colors to convey a non-serious, funny vibe. The overall visual is simple but highlights the tautology in the statement through the character''s puzzled look and the straightforward environment.'),
 (1389, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A day without sunshine is like night.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two panels side by side. The left panel shows a bright sunny day with a cheerful sun shining down on a happy character standing outdoors, smiling and enjoying the sunshine. The right panel shows the same outdoor scene at night, with a dark sky filled with stars and a crescent moon, and the same character now looking puzzled or mildly bemused, as if realizing that a day without sunshine effectively means it is night. The background should be simple and colorful, emphasizing the contrast between bright daytime and dark nighttime. Include a subtle light-hearted vibe with exaggerated expressions to convey the joke in a gentle, amusing way.'),
 (1434, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A little ignorance can go a long way.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, cheerful person standing proudly on top of a very long, winding road that stretches far into the distance. The character has a blissfully clueless expression and is holding a tiny map titled ''Ignorance'' upside down. Alongside the road are little signs with humorous warnings like ''Beware of Common Sense'' and ''Logic Ends Here.'' The background is bright and colorful, with exaggerated cartoonish trees and clouds to keep the mood light and playful. The overall vibe is innocent and funny, emphasizing the idea that a bit of ignorance can allow someone to go far without overthinking.'),
 (1705, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'From now on, I''ll connect the dots my own way.', 'Bill Watterson (Calvin & Hobbes)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a table with a typical dot-to-dot puzzle book open before them. The puzzle consists of dots numbered in sequence (1, 2, 3, etc.). Instead of connecting the dots in order, the person is drawing random, zigzagging, and looping lines creating a silly, nonsensical picture. The person looks mischievous and proud, smiling broadly while holding their pencil. Around them, completed dot-to-dot pictures hang on the wall—some neat and correct, others whimsically incorrect. The setting is bright and playful, with cartoon-style exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize fun and cheekiness. The puzzle book’s title says ''Connect the Dots'' in bold letters, and a small speech bubble from the person reads, ''From now on, I''ll connect the dots my own way.'' No violent, sexual, or political elements are included.'),
 (1832, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I not only use all the brains that I have, but all that I can borrow.', 'Woodrow Wilson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky character standing proudly with a confident smile. The character has an oversized head filled with visible cartoonish brains inside a transparent skull cap, suggesting they are using ''all the brains they have.'' Around them, several other smaller characters (humorously depicted as people with glasses or funny hats) have their brains literally popping out, floating gently toward the main character, who is catching or holding them in cupped hands as if ''borrowing brains.'' The setting is lighthearted and whimsical, perhaps a simple room or park background with bright colors. Facial expressions are exaggerated for comic effect, and the whole style should feel playful and silly, enhancing the joke’s notion of mentally borrowing extra brains to think harder or smarter. No violent or inappropriate elements, just funny, absurd imagery that visually represents the idea of collecting or borrowing brains from others.'),
 (1880, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'If I were two-faced, would I be wearing this one?', 'Abraham Lincoln (1809-1865)', 'Draw a cartoon character standing front and center looking slightly puzzled and amused. The character has an ordinary face but is tilting their head as if questioning something. To visually imply the joke, show a subtle, faint ghost-like transparent face exactly behind or overlapping the main face, slightly turned in the opposite direction, as if the character might literally have two faces but only one is visible and solid. The background should be simple and uncluttered, perhaps a plain light color. The character should wear casual modern clothes and have expressive eyes that convey mild confusion or playfulness. The style is exaggerated cartoon with bold outlines and bright colors, emphasizing the humorous, self-aware tone of the joke.'),
 (1930, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I''m not confused, just well mixed.', 'Robert Frost', 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a cheerful person with a quirky, slightly chaotic look. Their hair is tousled wildly, and their clothes are colorful and mismatched. Around their head, include humorous swirls and squiggly lines to represent ''mixing,'' like a blender or paint being stirred. Maybe add small, floating objects around them—like puzzle pieces, cups of coffee, or light bulbs—to symbolize mixed thoughts. The person should have a friendly, smiling expression with wide eyes, suggesting they''re embracing the playful confusion instead of feeling overwhelmed. The background should be simple and bright, emphasizing the lighthearted mood, with no clutter or anything serious.'),
 (2374, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'The reverse side also has a reverse side.', 'Japanese proverb', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a playing card held up by a smiling hand in the center of the frame. The card''s front side is visible and shows a typical design, but the card is shown partially flipped to reveal the reverse (back) side. However, the back side itself has a small image of another card, which is also flipping to show its own reverse side—implying an endless loop of card backs within backs. The background is simple and bright to keep focus on the card, with subtle motion lines around the cards to emphasize the flipping action. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features on the hand and the cards to amplify humor and the infinite recursion idea without any complexity or violence. Optionally, include a small, puzzled cartoon character or emoji in the corner looking at the card with a raised eyebrow or confused smile to enhance the joke''s whimsical, mind-bending nature.'),
 (2412, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'There are 4 kinds of Homicide: felonious, excusable, justifiable, and praiseworthy.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful police detective in classic detective attire—trench coat, fedora, and badge—standing beside a large whiteboard titled ''4 kinds of Homicide.'' The whiteboard is divided into four colorful sections, each labeled: ''Felonious,'' ''Excusable,'' ''Justifiable,'' and ''Praiseworthy.'' The first three sections have typical crime scene icons like a chalk outline, a handcuff, and a courtroom gavel. The last section, labeled ''Praiseworthy,'' includes an amusing twist—perhaps a golden trophy, a superhero cape, and a thumbs-up sign. The detective is scratching his head with a puzzled but amused expression. Surrounding the scene are lighthearted details like a coffee cup labeled ''Detective Fuel'' and a small office plant, all drawn in a bright, cartoon style with exaggerated, friendly shapes to keep the mood light and funny without any violence depicted explicitly.'),
 (2470, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'To be sure of hitting the target, shoot first, and call whatever you hit the target.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky marksman standing confidently in a shooting range. The marksman is holding a large, exaggerated rifle, aiming it without much care or focus. In front of him, a chaotic target board is shown with multiple bullet holes scattered wildly all over it. Some holes hit the bullseye, some are off to the side, and a few even hit random, funny objects like a nearby birdhouse, a squirrel on a branch, and a passing balloon. The marksman has a cheeky grin and a thought bubble above his head that says, ''I hit the target!'' The background is light-hearted and colorful, with a few wooden planks labeling the shooting range, and a whimsical scoreboard showing ridiculous scores. The overall style is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor and absurdity of the idea that whatever you hit counts as the target.'),
 (2521, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'We have deep depth.', 'Yogi Berra', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing next to a large well or deep hole in the ground labeled ''Depth Measurement.'' One character is holding a ridiculously long measuring tape or ruler that stretches far down into the well, with exaggerated length to emphasize the word ''deep.'' The other character looks confused or impressed, scratching their head or peering down the hole with wide eyes. Include a simple background like a grassy field or a construction site to keep focus on the hole and the characters. The style should be lighthearted and fun, with simple lines and expressive faces to highlight the silly exaggeration of ''deep depth.'' Avoid any violent or inappropriate elements.'),
 (2103, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Word Play, Workplace', 'Men have become the tools of their tools.', 'Henry David Thoreau (1817-1862)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing awkwardly in the middle of a workshop cluttered with various tools like hammers, screwdrivers, wrenches, and saws. The man looks confused and overwhelmed, holding a hammer loosely in one hand as if unsure what to do with it. Surrounding him, several anthropomorphized tools with expressive faces and little arms are pointing at him or giving him orders, almost like they’re in charge. One screwdriver is scolding him, a wrench is shaking its head, and a saw is smirking. The background includes a workbench with nails, screws, and blueprints scattered around. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions on the man and the tools to emphasize the joke about men being controlled by their tools rather than the other way around. The setting should feel like a typical handyman’s workshop but with the twist that the tools seem alive and dominant.'),
 (2003, 'Absurd Humor, Quotes, Youth Humor', 'It''s great to be young and insane.', 'Michael Keaton', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a young person with wild, exaggeratedly crazy hair and wide, playful eyes, grinning mischievously. They are energetically jumping on a trampoline or doing something silly like wearing mismatched clothes or bent glasses, symbolizing ''insane'' fun. Around them are playful visual elements like swirling stars, zigzag lines, little cartoon clouds, or exclamation marks to emphasize the crazy, energetic vibe. The background is bright and colorful, with a sunny sky and a carefree atmosphere. Nearby, an older person with calm, mild expression watches, possibly holding a cup of tea, representing the contrast between youthful insanity and age. The style is light-hearted, cartoonish, and exaggerated to keep the mood fun and lively without any negativity or violence.'),
 (3207, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable Humor, Steven Wright', 'If at first you don''t succeed, destroy all evidence that you tried.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene centered around a person who looks frustrated but sneaky. The character is wearing casual clothes and has messy hair, holding a large eraser in one hand and a big trash bag in the other. Around them are scattered broken or crumpled pieces of paper with scribbles, a spilled cup of coffee, and a torn notebook labeled ''Attempts.'' The background shows a desk with a computer and a calendar flipped to a motivational quote that reads ''Try, try again!'' The character is glancing around nervously as if trying to erase or throw away all evidence of their failures. The style should be colorful and exaggerated with playful expressions, emphasizing the humor of trying hard but opting to erase the effort instead of persisting.'),
 (3206, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable Humor, Steven Wright, Workplace', 'If at first you don''t succeed, destroy all evidence that you tried.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated character who looks like they just failed at something. The character is frantically erasing or ripping up papers labeled ''Attempt #1'' or ''Plan,'' tossing them into a small trash bin labeled ''Evidence.'' Nearby, there is a desk cluttered with crumpled papers and a broken pencil. The character wears casual clothing and has a comically exaggerated stressed expression, sweat drops flying off their forehead. A thought bubble above their head reads: ''If at first you don''t succeed... destroy all evidence!'' The background should be a simple room with a bulletin board, a calendar marked with a failed attempt day, and a clock showing late hours to imply persistence and frustration. The art style is light and playful with bold outlines and bright yet simple colors to emphasize the comic tone.'),
 (2775, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Do not walk behind me, for I may not lead. Do not walk ahead of me, for I may not follow. Do not walk beside me either. Just pretty much leave me the heck alone.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing alone on a simple path or sidewalk. The character is drawn in a lighthearted, exaggerated style with arms crossed and a slightly grumpy or annoyed expression. Around them, three footsteps labeled clearly as ''ahead,'' ''behind,'' and ''beside'' float in midair but all are empty—no one is walking in any of those positions. In the background, faint outlines of people are either way ahead, way behind, or far to the sides, emphasizing the person''s desire to be left completely alone. The setting is outdoors with simple trees or bushes, conveying a casual walking environment. The overall style should be bright, clean, and playful, capturing the comic frustration of wanting personal space in an amusing way without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2799, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Don''t rush me. I''m making mistakes as fast as I can.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a cluttered desk filled with papers, a half-empty coffee cup, a laptop, and a pencil holder. The person looks frazzled and overwhelmed, with wild hair and a stressed but determined expression, typing or writing hurriedly. Surrounding them are small chaotic details like crumpled papers flying in the air, crossed-out notes, and a clock showing time passing quickly. Above their head is a thought bubble containing the text: "Don''t rush me. I''m making mistakes as fast as I can." The overall style is light and exaggerated to emphasize the comedic frantic energy, with bright colors and playful lines that highlight the rush and error-making in a fun, relatable way.'),
 (2836, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable, Social Humor, Unknown', 'Everybody is somebody else''s weirdo.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a group of quirky characters in a casual setting, like a park or coffee shop. Each character is distinctly odd or eccentric in their own way: one might be wearing mismatched clothes with funky hairstyles, another could be doing an unusual hobby like juggling rubber chickens, and another has exaggerated glasses and a big grin while holding a pet rock. Above them floats a simple thought bubble or banner with the phrase, ''Everybody is somebody else''s weirdo.'' The expressions on each face are friendly and lighthearted, emphasizing acceptance and fun rather than judgment. The background should remain simple to keep focus on the characters and the quote, with soft, bright colors to keep the mood cheerful and playful.'),
 (2846, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'Everytime that I turn around, the room seems to spin.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing inside a simple room with basic furniture like a chair and a small table. The person is in the center, mid-turn, with a slightly dizzy or confused expression, eyes half-closed or swirly, and arms stretched out for balance. The background shows wavy, spinning lines or spirals around the room to visually represent the sensation of the room spinning. The walls are slightly tilted or curved to enhance the spinning effect, but the style stays light-hearted and funny without any distress. The overall scene is colorful and exaggerated in a cartoon style to emphasize the comedic dizziness, with the person possibly wearing casual clothes and a slight smile or humorous bewilderment on their face. No violence, dark tones, or inappropriate elements.'),
 (3016, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable, Unknown, Workplace', 'I love deadlines. I especially like the whooshing sound they make as they go flying by.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a stressed-out office worker sitting at a cluttered desk with a calendar and a clock on the wall behind them. The calendar prominently shows a deadline date circled in red. The worker has an exaggerated surprised or frustrated expression as they look toward an invisible event. Above the worker, show large, stylized whooshing sound lines and motion effects passing by, emphasizing the sense of an opportunity or deadline zooming past quickly. In the foreground, include some scattered papers, a coffee cup, and a computer screen with a document labeled ''Project'' open but untouched. The setting is a typical, brightly colored modern office environment with a humorous, slightly exaggerated cartoon style that emphasizes the absurdity of missing deadlines with lively motion lines and expressions.'),
 (3017, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable, Unknown, Workplace', 'I may be here in body but my mind is vacationing in Hawaii.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a person physically sitting at a desk in a dull office environment, looking tired and distracted. The office has a computer, papers, and a coffee mug with steam rising. Above the person''s head is a large, colorful thought bubble depicting a sunny Hawaiian beach with bright sun, palm trees, clear blue ocean, and a hammock tied between two palms. In the hammock, a small version of the same person is relaxing with sunglasses and a drink with a little umbrella. The contrast between the bland office and vibrant beach is clear and humorous, capturing the idea that the person''s mind is far away while their body remains at work.'),
 (3042, 'Absurd Humor, Relatable, Unknown, Workplace', 'I think I''ll go to work today. I need the sleep.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in pajamas and slippers sitting at a messy kitchen table in the early morning. The person looks groggy and sleepy, rubbing their eyes while holding a steaming cup of coffee. A calendar on the wall clearly marks the day as a weekday. Behind the person, a clock shows an early hour, like 7 AM. The person has a dreamy thought bubble that shows a cozy bed with fluffy pillows and blankets, symbolizing their desire for sleep. To add humor, nearby a briefcase or work bag is sitting unused on the floor, contrasting with the person''s sleepy demeanor. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the ironic statement that they need to go to work precisely because they want to sleep.'),
 (3092, 'Absurd Humor, Satire, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, lifeguards could remove citizens from beaches for violating the ''public ugliness'' ordinance.', NULL, 'A colorful humorous cartoon scene set at a sunny beach filled with people. In the center, a lifeguard tower stands tall with a stern male lifeguard wearing sunglasses, a whistle around his neck, and a lifeguard uniform. The lifeguard holds a large red stop sign labeled ''Public Ugliness Ordinance Violation''. Around him, several beachgoers with exaggeratedly funny, unconventional, or awkward appearances (such as mismatched swimsuits, wild hairstyles, odd expressions) are being gently but definitely escorted away from the beach by the lifeguard. Other relaxed beachgoers lounge in the sand, sunbathing or playing beach games, looking amused or bewildered by the scene. The sky is bright and there is a large, comical sign near the entrance to the beach reading ''Public Ugliness Ordinance Enforced Here''. The tone is lighthearted and silly, with exaggerated cartoon faces and playful expressions emphasizing the absurdity of the imagined rule.'),
 (2630, 'Absurd Humor, Satire, Unknown', '42.7 percent of all statistics are made up on the spot.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confident character—perhaps a casual, goofy-looking man with a pointer—standing in front of a large flip chart or whiteboard filled with various absurd graphs and numbers. The character is mid-presentation, smiling and pointing to a big, bold statistic written as ''42.7% of all statistics are made up on the spot.'' Around him are several confused or amused listeners, some scratching their heads, others laughing or whispering to each other. The setting is a casual office or classroom with scattered papers, a coffee mug, and a laptop. In the background, a poster humorously displays random made-up data like ''56.3% of statistics are exaggerated,'' emphasizing the joke’s playful critique of statistics. The overall style is exaggerated cartoon with bright colors and expressive faces to highlight playfulness and absurdity without seriousness or anything inappropriate.'),
 (2857, 'Absurd Humor, Science Fiction Humor, Space Humor, Unknown', 'Federation Express: We positively absolutely guarantee to get it there before the Romulans!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a futuristic space delivery office labeled ''Federation Express'' with a flashy neon sign showing their company logo. In the foreground, a confident delivery person wearing a sci-fi uniform with a headset is holding a package marked with a Starfleet emblem. Behind them, a large window looks out onto space, showing a sleek starship speeding away, a Romulan Warbird lurking menacingly nearby but clearly trailing behind. The delivery person has a big, enthusiastic grin and is giving a thumbs-up. A wall poster with the slogan ''Positively absolutely guarantee to get it there before the Romulans!'' is visible, with cartoonish speed lines and a clock icon emphasizing speed. The overall style is colorful, bright, and exaggerated for comedic effect, avoiding any threatening or dark tones.'),
 (3187, 'Absurd Humor, Science Humor, Statistics Humor, Steven Wright', '82.7% of all statistics are made up on the spot.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, confident-looking statistician standing at a podium labeled ''Statistics Conference.'' The statistician, wearing glasses and a lab coat with a pocket full of pens, holds a microphone in one hand and a pie chart in the other. The pie chart is obviously comical—divided into wildly uneven and silly sections like ''99% made up,'' ''1% guess,'' and ''100% nonsense.'' Behind the statistician, a large, colorful presentation screen displays the phrase ''82.7% of all statistics are made up on the spot'' in bold, playful font with exaggerated sparkles or stars around the text. The audience, drawn with exaggerated puzzled and confused expressions, includes a mix of cartoon characters: a person scratching their head, someone raising an eyebrow, and another taking frantic notes. The setting is light-hearted, with bright colors and exaggerated features to emphasize the joke’s playful absurdity. Include subtle visual hints that statistics can be tricky or unreliable, like scattered papers titled ''FACTS?'' or a calculator with crossed-out numbers on it, to add to the comedic atmosphere.'),
 (2770, 'Absurd Humor, Science Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'DNA: A complex organic molecule characterized as the building block of life and appropriately shaped like a spiral staircase to nowhere.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a giant DNA double helix twisted like a spiral staircase standing in the center of an empty, plain room with no doors or windows. The staircase has handrails and steps made of colorful base pairs (A, T, C, G) depicted as cartoonish blocks. At the top of the staircase, a confused cartoon character (scientist with a lab coat and glasses) looks puzzled and scratches their head. The floor around the staircase is blank, emphasizing the ''nowhere'' destination. The overall style should be bright, simple, and exaggerated, emphasizing the absurdity of a beautiful structure leading nowhere.'),
 (2666, 'Absurd Humor, Science Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Basic research is what I am doing when I don''t know what I am doing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a scientist in a messy lab, scratching their head with a confused but determined expression. The scientist wears a lab coat and glasses, standing in front of a cluttered workbench scattered with test tubes, beakers, papers, and open books. Behind the scientist is a large chalkboard filled with scribbles, question marks, and half-drawn formulas, emphasizing confusion and ongoing thought. A small sign on the lab door reads ''Basic Research Lab''. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor of doing serious research while clearly unsure what is happening.'),
 (2919, 'Absurd Humor, Social Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'He who laughs last thinks slowest!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a group of four friends laughing at a joke. Three friends are laughing heartily, pointing or wiping tears of laughter, looking lively and quick-witted. The fourth friend, standing slightly behind them, has a confused, slow-to-react expression, scratching his head as he lets out a delayed, small chuckle. The setting is casual, perhaps a park bench or a living room with simple furniture like a couch and a lamp, emphasizing a friendly gathering. Above their heads, speech bubbles show quick laughter for the first three and a slow, small ''Haha...'' from the last friend, highlighting the punchline ''He who laughs last thinks slowest!'' The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the slow reaction humor.'),
 (3050, 'Absurd Humor, Social Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I went to a 12 step program for compulsive talkers - On and On Anon', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a meeting room labeled ''12 Step Program for Compulsive Talkers'' with a banner in the background reading ''On and On Anon.'' The room has a circle of chairs occupied by cartoon characters who all have exaggerated expressions of endless talking: some have animated speech bubbles filled with continuous lines or gibberish symbols showing nonstop chatter. One character in the center looks a bit overwhelmed, raising a hand as if to speak but unsure when to stop. Include a sign on the wall with the program name to emphasize the joke. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and friendly character designs.'),
 (2839, 'Absurd Humor, Social Humor, Unknown, Words Humor', 'Everyone has the right to be stupid, but some abuse the privilege.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a public park or town square. In the foreground, show a cheerful-looking, slightly goofy character wearing a t-shirt that says ''I Abuse My Privilege'' in big letters. This character is confidently doing something silly or absurd, like trying to fit a huge square peg into a tiny round hole, or holding a sign that says ''Official Stupidity Champion.'' Nearby, a friendly-looking judge or official figure wearing a traditional judge''s wig and robe is holding a large book titled ''Rights and Privileges.'' The judge is watching with an exaggeratedly stern but slightly amused expression. Around them, several ordinary people of various ages and looks are watching with puzzled or entertained expressions. Include a small pet or two, like a curious dog tilting its head or a bird on a branch, adding to the light-hearted tone. The colors should be bright and cheerful, and the style should be a clean, approachable cartoon to emphasize humor and friendliness without any negativity or offense.'),
 (3209, 'Absurd Humor, Steven Wright, Toys, Word Play', 'If Barbie is so popular, why do you have to buy her friends?', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a young girl in a brightly colored playroom full of Barbie dolls. The girl is holding a single Barbie doll in one hand with a puzzled and slightly amused expression. Around her are empty shelves or boxes labeled ''Barbie Friends'' that are conspicuously empty or have price tags on them, emphasizing the idea she has to buy friends separately. A few Barbie dolls are standing apart from each other, looking cheerfully posed but clearly separate. The background includes typical toy room elements like a small table, toy blocks, and posters on the wall with Barbie-themed decorations. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features on the dolls and the girl to enhance the humor of questioning why Barbie’s ''friends'' are sold separately as products.'),
 (3200, 'Absurd Humor, Steven Wright, Wit', 'Half the people you know are below average.', 'Steven Wright', 'Draw a simple, colorful cartoon scene showing a diverse group of cheerful, everyday people standing in two rows. The top row has happy characters standing on a slightly higher platform labeled ''Above Average,'' smiling confidently. The bottom row stands on a lower platform labeled ''Below Average,'' looking normal and relaxed, not upset. A large label or banner overhead says ''Half the People You Know.'' Include subtle visual cues like a graph bar or ruler in the background, humorously emphasizing the split. Make it lighthearted and friendly, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (2753, 'Absurd Humor, Technology Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Deja Fail: A failure which one finds vaguely familiar as if experienced previously, but cannot be sure of.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing in front of a computer screen displaying an error message. The person has a puzzled expression, scratching their head, with a thought bubble above them containing a looping arrow symbol (representing repetition) and a question mark. Nearby, include a calendar with the date circled repeatedly and a post-it note with the phrase ''Deja Fail'' humorously written on it. The background should be an office or home workspace, with a coffee mug labeled ''Oops!'' and scattered papers, emphasizing the frustration of repeatedly encountering the same error without recalling it clearly. The style should be simple, colorful, and lighthearted, avoiding any serious or negative imagery, capturing the idea of vaguely familiar failure in a playful way.'),
 (3060, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'I''d explain it to you, but your brain would explode.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one person confidently explaining something, leaning slightly forward with a finger raised as if making a point. The other person looks on with a confused, slightly dazed expression, eyes wide and mouth slightly open. Above the listener''s head is a stylized cartoon brain that is literally popping or exploding like a colorful comic-style burst, with small pieces flying outward and little stars or sparkles, emphasizing the ''brain explosion''. The background is simple and bright, perhaps with a speech bubble from the explainer saying, "I''d explain it to you, but your brain would explode." The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated to highlight the funny, absurd exaggeration of the phrase, with rounded, friendly character designs and clear facial expressions. No violent or scary elements, just a playful depiction of the mental overload metaphor.'),
 (2915, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor, Word Play', 'He was so narrow-minded he could see through a keyhole with both eyes.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a man with a very narrow, elongated head shaped like a keyhole. The keyhole shape is exaggerated so that the widest part is his eyes, which are looking straight forward, clearly visible on the narrow keyhole face. The man is peeking through an actual door keyhole with both eyes comically aligned exactly with the keyhole shape of his head. The setting is simple: a wooden door with a brass keyhole at eye level. The man’s expression should be curious and focused, as if he is spying or peeking through. The background is plain, to keep focus on the character and the door. Use bright colors and simple lines typical of a lighthearted cartoon style. No other people or objects needed, keep the scene uncluttered and funny by emphasizing the absurd narrowness of the character’s head and his simultaneous use of both eyes through the tiny keyhole opening.'),
 (2979, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor, Word Play', 'I don''t suffer from insanity.  I enjoy every minute of it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a cheerful and slightly wild-looking person sitting comfortably in a cozy armchair, grinning ear to ear with wide eyes that suggest playful craziness. Around them, whimsical objects float or hover in the air: a spinning top, a rubber duck with a party hat, colorful confetti, and scattered playing cards. The background is a bright, lively living room with exaggerated, cartoonish furniture like an oversized lamp and a crooked bookshelf packed with odd items such as a whoopee cushion and a jack-in-the-box popping open. The person wears casual, slightly mismatched clothes with quirky patterns, emphasizing their carefree attitude. A speech bubble above them reads, "I don''t suffer from insanity. I enjoy every minute of it." The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with vibrant colors and playful expressions to capture the joy and fun implied by the joke without any hint of negativity or seriousness.'),
 (3156, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor, Zombies', 'Zombies eat brains. You are safe.', 'Jon Stewart', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple, colorful city park. In the foreground, a worried-looking person with a puzzled expression stands confidently, pointing at their own head as if assuring the audience that their brain is safe. In the background, a group of goofy, cartoonish zombies with exaggerated features—greenish skin, tattered clothes, and droopy limbs—are wandering around. The zombies are looking disappointed or confused, scratching their heads or shrugging because they can''t find any brains to eat. The scene should be light-hearted and playful, with bright colors and no scary or violent elements. Include a simple park bench, a trash can, and a tree to set the scene, but keep the focus on the person and the zombies. The style is clean and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect.'),
 (2680, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Blessed are they that run around in circles, for they shall be known as wheels.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of cheerful people running in exaggerated large circles. The runners are silly and playful, with exaggerated expressions of excitement and determination. Around them, literal wheels with smiling faces roll alongside, suggesting the runners are metaphorically becoming wheels. The background is simple – a park or open field with a clear sky and a few trees. Above the scene, a cheerful banner or sign reads: ''Blessed are they that run around in circles.'' The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing fun and whimsy without any seriousness or stress.'),
 (2725, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Counting in binary is just like counting in decimal, if you are all thumbs.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a table trying to count on their thumbs. The person is looking confused and holding up their thumbs in front of them, as if trying to count using binary numbers. Around the person, small digital numbers or binary digits (0s and 1s) float in the air, representing binary counting. On the table, include a simple piece of paper with decimal numbers written out (1, 2, 3, 4, etc.) and a pencil. The person’s thumbs should be emphasized humorously, maybe exaggerated in size or shown in close-up to highlight the ''thumbs'' pun. The style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to convey the joke visually without any violent, sexual, or political elements.'),
 (2749, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Daylight savings time - why are they saving it and where do they keep it?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing next to a giant, oversized clock with exaggeratedly long clock hands. The person scratches their head, looking puzzled. Around them are several small jars, boxes, and a piggy bank labeled ''Daylight Savings Time'' as if time was a physical item being stored. There''s a shelf behind them filled with various labeled containers like ''Time Saved,'' ''Extra Hour,'' and ''Lost Minutes,'' adding to the silliness of the idea that daylight savings time is something tangible to keep or save. The background is bright with a sun and a moon partially visible, indicating the change between day and night. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish to emphasize the joke’s playful confusion about the literal meaning of ''saving'' time.'),
 (2756, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Deja-intendto: feeling you were going to do this before.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person with a surprised and confused expression, looking at their own hand holding an open notebook or checklist titled ''To-Do List.'' Above their head is a floating thought bubble showing a clock and a calendar marked with previous dates, implying they thought they''d already done the task. The character''s eyes are wide, eyebrows raised, and mouth slightly open as if saying ''Huh? Didn’t I already do this?'' The background is simple and uncluttered to keep focus on the character and their reaction. The caption or a comic-style label above or below reads: ''Deja-intendto: feeling you were going to do this before.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the mental mix-up between intention and action, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features for comedy.'),
 (2789, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Don''t burn your bridges at both ends.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a literal interpretation of the idiom ''Don''t burn your bridges at both ends.'' The central focus is a small wooden bridge over a calm river. One end of the bridge is on fire, with small bright flames and wisps of smoke rising, while the other end is also catching fire, with similar flames and smoke. Near the bridge, a cartoon character (looking worried and cartoonishly panicked) stands on a riverbank holding a bucket of water but looking uncertain how to save both ends. In the background, there could be two separate groups of cartoon people on each side of the river looking confused or stranded, emphasizing the problem caused by burning both ends of the bridge. The scene should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with playful facial expressions and lighthearted fire details, maintaining a fun, non-threatening atmosphere.'),
 (2817, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'ECNALUBMA (ek na leb'' ma) n. A rescue vehicle which can only be seen in the rear view mirror.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a rear view mirror attached to a car''s windshield. In the mirror, a big, bright ambulance with flashing red and blue lights is visible, rushing closely behind, but outside the mirror, there is no ambulance anywhere on the road. The setting is a sunny day on an open highway with a few cars driving ahead. The driver''s hand is visible gripping the steering wheel, and their surprised eyes can be seen in the mirror''s reflection as they notice the ambulance only behind them and nowhere else. Include lighthearted style with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the absurdity of the ambulance only appearing in the rear view mirror.'),
 (2886, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Give me ambiguity or give me something else.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a character standing on a stage with a microphone, as if giving a speech or a dramatic presentation. The character looks slightly confused or caught off guard, shrugging with arms spread wide. Above them is a speech bubble with the words ''Give me ambiguity or give me something else.'' The background is simple, resembling a small comedy club or conference room, with a spotlight on the character. The style is playful and exaggerated, emphasizing the ironic and ambiguous nature of the statement. Include minimal props: a microphone stand, a stool nearby, and an audience of shadowy cartoon figures reacting with puzzled or amused expressions.'),
 (2955, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I am always late, my ancestors arrived on the Juneflower.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person checking their watch with an exaggerated expression of frustration and apology for being late. Behind them, there is a whimsical, old-fashioned wooden sailing ship labeled ''Juneflower'' arriving slowly at a dock with smoke gently puffing from its chimney. Around the dock, there are cartoon ancestors disembarking dressed in old-timey clothing, looking relaxed and unhurried. The setting is bright and cheerful, with a calendar on a nearby wall showing the month of June to emphasize the pun. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and slightly caricatured characters to enhance the humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2998, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I have 6 legs, 8 arms, and 10 heads. What an I? A liar', NULL, 'Draw a comical cartoon character composed of multiple human body parts mismatched and exaggerated. The figure should have six legs spread out in different directions, eight arms waving or gesturing wildly, and ten heads with varied facial expressions, some confused, some smiling, and some looking skeptical. The character should be standing on a simple plain or stage, with a sign or speech bubble above saying, ''What am I?''. The overall style is playful and humorous, with bright colors and exaggerated proportions to emphasize the absurdity. The heads and limbs should clearly look human but cartoonish, arranged in a somewhat chaotic but balanced way to keep the scene funny rather than scary or disturbing. Avoid any violent or mature elements.'),
 (3002, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I haven''t lost my mind -- it''s backed up on tape somewhere.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person with a slightly bewildered expression, standing next to a large, old-fashioned cassette tape recorder. The person is holding a tangled cassette tape that trails from the machine, suggesting it contains their ''mind.'' Around them, scattered thought bubbles contain random symbols, question marks, and lightbulbs to represent ideas and thoughts. In the background, a shelf holds more tapes labeled ''Memories,'' ''Ideas,'' and ''Emotions.'' The overall mood is lighthearted and silly, with bright colors and exaggerated facial features to emphasize the humor of the mind being ''backed up on tape.'' The style should be playful and cartoonish, avoiding any dark or negative tones.'),
 (3006, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I just got lost in thought, it was unfamiliar territory.', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon character standing in a simple landscape that humorously represents ''thoughts'' as a physical place. The character looks confused and slightly lost, scratching their head or holding a map upside down. Surround the character with whimsical, floating thought bubbles shaped like winding paths, question marks, and light bulbs. The background should show a signpost labeled ''Unfamiliar Territory'' with arrows pointing in different directions, emphasizing the idea of being lost in the mind. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to keep the tone light and humorous.'),
 (3035, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I saw a parachute on Craigslist - seller said it was in mint condition - used only once and never opened.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a man looking at a computer screen displaying a Craigslist ad for a parachute. The ad headline says ''Parachute for Sale - Mint Condition.'' Next to the computer, show a brand-new parachute neatly packed in its case sitting on the floor. The man has a confused and amused expression, scratching his head as he reads the ad text: ''Used only once and never opened.'' Above the man, include a thought bubble depicting a skydiver jumping out of a plane with the parachute case unopened, emphasizing the joke. The background is simple, resembling a cozy living room or home office to keep focus on the character and the ad. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions for humor. The style should be lighthearted and family-friendly with no violence or negativity.'),
 (3102, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Spilling your guts is just exactly as charming as it sounds.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting nervously at a small café table, mid-conversation, with their chest humorously exaggeratedly open to reveal comically oversized, cartoonish guts spilling out like a bowl of noodles or spaghetti. The person''s face shows an awkward, embarrassed smile. Around them, two other café patrons at nearby tables look on with surprised and uncomfortable expressions, some shielding their eyes or leaning away. The setting is light and colorful with simple café elements like chairs, tables, coffee cups, and a small potted plant. The style is playful and exaggerated, emphasizing the absurd literal take on the phrase ''spilling your guts'' without any graphic or violent detail.'),
 (2705, 'Absurd Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Character density: The number of very weird people in the office.', NULL, 'A cartoon office scene with a group of quirky, exaggeratedly odd coworkers clustered together. Each character looks eccentric—one wearing mismatched socks and spiral glasses, another with wild hair and colorful clothes, a third holding a rubber chicken or a strange gadget. They stand around a simple office desk with a computer, coffee mugs, and scattered papers. A whiteboard behind them has the phrase ''Character Density = Number of Very Weird People in the Office'' written in playful letters. The expressions on their faces range from proud to goofy, and a background office door is slightly ajar, hinting at more weirdness inside. The overall style is bright, whimsical, and humorous, emphasizing the fun absurdity of the idea.'),
 (1493, 'Acting, Art Humor, Comedy, Quotes', 'Acting is not being emotional, but being able to express emotion.', 'Kate Reid', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters on a simple stage set with a spotlight above. One character is an actor in a dramatic costume, standing rigidly and trying very hard to look emotional but with a comically blank expression. The other character, perhaps a director or teacher, is pointing at the actor with a big smile and encouraging gesture, holding a clipboard. Around them, exaggerated large emoticons (like a happy face, sad face, and angry face) float in the air to symbolize ''expressing emotion.'' The background is a basic theater setting with red curtains and a wooden floor. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between just feeling emotion and clearly showing it for the audience''s benefit.'),
 (2168, 'Adventure Humor, Classic Quotes, Inspirational, Quotes', 'Oh! The places you''ll go! you''ll be on your way up! you''ll be seeing great sights! you''ll join the high fliers who soar to high heights.', 'Dr. Seuss', 'A colorful cartoon scene inspired by a whimsical travel adventure. Show a cheerful character (child or cartoon person) confidently stepping upward on a winding staircase or a series of floating stepping stones ascending into the sky. Around them, draw vibrant clouds, birds, and balloons to emphasize ''soaring to high heights.'' Include playful elements like a signpost with arrows pointing to ‘Great sights’ and ‘High fliers.’ In the background, a bright sun, distant mountains, or tall buildings add depth. The character should have an excited expression, with arms spread wide as if embracing the journey ahead. Make the style lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated, rounded shapes and bright colors to match the upbeat tone of the quote. Overall, the illustration should evoke a sense of optimism and adventure without any clutter or complexity.'),
 (2495, 'Adventure Humor, Inspirational, Motivational, Quotes', 'Twenty years from now, you will be more disappointed by the things you didn''t do than by the ones you did. So throw off the bowlines, sail away from the safe harbor. Catch the trade winds in your sails. Explore. Dream.', 'Mark Twain', 'A colorful, whimsical cartoon scene depicting a cheerful person standing on a wooden dock at a safe harbor. The harbor is calm, with gentle waves and a few moored sailboats tied to the dock. The person is happily throwing off the ropes (bowlines) from a classic sailboat, which is ready to set sail. The sailboat has billowing sails catching bright trade winds, depicted as playful, swirling gusts with little smiley faces. In the background, there is an open sea stretching toward a distant horizon with a bright rising or setting sun, conveying both adventure and possibility. Seagulls fly in the sky, and a small sign on the dock reads “Safe Harbor.” The overall style is lighthearted and uplifting, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright, bold lines to create a warm, inspiring cartoon illustration that captures the spirit of exploration, dreaming, and taking chances.'),
 (1633, 'Adventure Humor, Inspirational, Quotes, Word Play', 'Do not follow where the path may lead. Go instead where there is no path, and leave a trail.', 'Emerson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful character wearing a hiking outfit standing proudly in a wilderness setting. The scene shows two parts: on the left, a well-trodden dirt path winds through a forest with clear footprints and signposts. The character stands on the right side in tall grass and shrubs, off the beaten path, holding a big paintbrush or a large stick, happily painting or marking a trail behind them. The character has a playful smile, as if excited about blazing a new trail where none existed. Around them, funny little animals like birds or squirrels watch curiously. The sky is bright and the overall mood is lighthearted and adventurous, emphasizing creativity and individuality in exploring unknown places. The cartoon style should be colorful, exaggerated, and friendly with clear details of the path, nature, and trail-making tool, suitable for all ages.'),
 (2150, 'Adventure Humor, Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'No pessimist ever discovered the secrets of the stars, or sailed to an uncharted land, or opened a new heaven to the human spirit.', 'Helen Keller', 'A cheerful, cartoon-style scene showing a bright starry sky in the background. Foreground features an optimistic explorer dressed in classic sailing attire, standing confidently on a small ship deck, looking through a telescope aimed at the sky. Nearby is an ancient map dotted with stars and uncharted islands, alongside a glowing book titled ''Secrets of the Stars.'' The explorer''s expression radiates wonder and hope. Around the ship and in the sky, subtle whimsical elements float: sparkling stars, a shining compass rose, and faint outlines of mythical lands in clouds. The overall tone is uplifting and inspiring, with bright colors and smooth lines emphasizing adventure, discovery, and optimism. The scene conveys the spirit of exploration and growth, without any gloom or hopeless characters present, highlighting the contrast implied by the joke.'),
 (1587, 'Adventure Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Believe me! The secret of reaping the greatest fruitfulness and the greatest enjoyment from life is to live dangerously!', 'Nietchze', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing on a precarious, exaggeratedly tall and narrow cliff edge. They have a wide grin and arms stretched out, as if embracing the thrill of living dangerously. Surrounding the cliff are oversized juicy fruits like apples, oranges, and grapes hanging invitingly within reach but just beyond the safe ground, symbolizing ''fruitfulness''. In the background, a bright sunny sky with fluffy clouds adds to the lighthearted mood. The person might be wearing casual, colorful clothes with playful expressions. The style is cartoonish with bold outlines and vibrant colors, emphasizing the fun and adventurous spirit of the message without any real danger or threat depicted.'),
 (3118, 'Adventure Humor, Philosophy Humor, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'Without adventure, civilization is in full decay.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a lively cityscape split into two halves. On the left, depict a dull, gray, and crumbling city where buildings are crooked, some streets have cracks, and people appear bored and slouching. On the right, show a vibrant, colorful adventure park with happy people climbing mountains, rafting down rivers, and exploring caves. Place a giant banner overhead connecting the two scenes reading ''Civilization''. Above the city, include a sign saying ''Without Adventure'' on the gray side and ''With Adventure'' on the colorful side. Include small whimsical details like a snail slowly crawling on the dull side and a soaring bird on the lively side to symbolize decay versus vitality. The style should be lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions on people to emphasize boredom vs excitement, rendered in a clean, cartoon format without any violence or negative content.'),
 (1496, 'Adventure Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Adventure is worthwhile in itself.', 'Amelia Earhart', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful adventurer standing on top of a small, rounded hill. The adventurer is wearing a bulky backpack with various adventure gear poking out, like a map, a compass, and a walking stick. The adventurer has an exaggeratedly happy expression, wide smile, and is gazing proudly at the horizon where a tiny glowing sun or rainbow shines, emphasizing optimism. Around the hill are simple details like a campfire, a tent, and a curious animal (such as a squirrel or bird) looking up at the adventurer. The background is light and colorful with a few fluffy clouds. The tone is lighthearted and playful, with clean lines and bright colors, capturing the spirit of enjoying the journey itself rather than focusing on a destination.'),
 (1882, 'Advertising Humor, Everyday Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'If it looks good, you''ll see it. If it sounds good, you''ll hear it. If it''s marketed right, you''ll buy it. But if it''s real, you''ll feel it.', 'Kid Rock', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing four distinct panels side by side, each illustrating one line of the joke. Panel 1: A person admiring a shiny, perfectly packaged product on a store shelf, eyes wide and sparkling, with sparkling stars around the product indicating it ''looks good.'' Panel 2: Another person happily listening to a radio or headphones, singing along or bobbing head, with musical notes floating around, emphasizing ''sounds good.'' Panel 3: A different person excitedly handing money to a smiling store cashier, with a big red ''Marketing'' banner overhead and promotional signs around, showing ''marketed right'' causes purchase. Panel 4: Finally, a thoughtful person holding the actual product (slightly different from the advertised one), closing eyes and placing hand on chest with a small heart symbol, showing ''if it''s real, you''ll feel it.'' The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors, and no harsh lines or intense detail, just simple humor focusing on the different sensory and emotional reactions to a product.'),
 (2978, 'Advertising Humor, Irony, Unknown, Word Play', 'I don''t mind that the phrase ''truth in advertising'' was probably just some lie thought up by some guy in advertising.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a man in a retro advertising office from the mid-20th century. The man is casually leaning back in a swivel chair with a sly, mischievous grin, holding a pen poised over a large sheet of paper on a drafting table labeled ''Ad Slogans.'' Around him, vintage advertising posters hang on the walls, with ironic slogans like ''Totally Honest!''. On his desk, scattered papers show scribbles of slogans, and a thought bubble above his head reads: ''Truth in advertising — probably just a lie I made up.'' The style is light-hearted, colorful, and exaggerated, with the man''s exaggerated facial expression highlighting the joke. The background includes typical office elements like a typewriter, telephone, and a coffee mug that says ''World''s Best Liar.'' The tone is playful and cartoonish, emphasizing irony without being negative or mean spirited.'),
 (1205, 'Advice Humor, Humor, Insults, Irony', 'Whoever told you to be yourself simply couldn''t have given you worse advice.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a large mirror. The person looks confused and a bit disheveled, scratching their head and staring at their reflection, which looks exaggeratedly awkward or silly to emphasize the idea of ''being yourself'' as bad advice. Next to the person, a whimsical, friendly-looking advisor character (perhaps resembling a quirky life coach or a well-meaning friend) stands with a clipboard, shrugging apologetically, as if admitting their advice backfired. The background is a simple room with a few personal items like a chair, a small table with a plant, and a framed motivational poster on the wall that reads ironically, ''Be Yourself!''. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor behind bad advice.'),
 (2355, 'Advice Humor, Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The only thing to do with good advice is pass it on. It is never any use to oneself.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful character handing a glowing, oversized scroll labeled ''Good Advice'' to a surprised second character. The first character has a sly smile and is animatedly pointing away from themselves, as if passing something along. The second character looks both confused and intrigued as they receive the scroll. In the background, a thought bubble above the first character’s head contains an empty lightbulb or a comically ignored self-help book gathering dust. The setting is a simple office or living room with a couch, a small table with a teacup, and a wall clock to convey a casual, everyday environment. The overall composition uses bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the irony that good advice is only useful when given to others, never oneself.'),
 (1497, 'Advice Humor, Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Advice is what we ask for when we already know the answer but wish we didn''t.', 'Erica Jong', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting on a park bench. One character looks contemplative and slightly stressed, holding their chin as if deep in thought. The other character, portrayed as a friendly advisor, is cheerfully giving advice, gesturing with one hand. Above them is a floating thought bubble showing a light bulb crossed out, symbolizing that the thinker actually already has the answer but doesn''t want to face it. The setting includes a sunny park background with trees and flowers, a few birds in the sky, and a small trash can nearby. Use bright, cheerful colors and rounded shapes to give a lighthearted, relatable feel to the scene, emphasizing the internal conflict of wanting advice despite knowing the truth.'),
 (1522, 'Advice Humor, Life, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Always make the right thing easy and the wrong things difficult.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, friendly-looking signpost at a crossroad. One arrow points right and is oversized, bright green, and labeled ''Right (Easy)'' with a smooth, wide, brightly lit path leading into a sunny, peaceful park with flowers and a smiling sun overhead. The other arrow points left and is small, crooked, dark red, and labeled ''Wrong (Difficult)'' with a narrow, rocky, steep path full of obstacles like rocks, mud puddles, and thorny bushes. A cartoon character stands at the crossroads looking puzzled but slightly amused, scratching their head as they decide which way to go. The character wears casual clothes, and the whole setting is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the contrast between the easy and difficult paths in a playful manner.'),
 (1524, 'Advice Humor, Life, Quotes, Workplace', 'Always put the important before the merely urgent.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two large folders or papers on a desk, each clearly labeled. One folder is labeled ''Important'' and looks calm, neat, and dignified, with a glowing aura or shining light above it. The other folder is labeled ''Urgent'' and looks frantic, with scribbles, exclamation marks around it, and steam or frantic motion lines to show urgency. A relaxed, wise cartoon character (perhaps a friendly office worker or librarian) stands beside the desk, pointing to the ''Important'' folder with a confident smile, while ignoring the frantic ''Urgent'' folder. The background shows a cluttered office with humorous exaggerated clocks and deadlines pinned on a wall but the character clearly prioritizes the calm ''Important'' folder over the stressed ''Urgent'' one. The overall vibe is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to illustrate the joke''s message about priorities.'),
 (2244, 'Advice Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'Some people like my advice so much that they frame it upon the wall instead of using it.', 'Gordon R. Dickson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cozy living room or office wall prominently featuring a framed piece of paper or a plaque labeled ''Advice.'' The advice is displayed like a prized artwork, with a fancy frame, hanging straight and centered. Nearby, a person is standing or sitting, looking amused or slightly confused, holding another similar piece of paper with written advice that they''ve just received. The person does not seem to be using the advice but instead admiring the framed one on the wall. Add a small side table with a cup of coffee, maybe a potted plant in the corner, and a few scattered papers to suggest ongoing attempts at giving or receiving advice. Keep the style light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor about advice being valued more as decoration than practical help.'),
 (1582, 'Advice Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Be wiser than other people if you can; but do not tell them so.', 'Lord Chesterfield', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual conversation in a park setting. One character looks confident and wise, wearing glasses and holding a book titled ''Wisdom.'' This character has a slightly smug but quiet smile, with a thought bubble above their head that reads, ''I''m wiser than you.'' The other character listens with a neutral or slightly puzzled expression, unaware of the first character''s inner thought. The background includes a bench, trees, and a sunny sky to keep the mood light. The scene should emphasize the first character''s internal cleverness paired with the external silence, highlighting the advice of being wise yet not telling others about it. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to maintain a playful, cartoonish tone without using any text in the image except the book title and thought bubble.'),
 (2136, 'Advice Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Never pass up a chance to keep your mouth shut.', 'God''s Little Instruction Book', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a casual social setting, like a small party or coffee shop. The central character is a person with their finger pressed firmly to their lips in a classic ''shhh'' gesture, wearing a subtle mischievous grin. Surrounding them are a few other cartoon characters looking at them, some with amused expressions and others looking curious or confused. In front of the main character is an open mouth-shaped speech bubble, but it’s empty with a big red ''no'' symbol (like a circle with a slash) over it, emphasizing ''keeping your mouth shut.'' The background is simple, with playful colors and minimal details like a table with snacks or a cup of coffee to indicate a relaxed social environment. The style is exaggerated and lighthearted, with clear facial expressions highlighting the humor of the advice to avoid talking too much.'),
 (19, 'Aging, Animals, Bad Puns, Science', 'If swimming is good for your shape, then why do the whales look the way they do?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an ocean environment. In the foreground, a large, plump whale with a friendly, puzzled expression is floating lazily near the water surface. The whale looks round and chubby, clearly not fitting the typical idea of ''good shape.'' Nearby, a slender, fit human swimmer in a classic swimming cap and goggles is actively swimming and looking confusedly at the whale. Around them, a few small fish with exaggerated, toned physiques are swimming energetically, adding contrast. The background should show a sunny sky and gentle waves, keeping a lighthearted and cheerful tone. The style should be colorful and cartoony with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of the whale''s shape despite swimming being ''good for your shape.'' No text is required in the image, but the scene should clearly communicate the joke''s playful question about swimming and body shape.'),
 (20, 'Aging, Bad Puns, Good Question!, Humor about Gender', 'If women ran the world, there would be no war.  Just a bunch of countries not talking to each other', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of people on opposite sides of a globe. One side shows women with confident, determined expressions, arms crossed or pointing fingers, standing on a cartoon-style colorful country labeled with flags. On the other side, another group of women with crossed arms, backs turned, glaring or giving side-eye looks, clearly not speaking to each other. Between them is a globe emphasizing division, with jagged lines or a crack showing separation. The atmosphere is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions of mild annoyance or stubbornness, no anger or violence. The background is simple with a blue sky and a few peace symbols floating around to contrast the lack of communication with the theme of peace. The artistic style is bright, cartoonish, and playful with clear outlines and exaggerated body language to emphasize the joke’s idea of diplomacy replaced by silent standoffs rather than war.'),
 (21, 'Aging, Bad Puns, Humor', 'I run like the winded.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person trying to run but clearly out of breath and struggling. The character should be shown mid-run with exaggerated tired expressions: sweat pouring down their face, tongue hanging out, and puffed cheeks. Their legs could be comically wobbly or dragging slightly to emphasize exhaustion. The background could include a running track or a park path with a few cartoon-style dust clouds or motion lines to indicate movement. Nearby, a small gust of wind character with a cheeky smile and little arms blowing air towards the runner would add to the pun. The overall style should be light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the joke’s humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (22, 'Aging, Bad Puns, Science', 'Old chemists never die, they just stop reacting.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two elderly male chemists in a colorful chemistry lab filled with beakers, test tubes, and bubbling flasks. One chemist has gray hair and glasses, wearing a white lab coat, looking spry and lively as he holds a flask with bubbling liquid, showing a cheerful smile. The other chemist, also elderly with a gentle smile, is sitting back in a chair with a tired or sleepy expression, but still wearing a lab coat. Above them is a large chemistry reaction equation on a chalkboard that appears to be balanced but fading or disappearing near the older chemist to humorously represent ''stopping reacting.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the wordplay on ''reacting'' in chemistry and aging, with bright colors and simple cartoon-style drawing. The background includes periodic table posters and typical lab equipment to set the chemistry theme clearly.'),
 (23, 'Aging, Cars Humor', 'Old cars don''t die - but they do scatter their body parts everywhere.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an old, beat-up car on a quiet country road or in a junkyard. The car has a friendly, anthropomorphic face with big eyes on the windshield and a smiling grille. Parts of the car, such as a detached door, a rusty muffler, a tire, and a bumper, are scattered around on the ground nearby. A crow or small bird is perched on one of the removed parts looking curious or amused. The background is simple and bright, with a few trees or a fence, emphasizing a lighthearted mood. The car looks like it’s trying to ''stay alive'' despite its missing parts, adding to the humor without any violence or negativity. Cartoon-style, bright colors, and exaggerated expressions to keep it playful and fun.'),
 (24, 'Aging, Don''t Say It!, Humor, Social Commentary', 'I had a joke about Social Security, but most Baby Boomers won''t get it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two groups of people, clearly differentiated by age. On the left, a younger person, perhaps in their 20s or 30s, is holding a microphone or telling a joke with a speech bubble showing the text: ''I had a joke about Social Security, but most Baby Boomers won''t get it.'' On the right, a group of Baby Boomer-aged characters look confused or bewildered, scratching their heads or raising eyebrows. The background can have subtle hints like a calendar showing a recent year and maybe a Social Security card or symbol floating faintly behind to emphasize the topic. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated to keep a humorous and friendly tone. The characters should have expressive faces to highlight the generational gap in understanding the joke, with the younger group smiling and the Baby Boomers appearing puzzled.'),
 (25, 'Aging, Facts, Humor', 'Only one person in two billion will live to be 116 or older.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a very long line of people waiting outside a giant, whimsical birthday cake-shaped building with a big sign that reads ''116th Birthday Club.'' The line stretches far into the distance, almost disappearing on the horizon. Near the front, a small elderly person with a party hat and a big smile stands proudly holding a gold medal labeled ''116+'' while others behind look surprised or doubtful. Above the scene, a large speech bubble shows the text ''Only one person in two billion will live to be 116 or older.'' The setting is bright and cheerful with balloons and confetti scattered around, emphasizing the rarity and celebration of reaching that age. The style is colorful and exaggerated like a funny cartoon or comic strip, with expressive faces and lighthearted details like a party banner and a clock showing the time as ’116 years.'' No violence, adult themes, or political elements.'),
 (26, 'Aging, Family, Humor', 'The best revenge is to live long enough to be a problem to your children.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing an elderly person sitting comfortably in a cozy living room, with a mischievous grin. The elderly person is surrounded by two grown-up children who look exasperated and slightly overwhelmed. One child is holding a phone and looking stressed, while the other is trying to tidy up but hesitates. Include typical home elements like a comfy armchair, a small table with a cup of tea, family photos on the wall, and a clock showing late afternoon. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the idea that the older person is still active and causing harmless trouble for their adult children.'),
 (2614, 'Aging, Food Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'You know you''re old when you''ve lost all your marvels', 'Merry Browne', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly person sitting in a cozy living room with a puzzled or mildly amused expression. The elderly person is holding a small empty glass jar labeled ''Marvels'' (implying the candy). Around them, there are empty wrappers or a completely empty jar on a nearby table, emphasizing that all the ''marvels'' have been lost or eaten. In the background, family photos or memorabilia hang on the wall to hint at the passage of time. The style should be lighthearted and whimsical with soft colors and exaggerated features for humor. The overall mood is funny and gentle, highlighting the wordplay between ''marvels'' as a candy and ''marvels'' as wonders in life.'),
 (27, 'Aging, Good Question!, Jobs, Science', 'If Moses were alive today, the Ten Commandments would be known as the Ten Best Practices, presented in PowerPoint and followed by 40 years of status meetings.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a modern-day Moses in business attire standing at a conference room podium. Behind him is a large screen with a colorful PowerPoint slide titled ''The Ten Best Practices'' featuring bullet points numbered 1 to 10. Moses holds a remote clicker in one hand and looks slightly overwhelmed but professional. Seated around a long table are diverse office workers in typical corporate clothing, looking bored or checking their watches. On the table are laptops, coffee cups, and notepads. A large office clock on the wall shows time passing quickly. In the background, a calendar is visible marking ''Year 1 to Year 40'' with repeated sticky notes labeled ''Status Meeting.'' The overall tone is light and funny, capturing the clash between ancient biblical events and modern corporate culture in a colorful cartoon style.'),
 (28, 'Aging, Health Humor, Puns', 'Running in your 50s-60s is a great way to meet people. A friend just met a paramedic, 3 nurses, a cardiologist, and nearly met Jesus himself!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a middle-aged person, jogging outdoors on a park trail with an exaggerated expression of surprise and slight distress. Around the runner, several characters are approaching or attending to them: a friendly paramedic with a medical bag crouching next to the runner, three nurses with stethoscopes and clipboards standing nearby offering help, and a cheerful cardiologist with a heart model smiling. In the background, a humorous, glowing, slightly transparent figure representing ''Jesus himself'' is depicted waving or smiling warmly. The setting is a sunny park with trees, a running path, and a bench. The tone is light-hearted and playful, with cartoon-style exaggerated expressions, emphasizing the irony and the joke about meeting medical professionals due to the risks of running at that age.'),
 (29, 'Aging, Humor', 'I remember being able to get up without making sound effects.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a middle-aged or elderly person slowly rising from a chair in a cozy living room. The person looks slightly exaggerated with a theatrical grimace of effort on their face. Around them, several colorful sound effect words like ''Creak!'', ''Squeak!'', and ''Groan!'' are whimsically drawn in comic-style bubbles, emphasizing the noise they make while standing up. The room includes a comfortable armchair, a small side table with a cup of tea, and a pair of slippers left neatly on the floor. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, with warm colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to create humor out of the everyday struggle of aging bodies making sounds when getting up.'),
 (30, 'Aging, Humor', 'Old is always fifteen years older than I am.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an adult person standing next to an elderly person. The elderly person looks cheerful and holds a large birthday cake with the number ''75'' on it. The adult, looking slightly confused or mildly frustrated, is holding a calendar or a birthday card that shows their age as ''60''. Above them is a comical thought bubble where the adult imagines the elderly person grinning and saying, ''Old is always fifteen years older than I am!'' The background is simple, perhaps a party setting with balloons and a ''Happy Birthday'' banner. Both characters should have exaggerated, friendly cartoonish features with bright colors to keep the tone light and funny.'),
 (31, 'Aging, Humor, Jobs', 'Old taxi drivers don''t die, they just get lost. As usual.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly taxi driver sitting behind the wheel of a classic yellow taxi cab. The driver is an older man with gray hair, glasses slipping down his nose, and a slightly confused but good-natured expression. The taxi is parked at a crossroads with multiple street signs pointing in all directions, each sign humorously labeled with various confusing or contradictory place names (e.g., ''This Way'', ''That Way'', ''Are We There Yet?''). Around the cab, small cartoonish swirls or question marks float to emphasize his confusion. The background shows a cityscape with a few pedestrians looking on with mild amusement. The tone is lighthearted with bright colors, exaggerated features, and clear, simple lines to emphasize the joke about the taxi driver ''not dying but just getting lost again,'' playing on the stereotype of taxi drivers and their sometimes erratic navigation. No violence or inappropriate elements are present, and the overall mood is silly and charming.'),
 (32, 'Aging, Humor, Life', '60 might be the new 40, but 9:00 pm is the new midnight.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing an older person, around 60 years old, looking tired but content on a cozy couch at home. The background includes a clock on the wall clearly showing 9:00 pm. Nearby, a calendar page or a sign reads ''60 = 40?'' to humorously suggest age comparison. The person is yawning or half-asleep with a warm blanket and a cup of tea or hot cocoa on a side table. The room is softly lit, emphasizing a peaceful early evening vibe. The scene captures the joke that while 60 might feel like 40 in spirit, the usual going-to-bed time has gotten much earlier, with 9:00 pm now feeling as late as midnight once did. The style is light, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions for a funny yet relatable mood.'),
 (33, 'Aging, Humor, Life', 'Seen it all, done it all, can''t remember most of it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an older person sitting comfortably in a cozy living room armchair. The person has a relaxed, slightly amused expression and is surrounded by humorous visual cues indicating forgetfulness: empty thought bubbles above their head with question marks, a calendar with many crossed-out dates, and scattered items like photo albums, a pair of reading glasses, and a cup of tea on a side table. Behind them, a wall filled with framed photos showing different fun activities (like traveling, parties, sports) but the person looks puzzled or shrugging as if trying to recall. The overall style is lighthearted and warm, emphasizing the humor in having experienced many things but struggling to remember them clearly.'),
 (34, 'Aging, Humor, Life', 'The older I get, the earlier it gets late.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an older person sitting in a cozy living room with a puzzled and slightly amused expression, glancing at a traditional wall clock. The clock’s hands show an unusually early time, like 6 PM, but a calendar or a window outside suggests it''s already ''late'' in the day (dusk or early evening light). Nearby, there''s a comfy armchair, a small side table with a cup of tea or coffee, and a calendar or a newspaper with the date prominently displayed. The older person''s casual clothes and gray hair hint at their age. The setting is warm and inviting, emphasizing the idea that ''late'' arrives earlier as one ages. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and simple but clear lines, reinforcing the joke without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (1685, 'Aging, Humor, Life, Quotes', 'Experience is a great advantage. The problem is that when you get the experience, you''re too damned old to do anything about it.', 'Jimmy Connors', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly person standing with a thoughtful expression, maybe stroking their chin or holding a large book labeled ''Experience.'' Around them, several younger people are energetically running, playing sports, or pursuing active hobbies like cycling or hiking. The elderly character looks wistful or slightly frustrated, watching the youths with a small speech bubble above their head containing the words, "Experience is a great advantage... if only I had the time!" The background is a sunny park or outdoor setting to emphasize the contrast between youthful activity and aged contemplation. The art style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with vibrant colors and expressive faces to enhance the comedic mood without any harsh or serious tones.'),
 (1879, 'Aging, Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'If I knew I was going to live this long, I''d have taken better care of myself.', 'Mickey Mantle', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an older person, looking a little worn out but with a playful smile, sitting on a cozy armchair. Around them are humorous signs of neglect like a messy pile of empty snack wrappers, a tangled mess of hairbrush and comb on a side table, and a calendar with years marked off rapidly. The person is scratching their head thoughtfully with a cartoon-style thinking bubble above them that shows a past version of themselves looking younger, healthier, and filled with energy, jogging or eating a salad. The background should feel light-hearted and warm, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the irony of the statement. Add subtle humorous details such as a neglected plant wilting nearby or a dusty exercise bike in the corner to underline the joke about not taking better care of oneself earlier in life.'),
 (2444, 'Aging, Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'There''s no fool like an old fool -- you can''t beat experience.', 'Jacob Braude', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly man who looks cheerful but slightly silly. He is wearing oversized glasses, a colorful old-fashioned sweater, and a cap sitting crookedly on his head. The man stands proudly with one foot on a small stack of books labeled ''Experience,'' while holding a walking cane that has a worn-out shoe at the tip. Around him are scattered funny props that suggest past mistakes — for example, a whoopee cushion, an old broken clock, and a spilled paint can. Behind him is a chalkboard with the phrase ‘You can’t beat Experience’ written in playful, exaggerated lettering. The background is a cozy living room with a comfy chair and a cat looking at him with amused eyes. The overall vibe is lighthearted, poking fun at how wisdom often comes from repeated silly mistakes made over a lifetime.'),
 (1812, 'Aging, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I find that we all get more legendary as time goes by. ''Legend'' means, basically, ''bullshit.''', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an older person sitting on a park bench with a content and slightly amused expression. Around them are faint, glowing outlines or ghostly, exaggerated ‘legendary’ versions of themselves—like heroic, mythical figures with capes or crowns, but clearly playful and exaggerated. Above the person, a whimsical thought bubble shows the word ''LEGEND'' in bold, dramatic lettering, with a smaller, cheeky subtext underneath reading ''bullshit'' in a casual handwritten font. The setting is lighthearted with simple trees, clouds, and birds chirping. The style is playful and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the witty contrast between the noble ''legendary'' and the humorous truth behind it. No violence or politics, just a gentle poke at how stories become grander with age through exaggerated memory or storytelling.'),
 (2970, 'Aging, Humor, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'I could make a joke about Social Security, but most of you Boomers won''t get it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of older adults (boomers) sitting in a cozy living room, looking puzzled or confused. One person, younger and smirking, is standing in front of them holding a microphone as if about to tell a joke. Above the younger person is a speech bubble with the text: ''I could make a joke about Social Security, but most of you Boomers won''t get it.'' Include small details like a TV remote, a comfortable couch, a coffee table with reading glasses and a newspaper titled ''Social Security Updates,'' and maybe a wall clock to indicate afternoon time. The style should be colorful and light-hearted with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing confusion, humor, and mild teasing.'),
 (35, 'Aging, Humor, Sports Humor', 'Old hockey fans don''t die, they just move to Toronto.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a hockey rink with a group of elderly hockey fans gathered together. They wear vintage hockey jerseys and hats with classic team logos. Instead of being sad or serious, the fans are smiling and enthusiastically cheering. One of the older fans is shown packing a suitcase labeled ''Toronto Trip'' while another waves a Canadian flag excitedly. In the background, a scoreboard reads ''Old Fans Forever'' and the stands are decorated with banners that say ''Toronto - The Final Move.'' The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated cheerful expressions and a sunny day outside the rink, emphasizing the joke that old hockey fans don''t die, they just move to Toronto, a city known for its passionate hockey culture. The style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with playful, exaggerated features on the characters to emphasize the humor and warmth of the scene.'),
 (36, 'Aging, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'The best thing about growing older is that it takes such a long time.', NULL, 'A cheerful elderly person with gray hair and glasses is sitting comfortably in a rocking chair on a porch during a sunny day. They have a relaxed smile and are holding a cup of tea. Around them, there are elements that symbolize the passage of time: an old-fashioned grandfather clock, a calendar with many pages flipped off, and a long winding path stretching into the distance, symbolizing the long journey of aging. The scene is drawn in a bright, colorful cartoon style with soft edges and exaggerated features to enhance the humor and lightheartedness of the message. The overall mood is calm and positive, emphasizing patience and the slow but steady nature of growing older.'),
 (1732, 'Aging, Optimism Humor, Quotes', 'Growing old isn''t so bad when you consider the alternative.', 'Maurice Chevalier', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting an elderly person sitting comfortably in a cozy armchair, smiling and looking relaxed. The person wears simple, slightly oversized glasses and a warm sweater, holding a steaming cup of tea or coffee. Around them, there are signs of age like a walking cane leaning against the chair, a pair of slippers on the floor, and a clock showing afternoon time. Near their feet, a pet dog or cat lounges peacefully. In the background, a window reveals a pleasant sunny day outside, reinforcing a calm and positive mood. The scene should convey a friendly, lighthearted atmosphere emphasizing contentment with aging rather than fear or negativity. The drawing style should be a colorful, slightly exaggerated cartoon to enhance the humor and warmth of the message without any suggestion of violence, sexuality, or politics.'),
 (2563, 'Aging, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'When I was younger, I could remember anything, whether it had happened or not; but my faculties are decaying now and soon I shall be so I cannot remember any but the things that never happened. It is sad to go to pieces like this but we all have to do it.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly man sitting in a cozy armchair, looking slightly confused but amused. Around him are floating symbolic thought bubbles: some showing clear memories like walking a dog or birthday parties, and others showing absurd, impossible scenes like flying elephants or people made of clouds, representing things that never happened. The man’s face shows a mix of nostalgia and mild bewilderment, with a small crumbling hourglass or cracked brain illustration subtly in the background to symbolize decaying faculties. The room has warm lighting, a bookshelf with slightly disorganized books, and a clock on the wall with melting numbers, adding to the playful, surreal atmosphere. The style is lighthearted, cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and soft lines to keep it gentle and funny rather than sad.'),
 (1604, 'Aging, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Childhood: The period of human life intermediate between the idiocy of infancy and the folly of youth -- two removes from the sin of manhood and three from the remorse of age.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing five stages of a man''s life in a single line from left to right. From left, a toddler with a pacifier looking clueless (representing ''idiocy of infancy''), followed by a cheeky, playful young boy acting silly (representing ''folly of youth''). Next, a confident adult man wearing a business suit with a little devil figure whispering near him (representing ''the sin of manhood''). Then, an older man with gray hair, wearing glasses, looking regretful and holding a calendar or diary (representing ''the remorse of age''). Above the characters, arrows with labels indicate the stages and counts: infancy, youth (two steps after infancy), manhood (two steps after youth), and age (three steps after infancy). The style is bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize idiocy, folly, sin, and remorse in a lighthearted, non-offensive way. Include simple background elements like a park or room that subtly shift from playful to serious as the figures age.'),
 (1441, 'Aging, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'A man is as old as he feels. But never as important.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a middle-aged man standing in front of a mirror in a cozy bedroom. The man looks energetic and youthful, maybe with a big smile and an enthusiastic pose, showing he ''feels young.'' Reflected in the mirror behind him, an older, grumpy version of himself looks tired and unimpressed, signaling the ''never as important'' feeling. Around the room are small funny details: a calendar with its dates marked, a clock showing time passing, and perhaps a small stack of papers labeled ''Life Responsibilities'' on a nearby table. The overall tone is light and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the contrast between feeling young and the reality of feeling less significant as time passes. The style should be cartoonish and friendly, with rounded edges and clear contrast between the two versions of the man.'),
 (2105, 'Aging, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Social Humor', 'Middle age is when you''ve met so many people that every new person you meet reminds you of someone else.', 'Ogden Nash', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a middle-aged person standing in the center with a friendly but slightly bemused expression. Around them are several diverse people, each with distinct appearances, but all share a subtle common trait that visually links them—like matching hats, similar hairstyles, or identical quirky glasses—to hint that the main character is reminded of someone else with each new encounter. The setting is a casual social environment like a park or a coffee shop, with simple background elements such as benches, trees, or a few tables. The style should be light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor of recognizing similarities among strangers. Include visual thought bubbles or small icons above the middle-aged person''s head showing miniature versions of previously met people to reinforce the joke''s concept without any text, keeping the focus on the visual pun about memory and social encounters.'),
 (37, 'Aging, Sports Humor, Word Play', 'Old tennis pros don''t die, but they don''t bounce back, either.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a tennis court with a humorous twist. In the center, an elderly tennis player with gray hair in a quintessential tennis outfit (headband, wristbands, polo shirt, shorts, and tennis shoes) leans on a tennis racket for support, looking tired but amused. Instead of the usual bright, bouncy tennis ball near them, there is a deflated, flabby-looking tennis ball lying on the court, partially squished. The tennis net is slightly sagging, echoing the ''no bounce back'' theme. In the background, a scoreboard reads something like ''Old Pros Match.'' The atmosphere is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated features to emphasize the joke about aging athletes and losing their bounce. No other players are in the scene to keep the focus on the old pro and the deflated ball.'),
 (38, 'Agnosticism, Dyslexics, Word Play', 'Did''ya hear about the agnostic dyslexic that believes there is no dog?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing between two large signs. One sign says ''God'' with a question mark above it, and the other sign says ''Dog'' but the letters are jumbled to represent dyslexia (e.g., ''Dgo''). The person scratches their head, with a puzzled expression, trying to decide which sign to believe. In the background, a cute cartoon dog looks bewildered, possibly tilting its head. The setting is simple, with soft colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize confusion and irony. The style is light and playful, reminiscent of classic comic strips, ensuring the tone is cheerful and non-serious.'),
 (1777, 'Agnosticism, Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'I am an agnostic; I do not pretend to know what many ignorant men are sure of.', 'Clarence Darrow', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing on a small stage with a microphone, confidently addressing an audience. The speaker is wearing casual clothes and has a thoughtful, somewhat amused expression. Around them, a diverse crowd of men with exaggerated confident expressions are shown, some with puffed chests or smug looks, clearly sure of themselves. The setting is simple: a spotlight shines on the speaker, and the audience sits in rows of chairs in a cozy, informal venue like a small comedy club or lecture hall. Speech bubbles or subtle labels highlight the contrast: the speaker''s bubble says, "I am an agnostic; I do not pretend to know," while some audience bubbles say funny confident statements representing ignorance (like "I know it all!"). The style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial features to emphasize humor and irony, capturing the witty observation about knowledge and ignorance without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1483, 'Agriculture, Animals, Humor, Quotes', 'About the only thing on a farm that has an easy time is the dog.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a classic farm. In the center, a happy, relaxed dog lounges contentedly on a shaded porch or a cozy spot near a farmhouse, tongue happily out and tail wagging slightly. Around the dog, depict the typical tough, busy farm animals like a tired-looking cow chewing cud, a muddy pig wallowing, a scruffy sheep looking worn out, and a hardworking farmer carrying a heavy basket or hoeing the ground. Include a rustic barn and fields in the background to establish the farm setting. All characters should have exaggerated, cartoonish expressions emphasizing the contrast: the dog looks carefree and comfortable, while the others look exhausted or stressed. Bright, cheerful colors and lighthearted style keep the tone funny and wholesome, with no violence or harsh elements.'),
 (1395, 'Agriculture, Everyday Life, Optimism Humor, Quotes', 'A farmer is always going to make it rich the next year.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful farmer standing in the middle of a large farmland with a big hopeful smile. The farmer is wearing classic overalls, a straw hat, and holding a pitchfork. Around him are exaggeratedly empty fields with little or no crops growing, maybe a few sad-looking plants or a fence that’s slightly broken. In the background, there is a rustic barn and a tractor that looks a bit old-fashioned. Above the farmer’s head, a thought bubble shows a fantasy of a mountain of money or piles of gold coins labeled "Next Year". The overall tone is lighthearted and optimistic despite the barren field, emphasizing the farmer’s perpetual hope that next year will be the big break. The style should be colorful, playful, and cartoonish without any violence or negative imagery.'),
 (2118, 'Agriculture, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable', 'Most things, except agriculture, can wait.', 'Jawaharial Nehru', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a peaceful farm. The foreground shows a relaxed farmer sitting in a rocking chair under a large oak tree, sipping lemonade with a calm, content smile. Around him, various farm chores and modern distractions are portrayed humorously on pause: a half-mowed lawn with a stopped lawnmower; a bakery delivery truck with a driver yawning and shrugging; a pile of unopened letters on a mailbox; and a clock on the barn wall with its hands stopped. In the background, crops like corn and wheat are growing steadily with a bright sun shining, symbolizing that agriculture keeps moving regardless. Above the scene, a playful banner or sign reads, "Most things, except agriculture, can wait." The style is colorful, lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions and clear farm elements (hay bales, pitchfork, watering can) to emphasize the slow, steady agricultural pace contrasted against everyday hustle paused humorously.'),
 (39, 'Agriculture, Humor, Word Play', 'Old MacDonald had an agricultural real estate tax abatement.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Old MacDonald, a cheerful farmer wearing a classic straw hat, overalls, and boots, standing proudly in front of his large, colorful farm. The farm features a barn, a tractor, and various crops growing in neat rows. Above him is a large official-looking paper or sign labeled ''Agricultural Real Estate Tax Abatement'' with a big red stamp saying ''Approved.'' Old MacDonald is smiling widely, holding the document in one hand and tipping his hat with the other. Around him, animals like cows and chickens look confused or mildly amused. The background includes a sunny sky and a few trees, setting a peaceful farm atmosphere. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to enhance the joke''s play on the classic nursery rhyme and the modern tax concept.'),
 (2511, 'Alcohol Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'We are in such a slump that even the ones that aren''t drinkin'' aren''t hittin''.', 'Casey Stengel', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a casual bar or pub with a few cartoon characters sitting slouched over at a wooden bar counter. Their expressions show exaggerated exhaustion or disappointment. Some characters are holding empty or half-full drinks, while one or two have no drinks at all but look just as tired or bored. Behind the bar, a bartender with a mildly confused expression watches the patrons. The background includes shelves with bottles, a small chalkboard with specials, and a couple of empty beer mugs on the counter. The overall mood should feel like a funny depiction of a slow, lackluster night where no one seems lively or energized, whether they are drinking or not. The style is lighthearted, with simple, rounded cartoon features and bright, soft colors to keep it cheerful and non-threatening.'),
 (2988, 'Alcohol Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'I get my best ideas drinking beer, because two heads are better than one.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man relaxing at a cozy bar counter with a frothy beer mug in hand. His head is cleverly depicted as two heads joined together side-by-side, both wearing casual expressions as though in deep thought or brainstorming. The bar background includes typical elements like stools, a beer tap, and shelves stocked with various colorful bottles. The two-headed man looks pleased, with lightbulbs above each head symbolizing bright ideas. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, capturing the pun that drinking beer results in ''two heads'' being better than one.'),
 (2228, 'Analogy Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Science is not a sacred cow. Science is a horse. Don''t worship it. Feed it.', 'Aubrey Eben', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set outdoors with a large, friendly-looking horse standing calmly in the center. The horse wears a pair of round glasses and has a playful, wise expression. In front of the horse is a wooden feed bucket labeled ''SCIENCE FOOD'' filled with books, test tubes, and light bulbs instead of hay. Nearby, a person in casual clothing is gently offering the bucket to the horse, looking thoughtful but amused. Surrounding the scene, subtle background details include a pasture with a small fence and a big sign that reads ''Science Stable.'' The overall mood is lighthearted and encouraging, with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize humor and the metaphor of science as a horse that needs care rather than worship. Make sure the style is simple and playful with bright colors and soft outlines to give it a friendly vibe.'),
 (2108, 'Analogy Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Minds are like parachutes -- they only function when open.', 'Thomas Dewar', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing on the edge of a cliff about to jump off with a colorful parachute on their back. The parachute is open, but instead of the usual parachute fabric, it''s shaped like a giant cartoon brain with a smiling face and eyes, looking lively and alert. The person looks enthusiastic and ready to jump, wearing casual outdoor gear. In the background, a clear blue sky and fluffy white clouds are visible. Below the cliff, a valley or landscape shows small trees and hills. A whimsical banner or sign near the cliff’s edge reads: ''Minds are like parachutes – they only function when open.'' The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, emphasizing the connection between open minds and functioning parachutes in a playful way.'),
 (1724, 'Analogy Humor, Quotes, Religious Humor, Word Play', 'Going to church doesn''t make you a Christian any more than going to a garage makes you a car.', 'Laurence J. Peter', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a moderately sized church building on the left with a person happily walking toward its entrance, perhaps holding a Bible. On the right, a classic car garage with an open door revealing some cars inside. Outside the garage, a confused person is standing looking at the garage as if wondering if entering it would magically transform them into a car. The expressions of both people are exaggeratedly humorous and puzzled. The background is simple with a bright sky and some clouds. Both buildings are clearly labeled: "Church" on the left and "Garage" on the right. The style is light-hearted and colorful, with clear visual contrast between the church’s traditional architecture and the industrial appearance of the garage. No additional characters or objects that distract from the message.'),
 (623, 'Anatomy Humor, Good Question!, Puns, Word Play', 'Why can''t a nose be 12 inches long? Because then it would be a foot!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a giant nose that measures exactly 12 inches, portrayed as unusually long and exaggerated to stretch across a ruler or tape measure held by a character. Nearby, depict an oversized human foot with toes wiggling or slightly smiling, emphasizing the punchline that a 12-inch nose would essentially be a ''foot.'' The scene should be lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and a simple, clear background such as a plain room or outdoor park to keep the focus on the nose and foot characters. Consider adding a measuring tape or ruler labeled with inches to visually reinforce the joke. The nose can have comical nostrils and be anthropomorphized slightly, while the foot should also look a bit animated for extra humor. Avoid any complex or distracting elements to keep the joke intuitive and funny at a glance.'),
 (40, 'Anatomy Humor, Humor, Word Play', 'The strongest muscle in the body is the tongue.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a human figure standing with an exaggeratedly oversized tongue stretching out from their mouth. The tongue should look muscular, with bold defined biceps-style muscles drawn on it, as if it’s a strong arm. The character should have a confident or proud expression, pointing at the tongue to emphasize its strength. Surround the figure with a few floating, simplified anatomical illustrations of other muscles (like an arm or leg muscle) looking smaller and less impressive in comparison to the tongue. Use bright, cheerful colors and keep the style playful and light-hearted without any aggressive or violent elements.'),
 (1425, 'Anatomy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Word Play', 'A kiss: the anatomical juxtaposition of 2 orbicularis oris muscles in a state of contraction.', 'Dr. Henry Gibbons', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two smiling people leaning in to kiss, but instead of focusing on their faces, the spotlight zooms in on their lips. The lips are exaggerated and glowing slightly, with cartoonish muscle fibers labeled ''orbicularis oris'' wrapping around them. Above or beside them is a playful scientific-style label or diagram pointing to the lips, with the phrase: ''Anatomical juxtaposition of 2 orbicularis oris muscles in a state of contraction.'' The background is simple and colorful to keep the focus on the lips and muscles. The characters should look friendly, lighthearted, and the style should be clear and clean with a touch of whimsy, like a comic illustration.'),
 (41, 'Animals, Bad Puns', 'A bicycle can''t stand on its own because it''s two-tired.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bicycle with exaggerated tired-looking eyes and droopy posture, leaning over with its two wheels flattened as if it''s exhausted. The bike is on a simple flat road or pavement with a subtle, wavy line suggesting fatigue. Nearby, a small speech bubble from the bike says, "I''m two-tired!" The background is light and cheerful with a sunny sky and a few fluffy clouds. Optional: a small cartoon character or animal nearby looking amused or puzzled by the bike''s condition. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and soft lines to emphasize the pun without any people or complex backgrounds.'),
 (42, 'Animals, Bad Puns', 'A chicken crossing the road is poultry in motion.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful chicken mid-stride crossing a two-lane road. The chicken is slightly exaggerated with big eyes and a confident smile, emphasizing its purposeful walk. The road should be simple, with clear lane markings, and a simple countryside or suburban background including a few trees and perhaps a friendly sun in the sky. Above or near the chicken, a small motion blur or speed lines indicate movement to emphasize ''in motion.'' Include a playful signpost on the roadside that says ''Crosswalk'' or ''Chicken Crossing.'' The overall art style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish with clear outlines, making it suitable for light-hearted humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (43, 'Animals, Bad Puns', 'My dog has no legs, nobody likes him. He can''t even stand himself', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a sad-looking dog with no legs sitting on the ground. The dog appears to be glancing downwards, conveying a feeling of self-pity. Nearby, a few other cartoon dogs with legs are walking away or looking uninterested, illustrating that nobody likes him. A speech bubble above the legless dog reads, "I can''t even stand myself," emphasizing the pun. The background is a simple park with green grass and a few trees, keeping the focus on the dog and the play on words. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish to keep the mood funny, not depressing.'),
 (44, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Butter, Pessimistic', 'If we removed all the margarine on earth the world would be a much butter place', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon scene depicting planet Earth as a giant round buttered toast. The Earth has a smiling face, with continents shaped like chunks of golden butter melting across the surface. Surrounding the Earth are several oversized sticks and tubs of margarine with sad, droopy expressions, looking like they are being pushed away with little cartoon arms. Above the planet, whimsical text or a banner reads: ''A much butter place!'' The background is bright and cheerful with a clear blue sky and a few fluffy clouds. The overall art style should be simple, colorful, and playful to highlight the pun, without any people or complex elements.'),
 (45, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Camping', 'Two Eskimos sitting in a kayak were chilly, so they lit a fire in the craft. Unsurprisingly it sank, proving once again that you can''t have your kayak and heat it too.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two Eskimos sitting inside a small wooden kayak floating on calm water. Both Eskimos wear traditional fur-lined parkas and look shivery and cold, with visible cartoonish shivers and chattering teeth. One Eskimo is holding a small wooden matchbox and the other is carefully lighting a small campfire inside the middle of the kayak. The kayak is visibly starting to take on water around the fire, with small splashes and bubbles showing the effects of the fire''s heat on the water. Both Eskimos have surprised, worried expressions as the kayak begins to sink, tilting slightly forward. The background should be a chilly arctic scene with icebergs and snow-covered land visible in the distance under a pale blue sky. The cartoon style should emphasize exaggerated expressions and a playful, light-hearted mood without any danger or discomfort to the characters.'),
 (46, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Cartoon', 'The Energizer Bunny was arrested - charged with battery.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing the Energizer Bunny, the iconic pink rabbit wearing sunglasses and holding drumsticks, standing at a police station being ''arrested.'' The bunny should look slightly mischievous but not scared. A police officer, with a friendly smile, is holding a clipboard labeled ''Charge: Battery.'' Next to the bunny, include a large battery symbol or an oversized AA battery on the floor to emphasize the pun. The background should have typical police station elements like a badge on the wall, a wanted poster with a picture of the bunny, and a holding cell door partly open. The style is colorful and lighthearted with exaggerated cartoon features to keep it funny and playful.'),
 (47, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Chickens, Food Humor', 'Which day of the week do chickens hate most? Fry-day!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of cartoon chickens standing outside on a farm. The setting shows a bright sunny day with a classic red barn in the background and a wooden fence. In the foreground, three chickens are gathered, looking alarmed and gossiping as they point towards a calendar hanging on a fence post. The calendar clearly highlights the day labeled ''Friday,'' but with the word replaced humorously as ''Fry-day'' in bold, sizzling letters with little cartoon flames around it. Nearby, a chef''s frying pan floats in the air with steam rising, hinting at cooking but portrayed in a light-hearted, non-threatening way. The chickens have exaggerated, expressive faces showing nervousness and fear. The overall style is colorful, exaggerated, and playful, emphasizing the wordplay on ''Friday'' and ''fry.'' The scene invites laughter without any violence or negativity, capturing the pun visually.'),
 (48, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Chickens, Humor', 'Why did the chicken cross the playground? To get to the other slide.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene set in a playground on a sunny day. The main focus is a cheerful cartoon chicken mid-step, crossing from one side to the other. On one side of the playground is a classic slide with a ladder, and on the other side is another identical slide to emphasize ''the other slide.'' Around the playground, include swings, a sandbox, and a few playful trees to add context. The chicken should have a cute, slightly exaggerated expression of determination or curiosity. The style is lighthearted and whimsical with bright colors and simple shapes to evoke humor and playfulness. No people are needed, only the chicken and playground equipment to keep the focus on the joke''s punchline about the chicken crossing to the other slide, a pun on ''other side.'''),
 (49, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Chuck Norris', 'Chuck Norris can kill two stones with one bird.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in a rugged outdoor setting. He is in mid-action, throwing a small colorful bird with exaggerated motion lines flying from his hand. Nearby, two smooth, round stones are placed close together on the ground, and one stone shows a tiny shocked face while the other looks surprised, as if about to be affected by the bird. Chuck Norris has a determined, calm expression, wearing his signature martial artist outfit or casual tough-guy clothes. The background should be simple with a hint of nature: a few trees, some grass, and a clear sky. The style should be bright, cheerful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, like a classic cartoon. Include a small comic-style text bubble near Chuck saying something like “Watch this!” to emphasize the joke''s punchline. The scene must avoid any violence, showing a playful, absurd interpretation of the phrase.'),
 (50, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Computers, Engineers', 'If this computer were a horse, I''d have to shoot it!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a desk with an old, slow-looking computer on it. The computer has exaggerated horse-like features such as ears, a mane, and a tail attached to the monitor and tower. The person is holding a large red toolbox in one hand and looking exasperated, while the computer-horse is sluggish, with sleepy eyes and a patchy mane, maybe with a small thought bubble showing a snail or a loading icon. The background is a simple office or home workspace with a coffee mug and scattered papers. The overall tone is light and comical, emphasizing the computer’s slowness by likening it to a worn-out horse that one might ''shoot'' to put out of its misery, but without any violence shown explicitly—just humorous expressions and body language.'),
 (51, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Corona, Humor', 'What''s the difference between a hot dog and an anti-vaxxer? The hot dog might have SOME brains in it', NULL, 'A colorful and humorous cartoon scene featuring two main characters side by side. On the left, a classic hot dog with ketchup and mustard in a bun, smiling and showing a tiny cartoon brain popping out of its top bun in a playful way. On the right, a person depicted as an anti-vaxxer with a confused expression, exaggeratedly scratching their head as if puzzled or lacking understanding. The background is simple and bright, suggesting a lighthearted mood. Include a speech bubble above the hot dog saying, "I''ve got some brains!" and another from the anti-vaxxer with a question mark to emphasize confusion. No violence or negativity should be present. The style is cartoonish with bold outlines and vibrant colors, focusing on the humorous contrast between the two characters'' expressions and the small brain detail on the hot dog.'),
 (52, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Fishing Humor', 'I''ve always admired fishermen - they are reel men.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a fisherman standing proudly on a small wooden dock by a lake. He is wearing classic fishing gear: a fishing hat with hooks and lures attached, a vest with many pockets, and rubber boots. In one hand, he is holding a fishing rod with a big fish caught on the line, and in the other hand, he is giving a thumbs-up. Nearby, a smiling fish is leaping out of the water, with cartoonish motion lines showing the jump. Above the fisherman, a speech bubble reads, ''I’m a reel man!'' emphasizing the pun. The background includes a bright sunny sky, trees lining the lake, and a wooden sign by the dock that reads ''Welcome to Reel Lake.'' The style is colorful, cheerful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, capturing the pun on ''reel'' and ''real'' in a lighthearted way.'),
 (53, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'I heard about a lab in California growing medical marijuana - a flock of terns landed in their field and ate all their weed. They say no tern was left unstoned.', NULL, 'A colorful and whimsical cartoon scene set in a sunny California field filled with tall cannabis plants. Several cheerful terns (small seabirds with white and gray feathers and black caps) are perched on and flying around the marijuana plants. Some terns are shown playfully nibbling on the leaves, with silly expressions suggesting they are ''high'' or goofy, like blurry eyes or goofy smiles. The field should look lush and green, with a simple sign that reads ''Medical Marijuana Lab'' near the edge. In the background, a surprised scientist or farmer wearing a lab coat and sunglasses stands scratching their head, watching the birds. Add a subtle smoke wreath drifting around the terns to hint humorously at the ''stoned'' pun. The whole style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun and playful mood without anything inappropriate or violent.'),
 (54, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'The dog''s kennel is not the place to keep a sausage.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a cheerful doghouse (kennel) in a backyard. The doghouse is typical with a little arched entrance and a nameplate above it labeled ''Fido''. Inside the doghouse, instead of a dog, there is a plump, cartoon-style sausage lying comfortably on a small cushion, looking surprised or confused. Outside the kennel, a happy dog with a wagging tail looks at the sausage inside, tilting its head in curiosity. The background includes simple grass, a fence, and a bright sunny sky to give it a lighthearted and funny atmosphere. The style should be clear, bold lines, with playful expressions to emphasize the absurdity of putting a sausage inside a doghouse rather than a dog.'),
 (55, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'Which day do chickens hate the most? Friday', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of chickens standing in a farmyard. The central chicken has an exaggeratedly annoyed or frustrated expression, possibly crossing its wings or shaking its feathers in displeasure. Around them, a colorful calendar is prominently displayed, with the day ''Friday'' circled or marked in bright red, emphasizing its significance. Other days on the calendar are visible but less emphasized. The background includes a classic red barn, green grass, a few haystacks, and a bright blue sky with a smiling sun to enhance the cheerful yet funny mood. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bold lines and bright colors typical of cartoons, making the chicken''s dislike for Friday clear and funny without any hostility or negativity.'),
 (3232, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Food Humor, Thanksgiving', 'What do you get when you cross a turkey with a centipede? Drumsticks for everyone!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, plump turkey with many legs like a centipede, each leg ending in a drumstick instead of a foot. The turkey looks cheerful and slightly confused. Around the turkey, a group of happy people of various ages excitedly grabbing drumsticks from the turkey''s many legs. The background is a casual kitchen or dining room with a table set for a feast, including a few empty plates and utensils. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the absurdity of a multi-legged turkey with drumstick ''feet''.'),
 (56, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Good Question!', 'Do hungry crows have ravenous appetites?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a crow perched on a tree branch, looking enthusiastically at a picnic table filled with various food items. The crow has a cheeky, eager expression and is wearing a little bib to emphasize its hunger. On the picnic table are plates with food such as sandwiches, fruit, and crumbs scattered around. In the background, other woodland animals like squirrels and rabbits watch the crow with amused expressions. The setting is a bright, sunny park with green grass and a few trees. The style is colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions to bring out the humor of the crow being ''ravenous.'' No text is included in the image, but the visual should clearly evoke the pun linking ''crows'' and ''ravenous appetites.'''),
 (592, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Good Question!, Word Play', 'What is a zebra? 26 sizes larger than an ''A'' bra.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a zebra standing proudly in a simple grassy field. Beside the zebra, a comically oversized lingerie sized tag hangs from its neck or tail that reads ''26 sizes larger than an A bra.'' Next to the zebra, on the ground, place a tiny, delicate A-cup bra that looks clearly dwarfed compared to the zebra and the large size tag. The scene should look lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the pun on bra sizes by visually exaggerating the comparison. The zebra should have a cheerful, slightly goofy expression to enhance the joke’s playful tone. The background is minimal, with just a few tufts of grass and a clear sky to keep the focus on the zebra and the bra size humor. Make the colors bright and cartoonish for added comedic effect, and use big, bold, easy-to-read letters for the size tag.'),
 (57, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Humor', 'How do bears catch fish? With their bear hands!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, friendly-looking bear standing by a lively riverbank surrounded by trees. The bear is playfully trying to catch fish with its bare paws, splashing water everywhere. The fish are mid-jump, looking surprised or amused. Nearby, a few fish jump out of the water attempting to avoid the bear''s ''bear hands.'' Include some whimsical, exaggerated expressions on the bear and fish to enhance the humor. The background should be bright and cheerful with a clear blue sky, and some rocks and plants along the riverbank. The overall style is colorful and lighthearted, capturing a fun, pun-inspired moment without any violence or danger.'),
 (58, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'A friend of mine tried to annoy me with bird puns, but I soon realized that toucan play at that game.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two birds interacting in a playful way. One bird is a toucan with its large, colorful beak, looking cheeky and confident. The other bird looks slightly annoyed or frustrated, perhaps a small songbird or parrot, holding a tiny speech bubble with a pun or joke symbol (like a word bubble with a bird silhouette or a pun-related symbol). The background should be a simple, bright outdoor setting with a tree branch where they perch. Include playful visual cues like small musical notes or speech bubbles to indicate conversation and puns. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the birds'' faces to highlight the humor about wordplay related to the toucan pun.'),
 (59, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Puns, Word Play', 'Time flies like an arrow. Fruit flies like a banana.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two parts side-by-side. On the left, a classic arrow is soaring swiftly through the air with a bright blue sky and a stopwatch or clock nearby to emphasize the phrase "Time flies like an arrow." On the right, a bunch of cheerful, cartoonish fruit flies with tiny wings are buzzing happily around and landing on a large, ripe banana. The fruit flies should have exaggerated, cute features like big eyes and smiling faces to add humor. The background is light and simple, with maybe a kitchen table or fruit bowl hinted at behind the banana. The overall style is playful and colorful with clear visual contrasts between the two parts representing the wordplay in the joke.'),
 (3253, 'Animals, Bad Puns, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call a duck with a drug problem? A quackhead', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a duck standing upright with a slightly goofy, dazed expression. The duck wears a small beanie tilted to the side and has tiny red cartoonish eyes to subtly show it’s under the influence, but in a lighthearted, funny way. Surrounding the duck are a few small empty pill bottles and a discarded rolled-up paper on the ground near its feet to hint at a drug problem without any harsh or explicit imagery. The duck is saying the word ''Quackhead'' in a speech bubble above its head. The background is simple and bright, maybe a park or pond with cartoonish lily pads and reeds to keep the focus on the duck. The overall tone is playful and silly, with exaggerated duck features (big bill, webbed feet) to emphasize the joke visually.'),
 (60, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Word Play', 'Is that a boy ant or girl ant? How do you tell? Put it in water. If it sinks, it''s a girl ant. If it floats, it''s boy-ant.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing two large ants standing next to a small, clear glass filled with water on a simple table. One ant looks curious and is pointing at the glass, while the other ant appears nervous or worried. The glass contains one ant sinking to the bottom, labeled ''girl ant,'' and another ant floating on top of the water surface, labeled ''boy-ant'' as a pun. The background is simple and bright with a few green leaves and a blue sky visible, emphasizing a lighthearted mood. The ants have big expressive eyes and exaggerated facial expressions, highlighting the joke. Include a small speech bubble near the curious ant that says, ''Is that a boy ant or girl ant? How do you tell? Put it in water!'''),
 (61, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Word Play', 'My horse will not come out of her stable after dark. She''s becoming a night mare.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at dusk or nighttime outside a stable. The stable is wooden with an open door showing a cozy interior. Just inside the doorway, a horse looks tired or sleepy with droopy eyes, half-lidded, and maybe wearing a cute little sleeping cap. Outside the stable, moonlight shines softly, casting shadows. Above the stable, floating in the air as a ghostly figure, is a playful, friendly-looking nightmare—depicted as a small, cartoonish horse with wings and a goofy grin, representing the pun on "nightmare." The main horse looks reluctant to leave the stable, clearly preferring the safety inside. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun without anything scary or threatening.'),
 (62, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Word Play', 'My wife asked me is I''d seen the dog bowl. I said I didn''t know he bowled', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy kitchen. A man stands confused with a raised eyebrow and a slight smile, looking towards his wife who is holding an empty dog bowl in one hand and pointing at it. Nearby, a friendly dog wearing a bowling ball patterned collar looks up innocently. In the background, a few bowling pins and a brightly colored bowling ball sit beside the dog’s feeding area as a playful nod to the pun. The kitchen is warm and inviting, with typical elements like a countertop, a bowl rack, and a small rug. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the joke’s wordplay between ''dog bowl'' and ''bowled.'''),
 (63, 'Animals, Bad Puns, Word Play', 'What''s the difference between a hippo and a zippo? One is really heavy, and the other is a little lighter.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two main objects side by side on a simple white or light-colored background. On the left, draw a large, cute, and chubby hippopotamus with a friendly and slightly puzzled expression. It should be clearly heavy and bulky, sitting or standing solidly on the ground. On the right, illustrate a small, shiny Zippo-style lighter with the lid open and a small flame flickering. The lighter should look tiny compared to the hippo, emphasizing the size and weight difference. Between them, add a light-hearted caption or speech bubble with the joke text: ''What''s the difference between a hippo and a zippo? One is really heavy, and the other is a little lighter.'' Make the style bright and colorful with exaggerated, rounded cartoon features to enhance the playful mood.'),
 (2632, 'Animals, Bar Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'A bear walks into a bar and says, ''I''d like a beer . and some of those peanuts.'' The bartender says, ''Sure, but why the big paws?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a classic bar setting. A large, friendly-looking bear stands upright at the bar counter, facing the bartender. The bear is holding a menu or pointing at the beer taps with one paw, and in front of him on the counter are a frothy beer mug and a small bowl of peanuts. The bartender is a smiling human, wearing a white shirt and black vest, standing behind the counter with a slightly puzzled but amused expression as he asks the question. Include details like a wooden bar counter, stools, shelves stocked with bottles and glasses, and a small sign behind the bar that says ''Peanuts are complimentary.'' The focus is on the visual pun: the bear''s very large paws emphasized humorously, perhaps with motion lines or a subtle spotlight on the paws to highlight the joke. The style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing friendly and humorous vibes without any suggestion of aggression or violence.'),
 (2939, 'Animals, Bathroom Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'How do you make a Kleenex dance? You put a little boogie in it!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, anthropomorphic Kleenex tissue with arms, legs, and eyes. The Kleenex is mid-dance with a joyful expression, raised hands, and little motion lines around its body to show movement. Below or beside it, a small green booger character with a playful smile is either hopping on one foot or appearing to ''join'' the dance, emphasizing the pun in the joke. The setting is simple, with a clean background, maybe a table surface or a plain room, keeping the focus on the dancing Kleenex and the booger. Bright, vibrant colors should be used to enhance the whimsical and lighthearted feel of the cartoon.'),
 (64, 'Animals, Bible Humor, Good Question!, Puns', 'Did Noah keep his bees in archives?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon featuring Noah''s Ark floating on calm water with a large wooden box labeled ''ARCHIVES'' prominently on the deck. Around the box, several cartoon bees with tiny wings and cheerful expressions are buzzing and hovering. Noah, a kindly old man with a long beard and biblical attire, is smiling and pointing at the box as if explaining it to a pair of curious animals nearby, such as a giraffe and a lion. The sky is bright with a rainbow in the background, enhancing the lighthearted and punny atmosphere. Make sure the bees look cute and friendly, and the ark is recognizable with animals peeking out from the windows or decks, but no other distractions. The scene should have a playful, whimsical cartoon style, emphasizing the pun on ''archives'' as a place where bees might be kept by Noah.'),
 (617, 'Animals, Bible Humor, Good Question!, Puns', 'Where did Noah keep the bees? In the Ark Hives', NULL, 'A cheerful, cartoon-style Noah''s Ark floating on calm water under a bright sky. The Ark should have a large wooden structure with simple windows and a door. Next to the Ark, show a few cartoon bees wearing tiny, stripy helmets and holding little beekeeping tools like smokers. On one side of the Ark, depict a humorous sign reading “Ark Hives” with a bee logo and a small entrance resembling a hive. The scene should be colorful and lighthearted, with bees buzzing happily around the Ark, some hovering near the hive entrance, and maybe a few bees wearing little captain hats or bee-sized raincoats to add whimsy. The overall mood is playful and cute, emphasizing the pun without any threatening or dark elements.'),
 (2950, 'Animals, Biology Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'Humans are the only primates that don''t have pigment in the palms of their hands.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of primates gathered together in the jungle clearing. Three different primates—like a chimpanzee, a gorilla, and an orangutan—are sitting or standing, proudly showing off their pigmented palms with dark, boldly colored hands. In the center, a human character (wearing casual modern clothes) is looking down at their own pristine, pale palms with a confused or embarrassed expression. The human''s hands are clean and noticeably lighter compared to the others. The setting should be bright and colorful with leafy jungle plants and trees in the background. Each primate has exaggerated, cartoonishly large palms showing their dark pigment clearly to highlight the contrast. The mood is light, playful, and funny, with maybe a speech bubble over the human reading something like, "Wait, we’re missing something?" Humorous style with rounded shapes and expressive faces to emphasize the joke.'),
 (65, 'Animals, Camping, Good Question!', 'Yo momma''s so fat the bears have to hide their food from her when she goes camping.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon set in a forest campsite. In the center, a large, friendly-looking woman with a big smile and casual camping clothes (like a flannel shirt and hiking boots) stands near a picnic table overflowing with food. Around her, three bears peek out from behind trees and bushes, looking both cautious and mischievous as they hide various foods like jars of honey, sandwiches, and picnic baskets from her. The scene includes typical camping elements like a tent, a campfire with a pot hanging over it, pine trees, and a bright blue sky. The overall tone is light, playful, and exaggerated to emphasize the joke, with the bears clearly acting as if they are hiding their stash from the woman rather than threatening her.'),
 (645, 'Animals, Cartoon, Good Question!, Pun', 'Why doesn''t Tarzan have a beard?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Tarzan, a muscular man wearing a loincloth, standing in the jungle. He is looking at himself in a large leaf-shaped mirror hanging from a tree branch. Tarzan has a clean-shaven face with no beard and a slightly puzzled, innocent expression. Around him, the jungle is lush with tropical plants, vines, and a few friendly animals like a monkey hanging from a vine and a parrot perched on a branch. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated features to emphasize the humor of Tarzan not having a beard despite being a wild jungle man.'),
 (66, 'Animals, Cartoon, Humor', 'The ant always falls over on its right side when intoxicated.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon of a small ant standing on a tiny patch of ground or a leaf. The ant is shown in mid-fall, tipping dramatically to its right side with wide, exaggerated eyes and a silly grin, clearly looking intoxicated. Around its head, classic cartoon-style swirling stars or bubbles float to indicate dizziness. Nearby, a small bottle labeled with a comical ''ant-sized'' drink (such as a tiny bottle with a leaf or sugar cube icon) lies tipped over, spilling a few drops. The background is simple and bright, focusing on the ant''s funny predicament without clutter. The overall style is lighthearted, cute, and family-friendly, emphasizing the ant''s silly stumble as if it were a tiny cartoon character in a playful situation.'),
 (1243, 'Animals, Cartoon, Knock Knock, Word Play', 'KK/WT: Cows go ? No silly - owls go Hoo, cows go Moo', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused character (could be a child or an adult) standing between a cow and an owl on a farm. The cow is large, friendly-looking, and mid-''Moo,'' with a speech bubble showing ''Moo.'' The owl is perched on a tree branch nearby, with a speech bubble showing ''Hoo.'' The character is scratching their head with a puzzled expression, looking at both animals. The background is a simple, sunny farm scene with grass, a wooden fence, and a barn in the distance. Add a comic-style caption near the character that reads: ''Cows go? No silly - owls go Hoo, cows go Moo.'' Keep the style lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the play on expecting a cow to say ''Hoo'' but correcting with the familiar animal sounds instead.'),
 (1306, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pirates, Pun', 'Did''ya hear about the pirate''s parrot that fell in love with a duck? The bird kept saying, ''Polly wants a quacker''.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a colorful pirate parrot and a cute duck standing together near a pirate ship dock. The parrot is wearing a tiny pirate hat and an eye patch, looking lovestruck with hearts floating above its head. The duck, looking slightly amused and surprised, stands beside the parrot. Above them, a speech bubble from the parrot says, ''Polly wants a quacker.'' In the background, part of the pirate ship with its wooden deck and a flag can be seen, along with a calm water body and a sunny sky. The overall style is lighthearted and silly, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s punchline about the parrot confusing a ''cracker'' with a ''quacker.'' Include playful colors and cartoonish proportions to enhance the humor and charm of the scene.'),
 (1319, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pirates, Pun', 'Why did the pirate join the debate team? Because he liked to Arrrrrrgue!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly-looking pirate with a classic tricorn hat, eye patch, and striped shirt standing confidently behind a podium in a classroom or debate hall setting. The pirate is dramatically raising one hand as if making a strong point, with a speech bubble above his head containing a playful ''Arrrrrrgue!'' in bold letters. Around him, a few amused or intrigued classmates, dressed in typical school attire, watch with raised eyebrows and smiles. The background features a chalkboard with debate-related notes or simple decorations like stars or thumbs-up symbols to enhance the lively debate atmosphere. The overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and fun, with exaggerated expressions and cartoony proportions to emphasize the joke’s pun and playful spirit.'),
 (3235, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'What sound does a turkey''s phone make? Wing-wing-wing', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a turkey holding a smartphone up to its beak as if talking or listening. The turkey should look surprised or amused. Around the turkey, include comic-style sound effect letters showing ''Wing-wing-wing'' coming out of the phone''s speaker, mimicking a ringing sound. The background can be a simple farmyard scene with a barn and some scattered autumn leaves to give a light, fun atmosphere. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerate the turkey’s features for comedic effect, such as big eyes and an expressive wattle to enhance the joke''s playful tone.'),
 (2922, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, Unknown', 'Heard on Noahs'' ark: Sailing is fun, but scrubbing the decks is aardvark.', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene set on the deck of Noah''s Ark, showing a cheerful Noah dressed in biblical robes and sandals holding a large scrubbing brush with soap bubbles floating around. Next to him is a cute, slightly perplexed aardvark wearing a tiny sailor hat, holding a scrub brush in its little paws and scrubbing the wooden deck. The ark''s wooden planks and the rails are visible, with a few soap suds scattered around. In the background, pairs of various animals are standing calmly on the deck, watching the cleaning with amusement. The sky is clear with a few fluffy clouds, and the ocean is gently visible beyond the side of the ark. The overall style is bright, colorful, and humorous, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the playful pun in the joke.'),
 (2942, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, Unknown', 'How do you tell the difference between an alligator and a crocodile? Pay attention to whether the animal sees you later or in a while', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene featuring two cartoon reptiles: one an alligator and the other a crocodile, standing side by side in a swampy environment with water, reeds, and trees. The alligator is waving goodbye with a cheerful expression, saying “See you later!” in a speech bubble. The crocodile, looking slightly sly and smiling, responds with “In a while...” in its speech bubble. Both animals have exaggerated features typical of cartoons—big eyes, wide mouths with visible teeth, and friendly, anthropomorphic poses. The background is bright and colorful, adding to the lighthearted mood. Include a small sign near them labeling ''Alligator'' and ''Crocodile'' to clarify which is which, helping the viewer understand the joke visually. The art style is whimsical and playful, similar to classic cartoons.'),
 (3106, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, Unknown', 'Why did the rooster cross the road? To prove he wasn''t chicken', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident rooster standing in the middle of a road. The rooster has a proud and determined expression, with one wing raised as if to wave or strut. The road is a typical two-lane street with a dashed white line in the center. On one side of the road, a group of smaller, nervous-looking chickens watch the rooster with surprised and impressed expressions. Behind the rooster, on the other side of the road, a small farm fence and a barn can be seen in the background. The style is bright and colorful with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize whimsy and humor. The scene captures the play on words: the rooster is literally crossing the road and figuratively proving he’s not ''chicken'' (cowardly). No text bubbles are necessary, just clear visual cues to the joke''s punchline.'),
 (3108, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, Unknown', 'Why does Waldo wear striped shirts? Because he doesn''t want to be spotted', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene centered around Waldo from the famous ''Where''s Waldo?'' books. Waldo should be standing in the middle, wearing his iconic red-and-white striped shirt, round glasses, and bobble hat. He looks slightly mischievous or sly, glancing sideways. Surrounding him are several cartoon-style, exaggerated leopard-spotted animals—like a big cat or a dog—with confused or surprised expressions, as if they’re unsure whether Waldo is one of them. The background can be a simple outdoor setting, like a park or forest, with bright colors to keep the mood light and funny. Include a speech bubble or small caption near Waldo that says, ''Because he doesn''t want to be spotted.'' The overall style should be playful and whimsical, emphasizing the pun between wearing stripes and not being ''spotted'' like an animal with spots.'),
 (3248, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, What do you call...', 'What do you call a camel with no humps? Humphrey', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a smiling camel standing proudly in the middle of a sunny desert. The camel has a sleek, smooth back with no humps at all, looking slightly puzzled but cheerful. Above the camel, there is a playful speech bubble or sign that says ''Humphrey'' in fun, bold letters. Around the camel, include simple desert elements like sand dunes and a cactus or two to set the scene. The style is colorful, exaggerated, and lighthearted, with the camel drawn in a friendly and cartoonish manner to emphasize the joke about the name pun on ''humps.'' The background should remain uncluttered and bright, keeping the focus on the camel and the pun.'),
 (3251, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, What do you call...', 'What do you call a cow with no legs? Ground beef', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cow lying flat on the ground with no legs visible. The cow looks content and smiling, with big friendly eyes and a cartoon-style cheerful expression. Around the cow, patches of green grass and a clear blue sky create a simple farm setting. Nearby, a butcher''s sign reads ''Ground Beef'' with a playful font. The cow''s body is detailed with classic spots, and the scene has a lighthearted, whimsical tone with soft, rounded lines typical of a cartoon. No other animals or people are present to keep the focus on the key visual pun of the legless cow on the ground.'),
 (3260, 'Animals, Cartoon, Pun, What do you call...', 'What do you call an alligator that uses GPS? A navigator', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene featuring a cheerful alligator standing upright with a big smile, holding a handheld GPS device. The alligator should be wearing explorer''s gear, like a safari hat and a small backpack, to emphasize the navigator theme. Behind the alligator, show a simple, colorful map with a marked trail and a red ''X'' to imply navigation. The background is a swamp or jungle environment with trees and water. The GPS device screen visibly shows a winding path or a compass arrow pointing the way. The style should be playful and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon features for the alligator to look friendly and amusing.'),
 (3234, 'Animals, Cartoon, Puns, Thanksgiving', 'What sound does a dizzy turkey make? Wobble, wobble', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a turkey that looks dizzy and unsteady. The turkey is standing upright but leaning side to side as if wobbling, with spirals or stars circling its head to indicate dizziness. The turkey should have wide, slightly crossed eyes and a goofy, confused expression. Its wings are raised slightly as if trying to keep balance. Around the turkey, cartoon-style motion lines illustrate the wobbling movement. Optionally, include a speech bubble above the turkey containing the words ''Wobble, wobble'' in playful, wavy letters. The background can be simple with a plain farmyard setting, like some green grass and a wooden fence, to keep focus on the turkey. The overall style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, suitable for all ages.'),
 (1827, 'Animals, Cartoon, Quotes, Romance Humor', 'I love Mickey Mouse more than any woman I have ever known.', 'Walt Disney (1901-1966)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a man sitting happily on a couch, lovingly hugging a large Mickey Mouse plush toy. The man should have an exaggerated joyful expression, eyes closed in contentment. Around him, several female characters look on with surprised or puzzled expressions. The setting is a cozy living room with typical furniture like a coffee table and a lamp. Mickey Mouse plush is big and colorful, clearly the center of attention. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, with clean, exaggerated cartoon features and bright colors to emphasize the humor of prioritizing a beloved cartoon character over real people.'),
 (3241, 'Animals, Cartoon, Thanksgiving, Word Play', 'Why did the turkey cross the road? He wanted people to think he was a chicken', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a bright, sunny day with a simple country road stretching from left to right. On one side stands a plump, confused-looking turkey with colorful feathers, mid-step as it crosses the road. The turkey wears an exaggerated chicken costume that is clearly too small or ill-fitting, with a floppy chicken hat and fake wings that look comically out of place. On the other side of the road, a group of chickens stands watching, looking surprised and curious. The background includes a few farmyard elements such as a wooden fence, a red barn, and a couple of fluffy clouds in the sky. The cartoon style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions on the turkey and chickens to emphasize the humor of the turkey’s attempt to pass as a chicken.'),
 (67, 'Animals, Chickens, Humor, Social Commentary', 'I have a dream that one day chickens will be able to cross the road without being judged on their motives.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confident, anthropomorphic chicken standing at a crosswalk, ready to cross a road. The chicken has an expressive face showing a mix of determination and slight frustration. On the sidewalk, several other animals and humans are standing, whispering and side-glancing at the chicken with exaggerated judging expressions (raised eyebrows, crossed arms, side-eye). Above the scene, a large billboard or sign resembles a famous inspirational quote style, with the words: "I have a dream that one day chickens will cross the road without being judged." The background includes a simple country road with a few trees, a bright sky, and a peaceful neighborhood setting. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the chicken''s desire for equality and fairness in crossing the road without suspicion or judgment. The art style is colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and simple, clear lines to enhance humor.'),
 (68, 'Animals, Chickens, Puns', 'Did''ya hear about the chicken who could only lay eggs in the winter? She was no spring chicken.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a chicken standing proudly on a snowy winter landscape, surrounded by a few freshly laid eggs on the ground. The chicken wears a tiny scarf and earmuffs to emphasize the cold season. In the background, leafless trees and snowflakes falling from the sky reinforce the winter setting. A small sign next to the chicken reads ''No Spring Chicken'' as a playful pun. The style is bright and colorful, with exaggerated, cute features on the chicken to enhance the humor and friendliness of the scene.'),
 (69, 'Animals, Chickens, Puns', 'What do you call a chicken crossing the road? Poultry in motion.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene depicting a cheerful chicken walking briskly across a typical two-lane road. The chicken wears a determined expression and mid-step its wings are slightly out to balance itself. The road should be shown from a side view with a dashed center line. On the side of the road, include a small signpost with a playful hint of motion—like cartoon motion lines around the chicken''s legs or dust clouds behind to emphasize movement. The background features green grass and a bright blue sky with a few fluffy clouds. The overall style is lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated, rounded shapes to enhance the humor and cuteness of the scene. No people or vehicles are needed to keep the focus on the ''poultry in motion'' pun.'),
 (70, 'Animals, Chickens, Puns', 'What do you get when a chicken lays an egg on top of a barn? An eggroll.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic red barn with a slanted roof under a bright blue sky with a few fluffy white clouds. On top of the barn''s roof sits a plump, cartoon-style chicken looking a bit proud or surprised. Directly beneath the chicken, a large egg is gently rolling down the curved roof, depicted with motion lines to show it''s moving. Nearby on the ground, a smiling egg character with arms and legs looks up at the rolling egg, as if excited or cheering. The setting is a cheerful farmyard with some green grass, a wooden fence, and a couple of cartoon-style chickens pecking around in the background. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated, rounded shapes and big expressive eyes on the animals and the egg for extra humor.'),
 (71, 'Animals, Chickens, Puns, Sports Humor', 'Why did the chicken cross the basketball court? He heard the referee calling fowls', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene on a basketball court with a chicken walking confidently across the court. The chicken is in mid-stride, looking slightly puzzled but determined. The basketball court has clear markings, hoops on both ends, and a referee standing in the background blowing a whistle while making a hand signal as if calling a foul. Above the referee, a speech bubble says ''Fowls!''. The setting is bright and colorful, with a few scattered basketballs and a scoreboard visible. The overall style is playful and exaggerated, emphasizing the pun between ''fouls'' in basketball and the chicken ''fowls''.'),
 (72, 'Animals, Christmas, Pop Culture, Puns', 'What is the Grinch''s least favorite band? The Who', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene showing the Grinch standing with a grumpy expression, crossing his arms, next to a simple cartoon stage. On the stage, depict a silhouette or iconic logo of the rock band The Who, such as a large target symbol or a figure with a guitar. The background should hint at a Whoville setting with whimsical houses and holiday decorations, but keep the focus on the Grinch’s annoyed face and the band''s symbol. The atmosphere should be lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated features for comedic effect. Include small musical notes floating around the band symbol to show it represents music. The Grinch should clearly look displeased or irritated by the presence of ''The Who.'' No other characters are needed.'),
 (73, 'Animals, Christmas, Puns', 'Why did Rudolph never go to school? He was elf-taught.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring Rudolph the red-nosed reindeer standing proudly outside a small rustic schoolhouse with a big ''School'' sign above the door. Rudolph is wearing a mischievous, confident smile and has a little book open in front of him as if he’s been studying by himself. Next to him, a group of elves dressed in classic green outfits with pointy hats are looking puzzled or shrugging their shoulders. The background shows snowy ground and a few pine trees. The style is lighthearted and humorous, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the playful pun. The focus is on Rudolph being independent and self-learning, highlighting the ''elf-taught'' wordplay with elves nearby for context.'),
 (74, 'Animals, Christmas, Puns, Winter Humor', 'What did one snowman say to the other? ''Is it just me, or do you smell carrots?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two snowmen standing outdoors in a snowy winter landscape. One snowman is leaning slightly toward the other, with a curious expression. Both snowmen have classic coal eyes, a carrot nose, stick arms, and a scarf. The snowman on the left is sniffing the air with a puzzled look, while the other snowman looks amused or surprised. Around them, snow-covered trees and a gentle snowfall set the scene. There could be a subtle hint of melted carrot pieces or small orange smells visually represented as wavy lines near their noses to emphasize the joke. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features such as big eyes and wide smiles to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (75, 'Animals, Chuck Norris, Exaggeration', 'Chuck Norris once kicked a horse in the chin. Its descendants are now known as giraffes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in a cowboy outfit with one leg raised as if he just delivered a powerful side kick. Nearby, a bewildered horse is humorously stretched upward with an extremely long neck, resembling a giraffe. The background includes a simple ranch setting with a wooden fence and some green grass. The horse-turned-giraffe looks surprised and slightly confused, emphasizing the absurdity of the joke. The style should be playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and clear, bold outlines to enhance the humor.'),
 (76, 'Animals, Chuck Norris, Exaggeration', 'If you want a list of Chuck Norris'' enemies, just check the extinct species list.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris standing confidently in the center with his arms crossed and a serious expression. Around him are several extinct animals like a dodo bird, a woolly mammoth, a saber-toothed tiger, and a dinosaur, looking defeated or scared. In the background, a large open book titled ''Extinct Species List'' is propped up on a stand, with a page clearly showing pictures or sketches of these creatures. The setting is bright and colorful, with exaggerated cartoon features, comical expressions on the animals, and a light-hearted tone to emphasize the joke that Chuck Norris is responsible for extinction of species.'),
 (77, 'Animals, Chuck Norris, Exaggeration', 'Once time a cobra bit Chuck Norris. After five days of excruciating pain, the cobra died.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing calmly and confidently, arms crossed, with a slight smirk on his face. Nearby, a cobra lies on its back with X''s over its eyes, clearly defeated and cartoonishly exaggerated to show it has ''died.'' The cobra shows signs of weakness like limp coils and a small sweat drop. Chuck Norris is depicted as a tough, muscular man wearing casual clothes with a martial arts vibe (e.g., a black belt or simple shirt and jeans). The background is simple and bright, maybe a desert or jungle edge to imply the cobra''s habitat. There could be a small clock or calendar page showing ''5 days later'' to emphasize the time element of the joke. Overall, the style is lighthearted, colorful, and playful, capturing the absurdity and exaggeration of the joke without any violence or threat.'),
 (78, 'Animals, Chuck Norris, Exaggeration', 'The dinosaurs looked at Chuck Norris the wrong way once. You know what happened to them.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a group of dinosaurs, including a T-Rex, Triceratops, and Stegosaurus, looking confused and a bit worried. They are standing in a prehistoric landscape with volcanoes and palm trees in the background. In front of them stands a muscular, confident Chuck Norris character wearing his signature outfit (casual, with a beard and a stern expression). Chuck Norris is casually cracking his knuckles or flexing his muscles, looking calm but intimidating. The dinosaurs, wide-eyed and slightly backing away, give the impression that they just realized they made a big mistake. The style is humorous and light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions on the dinosaurs and Chuck Norris to emphasize the joke''s punchline. Include a subtle caption or speech bubble near the dinosaurs with something like ''Uh-oh...'' for added effect.'),
 (79, 'Animals, Chuck Norris, Puns', 'Chuck Norris makes onions cry.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in the center, with a big, tough grin on his face. Around him are several onions, anthropomorphized with cartoon eyes and teardrops streaming down their cheeks, clearly crying. The onions should look cute and exaggerated, with small faces expressing sadness or fear. Chuck Norris can be shown with his signature beard and martial arts attire, maybe with his arms crossed or performing a classic roundhouse kick. The background is simple—a kitchen counter or garden setting to hint where onions grow or are prepared. Bright, bold colors and clean lines keep the image lighthearted and fun with no violence, just the idea that Chuck Norris’s presence alone causes onions to cry, flipping the usual concept of onions making humans cry on its head.'),
 (3033, 'Animals, Comedy, Pun, Unknown', 'I returned my lizard to the pet store because it wouldn''t stop telling dad jokes. The pet shop owner informed me that wasn''t a lizard - it was a stand up chameleon', NULL, 'Create a colorful, humorous cartoon scene inside a quirky pet store filled with animals. In the center, show a frustrated customer holding a small chameleon on a leash or perched on the counter. The chameleon has an exaggerated goofy expression, maybe mid-speech with a little speech bubble showing a typical dad joke pun related to lizards. Nearby, the pet store owner, a cheerful person wearing a store apron and glasses, is pointing at the chameleon with a knowing smile. A sign behind the counter reads ''Pet Returns & Exchanges.'' Around them, include various pets in cages or tanks—fish, rabbits, birds—but make the focus clearly on the chameleon and the customer interaction. The chameleon should look like it''s about to deliver another joke, embodying the punchline being a ''stand up chameleon'' (so maybe standing upright on hind legs, holding a tiny microphone or a comedy spotlight shining on it). Keep the style lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor without being violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (2639, 'Animals, Comic Humor, Religious Humor, Unknown', 'A priest, a minister, and a rabbi want to see who''s best at his job, so they each go into the woods, find a bear, and attempt to convert it and report back. The priest said, ''When I found a bear, I read to him from the Catechism and sprinkled him with holy water. Next week is his first communion.'' ''I found a bear by the stream,'' said the minister, ''and preached God''s holy word. The bear was so mesmerized that he let me baptize him.'' They both look down at the rabbi, who was lying on a gurney in a body cast. ''Maybe I shouldn''t have started with the circumcision.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring three religious figures standing side by side in a sunny forest clearing. On the left, a cheerful priest dressed in traditional white and black robes holds a small bottle of holy water and a catechism book, with a friendly bear nearby wearing a small First Communion outfit. In the middle, a smiling minister in a simple suit and clerical collar stands next to a bear sitting calmly by a sparkling stream, with water splashed over its head showing it was recently baptized. On the right, a rabbi lies comically on a gurney wrapped in a full body cast, with a surprised look and some bandages too, suggesting he is recovering from an exaggeratedly humorous mishap. The background includes trees, a few birds, and a forest path to set the woods atmosphere. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish to enhance the joke''s lighthearted tone.'),
 (3229, 'Animals, Computers, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'What did the turkey say to the computer? Google, google.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly-looking cartoon turkey standing next to a desktop computer on a simple office desk. The turkey has a cheerful expression and appears to be speaking or making a sound. The computer screen shows an open web browser with the Google homepage visible. Around the scene, include playful sound effects written as ''Google, google'' in comic-style text bubbles coming from the turkey. The background is simple and bright to keep the focus on the turkey and the computer setup, emphasizing the pun between the turkey''s gobble (''gobble'') and the search engine ''Google.'' The style is colorful, lighthearted, and aimed for a fun cartoon vibe.'),
 (2631, 'Animals, Computers, Puns, Unknown', '640k = 4480k in dog bytes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused computer nerd sitting in front of an old-school computer with a black screen filled with green vintage text and numbers. Next to the computer, there is a cartoon dog wearing oversized glasses and typing on a tiny keyboard, with a big thought bubble above its head that says ''640k = 4480k in dog bytes.'' The room has typical geeky decorations like binary code posters, a coffee cup labeled ''Byte Me,'' and a calendar showing ''1980s.'' The computer screen humorously highlights the pun, and the dog looks both serious and playful, as if it’s computing seriously in its own dog language. The style is colorful and exaggerated, emphasizing the playful mix of computer jargon and dog humor without any violence or inappropriate content.'),
 (2727, 'Animals, Country Humor, Humor, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: How Come Your Dog Don''t Bite Nobody But Me?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a rustic country and western setting. In the foreground, a man with a cowboy hat, plaid shirt, and boots looks confused and slightly worried as a scruffy, playful dog stands on its hind legs, gently pawing at him. The dog has a goofy but friendly expression, clearly more interested in the man than attacking. Behind them is a simple wooden fence and a barn with a sign reading ''Country & Western Music Festival.'' On the fence, a poster humorously shows a fictional album with the title ''How Come Your Dog Don’t Bite Nobody But Me?'' The background features rolling hills, a few cacti, and a setting sun to evoke a late afternoon or early evening. The style is colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and lighthearted details like musical notes floating in the air to highlight the country music theme. No violence, just playful confusion and a funny misunderstanding.'),
 (80, 'Animals, Dad, Humor, Puns', 'If a clown farts, does it smell funny?', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a cheerful clown in a classic circus outfit: oversized shoes, bright red nose, big curly hair, and striped pants. The clown is standing on a simple circus ring with a red carpet circle beneath. The clown has a surprised yet amused expression, holding its nose while small comic-style odor lines (wavy lines) rise from its rear. Nearby, a small bunch of circus animals including a laughing seal, a giggling elephant, and a smiling monkey are reacting to the smell in a humorous, exaggerated way. The background is cheerful with balloons and circus tents lightly sketched. The overall style is lighthearted, playful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, resembling a colorful, kid-friendly cartoon.'),
 (81, 'Animals, Dad, Humor, Puns', 'Why don''t cannibals eat clowns? Because they taste funny.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a puzzled but friendly-looking cannibal sitting at a rustic wooden table in a jungle setting. On the table is a cartoon clown character, complete with colorful oversized shoes, a red nose, rainbow-colored wig, and bright makeup, looking surprised but unharmed. The cannibal holds a fork and knife hesitantly, sniffing or tasting a small bite from the clown''s shoe or hand with a confused expression. Nearby, a speech bubble above the cannibal reads, "They taste funny!" The background includes jungle foliage with vines and trees, and a bright sunny sky to keep the mood light and funny. The overall style is exaggerated and playful, with bold outlines and vibrant colors, capturing the pun visually without any scary or violent elements.'),
 (82, 'Animals, Dark Humor', 'My friends dog died the other day so I got her an identical one to make her feel better, although I''m not sure what she''s gonna do with two dead dogs', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing with a slightly confused or awkward expression, holding two identical dogs who are cartoonishly portrayed as clearly ''dead'' in a funny, non-offensive way (e.g., stiff limbs, X eyes, a small cloud above their heads indicating being lifeless, or little ''zzz'' symbols). The background is a simple domestic setting, like a living room with a couch and a picture of a happy dog on the wall. The person you see is trying to comfort a friend, who stands nearby looking surprised or bewildered at holding two identical lifeless dogs. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to enhance the comedic effect without anything dark or upsetting.'),
 (83, 'Animals, Dark Humor, Historical Humor', 'The sinking of the Titanic must have seemed like a miracle to the lobsters in the kitchen.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside the Titanic ship’s kitchen. In the foreground, a group of lively lobsters are inside a large kitchen pot, looking wide-eyed and surprised. Some lobsters wear little chef hats or have expressive faces showing relief and astonishment. Around them are typical kitchen items like pots, pans, and utensils scattered about. In the background, through a window, waves and the dark ocean are visible, with the Titanic tipping slightly to show it is sinking. The kitchen has a slightly chaotic atmosphere but in a lighthearted, funny way. The overall style is colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing the lobsters’ expressions as the focal point to highlight the joke’s punchline about their unlikely ''miracle'' escape from boiling in a sinking ship’s kitchen.'),
 (84, 'Animals, Did''ya Hear, Puns', 'Did''ya hear the one about the skeleton that couldn''t go to the party? He had no body to go with', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful skeleton standing outside a lively party. The skeleton is portrayed as a classic white bone figure with a friendly smile but looking slightly sad or disappointed as it stands alone. In the background, there''s a colorful party inside a warmly lit house with a welcome banner reading ''Party Time!'' Visible through partly open doors and windows are silhouettes of dancing figures and decorations like balloons and streamers. The skeleton holds a small party invitation card in one hand and scratches its skull with the other, emphasizing its loneliness. Around the skeleton’s feet lies a shadow that forms the shape of a human body silhouette, hinting at the joke''s pun. The scene should be bright, cartoonish, playful, and non-threatening, capturing a light-hearted and silly mood without any horror elements.'),
 (85, 'Animals, Did''ya Hear, Puns', 'Did''ya know alligators can grow up to 15 feet? Most only have 4 though.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a grassy swamp with a large, proud alligator smiling as it stands next to a giant 15-foot tall measuring stick. The alligator is clearly oversized and impressive. Nearby, four tiny alligators, each about the height of a small child, stand lined up next to the same measuring stick looking tiny and somewhat bewildered. The large alligator gestures towards the measuring stick while the little ones look up at it. The setting should be colorful and lighthearted, with some reeds, lily pads, and water in the background to express a swamp environment. The overall tone is playful and comical, emphasizing the joke''s pun on ''feet'' as both length and actual ''feet'' (toes) on alligators. The alligators’ feet could be exaggeratedly large or small to reinforce the humor without feeling threatening or scary.'),
 (86, 'Animals, Did''ya Hear, Puns, Space Humor', 'Did''ya hear that SpaceX launched several cows into orbit? It was the herd shot around the world.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in outer space showing several cows floating in zero gravity wearing tiny astronaut helmets. The cows look surprised and cheerful as they orbit around a small, stylized Earth visible in the background. One cow is holding a small flag that says ''SpaceX'' while another is happily mooing with stars twinkling around. The cows are arranged in a loose circular orbit path labeled ''The herd shot around the world.'' The backdrop features a few planets and a rocket ship with the SpaceX logo blasting off from Earth in the distance. The whole scene has a lighthearted, colorful, and playful cartoon style with exaggerated expressions on the cows to emphasize the joke.'),
 (3058, 'Animals, DIY Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'I’ve been teaching my dog to fetch tools for me. He’s not perfect yet, but he knows the drill.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly dog and its owner in a backyard workshop setting. The dog is a happy, medium-sized breed sitting proudly with a playful expression, holding an actual drill tool gently in its mouth. Nearby, the owner, a casual person wearing a tool belt and casual clothes, is smiling and giving the dog a thumbs-up. The background shows a toolbox, scattered tools like a hammer, wrench, and screwdriver on a wooden workbench, and a partially built birdhouse or small project to emphasize the DIY atmosphere. The scene should be bright, cheerful, and cartoonish with exaggerated, rounded features to emphasize humor and lightheartedness. Include a speech bubble above the owner with the phrase "He knows the drill!" for clarity and pun emphasis. Keep the colors vibrant and the overall style clean and playful, adaptable for a comic strip.'),
 (87, 'Animals, Don''t Say It!, Humor, Puns', 'Some people say giving animals helium is just wrong, but I say - Hey - whatever floats your goat', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small confused goat floating gently in the air, tied to a big helium balloon. The goat looks surprised but calm, with a simple light blue sky background and a few fluffy clouds. Below, a person with a playful grin holds the string of the balloon. The person is shrugging as if saying ''Hey - whatever floats your goat.'' The scene should be colorful, friendly, and light-hearted, emphasizing the pun visually without any negativity or harm to the goat. Balloons and the goat should be drawn with exaggerated cartoonish features to enhance the humor.'),
 (462, 'Animals, Dyslexics, Humor, Pirates, Pun', 'What does a Dyslexic Pirate Say? RRAAAAAAAAAAA!', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon pirate standing on a wooden ship deck with a large, billowing sail behind him. He has a traditional pirate hat with a skull and crossbones, an eye patch over one eye, and a scruffy beard. The pirate is shouting loudly, with an exaggerated open mouth and a speech bubble filled with long, wavy ''RRAAAAAAAAAAA!'' letters to emphasize the pirate''s iconic roar. Around him, seagulls fly in the sky, and the ocean waves are gently visible in the background. The style should be colorful and playful, with bold outlines and exaggerated facial expressions to give a humorous, light-hearted vibe. Avoid any threatening or scary features to keep the scene friendly and funny.'),
 (88, 'Animals, Dyslexics, Word Play', 'What do dyslexic zombies eat? Brians', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two zombies in a graveyard under a full moon. One zombie looks confused, scratching its head, while the other eagerly holds out a large, realistically drawn human brain as if about to eat it. A sign nearby reads ''Brain Buffet'' with letters slightly jumbled or wobbly to hint at dyslexia. The zombies have typical cartoonish zombie features: greenish skin, tattered clothes, and exaggerated expressions. The background includes tombstones and a spooky tree, but with a lighthearted and playful atmosphere rather than scary. The brain should look a bit comical and oversized to emphasize the joke, and the zombies should appear more silly than frightening. The style is colorful and cartoonish, with clear visual cues to dyslexia and zombies combined humorously without any violence.'),
 (2698, 'Animals, Everyday Life, Humor, Unknown', 'Cats sleep 16 hours a day. Humans sleep 8 hours a day. Who''s in charge?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side in a cozy living room. On the left, a large, fluffy cat is sprawled out sleeping on a cushy armchair, with a serene smile, eyes closed, and a small ''Zzz'' bubble above its head. On the right, a human figure (adult, casual clothing) is dozing off on a couch, half-covered with a blanket, also with eyes closed and a ''Zzz'' bubble but visibly tired and less peaceful. Between them, a simple clock on the wall shows the time, and above the scene is a playful question in a speech bubble or caption: "Cats sleep 16 hours a day. Humans sleep 8 hours a day. Who''s in charge?" The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between the cat''s confident comfort and the human''s sleepy demeanor, evoking mild envy or speculation. The background is minimal with a few homey details like a small side table with a coffee cup and a framed picture of a fish on the wall to hint at typical cat interests, enhancing the humor without overcrowding.'),
 (1247, 'Animals, Everyday Life, Knock Knock, Pun', 'KK/WT: Scold ? It''s cold outside - let me in!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, shivering character or animal (like a cute dog or a cartoonish kitten) standing outside a frosty window. The outside environment has falling snowflakes and visible breath clouds to emphasize the cold. The character is pressing its little paws or hands against the glass and looking inside with big, pleading eyes. Inside the window, a smiling person is seen, perhaps holding a cup of hot drink and wearing cozy clothes. There is a visible speech bubble from the character outside saying, "Scold? It''s cold outside – let me in!" with a playful tone. The window frame shows frost patterns to emphasize coldness, with a simple background of a snowy yard or street. The overall style is light, cute, and cartoonish, avoiding any violent or negative imagery.'),
 (1371, 'Animals, Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes', 'A bug in the hand is better than one as yet undetected.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, exaggerated hand held out in the foreground with a small, comically oversized bug resting on the palm. The bug should have a surprised or goofy expression. In the background, a second bug, smaller and sneaky-looking, hides behind a leaf or behind a person''s ear, trying to remain hidden. The setting is simple and brightly colored, with a subtle whimsical style emphasizing the contrast between the visible bug and the hidden one. The scene should play on the idea of ''a bug in the hand'' vs. an unseen bug, using playful character design and exaggerated expressions to bring out the joke without any scary or gross elements.'),
 (2986, 'Animals, Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown', 'I forgot how to throw a boomerang, but then it came back to me', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in an open park or backyard, looking puzzled and scratching their head while holding a boomerang in one hand. In the background, the boomerang is humorously flying through the air and about to land right back near the person, as if it ''came back to them.'' The person''s facial expression is a mix of confusion and mild surprise. The setting is bright and cheerful with green grass, a few trees, and a sunny sky. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the pun in the joke.'),
 (3086, 'Animals, Everyday Life, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'If it''s so great outside, why are all the bugs trying to get in my house?', 'Jim Gaffigan', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the exterior of a charming suburban house with a sunny, pleasant day outside. The sky is bright blue with a few fluffy clouds and birds flying. At the center, a front door is wide open, and a colorful crowd of various bugs (like ladybugs, bees, butterflies, ants, mosquitoes, and flies) is clamoring to get inside, some pushing small suitcases or bags. The bugs wear tiny sunglasses or sun hats, suggesting they don''t really want to be outside despite the nice weather. On the porch, a human figure (maybe confused or annoyed) looks at the scene with a raised eyebrow and a hand on their hip. Surrounding the house are green bushes and flowers to emphasize a nice outdoor environment. The style should be lighthearted, bright, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the bugs for comedic effect, reflecting the joke about bugs trying to escape the great outdoors by coming into the house.'),
 (89, 'Animals, Exaggeration, Facts, Sports Humor', 'Average life span of a major league baseball: 7 pitches.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a baseball stadium. Center the image around a sad, anthropomorphic baseball character with big, expressive eyes and a small frown. The baseball should have arms and legs, and be dramatically worn out with scuff marks, stitches coming loose, and sweat drops to show exhaustion. The baseball is standing near the pitcher''s mound, holding a small white flag as if surrendering. Around it, a scoreboard or sign displays the text ''Average life span: 7 pitches!'' In the background, a cheerful pitcher is winding up to throw another pitch, while teammates and fans look on with surprised or amused expressions. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and clearly cartoonish, exaggerating the baseball''s worn-out expression and the comical short life span it depicts. Avoid any aggressive or violent poses, focusing instead on the baseball’s tired, comedic personality.'),
 (90, 'Animals, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Some lions mate over 50 times a day.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an African savanna with a male lion looking astonished and overwhelmed, sitting on a large rock. Around him, several female lions are eagerly approaching or surrounding him, some with playful, expectant expressions. A cheeky speech bubble above the male lion reads, ''Some lions mate over 50 times a day!'' In the background, a comically tired lion nearby is lying flat on the ground with sweat drops and cartoon stars around his head, clearly exhausted. The sun shines brightly, highlighting the bustling nature of the scene. The art style is colorful, exaggerated, and light-hearted, emphasizing the humor of the lion''s predicament without any aggressive or sexual imagery.'),
 (2850, 'Animals, Eye Humor, Humor, Unknown', 'Eyes like a waitress - no peripheral vision.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a young man sitting at a restaurant table, looking confused and slightly annoyed. Nearby, a waitress with exaggeratedly large, forward-facing eyes—like binoculars—stands rigidly, staring straight ahead and completely oblivious to anything happening to her sides. The waitress''s face shows intense focus straight ahead, but her side views show blank spaces to emphasize her lack of peripheral vision. Around them, plates and menus are scattered on the table, and other customers and restaurant details can be blurred in the background to emphasize the joke. The style should be lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions and playful, simple lines to capture the punchline visually without any harshness.'),
 (91, 'Animals, Facts, Food Humor, Science', 'Mosquitoes are attrracted to people who have recently eaten bananas.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of playful mosquitoes eagerly flying toward a person who just finished eating a bunch of bananas. The person is standing in the center, happily holding a peeled banana with a big smile. Around the person, multiple tiny mosquitoes with exaggerated eager expressions and cartoonish big eyes are attracted, buzzing and hovering close, some wearing little noses sniffing the air. In the background, a confused person who hasn''t eaten bananas stands nearby, swatting mosquitoes away unsuccessfully. The setting is a simple outdoor park with green grass and a clear blue sky. To add to the humor, a small sign on the ground reads ''Banana Buffet: Beware!'' The overall style should be lighthearted, colorful, and funny without any dark or scary elements.'),
 (92, 'Animals, Facts, Fun Facts, Good Question!', 'Slugs have 4 noses', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful slug character in a simple garden setting (grass, a few flowers, maybe a small rock). The slug is facing the viewer with a friendly smile. On its head, prominently show four distinct, cute, and exaggerated noses arranged in a row, each with different shapes or sizes to stand out. Surround the slug with a few small insects or garden elements looking surprised or intrigued by the slug''s multiple noses. Use bright, playful colors and a lighthearted comic style, emphasizing the unusual and funny fact about the slug’s noses without any scary or unpleasant elements.'),
 (93, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!', 'A crocodile cannot stick out its tongue.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly-looking crocodile with its mouth wide open. The crocodile is sitting on a riverbank with bright green scales and a big, goofy smile. Emphasize that its tongue is completely inside its mouth and clearly not sticking out. Nearby, a puzzled frog or bird looks up at the crocodile in amazement or confusion. Include a sunny sky, some water reeds, and a small sign next to the crocodile that reads: ''Try sticking out your tongue!'' The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with the crocodile’s tongue noticeably hidden and the other animal reacting playfully to the fact that the crocodile cannot stick its tongue out.'),
 (94, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!', 'All polar bears are left handed.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of polar bears on an icy landscape. Each polar bear is playfully using its left paw for various activities, such as waving, holding a fish, or giving a thumbs-up with its left paw. One polar bear is looking confusedly at its right paw, as if trying to figure out what to do with it. The background includes icebergs and a light blue sky with a few clouds. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions on the bears to emphasize the joke. The scene is friendly and funny, avoiding anything violent or inappropriate.'),
 (95, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!', 'Fish cough.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a small fish underwater inside a brightly colored coral reef environment. The fish is mid-swim with wide, surprised eyes and is depicted with exaggerated cartoon-style bubbles coming out of its mouth that resemble a cough. Around the fish, other sea creatures like a crab, starfish, and a snail look on with curious or shocked expressions. Include light beams filtering from the water surface above to add depth. The style should be playful and whimsical, with vivid underwater colors like blues, greens, and coral reds. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the absurdity of a fish coughing underwater.'),
 (96, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!', 'Squids can have eyes the size of a volleyball.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a giant squid underwater with one enormous eye exaggeratedly the size of a volleyball. The squid should look friendly and a bit surprised or proud to show off its huge eye. Nearby, a scuba diver wearing classic diving gear looks amazed, with their mouth open and hands raised. Include some underwater elements like fish, seaweed, and bubbles to set the scene. The volleyball should be clearly sized compared to the squid’s eye for comic effect, perhaps with the squid holding it like a trophy or comparing the eye to a nearby actual volleyball floating underwater. The style should be playful, colorful, and light-hearted, focusing on the absurdity and fun of the squid''s huge eye size without any scary or dark elements.'),
 (97, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!', 'The catfish has over 27,000 taste buds.', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene showing an exaggerated catfish underwater, drawn with a big silly grin. The catfish should have oversized lips and whiskers, and its entire body is covered with little labeled taste buds. Around the catfish, small bubbles contain tiny flavor icons like a lemon slice, a chili pepper, a drop of honey, and a salt shaker to highlight its taste senses. The underwater background is simple with a few playful fish and water plants. Use bright, cheerful colors with a lighthearted cartoon style and include a quirky sign underwater that reads ''27,000 Taste Buds!'''),
 (98, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!', 'The world''s termites outweigh the world''s humans 10 to 1.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an enormous mound of termites on one side of a scale, clearly outweighing a group of small, cartoonish humans on the other side. The termites should be exaggerated in size for comedic effect, with little smiling or busy termite characters crawling over the mound. The humans look surprised or confused as they balance precariously on their scale side. The setting is simple, with the scale standing on a neutral background, emphasizing the size difference. Lighthearted, bright colors with clear, simple lines to evoke a playful cartoon style.'),
 (99, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!, Humor', 'A camel has 3 eyelids.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful camel standing in a sunny desert landscape with dunes and a bright blue sky. The camel, drawn with exaggerated large eyes, is winking to emphasize its unique feature. The camel''s three eyelids should be clearly visible and distinct — the top, middle, and bottom eyelids layered humorously with playful expressions on each eyelid, as if the middle eyelid is waving hello or making a funny face. Nearby, a curious desert explorer or a scientist wearing a safari hat holds a magnifying glass up to the camel’s eye, looking surprised or amazed. The style is colorful and lighthearted, with simple but expressive character designs. Include a small desert cactus and a few scattered rocks to add to the desert environment. The overall mood is playful and educational, highlighting the interesting fact about camels in a fun way.'),
 (100, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!, Humor', 'Cows kill more people than sharks every year. As a matter of fact - cows don''t kill ANY sharks!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two animals: a large friendly-looking cow standing on dry land, maybe a farm setting with a few tufts of grass and a simple wooden fence in the background; and nearby, a confused or surprised-looking shark half-submerged in a small pond or water trough beside the cow. The cow should appear calm and innocent, while the shark looks bewildered or shocked, as if it cannot believe it''s being compared to the cow. Add a lighthearted tone with exaggerated facial expressions (big eyes, raised eyebrows) to emphasize the joke. Include a simple caption or speech bubble from the cow saying something like ''I don''t kill any sharks!'' or from the shark, ''Wait, what?'' This cartoon should be colorful, playful, and not serious or scary, delivering the irony in a fun visual way.'),
 (101, 'Animals, Facts, Good Question!, Humor', 'Humans with two legs have an above average number of legs, compared to the entire population.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing various creatures standing together on a grassy field. In the center, a confident human character with two legs stands tall and proud, smiling broadly. Around the human, there are different animals and imaginary creatures with a variety of leg counts: a snake slithering with no legs, an insect with six legs, a crab with eight legs, a bird with two legs but wings visible, and a cartoon alien with multiple legs. Above the group, a simple caption or thought bubble reads: ''Humans with two legs have an above average number of legs!'' The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing surprise and curiosity on the faces of the animals as they look toward the human. The background is simple with a clear sky and a few clouds to keep focus on the characters. The overall tone is bright, colorful, and friendly.'),
 (102, 'Animals, Facts, History Humor', 'In the last 4000 years, no new animals have been domesticated.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an ancient timeline stretching left to right with a caveman on the far left trying to domesticate various wild animals like a mammoth and a saber-toothed tiger, looking hopeful. Moving right along the timeline, there are early civilizations with people attempting to domesticate animals such as wolves and wild cats, all failing or giving up. Finally, on the far right labeled ''Modern Day,'' a frustrated person in contemporary clothes is looking at a computer screen displaying a ''No new animals domesticated in 4000 years'' headline. Around them are familiar domesticated animals like dogs, cats, cows, horses, and chickens happily lounging. The tone is light and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions and clear indication that domestication attempts have stopped long ago. The background features a simple environment with trees, houses, and time markers indicating the passage of thousands of years. Overall, the cartoon style is colorful and playful with big eyes and round shapes for characters and animals to enhance humor.'),
 (103, 'Animals, Facts, Humor', 'A snail can sleep for three years.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, sleepy snail resting comfortably on a green leafy bed. The snail should look exaggeratedly relaxed, with half-closed eyes and a tiny nightcap on its head to emphasize sleepiness. Around the snail, place whimsical elements suggesting a long nap: a calendar showing three years with pages flying off, a clock with its hands spinning, and a dust-covered book titled ''Snail Sleeping Guide.'' The background should be a peaceful garden setting with soft colors and a gentle sunny sky indicating the passage of time. The all-around vibe is light and funny, emphasizing the snail''s extended sleep rather than anything threatening or serious.'),
 (104, 'Animals, Facts, Humor', 'If cats COULD text you back, they would not.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting on a couch holding a smartphone with a missive screen showing a blank message screen or a question typed out but no response yet. Nearby, a cat is perched lazily on the back of the couch, looking completely indifferent with half-closed eyes and a smug expression. The cat is ignoring the phone entirely, maybe playfully batting or sitting on a tangled phone charger or phone remote. The setting is a cozy living room with soft colors and playful details to highlight the cat''s aloof personality. The person looks expectant but puzzled or frustrated, while the cat embodies complete disinterest as if texting back is a ridiculous idea. The overall vibe should be lighthearted with exaggerated expressions on both characters to emphasize the humor of cats being notoriously unresponsive to humans'' attempts at communication.'),
 (105, 'Animals, Facts, Humor', 'Lizards communicate by doing pushups.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two lizards in a sunny desert setting with cacti and rocks. One lizard is lying on its belly, comically doing exaggerated pushups with small puffed cheeks of effort. The other lizard watches nearby with a cartoonish speech bubble showing simple symbols like ''Hi!'' and ''Hello!'' to suggest they''re trying to ''talk.'' The background is minimal but colorful, emphasizing the humor in lizards communicating through exercise movements rather than sound. Make the lizards cute and slightly anthropomorphic, with big expressive eyes to add charm and humor.'),
 (106, 'Animals, Facts, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Debra Winger was the voice of E.T.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused animation studio recording booth. Inside the booth is a microphone stand with a big microphone and headphones hanging nearby. A large poster of E.T., the famous alien from the movie, is on the wall behind the microphone. A female voice actress with short brown hair is nervously looking at a script titled ''E.T. Lines''. Outside the booth, two cartoon animators or sound engineers are whispering to each other, one holding a clipboard with a speech bubble showing the text ''Debra Winger was the voice of E.T.?'' The expressions on their faces are puzzled and surprised. The studio is filled with typical soundproofing panels, a mixing board with knobs and sliders, and a few sci-fi props like a small glowing alien figurine on the desk. The overall style is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the mismatch of the famous Hollywood actress Debra Winger with the iconic voice of a beloved alien character.'),
 (107, 'Animals, Facts, Humor, Science', 'A snail breathes through it''s foot.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, colorful snail with a comically exaggerated foot, like a big, fleshy shoe or sock with visible nostrils on the sole, inhaling deeply through it. The snail''s face is cheerful with big, expressive eyes and a wide smile, clearly enjoying the air intake through its foot. The background is a simple garden setting with green grass, a few flowers, and maybe a small mushroom for context. Nearby, a curious insect or small animal, like a ladybug or worm, looks up at the snail with a puzzled or surprised expression. The overall style is playful and cartoonish, using bright colors and bold outlines to emphasize the humor and absurdity of a snail breathing through its foot.'),
 (108, 'Animals, Facts, Humor, Word Play', 'A chicken is a means for one egg to produce another.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful chicken standing proudly in the center of a farmyard. The chicken has an exaggerated, smug expression, maybe wearing glasses or a tiny graduation cap to suggest intelligence. Around the chicken, two large eggs are depicted with friendly faces, one on each side. Between the eggs, a simple, playful arrow or dotted line connects one egg to the chicken and then another arrow leads from the chicken to the second egg, illustrating the joke that the chicken acts as a means for one egg to produce another. The background is a bright and colorful barnyard setting with a wooden fence, a few tufts of grass, and maybe a sunrise to set a joyful tone. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bold outlines and expressive characters to clearly convey humor without text or speech bubbles.'),
 (109, 'Animals, Facts, Sports Humor', 'It takes 3,000 cows to supply the NFL with enough leather for a year''s supply of footballs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a huge group of cows in a green field stretching far into the background. In the foreground, one cow is looking confused or surprised, perhaps scratching its head. Nearby, a large conveyor belt is transporting a pile of footballs labeled ''NFL Footballs.'' A factory building in the background has giant football logos and leather hides hanging on racks visible through windows. The sky is bright and sunny. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon styles and smiling cows, emphasizing the connection between cows and football manufacturing without showing anything distressing or violent.'),
 (1347, 'Animals, Fantasy Humor, Programmers, Word Play', 'What do you call 8 hobbits? A hobbyte', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring eight small hobbit characters standing closely together, all smiling and looking cheerful. Each hobbit is dressed in typical hobbit attire: simple medieval clothes, curly hair, and big hairy feet. They form a tight circle as if posing for a group photo. Above or beside them is a cartoon-style text bubble or sign that reads ''Hobbyte''. The background is a whimsical, green, pastoral setting reminiscent of the Shire with rolling hills, a few mushrooms, and a small round door in a hill in the distance. The overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the pun on ''hobbit'' and ''byte'' (implying a playful computer-related word). No technology needs to be shown explicitly, just the group of hobbits to reflect the ''byte'' pun with a subtle computer feel through the grouping count of eight, which is important in digital bytes.'),
 (1231, 'Animals, Farmers Humor, Jobs, Pun', 'I spent one summer as a kid working on a rabbit farm - that was a hare raising experience!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set on a sunny, cheerful rabbit farm during summer. The foreground shows a young kid wearing a straw hat and overalls, looking both surprised and slightly overwhelmed while holding a handful of carrots. Around the kid are several lively rabbits hopping around excitedly, some with exaggerated, comical expressions like wide eyes and big smiles. One rabbit might be mid-leap with its ears flapping dramatically as if ‘raising’ the hair on the kid’s head. The background features wooden rabbit hutches, green grass, a bright blue sky with a shining sun, and a simple wooden sign reading ''Rabbit Farm''. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun with the kid’s slightly frazzled hair standing up humorously as rabbits cause chaos nearby, capturing the ‘hare raising’ (hair raising) feeling in a playful way.'),
 (3032, 'Animals, Farmers Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I replaced my rooster with a duck - now I wake up at the quack of dawn', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a small farm at early dawn. In the foreground, a cheerful duck wearing a tiny farmer''s hat stands proudly on a wooden fence post instead of a rooster. The duck is animatedly quacking, with a comic speech bubble showing ''Quack!'' Above or near the duck, the sky is painted with soft pastel colors indicating sunrise. Nearby, a sleepy human character in pajamas stands rubbing their eyes, holding a coffee mug, looking tired yet amused by the duck''s replacement. Around them, typical farm elements like a red barn in the background, some hay bales, and a traditional rooster coop now empty are visible. The overall style should be bright and cartoony, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and whimsy. The scene should avoid any violence or complex political references, focusing purely on the silly idea of waking up to a duck''s quack instead of a rooster''s crow.'),
 (110, 'Animals, Farmers Humor, Puns', 'What happened to the cow that jumped over the barbed wire fence? Udder destruction.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a startled cow mid-jump over a rusty barbed wire fence. The cow has wide, expressive eyes and exaggerated motion lines to emphasize the jump. Its udder is visibly stretched or exaggerated to highlight the pun. Below or next to the fence, the ground is slightly disturbed to suggest impact or ''destruction.'' The background is a simple farm setting with a few tufts of grass and a blue sky with fluffy clouds. The overall tone is light-hearted, colorful, and comical, focusing on the pun ''udder destruction'' without any injury shown. The cow appears more surprised than hurt, emphasizing the joke rather than any real harm.'),
 (3031, 'Animals, Farmers Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'I replaced my rooster with a duck - now I wake up at the quack of dawn', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a small farm at early dawn. In the foreground, a proud person with a sleepy but amused expression stands outside a cozy wooden farmhouse, holding a small tired pillow. Nearby, instead of a rooster on a classic wooden fence post, there''s a cheerful duck making the ''quack'' sound with a cartoon speech bubble that says ''Quack!''. The sky shows the sun just starting to rise with soft pink and orange hues. In the background, a traditional rooster looks confused and a bit sad, standing off to the side. Include some hay, a few farm tools leaning against the house, and a peaceful countryside with a few trees. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated in a lighthearted cartoon manner emphasizing the comedic contrast between the rooster and the duck wake-up calls.'),
 (111, 'Animals, Farming Humor, Puns', 'Studies show that cows produce more milk when the farmer talks to them. It''s a case of in one ear and out the udder.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a sunny farm in a green field with a red barn in the background. In the foreground, a friendly farmer, smiling and wearing overalls and a wide-brimmed hat, is leaning forward talking enthusiastically to a group of cows. The cows look happy and attentive, some with slight smiles. One cow in the center has oversized, exaggerated udders shaking slightly to emphasize milk production. To add humor, a speech bubble from the farmer says something like ''Good girl, keep it up!'' Above the scene, include a playful pun caption: ''In one ear and out the udder.'' The style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated features for both humans and cows to maximize the joke''s lightheartedness. No violent or inappropriate imagery, just a happy farm scene focused on the cows and the talking farmer.'),
 (576, 'Animals, Food Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What did the gingerbread man put on his bed to keep warm at night? A cookie sheet', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a gingerbread man tucked into bed inside a cozy bedroom. The gingerbread man looks happy and snug under a large silver cookie sheet, used as a blanket. The bed should be simple and inviting, with a pillow and a mattress. Nearby, a nightstand holds a glass of milk and a small plate with a half-eaten cookie, emphasizing the cookie theme. The walls can be decorated with cookie cutter shapes framed like pictures, and a window shows a starry night sky. Overall, the style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated, rounded features to enhance the cartoonish vibe.'),
 (582, 'Animals, Food Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What do you get from a pampered cow? Spoiled milk.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a well-groomed, pampered cow standing proudly on a small red carpet in a barn setting. The cow wears a pink bow on its head, shiny hooves with nail polish, and a pearl necklace. Nearby, a silver tray holds a fancy glass bottle of milk labeled ''Spoiled Milk'' with a small crown or tiara on top of the bottle, emphasizing its ''pampered'' status. The background includes typical barn elements like a wooden fence, hay bales, and a milk pail, but adds a luxurious touch with a velvet rope barrier around the cow. The cow poses with a smug, content expression, as if being treated like royalty, creating a playfully absurd yet lighthearted atmosphere.'),
 (596, 'Animals, Food Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What kind of bagel can fly? A plain bagel', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, anthropomorphic plain bagel with tiny, colorful wings attached to its sides. The bagel should be happily flying in the sky above a simple cityscape or park. Surround the bagel with small, whimsical clouds and maybe a few birds looking confused or surprised at the flying bagel. The bagel''s expression should be playful and proud. Keep the art style lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright, inviting colors to emphasize the joke''s silliness.'),
 (604, 'Animals, Food Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What''s orange and sounds like a parrot?   A carrot!', NULL, 'A colorful and humorous cartoon scene featuring a bright orange carrot standing upright like a person. The carrot has a friendly face with big eyes and a wide smile, and it''s enthusiastically squawking like a parrot with an open beak. Nearby, a parrot with similar bright orange feathers is perched on a branch, looking surprised or confused as it listens to the carrot. The background is a simple garden or kitchen table setting, with a few vegetables and a leafy plant to reinforce the carrot''s identity. The style is playful and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s pun on how the carrot ''sounds like a parrot.'' The overall scene radiates fun and whimsy, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon.'),
 (586, 'Animals, Food Humor, Good Question!, Puns', 'What does a grape say when it''s stepped on? Nothing - it just lets out a little wine', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a purple grape character on the ground with a surprised, slightly pained facial expression as a large shoe steps on it gently. The grape is personified with big, innocent eyes, a small mouth slightly open as if about to say something but remaining silent. From the grape, show a little whimsical ''wine'' droplet rising upward, shaped like a tiny speech bubble or musical note to highlight the pun. Around them, keep the background simple, like a kitchen floor or picnic blanket, to avoid distractions. The shoe should look exaggeratedly large and cartoonish to emphasize the stepping action without being threatening. Use bright colors and friendly, lighthearted drawing style to make the scene funny and cute rather than realistic or harsh.'),
 (773, 'Animals, Food Humor, Halloween, Pun', 'What does a skeleton order at a restaurant? Spare ribs', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cozy restaurant. At the center, a cheerful skeleton is sitting on a chair at a table with a menu open in front of it. The skeleton is animated with expressive eye sockets and a wide, playful grin, clearly ready to order. On the menu front cover, the words ''Today''s Specials'' are visible. Across from the skeleton, a friendly waiter with an apron and notepad is ready to take the order, looking slightly amused. The table has typical restaurant items like a napkin holder, a candle, and a glass of water. On the wall behind them, a framed picture of ribs hangs as a subtle pun reference. The overall atmosphere is light-hearted and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the joke about the skeleton ordering ''spare ribs.'' The scene should feel warm and inviting, with no dark or scary elements.'),
 (3231, 'Animals, Food Humor, Holiday Humor, Thanksgiving', 'What do you call a turkey the day after Thanksgiving? Lucky!', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon turkey looking bright-eyed and happy stands in the middle of a kitchen or dining room the day after Thanksgiving. Surrounding the turkey are empty plates and a few leftovers like cranberry sauce bowls, mashed potato dishes, and a partially eaten pumpkin pie. The turkey is wearing a simple pilgrim-style hat, adding to the Thanksgiving theme. The scene uses warm, autumn colors and includes a calendar on the wall prominently showing the day after Thanksgiving. The turkey has a big smile and possibly a small speech bubble above its head that says, "Lucky!" to highlight the punchline. The overall style is lighthearted and humorous with exaggerated expressions and cute, rounded cartoon features to emphasize the turkey’s ''luck'' in surviving the feast.'),
 (112, 'Animals, Food Humor, Humor', 'Ole''s bull was not getting the job done with the female cows so he asked the vet for some medicine. A few weeks later: Sven: ''how''s that bull doing?'' Ole: ''he''s back to his old frisky self, getting the job done!'' Sven: ''What fantastic medicine did the vet prescribe him?'' Ole: ''I don''t know, but it tastes like licorice!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene on a sunny day at a farm. In the foreground, Ole, a friendly-looking farmer wearing denim overalls and a straw hat, is chatting with Sven, another farmer dressed similarly but with a simple flat cap. Between them, a large, muscular bull stands proudly, looking energetic and lively with a happy, confident expression. Nearby, several content female cows graze lazily in a green pasture dotted with flowers. Ole holds a small medicine bottle labeled with a bright red cross, and a few black licorice candies scattered on a small wooden fence post next to the bottle hint at the medicine''s peculiar flavor. In the background, a sturdy red barn and a vet''s truck parked nearby give context to the scene. Both Ole and Sven are smiling and engaged in conversation, emphasizing the comedic punchline without any aggressive or suggestive behavior. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated cartoon expressions to enhance the humor.'),
 (1315, 'Animals, Food Humor, Pirates, Pun', 'Where did the one-legged pirate go for breakfast? IHOP!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a one-legged pirate standing happily outside an IHOP restaurant. The pirate has a classic look with a pirate hat, eye patch, and a brightly colored parrot on his shoulder. He stands confidently on one leg, with a peg leg clearly visible on the other side. The IHOP restaurant in the background has a large, playful sign with blue and red letters reading ''IHOP'' and pancakes shown on a menu board outside. Include a few tables outside with freshly stacked pancakes, butter, and syrup to emphasize breakfast. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the joke’s playful tone.'),
 (3224, 'Animals, Food Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'How does a turkey travel? He rides the gravy train!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful cartoon turkey riding a train made entirely out of gravy. The train cars should look like brown gravy boats connected, steaming slightly. The turkey is sitting proudly in the front car, holding a ticket and wearing a conductor''s hat tilted jauntily. The background is a simple countryside with a few autumn leaves falling and a signpost that says ''Gravy Train Express.'' The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated with big eyes on the turkey and a playful expression to emphasize the pun.'),
 (3230, 'Animals, Food Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'What do you call a running turkey? Fast food.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene centered on a turkey depicted in mid-run across a simple grassy field. The turkey should have exaggerated running features like flapping wings, flying feathers, and sweat drops to emphasize its speed and effort. Nearby, a fast food restaurant sign is visible with a classic red and yellow color scheme, featuring a whimsical turkey image instead of a regular burger or chicken. The turkey looks slightly panicked or determined, adding to the comic effect. The background is light and cheerful with a sunny sky and a few fluffy clouds to keep the tone lighthearted and fun.'),
 (3236, 'Animals, Food Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'What''s a turkey''s favorite dessert? Peach gobbler!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a farm with a large, colorful turkey standing upright with a big, happy grin. The turkey is holding a dessert plate with a slice of peach cobbler topped with whipped cream. Next to the turkey is a sign that says ''Peach Gobbler Special!'' in playful letters. The background shows a sunny sky, a wooden fence, some peach trees with ripe peaches hanging, and a barn in the distance. The turkey looks excited and is wearing a chef''s hat to emphasize its ''favorite dessert.'' Include bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated, expressive features on the turkey to enhance the cartoonish humor.'),
 (2772, 'Animals, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Do jellyfish get gas from eating jellybeans?', NULL, 'A colorful, cartoon underwater scene featuring a large, friendly-looking jellyfish with a surprised and slightly uncomfortable expression. The jellyfish is surrounded by floating jellybeans of various bright colors and shapes. Some jellybeans are hovering near its tentacles as if just eaten. Small cartoon air bubbles shaped like little gas clouds rise from the jellyfish''s body, adding to the humorous idea of it getting ''gas.'' The background shows a whimsical ocean floor with smiling fish and coral in playful shapes, enhancing the lighthearted, humorous mood of the drawing.'),
 (3034, 'Animals, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I saw a bird eating some avocado toast. I think it was a millennial falcon.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a bird perched on a park bench or café table. The bird should look like a playful falcon but with a casual, millennial vibe—perhaps wearing hipster glasses or tiny earbuds. In front of the bird is a plate with a neatly arranged slice of avocado toast, complete with recognizable green avocado slices and maybe a sprinkle of seeds. The setting should be light and casual, maybe with a city café backdrop showing a few potted plants and a simple coffee cup on the table. The bird appears to be cheerfully pecking at the avocado toast. The overall art style is colorful, cartoonish, and playful to emphasize the pun and the absurdity of a falcon eating avocado toast as if it’s a trendy millennial. Avoid any harsh lines or overly dramatic expressions to keep it light and funny.'),
 (113, 'Animals, Food Humor, Puns', 'What''s the difference between deer nuts and beer nuts? Beer nuts are $1.49 and deer nuts are under a buck.', NULL, 'A colorful and humorous cartoon scene split into two halves side-by-side. On the left side, depict a cheerful deer standing casually in a forest clearing, with a small pile of cartoonish acorns or nuts labeled ''Deer Nuts'' on the ground next to it. A small price tag attached to the nuts clearly shows ''Under $1''. The deer should have a humorous smile, giving a playful vibe. On the right side, show a bright, eye-catching grocery store shelf stocked with a can or bowl of classic crunchy peanuts labeled ''Beer Nuts,'' with a clear price tag showing ''$1.49''. The scene should emphasize the contrast between the natural setting and the grocery store aisle, with clear and exaggerated price tags to highlight the pun. Keep the art style light, simple, and cartoonish, with friendly characters and bold text for the labels and prices. No people are required, just the deer and the grocery item as main subjects.'),
 (3240, 'Animals, Food Humor, Puns, Thanksgiving', 'Why did the sweet potato pie cross the road? It saw a fork up ahead.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a sweet potato pie with a cute, slightly nervous face and little stick-figure legs crossing a road. The road should be a simple two-lane street with a visible center line. Ahead of the pie, on the roadside or in the middle of the road, show a large, shiny fork standing upright as if it were an obstacle or something the pie is wary of. The scene should emphasize the pie''s wary or startled expression looking toward the fork. Add a simple sunny sky or daytime background with minimal details to keep focus on the pie and fork. Use bright, cheerful colors and a playful cartoon style to keep the tone light and funny.'),
 (3107, 'Animals, Food Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'Why do you always hear about French people eating snails? They don''t like fast food.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful snail wearing a tiny beret and a striped French scarf, slowly crawling on a plate. The plate sits on a bistro-style table with a checkered red-and-white tablecloth. Next to the plate is a small bottle of wine and a baguette partially visible. In the background, a French cafe setting is suggested with a little outdoor table, a window with flower boxes, and a sign with a small French flag. Above the scene, a speech bubble or a humorous caption reads, ''They don''t like fast food.'' The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated features on the snail to emphasize its slowness and French identity, capturing the pun in a friendly and inviting cartoon format.'),
 (3250, 'Animals, Food Humor, Puns, What do you call...', 'What do you call a cow with a twitch? Beef Jerky', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a cow standing in a grassy field with a surprised expression. The cow’s eye should be wide open, and one of its legs or the whole body is twitching or shaking visibly with little motion lines around it. Nearby, there should be a signpost or a speech bubble with the words "Beef Jerky" in a playful font. The background should be simple with a blue sky and a few clouds to keep focus on the cow. Make it colorful and lighthearted, emphasizing the surprise of the twitching cow, with no scary or violent elements.'),
 (2688, 'Animals, Fun Facts, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Butterflies taste with their feet', NULL, 'A colorful, cheerful cartoon scene featuring a large, whimsical butterfly perched on a vibrant flower in a sunny meadow. The butterfly has exaggerated, comical eyes looking down at its feet, which are humorously touching the petals of the flower as if ''tasting'' them. Around the butterfly, playful little taste buds or sparkles can be drawn on its feet to emphasize the tasting action. The background includes other flowers, buzzing bees, and a bright blue sky with a smiling sun. The style should be light-hearted, simple, and cartoonish with bright colors to create a fun and educational vibe.'),
 (114, 'Animals, Good Question!', 'Snails can sleep for 3 years without eating', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a snail comfortably asleep inside a tiny, cozy snail shell bed. The snail is wearing a cute sleeping cap and has a peaceful smile. Around the snail, there is a calendar on the wall with pages flying off rapidly, indicating the passage of several years. Beside the snail’s bed, a small alarm clock shows a huge time gap with years marked. There is no food nearby, emphasizing the joke about not eating. The background can be a simple garden with a few leaves and grass blades to set the outdoor scene. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated features to highlight the snail’s unusual long sleep habit.'),
 (115, 'Animals, Good Question!', 'Starfish haven''t got brains.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a starfish lying flat on a sandy ocean floor looking confused with wide, googly eyes. It''s surrounded by coral, shells, and small fish that are swimming around it, some shaking their heads or looking amused. Above the starfish, a little thought bubble shows a tiny empty brain outline or a question mark to emphasize the joke about it having no brain. The style should be light-hearted and colorful with exaggerated expressions to add humor, avoiding any aggression or negativity.'),
 (116, 'Animals, Good Question!, History Humor', 'In ancient Egypt, priests plucked EVERY hair from their bodies, including their eyebrows and eyelashes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in ancient Egypt, showcasing two Egyptian priests standing outside a large stone temple adorned with hieroglyphics and pyramids in the background. The priests are completely hairless from head to toe: no hair on their scalp, eyebrows, eyelashes, or body. One priest is humorously holding an ancient, oversized feather duster and a few tiny eyebrow tweezers, looking proud while examining his smooth, bald skin. The other priest squints humorously, trying to blink without eyelashes, with a slight exaggerated expression. Nearby, a basket filled with plucked hairs piled up high adds to the comic effect. The sky is bright blue with a blazing sun to emphasize the idea of hairless skin under the hot desert sun. The style should be lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated, with bold outlines and facial expressions emphasizing the absurdity of being entirely hairless, especially the missing eyelashes and eyebrows which are usually subtle. The scene should avoid anything scary or unpleasant, focusing on the funny, odd historical fact in a playful way.'),
 (117, 'Animals, Good Question!, Humor', 'How do you lift an elephant with one hand? You can''t, because elephants don''t have any hands.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing next to a very large elephant. The person is looking perplexed and holding up one hand as if trying to figure out how to lift the elephant. The elephant should be very large, with an expression of calm confusion, and clearly have only four legs and a trunk—no hands. Around them, add a few humorous details like a speech bubble above the person reading, ''How do you lift an elephant with one hand?'' and a thought bubble from the elephant saying, ''I don''t have any hands!'' The background should be simple, maybe a savannah or plain park setting, to keep the focus on the interaction. The style should be exaggerated and cartoony, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s silliness.'),
 (118, 'Animals, Good Question!, Humor', 'If cats and dogs didn''t have fur would we still pet them?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting on a couch looking puzzled and curious. In front of them are a cat and a dog, both completely hairless and looking slightly surprised or confused. The cat is sleek and wrinkled like a Sphynx breed with large ears, while the dog is similarly hairless, showing smooth skin with visible playful expressions. The person’s hand is hesitantly reaching out mid-air as if unsure whether to pet them or not. Around the room are small humorous details like a scratching post and a dog toy nearby. The setting is a cozy living room with warm colors to add lightheartedness. Perhaps a thought bubble above the person’s head with a question mark or the words “Would we still pet them?” to emphasize the joke’s core question.'),
 (119, 'Animals, Good Question!, Humor', 'If your not the lead sled dog, the scenery never changes...', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a team of sled dogs harnessed together, pulling a sled across a snowy landscape. At the front is the lead sled dog, looking proud and happy, facing forward and clearly enjoying the view of the changing scenery—a mix of snowy mountains, trees, and a rising sun. Behind the lead dog are the other sled dogs, looking bored, tired, or annoyed, because they see only the backs of the dogs in front and the same unchanging white snow and sled runners. The background should emphasize the contrast between the exciting view for the lead dog and the monotonous, unchanging view seen by the other dogs. Include details like fur hats or scarves on the dogs for extra humor, and make the dogs expressive with big eyes and exaggerated facial expressions. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, highlighting the joke about perspective and effort in a playful, family-friendly manner.'),
 (120, 'Animals, Good Question!, Humor', 'The average human eats eight spiders in their lifetime at night. (In this case I HOPE I am not average!)', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a person sleeping peacefully in bed at night, with a worried expression and wide-open eyes as if just having a nightmare. Above the bed, a humorous thought bubble shows eight tiny cartoon spiders sneaking toward the person, each spider comically tiptoeing with exaggerated sneaky poses. The bedroom is cozy and simple, with a lamp on a nightstand and a window showing a dark night sky with stars. The overall style is lighthearted and humorous, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the funny fear of eating spiders unknowingly during sleep.'),
 (121, 'Animals, Good Question!, Humor', 'The longest recorded flight of a chicken is thirteen seconds.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a surprised chicken mid-air, flapping its wings wildly as it makes a shaky flight lasting exactly thirteen seconds. Draw a cartoon stopwatch or clock in the corner showing thirteen seconds to emphasize the flight duration. The background should be a simple farmyard with a wooden fence, green grass, and a red barn in the distance. Add a small group of chickens watching with amazed or curious expressions. Include a lighthearted banner or scoreboard above that says “Longest Chicken Flight: 13 Seconds.” The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and playful to accentuate the joke''s absurdity without any harsh or scary elements.'),
 (632, 'Animals, Good Question!, Humor, Puns', 'Why do gorillas have big nostrils? Because they have big fingers.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly-looking gorilla in a jungle setting. The gorilla is the central character, shown from the chest up, with exaggeratedly large nostrils on its nose. The gorilla is using oversized, thick fingers to pick its nose in an exaggerated and silly manner. Around the gorilla, add lush green jungle foliage, trees, and some bananas hanging nearby to set the environment. The gorilla''s facial expression should be playful and goofy, emphasizing the joke''s punchline in a lighthearted way. The overall style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish to highlight the humor without being scary or gross.'),
 (614, 'Animals, Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'When it rains, why don''t sheep shrink?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of fluffy sheep standing outside under a gentle rain shower. The sheep are comically large and fluffy, with exaggerated wool that looks thick and puffy rather than soaked or shrunken. Raindrops are clearly falling around them, some hitting the wool, but the wool remains perfectly unchanged. The sheep have cheerful or puzzled expressions as if they are aware of the question but confidently unfazed. The background shows a simple green field with a few tufts of grass and a cloudy sky with visible raindrops. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the softness and volume of their wool to illustrate why they don''t shrink when wet. No darker or negative elements, just a playful and bright cartoon atmosphere.'),
 (578, 'Animals, Good Question!, Pun', 'What do prisoners use to call each other? Cell phones.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cheerful prison common area. Show two prisoners in orange jumpsuits standing a few feet apart, each holding an oversized, old-fashioned mobile phone with large antennae. Both are smiling and happily talking to each other. Around them, simple prison elements like barred windows, a clock on the wall, and a table with a deck of cards should be visible to indicate the setting without looking grim. The overall art style is light, colorful, and cartoonish to keep the mood playful and non-threatening.'),
 (585, 'Animals, Good Question!, Pun', 'What do you say if a porcupine gives you a kiss?  Ouch!', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene featuring two characters: a porcupine and a person. The porcupine, drawn with exaggeratedly long and sharp quills sticking everywhere, is leaning forward to give the person a kiss on the cheek. The person looks surprised and has a comic expression of shock and slight pain, with their eyes wide and mouth open saying ''Ouch!''. Tiny little stars or cartoon pain symbols appear around the cheek where the quills touch. The background is simple and light-colored to keep focus on the interaction. Both characters should be drawn in a bright, colorful, and playful cartoon style with rounded edges and expressive faces for a humorous effect.'),
 (605, 'Animals, Good Question!, Pun', 'What''s orange and sounds like a parrot? A carrot', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bright orange carrot standing upright on a wooden table. The carrot has a comically exaggerated mouth wide open as if it is squawking or mimicking a parrot''s call. Nearby, a colorful parrot sits on a small perch, looking confused or surprised at the carrot. The background is simple and cheerful, with light pastel colors and perhaps a few playful sound wave lines emitting from both the carrot and the parrot to emphasize the idea of sound. The carrot should have small cartoonish eyes and a leafy green top to clearly identify it as a carrot. The parrot should be typical with vibrant feathers in blue, green, and red. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful.'),
 (619, 'Animals, Good Question!, Pun', 'Where does the three legged horse live? In the unstable', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a horse with three legs standing clumsily on a wobbly wooden table labeled ''Unstable.'' The horse looks slightly off-balance, with a surprised or confused expression. Around the table, a simple rustic farmyard setting is visible, with a stable in the background. The table should be visibly shaky or rocking, with motion lines emphasizing instability. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and rounded shapes to emphasize the cartoon humor.'),
 (587, 'Animals, Good Question!, Pun, Space Humor', 'What does a turkey in space sound like?   Hubble, hubble, hubble.', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon scene set in outer space with a cheerful turkey wearing a simple, classic astronaut helmet floating among colorful stars and planets. The turkey is gently flapping its wings, with a goofy, happy expression as if it''s trying to make a sound. Around the turkey, comic-style text bubbles show the phrase ''Hubble, hubble, hubble.'' In the background, a famous telescope resembling the Hubble Space Telescope is visible, floating nearby to connect the pun visually. The overall style is bright, whimsical, and cartoonish with exaggerated features and friendly colors to emphasize humor and space adventure without any complexity or intensity.'),
 (627, 'Animals, Good Question!, Pun, Supernatural Humor', 'Why did the chicken go to the séance? To get to the other side', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a slightly nervous chicken standing in front of a round, glowing séance table draped with a purple cloth. Around the table, a quirky group of cartoon ghostly spirits float, looking curious and friendly. On the table lies a classic Ouija board with a planchette, and a crystal ball emitting a soft glow. The background is a dimly lit room with flickering candles and a crescent moon visible through a window. The chicken faces the séance table, appearing eager yet unsure, with a speech bubble above it saying, ''To get to the other side.'' The overall style is light-hearted and whimsical, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke''s pun about the chicken crossing over both physically and spiritually.'),
 (622, 'Animals, Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'Why are skeletons so calm? Because nothing gets under their skin.', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon scene featuring a relaxed skeleton sitting cross-legged on a comfy armchair, smiling serenely. The skeleton should look peaceful and unbothered, with its empty eye sockets conveying calmness. Around the skeleton, show a few small, harmless irritant objects like a tiny bug, a little pin, and a small thorn hovering or trying to poke, but clearly unable to penetrate since there is no flesh. The background is simple, maybe a cozy living room with a lamp and a potted plant, to emphasize the calm environment. Use bright colors and soft lines to keep the mood light and humorous, making sure the overall style is playful and cartoonish rather than spooky or scary. Include a subtle speech bubble or caption near the skeleton that says, "Nothing gets under my skin," reinforcing the joke visually.'),
 (122, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns', 'Did''ya hear about the chameleon that couldn''t change color? He had a reptile dysfunction', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a frustrated chameleon sitting on a leafy tree branch. The chameleon looks confused and sad, with wide eyes and drooping posture. Surrounding it are bright leaves and colorful flowers, but the chameleon is a dull, unchanging gray color, clearly standing out. Nearby, another chameleon character (happy and colorful) looks on sympathetically or puzzled. Include a small, humorous sign hanging from the branch that reads ''Reptile Dysfunction Clinic.'' The style should be lighthearted and whimsical, with rounded shapes and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke without any harshness. The background is a simple jungle environment with vibrant greens and a clear sky. The overall tone is playful and silly, capturing the humor of the chameleon’s unfortunate condition in a cartoon style.'),
 (123, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns', 'Have you ever seen a toad on a toadstool?', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a small, cute toad sitting comfortably on top of a large, classic red-and-white spotted toadstool mushroom. The toad looks slightly surprised or puzzled, with big, wide eyes, as if caught in an unexpected situation. Around them is a whimsical forest floor with green grass, small flowers, and other smaller mushrooms. The lighting is bright and cheerful, emphasizing the playful and lighthearted mood of the joke. The style is simple and exaggerated, with bold outlines and vibrant colors. The focus is on the toad perched on the toadstool, clearly showing the pun visually.'),
 (124, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns', 'If a pig can''t squeal, does that mean it''s disgruntled?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with a confused pig standing in a typical farmyard setting, looking sideways with a puzzled expression. The pig should have a small speech bubble containing a question mark or a little scribble to show confusion. Around the pig, include a classic red barn and some hay bales, with a few farm animals like a chicken or a cow looking curiously at the pig. Make sure the pig looks normal but silent—no open mouth, indicating it can''t squeal. Emphasize a light-hearted, playful style with bright colors and round shapes to keep the tone very friendly and funny. Include a small signpost near the pig that says ''Disgruntled?'' as a visual pun to reinforce the joke''s wordplay. The whole scene should look like a single panel comic strip with a clean and simple background to keep focus on the pig and the pun.'),
 (625, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns', 'Why can''t you hear a pterodactyl going to the bathroom? Because the ''P'' is silent', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a prehistoric environment with a comical pterodactyl. The pterodactyl looks slightly embarrassed or sneaky, perched on a rock or tree branch in a sparse, rocky landscape with ferns and volcanoes in the background. Nearby, a cartoon speech bubble or small sign reads ''Shh... the P is silent!'' To visually emphasize the pun, the letter ''P'' is large and clearly visible but drawn as transparent or ghostlike, while the word ''terodactyl'' is bold and colorful. There is a subtle bathroom element, like a small dinosaur footprint or stylized water splash near the dinosaur, keeping everything light and silly without showing anything explicit. The art style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and big expressive eyes on the pterodactyl to enhance the joke’s fun and innocent vibe.'),
 (629, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns', 'Why do cows wear bells? Because their horns don''t work!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a sunny farm field with green grass and a blue sky. In the foreground, a friendly, chubby cow stands smiling. The cow wears a large, shiny brass bell hanging from a colorful leather collar around its neck. Nearby, the cow''s two horns are humorously depicted with tiny, old-fashioned telephone handsets attached to them, with little ''zzz'' or silence lines indicating they aren''t working. In the background, there are a few other cows casually grazing, some with bells and some without. The overall style is cheerful, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the joke about the horns not working, blending cute farm imagery with the playful pun.'),
 (125, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns, Science', 'Do radioactive cats have 18 half-lives?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky laboratory with a whiteboard covered in scientific formulas and a big chart titled ''Radioactive Half-Lives.'' In the center, a comically exaggerated cat with bright green glowing stripes and a slightly frazzled, surprised expression sits on a lab table. The cat is surrounded by test tubes, Geiger counters with happily clicking needles, and a scientist wearing oversized glasses, holding a calculator and scratching their head in confusion. Nearby, a large poster on the wall humorously illustrates the concept of half-life using slices of cheesecakes gradually disappearing. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors emphasizing the cartoon style and making the radioactive theme fun rather than scary. No dark or serious elements are included.'),
 (618, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns, Travel Humor', 'Where do sharks go on vacation? Finland', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene showing a group of sharks enjoying a tropical vacation but with a twist: instead of a sunny beach, they are relaxing in a snowy Nordic setting. The scene features several sharks wearing vacation accessories like sunglasses and Hawaiian shirts, lounging on deck chairs on snow-covered ground. In the background, there are simple pine trees with snow on branches, and a first-class airplane labeled ''Finland Airlines'' landing nearby. One shark is holding a hot drink (like coffee or hot chocolate) with a small Finnish flag stuck in it, while another shark skis down a gentle slope wearing a scarf. The sky is blue with a few fluffy clouds, and there’s a big wooden sign that says ''Welcome to Finland'' with an image of a smiling Viking helmet, adding to the vacation vibe. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the pun on ''Finland'' sounding like ''fin land,'' humorously connecting sharks and their fins with the northern country.'),
 (590, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns, Vehicles', 'What has 4 wheels and flies? A garbage truck', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a big garbage truck on a city street. The truck is clearly labeled ''Garbage Truck'' on its side and has four large wheels. Around and above the truck, animated flies buzz in exaggerated cartoon style, with big eyes and small wings. The flies are comically large compared to normal flies to emphasize the joke. The background includes simple buildings, a sidewalk, and a trash bin nearby. A smiling character, maybe a bystander or a kid, looks at the truck with an amused expression, pointing at the flies. The overall style is light-hearted and playful with bright colors and clean lines.'),
 (126, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns, Word Play', 'Can one bird make a pun? No, but toucan', NULL, 'A colorful, cheerful cartoon scene featuring two birds perched on a tree branch. One bird is a toucan with its large, distinctive beak, looking proud and playful. The other bird is smaller and more ordinary-looking, perhaps a simple sparrow, looking confused or unimpressed. Above them is a speech bubble from the smaller bird asking, ''Can one bird make a pun?'' and the toucan answering with a big smile, ''No, but toucan!'' The background is a sunny blue sky with fluffy clouds and green leaves, drawn with bright, bold colors to emphasize the lighthearted and humorous tone. The style should be whimsical and exaggerated, like a simple cartoon or comic strip, making it clear the joke revolves around the pun on ''toucan'' and ''two can.'''),
 (635, 'Animals, Good Question!, Puns, Word Play', 'Why do seagulls live near the sea? Because if they lived near the bay they''d be bagels.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful seaside setting. On the left side, show a group of happy seagulls standing or flying near a beach with the ocean visible in the background. The seagulls should look typical—white and gray with yellow beaks—but with friendly, exaggerated cartoon eyes to enhance the humor. On the right side, depict a group of anthropomorphic bagels with seagull-like features, such as small wings and beak-shaped noses, standing near a calm bay with docks or boats in the background. The bagels should be round with sesame seeds on top, smiling and looking playful. Above the scene, include a simple caption or a speech bubble that says, “Why do seagulls live near the sea? Because if they lived near the bay they''d be bagels.” The overall art style should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun through the visual contrast between the two groups near their respective bodies of water, evoking a clever and silly mood without any elements that are violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (775, 'Animals, Halloween, Humor, Puns', 'What is a mummy''s favorite kind of music? Wrap music', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful mummy standing on a small stage with a microphone. The mummy is wrapped in traditional white bandages with a few loose ends playfully fluttering. Around the mummy, there are musical notes floating in the air to indicate music is playing. Behind it, a classic boombox or turntable labeled ''Wrap Music'' is playing tunes. The background is a simple party setting with colorful streamers and balloons. The mummy is striking a fun pose, appearing as if it’s enjoying or performing music, with a big smile or wink. Add a small audience of amused cartoon ancient Egyptian figures (like a Pharaoh or a Sphinx) clapping or bobbing their heads. The overall mood should be lighthearted and silly to emphasize the pun on ''wrap'' and ''rap'' music.'),
 (793, 'Animals, Halloween, Humor, Puns', 'Why don''t zombies eat clowns? They taste funny.', NULL, 'A colorful and humorous cartoon scene featuring a zombie standing in front of a circus tent. The zombie is greenish with typical zombie features: tattered clothes, missing an eye, exposed bones, and drooling. It holds a partially eaten clown shoe in one hand, looking confused and disgusted. Nearby, a cheerful clown with exaggerated facial makeup, a big red nose, polka-dot costume, and oversized shoes waves happily while holding a plate of brightly colored clown donuts. The background shows a bright circus environment with balloons and circus banners. The zombie''s speech bubble says, ''Yuck! They taste funny!'' making the pun clear. The overall tone should be lighthearted, colorful, and comical, with exaggerated expressions on both characters to highlight the joke’s pun on ''funny taste.'' No gore, just silly.'),
 (769, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'What do mummies invest in? Cryptocurrency.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic mummy character wrapped in white bandages, sitting at a small desk covered in papers and a laptop screen showing colorful cryptocurrency charts. The mummy looks excited and slightly confused, with one bandaged finger pointing at the laptop. Around the desk are scattered coins and digital symbols like Bitcoin and Ethereum logos floating above. The background is a dimly lit ancient tomb with hieroglyphics on the walls and a small glowing sarcophagus nearby. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions and clear, playful details to emphasize the contrast between ancient and modern technology.'),
 (770, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'What do vampires get in the winter? Frost bite.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a vampire standing outside on a snowy winter day. The vampire looks slightly shivering with a comical expression of surprise and mild discomfort. His cape is wrapped tightly around him, and tiny visible frost or icicles are forming on his pointed teeth and fingertips. Snow gently falls around him, and there are snowy trees and a pale winter sky in the background. The vampire''s pale skin contrasts with the cold environment, emphasizing the joke about ''frost bite.'' Include a small speech bubble or sign next to him with the words ''Frost bite!'' in playful, bold letters. The overall style should be lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, avoiding any scary or dark elements, focusing instead on the funny visual pun.'),
 (776, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'What is the ghost''s favorite desert? I scream', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly, cute ghost hovering above a colorful ice cream cone. The ghost should look happy and excited, with wide eyes and a big smile. The ice cream cone is towering with multiple scoops in bright colors like pink, green, and brown. The background is simple and cheerful, maybe with a sunny sky and a few fluffy clouds. The ghost could be pointing at the ice cream or about to take a lick, emphasizing the pun between ''I scream'' and ''ice cream''. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, suitable for a family-friendly comic strip or children’s book illustration.'),
 (777, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'What is the zombie''s favorite type of bean? A human bean', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly-looking zombie with green skin, tattered clothes, and a goofy smile, standing in front of a giant can labeled ''Human Beans''. The zombie is holding a single giant bean shaped unmistakably like a tiny human figure with arms and legs. Around the zombie, there is a playful kitchen setting with a stove, pots, and a table where other strange beans (like kidney beans and black beans with smiley faces) are scattered. The background is bright and colorful with whimsical details like a recipe book titled ''Zombie Cuisine'' open nearby. The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the pun by clearly illustrating the ''human bean'' as a bean shaped like a little person, enjoyed by this cute zombie character.'),
 (779, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'What type of muffins do ghosts like? Boo-berry', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly ghost floating happily in a kitchen. The ghost should be semi-transparent white with big, playful eyes and a wide smile. In front of the ghost, place a plate or tray filled with muffins labeled "Boo-berry Muffins." The muffins should look plump and delicious, with subtle, ghost-shaped faces or little ghost icons imprinted on them, emphasizing the pun. Include a kitchen counter with a few baking tools like a rolling pin, mixing bowl, and oven mitts in the background to set the scene. The overall mood should be lighthearted and silly, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor of the pun "Boo-berry." Avoid any scary or dark elements to keep it fun and inviting.'),
 (780, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'Where do ghosts go on vacation? To the Boo-hamas', NULL, 'A colorful humorous cartoon scene showing a sunny tropical beach labeled ''Boo-hamas.'' The scene features cheerful ghost characters wearing sunglasses, sun hats, and Hawaiian shirts. Some ghosts are lounging on beach chairs with tropical drinks, while others play beach volleyball or build sandcastles shaped like haunted houses. Palm trees sway gently, and a tiki bar serves ghost-shaped cocktails. In the background, a ghostly cruise ship or airplane with a friendly ghost captain arrives to drop off vacationers. The overall vibe is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing a spooky but fun beach vacation spot named ''Boo-hamas.'''),
 (784, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'Why are skeletons always calm? Because nothing can get under their skin.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly skeleton standing calmly with a relaxed smile, arms crossed or hands behind its back. The skeleton should be fully visible, showing its bones clearly and no skin at all, emphasizing its bony structure. Around the skeleton, include small comedic elements like a tiny bug or an arrow trying and failing to ''get under'' the skeleton''s bones, bouncing off or floating nearby harmlessly. The background is simple, maybe a light pastel color or an empty room to keep focus on the skeleton. Make the style playful and lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions for humor rather than anything spooky or scary.'),
 (785, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun', 'Why can vampires be easily tricked? Because they are suckers.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic vampire character standing in a spooky but lighthearted setting, with a cartoonish expression of confusion or surprise. The vampire should have exaggerated fangs and a flowing cape. Nearby, a mischievous character (a human or animal) is holding a large cartoonish sucker lollipop, playfully offering it to the vampire. The background can include gothic elements like a full moon, bats, and a creepy castle silhouette, but keep the atmosphere fun and silly rather than scary. The vampire''s eyes should be focused on the sucker lollipop with a silly, bewildered look, emphasizing the pun that vampires are ''suckers.'' Use bright, vibrant colors and simple, exaggerated shapes for a playful cartoon style.'),
 (767, 'Animals, Halloween, Pun, Word Play', 'What did the vampire say about his true love? It was love at first bite', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly vampire character with classic traits: pale skin, pointy ears, small fangs showing in a smile, and a black cape with a red inner lining. The vampire is standing in a romantic setting under a full moon and a starry sky. He is gazing lovingly at a heart-shaped object that looks like a juicy red apple but with a small bite taken out of it. The vampire’s expression is dreamy and slightly goofy, starring wide-eyed with a slight blush on his cheeks. Around him, little red hearts float in the air to emphasize the theme of love. The background can include a silhouette of an old gothic castle on a hill, with a few bats flying around to add vampire ambiance but keep it light and friendly rather than spooky. The overall tone should be playful and whimsical, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon style.'),
 (765, 'Animals, Halloween, Puns', 'What brand of underwear do mummies wear? Fruit of the tomb.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a mummy standing proudly in an ancient Egyptian tomb. The mummy is wrapped in typical white bandages but is wearing colorful, modern-style boxer shorts or briefs decorated with a fruit pattern (bananas, apples, grapes, etc.). The mummy should have a cheerful or cheeky expression, possibly giving a thumbs-up or posing confidently. The tomb setting includes hieroglyphics on the walls, stone sarcophagi, and an ancient Egyptian lamp or torch for atmosphere. Add a small basket or crate filled with assorted fruit placed near the mummy to emphasize the pun on ''Fruit of the Loom.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, with bright colors and exaggerated features to enhance the cartoon humor without any scary elements.'),
 (774, 'Animals, Halloween, Puns', 'What game do little ghosts like to play? Hide & shriek.', NULL, 'A cheerful, cartoon-style scene set in a haunted house or spooky graveyard with a playful vibe. Depict three or four small, cute, translucent white ghosts with big, round eyes and friendly smiles. They appear to be having fun playing a game similar to hide-and-seek. One ghost is peeking out from behind a tombstone or a large creaky old door, while another ghost is hiding behind a floating sheet of a curtain or a tree branch. A third ghost is covering its mouth with a ghostly hand, as if trying to stay quiet. Include a playful speech bubble above one ghost that says “Hide & shriek!” in fun, bubbly letters. The background features exaggerated spooky elements like crooked trees, friendly-looking bats hanging upside down, and a glowing full moon, all drawn in a lighthearted, humorous cartoon style to emphasize fun rather than fear or creepiness. Bright, pastel colors should be used to keep the mood funny and inviting rather than dark or scary. The overall tone is whimsical and silly, capturing the pun in the joke visually.'),
 (782, 'Animals, Halloween, Puns', 'Where do vampires keep their money? At a blood bank.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a vampire wearing a classic black cape with a popped collar, smiling slyly as he stands next to a traditional bank building. The bank facade should have a large red sign above the door that says ''Blood Bank'' with stylized dripping blood details. To add to the humor, depict the vampire holding a large clear money bag filled with red-colored coins or bills with little blood drops on them. Around the vampire, include a few stereotypical vampire elements such as fangs, a pale complexion, and subtle bats flying in the background. The scene should have bright, cheerful colors and a lighthearted, comical style. Avoid any scary or dark elements, keeping the mood playful and fun.'),
 (786, 'Animals, Halloween, Puns', 'Why did the skeleton start a fight? He had a bone to pick.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a goofy, friendly-looking skeleton standing upright in a slightly exaggerated pose as if ready to argue or start a quarrel. The skeleton should be smiling mischievously with a raised eyebrow. The key visual pun is that the skeleton is literally holding a large, comically oversized femur bone in one hand, as if it''s about to ''pick a fight'' with the bone itself. Surround the skeleton with a simple background like a plain room or a park to keep focus on the character and the bone. The style should be lighthearted, colorful, and playful with exaggerated cartoon proportions to emphasize the joke. Include no violence or aggression in the expression or poses to keep the tone funny and silly.'),
 (783, 'Animals, Halloween, Word Play', 'Where do zombies live? On the dead end street', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a stereotypical suburban street sign that says ''Dead End Street.'' The street looks quiet and slightly spooky with a few cracked, dead trees and scattered autumn leaves. Along the street, a group of loosely drawn, funny cartoon zombies (greenish skin, tattered clothes, slightly goofy expressions) casually hang out—some leaning on the street sign, others sitting on the curb or wandering around. The zombies look more silly than scary and have exaggerated, goofy features. The background shows a row of cartoon houses with slightly neglected yards to add to the ''dead end'' vibe. The overall setting is bright but with a slightly eerie atmosphere, emphasizing the pun. The style is playful, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with no gore or horror elements.'),
 (127, 'Animals, History Humor, Word Play', 'What do Atilla the Hun and Winnie the Pooh have in common?  Their middle name!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, a caricature of Atilla the Hun is shown — wearing a traditional Hun warrior helmet with horns, fur clothing, and holding a small battle axe. He looks puzzled as he holds a name tag or scroll that says ''Atilla H. Hun.'' On the right side, Winnie the Pooh is standing, looking similarly puzzled and holding a honey pot labeled ''Pooh H. Bear.'' Both characters have exaggerated confused expressions, glancing at each other''s name tags or scrolls to emphasize the joke about their shared middle name initial ''H.'' The background is lighthearted with bright colors and simple shapes to keep it playful, and a big question mark floats above both characters to highlight the joke''s theme. No violence or intimidating features, just goofy and friendly cartoon vibes.'),
 (128, 'Animals, Humor', 'Impeccable: the ability to avoid being bitten by chickens.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a nervous person standing in the middle of a small farmyard filled with chickens. The person is wearing bright clothes and has wide eyes, leaning back slightly with arms raised defensively to avoid the flapping wings and snapping beaks of several angry chickens lunging towards them. The chickens look comically aggressive with exaggerated expressions, some mid-bite or peck, while one chicken is actually in mid-air as if about to attack. In the background, there is a rustic wooden fence, a small barn, and some scattered eggs on the ground. Above the person’s head is a comic-style thought bubble that says “Impeccable: the ability to avoid being bitten by chickens.” The overall style is colorful and lighthearted with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the humor of avoiding chicken bites like a special skill.'),
 (129, 'Animals, Humor', 'PUPKUS (pup kus'') n. The moist residue left on a window after a dog presses it''s nose to it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a cheerful dog pressing its nose firmly against a glass window from the outside. The window shows a clear, exaggerated wet nose print shaped like a heart or paw on the glass. Inside, a person looks amused or puzzled, pointing at the funny nose mark. The setting is a bright, sunny day with simple background details like a house exterior and a few flowers near the window. The style is colorful and playful, capturing the silly and endearing moment of a dog leaving a moist smudge on the glass.'),
 (130, 'Animals, Humor, Life', 'Never wrestle with a pig: You both get all dirty, and the pig likes it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a muddy farmyard scene with a person and a pig both covered in mud. The person is sprawled on the ground looking frustrated and dirty, wearing casual clothes now splattered with mud. The pig, in contrast, looks quite happy and content, smiling with mud dripping from its snout and body. Around them, tufts of grass and a wooden fence frame the background. The person and pig are mid-wrestle stance, with the pig clearly enjoying the mess while the person is annoyed. The style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the contrast between the pig''s enjoyment and the person''s displeasure.'),
 (131, 'Animals, Humor, Life', 'No one can feel as helpless as the owner of a sick goldfish.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a worried person sitting at a small table next to a goldfish bowl. The person looks distressed, with exaggerated worried eyebrows and hands gripping their cheeks. The goldfish inside the bowl appears slightly droopy or sad, with tiny cartoonish sweat drops and a thermometer stuck in the water. Around the scene, include typical home details like a couch, a small plant, and a clock on the wall to create a cozy living room vibe. The overall style is bright and friendly with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the helplessness and seriousness the person feels over something seemingly minor like a small sick goldfish.'),
 (1490, 'Animals, Humor, Life, Quotes', 'Accept that some days you''re the pigeon, and some days you''re the statue.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused cartoon pigeon and a stone statue on a city square. The pigeon looks slightly annoyed or resigned, standing beside or on the base of a detailed but exaggerated human statue with an unamused expression. The statue is static, with a few pigeons perched on it, including the annoyed pigeon from the scene. The background shows a simple urban park or plaza setting with trees, a bench, or lamp posts to suggest a lively but ordinary day. Use bright, cheerful colors and slightly exaggerated character features to maintain a lighthearted, comical feel. The pigeon’s body language should express the joke’s message of sometimes being active and carefree (the pigeon), and sometimes being stuck or ignored (the statue). No violence or negativity; the focus is on humorous acceptance of life''s ups and downs.'),
 (132, 'Animals, Humor, Nature Humor', 'When opossums are playing ''possum, they are not ''playing.''  They actually pass out from sheer terror.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two opossums in a forest setting. One opossum is standing upright with wide, scared eyes and sweat drops flying off its head to indicate terror. The other opossum is lying on the ground with eyes closed, limp body, and tongue sticking out slightly, mimicking ''playing possum'' (pretending to be dead). Include a few trees, bushes, and maybe an annoyed squirrel or bird watching the scene, looking confused or unimpressed. Use exaggerated facial expressions for humor and make the overall tone lighthearted and playful. Bright colors and simple cartoon style recommended to emphasize the comedic effect of the opossums'' misunderstanding of “playing possum.” Avoid any violent or dark elements.'),
 (1910, 'Animals, Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'If you pick up a starving dog and make him prosperous, he will not bite you. This is the principal difference between a dog and a man.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two main figures: a happy, well-fed dog and a smug-looking man. The dog is sitting comfortably with a shiny collar and a full food bowl beside him, wagging its tail and looking grateful. Nearby stands a man with crossed arms, wearing business casual clothes, looking less friendly with a slightly annoyed or scheming expression. Around them are subtle visual cues: the dog''s food bowl labeled ''Prosperity'' and the man standing just out of reach of the dog’s mouth, highlighting the joke that the dog won''t bite because it’s well cared for while the man might. The background is simple, perhaps an outdoor yard with a fence, keeping focus on the dog and man. The overall style is light, cartoonish, and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the loyal dog and the ungrateful man without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2010, 'Animals, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'It''s not the size of the dog in the fight, it''s the size of the fight in the dog.', 'Mark Twain (1835-1910)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a small, scrappy dog (like a little terrier) standing defiantly on its hind legs with a fierce, determined expression. The tiny dog should look tough and ready to fight, perhaps growling or showing its teeth. Nearby, include a large, relaxed dog (such as a big but gentle-looking mastiff or Saint Bernard) sitting calmly with a puzzled or amused expression, maybe slightly confused by the little dog''s attitude. The background should be simple, like a sunny park or a backyard, with some grass and a few bones or dog toys scattered around to add a playful touch. Emphasize the contrast between the small dog’s fierce attitude and the big dog’s calm demeanor to capture the joke’s meaning visually.'),
 (133, 'Animals, Humor, Relatable', 'What if the dog only brings the ball back because he thinks I like throwing it?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in a park holding a tennis ball, with a dog sitting nearby looking slightly puzzled. The dog has a thought bubble that shows the dog thinking about the human happily throwing the ball, but with a question mark, as if wondering whether the human actually enjoys the game. The person looks excited and ready to throw the ball again. Include trees, a bench, and a frisbee on the grass to give a playful outdoor vibe. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the dog''s curiosity and the human''s joy.'),
 (134, 'Animals, Humor, Science', 'Ironic isn''t it, that the tortoise has a drag factor of 0.03.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a tortoise slowly crawling along a racetrack. The tortoise looks calm and slightly smug, wearing oversized sporty sunglasses. Above the track is a caption or scoreboard showing ''Drag Factor: 0.03'' in bold, playful lettering. The racetrack should visually emphasize speed with aerodynamic lines and a finish line in the distance, contrasting with the tortoise''s slow, steady pace. Nearby, a sleek racing car or motorcycle zooms past, leaving exaggerated motion lines and faint dust clouds, highlighting the irony of the tortoise''s very low drag value despite its slow speed. The background is bright and simple with a few clouds and a sun smiling down, adding to the lighthearted, cartoonish style. Overall, the style should be colorful, cartoony, and non-violent, highlighting the funny contradiction between drag factor (a physics term related to speed) and the tortoise''s famously slow movement.'),
 (135, 'Animals, Humor, Science', 'It has just been discovered that research causes cancer in rats.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a scientific research laboratory. In the center, a slightly confused cartoon rat wearing tiny glasses and a lab coat stands next to a large, old-fashioned microscope. Around the rat are various scientific equipment like test tubes, beakers bubbling with colorful liquids, and charts on the wall showing graphs and mouse silhouettes. The rat is holding a clipboard and looking curiously at a sign on the wall that reads, ''Research Causes Cancer.'' Other lab rats peek out from behind equipment, some looking worried, others bemused. The room has a lighthearted, playful vibe with exaggerated expressions on the rats to emphasize the joke''s irony that research itself is causing cancer in rats, not the usual expectation that research is trying to prevent disease. The style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, suitable for a family-friendly humorous panel.'),
 (136, 'Animals, Humor, Science', 'The fingerprints of koala bears are virtually indistinguishable from those of humans, so much so that they could be confused at a crime scene.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a detective''s crime lab. In the foreground, a confused detective dressed in classic detective attire (trench coat, magnifying glass in hand) is examining a fingerprint on a glass slide under a microscope. On the lab table next to him, there is a sleepy, cute koala bear wearing tiny reading glasses and holding a magnifying glass as if trying to solve a mystery itself. The background shows a typical forensic wall with fingerprint charts pinned up and a whiteboard labeled ''CASE: Koala or Human?''. The koala should look innocent and slightly puzzled. The overall mood is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated expressions on the detective and koala to emphasize the surprising similarity of their fingerprints. The style should be bright with clear cartoonish lines and comical facial features to highlight the joke without any realistic or dark elements.'),
 (137, 'Animals, Humor, Science', 'When a male fish is ready to spawn, it blows bubbles.', NULL, 'A colorful underwater cartoon scene featuring a cheerful male fish puffing out a big bubble from its mouth. The fish should have exaggerated, expressive eyes looking proud and maybe a little shy. Around the fish, include smaller bubbles rising upwards to emphasize the blowing action. Add some seaweed, coral, and a couple of curious smaller fish watching the bubble-blowing fish in amusement or surprise. Keep the style lighthearted and humorous, with bright colors and rounded shapes, capturing a friendly ocean environment without any threatening or scary elements.'),
 (3040, 'Animals, Humor, Science Fiction Humor, Unknown', 'I suggest a new strategy, R2. Let the Wookiee win.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a spaceship''s control room, inspired by a sci-fi universe. In the foreground, a small humanoid robot with a dome-shaped head and mechanical features (like R2-D2) is communicating with a tall, furry giant creature resembling a Wookiee. The Wookiee looks intimidating but is smiling slyly, as if about to win a game or contest. The robot appears nervous or hesitant, possibly raising a mechanical arm in a giving-up gesture. Between them is a board game or gaming device with simple recognizable elements like dice or tokens. The background includes typical spaceship control panels with blinking lights and buttons. The overall atmosphere is lighthearted and playful, conveying a moment of comic surrender. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and friendly, with emphasis on character expressions to highlight the comic tone.'),
 (2699, 'Animals, Humor, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Cats urine glows under a black light.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room at night. In the center, a mischievous-looking cat with a sly grin is trekking across the floor, leaving a glowing trail behind it. The trail is bright neon green to mimic the effect of urine glowing under a black light. Nearby, a person holding a flashlight is shining a purple black light over the floor with a surprised and slightly horrified expression, eyes wide open. The room has typical home elements like a couch, a houseplant, and a cat toy scattered around. The glowing trail humorously contrasts with the otherwise normal-looking room, emphasizing the unexpected glow. The art style is colorful and exaggerated to bring out the joke’s playful and absurd vibe, with cartoonish expressions and light effects highlighting the glowing urine trail behind the cat. No violent or disturbing images included.'),
 (138, 'Animals, Humor, Theme Park Jokes', 'Please wait until your Dumbo has come to a complete stop before disembarking.  Overheard at Disneyland', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, whimsical cartoon scene set in Disneyland. In the foreground, show a family waiting to disembark from a Dumbo ride vehicle, which is an elephant-shaped ride car. The Dumbo should be mid-air but clearly stationary, with its ears spread wide and a big friendly smile. The family members are smiling and holding onto the ride bar, looking ready but patiently waiting. In the background, include other Dumbo ride vehicles hovering gently in the sky above the circus-themed ride, bright and cheerful with vibrant reds, blues, and yellows. The setting has classic Disney amusement park elements like decorative banners, spotted tents, and happy guests walking around. Include a whimsical sign near the ride that reads, "Please wait until your Dumbo has come to a complete stop before disembarking," styled like an official ride instruction but with a slightly funny tone. The overall art style should be playful and cartoonish, emphasizing the lightheartedness of the scene without any overcrowding or complicated details, suitable for a family-friendly amusement park atmosphere.'),
 (2697, 'Animals, Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Cats have over one hundred vocal sounds, dogs only have about 10.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cat and a dog in a living room. The cat is perched on the back of a couch, proudly opening its mouth wide, with multiple colorful speech bubbles around it containing various cartoon-style sounds such as ''Meow!'', ''Purr!'', ''Hiss!'', ''Chirp!'', and ''Mrrrow!''. The dog sits on the floor looking up at the cat with a confused, slightly overwhelmed expression, with only a few simple speech bubbles around it saying ''Woof!'', ''Bark!'', and ''Growl!''. The background includes a cozy living room setting with a carpet, a small side table with a plant, a window with curtains, and a food bowl labeled ''Cat Food'' and another labeled ''Dog Food''. The overall style is bright and exaggerated to emphasize the difference in vocal variety between the cat and dog, capturing a lighthearted and funny moment without any harm.'),
 (2781, 'Animals, Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Dogs come when you call. Cats have answering machines.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing outside their house calling out. To the left, a happy, eager dog runs towards the person with a big smile and wagging tail, clearly excited to answer the call. To the right, a cool, aloof cat sits comfortably near a vintage-style answering machine with a blinking light, smirking casually. The answering machine displays a small speech bubble with a message icon, suggesting the cat is ignoring the caller and relying on the machine instead. The background shows a bright sunny day with a suburban house, simple lawn, and a tree. The style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on the animals to emphasize the joke''s contrast between the dog’s enthusiasm and the cat’s aloof independence.'),
 (139, 'Animals, Humor, Word Play', 'It''s possible to lead a cow upstairs...but not downstairs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a frustrated farmer standing at the top of a staircase inside a rustic farmhouse. The farmer, wearing overalls and a straw hat, is gently trying to guide a large, bewildered cow onto the stairs going up. The staircase is narrow with a simple wooden banister. The cow''s hooves are awkwardly positioned halfway up the stairs, looking confused. Below the stairs is a sign that says ''Downstairs? No way!'' with a little arrow pointing down. The overall scene is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the cow''s clumsiness with stairs. Background elements include a farmhouse kitchen visible through a doorway, with rustic farming tools hung on the wall. The art style is cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on both the farmer and the cow to highlight the humor in the impossibility of leading the cow down the stairs.'),
 (140, 'Animals, Humor, Word Play', 'My dog ate a bag of Scrabble tiles. Took him to the vet. No word yet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a veterinarian''s office. In the foreground, a worried owner stands next to an anxious-looking dog sitting on the exam table. The dog looks slightly sheepish with a few Scrabble tiles stuck out of its mouth. Scattered on the floor near the table are colorful Scrabble tiles with letters clearly visible. The vet, wearing a white coat and stethoscope, bends over the table reviewing a clipboard with a puzzled expression. A wall clock shows time passing to emphasize the ''waiting'' element of the joke. The background includes typical vet office details like animal posters, a scale, and a small reception desk to create a comforting yet professional atmosphere. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to capture the humor and confusion from the situation. No violence or negativity—just whimsical and funny.'),
 (141, 'Animals, Humor, Word Play', 'Researchers for the Massachusetts Turnpike recently found 200 dead crows and there was an immediate concern about Avian Flu. A pathologist examined the crows and found the cause of death to be vehicular impacts. They then determined that 98% of the vehicles were trucks, and only 2% were cars. They then hired an Ornithological Behaviorist to determine the cause of that disproportionate percentage, and he quickly determined the cause. When crows eat road kill, they always have a look-out crow in a nearby tree to warn of danger. They discovered that while all the lookout crows could shout ''Cah!'', not a single one could shout ''Truck!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene near a busy highway depicting several cartoon crows. Most crows are gathered around a roadkill animal on the side of the road, pecking away. One crow is perched high up in a tree nearby acting as a lookout. This lookout crow has its beak open, as if shouting, with a speech bubble that says ''Cah!'' Numerous vehicles—mostly large trucks and a few small cars—are passing by on the road. The trucks look intimidating and large, while the cars are smaller and more nimble. Some crows are shown startled or reacting to the trucks but not the cars. The overall tone is light and funny, with exaggerated expressions on the crows. Include a highway sign that says ''Massachusetts Turnpike'' to set the location. The scene is colorful and playful, emphasizing the irony that the crows only recognize the sound "Cah!" (mimicking cars) and not "Truck!" as a warning, leading to the disproportionate number of crow-truck collisions.'),
 (142, 'Animals, Humor, Word Play', 'Take time to smell the roses and eventually you''ll inhale a bee.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene set in a sunny garden filled with blooming roses. In the foreground, a cheerful person is bending down with their nose very close to a bright red rose, enjoying the scent. Nearby, a comically large bee with wide eyes and little motion lines is zooming right toward the person''s nose. The person''s eyes are slightly wide, indicating surprise or imminent reaction. Surrounding elements include other flowers, a clear blue sky, and a few playful buzzing bees to emphasize the garden atmosphere. The overall tone is lighthearted and humorous, with exaggerated expressions and playful design to highlight the unexpected moment of inhaling a bee while smelling the flowers.'),
 (143, 'Animals, Humor, Word Play', 'What do you get when you cross a polar bear with a seal? A polar bear.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a snowy Arctic landscape under a bright, clear sky. In the center, a large polar bear is standing looking confused or puzzled. Next to it, a cute, smiling seal is lying on the ice. Between them, a comically simple ''crossed'' sign—a big plus symbol or an ''X''—is drawn, suggesting a mashup. The caption below reads: ''What do you get when you cross a polar bear with a seal? A polar bear.'' The style is lighthearted and playful with exaggerated expressions on the polar bear and seal, emphasizing the joke''s punchline that the result is just a polar bear anyway. Include small details like ice chunks, snow mounds, and maybe a few distant snowy mountains to set the Arctic scene creatively but simply.'),
 (1251, 'Animals, Knock Knock, Pun', 'Why did the chicken cross the road? To get to the idiot''s house.\nKnock Knock. Who''s there?\nChicken!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene split into two parts. On the left side, show a confident cartoon chicken standing at a crosswalk or road edge, looking determined as it crosses a simple two-lane road. Across the street, depict a modest, cartoonish house with a sign or a speech bubble implying it''s the ''idiot''s house'' in a playful way—nothing mean-spirited, maybe a simple welcome mat or a quirky decoration hinting at silliness. On the right side, zoom in on a cheerful person at the door of the house, answering it with a surprised but friendly expression. The person says, ''Who''s there?'' and the chicken replies, ''Chicken!'' in a speech bubble. Use bright colors, simple shapes, and exaggerated expressions for a lighthearted, cartoonish vibe. The scene should clearly convey the classic ''chicken crossing the road'' joke link to a knock-knock joke punchline, emphasizing fun and innocence with no negativity.'),
 (144, 'Animals, Love Humor, Relatable', 'Whoever said you can''t buy happiness forgot about little puppies.', NULL, 'A colorful, cheerful cartoon scene featuring a smiling person kneeling on a grassy park lawn, holding a small, adorable fluffy puppy in their arms. The puppy looks happy, wagging its tail enthusiastically. Around them, little hearts and sparkle icons float in the air to emphasize joy and happiness. Nearby, a simple park bench, a tree with green leaves, and a bright blue sky with a shining sun create a lighthearted, warm atmosphere. The person’s face expresses delight and contentment, showing that the puppy is the source of their happiness. The cartoon style is playful and cute, with exaggerated expressions and rounded, soft shapes to enhance the uplifting mood.'),
 (2629, 'Animals, Math Humor, Pun, Unknown', '3.14% of sailors are Pi Rates', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of sailors on a ship deck. Half of them are regular sailors dressed in typical navy uniforms, while a smaller portion are dressed as stereotypical pirates with eye patches, striped shirts, bandanas, and holding pirate accessories like a hook hand or a treasure map. Above the group, a large speech bubble or a banner reads ''3.14% of sailors are Pi Rates''. The ship should look cartoonish and old-fashioned with sails and a wooden deck. Optionally, include a large math symbol for Pi (π) humorously integrated into the scene, such as painted on the sail or hovering above the pirates. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and playful, capturing the pun combining math (Pi) and pirates.'),
 (1457, 'Animals, Math Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'A polar bear is a rectangular bear after a coordinate transform.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, friendly-looking polar bear standing in a snowy Arctic landscape. The bear''s body is perfectly rectangular, with sharp right angles instead of rounded edges, clearly shaped like a box. Next to the bear is a chalkboard or flip chart on an easel with mathematical coordinate axes drawn and a few simple geometric shapes, hinting at a coordinate transform. The polar bear looks slightly puzzled or quirky, glancing at the chart as if it just realized it''s been transformed. The background includes icy mountains and a few snowflakes falling. The style is bright, colorful, and playful with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the joke about geometry and bears.'),
 (1909, 'Animals, Money Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'If you pay peanuts you get monkeys.', 'James Goldsmith', 'Draw a colorful and humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated businessperson standing behind a small store counter labeled ''Cheap Pay''. On the counter, there is a big bowl of peanuts. In front of the counter, a group of mischievous monkeys wearing tiny business suits and glasses are causing playful chaos—some monkey is hanging from the ceiling light, one is holding a briefcase upside down, and another is juggling peanuts. The businessperson looks both surprised and overwhelmed. The background shows a simple office or storefront setting with a sign that reads ''Pay peanuts, get monkeys!''. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the idea that paying very little attracts less qualified or troublesome workers. Use bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (3233, 'Animals, Music Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'What instrument does a turkey play? The drumsticks!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful turkey standing upright on two legs in the center. The turkey should be anthropomorphized with a big friendly smile and bright eyes. It is holding two drumsticks (pieces of cooked chicken legs) like drumsticks used for playing drums. In front of the turkey, there is a classic drum set with visible snare drum, bass drum, and cymbals. The turkey is mid-action, about to hit one of the drums with a drumstick. The background can be a simple stage or music room with musical notes floating in the air to emphasize the musical theme. The overall style is colorful, fun, and cartoonish without any hint of violence or food preparation, focusing solely on the pun between a turkey and drumsticks as musical instruments.'),
 (3008, 'Animals, Music Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I just hate the key E-Minor - it gives me the E-B-G-Bs', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a frustrated musician sitting at a piano or with a guitar. The musician looks annoyed and is holding a sheet of music titled ''E-Minor.'' Around the musician, small cartoon bees with exaggerated angry faces and buzzing motion lines fly around, especially near the music sheet and instruments. Some bees are holding tiny musical notes shaped like E, G, and B to represent the chord notes. The setting is lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to convey annoyance mixed with silliness. Musical notes float in the air, and a speech bubble from the musician says, ''I just hate the key E-Minor - it gives me the E-B-G-Bs.'' The overall vibe is cartoonish and playful without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1478, 'Animals, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wise Sayings', 'A wise old owl sat on an oak, the more he sat, the less he spoke; the less he spoke, the more he heard; why aren''t we like that wise old bird?', 'E.H. Richards', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise old owl perched comfortably on a thick, sturdy oak tree branch. The owl has large, round glasses perched low on its beak, suggesting wisdom, and its eyes are half-closed as if thoughtfully listening. Around the owl, small musical notes or sound waves gently flow toward its face, symbolizing it hearing more. Below the tree, a group of colorful, diverse human characters stand looking puzzled or contemplative, scratching their heads or shrugging their shoulders, reflecting on why they aren''t more like the owl. The background is a simple, bright forest scene with soft green leaves and a clear blue sky to keep the tone light and friendly. The style is playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the humans and a slightly cartoonish owl, emphasizing the humor of the owl being silent yet attentive.'),
 (1312, 'Animals, Pirates, Pun', 'What''s a pirates favorite kind of fish? A gold fish', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a cheerful pirate standing on a small wooden dock by the sea. The pirate is wearing a classic outfit: a tricorn hat with a skull and crossbones, an eye patch, a striped shirt, and a big gold earring. In front of the pirate, just above the water, is a shiny, golden-colored fish with a happy, cartoonish expression. The fish sparkles with little glints to emphasize it being made of gold. The pirate looks excited, pointing at the goldfish with a wide grin. The background shows calm ocean waves, a clear blue sky with a few fluffy clouds, and a distant pirate ship with sails. The overall style should be playful and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor of the pun on ''gold fish'' and ''gold'' as pirate treasure.'),
 (1318, 'Animals, Pirates, Pun', 'Why did the pirate cross the sea? To get to the other tide!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful pirate standing on the bow of a classic wooden pirate ship sailing on the ocean. The pirate is dressed in a typical pirate outfit with a tricorn hat, eyepatch, striped shirt, and a big smile. He is looking ahead toward the horizon where a visible wavy line labeled ''The Other Tide'' appears, as if it''s a destination across the water. The sea has playful waves, some with little smiling faces. Above the scene, include a whimsical banner with the joke text split: ''Why did the pirate cross the sea?'' on the left, and ''To get to the other tide!'' on the right. The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun on ''tide'' versus ''side'' without any threatening or scary elements.'),
 (1320, 'Animals, Pirates, Pun', 'Why do pirates like communists? Because they''re from the U.S.S.AARRRRRRRRR!', NULL, 'A colorful and humorous cartoon scene featuring a pirate standing proudly on the deck of a wooden ship. The pirate wears a classic pirate hat with a skull and crossbones, an eye patch, a striped shirt, and a hook hand. Instead of a typical pirate flag, the ship flies a red flag with a yellow hammer and sickle symbol mixed with a pirate-themed twist, like a skull wearing a communist hat. The pirate is shouting "Arrrr!" with a big speech bubble that cleverly blends the letters U.S.S.A. with exaggerated pirate-style ''ARRRRRRRR'' sounds, making the pun visible. Around the pirate, waves splash and seagulls fly in the sky. The scene has a playful and exaggerated cartoon style with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, emphasizing the pun connecting pirates and communists in a light-hearted, silly way.'),
 (1309, 'Animals, Pirates, Puns, Travel Humor', 'What does a pirate drive on vacation? An AAAARRRRRRRRR V.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful pirate on vacation. The pirate is driving a large recreational vehicle (RV) styled to look like a pirate ship on wheels. The RV has wooden planks, a skull-and-crossbones flag, and a steering wheel resembling a ship''s helm. The pirate, wearing a traditional pirate hat, eye patch, striped shirt, and hook hand, is happily behind the wheel, smiling with exaggerated enthusiasm. The RV is emblazoned with the letters ''AAAARRRRRRRRR V'' on the side in big, bold, playful font. The background should be a sunny campground or seaside vacation spot with a few cartoonish palm trees, a picnic table, and perhaps a treasure chest sitting nearby. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated to highlight the pirate and the pun in a family-friendly and lighthearted way.'),
 (1335, 'Animals, Programmers, Programming Humor, Puns', 'If you put a million monkeys at a million keyboards, one of them will eventually write a Java program. The rest of them will write Perl programs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large group of monkeys seated at desks, each with a computer keyboard in front of them. The background is a simple bright room or jungle clearing. One monkey is spotlighted or has a glowing aura, proudly presenting a neat and colorful computer screen displaying a clean Java program (maybe with a coffee cup icon to symbolize Java). Surrounding this monkey are many others looking confused or frustrated, with cluttered, messy computer screens filled with complicated, tangled lines of code and symbols to represent Perl programs. Some monkeys scratch their heads or throw up their hands in comic exasperation. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions and simple but expressive detail, emphasizing the contrast between the one successful Java coder and the many struggling Perl coders.'),
 (3242, 'Animals, Pun, School, Thanksgiving', 'Why did the turkey get detention at school? He used fowl language.', NULL, 'Draw a colorful and humorous cartoon scene set inside a school classroom. Center the image on a disgruntled turkey sitting at a wooden school desk with textbooks and a notebook in front of it. The turkey should look mischievous or slightly embarrassed. Around the turkey, include a teacher — a stereotypical human teacher wearing glasses and holding a red pen with an exaggerated disappointed expression, pointing at a large chalkboard behind them. On the chalkboard in big letters, write the phrase ''Detention for Using Fowl Language!'' Emphasize the pun by including little speech bubbles around the turkey with random silly squawks or exclamation marks to represent ''language.'' The classroom background should have typical school elements such as posters, a clock on the wall, and a window showing a sunny day. Make the overall tone lighthearted and funny, using bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated cartoon style to highlight the pun between ''fowl'' and ''foul'' language.'),
 (3166, 'Animals, Pun, Science, Space Humor', 'Why are there no cats on Mars? Curiosity killed them all', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on the surface of Mars, with a red rocky landscape and a dusty reddish sky. A group of curious cats are poking around with wide eyes and alert ears, sniffing rocks, pawing at strange Martian plants, and looking perplexed. One cat is peering inside a weird alien crevice with exaggerated curiosity, while another is cautiously stepping over a small crater. In the background, a cartoonish rover labeled ''Curiosity'' is parked, with a thought bubble above it showing a playful, sly grin. Scattered around are whimsical Mars elements like small alien plants and rocks shaped like cat toys to emphasize the playful scene. The overall style should be light-hearted and silly, with exaggerated expressions on the cats'' faces to highlight the joke’s play on the word ''Curiosity''.'),
 (3181, 'Animals, Pun, Star Wars, Star Wars Humor', 'What side of an Ewok has the most hair? The outside.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cute, fuzzy Ewok standing outdoors in a forest setting reminiscent of the Star Wars universe. The Ewok is shown from the side with its thick fur clearly visible all over its body. To emphasize the joke, a large arrow points to the outside edge of the Ewok’s silhouette labeled ''The outside''. The Ewok has a friendly, slightly puzzled expression as if reacting to the silly question. In the background, tall trees with broad leaves and some glowing lights resembling fireflies add to the whimsical, lighthearted mood. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and playful, with exaggerated fur texture to highlight the “most hair on the outside” punchline. No other characters or elements to distract from the Ewok and the humor are included.'),
 (2633, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown', 'A dog can bark up to 500 times a day - but that''s just a ruff estimate', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring a happy, energetic dog standing next to a tall tree, looking upwards with its mouth open as if barking. Around the dog''s head are multiple little sound notes or comic-style ''bark'' words repeated several times to imply frequent barking. Nearby, a speech bubble coming from an unseen narrator or a signpost displays the joke text: "A dog can bark up to 500 times a day - but that''s just a ruff estimate." The style is colorful and light-hearted with playful fonts for the text. The dog should be a cute, friendly-looking breed, and the background is a simple park setting with grass, a tree, and a sunny sky. The overall vibe is humorous and punny, matching the tone of the joke in a cartoon format.'),
 (2647, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown', 'A termite walks into a bar and says, ''where is the bar tender?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a bar with typical features: a long wooden bar counter, several bar stools, a few bottles and glasses displayed on shelves behind the counter, and warm lighting. In the foreground, a small, friendly-looking termite stands upright on its hind legs at the bar counter, wearing tiny glasses and looking curious or puzzled. The termite speaks to a human bartender, who has an amused or slightly confused expression, wearing a classic bartender apron. The termite is saying, with a speech bubble above its head: ''Where is the bar tender?'' The humor relies on the double meaning of ''bartender'' and the termite''s association with ''tender wood.'' The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing whimsy with exaggerated expressions and simple backgrounds that keep the focus on the characters and the pun.'),
 (2790, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown', 'Don''t count your chickens before they cross the road.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of cheerful chickens standing on one side of a road, looking curiously and hesitantly at the street ahead. On the opposite side, a single confident chicken is midway crossing the road with a big smile. The road is a classic two-lane street with simple road markings. In the background, there are green fields and a bright blue sky with a few fluffy clouds. A whimsical road sign reads, ''Chicken Crossing.'' The chickens on the starting side appear to be counting or gesturing with their wings, some looking uncertain. The overall style is bright and playful, emphasizing fun and lightheartedness without any violence or negativity. The atmosphere highlights the joke’s wordplay about not assuming chickens are safely on the other side yet.'),
 (2652, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Apparently to start a zoo you need at least two pandas, a grizzly and three polars. It''s the bear minimum.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a small zoo entrance with a prominent sign that reads ''Bear Minimum Zoo.'' Inside, there are four enclosures visible, each clearly labeled and distinct: one with two cute pandas munching on bamboo, one with a large grizzly bear sitting on a rock, and a third with three playful polar bears sliding on ice. The zookeeper, cartoonishly cheerful and holding a clipboard, stands by the gate looking proud but slightly amused. Nearby, a pun banner or sign says ''It''s the bear minimum!'' The background should be bright and inviting, with some zoo visitors—adults and kids—laughing and pointing at the animals. Include amusing animal expressions to emphasize the joke, such as the animals looking relaxed or goofy. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, focusing on conveying the pun visually with clarity and charm.'),
 (2755, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Deja Moo:  The feeling that you''ve heard this bull before.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, smug-looking bull standing in a green pasture. The bull has an exaggerated expression of boredom or mild annoyance, as if tired of repeating himself. Above the bull''s head is a comic-style thought bubble or speech bubble that says ''Deja Moo.'' Surrounding the bull are grassy fields with a few simple flowers and maybe a wooden fence in the background. Nearby, a confused farmer or cowhand with a pitchfork scratches his head, looking as if he just heard the same story or statement from the bull multiple times. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and playful, emphasizing the pun on "deja vu" with the word "moo" related to the bull. Avoid any background clutter or other animals to focus on the bull and the pun.'),
 (2877, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Frogs don''t tell the truth; they amphibian.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a frog sitting at a small podium or stage, as if giving a speech or telling a joke. The frog has a cheeky, mischievous expression and is mid-sentence, with a speech bubble coming out that reads ''I’m amphibian!'' Around the frog, a small audience of various frog characters are either laughing or looking confused. The background is a simple swamp or pond with lily pads, cattails, and a bright blue sky. The style is colorful, lively, and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the pun on ''amphibian'' sounding like ''I’m fibbing'' or ''I’m lying.'''),
 (2937, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'How do fish get high? Seaweed.', NULL, 'A colorful underwater cartoon scene featuring a happy, goofy-looking fish with big eyes and a wide smile. The fish is surrounded by several strands of seaweed that are whimsically shaped like clouds or puffs of smoke rising gently around it, implying the ''high'' effect humorously. The background shows vibrant coral reefs and bubbling water with light rays filtering down from the surface. The overall tone is bright, playful, and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon features to enhance humor.'),
 (3043, 'Animals, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I think that statistically a dog barks approximately 487 times a day, but that''s just a ruff estimate.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, slightly scruffy dog standing next to a large cartoon-style clipboard or whiteboard with a big number ''487'' written on it. The dog is shown mid-bark with a speech bubble containing ''Ruff!'' The background is a simple park or backyard setting with a few trees and a fence. The clipboard or whiteboard has a handwritten label above the number saying ''Average dog barks per day''. The dog looks confident, almost like it''s proud of the statistic. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon-style expressions and bright colors.'),
 (3246, 'Animals, Pun, Visual Humor, What do you call...', 'What do you call a beehive with no exits? Unbelievable!', NULL, 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a large beehive shaped like a typical hanging honeycomb cluster, but with no visible holes or exits. The beehive hangs from a tree branch in a sunny meadow with flowers around. Nearby, a few confused cartoon bees buzz around outside the hive, looking puzzled and trying to find a way in or out. One bee even has a tiny magnifying glass, inspecting the hive closely. Above the scene, a playful caption reads: ''Unbelievable!'' The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize humor, with smiling bees and oversized flowers for a lighthearted, cheerful vibe.'),
 (3249, 'Animals, Pun, What do you call...', 'What do you call a cow during an earthquake? A milkshake', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with a cow standing on a cracked, shaky ground to illustrate an earthquake. The cow looks startled and wobbly, with its eyes wide open and small lines around its body to emphasize the shaking motion. Surround the cow with small tilted objects like a falling bucket of milk and a milk carton spilling milk that splashes and mixes on the ground, resembling a ''milkshake.'' The background should show simple house outlines with cracked walls and some dust clouds to suggest the quake. Keep the style light and funny, with exaggerated expressions on the cow to highlight the pun in the joke. The overall tone is playful and cartoonish without any scary or intense elements.'),
 (3257, 'Animals, Pun, What do you call...', 'What do you call a three legged hippo? A hoppo', NULL, 'Draw a cute, cartoon-style hippopotamus with three legs instead of the usual four. The hippo should be standing upright or in a playful pose to emphasize its odd number of legs. One of its legs should look like it''s mid-hop, suggesting movement like hopping. Surround the hippo with a simple grassy or muddy riverbank environment, typical for a hippo''s habitat, but keep the background minimal to focus on the unusual hippo. Add a speech bubble or a small sign nearby with the word "Hoppo" in playful, bold letters. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated, rounded features for a humorous and lighthearted vibe.'),
 (3245, 'Animals, Pun, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call a bear with no teeth? A gummy bear.', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene featuring a large, friendly-looking bear sitting down with a big smile but noticeably no teeth in its mouth. The bear should look cute and harmless. In front of the bear, place a small colorful gummy bear candy on the ground or held in the bear’s paw, clearly showing the connection between the bear and the candy. The background can be a simple forest clearing with green trees and bushes. The style should be playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and rounded shapes to emphasize humor and lightheartedness.'),
 (3254, 'Animals, Pun, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call a mother cow after it gives birth? De-calf-in-ated', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a happy mother cow standing proudly in a green grassy pasture just after giving birth. Next to her on the ground is a tiny, cute calf looking content. The mother cow has a tired but relieved expression, droopy eyes, and little lines around her face to show exhaustion. Above her head is a comic-style text bubble containing the pun ''De-calf-in-ated'' with playful, wavy lines emphasizing tiredness, as if she''s really drained. The setting includes a bright blue sky, a few fluffy clouds, and a rustic wooden fence in the background. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoony, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to enhance the joke''s playful tone. No other animals or people are visible to keep focus on the mother cow and her calf.'),
 (3261, 'Animals, Pun, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call an elephant that doesn''t matter? An irrelephant', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, goofy-looking elephant with exaggerated big ears and a slightly puzzled expression. The elephant stands in the center of the frame on a simple grassy patch under a bright blue sky with a couple of fluffy clouds. Near the elephant is a small, unimpressed character (like a tiny mouse or a person with arms crossed) looking up at the elephant with a slight smirk or shrug, to emphasize the joke that the elephant ''doesn''t matter.'' A playful sign or speech bubble above the elephant reads, ''I''m an irrelephant!'' The overall art style is light-hearted and colorful, with rounded lines and exaggerated features to keep it funny and friendly. Include subtle visual cues like a spotlight fading out around the elephant to hint at the ''doesn''t matter'' meaning, reinforcing the pun visually. The scene should be simple, cheerful, and clearly focused on the pun for easy comedic effect.'),
 (3081, 'Animals, Puns, Science Humor, Unknown', 'If H2O is inside the fire hydrant, what''s on the outside? K9P', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic red fire hydrant standing on a city sidewalk. The fire hydrant is partially cut away on one side to reveal clear blue water labeled ''H2O'' inside. Outside the hydrant, floating in the air or hovering nearby, are three playful cartoon dogs representing ''K9P'' as a pun on chemical symbols, with ''K9'' visually shown as a cute, friendly dog (like a cartoon puppy) and the letter ''P'' floating beside them. The setting is bright and cheerful with a simple urban background, some grass tufts near the hydrant''s base, and a friendly neighborhood vibe. The style should be colorful and exaggerated with rounded lines to emphasize the joke''s playful and clever nature, avoiding anything realistic or serious-looking. The dogs should look happy and cartoonish to highlight the pun without implying any threat or aggression.'),
 (3184, 'Animals, Puns, Star Wars, Star Wars Humor', 'When do Gungans store their food? In a Jar Jar', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a whimsical kitchen setting inspired by Star Wars. In the foreground, depict a cartoonish Gungan character (like Jar Jar Binks) cheerfully holding a transparent, oversized jar packed with various food items inside—fruits, vegetables, and snacks visible through the jar. The jar should have a label that says ''Jar Jar'' in playful letters. Around the kitchen, include simple shelves stocked with other jars and containers, some of which have funny food labels referencing Star Wars or the Gungan culture humorously. The Gungan character should have exaggerated eyes and big floppy ears for comical effect, smiling as if proud of their food storage method. The overall style should be colorful and lighthearted, with clear outlines and exaggerated features typical of a funny cartoon.'),
 (3239, 'Animals, Puns, Thanksgiving', 'Which side of a turkey has more feathers? The outside!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, plump cartoon turkey standing proudly in the center. The turkey is smiling and puffing out its chest, with bright, well-detailed feathers all over its body. To the left of the turkey, a flat, comical cutaway view of the turkey’s inside is shown with dramatically fewer or no feathers, emphasizing the joke. A person, drawn in a lighthearted cartoon style, stands next to the turkey scratching their head and holding a question mark sign or a puzzled expression, looking between the outside feathers and the inside. The background is simple and cheerful, perhaps with a sunny farmyard or kitchen setting. The style is colorful and exaggerated, with funny expressions and clear emphasis on the feathers outside versus the featherless inside, to highlight the punchline “the outside”.'),
 (3259, 'Animals, Puns, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call an alligator in a vest? An investigator', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly alligator standing upright on two legs. The alligator is wearing a neat, small vest that looks like a detective''s vest. It has a magnifying glass in one hand (or claw), held up close to one eye as if inspecting something carefully. The alligator wears a small detective''s hat tilted playfully on its head. The setting is a simple grassy area with a few small plants and perhaps a subtle cityscape or forest background to keep it light and fun. The overall style is colorful and exaggerated, with big eyes on the alligator showing curiosity and cleverness. The tone is playful and inviting to highlight the pun in the joke.'),
 (3264, 'Animals, Puns, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call dinosaur with a large vocabulary? A Thesaurus', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly dinosaur standing upright like a person. The dinosaur should look big but approachable, with a slightly goofy expression. It wears large round glasses perched on its nose to emphasize intelligence. Around its neck, it sports a librarian-style scarf or a bow tie. In one claw, it holds an open oversized book titled "Vocabulary" or "Thesaurus." Nearby, scattered on the ground or a small table, have other books labeled with words like "Synonyms" and "Antonyms." The background is a simple library setting with tall bookshelves filled with oversized books, some labeled with word-related titles. Add a small speech bubble above the dinosaur''s head with the phrase "A Thesaurus!" in playful font. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, suitable for all ages, highlighting the pun involving a dinosaur and a thesaurus (word reference).'),
 (145, 'Animals, Puns, Winter Humor', 'What do you call a snowman with a 6-pack? The abdominal snowman', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful snowman standing outdoors in a snowy winter setting. The snowman should have classic features: a carrot nose, coal eyes and buttons, a scarf, and a top hat. However, instead of a round belly, the midsection of the snowman clearly shows defined six-pack abs made of snow. The snowman poses proudly with its twig arms flexed, showing off its muscular ''abdominal'' area. Around the snowman, gentle snowflakes fall from the sky, and a few evergreen trees dusted with snow are in the background. The overall tone is light, playful, and funny, emphasizing the pun ''abdominal snowman.'' The art style should be cartoonish and exaggerated to highlight the joke without any aggressive or dark elements.'),
 (146, 'Animals, Puns, Winter Humor', 'What do you get when you cross a snowman and a shark? Frostbite!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a large snowman with classic features: a carrot nose, coal eyes and buttons, stick arms, and a scarf. Above or next to the snowman, draw a friendly-looking shark wearing a winter hat and a scarf as well, swimming in icy blue water or snow. To illustrate the joke''s punchline ''Frostbite,'' show the snowman''s hand or one of its stick arms clearly bitten by the shark, but keep the expression comedic and light-hearted rather than scary—maybe the snowman looks surprised but amused. Include snowy landscape elements like snowflakes falling, a few snow-covered trees, and a chilly atmosphere with visible breath clouds to emphasize the cold. The tone should be bright, playful, and cartoonish to enhance the pun-based humor.'),
 (147, 'Animals, Puns, Word Play', 'To err is human, to moo bovine.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a sunny green farm with a blue sky and fluffy white clouds. In the center, a cartoon cow stands upright like a human, with a comically thoughtful expression, holding a large book titled ''Human Mistakes'' in one hoof. Nearby, a confused-looking cartoon human wearing simple farmer clothes scratches his head. The cow is saying the phrase ''To err is human, to moo bovine'' in a speech bubble. Around them are classic farm elements: a red barn, a wooden fence, some hay bales, and a few other cows grazing or watching curiously. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated with big eyes and friendly expressions to enhance the pun’s humor without any aggressive or negative tones.'),
 (148, 'Animals, Puns, Word Play', 'What did the fish say when he hit a wall? Dam.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a surprised fish swimming underwater right in front of a large, cartoonish brick wall labeled ''DAM'' to clarify it''s a dam wall. The fish has wide eyes and its mouth open as if speaking or shocked. Bubbles rise from the fish''s mouth to emphasize speech. The underwater environment includes simple aquatic elements like seaweed, small rocks, and water plants to set the scene. The style is lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated expressions to enhance the joke''s punchline.'),
 (149, 'Animals, Puns, Word Play', 'What do cows like to read? Cattle-logs', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly cow sitting comfortably in an armchair, wearing reading glasses, and holding a book titled ''Cattle-logs'' with a cover that shows a cartoon log and a cow. Around the cow, add a cozy living room setting with a small side table holding a cup of tea and a lamp. In the background, a bookshelf contains other animal-themed books. The cow has a delighted expression as it reads. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and playful to emphasize the pun on ''cattle'' and ''catalogs.'' The focus is on the cow enjoying its reading, reinforcing the joke visually without any other characters or complicated elements.'),
 (150, 'Animals, Puns, Word Play', 'What do you get when you cross a bee and a sheep? A bah-humbug.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky hybrid animal with the body of a fluffy white sheep, complete with wool, and the distinct yellow and black stripes of a bee. The creature has delicate bee wings fluttering on its back and large bee antennae on its head, but it’s standing on sheep-like legs. It is standing in a green meadow under a bright sunny sky with cartoon flowers around. The sheep-bee hybrid is making a grumpy or annoyed face, with a visible speech bubble above it that says ''Bah-humbug'' in a playful comic font. Nearby, a simple wooden signpost labeled ''Pun Meadow'' adds a lighthearted touch. The style should be colorful, clean, and charmingly exaggerated to emphasize the humor of the pun, with rounded shapes and friendly expressions typical of a children''s cartoon.'),
 (1825, 'Animals, Quotes, Social Humor, Word Play', 'I like pigs. Dogs look up to us. Cats look down on us. Pigs treat us as equals.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a human character standing in the middle, smiling warmly. To their left is a cheerful dog looking up at the human with wide admiring eyes and a wagging tail. To their right is a cat sitting on a higher surface, like a table or shelf, looking down with an aloof, slightly disdainful expression. In front of the human is a happy pig standing on the ground at the same level, gazing at the person with a friendly and equal, almost brotherly expression. The background is simple and bright, like an open grassy park or backyard, with a few plants or trees for context but no distractions. The style is whimsical and cute, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the attitudes: admiration, superiority, and equality respectively. The overall vibe is warm, humorous, and charming, with a clear visual contrast among the three animals'' interactions with the person.'),
 (2396, 'Animals, Quotes, Word Play, Workplace', 'The trouble with the rat race is that even if you win, you''re still a rat.', 'Lily Tomlin', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a literal rat dressed in business attire, like a suit and tie, running on a giant race track shaped like a hamster wheel or treadmill. The rat looks exhausted but determined, holding a briefcase. In the background, other rat competitors dressed similarly also run on the track. At the finish line, there’s a large banner that says ''WINNER'' but instead of a trophy, there is a big piece of cheese labeled ''Success.'' The rat at the finish line looks happy yet slightly puzzled, emphasizing the irony. The environment should have office-like details, such as a water cooler and a clock with a late hour. The overall tone is playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to convey the joke visually without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2640, 'Animals, Religion Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'A priest, a pastor, and a rabbit enter a blood donation clinic. The nurse asks the rabbit ''What is your blood type?'' The rabbit says ''I''m probably a Type O''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a bright, friendly blood donation clinic. Three characters stand in a line near the reception desk: a priest wearing a traditional black clerical outfit with a white collar, a pastor in casual yet neat clothing holding a Bible, and a rabbit standing upright on two legs, looking mildly confused or thoughtful. The nurse, positioned behind the reception desk, holds a clipboard and looks at the rabbit with a questioning expression. The rabbit’s speech bubble says, ''I''m probably a Type O.'' In the background, typical blood donation posters and medical equipment like chairs and blood bags are visible to set the scene. The overall style is light, colorful, and cartoonish to emphasize the joke''s play on words and the rabbit’s misheard identity as ''a rabbi'' versus ''a rabbit.'''),
 (151, 'Animals, Science', 'If you put a raisin in a glass of champagne, it will keep floating to the top and sinking to the bottom.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tall, elegant champagne glass filled with bubbly champagne. Inside the glass, a single raisin is depicted with animated eyes and tiny arms, looking surprised or dizzy as it repeatedly floats up to the surface and sinks back down. Bubbles surround the raisin, with a few popping at the top of the glass. The background is simple and light to keep focus on the glass and the active raisin. The style is playful and exaggerated, capturing the movement of the raisin going up and down in a loop, creating a fun, lively vibe.'),
 (3119, 'Animals, Science Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'Women blink nearly twice as much as men.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene split in two halves. On the left side, illustrate a man with one eye open widely and a single slow blink in progress. On the right side, show a woman with exaggeratedly large eyes blinking rapidly, with multiple curved motion lines around her eyes to emphasize frequent blinking. Both characters are standing side by side, facing forward, with amused expressions. Include a small clock above them showing time passing quickly to suggest blink frequency. Use soft pastel colors and clear, simple lines for a lighthearted, fun cartoon feel. Avoid any suggestive or offensive elements.'),
 (2996, 'Animals, Unknown, Word Play', 'I hate those Russian dolls - they are so full of themselves.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a classic set of Russian nesting dolls (matryoshka) lined up in descending size from left to right. The largest doll has a smug, overly confident facial expression with raised eyebrows and a sly smile. The other smaller dolls inside are peeking out slightly, all with similarly arrogant looks, showing they are ''full of themselves.'' The background is simple and cheerful, with soft pastel colors to emphasize the playful tone. Include a small speech bubble near the largest doll saying, ''I’m the best!'' or something that suggests ego. The style should be colorful and exaggerated in a lighthearted, cartoonish way, with round shapes and expressive faces emphasizing humor without any negative or aggressive emotions.'),
 (152, 'Animals, Word Play', 'Most people think that T-rex can''t clap because they have short arms, but really they can''t clap because they are dead.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly T-rex skeleton standing upright in a museum or prehistoric setting. The skeleton has tiny, short arms extended slightly forward but clearly too small to clap. Around the T-rex are a few curious cartoon characters or children looking up at it with puzzled expressions. Above or beside the skeleton is a playful speech bubble or a sign that says, ''Most people think T-rex can’t clap because of short arms, but really it’s because they’re dead!'' The background could show dinosaur bones or fossils in display cases. The overall tone should be light-hearted and comical, emphasizing the irony in the joke without any dark or scary elements.'),
 (153, 'Animals, Word Play', 'My father has the heart of a lion, and a lifetime ban from the zoo.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful middle-aged man with a big smile standing outside a zoo entrance. The man is holding a certificate or piece of paper labeled ''Lifetime Ban Notice'' with a cartoon lion behind a fence in the background. The lion looks mildly amused or indifferent. The zoo gate has a sign that says ''Zoo Entrance'' and another sign next to the man saying ''No Entry for This Visitor.'' Around the man, add subtle comical elements like a few broken tree branches or a knocked over trash can hinting at prior mischief. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and lightheartedness.'),
 (154, 'Animals, Word Play', 'My sea sickness comes in waves.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene on a small boat in the ocean during the day. The boat is gently rocking on stylized cartoon waves that look like large rolling blue waves with white foam tops. A person on the boat looks queasy, holding their stomach with one hand and gripping the boat''s railing with the other. Their face is a bit greenish and shows discomfort but good-spirited humor. Around the boat, the waves are exaggerated, clearly emphasizing the motion. The background features a bright blue sky with a happily smiling sun and a couple of seagulls flying. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful with exaggerated, simple shapes and bright colors to emphasize humor.'),
 (155, 'Animals, Word Play', 'Not enough bucks stop here.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bus stop sign that reads ''Not enough bucks stop here.'' Next to the sign is a confused male deer (a buck) wearing a backpack, looking puzzled as he waits for a bus. The bus is a bright, simple cartoon style vehicle approaching in the background, and a couple of other animals (like a squirrel and a rabbit) are waiting alongside the buck on the sidewalk. The setting is a suburban street with a sidewalk, a small green patch with a tree, and a clear sky. The sign is the central focus, with bold lettering to highlight the pun. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor in the play on words involving ''bucks'' as deer and ''bucks'' as money, implying not enough money to stop the bus here.'),
 (1564, 'Archaeology Humor, Cartoon, Pun, Quotes', 'Archaeologists take sedimental journeys.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two archaeologists dressed in typical expedition gear (khaki hats, vests, and boots) standing in a desert-like dig site. One archaeologist is holding a pickaxe and a brush while the other looks thoughtfully at a half-buried artifact. Around them, layers of earth are visibly stratified like a cake or a sandwich, emphasizing sediment layers. In the background, a thought bubble rises from one archaeologist showing a winding road or a scenic route, symbolizing a ''journey.'' The setting should invoke the pun on ''sedimental journeys'' by combining a literal archaeological dig with a playful travel or reflection theme. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated, friendly facial expressions to enhance the humor and cartoon style. Include simple tools like shovels and brushes scattered around to cement the archaeological theme without clutter.'),
 (1670, 'Art Humor, Cartoon, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Every artist dips his brush in his own soul, and paints his own nature into his pictures.', 'Henry Ward Beecher', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an artist standing in front of an easel with a large canvas. The artist, a friendly-looking person wearing a painter''s beret and smock, is holding a paintbrush that is literally dipped into a glowing, colorful soul-shaped jar labeled ''Soul''. The soul jar emits sparkles or light to emphasize its magical or precious nature. The canvas shows a whimsical painting mirroring the artist’s personality, like a self-portrait with exaggerated, expressive features or quirky elements (e.g., a playful smile or colorful aura). The background is a simple cozy art studio with a palette resting nearby, some paint tubes, and a window letting in soft daylight. The cartoon style is lighthearted and fun, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke’s metaphorical meaning that artists put their essence into their art.'),
 (2812, 'Art Humor, Classic Joke, Pun, Unknown', 'Drop the vase and it will become a Ming of the past.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person accidentally dropping a delicate vase. The vase should be elaborately decorated like a classic Ming dynasty vase, mid-fall, about to shatter on the floor. Below, the floor has faint cracks and tiny shards already forming to emphasize the moment just before breaking. In the background or as a ghostly overlay, illustrate a faint, transparent montage of traditional Chinese art or ancient Ming dynasty imagery, visually representing ''a Ming of the past.'' The person dropping the vase should have a surprised, worried expression, perhaps with their hands in the air or fingers splayed out. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated cartoon features and expressions. No violent or frightening elements, just a comical mishap emphasizing the pun in the phrase.'),
 (1787, 'Art Humor, Craft Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'I choose a block of marble and chop off whatever I don''t need. (when asked how he managed to make his remarkable statues)', 'Francois-Auguste Rodin (1840-1917)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, well-lit sculptor''s studio. In the center, a cheerful sculptor stands next to a large, partially carved block of marble shaped vaguely like a statue. The sculptor is playfully holding a chisel and hammer, mid-swing but smiling confidently, as chips of marble fly off. Nearby, there is a pile of marble pieces labeled ''discarded'' to emphasize the idea of chopping off what he doesn''t need. Around the studio are typical sculpting tools, a sketch or blueprint pinned to the wall, and classic sculptures in various stages — some rough, some refined. The sculptor wears a smock with a name tag and a friendly expression, demonstrating casual pride in his work. The overall style is light and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and simple, clean lines to keep it fun and approachable without any violence, just humorous dedication to the craft.'),
 (2198, 'Art Humor, Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Perfection is achieved, not when there is nothing left to add, but when there is nothing left to take away.', 'Antoine de St. Exupery', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an artist in a minimalist studio. The artist stands proudly next to a sculpture or painting that is extremely simple and clean—like a plain white cube or an empty canvas. Around the artist are various art tools (brushes, paint tubes, chisels) scattered on a cluttered table. Above the artist''s head is a thought bubble showing a chaotic, overloaded version of the artwork with tons of unnecessary details, clearly rejected. The artist looks satisfied and relaxed, holding a chisel or paintbrush, symbolizing the act of removal or simplification. The background is light and airy with some framed minimalist abstract art on the walls, emphasizing the concept of ''less is more.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and clever, highlighting the idea that true perfection comes from removing excess rather than adding more, in a witty yet gentle way.'),
 (2367, 'Art Humor, Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The poet ranks far below the painter in the representation of visible things, and far below the musician in that of invisible things.', 'Leonardo Da Vinci', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, a frustrated poet is sitting at a cluttered desk with scribbled paper and a quill, looking unhappy while trying to describe a simple apple. Above the poet, floating imaginary clouds or abstract symbols represent ''invisible things.'' On the right side, a confident painter is standing proudly in front of a colorful canvas clearly showing the apple with vivid detail. Next to the painter, a cheerful musician is playing a violin or a flute with musical notes swirling around, symbolizing the representation of invisible things (music, emotions). The expressions highlight the poet’s struggle compared to the painter''s and musician''s ease. The overall style should be cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors, emphasizing the joke’s contrast between art forms without any harsh or negative tone.'),
 (2867, 'Art Humor, Creative Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'For every vision there is an equal and opposite revision.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting an office or creative workspace where a person is presenting a large, colorful vision board or blueprint on an easel. The vision board has grand ideas like sketches of futuristic buildings, innovative gadgets, or artistic designs. Nearby, another person stands with a puzzled or slightly overwhelmed expression, holding a giant eraser or a huge red pen labeled ''Revision.'' Behind them is a whiteboard or flip chart filled with crossed-out notes, corrections, and new scribbles. The scene should have exaggerated, playful expressions and vibrant colors to enhance the cartoon feel. Include typical office elements like desks, computers, coffee cups, and sticky notes scattered around, emphasizing a creative but chaotic environment that visually represents the constant back-and-forth between vision and revision in the creative process.'),
 (2275, 'Art Humor, Cultural Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The art of a people is a true mirror to their minds.', 'Jawaharial Nehru', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of diverse people standing in front of a large, ornate mirror labeled ''The Mirror of Minds.'' The mirror’s surface isn''t reflecting their physical appearances but instead shows various abstract, colorful thought bubbles and imaginative symbols above their heads, such as light bulbs, paintbrushes, gears, musical notes, and books. The setting is an art gallery or museum with framed paintings on the walls depicting quirky and funny aspects of human nature (like a brain painting or a whimsical mind map). The people look curious and amused, some pointing at their own thought reflections in the mirror. The overall style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the idea that the mirror reveals the minds of a culture through its art.'),
 (2745, 'Art Humor, Culture Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Culture is the habit of being pleased with the best and knowing why.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting in a cozy art gallery or museum. One character is pointing proudly at a beautifully framed painting titled ''The Best,'' which depicts a grand trophy or shining gem. The other character looks thoughtfully pleased, with a small notebook labeled ''Why'' open on their lap. Around them, other artworks have comical titles like ''Mediocre,'' ''Average,'' and ''Good Enough,'' each with exaggerated, silly visuals to emphasize contrast. The walls have elegant spotlights highlighting the ''best'' piece with a glowing aura. The characters are drawn in a lighthearted cartoon style, with expressive faces showing delight and thoughtful understanding. Include a small, humorous plaque under the main painting that reads: "Culture: The art of liking the best and knowing why." The overall tone is bright, friendly, and funny without any complex background details beyond the gallery setting and the artworks on walls.'),
 (1693, 'Art Humor, Fantasy Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Fantasy, abandoned by reason, produces impossible monsters; united with it, she is the mother of the arts and the origin of marvels.', 'Goya', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene depicting a whimsical and imaginative artist''s studio. The artist is a playful cartoon character with a big, inspired smile and wide eyes, holding a paintbrush dripping with colorful paint. Around the artist, surreal and impossible creatures are emerging from canvases and floating in the air—such as a multi-headed dragon with butterfly wings, a fish with legs walking on a trail of sparkles, and musical notes turning into birds flying away. The studio background is filled with scattered art supplies like paint tubes, brushes, easels, and sketchbooks. Include a thought bubble above the artist''s head showing a clash between a serious, grey figure labeled ''Reason'' looking confused and an exuberant character labeled ''Fantasy'' dancing joyfully, surrounded by stars and swirls. The overall tone is lively and creative, emphasizing how fantasy and reason come together to create marvelous art. Keep the colors bright and playful to emphasize the joyful chaos of creative imagination.'),
 (1162, 'Art Humor, Humor, Insults, Philosophy Humor', 'Art is not a handicraft, it is the transmission of feeling the artist has experienced.', 'Leo Tolstoy', 'A humorous cartoon scene in an art studio. An eccentric artist with a paint-splattered smock and messy hair stands proudly in front of an abstract painting on an easel. The painting looks like random colorful blobs and strokes. The artist is dramatically holding a paintbrush like a microphone, with eyes closed and a big theatrical smile to show deep emotion. In the background, unfinished pottery, knitting yarn, or other handicraft tools sit untouched on a shelf labeled ''Handicrafts''. A small confused character, wearing simple clothes and holding a pottery bowl, looks on puzzled while scratching their head, standing next to a sign that says, ''Handicraft Studio''. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between simple handiwork and the artist’s exaggerated emotional expression. Use bright colors and whimsical facial expressions to highlight the humor.'),
 (1569, 'Art Humor, Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Art is either plagiarism or revolution.', 'Paul Guaguin', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two contrasting panels side by side. On the left panel labeled ''Plagiarism,'' an artist is copying a famous painting exactly, using a huge stencil or tracing paper over the original artwork hanging on an easel. The artist looks sneaky and mischievous, wearing a beret and a striped shirt. On the right panel labeled ''Revolution,'' a rebellious artist is wildly creating an abstract, chaotic, and colorful piece full of splatters, strange shapes, and odd figures. This artist looks ecstatic and free-spirited, holding a paintbrush in mid-air with vibrant paint flying everywhere. Both panels have exaggerated cartoon expressions and bright colors to emphasize the humor and contrast between copying art and creating revolutionary art. Background items could include paint tubes, brushes, easels, and canvases to set the art studio scene in a lighthearted, playful style.'),
 (1655, 'Art Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Each life makes its own immitation of immortality.', 'Stephen King', 'Draw a whimsical, cartoon-style scene showing a variety of different creatures and objects each leaving a unique ''imitation of immortality'' behind. In the center, have a large, friendly tree with visible rings representing its age, symbolizing natural longevity. Around it, depict a butterfly leaving behind a small, glowing trail that transforms into tiny sparkling stars, representing fleeting beauty. Nearby, a handwritten diary lies open with glowing letters floating upward, illustrating memories or stories as a form of immortality. Include a smiling elderly person planting a sapling, symbolizing legacy and ongoing life. Above, a cheerful bird holds a paintbrush, painting a colorful rainbow in the sky, symbolizing artistic contribution transcending time. The scene should have a light, hopeful feeling with soft colors and playful expressions on the characters, emphasizing the diverse ways that life leaves enduring marks. The background can be a sunny park or garden setting, cartoonish clouds and flowers around. Avoid any dark or serious tones to keep it uplifting and imaginative.'),
 (1456, 'Art Humor, Literary Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'A poem is never finished, only abandoned.', 'Paul Valery (1871-1945)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated poet sitting at a cluttered wooden desk covered in crumpled papers, with many half-finished poems scattered around. The poet, wearing glasses and a slightly disheveled look, is looking tired and rubbing their temple while staring at an open, slightly wrinkled notebook with a half-written poem inside. A small but expressive clock on the wall shows late night time, and a coffee cup with steam rising is placed prominently on the desk. In the background, an easel holds a large scroll labeled ''Poem in Progress,'' which has scribbles and numerous edits. Near the poet’s feet, a trash bin overflowing with scrunched-up sheets emphasizes the abandonment concept. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and whimsical details that convey the poet’s endless struggle to finish their work, highlighting the joke’s idea that poems are never really completed, just abandoned.'),
 (2094, 'Art Humor, Mathematics, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Mathematics, rightly viewed, possesses not only truth, but supreme beauty -- a beauty cold and austere, like that of sculpture.', 'Bertrand Russell', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classical marble sculpture of a person—like a famous ancient Greek statue—standing on a pedestal. The statue has chiseled, elegant features and is depicted holding an open math book with formulas floating above its hand, glowing softly. Around the statue, there are geometric shapes and math symbols artistically arranged, such as triangles, circles, and equations, emphasizing the ''beauty'' of mathematics. The setting is a bright museum room with a plaque on the pedestal that reads: ''Mathematics: Beauty Cold and Austere.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, capturing the idea that math is as majestic and carefully crafted as fine sculpture, but without any people, violence, or political imagery included.'),
 (2276, 'Art Humor, Motivational Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The artist is nothing without the gift, but the gift is nothing without work.', 'Emile Zola (1840-1902)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one representing ''The Artist'' and the other representing ''The Gift.'' The Artist is a creative-looking person holding a painter''s palette and brush, dressed with a beret and paint-splattered clothes, standing proudly but with empty hands. The Gift is depicted as a glowing, shining present box with a smiling face and arms, shrugging helplessly while standing next to The Artist. In front of them is a large workbench cluttered with sketchbooks, paint tubes, crumpled papers, and some half-finished art pieces. The background is a vibrant art studio with easels and colorful paintings on the walls. Include a speech bubble from The Artist saying, "Without you, I’m nothing," and from The Gift saying, "Without work, I’m nothing!" The overall style should be light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the collaboration and humor in the relationship between talent and effort.'),
 (2041, 'Art Humor, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Life beats down and crushes the soul and art reminds you that you have one.', 'Stella Adler', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a sad, cartoonish character hunched over, looking defeated with a gloomy gray cloud hovering just above their head symbolizing life''s hardships. The character is shown walking on a cracked, barren ground labeled ''Life''. To the side, a vibrant, colorful easel with a lively painting of a bright, smiling soul character is being held up by a cheerful artist wearing a beret and holding a paintbrush. The painting emits a glowing aura, contrasting sharply with the dull surroundings. The artist is smiling warmly and gesturing toward the painting as if saying, ''See? You do have one!'' The environment should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive, simple shapes and bright colors around the art to emphasize the uplifting effect of art on the person''s crushed spirit. The overall tone is encouraging and humorous, emphasizing the contrast between life''s difficulty and art''s life-affirming power without any harsh or dark elements.'),
 (2594, 'Art Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Works of art, in my opinion, are the only objects in the material universe to possess internal order, and that is why, though I don''t believe that only art matters, I do belive in Art for Art''s sake.', 'E. M. Forster', 'Draw a lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a thoughtful person standing in an art gallery. The individual is gazing intently at a variety of colorful paintings and sculptures displayed neatly. Around them, the artworks subtly glow or have sparkles to suggest a sense of ''internal order'' or special quality. The gallery should have frames, pedestals, and classic art pieces, like a framed abstract painting, a marble bust, and a modern sculpture. The person wears casual but artistic clothing (such as a beret and a scarf) to suggest their love for art. Include a small caption or thought bubble above their head containing the phrase: ''Art for Art’s sake.'' The overall tone is humorous and whimsical, with exaggerated expressions and a clean, simple cartoon style. Avoid any elements that are violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (2059, 'Art Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Romance Humor', 'Love is a canvas furnished by Nature and embroidered by imagination.', 'Voltaire', 'A whimsical cartoon scene featuring a large blank painter''s canvas set on an easel outdoors in a natural setting. The background shows trees, flowers, a bright sun, and clouds to represent ''Nature.'' Surrounding the canvas are nature-themed elements like birds, butterflies, and blooming plants. A cheerful artist character stands beside the canvas holding a colorful embroidery hoop and needle, stitching colorful, imaginative patterns like hearts, stars, swirls, and playful shapes onto the blank canvas. The artist has a joyful, inspired expression. The scene has a light, playful cartoon style with vibrant colors, emphasizing creativity and romance without any people explicitly shown in a romantic act—just the metaphorical representation of love through art and nature combined. Small details might include a paint palette with natural colors and embroidery thread spools in bright hues. The overall tone is uplifting, imaginative, and poetic, suitable for a humorous but tender interpretation of the idea that love is both natural and creatively enriched by imagination.'),
 (2348, 'Art Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'The most beautiful thing we can experience is the mysterious. It is the source of all true art and science.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'Draw a whimsical, cartoon-style scene where a wide-eyed person stands in front of a large, glowing mysterious object shrouded in swirling mist or sparkles. The setting is an art studio merged with a science lab, featuring an easel with a half-finished colorful abstract painting on one side and scientific equipment like a microscope and open books on the other side. The person looks fascinated and inspired, with lightbulbs and little stars floating above their head to indicate creativity and discovery. The background should be bright and inviting, emphasizing wonder and curiosity, with elements like paintbrushes, test tubes, and sheet music scattered around to represent different forms of art and science. The overall tone is playful and magical, highlighting the beauty of mystery as the spark for creativity and exploration.'),
 (3262, 'Art Humor, Pun, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call an imaginary color? A pigment of your imagination', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an artist’s palette with vibrant colors on it. In the center, a thought bubble emerges from the palette, containing a colorful, swirling cloud labeled ''Imaginary Color.'' Nearby, the artist—wearing a beret and holding a paintbrush—looks puzzled and amused while staring at the cloud. Around the palette, include tiny humorously exaggerated paint tubes labeled with typical colors like red, blue, green, but one tube is transparent or glowing faintly with a question mark on it. The background should be simple, like an art studio with an easel, canvas, and paint splatters on the floor. The overall style is playful and cartoonish with clear, bold outlines and bright colors to emphasize the creative and imaginative theme without any violence or political elements.'),
 (2665, 'Art Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'Baroque: what happens when you''re out of Monet.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set inside a classic art museum gallery. On one side, depict a frustrated artist or visitor standing near an empty, plain wooden frame labeled ''Monet''—indicating there is no Monet artwork present. On the other side, show a baroque-style painting frame overflowing with exaggerated ornate gold curls, swirls, and floral decorations, with the word ''Baroque'' artistically written on or near it. The person looks confused or puzzled, scratching their head or shrugging, searching for a Monet painting but only finding an overly elaborate Baroque piece. Include subtle details like a museum plaque on the wall, a bench, and maybe a small sign that says ''Out of Monet.'' The style should be bright, colorful, and caricature-like to enhance the pun and visual joke, keeping the tone light and playful without any violent or sensitive elements.'),
 (156, 'Art Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'We were state-of-the-art, but the art moved to a different state.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a modern, sleek art gallery labeled ''State-of-the-Art Gallery''. The gallery looks very high-tech and polished with shiny floors, digital screens, and contemporary sculptures. In front of the gallery is a large map of the United States with the gallery located in one state (e.g., California). From the gallery, various pieces of framed artwork, sculptures, and paintings are shown physically moving off the gallery walls and out of the building, animated with happy faces or tiny legs as if they are walking or floating. These artworks are heading towards another state on the map (e.g., New York), where a new bustling art scene is depicted with another gallery labeled ''New Art State'', with excited people admiring the incoming art. The overall mood is playful, with exaggerated expressions on the art pieces and a sunny background. The style is bright and cartoonish with clear labels on the buildings and map for clarity, emphasizing the pun that ''the art moved to a different state,'' both geographically and conceptually.'),
 (1593, 'Art Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'But that''s what being an artist _is_ -- feeling crummy before everyone else feels crummy.', 'New Yorker', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a tired artist sitting in a cluttered, cozy studio. The artist looks a bit disheveled and weary, slumped in a wooden chair in front of an easel holding a half-finished, moody painting. Around the studio, depict various art supplies such as paintbrushes, palettes, tubes of paint, and crumpled sketches scattered on a table and floor. The background includes a window showing a gloomy sky, hinting at a sad or ''crummy'' mood outside. The artist has a slightly exaggerated sad or pensive expression, maybe with dark circles under their eyes. A speech bubble or sign near the artist reads, "Being an artist is feeling crummy before everyone else does." The overall tone is light-hearted and charming, emphasizing the artist''s emotional sensitivity in a funny, relatable way. Use soft, muted colors to reflect the mood, but keep it visually engaging and cartoonish rather than somber.'),
 (2295, 'Art Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Wit', 'The difference between art and science is that science is what we understand well enough to explain it to a computer. Art is everything else.', 'Donald Knuth', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, depict a friendly-looking scientist in a white lab coat standing next to a chalkboard filled with clear, neat formulas and diagrams, holding a large book titled ''Science Explained to Computers.'' Beside the scientist, a friendly robot or computer with a smiling digital face is attentively listening or taking notes. On the right side, show a colorful, whimsical artist in a paint-splattered smock, holding a paintbrush with vivid paint dripping onto a chaotic canvas filled with abstract shapes, swirls, and splashes of color. Around the artist, place various art tools like a palette, crayons, and clay sculptures. The background should reflect contrast: the science side is clean and orderly, while the art side is messy and creative. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the difference between structured science and freeform art, without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2655, 'Art Humor, Religious Humor, Unknown, Wit', 'Art is a collaboration between God an the artist, and the less the artist does the better.', 'Andre Gide', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an artist in a paint-splattered smock standing in front of a giant canvas on an easel. The canvas is mostly blank except for a tiny, glowing spark or aura at the center representing divine inspiration. Above the artist, a friendly, benevolent-looking God figure, depicted cartoon-style with a white beard, flowing robes, and a gentle smile, lightly guides the artist''s hand from the clouds. The artist looks happily surprised and relaxed, with a paintbrush loosely held and a minimal stroke painted on the canvas. Around them are typical art supplies like paint tubes, brushes, and palettes, but most are untouched, emphasizing that the artist did very little. The background is a bright, airy art studio with windows showing a sunny sky. The overall tone is light, playful, and whimsical, emphasizing the joke that the less the artist does, the better the collaboration turns out to be.'),
 (1481, 'Artificial Intelligence Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'A year spent in artificial intelligence is enough to make one believe in God.', 'Alan J. Perlis', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bewildered human figure standing in a futuristic laboratory filled with AI-themed gadgets. The person looks dazed, with wide eyes, scratching their head while staring at a complex robot or computer screen displaying intricate code and neural network patterns. Nearby, a large calendar or wall digital display shows a full year circled or highlighted. Above the person, a glowing question mark and a subtle glowing halo hover, symbolizing sudden belief or questioning of God. The background should enhance the sci-fi/artificial intelligence vibe with wires, screens, and robotic arms but maintain a light, non-threatening, comical atmosphere. Include a small thought bubble from the person saying something like "Maybe there is a God?". The style should be colorful, lively, and cartoonish to emphasize the joke’s ironic and lighthearted tone without any dark or serious elements.'),
 (2975, 'Astrology Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I don''t believe in horoscopes...but, of course, that''s typical of a Taurus.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene centered around an amused person, mid-30s, with a skeptical but playful expression, holding a horoscope newspaper or smartphone showing zodiac signs. Above their head is a visible thought bubble with the Taurus zodiac symbol (a bull''s head emblem). Surrounding the person are subtle whimsical elements, like stars, moons, astrological charts, and maybe a small, cartoonish bull wearing glasses and looking mischievous. The setting is casual—a cozy living room or café table with a coffee cup, adding a relaxed vibe. The style is light, colorful, and playful, emphasizing the irony of rejecting horoscopes despite the sign indicating Taurus, known for stubbornness, making the joke clear without violence or negativity.'),
 (157, 'Aviation, Bad Puns, Good Question!, Jobs', 'Do pilots take crash-courses?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a confused pilot standing beside a small airplane on a runway. The pilot is wearing a classic pilot''s uniform with a hat and sunglasses, scratching their head in puzzlement. Next to the pilot is a large, colorful book titled "Crash Courses" with an image of a plane on the cover. Around them are speech bubbles with question marks, emphasizing confusion. The background is a simple airport runway with a control tower far in the distance, and the sky is clear and bright. The overall style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the pun in the joke about ''crash courses.'' No violent or serious elements – just a fun take on wordplay involving pilots and learning courses.')
INSERT INTO @tmpJokes (JokeId, Categories, JokeTxt, Attribution, ImageTxt) VALUES
 (2455, 'Aviation, Classic Joke, Historical Humor, Quotes', 'This fellow Charles Lindbergh will never make it. He''s doomed.', 'Harry Guggenheim, millionaire aviation enthusiast.', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing an old-fashioned 1920s airfield. In the foreground, a man dressed in period-appropriate clothes with a skeptical and dismissive expression is pointing at a classic, single-engine biplane preparing for takeoff. Nearby, a young Charles Lindbergh, confidently dressed in pilot gear (goggles, leather jacket), is standing next to his plane, smiling determinedly and ready for flight. The plane is visibly worn but sturdy, and a small crowd of onlookers watches with mixed expressions of doubt and curiosity. Include a signpost reading ''Spirit of St. Louis'' next to the plane. The sky is bright and clear, emphasizing the hopeful yet doubtful mood. The artwork should have exaggerated cartoon features, with characters sporting big heads and expressive faces. The overall tone is lighthearted and captures the irony of the dismissive comment about Lindbergh''s chances of success, without any negativity toward the characters.'),
 (3205, 'Awards Humor, Irony, Pun, Steven Wright', 'I''d kill for a Nobel Peace Prize.', 'Steven Wright', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a well-dressed, mild-mannered person standing on a stage at an awards ceremony. The person has a big grin and is holding a large, shiny Nobel Peace Prize trophy. Behind them is a banner that says ''Nobel Peace Prize Ceremony.'' The background should show an applauding audience looking both surprised and amused. To emphasize the joke, include a thought bubble above the person’s head with a playful, exaggerated grimace showing the internal phrase ''I’d kill for a Nobel Peace Prize'' with a crossed-out image of a weapon or a cartoonish ''no violence'' symbol for humor and clarity. Make sure the style is lighthearted and cartoonish, using bright colors and soft lines to keep it funny and non-threatening. The setting is formal but the expression and thought bubble add comedic irony.'),
 (158, 'Bad Puns, Bathroom Humor, Don''t Say It!', 'Poop jokes aren''t my favorite, but they''re a solid #2', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly, smiling number 2 character standing upright with arms and legs. The number 2 is made to look lively and cheerful, maybe with cartoon eyes and a big grin. Next to it, place a simple cartoon poop emoji with a similarly friendly face, looking slightly embarrassed or shy. They are standing side by side on a plain background, perhaps with a subtle joke setting like a bathroom door labeled ''Restroom'' in the background or a hint of bathroom tiles. The overall vibe should be lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the pun on ''solid #2'' with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor.'),
 (658, 'Bad Puns, Bathroom Humor, Everyday Life, Good Question!', 'Why was the toilet paper rolling down the mountain? To get to the bottom.', NULL, 'Draw a funny cartoon scene of a roll of toilet paper rolling down a green mountain slope. The toilet paper should have a cheerful face with big eyes and a wide smile, arms flailing playfully as it tumbles. The mountain is moderately steep with grass and a few small, colorful flowers scattered around. In the background, show a bright blue sky with a shining yellow sun and a couple of fluffy white clouds. At the bottom of the mountain, draw a literal large ''bottom'' shaped like a cartoon butt with a happy expression waiting for the toilet paper to arrive. The overall scene should look light-hearted, colorful, and humorous, using exaggerated proportions and expressions to amplify the silliness of the joke.'),
 (2941, 'Bad Puns, Bathroom Humor, Language, Unknown', 'How do you say constipated in German.....  Far-from-poopin', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused person holding a German-English dictionary or phrasebook, looking puzzled as they try to say a German word. Near them, illustrate a speech bubble with the phrase ''Far-from-poopin'' spelled out comically. To emphasize the joke, include a toilet or bathroom sign nearby, subtly indicating the subject of constipation, but keep it light-hearted and playful. The person should have a funny, slightly strained expression, with a comic squiggle or sweat drop to show frustration or discomfort. The background can be simple and colorful, typical of a cartoon style, with exaggerated features to enhance the humor and keep the tone friendly and goofy.'),
 (2952, 'Bad Puns, Bathroom Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I accidentally swallowed some Scrabble pieces - I am NOT looking forward to my next vowel movement. My next dump could spell disaster.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting nervously on a bathroom toilet, clutching their stomach with a worried expression. Around them, scattered on the floor and nearby surfaces, are colorful Scrabble tiles with letters on them. Some tiles could be floating midair as if just swallowed. Above the person''s head is a thought bubble showing a mix of vowels and consonants, with the vowels looking like little characters anxiously waiting to move. The bathroom should look bright and clean with humorous details like a bathroom magazine titled ''Word Games Weekly'' or a Scrabble board leaning against the wall. Make the style light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun and the awkward situation without any unpleasant or graphic elements. The overall tone should focus on wordplay and gentle embarrassment rather than anything gross or offensive.'),
 (3010, 'Bad Puns, Books, Unknown, Word Play', 'I just picked up a book called ''Glue in Many Lands'' and I can''t put it down.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a person sitting comfortably in an armchair, holding a book titled ''Glue in Many Lands'' with a sticky mess of glue visibly oozing out of the pages, causing the book to literally stick to the person''s hands. The person looks both amused and frustrated, unable to let go of the book. Around them, include a couple of small sticky notes or glue bottles on a nearby table to emphasize the sticky theme. The scene should be colorful and exaggerated in classic cartoon style, with lighthearted facial expressions and exaggerated sticky glue texture to highlight the pun.'),
 (159, 'Bad Puns, Camping', 'Let sleeping bags lie.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors at a campsite. In the foreground, a couple of brightly colored sleeping bags lie on the grass, looking slightly puffed up as if they are ''sleeping'' creatures. Nearby, a camper character tiptoes carefully past them with wide eyes and a finger held up to their lips, signaling to be quiet. The background includes a simple tent, a campfire with small flames but no smoke, and a few trees under a clear night sky with twinkling stars. The overall tone is light and playful, emphasizing the pun on ''Let sleeping bags lie,'' visually representing the idea that the sleeping bags are left undisturbed, with the camper humorously treating them as if they were alive and sleeping. Draw everything in bright, cartoonish colors with exaggerated expressions to enhance the joke''s charm and make the scene whimsical and inviting.'),
 (160, 'Bad Puns, Camping, Word Play', 'You can''t run through a campsite. You can only ran. Because it''s past tents.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a campsite with a cheeky play on words. In the foreground, a person mid-run looks confused and slightly frustrated as they try to run through a campsite entrance. The campsite entrance is marked by a sign that says ''Campsite'' and a large wooden gate with several colorful tents pitched beyond it. Nearby, a small campsite map is shown with a dotted path leading through the ''tents'' area. To emphasize the pun, an anthropomorphic tent with eyes and a smirking face stands blocking the runner’s path, holding out a hand to signal ''stop.'' The runner is cut off mid-stride, and a speech bubble coming from the tent says, "You can''t run here, it''s past tents!" The sky is bright and sunny, with some trees and campfires in the background to set the outdoorsy vibe. The overall art style is light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke.'),
 (1232, 'Bad Puns, Career Humor, Jobs', 'I used to be a banker, but then I lost interest.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a former banker standing sadly outside a bank building. The bank looks like a classic stone building with large pillars and a big sign reading ''BANK''. The banker is a middle-aged person in a suit, holding a giant, comically oversized bank ledger or interest rate document, with pages flying away or disappearing to emphasize ''losing interest.'' The expression on the banker''s face is a mix of disappointment and comic resignation. Around them, dollar signs or percentage symbols are fading or evaporating from the air, symbolizing the loss of financial interest. The background can include a small, lighthearted cityscape or street to add context without clutter, drawn in a bright, colorful, and simple cartoon style to keep the tone light and funny.'),
 (161, 'Bad Puns, Cartoon, Food Humor', 'In the army of corny jokes, I''m the kernel', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon scene featuring a small army of anthropomorphic popcorn kernels dressed in military uniforms. The central figure is a proud, smiling popcorn kernel standing confidently at attention, wearing a general''s hat and holding a tiny flag with a corny joke symbol (like a smiling ear of corn). Surrounding this ''kernel'' are other popcorn kernels in soldier gear, some with goofy expressions, some mid-popping into fluffy popcorn. The background should look like a whimsical battlefield made of popcorn boxes and popcorn bags scattered around. Use bright, cheerful colors and a lighthearted, humorous cartoon style to emphasize the pun on ''army'' and ''kernel.'' Avoid any weapons or violence; the focus is on cute popcorn characters in a playful military setting.'),
 (626, 'Bad Puns, Cartoon, Good Question!, Workplace', 'Why did the ax factory have to close? They had too many ax-idents.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a small, bustling ax factory. The factory floor is filled with cartoonish machinery designed to make axes, with logs, axe handles, and sharp blades scattered around. Several axes are drawn with cute, exaggerated faces showing surprise or minor bumps and scratches, indicating ''accidents.'' There are piles of broken wood and smashed axe parts humorously strewn about. A factory worker, wearing a hard hat and factory uniform, scratches their head with a confused yet amused expression while holding a sign that reads ''Closed due to too many ax-idents.'' In the background, a large clock on the wall humorously shows quitting time. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the pun without any danger or negativity.'),
 (162, 'Bad Puns, Cartoon, Word Play', 'I heard Swedish war ships have bar codes on the sides. That way, when they return to port, they can Scandinavian', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, classic Swedish warship docked at a bustling harbor. The ship''s hull is humorously covered with big black and white barcode stripes running vertically, resembling a supermarket barcode. Nearby, a couple of dock workers wearing typical uniforms look amused or puzzled, holding clipboard and scanners as if they are scanning the ship. One of them holds a handheld scanner beeping as it points at the barcode on the ship. In the background, a signpost reads ''Swedish Naval Base'' in a simple font. The water is calm, and seagulls fly overhead. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the dock workers and the ship''s barcode clearly visible and central to the image. No violence or complexity, just a playful scene blending naval imagery with a grocery-store barcode concept.'),
 (163, 'Bad Puns, Christmas', 'Did you know Santa has a 10th reindeer named Olive? It''s in that Rudolph song - you know - ''Olive the other reindeer''', NULL, 'Draw a cheerful cartoon scene featuring Santa Claus in his traditional red suit and hat, standing next to his sleigh filled with presents. In front of the sleigh, show nine classic reindeer pulling it, but in the center, instead of a reindeer, draw a cute, whimsical olive with tiny reindeer antlers and a red nose, playfully blending in with the other reindeer. Make the olive slightly anthropomorphic, with big expressive eyes and a smile. Above them, include a musical note or a speech bubble referencing the famous Rudolph song lyric "Olive, the other reindeer." The background should be a snowy night sky with stars to set a festive Christmas mood. The overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and humorous, emphasizing the pun visually.'),
 (164, 'Bad Puns, Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris can start a fire with an ice cube.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in the center. He is holding a small, clear, shiny ice cube in one hand, with a playful smirk on his face. In front of him, a small campfire ignites instantly, with bright, warm orange and yellow flames licking upward from the ice cube itself, despite the obvious contradiction. Around him are symbolic outdoor elements like a simple log bench, a few rocks forming a campfire circle, and a backdrop of trees or a wilderness area to suggest a camping setting. Chuck is drawn with exaggerated strong features and a rugged look—mustache, bandana, and a cowboy-style shirt—to accentuate the classic Chuck Norris meme vibe. The style should be colorful, cheerful, and in a lighthearted cartoon style, emphasizing the impossible nature of starting a fire with ice, making the scene amusing and exaggerated without any danger or negativity.'),
 (165, 'Bad Puns, Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris does not hunt because the word hunting implies the possibility of failure. Chuck Norris goes killing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in a rugged outdoor setting. He is muscular and wearing a cowboy hat, with a serious but slightly exaggerated determined expression. Around him are scattered hunting gear like a bow, rifle, and a camouflage backpack lying unused on the ground. In the background, instead of animals hiding or running, cartoon animals (like a deer, rabbit, and boar) are cartoonishly scared and fleeing in all directions. The caption or a thought bubble above Chuck Norris reads, ''I don''t hunt... I go killing.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing Chuck Norris''s legendary tough persona without any violence shown explicitly. Draw in a colorful, clean cartoon style with exaggerated expressions and dynamic motion lines to show the fleeing animals'' panic.'),
 (166, 'Bad Puns, Computers, Office Humor, Puns', 'To whoever took my Microsoft Office: I will find you. You have my Word.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an office environment. In the foreground, a frustrated office worker stands with crossed arms, wearing business casual clothes, staring at an empty desk where a computer monitor and keyboard should be. A sticky note is prominently stuck on the desk or monitor stand that says ''To whoever took my Microsoft Office: I will find you. You have my Word.'' In the background, subtle visual hints show missing icons labeled ''Word,'' ''Excel,'' and ''PowerPoint'' floating away like little cartoon characters or ghostly app icons flying out an open window. The atmosphere is light and amusing, with exaggerated facial expressions and playful details like a spilled coffee cup or scattered papers to add to the chaos, but no violence or negativity. The style is colorful, simple, and whimsical to emphasize the pun on Microsoft Office and Word.'),
 (167, 'Bad Puns, Computers, Word Play', 'Off the modem, through the phone line, nothing but Net.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a whimsical, old-fashioned telephone line running across the image. On one end, there''s a vintage modem with blinking lights, depicted with a small face looking confused or tired. The telephone line stretches out like a path or tunnel leading to a net (like a fishnet) hanging in the air or caught between two poles. The net should look empty and a bit lonely. Surrounding the net and modem, there could be subtle digital or internet-related icons (like small Wi-Fi symbols or pixel fragments) to emphasize the pun on ''Net.'' The overall style is light, colorful, and humorous, with exaggerated expressions on the modem to convey its frustration or resignation about being ''off the modem'' and ending up with ''nothing but Net.'' There should be no people, just the tech items anthropomorphized for comedic effect.'),
 (1175, 'Bad Puns, Cooking Humor, Insults, Word Play', 'If you were a spice, you''d be flour.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two anthropomorphic kitchen ingredients standing next to each other on a kitchen countertop. One character is a cheerful spice jar with a bright colorful label clearly marked ''Spice''—it looks vibrant, with sparkles or stars around it to emphasize its spicy personality. Next to it, an embarrassed-looking bag of white flour with simple eyes and a shy smile, maybe with a little blush on its cheeks to show it''s a little out of place next to the spice. The background shows typical kitchen items like a rolling pin, measuring spoons, and a mixing bowl. The style is light-hearted and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to convey humor. The spice jar could be striking a confident pose, while the flour bag stands awkwardly, highlighting the joke that flour is not really a spice but is humorously included in that category here.'),
 (168, 'Bad Puns, Cooking Humor, Life', 'Jim''s bachelor cooking tip #2: If you put food in a Tupperware container and put it in the dishwasher, you can cook the food while you do the dishes!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a messy bachelor apartment kitchen. Center the image on a grinning young man named Jim, wearing a casual T-shirt and apron, standing proudly next to an open dishwasher. Inside the dishwasher, instead of dishes, there''s a transparent Tupperware container with visible, cartoon-style food inside (like pasta or a sandwich). Steam is rising from the container to show cooking in progress. Around the kitchen, include typical bachelor mess: a few empty pizza boxes, dirty dishes piled up nearby, and a sink full of soapy water. The background should feature a simple tiled wall and a kitchen counter with a coffee mug and a dirty sponge. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated for comic effect, emphasizing Jim''s proud yet lazy cooking hack. No people besides Jim, no violence or complex detail needed; just a clean, funny snapshot of his quirky life hack.'),
 (169, 'Bad Puns, Dad, Food Humor, Workplace', 'The CEO of Pepsi was fired this morning. He tested positive for coke.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a business office with a surprised CEO sitting at a large desk labeled ''Pepsi.'' The CEO is a middle-aged man in a business suit, looking shocked with wide eyes and raised eyebrows. On the desk is a big soda bottle clearly labeled ''Pepsi.'' Standing next to the CEO is a friendly-looking doctor or lab technician holding a clipboard that reads ''Test Results'' with a positive ''+'' sign next to a smaller bottle labeled ''Coke.'' In the background, a bulletin board or whiteboard shows the word ''Fired!'' in big red letters. The office has a few playful soda-related decorations like a Pepsi logo poster and a cup with a straw. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun on the word ''coke'' as both a drug test and the rival soda brand, with no aggressive or negative elements in the scene.'),
 (170, 'Bad Puns, Dad, Good Question!', 'If you have half as much fun reading these cookies as we had assembling them, then we had twice as much fun as you.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a cheerful group of diverse people sitting around a table cluttered with puzzle pieces shaped like giant fortune cookies. Some people are laughing and fitting puzzle pieces together, while others hold up a finished cookie proudly. On the table, a stack of oversized fortune cookies is visible. Above the group, a large whimsical banner reads: ''Half as much fun reading these as we had assembling them!'' The atmosphere is casual and lighthearted, with playful facial expressions and exaggerated movements to emphasize the fun of assembling the cookies. The background is simple with warm colors and a few scattered confetti pieces to highlight the joyful mood.'),
 (171, 'Bad Puns, Dad, Good Question!, Humor', 'If you do something tonight that you''ll regret in the morning---sleep late!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bedroom early in the morning with a cozy bed in the center. The main character is a person happily sleeping in, snuggled under the covers with a big smile on their face and a relaxed posture. On the bedside table, there''s an alarm clock showing a late morning time (like 11:00 AM). A window reveals bright sunlight streaming in, indicating it''s well past the usual waking hour. To add to the humor, include a small thought bubble above the sleeper with the text: ''Best regret ever!'' The room should have light, cheerful colors and a warm atmosphere to emphasize comfort and relaxation. No other people should be in the scene, and nothing violent or inappropriate. The overall vibe is lighthearted and relatable, emphasizing the joke’s idea that sleeping late is a harmless regret.'),
 (172, 'Bad Puns, Dad, Humor, Insults', 'If you lend someone $20, and you never see that person again, it was probably worth it.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual setting, like a small park bench or a street corner. On one side, a person looks slightly annoyed but resigned, holding an empty wallet or a torn twenty-dollar bill with a sad face. On the other side, the second character is happily walking away quickly, looking over their shoulder with a mischievous grin and waving goodbye. Include visual cues like the money clearly shown as borrowed, a speech bubble above the annoyed character saying, ''If you lend someone $20...'' and a thought bubble above the departing character implying they won’t be seen again. Make the style lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated facial expressions and bright, simple colors to emphasize the joke’s humor without any negativity or violence.'),
 (173, 'Bad Puns, Dad, Humor, Word Play', 'I really feel like I have a bad posture. I have a hunch.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a character, standing slightly hunched over with exaggerated bad posture to highlight their discomfort. The character could be an ordinary adult wearing casual clothes, with a visible ''hunch'' on their back that looks like a small bump or lump shaped like a question mark, to visually represent the pun. The character has a puzzled or slightly concerned expression on their face, maybe holding their lower back with one hand. The background is simple, like a plain room or park setting, with no additional characters or objects distracting from the scene. Use a lighthearted, cartoonish style with bright colors and clear outlines to keep the mood funny and light, rather than serious.'),
 (174, 'Bad Puns, Dad, Puns', 'When does a bad pun become a dad joke? When it becomes apparent', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large pun-themed courtroom or science lab labeled ''Pun Lab'' with a giant shining light bulb above it to signify ''apparent.'' In the center, a bad pun character personified as a goofy, sad-looking pun with googly eyes and a frown is crossing an imaginary line titled ''Dad Joke Threshold.'' Nearby, a cheerful dad figure with a thumbs-up and a classic ''Dad'' hat is pointing at the pun, smiling and perhaps rolling his eyes. Surrounding them are floating, oversized word bubbles containing silly puns and dad joke elements, with the word ''Apparent'' brightly highlighted. The background is colorful and playful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions and simple props like a big magnifying glass or pun-related symbols such as a banana peel or cheese wedge to emphasize humor without any violence or politics.'),
 (175, 'Bad Puns, Did''ya Hear', 'Did''ya hear about the guy who broke both his left arm and left leg? He''s all right now.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man with crutches and a sling supporting his left arm and a cast on his left leg. He is smiling confidently and giving a thumbs-up with his right hand. The setting is a simple doctor’s office or waiting room with a small chair, a medical poster on the wall showing a human skeleton with left limbs highlighted, and a calendar. The man’s left arm and leg appear obviously injured, yet he looks cheerful and relaxed, emphasizing the pun. A speech bubble above him says, "I''m all right now!". The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated to highlight the joke without any grim or serious tone.'),
 (176, 'Bad Puns, Did''ya Hear, Humor', 'Did''ya hear about the guy who got hit in the head with a can of soda? He was lucky it was a soft drink.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a slightly dazed man standing with a surprised and confused expression on his face. Above his head, a smiling, anthropomorphic can of soda is gently bouncing off him, depicted with soft motion lines to indicate it''s not hard or painful. The soda can has big friendly eyes and a playful grin, emphasizing it as a ''soft drink.'' Around them is a simple urban or park background with a few bushes and a bench to keep the scene light and relatable. The man''s hair is slightly ruffled from the gentle impact. The style is bright and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the joke''s pun. No harsh or violent imagery, just playful and cartoonish interaction between the man and the ''soft'' soda can.'),
 (177, 'Bad Puns, Did''ya Hear, Movies, Word Play', 'Did''ya hear about the movie ''Constipation''? No? That''s because it hasn''t come out yet', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room with a classic movie poster stand prominently displaying a poster titled ''Constipation''. The poster shows a lock with chains over an old-fashioned film reel, symbolizing the movie being ''locked'' or ''not released''. Nearby, a confused person with exaggerated puzzled expression is scratching their head or looking around, clearly unaware of the movie. Include subtle visual puns like a calendar on the wall with the current date circled and a toilet paper roll on a side table to hint at the theme without being explicit. Use bright colors, rounded lines, and lighthearted character design for a family-friendly, approachable, and funny feel.'),
 (178, 'Bad Puns, Did''ya Hear, Pessimistic', 'If we can''t fix it, it ain''t broke.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person casually sitting on a broken, visibly cracked chair with one leg shorter than the others, causing it to wobble heavily. The person appears completely relaxed and unconcerned, perhaps sipping a cup of coffee or reading a newspaper. Nearby, a friend or another person looks puzzled or confused, staring at the chair’s broken leg. The setting is a simple living room with a small side table and a floor lamp. There should be a speech bubble above the relaxed person saying, ''If we can''t fix it, it ain''t broke.'' The overall tone is light and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of ignoring the problem because it hasn’t been fixed yet. The style should be colorful and cartoonish, with clean lines and a comedic, cheerful vibe.'),
 (179, 'Bad Puns, Don''t Say It!, Food Humor', 'I was going to share a vegetable joke, but it''s corny', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful ear of corn standing upright with a big, friendly grin. The corn should have cartoonish eyes and arms, holding a microphone as if about to tell a joke on a small stage. Around it are audience members that are various vegetables like a smiling carrot, a broccoli with glasses, and a tomato laughing. The background shows a simple comedy club setting with a small spotlight over the corn and a brick wall behind. Include a small sign on the wall reading ''Vegetable Comedy Night.'' The overall mood is light and funny, emphasizing the pun ''corny'' through the main character being literally corn ready to deliver a joke but hesitating.'),
 (180, 'Bad Puns, Don''t Say It!, Health Humor, Humor', 'People think my diabetic jokes are harsh, but hey - it''s not like I can sugarcoat them', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing at a comedy club stage with a microphone. The backdrop has a sign saying ''Comedy Night''. The person should have a playful smirk and be gesturing with one hand while holding the microphone in the other. Nearby, a big sugar cube shaped like a microphone stand is melting, with droplets running down to the floor. Around the stage, a few audience members are shown either groaning, laughing nervously, or shaking their heads. Include a small diabetic test kit and an insulin pen casually resting on a stool next to the comedian. The overall vibe should be lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the pun about not being able to ''sugarcoat'' the jokes. Avoid any dark or serious tones.'),
 (181, 'Bad Puns, Don''t Say It!, Humor, Word Play', 'I don''t make jokes about unemployed people, because they never work', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stand-up comedian on a small stage with a microphone in hand, smiling and delivering the joke. In the audience, there are a few characters representing unemployed people, sitting in chairs looking surprised but not offended. The backdrop shows a simple comedy club setting with a ''Comedy Night'' sign and a spotlight on the comedian. The comedian''s speech bubble reads, "I don''t make jokes about unemployed people, because they never work." The overall tone is light and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the pun.'),
 (182, 'Bad Puns, Don''t Say It!, Sports Humor', 'I''m not a big fan of archery - it has too many drawbacks', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of a cheerful cartoon character standing next to an archery target. The target is full of arrows stuck in it, but some arrows are humorously bent, broken, or stuck in awkward places like the floor or the character''s quiver. The character is holding a bow limply with a slightly disappointed or unimpressed expression, shrugging their shoulders. A speech bubble above the character reads, ''I''m not a big fan of archery - it has too many drawbacks.'' In the background, include a few comical ''drawbacks'' such as arrows bouncing off tough objects like trees or arrows tangled in a nearby bush. The scene should be bright and colorful, emphasizing the lighthearted and silly nature of the pun without any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (183, 'Bad Puns, Dyslexics, Humor', 'Did''ya know there''s a special razor for dyslexics? It''s the best thing since sliced beard', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful man standing in front of a bathroom mirror holding a razor. Above him is a sign or label on the razor box that reads ''Special Razor for Dyslexics.'' The man has a neatly trimmed beard, but his beard is humorously sliced like a loaf of bread, with each slice separated and slightly floating apart to emphasize the pun. The bathroom setting includes a sink with shaving foam, a towel hanging nearby, and a small loaf of sliced bread on the counter for visual comparison. The man’s expression is proud and amused, as if excited about his new razor. The overall atmosphere is light and comical with vibrant colors and exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the pun ''sliced beard'' playing off ''sliced bread.'' No other characters or complex backgrounds are needed to keep the focus on the joke.'),
 (184, 'Bad Puns, Dyslexics, Word Play', 'If life gives you melons you may be dyslexic', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing outdoors under a bright sun, holding a large watermelon in one hand. The character has a puzzled or slightly confused expression while looking at the watermelon. Nearby, a speech bubble shows the phrase: "If life gives you melons you may be dyslexic." Around the person, a few other assorted fruits (like lemons and apples) lie on the grass to emphasize the play on words. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bold, simple lines and bright colors to create a fun comic vibe.'),
 (185, 'Bad Puns, Engineers, Good Question!', 'If you only have a hammer, you tend to see every problem as a nail.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in the middle of a room cluttered with various objects representing different problems. The person, looking slightly confused or determined, is holding a large, oversized hammer in both hands. Surrounding them are objects like a computer with a cracked screen, a leaky faucet dripping water, a broken clock showing the wrong time, and a flat tire leaning against a wall. Each object has a little label or symbol hinting at its problem. The person is about to hit one of these non-nail objects with the hammer, implying they''re trying to solve every problem the same way. The style is bright and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and playful details to emphasize the humor and absurdity without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1188, 'Bad Puns, Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'May you always step in a wet spot after putting on fresh socks', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing indoors with visible discomfort. The character wears brightly colored fresh socks—clearly new and clean, perhaps with a little tag or shimmer indicating freshness. Their facial expression shows surprise and mild annoyance. One foot is awkwardly stepping into a clearly wet spot on the floor, depicted with shiny blue puddles or droplets and ripples around the foot. Around the person’s legs, little motion lines emphasize a sudden, unexpected step. The setting is a simple home hallway or living room with a doormat nearby, enhancing the idea of freshly put on socks and an unexpected wetness. The overall art style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with cartoonish features like big eyes and expressive poses to capture the amusing misery of the moment. The background is clean and simple, keeping the focus on the socks, the wet spot, and the character''s reaction.'),
 (3072, 'Bad Puns, Everyday Life, Objects Humor, Unknown', 'If at first you don''t succeed, get new batteries.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person trying to turn on a small, handheld electronic device like a remote control or a flashlight that is not working. The person is holding the device with one hand and has an empty battery compartment visible in the other. Nearby, there is a small open box of fresh batteries with a few batteries scattered around. The person''s expression should be exaggeratedly annoyed or puzzled, as if they''ve been trying unsuccessfully to make the device work. The background is simple and clean to keep the focus on the character and the device. The style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the funny idea that the problem is just dead batteries rather than the person''s skill or effort.'),
 (1824, 'Bad Puns, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I know I can quit smoking because I''ve done it a thousand times.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently with a big smile, holding a broken cigarette in one hand. Around them, there are multiple empty cigarette packs scattered on the ground, some thrown into a nearby trash can labeled ''Quit Attempts.'' Above the person’s head is a thought bubble featuring a calendar with many crossed-off days, emphasizing repeated tries. The background should be simple, like a living room or a park, with a casual vibe. The person’s expression and pose should convey a mix of irony and optimism, highlighting the joke’s self-deprecating humor about repeatedly quitting smoking.'),
 (2995, 'Bad Puns, Everyday Life, Unknown, Word Play', 'I hate it when people ask me what I''ll be doing in 5 years. C''mon - I don''t have 2020 vision!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a frustrated person standing in the center, holding a large, comically oversized eye chart typically seen at an optometrist''s office. The eye chart displays ''2020'' in big bold letters near the top. The person has a puzzled and slightly annoyed expression, scratching their head while looking at the chart. Around them, little thought bubbles show question marks and a calendar with ''5 years'' highlighted, emphasizing the confusion about the future. The background is a simple doctor''s office with an eye test machine and a couple of playful details, like a pair of glasses hanging from a string and a clock on the wall. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial features, bright colors, and expressive lines to amplify the joke about not having "2020 vision" to predict the future 5 years ahead. No violent, sexual, or political elements included.'),
 (2999, 'Bad Puns, Everyday Life, Unknown, Word Play', 'I have a pen that can write underwater. It can also write other words too.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person underwater wearing snorkeling gear (mask and snorkel), holding a large, exaggerated pen. The pen is mid-air with blue water bubbles and wavy lines around it indicating it''s underwater. The person looks proud and excited while writing the word ''Hello'' on an underwater notepad or a floating sheet of paper. Around them are cute sea creatures like a curious fish and a smiling crab watching the person write. The background is an underwater setting with light rays filtering through the water and some seaweed gently swaying. The style is colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of a pen that can write underwater but can also write other words too, adding a silly and playful vibe to the scene.'),
 (186, 'Bad Puns, Facts, Humor', 'There are 3 kinds of people: those who can count and those who can''t.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of people. On the left, a small group of three people confidently counting on their fingers with happy expressions. On the right, another group looking confused and frustrated, scratching their heads or holding a calculator upside down. Above them floats a large, playful text that reads: ''There are 3 kinds of people: those who can count and those who can''t.'' The background is simple and colorful, with a classroom or casual setting (like a park bench) to keep it light and friendly. Include subtle visual cues like numbers or math symbols around to emphasize counting.'),
 (187, 'Bad Puns, Facts, Objects Humor', 'A flashlight is a case for holding dead batteries.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a flashlight lying on a table. The flashlight''s body is slightly open or transparent, revealing several unhappy-looking, tiny batteries inside it. The batteries have cartoon faces with dull expressions, indicating they are ''dead'' or exhausted. Around the flashlight, scattered cartoon sparks or faint light rays struggling to shine add to the comedic effect that the flashlight isn’t working. The background can be a simple night-time indoor setting, like a dimly lit room with a small side table, to emphasize the flashlight context. The tone should be light and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions on the batteries to highlight the joke visually.'),
 (188, 'Bad Puns, Farming Humor, Humor, Puns', 'You know how farmers make crop circles? They use a protractor', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a farmer standing in a large wheat field under a bright blue sky. The farmer wears overalls, a straw hat, and holds an oversized protractor the size of a large sheet of paper. Behind him are several perfectly straight crop lines forming parts of a crop circle pattern, emphasizing angles and curves like a geometric drawing. A tractor is parked nearby with its wheels leaving neat lines in the soil. The farmer looks proudly at his work, with a friendly smile. Include a few crows or birds on the side watching curiously. The overall tone is light and playful, with clear lines and bright colors suitable for a family-friendly comic strip.'),
 (189, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'A boiled egg is hard to beat.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a kitchen countertop where a personified boiled egg stands like a boxer in a boxing ring. The egg has muscular arms with boxing gloves, a determined facial expression, and a shiny hard shell. Around the egg, other breakfast items like a frying pan, a raw egg with a worried face, and a whisk cheer or look surprised. The background includes kitchen elements like an egg carton, stove, and cooking utensils to set the scene. The atmosphere is lighthearted and comical, emphasizing the pun that a ''boiled egg is hard to beat.'''),
 (190, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'Imagine this: A Jello sandwich. Toasted.', NULL, 'A colorful and playful cartoon scene showing a sandwich on a simple white plate. The sandwich is made with two slices of toasted bread, but instead of typical fillings, there is a bright, shiny, translucent red Jello layer in between the slices. The bread slices have exaggerated toasted textures with small, cute steam lines rising to suggest it''s freshly toasted. The Jello looks wobbly and glossy, almost jiggling. Next to the plate is a cheerful fork and knife, both with friendly, smiling faces. The background is a simple kitchen table with a checkered tablecloth, and soft pastel colors keep the tone light and humorous. The overall style is cartoonish and exaggerated, emphasizing the absurdity and silliness of a toasted Jello sandwich.'),
 (191, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'My wife asked me to put ketchup on the shopping list. Now I can''t read any of it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a cozy kitchen. A man stands near a refrigerator with a confused and frustrated expression, holding a shopping list that is completely covered in bright red ketchup, making the writing illegible. Next to him, his wife looks amused or slightly exasperated, arms crossed or hands on hips. The kitchen counter features typical items like a bottle of ketchup clearly visible, a loaf of bread, and a grocery bag. The scene should be colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and simple, cartoon-style drawing. The ketchup should be dripping and smeared all over the paper so the list is comically unreadable.'),
 (192, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'Never eat more than you can lift.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person at a picnic or buffet table overloaded with food items piled high on a large tray or plate. The person struggles to lift the enormous, towering stack of food, with exaggerated effort shown by sweat drops, strained facial expression, and shaky arms. The food pile includes a mix of comical oversized sandwiches, cakes, fruits, and drinks. Around them, a few people watch, some laughing or giving knowing looks. The background is simple, bright, and cheerful to emphasize the lighthearted tone.'),
 (193, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'Soup that tastes great is souper', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring a steaming bowl of soup sitting on a small table. The bowl has a happy, smiling face with big eyes and is surrounded by little cartoon stars or sparkles to emphasize that it tastes great. Above or near the bowl, include playful lettering with the word "Souper!" in a fun, bold font. The background is simple and bright to keep focus on the bowl. Optional props include a spoon held by an unseen hand or resting next to the bowl, and maybe a small chef''s hat on top of the bowl to add humor and personality. The overall style is lighthearted and whimsical, suitable for a humorous pun visual.'),
 (194, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'Sour grapes: the type of grapes used to make fine whines.', NULL, 'A whimsical cartoon scene featuring a fancy wine tasting event set outdoors with a vineyard in the background. On one side, a bunch of grape characters with sour, grumpy faces are gathered together labeled as ''Sour Grapes.'' Nearby, a sophisticated sommelier, wearing a classic wine taster outfit and monocle, is holding a wine glass filled with red wine while curiously sniffing it. A speech bubble from the sommelier says, ''Ah yes, made from the finest whines!'' The grapes look offended and sour, with exaggerated facial expressions such as frowns, scrunched noses, and crossed arms. Include a wine barrel and a banner saying ''Fine Whines Vineyard'' to emphasize the pun. The art style should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect, avoiding any violent, sexual, or political content.'),
 (195, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor', 'Steak Puns: now there''s a medium where anything well done is rare.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a steakhouse restaurant setting where three steaks are anthropomorphized with cute eyes and expressive faces. One steak in the center is smiling confidently and labeled ''Medium'' with a chef''s hat on top. On one side, a steak looking tired and a bit rare is labeled ''Well Done'' and on the other side, a steak looking surprised and rare is labeled ''Rare''. Above them, a speech bubble coming from the ''Medium'' steak says, "Now there''s a medium where anything well done is rare." The background shows a wooden table with a plate, a knife, and fork, and a rustic steakhouse ambiance with warm lighting. The overall artistic style is light, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions on the steaks to emphasize humor and the pun.'),
 (196, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor, Humor', 'How do you turn deviled eggs into regular eggs? An eggsorcism', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a plate of deviled eggs on a kitchen table. The deviled eggs have little devil horns and tiny pitchforks, looking mischievous. Beside the plate, a cartoon priest or exorcist character, dressed in a robe with a small cross necklace, is performing an ''eggsorcism'' by waving a miniature holy water sprinkler or holding a tiny Bible over the eggs. The eggs look surprised or scared, with little sweat drops on their faces. The kitchen background is simple and bright, with a window showing sunshine outside. The style should be lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated expressions on both the eggs and the exorcist character to emphasize the pun.'),
 (197, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor, Word Play', 'I just swallowed some food coloring. I feel like I''ve dyed a little inside.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing in a kitchen with a slightly surprised expression. The person has a few colorful stains in their mouth and on their tongue, glowing or dripping with various bright food coloring shades like red, blue, and green. Nearby on the counter are several small bottles or tubes labeled as food coloring with vivid colors spilling or sprinkled around. The background is simple, maybe with a kitchen sink and counter, to keep focus on the character and bottles. The person''s thought bubble reads, "I feel like I''ve dyed a little inside," with a subtle smile, emphasizing the wordplay. The overall tone is playful and funny, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions in a cartoon style without any harsh or dark elements.'),
 (198, 'Bad Puns, Food Humor, Word Play', 'The fastest way to quit being vegan is cold turkey.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person looking shocked or surprised while holding a peeled, whole cold turkey (the raw, uncooked kind) in their hands. The person is standing in a kitchen with a refrigerator in the background and a calendar on the wall showing a crossed-out ''vegan'' label on a certain date, suggesting they''ve just quit being vegan. On a nearby counter, there are some fresh vegetables left untouched with a ''Vegan'' sign next to them. The cold turkey is dramatically emphasized, perhaps with speed lines or motion marks to illustrate the ''fastest way''. The overall tone is light and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expression that captures the pun on ''cold turkey'' meaning both quitting abruptly and the food itself.'),
 (631, 'Bad Puns, Golf Humor, Good Question!, Sports Humor', 'Why do golfers wear two pairs of pants? In case they get a hole in one!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful golfer on a bright green golf course. The golfer is mid-swing, dressed in traditional golf attire: a cap, polo shirt, golf shoes, and notably wearing two pairs of pants, one over the other. His pants have an obvious hole in the knee area of the outer pair, revealing the inner pair underneath. Nearby, a golf ball is flying through the air, heading toward a golf hole with a flag. In the background, a bright sunny sky with a couple of fluffy clouds and rolling hills. Include a small sign next to the golfer that says ''Hole in One'' to play on the pun. The style should be light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions—perhaps the golfer has a confident smile or a surprised look just noticing the hole in his pants. The scene should be colorful and playful, emphasizing the double pants and the golf theme without any text bubbles or speech.'),
 (199, 'Bad Puns, Good Question!, Humor', 'Did you know they won''t be making yard sticks any longer?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, slightly confused-looking man standing in a backyard holding an old-fashioned wooden yardstick. The yardstick should look classic with clear measurement markings. Behind him is a neatly trimmed lawn with a small garden fence, and a sign stuck in the ground that says, ''No More Yardsticks!'' Nearby, a factory with a ''Yardstick Factory'' sign has a ''Closed'' banner hanging on its gate. The man is scratching his head, looking at the yardstick with exaggerated puzzlement. The sky is bright and sunny to keep the mood light and funny. The overall style is simple, colorful, and cartoony with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s absurdity and the punchline about yardsticks no longer being made.'),
 (200, 'Bad Puns, Good Question!, Science', 'If poison is past it''s expiration date, is it more or less poisonous?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple kitchen with a bright window and a countertop. On the counter, there is a small, colorful bottle labeled ''Poison'' with a big, exaggerated expiration date sticker that looks very old and faded. Next to the bottle, a puzzled cartoon character with a raised eyebrow and a scratch on the head is holding the bottle, looking quizzically at the label. A question bubble above the character reads, ''If poison is past its expiration date, is it more or less poisonous?'' Nearby, a harmless-looking little mouse wearing glasses sits calmly, holding a clipboard with checkmarks, as if evaluating the poison. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the confusion and irony. The background should be simple to keep the focus on the character and the bottle, with bright and cheerful colors to contrast the morbid topic in a funny way.'),
 (201, 'Bad Puns, Good Question!, Science', 'If practice makes perfect, and nobody''s perfect, why practice?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple room with a person sitting at a desk, practicing a skill like playing the piano or painting. The character looks puzzled and slightly frustrated, with a thought bubble above their head showing the phrase ''If practice makes perfect, and nobody''s perfect, why practice?'' Nearby, scattered sheets of music or sketches lie messily on the floor, reinforcing the idea of ongoing practice. The background includes a clock showing time passing and a small motivational poster on the wall humorously crossed out or altered to say something like ''Practice makes perfect?...'' The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions and gentle, rounded lines typical of a funny cartoon.'),
 (202, 'Bad Puns, Good Question!, Science, Word Play', 'If the speed of light is 186,000 miles per second, what''s the speed of heavy?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or casual science setting. In the center, a quirky teacher or scientist with wild hair and glasses stands by a blackboard. On the blackboard, the equation ''Speed of light = 186,000 miles per second'' is clearly written. The teacher looks puzzled or amused, holding a pointer or piece of chalk, glancing at a confused student scratching their head. Near the bottom of the board, the phrase ''What''s the speed of heavy?'' is written, emphasizing the pun. The classroom has a few science-related props like a globe, a small telescope, and a physics textbook on a desk. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to capture the play on the word "heavy" vs. "light". No violence or inappropriate content is shown, just a funny moment of wordplay in a science learning environment.'),
 (203, 'Bad Puns, Good Question!, Word Play', 'If athletes get athlete''s foot, do astronauts get mistletoe?', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene featuring two characters side-by-side: on the left, a sweaty athlete in running clothes with exaggerated big feet covered in cute cartoonish spots or fungi labeled ''athlete''s foot''; on the right, an astronaut in a bulky space suit floating in zero gravity with a big sprig of green mistletoe hanging above or attached to their helmet. Both look puzzled and slightly amused as they glance at each other. The background is split: a sports field with a running track behind the athlete, and a starry outer space scene with planets and stars behind the astronaut. Use bright, cheerful colors and playful, exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor and whimsy of the joke without any harsh or scary details.'),
 (647, 'Bad Puns, Good Question!, Word Play', 'Why is dark spelled with a K and not with a C? Because you can''t C in the dark', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a confused, slightly puzzled person standing in a very dark room. The room is dimly lit by a faint, flickering candle on a small table, casting shadows everywhere. The person is holding a large, oversized open dictionary or book titled ''Spelling Rules'' and squinting as if trying to read the word ''dark'' while looking around helplessly in the darkness. Nearby, a floating, translucent letter ''C'' with cartoonish eyes and a surprised expression is fading away, while a bold, clear letter ''K'' is brightly glowing or sparkling next to the word ''dark'' in the book. The background should be simple and uncluttered, emphasizing the contrast between ''C'' that you can''t see and ''K'' that you can see. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the pun.'),
 (2222, 'Bad Puns, History Humor, Office Humor, Quotes', 'Remember the bookkeeper, Perched on his stool, Green eyeshade tilted, Quill for a tool? He wasn''t too fast, But nowhere in town, Did you hear the excuse, Our computer is down.', 'R.S. Sullivan in The Wall Street Journal', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an old-fashioned office from the early 1900s. The central character is a bookkeeper sitting on a tall wooden stool behind a large desk cluttered with stacks of paper, ledgers, and a large quill pen in an ink bottle. He is wearing a green eyeshade tilted slightly to one side and round spectacles. The bookkeeper has a slow, somewhat dazed expression, emphasizing his sluggishness. There is no visible computer in the room, highlighting the era before computers. A small wall clock shows mid-morning time. Nearby, a window looks out onto a quiet town street with no activity. The overall style is colorful and exaggerated, with the bookkeeper''s large eyes and accessories cartoonishly emphasized for comedic effect. The scene captures the feeling of someone stubbornly sticking to old methods while modern technology has not yet arrived, with a slight whimsical mood appropriate for a lighthearted office joke.'),
 (204, 'Bad Puns, History Humor, Science', 'Two wrongs don''t make a right, but two Wrights did make an airplane.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two men labeled ''Wright Brothers'' standing proudly beside their vintage airplane. The airplane should be an early biplane with fabric wings and wooden propellers, styled like the Wright Flyer. The two men are smiling and dressed in early 1900s attire with caps and suspenders. Above them, a comic-style speech bubble or sign reads: ''Two wrongs don''t make a right, but two Wrights did make an airplane.'' The background is a simple open field with a clear sky. The overall mood should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the pun on the word ''Wright'' and the phrase ''make a right.'' No violent or political elements, just cheerful historical humor in a clean cartoon style.'),
 (205, 'Bad Puns, History Humor, Word Play', 'I, for one, like Roman Numerals.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person happily standing next to a large, ancient Roman numeral chart on a scroll or stone tablet. The character is smiling proudly with thumbs up, wearing casual modern clothes and perhaps a laurel wreath loosely on their head as a playful nod to Roman culture. Around them are various Roman numerals (I, V, X, L, C, D, M) displayed prominently, with some characters reading the numbers in an exaggerated or playful way. The background is simple and bright to emphasize the cheerful mood, with a lighthearted tone suggesting someone genuinely enthusiastic about Roman numerals. No dark or violent imagery, just an upbeat, pun-friendly environment that conveys a mild joke about liking Roman numerals, which can be read both as ''like them'' and a possible subtle nod to the complexity or iconic style of these numbers.'),
 (206, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'I didn''t like my new beard, but then it grew on me.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man looking at himself in a bathroom mirror with a skeptical or unhappy expression. On his chin, a patchy or small beard is starting to visibly grow. Nearby, an animated beard character with eyes and a smiling face is happily climbing up his cheek or jawline, as if literally ''growing on'' him. The background shows typical bathroom elements like a sink, toothbrush, and mirror with a few humorous details such as beard grooming tools or a calendar marking days passing. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the pun in the joke with clear facial expressions and the animated beard as a whimsical character.'),
 (207, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'I know a guy who''s addicted to brake fluid. Says he can stop anytime.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing beside a car, holding a large bottle labeled ''Brake Fluid'' with a mischievous grin. The man should appear slightly exaggerated with wide eyes and a cheeky smile. The car''s brake pads and wheels are visible to emphasize the theme. Nearby, include a small comic-style speech bubble above the man that reads, ''I can stop anytime.'' The background should be simple, possibly a garage or a road setting, with bright, friendly colors to keep the mood light and funny. The style should be playful and exaggerated, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon joke.'),
 (208, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'If you say ''gullible'' really slowly, it sounds like ''oranges''', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or casual setting where a person is whispering something to a friend. The whispering person has a mischievous grin and is leaning close to the other person''s ear. The friend looks puzzled with wide eyes and a slightly open mouth, trying to understand what is being said. Around them, small floating speech bubbles show the word ''gullible'' written very slowly and stretched out, and another bubble next to it shows the word ''oranges'' to visually represent the joke. The background is simple and cheerful, with a few playful details like a clock on the wall and a small plant or poster, emphasizing a lighthearted, playful atmosphere. The expressions and body language should be exaggerated and cartoonish to underline the joke''s silly and funny nature.'),
 (209, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'I''m afraid of elevators. I''ll be taking steps to avoid them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a nervous-looking person standing next to an elevator in a building hallway. The elevator doors are open, revealing a shiny interior with buttons. The person is visibly hesitant with wide eyes and a hand raised as if saying no. Next to them, a cute staircase is personified with a friendly, inviting smile and little feet, waving them over to take the stairs instead. Above the scene, a speech bubble coming from the person says, "I''ll be taking steps to avoid them." The hallway is bright and simple, with clear elevator signs and a few floor indicators. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on the character and the friendly staircase to emphasize the pun on ''taking steps.'' No dark or intense elements.'),
 (210, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'I''m in shape ... round''s a shape isn''t it?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person looking into a mirror in a brightly lit bathroom. The person has a cheerful, slightly cheeky expression and a noticeably round body shape. They are standing with hands on hips, posing proudly. The mirror shows a reflection with the same round shape, emphasizing the joke that round is a shape too. Around the character, simple bathroom details like a sink, a towel hanging on a rack, and a small plant on the windowsill add context. The style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated roundness to emphasize the humor.'),
 (211, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'Instant idiot: just add alcohol.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a simple kitchen counter with a large, clear glass labeled ''Instant Idiot Mix'' filled with a bubbly liquid. Next to the glass is a bottle of alcohol with a cheerful, exaggerated label, like ''Funny Juice'' or ''Alcohol''. Above the glass is a sparkling sign or a comic-style bubble that reads ''Just Add Alcohol!'' In the background, a surprised cartoon character with exaggerated wide eyes and a goofy grin is looking at the glass, as if startled by the sudden transformation after adding alcohol. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s punchline.'),
 (212, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'It is now beyond any doubt that cigarettes are the biggest cause of statistics.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple office environment with a quirky, slightly stressed middle-aged statistician sitting at a cluttered desk filled with papers, charts, and a large cup of coffee. He is holding a lit cigarette with an exaggerated long trail of smoke curling above him. Nearby, a large graph or pie chart on a whiteboard or computer screen behind him shows a rising curve labeled ''Statistics''. Floating humorously in the smoke are tiny numbers and percentages swirling around, as if the cigarette smoke itself is generating data points. The statistician wears glasses, has a somewhat bewildered expression, and a thought bubble above his head reads ''Cigarettes cause statistics... literally!''. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and lighthearted with no harsh details or negativity. The office is simple, with a potted plant, an overflowing ashtray on the desk, and a calendar on the wall pointing to a generic date.'),
 (213, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'It works better when you turn the brightness up.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a dimly lit room showing a person squinting at a very old, tiny, rudimentary light bulb dangling from the ceiling with a hand crank. The person, looking confused and slightly frustrated, is reaching to turn up a large, ridiculous, oversized brightness dial labeled ''Brightness'' that is humorously attached to the bulb socket. The background is shadowy, with exaggerated dark corners to emphasize the low light. The character''s facial expression should be cartoonish and exaggerated for humor. Nearby, a small table lamp with a big glowing bulb is off to the side, contrasting with the tiny bulb struggling to illuminate the room. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the playful misunderstanding of why turning brightness up would help.'),
 (214, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'It''s always darkest before dawn. So if you''re going to steal your neighbor''s newspaper, that''s the time to do it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a quiet suburban neighborhood at night, just before dawn. The sky is dark with a few stars, and a faint hint of early morning light is starting to appear on the horizon. In the foreground, a sneaky-looking cartoon character, wearing a striped burglar outfit and a black eye mask, tiptoes exaggeratedly toward a front lawn. The character is reaching out to grab a rolled-up newspaper from a typical residential mailbox or placed on a doorstep. Nearby, a friendly dog watches but looks more confused or curious than alarmed. The houses in the background have some lit windows, and a streetlamp casts a soft glow. The scene conveys the joke’s punchline in a lighthearted and playful manner without any menace.'),
 (215, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'It''s the start of a brand new day, and I''m off like a herd of turtles.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bright, cheerful morning with a shining sun and a few fluffy clouds. In the foreground, a group of turtles is slowly moving away from the viewer, all looking determined but clearly slow-paced. They are arranged somewhat like a herd of animals running off, but their tiny legs and turtle shells emphasize their sluggishness. Nearby, a human figure (only partially visible from the waist down) is starting to walk or jog with energetic movement, contrasting with the slow turtles. The background can include a simple grassy field or a quiet suburban street to keep it light and funny. The overall style is colorful, playful, and exaggerated to emphasize the irony of a ''herd'' of naturally slow turtles setting off at the start of the day.'),
 (216, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'Keep America beautiful. Swallow your beer cans.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing proudly with a big, exaggerated smile and bulging cheeks as if they just swallowed something large. Around them, several empty beer cans trail behind on the ground, some crushed and others whole. The setting is a sunny outdoor park or backyard with a "Keep America Beautiful" sign prominently displayed in the background. The character is wearing casual clothes and holding an empty empty-handed, implying they''ve "swallowed" the cans instead of throwing them away. Include lighthearted details like a recycling bin nearby looking confused or surprised. The overall tone is playful and silly, emphasizing the absurdity of literally swallowing beer cans to keep the environment clean. No violence or any unpleasant imagery.'),
 (217, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'Murphy''s Law is recursive. Washing your car to make it rain doesn''t work.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person standing next to a shiny, freshly washed car with soap suds dripping off. The person holds a garden hose and looks up at dark, menacing rain clouds forming directly overhead. The rain clouds have a comical, sly facial expression, as if they are mocking the person. In the background, a calendar or sign displays ''Murphy''s Law: Things go wrong, recursively.'' The setting is a suburban driveway with a lawn and maybe a cheerful sun trying to peek out behind the clouds. Add subtle details like water puddles on the ground reflecting the sky and a small weather vane spinning in confusion. The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the irony that trying to wash the car causes the rain to start, but the rain doesn''t help the situation—playing on the idea of recursion and Murphy''s Law.'),
 (218, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'My favorite genre of movie is ''someone coughs up blood into a napkin and doesn''t tell anyone''.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cozy movie theater. The foreground shows a person seated in a movie chair, looking suspicious and nervous, holding a napkin with visible red spots on it. Around them, other moviegoers are glancing over with puzzled or suspicious expressions. The background shows a typical movie theater setting with a large screen, dim lights, and rows of seats. A faint silhouette of someone on screen is coughing dramatically but everyone in the room looks uncomfortable and whispering to each other. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive faces and clear focus on the awkwardness created by the secretive napkin incident.'),
 (219, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'My luck is like a bald guy who just won a comb.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful bald man holding a shiny new comb in one hand. The man should be standing in the center with an excited expression, but clearly, he has no hair on his head to use the comb on. Maybe add little sparkle effects around the comb to emphasize its newness. Surround the man with a few exaggerated unlucky symbols, like a broken mirror, a black cat crossing behind him, or a spilled salt shaker on the ground, to reinforce the idea of bad luck despite the ''win.'' The overall style should be lighthearted and colorful, with a clear focus on the contrast between the baldness and the useless comb prize. The background can be simple, like a lottery or game show stage with a banner that says ''Lucky Prize!'''),
 (220, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'My wife told me to stop impersonating a flamingo. I had to put my foot down.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene featuring a man standing on one leg, imitating a flamingo. He looks determined but slightly comical, with a goofy smile. His raised foot is firmly planted on the ground below him like he’s ''putting his foot down.'' Nearby, a woman (his wife) stands with her arms crossed, giving him a mock-serious or slightly annoyed look. In the background, a couple of flamingos wade in a pond, looking confused or amused by the man’s attempt. The setting is a bright, simple backyard or park area with grass and a few trees. The style is humorous and exaggerated, with bright colors and rounded shapes to emphasize the playful mood.'),
 (221, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'Never, under any circumstances, take a sleeping pill and a laxative on the same night.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy bedroom at night. A tired-looking adult character, in pajamas, is standing between two nightstand drawers labeled ''Sleeping Pills'' and ''Laxatives.'' The character looks worried and confused, holding a sleeping pill in one hand and a laxative bottle in the other. In the background, a bed with a fluffy pillow and blanket is visible, and a digital alarm clock shows late-night time (around 11 PM). To add humor, next to the bed is a bathroom door slightly ajar with animated comic-style motion lines going in opposite directions, symbolizing conflicting bodily reactions. The character’s expression is exaggerated, wide-eyed, with sweat drops to emphasize anxiousness. The style is vibrant, lighthearted, and cartoonish with bright colors and simple shapes to invoke humor without any threat or discomfort. No explicit or graphic elements—just expressive facial features and the implication of the joke’s meaning through objects and reaction lines.'),
 (222, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'Okay, who stopped the payment on my reality check?', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a confused person standing in front of a giant oversized check labeled ''Reality Check'' with a large ''Cancelled'' stamp across it. The person looks bewildered, scratching their head with a question mark bubble above them. Around them, there are floating symbols representing reality: a calendar, a clock, and a small globe. The setting is simple, like an office or a casual indoor space. The comic style is bright and exaggerated with clear, humorous expressions to emphasize the pun on ''reality check'' as both a literal financial check and a metaphor for facing reality.'),
 (223, 'Bad Puns, Humor', 'People with narrow minds usually have broad tongues.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person with an exaggeratedly narrow head and a very wide, large tongue sticking out. The person''s head should be drawn slim and elongated vertically to emphasize the ''narrow mind,'' while their tongue extends wide and thick horizontally, almost comically oversized compared to the rest of the face. The character should have a surprised or slightly confused expression, with raised eyebrows and big eyes. Surround the character with a simple, light-hearted background like a plain color or a soft gradient to keep focus on the face. No other people or objects are necessary, but the overall tone should be playful and silly to match the joke''s pun on narrow minds and broad tongues.'),
 (224, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Insults, Pessimistic', 'If you make something idiot proof, they''ll just make a better idiot.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a simple, colorful style. In the foreground, a person with a confused and somewhat silly facial expression is holding a very basic, oversized instruction manual labeled ''Idiot Proof Device.'' Nearby is a machine or gadget with several big, obvious safety features and warning signs, like large red buttons, locks, and flashing lights, clearly designed to be foolproof. In the background, another person with an exaggerated, goofy look—wearing mismatched clothes and tripping over their own feet—is interacting with the gadget, somehow causing a small harmless accident or mishap (like pressing the wrong button or fumbling the gadget). The setting is a kitchen or a workshop with tools and everyday objects, adding a casual vibe. Above or beside the scene, a comic-style speech bubble shows the phrase ''If you make something idiot proof, they’ll just make a better idiot.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing irony and the humor of human error despite attempts at simplicity.'),
 (225, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Life', 'Insomnia isn''t anything to lose sleep over.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person lying in bed wide awake at night, eyes wide open and staring at the ceiling. The clock on the bedside table clearly shows it is past midnight. The room is dimly lit by a small lamp, with a window showing a dark night sky with a crescent moon and stars. The person looks tired but is trying to stay optimistic, perhaps with a subtle smile or a raised eyebrow. Above them, a thought bubble contains the text: ''Insomnia isn''t anything to lose sleep over.'' The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony of the statement. The setting should clearly convey nighttime bedtime frustration but in a gentle, comical way without serious distress or anxiety.'),
 (226, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Life', 'I''ve been on a diet for two weeks and all I''ve lost is two weeks.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on a scale, looking confused and slightly disappointed. The scale''s screen or dial clearly shows ''0 lbs'' or no weight change. Around them, a calendar on the wall displays two weeks marked off, perhaps with red circles or Xs. The person might be holding a salad bowl or a water bottle to hint they''re trying to diet. Their posture and facial expression should convey the irony that despite dieting for two weeks, they''ve lost nothing but time. The setting is simple, like a bathroom or kitchen corner, with humorous details such as an uneaten cake or a fast food wrapper tossed aside nearby, emphasizing the struggle. The art style should be colorful and cartoony, with exaggerated expressions to enhance the joke''s punchline.'),
 (227, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Life', 'Last night I thought I was going to die and my whole life flashed before me. It was awful. I hate re-runs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person lying awake in bed at night with wide, alarmed eyes staring at the ceiling. Above their head is a thought bubble filled with a series of TV screens all showing repetitive scenes of the person''s daily life, as if their entire life is playing like dull reruns on TV. The room should be simple, with a bedside lamp casting a soft yellow light. The facial expression should convey frustration and disbelief. The TV screens in the thought bubble can include funny, exaggerated scenes such as the person brushing their teeth, spilling coffee, and sitting at a desk looking bored, repeated multiple times to emphasize the ''rerun'' concept. Style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect.'),
 (228, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Life', 'Nothing is foolproof, to a sufficiently talented fool.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple home office. In the center, a cheerful but clueless-looking person (the ''fool'') is sitting confidently at a desk cluttered with papers, blueprints, and gadgets clearly labeled ''Foolproof Machine.'' The machine is humorously malfunctioning: smoke or sparks pop out, a warning light flashing, and parts falling off. The fool is oblivious to the chaos, smiling proudly while holding a tool upside down. Behind them, a bulletin board contains a big title saying ''Foolproof Plan'' with various diagrams, all humorously complicated and clearly flawed. The overall style is light and playful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke''s irony about how no plan is truly foolproof for a ''talented fool.'' No violence or negative imagery.'),
 (229, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Office Humor', 'Paper clips are the larvae of coat hangers.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a small group of shiny silver paper clips on one side, looking like tiny creatures with cheerful faces. On the other side, depict larger coat hangers with friendly faces, wings or antennae, giving the impression they just hatched or evolved from the paper clips. The background can be a simple closet or office desk setting with a few scattered papers and a clothing rack. Add playful motion lines or sparkles around the paper clips transitioning into coat hangers to emphasize the joke that paper clips are ''larvae'' of coat hangers. Keep the style light, colorful, and exaggerated to enhance the whimsy and humor of the scene.'),
 (230, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Science', 'I''ve been reading a sci-fi book about anti-gravity -- I can''t put it down!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting comfortably in a cozy armchair, deeply engrossed in a book titled ''Anti-Gravity Sci-Fi.'' The person has a delighted expression, eyes wide with fascination. The twist is that the person and the armchair are both gently floating slightly above the ground, emphasizing the anti-gravity theme. Around them, several small objects, like a floating cup of coffee, a book, and a pair of glasses, are also hovering mid-air, adding to the lighthearted, weightless atmosphere. The background is a simple living room setting with a window showing stars and a spaceship silhouette outside, hinting at the sci-fi context. The drawing style is playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and soft, rounded lines to keep it friendly and funny.'),
 (231, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Science', 'Last week a hypnotist convinced me that I was a soft, malleable metal with an atomic number of 82. I''m easily lead.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting in a comfy chair with a hypnotist standing nearby. The hypnotist is wearing classic hypnotist attire—perhaps a suit with a bow tie and holding a swinging pocket watch. The person in the chair has dazed, dreamy eyes and a goofy smile, clearly under hypnosis. Above their head is a thought bubble containing the image of a soft, shiny, gold bar labeled with the atomic number ''82'' and some little waves or wrinkles to emphasize it''s malleable. The background is simple, maybe a cozy room with a few framed certificates on the wall and a small table with a spilled glass of water. The overall style is bright and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and rounded shapes, focusing on the pun about lead acting like gold (soft malleable metal), making the joke visually clear and lighthearted.'),
 (232, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Science', 'Psychoceramics: the study of crackpots.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, eccentric-looking professor standing next to a large, ancient pottery vase with a big visible crack down the middle. The professor wears round glasses, a tweed jacket with elbow patches, a bow tie, and holds a magnifying glass examining the crack closely. Around him are shelves filled with various pots and vases, some intact and some obviously cracked, labeled with funny names like ''Crazy Vase'' and ''Wobbly Jug''. A small chalkboard nearby reads ''Psychoceramics: The Study of Crackpots'' in playful handwriting. The room looks like a lighthearted mix of a pottery studio and a wacky science lab. The overall style is colorful and exaggerated, typical of a cartoon, emphasizing the pun by visually combining ''psychology/psychoceramics'' and cracked pottery (''crackpots''). No people other than the professor, no violence or political elements included.'),
 (233, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'I wanted to watch the world origami championships, but it was only on paper view.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person sitting in front of a TV or computer screen labeled ''World Origami Championships.'' The screen displays simple paper shapes like cranes and boats instead of live video. Next to the person, there''s a large paper folded into an origami shape with a tiny ticket stub or sign that says ''Paper View Only.'' The person scratches their head or looks puzzled. The background is a cozy living room with a lamp and a stack of origami papers on a table. The overall mood is light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the pun on ''paper view'' instead of ''pay-per-view.'''),
 (234, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'It''s hard to explain puns to kleptomaniacs because they always take things literally.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one is a person looking slightly confused or frustrated, trying to explain something, while the other is a kleptomaniac depicted humorously, sneaking away holding a big oversized pun displayed as a word or phrase on a large sticky note or speech bubble. The kleptomaniac should have a playful, exaggerated sneaky expression and be tiptoeing away, literally ''taking'' the pun. The setting can be a simple room or park bench to keep focus on the interaction. Include a thought bubble above the confused person showing different puns or wordplays to reinforce the joke about puns. Keep the colors bright and the expressions exaggerated for comedic effect in a clear cartoon style without any threatening or negative elements.'),
 (235, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'Lefties have rights too.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one is a left-handed person happily writing with a giant pen using their left hand, while a smiling, anthropomorphic right hand stands beside them holding a small protest sign that reads ''Rights!'' Above them, a playful banner says ''Lefties have rights too!'' The background is simple and cheerful, with bright colors and a classroom or office setting. The characters should have exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and friendliness, making it clear that it''s a lighthearted take on left-handedness and rights. No violence or negativity; just a fun, upbeat vibe focused on the pun.'),
 (236, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'Morfy''s law - Enythink thit ken go rong willl.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, slightly disheveled scientist character standing next to a whiteboard or chalkboard. On the board is a large, hand-drawn text that humorously misspells Murphy''s Law as ''Morfy''s law - Enythink thit ken go rong willl.'' The scientist scratches their head, looking puzzled but amused at the misspelling. Nearby, objects are scattered in mild disarray: a tipped-over coffee mug, scattered papers with more funny spelling errors, and a broken gadget emitting a small puff of smoke to emphasize things going wrong. The overall tone is light and playful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the comedic effect of Murphy''s Law inevitably leading to errors, especially with spelling. The background is a simple lab or office setting with a few humorous details like a poster labeled “Law of Murphy” slightly peeling from the wall, and a small mischievous cat knocking over a plant in the corner, embodying chaos.'),
 (237, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'Most people have photographic memories, some just don''t have any film.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside an old-fashioned photo studio with a photographer dressed in vintage clothes holding a large, classic box camera mounted on a tripod. In front of the camera stands a confused person with a blank expression, holding an empty photo film cartridge. Around them, framed pictures of various people with perfectly clear, colorful photos hang on the studio walls, labeled ''Photographic Memory.'' The empty film cartridge in the person''s hand is humorously oversized, with a label reading ''No Film.'' The background should be lightly detailed to highlight the studio setting, with props like old photo albums and camera equipment. The art style should be bright, friendly, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s pun about memory and photographic film without any violent or inappropriate elements.'),
 (238, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'No matter how much you push the envelope it will still be stationary.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, traditional paper envelope sitting on a wooden table. A cartoon character, looking slightly frustrated and determined, is shown with both hands pushing against the envelope, which is clearly not moving despite their effort. The character''s cheeks can be puffed or showing strain to emphasize pushing. Add small motion lines around the character''s hands to show effort and some comic-style ''no movement'' sign around the envelope, like sweat droplets or a small comic ''stuck'' sign above it. The setting is simple, with a bright, cheerful background and maybe a wall clock or a small plant to fill space but not detract from the humor. The overall feel is light and funny, highlighting the pun about "pushing the envelope" literally, instead of its figurative meaning.'),
 (239, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'The short fortune teller who escaped from prison was a small medium at large.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a short, quirky fortune teller who has just escaped from prison. The fortune teller is small in stature, wearing colorful, stereotypical fortune teller clothes including a headscarf, large hoop earrings, and holding a crystal ball that glows mysteriously. He stands confidently just outside orange prison bars or a broken cell door labeled ''Prison.'' Around him are comic-style motion lines showing movement away from the prison. Above or beside him, a sign reads ''Small Medium at Large'' in playful, bold letters. The background should be simple, focusing on the fortune teller, the jail cell, and the pun expressed visually, making it clear this is a lighthearted cartoon pun. The style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated with a slight caricature look, emphasizing the joke on the fortune teller being a ''medium'' and at ''large'' (escaped). No violence or harsh imagery.'),
 (240, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'This is a test as required by the FCC (Fortune Cookie Commision). Had this been a real cookie, it would have been much funnier.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene resembling a public service announcement broadcast setup. A cheerful fortune cookie mascot, anthropomorphized with big eyes and a wide smile, stands behind a podium labeled ''FCC - Fortune Cookie Commission''. The background features a simple banner with FCC initials and a few fortune cookies scattered around. The fortune cookie mascot holds a small paper scroll like a fortune message and speaks into an old-fashioned microphone. A speech bubble above the mascot reads: ''This is a test as required by the FCC (Fortune Cookie Commission). Had this been a real cookie, it would have been much funnier.'' The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions, bright colors, and a playful tone. No people or anything violent, just the cute cookie character delivering a mock official message.'),
 (241, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'What''s the difference between snowmen and snowwomen? Snow balls', NULL, 'A cheerful, colorful cartoon scene showing two snowmen and two snowwomen standing side by side in a snowy landscape with pine trees and a bright blue sky. The snowmen have traditional features like carrot noses, coal eyes and buttons, and stick arms. The snowwomen are similarly styled but with cute winter accessories like scarves and earmuffs. In front of the snowmen, the artist should draw two large shiny snowballs (round snow spheres) clearly labeled or emphasized humorously. The snowwomen have no snowballs visible to show the joke''s punchline visually. The characters have friendly, smiling faces, and the overall art style is lighthearted and playful but clearly cartoonish and easily recognizable. Include some snowflakes falling gently around them to enhance the winter vibe. No backgrounds or elements that imply anything violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (242, 'Bad Puns, Humor, Word Play', 'When puns are outlawed, only outlaws will be punished.', NULL, 'Draw a playful cartoon scene set in a Wild West style town with a humorous twist. In the foreground, show two exaggeratedly outlawish characters wearing classic cowboy hats, boots, and bandanas over their faces. One outlaw is holding a large scroll that says ''Pun Laws'' with a red seal that reads ''Outlawed!''. Another character, a sheriff with a comically large badge labeled ''Pun Enforcement'', looks serious but confused, holding a giant mallet labeled ''Punisher''. Around them, a few amused townsfolk peek from behind buildings, some snickering or covering their mouths, clearly enjoying the pun chaos. Add a wooden signpost in the background saying ''Welcome to Punville'' with a bullet hole, and a wanted poster on a wall that features a smiling face with ''Wanted for Puns''. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the pun-themed humor without any violence, just a lighthearted comic setting.'),
 (243, 'Bad Puns, Insults, Quotes', 'If Satan ever loses his hair, there will be hell toupee', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a fiery, classic depiction of hell with red and orange flames around. In the center, a devilish character with small horns, red skin, a mischievous grin, and an exaggerated bald spot on his head is looking surprised. Next to him is a floating toupee with little devil horns attached, as if it belongs to him. The toupee is stylized to look like it''s made of flames or fiery hair. The background includes pitchforks stuck in the ground and small flames flickering up. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and simple cartoon lines fostering a comedic vibe rather than anything scary or dark.'),
 (244, 'Bad Puns, Jobs', 'If you see me talking to myself, just move along. I''m self-employed and having a staff meeting.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a mirror, talking to their own reflection as if holding a serious meeting. The person is dressed casually, with arms slightly raised in a talking gesture, while their reflection looks attentive and engaged. Around them, include simple office-like items — a small desk with a coffee mug labeled ''CEO'', a notepad, and maybe a tiny nameplate that says ''Staff Meeting''. The background is a cozy home office or living room to emphasize a self-employed setting. The style should be lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated facial expressions showing the person earnestly talking and the reflection ''listening''. No other people are in the scene, highlighting the joke''s punchline about talking to oneself as a staff meeting.'),
 (245, 'Bad Puns, Jobs, Mining Humor', 'I pulled a muscle digging for gold. It was a miner injury.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful miner wearing a yellow hard hat with a headlamp, overalls, and sturdy boots. He is struggling a bit, holding his arm or shoulder with a pained but comedic expression. Around him are mining tools like a pickaxe stuck in a small pile of dirt and scattered gold nuggets sparkling nearby. The background shows a simple mine entrance with wooden supports and a cart full of gold pieces. The miner’s speech bubble reads, ''It was a miner injury.'' The art style is lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the pun on ''miner'' and ''minor'' injury without any harsh or serious tone.'),
 (246, 'Bad Puns, Jobs, Word Play', '''Officer, are you crying while you are writing me a ticket?'' ''Well, it is moving violation.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set beside a roadside where a police officer is writing a ticket. The officer is depicted as slightly teary-eyed with subtle tears streaming down the cheeks but still holding a ticket book and pen. The officer wears a typical police uniform with a badge and a peaked cap. In front stands a surprised and slightly confused driver leaning out of the car window, looking at the officer and asking the question. The background shows a simple street scene with a stopped car, maybe a traffic sign indicating a speed limit or stop sign. The overall tone is light-hearted and comical, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the pun about the "moving violation." Thought bubbles or speech lines can be used to show the dialogue, highlighting the joke in the caption. The style should be colorful, cartoony, and non-threatening, suitable for all ages.'),
 (247, 'Bad Puns, Jobs, Word Play', 'Postmen never die, they just lose their zip.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful postman standing in the middle, looking a bit confused or surprised. His uniform looks slightly disheveled, with his postal jacket partially unzipped and the zipper visibly missing or broken. Around him are flying envelopes and letters, some mid-air as if they''ve just slipped out of his bag. The background is an urban street with mailboxes and houses. Above or beside him, a whimsical wavy line or ghostly outline suggests he is fading or ''losing his zip,'' playing on the idea of losing energy or life. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the pun without any harsh or negative elements.'),
 (248, 'Bad Puns, Math Humor', 'Lottery: A tax on people who are bad at math.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a lottery ticket booth looking confused while holding multiple lottery tickets and a calculator. The person has a puzzled expression, scratching their head as they try to add up the odds or costs. The lottery booth is colorful with flashing signs saying ''Lottery'' and ''Win Big!''. Nearby, a friendly cashier behind the counter smiles knowingly. The background is simple, maybe a few people walking by, with some dollar bills fluttering away in the wind to symbolize money lost. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the idea that playing the lottery is a kind of math challenge that most fail.'),
 (249, 'Bad Puns, Math Humor', 'Math illiteracy affects eight of every five people.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of five people standing together. Above them, a large, comically exaggerated math equation floats in the air reading ''8 of every 5 people.'' The characters look confused and puzzled, scratching their heads or staring at the equation with exaggerated expressions. Some have question marks or little swirling lines above their heads to represent confusion. The background is a simple classroom or casual setting with a chalkboard showing random numbers and symbols faintly. The style is lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated facial features to emphasize the joke about math illiteracy and the absurdity of the fraction.'),
 (250, 'Bad Puns, Money Humor', 'Money talks. The last thing I heard it say was ''Goodbye''.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing next to an open wallet that is empty. The wallet has eyes and a mouth, animated like a talking character, and it is waving goodbye with a little hand. The person looks surprised and sad, scratching their head or shrugging with a comic expression. Around them are scattered coins and bills flying away into the distance, as if the money is literally saying ''Goodbye'' and walking away. The background is simple, with maybe a city park bench or a kitchen table to set an everyday scene. The style should be light-hearted and playful, with bold lines and bright colors typical of a cartoon comic strip.'),
 (251, 'Bad Puns, Music Humor', 'He often broke into song because he couldn''t find the right key.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a man standing confused in front of a giant piano door with multiple exaggerated oversized keys scattered around on the ground. The man is holding a tiny, comically oversized keychain with a single key on it, looking puzzled as if trying to open the piano door with it. Musical notes float around his head, and he is mid-song, mouth open as if singing. The setting is simple, indoors, with a spotlight highlighting the man and the piano door. Add a small speech bubble with a musical note and a question mark to emphasize confusion about the ''right key''. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated expressions.'),
 (252, 'Bad Puns, Music Humor', 'Old musicians never die, they just decompose.', NULL, 'A playful cartoon scene showing a group of old musicians styled as classic band members (e.g., one with a saxophone, one with a guitar, one with a drumsticks) standing on a grassy patch outside. Instead of looking alive, they are humorously turning into compost or soil right beneath their feet, with bits of leaves, mushrooms, and worms popping out around them. The musicians have slightly exaggerated worried but comedic expressions, with musical notes floating above their heads fading into little brown leaves. The background is bright and cheerful with a sunny sky and some flowers growing from the decomposing ground, reinforcing the pun on decomposition. The overall style is colorful, cartoonish, and lighthearted, emphasizing humor without any scary or sad elements.'),
 (253, 'Bad Puns, Objects Humor', 'Rubber bands have snappy endings!', NULL, 'Draw a cheerful, cartoon-style rubber band character with big expressive eyes and a wide smile. The rubber band is in mid-air, stretched out and about to snap back with a small comic ''SNAP!'' motion line. Around it, show a little comic-style speech bubble or caption that reads ''Snappy endings!'' The background can be simple, maybe a desk or office environment to hint at everyday use. The overall vibe should be lighthearted and playful, with bold outlines and bright colors to emphasize the humor.'),
 (254, 'Bad Puns, Office Humor', 'Whiteboards are remarkable.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a whiteboard in a bright, cheerful classroom or office setting. The whiteboard has a big smiley face drawn on it with expressive eyes and a wide grin. Around the whiteboard, a few colorful markers are scattered, some with little limbs and happy faces, looking proud or excited. The whiteboard stands on an easel or mounted on a wall, slightly angled as if ''posing''. The background includes a teacher or office worker gesturing toward the whiteboard with an impressed or amazed expression. The style is light-hearted and fun, using simple, bold lines and bright colors, evoking a playful and friendly atmosphere that highlights the pun on "remarkable" (as the whiteboard can be written on with markers).'),
 (255, 'Bad Puns, Office Humor, Word Play', 'Remember, the paper is always strongest at the perforations.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person holding a large piece of notebook paper with visible perforations. The person has a puzzled or thoughtful look on their face as they tug gently on the paper right at the perforated edge. The paper is exaggeratedly large, almost poster-sized, to highlight the perforations. Nearby, a comically exaggerated ruler or strength-testing device (like a dumbbell) is resting, implying the person is ''testing strength.'' The background is simple, perhaps a classroom or a home office with a desk, pencil, and maybe some scattered torn pages. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the irony that the paper is strongest where it is actually weakest (the perforations). No violent or political elements; just a playful visual pun about paper strength and perforations.'),
 (256, 'Bad Puns, Pessimistic, Quotes', 'If there was an award for most pessimistic, I probably wouldn''t even be nominated.', 'Jim Gaffigan', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a character standing on a small stage at an award ceremony. The character looks unimpressed and somewhat gloomy, wearing semi-formal clothes and holding a microphone with one hand. A large banner overhead says ''Most Pessimistic Award.'' The audience in front of the stage looks enthusiastic and ready to cheer while holding programs and clapping, but the character looks detached and disinterested, as if thinking, ''I probably wouldn''t even be nominated.'' Include a trophy stand next to the character with a quirky, empty pedestal labeled ''Most Pessimistic Award'' to emphasize the joke. The setting is indoors with spotlights and cheerful decorations to contrast with the character’s pessimism. Keep the overall art style light, simple, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor without any negative or harsh tones.'),
 (257, 'Bad Puns, Photography Humor', 'Photographic Department Door Sign: DARK ROOM: IF YOU OPEN THE DOOR ALL THE DARK WILL LEAK OUT', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a photography studio hallway. On the wall, there is a large door with a big, bold sign above it reading: ''DARK ROOM: IF YOU OPEN THE DOOR ALL THE DARK WILL LEAK OUT.'' The door is slightly ajar, and from the opening, cartoon-style black darkness (like a smoky, shadowy cloud) is whimsically floating out and spreading into the bright hallway. Nearby, a surprised photographer wearing a lab coat and holding a developing photo is backing away with wide eyes and raised hands as if trying to stop the darkness from escaping. The hallway itself is well lit and cheerful, with framed photos hanging on the walls showcasing classic black and white pictures. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and playful, capturing the pun of the phrase visually in a fun and innocent way, perfect for all ages.'),
 (258, 'Bad Puns, Pop Culture', 'Might as well be frank, Monsieur. It would take a miracle to get you out of Casablanca.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in 1940s-style attire to evoke the classic movie Casablanca setting. One character is dressed as a French waiter or a suave gentleman (labeled ''Monsieur''), who looks stubbornly seated inside a cozy, dimly lit cafe reminiscent of Rick''s Café Américain. The other character, a friend or fellow patron, is standing nearby with a playful smirk, holding a plate with a frankfurter sausage on it, making a pun on the name ''frank''. The background includes classic 1940s decor—wooden tables, a vintage jukebox, and an old-fashioned clock showing late evening. A window shows a dimly lit street outside, hinting that ''getting out of Casablanca'' would be difficult. The expressions convey witty banter: the standing character is amused while ''Monsieur'' looks resigned or cheeky. The overall style is light and friendly with bold outlines and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun humor.'),
 (1646, 'Bad Puns, Quotes, Word Play', 'Don''t misunderestimate me.', 'George W. Bush', 'Humorous cartoon scene showing a confident character standing boldly with one foot on a rock, chest puffed out and fists on hips. The character is mid-sentence, with a large speech bubble above their head containing the phrase "Don''t misunderestimate me." Their expression is determined but slightly goofy, emphasizing the playful misuse of words. The background is simple, maybe a clear sky or plain color to keep focus on the character. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with cartoonish proportions and vibrant colors to highlight the comedic spirit of the phrase. No other characters or objects are needed, but the speech bubble should be large and prominent to make the joke clear.'),
 (2765, 'Bad Puns, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'DIMP (dimp) n. A person who insults you in a cheap department store by asking, ''Do you work here?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a brightly colored, slightly cluttered cheap department store. In the foreground, a confused shopper stands wearing casual clothes and carrying a few shopping bags. Opposite them, a cheeky person with an exaggerated smirk and a raised eyebrow points at the shopper, asking, ''Do you work here?'' Around them, aisles filled with low-priced items like clothes, household goods, and random knick-knacks. Include a store sign with the words ''Cheap Department Store'' visible in the background. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with big expressive faces to capture the awkward insult and the confused reaction, using warm and playful colors to emphasize the comedic tone without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (259, 'Bad Puns, Science, Word Play', 'Entropy: it ain''t what it used to be.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a relaxed scientist or professor standing next to a large chalkboard filled with doodles and equations about entropy and disorder. The scientist has a whimsical, slightly tired expression and is holding a piece of chalk in one hand while shrugging with the other. On the chalkboard, write the phrase "Entropy: it ain''t what it used to be" in bold letters. Around the scientist, depict everyday objects getting messier or more disorganized: a spilled box of papers, an unraveling ball of yarn, and a melting ice cube on a plate. The background should be a simple laboratory or classroom setting with a humorous and light atmosphere, using bright, cheerful colors. The style should be cartoonish with exaggerated features to emphasize the joke''s playful tone, avoiding any negative or controversial imagery.'),
 (260, 'Bad Puns, Shopping Jokes', 'If the shoe fits, buy the other one too.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing in front of a shoe store display. The person is trying on one brightly colored sneaker and has a big smile on their face. The display shelf shows a matching empty spot next to the worn shoe, implying the other shoe is waiting to be bought. Around the character are speech bubbles with playful text like ''If the shoe fits...'' and the person thinking ''Better get the other one too!'' The background shows typical shoe store elements like shelves filled with various shoes and a friendly sales clerk giving a thumbs-up. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with the character wearing casual clothes and the shoes being slightly oversized for comedic effect.'),
 (261, 'Bad Puns, Shopping Jokes', 'If you see someone shoplifting an iPhone, are you an iWitness?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a brightly colored, modern electronics store. In the foreground, a person with wide eyes and a surprised expression is pointing at another person who is slyly slipping an iPhone into their jacket pocket. Above them, a big, bold comic-style caption reads ''iWitness?'' with a question mark. The store shelves are lined with obvious tech gadgets like smartphones, tablets, and headphones. Other shoppers in the background are casually browsing or looking amused. The style should be lighthearted with exaggerated facial expressions and a clear focus on the iPhone and the witnesses'' reaction, emphasizing the pun with a playful and friendly vibe without any threat or aggression.'),
 (262, 'Bad Puns, Technology Humor, Word Play', 'The inventor of auto-correct just died -- may he roast in piss.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simplistic graveyard with a single headstone. The gravestone has the words ''Auto-Correct Inventor'' engraved on it. Standing next to the gravestone is a confused-looking cartoon character holding a phone, looking frustrated because the phrase ''roast in peace'' on his phone autocorrected to ''roast in piss''. The phone screen humorously shows the autocorrect suggestion with a red underline or popup bubble highlighting the mistake. In the background, there is a scroll-like signpost with the original phrase ''rest in peace'' crossed out and replaced with ''roast in piss''. The style should be lighthearted and comical, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors, emphasizing the irony and annoyance of autocorrect mistakes without any harsh tone.'),
 (263, 'Bad Puns, Travel Humor', 'I was going to buy a money belt for our latest trip, but it seemed like such a waist of money', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in a store aisle filled with travel accessories. The main character is holding a money belt around their waist with a puzzled and slightly amused expression. The money belt is exaggeratedly bulky and clearly labeled ''Money Belt.'' Nearby, a price tag floats showing an expensive price. Around the character, there are travel items like suitcases, passports, and maps on shelves. The background has playful travel posters on the walls. The setting is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the pun by visually focusing on the money belt around the waist as a ''waste'' of money, with a slight visual emphasis on the waist area (perhaps with small motion lines or sparkles). No people are upset or serious, and the overall style is goofy and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the humor without any negativity.'),
 (264, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'A pun entered the room and kills 10 people. Pun in, ten dead.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set in a simple room with a door labeled ''Room.'' In the center, a large walking pun character is personified: a playful word bubble with a smiling face and arms and legs. The pun is cheerfully stepping into the room. Scattered nearby are cartoonish characters looking surprised or fainted, with subtle ''Zzz'' or dizzy stars above their heads to indicate they are unconscious rather than harmed. The phrase ''Pun in, ten dead'' is whimsically illustrated above in bubbly, playful lettering. The overall atmosphere is lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated expressions on all characters, emphasizing wordplay rather than violence. The style is clean and bold, typical of a funny comic strip.'),
 (265, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'Broken pencils are pointless.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a broken pencil lying flat on a wooden desk or table. The pencil is visibly snapped in two near the tip, with the sharpened end showing bluntness and no lead sticking out. The pencil has expressive cartoon eyes and a small frowning mouth to convey a sad or frustrated emotion. Around the pencil, a few small paper scraps or a crumpled note add to the environment of uselessness. The background is simple and light-colored to keep focus on the pencil. Optionally, the scene could include an unbroken pencil standing upright nearby, looking smug or confident, emphasizing the contrast between the broken pencil''s ''pointlessness'' and the intact pencil''s usefulness. The overall style is whimsical and friendly, with bold outlines and bright colors suitable for a lighthearted cartoon joke.'),
 (266, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'I broke my finger last week. On the other hand, I''m okay.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing with a cheerful expression. The person is holding up one hand showing a bandaged finger clearly broken, with a little plaster or splint visible. The other hand is raised in a thumbs-up gesture, clean and perfect. The background is simple, perhaps a plain wall or a kitchen setting, to keep the focus on the hands. The caption or speech bubble from the person says: ''I broke my finger last week. On the other hand, I''m okay.'' The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoonish features like big eyes and a wide smile to emphasize the pun.'),
 (267, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'I once entered 10 puns in a best pun contest and thought I would win, but no pun in ten did', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a cheerful man standing on a stage at a pun contest. The stage has a banner reading ''Best Pun Contest'' in big colorful letters. The man is holding a pile of papers labeled ''10 Puns'' with a confident smile, but nearby a judge is shaking their head or shaking a finger disapprovingly. Around them are audience members in the background, some giggling, some looking unimpressed. The setting should be bright and lighthearted with simple stage props like a microphone stand and a spotlight focused on the man. Emphasize playful expressions to capture the pun and wordplay humor without any negative or aggressive vibes.'),
 (268, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'I tried to catch some fog, but I mist', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing in a foggy landscape early in the morning. The person should look slightly frustrated or puzzled, with arms outstretched as if trying to grab something intangible. Around them, the fog is thick and swirly, visually emphasizing that it’s impossible to catch. Include subtle visual pun elements, like a thought bubble showing a net or a lasso aimed toward the fog but with the word ''MIST'' humorously floating away just out of reach. The setting is outdoors with a few faint outlines of trees or hills in the background to highlight the foggy atmosphere. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, using soft colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the joke without any violence or complex backgrounds.'),
 (269, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'If you replace the W with a T in What, Where and When... you get the answer to each of them.', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon scene showing three large colorful question words arranged side by side: ''What'', ''Where'', and ''When''. Each word has friendly cartoon eyes and smiling faces. Above them, a large whimsical letter ''W'' is shown being playfully swapped out by a cheerful animated letter ''T'' using cartoon hands or arms. As the letter ''T'' replaces the ''W'' in each word, the resulting transformed words appear below them as humorous answers: ''That'', ''There'', and ''Then'', each with equally cheerful expressions. The background is simple and bright with a few question marks and lightbulbs floating around, symbolizing ideas and solving riddles. The overall style is colorful, fun, and exaggerated in a classic comic strip or children''s book illustration style, aimed at conveying a clever wordplay joke in a non-threatening, happy manner.'),
 (270, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'I''m an incorrigible punster -- so don''t incorrige me!', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring a quirky character standing confidently in the center. The character is holding a large, colorful dictionary labeled ''Puns & Wordplay'' in one hand, while with the other hand they make a playful ''stop'' gesture. The character wears round glasses and a big smile, emphasizing their love for puns. Around them are several floating word bubbles containing playful pun words and small doodles, like a broken pencil labeled ''incorrigible'' and a crossed-out word ''incorrige'' with a red X. The background is simple with bright colors, perhaps a classroom or library setting, adding to the linguistic vibe. The overall tone is lighthearted and humorous with exaggerated cartoon expressions that convey the character''s passion for puns and wordplay in a fun, non-threatening way.'),
 (271, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'I''m making a list of reasons to move to Switzerland. The flag is a big plus.', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene showing a person standing next to a large Swiss flag mounted on a flagpole. The person is holding a clipboard and pen, looking happy and thoughtful. The Swiss flag is bright red with a big white plus sign in the center. Around the person are small signs or notes floating in the air with funny reasons to move to Switzerland, with the largest and most prominent note showing a big white plus symbol emphasizing the pun. The background is a simple outdoor setting with green grass and a clear blue sky, giving a lighthearted, positive feel. The style is colorful, friendly, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions on the person to enhance the humor of the ''big plus'' joke, without any complex details or distractions.'),
 (272, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'I''m not a complete idiot, some parts are missing!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing with a goofy, confused expression on their face. Their body is drawn like a simple puzzle with missing pieces—some of the head and torso parts are obviously absent, creating gaps that float nearby. The person wears casual clothes and has exaggerated, wide eyes and a big, silly grin that suggests they are playfully acknowledging their ''incomplete'' state. Surrounding them are small labels or cartoonish tool icons like a wrench, screwdriver, and question marks, indicating the missing parts. The background is simple and cheerful to keep the focus on the character and their missing puzzle pieces. The overall tone is lighthearted and comical, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon strip or joke illustration.'),
 (273, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'I''m not loafing. I work so fast I''m always finished.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a relaxed, laid-back loaf of bread with a small, comical face, sitting comfortably on a tiny office chair behind a desk cluttered with papers. The loaf is leaning back with its arms behind its head, smiling confidently. A clock on the wall shows time passing quickly. Nearby, a tired-looking human coworker is frantically working, with sweat drops flying off their head. The loaf of bread has a small nameplate on the desk that says ''Employee of the Month.'' The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, capturing the pun that the loaf is not ''loafing'' (idling) but instead is so fast that they finish work instantly.'),
 (274, 'Bad Puns, Word Play', 'It got a new pair of gloves today, but they were both ''lefts''. On one hand, that''s great, but on the other hand, it''s not right.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful cartoon glove character with a smiling face on its palm. The glove character is holding up two gloves, both shaped as left-hand gloves, one in each hand. The setting is a simple glove store with a shelf behind displaying various gloves. The glove character has exaggerated cartoon eyes looking confused and amused at holding two left gloves. A speech bubble above the character says: "On one hand, that''s great, but on the other hand, it''s not right." The style is light and colorful, with the emphasis on the visual pun of two left gloves and the glove character''s expression reflecting the joke''s play on words about hands and being ''not right''.'),
 (275, 'Bad Puns, Workplace', 'Incontinence Hotline ... Can you hold, please?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a customer service phone operator sitting at a desk wearing a headset. There is a big, bright sign above the operator reading ''Incontinence Hotline''. The operator looks slightly confused but polite. In the foreground, a speech bubble comes from an unseen caller who says, ''Can you hold, please?'' The scene should include a ringing phone on the desk, a small clock on the wall to imply waiting, and some light-hearted office details such as a coffee mug and a notepad. The style is simple and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the joke''s pun on ''hold.'' The background is a cheerful, non-distracting office space with muted colors to keep the focus on the characters and the humorous text.'),
 (1576, 'Bank Humor, Everyday Life, Irony, Quotes', 'Banks are a place that will lend you money, if you prove that you don''t need it.', 'Bob Hope', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set inside a bank. Show a customer at a bank teller''s window holding an empty wallet turned inside out, looking confused and a bit frustrated. The bank teller, who is smiling politely, is handing a loan application back to the customer with a big red ''DENIED'' stamp on it. Behind the teller, depict a notice on the wall that says: ''Loans granted only if you prove financial stability.'' To emphasize the joke, add a thought bubble above the customer showing an image of a piggy bank filled with coins labeled ''Proof of Needlessness.'' The style should be bright and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the irony of banks lending money only to those who don’t actually need it. Include a queue of other customers in the background, some looking hopeful and others looking disappointed, to add depth and context to the scene.'),
 (276, 'Bathroom Humor, Don''t Say It!, Puns', 'I don''t have any jokes about toilet paper - they''re all tearable', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a roll of toilet paper sitting on a small stage with a microphone, as if performing stand-up comedy. The toilet paper roll has a cheerful, animated face with big eyes and a wide smile. Around the stage are a few rolls of toilet paper sitting in an audience, each showing expressions of groaning or laughing at the joke. In the background, a banner reads ''Toilet Paper Comedy Night.'' The setting should be lighthearted and colorful, with the roll under a spotlight and a simple comedy club vibe. Include some scattered torn pieces of toilet paper on the floor to hint at the pun ''tearable.'''),
 (1192, 'Bathroom Humor, Everyday Life, Insults, Pun', 'May your chair produce a fart noise, but only once, so you can''t reproduce it a prove it was the chair', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene in a cozy living room with a person sitting on a simple wooden chair. The person looks surprised and slightly embarrassed, with wide eyes and a small sweat drop by their head, glancing around nervously as if trying to figure out where the sound came from. The chair should have small sound lines or cartoonish motion lines near the seat to indicate the fart noise just happened. Include subtle, playful details like a little musical note or a classic ''pffft'' cloud near the chair to emphasize the sound humorously. The background can show a couple of houseplants, a small side table with a lamp, and maybe a curious pet (like a dog or cat) looking confused in the background. Overall, the style should be colorful, clean, and in a lighthearted cartoon format, enhancing the silly but relatable situation without any offensive elements.'),
 (1186, 'Bathroom Humor, Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'May the pin on the bathroom stall door never quite reach the lock', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a public bathroom stall. The focus is on the bathroom stall door with a slightly exaggerated, oversized metal latch and an off-center pin that just misses the lock mechanism, creating a comical gap between them. The door is slightly ajar, hinting that it won’t fully lock. Outside the stall, a frustrated but amused cartoon character (gender-neutral) is peeking in, with one eye squinting suspiciously, waiting in line. Inside the stall, a character sits on the toilet looking worried or surprised, holding the door with one hand as if trying to keep it closed. The background shows tiled walls typical of public restrooms and a humorous sign on the wall that reads, “May your doors always lock!” The overall art style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated with bold outlines to emphasize the absurdity of the near lock failure without any sense of threat or discomfort.'),
 (277, 'Bathroom Humor, Humor', 'No one is listening until you fart.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a quiet office meeting room where a group of diverse coworkers are sitting around a conference table, looking bored, checking their phones, and doodling. At the far end, a person suddenly looks surprised and a bit embarrassed, holding their nose and slightly blushing, indicating they just farted. Immediately, all the other coworkers abruptly stop their activities and turn their attention toward that person, wide-eyed with shocked or amused expressions. Include typical office items like laptops, coffee mugs, papers, and a whiteboard in the background. The mood is light-hearted and comical, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the sudden change in attention triggered by the fart. Cartoon style with bright colors and simple lines, no harsh or mean-spirited elements.'),
 (1190, 'Bathroom Humor, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'May you never be quite certain if that pressure is a fart or poop', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting awkwardly on a park bench or office chair. The character’s face expresses a mix of worry and confusion, with sweat drops and wide eyes. Around the character’s lower half, faintly illustrated cartoonish gas clouds or small wavy lines are drifting upward, with a question mark above to indicate uncertainty. Nearby, a small dog or bird nearby looks at the character with a puzzled expression, adding to the humor. The background is simple and bright to keep focus on the character’s dilemma, with minimal props such as a tree or office desk to set the scene in everyday life. The style should be light-hearted, exaggerated cartoon, with clear lines and vibrant colors to emphasize the comedic and relatable feeling of the situation without anything crude or offensive.'),
 (3030, 'Bathroom Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I renamed my toilet Jim instead of John.  People are impresses when I tell them I go to the Jim every morning.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a cozy, slightly quirky bathroom. In the center, show a clean, standard toilet with a nameplate attached to its tank reading ''Jim'' in bold, friendly letters. Nearby, a person (gender-neutral and cartoonish) is confidently smiling and speaking on the phone, holding it to their ear with one hand and giving a thumbs-up with the other. Include a speech bubble coming from them saying, ''I go to the Jim every morning!'' The bathroom should have lighthearted details like a small rug, a toilet paper holder, a towel rack, and a wall clock showing morning time. Use bright colors and exaggerated, playful proportions to emphasize the joke’s pun on the word ''Jim'' as a name and the informal British slang for toilet. The mood should be cheerful, and the style clearly cartoonish with clean lines and simple shading to highlight the humor without complexity.'),
 (278, 'Bathroom Humor, Word Play', 'My grandson laughs when I tell bathroom jokes. Poop jokes aren''t my favorite kind of joke, but they are a solid #2.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a cozy living room where a cheerful elderly grandfather is sitting on an armchair with a big smile, telling a joke. Nearby, his young grandson is laughing heartily, clutching his stomach. On a small coffee table between them is a comically oversized book titled ''Bathroom Jokes.'' The background shows a bathroom door with a visible number ''2'' on it, subtly referencing the joke''s punchline. A roll of toilet paper, a rubber duck, and a plunger are playfully placed around the room, adding to the bathroom humor. The art style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the jovial mood and the silly nature of the joke, suitable for all ages and free from any violence or sensitive content.'),
 (279, 'Bathroom Humor, Word Play', 'There are two things you need to know about constipation: 1. There is no #2.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting awkwardly on a simple toilet seat in a bathroom. The person looks frustrated and slightly distressed, holding their stomach with one hand and looking at an empty toilet paper roll holder next to them. Above the toilet, a small sign humorously states: ''Things to Know About Constipation: 1. There is no #2.'' The bathroom should be simple and brightly colored to enhance the lighthearted mood, with a small plunger leaning against the wall and a small window showing a sunny day outside. The overall style should be exaggerated and cartoonish, capturing the awkwardness and humor of the situation without being crude or graphic.'),
 (1237, 'Bible Humor, Cartoon, Jobs, Pun', 'If you ever need an ark, I Noah guy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly man named Noah standing next to a large wooden ark reminiscent of the biblical ark. Noah is smiling and giving a thumbs-up gesture. The ark looks comically oversized, with simple cartoon animals peeking out of windows and the door — animals like a pair of giraffes, elephants, and birds wearing goofy expressions. Above Noah''s head is a speech bubble with the pun: ''If you ever need an ark, I Noah guy.'' The background shows a light-hearted, sunny outdoor setting with green grass and a few fluffy clouds. The overall style is bright, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features for both Noah and the animals to enhance the joke''s silliness.'),
 (595, 'Bible Humor, Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'What is the search for Noah''s boat called? ''ark''eology', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors near a riverbank with muddy water. In the center, an archaeologist wearing a classic explorer outfit with a wide-brimmed hat and a magnifying glass is excitedly digging at the river’s edge. Partially buried in the mud is a small wooden ark-shaped boat with a cute pair of animal pairs (like two elephants or two giraffes) looking curiously at the archaeologist. A playful sign next to the digging spot reads ''ARK''eology Site.'' Background elements include palm trees, a bright sunny sky, and a small wooden crate labeled ''Ancient Artifacts.'' The overall style is lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated expressions on the characters to emphasize the pun on ''ark'' and ''archaeology.'' No humans look alarmed; instead, there is a sense of fun discovery and wordplay in the scene.'),
 (3114, 'Biology Humor, Cartoon, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Why Yawning Is Contagious:  You yawn to equalize the pressure on your eardrums. This pressure change outside your eardrums unbalances other people''s ear pressures, so they must yawn to even it out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting face-to-face. The first character is mid-yawn, with eyes half-closed and mouth wide open. Visible near their ears are small cartoonish pressure gauges or balloons slightly inflated, representing ear pressure. Around them, little wavy lines or motion effects show the ''pressure change.'' The second character looks surprised and is beginning to yawn as well, with similar pressure gauges near their ears showing imbalance, trying to ''equalize.'' The background is simple, perhaps a living room or park bench setting, with lighthearted colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the funny effect of yawning as a pressure equalizing reaction. The style is playful and cartoonish, with smooth lines and bright colors, capturing the silly science behind contagious yawning without any text or background distractions.'),
 (2185, 'Biology Humor, Puns, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Organic chemistry is the chemistry of carbon compounds. Biochemistry is the study of carbon compounds that crawl.', 'Mike Adams', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful scientist in a brightly lit laboratory wearing a white lab coat and round glasses, standing next to two labeled blackboards. The first blackboard reads ''Organic Chemistry'' and shows simple decorated illustrations of carbon atoms connected with lines into a neat molecule, such as a hexagon ring or chain. The second blackboard, labeled ''Biochemistry,'' depicts the same carbon atoms, but transformed playfully into tiny crawling creatures resembling ants or caterpillars, complete with little antennae and legs, crawling around the molecules. The scientist has a quirky smile, holding a test tube with bubbling colorful liquid, looking amused by the contrast between the two boards. Around the lab, include typical laboratory items like beakers, flasks, and molecular models. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the wordplay about carbon compounds that ''crawl'' in biochemistry.'),
 (3122, 'Biology Humor, Science Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'X-CHROMOSOME: A genetic double-cross that empowers women with the ability to bear children and reserves for men the right to be color-blind hemophiliacs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two anthropomorphized chromosomes standing side by side. The X-chromosome is portrayed as a confident, regal female character wearing a crown or tiara, holding a baby bottle or a pacifier, symbolizing the ability to bear children. She has a proud smile. Next to her is a smaller, bashful male character representing the Y-chromosome, wearing glasses with red and green lenses to indicate color blindness, holding a dripping test tube labeled ''blood'' to symbolize hemophilia. Both characters have cartoonish faces with expressive eyes. The background is a simple laboratory setting with genetic charts or DNA helixes on the walls. The style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to enhance the joke''s playful tone without any violence or offense.'),
 (2885, 'Blood Humor, Sports Humor, Unknown', 'Give blood.... play hockey!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on an ice hockey rink. In the foreground, a hockey player dressed in full gear (helmet, jersey, pads, skates) is skating aggressively toward a pile of hockey pucks nearby. He has a comically exaggerated surprised expression with one eye wide and mouth open as a small, exaggerated spray of blood spurts dramatically from his nose or mouth. To the side of the rink, a red donation box or table labeled ''Blood Donation'' sits with a big syringe and a heart symbol. A speech bubble near the player says, ''Give blood... play hockey!'' In the background, several other players watch with mixed reactions: some shocked, some amused. The overall style is colorful and playful with rounded, exaggerated cartoon characters. The scene should convey humor through the connection between the toughness of hockey and the idea of donating blood, without any violence or pain shown beyond the comical blood spritz.'),
 (2813, 'Board Games, Cartoon, History Humor, Unknown', 'Each king in a deck of playing cards represents a great king from history.  Spades - King David; Clubs - Alexander the Great; Hearts - Charlemagne; and Diamonds - Julius Caesar.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style scene showing four playing cards laid out side by side on a table, each card featuring a playful, exaggerated portrait of a famous historical king who matches the suit. The King of Spades is depicted as King David wearing a crown and holding a harp; the King of Clubs as Alexander the Great with a laurel wreath and a short sword; the King of Hearts as Charlemagne with a royal robe and a scepter; and the King of Diamonds as Julius Caesar wearing a Roman laurel crown and toga. The background is simple and colorful, with each card slightly oversized for emphasis. To add humor, each character can have a subtle smile or quirky expression, and the cards have suit symbols prominently visible. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, making the historical idea fun and approachable.'),
 (280, 'Board Games, Country Humor, Puns', 'What''s Canada''s favorite board game? Sorry', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful Canadian family sitting around a table playing the board game ''Sorry!''. The family members are wearing cozy winter clothing with visible maple leaf logos on sweaters or hats to emphasize Canadian identity. The board game ''Sorry!'' is sprawled out in the middle with colorful pawns and cards visible. One family member holds up a card that says ''Sorry!'' with a playful smile. In the background, a window shows a snowy landscape with a Canadian flag flying outside. The atmosphere is warm and friendly, highlighting the pun on ''Sorry'' being a common Canadian stereotype. Add lighthearted expressions and a cozy, inviting home environment with wooden furniture and a steaming mug of hot chocolate nearby.'),
 (1735, 'Board Games, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Half this game is ninety percent mental.', 'Yogi Berra', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting at a table playing a board game, such as chess or checkers. One character looks very focused and serious, hands on their temples as if concentrating hard. The other character is looking confused or skeptical, scratching their head. Above them is a large thought bubble with complicated brain graphics or squiggly lines to depict ''mental effort.'' Nearby, a scoreboard or timer suggests the intensity of the game. The setting is simple – a casual living room or game room with a cozy chair, a lamp, and a small bookshelf with games. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the irony of the phrase ''Half this game is ninety percent mental'' by visually exaggerating the mental struggle during a straightforward game, making it feel amusingly intense.'),
 (1562, 'Body Positivity Humor, Everyday Life, Parenting, Quotes', 'AQUADEXTROUS (ak wa deks'' trus) adj. Possessing the ability to turn the bathtub faucet on and off with your toes.', NULL, 'Humorous cartoon scene set in a colorful bathroom. The main focus is a playful toddler sitting in a bathtub filled with bubbles and rubber ducks. The toddler has a big, cheeky grin and is proudly pointing down at their feet, which are stretched out to reach the bathtub faucet. The faucet is mid-drip or showing water turning on, controlled by one of the toddler''s toes pressing the handle. Include a towel hanging on a rack, a bath mat on the floor, and bottles of shampoo and soap on the tub edge. The overall tone is lighthearted and cute, capturing the toddler’s amusing pride in this unique skill.'),
 (281, 'Body Positivity Humor, Good Question!', 'Can fat people go skinny-dipping?', NULL, 'A playful cartoon scene at a small, sunny pond surrounded by trees and bushes. In the foreground, a chubby person wearing a brightly colored swimsuit stands at the edge of the water, hesitating and scratching their head with a puzzled, innocent expression. The water looks inviting and sparkly. Nearby, a slimmer friend wearing sunglasses and confidently already swimming in the water, smiling and waving. A signpost by the pond humorously reads, ''Skinny-Dipping Zone.'' The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated, rounded character designs to emphasize the humorous contrast in body types. The scene feels cheerful and silly, without any negative or mean-spirited tone.'),
 (3088, 'Body Positivity Humor, Humor, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, breaking up would be a lot easier, a smack on the butt and a ''Nice hustle, you''ll get''em next time'' would pretty much do it.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of two people breaking up. The setting is a casual living room with a couch and a coffee table. The man, depicted with a lighthearted smirk, is gently giving the woman a playful pat on her backside, as if saying goodbye. The woman looks amused and slightly surprised, smiling with raised eyebrows. To emphasize the joke, include a speech bubble above the man that says, ''Nice hustle, you''ll get ''em next time.'' The overall style should be friendly and exaggerated for comedic effect, with bright colors and expressive faces. No violence or anger; just a cheeky and funny break-up moment with lighthearted body language and a warm, informal setting.'),
 (2626, 'Body Positivity Humor, Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Steven Wright', 'A conscience is what hurts when all your other parts feel so good.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a relaxed, smiling person lounging comfortably in a cozy living room. Their body is depicted with various exaggerated parts—muscles flexing, legs stretched out, a smiling face—each looking blissfully happy and relaxed, with little sparkling effects or smiley faces on them. However, the person''s conscience is personified as a small, cartoonish ghost or angel hovering near their shoulder, looking distressed or wincing in pain, holding its head or grimacing, as if troubled or in discomfort. The contrast is clear: the body parts are joyful and carefree, while the conscience looks uncomfortable or regretful. The background should be simple, cozy, with a couch or chair, a lamp, and a small coffee table, emphasizing the relaxed physical state apart from the conscience’s discomfort. Bright, cheerful colors for body parts, contrasting with a slightly muted or worried expression on the conscience figure. Nothing violent or intense, just a lighthearted visual emphasizing internal conflict in a funny, exaggerated cartoon style.'),
 (2627, 'Body Positivity Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Steven Wright', 'A conscience is what hurts when all your other parts feel so good.', 'Steven Wright', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a relaxed person lounging comfortably in a cozy armchair with a big smile and content expression. Around them, depict several body parts relaxing or celebrating—like a happy stomach holding a drink, smiling muscles flexing, and feet stretched out with sandals. Above the person’s head, include a small, ghostly or transparent figure labeled ''Conscience'' looking sore, uncomfortable, or holding its side as if in pain, contrasting sharply with the joyful vibe of the other parts. The setting should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated, comical facial expressions on all the elements to emphasize the contrast between the cheerful body parts and the pained conscience. Avoid any violent, sexual, or political imagery.'),
 (2875, 'Book Humor, Friends, Relatable, Unknown', 'Friends: People who borrow my books and set wet glasses on them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two friends sitting together in a cozy living room. One friend looks annoyed, holding a slightly soggy book with visible water rings on the cover and pages. The other friend, smiling sheepishly, holds a wet glass with some condensation dripping down. On a nearby small table, several books are stacked, some with clearly visible water stains and ring marks. The setting is casual with a couch, lamp, and a coffee table to suggest a relaxed bookish hangout. The overall style is lighthearted and clean, emphasizing the playful frustration of a book lover dealing with careless friends who put wet glasses on their books.'),
 (282, 'Books, Cartoon, Facts, Good Question!', 'The name Wendy was made up for the book ''Peter Pan''.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy old library or study room filled with shelves of books. At the center, show a cheerful author sitting at a wooden desk, writing in a large open book labeled ''Peter Pan''. Above the author’s head, depict a thought bubble with the name ''Wendy'' floating inside it, as if the author just invented it. Nearby, have a playful cartoon version of Wendy Darling with a surprised or curious expression, sitting on a pile of storybooks. The background should include classic elements from Peter Pan, like a small flying fairy with sparkles, a pirate hat on a shelf, and a globe or map pinned on the wall. The overall vibe should be light-hearted and whimsical, highlighting the origin of the character''s name in a fun, imaginative way. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor in the idea that the author simply made up the name ''Wendy'' for the story.'),
 (2804, 'Books, Classic Joke, School, Unknown', 'Don''t worry, the answer''s at the back of the book.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy classroom or library setting, with a student holding an open book looking confused or worried. The book is large and clearly labeled ''Textbook.'' Behind the student, the teacher or librarian leans slightly forward with a friendly smile, pointing to the back of the book where a big, exaggerated sticker or label says ''Answer Key.'' Around the scene, other students are looking curious or amused, some whispering to each other. The background includes bookshelves filled with colorful books, a chalkboard with some scattered notes, and a desk with scattered papers and pencils. The overall art style is playful with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s lighthearted reassurance.'),
 (1820, 'Books, Dry Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I have read your book and much like it.', 'Moses Hadas (1900-1966)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting in a cozy living room. One character is holding a book with a slightly confused or amused expression, while the other stands nearby with a modest smile. The book''s cover should be visible but generic, with a simple title like "Your Book." To emphasize the subtle humor, include a thought bubble above the reader that says, "I have read your book and much like it," with a slight pause or ellipsis to hint at the understated praise. The style should be lighthearted and expressive, with exaggerated facial features to convey the dry wit of the statement. The background can include a bookshelf, a comfy chair, and a small side table with a coffee cup to set a relaxed, informal atmosphere. The overall tone is polite but funny in a low-key way.'),
 (2443, 'Books, Education Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'There''s many a bestseller that could have been prevented by a good teacher.', 'Flannery O''Connor (1925-1964)', 'A humorous cartoon scene in a bright, colorful classroom. A teacher, looking slightly frustrated but good-natured, stands in front of a chalkboard filled with messy scribbles and crossed-out words. In front of the teacher, a student excitedly holds up a large, thick book labeled ''Bestseller'' with an exaggeratedly proud grin. Around the classroom, humorous visual cues convey the joke: for example, a bookshelf overflowing with famous books titled ''Could’ve Been Prevented,'' and a stack of graded papers marked with big red X''s and notes like ''Needs work'' and ''Rewrite this!''. Other students look amused or confused. The teacher wears glasses and holds a red pen like a baton, gesturing as if saying, ''If only...'' The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with expressive faces to emphasize the irony of the joke without any negativity.'),
 (2461, 'Books, Education Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Those who don''t read have no advantage over those who can''t.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room filled with scattered books and reading materials. In the center, two characters sit side by side on a couch. One is happily reading a thick book with glasses on, surrounded by neat piles of books labeled ''Knowledge'' and ''Learning.'' The other character looks equally relaxed but is casually scrolling on a phone or staring blankly into space, with a nearby closed book collecting dust. Both characters look similar, emphasizing that one is choosing not to read while the other is capable. Above them is a thought bubble showing a simplified thought process: the reader imagines themselves gaining knowledge and growing, while the non-reader imagines the same with a question mark or empty space. The overall vibe is lighthearted and slightly ironic, without any negative or hostile elements. The background might include a bookshelf, a comfy lamp, and a window with sun shining to reflect the positivity of reading.'),
 (3172, 'Books, Fantasy Humor, Pun, Star Wars', 'I’ve reading a book about using the Force to do levitation. I can’t put it down!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person excitedly holding an open book titled ''How to Use the Force for Levitation.'' The person is floating a few inches above the ground, looking surprised and joyful. Around them, small objects like a floating pencil, a hat, and a pair of glasses hover in midair, illustrating levitation. The background is simple, with a bookshelf labeled ''Magic & Mysticism'' and a few sparkles or magical stars around to emphasize the ''Force'' theme. The character wears casual clothes and sports a playful, wide-eyed expression. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features for comedic effect but no violence or inappropriate content.'),
 (283, 'Books, Humor, Movies', 'Never judge a book by a motion picture with the same title.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large open book sitting on a table with a small movie projector next to it. The book has a surprised or disappointed facial expression with eyes and a mouth, looking towards the projector. The projector is displaying a brightly colored, exaggeratedly bad or silly movie scene on a screen behind them. Around the scene, scattered popcorn and a few film reels add to the movie theme. The background suggests a cozy living room or library setting with shelves of books and framed movie posters on the wall, one showing the same title as the book. The art style is playful and cartoonish, emphasizing the idea that judging a book based on its film adaptation leads to mismatched expectations and humorous disappointment.'),
 (1706, 'Books, Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'From the moment I picked your book up until I laid it down I was convulsed with laughter. Some day I intend reading it.', 'Groucho Marx (1895-1977)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person holding a book with a big grin on their face, doubled over in laughter. The person is sitting comfortably in a cozy armchair with a side table nearby holding a lamp and a steaming cup of tea or coffee. The book''s cover is visible, with the title humorously exaggerated as a thick, dull book. Surrounding the person are floating cartoon-style laughter marks (like ''Ha Ha'' or squiggly lines) emphasizing uncontrollable laughter. The background should be a simple living room setting with a bookshelf filled with books to show a reader''s environment. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions and body language to portray the joke''s punchline—laughing at the book before actually reading it.'),
 (2268, 'Books, Humor, Quotes, Sarcasm', 'Thank you for sending me a copy of your book - I''ll waste no time reading it.', 'Moses Hadas (1900-1966)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing in a cozy, well-lit living room. One character is holding a freshly printed book labeled with the other person''s name on the cover, looking excited and hopeful. The second character, smirking with a raised eyebrow, holds the book casually and says, ''Thank you for sending me a copy of your book - I''ll waste no time reading it.'' Around them, playful details like a ticking clock showing the passage of time and a comfy armchair with a ''To Read'' pile of books add to the humor. The expressions should be exaggerated: the giver looks proud and optimistic, while the reader displays sarcastic amusement. The style is colorful and cartoonish, with clear facial expressions and simple background furniture (bookshelf, lamp, rug) emphasizing the casual but witty nature of the interaction.'),
 (1997, 'Books, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'It''s a good thing for an uneducated man to read books of quotations.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting an uneducated-looking man sitting in a cozy, cluttered room filled with stacks of books labeled ''Quotations.'' The man is wearing simple, slightly worn clothes with a confused yet determined expression on his face. He holds an open book titled ''Quotes'' in one hand while scratching his head with the other, surrounded by floating, whimsical speech bubbles containing famous quotes in quirky fonts. The background includes a small table with a teacup and reading glasses, emphasizing the reading setting. The overall atmosphere is lighthearted and playful, highlighting the irony of an uneducated man earnestly trying to learn through quotation books.'),
 (1674, 'Books, Inspirational, Quotes, Word Play', 'Every new beginning comes from some other beginning''s end.', 'Semisonic', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a cheerful, animated book standing upright with a smiling face on its cover, waving goodbye with one hand. Behind it, a slightly worn-out, old-looking book with a tired but content expression is closing itself, signaling the end of its chapter. The background shows a simple, cozy bookshelf with a few other colorful books, some standing, some leaning. Above them, a banner or a floating-caption reads the phrase: "Every new beginning comes from some other beginning''s end." The style is bright and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and lively colors to emphasize the positive and cyclical nature of beginnings and endings, evoking inspiration rather than sorrow or loss.'),
 (1810, 'Books, Internet Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I find that a great part of the information I have was acquired by looking up something and finding something else on the way.', 'Franklin P. Adams', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer or a tablet. The person has a curious, slightly surprised expression as they look at the screen. Around them, floating in bubbles or thought clouds, are random, unrelated objects or facts they seemingly ''discovered'' by accident: for example, a dinosaur skeleton, a slice of pizza, a rocket ship, a funny cat meme, and a historical figure with a question mark above their head. The background should convey a cozy study or home office with bookshelves and quirky items, emphasizing the theme of unexpected learning journeys. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, highlighting the idea of wandering through information and finding surprising things along the way.'),
 (2363, 'Books, Puns, Quotes, Word Play', 'The paperback is very interesting, but I find it will never replace the hardcover book -- it makes a very poor doorstop.', 'Alfred Hitchcock', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two books on a wooden floor near a front door. One book is clearly a bulky hardcover with a serious, proud facial expression, standing upright like a dignified character. The other is a thin paperback, slightly worn and a bit scruffy, looking a bit frustrated or resigned. The paperback is lying flat on the floor, but instead of being used as a doorstop, the door remains wide open, emphasizing the paperback’s failure to serve as an effective doorstop. The door itself should be simple and slightly ajar, with a small breeze indicated by fluttering papers nearby or a curtain moving. Add a subtle thought bubble above the paperback expressing the line, “I make a very poor doorstop.” The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoonish expressions on the books to convey humor without words. Avoid any real people or violence, focusing solely on the books and the door to illustrate the joke visually.'),
 (1376, 'Books, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'A classic is something that everybody wants to have read and nobody wants to read.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cozy, slightly cluttered living room. Center the image around a stylish bookshelf packed with colorful, well-worn classic books. In front of the bookshelf, depict a group of people standing or sitting together, each looking at the books with eager, admiring expressions but none holding or actively reading a book. One person might be holding a cup of tea, looking slightly hesitant as if about to start reading but unsure. Nearby, a pile of classic books lies untouched on a small table or on the floor. Add small humorous details like a reading lamp casting warm light, glasses resting on the table, and a cat napping peacefully on one of the books. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the irony that everyone values classics but avoids actually reading them. The style should be colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to capture the joke’s ironic nature, without any violent or inappropriate content.'),
 (2147, 'Business Humor, Cultural Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'No one ever went broke underestimating the taste of the American public.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident, slightly smug-looking businessman standing behind a display table labeled ''American Public Taste''. The table is cluttered with odd, unattractive products like a weirdly-flavored snack, a garish neon-colored appliance, and a bizarrely designed clothing item that looks clearly unpopular. The businessman is shrugging with a speech bubble that says, ''No one ever went broke underestimating the taste of the American public.'' Around him, a small group of puzzled or unimpressed cartoon shoppers walk by without interest. The setting is a bright, exaggeratedly colorful marketplace with exaggeratedly large signs and banners advertising the strange products. The style is playful, with exaggerated expressions and clear visual cues of bad taste and poor product appeal, emphasizing the joke’s sarcastic tone without any negativity or criticism towards any individuals.'),
 (2933, 'Business Humor, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Hooters has filed for bankruptcy. Apparently their business model was a bust.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon depicting the front of a Hooters restaurant with the iconic orange logo visible. The building looks slightly sad or tired, maybe with a ''For Sale'' or ''Bankruptcy'' sign hanging crookedly on the front door or in the window. In front, a few owl mascots (friendly and funny-looking) are sitting with disappointed or worried expressions. Around the entrance, some spilled chicken wings and empty soda cups lie on the ground to suggest business is down. The scene should be colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoonish style emphasizing the ''bust'' pun by maybe showing a small, silly cartoon chicken literally ''bursting'' or ''busting'' near the sign, but in a non-violent, playful way. The overall mood is comical, poking fun at the business situation without being harsh or mean.'),
 (2239, 'Business Humor, History Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'So we went to Atari and said, ''Hey, we''ve got this amazing thing, even built with some of your parts, and what do you think about funding us? Or we''ll give it to you. We just want to do it. Pay our salary, we''ll come work for you.'' And they said, ''No.''   Apple Computer founder Steve Jobs on attempts to get Atari and H-P interested in his and Steve Wozniak''s personal computer.', 'Steve Jobs', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a simple, retro office resembling an early 1980s Atari workspace. On one side, two enthusiastic characters clearly inspired by Steve Jobs and Steve Wozniak hold a quirky-looking, homemade personal computer with visible circuit boards and wires labeled ''with some of your parts.'' The men are dressed casually but in a slightly nerdy, friendly way. Opposite them, a skeptical Atari executive sits behind a cluttered desk with a big Atari logo on the wall, arms crossed and wearing a disinterested expression as he says ''No.'' The setting includes early computer posters, old-school floppy disks scattered around, and a ''Funding Meeting'' sign on the door to set the context. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated with cartoonish facial expressions to emphasize the humor of rejection despite the innovation.'),
 (1631, 'Business Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'Distrust any enterprise that requires new clothes.', 'Henry David Thoreau (1817-1862)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a lighthearted business meeting room. At the center, a confident-looking business person stands holding up a very flashy, brand-new suit on a hanger, grinning widely. Around a conference table, a group of skeptical and slightly suspicious-looking people dressed in plain clothes stare at the new outfit with raised eyebrows and crossed arms. The background shows a whiteboard with a pie chart titled ''New Clothes Budget.'' A small sign on the table says ''Enterprise Meeting.'' Include exaggerated facial expressions to highlight distrust and skepticism, and play up the contrast between the flashy new clothes and the plain attire of the others. The style should be colorful and cartoonish, capturing the comic irony of the joke without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2499, 'Business Humor, Motivational, Office Humor, Quotes', 'Underpromise; overdeliver.', 'Tom Peters', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a business or office setting. In the foreground, a cheerful, confident professional (wearing a suit or business casual) is speaking to a happy-looking client or customer across a desk. The professional holds a large, empty-looking box labeled ''Promise'' and next to it is a huge overflowing box labeled ''Delivery'' with various big, unexpected goodies spilling out like gifts, trophies, or shiny products. The client looks impressed and pleasantly surprised, eyebrows raised and mouth open in delight. The background includes typical office items like a computer, papers, and motivational posters with the phrase ''Underpromise; Overdeliver'' humorously displayed on one of them. The cartoon style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated to enhance the comedic effect, highlighting the contrast between the small promise and the large delivery without any negative elements or references.'),
 (2158, 'Business Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Workplace', 'Nothing is ever gained by winning an argument and losing a customer.', 'C.F. Norton', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a small, cozy shop where a shopkeeper is having a verbal argument with a customer at the counter. The shopkeeper looks confident but slightly smug, pointing a finger upward as if making a strong point. The customer, looking frustrated or annoyed, is turning away while walking out the door, holding a shopping bag. Outside the shop window, a sign reads ''Open'' and a small queue of potential customers is shown diminishing as they notice the departing customer. The background should include shelves with products, a cash register, and a tiny ''Customer is always right'' poster ironically ignored. The style is light-hearted with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the comic irony in winning the argument but losing business.'),
 (2660, 'Calendar Humor, Comedy, Unknown, Word Play', 'At 12:01 am on Jan 1 2021 - for the first time ever, Hind Sight actually was 2020.', NULL, 'A bright, humorous cartoon scene showing a large digital clock mounted on a brick wall, displaying the exact time ''12:01 AM'' and the date ''Jan 1, 2021''. Below the clock is a fashionable, personified character named ''Hind Sight'' represented as a friendly, quirky figure with glasses and a party hat, holding a large magnifying glass labeled ''2020'' that shines a light backward. Behind Hind Sight is a large banner or billboard with bold text stating: ''For the first time ever, Hind Sight was 2020''. The background includes subtle festive New Year decorations like confetti, balloons, and streamers, suggesting a celebratory atmosphere. The art style should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun and the clever wordplay. The setting should feel like a city street or plaza at midnight, visually hinting at the passage of time and reflective wisdom tied to the year 2020.'),
 (284, 'Calendar Humor, Facts, Good Question!', 'Months that begin on a Sunday will always have a ''Friday the 13th.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon calendar page is shown prominently in the center, with the month labeled at the top. The month starts with a big, bold Sunday highlighted in bright yellow or a cheerful color. The dates line up clearly, making the 13th day fall on a Friday, which is marked with both a smiling cartoon sun wearing sunglasses and a little mischievous black cat sitting next to the number 13. Nearby, a character (a friendly looking person or an imaginative calendar mascot) points happily at the Friday the 13th date, as if revealing a fun fact. The background is light and cheerful with subtle calendar motifs, such as a clock or leaf icons, to keep the focus on the calendar month and the connection between Sunday beginnings and Friday the 13th. The style should be clean, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the amusing relationship between the days of the week and dates without any scary or negative elements.'),
 (574, 'Calendar Humor, Good Question!, Puns, Word Play', 'What days are the strongest? Saturday and Sunday, because the rest are weekdays', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a calendar character personified as days of the week. Saturday and Sunday are drawn as muscular, strong characters with flexed biceps, confident smiles, and sporty outfits or superhero capes. The other days—Monday through Friday—are portrayed as ordinary, less impressive characters with tired or neutral expressions, wearing office or school clothes. The background is a simple calendar grid with the days clearly labeled. Optional fun detail: Saturday and Sunday could be standing on small podiums or lifting cartoonish weights labeled with ''Strong'' while the ''weekdays'' stand aside looking plain or slightly weary, emphasizing the pun on ''weekdays'' versus ''weak days.'' The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and playful, suitable for a general audience without any violence or controversy.'),
 (2856, 'Calendar Humor, History Humor, Science Humor, Unknown', 'February 1865 is the only month in recorded history not to have a full moon.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a vintage calendar page for February 1865 pinned on a wall. The calendar should look old-fashioned and slightly yellowed, with the month and year clearly labeled at the top. Each day is visible but instead of full moon icons usually placed on the full moon nights, there are empty circles with an ''X'' or a sad face on them to indicate no full moon. In the foreground, a confused, slightly exaggerated Victorian-era astronomer or scientist character stands looking at the calendar through round glasses, scratching his head or holding a magnifying glass. Nearby is a telescope pointing at a dark, starry sky with no full moon visible, perhaps just stars and a crescent moon. The overall style is colorful, whimsical, and cartoonish with lighthearted expressions focusing on the rarity of this lunar event without any supernatural or scary elements.'),
 (285, 'Camping, Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Ghosts tell Chuck Norris stories around the campfire.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at night in a forest clearing around a glowing campfire. Several friendly, translucent ghosts with exaggerated, playful expressions sit in a circle, each with wavy, ethereal bodies and floating slightly above the ground. In the center, one ghost animatedly gestures as if telling an exciting story. Nearby, the iconic figure of Chuck Norris stands confidently, wearing his classic martial arts outfit, with a subtle, amused smile. The background includes tall trees and a moonlit sky with a few stars. The campfire has small logs arranged in a circle, and there''s a light smoke trail rising. The overall mood is lighthearted and funny, capturing the idea that even ghosts tell tales about Chuck Norris around the campfire.'),
 (286, 'Camping, Humor', 'You might be a RVer if roughing it is only water and electric.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a cozy RV parked in a scenic campground with trees and a campfire nearby. Inside the RV, a relaxed person is sitting comfortably on a plush chair with a cup of coffee, watching TV. Outside, the usual camping survival elements like a rugged tent and a small campfire with marshmallows on sticks are lightly faded or overshadowed by the RV''s creature comforts. A water hose and an electric cable are connected from the RV to nearby hookup posts labeled ''Water'' and ''Electric.'' The caption or a small signboard near the RV says ''Roughing It.'' The overall atmosphere is cheerful and lighthearted, contrasting the rustic outdoors with the convenience of a fully hooked-up RV experience.'),
 (287, 'Camping, Humor', 'You might be a RVer if you think it is completely normal to drive a F-450(or any dually) to the store to pick up a few groceries.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing beside a huge, exaggeratedly large Ford F-450 dually truck parked right outside a small grocery store. The truck looks oversized and comically big compared to the modest-sized store and a few shopping carts nearby. The person is casually holding a small grocery bag, appearing completely unfazed by the massive vehicle they drove just to get a few groceries. There should be a sign on the store reading ''Grocery Store'' and a few other shoppers with normal-sized cars giving amused or confused looks at the large truck. The colors should be bright and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity of using such a big vehicle for a small errand.'),
 (288, 'Camping, Humor, Life', 'You might be a RVer if you find yourself spending an inordinate amount of time discussing the merits of different toilet papers.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two middle-aged RV travelers standing next to a colorful camper van parked at a sunny campsite. They are both intensely examining several different rolls of toilet paper laid out on a folding table between them. One person holds up a roll labeled ''Ultra Soft,'' while the other holds a roll labeled ''Eco-Friendly.'' Around them, typical camping elements like a campfire, folding chairs, and trees can be seen. Both travelers have amused yet serious expressions, as if engaged in a deep debate about which toilet paper to choose. Include small details like a picnic basket, a map, and a sign that says ''Welcome to Happy Trails RV Park.'' The overall style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the quirky obsession with toilet paper among RV enthusiasts without any negative or political undertones.'),
 (289, 'Camping, Humor, Life', 'You might be a RVer if you think 300 square feet of living space is really living!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the interior of a very cozy RV. The RV is drawn in cross-section so the entire interior is visible. Inside, a cheerful person is happily lounging on a tiny sofa that looks almost as big as the available space. Around them, there are compact furniture pieces like a foldable table, a small kitchenette, and a bed folded up to maximize space. A window shows a sunny outdoors with a campfire and a forest scene, indicating they''re in nature. The person has a big smile and relaxed posture, portraying contentment with their small living area. A small caption or sign inside the RV reads "300 sq ft = Really Living!" to emphasize the joke. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, with exaggerated proportions to highlight the smallness of the space yet the person''s happiness. Nothing crowded or claustrophobic, just cozy and cheerful.'),
 (290, 'Camping, Humor, Life, Word Play', 'God gave us shin bones so we could find trailer hitches in the dark.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing barefoot in a dark backyard at night. The person looks surprised and slightly in pain, holding their leg where their shin has just bumped into a trailer hitch attached to a parked trailer or truck. The trailer hitch is clearly visible and glowing faintly to indicate that it is the ''hidden'' object causing the pain. Nearby, a cheeky, friendly-looking cartoon depiction of God is subtly shining a small spotlight or holding a flashlight aimed just at the trailer hitch, smiling knowingly. The background should be simple with a fence, some grass, and a moon in the sky to emphasize the night setting. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, focusing on the relatable scenario of accidentally hitting your shin on a trailer hitch in the dark.'),
 (291, 'Camping, Humor, Word Play', 'How many RVers does it take to change a light bulb? Only one - the others are dealing with their grey water issues.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large RV or camper parked at a campsite. In front of the RV, one cheerful camper stands on a small ladder changing a light bulb in the RV’s exterior light fixture. Nearby, two other campers are busy with exaggerated and messy grey water tanks or hoses, struggling comically with leaking or overflowing grey water. One camper might be holding a bunch of tangled hoses with water splashing out, while the other looks frustrated and is holding a wrench or bucket. The background shows a simple campsite with trees and a picnic table, adding to the outdoor setting. The style is lighthearted, detailed enough to clearly show the RV, the actions of the characters, and the humorous struggle with grey water tasks.'),
 (292, 'Camping, Humor, Word Play', 'You might be a RVer if you hang a ladder on your ladder.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing the side of a recreational vehicle (RV) parked at a campsite. On the RV, there is a large, extendable ladder attached for climbing onto the roof. Hanging from that ladder is a smaller, traditional household ladder dangling loosely as if ready to be used. Include a cheerful person dressed in casual camping clothes, glancing at the setup with a playful smirk or amused expression. Surround the RV with typical campsite elements such as a picnic table, a campfire, some trees, and a few camping chairs, creating a relaxed outdoor atmosphere. The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the silliness of putting a ladder on another ladder as an essential RV hack or quirk.'),
 (293, 'Camping, Puns, Travel Humor', 'An RV is the best investment you can make in wheel estate!', NULL, 'Draw a colorful cartoon scene featuring a large, cheerful RV parked prominently in a sunny campground. The RV should look inviting and well-kept, with wheels clearly visible. Surround the RV with a playful sign that reads ''Best Investment in Wheel Estate!'' in bright, fun letters. Include some happy campers around the RV, maybe a family or friends smiling and admiring the vehicle. The background can show trees, a picnic table, and maybe some rolling hills to set a relaxing vacation vibe. The overall tone is lighthearted and humorous, emphasizing the pun on ''real estate'' by focusing on a ''wheel estate'' pun with the RV as the centerpiece.'),
 (294, 'Camping, Puns, Travel Humor', 'You might be a RVer if you think the capital of the United States is Elkhart, Indiana', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an RV parked in a scenic spot with a family or an individual happily standing outside the RV. In the background, a large, colorful road sign reads ''Welcome to Elkhart, Indiana'' and looks oversized and prominent, as if mistaken for the nation''s capital. The character(s) should be pointing or looking proudly at the sign, with exaggerated happy or confident expressions. The RV should look detailed but friendly and inviting, with outdoor camping gear like folding chairs and a small grill nearby. The setting includes a sunny sky, trees, and a hint of a highway or rest stop to emphasize travel. The overall tone is lighthearted, poking fun at RV enthusiasts'' close connection to travel locations like Elkhart, known for RV manufacturing.'),
 (2694, 'Canadian Humor, Computer Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Canadian Dos Prompt: Eh?>', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a computer screen with a command prompt window open. Inside the window, the text input line is styled like a classic Windows command prompt, but instead of a normal prompt symbol (like ''>''), there is a flashing prompt that reads ''Eh?>''. Nearby, include a friendly-looking cartoon beaver wearing a Mountie hat, looking at the screen with a curious expression. The background can be a simple office or home desk setting with a coffee mug that has a maple leaf on it. The whole scene should have a lighthearted and fun Canadian theme, emphasizing the pun on the Canadian interjection ''Eh'' combined with a computer command prompt to create ''Canadian Dos Prompt''. Keep the style bright and colorful with rounded, expressive characters and simple lines to enhance the joke’s playful nature.'),
 (2722, 'Career Humor, Corporate Humor, Satire, Unknown', 'CONSULTANT: A jobless person who shows executives how to work.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a modern office setting. Show a confident-looking consultant, dressed neatly in business casual clothes, holding a clipboard or tablet and confidently explaining something. Nearby, depict a few executives sitting in chairs looking puzzled, tired, or even slouched with coffee cups or laptops in front of them. The consultant’s speech bubble reads, ''This is how you work,'' or something similar. The background can have typical office elements like a desk, a whiteboard with charts, a potted plant, and maybe a clock on the wall. The overall mood is light-hearted and ironic, emphasizing the contrast between a jobless person giving work advice to busy executives. The style should be simple and playful with exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (295, 'Career Humor, Don''t Say It!, Humor, Irony', 'People used to laugh when I said I wanted to be a comedian - well - nobody''s laughing now.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small comedy club stage with a single spotlight on a sad-looking stand-up comedian holding a microphone. The comedian is a middle-aged person with a slightly disheveled appearance and a hopeful smile fading into disappointment. Around the club, the audience seats are completely empty, emphasizing that no one is laughing or watching. A small sign behind the comedian reads ''Comedy Night.'' On the floor near the comedian, a single crumpled-up joke sheet lies, with a faint laughing face doodle crossed out. The overall mood is light-hearted but depicts the irony that the comedian once dreamed of making people laugh, but now no one is laughing at all. The style should be colorful and exaggerated facial expressions, typical of the cartoon humor genre, keeping it cheerful yet fitting the joke''s tone.'),
 (1572, 'Career Humor, Economics Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Ask five economists and you''ll get five different answers (six if one went to Harvard).', 'Edgar R. Fiedler', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing five economists standing together in a semi-circle, each holding a clipboard or chart with different and clearly conflicting graphs or answers. Their expressions should reflect confident disagreement or thoughtful confusion. Nearby, a sixth economist, distinguished by a Harvard sweatshirt or a Harvard pennant on their desk, stands slightly apart, smugly holding a unique answer or chart that differs from all others. The setting is a simple office or lecture hall with economic symbols like dollar signs, charts, and calculators floating around. Emphasize the playful contrast between the fifth and sixth economists to highlight the joke about varied opinions and Harvard prestige, without any hostility or negativity. Use bright, cheerful colors and round, friendly caricature styles to keep it light and funny.'),
 (2810, 'Career Humor, Everyday Life, Relatable, Unknown', 'Dreaming is what you do until the load is approved.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene inside a small, cluttered home office. In the center, a person sits at a desk with their head resting on one hand, eyes closed, clearly daydreaming with a peaceful smile. Floating thought bubbles above their head show whimsical, cheerful images like a beach vacation, flying in a rocket, and winning a lottery ticket. On the desk in front of them is a large, red stamp reading ''PENDING'' on top of a thick paperwork folder labeled ''Loan Application.'' A small calendar on the wall shows the current date circling the word ''Loan Approved'' sometime in the near future. The room has a window where sunlight streams in, emphasizing a hopeful mood. The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and playful cartoon with exaggerated expressions and soft lines to emphasize the humor of procrastinating real life responsibilities by daydreaming.'),
 (3021, 'Career Humor, Food Humor, Unknown', 'I once had a job as a waiter. It didn''t pay much, but it put food on the table.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a simple restaurant or diner. Show a cheerful waiter wearing a classic white apron and a bow tie, carrying a tray with a modest meal—like a small plate of food and a glass of water. The waiter is standing next to a wooden table with a few diners eating or chatting. The expression on the waiter''s face is upbeat and proud, highlighting the joke''s idea that although the job paid little, it literally put food on the table. Include speech or thought bubbles that emphasize his positive attitude about the job. The background should be light and friendly, with a menu board on the wall and some simple decorations to suggest a cozy but modest eatery. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerate the waiter''s smile to add to the humor without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (1779, 'Career Humor, Honesty Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I am not an economist. I am an honest man!', 'Paul McCracken', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing behind a wooden podium labeled ''Economics Lecture.'' The man looks like an everyday honest fellow, wearing simple clothes like a button-up shirt and glasses, with a friendly but slightly confused expression. Around him, there are scattered piles of coins, paper money, and economic charts with confusing graphs, some comically upside down or nonsensical. To emphasize the joke, a speech bubble above him says, ''I am not an economist. I am an honest man!'' The background is simple, perhaps with a classroom blackboard showing irrelevant doodles or question marks instead of serious economic formulas. The overall vibe is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and playful visual elements that highlight the man''s straightforward honesty contrasting with the complexity usually attributed to economists.'),
 (1584, 'Career Humor, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Being a hero is about the shortest-lived profession on earth.', 'Will Rogers', 'A humorous cartoon showing a comically exaggerated scene of a superhero recruitment agency or ''Hero Employment Center''. There is a colorful sign that reads ''Hero Jobs: Apply Within''. Inside, a long line of superheroes featuring classic costume elements like capes, masks, and emblems on their chests, all looking tired, frustrated, or worn out. Some have exaggerated wrinkles, torn costumes, or bandages. One hero in front is holding a resume while looking bewildered. Another hero, dressed in bright colors and mid-flight, is already fading or dissolving into small sparkles, symbolizing the ''short-lived'' nature of the career. The background includes a large clock with spinning hands or a calendar with many pages flying away, to emphasize time passing quickly. The overall style is light, cartoonish, and exaggerated for comedic effect, without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1536, 'Career Humor, Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'An executive is a person who always decides; sometimes he decides correctly, but he always decides.', 'John H. Patterson', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an executive in a typical office setting. The executive is a middle-aged person wearing a suit and tie, sitting at a large desk cluttered with paperwork, charts, and a cup of coffee. The executive is shown with a confident expression, holding a large stamp labeled ''DECIDE'' in one hand, which they are about to press down on a document. Surrounding the executive are two smaller thought bubbles: one with a green checkmark labeled ''Correct Decision'' and another with a red ''X'' labeled ''Wrong Decision.'' The executive is oblivious to which is which, emphasizing that they always make decisions regardless of the outcome. In the background, a calendar on the wall shows many crossed-out days, highlighting the ongoing nature of decision-making. The overall style is colorful and exaggerated in a lighthearted cartoon format with clear lines and simple shapes to enhance humor and relatability, avoiding any dark or negative tones.'),
 (2786, 'Career Humor, Irony, Unknown, Workplace', 'Don''t be irreplaceable. If you can''t be replaced, you can''t be promoted.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon office scene showing an employee at their desk looking both anxious and hopeful. The desk is cluttered with typical office items: a computer, papers, coffee mug, and a small plant. Behind the employee stands a boss holding a stack of promotion paperwork, pointing towards a taller desk labeled ''Manager.'' Nearby, an empty chair with a ''Replacement Ready'' sign is visible, indicating someone ready to take the employee’s place. The employee’s expression should capture the tension between wanting to be valued but also realizing that being too indispensable means no chance for advancement. Include a motivational poster on the wall ironically stating ''Be Irreplaceable!'' to add humor. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s irony, avoiding anything violent or political.'),
 (3020, 'Career Humor, Massage Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I once had a job as a massage therapist but I got fired because I rubbed people the wrong way', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person dressed as a massage therapist sitting sheepishly in a small spa treatment room. The therapist has an exaggerated worried or awkward expression, holding their hands mid-air as if they just finished a massage. Around them are a few cartoon clients looking surprised or uncomfortable, with exaggerated expressions of displeasure or confusion. The clients should have visible red lines or wavy lines near their backs or shoulders to humorously indicate discomfort. The background includes typical massage room elements like a massage table with a face cradle, a towel, some calming plants, and soft lighting. A small sign labeled ''Massage Therapy'' is visible on the wall. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun that the therapist ''rubbed people the wrong way'' literally and figuratively, without any mean or negative undertones.'),
 (1801, 'Career Humor, Music Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'I don''t know anything about music. In my line you don''t have to.', 'Elvis Presley (1935-1977)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a workplace setting. One character, looking clueless and slightly confused, is standing next to a musical instrument like a guitar or a piano with question marks above their head. The other character, dressed in a typical office outfit, is smiling knowingly and pointing at a sign on the wall that reads ''Job Requirements: No Music Knowledge Needed.'' The background features a simple office or workspace with desks, papers, and a computer, reinforcing that this is a non-musical job. The overall tone is light and comedic, with exaggerated facial expressions and clear visual contrast between the idea of music and the actual job responsibilities, emphasizing the joke about not needing to know music in the character''s line of work.'),
 (1338, 'Career Humor, Programmers, Programming Humor, Workplace', 'One bad programmer can easily create two jobs a year.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring an office scene with a stressed-out programmer sitting at their cluttered desk surrounded by multiple computer monitors showing confusing, error-filled code. Nearby, two bewildered IT workers or software testers are busy jotting notes and working to fix issues. Papers labeled with bugs, glitches, and error messages scatter the desk and floor. There’s a calendar on the wall highlighting two job openings posted this year. The programmer looks overwhelmed but oblivious to the chaos they''re causing. The overall style is lighthearted and comical, with exaggerated facial expressions and a mess of tangled cables to emphasize the programmer’s impact on creating extra jobs unintentionally. Include typical office items like coffee cups, sticky notes, and a motivational poster in the background that humorously says “Keep Coding!”.'),
 (2241, 'Career Humor, Puns, Quotes, Writing Humor', 'Some editors are failed writers, but so are most writers.', 'T. S. Eliot (1888-1965)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a cozy, cluttered writer''s den. One character is sitting at a typewriter or laptop, looking frustrated with crumpled papers scattered around, representing a struggling writer. The other character stands nearby with a slightly smug or self-aware expression, holding a red pen and a thick manuscript, symbolizing the editor. Both characters look somewhat disheveled and tired, emphasizing a shared sense of failure or struggle. In the background, there are bookshelves filled with books, piles of paper, and a coffee mug labeled ''Writer Fuel.'' A small, humorous detail: a wall clock shaped like a brain to represent creativity or mental effort. The overall style is light-hearted, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the comedic effect, using bright colors and simple lines typical for a funny cartoon.'),
 (1986, 'Career Humor, Quotes, Satire, Self-Deprecation', 'It is time I stepped aside for a less experienced and less able man.  (Said on his retirement from Cornell)', 'Professor Scott Elledge', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a formal office or academic setting at Cornell University. The central character is an older man in academic robes or a professional suit standing confidently at a podium or behind a desk, with a gentle, self-deprecating smile. He gestures with one hand outward as if making a dignified announcement: ''It is time I stepped aside for a less experienced and less able man.'' Around him, a few younger colleagues or assistants look surprised or puzzled, glancing at each other with raised eyebrows or sheepish smiles. The background includes Cornell University banners or an emblem to clearly indicate the location. The style should be light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the irony in the statement, with exaggerated expressions on characters for comedic effect. No dramatic or negative tones, just a cheerful and whimsical retirement moment.'),
 (296, 'Cars Humor, Food Humor, Word Play', 'Pound for pound, hamburgers cost more than new cars.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, juicy hamburger with a price tag hanging from it that reads a very high dollar amount, placed on a scale. On the opposite side of the scale is a shiny, compact new car with a much smaller price tag. The scale is tilted dramatically toward the hamburger side to exaggerate the idea that the hamburger ''weighs'' more monetarily. The background is simple, with a grocery store aisle visible behind the hamburger and a car dealership lot behind the car. The style is colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions: the hamburger might have a smug or proud face, while the car looks surprised or confused. No people are necessary, and the focus is on the scale, the price tags, and the two objects—highlighting the joke about cost comparison in a playful way.'),
 (297, 'Cars Humor, Humor, Life', 'Rule Of Thumb For Taxi Drivers: Stopping A Car: If you can''t read the odometer of the car in front of you at a stoplight, you''re too far back.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a red traffic light with two cars lined up. The focus is on the back car, driven by a friendly-looking taxi driver wearing a classic taxi cap and a big smile. The taxi driver is leaning forward, squinting intensely to try to read the odometer of the car directly in front. The front car is a typical sedan with its dashboard clearly visible through the windshield, showing a large, exaggerated odometer display with big numbers. Around the taxis, there are comical motion lines suggesting the driver''s effort to focus. Both cars are drawn with exaggerated, expressive faces on their front grills to add personality and humor. The background shows a simple city street with a red traffic light overhead and a few stylized buildings to set the urban scene. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and round, playful shapes to emphasize the joke visually without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (3214, 'Cars Humor, Humor, Mechanics, Pun, Steven Wright, Word Play, Workplace', 'My mechanic told me, ''I couldn''t repair your brakes, so I made your horn louder.''', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an auto repair shop. In the foreground, a cheerful mechanic wearing a blue jumpsuit and a cap is talking to a confused-looking car owner standing beside a small car. The mechanic is holding a shiny wrench in one hand and has a big grin, showing he replaced the brakes'' function with another trick. The car is drawn with exaggerated features: noticeably large, bulging tires and a comically oversized horn on the front bumper, exaggerated like a giant trumpet or megaphone. There are some car repair tools scattered around and a wall in the background with a sign saying ''Joe''s Auto Repair.'' A small speech bubble from the mechanic says, "I couldn''t repair your brakes, so I made your horn louder." The car owner looks puzzled but amused. The style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish with rounded shapes and simple but expressive faces to emphasize the humor without violence or negativity.'),
 (298, 'Cars Humor, Humor, Puns', 'This car will never age - it won''t go over 40!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of a car proudly parked in the center of the scene with a big, friendly smiling face on its windshield, as if it were a character. The car is small and boxy, clearly vintage, with exaggerated features like large eyes in place of headlights and a wide grinning bumper. Above the car is a large speedometer dial showing the needle stuck at 40 mph. Around the car, there are some subtle visual cues to indicate “aging” being stopped: a calendar with pages fluttering but staying on the same date, a cobweb nearby untouched, and an old-fashioned clock frozen in time. The background is a simple city street or driveway, bright and cheerful, emphasizing the car''s eternal youth due to its limited speed. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and expressive lines that emphasize the joke’s pun about the car never aging because it never goes over 40 mph.'),
 (299, 'Cars Humor, Humor, Travel Humor', 'The journey of a thousand miles begins with a broken fan belt and a leaky tire.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a long, winding road stretching far into the background, implying a very long journey. In the foreground, there is a small, vintage car that looks old and a bit run-down. The car has a visibly broken fan belt flapping loosely and a flat, leaky tire with air slowly hissing out, illustrated with little wavy lines or drops of air. The driver, a frustrated yet comical character wearing a cap, is standing next to the car looking at both problems with exaggerated surprise or disbelief. The sky is clear, and there are roadside signs indicating "1000 miles to go". The overall mood is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated cartoon expressions and bright colors to emphasize the misfortune at the very start of a long trip.'),
 (300, 'Cars Humor, Humor, Workplace', 'Never get in the way of a car that needs extensive body work.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a battered, old car with exaggerated dents, scratches, and missing parts like doors and a bumper. The car looks almost like a cartoon character with tired eyes formed by the headlights and a frowning front grille. There is a confused pedestrian or character standing in front of the car with a worried expression, hesitating to cross or get near it. Surrounding the car are obvious signs of heavy damage, like tools, paint cans, and a mechanic''s clipboard nearby. The background is a simple garage or street setting with a cartoonish style. The overall tone is light-hearted and funny without any violence or negative elements.'),
 (3003, 'Cars Humor, Pun, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'I heard Apple is designing a new electric car, but they''re having trouble installing Windows.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sleek futuristic car with an Apple logo prominently displayed on the hood. In the foreground, a frustrated cartoon character dressed as a software engineer wearing Apple-branded clothing struggles to fit a giant, old-fashioned computer window (like a Microsoft Windows logo designed as an oversized physical window frame) onto the car’s windshield area. Surrounding the car and engineer are scattered tech gadgets like a MacBook, iPhone, and charging cables. The car is parked inside a modern Apple-style design studio with minimalist furniture and large displays featuring Apple products. The engineer has a puzzled and comedic expression, scratching their head. The scene should feel lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the mix of technology and car design with a pun on the word “Windows.”'),
 (3082, 'Cars Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'If I had a DeLorean, I would probably only drive it from time to time.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing next to a shiny, classic DeLorean car with gull-wing doors open. The person looks thoughtful and a bit lazy, dressed in casual clothes, maybe with one hand on their chin. The background should be simple, perhaps a suburban home driveway or a quiet street during daytime. Include a clock or calendar showing dates passing quickly to emphasize ''time to time.'' The car should have exaggerated, slightly comical features to hint at its iconic time-machine reputation but without futuristic gadgets visible to keep it simple. The overall style is lighthearted and whimsical, capturing the pun on ''time'' through the car and the expression of the person reluctant to drive it often.'),
 (301, 'Cartoon, Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Weather Humor', 'There has never been a hurricane named Chuck because it would have destroyed everything.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a giant, menacing tropical hurricane with a swirling storm cloud in the shape of a strong, tough man named ''Chuck.'' This character is flexing his bulging muscles and has a confident, cocky grin. Around him, trees are bent over, houses are tilted or slightly damaged, fallen street signs and debris swirl in the wind, and a few frightened animals like birds and squirrels scatter away. In the background, a weather station building looks on in shock, with a meteorologist holding a clipboard and waving hands in disbelief. A large wooden sign next to the character reads ''Hurricane Chuck.'' The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and action lines to emphasize the power of ''Chuck'' the hurricane. The color palette uses stormy blues, grays, and a hint of vibrant colors for the sign and house details to keep it fun and visually engaging.'),
 (3177, 'Cartoon, Comedy, Star Wars, Star Wars Humor', 'What goes ''Ha, ha, ha, haaaa -- AGGGHHHH! -- Thump''? An Imperial Officer laughing at Darth Vader', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a Star Wars-themed environment inside the Death Star''s corridor. In the foreground, an Imperial Officer is laughing exaggeratedly with a big, open-mouthed grin and eyes closed, arms almost doubled over with laughter. His head is tilted back, and his mouth is wide open as he goes ''Ha, ha, ha, haaaa''. Suddenly, the next frame or scene shows the same Imperial Officer with a startled expression, mouth wide open shouting ''AGGGHHHH!'', eyes wide, and him stumbling backward. Behind him, Darth Vader is gently but clearly pushing or holding the officer''s shoulder causing him to fall or stumble, indicated by motion lines and a cartoonish ''Thump'' sound effect near the floor where the officer’s body almost hits the ground. Both characters are drawn in a fun, exaggerated cartoon style with clear Star Wars costume details: the officer wearing a grey uniform and hat, Darth Vader in his iconic black helmet and cape. The background is simple, with clean metallic panels and slight sci-fi details to emphasize the Death Star setting. The tone is light, playful, with vibrant colors to enhance the comedic moment.'),
 (2738, 'Cartoon, Country Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: Timber, I''m Falling In Love', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a playful country and western theme. Draw a rustic wooden signpost with the words ''Country and Western Song Titles'' written on it. Below the sign, have two exaggerated, anthropomorphic trees with comical faces and arms. One tree appears to be SPLITTING in half with a surprised expression, while the other tree is leaning or tilting forward as if about to fall, eyes wide with a happy expression. Above the scene, include whimsical musical notes floating around to indicate the song theme. The background should be a simple countryside setting with rolling hills, a fence, and a cowboy hat resting on a fence post to enhance the country vibe. Add a guitar leaning against one tree to reinforce the musical context. Use bright, bold colors and playful, exaggerated features to keep the tone light, fun, and cartoonish without any menace or negativity.'),
 (2729, 'Cartoon, Country Humor, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: If You Don''t Believe I Love You Just Ask My Wife', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room decorated with classic country and western elements, like a mounted guitar on the wall, cowboy boots by the door, and plaid curtains. At center stage is a middle-aged man wearing a cowboy hat and a slightly worried but playful expression, holding a microphone as if about to sing. Next to him stands his wife with an amused, knowing smile and arms crossed. A vintage jukebox in the corner displays a blinking sign that reads: "Country & Western Song Titles." Above the man’s head is a speech bubble that reads: "If you don''t believe I love you, just ask my wife." The setting should be lighthearted and comical, emphasizing the contrast between the man’s declaration and the wife''s amused skepticism. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated in typical cartoon fashion, with exaggerated facial expressions and clear, bold outlines.'),
 (588, 'Cartoon, Dental Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What does the dentist of the year get? A little plaque', NULL, 'Draw a lighthearted cartoon featuring a cheerful dentist standing proudly on a small stage holding a shiny trophy shaped like a tooth. Nearby, place a comically oversized, humorous plaque (a flat award) resting on a pedestal labeled ''Dentist of the Year.'' The plaque should look like a typical award plaque but with funny dental elements, such as cartoon germs or sparkling tooth illustrations. The background is a dental office with a chair, dental tools, and a big smiling tooth mascot cheering in the audience. The overall tone is bright, colorful, and fun with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun on ''plaque'' (the dental deposit vs. an award plaque). No realistic or scary dental images, keep it friendly and silly.'),
 (2481, 'Cartoon, Education Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'To teach is to learn twice.', 'Joseph Joubert', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, cheerful classroom. In the center, a smiling teacher is standing beside a large blackboard. On the blackboard, the phrase ''To teach is to learn twice'' is written in big, playful letters with colorful chalk. The teacher is holding a book open in one hand and pointing at the phrase with the other. Around the teacher, a few students are sitting at desks, looking amused or thoughtfully smiling. One student is raising a hand, perhaps about to ask a question, while another is lightly chuckling. The classroom is decorated with educational posters, a globe, and small stacks of books on desks. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions that convey the joy and irony of the joke, emphasizing the idea that teaching involves re-learning the information, hence learning it twice. No complex backgrounds, just a simple, relatable classroom atmosphere.'),
 (302, 'Cartoon, Engineering, Humor', 'Rube Goldberg, famed for his cartoons of crazy inventions, was a sewer engineer for the city of San Francisco.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a city engineering office labeled ''San Francisco Sewer Department.'' At the center is a quirky, slightly disheveled man resembling Rube Goldberg, wearing a hardhat and holding a blueprint covered with wildly complicated contraptions involving pipes, levers, pulleys, and buckets of water all interconnected in absurd ways. Behind him, a wall has framed cartoons showing intricate, nonsensical machines. Nearby is a large open manhole with a confused city worker peeking inside at a bizarre Rube Goldberg-style invention managing the sewer flow, complete with spinning wheels, swinging pendulums, and dripping pipes. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with bright colors, exaggerated expressions, and playful mechanical details, capturing the whimsical madness typical of Rube Goldberg inventions in an everyday city engineering context. No violence, politics, or anything inappropriate included.'),
 (1193, 'Cartoon, Everyday Life, Food Humor, Insults', 'May your cookie always be too big to fit in your glass of milk', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a tall, thin glass of milk sitting on a kitchen table. In front of the glass is a gigantic cookie way too large to fit inside the glass—its diameter is much wider than the glass opening. The cookie is round, chocolate chip style, with big, exaggerated chips. A quirky, smiling character (maybe a happy child or a simple cartoon person) is trying to dunk the oversized cookie into the glass, looking puzzled and playful. The background is a simple kitchen setting with a checkered tablecloth, a milk carton off to the side, and a plate with a few smaller cookies. The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the large cookie and the tiny glass of milk in a classic, friendly cartoon style without any complex details or backgrounds.'),
 (768, 'Cartoon, Everyday Life, Halloween, Pun', 'What do ghosts wear in the car? A sheet-belt.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a car where a friendly, classic cartoon ghost is sitting in the driver''s seat. The ghost is semi-transparent white, shaped like the traditional ghost costume with a flowing sheet-like appearance and two round eyes. Instead of a regular seatbelt, the ghost is wearing a seatbelt made from a white bedsheet, tied around its ''body'' just like a car seatbelt. The car interior should look simple and colorful, showing a steering wheel and a dashboard. The ghost looks happy and safe, with a small smile. Outside the car windows, a clear daytime sky with a few fluffy clouds can be seen. The overall tone is light and playful, emphasizing the pun on ''seatbelt'' and ''sheet-belt.'' Avoid any spooky or scary elements; keep the mood friendly and fun.'),
 (303, 'Cartoon, Facts, Good Question!, Humor', 'If Barbie were life-size, her measurements would be 39-23-33.  She would stand 7 foot tall and have a neck twice the length of a normal human''s neck.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a tall, exaggerated life-size Barbie doll standing next to a normal-sized adult woman for scale. Life-size Barbie should be about 7 feet tall with a ridiculously long neck twice as long as an average human''s neck, curving slightly. She has the classic Barbie blonde hair, bright pink dress, and iconic high-heeled shoes. The woman''s expression is a mix of surprise and disbelief as she looks up at Barbie''s towering height and impossibly long neck. Include a height chart on the wall behind them, clearly showing the 7-foot mark beside Barbie. Place a measuring tape stretched vertically from Barbie''s head to her feet. The setting is a brightly lit room with pastel colors and a simple background to keep focus on the giant doll and comparison. The cartoon style should be lighthearted, with exaggerated proportions to emphasize the humor without being mean-spirited.'),
 (1245, 'Cartoon, Family, Humor, Knock Knock', 'KK/WT: Hike? Unsuspecting son. Dad waiting with bated breath. Sets the perfect trap.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a picturesque forest trail. At the center, a dad with a mischievous grin and exaggerated anticipation is hiding partially behind a tree, holding a picnic basket and binoculars, clearly waiting in suspense. Nearby, an unsuspecting teenage son casually adjusts his backpack, looking ahead with innocence and excitement about the hike. The dad’s eyes are wide and sparkling as he sets a comically large and obviously fake trap on the ground made of sticks and leaves, resembling a typical jungle-style trap but exaggerated and cartoonish. The background includes tall trees, some birds, and a winding path continuing into the forest. The overall mood is lighthearted and fun, with vibrant colors and emphasized facial expressions to highlight the dad’s playful plotting and the son''s cluelessness. The art style should be colorful and exaggerated, typical of a family-friendly comic strip or cartoon, inviting viewers to share the joke about a dad eagerly preparing a ''trap'' for a simple hike outing with his son, symbolizing the classic playful dad-son dynamic.'),
 (781, 'Cartoon, Fantasy Humor, Halloween, Pun', 'Where do ghosts like to shop? At Bootiques!', NULL, 'A funny cartoon scene featuring a friendly, semi-transparent ghost shopping inside a boutique store called ''Bootiques.'' The ghost, smiling and slightly floating, is holding a stylish boot in one hand and looking pleased. The boutique should have a colorful, charming shop interior with shelves displaying various fancy boots—some sparkling or glowing faintly to match the ghostly theme. Include a playful logo sign above the entrance that combines a ghost icon and a boot, making it clear this is a ghost-themed shoe store. Add a cheerful shopkeeper, maybe a human or a cute ghost assistant, standing behind the counter, helping the ghost customer. The overall style should be lighthearted, bright, and whimsical, aimed to evoke humor through the pun on ''boutiques'' and boots with a ghostly twist.'),
 (612, 'Cartoon, Food Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What''s the fastest liquid on the planet? Milk... it''s pasteurized before you even see it!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a glass of milk with anthropomorphic features, like eyes and legs, dashing energetically across a kitchen countertop as if running a race. The milk is drawn in mid-stride, with little motion lines emphasizing its speed. Nearby, a surprised person or child watches wide-eyed with a stopwatch or a race timer in hand. In the background, a large calendar or clock shows the short time frame (to emphasize ''before you even see it''). The setting is a simple, bright kitchen with a milk carton labeled ''Pasteurized'' visible on the counter. The overall tone is light and playful, capturing the pun about milk being the fastest liquid because it''s ''pasteurized'' (played on as ''pasteurized'' sounding like ''past your eyes''). The style is colorful cartoon with exaggerated expressions and movement to enhance humor, avoiding any violence or inappropriate elements.'),
 (3227, 'Cartoon, Food Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'KKWH: Don. Don who? Don eat all the food, I want some more!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters at a dining table. One character is playfully scolding the other, who looks sheepish and guilty. The guilty character is holding an empty plate with a few crumbs left, while the other character gestures towards it. The table is set with various types of food—plates with half-eaten meals, an empty serving dish, a loaf of bread, and a bowl with a spoon. Both characters are smiling in a lighthearted way, emphasizing the joke’s playful tone. The background is a simple kitchen or dining room setting with a window showing daylight. The style is cartoonish and exaggerated, with slightly oversized heads and expressive faces to capture the humor in the wordplay. Include a speech bubble coming from the scolding character saying, “Don eat all the food, I want some more!” to highlight the pun in the joke.'),
 (2778, 'Cartoon, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Do you think Popeye''s chicken is fried in olive oil?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Popeye the Sailor standing in a rustic kitchen wearing his classic sailor outfit and pipe. In front of him is a large frying pan sizzling with pieces of fried chicken. A small bottle labeled ''Olive Oil'' is prominently next to the pan, with a few drops visibly falling into the oil. Popeye looks puzzled and curious, scratching his head with a raised eyebrow. In the background, a chicken wearing a tiny pirate hat watches the scene nervously, adding to the humor. The kitchen has a nautical theme, with ropes, an anchor hanging on the wall, and a tin of spinach on the counter. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated with bold lines and expressive faces, typical of a lighthearted cartoon.'),
 (2863, 'Cartoon, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'FLOPCORN: n. The unpopped kernels at the bottom of the cooker.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a popcorn cooker or popcorn box with a few unpopped kernels visible clearly at the bottom. The unpopped kernels should have little tired or disappointed facial expressions, looking like they''ve given up popping. The popped popcorn should be fluffy, cheerful, and overflowing from the cooker, contrasting with the sad ''flopcorn'' at the bottom. Add a playful label or title near the unpopped kernels that says ''FLOPCORN'' in a fun, bold font. The setting can be a kitchen countertop with a bag of popcorn kernels nearby. Bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated cartoonish expressions make it lighthearted and funny.'),
 (2960, 'Cartoon, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I ate too much Greek food - now I falafel', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person sitting at a table filled with various Greek dishes. The dishes include a plate of falafel balls, a bowl of tzatziki, pita bread, and a Greek salad with olives and feta cheese. The person looks full and slightly uncomfortable, rubbing their stomach with a big smile. Next to them on the floor is a single fallen falafel ball with cartoon motion lines indicating it has just ''fallen'' off the table or plate. The background has subtle Greek elements like a blue and white color scheme, a small Greek flag, or iconic white-walled buildings with blue roofs in the window view. The style should be bright, colorful, and playful to emphasize the pun about ''falafel'' and ''falling over,'' without implying any harm or violence, just lighthearted food humor.'),
 (3076, 'Cartoon, Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'If Burger King and Dairy Queen got married, would they live at White Castle?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two anthropomorphic fast food mascots dressed as a bride and groom getting married. The Bride is a Dairy Queen mascot, depicted as a smiling ice cream cone with a delicate veil and bouquet of sprinkles. The Groom is a Burger King mascot, shown as a cheerful king wearing a crown, sash, and holding a burger as a bouquet. They are standing under a wedding arch made of burger buns and ice cream cones, exchanging rings. In the background, there is a cute, whimsical house shaped like a White Castle building, complete with the iconic castle turrets and a welcoming front door. The setting is colorful and bright, with confetti shaped like fries and small soft serve swirls falling from the sky. The scene is playful, light-hearted, and cartoonish without any harsh lines or serious expressions, meant to evoke a silly idea of fast food chain characters marrying and living together in a castle-shaped home.'),
 (3238, 'Cartoon, Food Humor, Puns, Thanksgiving', 'What''s the best thing to put in pumpkin pie? Your teeth!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, fresh pumpkin pie sitting on a kitchen table. In front of the pie, there is a smiling cartoon character eagerly leaning forward with an exaggerated, open mouth and visible teeth ready to bite into the pie. The setting is a cozy kitchen with a window showing autumn leaves outside. The pie has a slice cut out, and crumbs fly humorously in the air near the character''s mouth, emphasizing the idea of biting. The style is lighthearted and playful, with bright, warm colors typical of fall/harvest season. The character should look cheerful and animated, enhancing the silly punchline of ''putting your teeth in pumpkin pie.'' No scary or harsh elements, just fun and friendly.'),
 (2873, 'Cartoon, Friendship Humor, Positive Humor, Unknown', 'Friends are like stars. Even though you can''t always see them, you know they''re always there.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a nighttime sky filled with twinkling stars. In the foreground, show a cheerful group of diverse friends sitting around a campfire, smiling and looking up at the stars. Each star should have a tiny smiling face to personify the ''friends like stars'' idea. Include a cozy setting with a tent, marshmallows on sticks, and a few trees for an outdoor camping vibe. The friends should look relaxed and happy, bonding under the starry sky, with speech bubbles showing phrases like ''Even when we can''t see each other...'' and ''We know we''re always there!'' The overall tone should be light, warm, and humorous without being overly sentimental, in a colorful cartoon style with exaggerated facial expressions for friendliness and whimsy.'),
 (1565, 'Cartoon, Geography Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'Are fjords sort of like pjontiacs?', 'Ingo Jobling', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing near a scenic fjord, which is a steep-sided coastal inlet with calm water surrounded by tall cliffs. One person is gesturing toward the fjord while holding a small toy car labeled ''Pjontiac'' (a pun on Pontiac) in their hand, looking confused but curious. The other character has a thought bubble showing a small, funny hybrid of a fjord and a car—imagine the fjord water shaped like the car with little cliffs as wheels. Include typical fjord elements like pine trees on cliffs, water reflecting blue sky, and a small boat floating on the water. The style should be colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions showing playful confusion and amusement. The background should emphasize the natural beauty of the fjord, while the characters'' interaction focuses on the pun comparing a geographic feature to a type of car. No text needed except the toy car label.'),
 (659, 'Cartoon, Good Question!, Math Humor, Pun', 'You know what seems odd to me? Numbers that aren''t divisible by two', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused cartoon character with a puzzled expression, scratching their head. The character is standing in front of a large chalkboard or whiteboard filled with numbers and math symbols. Prominently on the board are several numbers, some circled in red, clearly marked as ''Not Divisible by Two,'' such as 1, 3, 5, 7, 9. The character wears casual clothing and has exaggerated cartoon features for comedic effect. Around the scene, visual emphasis on ''odd numbers'' could include a cute anthropomorphized number 3 and 5, each with quirky facial expressions looking sly or cheeky. The background is light and simple to keep the focus on the character and the numbers. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, suitable for a general audience, focusing on the simple math joke about odd numbers being ''odd'' or strange.'),
 (571, 'Cartoon, Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'What can you hold in your right hand but never in your left hand? Your left hand!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing two hands floating in the air against a simple, light-colored background. The right hand is palm-up and holding a smaller left hand, as if cradling it carefully. The left hand, looking slightly puzzled with eyes and a quirky smile drawn on its palm, is held just above an open right palm. Around them, small motion lines emphasize the idea of holding. The scene should be bright, cheerful, and playful, with exaggerated cartoon proportions and a friendly style that emphasizes the silly logic of the joke. Include subtle comedic elements like the left hand''s eyes and smile to personify it and add to the humor.'),
 (608, 'Cartoon, Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'What''s the best time of day? 6:30, hands down.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, classic analog clock with clearly visible hour and minute hands pointing exactly at 6:30. The clock has exaggerated, expressive eyes and a wide smile, as if it is proudly declaring the best time. Around the clock, several smaller clocks look on in admiration or surprise. The background is a simple indoor setting like a living room or a classroom wall. One or two characters, drawn in a light-hearted, cartoonish style, stand nearby laughing or giving thumbs-up, emphasizing the pun ''hands down.'' The phrase "6:30, hands down" could be playfully written or included as a caption or speech bubble from the main clock, reinforcing the pun visually. The scene should be bright, cheerful, and kid-friendly with bold lines and vibrant colors to enhance the joke''s playful tone.'),
 (613, 'Cartoon, Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'When is a door not a door? When it''s ajar', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic wooden door standing slightly open (ajar) inside a simple hallway. The door has eyes and a mouth, giving it a surprised or quirky expression as if reacting to being ''not a door.'' The door''s edge is visibly tilted to emphasize that it is slightly open. Behind the door, faint light spills through the opening, and a small caption bubble above the door says, "When is a door not a door?" with a second bubble near the door saying, "When it''s ajar!". The background is a simple interior room with a doormat and a wall clock to provide context. The style is colorful and playful, exaggerated facial features on the door to enhance the joke''s pun, making it clear and amusing without any threatening or inappropriate content.'),
 (304, 'Cartoon, Good Question!, Puns, Space Humor', 'Do stars clean themselves with meteor showers?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in outer space showing a big, bright star personified with a friendly face, big eyes, and a wide smile. The star is holding a large cartoon-style broom or mop, sweeping or cleaning space dust off its glowing surface. Around the star, several small meteors are flying toward it like a shower of droplets, as if they are water droplets falling to help clean the star. Include a backdrop of sparkly stars, planets in the distance, and a dark starry sky to set the space environment. The overall tone is lighthearted, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated expressions on the star to show it enjoying or responding to the ''meteor shower cleaning.'' The style should be simple, bright, and cartoonish to emphasize the joke visually without any threatening or negative imagery.'),
 (600, 'Cartoon, Good Question!, Puns, Word Play', 'What word become shorter if you add two letters to it? Short', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a large, colorful sign or poster with the word ''SHORT'' written bold and big in the center. To the right, two big, cartoonish letters ''E'' and ''R'' are playfully jumping or being added onto the end of the word ''SHORT''. The letters appear lively and cheerful, as if proudly joining the word. Above the scene, include a whimsical question text: ''What word becomes shorter if you add two letters to it?'' The background is simple and bright, resembling a classroom or comic strip style, with a puzzled character (perhaps a curious child or a thinking cartoon animal like a fox) looking at the word and the letters with an intrigued expression. The overall style should be humorous and lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions and simple, bold lines to emphasize the joke visually.'),
 (788, 'Cartoon, Halloween, Pun', 'Why do ghosts go to bars? For the booos', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy, dimly lit bar decorated with cobwebs and spooky Halloween-themed decorations like pumpkins and bats. Several cute, translucent ghosts with friendly expressions are sitting at the bar stools, holding drinks in their ghostly hands. One ghost is cheerfully raising a glowing drink, and a bartender ghost wearing a bow tie is smiling behind the bar. The bar counter has a sign or label with the word ''Booos'' humorously written on it, like a special drink menu. The atmosphere is lighthearted and not scary, with exaggerated cartoon features making the ghosts playful and charming rather than spooky. The background shows shelves with bottles emitting a faint ghostly glow and a few spectral patrons chatting happily, creating a fun, pun-focused visual pun on ''boos'' and ''booze.'''),
 (2608, 'Cartoon, Humor, Inspirational, Quotes', 'You have brains in your head. You have feet in your shoes. You can steer yourself any direction you choose. you''re on your own. And you know what you know. And YOU are the guy who''ll decide where to go.', 'Dr. Seuss - Oh, The Places you''ll Go', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful cartoon character standing confidently at a crossroads or street intersection. The character is wearing bright shoes and has a big, cartoonishly large brain visible inside a transparent head, emphasizing ''brains in your head.'' The character is holding a map loosely in one hand, while with the other hand, they are pointing forward, symbolizing ''steering yourself any direction you choose.'' Around the character are whimsical directional signs pointing in multiple funny directions (like ''Your Choice,'' ''Adventure,'' ''Mystery,'' and ''Success''). The background is simple with a sunny sky and a few trees, giving an optimistic, uplifting vibe. The style should be lighthearted and playful with bright colors and exaggerated features to capture the motivational tone in a humorous way, suitable for all ages and free of any violence or controversial themes.'),
 (305, 'Cartoon, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Walt Disney is in suspended animation.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Walt Disney inside a large, clear, futuristic glass tube or chamber labeled ''Suspended Animation.'' Walt is depicted with his iconic glasses, mustache, and neat suit, looking calm and peaceful as if simply resting. Around the chamber are whimsical Disney-themed decorations like Mickey Mouse ears, a small castle model, and animated sketches floating in the air, suggesting creativity in pause. Nearby, a quirky scientist in a lab coat with cartoonish gadgets looks on, scratching his head in mild confusion. A small sign on the chamber reads: ''Wake Me Up Before Tomorrowland!'' The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated with soft lines, capturing a lighthearted, playful mood without any threatening imagery or dark tones.'),
 (1837, 'Cartoon, Humor, Quotes, Science Fiction Humor', 'I sense danger, Will Robinson!', 'Robot YM3', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a young boy named Will Robinson standing in the middle of a futuristic spaceship control room. Will looks startled and is pointing outward with wide eyes. Beside him is a classic-style robot, designed with retro sci-fi elements, raising its arm dramatically as if warning him. The background includes glowing control panels, blinking lights, and futuristic monitors showing warning signs. The atmosphere is colorful and playful, emphasizing a slightly exaggerated, cartoonish sci-fi vibe. The robot''s speech bubble says: ''I sense danger, Will Robinson!'' The boy''s expression is a mix of surprise and concern, adding to the humor of an alarm being raised in an exaggeratedly serious and dramatic way in a family-friendly, sci-fi setting.'),
 (3111, 'Cartoon, Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Why is E the nicest letter? Because all the other letters are naughty', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, lighthearted cartoon scene featuring alphabet letters personified as playful characters. The letter ''E'' stands in the center with a big, friendly smile, looking kind and approachable. Surrounding ''E'' are various other letters that appear mischievous or cheeky: they have sly grins, are winking, or engaging in small playful antics like sticking out their tongues, crossing their arms in a defiant pose, or whispering to one another. The letters are floating or standing on a simple plain background with soft pastel colors to keep the tone cheerful. Each letter should have expressive eyes and playful limbs to convey personality. The overall composition should be whimsical and fun, capturing the idea that ''E'' is the only well-behaved or ''nice'' letter, while the rest are clearly ''naughty'' but in a harmless, cartoonish way. No violent or mean expressions—just innocent mischief.'),
 (306, 'Cartoon, Humor, Word Play', 'PROFANITYPE: n. The special symbols used by cartoonists to replace swear words (points, asterisks, stars, and so on). It is yet to be determined which specific character represents which specific expletive.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a comic artist at a drawing table cluttered with pencils, sketch pads, and cartoon strips. The artist is mid-draw, looking thoughtfully at the panel where a character''s speech bubble is filled with a jumble of special symbols such as @, #, %, and *. The comic strip on the table clearly shows these symbols used to censor swear words, with small doodles or notes pointing to each symbol like a legend, humorously trying to guess which symbol stands for which curse. In the background, there is a whiteboard or poster titled ''PROFANITYPE'' with a playful definition written underneath. The setting is lighthearted and creative, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions on the artist to emphasize the fun confusion about the use of these symbols. No violence or offense is depicted; it’s purely about cartoon censorship symbols.'),
 (2959, 'Cartoon, Irony, Political Humor, Unknown', 'I asked my North Korean friend how it was there - he said he couldn''t complain.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two friends chatting. One friend is a smiling, ordinary person wearing casual clothes. The other friend is a stereotypical North Korean character, wearing a traditional uniform with a small red star pin on the chest, standing stiffly with a tight-lipped, serious expression. The setting is a simple park bench or café table signifying friendly conversation. Above the North Korean friend’s head is a small speech bubble that says, ''I can''t complain.'' Nearby, subtle visual hints imply the strict atmosphere: a small poster on the wall with a stylized eye watching, and a faint shadow of a guard in the background, drawn humorously but not threatening. The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon eyes and expressions emphasizing the irony, without any violence or political aggression.'),
 (1240, 'Cartoon, Jobs, Pun, Workplace', 'The man who fell into the upholstery machine is fully recovered.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing next to an upholstery machine in a factory or workshop. The man looks cheerful and relaxed, completely fine despite appearing a little disheveled, with a few tufted cushions or foam pieces stuck lightly to his clothes and hair, as if he’d been inside the machine. The upholstery machine should look like a large industrial sewing or stuffing machine used for upholstering furniture, with visible springs, cotton stuffing, and fabric rolls nearby. The background can include a few pieces of partially upholstered chairs or sofas. The man’s pose is upright and confident, smiling broadly to suggest he’s ‘fully recovered’ from his amusing accident. The overall style should be cartoonish and lighthearted, emphasizing the pun and visual irony without any threat or injury implied.'),
 (3112, 'Cartoon, Language, Unknown, Word Play', 'Why is the letter ''W'' not called ''double V''?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large friendly-looking letter ''W'' standing proudly in the center. Around it, smaller letters ''V'' are positioned side-by-side, looking confused and trying to justify why ''W'' should be called ''double V''. The ''W'' has arms and legs, smiling confidently, while the two ''V''s appear to be pointing at themselves and whispering to each other with puzzled expressions. In the background, a teacher-like figure, possibly a cartoon alphabet book or a wise old letter ''A'' wearing glasses and holding a pointer stick, stands beside a blackboard with the words "Why ''W'' isn''t ''double V''?" written on it. The scene should be colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions for all letters to emphasize the joke. The style is simple and playful, suitable for a cartoon humor strip about letters and language.'),
 (1365, 'Cartoon, Lawyer Humor, Pun, Quotes', '99 percent of lawyers give the rest a bad name.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a large courtroom setting. At the center, show a group of exaggeratedly sneaky-looking lawyers in suits, whispering to each other with sly grins, holding briefcases and legal documents. Around them, place one or two honest-looking lawyers standing apart, looking frustrated or dismayed as they contrast with the others. Above or below the group, include a large, bold sign or banner that reads: ''99% of Lawyers Give the Rest a Bad Name.'' The style should be lighthearted and caricatured, emphasizing the playful exaggeration of the idea without anything mean-spirited. Optional comedic details could include a judge shaking their head or a jury looking confused. Scene should avoid any realistic or harsh imagery and keep tone clearly cartoonish and funnier than critical.'),
 (1586, 'Cartoon, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Being on the tightrope is living; everything else is waiting.', 'Karl Wallenda', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a tightrope walker in mid-air, balancing carefully on a thin rope stretched between two tall buildings. The tightrope walker is drawn with exaggerated expressions of thrill and excitement, arms outstretched for balance, dressed in colorful circus-like attire with a small balancing pole. Below the rope, a crowd of relaxed people wait on the ground, sitting on benches, reading newspapers, or chatting, all looking bored and glancing occasionally at the tightrope walker with indifferent expressions. The background shows a clear sky with fluffy clouds, and a simple cityscape. A speech bubble from the tightrope walker reads, ''Being on the tightrope is living; everything else is waiting.'' The style is lighthearted, vibrant, and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the excitement above and the mundane waiting below, all portrayed in a clean, comedic cartoon format.'),
 (1417, 'Cartoon, Music Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'A harp is a nude piano.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a grand piano drawn in a simple and cute style, with no keys or strings visible, standing upright. Next to it is a harp drawn with an exaggeratedly elegant and fancy frame, displaying visible strings. The harp looks like a ‘naked’ version of the piano, so the piano is fully covered with its wooden outer shell, while the harp is shown without the solid wooden keyboard cover, exposing all its strings. The piano has a slightly surprised or confused facial expression with cartoon eyes and a mouth, while the harp looks proud or smug. The background is minimal with a music stand and a few musical notes floating in the air to emphasize the musical theme. Both instruments stand on a wooden stage floor. The overall style is colorful and playful, suitable for a lighthearted, family-friendly cartoon.'),
 (1626, 'Cartoon, Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes', 'Democracy without morality is impossible.', 'Jack Kemp', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, classic ballot box labeled ''Democracy'' with a friendly, smiling face, arms, and legs. Next to it stands a smaller, confused-looking character labeled ''Morality,'' depicted as a glowing light bulb wearing glasses and holding a small rulebook. The ballot box looks happy and energetic, but without the light bulb nearby, it appears unsteady and wobbly, as if it''s about to topple over. In the background, a peaceful town square with voting booths and citizens casting ballots, some puzzled by the wobbling ballot box. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the metaphor of dependence between democracy and morality. Bright colors and simple shapes to keep it cartoonish and humorous.'),
 (1310, 'Cartoon, Pirates, Pun', 'What has 8 arms and 8 legs? 8 Pirates!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon featuring eight pirates standing side by side, each with a typical pirate look: eye patches, bandanas, striped shirts, and pirate hats with skull and crossbones. The pirates are arranged closely together so their combined arms and legs total eight arms and eight legs—meaning each pirate humorously has only one arm and one leg visible, highlighting the pun. The background is a simple pirate ship deck with a wheel, cannon, and treasure chest for context, under a bright sunny sky with a few fluffy clouds. The pirates show exaggerated, cheerful expressions with wide grins, some holding cutlasses or treasure maps. The style is playful and lighthearted, using bright, bold colors and rounded shapes to emphasize the joke’s comedic, friendly tone.'),
 (1313, 'Cartoon, Pirates, Pun', 'What''s the pirate''s wife''s name? Peggy!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful pirate and his wife on a small pirate ship deck. The pirate, dressed in traditional pirate attire with a tricorn hat, eye patch, striped shirt, and a peg leg, is smiling broadly. Next to him is his wife, a friendly woman with a pirate-themed bandana and colorful dress. A parrot perches on the pirate''s shoulder. A speech bubble near the pirate says: "My wife''s name? Peggy!" The background shows an ocean with a small treasure chest and a Jolly Roger flag fluttering on the mast. The overall style is bright, playful, and caricatured, emphasizing the lighthearted pun on the ''peg leg'' sounding like the name ''Peggy.'''),
 (2861, 'Cartoon, Pop Culture Humor, Science Fiction Humor, Unknown', 'Fire when ready, Mr. Sulu.', 'James T. Kirk', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a spaceship''s control bridge styled like a retro sci-fi setting. In the center is a pilot in futuristic uniform labeled ''Mr. Sulu'' sitting confidently in a captain''s chair in front of a large control panel with buttons and levers. The view outside the large window shows outer space with stars and a nearby planet or asteroid. A speech bubble from an off-panel character says, ''Fire when ready, Mr. Sulu.'' Mr. Sulu is hesitating or looking confused, with a thought bubble showing a big red ''Fire'' button that he is unsure about pressing. The cartoon style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and clear, colorful details to highlight the humorous moment of hesitation before a big command.'),
 (1340, 'Cartoon, Programmers, Pun, Word Play', 'Several fonts walk into a bar. ''Get out of here!'' shouts the bartender. ''We don''t serve your type here.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a classic bar setting. In the foreground, a stern bartender stands behind the counter, pointing dramatically at the entrance. The bartender should look animated and expressive, wearing a bar apron and bowtie. At the bar''s entrance, several anthropomorphized fonts each take on distinguishable appearances that hint at their font styles. For example, a bold blocky font character looks tough and square, a curly script font character appears elegant with flowing swirls, and a thin serif font character looks slender and refined. Each font character has arms and legs, and faces with exaggerated expressions of surprise or disappointment. The background should include typical bar elements like stools, shelves with bottles, and a signboard overhead that subtly displays the phrase ''No type allowed''. The overall tone is light, whimsical, and playful to emphasize the pun without any negativity.'),
 (1487, 'Cartoon, Pun, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Absolute zero is cool.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a thermometer character with a chilled, laid-back personality. The thermometer has a smiling face, sunglasses, and is reclining on a small lounge chair made of ice cubes. Around it, there are snowflakes gently falling and a frosty background suggesting extreme cold. A speech bubble above the thermometer says, ''Absolute zero is cool.'' The scene is lighthearted and colorful, focusing on the visual pun of ''cool'' with absolute zero temperature being extremely cold yet portrayed as ''cool'' in the slang sense. No people present, only the personified thermometer and wintery elements like snowflakes and ice cubes to emphasize the cold theme.'),
 (1736, 'Cartoon, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'Hanging is too good for a man who makes puns; he should be drawn and quoted.', 'Fred Allen', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man who looks like a classic pun enthusiast standing confidently in the center. Instead of facing traditional punishment, he is literally being ''drawn and quoted.'' The man is half-real and half-sketch: the left side of his body is fully colored and detailed, while the right side is drawn as a simple black ink line drawing as if an artist is halfway through sketching him on a giant easel or canvas behind him. Around the scene are large speech bubbles filled with clever, visible pun phrases emanating from the man''s mouth, emphasizing the ''quoted'' part. The setting is lighthearted with an artist''s workspace vibe—an oversized pencil or paintbrush rests nearby, and a drawing board or canvas stands prominently in the background. The man''s expression is one of joy or pride rather than fear, and the overall tone is silly and playful, not serious or dark.'),
 (2279, 'Cartoon, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'The backbone of surprise is fusing speed with secrecy.', 'Von Clausewitz (1780-1831)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a large, anthropomorphic spine (backbone) character looking both surprised and mischievous. The spine is illustrated with exaggerated vertebrae that have expressive cartoon eyes and a big, cheeky grin. The backbone is shown in mid-motion, slightly blurred to suggest speed, while sneaking around behind a large curtain or wall to convey secrecy. In the background, there are small comic-style motion lines indicating rapid movement. The setting is simple and bright, with no other characters but perhaps some faintly open doors or windows peeking to show the element of surprise. The overall tone is playful, colorful, and lighthearted, emphasizing the pun by combining the physical ''backbone'' with the abstract concepts of surprise, speed, and secrecy.'),
 (3256, 'Cartoon, Pun, Religion Humor, What do you call...', 'What do you call a sleepwalking nun? A roamin'' Catholic', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a nun with a surprised and slightly confused facial expression, walking in her sleep. She wears a traditional nun''s habit and veil. The nun is shown with her eyes closed, arms slightly outstretched as if sleepwalking. The setting is a simple hallway inside a convent, with soft lighting and a few religious details like a crucifix on the wall and a small window with stained glass. Around her feet, little movement lines hint at walking motion. To emphasize the joke, a subtle pun illustration element like a tiny pair of sneakers or shoes labeled ''roamin'''' could be added humorously at her feet, suggesting she''s roaming while sleepwalking. The style is light, fun, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect, using bright but soft colors to keep it friendly and gentle.'),
 (2822, 'Cartoon, Pun, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Electricity travels a foot in a nanosecond.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a tiny lightning bolt character wearing sneakers, depicted running along a ruler that is marked in feet. The ruler is stretched horizontally across the image and labeled ''1 foot''. Next to the ruler, include a very small stopwatch or digital clock showing ''1 nanosecond'' on its display. The lightning bolt character looks energetic with exaggerated motion lines to emphasize speed. The background is simple and bright, like a classroom or a science presentation setting, with a chalkboard or poster behind showing the words ''Electricity travels a foot in a nanosecond'' written in playful, hand-drawn letters. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, suitable for a science joke that''s fun and educational without being overly technical.'),
 (2825, 'Cartoon, Pun, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Entropy isn''t what it used to be.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room with a vintage-style clock melting and drooping off a mantelpiece, reminiscent of a Salvador Dalí painting but in a lighthearted cartoon style. Nearby, a book titled ''Entropy for Beginners'' lies open but with its pages slowly disorganized, fluttering as if caught in an invisible breeze. A confused cartoon character, an eccentric scientist wearing round glasses and a lab coat with a bow tie, scratches their head while looking at the melting clock and the chaotic book pages. The room contains typical quirky scientist elements like beakers with bubbling liquids, a blackboard with messy scribbles about thermodynamics, and a small fan gently scattering papers to emphasize disorder. The overall tone is whimsical and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, emphasizing the ironic pun that ''Entropy isn''t what it used to be'' by visually representing increasing disorder in a non-threatening, amusing manner.'),
 (2923, 'Cartoon, Pun, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Heisenberg may have slept here.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a simple, messy bedroom. A bed with crumpled sheets is centered under a bright window. On the wall above the bed is a quirky sign that reads, ''Heisenberg may have slept here.'' Next to the bed, place a blackboard or chalkboard with scribbles of physics equations related to uncertainty, like wave functions and question marks. Scatter a few scientific items around: a pair of thick glasses, a half-empty coffee cup, and a physics textbook lying open. The room should feel slightly disorganized but cozy, with soft lighting. The overall tone is light and playful, capturing the humorous suggestion that the famous physicist Werner Heisenberg, known for the uncertainty principle, might have rested in such a place, hinting at the idea of uncertainty in both physics and the exact location of his sleep. Draw in a simple, colorful cartoon style with exaggerated but friendly details, emphasizing the humor and whimsy of the reference without any complexity or aggression.'),
 (3158, 'Cartoon, Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'A physicist is trying to talk a man off the tip of the Empire State Building; he says, ''Don''t jump, you have so much potential!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting the tip of the Empire State Building on a bright, clear day. At the top edge, a nervous-looking man stands near the ledge, hesitating. Beside him is a calm, smartly dressed physicist with glasses, holding a clipboard and gesturing reassuringly. The physicist appears to be trying to reason with the man. Below them, the cityscape of New York City is visible in the background with tiny cars and buildings. Include a speech bubble coming from the physicist with the line: ''Don''t jump, you have so much potential!'' The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, focusing on the characters'' expressions to convey the pun on the physics term ''potential'' and the man''s situation. No dark or violent tones—keep it playful and silly.'),
 (3167, 'Cartoon, Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'Why can''t you trust an atom? They make up everything.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly-looking atom character standing in the center. The atom has a cheerful face with big cartoon eyes and a sly grin. Around the atom, several electron orbits circle with small, smiling electrons. Behind the atom, there is a large, exaggerated speech bubble with the text ''I make up everything!'' The background is a simple science classroom or lab, with a chalkboard showing a basic atomic diagram. The style should be colorful and light-hearted, with clean, rounded lines to emphasize the fun nature of the joke. The overall tone is playful and non-threatening, suitable for all ages.'),
 (3185, 'Cartoon, Pun, Star Wars', 'Why did Anakin cross the road?  To get to the dark side', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Anakin Skywalker standing at the edge of a crosswalk on a sunny, suburban street. Anakin is wearing his Jedi robes, looking determined but slightly confused. The road in front of him stretches across the image with whimsical crosswalk stripes. On the other side of the road is a large, dark, foreboding silhouette shaped like Darth Vader’s helmet, glowing subtly with dark purple and black shades to represent the ''dark side.'' Add a street sign reading ''Dark Side'' pointing toward that silhouette. Anakin is mid-step, crossing toward the dark side, with a small smile or smirk to show he is deliberately heading there. The scene should be colorful and playful with exaggerated expressions and cartoon-style proportions, avoiding anything too serious or threatening.'),
 (3176, 'Cartoon, Pun, Star Wars, Star Wars Humor', 'What do Imperial pilots eat for lunch? TIE food', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two Star Wars Imperial pilots sitting at a small cafeteria table inside a spaceship. Each pilot wears the iconic black helmet and uniform of an Imperial TIE fighter pilot. On the table between them is a lunch tray with a plate labeled ''TIE Food,'' which looks like a playful representation of a TIE fighter-shaped sandwich or meal. One pilot looks excitedly at the food, while the other looks amused. The background should hint at a spaceship interior with control panels and small windows showing space stars. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun.'),
 (3041, 'Cartoon, Puns, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'I swapped out our bed for a trampoline. My wife hit the roof', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, colorful bedroom. In the center, replace the usual bed with a large, bouncy trampoline that has a soft frame and springs visible around the edges. A surprised woman mid-jump is comically stretched out as if she just bounced off the trampoline and is hitting the ceiling with her head. Show a small dent or a slight crack with cartoonish impact lines on the ceiling to exaggerate the ''hit the roof'' phrase. The husband stands to the side, grinning mischievously with his arms crossed or giving a thumbs up. Include typical bedroom elements like a nightstand with a lamp, a window with curtains, and a rug, but keep the focus on the trampoline and the wife''s exaggerated bounce. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bold outlines and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s punchline.'),
 (2663, 'Cartoon, Star Wars Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Baby Yoda''s first word probably came out after his second word', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Baby Yoda (Grogu) standing in the middle of a room with an innocent but confused expression. Baby Yoda is saying a jumbled mix of sounds or words, with speech bubbles showing scrambled letters or funny symbols representing ''second word before first word.'' Around him, a human parent or caretaker watches with a puzzled or amused look, scratching their head. The room should be cozy and simple, maybe with some Star Wars-themed decor like a small floating cradle, some futuristic toys scattered about, and a wall poster featuring the Mandalorian helmet. The style is cute and exaggerated, emphasizing Baby Yoda’s adorable confusion and the humor of the language mix-up without any harsh or complex details.'),
 (2748, 'Celebrity Humor, Comic Humor, Movies, Unknown', 'David Prowse was the guy in the Darth Vader suit in Star Wars.  He spoke all of Vader''s lines, and didn''t know that he was going to be dubbed over by James Earl Jones until he saw the screening of the movie.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a movie screening room. In the foreground, a slightly confused and disappointed David Prowse, wearing the full Darth Vader costume and helmet, sits in a theater chair holding popcorn but staring wide-eyed at the movie screen. The screen shows a speech bubble with the iconic deep voice text, clearly labeled as James Earl Jones, while a small ghost-like figure of David Prowse’s own voice floats confused nearby with a question mark above it. Around him, other moviegoers smile or chuckle at the irony. The room has classic theater details like rows of chairs, dim lighting, and a movie projector in the back emitting light beams toward the screen. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the surprise and irony of the situation.'),
 (2656, 'Celebrity Humor, Comic Humor, Music Humor, Unknown', 'As James Brown says: ''Get up! Get Down! Owwww!''', 'James Brown', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene centered on a charismatic performer resembling James Brown on stage. The performer is in mid-dance pose with exaggerated energetic movements—one arm raised high and the other bent down low—capturing the essence of ''Get up! Get down!'' His mouth is wide open, caught in the middle of a powerful vocalization, illustrating the famous ''Owwww!'' He wears a flashy vintage stage outfit: a sparkling suit with wide lapels, platform shoes, and a big, stylish afro hairstyle. The background shows a lively stage with bright spotlights and a cheering audience drawn as simple, smiling cartoon faces in the shadows. Musical notes and comic-style action lines emphasize the movement and sound. The overall style should be playful and vibrant, capturing the dynamic energy and soul of a classic funky performance with a touch of exaggerated cartoon fun.'),
 (307, 'Celebrity Humor, Facts, Good Question!, Humor', 'Marilyn Monroe had six toes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style portrait of Marilyn Monroe styled like an old Hollywood movie poster. The scene focuses on Marilyn sitting elegantly on a classic dressing room stool, looking surprised as she lifts up one foot toward the viewer. The foot humorously shows six toes, each toe exaggerated and cartoonishly rounded to highlight the extra one. The dressing room mirror behind her reflects her face with a playful shocked expression. The background includes classic Hollywood elements like bright round vanity lights around the mirror, a makeup table with brushes and lipstick, and a star-shaped nameplate that reads ''Marilyn Monroe.'' The mood is light-hearted and whimsical, with soft pastel colors and smooth, rounded lines to keep the tone funny and non-threatening. No other characters are needed in the scene.'),
 (1361, 'Celebrity Humor, History Humor, Movie Humor, Quotes', '1955-1975: 36 Elvis movies. 1975-1989: nothing.', 'Tom Neff', 'A humorous cartoon scene divided into two panels side-by-side. The left panel shows a cheerful, vintage 1950s-1970s Elvis Presley character wearing his iconic jump suit and hairstyle, surrounded by film reels and movie posters with titles hinting at classic Elvis movies. The background is colorful, with spotlights and a crowd of fans waving and cheering. The right panel contrasts sharply, showing a dim, empty movie theater with a cobweb-covered projector, dusty chairs, and a blank movie screen. The Elvis character is missing, replaced by a large calendar page showing the years 1975-1989 with a big red zero or a sign reading ''No Movies.'' The cartoon style is exaggerated and playful, emphasizing the stark difference in movie production between the two periods without any people looking sad or angry, just the visual gap in Elvis’s movie career timeline.'),
 (1678, 'Celebrity Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Everyone wants to be Cary Grant. Even I want to be Cary Grant.', 'Cary Grant', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a casual, everyday person looking at a large, glossy old Hollywood movie poster of Cary Grant. The person, wearing simple modern clothes and glasses, has a dreamy expression with hearts or sparkles around their head to show admiration. The poster shows Cary Grant as a classic, suave gentleman in a tuxedo, flashing a confident smile. The background is a simple living room or a small movie theater lobby with vintage film reels or posters on the walls to evoke classic cinema atmosphere. The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between the everyday person and the glamorous Hollywood icon they admire.'),
 (2131, 'Character Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Nearly all men can stand adveristy, but if you want to test a man''s character, give him power.', 'Abraham Lincoln (1809-1865)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing with a confident smile holding a large, shining golden crown, symbolizing power, in one hand. Behind him, a group of diverse men is trying to stand tall on a rocky path representing adversity, looking tired but determined. The setting is outdoors with a simple, cartoon-style rocky hill or mountain path on the left side, with the men facing uphill holding various symbolic challenges like weights labeled ''problems'' or ''struggles.'' On the right, the powered man stands on a small pedestal or throne, holding the crown proudly but with a slightly mischievous or exaggerated expression to reflect inner character. The background is bright and simple, emphasizing the contrast between enduring hardship and wielding power. Include lighthearted details like small sweat droplets on the struggling men and a humorous sparkle on the crown to emphasize its allure. The overall tone is whimsical, non-violent, and clear in symbolism to illustrate the joke visually.'),
 (2505, 'Chess Humor, Games, Irony, Quotes', 'Victory goes to the player who makes the next-to-last mistake.', 'Chessmaster Savielly Grigorievitch Tartakower (1887-1956)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a chessboard where two players sit facing each other. One player, looking surprised but slightly smug, has just made a move and is pointing to the chessboard. The other player appears puzzled and is scratching their head, holding a chess piece mid-air as if unsure. On the chessboard, there are scattered chess pieces with one piece clearly knocked over to show a recent mistake. A small scoreboard beside the board humorously reads: ''Next-to-Last Mistake Wins!''. The room is simple and friendly, with a clock on the wall ticking and a little thought bubble above the surprised player''s head showing a tally of mistakes made so far. The style is colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the irony of the joke that winning comes from making the next-to-last mistake, rather than the last one. No aggression or negative emotions, just playful confusion and amusement.'),
 (308, 'Chickens, Food Humor, Puns', 'Egg salad is technically still chicken salad.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sandwich sitting on a plate with a thought bubble. Inside the thought bubble is a confused, cartoon-style chicken wearing glasses and holding a recipe book titled ''Salads.'' The sandwich is labeled ''Egg Salad'' with a few chopped eggs visible, while next to it on the table is a separate, traditional chicken salad sandwich with chunks of chicken. The chicken is scratching its head, looking puzzled as if trying to understand why egg salad might count as chicken salad. The background is a simple kitchen setting with a window and a salt shaker for added detail, all drawn with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor.'),
 (2578, 'Childhood Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'When you''re eight years old, nothing is your business.', 'Lenny Bruce', 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a playful 8-year-old kid with a mischievous grin, standing with arms crossed confidently. Around the child, exaggerated comic-like question marks and speech bubbles float, showing phrases like "Not my problem!" and "Don''t tell me!" The background is a bright school playground with swings, slides, and other children playing but ignoring the kid. The child is dressed in casual, fun clothes, like a t-shirt with a comic character and sneakers. The atmosphere is light-hearted and humorous, capturing the innocent carefree attitude of a kid who avoids getting involved in adult or complicated matters. The style should be exaggerated and whimsical, with bold lines and bright, cheerful colors that emphasize the humor and innocence of the child''s mindset.'),
 (3036, 'Children, Education Humor, Spelling Humor, Unknown', 'i souport publik edekasion', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a child standing in front of a classroom chalkboard. The chalkboard has the phrase ''i souport publik edekasion'' written in large, misspelled letters. The child is holding a piece of chalk, smiling proudly but clearly making spelling errors. Around the child, other children are giggling or looking confused. The classroom looks typical, with desks, chairs, a globe, and educational posters on the wall (some with playful misspellings as well). A teacher stands off to the side with a playful, amused expression, possibly scratching their head or facepalming gently. The overall mood is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the innocence and struggle of spelling words correctly in public education. The art style is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to highlight the humor without being harsh or mean.'),
 (309, 'Christmas, Food Humor, Holiday Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'The sweater I got for Christmas was picking up lots of static electricity. I took it back and exchanged it and they gave me a different one free of charge.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy clothing store decorated for Christmas, with garlands and a small Christmas tree nearby. In the foreground, a smiling customer is holding a large, fluffy sweater that has visible ''static electricity'' sparks illustrated as small zigzag yellow lines crackling around it, making their hair stand on end humorously. Across the counter, a friendly store clerk is handing over another sweater that has a smooth, harmless look with no sparks. Both characters wear casual winter clothes, and the setting includes shelves filled with folded sweaters and holiday gift signs. The mood is lighthearted and festive, emphasizing the funny situation of exchanging a ''static-charged'' sweater for one ''free of charge.'''),
 (315, 'Christmas, Food Humor, Holiday Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'The sweater I got for Christmas was picking up lots of static electricity. I took it back and exchanged it and they gave me a different one free of charge.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy clothing store during Christmas time. In the center, a smiling customer holds up a brightly colored Christmas sweater with visible blue static sparks crackling around it. The sweater should look festive with holiday patterns like snowflakes or reindeer. The customer looks a bit surprised but amused. Next to them, a friendly store clerk is handing over another new sweater, identical but with no static electricity visible, looking cheerful and helpful. A small sign on the counter reads ''Holiday Sweater Exchange''. In the background, shelves display more sweaters and Christmas decorations like a small Christmas tree with twinkling lights. The overall tone is lighthearted and festive, with exaggerated, cartoon-style expressions to emphasize the joke about static electricity and the pun on ''free of charge''.'),
 (310, 'Christmas, Good Question!, Humor', 'Didn''t you ever wonder how Santa Claus got into your house when you didn''t even have a chimney?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room decorated for Christmas, with a Christmas tree, presents underneath, and festive decorations like stockings and lights. In the center, show a puzzled child looking toward a surprised Santa Claus who is standing awkwardly next to a closed fireplace that clearly has no chimney above it. Santa should be wearing his classic red suit and hat, scratching his head or shrugging with a comical expression as if unsure how he got in. The room should also include a window with curtains drawn, adding to the mystery. Overall, the style should be light and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the fun and whimsical nature of the question about Santa’s entry method without a chimney.'),
 (311, 'Christmas, Holiday Humor, Puns', 'How much does Santa pay to park his sleigh? Nothing - it''s in the house!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the interior of a cozy, festive house decorated for Christmas. Santa Claus is parked inside near a large fireplace, with his sleigh and a team of reindeer comfortably settled in like they are guests in a living room. The sleigh is full of colorful wrapped gifts. The reindeer are lounging on armchairs or a rug, looking relaxed and happy. A large ''No Parking'' sign is visible outside through a window, while inside a small sign humorously reads ''Parking: Free for Santa.'' The house has festive decorations such as stockings hung on the mantle, a brightly lit Christmas tree, and snow visible outside the window. The overall tone is warm, cheerful, and playful.'),
 (312, 'Christmas, Holiday Humor, Puns', 'I couldn''t decide over Christmas break if I liked eggnog or not. I think I''m eggnostic', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set during Christmas break inside a cozy living room decorated with holiday decorations like a Christmas tree, stockings, and twinkling lights. In the center, depict a cheerful person holding a cup of eggnog in one hand, looking thoughtfully confused with a raised eyebrow and a slight smile, scratching their head with the other hand. Nearby on a table, show a carton or bottle labeled ''Eggnog'' with a few spilled drops to add humor. Include a small thought bubble above the person''s head containing a light bulb crossed out or a question mark next to an egg-shaped icon to hint at the pun ''eggnostic.'' The overall mood is light-hearted and playful, with bright, warm Christmas colors and a clean, simple cartoon style emphasizing the pun without needing words in the scene itself.'),
 (313, 'Christmas, Holiday Humor, Puns', 'What''s the very best Christmas present you can gives someone? A broken drum - nobody can beat that!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a Christmas living room decorated festively with a Christmas tree adorned with ornaments and a star on top. In the center, a cheerful person is handing over a wrapped gift shaped like a drum to another surprised recipient. The drum should look obviously broken — cracked shell, maybe a dent or a missing drumstick taped to the side. The recipient’s expression is a mix of confusion and amusement. Around them, subtle holiday decorations like stockings, gifts, and twinkling lights make the setting clear and warm. The style should be lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize humor without anything violent or inappropriate.'),
 (314, 'Christmas, Holiday Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'What nationality is Santa Claus? North Polish', NULL, 'A cheerful, cartoon-style Santa Claus dressed in his traditional red suit with white trim stands at the North Pole. Instead of his usual rosy cheeks, Santa has a friendly, exaggerated Polish folk hat on his head (like a colorful traditional Polish cap). Behind him is a snowy signpost that reads ''North Pole'' with a small Polish flag attached. Around Santa, elves look on with amused expressions, and reindeer peek out from behind snowy trees. The scene is bright, colorful, and playful, capturing a lighthearted cultural pun without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (316, 'Christmas, Humor', 'KK/WT: Ho-Ho ? (Ho-Ho-Who?) Your Santa impression needs some work...', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a living room decorated for Christmas with a Christmas tree, presents, and holiday lights. In the center, a child is standing with a playful smirk, holding a finger to their lips as if teasing. Opposite the child, an adult dressed as Santa Claus is trying to say ''Ho-Ho-Ho'' but instead looks confused and is saying ''Ho-Ho-Who?'' The adult''s Santa hat is slightly askew, and there’s a speech bubble coming from the child that says, "Your Santa impression needs some work..." The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, with warm colors and exaggerated, friendly expressions to emphasize the joke''s fun and gentle teasing tone. No one looks upset, just amused by the mix-up in the Santa impression.'),
 (317, 'Christmas, Humor, Word Play', 'What do you call a kid who doesn’t believe in Santa? A rebel without a Claus', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident, cheeky kid standing with arms crossed and a slight smirk on their face. The kid should be dressed in casual, modern clothing and appear slightly rebellious but playful. To the side, depict a classic jolly Santa Claus character looking surprised or confused, with his trademark red suit, white beard, and hat. Around them, add festive holiday decorations like Christmas trees, presents, and twinkling lights to set a Christmas atmosphere. The background could be indoors in a cozy living room with a fireplace and stockings hanging, highlighting the Santa theme. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with expressive faces and light-hearted cartoon proportions.'),
 (318, 'Christmas, Language, Puns', 'What do you call Santa''s helpers? Subordinate Clauses', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Santa Claus in his cozy North Pole workshop. Santa is at a wooden desk with a big book labeled ''Christmas List'' open. Around him are several small elves dressed in festive outfits, wearing pointy hats and shoes, busily working. These elves are depicted as ''subordinate clauses'' by having small captions with grammatical terms above their heads (e.g., ''because he said so,'' ''while making toys,'' ''if the reindeer rest''). Santa looks amused and is pointing at one elf holding a pencil. The background shows holiday decorations like a Christmas tree with twinkling lights, candy canes, and wrapped presents. The style is light, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun by blending Christmas helpers with grammar elements in a playful, non-threatening manner.'),
 (319, 'Christmas, Music Humor, Puns', 'Who is Santa''s favorite singer? Elfis.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon depicting Santa Claus standing in a cozy, festive North Pole workshop filled with Christmas decorations such as a Christmas tree, colorful lights, and wrapped presents. Santa is cheerfully listening to an elf dressed in a sparkly rockstar outfit reminiscent of Elvis Presley, complete with a pompadour hairstyle and flashy sunglasses. The elf is holding a vintage microphone and striking a classic Elvis pose with one hand in the air and one leg bent. Nearby, other elves are clapping and smiling, enjoying the performance. The setting is bright, colorful, and playful, emphasizing the holiday spirit with a fun musical twist.'),
 (320, 'Christmas, Pop Culture, Puns', 'How did the young Jedi always know what they were getting for Christmas? They could sense their presents.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a young Jedi child standing in front of a Christmas tree decorated with lights and ornaments. The Jedi wears a simple tunic and a small lightsaber hanging from a belt. The child has a peaceful, knowing smile on their face, eyes slightly closed as if concentrating or sensing something. Around them, faint, glowing, force-like waves or sparkles are illustrated emanating from the child toward several wrapped Christmas presents under the tree. The setting should be cozy and festive with holiday decorations like stockings on a nearby mantle and a glowing fireplace in the background. The tone is lighthearted and magical, emphasizing the child''s connection to the Force and holiday cheer.'),
 (321, 'Christmas, Puns', 'What do you call people who are afraid of Santa? Claustrophobic', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of nervous or scared people backed up against walls or each other inside a small room labeled ''Santa''s Workshop.'' The people look wide-eyed and anxious, some peeking over their shoulders. In the center, a friendly, classic Santa Claus stands with a big smile, holding a sack of presents, completely unaware of their fear. The room is decorated with Christmas lights, candy canes, and presents stacked around. The overall tone is light and funny, with exaggerated expressions of claustrophobia—such as a person pressed against a wall with their hands holding onto the sides, and another clutching a wrapped gift tightly in panic.'),
 (322, 'Christmas, Puns', 'What goes ''oh-oh-oh''? Santa walking backward.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Santa Claus walking backwards. Santa is in his classic red suit with white trim, black boots, and a big sack of gifts slung over his shoulder. His face has a surprised or confused expression as he looks over his shoulder while stepping backward. Above his head, three speech bubbles show the sounds ''oh-oh-oh'' to mimic the usual ''ho-ho-ho'' but reversed. The background is a snowy winter night with twinkling stars and a few decorated pine trees. The overall tone is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the wordplay in the joke.'),
 (323, 'Christmas, Puns', 'What kind of cars do Santa''s elves drive? Toy-otas', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing Santa''s workshop outside the North Pole. In the foreground, two small elves are happily driving tiny cars styled like classic Toyota models but clearly designed as toys — bright red and green with oversized wheels and playful details like candy cane stripes and bells. One elf waves cheerfully out the window. Nearby, a large ''Santa''s Workshop'' sign is visible with snow gently falling. In the background, a sleigh pulled by reindeer is parked beside a pile of wrapped presents. The overall tone is festive, cheerful, and whimsical, capturing the pun about ''Toy-otas'' with visual emphasis on the toy-like quality of the cars and the playful elves driving them.'),
 (324, 'Christmas, Puns', 'What kind of cars do Santa''s elves drive? Toy-otas', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Santa''s elves standing proudly next to several small, brightly colored cars that look like toys. The cars are styled like compact, playful versions of Toyota vehicles, featuring exaggerated features such as oversized wheels and candy cane-striped paint jobs, with little elf hats on the antennas. The elves are dressed in classic green and red outfits with pointy hats and curled shoes, smiling and waving. In the background, North Pole scenery is visible with snowy ground, candy canes, and Santa''s workshop. A sign next to the cars reads "Toy-otas" in a playful font. The overall atmosphere is cheerful and festive, emphasizing the pun between ''toy'' and ''Toyota'' in a lighthearted, cartoon style without any violence or negative elements.'),
 (325, 'Christmas, Puns', 'What''s every elf''s favorite type of music? Wrap, of course.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful elf in a festive workshop setting. The elf is wearing a classic green outfit with a pointy hat and curly-toed shoes. Around the elf are colorful Christmas presents wrapped in shiny paper with big bows. The elf is joyfully DJing on a turntable made from gift-wrapping supplies—like rolls of wrapping paper, scissors, and tape dispensers. Musical notes float around him, and the word ''Wrap'' appears in playful bubble letters above. In the background, Christmas decorations like a small decorated tree, hanging ornaments, and twinkling lights create a festive atmosphere. The elf’s face shows excitement and enjoyment as if he’s really into his favorite music genre: ''wrap'' music. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun.'),
 (326, 'Christmas, Puns', 'What''s the difference between the Christmas alphabet and the regular alphabet? The Christmas alphabet has no-el.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene split into two panels. On the left panel, show a regular alphabet block set (like children''s toy blocks arranged A to Z) on a plain background, with bright, simple colors. On the right panel, show a Christmas-themed alphabet set where the letters are decorated with festive elements: some blocks wrapped in red and green stripes, others with holly or candy cane patterns. Highlight the letters ''N'', ''O'', and emphasize ''EL'' glowing or sparkling to indicate the pun on ''No-el'' (like ''No L''). Include a cheerful, smiling Christmas tree in the background and maybe a Santa hat resting on one of the blocks to reinforce the holiday mood. Keep the style light, playful, and suitable for a broad, family-friendly audience. The text or caption can appear above or below the panels, reading "What''s the difference between the Christmas alphabet and the regular alphabet? The Christmas alphabet has no-el."'),
 (327, 'Christmas, Puns, Word Play', 'Did you know Santa has a 10th reindeer Olive? It''s in the Rudolph song - ''Olive the other reindeer''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Santa Claus standing next to his traditional team of eight reindeer plus Rudolph with his glowing red nose. In front of them is a cute reindeer wearing a small green olive as a necklace or hat, looking proud and slightly confused. Above them, a musical note banner floats with the lyrics ''Olive, the other reindeer'' in playful, whimsical font. The scene is set on a snowy rooftop under a starry night sky with the silhouette of a chimney and a sleigh filled with gift bags. Santa is smiling and pointing at the olive-wearing reindeer while the others look on with surprised expressions. Everything is drawn in bright colors with exaggerated cartoon features to amplify the joke''s playful tone.'),
 (328, 'Christmas, Puns, Word Play', 'How does Christmas Day end? With the letter ''Y''!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on Christmas Day evening. Central to the image is a large, smiling letter ''Y'' wearing a Santa hat and standing like a character. Around it, a cozy living room is decorated festively with a Christmas tree decked with ornaments and lights, stockings hanging on a fireplace mantel, and wrapped presents scattered on the floor. A family (two adults and a child) are sitting on a couch, looking amused as they point toward the letter ''Y''. The clock on the wall shows late evening (around 11:59 PM). The mood is cheerful and lighthearted, with warm colors and exaggerated cartoon features conveying a friendly holiday atmosphere. The letter ''Y'' is the punchline character, embodying the joke that Christmas Day ends literally with the letter ''Y''.'),
 (329, 'Christmas, Puns, Word Play', 'What did the wise men say after they offered up their gifts of gold and frankincense? Wait, there''s myrrh.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the three wise men from the Nativity story standing together. Two of them are holding out traditional gifts: one with a small treasure chest labeled ''Gold'' and the other holding a fancy bottle labeled ''Frankincense''. The third wise man is pointing forward with a lightbulb or a surprised expression as if he’s just realized something, with a speech bubble that says, ''Wait, there’s myrrh.'' They are all dressed in bright, colorful robes and turbans, standing in a desert-like setting with a simple starry night sky in the background. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the pun and moment of revelation.'),
 (330, 'Chuck Norris, Coronavirus, Humor', 'Chuck Norris was exposed to COVID, and the virus was in quarantine for a month.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris standing confidently with his arms crossed and a serious look on his face. Around him, a group of tiny, cartoonish virus characters wearing face masks and looking frightened or sad are trapped inside a transparent quarantine box or cage labeled ''Quarantine''. The box is placed near Chuck Norris, emphasizing that the virus is held captive and isolated because of him. The background is simple, with maybe a few stars or comic-style action lines radiating from Chuck to highlight his toughness. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated, suitable for a fun, family-friendly cartoon.'),
 (331, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, History Humor', 'The Great Wall of China was originally created to keep Chuck Norris out. It didn''t work.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the Great Wall of China stretching across a hilly landscape with traditional Chinese watchtowers. At one point, the wall has a large crack or gap where Chuck Norris is effortlessly kicking through the wall. Chuck Norris is depicted as a confident, strong action hero (in a simple cartoon style), wearing a martial arts outfit with a black belt. Around him, broken bricks fly into the air, emphasizing his unstoppable power. In the background, a frustrated, bewildered looking ancient Chinese soldier or guard stands holding a spear, scratching his head or looking defeated. The overall mood is light, playful, and exaggerated to show Chuck Norris''s legendary toughness against an iconic monument.'),
 (332, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris doesn''t do pushups, he pushes the Earth down.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris in mid-pushup position outdoors, with a confident, almost nonchalant expression. Instead of the usual floor beneath him, the Earth is depicted as a small globe being pushed down slightly by his hands. The globe looks like a classic Earth with blue oceans and green continents. Around him are exaggerated motion lines showing the Earth being pushed down with great force. The background is simple, perhaps a bright sky with a few clouds. Chuck Norris is drawn in an exaggerated heroic style, wearing a simple t-shirt and jeans, with a subtle smirk. The scene is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the absurdity of the punchline without any violence or tension.'),
 (333, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris doesn''t turn on the shower. He stares at it until it starts to cry.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing in a bathroom. Chuck is depicted with his iconic beard and stern, intense gaze directed at a classic showerhead mounted on the wall. The showerhead has animated, teardrop-shaped water droplets falling from it, looking like it''s crying. The bathroom setting is simple with tiles on the walls, a shower curtain slightly pulled back, and a soap dish. Chuck stands confidently with his arms crossed or hands on hips, giving the impression that his powerful stare alone is causing the shower to ''cry'' water. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the joke''s humor without any violence or aggression.'),
 (334, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris has a mug of nails instead of coffee in the morning.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris sitting at a kitchen table in the morning. Instead of a normal coffee mug, he is holding a large mug filled with shiny metal nails sticking out of the top. Chuck Norris has a serious, unfazed expression, with a slight smirk. Around him, typical breakfast items are on the table like a plate with toast and a newspaper, but the focus is on the mug. The background shows a cozy kitchen with a window letting in sunlight, adding warmth to the scene. The style is bright and colorful, exaggerated slightly for comic effect, with bold lines and simple shading to emphasize the joke that Chuck Norris’s morning ''coffee'' is as tough as him.'),
 (335, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris has never blinked in his entire life. Never.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently center frame. He has his trademark beard and intense gaze, with eyes wide open and unblinking. Around him, exaggerated flying dust particles or small objects aim toward his face as if testing whether he blinks, but he remains completely still and unfazed. The background is simple with a light gradient and some comic-style lines emphasizing his unblinking stare. The overall style is bold, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the joke''s hyperbolic nature, with a caption bubble or banner above Chuck reading: "Chuck Norris has NEVER blinked." The tone is light-hearted and playful, with no violence or intensity, just comic exaggeration.'),
 (336, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris is the only man who can fight himself and win.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris in a split image style: on one side, Chuck Norris stands in a classic martial arts fighting stance, looking fierce and confident. On the opposite side, an identical Chuck Norris mirror image is in a fighting stance matching the first, as if they are about to battle each other. The background is simple with a dojo or training mat floor. Between them, cartoon action lines and comic-style impact effects indicate an intense face-off. Chuck Norris’s expressions show determination and slight smirks, emphasizing that he’s fully in control and winning. The scene is lighthearted and exaggerated, with no violence shown, just the concept of him fighting himself.'),
 (337, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris is the only person that can punch a cyclops between the eye.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently and smiling, his fist extended forward as if mid-punch. In front of him is a large, comical cyclops with one giant central eye staring straight ahead. The cyclops is wearing a surprised expression, wincing slightly as if just got punched right in the middle of its eye. The background is simple and lighthearted, maybe an open field or a dojo setting to keep focus on the characters. The cyclops is exaggerated with a big round head, one large eyeball in the center, and oversized hands. Chuck Norris should look cool and calm, sporting his iconic beard and martial arts attire or plain clothes that hint at toughness. The style is bright, colorful, and playful, typical of a cartoon, with bold outlines and expressive faces to emphasize humor and absurdity of the scene.'),
 (338, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris made a Happy Meal cry.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, classic Happy Meal box from a popular fast food chain with a scared, teary-eyed face on the front. The box is personified with big cartoon eyes and a mouth trembling in fear, with tears streaming down the sides. Standing next to the Happy Meal is a larger-than-life, exaggerated caricature of Chuck Norris in a tough martial arts pose, wearing his iconic beard and karate gi, with an intense and confident expression. The background is simple, perhaps a fast food restaurant or playground setting, but the focus is on the contrast between the intimidating Chuck Norris figure and the crying Happy Meal. The overall tone is playful and lighthearted, using exaggerated facial expressions and poses to emphasize the joke without anything violent or aggressive depicted directly.'),
 (339, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris never retreats; he just attacks in the opposite direction.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing Chuck Norris in a confident martial arts stance on a battlefield. There are two arrows pointing forward to indicate an attack direction but Chuck Norris is shown with a smirk, turning and kicking energetically in the exact opposite direction of the arrows. The background should be playful and exaggerated with dust clouds or motion lines emphasizing speed and power. Nearby, a confused group of generic soldiers or opponents watch in bewilderment. Make sure the characters have exaggerated, expressive cartoon faces to highlight the humor and absurdity of attacking by going backwards.'),
 (340, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once bowled a perfect game with a marble.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently on a bowling lane. Instead of a regular bowling ball, he is holding a small shiny marble about the size of a marble game piece. The pins at the end of the lane are toppling dramatically, falling down in perfect alignment as if hit by an invisible force. Chuck Norris has a calm, slightly smug expression with his arms crossed or one hand holding the marble. The bowling alley is brightly lit with a scoreboard above displaying a perfect score of 300. Around him, a few surprised spectators with exaggerated shocked and amazed expressions are watching. The overall tone is light and humorous, with exaggerated cartoonish features and vibrant colors.'),
 (341, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once had a heart attack. His heart lost.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris as a muscular, confident action hero standing victoriously in the center. Nearby, his heart is depicted as a small, cartoonish pink heart character lying on the ground with a defeated, dazed expression — possibly with little cartoon stars circling its head to indicate it lost the fight. Chuck Norris strikes a triumphant pose with fists on hips and a slight smirk. The background is simple and focused on emphasizing the funny battle between Chuck Norris and his heart. Use bright colors and bold lines for a playful, lighthearted comic style. Include a small caption or speech bubble near Chuck saying something like ''Winner!'' for visual humor.'),
 (342, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once roundhouse kicked someone so hard that his foot broke the speed of light', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing in a classic martial arts pose with one leg extended mid-roundhouse kick. His expression is fierce but exaggeratedly confident. The background shows a blurred streak representing the broken sound barrier and a glowing trail illustrating the foot surpassing the speed of light, depicted as a colorful light beam shooting forward. Nearby, a surprised cartoon character is flying backward with exaggerated motion lines, eyes wide and mouth open in shock. The setting is simple with no violence, just dynamic action lines and comic effects emphasizing immense speed and power. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated, capturing a superhuman feat humorously.'),
 (343, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once shot an enemy plane down with his finger, by yelling, ''Bang!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon depicting Chuck Norris standing confidently on the ground with a stern, focused expression. He is pointing his index finger straight ahead like a gun, and from his mouth comes a bold comic-style speech bubble that says, ''Bang!''. In front of him, high in the sky, a cartoonish enemy plane appears to be dramatically falling out of control, with smoke trailing and its nose pointed downward. The background shows a clear blue sky with a few fluffy clouds. The style is exaggerated and playful, emphasizing Chuck Norris’ legendary toughness and the absurdity of shooting down a plane just by yelling.'),
 (344, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once went skydiving, but promised never to do it again. One Grand Canyon is enough.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris mid-air during a skydive. Show him with a confident, stoic expression wearing a jumpsuit and goggles, free-falling against a dramatic backdrop of the Grand Canyon below. Emphasize the canyon''s vast depth and recognizable red rock formations for clarity. Include a speech bubble above Chuck Norris that reads: ''One Grand Canyon is enough.'' Optionally, depict a tiny parachute just beginning to deploy or humorously absent to reinforce the joke. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and bold outlines, capturing a playful tone without any violence or danger.'),
 (345, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once won a game of Connect Four in three moves.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris sitting confidently at a small game table, with a bright aura of exaggerated toughness around him. On the table is a Connect Four vertical grid, where only three colorful game pieces have been placed by Chuck, already forming a winning line. Around him, three stunned and exaggeratedly shocked opponents, one dropping their game piece in disbelief, another holding their head, and the third with wide eyes and mouth agape. The background is simple, emphasizing the game and the characters, using vibrant colors and exaggerated facial expressions to amplify the humor. A small scoreboard nearby shows ''Moves: 3'' in bold letters. The scene should capture an epic, almost superhero-like vibe about an absurdly fast victory in what is normally a slow-paced game, making clear the joke about Chuck Norris'' legendary abilities, all depicted in a playful, non-violent manner.'),
 (346, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once won an arm wrestling tournament with both arms tied behind his back.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris sitting at a small arm wrestling table, grinning confidently. Both his arms are securely tied behind his back with thick ropes, clearly visible to the viewer. Across the table sits a surprised opponent, straining hard to win but clearly overwhelmed. The setting is a simple tournament room with a few spectators in the background, some with jaws dropped or hands on cheeks in disbelief. The overall style is exaggerated and playful, emphasizing the impossible feat with exaggerated facial expressions and a light-hearted atmosphere.'),
 (347, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris'' tears cure cancer. Too bad he has never cried.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon depicting Chuck Norris standing confidently in the center with a big, stern expression and arms crossed. Around him, glowing, sparkling teardrops hang in midair, shimmering as if magical, labeled ''Cure for Cancer'' in small text. The background shows a cheerful, sunny environment with flowers and a few mysterious broken bottles labeled ''Medicine'' on the ground to add humor. To emphasize the joke, a small speech bubble from Chuck Norris says, ''I never cry.'' The overall vibe should be lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoonish features and bright colors to highlight the joke''s fantastical nature.'),
 (348, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Chuck Norris used to beat up his shadow because it was following to close. It now stands 15 feet behind him.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris walking outside on a sunny day with a confident, tough guy expression. He is in casual clothes, maybe a denim jacket and jeans, fists clenched in a playful fighting stance. Behind him, his shadow is exaggeratedly far back — about 15 feet behind him instead of right at his feet as shadows normally are. The shadow looks scared or intimidated, with cartoonish wide eyes and a small sweat drop, peeking around nervously as if trying to stay as far away as possible. The setting is a simple outdoor sidewalk with some trees and grass. The overall style is bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions highlighting humor and the absurdity of a shadow standing so far behind its owner.'),
 (349, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'Death once had a near-Chuck-Norris experience.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Death personified as the Grim Reaper, complete with a black hooded cloak and a scythe. He should look surprised and a bit intimidated, with wide eyes and raised eyebrows, stepping back slightly. Opposite him stands a chiseled, larger-than-life Chuck Norris character in a confident martial arts stance, perhaps with a slight smirk, wearing his iconic beard, cowboy boots, and a karate gi or casual clothes emphasizing toughness. The background should be simple, like a neutral color or with subtle action lines to emphasize the confrontation. Add a small speech bubble above Death saying, ''Wait, what?!'' to enhance the humor. The overall style should be playful and exaggerated to emphasize the joke’s funny reversal of roles.'),
 (350, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'The dark is afraid of Chuck Norris.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a scene at night with a pitch-black shadowy darkness personified as a large, spooky, but comically scared figure with wide eyes and trembling. Facing it is Chuck Norris in his classic stoic martial arts pose, looking confident and unbothered. The darkness figure is shrinking back nervously, perhaps sweating or with cartoonish trembling lines around it. The background has a starry night sky and a simple landscape like a field or empty street to emphasize the night setting. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated to capture the funny contrast between Chuck Norris’s legendary toughness and the usually scary darkness being scared.'),
 (351, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'When Chuck Norris enters a room, he doesn''t turn the lights on, he turns the dark off.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris confidently stepping into a dimly lit room. Chuck is depicted with a strong, heroic stance in casual yet iconic attire (e.g., denim jacket, beard). Instead of a light switch, he is dramatically pressing an invisible button mid-air with a smirk, and around him, the darkness visibly ''retreats'' or ''recedes'' as if being pushed away by his presence. The room behind him has shadows and dark corners, but as he steps in, the shadows comically pull back like curtains or smoke vanishing, revealing a well-lit space. Make the lighting effect exaggerated and playful, with cartoonish beams of light pushing back dark swirling shadows. Include simple background elements like a couch, a lamp (off), and a small table to suggest an ordinary room. The style is colorful, fun, and clearly lighthearted without any violence or negativity.'),
 (352, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor', 'When Chuck Norris plays dodgeball, the balls dodge him.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a gymnasium during a dodgeball game. In the center is a muscular, confident Chuck Norris character with a stern but calm expression, standing with his arms slightly raised and ready to catch or dodge. Around him, several dodgeballs in mid-air are visibly moving away rapidly, with motion lines and small surprised cartoon eyes on the balls to emphasize they are trying to escape him. Several players on the sidelines watch in amazement, some shielding their eyes or dropping their own dodgeballs in disbelief. The gym has typical features like a basketball hoop, wooden floor, and a scoreboard showing ''Chuck Norris: 1, Everyone Else: 0''. Use bright, simple colors with exaggerated cartoon features for a light and funny atmosphere without any violence or aggression.'),
 (353, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Humor, Pop Culture', 'If paper beats rock, rock beats scissors, and scissors beats paper, what beats all 3 at the same time? Chuck Norris.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a simple, colorful style. Show three oversized objects on a table or platform: a crumpled sheet of paper, a jagged rock, and a pair of shiny scissors arranged in a circle to represent the classic rock-paper-scissors game. In the center, draw a larger-than-life, cartoonish Chuck Norris character standing confidently with a bold stance, wearing a martial arts gi and a black belt. His expression should be calm but imposing, with a slight smirk. Around him, add comedic motion lines or glow to emphasize power and invincibility. The background should be minimal and bright, keeping the focus on the game objects and Chuck Norris. Ensure the scene is lighthearted, fun, and clearly references the iconic martial artist as the unbeatable force who can beat all three items at once.'),
 (354, 'Chuck Norris, Exaggeration, Math Humor', 'When Chuck Norris does division, there are no remainders.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing Chuck Norris standing confidently at a classroom chalkboard filled with math division problems. The division problems have no remainders and are perfectly solved, with large zeros prominently displayed. Chuck Norris is drawn with a slight smirk, wearing his iconic beard and casual martial arts attire. Around him, shocked students and a surprised math teacher hold their hats or scratch their heads in amazement. The chalkboard has bold, clean division signs and numbers, emphasizing the absence of any remainders. The setting is a bright, simple classroom with desks and posters of multiplication tables on the walls. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to amplify the joke''s essence.'),
 (355, 'Chuck Norris, Good Question!, Humor', 'Chuck Norris can tie his shoes with his feet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style drawing showing Chuck Norris sitting on the ground with a confident smirk. His legs are crossed in front of him, and both of his feet are up near his hands, each foot tying the laces of a sneaker on the opposite foot. The shoes are classic sneakers with visible untied laces, mid-tying. Around him, subtle action lines emphasize his skill and balance. The background is simple and clean to keep focus on the character. Chuck Norris is depicted with his iconic beard and hairstyle, wearing casual clothes like a plain T-shirt and jeans. The overall tone is lighthearted, showcasing the absurd idea of someone being able to tie shoes with their feet in a funny and exaggerated manner.'),
 (356, 'Chuck Norris, Good Question!, Humor', 'Chuck Norris counted to infinity... twice.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris standing confidently with arms crossed and a smirk on his face. Behind him is a giant, swirling infinite loop symbol (8) glowing brightly, representing infinity. To emphasize the joke, have two identical infinite loop symbols side by side floating above his head, indicating he counted infinity twice. The background is simple and playful with stars or sparkles to add a legendary vibe. Chuck Norris should be drawn in a classic action-hero style, with a martial arts outfit or casual tough-guy clothes, and exaggerated facial hair to make him instantly recognizable. The overall tone is light-hearted and exaggerated, capturing an impossible feat done with effortless coolness.'),
 (357, 'Chuck Norris, Good Question!, Humor, Pop Culture', 'On the day the man who invented the telephone got home He had five missed calls from Chuck Norris', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a vintage setting with a man dressed in old-fashioned 19th-century clothes, standing at the doorstep of his quaint home holding an early model of a telephone. The man looks surprised and slightly overwhelmed as he looks at the device, which is ringing relentlessly with flashing icons representing five missed calls. Above or beside him, a tough, cartoonish Chuck Norris character stands confidently with crossed arms, wearing cowboy attire with a determined expression, as if daring or jokingly intimidating. The background shows a simple, cozy house facade with a wooden door and a mailbox. The overall mood is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the contrast between the historical inventor and the modern, legendary figure of Chuck Norris.'),
 (358, 'Chuck Norris, Good Question!, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Superman owns a pair of Chuck Norris undies.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing Superman standing proudly with his iconic red cape and blue suit. The focus is on his underwear area, where a flashy, oversized pair of white briefs is visible over his pants. These briefs have a bold, exaggerated ''Chuck Norris'' label on the waistband, making it clear they belong to Chuck Norris. Superman has a confident, slightly amused expression. Next to him stands a cartoonish Chuck Norris character, arms crossed with a stoic look, wearing his signature beard and casual clothes. The setting is simple—a bright, colorful cityscape background with a few skyscrapers and a clear blue sky, emphasizing the superhero context humorously. The style is playful and vibrant, with exaggerated expressions and clear text on the underwear waistband for comedic effect.'),
 (359, 'Chuck Norris, Good Question!, Math Humor', 'Chuck Norris can divide by zero.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of Chuck Norris standing confidently at a large, old-fashioned chalkboard filled with complicated math equations. Chuck Norris is shown punching the air triumphantly with one fist. On the chalkboard, prominently displayed, is the equation ''1 ÷ 0 ='' with a big question mark and a spiral-like explosion of colorful mathematical symbols swirling around it, illustrating the impossible nature of dividing by zero. Chuck Norris has his iconic beard and cowboy attire, with a glint in his eye suggesting superhuman strength and calm mastery over the impossible math challenge. The setting is a classroom or a funny math competition stage with a few bewildered cartoon mathematicians or students looking on with surprised expressions. The overall style is light, exaggerated, and playful to capture the larger-than-life fictional abilities of Chuck Norris in a comical way.'),
 (360, 'Chuck Norris, Health Humor, Puns', 'The flu gets a Chuck Norris shot every year.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the flu virus as a tiny, green, angry-looking germ trying to enter a human body. Next to it stands Chuck Norris depicted as a strong, tough cowboy character wearing a hat and cowboy boots, with a confident, no-nonsense expression. Chuck Norris is holding a giant oversized syringe labeled ''Chuck Norris Shot'' aimed toward the flu virus. The background is a simple doctor''s office or clinic setting with a medical poster showing immune system cells cheering. The flu virus looks startled and scared, backing away comically from the syringe. Bright, bold colors and exaggerated facial expressions emphasize the humor.'),
 (361, 'Chuck Norris, Horror Humor, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Freddy Krueger has nightmares about Chuck Norris.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a dark, spooky bedroom with Freddy Krueger lying in bed, eyes wide open and clearly terrified. Freddy, recognizable by his iconic striped red-and-green sweater, brown fedora, and bladed glove, is clutching his blanket tightly. Above him, thought bubbles show an intimidating and exaggeratedly tough Chuck Norris, posed in a classic martial arts stance with a stern expression. The room is decorated with typical scary elements like cobwebs, a creaky wooden floor, and moonlight casting eerie shadows. Freddy''s bed is styled like a horror-themed bed but with a comedic twist, such as a ‘Nightmare on Elm Street’ poster on the wall with Freddy looking worried. Chuck Norris appears larger-than-life in the thought bubble, almost superhero-like, to emphasize the joke that Freddy, the master of nightmares, is the one who actually fears Chuck Norris. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to evoke humor rather than fear.'),
 (362, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris beat the sun in a staring contest.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris and the sun engaged in a staring contest. Chuck Norris is portrayed as a confident, strong man with a slight smirk, sitting calmly in a simple armchair outdoors. The sun, anthropomorphized with a big face, eyebrows furrowed and glaring intensely, is positioned directly opposite Chuck, shining brightly with expressive eyes locked onto his. The background shows a simple blue sky with a few clouds, emphasizing the outdoor daytime setting. Both characters have exaggerated, focused eyes to highlight the intensity of the contest. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and playful expressions, creating a fun and absurd scene without any violence or complexity.'),
 (363, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris can clap with one hand.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in a simple outdoor setting, such as a sunny park or plain background. Chuck Norris is drawn as a strong, iconic martial artist with his signature beard and serious expression. He is shown attempting to clap with just one hand: his palm is facing upward, fingers slightly curled, and the other hand is nowhere to be seen, emphasizing the impossible feat. To add humor, a small cloud of dust or ''clap sound'' lines are emanating from the single hand. Around him, a few amazed cartoon characters—perhaps children or onlookers—watch with wide eyes and dropped jaws to accentuate the absurdity of the joke. The style should be light-hearted, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the comedic, impossible nature of the scenario without any violence or danger.'),
 (364, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris can get in a bucket and lift it up with himself in it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing Chuck Norris, depicted as a strong, confident man with his iconic beard and intense stare, inside a large metal bucket. The bucket is being lifted off the ground, held firmly by Chuck Norris himself, who is gripping the rim with both hands from inside. The setting is simple, with a plain light-colored background to keep focus on the scene. Chuck Norris is smiling slightly, showing his effortless strength. The bucket should look like an ordinary large bucket, big enough to fit a person, and the drawing style should be bold and colorful, emphasizing exaggerated cartoon features to add humor and charm.'),
 (365, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris can make a slinky go upstairs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing at the bottom of a staircase in a casual but confident pose, with his iconic beard and cowboy boots. In front of him, a colorful metal slinky is stretched out and animatedly climbing the stairs on its own, defying gravity. The staircase is indoors, simple with carpeted steps, and there is a surprised cartoon character (maybe a bystander with a shocked expression and raised eyebrows) watching the slinky''s impossible upward movement. The atmosphere is light and funny, emphasizing the absurdity of the slinky going upstairs because of Chuck Norris’s legendary tough persona. Bright colors and exaggerated expressions enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (366, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris can slam a revolving door.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing Chuck Norris, a muscular man with a confident expression and iconic beard, standing next to a revolving door. The revolving door is depicted as a typical glass and metal entrance to a building, but humorously it appears to be stopped mid-spin with exaggerated motion lines showing it trying to turn. Chuck Norris is posed in mid-action, one hand open and pressing firmly against the revolving door panel like he''s about to slam it shut, with comic-style impact effects like “BAM!” or “SLAM!” around the door. Around him, bystanders look surprised or amazed. The scene should have bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated features to emphasize the impossibility and humor of slamming a revolving door. No violence, just playful exaggeration of Chuck Norris’s legendary strength and abilities.'),
 (367, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris can sneeze with his eyes open.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a muscular, serious-looking Chuck Norris standing confidently in the center of the frame. His head is tilted slightly back as he is mid-sneeze, with his mouth open and eyes wide open, clearly not blinking or closing his eyes despite the sneeze. Around him, various cartoon-style motion lines emphasize the force of the sneeze. Nearby, some small objects like cups or papers shake or flutter as if affected by the sneeze''s power. The background is simple and colorful, keeping the focus on Chuck Norris and the exaggerated sneeze action. The style is lighthearted and fun, capturing the joke''s absurdity in a playful way without any violence or political references.'),
 (368, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris does not get frostbite. Chuck Norris bites frost.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in a snowy, icy landscape. He is wearing a casual outfit with rolled-up sleeves and a determined expression. In front of him is a large, cartoonish frost monster or icicle creature, which looks surprised and a bit scared as Chuck reaches out and bites it with exaggerated teeth. Snowflakes fall gently around, and the chilly environment is emphasized by frosty breath and icy details on the ground. The overall style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and bold outlines to emphasize the absurdity of Chuck Norris biting frost instead of getting frostbite himself.'),
 (369, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris does not sleep. He waits.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon featuring Chuck Norris as a tough, rugged man sitting calmly in a simple armchair. The room is dimly lit like a typical living room with a clock on the wall showing a late hour. Chuck Norris is wide awake, eyes open and alert, with a slight smirk. Instead of lying in bed, he is patiently waiting with crossed arms and legs, radiating calm confidence. Around him, objects like a sleeping bag or a bed stand unused and lonely, emphasizing that he does not sleep. The style is bold, colorful, and exaggerated to capture the humorous essence of Chuck Norris''s legendary toughness and stoicism.'),
 (370, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris doesn’t turn on the shower. He stares at it until it starts to cry.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in a simple bathroom. He is a muscular man with a stern expression, arms crossed, and a slightly intimidating aura. In front of him is a shower with water droplets transforming into animated cartoon tears running down its glass door and a sad face on the showerhead or glass, as if it’s crying. The bathroom is minimalistic but clearly a shower stall with a shower curtain or glass panel. The lighting highlights Chuck Norris’s serious stare directed at the shower. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the joke that the shower starts to cry rather than turning on.'),
 (371, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris doesn''t need to shave - his beard is scared to grow.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently with a slight smirk on his face. His beard is patchy and sparse, with tiny expressive eyes and a scared expression, looking nervously sideways or shrinking back as if intimidated. Show a close-up of Chuck''s face where the beard appears almost alive, cowering or slinking away. The background is simple and light-hearted, like a plain color or a subtle dojo setting to hint at Chuck’s martial arts persona. Make the overall style playful and exaggerated, emphasizing the beard''s ''fear'' humorously, without any violence or aggression.'),
 (372, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris doesn''t wear a watch. He decides what time it is.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in the center. He is depicted with a tough, determined expression, wearing casual clothes but notably without any watch on his wrists. Around him, multiple clocks on a wall show different times, but Chuck is pointing with his thumb over his shoulder at no particular clock, as if commanding the time itself. The background is simple and brightly colored to highlight Chuck as the focus. Include a few exaggerated visual elements like sparkles or glowing lines around Chuck''s finger to emphasize his power to decide the time. The overall style is lighthearted and comedic, with bold outlines and exaggerated features typical of funny cartoons.'),
 (373, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris is the only man to ever defeat a brick wall in a game of tennis.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris on one side of a tennis court, holding a tennis racket and looking confident and heroic. On the other side, instead of a human opponent, there is a large brick wall standing upright, with a quirky expression—eyebrows furrowed, eyes narrowed, and maybe even a sweat drop to show struggle. Tennis balls are flying back and forth between Chuck and the wall. The background should be a simple outdoor tennis court with a net in the middle. The style is exaggerated and playful, with bold outlines and bright colors, capturing the ridiculousness of a man competing against a brick wall.'),
 (374, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Chuck Norris once told a woman to calm down and she did', NULL, 'A cartoon scene with a large, tough-looking Chuck Norris character standing confidently with his arms crossed and a slight smirk. Facing him is a woman who looks visibly upset but is taking a deep breath, calming down noticeably. The setting is simple and humorous, maybe a park bench or a neutral background to keep the focus on the characters. Chuck Norris has exaggerated muscles and a cowboy-style outfit. The woman should appear surprised by her own calmness, with a small, relieved smile forming. The style is light-hearted, exaggerated, and cartoonish, making the intensity of Chuck Norris comically powerful but friendly.'),
 (375, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'In Pamplona, Spain, the people may be running from the bulls, but the bulls are running from Chuck Norris.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a sunny street in Pamplona, Spain, during the famous Running of the Bulls festival. Show a crowd of panicked people frantically running forward, faces wide-eyed and expressions of fear. Behind them, instead of bulls chasing the runners, depict several large bulls sprinting away in a comical, exaggerated frightened manner with sweating brows and scared eyes. The focus is on a confident, muscular Chuck Norris character leading the bulls, walking calmly and coolly with sunglasses on and a slight smirk. The bulls are clearly running away from him, looking back nervously. Include traditional Pamplona architecture in the background, like old stone buildings and banners. The overall style should be bright, cartoonish, and humorous, emphasizing the role reversal between bulls and people for a lighthearted and playful vibe.'),
 (376, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'It takes Chuck Norris 20 minutes to watch 60 Minutes.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring Chuck Norris sitting comfortably in a living room armchair with a large TV remote in one hand. The TV screen prominently shows the logo of the news magazine show ''60 Minutes'' (a simple clock face with the words ''60 Minutes''). Around Chuck Norris, include a visible clock on the wall showing 20 minutes passing. Exaggerate Chuck Norris’s confident, calm expression as if he’s unaffected by normal time constraints. Emphasize the contrast between the title ''60 Minutes'' on the TV and the much shorter 20-minute time span indicated by the clock. The style should be colorful and playful, with bold outlines and expressive exaggeration, like a classic cartoon about superhuman abilities. No violent or aggressive elements, just a lighthearted, slightly ironic tone highlighting the joke about Chuck Norris’s legendary toughness and speed.'),
 (377, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'The only time Chuck Norris was ever wrong was when he thought he had made a mistake.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently with his arms crossed and a slight smirk. Behind him is a chalkboard or digital screen with a large checkmark labeled ''Correct'' and a tiny, almost hidden, erased ''Mistake'' written faintly. Around him, a few smaller characters, looking puzzled or amazed, point at the board. The background is simple with a spotlight effect on Chuck Norris to emphasize his legendary infallibility. The style should be light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bold outlines to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (378, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'Time waits for no man. Unless that man is Chuck Norris.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a rugged, muscular Chuck Norris standing confidently in the middle of a city street. Around him, large, classic clock faces with arms and legs try to move forward but freeze in place, looking startled or intimidated by Chuck Norris. One clock might be sweating nervously or holding up its hands in surrender. Chuck is giving a stern, playful glare or a smirk, with his arms crossed. The background is simple but includes street elements like a sidewalk and a lamppost to set the urban scene. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated in a lighthearted cartoon style, emphasizing Chuck Norris''s legendary tough persona and the idea that even time is stopped by him.'),
 (379, 'Chuck Norris, Humor', 'When Chuck Norris was born, the only person who cried was the doctor. Never slap Chuck Norris.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a newborn baby Chuck Norris lying in a hospital bassinet, looking completely calm and unbothered. Nearby, a doctor wearing scrubs and a stethoscope is wiping tears from his eyes, looking shocked and emotional. The doctor should have exaggerated teary eyes and a trembling lower lip. The hospital room is simple, with a window showing a sunny day outside. Next to the bassinet is a bold sign or caption that says, ''Never slap Chuck Norris.'' The overall style should be lighthearted with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and the superhuman toughness implied by the joke.'),
 (380, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Movies, Pop Culture', 'Chuck Norris admitted to using a stunt double in one of his movies, but only for the crying part.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing proudly on a movie set. He should have a confident, tough-guy stance, wearing typical cowboy/action hero attire (boots, jeans, bandana or leather jacket). Next to him is a stunt double—a smaller, exaggeratedly sensitive-looking version of Chuck crying dramatically with tears streaming down his cheeks. The stunt double holds a tissue box and looks overly emotional. The movie set around them includes cameras, lights, and a director’s chair with a clapperboard showing the film title. Add a speech bubble above Chuck Norris that says, ''I only used a stunt double for the crying part.'' The overall art style should be lighthearted, cartoonish, and comical, emphasizing the contrast between tough Chuck and his overly emotional stunt double without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (381, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Chuck Norris'' email address is gmail@chucknorris.com', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in the center. He is drawn in a classic tough-guy pose with a slight smirk, wearing his iconic black outfit and clenched fists. Floating prominently in front of him is a large, stylized email envelope icon with the email address text: ''gmail@chucknorris.com'' in bold letters. The background is simple and clean, with a computer or a laptop on a nearby desk displaying an open email client. The atmosphere is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the joke about Chuck Norris having the most straightforward, no-nonsense email address. The style is colorful and exaggerated, typical of fun cartoon humor without any violence or political elements.'),
 (382, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Chuck Norris is the reason why Waldo is hiding.', NULL, 'A vibrant, humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently with his signature beard and martial arts outfit. He is looking directly at the viewer with a slight smirk. Nearby, a character resembling Waldo from ''Where''s Waldo?'' is peeking nervously from behind a large tree, partially hidden, clearly trying to avoid Chuck Norris. The background is a colorful park or forest setting full of bushes and trees to emphasize hiding spots. Waldo’s classic red-and-white striped shirt and glasses make him easily recognizable. The tone is light and playful, with exaggerated expressions on both characters: Chuck Norris looks intimidating but comedic, while Waldo looks comically fearful. Add a few small details like a magnifying glass or a ‘Where’s Waldo’ book resting on the ground to hint at the classic search game. The overall style should be a funny, clean cartoon with bold lines and bright colors, suitable for all ages.'),
 (383, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Chuck Norris knows Victoria''s secret.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently with his arms crossed and a slight smirk. He is positioned in front of a door labeled ''Victoria''s Secret'' with an exaggerated sparkling glow coming from behind the door to emphasize the ''secret.'' Nearby, amused onlookers like a few cartoon men and women are peeking at him with wide eyes and surprised expressions. The background should be simple, perhaps with a subtle hint of a lingerie boutique sign or display nearby, to set the context. The style is light and playful, with bold outlines and vibrant colors, emphasizing the humor and legendary toughness associated with Chuck Norris without implying anything inappropriate or serious.'),
 (384, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Chuck Norris tells Simon what to do.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris and Simon Cowell on a simple stage or spotlighted area. Chuck Norris stands confidently with a stern but calm expression, dressed in his iconic martial arts outfit or casual tough-guy clothes, pointing a finger authoritatively at Simon Cowell. Simon Cowell looks surprised, slightly confused, and a little intimidated, holding one hand up as if unsure how to respond. The background is minimal, perhaps with a few stylized stars or comic action lines around Chuck to emphasize his commanding presence. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with friendly cartoonish proportions and bright colors, focusing on the humorous role reversal of Chuck Norris, known for his domineering pop-culture persona, telling the usually authoritative Simon what to do.'),
 (385, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Pop Culture', 'The show Survivor had the original premise of putting people on an island with Chuck Norris, but there were no survivors.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a tropical island with sand, palm trees, and a small campfire. In the center stands a tough, exaggeratedly muscular Chuck Norris character wearing his iconic martial arts outfit, flexing his muscles with a serious expression. Surrounding him are several confused and defeated reality show contestants in typical Survivor gear (bandanas, casual outdoor clothing, backpacks) sitting or lying around looking exhausted, with no energy left. One contestant looks at the viewer with a speech bubble saying ''No survivors… literally.'' The background shows a bright sunny sky and a simple wooden sign that says ''Welcome to Survivor.'' The overall style is playful and exaggerated to clearly convey the joke without any violence: the ''no survivors'' punchline is expressed through the weary contestants overshadowed by the formidable Chuck Norris figure.'),
 (386, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Pop Culture', 'When the Boogeyman goes to sleep every night he checks his closet for Chuck Norris.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a bedroom at night. The Boogeyman, a shadowy and slightly scary but comical monster with glowing eyes, is standing beside his bed wearing pajamas and holding a flashlight. He is nervously looking toward an open, well-lit closet door. Inside the closet stands Chuck Norris, confidently posing with crossed arms, a stern yet calm expression, wearing a martial arts gi. The room is simple with a bed, bedside table with an alarm clock, and a window with moonlight shining through. The overall mood is playful and funny, emphasizing the role reversal where the Boogeyman is scared and cautious about Chuck Norris hiding in his closet. The style should be bright and colorful with exaggerated and cartoonish expressions to add humor.'),
 (387, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Programming', 'Chuck Norris writes code that optimizes itself.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris sitting confidently at a computer desk. The room is a simple programmer''s workspace with a monitor displaying lines of glowing green code that seem to be moving and rewriting themselves autonomously without any keyboard input. Chuck Norris is relaxed, leaning back in his chair with a calm, almost bored expression, one hand casually resting on the desk and the other holding a coffee mug. The background includes typical programming decor: a coffee cup, sticky notes with coding jokes, and a few tech-related posters. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the impossible power of Chuck Norris making code optimize itself magically, without any effort on his part.'),
 (388, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Puns', 'Chuck Norris can cook minute rice in 30 seconds.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris in a kitchen. He stands confidently next to a stove with a pot labeled ''Minute Rice'' on the burner, which has a tiny timer showing 30 seconds instead of one minute. Chuck is drawn with exaggerated tough-guy features—muscular, wearing a martial arts outfit or casual tough clothes. Around him, steam rises dramatically from the pot, creating an almost superhero-like aura. In the background, a clock on the wall grabs the viewer’s attention by clearly showing only 30 seconds passed. Add a few surprised or amazed characters watching Chuck from the side, their eyes wide and jaws dropped. The overall tone is light-hearted and comedic, with bright colors and a cartoonish style emphasizing the ridiculousness of the joke.'),
 (389, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Puns', 'Chuck Norris can do a wheelie on a unicycle.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring Chuck Norris performing an impossible stunt: doing a wheelie on a unicycle. Show Chuck in his iconic rugged look, wearing a martial arts outfit or casual tough-guy attire, with a confident expression. The unicycle should be exaggeratedly small and simple, with one large wheel. Chuck is lifting the front part of the unicycle up high, balancing effortlessly on the rear wheel only, displaying a sense of motion and balance. The background can be a simple outdoor park or street scene to keep focus on the stunt, with maybe a few surprised or amazed onlookers in the distance reacting with wide eyes and open mouths in comic amazement. Use bright, bold colors and clean lines to emphasize the cartoon style, and possibly add a small dust cloud or speed lines near the wheel to suggest movement and energy, enhancing the absurdity of the trick.'),
 (390, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Puns', 'Chuck Norris can dribble a bowling ball.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently on a bowling alley lane. He is mid-dribble, bouncing a giant, shiny bowling ball like a basketball. Chuck Norris is drawn with exaggerated muscles, wearing casual martial arts attire with a black belt, and his iconic beard and stern expression. The background shows bowling pins waiting at the end of the lane, with a few spectators in the stands looking amazed or bewildered. The bowling ball is oversized compared to a regular basketball, adding to the absurdity. The scene should capture a playful and exaggerated atmosphere with bright colors and dynamic motion lines emphasizing the dribbling action.'),
 (391, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Puns', 'Chuck Norris can unscramble an egg.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently in a kitchen, wearing a black martial arts gi with his signature beard and hair. In front of him on the table is a large, transparent egg shell that looks cracked and scrambled inside with its yolk and whites visibly flying around. Chuck is calmly holding a pair of chopsticks or a small knife, skillfully putting the flying scrambled egg contents back together into a whole, perfectly intact egg. The kitchen background is simple and bright, with a few cooking utensils and a frying pan on the stove. Several small cartoon-style sparks or magical swirls emanate around Chuck''s hands to emphasize his superhuman, almost magical ability. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated for comedic effect, highlighting the impossible ''unscrambling'' feat as a unique Chuck Norris power without any violence or negative imagery.'),
 (392, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Puns', 'Chuck Norris''s belly button is actually a power outlet.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of Chuck Norris standing confidently with his shirt slightly lifted to reveal his belly button. Instead of a normal belly button, show a classic power outlet embedded on his belly with two vertical slots and a round grounding hole. Sparks or light rays can humorously emit from the outlet to emphasize energy or power. Chuck Norris should have a serious, tough expression, iconic beard and hair, and a martial arts outfit or casual clothes to make him easily recognizable. The background should be simple, maybe a plain color or a subtle burst effect to highlight the power outlet belly button as the focal point. No violence or weapons; the tone is playful and exaggerated superhero-style humor.'),
 (393, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Video Games', 'Chuck Norris appeared in the ''Street Fighter II'' video game, but was removed by Beta Testers because every button caused him to do a roundhouse kick. When asked bout this ''glitch'', Chuck Norris replied, ''That''s no glitch.''', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set inside an arcade with a classic ''Street Fighter II'' arcade game machine front and center. On the screen, a pixelated character resembling Chuck Norris is shown mid-air executing a dynamic roundhouse kick with exaggerated motion lines to emphasize the action. Nearby, a group of frustrated beta testers, cartoonishly drawn with laptops and notepads, look surprised and bewildered as every button they frantically press causes the character to kick. The arcade background includes other classic arcade machines and posters on the walls. Above everything, a speech bubble from the Chuck Norris character saying, ''That''s no glitch.'' The overall tone is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive faces to highlight the absurdity of the non-stop roundhouse kicking action.'),
 (394, 'Chuck Norris, Humor, Word Play', 'Chuck Norris can have both feet on the ground and kick butt at the same time.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring Chuck Norris standing confidently with both feet firmly planted on solid ground, but with a dynamic action pose that shows him simultaneously delivering a powerful kick with one leg. Show a comic-style ''kick butt'' effect, such as an exaggerated burst or impact cloud near his foot, emphasizing the contradictory feat of standing still and kicking fiercely at the same time. The background should be simple, perhaps a plain outdoor scene with a few rocks or grass to emphasize his grounded stance. Illustrate Chuck Norris with his iconic beard and serious facial expression. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, reminiscent of a fun comic strip or superhero cartoon.'),
 (395, 'Chuck Norris, Programming, Puns', 'Chuck Norris doesn''t need garbage collection because he doesn''t call.Dispose() - he calls.DropKick().', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple, colorful computer programming office. In the center, a bold and confident cartoon character styled as Chuck Norris stands with crossed arms and a tough expression. Around him are floating computer code snippets and a large trash bin labeled ''Garbage Collection''. On one side, a confused-looking programmer wearing glasses is holding a laptop showing code with ''.Dispose()'' method. Chuck Norris points his finger dramatically toward the trash bin as if demonstrating, while the trash bin humorously shows action lines as if it’s about to be ''kick-dropped'' out of the scene. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated, with comic-style motion lines and expressive faces, emphasizing the joke about Chuck Norris replacing a technical programming method with a kick. The background should be a bright office with desks, computers, and some programming posters on the wall to reinforce the tech atmosphere.'),
 (396, 'Chuck Norris, Puns, Tech Humor', 'Chuck Norris burst the dot com bubble.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Chuck Norris in his classic pose—arms crossed, stern expression, wearing a cowboy-style outfit or martial arts attire. He stands triumphantly on top of a bursting bubble labeled ''.com'' which is dramatically popping beneath him, with exaggerated comic-style burst lines and small tech-related icons (like a computer mouse, a smartphone, and website symbols) flying out from the burst bubble. The background is simplified with a city skyline or office buildings representing the tech industry. Include a few small characters or tech workers looking shocked or surprised at the bubble bursting. The overall tone is light and playful, emphasizing Chuck Norris'' legendary tough-guy image causing the tech bubble to burst through sheer force.'),
 (2644, 'Classic Joke, Historical Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'A Roman walks into a bar and holds up two fingers and says ''Five beers, please''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cozy, old-fashioned Roman-style tavern with stone walls and a wooden bar counter. Behind the bar, a jovial bartender dressed in a toga and laurel wreath is looking confused and holding up three fingers. In front of the bar stands a Roman man wearing a white toga with a red sash and sandals, holding up two fingers in the classic V shape. The Roman man has a confident smile as he says, ''Five beers, please.'' On the bar counter are several amphora-style beer mugs filled with frothy beer, some already counting up to five. The setting should feel playful and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing the misunderstanding. Include small playful details like a scroll with the bar menu hanging on the wall, and other patrons in Roman attire glancing at the scene with amused expressions. The joke visually plays on the Roman numeral ''V'' meaning five, contrasting with the two fingers held up for peace or the number two in modern culture.'),
 (2642, 'Classic Joke, Religion Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'A rabbi, a priest, and a Lutheran minister walk into a bar. The bartender says, ''What is this? Some kind of a joke?!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy bar with a warm wooden interior. At the center, three distinct religious figures stand side by side: a rabbi wearing a yarmulke and glasses, a priest in traditional black clerical collar and white collar tab, and a Lutheran minister with a simple suit and a small cross necklace. They look slightly amused or bemused. Behind the bar, a surprised bartender with a raised eyebrow and a hand on his hip addresses the trio with a speech bubble saying, ''What is this? Some kind of a joke?!'' Various bar elements like stools, bottles on shelves, a dartboard in the background, and a few empty glasses on the counter complete the scene. The art style is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize expression and the comedic nature of the punchline.'),
 (2312, 'Classic Quotes, Comedy, Mythology Humor, Quotes', 'The gods too are fond of a joke.', 'Aristotle (384-322 B.C.)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of ancient gods sitting on fluffy clouds in the sky, each with classical robes and laurel wreaths. They are sharing laughter together as one god tells a joke while others chuckle, smile, or lightly slap their knees. Surround the gods with typical mythological symbols like lightning bolts, a trident, a winged helmet, and an owl perched nearby. The background shows a bright blue sky with a few whimsical, fluffy clouds shaped like question marks or smiley faces to emphasize the playful mood. The style should be lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, reminiscent of classic Greek mythology but with a modern cartoon twist.'),
 (2107, 'Classic Quotes, Comic Humor, Quotes, Science Fiction Humor', 'Mind your own business, Spock. I''m sick of your half-breed interference.', 'Dr. McCoy on Star Trek', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a classic Star Trek bridge. In the center, a character resembling Captain Kirk is pointing an annoyed finger at Spock, who stands nearby with his usual calm expression and raised eyebrow. Both characters have exaggerated, cartoonish features with bright colors and simple lines typical of a lighthearted comic strip. Kirk is wearing a yellow Starfleet shirt, while Spock dons his iconic blue uniform and pointed Vulcan ears. Around them are classic sci-fi control panels with glowing buttons and screens showing stars outside. The background is the familiar futuristic bridge setting but in a playful style, emphasizing the humorous tension of Kirk''s frustrated expression and Spock''s composed demeanor. Include a speech bubble from Kirk saying, "Mind your own business, Spock. I''m sick of your half-breed interference." No violent or aggressive posture, just expressive faces emphasizing comedy and mild exasperation.'),
 (2575, 'Classic Quotes, Detective Humor, Logic Humor, Quotes', 'When you have eliminated the impossible, whatever remains, however improbable, must be the truth.', 'Sherlock Holmes in ''The Sign of the Four''', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a Sherlock Holmes-style detective''s cluttered office. Sherlock Holmes, depicted with a magnifying glass and iconic deerstalker hat, is dramatically pointing toward a corkboard filled with scattered clues, red string connecting various notes, and photos. The clues include humorous items like a rubber chicken, a floating teacup, and a cartoonishly suspicious-looking cat. Beside him, his partner Watson looks confused but intrigued, holding a notebook labeled ''Impossible Cases.'' The office has a window showing a full moon and a foggy London street outside. The overall tone is light, whimsical, and exaggerated to emphasize the absurdity of ''eliminating the impossible'' and settling on a funny, improbable truth. The style should be colorful, with expressive faces, and clear visual humor in the unexpected clues pinned on the board.'),
 (2338, 'Classic Quotes, Economics Humor, History Humor, Quotes', 'The market is not an invention of capitalism. It has existed for centuries. It is an invention of civilization.', 'Mikhail Gorbachev', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bustling ancient marketplace in a lively civilization like Mesopotamia or ancient Egypt. The market is outdoors under colorful fabric awnings stretched between wooden posts. People in simple, historically inspired clothing are engaged in typical market activities: a merchant at a stall selling pottery, another weighing grain on a scale, and a customer examining vegetables. In the background, ancient-style buildings and a river or palm trees suggest an early civilization setting. The atmosphere is cheerful and lively, with animals like chickens or goats weaving through the crowd. A playful element shows a small scroll or sign hanging that reads: ''Market: Invented by Civilization, Not Capitalism!'' The style is cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and slightly oversized heads for humor, vibrant colors, and clean lines, focusing on a lighthearted educational tone without any modern symbols or references to capitalism directly.'),
 (1922, 'Classic Quotes, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I''ll have what shes having...', 'Movie ''When Harry met Sally''', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy diner or café. The focus is on a table where a woman is enjoying an extravagant, visually impressive meal—perhaps a towering burger with all the toppings, extra-large fries, and a giant milkshake. She looks delighted and satisfied, smiling as she takes a big bite. Nearby, a second character, maybe a puzzled but intrigued man or another diner, leans over the table or stands close by with an eager, wide-eyed expression and says the famous line, "I''ll have what she''s having." The background should include simple diner details, like a counter, stools, or a menu board, with warm colors and a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon style. The characters should have slightly exaggerated facial features to emphasize humor without being caricatures, and the scene overall should convey a sense of playful envy or admiration for the woman''s meal choice.'),
 (1805, 'Classic Quotes, Fantasy Humor, Quotes', 'I don''t think we''re in Kansas anymore, Toto.', 'Dorothy, Wizard of Oz', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inspired by the iconic line from The Wizard of Oz. Show a small, scruffy dog named Toto standing next to a bewildered-looking person (Dorothy) wearing simple clothes and ruby red slippers. They are stepping out of a basic, black-and-white Kansas farmhouse on one side, which looks plain and ordinary, and entering a colorful, fantastical landscape filled with bright flowers, unusual trees, and whimsical creatures in the background. The contrast between the drab Kansas setting and the vibrant fantasy world should be exaggerated for comedic effect. Dorothy is pointing forward with a surprised expression, and Toto looks up at her with a confused but loyal look. Above them, include a speech bubble from Dorothy saying, "I don''t think we''re in Kansas anymore, Toto." The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features and bright colors emphasizing the sudden, magical change of scenery.'),
 (2624, 'Classic Quotes, Historical Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Your Highness, I have no need of this hypothesis.   (Said to Napoleon on why his works on celestial mechanics make no mention of God.)', 'Pierre Laplace (1749-1827)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a grand royal study or throne room with Napoleon Bonaparte sitting on an ornate, slightly oversized throne wearing his iconic bicorne hat and military uniform. Standing respectfully before him is a well-dressed 18th-19th century scientist or mathematician holding an old scroll or parchment labeled ''Celestial Mechanics.'' The scientist is explaining something with one hand raised and a confident smile, while Napoleon looks slightly puzzled or dismissive. The background should include celestial charts or models of planets and stars, maybe a telescope pointing out a window, emphasizing the scientific theme. The atmosphere is light-hearted and whimsical, and the characters'' exaggerated expressions add to the comedy. The scene conveys the clash between science and royal authority in a playful way without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2098, 'Classic Quotes, Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Men always want to be a woman''s first love -- women like to be a man''s last romance.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with two characters: a man and a woman standing side by side. The man looks dreamily upward, holding a large, old-fashioned photo frame labeled "First Love," featuring a cute, young couple silhouette inside. He has a hopeful, slightly goofy expression. The woman stands beside him with a confident smile, holding a heart-shaped locket labeled "Last Romance," glowing warmly. She looks calmly content and mature. Behind them, include a whimsical calendar on the wall, marked from left to right depicting various faded hearts and romances fading out toward the past, but the woman''s side shows a glowing, large heart at the end of the timeline. Use bright, warm colors and exaggerated expressions for comic effect. The setting is simple, indoors with a cozy atmosphere. The visual focus should emphasize the contrast between "first" and "last" love preferences humorously.'),
 (2349, 'Classic Quotes, Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'The most exciting phrase to hear in science, the one that heralds new discoveries, is not ''Eureka!'' (I''ve found it!), but ''That''s funny...''', 'Isaac Asimov', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classic scientific laboratory filled with typical lab equipment—test tubes, beakers, microscopes, flasks, and a chalkboard with scientific formulas scribbled on it. In the center, a cheerful scientist wearing a white lab coat, oversized glasses, and messy hair is looking at a bubbling flask with a surprised and delighted expression. Above his head is a speech bubble with the words "That''s funny..." in bold letters. Around the scientist, subtle visual gags like a confused microscope with googly eyes or a beaker spilling colorful bubbles add whimsy. The background should feel busy but lively, emphasizing curiosity and discovery in a playful manner. The cartoon style should be bright and exaggerated, with exaggerated facial features on the scientist to amplify the humor and excitement of the moment, making it clear that this phrase is the highlight of their discovery process.'),
 (2506, 'Classic Quotes, Irony, Music Humor, Quotes', 'Wagner''s music is better than it sounds.', 'Mark Twain (1835-1910)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classical music concert setting. On stage is a small orchestra with musicians playing various instruments, including violins, cellos, and brass. Front and center is a proud, slightly pompous conductor named Wagner, dressed in traditional composer attire with a big mustache and dramatic pose. The audience includes a few people covering their ears or leaning away with exaggerated grimaces, suggesting they don’t enjoy the music. Above the stage, a large banner reads: ''Wagner''s Music Concert.'' The background shows musical notes swirling, but some look dissonant or wobbly to hint the music ''sounds'' bad despite being ''better.'' The overall style is light and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke’s contrast between reputation and actual sound experience.'),
 (2356, 'Classic Quotes, Irony, Quotes, Social Humor', 'The only thing worse than being talked about is not being talked about.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two situations side by side. On the left, a celebrity or popular character stands on a red carpet surrounded by a crowd of reporters and paparazzi shouting questions and taking pictures, looking overwhelmed but slightly pleased. Speech bubbles around them say things like ''Did you see that?'' and ''What do you think?''. On the right side, the same character is alone in a plain room, looking bored and sad, sitting on a chair with a big silence symbol (like a quiet emoji or a muted microphone icon) hovering above their head to represent nobody talking about them. The background contrasts: bright and busy on the left, dull and empty on the right. The overall style is bright and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions for comedic effect, emphasizing the irony that attention can be both a blessing and a curse.'),
 (1752, 'Classic Quotes, Literary Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Heav''n hath no rage like love to hatred turn''d, Nor Hell a fury, like a woman scorn''d.', 'William Congreve (1670-1729)', 'Create a humorous cartoon depicting a woman standing with arms crossed, clearly annoyed or scorned, possibly with steam or exaggerated red cheeks to show fury. Opposite her, represent ''Heaven'' and ''Hell'' as two separate scenes or cloud-like thought bubbles in the background. In the ''Heaven'' bubble, illustrate tranquil, peaceful imagery with soft colors, but a faint angry face or subtle rage symbol like a small thundercloud. In the ''Hell'' bubble, show a small comedic depiction of flames and a devil character looking surprised or alarmed at the woman''s fury. The main focus is the woman embodying the phrase ''a woman scorn''d'' with exaggerated, cartoonish fury that humorously overshadows the rage in Heaven and the fury in Hell. Include text banners or scrolls above each bubble labeling them ''Heaven'' and ''Hell'' with playful fonts. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, similar to classic comic strips or editorial cartoons, emphasizing the contrast between divine powers and human emotion.'),
 (2252, 'Classic Quotes, Literary Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Sometimes when reading Goethe I have the paralyzing suspicion that he is trying to be funny.', 'Guy Davenport', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting in a cozy armchair surrounded by piles of thick books, clearly immersed in reading. The person looks deeply puzzled and slightly overwhelmed, with wide eyes and a small drop of sweat on their temple. One book cover clearly says ''Goethe'' in an elegant font. Around the reader''s head are several small cartoon thought bubbles containing question marks, exclamation points, and tiny laughing emojis, showing their confusion about whether the writing is serious or funny. On a nearby side table is a steaming cup of tea, a pair of round reading glasses, and a quill pen resting on an open notebook full of scribbled, confused notes. The room is warmly lit, and a window shows a calm evening outside. The overall style is light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions and soft, warm colors to emphasize the comical internal struggle of understanding Goethe''s humor or seriousness.'),
 (2273, 'Classic Quotes, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Fiction Humor', 'The answer to the great question of Life, the Universe and Everything is Forty-two', 'Douglas Adams, The Hitchhiker''s Guide to the Galaxy', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inspired by ''The Hitchhiker''s Guide to the Galaxy.'' Show a quirky, slightly futuristic library or study filled with piles of books, papers, and colorful gadgets. At the center, depict a wise-looking, quirky robot or computer with an old-fashioned screen displaying the number ''42'' in big, bold digits. Around the robot, a few puzzled people of various ages and styles are scratching their heads or looking excitedly baffled. Include speech bubbles to suggest confusion or awe without text. The background could have stars or cosmic elements like planets or galaxies visible through a window to emphasize the cosmic theme. The overall style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the humor and whimsy of this iconic answer to a deep, philosophical question.'),
 (2466, 'Classic Quotes, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Time, and time alone, will show the just man, though scoundrels are discovered in a day.', 'Creon', 'A humorous cartoon-style scene featuring two characters standing in a simple setting like a park or a quiet street. On the left, a calm, dignified man dressed in neat, classic clothes, representing ''the just man,'' stands patiently with a gentle, knowing smile and a clock behind him showing the passage of time (with hands moving forward). On the right, a shady-looking scoundrel wearing a mask or sneaky expression tries to sneak away but is immediately caught by a large magnifying glass held by an exaggerated detective character or a giant eye representing quick discovery. The background can subtly include an hourglass or calendar to emphasize ''time alone'' versus ''a day.'' Use soft, warm colors for the just man side and more vibrant or suspicious colors for the scoundrel. The cartoon art should emphasize the contrast humorously and clearly show the moral that justice takes time, but wrongdoing is quickly uncovered.'),
 (2833, 'Cleaning Humor, Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Every time you clean something, you just make something else dirty.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a typical messy living room. In the center, show a person cheerfully wiping a shiny coffee table with a cleaning cloth, smiling proudly. Around them, depict dust and dirt clouds drifting away from the table and settling onto other objects, like a couch, a bookshelf, and the floor, which all look visibly dirtier than before. Include exaggerated, animated dust particles flying and landing comically on different surfaces. Add a small, playful pet (like a cat or dog) looking curiously at the dust settling on its paws or fur. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, with bright colors and expressive faces that emphasize the ironic situation: cleaning one spot just moves the mess somewhere else, creating a continuous loop of cleaning and dirtying. The style should be cartoonish and whimsical, suitable for a family-friendly comic strip or humorous illustration.'),
 (397, 'Clothing Humor, Good Question!, Laundry Humor', 'No use looking at the tag after the clothes have been shrunk.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person looking frustrated while holding a tiny shrunken sweater in one hand. The person is standing in front of a washing machine with soap suds spilling over. Nearby, the original oversized sweater with a clearly visible clothing tag is lying crumpled on a laundry basket. The tag zoom-in bubble shows a witty detail such as ''Machine wash cold'' or ''Do not shrink.'' The background includes a laundry room with a detergent bottle and drying rack, emphasizing the laundry context. The person''s exaggerated facial expression and body language highlight the humor of realizing the tag’s advice only after the clothes are ruined.'),
 (2737, 'Comedy, Country Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: The Pint of No Return', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a rustic country bar with a wooden sign above the door that reads ''The Pint of No Return.'' Inside, a row of empty pint glasses is lined up on the bar counter, some spilling beer over the edge. A sad-looking cowboy wearing a hat and boots sits slumped on a barstool, nursing his last pint. Behind the bar, a bartender wipes a glass with a resigned expression. The setting includes country-western décor, such as a guitar hanging on the wall, a cowboy hat rack, and a wanted poster with a pint glass caricature. The overall style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and rounded lines to emphasize the comedic and lighthearted mood.'),
 (2157, 'Comedy, Creative Humor, Motivational, Quotes', 'Nothing great was ever achieved without enthusiasm.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky inventor in a cluttered workshop full of half-finished inventions. The inventor is energetically and enthusiastically waving their arms while surrounded by sparks, smoke, and flying gears, clearly excited about their latest creation. A few whimsical inventions—like a rocket-powered bicycle or a robotic toaster—are visible on workbenches. In the background, a framed motivational poster on the wall reads, ''Nothing great was ever achieved without enthusiasm,'' emphasized with big, bold letters. The inventor''s exaggerated facial expression conveys an infectious excitement and passion. Bright colors and dynamic lines highlight the inventor’s lively energy, making the scene feel both inspiring and comically chaotic.'),
 (1727, 'Comedy, Education Humor, Quotes, Teaching Humor', 'Good teaching is one-fourth preparation and three-fourths theater.', 'Gail Godwin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon classroom scene from a slightly elevated angle. On one side, a confident teacher stands in front of a blackboard, dressed in a classic teacher outfit with glasses and a pointer stick. The teacher is enthusiastically acting out an exaggerated, dramatic gesture as if performing on stage. The blackboard behind them has the phrase: ''Good teaching = 1/4 preparation + 3/4 theater'' written in chalk. On the teacher''s desk, there are scattered lesson plans and notes representing the ''preparation.'' Around the classroom, a few students watch in amused surprise, some holding notebooks, one raising an eyebrow skeptically, and another pretending to be applauding like in a theater audience. The overall mood is light and playful, capturing the idea that teaching is part lesson, part performance. Use bright colors and rounded, friendly character designs to emphasize humor and make the scene inviting and fun.'),
 (1697, 'Comedy, Everyday Life, Public Speaking Humor, Quotes', 'Finally, in conclusion, let me say just this.', 'Peter Sellers', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a simple stage with a wooden podium. A speaker, dressed in a suit and tie, stands behind the podium with a serious expression while holding papers. The background is a plain curtain typical of a conference or speech setting. Above the speaker, a large banner reads ''Conference'' or ''Speech Day.'' The speaker is mid-sentence, confidently saying, "Finally, in conclusion, let me say just this." In front of the stage, a scattered audience looks confused or bored, some scratching their heads or yawning. One or two audience members might be whispering or clearly expecting a follow-up statement. The overall atmosphere pokes fun at the clichéd and often anticlimactic way people give speeches, suggesting the phrase signals the end without actually adding substance. The drawing style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor and mild frustration of the audience.'),
 (1740, 'Comedy, Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Having it all doesn''t necessarily mean having it all at once.', 'Stephanie Luetkehans', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person juggling a variety of everyday objects all at once, symbolizing ''having it all.'' The person looks slightly overwhelmed but determined, with a mix of office items (like a laptop and papers), household items (a baby bottle, vacuum cleaner), and leisure objects (a coffee cup, a guitar) flying around. Their facial expression shows a mix of concentration and mild panic. Around them, there are several empty hands and shelves suggesting these things could be handled one at a time instead. The background is a simple home or office setting, lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the chaos without being stressful. The overall tone is funny and relatable, visually representing the idea that managing everything simultaneously is tough, but having everything eventually is possible.'),
 (1526, 'Comedy, Irony, Quotes', 'Always try to be modest and be proud of it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a character standing proudly on a small stage with a large gold trophy labeled ''Modesty Award'' held high above their head. The character is beaming with a confident smile and wearing a sash that reads ''Most Modest.'' Around the stage, an audience applauds enthusiastically. The background is a simple hall decorated with modest but celebratory banners. The scene should highlight the irony of being overly proud about modesty, emphasizing an amusing contradiction in the character''s expression and pose. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated cartoon features to enhance the humor without being aggressive or mean.'),
 (2365, 'Comedy, Irony, Quotes, Social Humor', 'The people I distrust most are those who want to improve our lives but have only one course of action.', 'Frank Herbert', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of serious-looking people gathered around a long table labeled ''Life Improvement Committee.'' One character, standing at the head of the table with a pointer stick, enthusiastically points to a giant chart that only shows a single arrow pointing forward labeled ''One Course of Action.'' Around the table, others look skeptical or suspicious, crossing their arms or raising eyebrows. The setting is a bland conference room with a whiteboard and a few scattered papers, emphasizing the redundancy of the plan. The expressions should convey distrust and doubt with a comedic touch. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated to highlight the absurdity of having only one solution to improve everyone''s lives, with bright colors and simple lines typical of cartoon humor.'),
 (1421, 'Comedy, Irony, Quotes, Word Play', 'A joke is a very serious thing.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stand-up comedian on stage dressed in a suit and bowtie, holding a microphone. The comedian wears an overly solemn and exaggeratedly serious expression as he delivers the line “A joke is a very serious thing.” The stage is decorated with a classic red curtain backdrop and a spotlight focused on the comedian. In the audience, caricatured people are laughing uproariously, some wiping tears from their eyes, clearly finding the seriousness ironic and funny. Near the stage, a small sign or poster reads: “Tonight’s Comedy Show.” To emphasize the joke’s play on words, a large, oversized book titled “The Serious Art of Jokes” rests on a stand beside the comedian. The overall style is lighthearted, with vibrant colors and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the contrast between the comedian’s earnest demeanor and the audience’s amusement.'),
 (2845, 'Comedy, Life, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Everything up to age 40 is just rehearsal.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stage with a big curtain drawn back. In the foreground, a cheerful middle-aged person (looking about 40) stands confidently at a microphone center stage, smiling and gesturing as if addressing an audience. Behind them, in the wings or off to the side, a series of smaller cartoon figures representing the same person at various younger ages (from a toddler to a teenager to a young adult) are acting dramatically or goofing off, clearly labeled with their ages like ''5'', ''15'', ''30''. Above the main character is a banner that says ''Life: Act 2 Starts at 40!'' The backdrop features playful stage props like theatrical masks, a spotlight shining on the 40-year-old, and a sign that reads ''Rehearsal Over''. The entire style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated in true cartoon fashion, evoking the idea of life as a theatrical play with the first 40 years being just practice.'),
 (2439, 'Comedy, Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'There just isn''t any pleasing some people. The trick is to stop trying.', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room. On the left side, a cheerful person is holding a brightly wrapped gift with a hopeful smile, offering it out. On the right side, another character looks unimpressed, crossing their arms with a frown or disapproving expression. Between them, a floating thought bubble shows a chaotic jumble of confused symbols and question marks, representing frustration. The background includes a comfy armchair, a small table with a coffee cup, and a framed motivational quote on the wall that reads ''Happiness is a choice.'' The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor of trying to please someone who clearly can''t be pleased. The overall vibe is playful, conveying the joke’s message about the futility of constant effort to satisfy difficult people.'),
 (1571, 'Comedy, Motivational, Quotes, Wisdom', 'As soon as you can say what you think, and not what some other person has thought for you, you are on the way to being a remarkable man.', 'James Mathew Barrie', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing confidently on a small podium labeled ''Remarkable Man.'' He is cheerfully speaking into a vintage microphone, with a speech bubble showing a unique, original light bulb symbol above his head. Around him are three other characters looking confused, each holding speech bubbles filled with jumbled, scribbled symbols representing copied or unclear thoughts. The setting is a simple stage with a spotlight highlighting the man. The atmosphere is light, encouraging individuality and original thinking. The characters should be drawn in a friendly, exaggerated cartoon style with expressive faces emphasizing the difference between original thought and parroting others.'),
 (1665, 'Comedy, Office Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'E-Mail is not to be used to pass on information or data. It should be used only for company business.', '(Actual Dilbert Manager Quotes)', 'A humorous cartoon office scene with two employees sitting at adjacent desks. One employee looks confused while staring at a computer screen displaying a long email titled ''Official Company Communication.'' The other employee, standing nearby with a big smile and holding a printed company memo that says ''E-Mail Policy,'' is pointing toward a large, old-fashioned office bulletin board labeled ''Company Business Only.'' Above this board is a humorous sign that reads: ''E-Mail is NOT for passing on info or data!'' The room has typical office items like a potted plant, coffee mugs, a printer, and a wall clock. The style is bright and cheerful with exaggerated, friendly character expressions to amplify the irony and create a lighthearted, everyday office atmosphere.'),
 (2418, 'Comedy, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'There are things that are so serious that you can only joke about them.', 'Heisenberg', 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting thoughtfully at a small table with a notepad and pen, appearing to be a comedian or joke writer. The background is a cozy room with a spotlight focused on them, suggesting a comedy stage vibe. Above their head is a big, glowing thought bubble containing serious symbols such as a judge''s gavel, a heart with a bandage, and a peace symbol, representing serious topics. Around the room are framed pictures on the walls with subtle, funny depictions of serious moments (like a smiling clock or a playful scale of justice). The character has a slight smile, showing they are carefully considering how to joke about serious subjects. The overall tone is light and respectful, with bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the thoughtful but humorous nature of the concept.'),
 (1822, 'Comedy, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I have yet to see any problem, however complicated, which, when you looked at it in the right way, did not become still more complicated.', 'Poul Anderson', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered office filled with papers, charts, and a large blackboard. In the center, a stressed-out character sits at a desk scratching their head, looking confused. Around them, several versions of the same problem—depicted as a tangled ball of strings or a complex diagram—appear: one labeled ''Original Problem'' and the others labeled ''After Looking at it the Right Way'' but increasingly messier and more complicated. The character’s expression changes from hopeful curiosity to bewilderment as the problem complexity grows. The background includes humorous details like overturned coffee cups, crumpled papers, and an open book titled ''How to Solve Problems''. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the irony that the ''right way'' of looking only makes problems more complicated instead of simpler.'),
 (1979, 'Comedy, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'It is impossible to defeat an ignorant man in argument.', 'William G. McAdoo', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters arguing. One character looks frustrated, with eyebrows furrowed and mouth open mid-sentence, holding a stack of books and pointing at a blackboard full of complex diagrams and facts. The other character appears completely oblivious and unfazed, wearing a simple outfit, smiling confidently with arms crossed, eyes closed as if ignoring the argument. The setting is a casual debate stage or school classroom with audience members in the background looking entertained and confused. Speech bubbles show the frustrated character’s complicated argument, while the ignorant character’s bubble is blank or filled with symbols like question marks and squiggles, emphasizing misunderstanding or refusal to engage. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated to highlight the futility and humor of arguing with an ignorant person.'),
 (2913, 'Comedy, Philosophy Humor, Self-Improvement Humor, Unknown', 'He that would govern others, first should be the master of himself.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person trying to ''master'' themselves as if they were their own servant. The person is standing in front of a large full-length mirror with a determined but slightly confused expression. Behind the person, a smaller version of themselves dressed like a royal servant (complete with a fancy waistcoat and a tray holding a cup of tea) is awkwardly trying to follow orders, looking overwhelmed. Around the room, a few comical self-control items like a locked fridge, a treadmill, and a meditation cushion are scattered. The background is a cozy, simple living room with a clocks and a motivational poster on the wall that says, "Be Your Own Boss!" The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, done in bright colors with exaggerated cartoon expressions and a touch of whimsy.'),
 (1804, 'Comedy, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'I don''t make jokes. I just watch the government and report the facts.', 'Will Rogers', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk with a notepad and pen, looking serious but slightly amused. The person is dressed in casual clothes and wearing glasses, acting like a reporter. Behind the person, a large window reveals a chaotic government office with humorous elements: papers flying, a confused politician scratching their head, and a big sign that says ''Government Facts'' on the wall. On the desk is a microphone labeled ''Truth Booth.'' The overall style is lighthearted and caricature-like, emphasizing the absurdity and humor of simply reporting government actions as if they are naturally funny or unbelievable facts.'),
 (2445, 'Comedy, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'There''s no trick to being a humorist when you have the whole government working for you.', 'Will Rogers', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person labeled ''Humorist'' sitting comfortably at a desk with a big grin, surrounded by papers and a typewriter or laptop. Behind them, a caricatured group of government officials—wearing typical suits with badges, holding documents, or sitting at a long conference table—are all laughing or looking goofy, clearly unintentionally supplying punchlines or ridiculous situations. There should be visual cues to indicate bureaucracy, like stacks of paperwork, a government building in the background, and exaggerated facial expressions showing confusion or silliness among officials. The humorist looks relaxed and almost smug, as if the government’s shenanigans are making their job easier. The overall tone is lighthearted and satirical but non-threatening, rendered in simple, colorful cartoon style with exaggerated features for comedic effect.'),
 (2893, 'Comedy, Pop Culture Humor, Satire, Unknown', 'GRADUATE: Han Solo School of Action without Thought', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a graduation ceremony at a fictional school named ''Han Solo School of Action without Thought.'' Center stage is a proud graduate in a cap and gown striking a confident, adventurous pose reminiscent of Han Solo from Star Wars—one hand on their hip and the other holding a diploma like a blaster. Behind them is a banner with the school name in bold letters. The audience consists of cartoon characters clapping and looking amused or surprised. Props include a spaceship model partly visible near the stage and scattered star-shaped confetti. The style is colorful and playful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke about acting without thinking, capturing the spirit of the Star Wars character''s impulsiveness in a light-hearted graduation setting.'),
 (3163, 'Comedy, Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'Really? I told my best chemistry joke and there was no reaction?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on a small stage or platform holding a microphone, as if telling a joke to an audience. The speaker looks hopeful and animated, mid-sentence. The background shows a few audience members with completely neutral or bored expressions, maybe with blank speech bubbles to indicate silence. To the side of the stage, there is a comically oversized chemistry setup: visible beakers, test tubes, and flasks bubbling or emitting puffs of smoke, to visually represent a ''reaction.'' The contrast emphasizes the joke’s punchline about ''no reaction.'' The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and simple shapes to keep it light and funny without complexity or harsh details.'),
 (2397, 'Comedy, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'The trouble with unemployment is that the minute you wake up in the morning, you''re on the job.', 'Lena Horne', 'A humorous cartoon showing a disheveled person waking up in the morning in their bedroom. The character has exaggerated bed hair, droopy eyes, and is stretching while still half-lounging on a messy bed. A large alarm clock shows early morning time nearby. Surrounding the character are several quirky symbols representing ''work'': a briefcase by the bedside, a computer on a small desk, and a sticky note with to-do items floating in the air. The setting clearly conveys a contrast between waking up and immediately being ''on the job'' despite no formal work being done. The room is cozy but cluttered to add a humorous sense of being stuck in a work mindset even while at home. The overall tone is light and playful, using bright pastel colors and soft lines typical of a friendly cartoon style.'),
 (2254, 'Comedy, Quotes, Social Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Speak the truth, but leave immediately after.', 'Slovenian proverb', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in a doorway of a room where a small group of other people are listening attentively. The speaker has just delivered a bold, honest statement with an exaggerated serious expression and wide eyes. Behind the speaker, the doorway is open and the person is mid-step, clearly walking away quickly, perhaps slightly leaning forward to emphasize hurry. The listeners display a mix of stunned, surprised, and awkward facial expressions, with some whispering or wide-eyed. The setting is casual, like an office break room or living room, with a clock on the wall showing an early hour as if this is an unexpected moment. Include speech bubbles with a single bold phrase: "Speak the truth," coming from the speaker, and a smaller bubble from the speaker at the doorway saying: "But leave immediately after." The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and simple, clean lines, emphasizing the comedic timing of speaking truth and then hastily exiting the social situation.'),
 (1936, 'Comedy, Quotes, Television, Word Play', 'Imitation is the sincerest form of television.', 'Fred Allen (1894-1956)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two old-fashioned television sets side by side. One TV is classic, with rabbit ear antennas and a wooden cabinet, showing a black and white image of a popular TV show character acting. The second TV next to it looks almost identical but is slightly distorted or glitchy, clearly copying the image and movements of the first one, as if trying to imitate exactly what the original is showing. Both TVs have exaggerated expressive cartoon eyes on their screens to make them anthropomorphic and funny—one looks proud while the other looks admiring and trying hard to copy. The background is a simple living room with a cozy couch, a small plant, and a framed picture on the wall, emphasizing a homey environment. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, using bright colors and simple lines to create a playful and comical homage to the phrase “Imitation is the sincerest form of television.” No people are present, just the two personified TVs engaging in the visual pun.'),
 (2974, 'Comedy, Relatable, Unknown, Word Play', 'I didn''t say it was your fault. I said I was going to blame you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual living room setting. One character, with an innocent yet slightly mischievous expression, is pointing a finger playfully at the other character, who looks surprised and a little worried. Both characters are cartoon-style with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke. The room has a couch, a small table with a lamp, and a framed picture on the wall, creating a relaxed, informal atmosphere. Above them is a speech bubble from the first character saying, "I didn''t say it was your fault." and the second speech bubble below continuing, "I said I was going to blame you." The style should be light and fun, with bright colors and simple lines to enhance the comedic effect without any hostility.'),
 (2767, 'Comic Humor, Communication, Office Humor, Unknown', 'Disclaimer:  Any errors in spelling, tact, or fact are transmission errors.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene resembling a simple office or studio setting with a large old-fashioned radio or television in the center. The radio or TV has a whimsical label or speech bubble coming from it stating, ''Disclaimer: Any errors in spelling, tact, or fact are transmission errors.'' Around it, people are watching or listening with puzzled yet amused expressions, holding newspapers or notes with visible spelling mistakes or silly errors. Include comical details like a confused cat or dog nearby, and a small stack of manuals or dictionaries with some papers fluttering around, emphasizing the theme of errors and miscommunication. The overall scene should be lighthearted and simple, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to convey the joke’s playful nature about disclaimers and errors being blamed on transmission.'),
 (1649, 'Comic Humor, Computers Humor, Everyday Life, Quotes', 'Drat these computers. They are so naughty and so complex.', 'The Martian', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a frustrated person sitting in front of a cluttered desk with multiple computers and screens showing confusing error messages and tangled wires. The person is pulling their hair or making an exaggerated annoyed face. The computers are drawn with playful, mischievous expressions like cartoon faces with eyes and smirks, emphasizing their ''naughty'' behavior. On the desk, include typical office items like a coffee mug, sticky notes with scribbles, and a keyboard with some keys popping off to add to the chaotic and complex atmosphere. The background shows a typical home or office setting with a window and a clock, giving context but keeping the focus on the interaction between the person and the ''naughty'' computers. The overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated to enhance the comedic effect without any negativity or anger.'),
 (2628, 'Comic Humor, Computers, Pun, Unknown', '29A: the hexadecimal of the Beast.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly-looking computer screen displaying the hexadecimal number ''29A''. Standing next to the screen is a small, cute red cartoon devil with tiny horns and a mischievous grin, pointing at the number. The setting is a cozy office or home workspace with a desk, keyboard, mouse, and a coffee mug. The computer monitor shows a simple black background with large white text: ''29A''. The devil character is drawn in a lighthearted style, non-threatening and cartoonish, to emphasize humor. Maybe add a small calendar or a poster on the wall jokingly referencing ''The Beast'' with a playful tone, like a calendar page titled ''Hex Beast Schedule''. The overall mood is playful and techy, making a clever visual pun connecting the number 29A with ''the Beast'' in hexadecimal form.'),
 (2783, 'Comic Humor, Cultural Humor, Unknown', 'Donald Duck comics were banned in Finland because he doesn''t wear any pants.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a store aisle in Finland labeled with a big, bold sign saying ''Donald Duck Comics - Banned!''. The main focus is a display of Donald Duck comic books with cover art featuring Donald Duck happily standing in his classic sailor shirt and hat but noticeably no pants. Nearby, a group of cartoonish Finnish people—some looking slightly puzzled, others chuckling—are standing behind a large sign saying ''No Pants Allowed!''. The background includes a cozy Finnish bookstore setting, with shelves filled with other comic books that are clearly allowed. Bright and colorful colors enhance the playful tone, and a small speech bubble from one person says, ''He really should wear pants!''. Make sure Donald Duck looks iconic and friendly but clearly pantless, and the entire scene has a lighthearted, family-friendly cartoon style with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect.'),
 (1681, 'Comic Humor, Education Humor, Literary Humor, Quotes', 'Everywhere I go I''m asked if I think the university stifles writers. My opinion is that they don''t stifle enough of them.', 'Flannery O''Connor (1925-1964)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a university hallway lined with lockers and a bulletin board filled with creative writing flyers. In the foreground, a casual-looking, slightly sarcastic person, maybe a professor or a student, stands with a smirk and one eyebrow raised, holding a notebook labeled ''Writers.'' Around them, a few exaggerated, quirky-looking writers appear stressed or overwhelmed—one frantically typing with papers flying, another tangled in a bunch of manuscripts, and one holding a ''Help!'' sign. The scene should be colorful and playful, emphasizing an atmosphere where writers seem to be everywhere but under a bit of comedic pressure. A speech bubble from the main character reads: "My opinion is that they don''t stifle enough of them." The style is light and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and a lively academic environment without any aggressive or harsh elements.'),
 (2327, 'Comic Humor, Education Humor, Public Speaking Humor, Quotes', 'The lecturer should give the audience full reason to believe that all his powers have been exerted for their pleasure and instruction.', 'Michael Faraday', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or lecture hall. A slightly exaggerated, expressive lecturer stands confidently on a stage or platform, wearing glasses and holding a pointer stick in one hand and a book in the other. The lecturer looks proudly at the audience, clearly emphasizing effort and dedication. The audience members—diverse in age and style—sit in rows of seats, some looking amused, some sleepy, some impressed. Visual cues like light bulbs or exaggerated sweat drops on the lecturer emphasize the ''exertion of powers.'' The background includes a blackboard or projection screen with vague academic-looking scribbles. The overall mood is lighthearted, with playful, cartoonish facial expressions and exaggerated body language to highlight the joke’s tone about the lecturer’s dedication to the audience’s pleasure and instruction, almost like superhero-like effort in teaching. The style should be colorful and friendly, with clean, bold outlines typical of cartoons.'),
 (2266, 'Comic Humor, Education Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Tell me and I forget. Show me and I remember. Involve me and I understand.', 'Chinese Proverb', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a bright, colorful classroom. The teacher stands at the front with three distinct panels above or around her illustrating the quote. The first panel shows her speaking to bored students with blank faces, reflecting ''Tell me and I forget.'' The second panel shows her demonstrating something simple, like holding a globe or a model, with students looking interested but still passive, captioned ''Show me and I remember.'' The third panel shows the teacher handing out tools or materials to the students, who are now actively building or experimenting together, smiling and engaged, captioned ''Involve me and I understand.'' The classroom should have typical educational items like a chalkboard, books, desks, and a globe. The teacher should be animated and friendly-looking, and the students diverse and expressive, emphasizing growing engagement and understanding. The style is light, bright, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and meaning behind each learning stage without any text outside the dialogue or captions in panels.'),
 (1438, 'Comic Humor, Everyday Life, Motivational, Quotes', 'A man can be as great as he wants to be. If you believe in yourself and have the courage, the determination, the dedication, the competitive drive and if you are willing to sacrifice the little things in life and pay for the things that are worthwhile, it can be done.', 'Vince Lombardi', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confident man in casual clothing standing on a small mountain peak labeled ''Success.'' Around him are exaggerated, playful symbols representing each quality mentioned: a heart labeled ''Belief,'' a brave lion with a tiny cape labeled ''Courage,'' a determined runner holding a torch labeled ''Determination,'' a book titled ''Dedication,'' a trophy with a fierce face labeled ''Competitive Drive.'' Nearby, the man is holding a tiny shopping basket with a few simple items crossed out and a big golden coin labeled ''Sacrifice'' in his other hand. The background is bright and cheerful with blue skies and cartoon-style clouds. The overall tone is lighthearted and motivational but with a fun, exaggerated feel, emphasizing the idea that greatness is achievable by juggling many attributes and making some sacrifices.'),
 (1471, 'Comic Humor, Everyday Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'A timid person is frightened before a danger, a coward during the time, and a courageous person afterward.', 'Jean Paul Richter', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into three panels side-by-side, each depicting the same timid character reacting differently to an approaching danger. The first panel shows a small, wide-eyed person nervously peeking around a corner with a worried expression, backs slightly hunched, glancing at a shadowy, vague shape symbolizing danger in the distance. The second panel shows the same character cowering in the middle of the scene, eyes closed tightly, trembling with exaggerated fear, knees bent as if ready to run or hide, while the threat—a harmless but exaggerated cartoon monster or shadow—is right in front of them but without any action. The third panel shows the character standing tall and proudly, chest puffed out, smiling confidently with a thumbs-up, while the ''danger'' is shown retreating or completely gone, looking small and harmless now. The background is simple with soft colors, focusing on the character''s expressions and body language, and the style is light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated emotional cues to emphasize the transformation from fear to courage after the danger is over.'),
 (2894, 'Comic Humor, Grammar Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Grammar Fumblerule: Avoid run-on sentences they are hard to read.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classroom setting. In the center, a friendly-looking teacher stands next to a blackboard with the sentence: ''Avoid run-on sentences they are hard to read.'' The teacher looks a bit puzzled or sheepish, scratching their head, highlighting the irony of the run-on sentence on the board. Around the teacher, a few students sit at desks with exaggerated confused or amused expressions. One student might be whispering to another, pointing at the blackboard. The classroom should have typical school elements like desks, chairs, books, and educational posters on the walls. The art style is colorful and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke. No violence or political elements included.'),
 (1714, 'Comic Humor, Historical Humor, Quotes, Science Fiction Humor', 'Get rid of the pointed-ears guy.  (said to Gene Roddenbery, creator of Star Trek, regarding Mr. Spock, 1966)', 'NBC Excecutive', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a 1960s-style television studio. In the center, a director resembling Gene Roddenberry sits confidently in a director''s chair labeled ''Director.'' He is holding a clipboard and gesturing with one hand as if giving instructions. In front of him stands Mr. Spock, easily recognizable with his sharp, pointed ears, Vulcan haircut, and Starfleet uniform. Mr. Spock looks calm but slightly puzzled. Nearby, a producer or assistant is whispering into the director''s ear with a speech bubble saying, ''Get rid of the pointed-ears guy.'' The background shows bright studio lights, cameras on tripods, and a partial Star Trek set piece like a futuristic control panel. The style is lighthearted and cartoony, with exaggerated expressions and bold lines to emphasize the humor in the directive to remove such an iconic character feature, highlighting the moment as a behind-the-scenes joke from TV history.'),
 (2469, 'Comic Humor, Inspirational, Motivational, Quotes', 'To accomplish great things, we must not only act, but also dream; not only plan, but also believe.', 'Anatole France', 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene showing a determined person standing at the edge of a cliff, looking out over a vast landscape that blends reality and imagination. On one side, the person is holding a rolled-up action plan or blueprint, symbolizing planning and action. On the other side, fluffy dream-like clouds float overhead, some shaped like imaginative ideas such as stars, light bulbs, and rockets, representing dreams and belief. The character should have a thoughtful but hopeful expression, wearing casual clothes suitable for an adventurer or visionary. Include subtle symbols of belief, like faint glowing sparkles around the dream clouds. The style should be colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions and friendly shapes to emphasize inspiration and positivity in a humorous, cartoon format.'),
 (1675, 'Comic Humor, Irony, Movie Humor, Quotes', 'Every once in a while a film comes along. This is such a film.', 'Mad Magazine', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a movie theater auditorium. The movie screen prominently displays the text: ''This is such a film.'' The audience is a diverse group of cartoon characters with exaggerated expressions of genuine surprise, awe, or deep contemplation, as if they are witnessing something incredibly profound or groundbreaking. Include popcorn buckets, soda cups, and 3D glasses to clearly show it''s a movie setting. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the deadpan humor of the statement that the film is notable simply by the line itself. The colors should be vibrant and inviting to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (1234, 'Comic Humor, Jobs, Pun, Workplace', 'I used to work at a keyboard factory, but I got fired because I didn''t put in enough shifts', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene inside a keyboard factory. In the foreground, show a cheerful factory worker standing beside a large conveyor belt filled with computer keyboard keys (letters, numbers, and symbols). The worker looks a bit confused or sheepish, holding a tiny wrench, wearing factory overalls and a cap. Above the conveyor belt, include some boxes labeled “SHIFT” with arrow symbols pointing to the worker, but the worker is clearly ignoring or missing these boxes. To emphasize the pun, show a few shifted keys literally floating around or slipping out of the worker''s hands. The background can have factory elements like machinery, gear wheels, and posters illustrating keyboard keys. The style should be bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions that highlight the joke’s wordplay on “shifts” (both work shifts and keyboard keys). No people look angry or aggressive; it should be lighthearted and silly.'),
 (1242, 'Comic Humor, Knock Knock, Objects Humor, Pun', 'KK/WT: Broken Pencil ? Never mind - it''s pointless', NULL, 'A cartoon showing a broken pencil lying on a blank sheet of paper on a wooden desk. The pencil is snapped in half, with the broken end jagged and graphite tip exposed. Nearby, a little speech bubble coming from the pencil reads ''Never mind - it''s pointless.'' The background should be simple and light-colored to keep focus on the pencil. The style should be bright, cheerful, and humorous, with exaggerated expressions like the pencil having a tiny sad face or small arms showing a shrug to emphasize the pun. No people or other distracting objects should be included, just the pencil and the paper on a desk, drawn in a cute, cartoonish style that clearly illustrates the pun about the pencil being broken and pointless.'),
 (2891, 'Comic Humor, Life, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'Good judgment comes from experience, and experience comes from bad judgment.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two panels side-by-side. In the first panel, a character (a friendly-looking adult person with a puzzled yet determined expression) is making an obviously poor decision, such as stepping confidently onto a banana peel or holding a paint bucket upside down. In the second panel, the same character looks wiser and more thoughtful, wearing glasses and holding a book titled ''Experience,'' with a lightbulb above their head symbolizing ''good judgment.'' Around them, subtle visual hints of past mistakes are displayed as small framed pictures on the wall, each showing the character in various silly mishaps (like slipping, spilling, or tripping). The background should be simple and clean, with soft pastel colors to keep the tone light and funny. The style is a playful cartoon with exaggerated expressions and clear, readable visuals emphasizing the cause-effect relationship of bad judgment leading to experience and then good judgment.'),
 (3128, 'Comic Humor, Life, Unknown, Wit', 'You can fool some of the people all of the time, and all of the people some of the time, but you can make a fool of yourself anytime.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing three panels side by side. Panel one: a group of diverse cartoon people looking confused or tricked, some with question marks above their heads, representing ''You can fool some of the people all of the time.'' Panel two: another group of people, different from the first, with puzzled expressions and clocks or calendars floating above them, illustrating ''and all of the people some of the time.'' Panel three: a silly-looking character in the center, tripping over their own feet or accidentally spilling something on themselves, with a big goofy grin and a sign overhead saying ''Make a fool of yourself anytime!'' The characters are drawn with exaggerated expressions, bright colors, and a lighthearted, playful style. Backgrounds are simple, with subtle hints like crowds or clocks to support the joke''s meaning, portraying the idea of fooling others contrasted with the inevitability of self-embarrassment in a funny, non-threatening way.'),
 (3148, 'Comic Humor, Mental Health Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'You seem reasonable - time to increase my medication.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon depicts two characters in a casual living room setting. One character looks very calm, kind, and reasonable, sitting comfortably in an armchair with a relaxed expression. The other character, holding a bottle of pills labeled ''Medication,'' looks mischievous and slightly exaggerated with wide eyes and a sly grin, as if plotting a joke. The mischievous character is saying the punchline: "You seem reasonable - time to increase my medication." Around them, include typical living room elements like a small table, a lamp, and a framed picture on the wall showing a whimsical or abstract pattern. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with friendly, rounded cartoon characters emphasizing expressions of calmness and playful scheming, avoiding anything edgy or offensive.'),
 (2410, 'Comic Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The years teach us much the days never knew.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson', 'A whimsical, lighthearted cartoon scene illustrating the concept of time teaching lessons. Depict a friendly, wise old calendar character with a kind face, glasses, and a graduation cap, holding a large open book titled ''Life Lessons.'' The calendar is pointing to the pages with a cane. In front of the calendar, show a group of small, eager-looking daily calendar pages or sticky notes with expressive eyes and curious faces, gathered around as if attending a class. In the background, a cheerful sun with a gentle smile shines down, symbolizing the passing of days. The setting is a cozy classroom with a chalkboard that reads ''Years vs. Days: What They Teach Us.'' Include humorous little details like a clock on the wall whose hands are spinning rapidly, and a stack of books labeled ''Patience,'' ''Experience,'' and ''Wisdom'' beside the teacher calendar. Use bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and warmth without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (3138, 'Comic Humor, Police Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'You have the right to remain silent, anything you say will be misquoted, then used against you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a police interrogation room. A nervous suspect sits at a metal table with their hands raised slightly, looking confused and worried. Across from them, a police officer leans forward with a sly grin, holding a giant exaggerated speech bubble that reads, "Anything you say will be misquoted!" The officer also holds a second, even bigger speech bubble that says, "Then used against you!" On the wall behind them is a typical ''Miranda Rights'' poster, but it comically lists ''Right to remain silent'' with a big red cross over it, implying it won''t be respected. The room includes standard interrogation elements: a single overhead light casting dramatic shadows, a metal chair, and a one-way mirror with faint silhouettes watching. The overall style is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright, simple colors to keep the tone playful and non-threatening.'),
 (2704, 'Comic Humor, Pun, Unknown, Workplace', 'Change is inevitable, except from a vending machine.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a vending machine in the center. The vending machine has a classic design with a glass front showing various snacks and drinks inside. It has a coin slot and a handle for dispensing change. To emphasize the joke, above the vending machine, draw a playful animated sign or thought bubble that says ''Change is inevitable... except from me!'' Nearby, show a confused and slightly frustrated person or character trying to get change from the machine, shaking their fist or looking bemused. The setting can be a simple indoor area like an office break room or hallway, with a water cooler or bulletin board in the background to add context but keep the focus on the vending machine and the character. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated facial expressions in a lighthearted cartoon style to enhance the humor and playfulness of the scene.'),
 (1907, 'Comic Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Social Humor', 'If you haven''t got anything nice to say about anybody, come sit next to me.', 'Alice Roosevelt Longworth (1884-1980)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people sitting on a bench or couch. One person looks friendly and inviting, gesturing with an open arm toward the empty seat next to them with a big mischievous grin. The second person, a bit hesitant but curious, is walking toward the seat, unsure but intrigued. Around them, small cartoon-style speech bubbles or thought bubbles show little jabs or sarcastic comments about funny or silly traits of imaginary third characters, illustrating the idea of sharing negative but lighthearted gossip. The setting is casual and friendly, maybe a park or a living room, with simple background elements like trees or a lamp to keep the focus on the two characters. The style is playful and exaggerated with bright colors, rounded shapes, and cartoonish expressions to emphasize the joke’s invitation to share unkind but humorous remarks without malice.'),
 (2216, 'Comic Humor, Quotes, Social Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Rare is the person who can weigh the faults of others without putting his thumb on the scales.', 'Byron J. Langenfield', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, old-fashioned balance scale standing on a simple wooden table. On one side of the scale, there are small paper labels with words like ''faults'' and ''mistakes'' written on them. A person (gender-neutral, casually dressed) is standing next to the scale with a sly smile, holding their oversized thumb pressing down heavily on that same side of the scale, visibly bending it down unfairly. The other hand holds a small magnifying glass, as if inspecting the scale seriously, but clearly cheating. The background is plain with soft colors to keep focus on the person and the scale. The style is bright, playful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the exaggerated size of the thumb and the crooked scale pointer to heighten the comedic effect. The person''s expression is both amused and slightly guilty, illustrating the internal contradiction behind the quote.'),
 (1475, 'Comic Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A verbal contract isn''t worth the paper it''s written on.', 'Samuel Goldwyn', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual office or meeting room setting. One character, looking confident and smug, is holding up a piece of paper labeled ''Verbal Contract'' with big, bold, and obvious quotation marks around the words. The other character looks confused or annoyed, with a puzzled expression and crossed arms. The paper is crumpled or clearly flimsy as if it''s fragile or pointless. On the table between them is an empty sheet of paper with the words ''Written Contract'' clearly typed on it, untouched and pristine. Include subtle visual cues like a clock on the wall and some office décor to set the professional tone. The style should be cartoonish and lighthearted, emphasizing the irony of a ''verbal contract'' literally being on paper but meaningless. Keep the colors bright and the characters exaggerated for a comedic effect, avoiding any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (398, 'Comic Humor, Word Play', 'THINK! or THWIM!', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a superhero standing in a heroic pose on a city rooftop. The superhero looks confused, wearing a classic comic-style costume with a cape fluttering in the wind. Above the hero''s head are two large comic-style speech bubbles: one says ''THINK!'' in bold letters, and the other says ''THWIM!'' in action sound effect style lettering, emphasizing the sound of a web-shooting or teleportation move. The background displays a simple city skyline with a few buildings and a bright blue sky with fluffy clouds. The style is colorful and exaggerated, with the superhero having a slightly puzzled or unsure expression, hinting at the humorous confusion between thinking seriously and making a comic book sound effect. Emphasize the contrast between the thoughtful word and the whimsical sound effect, creating a visual pun in a lighthearted cartoon format.'),
 (2881, 'Communication, Educational Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Generally speaking, you aren''t learning much when your lips are moving.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting at a classroom desk or office meeting table. One character, a teacher or a boss, is speaking enthusiastically with animated lips moving. The other character looks bored or sleepy, with their head resting on one hand and eyes half-closed, clearly not learning. Above the speaker''s head are whimsical, floating speech bubbles with lots of squiggly lines and words, showing excessive talking. Around the listener are small doodles like a tiny light bulb flickering off or a Zzz symbol to emphasize disinterest. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated to capture the humor of someone talking at length while the other person isn’t absorbing anything. The background should be simple, with a blackboard or whiteboard hinting at a learning environment. No aggressive or negative expressions—just mild frustration or boredom on the listener’s face.'),
 (1209, 'Communication, Everyday Life, Humor, Insults', 'You have the communication skills of an alarm clock.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing next to a large, anthropomorphic alarm clock with an annoyed expression. The alarm clock has big, cartoon eyes and a wide-open mouth, as if yelling loudly, with sound lines representing noise bursting out. The person looks frustrated, covering their ears or with a slightly annoyed face, maybe scratching their head to show confusion or irritation. The background is a simple bedroom or living room setting with a bedside table that the alarm clock is sitting on, adding context. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor. The overall tone should be lighthearted and fun, emphasizing the comparison between the person''s communication style and the loud, attention-grabbing alarm clock.'),
 (2162, 'Communication, Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes', 'Nothing lowers the level of conversation more the raising the voice.', 'Stanley Horowitz', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people having a conversation in a cozy living room. One person is speaking loudly, with exaggeratedly big, colorful sound waves coming out of their wide-open mouth, shaking nearby objects like a lamp and a picture frame on the wall. The other person looks unimpressed or annoyed, slouching on a couch with crossed arms and rolling eyes. Above them, a speech bubble from the quiet person says, ''Nothing lowers the level of conversation more than raising the voice.'' The setting includes a small coffee table with a conversation-starting book and a cup of tea, emphasizing a calm environment disrupted by loudness. Use bright, cheerful cartoon colors and simple, exaggerated facial expressions for humor, avoiding any aggressive or negative visuals.'),
 (1435, 'Communication, Everyday Life, Quotes, Wise Sayings', 'A little inaccuracy sometimes saves a ton of explanation.', 'H. H. Munro (Saki) (1870-1916)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person happily telling a story to a small, attentive group of listeners. The storyteller is using exaggerated hand gestures and has a speech bubble with a big, complex diagram full of tiny, confusing details and notes that look overwhelming. Next to this, another smaller speech bubble shows a simple, neat, and clearly labeled version of the story with a smiling face icon. Around them, the listeners look relieved and amused, clearly preferring the simpler version. The setting is casual, like a living room or a coffee shop, with cozy furniture. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between complexity and simplicity in storytelling with friendly characters and a warm atmosphere.'),
 (2537, 'Communication, Humor, Journalism, Quotes', 'What do you take me for, an idiot?  (Said when a journalist asked him if he was happy)', 'General Charles de Gaulle (1890-1970)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused journalist holding a microphone, looking puzzled. Opposite the journalist stands a man with an exaggeratedly stern and slightly annoyed expression, pointing a finger at the journalist as he says the punchline. The setting can be a simple outdoor or press conference background with a few microphones or a reporter''s notepad visible. The style should be lighthearted and humorous, with vivid facial expressions that emphasize misunderstanding and surprise. The man’s speech bubble reads, "What do you take me for, an idiot?" The journalist’s thought bubble shows a question mark and a tiny light bulb flickering off to signify confusion. Include a slight comedic exaggeration in body language—like the journalist leaning back a bit and the man standing confidently, adding to the humor in their exchange.'),
 (2347, 'Communication, Humor, Life, Quotes', 'The more you say, the less people remember. The fewer the words, the greater the profit.', 'Felelon', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or conference room where a speaker or teacher is holding a very long, winding scroll of paper with many words written on it. The speaker looks frustrated or tired as a few audience members in the room appear confused or overwhelmed, scratching their heads or dozing off. In contrast, at the side of the scene, there is a second person holding a very short, simple sign or a tiny piece of paper with just a few words, smiling confidently. Nearby, a cash register with money or coins overflowing represents the ''greater profit'' from fewer words. The style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the humor of talking too much vs. saying less and gaining more. The setting is clear enough to show it''s about communication and impact, without any dark or sensitive themes.'),
 (2025, 'Communication, Humor, Quotes, Wise Sayings', 'Know how to listen, and you will profit even from those who talk badly.', 'Plutarch', 'A cartoon scene showing a person sitting calmly with their eyes closed and a peaceful smile, wearing casual clothes. Around them are several other cartoon characters who are talking energetically, but with visible signs that their speech is somewhat unpleasant or silly—like squiggly speech bubbles with jumbled or silly words, or exaggerated facial expressions showing negativity (e.g., frowns, eye rolls). The listener is in the center, relaxed and taking notes on a notepad, showing they are learning or profiting from the chatter. The setting is a simple light-hearted office or park bench, with a few trees or desks in the background to keep it cheerful. The overall tone is humorous and gentle, using bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the contrast between the calm listener and the noisy talkers without any hostility.'),
 (2554, 'Communication, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Relationship Humor', 'When a woman says ''what?'', it''s not that she didn''t hear you. She''s giving you a chance to change what you said', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man and a woman having a conversation in a living room. The man looks a bit nervous and confused, with raised eyebrows and mouth slightly open as if caught off guard. The woman stands with one eyebrow raised and her hand on her hip, wearing a playful but slightly stern expression. Her mouth is open as she says ''What?'' in a speech bubble. Around the couple, small comic-style emphasis symbols like question marks and exclamation points float to show tension and humor. The setting shows a cozy couch, a coffee table with a magazine, and a small potted plant in the background. The style is colorful and exaggerated, with expressive faces to emphasize the miscommunication joke. No violence or offensive imagery, just friendly, relatable interaction between a couple in a lighthearted tone.'),
 (3152, 'Communication, Social Humor, Unknown, Wit', 'Your ignorance cramps my conversation.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting at a small café table outdoors. One character speaks animatedly, with a big smile and expressive hand gestures, clearly enjoying the conversation. The other character looks confused or clueless, scratching their head with a thought bubble showing a question mark. Between them on the table is a large speech bubble containing the phrase "Your ignorance cramps my conversation." The setting should be colorful and lighthearted, with a few other café tables and some greenery in the background. Emphasize the contrast between the lively speaker and the puzzled listener to visually represent the joke''s meaning without any harshness or hostility.'),
 (1795, 'Compliments, Family, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'I don''t care what you say, women make the best wives.', 'Dagwood Bumstead', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a smiling man and a smiling woman in a cozy living room setting. The man, looking cheerful and slightly proud, is sitting comfortably on a couch holding a cup of coffee or tea. The woman, happily doing a household task like folding laundry or cooking, stands nearby with a pleasant expression. The room is warm and inviting, with simple details like a framed picture of a happy couple on the wall, a potted plant, and a cozy rug. The overall mood is cheerful and affectionate, emphasizing harmony and partnership. The style should be colorful, simple, and caricature-like to highlight humor without exaggeration or stereotype, focusing on the positive theme of complimenting wives in a playful manner.'),
 (1343, 'Computer Humor, Education Humor, Programmers, Pun', 'To understand what recursion is, you must first understand recursion.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a teacher or professor standing in front of a classroom blackboard. On the blackboard, the word ''Recursion'' is written, followed by the phrase ''To understand recursion, you must first understand recursion.'' The teacher is scratching their head with a slightly puzzled but friendly expression, holding a pointer stick aimed at the text. The classroom has a few students sitting at desks, some looking confused, some with raised eyebrows or scratching their heads. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and simple, rounded character designs to emphasize the confusion and circular nature of the joke. Include a poster on the classroom wall that says ''Math Humor,'' and maybe a small stack of books labeled ''Computer Science'' and ''Mathematics'' on the teacher''s desk.'),
 (2907, 'Computer Humor, Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown', 'Hardware:  The parts of a computer system that can be kicked.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person standing next to a desktop computer on a desk. The person is mid-kick, with one foot raised, about to kick the computer’s CPU tower. The tower is designed with a few anthropomorphic features like surprised eyes on the monitor and a shocked expression on the CPU case. Around them, typical computer setup items like a keyboard, mouse, and a coffee mug sit on the desk. The background is a simple office or home office environment with a window and a plant. The cartoon style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the funny idea that computer hardware can be physically kicked out of frustration.'),
 (1547, 'Computer Humor, Exaggeration, Programming Humor, Quotes', 'Any given program will expand to fill available memory.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a computer desk with a very confused programmer sitting in front of a large, old-style desktop computer. The computer''s monitor displays a funny, exaggerated bar graph labeled ''Memory Usage'' that is completely filled with colorful blocks, stretching beyond the edges of the screen. Around the desk, various memory chips or RAM sticks are scattered, some overflowing like paper spilling off a desk. The programmer is scratching their head with one hand while holding a small, tiny computer chip in the other, looking bemused. In the background, a calendar or sticky note with the words ''Programmer''s Law: Programs fill all memory!'' adds to the joke. The style is bright, exaggerated, and cartoonish, with playful expressions and a cluttered, amusing workspace atmosphere to emphasize the ironic and inevitable growth of programs to use all available memory, creating a mental image of a memory-hungry program expanding endlessly on a computer screen.'),
 (2954, 'Computer Humor, Irony, Unknown, Workplace', 'I am a computer, dumber than any human and smarter than an administrator.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a large, classic desktop computer with anthropomorphic features—a simple digital face on the monitor looking slightly confused or dazed. The computer sits on a cluttered desk filled with sticky notes, tangled cables, a coffee mug labeled ''Admin Fuel,'' and an open manual titled ''User Guide for Dummies.'' Next to the computer, a frazzled administrator character, wearing glasses and a name badge reading ''Admin,'' scratches their head in exasperation while staring at the screen. Above them, a thought bubble shows a simple bar graph with the computer marked ''Dumber than any human'' but ''Smarter than an administrator.'' The background is a typical office environment with filing cabinets, a clock showing mid-morning, and a motivational poster about teamwork humorously crooked on the wall. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoony with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s play on intelligence hierarchy between computers, humans, and system administrators.'),
 (2701, 'Computer Humor, Obsolescence Humor, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'CD-ROM: Consumer Device, Rendered Obsolete in Months', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sad-looking CD-ROM drive sitting on a desk next to a brand-new USB flash drive. The CD-ROM drive has eyes and a mouth, looking tired and confused, with a small cobweb on it to show it''s old and unused. The USB flash drive stands upright with a confident smile and a shiny, modern look. Behind them, a computer tower is open with an empty CD drive slot and a happy USB port glowing. A calendar on the wall shows the passing of months quickly flipping by, emphasizing how quickly the CD drive became obsolete. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to evoke humor in a non-threatening way.'),
 (1352, 'Computer Humor, Programmers, Programming Humor, Word Play', 'Why doesn''t Objective C have a garbage collector? Because there would be nothing left!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a programmer''s office workspace. Depict a computer desk with a large desktop monitor displaying code snippets labeled ''Objective C'' in a friendly, exaggerated font on the screen. Next to the monitor is a traditional metal trash can labeled ''Garbage Collector,'' which is completely empty and sparkling, emphasizing ''nothing left.'' A confused or puzzled cartoon programmer (wearing glasses and a casual tech T-shirt) stands beside the desk scratching their head or looking bewildered. Above or near the trash can, cartoon dust particles or cobwebs emphasize how unused it is. The background includes typical office elements like sticky notes, a coffee mug with a smiley face, and a small stack of programming books or manuals titled ''Programming Languages.'' The overall style is light, colorful, and playful to convey the joke without complexity or negativity.'),
 (1346, 'Computer Humor, Programmers, Pun, Technology Humor', 'What are clouds made of? Mostly linux servers.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a fluffy white cloud floating in a bright blue sky. The cloud should be stylized with soft rounded edges, but instead of just being smooth, it should have visible cartoon-like computer server racks inside it, with blinking lights and cables peeking through the cloud fluff. Add a small cartoon laptop or computer icon on the cloud’s surface to emphasize the tech element. Below the cloud, draw a person looking up, scratching their head with a confused yet amused expression, holding a smartphone or tablet displaying a cloud computing symbol. The overall style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and simple, clean lines to highlight the joke about clouds being made of ''Linux servers'' rather than water vapor.'),
 (2972, 'Computer Humor, Programming Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I did it! I found the program''s last bug!   bug!  bug!  bug!  bug!  bug!  bug!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a cluttered programmer''s desk with a stressed-out programmer sitting in front of a computer. The monitor shows colorful lines of code with a red exclamation mark indicating an error. Around the desk and keyboard, dozens of tiny cartoon bugs—cute, small insects with big eyes and little antennae—are crawling and flying chaotically. The programmer looks both triumphant and overwhelmed, raising a fist in victory while bugs swarm everywhere. Speech bubble above the programmer says, ''I did it! I found the program''s last bug!'' with the word ''bug!'' repeated multiple times around them as if the bugs themselves are echoing the word humorously. The background shows a window with a barely visible clock to hint at time spent debugging. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the endless nuisance of debugging in programming, making it a fun and relatable scene for coders.'),
 (2474, 'Computer Humor, Programming Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'To iterate is human; to recurse, divine.', 'Robert Heller', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a casual human figure with a thoughtful expression holds a notebook labeled ''Iteration'' with a looped arrow diagram drawn inside. On the right, a whimsical, glowing, angelic or divine figure marked with a halo and wings smiles knowingly, holding a magical staff shaped like a spiral (representing recursion). Between them, a speech bubble floats containing the phrase: ''To iterate is human; to recurse, divine.'' The background is simple and tech-themed, with light circuit board patterns or binary code softly fading behind the characters. The style is playful, with exaggerated expressions and clean lines to emphasize the joke''s cleverness about programming concepts in a lighthearted way.'),
 (2851, 'Computer Humor, Programming Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'f u cn rd ths, u cn gt a gd jb n cmptr prgrmmng.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a computer screen with a message written in deliberately misspelled and abbreviated text: ''f u cn rd ths, u cn gt a gd jb n cmptr prgrmmng.'' The screen is surrounded by a frustrated-looking person wearing casual office clothes and glasses, scratching their head while trying to read the text. Around them are typical programming-related items like a coffee mug labeled ''Code Fuel,'' a keyboard with some keys labeled in funny ways, scattered sticky notes with cryptic code snippets, and a small digital clock displaying late hours to emphasize late-night coding. The overall style is playful and exaggerated to emphasize the challenge of reading this ''text-speak'' and the humor about computer programming jobs requiring this kind of deciphering skill. The background is a simple office or home workstation setting, with a comfy chair and a poster on the wall saying ''Keep Calm and Code On.'' The atmosphere should be light-hearted and funny, suitable for a cartoon humor style.'),
 (2692, 'Computer Humor, Programming Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'C program run.  C program crash.  C programmer quit.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated computer programmer sitting at a desk cluttered with coding books, coffee cups, and scattered papers. The programmer looks exasperated, holding their head in one hand while staring at a computer screen displaying a large red error message saying ''PROGRAM CRASHED!''. On the desk, a sticky note reads ''C Program Run''. Behind the programmer, a small whiteboard or poster shows a progress sequence: ''C program run → C program crash → C programmer quit'', with each phrase crossed out except for the last one. The programmer is dressed casually, with messy hair and glasses, emphasizing the stereotypical stressed coder vibe. Around the room, add typical programmer items like a small plant, a poster of a programming joke or meme on the wall, and a clock showing late hours to convey persistence and exhaustion. The style should be colorful, exaggerated with cartoonish expressions to highlight frustration and humor, but lighthearted and non-violent.'),
 (1731, 'Computer Humor, Puns, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'Grove giveth and Gates taketh away.  (Said about the trend of hardware speedups not being able to keep up with software demands)', 'Bob Metcalfe (inventor of Ethernet)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, ancient tree labeled ''Grove'' on the left, with hands made of branches gently handing over a shiny, fast computer chip or hardware component to a figure on the right. This figure is a stern, business-like man labeled ''Gates,'' dressed in a suit with a computer mouse in one hand, who is taking away a large, oversized software box or a bundle of code scrolls from a frustrated user standing in the middle. The user looks overwhelmed and confused, surrounded by tangled wires and stacks of software manuals. The background shows a speedometer labeled ''Hardware Speed'' trying hard to rise, but a giant wave called ''Software Demands'' is pushing it down. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and clear labels on all key elements to emphasize the pun and the theme of hardware vs. software performance struggle without any negative or aggressive imagery.'),
 (1396, 'Computer Humor, Puns, Quotes, Workplace', 'A feature is a bug with seniority.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon office scene focused on two characters. One is a frustrated software developer sitting at a cluttered desk with multiple computer monitors filled with code and error messages. Opposite them stands a confident middle-aged office manager wearing a suit and glasses, proudly pointing at a large poster on the wall titled ''Features,'' which humorously looks like a checklist but is full of obvious coding bugs labeled as features. In the background, include a whiteboard with scribbled notes and a sticky note that says ''Bug #101: Senior Feature.'' The developer looks exasperated while the manager smiles smugly, as if defending the bugs as valuable features due to their longevity. Keep the style light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between the frustrated coder and the proud manager celebrating bugs as senior features.'),
 (2503, 'Computers Humor, Humor, Programming Humor, Quotes', 'User interfaces can be hard to program because users can be so - original - at times. (Was that the word you were thinking of? Original?)', 'KBR', 'Illustrate a humorous cartoon office scene where a frustrated programmer sits at a cluttered desk with multiple computer monitors displaying chaotic and confusing user interface screens. The programmer has exaggerated tired eyes and holds their head with one hand while typing frantically with the other. Behind them, ghost-like thought bubbles show quirky, unexpected user actions—such as clicking random buttons, dragging icons into strange places, or wildly typing nonsensical input. Nearby, a small whiteboard lists ''User Interface Bugs'' with funny sketches of bugs wearing tiny user masks. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and caricatured facial expressions emphasizing the comic challenge of programming for unpredictable users. No text is required in the scene, but the mood should clearly convey the struggle and amusement of handling unique and unusual user behavior during software development.'),
 (2472, 'Computers Humor, Irony, Quotes, Workplace', 'To err is human -- and to blame it on a computer is even more so.', 'Orben''s Current Comedy', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an office environment. In the foreground, a human employee looks sheepish and nervous while sitting at a desk cluttered with papers and a computer. The computer screen displays a glaring error message or a large red ''ERROR'' alert. The employee is shrugging with a guilty smile, as if blaming the computer for the mistake. Behind the employee, a skeptical boss or coworker is looking over with crossed arms, clearly doubtful. The setting includes typical office items like a coffee mug, a desk lamp, and some sticky notes on the monitor. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the age-old excuse of blaming technology for human error. The style should be a colorful, cheerful cartoon with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor, avoiding any harsh or negative elements.'),
 (2717, 'Computers Humor, Irony, Unknown, Workplace', 'Computers are a more fun way to do the same work you''d have to do without them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated office worker sitting at a messy desk cluttered with papers, books, and a quill pen, looking tired and overwhelmed. Beside him, the same worker is happily using a computer on a tidy desk, smiling and sipping coffee as colorful icons and fun graphics float off the screen, suggesting entertainment. Both desks are side by side, highlighting the contrast. In the background, a clock shows the same time for both to emphasize that work takes just as long, but the computer user looks much more entertained and relaxed. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with the office worker’s expressions clearly showing the difference in mood between the two setups, capturing the ironic humor that computers don''t reduce work, they just make it more fun.'),
 (2794, 'Computers Humor, Office Humor, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'Don''t make the user provide information that the system already knows.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a futuristic or high-tech control room where a cheerful, slightly confused computer or AI assistant sits at a desk, surrounded by blinking screens and digital interfaces. The AI has a friendly face displayed on a monitor or as a robot with big eyes and a slightly raised eyebrow, looking directly at a user sitting opposite it. The user is holding a long list or form filled with questions, appearing frustrated or overwhelmed by the redundant requests. Around them, various icons symbolize stored data, like folders, files, or cloud symbols, indicating the system already knows the info. A speech bubble from the AI says, "Don''t make the user provide information that the system already knows," emphasizing the joke. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor and the absurdity of repeatedly asking for known information.'),
 (2718, 'Computers Humor, Pop Culture, Unknown', 'Computers have heroes too, you know. Let''s see, there''s HAL...', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a computer room filled with classic computers from different eras, each depicted with cute, anthropomorphized faces and small superhero capes or masks. In the center, a large, slightly menacing but cartoonish representation of HAL 9000 (a round red eye on a black computer screen) is wearing a tiny superhero cape, looking proud and heroic. Around HAL, other computers like an old desktop, a laptop, and a tablet also wear colorful superhero accessories, striking funny heroic poses. The background is a bright, cheerful tech lab with blinking lights, wires, and computer parts scattered around. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing that even computers can be heroes in their own quirky way.'),
 (3139, 'Computers Humor, Programming Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'You have to know when to code''em and know when to modem...', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful programmer sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer and a retro modem. The programmer is winking, gesturing with one hand as if giving advice. On the desk, there''s a keyboard, coffee mug, and some scattered code printouts. Behind him is a whiteboard with some simple code snippets and a drawing of a cow wearing glasses, referencing the pun on ''code''em'' (coding) and ''modem'' (mom). The atmosphere is light and playful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions and bright colors to emphasize the pun and tech humor. The setting should clearly suggest an office or home workspace with a computer-themed joke vibe, no violence or anything inappropriate.'),
 (2716, 'Computers Humor, Programming Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Computer programmers never die, they just get lost in the processing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly-looking computer programmer sitting at a cluttered desk filled with multiple monitors and keyboards. Around the programmer, swirling clouds resembling computer data or code fragments float in the air, representing ''processing.'' Instead of a ghost or typical depiction of death, the programmer''s body is partially transparent and fading into the digital clouds, as if getting lost inside the code. The programmer has a puzzled yet calm expression, wearing casual clothes with a coffee mug nearby labeled ''Code Fuel.'' The background shows a cozy office environment with a small plant, a poster of binary digits on the wall, and a clock showing late-night hours to emphasize the programming theme. The overall tone is light-hearted and fun, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon style emphasizing the abstract concept of being ''lost in processing'' rather than any morbid imagery.'),
 (2715, 'Computers Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Computer programmers do it byte by byte.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two friendly computer programmers sitting at desks facing each other. Each programmer is typing enthusiastically on their laptops. Between them floats a large smiling 8-bit pixelated heart symbol made up of colorful bright squares (bytes). Surrounding the characters are playful digital elements like floating binary code (1s and 0s) and small pixelated computer icons. The setting is a cozy office space with coffee mugs, some computer cables, blinking monitors, and a poster on the wall that reads “Code with Love.” The overall tone is lighthearted and fun, highlighting the wordplay on ''byte by byte'' in a cute, tech-themed romantic vibe without any inappropriate content.'),
 (1506, 'Computers Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'All computers run at the same speed...  with the power off.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene featuring a desktop computer and a laptop sitting side by side on a simple wooden desk. Both screens are completely black, showing they are off. The computer and laptop have anthropomorphic features: friendly eyes and smiling mouths, giving them a cute, humorous personality. Above them, a speech bubble from one device reads, ''All computers run at the same speed... with the power off.'' In the background, add a simple clock on the wall to subtly emphasize time passing, and a coffee mug next to the computer for a cozy office vibe. The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the joke through their identical ''off'' state and the playful expressions.'),
 (2383, 'Computers Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'The software is only human, you know!', 'Bob Green', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a personified computer sitting at a desk. The computer has a smiling human-like face on its monitor screen with eyes and a mouth, looking slightly tired or overwhelmed but trying to smile. Around the computer are scattered papers, coffee cups, and sticky notes showing typical software bugs or error messages like ''404 Error'' or ''Crash!''. The setting is a colorful office space, with a frustrated human coder standing nearby, shrugging apologetically with a speech bubble above saying, ''The software is only human, you know!'' The style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (3140, 'Computers Humor, Technology Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'You know computers are getting too sophisticated when a message comes up on the screen: ''Go home. I can finish this without you.''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a small modern office workspace. Show a visibly tired or frustrated person sitting at a desk with a desktop computer or laptop in front of them. The person''s facial expression should be a mix of surprise and amusement. On the computer screen, depict a large pop-up message box with the text: ''Go home. I can finish this without you.'' Include typical office elements such as a coffee mug, scattered papers, maybe a clock on the wall showing late hours, and a small plant. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated for comedic effect, with soft lines and bright colors. The overall mood conveys that the computer is humorously independent, almost like it''s bossing the user around, while the person reacts with disbelief.'),
 (3085, 'Computers Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'If it was easy, the hardware people would take care of it.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a tech repair shop labeled ''Hardware Repairs.'' Behind the counter stands a cheerful, slightly overwhelmed computer hardware technician wearing a work apron with small tools in the pockets (screwdriver, pliers). In front of the counter is a customer holding a broken computer part and looking confused or frustrated. Around the shop are various computer hardware pieces like motherboards, hard drives, and cables on shelves and workbenches. Include a small sign on the wall that reads ''If it was easy, the hardware people would take care of it.'' The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and the implied difficulty of hardware repair. Avoid any aggressive or negative body language; keep it friendly and comical.'),
 (399, 'Computers, Good Question!, Holiday Humor, Puns', 'Do you know why computer scientists confuse Christmas and Halloween? Because 31 OCT = 25 DEC.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a computer scientist sitting at a desk cluttered with tech gadgets and empty coffee cups. On one side of the desk, there is a small decorated Christmas tree with lights and ornaments. On the other side, there is a pumpkin carved with a silly face, glowing from inside. A computer monitor in front of the scientist displays the code snippet ''31 OCT = 25 DEC'' in large font. The scientist looks puzzled yet amused, scratching their head. The background includes typical office elements such as shelves with programming books, a calendar flipped to December, and a small stack of Halloween candy. The overall style is colorful and playful to convey the nerdy humor about number systems (octal and decimal) mixing holiday dates.'),
 (642, 'Computers, Good Question!, Pun, Workplace', 'Why do you continue to press Return; it does NOT make me work any faster.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy office. A computer monitor takes center stage, anthropomorphized with a friendly, slightly annoyed face displayed on the screen. The computer ''speaks'' a dialogue bubble with the text: ''Why do you continue to press Return; it does NOT make me work any faster.'' In front of the computer is a frustrated office worker sitting at a desk cluttered with papers, a coffee cup, and a keyboard. The worker is repeatedly pressing the Return key with an exaggerated, almost desperate expression. Around them, subtle motion lines convey the repetitive pressing. The background is a simple office setting with a plant and a clock on the wall showing time passing, emphasizing the slow progress. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor.'),
 (1160, 'Computers, Humor, Insults, Pun', 'Any nitwit can understand computers.  Many do.', 'Ted Nelson', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing next to a large, old-fashioned computer with blinking lights and buttons. One character looks confident, wearing glasses and a shirt with a ''computer expert'' vibe, proudly explaining the computer''s functions. The other character, a bit clueless and sheepish, is scratching their head with a bewildered expression, surrounded by floating question marks. To emphasize the joke, include several small cartoon ''nits''—tiny cartoon insects wearing glasses, each holding a miniature laptop or tablet, also with confused or silly expressions, interacting with the large computer. The background should be a simple tech office setting with a framed poster of a circuit board and a coffee mug labeled ''I Love Computers'' on a desk. Keep the style bright, cartoony, and lighthearted to highlight the playful insult in a fun way without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (400, 'Computers, Humor, Irony', 'The program is absolutely right; therefore, the computer must be wrong.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a desk in front of an old-fashioned desktop computer with a classic CRT monitor. The computer screen displays a message saying: ''The program is absolutely right.'' The person looks confused and is scratching their head while pointing a finger at the screen, as if arguing with the computer. Around the desk, scattered papers and a coffee mug add to the office environment. The room looks like a typical home office, with a small wall clock and a plant on the windowsill. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the irony and humor of the statement that the computer must be wrong even though the program is right. The background is simple to keep focus on the interaction between the person and the computer.'),
 (401, 'Computers, Humor, Nerd Humor', 'Some people really know how to have fun. But they''re probably not computer nerds.', NULL, 'A colorful, lighthearted cartoon scene showing two contrasting groups having fun. On the left, a small group of happy, lively people is outdoors playing frisbee, laughing, and enjoying bright sunshine. They wear casual, summer clothes and have wide smiles. On the right, a group of stereotypical ''computer nerds'' sits indoors in front of glowing computer screens filled with code and game graphics. They wear glasses, hoodies, and headphones, looking focused or excited but in a more subdued way. The background around them is a dimly lit room with tech gadgets and snacks scattered. The overall style is cheerful and exaggerated to emphasize the difference in energy levels and types of fun, without being mean-spirited. Include a humorous contrast in posture and expression between the two groups. The scene should look like a simple, friendly cartoon strip style, clear and visually playful.'),
 (402, 'Computers, Humor, Philosophy', 'Life after death? Is that like terminate and stay resident?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a computer-themed afterlife. The background resembles a whimsical, glowing circuit board with soft pastel colors. In the center, a friendly ghost with a slight pixelated or digital appearance floats, looking puzzled and scratching its chin. Next to the ghost, a classic old computer with a monitor displaying a message box that reads "Terminate and Stay Resident?" A thought bubble from the ghost shows the words "Life after death?" Above this setup, a playful sign reads "Afterlife Operating System." Scattered around are lighthearted computer elements like floppy disks, a mouse, and a keyboard, all with cute faces. The overall tone is cartoonish and fun, emphasizing the pun on computer terminology and the concept of life after death, without any scary or dark elements.'),
 (1345, 'Computers, Humor, Programmers, Word Play', 'Unix is user friendly. It''s just very particular about who its friends are.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a computer setup with a monitor, keyboard, and mouse on a desk. The computer screen displays a friendly smiling face labeled ''Unix'' wearing glasses, with an inviting wave, but standing behind a velvet rope or a velvet rope barrier like at an exclusive club entrance. Nearby, various stick-figure characters labeled ''Users'' wait in line, looking hopeful or confused, but only a few are shown with VIP badges or special ''Access Granted'' tags to indicate they are allowed past the rope. Others look puzzled or disappointed, unable to get in. The background includes a sign saying ''User Friendly Club - Members Only'' with a bouncer at the door holding a clipboard and checking badges. The overall vibe is light-hearted and funny, portraying Unix as a welcoming but selective friend. The art style should be colorful, simple, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect.'),
 (403, 'Computers, Humor, Programming', 'The computer is mightier than the pen, the sword, and usually, the programmer.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a quirky office or workspace. At the center is a large, classic desktop computer with an exaggeratedly big screen and keyboard, looking confident and almost regal. Next to it, a traditional pen with eyes and a smirk is standing upright on a desk, looking slightly annoyed or defeated. Nearby, a shiny sword with cartoonish eyes and a frown leans against the desk, looking irritated. In the foreground, a frustrated programmer slouches in a chair, rubbing their temples, wearing casual clothes and glasses, surrounded by scattered coffee cups and crumpled papers. The programmer looks tired and overwhelmed, while the computer appears to be smugly ''winning'' this silent battle. The background should be a simple office setting with humorous details like tech posters or scribbled notes. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s irony about computers being mightier than the pen, the sword, and the programmer themselves.'),
 (404, 'Computers, Humor, Puns', 'Simple Analogies Used to Explain Computer Concepts to Laypeople: Disc caching is like Gin Rummy: you keep what you think you might need, except you can pick up as many cards as can fit in your hand.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting at a small table playing Gin Rummy. One character is a friendly-looking computer with a smiling face on its monitor, holding a hand of playing cards. The other is a casual person looking slightly puzzled but intrigued. On the table, instead of normal cards, some cards are decorated with little icons representing files or digital documents. Above them is a speech bubble coming from the computer character that says: "Disc caching is like Gin Rummy—you keep what you think you might need, except you can pick up as many cards as can fit in your hand." The background is a cozy living room with a bookshelf containing a few computer textbooks and a small plant, emphasizing a lighthearted, educational vibe. The overall style should be bright, friendly, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor of the analogy.'),
 (405, 'Computers, Humor, Puns', 'Sometimes user keys can be shifty.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a computer keyboard with a few keys literally sliding or shifting out of place, like small people or objects moving on a conveyor belt. The keys have little animated eyes and arms, some looking mischievous or surprised. The keyboard is on a desk with a computer monitor visible in the background. A frustrated but amused user is sitting at the desk, scratching their head or raising an eyebrow, looking at the shifting keys. The scene should be light, playful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the pun on ''shifty'' keys by making the keys appear physically shifty or mobile.'),
 (2956, 'Computers, Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'I am the computer your mother warned you about.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sleek, modern computer with anthropomorphic features. The computer has a smug, mischievous smile on its monitor screen, with eyebrows raised as if it''s confidently making a cheeky statement. Around it, a few floating digital icons or emojis (like a heart, a thumbs-up, and a Wi-Fi symbol) emphasize its playful personality. The computer is sitting on a desk cluttered with typical items: a mouse, keyboard, a coffee mug, and maybe a small sticky note with ''Mom said no!'' written on it. In the background, a framed family photo shows a mother figure wagging her finger in a warning gesture toward the computer. The whole illustration is bright, colorful, and cartoonish to enhance the lighthearted, cheeky vibe of the joke, avoiding any harsh or negative expressions.'),
 (406, 'Computers, Humor, Science', 'The human mind ordinarily operates at only ten percent of its capacity - the rest is overhead for the operating system.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a human brain depicted as a large, complex computer control center inside a person''s head. The brain is illustrated like an old-fashioned computer room with colorful buttons, screens, and blinking lights. Half of the brain area is bustling with tiny cartoon figures (representing the ''mind'') working energetically, while the other half is filled with a maze of cables, wires, and a bulky, slightly outdated-looking ''operating system'' machine labeled as ''OS Overhead.'' The person appears puzzled, with their head slightly open like a computer tower, showing the inner workings. Above the scene, a light, playful caption reads, "Only 10% mind power, 90% OS overhead." The style is whimsical and exaggerated with bright colors and friendly, simple characters to enhance the joke’s playful tone.'),
 (407, 'Computers, Humor, Workplace', 'Never let a computer know you''re in a hurry.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a desk quickly trying to finish work on a slow, old-fashioned desktop computer. The computer screen displays a loading bar moving painfully slowly with a little snail icon next to it. The person''s face shows impatience and mild exasperation, tapping their fingers on the desk. Around the desk are scattered papers, a coffee cup, and a clock on the wall swirling around to emphasize the slow passage of time. The setting is a simple office or home workspace with a cheeky, lighthearted vibe emphasizing the irony of technology slowing down just when you''re in a hurry.'),
 (1362, 'Computers, Nostalgia, Quotes, Technology Humor', '640K ought to be enough for anybody.', 'Bill Gates In 1981', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a vintage 1980s-style computer room. In the center, a slightly confused but confident person dressed in retro attire is looking proudly at an old, bulky personal computer (like an IBM PC) with a tiny green-on-black screen showing a simple command prompt. Above the computer, a large, exaggerated speech bubble reads: ''640K ought to be enough for anybody.'' Around the person and computer, include old floppy disks, tangled cables, and a large dusty manual labeled ''Memory Management.'' The background features outdated tech posters and a calendar showing the year 1984. The overall mood is light and clean, with a bit of nostalgia and a playful exaggeration of how small 640K memory was. The style should be a colorful cartoon with friendly facial expressions and rounded, exaggerated features typical of vintage comic strips, emphasizing the joke about the early days of computer memory limitations without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (1336, 'Computers, Programmers, Pun, Technology Humor', 'I''ve got a great UDP joke but I''m afraid you wouldn''t get it', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a large, old-fashioned computer or server setup labeled ''UDP Joke Server.'' The person is smiling awkwardly while holding a speech bubble that says, ''I''ve got a great UDP joke, but I''m afraid you wouldn''t get it.'' Around them, several other cartoon characters look confused or have question marks over their heads, illustrating that the joke is not ''received.'' In the background, include a playful visual metaphor for lost or dropped messages, such as paper airplanes or envelopes floating away or missing their targets. The setting is a lighthearted tech office or geeky room, with computer monitors showing code snippets or network diagrams. The overall style should be colorful, clean, and exaggerated for maximum humor and clarity, emphasizing the joke''s play on the UDP (User Datagram Protocol) communication method that does not guarantee message delivery.'),
 (1334, 'Computers, Programmers, Pun, Workplace', 'How many programmers does it take to change a light bulb? A: none, that''s a hardware problem', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of programmers in a typical office setting filled with computers, keyboards, and monitors displaying lines of code. One programmer stands near a ceiling light fixture with a burnt-out light bulb, holding a screwdriver but looking confused or shrugging. Their colleagues sit at desks, typing away or looking at their screens, clearly uninterested in the light bulb issue. Above the group, a speech bubble contains the punchline, ''None, that''s a hardware problem.'' The office is decorated with typical geeky items like coffee mugs, code posters, and a whiteboard with software diagrams. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the division between software and hardware roles without any mean-spirited tone.'),
 (1553, 'Computers, Programming Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Any sufficiently advanced bug is indistinguishable from a feature.', 'Kulawiec', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a typical software developer at a cluttered desk in front of a computer screen. The screen displays a magnified cartoonish bug—like a cute, oversized insect with exaggerated features—crawling on top of a software interface window. The developer looks both confused and amused, scratching their head with a puzzled expression. Nearby, a whiteboard shows the phrase “Bug or Feature?” with arrows pointing both ways, emphasizing ambiguity. On the desk, scattered papers and coffee cups add to the chaotic developer atmosphere. The overall style is light-hearted and colorful, emphasizing the playful confusion between bugs and features in software development without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (2791, 'Computers, Programming Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Don''t debug standing up. It cuts your patience in half, and you need all you can get.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a frustrated software developer sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer screen filled with lines of buggy code and error messages. The developer has tired, squinty eyes and a mildly exasperated expression, holding a coffee cup labeled ''Patience.'' Next to the desk, a calendar or sticky note humorously says ''Debugging Day.'' There is a clock on the wall showing time passing slowly. In the background, a standing developer looks stressed and impatient, tapping fingers or pacing. The contrast between the sitting developer calmly debugging and the standing one impatiently suggests the joke’s punchline. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor, avoiding any violence or negativity.'),
 (2196, 'Computers, Pun, Quotes, Tech Humor', 'People who deal with bits should expect to get bitten.', 'Jon Bentley', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful computer technician or coder sitting at a desk cluttered with computer parts, cables, and a keyboard. The technician is pretending to get ''bitten'' by a tiny, cartoonish byte-shaped creature or a small, exaggerated ''bit'' with sharp but non-threatening teeth snapping playfully at the technician''s finger or hand. Include a computer screen showing binary code (ones and zeros) glowing in the background. The technician’s face shows a mock surprised or playful reaction, as if reacting to the cute nibble. The setting should look like a friendly tech workspace with posters or stickers referencing computers, coding, or technology to reinforce the pun. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, focusing on the pun between digital ''bits'' and being ''bitten'' by a playful creature representing data. The tone is fun and clever without any threat or harm implied.'),
 (1381, 'Computers, Pun, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'A computer program does what you tell it to do, not what you want it to do.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk in front of a computer. The person looks confused and frustrated, scratching their head or holding their chin thoughtfully. On the computer screen is an exaggeratedly literal cartoon robot or computer program character with a big smile, holding a checklist or manual that says ''Instructions''. The robot is following instructions very literally, showing a printed page with a silly, incorrect interpretation of a command (e.g., someone typed ''make me a sandwich,'' and the robot holds a literal drawing of a sandwich or a sandwich blueprint rather than preparing food). The background includes typical office or home office elements like a coffee mug, a plant, and a few scattered papers. The overall style is colorful, playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of misunderstandings between human intent and literal computer execution. The caption or speech bubble could say, ''I did exactly what you told me!,'' emphasizing the joke’s punchline about the difference between what is said and what is truly meant.'),
 (2900, 'Computers, Pun, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'Hackers have kernel knowledge.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a stereotypical hacker sitting in front of a computer. The hacker is wearing a hoodie and glasses, looking confident and mischievous. Around the computer screen, show a glowing kernel (a literal corn kernel) floating above the keyboard to represent ''kernel knowledge.'' The computer monitor can display lines of code or binary numbers. Add a small popcorn bowl on the desk to reinforce the kernel pun. The background should be a playful, slightly techy room with posters of computer icons or wires. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish to enhance the pun-based humor.'),
 (408, 'Computers, Puns, Technology Humor', 'This is your computer:  01001000 01000001 01010000 01010000 01011001 00100000.  This is your computer on drugs: 01001000 01003001 01010300 01333000 31011001 33333333', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two side-by-side computer monitors on desks. The left monitor displays a screen filled with neat and clear binary code (strings of 0s and 1s) perfectly aligned and orderly. Above it is a friendly cartoon computer with a happy face and a thumbs-up gesture, radiating a calm and productive vibe. On the right, a second computer looks dazed, with droopy eyes, a wobbly smile, and crossed wires sticking out. Its screen is full of garbled, mixed-up strings of numbers and symbols resembling random code mixed with some illegible characters, as if the computer is malfunctioning or ''on drugs.'' Around this computer are humorous motion lines or swirls to emphasize its confused state. The background is a simple office setting with desks, keyboards, and mouse devices visible, with bright, cheerful colors to keep the cartoon light and funny. The caption or speech bubble could say: "This is your computer" above the first, and "This is your computer on drugs" above the second, to reinforce the joke visually without words dominating the scene.'),
 (2260, 'Computers, Quotes, Tech Humor, Word Play', 'Supercomputer:  Turns CPU-bound problem into I/O-bound problem.', 'Ken Batcher', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a quirky, futuristic computer lab. In the center, there is a large supercomputer character with a friendly anthropomorphic face, sporting glasses and a confident smile. The supercomputer is juggling two oversized objects: one labeled ''CPU-bound problem'' represented by a heavy, tangled ball of wires and circuits, and the other labeled ''I/O-bound problem,'' depicted as a relaxed, floppy disk-shaped balloon floating gently. Around the supercomputer are smaller computers looking confused or surprised. The background has humorous technical posters like ''Keep Calm and Optimize'' and ''Speed Limits: 3.4 GHz.'' The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and playful details emphasizing the transformation of a tough problem (heavy and complex) into a more manageable, light one (balloon), conveying the joke about computing tasks. No violence or complex machinery is shown—just cartoon technology with a fun vibe.'),
 (2908, 'Computers, Relatable, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'hAS ANYONE SEEN MY cAPSLOCK KEY?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer keyboard in front of them. The keyboard is missing the Caps Lock key, leaving a blank empty space on the keyboard where it should be. The person is looking around wildly with exaggerated wide eyes, one hand raised to their head in confusion while the other hovers over the keyboard. Above their head is a thought bubble filled with jumbled uppercase and lowercase letters swirling around. The background is a simple office or home workspace setting with a coffee mug, a small plant, and scattered papers. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the frustration and confusion caused by the missing Caps Lock key, with bright colors and cartoonish expressions.'),
 (2814, 'Computers, Software Development, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'Each new user of a system uncovers a new class of bugs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of diverse computer users gathered around a large, old-fashioned computer or computer screen with visible bugs crawling on and around it. Each user has a puzzled or surprised expression, holding magnifying glasses or bug-catching nets. Some bugs resemble comical insects, wearing tiny glasses or hats, symbolizing different ''classes'' of bugs. The setting is a casual office or home workspace cluttered with coffee mugs, sticky notes with error messages, and a large banner overhead that reads ''Welcome New Users!''. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and cartoonish bug designs to emphasize the joke that each new user reveals a whole new type of software bug.'),
 (2808, 'Computers, Technology Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'DOS: Defunct Operating System', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a literal old computer labeled ''DOS'' looking ancient and worn out. The computer has anthropomorphic features: tired eyes with droopy eyelids on its monitor screen, a sagging keyboard as a mouth with a cracked space bar, and faded, rusty casing covered in cobwebs. Next to the computer, a dusty floppy disk with a tiny tombstone-shaped label that reads ''Defunct OS'' is planted in the ground, as if it were a grave. In the background, a modern sleek laptop or tablet looks on with a smug expression, showing a contrast between outdated and current technology. The setting is a cluttered, dusty office or basement filled with old tech paraphernalia like tangled cables, a CRT monitor, and stacks of floppy disks, all adding to the nostalgic, obsolete atmosphere. The overall vibe is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the joke that DOS is a defunct operating system by portraying it as an old, retired character in the tech world.'),
 (2801, 'Computers, Unknown, Word Play', 'Don''t sweat it, it''s only ones and zeroes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a relaxed character, maybe a smiling computer or robot, sitting comfortably in a lounge chair or hammock. The character should look calm and carefree, possibly with a tiny sweat drop that is fading or evaporating above its head. Surround the character with floating ones and zeroes (digits ''1'' and ''0'') drifting in the air like light bubbles or playful sprites. Include a simple digital or pixelated background to emphasize the computer/data theme. The overall tone is light-hearted and cheerful, with soft, rounded lines and bright colors to make the scene feel friendly and humorous rather than serious or intense.'),
 (409, 'Computers, Word Play', 'One picture is worth 128K words.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an old-fashioned computer monitor from the 1980s displaying a pixelated black-and-white photograph. Above the monitor, a speech bubble or a caption says: ''One picture is worth 128K words,'' playing on the phrase ''a picture is worth a thousand words'' but replacing it with computer memory units. The computer should have a bulky CPU tower next to it, with floppy disks stacked nearby. In the background, a confused character (cartoon person) wearing retro glasses scratches their head as they try to process the joke. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and simple, colorful lines to enhance the humor of mixing old tech with the classic phrase.'),
 (410, 'Conspiracy Humor, Humor, Word Play', 'Three conspiracy theorists walk into a bar. That can''t just be a coincidence.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a lively bar with colorful decorations and a few patrons in the background. In the foreground, three distinct characters labeled or visually styled as ''conspiracy theorists'' enter through the door together. Each has exaggerated, stereotypical features: one wearing tinfoil hat, another holding a magnifying glass or notebook filled with scribbles and charts, and the third looking suspicious, scanning the room cautiously. The bartender is behind the counter, looking quizzical and slightly amused. Above their heads, speech bubbles or a thought bubble shows the phrase, ''That can''t just be a coincidence.'' The overall tone is light and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (411, 'Construction Humor, Don''t Say It!, Word Play', 'I had a joke about construction, but I''m still working on it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly construction worker standing next to a half-built wooden sign that reads ''Joke Under Construction.'' The worker is wearing a yellow hard hat, a bright orange safety vest, and blue jeans. He has a cheerful smile and is holding a hammer in one hand and a blueprint rolled up in the other. The background features a simple construction site with orange cones, a small pile of bricks, a wooden sawhorse, and a partially built fence. Above the scene, a thought bubble shows a comedic unfinished joke being built with bricks and nails. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, emphasizing the idea that the joke is a work in progress without any pressure or stress.'),
 (1238, 'Construction Humor, Everyday Life, Jobs, Pun', 'Nobody could believe I worked on road construction, but when they came over to my house - all the signs were there.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the exterior of a house with multiple road signs posted all around the yard and on the house itself. The signs include common road signs like ''Stop,'' ''Yield,'' ''Detour,'' ''Road Work Ahead,'' and ''Caution,'' each clearly visible and colorful. The house looks cheerful and ordinary aside from the abundance of these official-looking signs stuck in the grass, hanging on the walls, and even leaning against the front porch railing. The homeowner, a smiling person wearing a bright orange safety vest and holding a traffic cone, stands proudly near the door, gesturing towards the signs as if to say, ''See? All the signs are here.'' Several neighbors or visitors stand confused or amused near the sidewalk, looking at the scene with raised eyebrows. The overall style is lighthearted, cartoonish with vibrant colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke about ''all the signs being there'' literally at the person''s home rather than just figuratively. No background distractions other than a simple suburban street and a clear sky, to keep focus on the house and signs.'),
 (1548, 'Consumer Humor, Everyday Life, Irony, Quotes', 'Any intelligent consumer knows what a warranty means. It means that whatever happens isn''t covered.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an appliance store. In the foreground, a frustrated customer stands holding a broken toaster with smoke curling up from it. The customer looks puzzled and slightly annoyed. Across from them, a cheerful, overly optimistic salesman stands behind a counter labeled '' WARRANTIES.'' The salesman is holding up a brightly colored brochure titled ''Warranty Details'' but the fine print is visible and comically says: ''Whatever happens is NOT covered.'' The background includes shelves stocked with various household appliances like blenders, microwaves, and coffee makers, some with little tags showing ''Warranty Included!'' There is a wall clock and store signage for an authentic feel. The style is light-hearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize irony and humor without any negativity or sarcasm that would feel harsh.'),
 (3037, 'Cooking Humor, Food Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'I started investing in stocks - chicken, beef, vegetable one day I hope to be a bouillonaire', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a kitchen resembling a stock market floor. The setting is a colorful kitchen with counters and a fridge. On the counters are market-style display boards like the ones in stock exchanges, but instead of companies, they show different food categories: "Chicken", "Beef", and "Vegetable", each with little price tags and arrows indicating rising or falling values. A cheerful character, maybe a person with a chef''s hat and business suit mix, is holding a clipboard and looking excited while pointing at the boards. In the foreground, there''s a large pot labeled "Bouillabaisse" simmering on the stove with little cartoon vegetables and meats happily inside, and a sign above it says "Next Big Investment." The overall scene combines stock trading with cooking ingredients humorously, emphasizing the pun "bouillonaire". Bright colors, smiling food items, and exaggerated expressions enhance the playful, lighthearted vibe of the cartoon.'),
 (3243, 'Cooking Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'Why didn''t the cook season the Thanksgiving turkey properly? There was no thyme!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy kitchen during Thanksgiving preparation. In the center, a plump, uncooked turkey sits on a baking tray inside an oven. Next to the tray, a frustrated cook wearing a chef''s hat and apron holds an empty spice shaker labeled ''Thyme''. Nearby on the counter is a small, sad-looking bunch of fresh thyme herb leaves drooping as if disappointed. The background shows typical kitchen elements like a stove, spice rack with missing thyme, a chopping board with a knife, and a calendar on the wall with ''Thanksgiving Day'' circled. The cook''s exaggerated facial expression reflects confusion or regret for not seasoning the turkey properly. The overall style is cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated features to evoke lightheartedness and amusement, emphasizing the pun on ''thyme'' and ''time''.'),
 (412, 'Corona, Health Humor, Humor, Word Play', 'You think Corona virus is bad? Peekaboo virus is even worse. You go straight to ICU.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a hospital ICU room with a surprised, wide-eyed patient lying in a bed. The patient is playfully covering their face with their hands like in a game of peekaboo, with a ghostly or mischievous virus character hovering nearby, playfully popping out from behind a curtain or medical equipment. The ICU setting should include typical hospital details such as a heart monitor, IV stand, and medical posters on the walls, adding to the humor by contrasting the serious setting with the silly peekaboo virus. The virus character should look silly and non-threatening, with a big smile and cartoonish eyes, emphasizing the joke''s playful nature rather than medical reality. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated expressions to keep the cartoon lighthearted and funny.'),
 (413, 'Corona, Humor', 'I tried to make a Corona Virus joke in April. Nobody laughed then, but eventually everyone got it.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene set in April with a nervous-looking person standing on a small stage labeled ''Comedy Open Mic April.'' The person holds a microphone and has a speech bubble that says, ''Why did the virus go on vacation? Because it wanted some social distancing!'' The audience is shown looking confused or not laughing. In the background, a calendar page clearly showing ''April'' is pinned on a wall. Next to this scene, a second panel shows the same person months later on the same stage, but now the audience is laughing heartily, holding masks and sanitizer. The caption above the two panels reads: ''Nobody laughed then... but eventually everyone got it.'' The style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the awkwardness and eventual humor. Avoid any depiction of illness symptoms, people looking sick, or anything scary.'),
 (414, 'Corona, Humor, Puns, Shopping Jokes', 'The LEGO store reopened after the lockdown, and folks were lined up for blocks.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene outside a LEGO store with a big LEGO logo above the entrance. The store has large glass windows showing shelves filled with LEGO sets inside. In front, a diverse line of happy, eager people extends outward, curving around the sidewalk. The line is cleverly made to look like it’s composed of LEGO blocks stacked one after another to represent ''lined up for blocks.'' Some people in line are holding LEGO bricks or small assembled LEGO figures, excited and chatting. The background shows a sunny day with a few fluffy clouds, and a small sign near the door reads ''Open after lockdown.'' The overall style is lighthearted, bright, and playful, emphasizing the pun with the visual of people forming a block-like queue.'),
 (2556, 'Corporate Humor, Economics Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'When better business decisions are made, economists won''t make them.', 'H. V. Prochnow', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office meeting room. In the foreground, a group of caricatured economists sit around a conference table, looking confused, worried, and a bit frustrated. Each economist is dressed in stereotypical business attire—suits, glasses, and holding charts or spreadsheets with downward-trending graphs. One economist is scratching his head, another has a big question mark over his head, and one peeks nervously at a big business decision announcement on a whiteboard that reads, “Better Business Decisions.” In the background, a large thought bubble from outside the room depicts a glowing light bulb over a person’s head confidently making a smart decision, contrasting the economists inside. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the irony that smart business decisions mean economists are out of work. No aggressive or negative imagery is included.'),
 (2879, 'Corporate Humor, Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Fuzzy objectives yield fuzzy results.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a business meeting room with a whiteboard at the front. The whiteboard has a vague and messy diagram labeled ''Objectives'' with fuzzy, blurred lines and unclear text. In front of the whiteboard, a confused presenter wearing glasses stands scratching their head, holding a pointer that is also fuzzy or wiggly. Around a table sit several employees with puzzled expressions, some shrugging and others with question marks above their heads. On the table are coffee cups and scattered papers with vaguely written notes. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the confusion caused by unclear goals, capturing the phrase ''Fuzzy objectives yield fuzzy results'' visually. The art style is cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humorous misunderstanding.'),
 (2494, 'Corporate Humor, Irony, Quotes, Workplace', 'Turnover is good for the company, as it proves that we are doing a good job in training people.', '(Actual Dilbert Manager Quotes)', 'A humorous cartoon office scene showing a cheerful manager standing confidently in front of a group of employees. The manager is pointing to a large flipchart or whiteboard that reads: ''Turnover = We''re great trainers!'' The employees look mixed: some happy and others packing their boxes filled with personal items, looking slightly confused or resigned. In the background, a couple of employees are walking out the office door carrying their boxes, waving goodbye. The office setting includes desks, computers, and motivational posters about teamwork and growth, with a lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated cartoon style emphasizing the irony of the ''positive'' turnover message.'),
 (3155, 'Corporate Humor, Irony, Unknown, Workplace', 'Zero Defects: the result of shutting down a production line.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a factory production line. The factory floor shows a long assembly line with various machines and conveyor belts, but everything is at a complete standstill — no workers in sight, no products moving. In the foreground, a factory manager wearing a suit and holding a clipboard is looking confused and scratching his head. Above the conveyor belt, a big sign reads ''Zero Defects.'' Nearby, a digital counter or scoreboard usually showing a number of defects prominently displays ''0'' in bright green. The entire factory looks clean and quiet, with tools hanging still on walls and no visible noise or action. The style is colorful and exaggerated to emphasize the irony—the ‘Zero Defects’ achieved because the entire production line is simply shut down. The tone is light and playful without any negativity.'),
 (2731, 'Country Humor, Humor, Music Humor, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: I''m the Only Hell Mama Ever Raised', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a vintage country and western album cover. At the center, show a proud, tough-looking Mama figure—an older woman wearing a cowboy hat, boots, and a denim jacket with a big smile and arms crossed. Surround her is a rustic farm background with a wooden fence, a windmill, and a few farm animals like cows and chickens looking on in amusement. The album title, styled in bold and western-style font, reads ''I''m the Only Hell Mama Ever Raised'' prominently across the top or bottom. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and a sunny countryside setting that conveys humor without any negativity.'),
 (2740, 'Country Humor, Humor, Music Humor, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: You''re the Reason Our Kids are So Ugly', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a rustic, cozy living room with country and western decor—like a wooden rocking chair, cowboy hat hanging on the wall, a guitar leaning near a fireplace, and plaid curtains. In the center, a cheerful couple dressed in stereotypical country attire (cowboy boots, hats, denim) is sitting on a couch, smiling awkwardly and holding their two kids. The kids look adorably quirky and a little funny-looking, maybe one has big buck teeth and the other has a wild hairstyle. Above them, a framed sign hangs on the wall reading: "Country and Western Song Titles:" and underneath it, in bold letters, "You''re the Reason Our Kids are So Ugly." The overall tone is light and playful, with exaggerated friendly expressions to reinforce the joke''s self-deprecating humor. Friendly pets like a dog with floppy ears lounging nearby can add warmth. The style should be colorful, exaggerated cartoon with soft lines and humorous expressions to enhance the comedic effect without being mean-spirited.'),
 (2728, 'Country Humor, Music Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: If the Phone Doesn''t Ring it''s Me', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a rustic, cozy country living room with wooden walls and a few country-themed decorations like a cowboy hat on a hook and a guitar leaning against a chair. In the center, a country singer with a big mustache and cowboy boots stands holding a microphone and a guitar. The singer has a confident, amused expression. Nearby, an old-fashioned rotary phone sits on a small wooden table, quietly silent. Above the scene, a large speech bubble shows the words: ''If the Phone Doesn''t Ring, It''s Me.'' The scene should have a warm, slightly exaggerated cartoon style with bold outlines and cheerful colors to evoke a lighthearted country music vibe. Maybe add a jukebox in the corner and a poster of a cowgirl to emphasize the country theme.'),
 (2733, 'Country Humor, Music Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: She''s Acting Single (I''m Drinkin'' Doubles)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a rustic country bar with wooden walls and a few stools. In the foreground, a man with a cowboy hat and a forlorn expression holds a large glass with two shots of whiskey (or some brown drink) in it, clearly labeled ''Doubles.'' Nearby, a woman dressed in country attire (boots, denim skirt, and a plaid shirt) confidently dances alone, looking carefree and smiling, indicating she''s ''acting single.'' Above the scene, a playful sign or banner reads the song title: "She''s Acting Single (I''m Drinkin'' Doubles)." Include some cowboy boots and a jukebox in the background to emphasize the country-western vibe. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of the situation without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2734, 'Country Humor, Music Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: Sorrow on the Rocks', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a rustic, country-style bar with a wooden counter and stools. Behind the bar is a sad-looking cowboy wearing a large cowboy hat, plaid shirt, and boots. He holds a glass with ice cubes and a splash of whiskey, staring forlornly at it. On the wall behind him hangs a framed poster titled ''Country and Western Song Titles.'' One of the highlighted song titles, written in exaggerated, playful lettering, says ''Sorrow on the Rocks.'' The bar has typical country decor like a horseshoe on the wall, a guitar leaning in the corner, and a neon sign shaped like a boot. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun where ''on the rocks'' normally refers to a drink but humorously doubles as an emotional state in a country song title.'),
 (2735, 'Country Humor, Music Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: The Beer That Made Milwaukee Famous (Made a Loser Out of Me)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a country and western singer on stage at a small rustic bar labeled ''Milwaukee Tavern.'' The singer is a cowboy wearing a hat, boots, and a plaid shirt, holding a guitar and looking downgraded and miserable. The background shows a beer mug with frothy beer spilling over with a big exaggerated label reading ''The Beer That Made Milwaukee Famous.'' Nearby, a neon sign flickers with the words ''Made a Loser Out of Me.'' The audience consists of cheerful, slightly exaggerated country-style characters laughing and clapping. The atmosphere is lighthearted and comical, with a vintage wooden bar counter and empty beer bottles scattered around. Include musical notes floating around the singer to indicate he is mid-performance. The style should be colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the humor and irony of the song title.'),
 (2736, 'Country Humor, Music Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: The Last Word in Lonesome is Me', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic country and western singer standing on a small stage with a microphone. Behind the singer, a large vintage-style sign reads: ''The Last Word in Lonesome is Me.'' The singer looks dramatically sad, wearing typical country attire like a cowboy hat, boots, and a fringed jacket. Around the stage, add small humorous details such as a broken heart-shaped guitar amplifier, a single wilting flower in a vase, and a small audience of animals like a crying dog and a sad-looking banjo-playing raccoon. The overall mood is exaggeratedly gloomy but funny to emphasize the pun on ''lonesome'' and ''the last word.'' Make the style colorful and cartoonish with expressive faces and slightly exaggerated proportions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (2739, 'Country Humor, Music Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Country and Western Song Titles: You''re Goin'' to Ruin My Bad Reputation', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a classic country music stage with a cowboy singer holding a guitar and singing into a microphone. The singer is drawn with exaggerated country attire: a cowboy hat, boots, and a fringed jacket. Behind him is a large wooden signboard displaying the exaggerated, silly song title "You''re Goin'' to Ruin My Bad Reputation" in bold, playful letters. The background includes a simple barn setting with hay bales and a few small animals like a curious cow or chicken peeking around, adding to the country feel. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and smiling characters, capturing the cheeky irony of the song title as a joke on reputation and country music stereotypes. No people look upset; it’s all in good fun.'),
 (2732, 'Country Humor, Music Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Country and Western Song Titles: Loving Here, Living There, and Lying in Between', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a vintage-style country music poster or album cover displayed on a rustic wooden wall. The poster prominently shows three exaggeratedly dramatic country and western song titles in bold, playful fonts: ''Loving Here,'' ''Living There,'' and ''Lying in Between.'' Illustrate a cartoon cowboy sitting on a wooden fence nearby, looking contemplative and a bit confused, with a guitar slung over his back. Surround the scene with classic country elements like a dusty dirt road, a lonely cactus, a setting sun, and maybe a small barn in the background. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the humor of the wordplay in the song titles, capturing the typical emotional storytelling vibe of country music but with a lighthearted twist.'),
 (1423, 'Courtroom Humor, Irony, Lawyer Humor, Quotes', 'A jury consists of twelve persons chosen to decide who has the better lawyer.', 'Robert Frost', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a courtroom. There is a judge sitting at the bench looking amused or slightly confused. In the jury box, twelve diverse jurors are depicted with exaggerated thoughtful or puzzled expressions, whispering among themselves. In front of them, two lawyers stand confidently on opposite sides, each with oversized briefcases overflowing with paperwork and legal books. One lawyer might be shown handing the jury a flashy, colorful brochure titled ''Who’s the Better Lawyer?'' Nearby, a scale of justice is tilted, emphasizing the joke. The courtroom backdrop includes typical elements: American flag, judge’s gavel, and a witness stand empty but with a microphone. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the irony that the jury’s real job is shown as choosing the better lawyer, not deciding the case facts.'),
 (3062, 'Courtroom Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'If a deaf person has to go to court, is it still called a hearing?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a courtroom. There is a judge sitting behind the bench wearing traditional robes and a wig, looking slightly puzzled. In front of the bench stands a person with a hearing aid and exaggeratedly large, visible cochlear implants or sign language hand gestures, clearly indicating that they are deaf. Around the courtroom, include typical elements like courtroom chairs, a witness stand, and a gavel resting on the judge''s bench. The deaf person looks confident and calm. The judge appears to be pondering the irony of the word ''hearing'' in this context. The style should be colorful, light-hearted, and exaggerated with friendly characters to emphasize the pun without any harshness or negativity. The setting should clearly communicate a courtroom vibe without any intimidating or aggressive visuals, focusing on the wordplay about ''hearing'' in court for a deaf person.'),
 (2406, 'Creative Humor, Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The whole art of teaching is only the art of awakening the natural curiosity of young minds for the purpose of satisfying it afterwards.', 'Anatole France', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a colorful classroom with a friendly teacher standing at the front near a blackboard. The blackboard features the phrase “Awaken Curiosity!” in playful letters. The teacher is wide-eyed and animated, holding a large magnifying glass up to a young student''s face, symbolizing curiosity being ''awakened.'' Several children sit at desks with exaggerated expressions of shock turning into curiosity, their eyes sparkling and hands raised eagerly. Scattered around the room are objects that highlight learning and exploration: an open book with question marks floating above it, an owl wearing glasses perched on a bookshelf, a globe spinning, and a treasure chest labeled “Knowledge.” In the background, a clock shows time passing quickly to hint at the challenge of later satisfying curiosity. The overall style is bright, cheerful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the playful relationship between awakening curiosity and the eventual need to satisfy it through teaching.'),
 (1862, 'Creative Humor, Everyday Life, Motivational, Quotes', 'Ideas won''t keep; something must be done about them.', 'Alfred North Whitehead', 'A cartoon scene depicting a person sitting at a cluttered wooden desk filled with scattered crumpled papers, sticky notes, and a glowing light bulb above their head symbolizing an idea. The person looks determined, mid-action, reaching out to catch or trap a small collection of literal ideas depicted as whimsical, colorful cartoon thought bubbles or tiny creatures fluttering around. The background is a simple, bright office or study space with a window letting in daylight and a motivational poster on the wall saying, ''Catch your ideas!''. The style is cheerful and exaggerated, emphasizing the struggle to hold on to creative thoughts in a funny, lighthearted way.'),
 (1767, 'Creative Humor, History Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Humanity has advanced, when it has advanced, not because it has been sober, responsible, and cautious, but because it has been playful, rebellious, and immature.', 'Tom Robbins', 'A humorous cartoon scene illustrating a timeline of human progress. On the left, a stern and serious-looking caveman wearing glasses and studying a book labeled ''Rules'' looks bored and restrained. On the right, a lively, playful caveman with a mischievous grin is tossing a stone playfully and wearing a party hat or something silly. Between them, a progression of cartoon humans shows silly, fun, and imaginative behavior leading to inventions like fire, wheel, and even a rocket in early crude forms, all with a playful twist (e.g., a stone wheel with smiley faces). Background includes scattered symbols of rebellion and creativity like graffiti, a slingshot tucked in a pocket, and colorful balloons floating. The overall style is light-hearted, cartoonish, and vibrant, emphasizing the joy and chaos of human innovation rather than seriousness or caution.'),
 (2246, 'Creative Humor, Inspiration Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Some people see things as they are and say why? I dream things that never were and say why not?', 'Robert Kennedy', 'Draw a humorous cartoon depicting two characters side by side with contrasting expressions and settings. On the left, a skeptical person with crossed arms, wearing regular clothes, looks at a simple, realistic object like a plain rock or a tree and says, ''Why?'' Their surroundings should be straightforward and dull, featuring muted colors and a plain background. On the right, a dreamer character with wide eyes and a big smile, wearing imaginative or whimsical clothing (like a star-patterned robe or a thinking cap), gazes at the same object but transformed fantastically—perhaps the rock is a glowing crystal or the tree is shaped like a castle. This side has vibrant colors, stars, and floating question marks turning into exclamation points, representing creativity and possibility. Between them, include a speech bubble containing the phrase: "Some people see things as they are and say why? I dream things that never were and say why not?" The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the contrast between practicality and imagination.'),
 (2186, 'Creative Humor, Language, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Originality is the fine art of remembering what you hear but forgetting where you heard it.', 'Laurence J. Peter', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk cluttered with papers, books, and a cup of coffee, looking both puzzled and thoughtful. Around the character''s head, illustrate floating speech bubbles or thought clouds containing jumbled fragments of phrases or ideas, with question marks and exclamation points to show confusion. Behind them, on a wall or bulletin board, include pinned notes or scraps of paper with half-visible quotes and question marks next to them. The person''s facial expression should be lighthearted and comical, showing they''re struggling to recall both the idea and its source. Use bright colors and exaggerated cartoonish features to emphasize humor and a sense of mental mix-up without any stressful or negative tone. The overall vibe is playful and a little ironic, highlighting the challenge of creative originality as a funny mental juggling act.'),
 (1766, 'Creative Humor, Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Human salvation lies in the hands of the creatively maladjusted.', 'Martin Luther, Jr. King', 'Create a humorous cartoon scene set in a quirky, colorful workshop filled with odd inventions and chaotic creativity. In the center, a cheerful, eccentric inventor wearing oversized glasses and a lab coat with patchwork, holding a bright glowing light bulb in one hand and a tangled mess of wires in the other. Around this character, various whimsical gadgets and doodads—like a clock with legs, a toaster shooting out wings, a robot assembling a sculpture made of odd objects, and scattered art supplies. In the background, a large banner reads ''Salvation Through Creative Chaos'' with playful lettering. The scene should feel lively, imaginative, and slightly messy but ultimately hopeful and inspiring, capturing the idea that unconventional creativity is key to future success. The style is a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon with bright colors and expressive faces—no violence or negativity.'),
 (2324, 'Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'The important thing in science is not so much to obtain new facts as to discover new ways of thinking about them.', 'Sir William Bragg', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a whimsical science lab. In the center, a quirky scientist with wild, frizzy hair and thick round glasses is standing proudly next to a large chalkboard filled with complex equations and diagrams. Instead of looking stressed or serious, the scientist has a thoughtful, amused expression, tapping their chin with a finger. Around them, common science equipment is scattered: a microscope, test tubes bubbling with colorful liquids, books titled ''Science Facts'', and a globe. Floating above the scientist’s head are several cartoon-style thought bubbles, one containing a lightbulb (symbolizing new ideas) and others showing amusing, unconventional ways to interpret data (like a smiley face made of atoms or a rocket-shaped graph). The background should be cheerful and bright with exaggerated, playful elements (like oversized tools and whimsical machinery) to emphasize creativity and fresh thinking in science. The overall style is light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish, capturing the idea that the key in science is imaginative thinking rather than just facts.'),
 (2543, 'Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'What is now proved was once only imagined.', 'William Blake', 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a quirky inventor or scientist in a cluttered workshop filled with imaginative gadgets and doodles pinned on the walls. The inventor is holding up a glowing light bulb or a prototype device with a proud, surprised expression. Floating above their head is a dream-like thought bubble filled with fantastical sketches and ideas, illustrating things being imagined. Nearby, a bookshelf or blackboard displays a scientific equation or diagram labeled ''Proved'' with a checkmark. The setting should be colorful and playful, emphasizing creativity and discovery rather than seriousness. Include details like scattered papers, tools, and imaginative inventions half-built, to capture the transition from imagination to proven fact in a humorous, optimistic way.'),
 (2565, 'Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'When I''m working on a problem, I never think about beauty. I think only how to solve the problem. But when I have finished, if the solution is not beautiful, I know it is wrong.', 'Richard Buckminster Fuller', 'A humorous cartoon scene in a neat, bright office or study room. At the center, a person (gender neutral, wearing casual smart clothes) is sitting at a desk cluttered with papers, math equations, sketches, and technical drawings. The person looks deeply focused, with furrowed brows and a pencil in hand, busy solving a complex problem on a large sheet. Behind them, a thought bubble shows a chaotic jumble labeled ''problem'', while another thought bubble emerging after finishing shows a perfectly shaped geometric design with sparkling stars around it, clearly labeled ''beautiful solution''. On the desk are scattered rulers, a calculator, and a coffee mug. The background includes a window letting in daylight and a small plant, keeping the mood light and friendly. The overall style is simple, bright, and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between serious concentration during work and joyful satisfaction at a neat, elegant final result.'),
 (1934, 'Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Imagination is more important than knowledge.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a person sitting cross-legged on the ground with their eyes closed and a big dreamy smile. Around their head are colorful thought bubbles filled with imaginative and magical ideas: flying elephants, dancing books, stars, and swirling galaxies. Behind the person, there is an open book with plain text and numbers spilling out but looking dull and gray. The background is bright and colorful with sparkles and swirls emphasizing creativity and imagination. The overall style is cheerful and light-hearted, using exaggerated expressions and playful details to highlight the contrast between imagination and plain knowledge.'),
 (2441, 'Creative Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'There was never a genius without a tincture of madness.', 'Aristotle', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, eccentric-looking scientist or inventor in a cluttered attic or laboratory. The character has wild, messy hair and a mischievous grin, wearing oversized round glasses and a white lab coat with colorful stains. Surrounding them are whimsical inventions and odd tools—test tubes bubbling with strange colors, a brain-shaped clock, a stack of books titled ''Madness and Genius,'' and a quirky painting on the wall showing a half-mad, half-genius split face. A small pet, like a curious cat or owl, looks up at the character with wide eyes. The overall vibe is playful and clever, capturing the balance between brilliance and madness in a lighthearted and imaginative way. The background should be bright and colorful to emphasize creativity and eccentricity, drawn in a light cartoon style with exaggerated features to enhance humor and charm.'),
 (2083, 'Creative Humor, Quotes, Writing Humor', 'Manuscript: something submitted in haste and returned at leisure.', 'Oliver Herford (1863-1935)', 'A humorous cartoon showing two characters in an office setting: one is an author who looks rushed and frazzled, holding a disorganized manuscript with pages flying out. The other is a calm and leisurely editor sitting at a desk, leisurely sipping coffee, with a large stack of returned manuscripts next to them. The editor has a smug smile and a relaxed posture, while the author looks anxious and impatient. The background includes a clock showing time passing slowly on the editor''s side and a calendar on the author''s side with crossed-out days, emphasizing delay. The manuscript pages have scribbles and handwritten notes. The overall tone is light-hearted and comical, using exaggerated expressions to highlight the contrast between the author''s haste and the editor''s leisurely pace.'),
 (2989, 'Creativity Humor, Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'I get my best ideas from other people.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk with a thoughtful expression, holding a pencil poised over a blank notebook. Behind them, a ghostly or transparent figure of another person floats, pointing at the notebook as if sharing an idea. The person at the desk looks surprised and inspired. Around them are lightbulbs and question marks to indicate thinking and brainstorming. The background is simple, maybe an office or home workspace with a lamp, a cup of coffee, and some scattered papers. The style is colorful and exaggeratedly cartoonish, emphasizing the comic idea that the person’s best ideas literally come from someone else''s presence nearby.'),
 (2564, 'Creativity Humor, Language, Quotes, Words Humor', 'When ideas fail, words come in very handy.', 'Goethe (1749-1832)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk cluttered with crumpled papers labeled ''Ideas,'' looking frustrated and scratching their head. Above their head are empty thought bubbles with question marks. Next to the desk is a large, friendly-looking speech bubble character holding a pen like a sword, ready to help. The speech bubble character is smiling confidently, symbolizing ''words'' coming to the rescue. The background is simple, with a light bulb above the person’s head that is dim or flickering, representing failed ideas. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the frustration of failed ideas and the helpfulness of words as a backup plan.'),
 (2498, 'Creativity Humor, Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Uncertainty and mystery are energies of life. don''t let them scare you unduly, for they keep boredom at bay and spark creativity.', 'R.I. Fitzhenry', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, colorful room with an artist''s easel, a light bulb above their head, and various creative supplies scattered around like paintbrushes, sketchpads, and colorful pencils. In the center, a cheerful character stands confidently holding a glowing spark or energetic swirl labeled ''Uncertainty & Mystery.'' Around them, playful symbols of boredom (like a yawn emoji or a slumped, sleepy figure) sit on one side looking dull, while vibrant, imaginative sketches, musical notes, and whimsical ideas float around the character on the other side, illustrating creativity being sparked. The character’s expression is fearless and excited, showing they embrace the unknown rather than fear it. The overall vibe is lighthearted and inspiring, emphasizing energy, mystery, and creativity in a fun, cartoon style with soft outlines and bright, inviting colors.'),
 (2558, 'Creativity Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'When I am working on a problem I never think about beauty. I only think about how to solve the problem. But when I have finished, if the solution is not beautiful, I know it is wrong.', 'Buckminster Fuller (1895-1983)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky inventor or scientist in a cluttered workshop with various tools and gadgets scattered around. The person is thoughtfully working on a complex mechanical device with gears, wires, and bulbs. Their face shows deep concentration, maybe furrowing their brow, as they tinker with the problem. Nearby, there is a large chalkboard or whiteboard filled with diagrams and equations. In the foreground or side, there is a small beautifully crafted glowing object—like an elegant machine or piece of artwork—that symbolizes the finished solution. The inventor looks proudly at this object, with a light bulb overhead to emphasize the moment of realization. The scene is bright and colorful in a playful, cartoon style, with exaggerated expressions and details to emphasize the focus on problem-solving coupled with the appreciation of beauty in solutions. The setting should feel inventive and inspiring, yet light-hearted and funny, avoiding any violence or negativity.'),
 (415, 'Crime Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'Two men broke into a drugstore and stole all the Viagra. The police are on the lookout for two hardened criminals.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set outside a small, colorful drugstore at night. Two cartoon men, looking sneaky but goofy rather than scary, are running away from the store carrying bags labeled ''Viagra'' in bold letters. One man should be taller and thinner, the other shorter and stockier, both with exaggerated expressions of mischief and excitement. Nearby, a police car with flashing lights is parked, and a couple of officers are looking around alertly, searching for the ''criminals.'' To add humor, show a wanted poster on a light pole featuring two muscular, tough-looking cartoon pills with stern faces, labeled ''Hardened Criminals.'' Make the style bright and playful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun and the joke''s wordplay. Avoid dark or threatening tones; keep it lighthearted and funny.'),
 (1583, 'Crime Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Behind every great fortune there is a crime.', 'Honore de Balzac (1799-1850)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, flashy mansion labeled ''Great Fortune'' with glittering gold coins and cash overflowing around it. In front of the mansion stands a sneaky-looking, stereotypical criminal cartoon character—wearing a striped shirt, a black eye mask, and holding a sack of money with a dollar sign on it—looking guilty but proud. Behind him, half-hidden, is a simple, unassuming detective or police officer making a sly smile or raising an eyebrow, hinting at the crime behind the fortune. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing humor over threat, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to keep it playful and fun. Include small visual clues like a ''Wanted'' poster or footprints to reinforce the crime theme in a comedic way, but avoid any violence or negativity.'),
 (416, 'Cultural Humor, Efficiency Humor, Good Question!', 'How many Germans does it take to screw in a light bulb? Just one. They are very efficient and not very funny.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene illustrating the joke about Germans and efficiency. Draw a single German person, dressed in stereotypical, light-hearted traditional German attire (like lederhosen, a hat with a feather, or a simple modern outfit with a name tag saying ''Efficient Worker''). They are standing on a small step stool, confidently screwing in a shining light bulb into a plain ceiling socket. Around them are several unscrewed light bulbs lying neatly in a row, showing the work was quick. In the background, include a wall clock with its hands moving very fast, emphasizing speed and efficiency. The character should have a serious, focused expression to contrast humorously with a thought bubble containing a blank face or a simple ''...'' to imply not very funny. Use bright, friendly colors and exaggerated cartoon style, with clean lines and simple backgrounds to keep the focus on the character and light bulb. Avoid any negative stereotypes or harsh elements, focusing instead on the idea of efficiency and the joke’s punchline about humorlessness.'),
 (2707, 'Cultural Humor, Facts, Language, Unknown', 'China has more English speakers than the United States.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters: one is a typical American person looking surprised and scratching their head, wearing casual clothes and holding a small map of the USA. The other character is a friendly Chinese person holding a large book titled ''English for Everyone,'' smiling proudly. Behind them is a stylized globe highlighting both China and the United States with exaggerated speech bubbles showing English words like ''Hello!'' and ''Welcome!''. The background includes iconic landmarks from both countries – the Statue of Liberty for the USA on one side, and the Great Wall of China on the other – with playful cartoon clouds above. The style should be light-hearted and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize surprise and pride, in a clear cartoon format without any political symbols or serious tone.'),
 (2311, 'Cultural Humor, Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'The genius of you Americans is that you never make clear-cut stupid moves, only complicated stupid moves which make us wonder at the possibility that there may be something to them we are missing.', 'Gamel Nasser', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of people representing Americans and foreigners. On the left, depict a group of Americans dressed in casual, slightly quirky outfits, smiling confidently while discussing a complex, convoluted diagram with many confusing arrows and question marks around it. On the right, a group of non-Americans with raised eyebrows and puzzled expressions, scratching their heads and whispering among themselves, trying to make sense of the complicated plan. Between them, a thought bubble or speech bubble from the foreigners saying, ''Is there really something clever here? Or are we just missing something?'' The background should be simple and cheerful, with playful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor about complicated yet seemingly intelligent stupid moves. Include elements like a whiteboard or flip chart to emphasize the complicated plans.'),
 (2300, 'Cultural Humor, Irony, Language, Quotes', 'The English have no respect for their language, and will not teach their children to speak it.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy English living room. In the center, an English parent is talking to their child, but speech bubbles show the child saying a jumble of letters and nonsense words instead of proper English. The parent looks bewildered or sheepishly shrugging. Around them are scattered language-related objects like an open, dusty English dictionary on the floor, a blackboard with phonetic symbols crossed out, and a globe with a faint British flag. A speech bubble from an off-scene narrator or a title banner above states, ''The English have no respect for their language, and will not teach their children to speak it.'' Keep the style lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke''s ironic criticism about not teaching proper English.'),
 (2484, 'Cultural Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'Too many of us look upon Americans as dollar chasers. This is a cruel libel, even if it is reiterated thoughtlessly by the Americans themselves.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a diverse group of Americans in various stereotypical outfits and activities, each chasing exaggerated dollar signs floating around them. One person might be wearing a business suit running after a giant, shiny dollar symbol, another dressed as a farmer holding a pitchfork while eyeing a dollar sign growing on a plant, and yet another casual person juggling coins. A narrator figure or a sign in the background reads a thoughtful or ironic statement contrasting the stereotype. The style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions of determination and mild confusion on the faces of the characters. The setting is an open, simple park-like environment allowing the characters and floating dollar signs to stand out. Avoid any aggressive or negative imagery, emphasizing the irony and humor of the stereotype rather than negativity about Americans.'),
 (1814, 'Cultural Humor, Irony, Quotes, Travel Humor', 'I had always loved beautiful and artistic things, though before leaving America I had had a very little chance of seeing any.', 'Emma Albani', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a traveler standing at an airport arrival gate in America, looking upward with an admiring, dreamy expression. Around the traveler are exaggeratedly mundane and typical American objects and signs humorously portrayed as ''artistic things''—for example, a giant fast-food burger statue, an oversized billboard of a neon-lit diner, and a large, colorful traffic cone sculpture. The background should include an airport setting with a welcoming sign that says ''Welcome to America,'' and subtle visual jokes like a graffiti wall with stick figures and a small street artist painting a very simple smiley face. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, capturing the irony of appreciating ''beautiful and artistic things'' but only encountering everyday American cultural icons in a cartoonish style.'),
 (2092, 'Cultural Humor, Language, Math Humor, Quotes', 'Mathematicians are like Frenchmen: whatever you say to them they translate into their own language and forthwith it is something entirely different.', 'Goethe', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one labeled as a mathematician and the other as a Frenchman. The mathematician is standing at a chalkboard filled with complex mathematical symbols, formulas, and geometric shapes, looking puzzled but thoughtful. The Frenchman is holding a speech bubble with French text, looking confident and slightly amused. Between them, show a large, comical translation machine or device that takes the Frenchman''s speech bubble, processes it, and outputs a completely different, confusing phrase in the mathematician''s language or symbols. Include small visual cues like question marks and exclamation points above both characters'' heads to indicate the confusion and surprise. The setting is a lighthearted, simple background like an office or classroom with a few chairs or desks. The overall mood is playful and witty, using bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor without any negativity.'),
 (2417, 'Cultural Humor, Music Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'There are some experiences in life which should not be demanded twice from any man, and one of them is listening to the Brahms Requiem.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting in a concert hall with an exaggeratedly long Brahms Requiem performance happening on stage. The man looks visibly bored and exhausted, clutching his ear as if overwhelmed by the music. On stage, a symphony orchestra is performing with classical instruments like violins, cellos, and a conductor dramatically waving a baton. Around the man, several empty seats emphasize a lack of enthusiasm, and a clock on the wall shows that a long time has passed. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize the man''s reluctance to experience the music again. The setting should look like an elegant, classical concert hall with red curtains, chandeliers, and polished wooden floors.'),
 (2038, 'Cultural Humor, Politics, Quotes, Social Humor', 'Liberalism is the supreme form of generosity; it is the right which the majority concedes to minorities and hence it is the noblest cry that has ever resounded on this planet.', 'Jose Ortega y Gasset', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large group of diverse people gathered outdoors in a sunny park. In the center, a cheerful, charismatic figure stands on a small podium or soapbox, holding a megaphone and making an exaggerated grand gesture, conveying an important speech about generosity and rights. Around them, smaller groups of happy and attentive people representing various minority groups smile and nod appreciatively. The cartoon style is colorful, friendly, and slightly exaggerated with lively expressions and simple backgrounds featuring trees and a clear sky. Include banners or signs with heart symbols and the word ''Generosity'' to reinforce the theme. The overall tone is positive, lighthearted, and respectful, capturing the essence of generosity and social harmony without any conflict or tension in the scene.'),
 (2958, 'Cultural Humor, Pun, Unknown, Video Games', 'I asked a French man if he played video games. He said ''wii''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a French man being asked a question about video games. The French man is standing confidently with a slight smirk, wearing a striped shirt, a beret, and a thin mustache to emphasize his French stereotype in a lighthearted way. In front of him is another character, casually holding a game controller or asking the question with a friendly expression. Above the French man''s head is a speech bubble containing the word "wii" in playful letters, referencing the Nintendo Wii console but also hinting at the French accent pronouncing "wee." The background is simple, perhaps showing a small French café or a neutral indoor space with minimal props like a table or chair to keep focus on the characters. The overall art style is cartoonish and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the pun and light humor.'),
 (2930, 'Cultural Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor, Word Play', 'HIP: Smartly attuned to the latest cutting-edge cliche', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cool, fashionable young person wearing modern, trendy clothing like skinny jeans, a graphic tee, and stylish sunglasses. They have a confident, knowing smirk and are bobbing their head slightly as if to music. Around their head are floating comic-style pop-up text bubbles with buzzwords and cliches like ''cutting-edge,'' ''trendsetter,'' and ''on fleek.'' The background is a simple urban setting with stylized graffiti that reads ''HIP'' in big, colorful letters. The overall vibe is light and playful, emphasizing the exaggerated coolness and awareness of being up-to-date with trendy expressions.'),
 (1770, 'Culture Humor, Humor, Quotes', 'Humor is a universal language.', 'Joel Goodman', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of diverse people from around the world standing in a circle, each modeled with distinct cultural clothing and features to represent different continents. They are all laughing together, with visible speech bubbles showing colorful symbols like smiley faces, musical notes, and funny doodles floating around instead of words. In the center, a large globe floats above the ground, glowing gently to emphasize the concept of universality. The background is cheerful and bright, with simple cartoon-style trees and clouds to keep the focus on the characters. The overall tone is lighthearted and friendly, highlighting the idea that humor transcends language barriers.'),
 (2690, 'Customer Service Humor, Everyday Life, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'BUZZACKS (buz'' aks) n. People in phone marts who walk around picking up display phones and listening for dial tones even when they know the phones are not connected.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a phone store filled with display phones mounted on stands and walls. Several silly-looking customers, labeled as ''Buzzacks,'' wander around holding old-fashioned and modern display phones up to their ears, peering at each handset with exaggerated curiosity. Some have puzzled expressions while others look amused or overly serious. The phones do not have any cords connected to service lines, but the Buzzacks are all trying to listen for a dial tone, eyebrows furrowed or ears pressed tightly to the phones. In the background, a tired store employee watches with a mix of amusement and slight frustration. Bright colors, simple lines, and exaggerated facial expressions emphasize the cartoon and lighthearted nature of the scene. The store has visible signs like "Phone Mart" and cartoonish props like phone boxes, promotional posters, and a cash register for added detail. The overall vibe is funny and friendly, capturing a quirky everyday observation.'),
 (2777, 'Dad Humor, Family, Pun, Unknown', 'Do you have kids? It''s inappropriate to make a dad joke if you''re not a dad. That''s a faux pa.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene in a lighthearted, humorous style featuring two characters having a conversation. One character is a cheerful middle-aged man wearing a casual shirt and glasses, proudly making a pun with a big grin. Above his head is a speech bubble with the pun: "That''s a faux pa." The other character is a younger person with a puzzled yet amused expression, responding to the pun. In the background, include subtle visual hints suggesting family or parenting such as children''s toys or framed family photos on the wall, to emphasize the theme of ''dad'' versus ''not a dad.'' The setting is a cozy living room with bright colors and a comfy sofa, giving a warm, conversational atmosphere. The style should be cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the joke''s playful tone.'),
 (3244, 'Dad Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'You want me to stop telling Thanksgiving Day Dad jokes? OK, but I can''t just quit... cold turkey!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly middle-aged dad wearing a turkey-themed novelty apron and a ''Happy Thanksgiving'' chef hat. He stands in a cozy kitchen decorated for Thanksgiving with pumpkins, autumn leaves, and a roasted turkey on the table. The dad is smiling mischievously, holding a speech bubble that says, "I can''t just quit... cold turkey!" Nearby, a literal cartoon turkey looks shocked and flutters its wings, as if reacting to the pun. The setting includes a calendar on the wall marking the date as Thanksgiving Day and warm fall colors to set the seasonal mood. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and playful, capturing the pun and family holiday vibe without any aggressive or inappropriate content.'),
 (3045, 'Dad Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'I told a dad joke in a Teams meeting and nobody laughed - turns out I''m not even remotely funny.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a virtual Teams meeting. Show a grid of several small video call windows with different cartoon characters who all have blank or unimpressed facial expressions. In one window, a character portrayed as a middle-aged person wearing a silly ‘dad joke’ style shirt or holding a coffee mug labeled ''Dad Jokes'' is speaking. Their face shows a hopeful smile, as if telling a joke. The other participants appear either confused, bored, or mildly annoyed. The background for each participant can be simple home offices or living rooms. Include typical video call UI elements: mute/unmute icon, chat bubble, and participant names below each window. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the awkwardness of telling a dad joke that falls flat during a remote meeting.'),
 (3025, 'Dad Humor, Sign Language Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I recently learned sign language - it''s really handy. I can even tell Dad jokes in sign language, and I guarantee you this - nobody''s ever heard those.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing with their hand raised, making a clear and exaggerated sign language gesture. Nearby, a small comic-style speech bubble shows simple stick-figure signs representing dad jokes: a groaning face and a thumbs-up. Next to this person, an older man labeled ''Dad'' looks puzzled and slightly amused with a question mark over his head, showing he can''t ''hear'' the joke. The setting is a brightly colored living room with a couch, a side table with a lamp, and framed family photos on the wall. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke about silent sign language and unheard dad jokes. The characters are drawn in a friendly, cartoon style, with smooth lines and warm colors to keep the scene inviting and funny without any negativity or offense.'),
 (2759, 'Dad, Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown', 'Did I tell you that dad joke about the broken pencil?  Never mind, it''s pointless.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a sad, broken pencil with a small visible crack and a dull, worn-down tip lying on a wooden desk. The pencil has large, expressive cartoon eyes looking disappointed or tired, and a tiny frown to match. Next to the pencil, a cheerful speech bubble reads: "Never mind, it’s pointless." In the background, a smiling dad character wearing casual clothes and a ''Dad Jokes Champion'' t-shirt is shrugging with a playful grin, as if telling the joke. The setting is a bright, simple room with a few scattered school supplies like a notebook, eraser, and sharpener to emphasize the writing theme. The overall style is light, colorful, and playful, with clear, bold outlines to create a friendly and funny mood.'),
 (418, 'Dad, Family, Puns', 'My son just became a father for the first time today... to pass the paternal torch, he asked me where I kept all my dad jokes, so I told him - they are stored in my dadabase.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two men—a proud father and his adult son—standing together in a cozy living room. The father is handing over a large, overflowing bookshelf labeled ''DAD JOKES'' to his son, who looks excited and slightly amused. The bookshelf is cartoonishly big, filled with books, scrolls, and sticky notes, all labeled with silly pun titles. Near the bookshelf is a computer terminal or server tower humorously labeled ''DADABASE'' with blinking lights and a digital screen displaying the word ''Loading Dad Jokes...''. Both men are smiling warmly, embodying a lighthearted passing of tradition. The room has family photos on the walls, including a framed picture of the father holding a baby. The style is colorful and friendly, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke’s pun on "database" and "dadabase." The overall vibe is cheerful and comical without any violence, politics, or inappropriate content.'),
 (419, 'Dad, Food Humor, Puns', 'Cannibal says: a sandwich is a sandwich, but a manwich is a meal!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly-looking cannibal sitting at a rustic wooden table in a jungle or tribal setting. The cannibal should be mid-sentence with a big grin, holding a large sandwich in one hand labeled simply ''Sandwich'' with typical sandwich fillings (lettuce, tomato, cheese). On the table in front of him is a giant sandwich labeled ''Manwich'' that humorously looks like a sandwich with a small cartoon man peeking out or sitting inside it, smiling as if he’s part of the meal. Surrounding the cannibal are lighthearted jungle elements, like palm leaves and vines. The atmosphere should be playful, colorful, and cartoonish without anything scary or violent, emphasizing the wordplay and pun on ''manwich'' as a meal rather than just a sandwich.'),
 (420, 'Dad, Good Question!', 'If you don''t know where you are, you shouldn''t be there.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing at a fork in the road with exaggeratedly large, confusing road signs pointing in opposite directions. The person is scratching their head with a puzzled expression. Nearby, a wise old owl perches on a signpost labeled ''You Should Know Where You Are.'' The background is a simple, sunny countryside path with trees and bushes. The style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors, and the characters have big eyes and expressive faces to emphasize the confusion and humor of the situation.'),
 (421, 'Dad, Good Question!, Humor, Pessimistic', 'If you must choose between two evils, choose the one you''ve never tried before.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two mischievous-looking ''evil'' characters standing side by side, each representing a different evil. One character looks like a classic devil with small horns and a pitchfork, smirking confidently. The other character is a quirky, friendly monster with an exaggerated goofy grin. In the foreground, a cartoon person with a confused but amused expression stands at a forked path or crossroads, scratching their head, looking toward the two evils. The background is light and colorful with simple shapes to keep the mood playful and funny. The signpost between the two evils reads ''Choose Your Evil''. The style should be simple, bold, and colorful with expressive faces to emphasize the joke’s meaning about choosing between two undesirable options but humorously opting for the unfamiliar one.'),
 (422, 'Dad, Good Question!, Humor, Quotes', 'If you can''t convince them, confuse them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of an audience, trying to give a serious presentation. The presenter is holding a pointer stick and pointing at a complicated, nonsensical chart filled with jumbled numbers and symbols that don''t make sense. The audience looks bewildered and confused, with some scratching their heads and others with swirling question marks above their heads. The presenter has a sly smile, as if intentionally trying to confuse rather than convince. The setting is a simple conference room or classroom with a whiteboard or projector screen. The overall vibe is light and playful, emphasizing confusion as a tactic.'),
 (609, 'Dad, Good Question!, Pun', 'What''s the difference between a bad joke and a dad joke? The first letter', NULL, 'A bright, colorful cartoon scene featuring two speech bubbles side by side. The first bubble says, ''A bad joke'' with a sad, droopy face character inside, looking disappointed and holding a broken joke card. The second bubble says, ''A dad joke'' with a cheerful, smiling middle-aged man wearing a classic dad outfit: a plaid shirt, jeans, and glasses, holding a sign with the letter ''D'' prominently displayed. Between the bubbles, there is a big bold letter ''D'' drawn as if it is the key difference. The background is simple, with light pastel colors and minimal props to keep the focus on the characters and text. The style is clean and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor, making it playful and lighthearted without any references to violence, politics, or anything adult-themed.'),
 (423, 'Dad, History Humor, Political Humor, Puns', 'Joseph Stalin should have known communism wouldn''t work... I mean seriously, there were red flags everywhere.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Joseph Stalin standing in a field filled with numerous large red flags planted in the ground all around him. Stalin, drawn with his iconic mustache and military uniform, has a puzzled or concerned expression on his face, scratching his chin as he looks around at the red flags. The background is a simple clear sky and some grass to keep the focus on the ''red flags.'' The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated for comedic effect, with bright colors emphasizing the red flags. No violence or political tension; just an amusing visual pun on "red flags" and communism.'),
 (424, 'Dad, Humor', 'When is a dad joke apparent? When it is delivered', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly middle-aged dad standing next to a speech bubble. The dad is smiling widely and wearing casual clothes, such as a plaid shirt and jeans. The speech bubble coming from him contains a very simple and obvious pun or joke, symbolizing a ''dad joke'' being told out loud. Around him, a few family members or friends have mixed reactions: one person rolling their eyes playfully, another person chuckling, and a child with an exaggerated groan or facepalm. The setting is a cozy living room with a couch, a lamp, maybe a wall clock showing ''pun time.'' The overall atmosphere is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the idea that a dad joke becomes obvious simply by being spoken aloud. The cartoon style should be colorful, friendly, and exaggerated to highlight the humor without being aggressive or sarcastic.'),
 (425, 'Dad, Humor, Puns', 'What happens to a dad joke once it is delivered? It''s fully groan', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful dad standing with a big grin, holding a microphone as if delivering a joke. In front of him, several audience members with exaggerated expressions of groaning—some have their hands on their faces, others rolling their eyes or leaning back dramatically. In the background, a large speech bubble coming from the dad contains the pun text: ''It''s fully groan.'' The setting is a simple living room or comedy stage with a spotlight on the dad, emphasizing the joke delivery. Include playful visual elements like musical notes or small cartoon groan sound effects around the audience''s heads to emphasize the pun on ''groan'' sounding like ''grown.'' The overall tone should be lighthearted and fun, in a colorful and exaggerated cartoon style, without any negativity or mean-spiritedness.'),
 (426, 'Dad, Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'Breaking news: A red ship and a blue ship have collided in the Caribbean... apparently, the survivors are marooned.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene set on a bright, sunny Caribbean beach. In the background, two ships lean toward each other, one painted bright red and the other bright blue, with obvious cartoonish damage where they have collided. On the sandy shore in the foreground, a group of people look surprised and slightly worried as they stand among scattered crates and beach items. Some survivors are wearing typical stranded expressions. To emphasize the pun, around their feet and scattered on the sand are several large maroon-colored backpacks or sacks labeled ''MAROONED,'' as if the survivors have literally been ''marooned'' with maroon items. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bold lines and vibrant colors to imply humor rather than drama or danger.'),
 (427, 'Dad, Humor, Shopping Jokes', 'The grocery store cashier asked dad ''do you want the milk in the bag'' He said ''No - just leave it in the carton''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a grocery store checkout aisle. Show a friendly, slightly bemused grocery store cashier standing behind the register, wearing a name tag and a standard cashier uniform. In front of the cashier is a typical middle-aged dad character holding a carton of milk. The dad has a deadpan or mildly confused expression, as if he’s not quite following the usual checkout routine. The milk carton should clearly be visible in his hand, and it should look like a typical milk carton with a label. The cashier has just asked, ''Do you want the milk in the bag?'' A speech bubble from the dad says, ''No – just leave it in the carton.'' Around them, add subtle grocery store details like a conveyor belt with a few items, shopping bags hanging on hooks, and shelves stocked with colorful products in the background. The mood is light, playful, and typical of a family-friendly cartoon gag. Use bright colors, clean lines, and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor.'),
 (428, 'Dad, Humor, Word Play', 'What starts with ''w'' and ends with ''hat''. (No, that wasn''t a question, just a statement of fact...)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky character—a smiling person with a surprised or amused expression—standing next to a large oversized word puzzle board. The board prominently displays the letters ''w'' at the start and ''hat'' at the end, with a big blank space in the middle to highlight the joke’s wordplay. The character is holding one finger up, as if making a point, while a speech bubble above them says: ''No, that wasn’t a question, just a statement of fact…''. The setting is bright and playful with simple background colors to keep focus on the character and the word puzzle. The font of the letters on the board should be bold and cartoonish. The scene is lighthearted and emphasizes the word joke without any violent or controversial elements.'),
 (429, 'Dad, Humor, Word Play, Workplace', 'I''m pretty sure that hotel receptionist was checking me out', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a modern hotel lobby. The main focus is a young man standing at the front desk, looking slightly flustered and blushing, with a shy smile on his face. Across the desk, a hotel receptionist, a friendly-looking woman, is glancing sideways at him with a knowing smirk and raised eyebrow, as if giving him a playful once-over. The desk should have a computer monitor and a bell, and behind the receptionist, a sign that reads ''Hotel Reception'' or a stylized hotel logo. The background shows some simple lobby details like a potted plant and a wall clock. The art style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the humor and playful mood without any suggestiveness or discomfort. The overall vibe is cheerful and silly, capturing the pun on ''checking out'' as both hotel procedure and flirtation.'),
 (430, 'Dad, Math Humor, Puns', 'I''m going to a Fibonacci conference this year. They promise it will be as big as the last two put together!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a conference hall with a big banner that reads ''Fibonacci Conference''. In the foreground, a cheerful character wearing a name tag is excitedly telling another person, ''They promise it will be as big as the last two put together!'' Behind them, three conference rooms are visible, labeled with numbers: ''Room 1'', ''Room 2'', and to the right, a much larger room labeled ''Room 3'', which is roughly the combined size of the first two rooms. The rooms could be illustrated as blocks whose sizes visually match the Fibonacci sequence (small, medium, then large). Add playful details like posters with spiral and number patterns and an audience or attendees milling about, some looking intrigued or puzzled by the concept. Make sure the style is lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish to emphasize the joke''s clever play on Fibonacci growth without any intense or complex elements.'),
 (2746, 'Dad, Occupational Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'Dad in lumberyard: ''I need some 2x4s''. Staff: ''How long do you need them?'' Dad: ''A long time - I''m building a house!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a busy lumberyard. In the foreground, a cheerful dad wearing a baseball cap and casual work clothes is talking to a lumberyard staff member behind a counter stacked with wood samples and price tags. The dad is holding a notepad or talking with an enthusiastic expression. The staff member looks slightly puzzled, scratching his head as he asks, ''How long do you need them?'' In the background, there are neatly stacked bundles of 2x4 wooden planks with bright labels. Near the dad''s feet, a simple blueprint or sketch of a house is partially visible, hinting at his project. The setting is bright and clean with humorous cartoon-style characters, emphasizing friendly interaction and playfulness without any harsh lines or dark tones.'),
 (431, 'Dad, Puns', 'I entered a dad joke competition and won $1000. It was a grand dad joke.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful man proudly holding a large trophy labeled ''Dad Joke Champion'' and a big check for $1000. Next to him, an old, dignified-looking man wearing a crown and a sash that says ''Grand Dad'' stands with a smile, as if sharing the prize or being part of the joke. The setting is a simple stage with a banner overhead reading ''Dad Joke Competition.'' There is a small audience in the background laughing and clapping. The style is colorful and light-hearted with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the pun on ''grand dad joke.'' No violence or anything inappropriate should be included.'),
 (432, 'Dad, Puns', 'It''s inappropriate to make a dad joke if you''re not a dad. That''s a faux pa.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful middle-aged man wearing a stereotypical "dad" outfit: a plaid shirt tucked into khaki pants, loafers, and glasses. He is standing in a living room with a big grin, holding a big book labeled "Dad Jokes" in one hand. Across from him stands a younger person looking confused and embarrassed, nervously trying to hold back a groan. Floating above the younger person''s head is a comic-style speech bubble with the phrase, "That''s a faux pa!" Behind them, a decorative wall clock shaped like a faux pas (pun on a foot in a shoe) adds a subtle visual cue for humor. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish with bright colors, exaggerated facial expressions, and playful details to emphasize the wordplay and social awkwardness of telling dad jokes when you’re not a dad.'),
 (2531, 'Dark Humor, Exaggeration, Historical Humor, Quotes', 'We who are about to die, are going to take one hell of a lot of the bastards with us.', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a group of determined, cartoon-style ancient gladiators or warriors standing together in a coliseum or arena. They should have exaggerated, fierce expressions but in a silly, non-threatening way, symbolizing their resolve and camaraderie. Around them, comic-style motion lines or dust clouds suggest they are ready to fight or cause chaos. The background is a simple arena with cheering cartoon spectators in the stands, some looking worried or surprised. Props like swords, shields, or helmets can be included, but nothing realistic or gruesome—keep it playful. Include a speech bubble from one leader who looks especially intense, saying the line from the joke: "We who are about to die, are going to take one hell of a lot of the bastards with us." Overall, the tone should be cartoonish, lively, and humorous without violence, highlighting the ironic bravado and camaraderie of the group preparing to face a tough fate together.'),
 (433, 'Dark Humor, Facts, Marine Humor, Word Play', 'Any ship can be a minesweeper ... once.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, simple ship labeled ''Minesweeper'' sailing on the ocean with a surprised and worried captain looking out over the bow. The ocean surface has comic-style floating sea mines with little angry faces and spikes, clearly menacing the ship. In the background, a second ship sails safely at a distance, labeled ''Regular Ship,'' looking calm and unaware. The sky is sunny with a couple of fluffy clouds. The style should be light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on the captain and the sea mines to emphasize the joke’s dark humor in a non-threatening way. Avoid any violence; focus on the imminent but comically over-the-top danger the ship is about to face.'),
 (434, 'Dark Humor, History Humor, Jobs', 'The electric chair was invented by a dentist.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a vintage dentist''s office with an old-fashioned wooden electric chair in the center, equipped with wires and electrodes attached to it. The dentist, wearing a white coat and a silly, exaggeratedly large dentist head mirror, stands beside the chair holding a giant electric drill and flashing a mischievous grin. Around the room, typical dental tools (mirror, pliers, toothbrush) are scattered casually, with a poster on the wall labeled ''Electric Chair: Dentists'' Greatest Invention.'' The style is bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s irony, making it clear and funny without any hint of violence or discomfort.'),
 (1657, 'Dark Humor, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Early to rise and early to bed, makes a man healthy, wealthy, and dead.', 'James Thurber', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a man in pajamas and slippers, looking very tired and disheveled, standing next to a large alarm clock showing an early hour. On the left side, show the man waking up bright and early with energetic morning sunlight through a window. On the right side, depict the same man early in bed, under the covers with a worried or defeated expression. Overlay a playful combination of symbols illustrating health (a heart with a pulse line), wealth (a bag of money or gold coins), and death (a white skull with a comic, non-frightening expression) hanging over the man or floating above his head. Use exaggerated cartoon style with bright colors, a cheerful living room or bedroom interior, and emphasize the contrast between the benefits and the grim final result suggested by the joke. The overall tone should be lighthearted and silly, not scary or dark.'),
 (435, 'Dark Humor, Irony', 'Remember it''s always darkest just before it goes totally black.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a dark room with a worried person holding a flashlight that just turned off. The setting is comically dim with the person squinting, looking confused and startled. Behind them, a wall clock shows late night hours to emphasize darkness. Around the person, various objects like a chair, a table, and a cat are barely visible in the gloom. Above the scene, a speech bubble reads: "Remember it''s always darkest just before it goes totally black." The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and simple line art to emphasize the irony of the phrase.'),
 (2263, 'Dark Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'Sure, it''s going to kill a lot of people, but they may be dying of something else anyway.', 'Othal Brand member of a Texas pesticide review board', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing at a crossroads with a giant, ominous-looking sign that says ''Danger Ahead'' pointing down one path. The person, looking puzzled and shrugging, holds a checklist labeled ''Risks'' with boxes ticked for various dangers like ''Traffic,'' ''Disease,'' and ''Accidents.'' Behind them, a subtle background shows everyday life continuing: people walking dogs, kids playing, and an ambulance passing by. The overall tone is light-hearted and thoughtful, capturing the irony that despite clear threats, life goes on, and risks are accepted. Use bright colors and exaggerated expressions to add humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (436, 'Dark Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'Treat each day as your last, one day you will be right.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person waking up in bed with an exaggerated, bright morning sun shining through the window. The character is stretching widely with a big smile, wearing pajamas. Around the room are typical morning objects like an alarm clock, a coffee mug, and a calendar on the wall with the date circled in red. Above the character, a thought bubble displays the quote: ''Treat each day as your last, one day you will be right.'' The overall tone is light and optimistic but with a subtle twist of dark humor. The colors are bright and vibrant to emphasize the contrast between the lively morning and the underlying grim twist of the phrase. The art style is cartoonish with rounded shapes and expressive faces to highlight the joke''s ironic nature.'),
 (2921, 'Dark Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Health is merely the slowest possible rate at which one can die.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful skeleton leisurely reclining on a hammock tied between two palm trees on a sunny beach. The skeleton is wearing sunglasses and sipping a tropical drink with a little umbrella. Above, a bright sun shines, and a small calendar hangs from one of the palm trees showing the passage of time with pages flipping rapidly. Nearby, a turtle with a stopwatch on its shell slowly crawls by, symbolizing slowness. The overall mood is lighthearted and ironic, emphasizing the joke that health is the slowest way to die by visually contrasting the peaceful, slow pace of life with the inevitability of death.'),
 (437, 'Dark Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'Time is the best teacher; Unfortunately it kills all its students!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an old-fashioned teacher, personified as a whimsical clock with arms, legs, and a friendly face, standing in front of a classroom. The classroom has a blackboard with the phrase ''Time is the best teacher'' written on it. Surrounding the clock-teacher are cartoon students depicted as various smaller clocks or wristwatches, all looking a little worn out or sleepy, some with cartoon ''X'' eyes to humorously imply they are ''dead.'' The classroom setting is light-hearted and colorful, with desks, a globe, and school supplies scattered around. The overall tone is playful and funny, emphasizing the pun that though time teaches us, it also eventually leads to the end of all students. No dark or scary elements; keep the scene cheerful and silly to match the joke’s ironic humor.'),
 (2189, 'Dark Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Outside of the killings, Washington has one of the lowest crime rates in the country.', 'Mayor Marion Barry', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a city skyline labeled ''Washington'' with tall government buildings like the Capitol and the White House. In the foreground, a cheerful, clean street with smiling citizens going about their day, holding shopping bags and walking dogs. Alongside, a tall, serious police officer is standing with a clipboard, looking a bit bewildered. Behind the officer, a few subtle shadowy figures sneak away, hinting at the ''killings'' mentioned in the joke but drawn in a very lighthearted, non-threatening way – maybe as silly cartoon ghosts or shadow figures tiptoeing comically. The mood is bright and exaggeratedly cheerful, emphasizing the irony that aside from those unusual events, crime seems very low. The sky is sunny, birds flying, and a newspaper headline in a corner reads, ''Washington Crime Rate Hits Record Low! Except...'' to add to the humor.'),
 (1329, 'Data Humor, Programmers, Programming Humor, Workplace', 'A manager, a programmer, and a data analyst went hunting. The manager shoots at the deer and misses 5 feet to the left. The programmer shoots and misses 5 feet to the right. The data analyst yells out ''We got ''em!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a forest clearing during daytime. Three characters are present: a manager, a programmer, and a data analyst. The manager is shown aiming a hunting rifle, with a speech bubble indicating a shot missed five feet to the left, illustrated by a bullet hole or impact mark on a tree well left of a startled deer. The programmer stands on the opposite side, also holding a rifle, and a speech bubble shows a miss five feet to the right, with a bullet hole or impact mark on a tree well right of the same deer. The deer looks confused and unharmed, standing in the middle. The data analyst stands slightly behind or between them, animatedly pointing at the deer with a big smile and a speech bubble shouting, "We got ''em!" emphasizing the humor of the optimistic data interpretation. The overall style should be bright, exaggerated expressions on the characters, and clear visual cues of the missed shots creating a funny contrast between actual events and the analyst’s declaration.'),
 (2615, 'Dental Humor, Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'You know, sometimes a man just can''t satisfy all of a woman''s desires. Which is why God invented dental floss.', 'Susanne Kollrack', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man looking overwhelmed with multiple exaggeratedly large thought bubbles around his head, each representing a different woman’s impossibly high or silly desires (e.g., diamonds, fancy dinners, spa days, romantic dinners). Nearby, a cheerful, cartoonish representation of dental floss with a smiling face and arms is holding up a small sign that says “Solved!” The background is simple and light, focusing on the man and the personified dental floss as the ‘hero’ solving the problem. The man wears casual clothes and looks slightly confused but hopeful. The dental floss character has a bright, friendly expression and is drawn as a small box or spool with floss string looping playfully around it. The overall tone is light, clever, and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the joke’s punchline.'),
 (2671, 'Dental Humor, Puns, Unknown, Word Play', 'Be true to your teeth or your teeth will be false to you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, anthropomorphic tooth standing upright with arms and legs. The tooth has a cheerful face with big eyes and a wide smile, holding a tiny toothbrush like a microphone as if giving advice. Surrounding the tooth are several smaller teeth in the shape of human molars, incisors, and canines, looking worried or surprised. Next to them, a mouth with lips is open, showing some sparkling clean teeth and a few crooked or missing ''false'' teeth that look like dental dentures with exaggerated expressions—one denture looking like it''s sneaking away or being disloyal. The background is simple, like a dentist’s office with a poster on the wall that shows a toothbrush and floss happily shaking hands with smiling teeth. The style should be bright, cartoonish, and playful, emphasizing the pun that teeth can be ''true'' or ''false'' like friends or partners. Avoid anything scary or medical—make it fun and approachable for all ages.'),
 (2073, 'Dictionary Humor, Dry Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Mad, adj: Affected with a high degree of intellectual independence.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a quirky, old-fashioned dictionary page brought to life. The page is open, with large, bold title text at the top reading ''Mad, adj:''. Below the heading, the definition is written in playful, exaggerated cursive: ''Affected with a high degree of intellectual independence.'' Around the dictionary page, draw a cartoon character symbolizing ''Mad'' as a scholarly-looking person with wild, spiky hair, thick round glasses, and a tweed jacket with elbow patches. The character is holding a giant feather quill pen, looking both proud and a little zany—smiling confidently as if embracing their ''intellectual independence.'' The background can be a simple library scene with stacks of books piled messily to add to the eccentric scholar vibe. Use bold outlines and expressive faces to enhance the humor and personality. The overall tone is lighthearted, whimsical, and witty, emphasizing the playful redefinition of the word ''mad'' in a way that feels both clever and welcoming.'),
 (438, 'Did''ya Hear, Dyslexics, Philosophy Humor, Puns', 'Did you hear about the dyslexic agnostic insomniac who stays up all night wondering if there really is a Dog?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a character looking tired and confused late at night. The character should have disheveled hair, dark circles under their eyes, and be sitting on a bed or armchair surrounded by nighttime elements like a clock showing a late hour and a moon visible through a window. Above the character, depict a thought bubble illustrating the mix-up: instead of the usual question ''Is there a God?'', show a dog with a questioning expression wearing a little halo or glowing softly, emphasizing the pun on ''Dog'' instead of ''God''. The setting should feel whimsical and playful, using bright, exaggerated cartoon expressions to highlight the character’s insomnia, doubt (agnosticism), and dyslexia through visual cues like jumbled letters or symbols floating around their head. Keep the style lighthearted with exaggerated, comical features and a cozy nighttime indoor background with a lamp casting a soft glow.'),
 (439, 'Did''ya Hear, Facts, Humor', 'On average, 100 people choke to death on ballpoint pens every year.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of about four funny-looking human characters standing around an oversized ballpoint pen that is lying on the ground like a big fallen log. The characters look exaggeratedly shocked and are making silly expressions of surprise or mild panic. One character is nervously pointing at the pen while another is holding their throat as if they almost choked. The setting is a simple, colorful office or school room with a desk in the background scattered with papers and a pencil holder. The oversized pen is very detailed, with a shiny tip and a bright blue or black ink tip, emphasizing its ballpoint pen nature. There are no violent elements; the tone is light and silly, capturing the funny, absurd idea that pens could be choking hazards. A small sign or chart in the background humorously reads: "100 people choke on ballpoint pens every year," reinforcing the joke in a visual way. The overall style is clean, bright, and cartoonish, focusing on exaggerated facial expressions and playful body language.'),
 (440, 'Did''ya Hear, Food Humor, Humor, Puns', 'Did''ya hear about the cheese factory explosion in Wisconsin? De brie was everywhere', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene of a cheese factory explosion. The factory building should be in the background with some smokey puffs and cartoon-style explosion lines emanating from it, but no flames. In the foreground and midground, portray chunks and drips of various types of cheese flying through the air—most prominently pieces of Brie with its distinctive white rind and soft interior. Include other cheese shapes like Swiss and cheddar for variety. Show some cheese pieces comically landing on nearby grass, animals (like cows looking surprised), and workers wearing casual factory uniforms with comical shocked expressions but no injury. The setting is a cheerful countryside farm with green rolling hills and a clear blue sky. The style is exaggerated and playful, emphasizing the pun by making the cheese explosion look silly and messy but not harmful or scary.'),
 (441, 'Did''ya Hear, Food Humor, Puns, Science', 'Did''ya hear about the new restaurant on the moon? The food is ok but there''s no atmosphere', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the inside of a futuristic restaurant located on the moon. The setting is a round dining area with large windows revealing the lunar surface and Earth in the background. Two cartoon characters—an astronaut and a casual diner in a space suit—are sitting at a simple table with plates of food that look ordinary and unimpressive. The astronaut is shrugging and looking disappointed. Above them, a speech bubble reads, ''The food is ok but there''s no atmosphere.'' The restaurant interior looks very bare and empty, emphasizing the pun on ''no atmosphere.'' Little details like floating crumbs or zero gravity food crumbs add whimsy. The overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and clearly a cartoon to match the joke’s playful tone.'),
 (442, 'Did''ya Hear, Good Question!', 'Did''ya know the latest version of the Oxford English Dictionary does not contain the word ''gullible''?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style drawing showing a large, thick Oxford English Dictionary open on a wooden desk. The focus is on a page with words and definitions, but the word ''gullible'' is missing, illustrated by a big empty space or a question mark. Nearby, a person with a puzzled and slightly embarrassed expression is scratching their head, clearly looking at the book, unsure if they believe the claim. Behind them, a mischievous-looking character or a small cartoon bird labeled ''Gullible'' is smirking or chuckling, adding to the joke. The setting is a cozy library or study room with bookshelves filled with colorful books in the background, giving a scholarly vibe. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated facial expressions and fun elements like question marks and thought bubbles to emphasize confusion and humor.'),
 (443, 'Did''ya Hear, Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'Did you hear about the underwear company that only allowed brief phone calls?', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon storefront scene depicting an underwear company shop named ''Brief Calls Inc.'' The shop has a large, eye-catching sign featuring an underwear icon and a vintage phone receiver with a clock dial integrated into the design to emphasize ''brief calls.'' Outside the shop, a cheerful shopkeeper wearing funny boxers and a nametag stands behind a counter, holding a classic telephone receiver to his ear with a big smile. Around him, customers line up, some holding phones, appearing amused or impatient. Above, playful speech bubbles show very short phone conversations with ellipses and quick ''Hello? Bye!'' text to reflect brief calls. The background should be simple and bright, with a sidewalk and a few humorous details like a clock showing very short time intervals and underwear hanging or displayed in the window. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, capturing the pun on ''brief'' as both underwear and short phone calls.'),
 (444, 'Did''ya Hear, Puns', 'Did''ya hear about the kidnapping at school? Everything''s fine now. He woke up.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, cheerful elementary school classroom. In the center, a confused but sleepy kid is just waking up on the floor near a small desk, rubbing his eyes. Nearby, a couple of kids and a teacher look relieved and slightly amused. There is a school backpack lying casually beside the sleeping kid, and a fun classroom background with colorful posters, a chalkboard, and desks. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the pun of ''kidnapping'' meaning a child literally ''napping'' (sleeping). The style is simple and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions of surprise, relief, and drowsiness to capture the joke''s clever wordplay.'),
 (445, 'Did''ya Hear, Puns, Word Play', 'Did''ya hear about the new broom that came out? It''s sweeping the nation', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a large, cheerful broom with eyes, a wide smile, and arms holding a tiny flag. The broom is sweeping across a simplified map of a country (like the United States), with tiny cartoon houses and trees being gently swept along behind it like a wave. Around the broom, little cartoon people cheer and wave small banners that say ''Go Broom!'' The sky is bright and sunny, and the style is lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the pun ''sweeping the nation'' by showing the broom literally sweeping the map in a playful, non-threatening way.'),
 (446, 'Direction Jokes, Humor, Relatable', 'When I ask for directions, please don''t use words like ''east.''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set outdoors at a road intersection or a simple street corner. Show a confused-looking person, maybe holding a map upside down, standing next to a quirky, overly enthusiastic local giving directions. The local should be animatedly pointing in a general direction with one hand while holding a compass labeled with cardinal points (N, E, S, W) in the other hand. Surround them with simple street signs, one labeled ''East'' prominently, to highlight the confusion. The confused person could have a thought bubble with symbols like question marks and arrows going in all directions. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize confusion and frustration, without any harsh or negative imagery.'),
 (447, 'Don''t Say It!, Food Humor, Puns', 'I don''t like jokes about pizza. They''re too cheesy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a large, anthropomorphic pizza slice standing upright with a slightly annoyed or tired facial expression. The pizza slice has exaggerated gooey cheese dripping off its edges, with pepperoni eyes and a mouth. Nearby, a small character (could be a person or a simple cartoon figure) is holding a microphone or telling a joke, looking amused. The background is simple, maybe a kitchen or pizzeria setting with a pizza oven and flour bags. The scene should emphasize the ''cheesy'' aspect by making the cheese notably thick and stringy, almost like melted goo, to visually reinforce the pun. The overall tone is light and playful, with bright colors like red, yellow, and green. No violence or anything inappropriate.'),
 (448, 'Don''t Say It!, Food Humor, Puns', 'I don''t make jokes about German sausage - they''re the wurst!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful German sausage character with a smiling face, wearing a traditional Bavarian hat (like a Tyrolean hat with a feather). The sausage is standing on a wooden platter with mustard and sauerkraut next to it. Above the sausage, a speech bubble says, "I''m the wurst!" In the background, there is a simple German beer hall atmosphere with a wooden bench and a sign featuring the German flag colors. The tone is light and playful, focusing on the pun without any violence or offense.'),
 (449, 'Don''t Say It!, Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'I don''t tell PMS jokes because they aren''t funny. Period.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly-looking stand-up comedian on stage holding a microphone, looking amused but polite. Behind the comedian is a large speech bubble with the text: "I don''t tell PMS jokes because they aren''t funny. Period." The audience is a small group of diverse cartoon characters reacting with mixed expressions — some smiling, some indifferent. The stage has a simple curtain backdrop and a spotlight focused on the comedian. A small clock on the wall shows the time, emphasizing the stand-up setting. The overall art style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the joke’s tone without offending anyone.'),
 (450, 'Don''t Say It!, Humor, Political Humor, Word Play', 'I don''t tell jokes about communism because aren''t funny unless you share them with everyone.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a casual living room. In the center, a cheerful person is standing with a big grin, holding a microphone or a paper with a joke written on it. Around them, several friends or family members are gathered, all smiling or chuckling, emphasizing a shared moment of laughter. Above the scene, a speech bubble from the person says, ''I don''t tell jokes about communism because aren''t funny unless you share them with everyone.'' Background elements include a cozy couch, a coffee table with snacks, and a few playful posters or decorations hinting at equality or sharing, such as a pie chart split evenly or people passing a pie around. The overall tone is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the communal humor concept.'),
 (451, 'Don''t Say It!, Humor, Pop Culture', 'What did Kermit the frog say at Jim Henson''s funeral? Nothing', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a simple funeral outdoors with a modest wooden coffin surrounded by a few mourners looking somber but calm. At the center is Kermit the Frog, standing quietly beside the coffin. Kermit should be drawn in his classic green puppet style, with his mouth closed to emphasize silence. The setting includes some wilting flowers and a banner or sign nearby that says ''Jim Henson'' to indicate whose funeral it is. The overall style is lighthearted and respectful with soft colors and gentle details to keep the tone humorous but appropriate.'),
 (452, 'Don''t Say It!, Humor, Puns', 'I can''t tell you the one about the roof, because it''s over your head', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a confused person standing outside their house looking up at the roof. Above them, a simple house with a peaked roof is clearly visible. On the roof, a cheerful cartoon character (personified roof) is leaning down, winking and holding a finger to its lips as if saying ''shh''. Above this character, a speech bubble reads, ''It''s over your head!'' The style should be colorful, light-hearted, and humorous, with exaggerated facial expressions on both the confused person and the animated roof to emphasize the pun. The background can be a sunny day with a few clouds to keep it bright and friendly.'),
 (453, 'Don''t Say It!, Humor, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'I don''t make fat people jokes, because they wouldn''t be appreciated by the wider audience', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a comedy stage with a microphone and a spotlight shining on a cheerful stand-up comedian. The comedian is holding a microphone and smiling broadly while facing an audience filled with diverse people of various shapes, sizes, and expressions, including a few overweight individuals who are smiling or laughing warmly. The background has a simple brick wall common to comedy clubs. Above the scene or on a small sign near the stage, include a visible gag in text: ''I don''t make fat people jokes, because they wouldn''t be appreciated by the wider audience.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and friendly, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoonish features to emphasize humor and inclusivity without offending anyone.'),
 (454, 'Don''t Say It!, Humor, Word Play', 'I can make apocalypse jokes like there is no tomorrow', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a cheerful character confidently standing on a stage with a microphone, delivering a joke. The background shows a dramatic, exaggerated apocalypse setting with a burning sun and cracked earth, but drawn in a lighthearted, cartoonish style without fear or violence. The character is smiling broadly, shrugging as if to say "there''s no tomorrow," while behind them, a calendar on a wall displays the date ''Today'' with the next day humorously torn off or missing. Include simple, bright colors and exaggerated expressions to keep the tone witty and playful.'),
 (455, 'Don''t Say It!, Humor, Workplace', 'I don''t make jokes about retired people, because they don''t work', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one active, middle-aged person holding a microphone and grinning as if telling a joke, and an elderly person relaxing in a rocking chair with a content smile, wearing casual retired clothing like a cardigan and slippers. The setting is a cozy living room with a small side table holding a coffee cup and a newspaper with the headline ''Retirement Life.'' The active person looks playful and animated while the retired person appears relaxed and amused. Include light-hearted speech bubbles: the active person says, ''I don''t make jokes about retired people…'' and the retired person happily finishes with, ''…because they don''t work!'' The overall tone is friendly and gentle humor, with bright colors and exaggerated, expressive cartoon faces to emphasize the joke’s playful vibe.'),
 (456, 'Don''t Say It!, Puns, Sports Humor', 'Jokes about bowling aren''t really funny, so I''ll spare you the pain', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a bowling alley with colorful bowling lanes and pins. In the foreground, a character with a friendly, slightly embarrassed expression is holding a bowling ball loosely at their side, shrugging. Above or beside them, a speech bubble says, "Jokes about bowling aren''t really funny, so I''ll spare you the pain." The scene should include pins set up at the end of the lane, a ball return machine, and perhaps a small scoreboard showing a low score. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions, bright colors, and clean lines to emphasize the playful mood without any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (650, 'Driving Humor, Everyday Life, Good Question!, Relatable Humor', 'Why is it that when you''re driving and looking for an address, you turn down the volume on the radio?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the inside of a car with a driver searching for an address. The driver is slightly puzzled, holding a map or looking at a GPS device. The radio in the car is visible with the volume knob turned down low. The car dashboard has clear details, including the steering wheel and radio. Outside the car window, a street sign can be barely seen, indicating the driver is looking for a location. The driver is depicted with an exaggerated confused or concentrated facial expression to emphasize the joke''s theme about turning down the radio volume for better focus when finding an address. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and simple lines, making the scene humorous without any clutter or additional characters.'),
 (3147, 'Driving Humor, Everyday Life, Humor, Unknown', 'You never really learn to swear until you learn to drive.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a learner driver behind the wheel of a small car, looking stressed and frazzled. Around the car, include various amusing symbols representing swearing, like comic-style starburst shapes with symbols like @#$% and exclamation marks floating above the driver''s head. The road should show a few common driving challenges such as a stop sign, a pedestrian crossing, and a tricky turn, emphasizing the difficulty. The car''s dashboard can display a ''Learner'' sign. The setting is a bright, friendly suburban street with some trees and houses in the background. The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated to highlight the frustration and learning process tied to starting to drive and the implied swearing without showing any actual rude language or violence.'),
 (2971, 'Driving Humor, Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown', 'I couldn''t figure out my seat belt, but then it clicked.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a car. The focal point is a person sitting in the driver''s seat looking slightly confused but then having a lightbulb moment. Their hands are fumbling awkwardly with a tangled or badly twisted seat belt strap. The seat belt buckle should be visible but not yet clicked in. Show a small sound effect text near the buckle that says "Click!" to emphasize the pun. The driver’s facial expression should be cartoonishly surprised and pleased. Include typical car interior details like the steering wheel, dashboard, and side window showing a simple outdoor background. Keep the colors bright and the style playful, similar to classic lighthearted comic strips.'),
 (2903, 'Dry Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Happiness is merely the remission of pain.', NULL, 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful stick figure sitting comfortably on a chair with a big smile, labeled ''Happiness.'' Nearby, a sad stick figure with a red face clutching its side in obvious pain is labeled ''Pain.'' Between them is a dotted line with an arrow labeled ''Remission,'' showing the sad figure gradually turning into the happy one as it moves along. The setting is minimalistic, perhaps just a plain white or light background to emphasize the characters and the concept. The happy figure could have little cartoon sparkles or a glow to emphasize joy, while the sad figure has tears or sweat drops. Above the scene is the text: ''Happiness is merely the remission of pain,'' styled as a simple caption. The overall style is light, clear, and playful, highlighting the dry wit of the joke without complexity.'),
 (3142, 'Dry Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Wit', 'You know what I hate? I thought so.', NULL, 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters having a casual conversation. The first character, with an annoyed or frustrated expression, is saying, ''You know what I hate?'' The second character, looking slightly smug or knowing, replies, ''I thought so.'' The setting is informal, like a living room or a park bench. Include minimal background details to keep focus on the interaction—a couch or park bench, a small table with a coffee mug or a simple tree can be included. The style should be clean and exaggerated with expressive faces to emphasize the humor and the punchline''s dry wit. No violent or aggressive gestures; just casual body language like crossed arms for the annoyed character and a slight smirk or raised eyebrow for the other.'),
 (2809, 'Dry Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Drawing on my fine command of language, I said nothing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently with a smug grin, their mouth closed tightly, holding a large fancy book labeled ''Fine Command of Language.'' Around them are floating speech bubbles filled with scribbles to indicate silence. The background is simple and cheerful, with exaggerated sparkles or rays radiating from the person to emphasize their proud silence. The person might be dressed in slightly formal or scholarly attire, like a blazer and glasses, to hint at their command of language, but the focus is on the irony that they are saying nothing. The style is playful and lighthearted, avoiding complexity or harsh expressions.'),
 (457, 'Dyslexics, Good Question!, Word Play', 'If you''re cross-eyed and have dyslexia, can you read all right?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person with noticeably crossed eyes holding a book upside down, squinting and looking confused. The person has a playful, puzzled facial expression as they try to read. Nearby, a small playful character or mascot labeled ''Dyslexia'' is playfully spinning some of the letters floating around the person’s head. The background is a simple cozy room with a bookshelf and a reading lamp, emphasizing the reading context. The tone of the drawing is lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated facial features and cartoonish, swirling letters around the person''s head to indicate confusion caused by both crossed eyes and dyslexia.'),
 (458, 'Dyslexics, Humor, Language, Word Play', 'I went to the doctor and got a prescription for dailysex, but my wife insists it''s for dyslexia', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene in a doctor''s office. Show a slightly confused man sitting on an examination table holding a prescription paper with the word ''dailysex'' clearly printed on it. Nearby, his wife stands with a raised eyebrow, arms crossed, holding a dictionary or book labeled ''dyslexia.'' The doctor, a friendly-looking character wearing a white coat and stethoscope, is smiling awkwardly behind a desk, as if unsure about the mix-up. Include typical doctor office elements like a medical chart on the wall, a window with a sunny sky outside, and a few medical instruments on a nearby table. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the humorous misunderstanding caused by the similar-looking words ''dailysex'' and ''dyslexia.'' No background clutter or anything violent or inappropriate.'),
 (459, 'Dyslexics, Humor, Pirates', 'What does a Dyslexic Pirate Say? RRAAAAAAAAAAA!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a pirate with typical pirate attire: a tricorn hat, eye patch, striped shirt, and a wooden leg. The pirate is standing on a wooden ship deck with the ocean and a bright blue sky in the background. He is shouting ''RRAAAAAAAAAAA!'' very loudly, with exaggerated sound waves coming out of his mouth. Around him are amusing little details: a parrot on his shoulder looking surprised, a treasure chest in the corner, and a pirate flag fluttering above. The pirate''s expression is comically fierce but friendly, showing his enthusiasm in saying his version of a pirate yell. The style should be colorful and playful, with bold outlines and exaggerated expressions to maximize comedic effect. No violence or scary elements, just a funny interpretation of a pirate’s typical shout distorted in a dyslexic way.'),
 (460, 'Dyslexics, Humor, Word Play', 'A dyslexic walks into a bra', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing with one foot halfway into a large, oversized bra hanging in a clothing store or lingerie shop. The person looks puzzled or slightly embarrassed, glancing down at their foot inside the bra cup as if they mistakenly walked into it instead of a door. The background should include clothing racks or shelves with bras and underwear to establish the setting. The style is lighthearted and comical, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the misunderstanding without any negativity or awkwardness.'),
 (461, 'Dyslexics, Humor, Word Play', 'What do the letters D.N.A. stand for? National Dyslexics Association.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of three people standing outside a building labeled ''National Dyslexics Association'' with a big sign that has the letters ''D.N.A.'' prominently displayed. One person looks confused scratching their head, holding a biology book with a DNA double helix on the cover, while another smiles holding a welcome pamphlet labeled ''National Dyslexics Association.'' The building''s facade is playful and colorful, with a banner that reads ''Welcome Dyslexics!'' In the background, a small poster illustrates the double helix structure of DNA but humorously crossed out or replaced with scrambled letters to highlight the dyslexia joke. The style should be light-hearted, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize confusion and humor, using bright, cheerful colors and simple cartoon lines.'),
 (463, 'Dyslexics, Poetry, Word Play', 'A dyslexic poet writes inverse', NULL, 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a poet sitting at a wooden desk cluttered with papers and an ink bottle with a quill. The poet looks quirky and slightly puzzled, wearing round glasses and a beret. The papers around the desk have visibly scrambled or backwards text and poetry lines written in an upside-down or inverse style, with letters and words appearing flipped or reversed. Behind the poet is a wall with a framed picture of a mirror or an inverted poem. The setting is cozy, with a softly lit room, a small stack of poetry books, and a cup of tea nearby. The overall tone is lighthearted and clever, emphasizing a playful mix-up of writing and language without any negativity. The style is a colorful, simple cartoon with exaggerated expression and visual wordplay to illustrate the ''inverse'' nature of the dyslexic poet''s work.'),
 (464, 'Dyslexics, Puns, Word Play', 'They said I''d never be any good at poetry - but so far I''ve made 3 jugs and a vase!', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly quirky person proudly standing in a cozy pottery studio cluttered with shelves. On the shelves are three handmade jugs and a uniquely shaped vase, all colorful and clearly hand-crafted with some whimsical imperfections. The person holds a lump of clay in one hand and a potter’s tool in the other, smiling confidently. Behind them is a chalkboard with the phrase “Poetry Workshop” crossed out and replaced by “Pottery Workshop” to emphasize the wordplay. The overall style is lighthearted and humorous, with exaggerated expressions and bright, inviting colors to capture the pun on ''poetry'' sounding like ''pottery.'','),
 (2256, 'Economic Humor, Finance Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Stocks have reached what looks like a permanently high plateau.', 'Irving Fisher, Professor of Economics, Yale University, 1929.', 'A humorous cartoon showing a wide, flat-topped mountain labeled ''Stock Market Plateau'' with a bunch of tiny cartoon figures wearing business suits happily standing, sitting, and relaxing on top like it’s a summer picnic spot. Below the plateau, rolling hills with jagged upward and downward trends are labeled ''Market Volatility'' but the plateau is completely flat and stable. In the sky, a smiling sun wearing sunglasses beams down, emphasizing the ''permanently high'' aspect. There may be a small sign at the base of the plateau that reads ''Here lies the permanently high plateau.'' The style is colorful and playful, with exaggerated, friendly characters and a lighthearted financial theme.'),
 (2693, 'Economic Humor, Nostalgia, Relatable, Unknown', 'Can anyone remember when the times were not hard, and money not scarce?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a nostalgic older person sitting on a park bench, gazing thoughtfully into the distance with a wistful smile. Around them is a bustling modern cityscape with signs of inflation: a grocery store with high price tags, someone looking stressed checking their empty wallet, and a newspaper headline visible titled ''Times are tough.'' The older person is surrounded by faint ghostly images or thought bubbles showing simpler, happy times with coins overflowing a piggy bank, people happily exchanging cash, and smiling faces. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and caricatured expressions emphasizing the contrast between then and now. The overall mood is nostalgic but funny, capturing the universal feeling of wishing for easier financial times.'),
 (1884, 'Economics Humor, Historical Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'If Karl, instead of writing a lot about capital, had made a lot of it ... it would have been much better.', 'Marx, Karl''s Mother', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Karl Marx sitting at a wooden desk cluttered with thick books and piles of papers labeled ''Capital.'' Karl looks frustrated and exhausted, scratching his head. Next to him, imagine a large, overflowing treasure chest labeled ''Capital'' brimming with gold coins and bills, sparkling brightly. Marx is glancing longingly at the treasure chest while holding a quill pen. The background is a simple study with a chalkboard featuring scribbles about economics. Emphasize exaggerated expressions and a playful, lighthearted style to highlight the joke about writing about capital versus literally making capital (money). Avoid anything dark or serious, to keep it whimsical and funny.'),
 (1658, 'Economics Humor, Irony, Office Humor, Quotes', 'Economics is extremely useful as a form of employment for economists.', 'John Kenneth Galbraith', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an economist character sitting at a desk piled high with charts, graphs, and economics textbooks, looking very busy and serious. Surrounding the economist are typical office objects like a computer, coffee cup, and calculator. Above the economist, a big thought bubble shows a large crowd of economists all working hard in identical cubes or small offices, illustrating the joke that economics jobs mostly exist to employ economists themselves. The scene should have bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated cartoonish features, emphasizing the irony and self-referential humor of the profession sustaining itself. Include humorous details like dollar signs on papers, a framed diploma on the wall, and perhaps another economist walking by holding a briefcase labeled "Economist''s Employment." The overall mood is light, funny, and ironic without any negativity.'),
 (1534, 'Economics Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'An economist is an expert who will know tomorrow why the things he predicted yesterday didn''t happen today.', 'Laurence J. Peter', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky-looking economist standing at a simple wooden desk cluttered with papers, graphs, and charts. The economist is scratching his head with a confused but confident smile, wearing round glasses and a loosely tied necktie. Behind him is a chalkboard or whiteboard filled with complicated economic graphs and arrows that zigzag unpredictably. A calendar hangs on the wall showing yesterday, today, and tomorrow with exaggerated dates clearly labeled. Thought bubbles float above his head—one bubble shows him confidently making a prediction yesterday, another shows a surprised reaction today as the prediction fails, and a third bubble shows him tomorrow confidently explaining why the prediction didn''t happen. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the irony and humor in economic predictions often missing the mark but sounding knowledgeable afterward. No people or objects outside this office scene are needed.'),
 (465, 'Economics Humor, Life, Word Play', 'The cost of living hasn''t affected its popularity.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a lively marketplace stall labeled ''Cost of Living''. The stall is packed with colorful items like fresh fruit, vegetables, bread, and household goods, all with price tags. Around the stall, joyful cartoon people crowd happily, clearly unfazed and very interested. Above the stall, a big sign reads ''Cost of Living'' but there are also little balloons or stickers indicating ''Popular!'' and ''Loved by All''. The expressions on the people’s faces show excitement or delight, indicating that despite rising prices shown by exaggerated, comically high price tags, the popularity or interest in the market stall stays strong. The style should be light, cheerful, and whimsical to reflect the joke’s irony, emphasizing the contrast between the high cost and the continued popularity without any negativity or stress.'),
 (1861, 'Economics Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Idealism is fine, but as is approaches reality the cost becomes prohibitive.', 'William F. Buckley, Jr.', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing next to each other. The first is a dreamily idealistic person wearing a light-colored outfit with a halo or soft glow around their head, symbolizing idealism. They are holding a large, colorful thought bubble above their head filled with bright, perfect images like hearts, rainbows, and peace signs. The second character is more practical, dressed in business casual with a calculator and clipboard in hand, showing a stressed or concerned expression while looking at an exaggerated, huge bill or invoice titled ''Reality Costs.'' Between them is a scale tipping heavily towards the side with the huge, mountainous stack of coins and bills labeled ''Costs,'' while the side with the idealism symbols is very light. The background includes a simple office or home setting to suggest everyday life, and subtle funny details like a calendar showing a due date or a ''budget'' poster humorously highlighting the challenge of turning dreams into reality. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between flying idealism and harsh reality costs without any negative or sensitive elements.'),
 (1598, 'Economics Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Capitalism is the astounding belief that the most wickedest of men will do the most wickedest of things for the greatest good of everyone.', 'Keynes', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a classical, slightly exaggerated caricature of a wealthy businessman with a sly, cunning smile. He is dressed in a sharp suit with a top hat and monocle, holding a bag labeled with a dollar sign. Around him are several ordinary, diverse citizens looking hopeful but puzzled. In the background, a large scale or balance is tipping unevenly, symbolizing imbalance. The businessman is standing on one side atop the scale, while a crowd representing ''everyone'' is on the other side at the bottom, struggling but hopeful. The setting is an old-fashioned town square, with buildings symbolizing banks and factories. Add a whimsical banner above that reads: “Capitalism’s Astonishing Faith” in playful lettering. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between the businessman’s greed and the citizens’ hopeful expressions without any malice.'),
 (2314, 'Economics Humor, Politics, Quotes, Satire', 'The government deficit is the difference between the amount of money the government spends and the amount it has the nerve to collect.', 'Sam Ewing', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, cartoonish government building with a big sign labeled ''Government'' on top. In front of the building, a character dressed as a sly, confident government official stands holding two large sacks: one overflowing with money labeled ''Spending'' and the other very small and almost empty labeled ''Tax Collection.'' The official has a cheeky smirk and raised eyebrow, as if daring or mocking. Around the official are piles of bills and coins scattered on the ground to emphasize the spending. A large, exaggerated arrow connects the big sack to the small sack with a visible gap between them clearly labeled ''Deficit.'' The background should be simple and bright, with a globe or national flag in the distance to suggest government context, drawn in a playful, cartoon style to emphasize the joke''s humorous critique of fiscal policy. No people appear distressed, just the single confident official, making the scene lighthearted and clever.'),
 (2502, 'Economics Humor, Politics, Quotes, Satire', 'Unquestionably, there is progress. The average American now pays out twice as much in taxes as he formerly got in wages.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused American worker looking at two large jars on a table. The jar labeled ''Taxes'' is brimming and overflowing with coins and bills, while the jar labeled ''Wages'' is almost empty with just a few coins. The worker, dressed in casual office clothes, scratches his head in disbelief. In the background, a calendar on the wall shows the current year to emphasize ''progress.'' The setting is a simple, comical office breakroom, with a coffee machine and a bulletin board with tax notices pinned up. The style is light-hearted, using exaggerated expressions and bright, simple colors to emphasize the irony of the worker paying more in taxes than earning in wages, creating a visual pun on financial ''progress.'' No negativity or distress should be shown, only comedic bewilderment.'),
 (1954, 'Economics Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Inflation is not all bad. After all, it has allowed every American to live in a more expensive neighborhood without moving.', 'Senator Alan Cranston', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an ordinary American family standing happily outside their house. The house looks the same but a street sign nearby changes from ''Affordable Lane'' to ''Expensive Neighborhood Blvd.'' The background depicts a typical suburban setting with other houses, trees, and a mailbox. The family members (parents and two children) have smiling, slightly exaggerated cartoon faces and are dressed casually. A speech bubble above the father says, "We didn’t move, but our neighborhood sure did!" The scene highlights the irony of inflation making homes pricier without physically moving. The color palette is bright and cheerful, emphasizing the joke''s lighthearted tone.'),
 (2758, 'Economics Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Despite inflation, the wages of sin are still the same.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, old-fashioned bank teller booth labeled ''Wages of Sin Bank.'' Behind the counter, a grumpy, cartoonish devil dressed in a suit with little horns and a tail is handing a paycheck to a surprised human character dressed in everyday clothes. The paycheck clearly reads ''$0'' or ''Same as Always.'' To the side, there is a price tag attached to a loaf of bread or a carton of milk showing a big price increase, representing inflation. The background has a simple street scene with a billboard that says ''Inflation on the rise!'' The overall style is colorful and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between rising prices and the unchanging ''wages of sin.'' The human looks puzzled while the devil looks indifferent or slightly annoyed, enhancing the joke’s irony and humor without any threatening or negative elements.'),
 (2036, 'Education Humor, Equality Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'Let the revolting distinction of rich and poor disappear once and for all, the distinction of great and small, of masters and valets, of governors and governed. Let there be no other difference between human beings than those of age and sex. Since all have the same needs and the same faculties, let there be one education for all, one food for all.', 'Francois Noel Babeuf', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a mix of people from various social classes humorously blended together in a chaotic classroom setting. The classroom is filled with an eclectic group: a stereotypical rich person in top hat and monocle, a poor person in tattered clothes, a governor wearing a sash, and a valet holding a silver tray. They all sit at identical desks, sharing the exact same plain bowl of food and identical books titled ''One Education for All.'' The room is lively, with a big chalkboard behind the teacher showing simplified phrases like ''No More Divisions!'' and ''Equality Rules!'' An elderly man and a young child—representing age differences—sit side by side, alongside male and female figures. Emphasize lighthearted expressions of surprise, confusion, and camaraderie on their faces. The setting is bright, with a comical school atmosphere and subtle visual contrasts that play on social stereotypes blending into one unified group. The overall tone is playful and optimistic, illustrating the joke’s call for equal treatment in a multicultural, multi-classroom environment without any harsh or negative imagery.'),
 (466, 'Education Humor, Exaggeration, Relatable', 'Trying to get an education here is like trying to take a drink from a fire hose.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a student sitting at a desk inside a classroom. The student looks overwhelmed, wide-eyed, and struggling to drink water from a gigantic fire hose that is blasting out a powerful stream of water directly at their open mouth. The water splashes everywhere, drenching the student and their books on the desk. The classroom background should include a chalkboard with some simple math or notes, a few scattered textbooks and papers flying from the impact of the water, and perhaps a small clock on the wall. The student wears casual school clothes and has exaggerated cartoon features expressing shock and being overloaded. The overall style is bright and goofy, emphasizing the absurdity of trying to ''drink'' from such an intense source, visually representing the phrase''s meaning about overwhelming education.'),
 (2681, 'Education Humor, Grammar Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Bob''s Rule of Grammar: Double negatives are a no-no.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a character named Bob standing by a whiteboard or chalkboard in a classroom setting. Bob is middle-aged, wearing glasses and a casual shirt, pointing at the whiteboard with a pointer stick. On the board is written in big, bold letters: "Double negatives are a no-no." Around Bob are a few confused students or characters scratching their heads or looking puzzled. Near Bob’s feet, there is a humorous visual of a speech bubble containing a sentence like: "I don''t need no help," which is crossed out with a big red X. The classroom has typical school elements like desks, books, a globe, and a poster labeled “Grammar Rules.” The overall style is bright, clean cartoon with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and lightheartedness of the grammar rule being stressed.'),
 (1938, 'Education Humor, Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'In a completely rational society the best of us would aspire to be teachers, and the rest of us aspire to something less.', 'Lee Iacocca', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, cheerful classroom. In the center stands a proud, confident teacher at a podium or desk, looking noble and wise, wearing a classic teacher’s outfit with glasses and holding a book or pointer. Around the teacher, a group of diverse, ordinary-looking people look slightly jealous or resigned, standing or sitting a little apart, each with thought bubbles showing various less prestigious professions or hobbies (such as a couch potato watching TV, a person holding a fast food tray, someone napping, or playing video games). The classroom background includes a chalkboard with a motivational quote about teachers written in playful handwriting. The overall tone should be lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the idea that aspiring to be a teacher is the “best” goal in a rational society, while others aim lower. Use bright, inviting colors and exaggerated expressions to heighten the cartoonish humor without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (1459, 'Education Humor, Humor, Quotes', 'A professor is someone who talks in someone else''s sleep.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a bedroom where a person is asleep in bed, looking peaceful with closed eyes and a slight smile. Standing next to the bed is a professor character: an older man with glasses, messy hair, and a tweed jacket with elbow patches. The professor is animatedly speaking, with a speech bubble coming from his mouth showing complex words or scientific symbols, indicating he is delivering a lecture. The professor looks confident and unaware of disturbing the sleeper. The room should have typical bedroom elements: a nightstand with a lamp, a book or two, and maybe a clock showing late night hours. The style should be colorful, light-hearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the professor''s big talk compared to the silent sleeper. The contrast between the calm, sleeping person and the talkative professor creates the humor visually.'),
 (1682, 'Education Humor, Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Examinations are formidable even to the best prepared, for the greatest fool may ask more than the wisest man can answer.', 'Charles Caleb Colton', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classic exam hall with rows of desks and students visibly stressed or confused. The central figure is a wise-looking man wearing round glasses and a thoughtful expression, sitting at a desk filled with books and papers, looking overwhelmed and scratching his head. Opposite him, a mischievous-looking fool, wearing a jester hat and goofy smile, confidently raises his hand holding a ridiculously exaggerated, complicated exam question on a paper. Around them, other students show reactions of surprise or frustration. The background includes a large chalkboard with the words ''Examinations'' and some complex formulas doodled humorously. The overall tone is lighthearted, emphasizing the irony of difficult questions challenging even the wisest, drawn in a colorful, cartoonish style with exaggerated expressions and comedic elements like question marks floating above heads.'),
 (1610, 'Education Humor, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Copy from one, it''s plagiarism; copy from two, it''s research.', 'Wilson Mizner (1876-1933)', 'A humorous cartoon scene with two characters sitting at desks side by side, each using a laptop. The first person is suspiciously glancing over at the second person’s screen, labeled ''Copy from one, it’s plagiarism.'' The second person is confidently pointing to multiple open books and research papers scattered around their desk, with a thought bubble saying, ''Copy from two, it’s research.'' Around them, comic-style text emphasizes the punchline with playful lettering. The setting is a lighthearted, colorful office or study room with minimal clutter, perhaps a small coffee mug or potted plant to add charm. Both characters should have exaggerated expressions—one confused and wary, the other smug and self-assured—to highlight the joke’s contrast in perspective. The overall tone is friendly and whimsical, with clear visual cues to the ideas of copying, plagiarism, and research in a non-threatening, funny way.'),
 (2298, 'Education Humor, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'The difference between science and the fuzzy subjects is that science requires reasoning while those other subjects merely require scholarship.', 'Robert A. Heinlein', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a school classroom split into two halves. On one side, labeled ''Science,'' a confident student wearing round glasses is enthusiastically working through a complex equation on a chalkboard filled with scientific symbols and graphs. The classroom decor includes beakers, a microscope, and a periodic table poster. On the other side, labeled ''Fuzzy Subjects,'' a relaxed student is lounging back in a chair reading a large, thick book titled ''Scholarship 101,'' with piles of books stacked around them. This side has soft, colorful cushions and a poster that reads ''Just Memorize!'' Both students have exaggerated expressions—the science student focused and intense, the fuzzy subjects student calm and carefree. The teacher, standing in the middle, holds a pointer and has a playful smirk, emphasizing the contrast. The overall style is vibrant and cartoonish, highlighting the humorous contrast between reasoning and mere memorization.'),
 (1470, 'Education Humor, Inspirational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'A teacher affects eternity; he can never tell, where his influence stops.', 'Henry Brooks Adams', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom where a friendly-looking teacher stands at the front with an open book in one hand and a glowing aura or light surrounding them to hint at their ''eternal'' influence. The classroom around them appears normal but subtly transitions to different time periods or ages. For example, on the left, younger students attentively listen while on the right, older students or even adults in modern or future attire receive knowledge from ghostly images or thought bubbles representing the teacher''s influence extending far beyond the room and time. The blackboard behind the teacher displays a simple inspirational quote: ''Where does influence end?''. The overall style is bright and colorful, emphasizing the timeless impact of teaching in a lighthearted, imaginative way without any negativity or harshness. Include elements such as desks, books, a globe, and a clock to represent the passage of time humorously flowing from past to future in the same image.'),
 (2055, 'Education Humor, Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Logic: The art of thinking and reasoning in strict accordance with the limitations and incapacities of the human misunderstanding.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a character sitting at a desk looking confused and deep in thought. The character is scratching their head while staring at a large open book labeled ''Logic for Beginners.'' Behind them, a blackboard displays a comically complicated flowchart full of nonsensical symbols and question marks, showing the complexity and confusion of logic. Nearby, thought bubbles float above the character''s head, containing funny images like a tangled knot, a broken puzzle piece, and a cartoon brain with a bandage, symbolizing ''human misunderstanding.'' The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the irony of trying to apply strict logic to imperfect human reasoning. The background is a simple home or classroom setting with a few scattered papers on the floor and a clock showing time passing to suggest prolonged contemplation.'),
 (1373, 'Education Humor, Kids Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'A child can never ask too many questions.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a curious child with wide eyes and a big smile, surrounded by a flurry of large, floating question marks of various sizes and colors. The child is seated at a small desk with an open book and a pencil, eagerly raising one hand as if about to ask yet another question. Around the child, a few speech bubbles contain simple question words like ''Why?'', ''How?'', and ''What?''. The background is bright and cheerful, possibly inside a classroom or a cozy home study area filled with bookshelves and educational posters. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing endless curiosity without frustration.'),
 (2957, 'Education Humor, Language, Unknown, Word Play', 'I am. is the shortest complete sentence in the English language.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large open book labeled ''English Language'' resting on a wooden desk. Above the book, a smiling, anthropomorphic speech bubble proudly displays the phrase ''I am.'' in big, bold letters. Around the desk, various other oversized, incomplete sentence fragments float confused or surprised, with question marks above their heads. The background is a cozy, light-filled study room with a quirky grammar poster on the wall that says ''Shortest Complete Sentence Contest.'' The overall tone is cheerful and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions on the speech bubble and sentence fragments to emphasize the joke about sentence structure.'),
 (1746, 'Education Humor, Life, Quotes, Wisdom', 'He who asks is a fool for five minutes, but he who does not ask remains a fool forever.', 'Chinese Saying', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, simple classroom or library. In the foreground, a curious person (a young adult or student) is shown raising their hand eagerly with a confused but hopeful expression on their face. Nearby, a teacher or wise older character looks approachable and encouraging, ready to answer questions. In the background, a second person sits slouched with crossed arms and a stubborn or sulky look, ignoring the chance to ask anything. Above the scene, a lightbulb is turning on above the eager person''s head, symbolizing gaining knowledge, while the other person has a tiny question mark hovering over their head, showing lingering confusion. The setting includes bookshelves, a chalkboard with a simple question mark drawn on it, and a clock showing a short span of time passing to illustrate the phrase ''five minutes.'' The overall tone is bright and friendly with playful exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor in the idea that a brief moment of foolishness (asking) leads to wisdom, whereas silence keeps one foolish forever. The style is bold line cartoon with bright colors and clear, expressive characters, perfect for a lighthearted motivational comic.'),
 (2947, 'Education Humor, Math Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'How many times can you subtract 10 from 100? Just once. The next time you would be subtracting 10 from 90.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, colorful number 100 with eyes and a surprised expression standing on the left side of the image. Next to it is a big friendly hand holding a giant eraser labeled ''-10''. The hand is playfully rubbing away the ''100'', transforming it into ''90''. A confused cartoon character, looking like a student or math learner with glasses and a puzzled look, stands to the right, scratching their head as they watch the transformation. Above them, a speech bubble from the character says, ''How many times can you subtract 10 from 100?'' Below, another bubble from an off-stage voice or wise-looking character answers, ''Just once. The next time you’d be subtracting 10 from 90.'' The background is a simple classroom setting with a blackboard showing ''100 - 10 = ?'', a few math symbols floating, and a lighthearted, bright color scheme to emphasize the joke’s light and clever nature.'),
 (1955, 'Education Humor, Metaphor Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Information is pretty thin stuff unless mixed with experience.', 'Clarence Day', 'A humorous cartoon showing a scientist or professor standing in front of a large, old-fashioned printing press labeled ''Information.'' The press is creating very thin, transparent sheets of paper labeled ''Info.'' Next to the press is a comical contraption called the ''Experience Mixer'' where a cheerful worker or character is adding colorful, lively objects like clocks, footprints, books, and light bulbs into a big bubbling cauldron marked ''Experience.'' Out of the mixer comes thick, vibrant books or stacks of papers glowing with energy, labeled ''Information + Experience.'' The scene is light-hearted with exaggerated, rounded cartoon figures and bright colors, emphasizing the transformation from thin, dull sheets into substantial, rich materials. Background includes a chalkboard with a simple diagram illustrating thin info turning into thick knowledge after mixing with experience.'),
 (1712, 'Education Humor, Metaphor Humor, Quotes', 'Genius without education is like silver in the mine.', 'Ben Franklin', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful miner deep inside a dark underground mine holding a shiny silver nugget. The miner wears a hard hat with a headlamp and looks excited holding the silver in one hand. Nearby, a brightly drawn glowing silver bar, labeled ''Genius,'' rests partially buried in the rocky walls of the mine, yet untouched and unnoticed. Above the scene, a thought bubble shows a graduation cap and diploma to represent education. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the contrast between raw talent (the silver) and the need for education to bring it out.'),
 (1579, 'Education Humor, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Be curious always! Knowledge will not acquire you; you must acquire it.', 'Sudie Back', 'A humorous cartoon scene shows a curious person standing in front of an oversized, anthropomorphic book with arms and legs. The book looks lively and a bit shy, hesitating to jump into the person''s open arms. The person, with a wide-eyed, eager expression, leans forward with outstretched arms, as if trying to catch the book. Around them, floating icons like question marks, light bulbs, and small gears emphasize curiosity and thinking. The background includes a simple library or study room setting with bookshelves filled with various colorful books to add context. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated, friendly expressions on both the person and the book to represent the idea that knowledge won’t come on its own; it must be actively sought and embraced.'),
 (1748, 'Education Humor, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'He who has imagination without learning has wings but no feet.', 'Joubert', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a whimsical character with large, colorful wings on their back but missing feet, instead hovering a few inches above the ground. The character looks excited and imaginative, maybe grinning widely with sparkling eyes. Around them, depict floating books and scrolls that are closed or drifting away just out of reach, symbolizing the absence of learning. The background should be bright and simple, like a clear sky with a few fluffy clouds, reinforcing the idea of flight and imagination. Include a signpost on the ground labeled ''Learning'' pointing firmly to the ground beneath the character’s invisible feet, indicating that without learning, they lack stable footing. The style is cartoonish and playful, with exaggerated expressions and soft, colorful lines to enhance the lighthearted tone without any dark or serious elements.'),
 (2323, 'Education Humor, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The illiterate of the 21st century will not be those who cannot read and write, but those who cannot learn, unlearn, and relearn.', 'Alvin Toffler', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a modern classroom or office with a quirky twist. In the center, a cheerful teacher or mentor is pointing to a large whiteboard with three big words written in bright colors: LEARN, UNLEARN, RELEARN. Around the teacher, diverse cartoon characters look either confused, curious, or overwhelmed, holding books and tablets. One character has a stack of books labeled ''Old Knowledge'' slipping from their hands, symbolizing unlearning. Another character excitedly writes on a digital tablet, showing enthusiasm for relearning. The background includes silly details like a pile of textbooks with cobwebs, a recycling bin labeled ''Old Ideas Only,'' and a lightbulb overhead flickering on and off, portraying the mental process of changing one''s mindset. The style should be light, colorful, and playful, emphasizing the abstract concept of adapting to change rather than traditional reading or writing. The overall tone is optimistic and funny, showing learning as an ongoing, sometimes confusing journey.'),
 (1784, 'Education Humor, Office Humor, Quotes, Writing Humor', 'I am returning this otherwise good typing paper to you because someone has printed gibberish all over it and put your name at the top.', 'English Professor Ohio University', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person holding up a sheet of typing paper with messy, nonsensical squiggles and random symbols covering the page instead of typed words. At the top of the page is a clearly written name tag or header with the owner''s name. The person stands at a desk cluttered with typical office or school items: a computer keyboard, a few scattered pens, and a coffee mug. Their expression is a mix of annoyance and disbelief, eyebrows raised and eyes wide, looking at the paper as if saying, ''What is this?'' The background is simple and light to keep the focus on the character and the paper. The style is a clean, exaggerated cartoon with bold lines and bright colors to emphasize the humor without any harsh or negative tone.'),
 (1660, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes', 'Education makes a people easy to lead, but difficult to drive; easy to govern but impossible to enslave.', 'Baron Henry Peter Brougham', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two different modes of transport depicted as metaphors for people. On one side, show a group of simple, cartoonish people shaped like uniform cars parked in a neat row, easily driven by a calm, smiling driver holding a steering wheel labeled ''Control.'' On the other side, illustrate a group of diverse, animated people shaped like autonomous, self-driving cars with light bulbs above their heads to symbolize education and awareness. These educated cars are confidently steering themselves on a winding road, looking thoughtful and determined. A friendly figure resembling a government official or leader stands between the two groups, scratching their head and trying to decide which group to interact with. Include a signpost with two arrows: one pointing to a smooth, straight road labeled ''Easy to Lead'' and the other to a rocky, uphill path labeled ''Impossible to Enslave.'' Make the setting bright and colorful with simple backgrounds like trees and clouds to keep it lighthearted and cartoonish, focusing on the contrast between being driven and driving oneself metaphorically representing control and freedom through education.'),
 (1535, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'An education isn''t how much you have committed to memory, or even how much you know. It''s being able to differentiate between what you do know and what you don''t.', 'Anatole France', 'Draw a humorous cartoon-style classroom scene. In the center, a friendly-looking teacher is standing by a blackboard with a thoughtful, slightly amused expression. The blackboard features a simple phrase written clearly: ''Education = Knowing what you know AND what you don''t know.'' Around the teacher are a few students sitting at desks, some looking confident, others scratching their heads in confusion, symbolizing the mix of knowledge and uncertainty. Above the scene, a large thought bubble shows a person juggling two symbols: a bright light bulb (representing what they know) and a question mark (representing what they don’t know). The style is light-hearted and fun, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the message without any complexity or seriousness. The room has typical classroom elements: desks, chairs, posters on the walls, and books lying around, reinforcing the educational atmosphere.'),
 (1390, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'A diploma proves only that you know how to find an answer.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a proud graduate standing next to a large diploma hanging on a wall. The graduate wears a cap and gown but looks a bit puzzled or contemplative rather than celebratory. The diploma is oversized with the words ''Diploma'' prominently displayed, but instead of traditional ornate text, it has a funny note below that reads ''Proof you know how to find an answer.'' Nearby, show a thought bubble above the graduate’s head containing a magnifying glass hovering over a large complicated maze or puzzle, symbolizing the search for answers. Add a few books or a laptop open with question marks floating above it to emphasize problem-solving and research rather than detailed knowledge. The background can be a simple graduation hall or a classroom to keep the academic context clear. Make the overall style lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect, emphasizing the irony that a diploma doesn''t necessarily prove knowledge but the skill to find answers.'),
 (1400, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'A fool''s brain digests philosophy into folly, science into superstition, and art into pedantry. Hence University education.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a whimsical university lecture hall. The central figure is a clueless, exaggeratedly silly student with a dazed expression, sitting at a desk with scattered books labeled Philosophy, Science, and Art. Above his head are three thought bubbles: one shows a tangled mess turning a deep philosophical book into a silly joke; the second bubble turns a detailed science textbook into a superstition superstition symbol (like a rabbit''s foot or a horseshoe); and the third bubble shows an art book transforming into a dictatorial professor pointing at tiny, nitpicky details, symbolizing pedantry. In the background, a chalkboard reads “University Education” ironically. Other students nearby look bored or confused, adding to the comedic tone. The art style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and caricatured characters, emphasizing a lighthearted satire of higher education turning complex subjects into distorted versions that cause folly, superstition, and pedantry.'),
 (1659, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Education is a method whereby one acquires a higher grade of prejudices.', 'Laurence J. Peter', 'A humorous cartoon classroom scene. In the center, a teacher with a slightly sarcastic, knowing smile holds an oversized, old-fashioned textbook titled ''Education.'' Around the teacher are several diverse students sitting at desks, each with exaggerated thought bubbles above their heads filled with stereotypical or silly symbols (like tiny blindfolded eyes, colored glasses, or simple symbols representing biases such as a small brain with a lock). The classroom walls have posters featuring a scale titled ''Knowledge vs. Prejudice'' tipping heavily toward ''Prejudice.'' The blackboard behind the teacher displays the phrase, ''Education: Acquiring Higher Grades of Prejudices'' in playful, bold chalk writing. The atmosphere is light and funny, emphasizing the ironic twist that education doesn''t necessarily reduce prejudice but sometimes transforms or complicates it. Bright colors, clear facial expressions, and exaggerated features should enhance the cartoonish humor without any negativity or offense.'),
 (1765, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.', 'H. G. Weels', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a large race track shaped like an infinity loop to symbolize ongoing history. On one side of the track, a tall stack of colorful books and a graduation cap represent education. On the opposite side, a chaotic pile of disasters such as a tiny erupting volcano, a cracked Earth, small storm clouds, and a ticking bomb with a countdown timer represent catastrophe. Show these two elements as anthropomorphic characters with arms and legs, racing each other on the track. The education character could be wearing glasses and holding a diploma, while the catastrophe character looks frantic and messy. In the background, include a crowd of tiny cheering people holding banners of hope and worry. The style should be bright, cartoonish, and light-hearted, emphasizing the competition between learning and disaster without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2399, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The truth is not simply what you think it is; it is also the circumstances in which it is said, and to whom, why and how it is said.', 'Vaclav Havel', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a wise-looking person, dressed as a philosopher with a toga and laurel wreath, standing in front of a classroom blackboard. The blackboard is filled with a complicated diagram full of arrows, question marks, and quotes illustrating "truth" factors: ''who,'' ''when,'' ''where,'' ''how,'' and ''why.'' The philosopher holds a pointer stick directed at the blackboard with a slightly amused, thoughtful expression. Around the room, diverse cartoon students scratch their heads or exchange bewildered looks, emphasizing the complexity of understanding truth. The setting is a classical-style lecture hall with columns and a bust of Socrates on a pedestal in the corner. The overall tone is lighthearted and educational, with exaggerated expressions and simple lines to give it a fun, cartoonish feel.'),
 (1661, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Education: That which discloses to the wise and disguises from the foolish their lack of understanding.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a classroom setting. On the left, a wise-looking person, perhaps wearing glasses and a graduation cap, is thoughtfully holding an open book titled ''Education.'' They have a confident and enlightened expression. On the right, a foolish-looking character with a confused face, scratching their head, is surrounded by question marks and broken pieces of a mask labeled ''Understanding'' hovering near them, symbolizing ignorance being hidden. The classroom includes a chalkboard with the words ''Education: Reveals to the wise, hides from the foolish'' written on it in a playful font. The style should be lighthearted and caricatured to emphasize the contrast between wisdom and foolishness, with bright, simple colors and exaggerated expressions for comedic effect. Include a small desk with a lamp and a stack of books nearby to emphasize the educational setting, and a window showing a sunny day outside to keep the mood cheerful.'),
 (1819, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'I have never let my schooling interfere with my education.', 'Mark Twain (1835-1910)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a casual, laid-back student sitting outdoors under a large tree, reading a book titled ''Life Lessons.'' The student wears casual clothes, maybe a t-shirt and jeans, looking relaxed and slightly mischievous with a smirk. Nearby, in the background, a traditional school building with a bell tower and a chalkboard with complicated math and history notes can be seen, with the word ''Schooling'' labeled above it. The student’s speech bubble says, ''I have never let my schooling interfere with my education.'' Around the student are objects representing informal learning: a globe, a magnifying glass, a paintbrush, a small pile of novels, and a nature guidebook. The overall tone is playful and light, with bright colors and exaggerated, cartoonish expressions emphasizing the contrast between formal schooling and real education. No violent, sexual, or political elements should be included.'),
 (1899, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'If you can''t explain it simply, you don''t understand it well enough.', 'A. Einstein', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a teacher standing in front of a chalkboard filled with an overly complicated, tangled web of equations, diagrams, and confusing symbols. The teacher looks frazzled and scratching their head. In the foreground, a student holds a simple flashcard with a very clear and straightforward explanation written on it. The contrast emphasizes the complicated versus the simple. The classroom has typical elements like desks, books, and a globe, but the focus is on the stark difference between the complex board and the student''s simple note. The overall vibe is light-hearted and playful, highlighting the idea that true understanding means simplicity in explanation.'),
 (2033, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Learning is finding out what you already know.', 'Richard Back', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a student sitting at a desk with an open book titled ''Knowledge.'' The student has a surprised yet amused expression as a large glowing light bulb floats above their head symbolizing a sudden realization. Floating around the light bulb are small icons like question marks, exclamation points, and tiny books flying like birds, representing the discovery and recall of knowledge. The background is a simple classroom or library with shelves of books and a chalkboard showing the phrase ''Learning = Finding out what you already know'' written in playful handwriting. The overall style is light, bright, and comical, with exaggerated expressions and whimsical floating objects to emphasize the irony and wit of the joke without any people appearing stressed or confused.'),
 (2074, 'Education Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Make everything as simple as possible, but not simpler.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a bright, minimalistic classroom or office. At the center, a wise-looking professor or teacher, with slightly exaggerated features like big glasses and a thoughtful expression, stands next to a large blackboard or whiteboard. On the board, the phrase ''Make everything as simple as possible, but not simpler.'' is written in neat handwriting. The teacher holds a pointer or chalk and looks proudly at the quote. Around the teacher, various humorous items or props emphasize the meaning: a cluttered, chaotic desk with papers and gadgets overflowing on one side, and on the other side, a perfectly neat and simple desk with just one pencil and notebook. In the background, a student or assistant looks confused or puzzled, scratching their head as they try to figure out the boundary between simple and simpler. The overall tone is light-hearted, witty, and educational, with soft colors and playful cartoon style to highlight the smile-worthy philosophical advice without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (1404, 'Education Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A good angle to approach any problem is the try-angle.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a character standing next to a giant, exaggeratedly large protractor shaped like a smiling triangle. The character, with a lightbulb above their head to show an idea, is pointing at the protractor labeled ''Try-Angle.'' Around them, scattered papers with doodles of angles and problem-solving symbols (like question marks and lightbulbs) emphasize the concept of approaching problems. The background is a simple office or classroom setting with a whiteboard showing a few basic geometric shapes and motivational sticky notes reading ''Keep Trying!'' and ''Angle of Success.'' The style is bright, colorful, and playful to highlight the pun and cleverness of the phrase.'),
 (3162, 'Education Humor, Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'I was going to tell a joke about sodium, but then I thought ''Na - nobody will get it''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a chemistry classroom or lab. In the center is a friendly-looking, animated sodium element character (an anthropomorphic letter ''Na'' with eyes, arms, and a big smile), standing next to a large chalkboard. On the chalkboard is written the phrase ''I was going to tell a joke about sodium, but then I thought ''Na - nobody will get it''''. The sodium character looks playful and cheeky, with one hand raised as if about to speak, but the other hand raised in a ''stop'' gesture. Around the character, a few students or cartoon people look puzzled or shrugging to emphasize that the joke might be missed. The background includes typical chemistry classroom elements like beakers, test tubes, and periodic table posters to set the scene. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and clearly in a cartoon/comic style with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor.'),
 (1446, 'Education Humor, Puns, Quotes, Science Humor', 'A mathematician is a machine for converting coffee into theorems.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a mathematician sitting at a cluttered desk covered with coffee cups, scattered papers filled with mathematical formulas, and a computer or chalkboard displaying equations. The mathematician should look focused yet a bit sleep-deprived, holding a steaming cup of coffee. Nearby, a comical coffee machine with a label reading ''Theorem Converter 3000'' is connected by pipes or tubes to the mathematician''s brain, with coffee entering the machine and papers with finished theorems emerging from the other side. The setting should be a cozy, slightly messy study room with bookshelves and mathematical symbols floating humorously around. Use exaggerated cartoon style to emphasize the humorous concept of coffee transforming into complex ideas.'),
 (2602, 'Education Humor, Puns, Quotes, Science Humor', 'You can pay attention to the fact, in which case you''ll probably become a mathematician, or you can ignore it, in which case you''ll probably become a physicist.', 'Dr. Len Evans', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels side by side. On the left panel, depict a person sitting at a desk surrounded by math books, formulas on a chalkboard behind them, and looking very focused with a pencil in hand. The setting should look like a typical math classroom or study room with numbers and equations floating around. On the right panel, show another person casually dressed and relaxed, leaning back on a chair with a telescope pointing at the stars outside a window, some physics books scattered around, and a playful expression as if ignoring the complicated math. Make the style colorful, whimsical, and light-hearted, emphasizing the contrast between focused attention (mathematician) and casual ignorance (physicist) in a friendly, funny way. Include subtle visual exaggerations like oversized glasses on the mathematician and a dreamy look on the physicist to enhance the humor.'),
 (1638, 'Education Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Do not worry about your difficulties in Mathematics. I can assure you mine are still greater.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a classroom. At the front of the room, a friendly teacher with a slightly exaggerated worried expression stands by a blackboard full of complicated math equations, some comically large and confusing with question marks and symbols like square roots, fractions, and integrals. The teacher is holding a piece of chalk and shrugging his shoulders, conveying the feeling of being equally confused or challenged. In the classroom, a few students sit at desks, looking relieved or amused to hear this, some with raised eyebrows or slight smiles. The background should include typical classroom details: a large window with sunlight, a wall clock, and posters related to math (like multiplication tables or geometry shapes). The art style should be bright and playful, with clean lines and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize humor and lightheartedness without any hint of negativity or embarrassment.'),
 (2026, 'Education Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Knowledge is of two kinds. We know a subject ourselves, or we know where we can find information on it.', 'Samuel, Dr. Johnson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a library. On the left, a confident person is holding an open book and proudly pointing to themselves, representing ''knowing a subject ourselves.'' On the right, another character is holding a large map or a giant index card labeled ''INFORMATION'' with a big magnifying glass, looking curious and slightly confused, representing ''knowing where to find information.'' The background is filled with tall bookshelves, some labeled with various subjects like Science, History, and Art. Above them, a playful banner reads ''Knowledge: Two Kinds!'' The style is lighthearted with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the humor without any violent or inappropriate elements.'),
 (2478, 'Education Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'To repeat what others have said, requires education; to challenge it, requires brains.', 'Mary Pettibone Poole', 'A humorous cartoon scene in a simple classroom or lecture hall setting. The room should have a blackboard or whiteboard at the front with the phrase ''To repeat what others have said requires education; to challenge it requires brains'' written on it in playful handwriting. In the foreground, a student with a thoughtful expression is standing with one hand on their chin, looking confident and intelligent. Behind them, a few other students are seated, one with a textbook open looking puzzled or just repeating aloud from the book. Add some academic props such as notebooks, books, and a globe or a lightbulb above the thoughtful student''s head to emphasize the ''brains'' concept. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor, and bright, cheerful colors. Avoid any complexity; keep the focus on the interaction between repeating and thinking intelligently to visually represent the joke’s meaning.'),
 (2587, 'Education Humor, Quotes, Wit, Word Play', 'Wit is educated insolence.', 'Aristotle (284-322 B.C.)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person dressed in formal academic attire, such as a graduation gown and mortarboard, standing confidently with an exaggerated smirk and raised eyebrow, as if delivering a clever retort. Around them, a few other characters in everyday clothes look both surprised and amused, some with wide eyes and hands on their cheeks. The setting is a classroom or a library with bookshelves filled with books labeled ''Wit,'' ''Insult,'' and ''Education.'' Above the main character''s head is a lightbulb glowing to symbolize cleverness. The art style should be exaggerated and playful, with bright colors and expressive facial features to capture the playful, cheeky tone of the phrase ''Wit is educated insolence.'' No violence or hostility, just a clever and confident vibe.'),
 (3116, 'Educational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'Wisdom is knowing what to do with what you know.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking owl wearing round glasses perched on an open book titled ''Wisdom.'' The owl points one wing toward a chalkboard behind it, where simple diagrams and phrases like ''Knowledge + Action = Wisdom'' are scribbled. Nearby, a cheerful human character scratches their head, looking slightly confused but intrigued, holding a book labeled ''Stuff I Know.'' The setting is a cozy library with shelves of books and soft lighting. The overall style is colorful, fun, and lighthearted, emphasizing the contrast between knowing facts and applying them wisely.'),
 (2796, 'Efficiency Humor, Relatable, Unknown, Workplace', 'Don''t mistake my efficiency as meaning I want to do your job too.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office environment. At the center, there is a worker sitting at a cluttered desk, typing briskly and looking very focused and efficient. Their computer screen shows a bar graph rapidly rising or a progress bar almost completed, emphasizing the efficiency. Nearby, a curious coworker peeks over the first worker''s cubicle wall, with a thought bubble containing an image of them trying to do both jobs at once—one person juggling two different work tasks comically, looking overwhelmed. The central worker is holding a coffee mug that says ''Efficiency Expert'' or something similar. The office background has typical cubicles, plants, and some motivational posters ironically about teamwork and workload. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggeratedly cartoonish to emphasize humor and expressions without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2249, 'Emotional Humor, Music Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Sometimes even music can''t substitute for tears.', 'Paul Simon', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting alone on a park bench, holding a music player with large headphones on, looking slightly sad but with a faint smile. Around them, musical notes swirl in the air, but some of these notes are shaped like little cartoon teardrops, emphasizing the connection between music and emotion. The setting is a peaceful park with a few trees, a distant fountain, and a few curious pigeons looking at the person. The person is dressed casually, with a slightly exaggerated sad expression mixed with a glimmer of hope, creating a funny but gentle mood. Include subtle visual contrast between the lively notes and the single real tear on the person''s cheek, symbolizing the joke''s idea that music sometimes can''t replace real tears. The style should be light-hearted and charming, with simple lines and expressive faces typical of cartoon humor.'),
 (2422, 'Emotional Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'There are very few people who are not ashamed of having been in love when they no longer love each other.', 'Duc de La Rouchefoucald Francois', 'A humorous cartoon scene that features two adults sitting awkwardly on opposite ends of a park bench. Both characters have subtle blushes and embarrassed expressions, avoiding eye contact. Around them, faded heart-shaped clouds drift away into the sky, symbolizing past love that has dissipated. In the background, a playful cupid figure is shrugging with a cheeky grin, holding a broken bow and arrow. Nearby, a small dog looks up at the couple quizzically, adding to the lighthearted tone. The setting is a sunny park with a few trees, a distant bench with other happy couples, and scattered fallen love letters on the ground between the two main characters. The overall art style is colorful and cartoony with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize embarrassment and awkwardness in a funny way. The mood is gentle and humorous, focusing on the relatable emotional experience of feeling slightly ashamed about past love now that feelings have faded.'),
 (467, 'Engineering, Engineers, Humor', 'Two engineering students were walking across a university campus when one said, ''Where did you get such a great bike?'' The second engineer replied, ''Well, I was walking along yesterday, minding my own business, when a beautiful woman rode up on this bike, threw it to the ground, took off all her clothes and said, ''Take what you want.'' The first engineer nodded approvingly and said, ''Good choice; the clothes probably wouldn''t have fit you anyway.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a sunny university campus with green grass and a few scattered trees. Two young male engineering students are walking side by side on a paved path. One student looks curious and is pointing at a shiny, somewhat nerdy-looking bike parked nearby. The other student appears calm and slightly smug as he tells the story. In the background, a ghostly or faint visual thought bubble shows a comical flashback: a confident, attractive woman riding the bike, suddenly throwing it down, and stepping away with a playful expression, arms wide open as if offering the bike and clothes. To keep it light and funny, the woman is drawn wearing a towel or exaggeratedly oversized sunglasses and a hat, suggesting she’s undressing but still tasteful and non-explicit. The first student’s face shows a knowing smile after his comment about the clothes not fitting. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the humor and exaggeration of the story without any inappropriate detail.'),
 (468, 'Engineering, Engineers, Humor, Pessimistic', 'Optimist: the glass is half-full. Pessimist: the glass is half-empty. Engineer: that glass is twice as big as it needs to be.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring three characters standing side-by-side, each holding a glass filled halfway with water. The first character, labeled ''Optimist,'' looks cheerful and points at their half-full glass with a big smile. The second character, labeled ''Pessimist,'' looks unhappy or worried, staring at their half-empty glass with a frown. The third character, labeled ''Engineer,'' looks analytical and amused, holding a tape measure or ruler, measuring the glass and saying something with a smirk. The glass in the Engineer''s hand is noticeably much larger than needed for the amount of water it contains, emphasizing the joke. Background is simple, clean, and bright, with a lighthearted, cartoonish style that emphasizes character expressions and the oversized glass. No other objects or complex backgrounds needed to keep focus on the three characters and their glasses.'),
 (469, 'Engineering, Engineers, Humor, Workplace', 'Normal: if it ain''t broke, don''t fix it. Engineer: if it ain''t broke, it doesn''t have enough features yet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an office or workshop. On the left side, a casually dressed person labeled ''Normal'' is holding a slightly broken gadget or machine, with a speech bubble saying, ''If it ain''t broke, don''t fix it.'' They look relaxed and confident. On the right side, an engineer wearing a shirt with a gear or circuit icon stands proudly next to a very overcomplicated, cluttered machine with many unnecessary gadgets, blinking lights, buttons, gauges, and wires everywhere. The engineer''s speech bubble says, ''If it ain''t broke, it doesn''t have enough features yet.'' The background shows tools and blueprints pinned to the wall to emphasize a technical workspace. Both characters have exaggerated, friendly cartoon expressions to enhance the humor without being aggressive or mean. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and playful, emphasizing the contrast between simplicity and over-engineering.'),
 (470, 'Engineering, Humor, Science', 'RAPID DECELERATION TRAUMA... is the trauma suffered by an object in motion, that decelerates at a rate more rapid than the object is able to absorb the stresses endured during the deceleration phase.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon style scene featuring a small car or toy car zooming forward with motion lines indicating high speed. The car suddenly hits a wall or a giant cushion labeled ''Rapid Deceleration'' with a comic impact effect (like stars or birds flying above). Above or next to the car, include a large text box in a scientific or technical font that reads: ''RAPID DECELERATION TRAUMA... is the trauma suffered by an object in motion, that decelerates at a rate more rapid than the object is able to absorb the stresses endured during the deceleration phase.'' The background should be simple and bright with exaggerated expressions of the car (like curved eyes or cartoonish ''pain'' marks) to emphasize the joke. Avoid any real human injuries or violent elements, keeping it light and funny. The overall style should be colorful and playful, similar to classic educational cartoons but with a comedic twist.'),
 (2436, 'Engineering, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'There is only one nature - the division into science and engineering is a human imposition, not a natural one. Indeed, the division is a human failure; it reflects our limited capacity to comprehend the whole.', 'Bill Wulf', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, majestic tree labeled ''Nature'' at the center, with its roots spreading deep underground. On one side of the tree, a scientist character with a white lab coat and glasses is examining a leaf with a magnifying glass, surrounded by scientific equipment like test tubes and charts. On the other side, an engineer character wearing a hard hat and holding blueprints is looking at a mechanical device built around the tree trunk, such as gears and levers. Both characters appear puzzled and are scratching their heads, emphasizing confusion or disagreement. Above them, a thought bubble shows the tree being split by a jagged line into ''Science'' and ''Engineering'' sections, but the line is clearly drawn by a human hand holding a red pen. The background is light and simple, focusing on the idea of the unnatural division, making the scene playful and insightful but non-violent and family-friendly.'),
 (1333, 'Engineering, Programmers, Puns, Technology Humor', 'How many engineers does it take to change a lightbulb? Hang on, I''m still flashing the firmware on this one.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a typical office or lab setting for engineers. In the center, an engineer is standing on a small step stool, reaching up toward a ceiling lightbulb. Instead of holding a new bulb, the engineer is focused on a sleek laptop or handheld device, intensely looking at its screen. Around them, floating symbols like small blinking gears and progress bars suggest software updating or flashing firmware. Nearby, another engineer in casual work attire watches confusedly, holding a regular lightbulb in one hand. The ceiling lightbulb above them flickers sporadically. The overall tone is lighthearted and tech-savvy, with bright, simple cartoon lines and expressive faces emphasizing the humor in treating a lightbulb change like a software upgrade. Background details can include a desk with technical manuals and tools like screwdrivers, reinforcing the engineering environment without cluttering the image.'),
 (471, 'Engineering, Programming, Science', 'Programming is part engineering, part science, part art, a little luck and usually not that difficult.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a programmer sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer surrounded by various symbols representing different fields. On one side, there is a blueprint and a wrench depicting engineering; on another side, a microscope and a chemistry flask to represent science; nearby, a painter''s palette and brush symbolize art. Above the programmer’s head is a small glowing four-leaf clover representing ''a little luck.'' The programmer looks calm and confident with a slight smile, typing away while a half-empty coffee cup sits nearby. The background includes a lightbulb overhead, suggesting ideas, and a few code snippets floating around. The style should be light-hearted and colorful with exaggerated cartoon features for each element, emphasizing the blend of disciplines, but also the casual ease implied by the ''usually not that difficult'' line.'),
 (472, 'Engineering, Puns, Science', 'Resistance is useless - if less than 1 ohm.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple electronics lab. In the center, a small resistor character with tiny arms and legs, a frustrated or defeated expression on its face, is being confronted by a large, tough-looking power source or current flow represented with animated electrical sparks or lightning bolts. The resistor wears a little headband or sweatband to emphasize struggling. Nearby, a digital multimeter shows a reading just below 1 ohm. The background includes typical electronics components like a breadboard, wires, and a circuit diagram with ohm symbols. The style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke about resistance values being ''useless'' if less than 1 ohm. No realistic humans or harsh elements are needed; just cute, anthropomorphic electronic parts in a lab setting.'),
 (473, 'Engineers, Humor, Jobs, Puns', 'The graduate with a science degree asks, ''Why does it work?'' The graduate with an engineering degree asks, ''How does it work?'' The graduate with an accounting k asks, ''How much will it cost?'' The graduate with an arts degree asks, ''Do you want fries with that?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a graduation ceremony or a social gathering with four graduates standing side by side, each dressed in different but clearly identifiable graduation gowns with labels or icons representing their fields: science (wearing a lab coat with a beaker emblem), engineering (wearing a hard hat and holding a wrench), accounting (wearing glasses and holding a calculator), and arts (wearing a beret and holding a fast-food tray with fries and a drink). Each graduate has a speech bubble with their respective question: science graduate''s bubble says, ''Why does it work?''; engineering graduate''s bubble says, ''How does it work?''; accounting graduate''s bubble says, ''How much will it cost?''; arts graduate''s bubble says, ''Do you want fries with that?'' The background should be simple, perhaps on a stage or at a diploma ceremony with a banner saying ''Graduation Day,'' and the overall style is colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing each character''s personality with exaggerated expressions showing curiosity, practicality, focus on money, and casual friendliness respectively.'),
 (2713, 'Etiquette Humor, Irony, Social Humor, Unknown', 'Common Courtesy Department: If you don''t go to a person''s funeral, don''t expect them to go to yours.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at an office-like room labeled ''Common Courtesy Department'' with a large sign on the wall behind the desk. Behind a counter sits a bored-looking, slightly grumpy clerk wearing glasses and a name badge, handing out small etiquette pamphlets to visitors. In front of the counter, two characters stand talking: one is dressed as a ghost with a ribbon that says ''I''m your funeral invite,'' holding a tiny invitation card and looking slightly annoyed. The other character is a casual person who looks confused and sheepish. Around them, funeral-related props like a wreath, coffin caricature, and a calendar with crossed-out dates are visible on the walls. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the ironic message. The overall mood is witty and playful, poking fun at the concept of social reciprocity regarding funerals, without any dark or depressing tone.'),
 (1368, 'Everyday Life, Exaggeration, Money Humor, Quotes', 'A billion here, a billion there; pretty soon you''re talking real money!', 'Everett Dirkson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wealthy-looking businessman wearing a suit and tie, standing next to a giant symbolic money bag labeled "$1,000,000,000" (one billion dollars). The businessman is holding a calculator or a clipboard, with a thought bubble showing stacks of money piling up rapidly. Around him are scattered piles of cash, coins, and some oversized bills. In the background, a large chart or sign says “A Billion Here, A Billion There,” with an arrow pointing to a much larger pile of money labeled “Real Money.” The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, using bright colors and playful expressions to emphasize the absurdity of casually throwing around the idea of billions. No violence or negativity, just a whimsical take on the concept of large sums of money adding up quickly.'),
 (1683, 'Everyday Life, Exaggeration, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Excess on occasion is exhilarating. It prevents moderation from acquiring the deadening effect of a habit.', 'W. Somerset Maugham', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person at a lively party, looking thrilled and wide-eyed while holding an exaggeratedly large slice of cake in one hand and an oversized drink in the other. Around them, other partygoers appear bored or mildly indifferent, representing ''moderation.'' The background should show a banner with the phrase ''Excess is exhilarating!'' with one side colorful and wild, while the other side is plain and dull to visually contrast excitement vs. habit. The central figure is drawn with exaggerated joyful expression, while the others have tired or neutral faces to emphasize the joke''s message about how occasional excess breaks the monotony of moderation. Include typical party elements like balloons, confetti, and a table with various food and drinks scattered about to set the festive mood. Style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors to reinforce the fun tone of the joke.'),
 (1595, 'Everyday Life, Exaggeration, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'By doing just a little every day, I can gradually let the task completely overwhelm me.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk cluttered with papers, sticky notes, and various small tasks represented as little cartoon icons (like a tiny clock, a checklist, a phone, and a calendar). The person looks overwhelmed, with frazzled hair and wide eyes, holding a tiny paintbrush or pen labeled "small effort." Tiny piles of tasks are slowly growing larger, some spilling over the desk edge and piling up on the floor, resembling a snowball effect. On one side, a small calendar shows daily check marks, emphasizing the "little every day" aspect. Above the person''s head is a thought bubble depicting a giant, intimidating mountain of paperwork towering over them, symbolizing the task completely overwhelming them despite the small efforts. The overall tone is light-hearted, playful, and relatable with exaggerated expressions and a bright, simple color palette.'),
 (2658, 'Everyday Life, Family, Humor, Unknown', 'Ask your child what he wants for dinner only if he''s buying.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy home kitchen. A cheerful parent stands near the stove holding a wooden spoon, wearing a chef''s hat and apron. The parent has a playful smile and is looking at their child, who is standing by the kitchen table with arms crossed and a mischievous grin, as if making a witty demand. The child is holding a wallet or a small purse in one hand, hinting that they need to pay for dinner. The kitchen is warm and welcoming, with pots on the stove, a fridge in the background covered with colorful magnets and a family photo. A speech bubble from the parent says, ''What do you want for dinner?'' and from the child, another bubble says, ''Only if I''m buying!'' The scene should be bright, cheerful, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor in the child''s cheeky response. No violent or inappropriate details included.'),
 (1393, 'Everyday Life, Family, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'A family reunion is an effective form of birth control.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a large, chaotic family reunion in a sunny park with picnic tables overloaded with food. Several generations of relatives are present: grandparents, parents, teenagers, and many young children running around. Some family members look visibly exhausted or overwhelmed, like a frazzled parent trying to juggle multiple kids or an older relative wiping sweat from their forehead. There are kids playing noisily with balloons and a dog chasing a frisbee. Signs or speech bubbles express mild chaos, such as ''Too many cousins!'' or ''When’s the break?'' The scene captures the lively but overwhelming nature of a big family gathering. In the foreground, one adult looks directly at the viewer with a humorous, resigned expression, implying this event is so exhausting it discourages having more kids. The overall style is cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the comedic effect without any negativity.'),
 (1480, 'Everyday Life, Family, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'A woman''s work that is never done is the stuff she asked her husband to do.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy, slightly messy living room. In the foreground, a woman stands with her hands on her hips, smiling wryly. She is dressed in casual home clothes, looking at her husband with a playful but knowing expression. The husband is in the middle of fixing a broken lamp or assembling a piece of furniture, looking overwhelmed and distracted by a long, chaotic to-do list floating beside him. Around them are small unpaid chore reminders like a basket of laundry, unwashed dishes on a side table, and scattered tools. The husband has a slightly tired but amused look. The background should be warm and inviting with soft colors. The style is cartoonish with exaggerated, expressive faces to highlight the humor of the never-ending chores the wife delegates to the husband. No violence or harshness - just lighthearted and relatable domestic comedy.'),
 (772, 'Everyday Life, Fantasy Humor, Halloween, Pun', 'What do you call witches when they live together? Broomates.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a cozy witch shared apartment. The main focus is on two or three friendly, cartoon witches wearing classic pointy black hats and colorful robes. They are smiling and casually hanging out together. Nearby, several brooms lean against the walls or rest in a broom holder, emphasizing the pun. The setting is a quirky, warmly lit room with cobweb decorations, a cauldron bubbling on a small stove, and maybe a black cat perched on a shelf. The witches appear relaxed and friendly, enjoying each other''s company like roommates, with typical household items around like a shared potion bottle or a floating broomstick with books stacked on it. The style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the pun through the shared living space full of witch-themed items.'),
 (1367, 'Everyday Life, Finance Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'A banker is a fellow who lends you his umbrella when the sun is shining, but wants it back the minute it begins to rain.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors on a bright sunny day. Show two characters: a well-dressed banker wearing a suit and tie with a name tag labeled ''Banker'', holding a large, stylish umbrella horizontally over a casually dressed person standing next to him, who is smiling and looking grateful. The banker has a polite but calculating expression. In the next visual moment of the scene (like a two-panel comic), clouds have appeared and raindrops begin to fall on both characters. The casually dressed person is now holding the umbrella as rain pours down, looking relieved, while the banker reaches out his hand with a stern expression, clearly wanting the umbrella back. Add subtle background details like a city street with a bank sign on a nearby building and a few wet puddles forming. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke about the banker’s behavior regarding lending an umbrella only when it is not needed.'),
 (1927, 'Everyday Life, Financial Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I''m living so far beyond my income that we may almost be said to be living apart.', 'e e cummings (1894-1962)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting inside a small, modest apartment on one side of the image, looking stressed while checking an empty wallet. On the opposite side of the image, the same person is happily lounging in a lavish, spacious mansion with fancy furniture, surrounded by luxury items like a chandelier, expensive paintings, and a large feast on a table. A dotted line or some comic effect visually separates the two settings, emphasizing the ''living apart'' idea. The expression on the person in the apartment is worried or tired, while the person in the mansion looks carefree and exaggeratedly comfortable. Include speech bubbles or a caption above with the joke''s line: "I''m living so far beyond my income that we may almost be said to be living apart." The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features to enhance the humor without any violence or sensitive content.'),
 (1797, 'Everyday Life, Food Humor, Humor, Quotes', 'I don''t even butter my bread; I consider that cooking.', 'Katherine Cebrian', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a slice of plain bread on a kitchen counter. Next to the bread is a small butter knife dripping with butter, but the butter is humorously missing from the bread, indicating the person hasn''t actually buttered it. In the background, a casually dressed character (standing or sitting) is shrugging with a goofy, self-satisfied smile, as if proudly explaining that just eating the plain bread counts as cooking. The kitchen should look simple and slightly messy, with a toaster, a butter dish, and a small pile of crumbs nearby to add detail. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, focusing on the minimal effort involved being dubbed ''cooking.'''),
 (1181, 'Everyday Life, Food Humor, Insults, Pun', 'May all the chocolate chips in your cookies turn out to be raisins', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person eagerly holding a freshly baked cookie with a big bite taken out of it. The cookie is clearly full of raisins, but the character''s thought bubble shows a hopeful image of chocolate chips. Nearby, a confused-looking cookie tray sits on a kitchen countertop, with several cookies visibly featuring raisins instead of chocolate chips. The background should be a simple, cozy kitchen setting with a mixing bowl, a wooden spoon, and a cookie sheet. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the irony and mild disappointment with exaggerated facial expression on the person who expected chocolate chips but got raisins instead.'),
 (1197, 'Everyday Life, Food Humor, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'May your tea be too hot to drink when you get it, and too cold when you remember to drink it', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene centered around a steaming cup of tea on a small, cozy kitchen table. The tea cup has exaggerated heat waves rising from it with a bright red and orange glow to suggest it’s too hot to drink. In the background, a person dressed in casual pajamas looks frustrated and eager, pointing at the tea but unable to take a sip. Next to the person, a small clock on the wall or table shows that a while has passed, and a thought bubble appears above the person''s head with a shivering blue and icy-looking cup of tea, indicating the tea has gotten too cold by the time they remember it. Include simple kitchen elements like a teapot, a sugar bowl, and maybe a calendar with a humorous phrase like “Tea Countdown” for added context. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize the contrasting temperatures and human frustration in a funny, relatable way.'),
 (1468, 'Everyday Life, Food Humor, Parenting, Quotes', 'A spoonful of sugar helps the medicine go down.', 'Mary Poppins', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful child sitting at a kitchen table with a spoon held out, containing a shiny, golden scoop of sugar. Across from the child, a friendly-looking adult, perhaps a parent or caregiver, is holding a small glass of medicine with a slightly exaggerated bubble or sparkle to emphasize the medicine''s unpleasantness. The child smiles happily, showing eagerness to take the medicine with sugar. The background is a bright, simple kitchen setting with cupboards, a window with sunlight streaming in, and a plate with a small cake or sugar cubes next to the child to emphasize sweetness. The overall tone is light and playful, using bright colors and smooth, rounded lines typical of a humorous cartoon style.'),
 (1500, 'Everyday Life, Food Humor, Quotes', 'Age does not diminish the extreme disappointment of having a scoop of ice cream fall from the cone.', 'Jim Fiebig', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing outside on a sunny day holding an ice cream cone with a single scoop. The scoop is depicted dropping mid-air, just a short distance from the cone, with a small splat forming below on the sidewalk. The person''s face shows exaggerated extreme disappointment and sadness, with big watery eyes and a small frown. Around them are simple park elements like a bench, a tree with birds, and a sun with smiling face in the sky to emphasize it''s a casual, happy day ruined by the ice cream mishap. The style is colorful, cheerful, and playful, emphasizing the universal frustration of the moment in a lighthearted way.'),
 (2635, 'Everyday Life, Friends, Pun, Unknown', 'A friend once told me ''All that matters is a good pair of headphones.'', and I thought to myself ''That''s sound advice''.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring two friends standing side by side. One friend is animatedly speaking, holding up a modern pair of stylish headphones with a big smile. The other friend is nodding thoughtfully with a lightbulb above their head to indicate a clever thought. Beside them, floating above or near the second friend, is a speech bubble containing the pun: ''That''s sound advice.'' The headphones should be large and eye-catching, with music notes gently floating around to emphasize sound. The background is simple and cheerful with soft pastel colors, maybe a park or street scene to keep it casual and friendly. The overall mood is light and playful, capturing the pun about headphones and advice with an expressive facial expression on both characters to enhance the humor.'),
 (2488, 'Everyday Life, Friendship Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'True friendship is never serene.', 'Marie de Rabutin-Chantal', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two friends sitting on a worn-out park bench. One friend is smiling calmly, holding a coffee cup, while the other is animatedly gesturing with wide eyes and a playful scowl, spilling a bit of their drink. Around them, typical signs of a chaotic friendship: an open bag of chips scattered on the ground, a frisbee stuck in a nearby tree, and a mischievous dog tugging on one friend''s shoelaces. The background shows a slightly messy picnic setup with a knocked-over drink and a playful squirrel watching the scene. The overall mood is light-hearted and comical, illustrating that true friendship involves lively, imperfect, and sometimes chaotic moments rather than peaceful serenity.'),
 (1472, 'Everyday Life, Friendship, Quotes, Word Play', 'A true friend never gets in your way unless you happen to be going down.', 'Arnold H. Glasow', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two friends on a staircase. One friend is ahead, sliding or going down the stairs fast with a surprised and slightly worried expression. The second friend is standing directly in front of them, cheerfully blocking the way with arms stretched out wide and an innocent, friendly smile. The staircase is simple with a handrail, and the setting should look lighthearted and playful with bright colors. Include small funny details like maybe a few scattered objects on the stairs or a pet watching the scene puzzled. The art style should be exaggerated and cartoonish with big expressive faces to emphasize the joke about a friend ''never getting in your way unless you happen to be going down.'' No violence or negativity, just warmth and silly irony.'),
 (3089, 'Everyday Life, Gender Humor, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, garbage would take itself out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a typical living room. A man is sitting comfortably on a couch watching TV with a remote in one hand and a half-eaten snack on a small table beside him. Nearby, a kitchen trash can is overflowing with garbage, looking messy and unattended. The garbage can has small cartoon eyes and a slightly annoyed face, as if it’s waiting impatiently. In the background, a woman stands by the doorway with a playful, knowing smile, arms crossed, shaking her head in a lighthearted way as she watches the man ignore the garbage. The overall mood is funny and exaggerated, emphasizing the idea that if men ran the world, things like taking out the trash would never happen on their own. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and non-threatening, with clear expressions and simple details to highlight the joke’s concept.'),
 (3093, 'Everyday Life, Gender Humor, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, nodding and looking at your watch would be deemed as an acceptable response to ''I love you.''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing with a slightly awkward or indifferent expression as a woman tells him ''I love you.'' The man is nodding his head and glancing down at his wristwatch, emphasizing that he is distracted or giving a minimal response. The woman looks surprised, puzzled, or unimpressed by his reaction, with a speech bubble containing ''I love you.'' The background can be a simple living room or park setting to focus on their interaction. Use exaggerated cartoon features: the man''s watch could be comically large, and both characters should have expressive eyes and body language highlighting the mismatch in emotional engagement. Keep the colors bright and the style friendly and light to emphasize the humorous, relatable moment without any negativity or discomfort.'),
 (653, 'Everyday Life, Good Question!, Objects Humor, Pun', 'Why is the third hand on the watch called a second hand?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an oversized, classic wristwatch with three hands clearly visible: the hour hand, the minute hand, and a smaller, distinct third hand labeled ‘Second Hand.’ The watch face should have exaggerated large numbers and funny, expressive eyes on it, as if the watch is alive and confused, looking at its third hand with a puzzled expression. Include a small speech bubble from the watch that says something like, ''Why am I called a second hand?'' The background should be simple, like a light, colorful gradient to keep the focus on the watch. Make sure the style is bright, playful, and cartoonish with bold lines and vibrant colors, emphasizing the comedic confusion about the terminology of the watch hands.'),
 (657, 'Everyday Life, Good Question!, Pun, Relatable', 'Why wait for spring? Procastinate now!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person lounging comfortably on a couch inside a cozy living room. The person is dressed in casual, slightly lazy attire—maybe pajamas or sweatpants—and is surrounded by typical procrastination items like an open book, a smartphone, a half-eaten snack bowl, and a TV remote. Outside the window behind them, it is clearly winter with snow piled up and bare trees, but bright signs of spring like blooming flowers or birds starting to appear are visible just outside, teasing the person. A calendar on the wall shows the month of February or early March, perhaps with days crossed out, emphasizing ‘waiting for spring.’ The caption or thought bubble from the person says: “Why wait for spring? Procastinate now!” The overall tone is lighthearted, playful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions of laziness and relaxation, and vibrant colors to contrast the indoor cozy laziness against the chilly outdoor season.'),
 (654, 'Everyday Life, Good Question!, Word Play', 'Why is the time of day with the slowest traffic called rush hour?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a typical city street during rush hour. The street is wide and filled with cars that are almost completely stopped, with visibly bored or frustrated drivers inside. There are clocks hovering above the street showing the time, indicating ''rush hour.'' On the sidewalk, a person is standing next to a street sign that says ''Rush Hour,'' looking confused and scratching their head. Nearby, an illustration of a snail slowly crawling on the street among the cars adds to the joke''s theme of slowness. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony of traffic being slow during the time called ''rush hour.'' The backdrop includes tall buildings, traffic lights, and some trees, giving a typical urban vibe without overcrowding the scene.'),
 (1161, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Insults', 'Are you short-tempered and grouchy because you don''t get enough sleep? Or do you have some other reason?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a grumpy, tired-looking person sitting at a messy desk with disheveled hair and dark circles under their eyes. The person is holding a coffee mug in one hand and rubbing their temples with the other, clearly frustrated. Behind them is a clock showing late night or early morning hours. Around the desk, include scattered papers, an alarm clock showing a very early time, and a notepad with scribbles about reasons for their grouchiness (like ''lack of sleep'' and ''other reasons'' written humorously). The background should be simple and bright to keep the mood light and funny, emphasizing the tiredness and irritation without any harsh or negative elements.'),
 (1184, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Insults', 'May both sides of your pillow be warm', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person about to go to bed with a whimsical, cozy bedroom setting. The person is holding a pillow in both hands, looking thoughtfully at it as if wishing for both sides to be warm. The bed should be neatly made, with a duvet, bedside lamp, and maybe slippers by the bed. The person''s expression should be hopeful and slightly amused. The room is softly lit, emphasizing comfort and warmth. To add humor, show little steam or heat waves coming off one side of the pillow and the other side as well, symbolizing the wish for both sides to be warm simultaneously. Keep the style lighthearted and cartoonish, with simple lines and bright, warm colors, focused on the pillow and the person''s hopeful face.'),
 (1194, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Insults, Parenting', 'May your five year old neighbor have violin lessons during all your hangovers', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outside a suburban house. In the foreground, a tired adult with messy hair is slumped in a chair on a porch or in a living room visible through a window, holding their head as if suffering from a hangover. Nearby, through a window or from the neighbor''s yard, a cheerful five-year-old child is enthusiastically playing the violin, eyes closed and focused, producing clearly audible music notes floating in the air. The setting shows morning light to suggest the adult is trying to recover, while the child appears oblivious and happy about their violin practice. The atmosphere should be lighthearted and comical, with exaggerated expressions: the adult looks weary and annoyed, while the kid is joyful. The background includes typical suburban elements like houses, fences, and maybe a potted plant or a chair. Music notes should be playful and clearly indicate sound, emphasizing the clash between the adult''s discomfort and the kid''s noisy activity.'),
 (1158, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'Am I getting smart with you? How would you know?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters engaged in a light-hearted exchange. One character has an exaggerated confident expression, leaning slightly forward with a raised eyebrow and a smirk, as if they just made a witty remark. The other character looks confused and playful, scratching their head or tilting their head in curiosity. Place them in a casual indoor setting like a living room with a couch, a coffee table, and maybe a lamp or a bookshelf in the background to give a cozy, everyday feel. Use bright, cheerful colors and emphasize the facial expressions to highlight the playful back-and-forth nature of the joke. Include a speech bubble above the confident character saying, "Am I getting smart with you?" and a thought bubble or speech bubble for the other character saying, "How would you know?" The overall vibe should be light, fun, and a little cheeky without hostility or discomfort.'),
 (1809, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'I figure you have the same chance of winning the lottery whether you play or not.', 'Fran Lebowitz', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters having a conversation. One character, looking upbeat, is holding a lottery ticket and grinning, while the other character looks skeptical with crossed arms. In the background, a lottery machine with numbered balls is visible, and a thought bubble from the skeptical character shows a humorous math equation with zeros and a tiny chance. The setting is casual, maybe a grocery store or convenience store counter where lottery tickets are sold. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors emphasizing the irony of the statement.'),
 (1943, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'In spite of the cost of living, it''s still popular.', 'Kathy Norris', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a lively city street filled with cheerful people enjoying various activities despite signs highlighting the high cost of living. Include a big, colorful billboard or neon sign that reads ''Cost of Living'' with a price tag symbol, but show people happily walking, shopping, eating ice cream, riding bikes, and having fun. Add a street vendor selling balloons or snacks with a friendly smile, and a small dog wearing a cute outfit. The overall atmosphere should be bright and vibrant, emphasizing the contrast between the expensive cost of living and the popular, joyful lifestyle of the people. Use exaggerated expressions to capture a light-hearted mood without any negativity or stress.'),
 (1585, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Life, Quotes', 'Being grown up isn''t half as fun as growing up.', 'The Ataris', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon showing two scenes side-by-side. On the left, a joyful child is playing with toys, running around outside with a big smile, balloons, and a sandbox nearby to emphasize the fun of ''growing up.'' On the right, an adult in business attire stands looking tired and bored at a cluttered office desk with piles of paperwork, a coffee cup, a ringing phone, and a calendar full of appointments, visually contrasting the dullness of ''being grown up.'' Both characters should be stylized with exaggerated expressions—exuberance on the child and weary resignation on the adult. The background is simple and clearly distinguishes childhood from adulthood with bright colors on the child''s side and muted tones on the adult''s side. Include a playful font headline at the top with the text: "Being grown up isn''t half as fun as growing up." The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, focusing on the contrast between carefree childhood and the responsibilities of adulthood without any harsh or negative elements.'),
 (2122, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Life, Quotes', 'My life has a superb cast but I can''t figure out the plot.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting on a cozy couch, looking puzzled and scratching their head. Around them, several quirky characters are acting out various roles: a superhero in a cape, a detective with a magnifying glass, a chef tossing a pan, and a clown juggling. These characters should appear lively and exaggerated, as if in a theatrical play or movie. In the background, show a large movie screen or stage with a question mark on it, symbolizing confusion about the story. The setting is bright and colorful, emphasizing a playful and chaotic atmosphere that suggests the person’s life is full of interesting people but lacks a clear storyline. Include small props like a script lying on the ground, popcorn spilling, and speech bubbles above characters filled with random symbols or nonsensical words to highlight the missing plot clarity. The overall tone should be lighthearted and whimsical, capturing the metaphor of life as a movie or play that is hard to understand despite the entertaining cast.'),
 (2798, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Motivational Humor, Unknown', 'Don''t quit now, we might just as well lock the door and throw away the key.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing in front of a slightly ajar door. One character is animatedly gesturing toward the door with an exaggerated hopeful expression, while the other looks uncertain but amused. The door has a large, old-fashioned keyhole. Nearby, there''s an oversized old-fashioned key on a ring labeled ''the key,'' dangling just out of reach or being held hesitantly by one of the characters. The setting is simple, like a cozy room with a small welcome mat outside the door and a wall clock showing a late hour, adding to the sense of urgency but lighthearted mood. The style is bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and clean lines, emphasizing the playful nature of the phrase about quitting and locking the door with the key thrown away as a metaphor for finality and irreversibility.'),
 (1403, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Motivational, Quotes', 'A goal is a dream with a deadline.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sleeping peacefully on a fluffy cloud labeled ''Dream.'' Above the cloud, a colorful thought bubble shows the person imagining a big, shining trophy or a finished project. To the right, a large calendar with big, red circled deadline dates clearly visible. The person wakes up looking determined, eyes wide open, while reaching towards the calendar. Make the scene bright and cheerful with soft pastel colors and add a playful clock showing time ticking. Include labels on the dream cloud and calendar to emphasize the contrast between ''dream'' and ''deadline.'' The style should be lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the transformation from dreaming to action.'),
 (1637, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Motivational, Quotes', 'Do not wait for leader; do it alone, person to person.', 'Mother Teresa', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two ordinary people standing face to face in a park or simple urban setting, each determinedly rolling up their sleeves and starting to work on a small project between them—like planting a tiny tree or building a birdhouse—without waiting for a larger crowd or a person with a leadership badge. One person has a slight puzzled but motivated expression, while the other looks confident and proactive. Between them, there is a sign that says, ''No leader needed!'' In the background, a larger group of people stands idly, looking confused or waiting. The atmosphere is light-hearted and optimistic, emphasizing individual initiative and collaboration on a small scale. The style should be colorful, bright, and clearly cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic and motivational tone.'),
 (1900, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Motivational, Quotes', 'If you can''t learn to do it well, learn to enjoy doing it badly.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon showing a cheerful person attempting a skill or hobby and clearly doing it very poorly. The scene is bright and lighthearted. Place the character in the middle, smiling confidently but with obvious mistakes or comical failures around them (e.g., a person painting a wildly messy picture with paint splatters all over, or playing a musical instrument out of tune with notes floating visibly wrong). Include a few props relevant to the activity, such as an easel and paintbrushes, or a guitar with musical notes. Add a small caption or speech bubble above the character with the quote: ''If you can''t learn to do it well, learn to enjoy doing it badly.'' The background is simple, playful, and colorful, emphasizing fun and positivity in failure rather than frustration. The art style should be cartoonish and exaggerated, with expressive facial features and lively posture to show enjoyment despite the poor performance.'),
 (1474, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Parenting, Quotes', 'A two-year old is like a blender without the top on.', 'Jerry Seinfeld', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small toddler, about two years old, standing on a kitchen counter next to a blender. The blender is turned on and spinning fast, but it has no lid, so colorful, chunky food splatters and flies wildly out of it in all directions. The toddler has a big, mischievous grin on their face and is raising their hands in excitement. The kitchen background is simple but lively, with a few scattered food items (like fruits and vegetables) flying around and a few splashes on the walls and floor. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the chaotic energy of a toddler and the messy chaos of an open blender in action.'),
 (1696, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Few wishes come true by themselves.', 'June Smith', 'A humorous cartoon showing a magical genie emerging from a classic lamp, looking tired and a bit overwhelmed. The genie is rubbing its temples while a person stands nearby with crossed fingers and a hopeful expression. Around them, several wish bubbles hover in the air, but some are half-faded or floating away, symbolizing unfulfilled wishes. The background is simple and bright, emphasizing the contrast between the eager person and the exhausted genie. The style is playful with exaggerated facial expressions and vibrant colors to bring out the humorous tone about the reality that few wishes come true on their own.'),
 (1406, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Physical Comedy, Quotes', 'A good many dramatic situations begin with screaming.', 'Barbarella', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a typical everyday living room. In the center, a person is dramatically screaming with exaggerated wide-open mouth and eyes, as if acting out on stage. Around them, various common dramatic situations are gently hinted at: a spilled cup of coffee, a torn book, a drooped houseplant, and a phone ringing off the hook. The expressions of other family members or pets nearby are calm or mildly surprised, contrasting with the main character''s over-the-top scream. The overall style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with bold lines and vibrant colors to emphasize the humor in how drama often starts simply with someone screaming.'),
 (1467, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'A signature always reveals a man''s character -- and sometimes even his name.', 'Evan Esar', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting at a desk signing a paper. The man looks confident but slightly puzzled as his signature is wildly illegible, with sprawling, messy scribbles. Above him, a playful thought bubble shows a detective looking at the signature with a magnifying glass, trying to decipher it. The background features a simple office setting with a pen holder, a stack of papers, and a small nameplate on the desk reading ''Mr. Character.'' The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the idea that a signature is meant to reflect identity but can sometimes be completely confusing or unrecognizable. The colors are bright and cheerful, and the characters have exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (1833, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'I often quote myself, it adds spice to my conversation.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person confidently talking to a small group of friends in a cozy living room setting. The main character is mid-sentence, smiling proudly, with a speech bubble that says, ''I often quote myself, it adds spice to my conversation.'' Around them, the friends have amused or surprised expressions. To emphasize the ''spice'' pun, include a visible table nearby holding a few spice jars like pepper, paprika, and chili powder. The character’s confident pose and lively facial expression highlight the self-quoting joke. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and warm colors to create a friendly, playful atmosphere. Avoid any backgrounds that distract from the conversation focus—just cushions, a lamp, and a coffee table with mugs to suggest a relaxed gathering.'),
 (1895, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'If you are going to do something wrong at least enjoy it.', 'Leo C. Rosten', 'Draw a cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, mischievous character who looks like they''re about to do something cheeky or borderline wrong but is visibly enjoying themselves. The character could be a playful person with a big grin, mid-action—maybe sneaking a cookie from a cookie jar labeled ''Do Not Eat.'' Surround them with lighthearted, humorous details like a spilled glass of milk or a toppled plant to hint at minor mischief. The background should be a simple kitchen or living room setting with bright, happy colors and a relaxed atmosphere. Emphasize the character''s joyful expression to reflect the joke''s message of enjoying doing something wrong, but keep it all friendly and non-threatening. The overall tone should be fun and silly, suitable for a lighthearted cartoon.'),
 (1563, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'AQUALIBRIUM (ak wa lib'' re um) n. The point where the stream of drinking fountain water is at its perfect height, thus relieving the drinker from (a) having to suck the nozzle, or (b) squirting himself in the eye (or ear).', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon showing a person drinking from a water fountain. The fountain has a stream of water perfectly arcing from the spout to just the right height for the drinker’s mouth. The person looks relieved and happy, neither bending too low to suck the nozzle nor splashing water in their eye or ear. Beside the scene, have a small comic-style thought bubble or label that says “AQUALIBRIUM” with the humorous dictionary-style definition beneath it. The setting is a simple park or school hallway with a water fountain mounted on the wall, and the overall style should be lighthearted and playful with exaggerated facial expression on the drinker to highlight the humor. No other characters or distractions, focus on the perfect water stream and the satisfaction of the drinker.'),
 (2555, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'When angry, count to four; when very angry, swear.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in the middle of a living room. The character looks mildly frustrated, holding up one finger while counting, with a thought bubble above their head showing the numbers "1, 2, 3, 4." Next to them is a second panel or smaller frame showing the same character with a very angry expression, steam coming out of their ears, fists clenched, and a speech bubble containing comic-style symbols like ''@#$%!'' representing swearing. The background should be simple, with a couch, a coffee table with a cup of coffee or tea, and a clock on the wall to emphasize the passage of time. The overall style is light and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the shift from mild anger to intense frustration and swearing humorously.'),
 (2012, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'It''s so expensive, you may have to read the manual.', 'Shumko', 'A humorous cartoon showing a person looking bewildered in front of an expensive, complicated-looking gadget (like a high-tech coffee machine or a shiny new electronic device with many buttons and screens). The device has a large price tag hanging from it, prominently showing a high cost. The person holds an oversized manual titled ''Instructions'' with a confused expression. Around them are smaller details like a piggy bank that looks empty and a receipt with lots of zeros. The background is simple indoor setting, maybe a kitchen or living room, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon style to emphasize frustration mixed with humor.'),
 (2031, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Laughter and tears are both responses to frustration and exhaustion. I myself prefer to laugh since there is less cleaning up to do afterward.', 'Kurt Vonnegut', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting on a couch looking tired and frustrated, with exaggerated tired eyes and a slouched posture. On one side of the couch, there is a bucket or box labeled ''Tears Cleanup Kit'' overflowing with tissues and water puddles around it. On the other side, the person is shown smiling and laughing, with some cheerful sound effects like ''Ha Ha!'' in comic-style lettering. The floor near the laughing side is clean and dry. The room should look cozy but slightly messy to emphasize exhaustion. Include a clock on the wall showing late night time to suggest tiredness, and some crumpled papers or empty coffee cups on a side table to add a sense of effort or frustration. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions highlighting the contrast between laughing and crying.'),
 (2321, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Self-Deprecation', 'The hardest secret for a man to keep is his opinion of himself.', 'God''s Little Instruction Book', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing in front of a mirror. The man looks slightly awkward and self-conscious, with a sly grin and raised eyebrow. The mirror shows a thought bubble above the man''s head depicting his exaggerated self-opinion—maybe an image of himself as a superhero or a confident figure wearing sunglasses and a cape. Around the man, small sticky notes or clouds show whispering words like ''Secret!'' and ''No one knows!'' to emphasize the difficulty of keeping his self-opinion hidden. The background is a simple bathroom or bedroom setting with lighthearted details, such as a dresser with neatly folded clothes and a small potted plant. The overall style is cartoonish and playful, with bold lines and bright colors to keep the mood light and funny, avoiding any negativity.'),
 (1808, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'I envy people who drink - at least they know what to blame everything on.', 'Oscar Levant', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two people at a bar counter. One character looks serious, sober, and slightly envious, standing next to an empty drink coaster. The other character is cheerfully holding a colorful cocktail with a little umbrella, looking carefree and relaxed. Around them, speech bubbles convey the sober character''s thought: ''I envy people who drink—they at least know what to blame everything on.'' The background includes classic bar elements: shelves of bottles, glasses, a neon ''Bar'' sign, and a bartender polishing a glass while smirking. Both characters have exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the humor: the sober person with a wistful, slightly jealous look, and the drinker with a mischievous grin. The art style is light, bright, and comical with rounded shapes and vibrant colors, capturing a playful, everyday humor vibe without any negativity or offense.'),
 (1445, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A man''s house is his hassle.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, slightly messy suburban house with a frustrated man standing in front of it. The man looks overwhelmed and scratching his head. Around him are various small visual representations of household hassles: a leaking faucet dripping water, a pile of unopened mail, a lawn mower stuck in the grass, and a broken window. The house appears normal but with exaggerated signs of minor problems to emphasize hassle. The background includes a mailbox and a small garden with some weeds. The overall tone is light, with bright colors and expressive, exaggerated facial features on the man to highlight his amused frustration. The scene should be clear and simple, focusing on the playful idea that a man’s house brings trouble—turning the common saying “a man’s home is his castle” into a joke about hassles.'),
 (1452, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A pat on the back is only a few inches from a kick in the pants.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side. One character is cheerfully giving the other a friendly pat on the back with a big smile, while the other character looks nervously over their shoulder as a foot is comically just inches away from delivering a kick to their pants. Emphasize the close proximity between the pat and the potential kick with motion lines to suggest both gestures happening almost simultaneously. The setting is simple, such as an office or casual social environment, with minimal background details to keep focus on the interaction. Use bright, vibrant colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect, creating a lighthearted and relatable visual pun about the thin line between praise and trouble.'),
 (1466, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A shortcut is the longest path between two points.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a character attempting to take a shortcut between two points labeled ''Start'' and ''End.'' The ''shortcut'' is actually a long, winding, and convoluted path making many loops and detours, stretching much farther than the direct straight line between the points. The character looks tired and confused, wearing hiking gear with a map in hand. The landscape includes trees, rocks, and signposts pointing toward the ''Shortcut'' path and the ''Direct'' path, with the direct path shown as a straight, shorter line. The style is light-hearted and colorful, emphasizing the irony that the shortcut is clearly the longest way. A speech bubble over the character says, "This doesn''t feel like a shortcut..." The overall tone is playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and simple, clear visuals that highlight the joke''s message.'),
 (1488, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Abstainer: a weak person who yields to the temptation of denying himself a pleasure.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a character standing at a dessert buffet table loaded with cakes, pastries, and ice cream. The character looks weak and conflicted, sweating nervously and biting their lip while reaching for a silver platter labeled ''Abstainer.'' The character wears casual clothes and has exaggerated wide eyes and shaky hands to show inner struggle. Nearby, a thought bubble shows a devilish slice of cake tempting the character while a little angel holding a sign that says ''Deny pleasure!'' stands on their shoulder. The background includes a simple room with a few party decorations like balloons and a banner that says ''Temptation Party.'' Bright, colorful, and lighthearted cartoon style focusing on the character''s humorous difficulty resisting desserts, with no real negativity or harshness.'),
 (1629, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Diplomacy -- the art of saying ''Nice doggie'' until you can find a stick.', 'Wynn Catlin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a nervous-looking person cautiously facing a large, friendly-looking dog. The person is smiling awkwardly and saying ''Nice doggie'' with exaggerated sweat drops on their forehead to show tension or anxiety. The dog is wagging its tail innocently, perhaps tilting its head in curiosity. Behind the person, slightly hidden but visible, is a large stick on the ground, as if they are ready to grab it if needed. The setting should be a simple outdoor park or backyard with grass and maybe a few trees. Make the characters cartoonish with exaggerated expressions: the person''s nervousness and the dog''s friendliness should be clear and exaggerated for comedic effect. Keep the image lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the idea of someone staying polite and diplomatic while secretly planning self-defense in a funny, non-threatening way.'),
 (1760, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'How come wrong numbers are never busy?', 'Stephen Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a vintage-style rotary phone with a comical anthropomorphic expression. The phone looks relaxed and carefree, sitting on a small table or desk with a cozy background of a home office or living room. Around the phone, there are speech bubbles showing missed call notifications and a text like "Wrong Number" repeatedly popping up. Nearby, a frustrated person is holding a mobile phone, looking confused or surprised as they try to make a call but see "Number Busy" on their phone screen. The wrong number phone itself humorously has no ''busy'' sign or any call in progress, maybe even wearing sunglasses or lounging, emphasizing that it’s never occupied. The overall tone is light and amusing, with bright colors and slightly exaggerated expressions to highlight the irony that wrong numbers never seem busy.'),
 (1773, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I always wanted to be somebody, but I should have been more specific.', 'Lily Tomlin', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a mirror, looking slightly puzzled or disappointed. The person is wearing everyday casual clothes and has a thought bubble above their head containing a vague or generic silhouette of a person labeled ''Somebody.'' Around the character, scribbled labels or sticky notes show various specific professions or roles, like ''Artist,'' ''Scientist,'' ''Musician,'' and ''Entrepreneur,'' all crossed out. The background is a modest bedroom with typical objects like a bed, a desk, and a lamp to suggest a casual, relatable setting. The overall tone is lighthearted, highlighting the wordplay on ''somebody'' and the frustration of vague ambition in a funny, cartoon style with exaggerated expressions and bright colors.'),
 (1786, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I can write better than anybody who can write faster, and I can write faster than anybody who can write better.', 'A. J. Liebling (1904-1963)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two quirky characters seated at desks facing each other in a friendly writing contest. One character is frantically scribbling pages with a giant pencil, sweat flying off them, clearly focused on speed but their writing looks a bit messy. The other character calmly composes their writing with neat, precise handwriting, looking confident and relaxed but slower. Both have exaggerated expressions reflecting their pride in their skill: the fast writer looks wild and determined, the better writer looks thoughtful and smug. Between them is a scoreboard with two columns labeled ''Speed'' and ''Quality,'' each side having ticks and crosses humorously highlighting their strengths and weaknesses. The background includes stacks of crumpled papers and an amused audience of cartoon animals or objects cheering them on. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, emphasizing the playful competition between fast writing and good writing without any tension or negativity.'),
 (1813, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I generally avoid temptation unless I can''t resist it.', 'Mae West', 'A humorous cartoon featuring a character standing at a fork in a path labeled ''Temptation'' on one side and ''Self-Control'' on the other. The character looks tempted but amused, scratching their head with a mischievous smile. Around them are floating symbols of temptations such as a glowing chocolate bar, shopping bags, a smartphone with social media icons, and a comfy couch. The signposts are bright and colorful with playful lettering. The background is light and cheerful, emphasizing a fun, lighthearted mood without any negative or threatening elements.'),
 (1826, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I like the word ''indolence''. It makes my laziness seem classy.', 'Bern Williams', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cozy living room with a relaxed character lounging comfortably on a plush armchair. The character is wearing a fancy robe and slippers, holding a book titled ''Fancy Words'' or ''Classy Vocabulary'' with a sly smile. A small pet, like a cat or dog, lies lazily beside the chair. Above the character, a speech bubble contains the words: "I like the word ''indolence''. It makes my laziness seem classy." The setting includes a side table with a cup of tea or coffee and a stack of books, emphasizing leisure and sophistication in a funny way. The overall vibe is lighthearted and silly, highlighting the contrast between the fancy word and the idea of laziness.'),
 (1919, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'If you''re going to do something tonight that you''ll be sorry for tomorrow morning, sleep late.', 'Henny Youngman', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy bedroom during morning time. The main character, a sleepy person in pajamas with messy hair, is comfortably stretched out in bed with a blissful smile. Sunlight streams through a window showing a bright morning sky, but a large clock nearby shows a late hour, like 11 AM. On a bedside table, include an alarm clock turned off and a cup of coffee untouched. The overall vibe should be relaxed and slightly mischievous, emphasizing the joke’s idea that sleeping late is the best way to avoid morning regrets. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated, friendly features and simple lines for a cartoon look.'),
 (2213, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Procrastination is the art of keeping up with yesterday.', 'Don Marquis', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a character sitting at a cluttered desk with a calendar on the wall behind them showing yesterday''s date circled prominently. The character looks relaxed and cheerful, casually leaning back in their chair with a big smile, clearly not rushing to do any work. On the desk are several crumpled papers and a clock showing the current time, suggesting time is moving forward but the character remains stuck in the past. The background could include a window showing the sun setting, implying the day is ending, while the character is focused on ''keeping up'' with yesterday''s tasks. Include playful details like a sticky note that reads ''Tomorrow''s work can wait!'' and a coffee mug labeled ''Procrastinator''s Brew.'' The overall art style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish to emphasize the humor and laid-back attitude of procrastination.'),
 (2991, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Sleep Humor, Unknown', 'I get my best ideas when I''m asleep.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a person sleeping peacefully in a cozy bedroom at night. They are lying in bed with a big smile, eyes closed, wearing pajamas and a nightcap for a touch of classic cartoon style. Above their head, inside a large thought bubble, show a glowing lightbulb to represent a ''best idea'' being born during sleep. The room should have a bedside table with a simple lamp and an alarm clock showing a late hour. Optionally, depict a small dreamlike cloud drifting from their head with whimsical shapes or symbols related to ideas, such as gears, stars, and question marks. The overall tone is lighthearted and fun, avoiding anything scary or complicated.'),
 (2691, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'By the time you can make ends meet, they move the ends.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a stressed-out adult trying to literally ''make ends meet.'' Show the character holding two ropes or puzzle pieces labeled ''ends'' that are clearly meant to connect. The character struggles to join these ends together, but in the background, a sneaky, playful pair of hands (maybe belonging to a mischievous child or an unseen character) are moving one ''end'' farther away, just out of reach. The setting is simple, indoor or outdoor is fine, with clear focus on the character and the two ends. Use exaggerated facial expressions showing frustration and mild confusion. The style should be light-hearted and comical with bright colors emphasizing the absurdity of the impossible task.'),
 (2832, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Every purchase has its price.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful shopper happily leaving a store with a large shopping bag in one hand. The shopper is looking at a receipt that is comically long, trailing behind like a scroll. Nearby, a clerk behind the cash register is shrugging with a smile. Above the scene, a large price tag floats in the air, but instead of a number, it shows a scale balancing money on one side and something humorous like a clock or a pile of chores on the other, implying the cost isn''t just money. The background includes a simple store counter, a sign that says ''Sale Today!'', and some playful, exaggerated expressions on the characters to emphasize the joke that buying things always comes with some kind of price beyond just money. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and rounded shapes to keep the tone fun and relatable.'),
 (2927, 'Everyday Life, Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'He''s a legend in his spare time.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting comfortably on a couch wearing casual clothes, holding a remote control in one hand and a trophy or medal labeled ''Legend'' casually balanced on his knee or resting beside him. The background includes a clock showing an unexpected time (like 3:00 AM) suggesting ''spare time,'' and maybe a calendar with some days marked ''busy'' and others ''spare.'' The man''s expression is proud but relaxed, emphasizing the irony that he''s only a ''legend'' when not doing his regular activities. The room should feel cozy and informal, with a few humorous details like a pet watching in disbelief or a snack bowl nearby. The style is cheerful, bright, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and clear emphasis on the casual, off-duty vibe of the man being a ''legend.'''),
 (2588, 'Everyday Life, Inspirational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'With the new day comes new strength and new thoughts.', 'Eleanor Roosevelt', 'A cheerful cartoon scene showing a person waking up in the morning, stretching widely next to a large, sunny window. The sunlight streams in brightly, casting warm, vibrant colors over a cozy bedroom. On a bedside table nearby, there is an alarm clock showing early morning time and a steaming cup of coffee or tea. Above or around the person’s head are cartoon-style thought bubbles illustrating energetic ideas and positive symbols, like light bulbs, muscles flexing, and smiling faces, representing ''new strength'' and ''new thoughts.'' The overall mood is optimistic and refreshing, capturing the feeling of waking up with renewed energy and ideas. The style should be lighthearted, colorful, and inviting, similar to a motivational cartoon panel.'),
 (1174, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Irony, Relatable Humor', 'If that''s how you feel, then I can''t trust your judgement.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual setting, such as a living room or coffee shop. One character, looking slightly exasperated or skeptical, is pointing a finger in mild disbelief towards the second character, who has a sheepish or guilty expression. The second character''s body language suggests they''ve just said something questionable or suspicious. Include a speech bubble from the first character with the phrase: ''If that''s how you feel, then I can''t trust your judgement.'' The setting is lighthearted, with simple warm colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and mild distrust without hostility. The scene should be playful and relatable, capturing a moment of humorous doubt between friends or acquaintances.'),
 (1185, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Physical Comedy, Relatable Humor', 'May every sock you wear but slightly rotated, enough to be uncomfortable', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a pair of feet wearing socks. One sock is perfectly normal, while the other sock on the opposite foot is clearly twisted or rotated awkwardly so that it looks uncomfortable. The feet rest on a floor with a few scattered shoes nearby, as if the person just put on their socks and is already annoyed by the way one is rotated. The person’s legs are visible up to mid-calf and their expression (off to the side or as a small inset bubble) shows mild discomfort or exasperation. The color palette is bright and playful, emphasizing the small but relatable daily annoyance of wearing a sock the wrong way. The style is a lighthearted cartoon, with exaggerated sock rotation and an expressive face to enhance the humor without any violence or sensitive content.'),
 (1172, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Pun', 'I wish for a moment you could stand in my shoes, then you''d know what it is a drag it is to see you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters. The first character stands looking slightly annoyed with an exaggerated expression of frustration. The second character stands next to them with a pair of oversized, cartoonishly large shoes on their feet, looking confused or uncomfortable. The setting is simple, like a plain background or a casual indoor scene. Between them is a whimsical cloud-shaped thought bubble showing the phrase, "I wish for a moment you could stand in my shoes," and below it a sad little shoe dragging along the ground to visually represent the pun, with exaggerated drag marks behind it. The style is colorful and playful, with bold lines and simple shapes to emphasize the joke’s lighthearted tone. No background distractions, focusing on the characters and the large shoes and drag marks to highlight the pun.'),
 (1176, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Pun, Relationship Humor', 'If you were the trophy at the end of my race, I''d walk backwards.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person running a race on a typical track, with a goofy and exaggerated expression. Ahead of them is a shining, comically oversized trophy placed on a pedestal at the finish line. The runner, instead of rushing forward, is depicted tiptoeing or walking backwards with a reluctant or mischievous look, glancing over their shoulder toward the trophy. The background includes a stadium with simple crowd silhouettes cheering, a finish line banner fluttering, and the classic running track lines clearly visible. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated features for comedic effect and a clear focus on the runner’s backward movement towards the trophy rather than forward running. No other people should be too detailed or intrusive.'),
 (1189, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'May you forever feel your cellphone vibrating in your pocket even when it''s not there', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting or standing with a puzzled and slightly startled expression, looking at their empty pocket or patting it as if feeling something there. Their other hand is holding a cellphone, looking calm or neutral. The pocket should be noticeably empty, without any phone inside. Around the person, wavy lines or small vibrating motion lines illustrate the sensation of a vibrating phone coming from the pocket, even though no phone is there. The setting is casual, like a street or home background lightly drawn to keep focus on the person. The style is playful and exaggerated, emphasizing the mental image of phantom phone vibrations as a common funny experience.'),
 (1203, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable Humor', 'This is why everyone talks about you.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a casual conversation. One character is standing with an exaggerated look of pride or smugness, pointing playfully at the other character, who appears surprised or sheepish. The setting is informal, like a simple urban park bench or a cozy café table, to suggest a friendly chat. Add subtle background details such as a few people in the distance whispering or glancing toward the main characters, reinforcing the idea that the subject of the conversation is well-known or talked about. Use bright, cheerful colors and expressive facial features to emphasize humor and lightheartedness. The style should be cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to capture the playful tone of the phrase "This is why everyone talks about you." No violent, sexual, or political content should be included.'),
 (1195, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable Humor, Technology Humor', 'May your laptop and phone charge all night without you noticing the cord isn''t plugged in', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person asleep peacefully in bed with a laptop open on their lap and a phone beside them on a bedside table. Both devices have prominent charging icons on their screens. However, the charging cords from both devices are visibly unplugged from the wall socket nearby. The unplugged cords droop loosely, with the wall socket clearly empty, highlighting the irony of charging. The room should look cozy, with a nightstand, a lamp turned off, and a digital clock showing a late hour. Include a thought bubble above the sleeping person with a smiley or Zzz to show deep sleep. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and bright, simple colors to emphasize the joke without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (1210, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'You haven''t been yourself lately. We''ve all noticed the improvement.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene in a cozy living room setting with three characters. In the center, a slightly surprised person with a neutral expression stands, representing ''you.'' To the left, a friend or family member with a big smile and exaggerated thumbs up gestures toward the surprised person. To the right, another character nods approvingly, also smiling. Speech bubbles above the two characters contain the phrase, ''You haven''t been yourself lately.'' and ''We''ve all noticed the improvement.'' The surprised person looks puzzled but slightly pleased. The room includes a comfy couch, a small coffee table with a plant, and a picture frame on the wall showing a happy group photo. The overall style should be lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated in a classic humorous cartoon format, emphasizing friendly and positive vibes without any harshness.'),
 (1187, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Relatable, Technology Humor', 'May you always get up from your computer with your headphones still attached', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk, working on a computer. The person is in mid-motion, standing up but looking surprised as their headphones are still plugged into their ears and connected to the computer. The headphones and cord are visibly stretched as the person moves away from the desk, creating a comical tension in the wire. The expression on the person''s face is a mix of surprise and mild frustration. The desk is cluttered with typical office items like a coffee mug, a notebook, and a mouse. The background is a simple office or home workspace setting, drawn in bright, cheerful colors to enhance the playful mood of the cartoon.'),
 (1201, 'Everyday Life, Insults, Relationship Humor, Wit', 'There is nothing you can do that will make me think less of you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side in a casual setting, such as a cozy living room or park bench. One character is confidently looking at the other with a calm, reassuring smile, arms crossed or hands casually in pockets. The second character appears surprised, maybe with wide eyes or a slight blush, as if hearing an unexpected compliment. Above them, a speech bubble from the first character says, ''There is nothing you can do that will make me think less of you.'' Include light-hearted visual elements like warm colors, friendly exaggerated expressions, and perhaps small hearts or sparkle effects around the speaking character to emphasize kindness and acceptance. The background should be simple and non-distracting, with fun cartoon lines or subtle patterns, giving the overall feel of a positive, heartfelt moment made funny by the sincerity and openness of the statement.'),
 (1734, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Life, Quotes', 'Half our life is spent trying to find something to do with the time we have rushed through life trying to save.', 'Will Rogers', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in two different moments side by side. On the left, the character is shown in a rush, wearing casual clothes, running hurriedly with a briefcase in one hand and a coffee cup in the other, looking stressed. The background shows a ticking clock prominently with the hands moving quickly. On the right side, the same character looks tired and bored, sitting in an armchair or on a couch with a blank expression, holding a remote control or staring out the window. Around them are scattered objects like a calendar, a phone, and maybe a clock showing slow, dragging time. The overall composition highlights the irony: the rushed, busy time contrasted with the later aimlessness trying to fill the time saved. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and simple bold lines to emphasize the humor in life''s irony without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1932, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Money Humor, Quotes', 'I''m opposed to millionaires, but it would be dangerous to offer me the position.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful middle-aged person sitting comfortably in a plush office chair behind an oversized desk piled high with money bags labeled with dollar signs. The person wears a slightly mischievous smile and casual business attire. Behind them is a sign or poster on the wall that says ''Millionaire Club.'' In the background, a few people looking serious or disapproving are observing from a distance, representing the ''opposed to millionaires'' stance. The setting is a bright, colorful office with stacks of coins, dollar bills, and investment charts scattered around, emphasizing wealth. The overall tone should be light-hearted and playful, exaggerated expressions, and cartoon style to convey the ironic contradiction in the joke, without violence or any negative connotations.'),
 (1695, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Few things are harder to put up with than the annoyance of a good example.', 'Mark Twain', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a typical everyday setting, such as a park bench or office break room. One character is trying to relax or take a break, looking visibly annoyed or frustrated. Nearby, the other character is standing upright with a confident, proud posture, wearing a superhero cape or a shining badge labeled ''Good Example.'' This character looks cheerful and exemplary, smiling as if they’ve just done something impressive or admirable. The annoyed character''s face should clearly show exasperation, rolling their eyes or scratching their head in disbelief at how difficult it is to ''put up with'' the other character''s shining behavior. Include simple background elements like trees or a coffee machine to give context without distraction. The overall style should be whimsical and lighthearted, emphasizing the playful irony of being annoyed by someone doing the right thing.'),
 (1815, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I hate advice unless I''m giving it.', 'Jack Nicholson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting comfortably in a cozy armchair, holding a megaphone and looking very confident and pleased while speaking. Around them, several smaller versions of themselves stand nearby, each holding a sign with advice written on it (e.g., ''Be patient,'' ''Stay positive,'' ''Eat healthy''). The person in the chair looks annoyed and is covering their ears, clearly disliking hearing the advice. The background is a simple living room with a bookshelf, a lamp, and a window. The overall tone is light and funny, capturing the irony that the character dislikes receiving advice but enjoys giving it to others.'),
 (1409, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'A good sport has to lose to prove it.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters after a sports match, like tennis or soccer. One character is clearly the winner, smiling and holding a trophy or medal confidently. The other character, the ''good sport,'' is mockingly losing on purpose — they have a playful, exaggerated sad face while gently letting the winner celebrate. Emphasize the theme of sportsmanship, with casual sports attire and a simple sports field or court background that includes a net or goalpost. Add subtle comic elements like sweat drops, a scoreboard showing the winner''s higher score, and a speech bubble or sign nearby that reads "A good sport has to lose to prove it." The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, focusing on friendly rivalry and the humorous irony of ''losing to prove good sportsmanship.'' Avoid any aggressive or negative expressions.'),
 (2834, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Relatable, Unknown', 'Every time you clean something, you make something else dirty', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene in a bright, clean kitchen. A character, shown mid-cleaning with a cheerful or slightly mischievous expression, is wiping down a sparkling countertop with a cloth in one hand. Meanwhile, their other hand is accidentally knocking over a colorful, slightly spilling flowerpot or a stack of dirty dishes onto the floor, creating a mess. Show little dust clouds or tiny splashes to emphasize the mess happening offscreen or nearby. Include a small trash bin or cleaning supplies like a mop and bucket in the background, with some soap bubbles floating playfully in the air. The overall vibe is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the irony that cleaning one spot leads to dirt or mess somewhere else.'),
 (2842, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Social Humor, Unknown', 'Everyone is entitled to my opinion.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a confident character standing on a small soapbox in the middle of a casual social setting like a park or a party. The character should have a proud, slightly smug expression, holding a megaphone labeled ''My Opinion''. Around them, a small group of diverse people look on with mixed reactions—some surprised, some amused, some skeptical. Include speech bubbles with playful reactions like ''Really?'' and ''Here we go again!''. The scene should be lighthearted, showing the character as someone who loudly believes their opinions are universally important, emphasizing the joke’s irony without hostility or conflict. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated with cartoonish proportions to maximize humor and approachability.'),
 (3124, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Unknown, Word Play', 'You always find something in the last place you look.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person searching for a lost object, such as a car key, inside a cluttered room. The person looks exhausted and slightly frustrated, holding a flashlight in one hand and looking down at an empty table or floor where the keys were just found. The room is messy with scattered items like books, clothes, and a small plant. A small, cheeky clock on the wall shows time passing. Above the person’s head is a thought bubble that says, ''You always find something in the last place you look.'' The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated with expressive facial features and playful colors to reinforce the joke’s irony, avoiding anything violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (2904, 'Everyday Life, Irony, Unknown, Workplace', 'Hard work has a future payoff.  Laziness pays off now.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, show a person working hard at a desk cluttered with papers, books, a laptop, coffee cup, and a clock on the wall showing early morning hours. They look determined but tired. On the right side, depict another person lounging on a comfy couch with a big grin, wearing pajamas, eating snacks, playing video games or watching TV, with a relaxed cat curled up nearby. Above the hard-working person, add a thought bubble showing a pile of money or a trophy symbolizing future payoff. Above the lazy person, show a thought bubble with a clock indicating ''now'' and images like a couch, snacks, or a relaxing sunny scene. Use bright, cheerful colors and expressive cartoon faces to emphasize the contrast humorously without any negativity.'),
 (1236, 'Everyday Life, Jobs, Pun, Workplace', 'I wasn''t happy being a glue salesman, but I stuck with it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a salesman standing proudly beside a large display shelf filled with various colorful glue bottles and tubes. The salesman has a slightly exaggerated cheerful smile but a subtle look of resigned acceptance, conveying mixed feelings. Around him, several glue products have comical faces and arms, and one glue bottle is literally stuck to the salesman’s hand or clothes, emphasizing the pun. The background shows a small shop setting with bright, simple colors. The overall style is playful and lighthearted, with bold outlines and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun in ''stuck with it.'' No violence or sensitive content is present.'),
 (1253, 'Everyday Life, Knock Knock, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'Will you remember me in a year? (Yes.) \n Will you remember me in a month? (Yes.)\nWill you remember me in a week? (Yes.)\nKnock Knock. Who''s there?\nYou forgot me already?!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently and talking to a friend or partner. The first three panels or thought bubbles display the familiar questions: ''Will you remember me in a year?'', ''Will you remember me in a month?'', and ''Will you remember me in a week?'' Each time, the friend cheerfully replies ''Yes.'' In the final panel, the person suddenly knocks on a door or on the friend''s forehead with a playful expression, saying ''Knock Knock.'' The friend looks surprised and confused, asking ''Who''s there?'' The person then delivers the punchline with an exaggerated shocked face: ''You forgot me already?!'' The setting is casual, indoors or outdoors, with bright colors and simple lines to emphasize expressions and timing, capturing the playful irony of quickly being forgotten despite earlier confident assurances.'),
 (1414, 'Everyday Life, Love Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'A guy knows he''s in love when he loses interest in his car for a couple of days.', 'Tim Allen', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a man standing next to his car in a driveway. The man looks somewhat surprised or contemplative, with a small heart above his head to signify love. The car is shiny and well-kept, perhaps with a little sparkle on its surface to show it''s usually cared for. Nearby, the man holds a phone or has a thought bubble showing a romantic interest (for example, a smiling person or a heart symbol). Around them, include subtle background details such as a mailbox, a garden gnome, and a tree to give the scene a cozy, everyday feel. Make sure the man''s expression and body language show that he has recently become more focused on love than on his usual enthusiasm for his car. The overall style should be playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the humor and light mood.'),
 (2088, 'Everyday Life, Marriage Humor, Quotes', 'Marriage is mostly about knowing which hand towels you can use, and which ones for the important people who visit your wife''s home', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy home bathroom with two clearly distinct sets of hand towels visible. One towel rack is labeled ''For Family'' with plain, well-used towels, and another labeled ''For Important Visitors'' with fancy, decorative towels. A married couple stands nearby: the husband looks slightly confused, scratching his head, while the wife points to the towel racks with a knowing smile. The bathroom includes typical elements like a sink, mirror, and soap dispenser. The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish to emphasize the everyday domestic humor without any harsh or serious tone.'),
 (1550, 'Everyday Life, Marriage Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Any man who knows what is good for him will let his wife decide what is good for him.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a husband and wife standing in a cozy living room. The wife confidently holds a large, comically oversized remote control labeled ''Decision Maker'' with big buttons such as ''Dinner,'' ''Weekend Plans,'' and ''Home Projects.'' The husband looks amused but slightly resigned, with his hands raised in a playful ''I give up'' gesture. The husband is casually dressed, possibly in slippers and a comfy robe, while the wife is standing tall and assertive with a friendly smile. Background details include a couch, a coffee table with a newspaper titled ''Marriage Advice,'' and a calendar on the wall marked with various activities the wife has planned. The overall tone is lighthearted and warm, highlighting the everyday dynamic of a couple with a fun power balance, drawn in a colorful, exaggerated cartoon style to enhance the humor without any hostility or discomfort.'),
 (1844, 'Everyday Life, Medical Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'I told my doctor I broke my leg in two places. He told me to quit going to those places.', 'Kenny Youngman', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a doctor''s office. The patient is a comically surprised person sitting on an examination table, holding one leg wrapped in a cast with exaggerated bandages at two distinct spots, clearly indicating two broken places. The doctor stands nearby, wearing a white coat and holding a clipboard, pointing with a knowing smile as if delivering witty advice. The doctor''s speech bubble reads: "Quit going to those places." The background includes typical doctor''s office items such as a wall chart of human bones, a skeleton model, a medical cabinet with jars, and a framed diploma on the wall. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and the pun.'),
 (1407, 'Everyday Life, Mental Health Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'A good memory is one trained to forget the trivial.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting comfortably in an armchair, smiling and looking relaxed. Around them, several thought bubbles pop up. Some bubbles contain silly, trivial items like a single misplaced sock, a forgotten shopping list, or a small spilled coffee, all faded or crossed out, indicating they are being forgotten. One large, bright thought bubble above their head contains an important image, such as a calendar marked with a meaningful event or a shining light bulb symbolizing a valuable idea. The background is cozy and simple, with a bookshelf, a clock, and a cup of tea on a small table nearby, giving the sense of peace and focus on what truly matters. The style should be light-hearted, cartoonish, with exaggeration on the expressions to emphasize the humor about selective memory and forgetting trivial things.'),
 (2570, 'Everyday Life, Metaphor Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'When the only tool you own is a hammer, every problem begins to resemble a nail.', 'Abraham Maslow', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a variety of everyday problems or tasks. The person is holding an oversized, comically large hammer with a confident but slightly goofy expression. Around them, depict several objects or situations that clearly aren''t nails but are being treated as such: for example, a bent spoon, a broken clock, a tangled ball of yarn, and a flat tire, all looking surprised or confused. The background can be a simple home setting or workshop filled with random items. Make the style lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between the hammer and the unrelated objects to visually represent the metaphor from the joke.'),
 (2676, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Office Humor, Unknown', 'Bills travel through the mail at twice the speed of checks.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting an anthropomorphic bill and a check at a post office. The bill should look like a lively piece of paper with eyes, arms, and legs, smiling broadly as it races ahead, zooming with speed lines behind it. The check, also personified with sleepy eyes and slow movement, lags far behind looking tired and frustrated. The background should show typical postal elements like a mailbox, envelopes flying in the air, and a postal scale. A postal worker with a surprised or amused expression watches the scene, perhaps holding a stopwatch. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the joke that ''bills'' move faster through the mail than checks. Use bright colors and simple cartoon style to enhance the humor and clarity of the visual metaphor.'),
 (1823, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'I just recently had my Visa card stolen. Now it''s every-where I want to be.', 'Scott Wood', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person looking surprised and holding an empty wallet or a phone with a Visa card missing. The background is a colorful map or globe marked with multiple destination points like famous landmarks (e.g., the Eiffel Tower, Statue of Liberty, tropical beach, mountain resort). Around the person, semi-transparent Visa cards are floating or flying playfully toward these destinations, emphasizing the idea that the stolen card is ‘everywhere’ the person wants to be. The person’s expression is a mix of confusion and disbelief. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with bold outlines and bright colors to convey humor without seriousness.'),
 (2696, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Cash Flow: the movement of a paycheck as it goes down the drain.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a kitchen sink with water flowing from the faucet into the drain. Above the drain, a shiny paycheck (a paper bill labeled ''PAYCHECK'') is visibly sliding down toward the drain, as if being flushed away by the water. The paycheck has a worried face with cartoonish eyes and a small sweat drop to emphasize its ''distress.'' Around the sink, include typical kitchen elements like a dish soap bottle, a sponge, and a stack of unpaid bills and expenses papers piled messily on the counter nearby. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke about money quickly disappearing like it''s literally going down the drain.'),
 (3007, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I just got you $25 worth of lottery tickets. To save you time, I went ahead and scratched them off for you, and you won $2 - so here''s your $2!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a cozy living room. One character, looking proud and slightly smug, is handing a small wad of cash labeled ''$2'' to the other character, who looks mildly disappointed but amused. On a nearby table are several lottery tickets, some already scratched off with big colorful X''s or dollar amounts visible. The background includes a comfy couch, a coffee table with a coffee mug, and maybe a small potted plant. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive faces emphasizing the anticlimax of winning only $2 on multiple tickets. Speech bubbles or text could reinforce the joke: the first character says something like, ''I scratched them all for you!'' and the second replies, ''Thanks, here''s your $2!''. The overall tone is playful and casual, capturing the irony and mild letdown of the situation without any negativity.'),
 (2112, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Money isn''t everything. It isn''t even enough!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a cluttered desk surrounded by bills, an empty wallet, and a nearly empty piggy bank. The person has a tired, exasperated expression, with one hand holding a tiny coin and the other hand scratching their head. Above them, a speech bubble reads: ''Money isn''t everything. It isn''t even enough!'' In the background, a calendar hangs on the wall, with several due dates circled. Nearby, a small plant wilts in a pot, and a clock shows late evening, emphasizing the stress of financial woes. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with playful expressions and slightly exaggerated proportions to keep the mood humorous rather than serious.'),
 (2392, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The trick is to stop thinking it as ''your'' money.', 'IRS Auditor', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room with a person sitting comfortably on a couch, looking relaxed and contemplative. In front of them is a piggy bank or a jar labeled ''Money''. Above their head is a large cartoon thought bubble showing a dollar bill flying away or a hand taking money out of the jar, symbolizing the idea of ''losing'' or ''letting go'' of ownership. The room includes simple furniture like a coffee table with scattered coins and bills and a small plant. The person has a sheepish or amused expression, suggesting they are trying to apply the joke''s advice about mentally detaching from the money. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and simple lines, making it clear it’s a funny and relatable take on personal finance.'),
 (2113, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Money, it turned out, was exactly like sex, you thought of nothing else if you didn''t have it and thought of other things if you did.', 'James Baldwin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person split in two halves side-by-side. On the left side, the person is sitting on a simple couch looking frustrated and distracted, with thought bubbles filled with dollar signs and coins above their head, showing they can''t think of anything else but money. On the right side, the same person is relaxed and smiling, holding a magazine or a book with hearts, a beach ball, or other fun, unrelated icons floating above their head, indicating thoughts turned elsewhere once they have money. The background is a cozy living room with a small plant, a lamp, and a coffee table scattered with scattered bills on the left and leisure items on the right. The style should be lighthearted, bright, and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the contrast in thoughts humorously. Cartoon style with clear, simple lines, expressive eyes, and over-the-top features to maximize comedic effect.'),
 (2618, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'You never realize how short a month is until you pay alimony.', 'John Barrymore', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting at a table looking at a calendar with only a few days visible, emphasizing the shortness of the month. The man looks stressed but comical, holding a large envelope labeled ''Alimony Payment.'' Around him are typical household items like a coffee mug, bills stacked on the table, and a clock showing time passing. Maybe some exaggerated dollar signs float around the envelope to symbolize money slipping away. The calendar should have pages flipping quickly or showing fewer days than usual to highlight how fast the month feels. The style should be lighthearted and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s tone without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2400, 'Everyday Life, Money Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'The two most beautiful words in the English language are ''Check Enclosed.''', 'Dorothy Parker', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person holding an envelope happily. The envelope is oversized and clearly labeled ''CHECK ENCLOSED'' in big, bold letters. The character should have a big smile, sparkling eyes, and a relaxed pose, as if they''ve just received great news. Surround the character with lighthearted elements like floating hearts or sparkles to emphasize joy. The background can be a simple office or home setting with a desk and a mailbox nearby. Include humorous details like a to-do list with an unchecked item labeled ''Pay Bills'' or a calendar with a large dollar sign on today’s date. The overall tone is bright, colorful, and playful, with a clean cartoon style that focuses on the excitement of receiving a check in the mail rather than any specific monetary amount or financial stress.'),
 (2625, 'Everyday Life, Motivational Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'You''re never a loser until you quit trying.', 'Mike Ditka', 'A humorous cartoon scene with a determined cartoon character climbing a tall hill or mountain labeled ''Goal.'' The character is cartoonishly sweating but smiling, wearing casual clothes and sturdy shoes. At the bottom of the hill, a pessimistic cartoon character sits slumped on a bench clearly labeled ''Loser,'' holding a white flag of surrender. The background is bright and colorful with a few fluffy clouds and a sun shining encouragingly. The scene shows a clear contrast between the motivated climber making progress and the defeated character who has given up. Include playful details like motivational signs along the hill that say ''Keep Going!'' and ''Almost There!''. The overall feeling is uplifting and funny, emphasizing persistence rather than failure.'),
 (2593, 'Everyday Life, Motivational Humor, Quotes', 'Work hard and try your best at everything you do. That way, when you look yourself in the mirror after every day, you will never be disappointed.', 'Jim Joseph', 'A cheerful cartoon character is standing in front of a large bathroom mirror. The character is smiling confidently with both hands on their hips, wearing casual clothes like a t-shirt and jeans. The room is bright and simple, with a sink, toothbrush holder, and a small potted plant on the countertop. The mirror reflects the character’s happy face clearly. Around the character, faint shining or sparkle effects symbolize pride and self-satisfaction. The overall mood is positive and uplifting, with a clean, light color palette to evoke freshness and daily routine. The cartoon style is playful, with exaggerated expressive eyes and a big smile to emphasize the feeling of not being disappointed when looking in the mirror after a hard day’s work.'),
 (2860, 'Everyday Life, Motivational Humor, Unknown', 'Find two good reasons to do something; you can always find one good reason to do anything.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy home office. A person, looking thoughtful and slightly puzzled, is sitting at a cluttered desk covered with sticky notes, papers, and a coffee cup. Above their head is a big light bulb with two smaller light bulbs branching off, each containing a symbol representing a ''good reason''—for example, a smiling face and a dollar sign. Behind the person, a wall calendar and a bulletin board filled with reminder notes add to the busy vibe. The person appears to be debating or listing reasons to do something, scratching their head while looking at a long list with only one clear checkmark next to the first reason. The cartoon style is lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize confusion and optimism about finding reasons to act. No aggressive or controversial elements, just a playful visual of the mental process described in the joke.'),
 (1601, 'Everyday Life, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Character cannot be developed in ease and quiet. Only through experience of trial and suffering can the soul be strengthened, ambition inspired and success achieved.', 'Helen Keller', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a cheerful, slightly frazzled cartoon character standing in the middle of a chaotic, exaggeratedly difficult obstacle course. The course includes quirky elements like a slippery banana peel, a tangled rope, a small fire pit with harmless cartoon flames, and a steep, rocky hill. The character is wearing casual clothes and has a determined but slightly stressed expression. In the background, a bright sunny sky contrasts with the tough events happening in the foreground. Nearby, a large inspirational poster or sign is visible, showing a motivational quote about strength and success, giving a slightly ironic tone. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions and playful details to emphasize the idea of character being built through challenge and suffering, but in a fun, non-threatening way.'),
 (1634, 'Everyday Life, Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Do not let what you cannot do interfere with what you can do.', 'John Wooden', 'Draw a cheerful, cartoon-style character standing confidently on a small patch of green grass. Around the character are two symbolic areas: one side is cluttered with lots of crossed-out objects or icons representing things they ''cannot do'' (e.g., a dumbbell with a big red X, a chessboard missing key pieces, an unfinished painting), and the other side is bright and full of objects they ''can do'' (e.g., a soccer ball, a paintbrush with a colorful palette, an open book). The character is smiling and pointing happily to the ''can do'' side, ignoring the messy ''cannot do'' side. The background is simple with a sun shining above to convey positivity and encouragement. Use rounded, exaggerated features and bright colors to add a light-hearted, motivational vibe in a humorous cartoon style. No text is needed in the image, only clear visual contrasts between limitations and abilities.'),
 (1729, 'Everyday Life, Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Great moments come from great opportunities.', 'Herb Brooks', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confident, smiling person standing at the edge of a large door labeled "Opportunity" that is wide open. Behind the person, a bright spotlight shines dramatically, highlighting them as if they are about to make a grand entrance. In front of the door, a small podium or stage area is set up with a sign that says "Great Moments Here!" The character is dressed casually but looks ready for something important. There is a subtle clock or calendar in the background showing a significant date, emphasizing timing. The overall tone is lighthearted and optimistic, with simple lines and bright colors to convey enthusiasm and the anticipation of success from seizing opportunities. No other people or complex backgrounds are needed, just the character, the door of opportunity, and the stage-setting to reflect the inspirational message with a touch of humor.'),
 (1580, 'Everyday Life, Motivational, Pun, Quotes', 'Be like a postage stamp... stick to one thing until you get there.', 'Josh Billings', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, cheerful postage stamp with a smiling face and tiny arms and legs. The stamp is determinedly clinging onto an envelope, which is flying through the sky with motion lines indicating speed. Below, the ground is visible with a post office building in the distance marked clearly with a sign. The stamp’s expression shows focus and persistence, embodying the phrase in the joke. The style should be bright, colorful, and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon features such as big eyes and a cute smile on the stamp. Include whimsical clouds and a faint path showing the flight trajectory towards the post office. The setting should be simple but clear, emphasizing the stamp’s journey and its dedication to ''sticking to one thing until it gets there.'' No other characters or distractions in the scene to keep the focus on the postage stamp''s mission.'),
 (1412, 'Everyday Life, Motivational, Quotes, Word Play', 'A great attitude is a great talent.', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon character standing confidently on a small stage or platform, with a big smile and arms wide open. The character is surrounded by simple props that represent talent, like a paintbrush, a microphone, and a pair of juggling balls, but they are all slightly set aside or dimmed. Instead, a glowing, large smiley face icon or light bulb hovers above the character’s head to symbolize a ''great attitude.'' The background is simple and bright with rays or sparkles emanating from the character to show positivity. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the uplifting message that attitude itself is a remarkable talent.'),
 (3023, 'Everyday Life, Object Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'I recently decided to sell my vacuum cleaner, all it was doing was gathering dust.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room. In the center, a vacuum cleaner sits idly with visible dust clouds and tiny dust particles swirling around it, emphasizing that it hasn''t been used. Nearby, a cheerful person (gender-neutral) holds a small ''For Sale'' sign while looking amused. The vacuum cleaner has exaggerated cartoon eyes and a sad, bored expression to anthropomorphize its uselessness. The background includes typical living room objects like a couch, a rug, and a side table with a lamp. The overall color palette is bright and inviting, with a lighthearted, funny tone to highlight the joke about the vacuum cleaner just gathering dust instead of cleaning.'),
 (1377, 'Everyday Life, Office Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'A clean desk is a sign of a cluttered desk drawer.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a perfectly clean, tidy desk with a big smile, next to a drawer that is bursting open and overflowing with a chaotic jumble of papers, office supplies, snacks, random objects, and little clutter monsters or tangled cords spilling out. The setting is a simple office or home workspace with a computer, lamp, and coffee mug on the spotless desk. The drawer is exaggeratedly stuffed and messy, contrasting strongly with the spotless desk surface. The person looks slightly guilty but proud, highlighting the irony of the tidy desk masking hidden clutter.'),
 (1439, 'Everyday Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Help Humor', 'A man cannot be comfortable without his own approval.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man sitting comfortably in an armchair at home. The man looks relaxed but has a thoughtful, slightly puzzled expression on his face. Above him is a cartoon-style thought bubble showing a mini version of himself giving a thumbs-up with a big approving smile. The room is cozy, with a lamp, a small side table with a cup of tea, and framed pictures on the wall showing happy moments or self-achievements. The style is bright, simple, and exaggerated to emphasize the idea that the man’s comfort depends on his own approval. The mini version of the man inside the thought bubble should be drawn as a friendly, cartoonish figure to add humor and charm without any negativity or stress.'),
 (1679, 'Everyday Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Everything has been figured out, except how to live.', 'Jean-Paul Sartre (1905-1980)', 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene showing a wise-looking, slightly puzzled character sitting cross-legged on a mountaintop at sunset. The character is holding a large, ancient scroll with drawings and diagrams representing various big discoveries and inventions (like the wheel, a light bulb, a telescope). Around the character, there are floating question marks and a small campfire beside them. Above the character, a thought bubble reads: ''Everything has been figured out...'' and a second thought bubble below says: ''...except how to live.'' The background shows a peaceful natural setting—trees, stars beginning to appear, a moon rising. The style should be light, friendly, and amusing, emphasizing the contemplative yet humorous tone of the joke without any aggression or tension.'),
 (1998, 'Everyday Life, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'It''s a good thing we don''t get all the government we pay for.', 'Will Rogers', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a confused citizen standing at a government office window. The citizen holds a large stack of money labeled ''Taxes'' in one hand, while the other hand gestures with a puzzled expression. Behind the window, a bored-looking government worker is casually sipping coffee, papers and files scattered messily on the desk. On the wall behind the worker is a poster that says ''More Government? Not Today!''. Around the room are various signs of inefficiency: a dusty clock stuck at noon, a ''Help Wanted'' poster, and a fax machine covered in cobwebs. Outside a window, people are holding empty government service forms or waiting in a long line. The style is colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish, with expressive faces and a lighthearted, satirical tone, highlighting the disconnect between money paid and services received without any aggressive or political imagery.'),
 (1519, 'Everyday Life, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Always do right- this will gratify some and astonish the rest.', 'Mark Twain (1835-1910)', 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, friendly-looking character standing at the center with a confident pose, giving a thumbs-up. Surrounding the character are two groups of cartoon people reacting differently: one group is happily clapping and smiling, clearly gratified by the character''s actions; the other group is wide-eyed and mouths agape, clearly surprised and astonished. The background is simple with soft, uplifting colors. Include a large, playful banner or sign overhead with the words “Always do right” in bold, fun lettering. The overall style is whimsical and lighthearted, using exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the contrasting reactions of the two groups. Avoid any violent or negative imagery.'),
 (2797, 'Everyday Life, Procrastination Humor, Unknown', 'Don''t put off till tomorrow what you can do today.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting leisurely on a couch in a messy living room, surrounded by piles of unfinished tasks like laundry, dishes, and papers. The character is happily watching TV while holding a remote in one hand and a snack in the other. A calendar on the wall prominently displays today''s date circled with a big red marker, and behind it, there is a prominently visible sticky note that says: ''Don''t put off till tomorrow what you can do today.'' Nearby, a clock shows the late afternoon time, emphasizing procrastination. The overall mood is light-hearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions of contentment and laziness on the character. Bright colors and simple, cartoony lines add to the comedic tone.'),
 (1771, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Husbands are like fires; they go out when unattended.', 'Zsa Zsa Gabor', 'Create a humorous cartoon featuring a husband personified as a campfire in a cozy backyard setting at dusk. The ''husband fire'' looks like an actual small campfire with a friendly face made from flames and smoke. Nearby, a wife cartoon figure stands holding a watering can labeled ''Attention,'' looking slightly amused and preparing to water the fire. The fire appears to be flickering weakly and a bit smoky, showing signs of going out. Include simple elements like lawn chairs, a picnic table with marshmallows on sticks, and a starry evening sky to set a relaxed domestic scene. The style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on both characters to emphasize the joke’s pun about needing attention to keep the husband-fire burning.'),
 (1872, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'If at first you don''t succeed, try doing it the way your wife told you to', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy home workshop or living room. A frustrated man, wearing casual clothes and holding a broken or half-assembled object (like a small piece of furniture, a gadget, or a simple DIY project), looks puzzled and slightly annoyed. Next to him stands a confident woman, his wife, with her arms crossed and a knowing smile, pointing toward a neatly drawn instruction manual or blueprint. The background includes household elements like a couch, a lamp, or tools scattered humorously to imply previous failed attempts. The expressions should clearly convey the man’s initial stubbornness and growing realization, while the wife appears calm and triumphant. Bright, simple, and exaggerated cartoonish styles, with clear facial expressions and a few comedic details like a spilled toolbox or bent nails to emphasize the repeated failure before trying the wife’s advice.'),
 (2129, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'My wife gives me the speaking treatment.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a husband sitting quietly on a couch looking bewildered and slightly overwhelmed. He has a blank, somewhat confused expression and is holding a TV remote loosely in one hand. In front of him, his wife stands confidently with her arms crossed, looking very serious but without speaking. Little white speech bubbles surround her that have ellipses ("... ... ..."), indicating silence or giving him ''the silent treatment''. The living room is cozy with typical furniture: a coffee table, a lamp, and a family photo on the wall. The overall style is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the husband''s silent suffering and the wife''s confident silence, visually playing on the pun "speaking treatment" as a twist on the silent treatment but with no actual speaking happening.'),
 (1364, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes, Sports Humor', '95% of this game is half mental.', 'Yogi Berra', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a golf course. In the center, a golfer stands confused, scratching his head while looking down at his golf ball resting near a hole. A thought bubble above his head shows a split brain: one side is colorful and active, the other side is dull and half faded. Nearby, a scoreboard shows a quirky stat: "95% of this game is half mental." Around the golfer, elements typical of a golf course appear — a flagstick in the hole, a few trees, a golf bag with clubs resting on the grass, and a bright sunny day with a few fluffy clouds. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated to emphasize the pun and mental confusion, with facial expressions showing bemusement and mild frustration from the golfer. The overall vibe is playful and comical, capturing the ironic phrase in cartoon visuals without any aggressive or sensitive content.'),
 (1566, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'Are oscillating fans those people at the ball park doing the wave? (Or would they be called undulating fans?)', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set at a sunny baseball stadium filled with excited spectators. The focus is on a group of people doing ''the wave'' in the stands. Among the fans, one person looks confused while holding a handheld oscillating fan (the small electrical kind). The oscillating fan is clearly drawn with visible motion lines showing it moving side to side. Nearby, other cartoon fans are depicted humorously moving their arms like waves, while a thought bubble from the confused person shows a play on words: the oscillating fan is imagining the people in the crowd as literal fans moving in a wave motion. The stadium background includes typical elements like a baseball field, scoreboard, and cheer signs. A small caption or banner near the oscillating fan reads ''Oscillating Fans'' and near the crowd ''Undulating Fans'' to emphasize the pun. The style is bright, lighthearted, and playful, emphasizing the wordplay joke in a way that’s clear and visually funny without any negativity.'),
 (1379, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A closed mouth gathers no foot.', NULL, 'Cartoon scene showing a person with their lips tightly sealed, cheeks puffed out as if holding their breath, with a whimsical expression of cautious silence. In the same frame, a comical foot is humorously sticking out near their mouth, exaggeratedly large and cartoonish, as if the person almost put it in their own mouth. The background is simple and bright, emphasizing the character and the foot. The setting is casual, maybe an office or home setting, with minimal props like a chair or desk to keep focus on the person avoiding saying something that would cause trouble. The overall artwork should be lighthearted and playful, in a cartoon style with bold outlines and vibrant colors, capturing the pun and humor visually without any aggressive or unpleasant elements.'),
 (1444, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A man with an obsession is a man who has very little sales resistance.', 'C. S. Lewis', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing in front of a sales counter in a brightly lit store. The man has wide, eager eyes and a goofy smile, clearly fixated or obsessed on a shiny product displayed on the counter—a flashy gadget or a trendy item. Behind the counter, a cheerful salesperson is handing him a shopping bag overflowing with purchases, indicating the man’s inability to resist buying. Around the man, scattered price tags and discount signs emphasize the shopping theme. The background includes shelves stocked with similar tempting products. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and lively colors to emphasize the joke about obsession and low sales resistance—like a pun on ''sales resistance'' as both a psychological barrier and an electrical term. No violence or controversial content, just a fun shopping scenario illustrated in a cartoon style with exaggerated features and bright colors.'),
 (3070, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown', 'If America switch from pounds to kilos overnight, there would be mass confusion.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, exaggerated map of the United States with confused cartoon characters all around it. People are looking puzzled and scratching their heads while holding different weight items with labels switched from pounds (lbs) to kilograms (kg). For example, a person holding a bag of sugar labeled ''5 lbs'' looks surprised as the label suddenly changes to ''5 kg,'' and a scale nearby shows a wildly inaccurate weight. A confused supermarket worker stands behind a counter where price tags have been hurriedly changed from lbs to kilos, with question marks floating above their head. In the background, highway signs and a weather vane also have their measurements humorously mixed up (e.g., temperature in °C with confused drivers). The cartoon style is lighthearted and exaggerated with bright colors and expressive faces, emphasizing the pun on ''mass confusion'' through scales and weights scattered around the scene.'),
 (2650, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'A truck full of Worcestershire sauce crashed.  Sheriff to Deputy: ''What''s the situation?''  Deputy: ''It''s hard to say!''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a large truck that has overturned on the side of a road, spilling an exaggerated flood of dark brown Worcestershire sauce all over the ground. Include a sheriff and a deputy in classic cartoon police uniforms standing nearby. The sheriff is leaning slightly forward with a serious expression, holding a walkie-talkie or radio, while the deputy looks confused or at a loss, shrugging or scratching his head. Have some detail showing the sauce puddling thickly on the road and maybe dripping off nearby objects like cones or street signs. The background should be simple but include a road, some roadside greenery, and a small signpost labeled ''Worcestershire Sauce Truck.'' Make the style lighthearted and exaggerated with bold lines and bright colors to emphasize the silliness of a sauce spill accident.'),
 (3038, 'Everyday Life, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I stayed up all night to find out where the sun went, then it dawned on me', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sleepy, cartoon character with huge, exaggeratedly tired eyes, sitting outdoors at night wearing pajamas. The character is looking up at a dark sky filled with stars, holding a magnifying glass as if investigating something. Nearby, a large, bright sun is peeking over the horizon, partially rising, with warm rays spreading out. The background shows a gentle transition from night (dark blue and starry) to dawn (light orange and pink). The character''s expression changes from confusion to sudden realization, with a lightbulb or cartoon ''aha!'' symbol appearing above their head to represent the pun. The overall mood is light and playful, emphasizing the joke about ''the sun going away'' and then ''it dawned on me.'' The art style is colorful, simple, and exaggerated to enhance the comic effect, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon strip.'),
 (1574, 'Everyday Life, Puns, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Bachelors know more about women than married men; if they didn''t they''d be married too.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two male characters in a friendly, exaggerated style. On the left, a confident bachelor is smirking, holding a book titled ''Women 101'' and wearing casual clothes. On the right, a disheveled married man looks confused and overwhelmed, holding a wedding photo with a questioning expression. Between them is a thought bubble above the bachelor showing a crossed-out wedding ring, emphasizing he is unmarried by choice or knowledge. The background should be simple, with a living room setting including a couch and a small table with a lamp. The tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor without any negativity or offense.'),
 (2638, 'Everyday Life, Puns, Unknown', 'A man tried to sell me a coffin today. I told him -- that''s the last thing I need!', NULL, 'Draw a lighthearted cartoon scene featuring two characters standing on a quiet suburban sidewalk. One character is a quirky-looking salesman holding a small coffin-shaped sample with a hopeful smile. The other character is a surprised man wearing casual clothes, shaking his head and looking amused or mildly exasperated. There should be a speech bubble coming from the man saying, "That''s the last thing I need!" The background can include simple trees and houses to set a friendly neighborhood scene. Emphasize exaggerated facial expressions and body language to highlight the humor, keeping the style colorful and playful without any dark or morbid tones.'),
 (2987, 'Everyday Life, Puns, Unknown, Word Play', 'I gave all my dead batteries away today. Free of charge.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing beside a small table or box labeled ''Free Batteries.'' The table is filled with various used batteries with little X''s or ''dead'' signs on them, indicating they are out of power. The person is happily handing over a battery to another character who looks surprised but amused. Include a small sign or speech bubble near the giver saying, ''Free of charge!'' The setting is bright and simple, maybe a park or front yard, with playful exaggeration in the characters’ expressions to highlight the pun. Batteries should look cartoonish with eyes or faces that look tired or drained to add extra humor.'),
 (1369, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'A bore is a person talking who can change the subject back to his topic faster than you can change it back to yours.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting at a small café table outdoors. One character is shown as a slow, dull speaker — depicted as slightly droopy-eyed and yawning, holding a coffee cup with a speech bubble trailing a long, repetitive monologue. The other character looks frustrated and bored, holding a smartphone or notebook, trying to steer the conversation by pointing or gesturing toward a different topic with a speech bubble showing a new subject. However, a comic visual loop shows the first character quickly shifting the conversation back with a determined expression, almost like a boomerang arrow bouncing back toward his own speech bubble. The background includes simple café elements like a menu board, potted plants, and other patrons who look mildly amused or tired. The style should be colorful, cartoonish, and exaggerated with expressive faces to emphasize the humor in the relentless topic-changing back to the original "bore''s" subject, capturing the cyclical and tiresome nature of the conversation.'),
 (2202, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Please don''t ask me what the score is, I''m not even sure what the game is.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon showing a confused person sitting in a crowded stadium. The person is looking around bewildered, holding a large foam finger upside down. Around them, other fans are animatedly cheering, wearing team colors, waving flags, and holding scoreboards that clearly show the current score. The confused person has a thought bubble above their head with question marks and a tiny sketch of a ball and various sports equipment (like a football, basketball, and soccer ball) mixed together to emphasize their confusion about the game. The overall atmosphere is lively and colorful, with banners and lights typical of a sports event, making the confused individual stand out comically in the enthusiastic crowd. The style is playful and exaggerated to emphasize the humor of someone not knowing what''s going on at a sports game.'),
 (2464, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Time Humor', 'Three o''clock is always too late or too early for anything you want to do.', 'Jean-Paul Sartre (1905-1980)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person looking confused and frustrated while looking at a large wall clock displaying 3:00. The setting is a cozy living room with a sofa, a coffee table with a cup of coffee or tea, and a calendar on the wall with several events visibly marked but none at 3:00. The person is scratching their head or checking their watch, with a speech bubble showing thoughts like ''Too late or too early?!'' Nearby, a calendar and a planner are open, emphasizing the awkward timing. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive facial features highlighting the irony of the time being inconvenient for any plan. The overall mood should be relatable and funny, without any harsh or mean elements.'),
 (1989, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'It isn''t what you know that counts; it''s what you think of in time.', 'Benjamin Franklin', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a cluttered desk with an open book and a large clock behind them. The person looks surprised and slightly panicked, scratching their head as they stare at the clock, implying they are trying to remember something important just before time runs out. The thought bubble above their head contains jumbled question marks and lightbulbs, symbolizing ideas and confusion. The setting is a cozy study room with a calendar on the wall marked with a deadline date. The overall mood is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and playful details like a half-filled coffee cup and scattered papers, emphasizing the joke about timing and memory rather than pure knowledge. Make sure the illustration uses bright colors and simple, cartoonish lines to enhance the humor and relatability of the moment.'),
 (1802, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'I don''t know why I did it, I don''t know why I enjoyed it, and I don''t know why I''ll do it again.', 'Bart Simpson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a puzzled person sitting in the middle of a messy room. The person has a confused and slightly amused expression, scratching their head as if baffled by their own behavior. Scattered around are various random objects symbolizing strange activities—such as a spilled bowl of popcorn, a video game controller, a half-read book with pages askew, an empty coffee cup, and a tangled earphone cord. The background includes a clock showing a random time to suggest the repeated nature of this mysterious action. Speech bubble above the person says, "I don''t know why I did it, I don''t know why I enjoyed it, and I don''t know why I''ll do it again." The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with exaggerated facial features and slightly cluttered surroundings to emphasize the confusion and repetitive cycle of behavior.'),
 (1917, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'If your name can be spelled wrong, it will be.', 'Monika Fuchs', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person standing at a reception desk or counter, looking at a nametag or nameplate that clearly spells their name incorrectly. The person has an exasperated or resigned expression. The nametag should have a name visibly misspelled in a funny or exaggerated way (e.g., extra letters, missing letters, or jumbled letters). Around the person, there could be a few other discarded or crumpled nametags on the floor with various misspellings to emphasize the recurring problem. The setting should be light and comical, such as a workplace or event lobby. Use bright, simple colors and exaggerated facial expressions typical of cartoon humor to enhance the joke’s punchline.'),
 (2095, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'Maybe I''m lucky to be going so slowly, because I may be going in the wrong direction.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person driving an old-fashioned car or riding a bicycle on a winding country road. The driver looks confused and is scratching their head, while a crooked road sign nearby points in multiple directions with question marks. A speedometer on the car or bike clearly shows a slow speed. The background shows a simple, exaggerated landscape with hills, trees, and maybe a confused dog or bird watching the driver. The style should be lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the slow pace and uncertainty of direction without any threat or negativity.'),
 (2284, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'The best cure for insomnia is a Monday morning.', 'Sandy Cooley', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tired person trying to sleep in bed, eyes half-open and looking frustrated. The clock beside the bed shows 3:00 AM. In the background, a calendar on the wall prominently displays ''Monday'' in big letters. The person has tousled hair and is surrounded by typical bedtime objects like a pillow and blanket. Outside the bedroom window, a bright morning sun is rising, emphasizing early morning. The overall style is light and funny, with exaggerated tired eyes and a slightly slumped posture to capture the feeling of insomnia and the dread of Monday morning as the unexpected ''cure.'' No violence or offensive elements, just relatable exhaustion and humor about starting the workweek.'),
 (1672, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relatable, Workplace', 'Every day I get up and look through the Forbes list of the richest people in America. If I''m not there, I go to work.', 'Robert Orben', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a modest bedroom in the morning. A person, looking a bit sleepy and wearing pajamas, sits on the edge of their bed with messy hair, holding a smartphone or tablet displaying the Forbes list heading and a scrolling list of richest Americans. The expression on their face is one of expectation turning into mild disappointment. Behind them, a window shows early morning light. To one side, there’s a small nightstand with an alarm clock and a coffee mug. In the background, a simple wardrobe and a work bag or lunchbox hint at getting ready for work. The thought bubble above the person reads: ''If I''m not there, I go to work.'' The overall cartoon style is light, cheerful, and exaggerated to emphasize the comedic tone of daily routine and the contrast between dreams and reality.'),
 (2142, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Social Humor', 'No man would listen to you if he didn''t know it was his turn next.', 'Ed Howe', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of men sitting on a bench or waiting in a line. One man in the middle is clearly trying to talk or share something with the others, but they all look distracted or uninterested, except one man who leans forward attentively, subtly pointing with his finger as if signaling that his turn is coming next. The setting can be a casual environment like a barbershop waiting room or a bus stop. Include speech bubbles to show the talking man’s attempt to communicate, while the other men have blank or disinterested faces, except the attentive man’s expression showing anticipation and readiness. The overall tone should be light and playful, capturing the social dynamic and the idea that men tune in only when their turn is near. Use bright, simple colors and exaggerated, expressive faces for comedic effect.'),
 (2483, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Social Humor', 'Too few rejoice at a friend''s good fortune.', 'Aeschylus', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two friends standing side by side. One friend is smiling broadly, holding a large, sparkling trophy or a big bag of money, clearly celebrating their good fortune. The other friend stands next to them with a grumpy or indifferent expression, crossing their arms and looking away. Around them, a small group of other people is gathered but they all look bored, distracted, or disinterested—some checking watches, others looking at phones, none paying attention to the celebration. The setting is a casual outdoor park or backyard with balloons and a ''Congratulations!'' banner that looks half-forgotten. The mood is lighthearted and exaggerated to show the contrast between joy and lack of enthusiasm. The overall style is colorful and cartoonish with big expressive faces and simple lines, emphasizing the humorous disconnect in the social response to one friend’s success.'),
 (1975, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wit', 'It is easier to be a lover than a husband for the simple reason that it is more difficult to be witty every day than to say pretty things from time to time.', 'Honore de Balzac (1799-1850)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two male characters in a split-frame format. On the left side, the ''lover'' is depicted as a relaxed, smiling man sitting casually on a park bench, giving a simple compliment like a small heart-shaped speech bubble that says ''You''re lovely!''. On the right side, the ''husband'' appears slightly stressed, surrounded by thought bubbles filled with symbols of wit and cleverness, such as light bulbs, clever quotes, and wordplay. The husband is sitting at a desk cluttered with crumpled paper balls, a pen, and a calendar showing every day marked with reminders, emphasizing the daily effort of being witty. Both characters wear casual clothes, and the overall tone is light-hearted with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the contrast between easy compliments and the challenge of daily wit. Include a simple background of a park on the lover’s side and a home office or study setting on the husband’s side to visually reinforce the difference in effort and environment.'),
 (2128, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Word Play', 'My wife and I tried to breakfast together, but we had to stop or our marriage would have been wrecked.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a husband and wife sitting opposite each other at a small breakfast table in a cozy kitchen. The table is filled with typical breakfast items like pancakes, eggs, bacon, coffee cups, and toast. Both are mid-bite or holding utensils, but their facial expressions show tension and discomfort rather than enjoyment, as if the act of eating breakfast together is proving difficult. Around the table, subtle visual cues like a cracked plate or slightly spilled coffee hint at the fragile state of their relationship. The background includes everyday kitchen details like a toaster, cereal box, and a window with morning sunlight. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish to emphasize the joke’s playful take on domestic life without any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (1673, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Self-Improvement Humor, Sports Humor', 'Every morning I ask myself two questions: ''What can I do today to be a better tennis player?'' And more importantly, ''What can I do today to be a better person?''', 'Andre Agassi', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a mirror in their bedroom early in the morning. The person looks thoughtful and determined, holding a tennis racket in one hand and a small book titled ''How to Be a Better Person'' tucked under their arm. On the bedroom wall behind them, a calendar with the day''s date is visible, and a tennis ball is rolling on the floor near their feet. The mirror reflects two imaginary thought bubbles above their head: one with a tennis court and a trophy, the other showing a heart symbol and a helping hand. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the person''s resolve to improve both in tennis and personal character. The setting includes simple bedroom furniture like a bed and a small plant for a cozy atmosphere.'),
 (2520, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Social Commentary, Sports Humor', 'We have become more and more not a nation of athletes but a nation of spectators.', 'JFK, NFL Hall of Fame Banquet, Dec 1961', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a large group of people sitting comfortably in a stadium-like setting. The majority are lounging in oversized chairs with snacks like popcorn, soda, and hot dogs, all intently watching a diverse group of athletes in the foreground who look somewhat tired, out of shape, or disinterested. Some athletes might be holding sports equipment lazily or sitting on the bench while spectators cheer wildly with foam fingers and banners. Include a scoreboard overhead showing the text ''Nation of Spectators.'' The overall atmosphere should be light-hearted and exaggerated, highlighting the contrast between active athletic participation and passive spectating in a fun and visually engaging way, with bright colors and clear expressions of enthusiasm from the crowd versus mild disinterest or fatigue from the athletes.'),
 (2148, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Wisdom Humor, Word Play', 'No one is as deaf as the man who will not listen.', 'Jewish proverb', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting on a park bench with his hands firmly clamped over his ears, eyes tightly shut, and an exaggeratedly stubborn expression on his face. Around him, a few people are trying to talk to him or get his attention—one person is leaning forward speaking animatedly, another is waving a hand, and a child nearby holds up a sign that reads ''Please listen!''. The background is a bright, cheerful park setting with trees, flowers, and a clear blue sky. The overall tone is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the man''s willful refusal to hear despite the obvious attempts of others to communicate with him.'),
 (1835, 'Everyday Life, Quotes, Wit, Word Play', 'I really didn''t say everything I said.', 'Yogi Berra', 'A simple humorous cartoon showing a character mid-conversation. The character is casually sitting or standing, possibly with one hand raised as if speaking. Speech bubbles float around the character''s head. Some bubbles contain clear, readable words or phrases, while others are blank or scribbled out to indicate things they ''didn''t say.'' The character''s expression is playful and slightly mischievous, as if admitting to holding back or editing their words. The background is minimal to keep the focus on the character and the speech bubbles, emphasizing the theme of selective speech or ambiguity in communication.'),
 (2967, 'Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Social Humor, Unknown', 'I can only be on my best behavior for so long. Then I need to laugh.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person sitting at a fancy dinner table, trying very hard to keep a serious, polite expression on their face. The person is surrounded by others who are elegantly dressed, sipping wine and chatting calmly. The person’s eyes start to widen and their mouth twitches as they struggle not to burst into laughter. A small thought bubble above their head shows a tiny laughing emoji or a burst of giggles to represent their rising urge to laugh. The setting is a bright, warm dining room with a chandelier, plates of food, candles, and wine glasses. The overall tone is light and fun, emphasizing the internal struggle of staying composed before giving in to laughter.'),
 (3127, 'Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Social Humor, Unknown', 'You are validating my inherant mistrust of strangers.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two strangers meeting awkwardly on a city street. One person is a suspicious-looking character with exaggerated features like narrow eyes and crossed arms, clearly showing mistrust. The other stranger appears somewhat puzzled but calm. A floating speech bubble from the suspicious character reads, ''You are validating my inherent mistrust of strangers.'' The background shows a few urban elements like a park bench, a lamppost, and a trash can to set a casual public scene. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the humorous mutual suspicion between strangers.'),
 (2977, 'Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'I don''t mean to interrupt people. I just randomly remember things and get really excited.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing in the middle of a casual group of three or four people who are talking. The person has an excited, wide-eyed expression and is enthusiastically raising one finger as if suddenly remembering or sharing an idea. Around the group, speech bubbles can be seen: the people around look slightly surprised or paused, highlighting the interruption. The background is a simple indoor setting like a coffee shop or living room, with a cozy vibe and minimal details so the focus remains on the characters'' expressions and body language. Draw the scene with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the humor and friendly social situation. No violent, sexual, or political elements, all lighthearted and relatable.'),
 (2990, 'Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'I get my best ideas in the morning.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in pajamas sitting upright in bed early in the morning, with messy hair and a sleepy but satisfied smile, holding a lightbulb above their head that is flickering weakly. The bedroom is softly lit by morning sunlight coming through a window with curtains slightly open. Nearby, an alarm clock displays an early time (around 6 or 7 AM). On the nightstand, a coffee cup with steam rising hints at the person needing caffeine to fully wake up. The overall tone is lighthearted and relatable, capturing the moment of groggy inspiration just after waking up.'),
 (2912, 'Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'He looked at me as if I was a side dish he hadn''t ordered.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a restaurant at a dining table with two characters. One character, a person sitting at the table, looks confused or slightly hurt, staring straight ahead. The other character, a waiter or a diner at the same table, looks at the first character with a puzzled or disappointed expression, as if they expected something else. The first character is drawn smaller, slightly off to the side like a side dish on a plate, perhaps with a small plate or tray subtly showing a side dish (like mashed potatoes or vegetables) nearby to reinforce the ''side dish'' metaphor. The restaurant background should be simple with a few tables and chairs, and soft warm lighting to keep it lighthearted. The style is cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor in the ''side dish he hadn''t ordered'' look. No text bubbles needed, just the visual interaction and expressions conveying the joke.'),
 (2968, 'Everyday Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'I can please only one person per day. Today is not your day. Tomorrow, isn''t looking good either.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a small office desk with a tired, slightly annoyed expression. The desk has a calendar prominently displayed, with today’s date circled in red. Above the desk, a wall sign reads: ''One Person Per Day Service.'' The person is holding a coffee cup with steam rising, looking at the calendar and shrugging. Nearby, a queue of two other characters waits with disappointed or frustrated faces. One character holds a clock showing time ticking forward, implying the wait for tomorrow. The overall setting is a friendly, everyday office environment with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and mild frustration of the day’s service limit. The mood is lighthearted and playful, without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (2997, 'Everyday Life, Relatable, Social Humor, Unknown', 'I hate when a couple argues in public, especially if I miss the beginning and don''t know whose side I''m on.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in the middle of a busy public park or street. The person looks confused and unsure, scratching their head with a puzzled expression. Nearby, a couple is engaged in a heated argument: the woman on the left is waving her finger angrily, with steam cartoon puffs coming out of her ears, and the man on the right looks equally upset, pointing back at her. No words or dialogue bubbles are visible to imply the argument just started before the observer arrived. Behind them are some onlookers with curious or bewildered faces. The setting includes simple park elements like a bench, some trees, and a lamppost. The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the confusion and social awkwardness, with bright, cheerful colors to keep the mood funny and relatable.'),
 (3013, 'Everyday Life, Relatable, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'I know the answer is in here somewhere, if I just keep on pressing buttons.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person sitting at a desk, staring at a complicated control panel or an old, overcomplicated microwave or device full of buttons of various shapes and colors. The person has a puzzled expression, scratching their head or looking slightly frustrated but determined. The control panel should have many buttons with no clear labels and maybe blinking lights. The background can be a simple kitchen or office environment with a clock, a cup of coffee, and scattered papers to enhance the feeling of a casual setting. The overall style should be colorful and exaggerated to emphasize the confusion and the endless pressing of buttons humorously.'),
 (3141, 'Everyday Life, Relatable, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'You know it is going to be a bad day when you forget your new password.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical home office or bedroom with a frustrated-looking person sitting at a desk in front of a computer. The person has a puzzled and slightly stressed expression while staring at the monitor. On the screen, there is a login page prompting for a password. Around the character, small visual elements emphasize their confusion: question marks floating over their head, a crumpled piece of paper marked ''Passwords'' tossed to the side, and a calendar on the wall showing the current day with a note saying ''New password day!''. The tone should be lighthearted and relatable, with exaggerated cartoonish facial features and body language to express the mental block and mild frustration of forgetting a new password. The environment should be tidy but casual, with perhaps a coffee mug labeled ''Need Coffee'' to add humor. No harsh or aggressive imagery—just a funny and friendly moment that many can identify with in everyday digital life.'),
 (2820, 'Everyday Life, Social Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'ELBONICS (el bon icks'') n. The actions of two people maneuvering for one armrest in a movie theater.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a dimly lit movie theater with two people sitting side-by-side in plush theater seats. Both individuals are reaching over toward the middle armrest between them, each awkwardly stretching their arm across the gap. Their facial expressions should show playful determination and slight frustration as they try to claim the single armrest. Around them, other moviegoers are enjoying the film, looking relaxed and not involved. Include typical movie theater elements such as a large screen in the background with faint silhouettes of characters showing, popcorn buckets by their feet, and dim overhead lights. The style should be colorful and exaggerated with big expressive eyes and cartoonish features to emphasize the awkwardness and competitiveness of the armrest battle without any anger or hostility.'),
 (2760, 'Everyday Life, Technology Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Did you ever try to reset the caps lock on your alarm clock first thing in the morning? Wow, talk about nightmares...', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person just waking up in bed with a groggy, confused expression, surrounded by typical bedroom objects like a nightstand and alarm clock showing early morning time. The alarm clock''s display prominently shows ''CAPS LOCK ON'' in large, bold, uppercase letters on a digital screen, glowing brightly. The person is pressing buttons on the alarm clock with furrowed brows, clearly trying to figure it out. Above them, a cartoon dream bubble shows a spooky, exaggerated nightmare scene with wild, screaming letters flying around—some shaped like monstrous uppercase letters. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the absurdity of trying to reset ''caps lock'' on an alarm clock and relating it to the nightmare experience of early mornings.'),
 (2899, 'Everyday Life, Unknown, Visual Humor, Word Play', 'Guess who I bumped into on my way to get my glasses fixed? Everybody', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a slightly confused person walking along a busy street or inside a crowded store on their way to an optometrist''s or glasses repair shop. The character is squinting and holding a smartphone or paper with an appointment note. Around them, a large group of diverse people are all bumping into each other and the main character, with exaggerated surprised and apologetic expressions. Some people are knocking over shopping carts, others accidentally bumping into displays or signs reading ''Glasses Repair'' or ''Optometrist.'' The scene captures the chaos caused by the main character''s poor vision before getting glasses fixed, with clear visual cues like distorted, blurry lines or squiggly light effects around the main character''s eyes to emphasize their impaired sight. The artwork should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish with rounded, exaggerated features to enhance the comedic effect, and no violent or inappropriate content.'),
 (474, 'Exaggeration, Facts, Humor, Science', '3026 years from now it will need to be really good or really bad. It''s 5050.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a futuristic calendar or digital clock displaying the year ''5050'' in big, bold numbers. Next to it, a quirky character (perhaps a time traveler or a futuristic historian) looks puzzled, scratching their head while holding a thick book labeled ''History of Years.'' Behind them, a simple timeline stretches from ''2023'' to ''5050,'' with a big question mark hovering over the year 5050. The background should be a light, playful futuristic cityscape with flying cars and robots casually going about their day, adding a subtle sci-fi vibe. The overall style is bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the character''s face to emphasize the joke about how, 3026 years from now, the year 5050 needs to be either really good or really bad to be notable. No violence, politics, or anything mature—just fun and lighthearted.'),
 (1702, 'Exaggeration, Friendship, Humor, Quotes', 'Friends may come and go, but enemies accumulate.', 'Thomas Jones', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a casual living room with two characters sitting on a couch. One character looks relaxed and is smiling, surrounded by a small group of cheerful, friendly-looking people standing or sitting nearby, symbolizing ''friends.'' On the other side, there is a large, comically growing pile of cartoonish, exaggeratedly angry or sneaky-looking figures clustering together with various mischievous or annoyed expressions, symbolizing ''enemies accumulating.'' The friends appear bright and open, while the enemies are crowded and slightly chaotic, almost stacking up like boxes or clutter in one corner. The setting should be light-hearted, colorful, and emphasize the contrast between the small manageable group of friends and the overcrowded building-up group of enemies to visually represent the joke’s idea. The overall style is fun and whimsical, with clear expressions showing friendliness versus irritation or cunning.'),
 (475, 'Exaggeration, Humor, Life', 'The best things in life are free. The second best things are very expensive.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels. The first panel shows a cheerful person standing outdoors with arms wide open, surrounded by simple pleasures like a bright sun, birds flying, flowers, and a smiling tree, emphasizing ''free'' things. The second panel contrasts this by showing the same person staring overwhelmed at a shopping cart overflowing with shiny, expensive items such as luxury gadgets, designer clothes, and fancy food, with a worried expression and dollar signs floating above their head. The setting should be lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the punchline that the best things in life cost nothing but the next best things cost a lot.'),
 (476, 'Exaggeration, Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'Ruckert''s Law: There is nothing so small that it can''t be blown out of proportion.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene featuring a tiny object—like a small pebble or an ant—in the center of the image. Surrounding it are exaggeratedly large objects or reactions: for example, a huge magnifying glass dramatically magnifying the small object to an enormous size, and a group of cartoon characters reacting with shock, surprise, or excitement as if the tiny object is a big deal. The background could be a simple living room or backyard setting to keep the focus on the tiny object and the exaggerated size difference. The style is playful and whimsical, with bright colors and expressive, humorous character faces emphasizing the joke about blowing something small way out of proportion.'),
 (477, 'Exaggeration, Humor, Science', 'The earth is like a tiny grain of sand, only much, much heavier.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a giant hand holding a tiny, detailed grain of sand. Inside the grain of sand is a miniature Earth with recognizable continents and oceans. The Earth/grain looks small and delicate, but a comic-style weight scale next to the hand shows an exaggeratedly high weight, represented with a big, bold number and a sweating cartoon character struggling to hold it. The background is simple with a bright sky and a few clouds, emphasizing the contrast between the Earth and the grain of sand. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with cartoonish expressions to highlight the joke about the Earth being a tiny grain of sand, but much heavier than one would expect.'),
 (2905, 'Exaggeration, Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Hard work never killed a man but it sure has scared a lot of them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a workplace setting where a timid man is nervously backing away from a large, anthropomorphic cartoon character labeled ''Hard Work.'' The ''Hard Work'' character looks intimidating but not violent: it might be a giant stack of papers with arms and an angry face, or a big toolbox with eyes and a stern expression. The man has wide eyes, sweat drops, and a worried expression, clearly scared but unharmed. The background shows a typical office environment with desks, a computer, and a clock on the wall. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the man''s exaggerated fear of the ''Hard Work'' character without any aggression or harm involved.'),
 (478, 'Exaggeration, Humor, Workplace', 'The average office chair on wheels travels about eight miles per year.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a typical office cubicle space. The main focus is a slightly worn office chair with wheels, depicted as if it’s a small vehicle, complete with a tiny road under its wheels drawn on the office floor. The chair looks tired but determined, maybe with little cartoon eyes on the backrest, giving it personality. Around the chair, typical office items like a computer monitor, keyboard, coffee mug, stack of papers, and a potted plant are visible. To emphasize the joke, include a small wall poster or whiteboard nearby with a sarcastic graph or note reading ''Annual Distance Traveled: 8 Miles'' as if it’s a serious statistic. The overall art style is colorful and playful with exaggerated expressions and clean lines, giving a light-hearted and funny representation of how little these chairs actually move despite their mobility potential.'),
 (1896, 'Exaggeration, Money Humor, Quotes', 'If you can count your money, you don''t have a billion dollars.', 'J. Paul Getty', 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a wealthy person surrounded by piles of money bags and stacks of cash so tall they reach beyond the frame. The character is standing confused, holding a giant abacus or calculator, trying to count the money but looking overwhelmed and frustrated, showing it''s impossible to keep track. Include exaggerated bags labeled with dollar signs and coins spilling everywhere. The background can have a fancy office or vault setting to emphasize extreme wealth. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated, focusing on the absurdity of counting such a huge fortune.'),
 (2485, 'Exaggeration, Music Humor, Quotes', 'Too many pieces of music finish too long after the end.', 'Igor Stravinsky (1882-1971)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an orchestra on stage. The conductor is looking at his watch with a tired or annoyed expression, while the musicians keep playing well past their expected stop time. In the audience, several people are dozing off, checking watches, or looking bored. A big clock on the wall behind the orchestra prominently shows that time has moved well past when the performance should have ended. Musical notes float whimsically into the air, extending far beyond the stage, emphasizing the long duration. The setting is a classic concert hall with elegant curtains and rows of seats.'),
 (2352, 'Exaggeration, Office Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'The nice thing about standards is that there are so many of them to choose from.', 'Andres S. Tannenbaum', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cheerful office or meeting room. At the center, a person is standing at a large whiteboard or bulletin board covered with numerous colorful charts, graphs, and documents, all labeled with different ''standards'' like ''Standard A,'' ''Standard B,'' ''Standard C,'' and so on. The person looks both overwhelmed and amused, scratching their head with a smile. Surrounding the board are piles of binders, manuals, and books, each labeled differently to emphasize the variety of standards. In the background, a few coworkers peek in, also looking puzzled but intrigued. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect of too many choices in standards.'),
 (2008, 'Exaggeration, Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'It''s not peace I want, not mere contentment. It''s boundless joy and ecstasy for me.', 'Kugell', 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene featuring a joyful character standing on top of a hill under a bright, sunny sky. The character is beaming with exaggerated happiness, eyes closed, arms stretched wide open as if embracing the entire world. Around them, vibrant colorful swirls and sparkles illustrate the ''boundless joy and ecstasy'' they desire. In the background, a peaceful meadow with flowers and a calm river contrasts with the character’s ecstatic energy. The scene should have a lighthearted, uplifting, and slightly exaggerated feel to emphasize the difference between simple peace and overwhelming joy.'),
 (1600, 'Exaggeration, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Chaos often breeds life, when order breeds habit.', 'Henry Brooks Adams', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two rooms side-by-side. In the first room labeled ''Chaos,'' things are wild and energetic: papers flying around, colorful paint splatters on the walls, a cat knocking over a plant, a person with messy hair excitedly painting, and various creative tools scattered haphazardly. The atmosphere is lively and spontaneous. In the second room labeled ''Order,'' everything is neat and repetitive: shelves lined with identical books, a person sitting at a desk asleep while folding the same paper repeatedly, a calendar organized perfectly, and a clock ticking monotonously. The contrast highlights energy versus dull routine. Both rooms are bright and detailed in a playful, exaggerated cartoon style to emphasize the difference between chaotic creativity and boring order without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (479, 'Exaggeration, Relatable', 'There must be hundreds of them.', 'Carl Sagan, age 8', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a huge wall completely covered with dozens of identical small sticky notes or paper scraps. The person, with a confused or overwhelmed expression, is scratching their head or shrugging as they look at the wall. The sticky notes are arranged haphazardly but packed densely, emphasizing the idea of ''hundreds of them.'' The setting should be lighthearted and simple, possibly an office or a study room. Include a small desk with a lamp and a computer to hint at a workspace without overcrowding the image. The style should be exaggerated and playful, with big eyes and expressive body language to highlight the amusement and slight bewilderment of the character. Avoid any detailed background or anything violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (2966, 'Exaggeration, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'I can be neat. I can be efficient. But why make everyone else look bad?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a tidy, organized person proudly standing in the center. They are wearing glasses and holding a clipboard, with a confident smirk. Around them are several other people looking disheveled and messy, with papers flying, coffee spills, tangled hair, and cluttered desks. The room looks like an office or classroom setting, with desks, chairs, a whiteboard, and scattered items on the floor. The neat person appears calm and collected, while the others look frazzled and chaotic. The contrast between the neat person and the messy crowd is exaggerated for comedic effect. Make the characters expressive and playful, with bright colors and cartoon-style outlines to emphasize the humor without any negative or hostile tones.'),
 (480, 'Facts, Food Humor', 'M&M''s stands for the last names of Forrest Mars, Sr., the candymaker, and his associate Bruce Murrie.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing two characters representing Forrest Mars, Sr. and Bruce Murrie standing side by side in a candy factory. Forrest Mars, Sr. is depicted as a friendly businessman in a suit with a lab coat over it, holding a giant, colorful M&M candy. Bruce Murrie, wearing a bow tie and suspenders, is smiling and holding another large M&M. Between them, a big sign reads ''M&M’s'' with the ampersand symbol styled as a candy. Around them are whimsical candy-making machines that are producing colorful M&Ms dropping into bags labeled ''Chocolate Candies.'' The background shows a bright factory setting with cartoon-style candy jars, conveyor belts, and candy decorations such as chocolate bars and peanuts to emphasize the candy theme. The style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated for humor, with playful expressions on both men as if proudly presenting their candy creation. No complex details or people in distress; the mood is light and educational-humorous.'),
 (481, 'Facts, Food Humor', 'Nutmeg is extremely poisonous if injected intravenously.', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, friendly-looking nutmeg spice jar with a smiling face. The jar has cartoon hands, one holding a giant oversized syringe filled with nutmeg powder instead of liquid. The syringe is aimed away from people, emphasizing no harm. Surrounding the jar are exaggerated warning signs like a cartoon skull-and-crossbones symbol with a big red ''X'' over it, and a speech bubble from the jar saying, ''Don’t inject me!'' The background is a simple kitchen counter with other spice jars looking surprised or shocked. The overall style is playful, bright, and exaggerated, with no real people or medical equipment other than the comical syringe made from spice elements. The tone is lighthearted and silly, focusing on the unusual fact rather than any scary or harmful imagery.'),
 (482, 'Facts, Food Humor, Good Question!', 'There are an average of 178 sesame seeds on a McDonald''s Big Mac bun.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a giant McDonald''s Big Mac bun as the central object. The bun is oversized and clearly labeled ''Big Mac Bun'' with sesame seeds visibly scattered all over the top. A cheerful cartoon character, resembling a scientist or statistician, stands next to the bun holding a clipboard and magnifying glass, counting or examining the sesame seeds with exaggerated focus. Around the bun, small speech bubbles or thought clouds float showing numbers like ''178'' with sesame seed icons. The background is a simple fast food restaurant setting with a whimsical vibe: a McDonald''s sign in the distance, a tray with fries and a soda next to the bun, and a few sesame seeds humorously floating or falling off the bun. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors, rounded shapes, and big smiles on the character. No text except the numbers and labels on objects should be included in the image.'),
 (483, 'Facts, Food Humor, Good Question!, Science', 'Pearls melt in vinegar.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a shiny pearl necklace resting in a small glass bowl filled with vinegar. The pearl necklace appears sad and slightly melting, with one or two pearls drooping or slipping off the string like they are dissolving. Nearby, a curious anthropomorphic pearl (with eyes and a worried face) looks on nervously at the vinegar. Add a kitchen counter setting with a vinegar bottle labeled clearly, and maybe a confused character holding a pearl, scratching their head while reading a small chemistry book titled ''Science Facts.'' The overall style should be lighthearted and playful with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s punchline about pearls melting in vinegar, capturing the unexpected chemical reaction humorously without any violence or complex elements.'),
 (484, 'Facts, Food Humor, History Humor, Puns', 'Hormel Foods mad the first batch of Spam in 1937. I heard they''re going to start making the second batch sometime next month.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a retro-style kitchen or factory floor with a large, old-fashioned machine labeled ''Spam Maker 1937''. The machine has a giant lever, gears, and steam coming out, all in a comical, exaggerated style. Nearby, there''s a calendar on the wall flipping to next month, emphasizing the long pause between batches. A confused worker in 1930s attire stands next to the machine scratching his head, holding a can of Spam from 1937, while a modern worker wearing a baseball cap and holding a clipboard looks puzzled at the machine, as if he just discovered it again. The background includes vintage posters advertising Spam and a clock showing that a very long time has passed. The overall tone is light and silly, using exaggerated expressions and an old-meets-new contrast to highlight the joke about the absurd delay in making the second batch of Spam.'),
 (485, 'Facts, Geography, Humor', 'The highest point in Pennsylvania is lower than the lowest point in Colorado.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon map scene showing two states side by side: Pennsylvania on the left and Colorado on the right. Above Pennsylvania, a small hill labeled ''Highest Point in PA'' barely peeks above the ground, looking very tiny and unimpressive, with a cartoon character shrugging or scratching their head. Colorado has a large mountain labeled ''Lowest Point in CO'' towering over the hill in Pennsylvania. The mountain should look very tall and exaggerated compared to the small Pennsylvania hill. Add playful clouds around the mountain top and a cheerful sun shining. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated to highlight the surprising fact that Pennsylvania’s highest spot is lower than Colorado’s lowest, adding a subtle, amusing vibe to geography.'),
 (486, 'Facts, Good Question!', 'If you have three quarters, four dimes, and four pennies, you have $1.19.  You also have the largest amount of money in coins without being able to make change for a dollar.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a kitchen table with coins spread out in front of them. The coins include three quarters, four dimes, and four pennies, each clearly visible and labeled. The person has a puzzled, slightly frustrated expression while staring at the coins. A thought bubble above their head shows a dollar bill with a question mark, emphasizing the challenge of making exact change for one dollar. On the table is a small coin jar labeled ''Change Jar'' and a calculator with a confused face emoticon on its screen. The background is a simple, cozy kitchen setting with minimal details so the focus remains on the coins and the person''s expression. The overall style is colorful, cartoonish, and lighthearted to highlight the quirky and tricky nature of the joke without any negativity or violence.'),
 (487, 'Facts, Good Question!, History Humor', 'The cigarette lighter was invented before the match.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in an old-fashioned inventor''s workshop filled with quirky gadgets and tools. One character is holding a classic cigarette lighter with a big proud smile, presenting it as if it were a brilliant invention. The second character looks confused and holds a simple matchstick in their hand, scratching their head as if puzzled by the claim. Display a timeline or signpost behind them with ''Cigarette Lighter: 1823'' and ''Match: 1826'' to subtly emphasize the joke. Make the setting vintage with wooden tables, blueprints scattered around, and an old incandescent light bulb hanging from the ceiling. Both characters have exaggerated cartoonish features such as big eyes and expressive faces to highlight the humor. Keep colors bright and playful to maintain a lighthearted mood.'),
 (488, 'Facts, Good Question!, History Humor, Music Humor', 'Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star was composed by Mozazrt when he was 5 years old.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a very young Mozart, a five-year-old child dressed in old-fashioned 18th-century clothing (a frilly collar and a small powdered wig), sitting at a small wooden piano with a big, satisfied grin. Above him, musical notes float playfully around. In the background, a night sky visible through a window shows a bright, twinkling star with a little smile, as if approving the music. The setting is a cozy room with classical music sheets scattered on the piano and floor. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the surprise of a child prodigy''s achievement with a fun, childlike atmosphere.'),
 (489, 'Facts, Good Question!, Humor, Pop Culture', 'At some point in your life, you will do an Elvis impersonation.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person mid-Elvis impersonation in a playful, exaggerated style. The character is wearing a classic Elvis-style outfit: a white jumpsuit with a high collar, flashy rhinestones, and a wide belt. They have slicked-back hair with sideburns and are striking a famous Elvis pose, one arm bent with fingers snapping, and legs apart in a dance stance. The background shows a casual room setting, like a living room with a couch, a small stage area or rug, and perhaps a mirror where the person is watching themselves perform. Include a small cat or dog looking confused or unimpressed nearby for extra humor. The colors are bright and vibrant, making the scene lively and funny without any violence or offense. The overall mood is lighthearted and celebratory, capturing the idea that everyone at some point tries to do an Elvis impersonation for fun.'),
 (490, 'Facts, Good Question!, Math Humor', '111,111,111 x 111,111,111 = 12,345,678,987,654,321', NULL, 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene showing a giant chalkboard or whiteboard in a classroom or study room. On the board, prominently display the math equation: ''111,111,111 x 111,111,111 = 12,345,678,987,654,321'' in bold, clear handwriting. In front of it, depict a friendly, slightly nerdy-looking teacher or professor with glasses and a pointer stick, smiling proudly as if revealing a magical mathematical secret. Nearby, show a few cartoon-style students or animals looking amazed, surprised, or baffled by the long, perfectly sequential number result, with wide eyes and exaggerated expressions. Add some playful mathematical symbols floating around, like plus signs, multiplication symbols, and question marks, to emphasize the cleverness of the number pattern. The overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and humorous, capturing the mind-blowing nature of the math trick as if it’s a fun discovery rather than a serious lesson.'),
 (491, 'Facts, Good Question!, Objects Humor', 'Ballpoint pens never run out of ink; they get lost.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a desk cluttered with papers and several ballpoint pens scattered everywhere. The person looks confused and is searching under the desk and behind objects, clearly looking for a pen. Some pens have little cartoon footprints leading away as if they walked off. A speech bubble from the person says, ''Ballpoint pens never run out of ink; they get lost.'' The background includes a calendar and a coffee mug, giving the feel of a casual office or home workspace. The style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated to enhance the humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (492, 'Facts, Good Question!, Puns', 'If the No. 2 pencil is the most popular pencil, why is it still No. 2?', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a yellow No. 2 pencil with a big, cheerful smile and expressive eyes standing proudly on a desk. The pencil wears a little crown or medal labeled ''#1'' to emphasize it being the ''most popular.'' Next to it, a confused or skeptical looking No. 1 pencil stands with raised eyebrows, holding a question mark sign. The background should resemble a simple classroom or office desk cluttered with scattered papers, an eraser, and a sharpener. Include a speech bubble coming from the No. 2 pencil that says, ''If I''m the most popular, why am I still No. 2?'' The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon-style expressions and bright colors to keep it fun and friendly.'),
 (493, 'Facts, Good Question!, Science', 'If the population of China walked past you in single file, the line would never end because of the rate of reproduction.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a long, winding, endless line of people stretching from the foreground far into the distance, curving beyond the horizon. Each person is drawn as a simple, friendly-looking figure to represent the population of China. Near the front of the line, a single surprised or bewildered person is standing, looking sideways at the line. Above the scene, include a playful banner or sign reading ''Single File Line.'' To emphasize the joke about reproduction, small cartoon baby storks or baby figures can be subtly integrated into the crowd, making it clear that the line keeps growing. The overall style should be lighthearted and colorful, ensuring a non-threatening, funny atmosphere that illustrates the concept of an endless line due to continuous population growth.'),
 (494, 'Facts, History Humor', 'Did you know that eye drops today use the same ingredients as were used in China 5,000 years ago?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a modern-day person holding a small bottle of eye drops and looking surprised. They are standing next to a large, ancient scroll unrolled on a table that has Chinese characters and illustrations of plants and herbs. Behind the scroll is a friendly, wise-looking ancient Chinese herbalist wearing traditional robes and a hat, pointing proudly at the scroll. Both characters appear in a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon style with big expressive eyes. The background should be simple, perhaps showing a mix of an ancient apothecary and a modern pharmacy shelf with various eye drop bottles. This contrast highlights the joke about the timeless ingredients used in eye drops. The mood is cheerful and whimsical, with soft colors and a few floating question marks or lightbulb icons over the modern person''s head to emphasize surprise and discovery.'),
 (495, 'Facts, History Humor, Military Humor, Word Play', 'The name Jeep came from the abbreviation used in the army for the ''General Purpose'' vehicle, G.P.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a classic military jeep in the center, painted in army green with a star on the door. Above it, a large speech bubble coming from the jeep says ''GP'' in military-style stencil font, followed by an arrow pointing to the full phrase ''General Purpose Vehicle'' written in a playful, hand-lettered style. In the background, a simple army base setting with a few tents, a soldier in green uniform scratching his head in confusion, and a signpost labeled ''Jeep History Museum.'' The overall vibe is lighthearted and educational, with exaggerated cartoon features like oversized wheels on the jeep and the soldier having a cartoonishly puzzled expression. The style should be colorful and clean with minimal detail to emphasize the joke about the abbreviation turning into the name ''Jeep.'' No violence or aggressive elements.'),
 (496, 'Facts, History Humor, Social Commentary', 'The Pentagon in Arlington, Virginia, has twice as many bathrooms as necessary. When it was built in the 1940''s, the state of Virginia still had segregation laws requiring separate toilet facilities for blacks and whites.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon drawing of the Pentagon building, shown as a large five-sided structure labeled ''The Pentagon'' with a small sign underneath reading ''Arlington, Virginia.'' Surrounding the building are multiple exaggerated, comically oversized bathroom signs indicating separate facilities labeled ''White Restrooms'' and ''Black Restrooms'' with arrows pointing in opposite directions. The cartoon should show two distinct restroom entrances clearly marked to highlight segregation from the 1940s era. The setting includes a 1940s-style background with vintage cars and people wearing period clothing to subtly indicate the time period. The tone is light-hearted and satirical, focusing on the absurdity of the historical context related to the number of bathrooms rather than any sensitive content.'),
 (497, 'Facts, Humor', 'Fact: the ten most frequently used words in the English language (making up about one-fourth of all our reading) are: the, of, and, a, to, in, is, I, that, it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, colorful, oversized book open on a table. The pages of the book are filled with giant, bold words: ''the'', ''of'', ''and'', ''a'', ''to'', ''in'', ''is'', ''I'', ''that'', ''it'', arranged in a playful, eye-catching way. The words appear to be animated characters with smiling faces and little arms, hopping around or waving cheerfully. In the background, a person wearing glasses and holding a magnifying glass is looking at the words with a curious, slightly amused expression. The setting is bright and friendly, with a simple library atmosphere including a couple of shelves with books and a cozy reading lamp. The art style is fun and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors, emphasizing the funny fact about these common words dominating English text.'),
 (498, 'Facts, Humor', 'Fact: the vocabulary of the average person consists of five to  six thousand words.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk with a huge open book labeled ''Vocabulary Dictionary'' that looks thick and intimidating. The person is scratching their head, looking puzzled and overwhelmed. Around the desk are scattered flashcards with simple words like ''cat'', ''dog'', ''run'', ''jump''. In the background, a thought bubble shows a string of random letters and words jumbling up, indicating confusion. The setting is a cozy study room with a cup of coffee and a small plant on the desk. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the irony of having a large vocabulary but still feeling confused.'),
 (499, 'Facts, Humor, Irony', 'Anybody can win, unless there happens to be a second entry.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two competitors standing side by side in a silly, exaggerated contest environment like a small game show stage or a backyard game setup. One competitor looks excited and confident, holding a trophy labeled ''Winner'' with a big smile. The other competitor appears frustrated or annoyed, arms crossed, facing away slightly. Between them on a small table or podium is a sign reading ''Competition''. Around them, a simple audience of cheerful or confused cartoon characters watches, some whispering to each other. The background is colorful with festive bunting or balloons to set a lighthearted, playful mood. The style is bright, friendly, and exaggerated for comic effect with no violence or negativity, emphasizing the irony of "anybody can win unless there''s a second entry."'),
 (500, 'Facts, Humor, Irony, Life', 'Anything free is worth what you paid for it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful character holding a large, brightly wrapped gift box with a big ribbon, looking proud and excited. Nearby stands another character with a skeptical or amused facial expression, pointing at the gift. The setting is a casual living room with a couch, a small coffee table, and a few scattered gift boxes labeled ''FREE.'' Above them, a speech bubble reads: "Anything free is worth what you paid for it." The style is simple and colorful, with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect, emphasizing the irony of receiving something free but questioning its value.'),
 (501, 'Facts, Humor, Language', 'The Hawaiian alphabet has only twelve letters - a,e,h,i,k,l,m,n,o,p,u,w.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful teacher standing in front of a classroom blackboard. On the blackboard, the Hawaiian alphabet letters a, e, h, i, k, l, m, n, o, p, u, w are neatly written in large, playful letters. The teacher holds a pointer and smiles broadly while several cartoon students, with puzzled or curious expressions, look on. Around the classroom, decorations include a ukulele leaning against the teacher''s desk, a small palm tree in a pot near the window, and a wall poster showing a map of Hawaii with a bright sun and waves. The atmosphere is lighthearted and educational, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s fun fact nature. The style is simple, clean, and clearly cartoonish, suitable for family-friendly humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (502, 'Facts, Humor, Language, Word Play', 'Fact: ''fasten'' and ''loosen'' have opposite meanings. Yet, attach the prefix ''un-'' to both and the words mean the same.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style scene showing two large word bubbles. One bubble depicts the word ''fasten'' with a smiling cartoon character trying to tie a big, knotted rope. Next to it, another bubble shows the word ''loosen'' with the same character struggling to untie the same rope. Between them, a playful character labeled ''Un-'' with a mischievous grin stands holding a big prefix banner ''un-''. Under these word bubbles, two smaller bubbles display ''unfasten'' and ''unloosen'' with the character happily waving both hands as if the words have become friends or twins. The background is simple, light color with a few comedic motion lines to emphasize the struggle and humor. The overall vibe is lighthearted and educational with a pun-filled personality.'),
 (503, 'Facts, Humor, Language, Word Play', 'The only 15 letter word that can be spelled without repeating a letter is uncopyrightable.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful dictionary character with eyes and a big smile, holding open a page showing the word ''uncopyrightable'' highlighted in bright colors. Surround the dictionary with letters of the alphabet, each letter appearing only once, arranged neatly around the word. Next to the dictionary, draw a playful banner or label that reads ''No Repeats!'' in bold, fun lettering. The background should be simple and colorful, resembling a school or library setting, with a few scattered letters floating or bouncing lightly to emphasize the uniqueness of the word. The overall style should be lighthearted and whimsical, suitable for all ages.'),
 (504, 'Facts, Humor, Life, Word Play', 'The adult version of head, shoulders, knees and toes is wallet, glasses, keys and phone.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an adult version of the classic children''s song ''Head, Shoulders, Knees and Toes.'' Show a cheerful adult standing upright with four labeled items on their body: a wallet positioned where the head would be, a pair of glasses resting on where the shoulders are, a set of keys hanging by the knees, and a smartphone held near the toes. The background is simple, such as a plain room or park, to keep the focus on the adult and their everyday essentials replacing body parts. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated, funny expressions to emphasize the clever twist on the children''s rhyme. Include subtle musical notes around the adult to hint at the song, but keep the overall tone light and silly, capturing the humor of grown-up priorities.'),
 (505, 'Facts, Humor, Math Humor, School', '10.0 times 0.1 is hardly ever 1.0.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon style scene featuring a classroom setting with a large blackboard in the background. On the blackboard is the math expression ''10.0 × 0.1'' written in big, bold chalk letters and below it, the answer ''1.0'' is faintly written and crossed out. In front of the board stands a quirky, slightly confused math teacher scratching their head, holding a piece of chalk. In the foreground, a student sits at a desk looking puzzled, with a thought bubble showing numbers and question marks swirling around. Around the room, small humorous math-related decorations like a calculator with googly eyes, a ruler looking surprised, and a poster saying ''Math is Fun!'' add to the lighthearted mood. The overall atmosphere is playful and educational, highlighting the joke about the uncommon but precise decimal math fact in a funny way without any tension or negativity.'),
 (506, 'Facts, Humor, Money Humor, Social Commentary', 'There are three classes of people: the haves, the have-nots, and the still paying for it''s.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring three distinct characters standing side by side. The first character, labeled ''The Haves,'' looks wealthy and relaxed, wearing fancy clothes with a smug smile, maybe holding a bag of money or a credit card. The second character, labeled ''The Have-Nots,'' appears frustrated or worried, in simple or worn-out clothes, empty pockets turned inside out. The third character, labeled ''Still Paying For It,'' looks tired but hopeful, holding a large receipt or bill labeled ''Loan'' or ''Installments,'' wearing casual clothes and maybe carrying shopping bags with tags that say ''Payment Plan.'' The background should be simple, like a plain city street or park, to focus on the characters. The style should be colorful and exaggerated with big facial expressions to emphasize the humor and contrast between the groups. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, with a clear visual distinction among the three classes and a playful text bubble above each character showing the label as a part of the joke.'),
 (507, 'Facts, Humor, Parenting', 'Babies are born without knee caps. They don''t appear until the child reaches 2 to 6 years of age.', NULL, 'A cute, humorous cartoon scene showing a toddler crawling on the floor with their knees bent, but instead of normal knees, their knees are soft and transparent as if they have no visible knee caps. Nearby, an adult pointing with a playful smile is showing a big, colorful chart on the wall titled ''Knee Cap Development Timeline,'' with cartoon knee caps gradually appearing on kids from ages 2 to 6, illustrated by progressively bigger and shinier knee caps on cartoon children in the chart. The background is a cozy living room setting with toys scattered around to emphasize the child''s age. The style should be bright, cheerful, and exaggerated in a gentle, fun way to illustrate the interesting anatomical fact humorously.'),
 (508, 'Facts, Humor, Pessimistic, School, Students', 'If you are given an open-book exam, you will forget your book.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a student sitting at a school desk looking puzzled and distressed. On the desk is a large, clearly open textbook labeled ''Exam Book,'' but the student is scratching their head as if confused and has a thought bubble showing an empty bookshelf or a book flying away. Behind the student is a teacher holding a stopwatch and looking amused. The classroom has a blackboard with the words ''Open-Book Exam Today!'' written on it. The overall mood is light and funny, emphasizing the irony that having the book doesn’t help because the student either forgot to bring it or forgot how to use it during the test.'),
 (509, 'Facts, Humor, Pop Culture', 'Actor Tommy Lee Jones and vice-president Al Gore were freshman roommates at Harvard', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a college dorm room with two young men resembling a young Tommy Lee Jones and a young Al Gore, styled in vintage 1970s college attire. They are roommates looking awkwardly at each other while sitting on their respective beds in a small, cluttered dorm room decorated with Harvard pennants and books. One side has a poster of a serious movie on the wall behind Tommy Lee Jones, who looks disinterested or deadpan, while the other side has a poster about environmental or scientific topics above Al Gore’s side. The beds have simple bedding, and there’s a small desk cluttered with typical student items like notebooks, a lamp, and coffee cups. The scene should have a lighthearted, slightly exaggerated cartoon style, emphasizing the contrast in their personalities and future paths, with playful facial expressions and body language suggesting the humor of imagining these two famous individuals as young college roommates without any direct references to politics or jobs.'),
 (510, 'Facts, Humor, Pop Culture', 'In every episode of Seinfeld there is a Superman somewhere.', NULL, 'A colorful, lighthearted cartoon scene showing Jerry Seinfeld sitting on a sofa in a typical 1990s-style NYC apartment living room. Around him, multiple small Superman figures are hidden in various amusing spots: one perched on the bookshelf, another flying past the window, and one tucked in a cereal box on the kitchen counter nearby. The TV screen shows the Seinfeld logo, and there''s a speech bubble above Jerry''s head saying, ''Did you notice Superman?'' The background should include typical Seinfeld props like a red couch, a coffee table with magazines, and a lamp. The style should be simple and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the fun of spotting Superman references in every episode, with bright colors and smiling characters, no violence or anything inappropriate.'),
 (511, 'Facts, Humor, Puns, Science', '186,000/mps: it''s not just a good idea, it''s the law.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a smiling, confident speedy character representing light zooming along a road at an extremely high speed. The road has a large, official-looking speed limit sign that reads "186,000 mps" (meters per second). The light character could be a bright, shining bolt or a glowing streak with eyes and a cheeky grin. Nearby, a friendly police officer is holding up a ''speed limit enforced by the laws of physics'' ticket book, pointing at the speed limit sign with a no-nonsense but comedic expression. The scene should be colorful, lively, and exaggerated to emphasize the absurdity and playfulness of enforcing physical constants like speed limits. Background can be simple, perhaps a starry sky or space theme to hint it’s the speed of light. The style should be a cartoon with clear, bold lines and expressive characters to enhance humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (512, 'Facts, Humor, Puns, Science', 'Scientists say the universe is made up of protons, neutrons and electrons. They forgot to mention morons.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a quirky scientist''s laboratory. Center the scene on a whiteboard or large chalkboard filled with a colorful, simplified diagram of an atom: a nucleus with protons and neutrons (small labeled spheres) and electrons orbiting around it. Introduce a third group of cartoon characters labeled ''morons'' — goofy-looking, silly creatures or humans with clueless expressions and exaggerated features (crossed eyes, drooling, or scratching heads) awkwardly standing or floating around the atom but clearly out of place. The scientist, wearing a lab coat, glasses, and holding a pointer, looks slightly baffled or amused standing beside the board. Add humorous props like beakers, test tubes, and atom models on tables and shelves to create a lively lab environment. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated, rounded shapes to enhance the cartoonish, lighthearted tone without implying anything negative about actual people.'),
 (513, 'Facts, Humor, Science', 'A sneeze travels at over 100 miles per hour.', 'Snapple bottle cap', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a giant sneeze depicted as a gust of wind zooming across a suburban street at high speed. The gust should have a playful, exaggerated face with puffed cheeks and blowing lips, to personify the sneeze. The street can have everyday elements like houses, trees, a mailbox, and maybe a cat or dog being blown backwards comically by the sneeze''s force. Add motion lines to emphasize the speed of the sneeze, and a nearby person caught mid-sneeze, with wide eyes and an open mouth just letting out the powerful burst. The overall tone is light and funny with bright colors and exaggerated expressions in a cartoon style to highlight the absurdity of a sneeze traveling more than 100 miles per hour.'),
 (514, 'Facts, Humor, Science', 'In 10 minutes, a hurricane releases more energy than all the world''s nuclear weapons combined.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a giant, swirling hurricane cloud taking up most of the frame, with exaggerated wind spirals and raindrops flying wildly. Below the hurricane, a cartoon Earth is looking startled with wide eyes and sweat drops to emphasize the massive power. Around the Earth, several colorful, cartoon-style nuclear bombs with little arms and worried expressions stand side by side, looking dwarfed and intimidated by the hurricane. To add a lighthearted touch, include a small scoreboard or meter labeled ''Energy Output'' next to the hurricane, glowing very high, while the bombs'' meter is barely moving. The background should be bright and simple, focusing attention on the contrast between the huge natural storm and the tiny nuclear weapons. The style is playful and exaggerated, with no scary or violent details, to keep it funny and informative.'),
 (515, 'Facts, Humor, Shopping Jokes, Word Play', 'Bargain: Something you can''t use at a price you can''t resist.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a store shelf labeled ''Bargains'' filled with unusual, impractical items like a single left sock, a broken clock, a tangled ball of Christmas lights, and an empty picture frame. The person looks puzzled but tempted, holding a price tag showing a ridiculously low price ($0.99). A cartoon thought bubble above their head reads: ''Something you can''t use at a price you can''t resist.'' The setting is a brightly lit, colorful discount store with exaggerated price tags and comically odd products. The character is dressed casually and exhibits a mix of confusion and desire, emphasizing the absurdity of buying useless items simply because they''re cheap.'),
 (516, 'Facts, Humor, Travel Humor', 'The cruise liner, Queen Elizabeth II, moves only six inches for each gallon of diesel that it burns.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, classic cruise liner labeled ''Queen Elizabeth II'' prominently on its side. The ship should look massive and slightly exaggerated with multiple decks, smokestacks puffing out small clouds of smoke. Next to the ship, a huge, oversized diesel fuel gauge or fuel tank is shown, and a tiny measuring tape or ruler stretched exactly six inches along the water just in front of the ship''s bow. On the side, a small cartoon character (an engineer or ship captain with a surprised expression) is holding a gallon-sized fuel canister, looking incredulous as the ship creeps forward just a tiny distance. The scene is set on a calm ocean with gentle waves and a bright sunny sky, drawn in a colorful, light-hearted cartoon style emphasizing the slow movement versus the large fuel consumption in a playful, non-serious way.'),
 (517, 'Facts, Humor, Word Play', 'The only ten-letter word you can create using the top line of letters on a typewriter keyboard is ''typewriter''.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classic vintage typewriter prominently in the center. Above the typewriter, the top row of keys is clearly visible and exaggeratedly highlighted or glowing to emphasize the letters on the top row. A piece of paper is loaded in the typewriter, and the typed word ''typewriter'' is clearly printed on it in large, playful letters. Around the typewriter, scattered loose letters or keys are flying or floating, adding to the playful vibe. The background should be simple, maybe a desk or a retro office space to keep focus on the typewriter. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions on the typewriter itself (like eyes on the front frame, smiling) to personify the device humorously.'),
 (518, 'Facts, Humor, Workplace', 'Michael Jordan has more money from Nike annually than all of the Nike factory workers in Malaysia combined.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Michael Jordan in a flashy basketball jersey holding a large bag overflowing with money marked with dollar signs. He is standing happily next to a huge, mountain-like pile of money. Nearby, a small group of factory workers from Malaysia, wearing simple work clothes and caps, look up at Jordan''s pile with surprised expressions. The factory workers are standing in front of a large factory building with the Nike swoosh logo prominently displayed on it. The setting is bright and cheerful, with exaggerated cartoon features and expressions emphasizing the disparity in earnings. The scene uses bright colors and caricature style to keep it light and funny.'),
 (519, 'Facts, Math Humor', 'There are 293 ways to make change for a dollar.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a perplexed person standing at a large shop counter labeled ''Change for a Dollar.'' The person is holding a dollar bill and looking confused at a huge, overflowing jar or box behind the counter filled with many different coins—pennies, nickels, dimes, and quarters—all jumbled together. Nearby, a shopkeeper wearing a striped apron and a quirky smile gestures at a large chalkboard or sign beside them that says ''293 Ways to Make Change for a Dollar!'' The background is a simple friendly store interior with shelves and a cash register. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the absurdity and complexity of so many ways to give change, creating a lighthearted and funny atmosphere without any violence or offense.'),
 (520, 'Facts, Math Humor, Programming, Puns', 'There are only 10 types of people in the world: Those who understand binary, and those who don''t.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two groups of people standing on either side of a large binary numeral ''10'' prominently displayed in the center. On the left side, depict a small group of tech-savvy characters with glasses, laptops, and lightbulbs above their heads, clearly understanding the ''10'' as the number two in binary. On the right side, show a confused group scratching their heads or looking puzzled, holding question marks above their heads as they try to interpret the ''10''. The background can be a simple classroom or office setting with a whiteboard or chalkboard displaying ''There are only 10 types of people in the world'' written at the top. Keep the style light and colorful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and the difference in understanding. Avoid any violence or negative stereotypes, focusing on a friendly and funny vibe emphasizing the joke about binary number knowledge.'),
 (521, 'Facts, Math Humor, Puns, Science', '2 + 2 = 5 for extremely large values of 2.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a classroom or office setting. In the center, a quirky-looking mathematician or scientist, wearing thick glasses and a lab coat, stands proudly next to a large blackboard or whiteboard. Written on the board in big, bold numbers is the equation ''2 + 2 = 5.'' Above or below the equation, in smaller handwriting, is the caption: ''for extremely large values of 2.'' The character strikes a confident pose, pointing at the equation with a pointer stick or marker. Around the character, a few puzzled onlookers with exaggerated confused expressions are scratching their heads or exchanging questioning looks. The background is simple, with a few math-related posters or charts, such as numbers, symbols, or graphs. The overall style is colorful, light-hearted, and exaggerated, emphasizing the absurdity and humor of the playful mathematical error.'),
 (522, 'Facts, Pop Culture, Puns', 'All of the clocks in the movie ''Pulp Fiction'' are stuck on 4:20.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inspired by a movie theater lobby with a big movie poster for ''Pulp Fiction'' prominently displayed. Around the poster, include several old-fashioned clocks hanging on the wall, all showing the exact same time: 4:20. The clocks should be exaggerated and comical, with big numbers and quirky clock hands. Include some popcorn buckets and movie tickets on a counter nearby to emphasize the cinema setting. Possibly add a few casually dressed moviegoers looking at the clocks with confused or amused expressions to add humor. Keep the overall style bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated features for comedic effect.'),
 (523, 'Facts, Pop Culture, Star Wars', 'James Doohan, who plays Lt. Commander Montgomery Scott on Star Trek, is missing the entire middle finger of his right hand.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly and slightly surprised caricature of James Doohan as Lt. Commander Montgomery Scott from Star Trek. He is wearing his recognizable Starfleet uniform with a Star Trek insignia. The focus is on his right hand, which is clearly visible but missing the entire middle finger. Around him could be a speech bubble or a small sign with a funny or lighthearted comment alluding to the missing finger without being offensive. The background is simple, maybe a subtle spaceship interior or the Star Trek bridge, depicted in cartoon style with clean lines and bright colors. The overall mood is lighthearted and respectful, emphasizing the unique fact about the actor with playful exaggeration of his hand for comedic effect.'),
 (524, 'Facts, Puns, Social Commentary, Technology Humor', 'If the software is free, YOU are the product', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a modern office environment. In the center, a cheerful software vendor (cartoon character) is enthusiastically handing out boxes labeled "Free Software" to a diverse group of people (users) who look excited and eager. Behind the vendor, a large conveyor belt humorously shows the users themselves being processed and wrapped up like products, complete with price tags and barcodes. The conveyor belt leads to a big shipping box labeled "Your Data" ready to be shipped out. The background includes computer screens with lines of code and social media icons to hint at digital services. The overall style is bright and friendly, with exaggerated expressions to enhance the comic effect, emphasizing the ironic twist that the free software users are actually the products being sold, not the software itself.'),
 (525, 'Facts, Puns, Word Play', 'Racecar backwards is still Racecar. Racecar upside down is very expensive.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon showing a sleek red racecar on a racetrack. The left side of the image shows the racecar from the side in a normal upright position, with a big smiling face on its windshield, looking proud. Above it, the word "Racecar" is written clearly. To the right, the same racecar is flipped upside down, showing its wheels in the air, looking surprised or shocked with wide eyes and a small speech bubble with a money symbol ($$$) to indicate expense. Floating near the upside-down car is a bright price tag dangling, labeled "$100,000" or similar. The background is a racetrack with cheering simple cartoon spectators in the stands. The style is light, fun, and exaggerated, with bold outlines and bright colors to emphasize the joke visually without any violence, politics, or inappropriate content.'),
 (526, 'Facts, Relatable, Sports Humor', 'The only two days of the year in which there are no professional sports games (MLB, NBA, NHL, or NFL) are the day before and the day after the Major League All-Star Game.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene focused on a large calendar hanging on a wall. The calendar is open to the month showing the Major League All-Star Game day highlighted brightly in the center. Around this day, the previous day and the following day are shown with big red X marks. Each of these marked days has little icons representing the four major sports leagues: a baseball for MLB, a basketball for NBA, a hockey puck with a stick for NHL, and a football for NFL. The previous and next day clearly have no sports icons, showing an empty schedule. Include small caricatures of fans looking puzzled or bored, with one holding a remote control and scratching their head humorously. Maybe add a TV screen in the background showing a countdown or ''No Games Today!'' message to emphasize the sports break. Use bright colors and exaggerated expressions to keep it lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the rarity of these two "no game" days flanking the All-Star Game day.'),
 (2121, 'Family, Financial Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'My father was a loner. I was a loanee.', 'Ken R', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room. On one side, an older man sits alone in an armchair, looking content yet solitary, symbolizing the ''loner'' father. On the other side, a younger man (his son) stands next to him, holding a giant, exaggerated loan document with a big stamp on it labeled ''LOANEE.'' The son is smiling sheepishly, maybe wearing slightly rumpled clothes to show a carefree or dependent vibe. The background includes a simple couch, a small coffee table with a calculator and a pile of bills or paperwork to emphasize money/loan themes. Both characters should have exaggerated cartoon expressions to enhance the humor: the father looks calm and indifferent, the son looks slightly nervous or guilty but still humorous. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and clear outlines to keep a friendly cartoon feel. No violence or sensitive content.'),
 (3228, 'Family, Food Humor, Thanksgiving', 'KKWH: Tamara. Tamara who? Tamara we''ll eat all the Thanksgiving leftovers!', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon family kitchen scene just after Thanksgiving dinner. In the center, show a cheerful woman named Tamara standing by the kitchen counter, holding a big platter piled high with assorted Thanksgiving leftovers—turkey slices, mashed potatoes, stuffing, cranberry sauce, and pie. Around her, a group of smiling family members eagerly look on, some holding plates or forks, ready to dive in. Include a large fridge in the background with a few containers and note papers stuck on it, hinting at stored leftovers. The atmosphere is warm and inviting, with autumn decorations like pumpkins and fall leaves visible. Style the characters and setting with exaggerated, playful cartoon features to emphasize humor and friendliness, evoking the common family experience of loving Thanksgiving leftovers.'),
 (527, 'Family, Good Question!, Humor, Life', 'Ever notice that when you move your couch you find many unusual items?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in a casual home setting lifting or pushing a couch to one side, revealing a cluttered floor space underneath and behind it. The floor under the couch is scattered with an assortment of unusual, unexpected items like a lone sock, a forgotten TV remote, a sandwich, an old shoe, a family photo frame, a rubber duck, coins, and maybe a stray cat or a small plant pot. The person has a surprised and amused expression, with wide eyes and raised eyebrows, clearly discovering these odd objects. The room should feel cozy but slightly messy, with a lamp, a coffee table, and a rug visible. The style is bright and cartoonish, emphasizing exaggerated facial expressions and the random nature of the hidden items, to capture the relatable humor of everyday life discoveries.'),
 (611, 'Family, Good Question!, Humor, Pun', 'What''s the difference between in-laws and outlaws?  Outlaws are wanted', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two distinct groups side by side. On the left side, depict a group of stereotypical outlaws from an old Western setting: wearing cowboy hats, bandanas over their faces, holding toy-like guns, and striking tough poses. They should look mischievous but exaggeratedly comical, with wanted posters featuring their faces hanging above them. On the right side, show a family gathering with typical in-laws: one or two older adults, dressed in casual family attire, looking slightly annoyed or uneasy but in a friendly, non-threatening way. Between the two groups, include a large signpost or banner with the joke question and answer written in fun, bold letters: "What''s the difference between in-laws and outlaws? Outlaws are wanted." The background should be simple and colorful to highlight the contrast, with playful exaggeration and light-hearted expressions to emphasize the pun without any hint of negativity or conflict.'),
 (1957, 'Family, Humor, Parenting, Quotes', 'Instant availability without continuous presence is probably the best role a mother can play.', 'Lotte Bailyn', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a mother multitasking in a lighthearted way. The setting is a cozy living room with a comfy armchair. The mother is depicted sitting calmly in the chair, holding a smartphone with a smiling face on the screen popping out as a hologram above the phone, symbolizing instant availability. Nearby, a young child is playing with toys scattered on the floor, looking up and waving at the hologram mom. Around them are small details like a clock on the wall indicating different times, symbolizing that the mother is present in spirit but not constantly physically watching. The mother appears relaxed and cheerful, embodying the idea of being there without hovering. The overall tone is warm and friendly, with bright colors and expressive, exaggerated cartoon features emphasizing the humor and affection in the concept.'),
 (2304, 'Family, Humor, Parenting, Quotes', 'The first half of our lives is ruined by our parents, and the second half by our children.', 'Clarence Darrow', 'A humorous cartoon split into two halves. On the left side, show a young adult looking slightly disheveled and frustrated, surrounded by exaggerated cartoonish parents who are messily interfering—one parent might be holding a gigantic rule book, another pointing with a stern look, and perhaps a spilled cup or broken toy on the floor. The setting is a chaotic living room with a calendar marked ''childhood'' and toys scattered. On the right side, depict the same adult now older and tired-looking, holding a crying toddler in one arm while trying to juggle a baby bottle and a ringing phone, with a chaotic mess of children’s toys and crayons everywhere. The background could be a messy family room with children''s drawings on the walls. Both sides highlight the humorous contrast of life stages and parental challenges in a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon style with bright colors, big expressive faces, and playful details emphasizing the ''ruined'' life by parents and then children without any negativity or sadness.'),
 (1738, 'Family, Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Happiness is having a large, loving, caring, close-knit family in another city.', 'George Burns', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person happily relaxing alone in their cozy living room, smiling contentedly while sipping a cup of tea or coffee. The room is neat and comfortable, with a couch, a small table, and a window showing a distant city skyline. In the background, through the window or on a wall calendar labeled with the distant city’s name, an illustrated large and lively family is seen far away, smiling and interacting warmly with each other—hugging, chatting, and sharing a meal together. The main character’s expression and body language show relief and happiness that the big, loving, close-knit family is somewhere else, implying the humor that sometimes distance is appreciated. The overall tone is light, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the joke’s punchline without any negativity or hostility.'),
 (1603, 'Family, Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Charming man, I wish I had a daughter so I could forbid her to marry him.', 'Arthur Dent', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two men standing and chatting in a park. One man looks somewhat ordinary but with a slightly mischievous or unimpressed expression, while the other man, labeled as ''Charming Man,'' is extremely well-dressed, confident, and smiling charmingly. Nearby, a father figure stands with a contemplative and slightly worried look, imagining a thought bubble showing his daughter looking loving but worried, next to the ''Charming Man.'' The setting is sunny and cheerful with green grass, trees in the background, and a park bench. The focus is on the interplay between the characters and the father''s thought bubble that humorously suggests he wants to forbid his daughter from marrying the overly charming man. The style is light, cartoonish, and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and irony of the statement.'),
 (1692, 'Family, Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Familiarity breeds contempt -- and children.', 'Mark Twain', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene depicting a family home environment. In the foreground, show two parents with tired or slightly annoyed expressions standing side by side, looking at a group of energetic children running wildly around them. The children should be smiling mischievously or making playful gestures that suggest chaos and noise. Around the room, include typical household elements like scattered toys, a tipped-over chair, and a family photo on the wall that hints at growing familiarity. Above them, include a light-hearted caption or thought bubble from one of the parents that reads: ''Familiarity breeds contempt -- and children.'' Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated cartoon features for all characters to enhance the humorous tone without any negativity.'),
 (528, 'Family, Humor, Relatable', 'The Wi-fi went down for five minutes, so I had to talk to my family. They seem like nice people.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a modern living room where a family of four is sitting awkwardly on a couch and chairs, looking at each other with shy or surprised expressions. In the background, a small Wi-Fi router is shown with a big red ''X'' or a disconnected symbol hovering over it to indicate the Wi-Fi is down. One family member (perhaps a parent) is nervously breaking the silence by saying something, while others glance at each other with hesitant smiles or raised eyebrows, as if rediscovering each other. Include a smartphone or tablet resting unused on the table to emphasize the lack of internet. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with clear facial expressions reflecting mild discomfort turning into amusement. The setting should feel cozy and familiar, like a typical contemporary family home, with humorous emphasis on the awkwardness of real-life conversation suddenly replacing screen time.'),
 (3052, 'Family, Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'I wish I''d listened to what my father told me... (what did he tell you?)  I dont know, I didn''t listen!!!', NULL, 'A cartoon-style drawing of two characters: a younger person and their father. The younger person has a puzzled or frustrated expression and is scratching their head, standing with arms slightly raised in confusion. The father looks a bit exasperated or amused, with his arms crossed and a slight smile. Include a speech bubble from the younger person saying, ''I wish I''d listened to what my father told me...'' and another speech bubble from the father replying, ''What did he tell you?'' The younger person responds in a separate bubble, ''I don''t know, I didn''t listen!!!'' The background can be simple, perhaps a living room with a couch and a small table, to keep the focus on the characters and their exchange. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and humorous, emphasizing the irony and playful nature of the conversation without conflict or negativity.'),
 (2670, 'Family, Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'Be nice to your kids.  They''ll choose your nursing home.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an elderly couple sitting together in a cozy but slightly old-fashioned living room. The grandparents look calm but a bit wary. In the foreground, two mischievous-looking kids (a boy and a girl) are positioned near a large window, each holding a brochure or miniature model of a fancy nursing home, smiling slyly as if plotting. There should be subtle visual cues suggesting the kids are in control of the situation—like one kid holding a remote control with a big red button labeled ''Nursing Home Selection.'' The atmosphere is light and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions emphasizing the joke''s irony. Include a small sign or calendar on the wall with the text ''Nursing Home Expo Today'' to reinforce the theme. The overall vibe is warm cartoon humor without anything harsh or threatening.'),
 (1596, 'Family, Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'By the time a man realizes that maybe his father was right, he usually has a son who thinks he''s wrong.', 'Charles Wadsworth', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring three generations of males. On the left, an elderly father with a wise, gentle expression and gray hair, maybe wearing reading glasses and a cardigan, is pointing or giving advice. In the middle, the adult man (his son), looking slightly puzzled or reflective, scratching his head or rubbing his chin. On the right, a teenage boy or young man (the grandson) is crossing his arms and rolling his eyes, clearly thinking his dad is wrong. The background can be a cozy living room with family photos on the wall, a couch, and maybe a coffee table with a cup of tea or coffee. The overall vibe should be lighthearted and slightly exaggerated in a cartoon style to capture the cycle of generational disagreements about advice and opinions, with expressions that emphasize the humor in realizing the truth too late and being doubted by the next generation.'),
 (2251, 'Family, Life, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Sometimes the poorest man leaves his children the richest inheritance.', 'Ruth E. Renkel', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a humble, ragged-looking man standing with his children. The man is holding an empty, old-fashioned treasure chest that''s labeled ''Inheritance,'' but the chest is comically overflowing with intangible ''riches'' represented by glowing hearts, wisdom books, and happy memories symbolized as cartoon thought bubbles showing smiling faces and family moments. The children look joyful and content, with shining eyes and wide smiles, clearly valuing these priceless gifts. The background is a simple home setting with worn-out furniture but bathed in warm, golden light to emphasize the richness of love and wisdom over material wealth. The style is lighthearted and friendly, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the irony and warmth of the message without any realistic wealth symbols like money or jewels.'),
 (2747, 'Family, Nostalgia, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'Daddy, why doesn''t this magnet pick up this floppy disk?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a curious child holding up a shiny, old-fashioned floppy disk with a puzzled look. Next to the child stands a dad figure, scratching his head with a confused smile. In the dad''s other hand is a classic horseshoe-shaped magnet, which he is trying to use to pick up the floppy disk, obviously failing. Around them, a living room setting with a computer desk in the background holding a dusty retro desktop computer and a stack of floppy disks nearby. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated with cartoon expressions to emphasize the lighthearted confusion about outdated technology that isn''t magnetic. The overall mood is playful and nostalgic about old tech quirks.'),
 (1956, 'Family, Parenting, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Insanity is hereditary.  You get it from your children.', 'Sam Levenson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frazzled parent sitting in a living room looking exhausted and disheveled, holding their head as if overwhelmed. Around them, several lively children are energetically running, jumping, and making playful messes—one child might be loudly shouting or laughing mischievously, while another is causing some mild chaos like throwing toys or spilling a drink. Include whimsical details like scattered toys, a toppled lamp, and exaggerated expressions on everyone’s faces to emphasize the playful chaos. The background should be a cozy, everyday family home environment with bright colors and a lighthearted mood. The overall tone is funny and relatable, capturing the idea that the parent''s ''insanity'' comes from the children''s antics, not the other way around.'),
 (3149, 'Family, Parenting, Relatable, Unknown', 'You want to know what it''s like having a fourth kid? Imagine you''re drowning, then someone hands you a baby', 'Jim Gaffigan', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tired parent standing waist-deep in water, struggling to stay afloat with worried eyes and messy hair. The parent’s arms are reaching out as if they are struggling to keep balance. Suddenly, someone from behind hands the parent a cute, smiling baby wrapped in a blanket. The baby giggles innocently, unaware of the parent''s overwhelmed expression. Around them, a few small waves splash to emphasize the ''drowning'' metaphor. The background is simple, with a vague water pattern and maybe a small rubber duck floating nearby for added humor. The overall style is light, colorful, and cartoonish, focusing on the exaggerated expressions of exhaustion and surprise on the parent''s face and the adorable innocence of the baby.'),
 (2571, 'Family, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'When we are planning for posterity, we ought to remember that virtue is not hereditary.', 'Thomas Paine', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a grandparent and a parent sitting at a kitchen table, looking thoughtfully at a family photo album labeled ''Posterity Plans.'' The grandparent, wearing glasses and a sweater, is pointing at a picture of their youngest child who is mischievously sticking out their tongue. The parent, looking amused but resigned, holds a pen and paper with a list titled ''Virtue Checklist.'' On the wall behind them, a framed diploma with the word ''Virtue'' crossed out and replaced with a question mark. A playful baby crawls nearby, pulling on a ''Good Behavior'' chart that’s half-blank. The overall mood is lighthearted and reflective, emphasizing the idea that good qualities aren’t guaranteed to pass down genetically. The art style is cheerful and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and colorful, cozy home setting details such as a teapot, potted plant, and patterned wallpaper.'),
 (1848, 'Family, Positive Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'I want the kind of marriage that makes my kids want to get married', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a happy married couple sitting contentedly on a cozy couch in their living room. The couple is smiling warmly and holding hands, radiating love and harmony. Nearby, two children stand watching them with wide eyes and curious expressions, one child holding a toy wedding ring or a mock invitation, symbolizing their budding desire to get married someday. The background includes a cheerful home setting with framed pictures of family moments and a sense of comfort. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing warmth and family connection without any specific cultural or religious symbols. The overall mood is inviting, showing a positive example of marriage inspiring the next generation in a playful cartoon style.'),
 (2675, 'Family, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Youth Humor', 'Beware: We are the people our parents warned us about.', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a group of quirky young adults or teens standing together with playful, mischievous expressions. They are casually dressed in trendy, slightly rebellious clothing. Each is doing something lightly ''rebellious'' but clearly harmless and funny, such as holding a pie ready to throw, wearing funny hats, pulling silly faces, or holding a loudspeaker with a cheeky sign that says ''Party Starts Here!''. In the background, a pair of elderly parents or grandparents stand watching with exaggerated worried, surprised, or amused expressions, perhaps shaking their heads or covering their mouths. Include details like a suburban house or a park setting to suggest a friendly neighborhood vibe. The overall tone is lighthearted and fun, visualizing the idea that these young people are exactly the kind of trouble their parents jokingly warned them about, but not in a serious way. Make the characters and setting cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor and playfulness.'),
 (3022, 'Family, Technology Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I put my grandma on speed dial. I call that InstaGram.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a cheerful young person holding a smartphone with a big, colorful screen displaying a list of contacts. One contact is labeled ''Grandma'' with a little grandma avatar icon next to it. The finger is about to tap on this contact. Nearby, a sweet old grandma is smiling and waving cheerfully, wearing classic grandma attire like glasses, a cozy sweater, and a bun hairstyle. Above the phone, cartoonish speed lines or motion marks can show the finger moving quickly toward ''Grandma'' on the speed dial. Include a playful caption bubble above the young person that says, ''I put my grandma on speed dial. I call that InstaGram,'' emphasizing the pun. The setting is light and cozy, perhaps a living room with a couch, a coffee mug, and a family photo on the wall to enhance the warm, family vibe. The overall style should be colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing friendliness, speed, and humor without any violence or politics.'),
 (778, 'Fantasy Humor, Halloween, Pun', 'What kind of monster likes to play tricks? Prank-enstein.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene featuring a friendly, goofy-looking Frankenstein monster standing in a spooky but colorful setting resembling a Halloween party or a playful haunted house. The monster has the classic green skin, bolts in its neck, a flat head, and big stitches on its face and arms but is smiling mischievously. It holds a whoopee cushion in one hand and a joy buzzer in the other, clearly ready to play tricks. Around it, small props like fake spiders, rubber snakes, and a sign that says ''Trick or Treat'' add to the playful atmosphere. The background includes smiling pumpkins, a friendly black cat watching curiously, and lighthearted cobwebs. The overall style is bright, cartoonish, and humorous, with exaggerated expressions and lively colors to emphasize the fun and prankish nature of the monster.'),
 (791, 'Fantasy Humor, Halloween, Pun, Word Play', 'Why don''t people like vampires? They are a pain in the neck.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a vampire character in classic attire: pale skin, fangs, a black cape with a red lining, and slicked-back hair. The vampire is standing with an exaggerated, comically annoyed expression, holding his neck as if it hurts. Nearby, a few people are shown with exaggerated, humorous expressions of discomfort or frustration as they back away from the vampire. You could include a simple background like a spooky, dark alley or a graveyard with tombstones to set the scene. Add a speech bubble above the vampire or a caption below the image with the joke: ''Why don''t people like vampires? They are a pain in the neck.'' Keep the drawing style bright and playful, emphasizing cartoon exaggeration and avoiding any scary or threatening imagery to maintain light-hearted humor.'),
 (771, 'Fantasy Humor, Halloween, Puns', 'What do witches use to style their hair? Scare-spray.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring two witches in a whimsical setting. One witch has wild, frizzy hair, and is holding a can labeled ''Scare-spray'' with spooky decorations like cobwebs and bats on it. The other witch is admiring her newly styled hair, which looks intentionally messy but amusingly ''styled'' with jagged spikes and curls. Both witches wear classic pointed hats and robes. In the background, a broomstick leans against a cauldron bubbling with green potion, and a full moon shines through twisted, leafless trees. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the pun with exaggerated hair and a fanciful magical setting. Include subtle Halloween elements like a black cat or pumpkins to enhance the witch theme without any scary or violent imagery.'),
 (2561, 'Fantasy Humor, Metaphor Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'When I investigate and when I discover that the forces of the heavens and the planets are within ourselves, then truly I seem to be living among the gods.', 'Leon Battista Alberti', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently on a small hilltop, looking enlightened and peaceful. Around the character, instead of a typical heavenly sky, the planets and celestial bodies are whimsically positioned within the person''s body, visible through a translucent outline. Inside the body, smiling cartoon versions of planets like Saturn with its rings, Jupiter with a red spot, and a shining sun near the chest, are arranged as if they coexist inside. The background includes a simple starry night sky and distant clouds. The person''s expression is one of awe and contentment, hands slightly raised as if embracing the cosmic discovery. The style should be colorful, playful, and light, emphasizing the idea that the heavens and planets are metaphorically inside the person, not outside. The overall vibe is uplifting, mystical yet funny in a gentle, philosophical way.'),
 (1639, 'Fantasy Humor, Movies, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Do, or do not. There is no ''try''.', 'Yoda (''The Empire Strikes Back'')', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a rocky, sparsely vegetated cliffside reminiscent of a mystical or ancient setting. In the center, a wise-looking, robed old master with a long white beard and bushy eyebrows is pointing a stern finger at a younger apprentice who looks uncertain and hesitant. The old master resembles a stereotypical sage or Yoda-like figure, but cartoonishly exaggerated to emphasize wisdom and seriousness. The apprentice, dressed in simple training robes, stands with one foot raised awkwardly mid-step, trying to do a martial arts pose but clearly struggling. Around them, broken boards and training weapons lie scattered to suggest failed attempts at training. A speech bubble from the old master says: "Do, or do not. There is no ''try''." The background is simple with soft clouds and a large moon or sun rising, giving a sense of a quiet but intense training moment. The style is bright and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight humor without aggression.'),
 (529, 'Fantasy Humor, Relatable', 'Three guys stranded on a desert island find a magic lantern containing a genie, who grants them each one wish. The first guy wishes he was off the island and back home. The second guy wishes the same. The third guy says: ''I’m lonely. I wish my friends were back here.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene on a small, sandy desert island with a few palm trees and a simple rock or two. Three men stand on the island looking a bit stranded and surprised. Near them lies an old, ornate magic lantern, from which a whimsical genie in a playful cloud of smoke is emerging. The first two men are happily disappearing in a sparkling swirl of magic, with joyful expressions as if they are being instantly transported back home. The third man, left behind and looking lonely and slightly confused, is surrounded by an empty space where his two friends once stood. His expression should be a mix of innocence and longing. The background shows a bright blue sky and a calm sea, emphasizing the isolation but keeping the tone light and funny. The style should be cartoony with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to highlight the humor and fantasy elements of the story.'),
 (530, 'Fantasy Humor, Relatable Humor', 'Some mornings I just don''t feel like slaying dragons.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a medieval knight waking up in bed looking tired and unmotivated. The knight is still wearing a sleepy expression with a soft, rumpled nightcap on his helmet. Around him, the room is decorated with classic dragon-slaying gear such as a shining sword, shield, and armor scattered on a chair and floor. Through a window, a dragon can be seen flying lazily outside, looking harmless and friendly rather than fierce. Include a bedside table with a mug of steaming coffee or tea and an alarm clock reading early morning hours. The overall vibe is cozy and relatable, with soft morning light coming in through the window. The image should be drawn in a lighthearted, colorful cartoon style emphasizing the knight’s humorous lack of enthusiasm for heroics this morning.'),
 (2706, 'Fashion Humor, Unknown, Wit, Word Play', 'CHIC: Considered smart without the deadening implication of intelligence.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a fashionable, stylish woman confidently walking down a city street. She is dressed in trendy, chic clothes such as a sleek blazer, skinny jeans, large sunglasses, and a designer handbag. Around her, people pause and look impressed. Above her, a thought bubble shows a small brain icon wearing sunglasses, symbolizing intelligence without dullness. The setting is cheerful and lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions. Include subtle visual cues like a street sign labeled "Smart St." and shop windows displaying witty slogans about style and intelligence. The overall tone is playful and clever, emphasizing the wordplay on "chic" as both stylish and smart in a fun, non-serious way.'),
 (797, 'Film Humor, Hipsters, Pop Culture, Puns', 'Hipsters love ''Raiders of the Lost Ark'' cuz it was the first Indie film.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene showing a hipster character excitedly holding a vintage VHS tape or DVD of ''Raiders of the Lost Ark''. The hipster should have stereotypical traits like thick-rimmed glasses, a beanie, a striped shirt or flannel, skinny jeans, and a quirky beard or mustache. Around them, place various indie film posters on the wall, with exaggerated artistic or quirky designs to emphasize the ''indie'' vibe. The hipster is smiling smugly, pointing at the ''Raiders of the Lost Ark'' cover which is highlighted with a glowing or spotlight effect to suggest it is special. Nearby, add a small chalkboard or sign that says: "First Indie Film" with a cheeky font. The overall vibe should be colorful, light-hearted, and playful, with no violence or negative tone. The setting can be a cozy room or a small independent movie store with film reels or popcorn subtly included as background details.'),
 (1971, 'Finance Humor, Life, Quotes, Wit', 'It is better to have a permanent income than to be fascinating.', 'Oscar Wilde (1854-1900)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring two characters sitting on a park bench. One character is casually dressed and looks relaxed, holding a briefcase or a bag labeled ''Permanent Income.'' The other character appears flamboyant and eccentric, wearing bright, flashy clothes with accessories like sunglasses and a hat, trying to look fascinating but looking a bit worried or stressed. Behind them, a simple background of a sunny park with trees, a path, and a few birds. Above the characters, include a playful speech bubble from the calm character, saying, ''It is better to have a permanent income than to be fascinating.'' Keep the style light, colorful, and cartoonish to emphasize the humor and contrast between practical stability and flashy personality.'),
 (2442, 'Finance Humor, Marriage Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'There''s a way of transferring funds that is even faster than electronic banking. It''s called marriage.', 'James Holt McGavran', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful married couple standing side by side. The husband is handing over a comically large envelope labeled ''Money'' to the wife, who is smiling broadly and holding it with one hand while balancing a shopping bag or bills in the other. Between them is a whimsical, exaggerated speedometer labeled ''Funds Transfer Speed,'' with the needle pointing past ''Electronic Banking'' into an area marked ''Marriage.'' The background is a cozy home setting, with a couch, a small table with a piggy bank, and maybe a calendar with hearts on the date. Both characters are drawn in a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon style to emphasize the joke''s playful tone without any negative or serious elements.'),
 (2684, 'Finance Humor, Math Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Budget: A mathematical confirmation of your suspicions.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a cluttered desk with a large, open spreadsheet or ledger titled "Budget". The person looks puzzled and slightly worried, scratching their head while staring at the numbers, which are jumbled and seem nonsensical. Above the person’s head, include a lightbulb-shaped thought bubble showing confused questioning marks and symbols implying suspicion or doubt. Nearby, include a calculator with a confused or sad face on its display and some scattered bills and receipts on the desk to emphasize financial concerns. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with the person’s facial expression clearly conveying realization mixed with disbelief about their finances.'),
 (2743, 'Finance Humor, Relatable, Unknown', 'Creditors have much better memories than debtors.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two characters sitting at a small café table outside. One character is labeled ''Creditor''—an older-looking person with a stern but slightly amused expression, holding a large, open notebook with ''DEBTS'' written in big letters. The other character, labeled ''Debtor,'' looks worried and is frantically trying to hide a tiny, almost empty wallet behind his back. Above them, a comic-style thought bubble appears over the Creditor’s head showing a large, detailed ledger filled with many remembered debts, while a thought bubble over the Debtor’s head shows a small cloud of thought with a single coin and a question mark. The setting is bright and sunny, with a simple background like a city street and a few passerby in the distance, emphasizing the contrast between the two characters'' memories. The style should be light and playful, capturing the irony of the creditor’s sharp memory versus the debtor’s forgetfulness in a cartoonish way.'),
 (1933, 'Financial Humor, Money Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I''m proud of paying taxes. The only thing is -- I could be just as proud for half the money.', 'Arthur Godfrey', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful middle-aged person standing next to a large, overflowing pile labeled ''Taxes Paid.'' The person is smiling proudly, wearing casual clothes and holding a large check or receipt with a big dollar amount visible. Next to them stands a smaller, identical pile labeled ''Half Taxes,'' looking slightly less cluttered. Above the scene is a thought bubble from the person showing a happy, daydream-like vision of themselves celebrating with half the pile, maybe throwing a small party with confetti or a cake. The background is light and simple, emphasizing the contrast between the two tax piles. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the humorous irony of being proud but wishing to pay less.'),
 (3057, 'Financial Humor, Office Humor, Satire, Unknown', 'I.R.S.: We''ve got what it takes to take what you''ve got!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a stern-looking IRS agent standing confidently with arms crossed in front of a large, old-fashioned safe that is overflowing with money and valuables. The IRS agent should be wearing a suit with an IRS badge clearly visible. Nearby, a worried-looking taxpayer nervously watches the agent. The background includes a typical office setting with a desk covered in paperwork labeled ''Taxes Due'' and a calendar showing April 15th circled in red. A speech bubble from the agent contains the slogan: ''We''ve got what it takes to take what you''ve got!'' The overall style should be light-hearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and comical facial expressions to emphasize the joke’s satirical tone without any negativity or threat.'),
 (3101, 'Financial Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'If Money doesn''t grow on trees then why does every bank have so many branches?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, friendly-looking tree with bank branches growing out from it as literal tree branches. Each branch has small bank signs hanging on it with logos like a dollar sign, coins, and a piggy bank. Below the tree, a confused-looking person in casual clothes is scratching their head while looking up at the tree and pointing at one of the ''bank branches.'' In the background, a traditional bank building can be seen with many branches (literal tree limbs) extending from it like oversized architectural features. The overall tone is light, playful, and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun between ''bank branches'' as tree branches and financial institutions'' multiple locations.'),
 (531, 'Food Humor', 'Never staple a peanut butter and banana sandwich together.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classic peanut butter and banana sandwich on a plate. The sandwich is exaggeratedly large and looks messy, with peanut butter oozing out and banana slices visible. A hand, wearing a funny glove or with comedic style, is holding a small stapler pressing it down on the sandwich''s corner as if trying to staple it together. The stapler should have a surprised or confused face, adding to the comedy. The background is a simple kitchen counter with a few typical kitchen items like a jar of peanut butter and a bunch of bananas. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and playful, emphasizing the absurdity of stapling a sandwich rather than eating it.'),
 (532, 'Food Humor, Friends, Word Play', 'What do you call friends you go out to eat with? Taste buds', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a lively group of friends sitting around a restaurant table, happily eating and laughing together. Each person should be depicted with a big, exaggerated smile and enjoying their food. On the table, include plates with various dishes like pizza, salad, and burgers to emphasize the eating scenario. Above them or nearby, floating with a slight glow, are several large, comical taste buds drawn as cute little characters with friendly faces and arms, mingling happily with the human friends like part of the group. The background should be a warm, cozy restaurant setting with light decorations and a few other diners in the background. The overall tone is cheerful and playful, with exaggerated, cartoonish expressions to highlight the joke’s pun on "taste buds" as both friends and literal taste buds on the tongue.'),
 (533, 'Food Humor, Good Question!, Humor', 'Is coffee a miracle drug? I think so.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person holding a large steaming cup of coffee with a delighted expression. The background shows a bright morning kitchen setting with a sun shining through the window and a coffee maker on the counter. To highlight the joke, a label on the coffee cup reads ''Miracle Drug'' in a playful font. The character is surrounded by everyday morning items: an alarm clock showing early morning time, a sleepy-eyed pet (like a cat or dog) nearby yawning, and a newspaper folded on the table. Lighthearted and colorful style with exaggerated facial expression to emphasize the joy and energy from drinking coffee. No harsh lines or complexity—simple and inviting cartoon style.'),
 (534, 'Food Humor, Good Question!, Humor, Puns', 'Ever slip a bar of chocolate into your pocket, ''just for a second''?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene centered around a person standing with a slightly guilty and sheepish expression, holding their empty pocket turned inside out. Behind them, another person is catching them mid-act, pointing at the pocket with a playful smirk. On the ground near the first person, a small half-eaten bar of chocolate wrapper is crumpled. The setting is casual, like a living room or a candy store, with a few exaggeratedly large chocolate bars on a table nearby. The style is light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke about ''just for a second'' slipping chocolate into a pocket leading to inevitable snacking. No violent or negative imagery, just fun and relatable mischief involving chocolate and pockets.'),
 (594, 'Food Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What is the difference between a Vietnamese restaurant and Indian restaurant? One is pho profit and the other is naan profit', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon scene showing two adjacent restaurant storefronts on a cheerful city street. The first restaurant has a large sign reading ''Pho Vietnamese Restaurant'' with steam rising from a bowl of pho noodles sitting on a small outdoor table, and a happy cartoon bowl with noodles and chopsticks. The second restaurant next door has a bright sign saying ''Naan Indian Restaurant'' with a smiling piece of naan bread character holding a fork. Between them is a large dollar sign divided into two halves: one with the word ''Pho Profit'' above the Vietnamese place and the other with ''Naan Profit'' above the Indian place. The scene should emphasize the pun visually without any people, focusing on the food items (pho bowl and naan bread) with expressive, friendly faces. The style should be colorful, bold, and cartoonish, evoking a playful, humorous tone that highlights the wordplay on ''for profit'' and ''non profit'' with the food items and signs matching the pun.'),
 (535, 'Food Humor, Good Question!, Puns', 'If a parsley farmer is sued, can they garnish his wages?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a small, sunny farm. In the foreground, a quirky parsley farmer wearing overalls and a straw hat stands looking surprised and a bit worried. Next to him is a large, leafy parsley plant with bright green leaves. To the side, two cartoonish, serious-looking business characters in suits hold a legal document labeled ''Lawsuit Notice.'' One of them points at the parsley plant, while the other holds out a briefcase with dollar signs on it. Above the scene, a playful, large text bubble contains the joke: ''If a parsley farmer is sued, can they garnish his wages?'' The background includes a simple farmhouse, a wooden fence, and a few garden tools whimsically arranged. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the pun on ''garnish'' — both the herb and the legal term, making the farmer look both confused and clever.'),
 (536, 'Food Humor, Good Question!, Puns', 'If white wine goes with fish, do white grapes go with sushi?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person sitting at a sushi bar. In front of them, instead of a usual sushi plate, there is a plate with neatly arranged bunches of white grapes. Next to the grapes, a bottle of white wine with a fish-shaped label is open with a wine glass half full. The person, with raised eyebrows and a quirky smile, is looking at the grapes and the sushi chef behind the bar who scratches his head puzzled. The setting is bright and cheerful with sushi rolls and traditional Japanese decor in the background. Include a small sign on the bar that reads, ''What pairs with sushi?''. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the funny question about pairing grapes with sushi instead of wine with fish.'),
 (639, 'Food Humor, Good Question!, Puns, Word Play', 'Why do they call it ''chili'' if it''s hot?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a bowl of chili on a kitchen table. The chili bowl should have steam rising from it with tiny little happy flames or sparks dancing above the steam to emphasize the heat. Nearby, a confused character (a person or a simple cartoon chili pepper with a puzzled face) is holding a thermometer in one hand that reads a high temperature, while scratching their head with the other hand. The background should be a simple kitchen setting with a stove and a pot labeled ''Chili'' simmering. Above the scene, include a playful question bubble that reads: "Why do they call it ''chili'' if it''s hot?" The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated to clearly express confusion and warmth with a lighthearted and friendly tone.'),
 (537, 'Food Humor, Good Question!, Word Play', 'If peanut butter cookies are made from peanut butter, then what are Girl Scout cookies made out of?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person, perhaps a child or teenager, looking thoughtfully at a plate piled with several colorful Girl Scout cookies varieties (like Thin Mints, Samoas, and Tagalongs). The person has a comical puzzled expression, with a big question mark floating above their head. On the table next to the plate, there is a jar of peanut butter labeled clearly, and a small stack of peanut butter cookies on a separate plate. Behind the person is a speech bubble with the joke text: ''If peanut butter cookies are made from peanut butter, then what are Girl Scout cookies made out of?'' The background is simple and cheerful, emphasizing the contrast between peanut butter cookies and Girl Scout cookies with distinct visual styles to highlight the joke''s play on ingredients. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and details to enhance the humor without any negative or violent elements.'),
 (764, 'Food Humor, Halloween, Pun', 'How do you fix a broken pumpkin? With a pumpkin patch', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, smiling pumpkin sitting on the ground with a visible crack or split along its side. Next to the pumpkin is a small patch of earth labeled ''Pumpkin Patch'', where a person dressed as a gardener or farmer is cheerfully sewing up the pumpkin''s crack with a giant colorful needle and thick yarn or thread. The background should be a sunny farm setting with other pumpkins growing on vines in the soil. The gardener looks comically focused and happy, emphasizing the pun. The style should be bright, cheerful, and exaggerated for humor, with playful expressions on the pumpkin and gardener, and clear visual emphasis on the ''patching'' action.'),
 (798, 'Food Humor, Hipsters, Pun', 'How did the hipster burn his tongue? He drank his coffee before it was cool', NULL, 'Create a colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a hipster character sipping coffee. The hipster is a young adult with a quirky style: thick-rimmed glasses, a beanie hat, and a plaid shirt. He holds a steaming cup of coffee with visible heat waves rising from it. His face shows a comical expression of surprise and slight pain, with one hand touching his tongue as if it’s burned. Around him, a trendy café setting is visible, with vintage decor and a "Coffee Shop" sign. A little thought bubble or small icon above his head indicates ‘cool’ in a trendy, ironic way, like a hipster symbol or a pair of sunglasses usually associated with being cool. The background should look lively but not overcrowded, emphasizing the coffee and the hipster’s funny reaction. Style should be light-hearted and exaggerated to highlight the pun in a friendly cartoon vibe.'),
 (2763, 'Food Humor, History Humor, Unknown, Wedding Humor', 'Did you know that the wedding cake dates from 100 B.C., when Roman bakers turned the traditional wheaten confetti into edible cakes, which guests at first persisted in throwing at the bride?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in ancient Rome with a wedding celebration taking place outdoors. In the center, a Roman bride and groom dressed in traditional Roman wedding attire (toga and stola with floral wreaths) stand nervously side by side. Surrounding them is a small crowd of guests, all in Roman clothing, holding small, round, crumbly edible cake pieces instead of confetti. Several guests are captured mid-action, throwing the cake pieces toward the bride, who looks surprised and slightly covered with cake crumbs on her dress and hair. The groom ducks or raises a hand to shield himself comically. In the background, a large, rustic but visibly decorated wheaten cake sits on a wooden table, looking simple but clearly the focal point. Roman columns or an ancient villa structure provides context. The style should be playful and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the surprise and messiness of edible confetti being thrown.'),
 (1540, 'Food Humor, Holiday Humor, Optimism Humor, Quotes', 'An optimist is a person who has Turkey for Christmas and asks next day: What''s for lunch?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person seated at a dining table decorated for Christmas. The table has a large roasted turkey as the centerpiece with Christmas decorations around, like a small Christmas tree or stockings in the background. The person looks excited and optimistic, with wide eyes and a big smile, asking a question with a speech bubble that says, "What''s for lunch?" The scene should capture a lighthearted and festive atmosphere, with warm colors and playful exaggeration of the person''s eager expression. Include typical holiday elements like wrapped gifts, holly, and maybe a window showing snow outside to emphasize Christmas time.'),
 (538, 'Food Humor, Humor', 'Most people eat as though they were fattening themselves for market.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a chubby person sitting at a dining table loaded with an exaggeratedly large feast: giant turkeys, mountains of mashed potatoes, oversized pies, and endless desserts. The person eagerly shovels food onto their plate with a satisfied grin, eyes gleaming with anticipation. In the background, a humorous twist shows a friendly-looking farmer wearing overalls and a straw hat, holding a clipboard and checking off the person''s name as if they were livestock being fattened for a market. The setting is warm and cozy, with a kitchen or dining room vibe, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke’s playful comparison of overeating to preparing animals for sale. No violence, just lighthearted and cartoonishly absurd imagery.'),
 (539, 'Food Humor, Humor, Life', 'Probably nothing in the world arouses more false hopes than the first four hours of a diet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a kitchen table looking hopeful and determined, with a calendar on the wall showing ''Day 1'' and a clock indicating four hours have passed. The table is mostly empty except for a small, sad salad bowl and a glass of water. Around the person’s head are thought bubbles depicting delicious and indulgent foods like pizza, cake, and burgers, symbolizing temptation. The person has a hopeful expression turning into slight disappointment or struggle as time passes. The kitchen should look bright and inviting, contrasting with the person''s wavering optimism about the diet. Style is colorful, light-hearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the mood shift from enthusiasm to doubt, with no violent or inappropriate elements.'),
 (540, 'Food Humor, Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'The optimist sees the donut; the pessimist sees the hole.', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon featuring two characters standing side by side, both looking at the same large donut on a simple table in front of them. The optimistic character is smiling broadly, eyes wide with delight, pointing excitedly at the whole donut. The pessimistic character frowns and squints, focusing on the donut’s empty center hole, with a thought bubble showing just the hole. The donut is oversized, with colorful sprinkles to make it visually appealing. The background is minimalistic, maybe a café or kitchen setting, to keep the focus on the characters’ contrasting expressions and the donut. The style is bright and cheerful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor in perspective difference, rendered in a clean, simple cartoon style without any violence or complexity.'),
 (541, 'Food Humor, Humor, Word Play', 'LACTOMANGULATION (lak to man gyu lay'' shun) v. Manhandling the ''open here'' spout on a milk container so badly that one has to resort to the illegal side.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a brightly lit kitchen. Central focus is a frustrated person holding a milk carton with multiple taped-up tears and crumpled sections around the official ''open here'' spout. The person''s facial expression is exaggeratedly annoyed and tired, with one hand clutching the damaged spout while the other hand awkwardly peeks under a non-official, taped-up side of the carton clearly marked with a small ''illegal side'' label or sticker. Nearby on the counter, a glass of milk is half-filled, showing the ongoing effort to get milk out. In the background, a clock and simple kitchen elements like a fridge and countertop accessories complete the setting. The overall style is colorful, cartoonish, and playful to emphasize the silly struggle of manhandling a stubborn milk carton.'),
 (542, 'Food Humor, Humor, Word Play', 'PEPPIER (pehp ee ay'') n. The waiter at a fancy restaurant whose sole purpose seems to be walking around asking diners if they want ground pepper.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a fancy, upscale restaurant with elegant tables covered in white tablecloths, crystal glasses, and fancy plates. At the center of the scene, a waiter with an exaggeratedly enthusiastic smile is standing next to a table. He is dressed in a classic waiter uniform with a bow tie and apron, holding a pepper grinder high up in one hand, as if about to offer pepper to several diners. The diners look slightly overwhelmed or amused by his persistent attention. Surrounding the table are other diners who glance over, some holding forks midair, others silently giving puzzled looks. The background features classy chandeliers and framed paintings, emphasizing the fancy atmosphere. The overall style is colorful, cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and lighthearted vibes, capturing the joke about the “peppier” waiter who seems to exist only to ask diners if they want pepper, making the waiter both the subject and the punchline of the image.'),
 (543, 'Food Humor, Irony, Puns', 'The perversity of nature is nowhere better demonstrated than by the fact that, when exposed to the same atmosphere, bread becomes hard while crackers become soft.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: a cartoon loaf of bread and a cracker, both with expressive faces. The bread is standing on the left side, looking tough and hard, with a strong, rough texture and a grumpy expression. On the right side, the cracker appears sad and soft, drooping slightly with a wilted, softened look. Between them is a transparent glass dome marked ''Same Atmosphere'' showing they are exposed to the same air. The background is a simple kitchen counter, with a small open window letting air in. Add subtle visual cues like a tiny clock to suggest time passing and some crumbs around the bread and cracker. The overall style is colorful and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the irony that bread hardens while crackers soften in the same conditions.'),
 (544, 'Food Humor, Irony, Relatable', 'There is something dishonest about putting bacon in a salad. You know? It''s kinda like smoking while you jog', 'Jim Gaffigan', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person jogging in a park while holding a cigarette awkwardly in one hand, looking slightly guilty or confused. Nearby, there is a picnic table with a large, fresh green salad bowl. Inside the salad bowl are vibrant leafy greens along with strips of crispy bacon visibly mixed in. The jogger is glancing over at the salad, mirroring their conflicted expression. The background includes a clear, sunny day with trees and a few other park-goers who look pleasantly surprised or amused. The art style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the absurdity of the juxtapositions—bacon in salad and smoking while jogging—without implying anything negative. The overall feel is playful and ironic, making the viewer smile at the ironic comparison between healthy and unhealthy choices combined in unexpected ways.'),
 (1239, 'Food Humor, Jobs, Pun', 'That guy who invented LifeSavers? They say he made a mint', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful man standing proudly next to a giant LifeSavers candy dispenser shaped like a lifesaver ring with the classic hole in the middle. The man is holding a large shiny gold coin or mint leaf in one hand with a satisfied smile. Behind him, oversized LifeSavers candies are scattered on the ground, some with shiny mint leaves around them to emphasize the pun. The setting is lighthearted and colorful, with a simple background such as a candy factory or a clean tabletop. The man wears casual inventor attire like a lab coat with a quirky name tag, possibly with a dollar sign or mint symbol on it. The overall atmosphere is playful and bright, emphasizing the pun that the inventor "made a mint" by creating LifeSavers.'),
 (1229, 'Food Humor, Jobs, Pun, Workplace', 'I had a job in an orange juice factory, but I got canned because I couldn''t concentrate.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set inside an orange juice factory. The focus is on a cartoon character – a worker wearing a factory uniform with an orange juice company logo on the chest – looking confused and worried. Around him, large oranges are being processed by factory machinery with a conveyor belt. On one side, a big can labeled ''Orange Juice'' is shown, with the worker being gently placed inside or next to it as if he got ''canned.'' To emphasize the joke, the worker is holding or looking at a heavy book titled ''Concentration'' with a puzzled expression, implying he struggles to concentrate. The background includes factory elements like orange crates, juice squeezers, and vats. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright oranges and cheerful colors to keep the mood fun and friendly.'),
 (1230, 'Food Humor, Jobs, Pun, Workplace', 'I once had a job crushing pop cans - it was soda pressing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person at a simple recycling station with a large, comical machine labeled ''Pop Can Crusher.'' The person, looking amused and slightly exasperated, is using their hands to crush a pile of brightly colored soda cans. Some cans are already flat and scattered around the floor. The soda cans have logos and bright colors typical of popular soda brands. The setting is outdoors on a sunny day, with a small sign near the station that reads ''Soda Crushing Station.'' The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the wordplay with the phrase ''soda pressing'' by showing the pressing (crushing) process in action. The character should be cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and lively posture to enhance the pun''s joke effect.'),
 (545, 'Food Humor, Jobs, Technology Humor', 'Real Techs don''t believe in health food. They can subsist indefinitely on Twinkies and Coca-Cola.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a simple, slightly messy tech office. In the center, a relaxed, tired-looking software technician sits at a cluttered desk with multiple computer monitors showing code. On the desk, prominently display a large stack of Twinkies boxes and several bottles or cans of Coca-Cola. The technician holds a half-eaten Twinkie in one hand and sips from a Coke can with the other, smiling contentedly. Around the workspace, include typical tech-related items such as a keyboard, mouse, coffee cup, and some cables. The background can show a whiteboard with technical doodles or flowcharts. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the joke that techs survive solely on junk food, without any hint of judgment or health concerns.'),
 (546, 'Food Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'Success in life doesn''t depend on your face or fate; it depends on your taste.', NULL, 'A humorous, colorful cartoon scene depicting a whimsical character standing proudly in front of a large display of various desserts, gourmet foods, and artful dishes on plates. The character has an exaggeratedly expressive face showing delight, holding a fork with a tiny bite of food. Around the character are floating symbols representing ''face'' (a mirror showing an average face) and ''fate'' (a classic dice or a four-leaf clover), both crossed out or fading away. Instead, a huge, shining golden chef''s hat floats above the character''s head symbolizing ''taste'' as the key to success. The background is lighthearted with a kitchen or banquet setting to emphasize food and taste rather than looks or luck. The style should be cartoonish, bright, and cheerful with exaggerated, funny expressions to evoke humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (547, 'Food Humor, Life, Puns', 'Rule Of Thumb: Opening A Bottle Of Wine: When deciding when to open a bottle of wine, remember most wine is as good when it''s a year old as it will ever be  and will go downhill after its third birthday.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person holding a wine bottle with a big smile, standing next to a large calendar showing the passage of time with dates marked: 1 year old, 2 years old, and 3 years old. The calendar has funny, exaggerated expressions on each date: the 1-year mark has a happy face, the 2-year mark looks neutral, and the 3-year mark is depicted with a sad or wilting face, as if the wine is going downhill. Nearby, a wine glass is half full with wine, and maybe a small thought bubble above the person’s head picturing a clock or hourglass. The setting is light and friendly, with simple lines, bright colors, and cartoonish exaggeration to make the concept of wine aging playful and easy to understand. Add a sign reading "Rule of Thumb" above the person or the calendar for clarity.'),
 (1912, 'Food Humor, Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'If you run out of room, don''t throw the good stuff away.', 'Virtual Memory', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered kitchen pantry or fridge. There are stacks of containers, jars, and boxes crammed tightly together on shelves, with some about to fall or squeezed awkwardly. In the center, a cheerful character (gender neutral) holding a small container labeled ''good stuff'' looking thoughtfully at the overcrowded shelves. Around them, other unlabeled, messy clutter of items spill over. The character is clearly trying to decide what to do but is smiling as if having a clever moment. The style is playful with exaggerated expressions and bright colors, emphasizing the ‘running out of space’ chaos but with a lighthearted vibe. The scene avoids cluttered violence or discomfort, focusing on the challenge of storage and the idea of preserving something valuable despite limited room.'),
 (548, 'Food Humor, Life, Relatable', 'Wanted: A 21-day diet that goes as fast as a 21-day vacation.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two split panels. On the left panel, a person excitedly packing a suitcase labeled ''21-day Vacation'' with sunglasses, a hat, flip-flops, and travel brochures scattered around. They have a big smile, and a calendar on the wall highlights 21 days marked off with bright colors. On the right panel, the same person is struggling at a kitchen table surrounded by vegetables, a salad bowl, a measuring scale, and a bottle of water. Their expression is tired and bored, glancing at a calendar also marked 21 days but dragging on with slow-moving clock hands above it. The contrast between the fast, happy anticipation of the vacation and the slow, arduous dieting journey is emphasized with exaggerated facial expressions and bright vs. dull colors. The whole scene should be drawn in a playful cartoon style with clear labels and visual humor to capture the joke about wanting a diet as fast and enjoyable as a vacation is.'),
 (2935, 'Food Humor, Money Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'How can you convert dollars into pounds?  By visiting McDonalds!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused character standing outside a McDonald''s fast-food restaurant. The character is holding a few American dollar bills in one hand and looking at a menu or sign that shows British pounds (£) next to food items like burgers and fries. The McDonald''s logo is clearly visible on the building. The character''s facial expression is playful and puzzled, as if expecting real currency exchange but facing fast-food prices instead. Around the character, a few iconic British symbols like a red double-decker bus or a small Union Jack flag are subtly placed to hint at the British pound. The overall tone should be lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated cartoon features, bright colors, and a clean, simple background emphasizing the mix-up between money and fast food currency conversion.'),
 (2708, 'Food Humor, Objects Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Chocolate donuts make poor doorstops.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a door that is slightly ajar with a chocolate donut placed at the base trying to hold it open like a doorstop. The donut looks sad and squished from the pressure, with melted chocolate dripping slightly and a few crumbs around it. The door is inside a simple room with a doormat, and there’s a confused cat or small dog nearby, looking at the donut as if wondering why it’s there. The overall tone is light and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions on the donut to emphasize its failure as a doorstop.'),
 (1575, 'Food Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Bad men live that they may eat and drink, whereas good men eat and drink that they may live.', 'Socrates', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene split into two panels side by side. On the left panel, depict a group of ''bad men'' looking mischievous and sly, seated at a lavish dining table piled high with extravagant food and drink, eating and drinking greedily. Their facial expressions should be exaggeratedly gluttonous and selfish. On the right panel, show a group of ''good men'' who are modestly and happily enjoying a simple, healthy meal with fruits, vegetables, and water, smiling and appearing content and lively. The background for the left panel can be a dark, cluttered dining room to match the bad men’s vibe, while the right panel has a bright and airy setting conveying health and life. Include subtle details like empty plates on the right side indicating they eat just enough for nourishment, and on the left side, overfilled plates and spilled drinks for comedic effect. Both sides should be cartoonish with clear visual contrast to highlight the joke’s meaning without any references to violence or negativity beyond humorous stereotyping.'),
 (549, 'Food Humor, Pop Culture', 'I''ve been seduced by the chocolate side of the Force.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inspired by a Star Wars theme but with a funny twist. In the middle, depict a smiling person wearing a Jedi robe with a chocolate bar in one hand instead of a lightsaber. Around them, have faint glowing chocolate-themed ‘Force’ effects, like swirling pieces of chocolate or cocoa bean shapes instead of light. Include a small, cute, and confused-looking droid beside the person looking at the chocolate bar. The background should resemble a Star Wars-style starship interior but also incorporate chocolate-themed elements like chocolate bars and cocoa pods on shelves or floating in the air. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, blending sci-fi with dessert humor, in a colorful, cartoon style with exaggerated expressions and clear references to both Star Wars and chocolate cravings.'),
 (2164, 'Food Humor, Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Nothing takes the taste out of peanut butter quite like unrequited love.', 'Charlie Brown', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, shiny jar of peanut butter sitting on a kitchen table. The jar has a sad, forlorn face with droopy eyes and a small frown, emphasizing its emotional state. Next to it is a speech bubble showing a heart with a broken line through it, symbolizing unrequited love. Surrounding the jar, a single peanut sits nearby, looking disinterested or turned away, as if ignoring the jar''s feelings. The background is a simple kitchen setting with a window showing a sunny day outside. The overall tone is light-hearted and exaggerated, using expressive facial features on the peanut butter jar to humorously convey the idea that unrequited love makes it lose its ''taste'' or joy. The style is colorful, clean, and cartoonish, emphasizing clear emotions and anthropomorphic food objects without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1415, 'Food Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A hangover is the wrath of grapes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an angry bunch of grapes with furious facial expressions and arms crossed, standing on a kitchen counter next to a half-empty wine bottle and a disheveled person lying on a couch with a clearly miserable hangover. The person has a red nose, messy hair, and a pained expression, holding their head with one hand and a glass of water in the other. The background includes a few empty wine glasses and a clock showing an early morning time. The angry grapes appear as cartoon characters with exaggerated scowls, little steam puffs above their heads, and are somewhat anthropomorphized to display their ''wrath.'' The overall style is playful and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated features to emphasize the humor of ''wrath of grapes'' as a pun linking hangovers and grapes.'),
 (3182, 'Food Humor, Pun, Star Wars', 'What’s Jar Jar Binks favorite meal? Miso soup', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Jar Jar Binks, the quirky Gungan character from Star Wars, sitting at a simple wooden table in a casual dining setting. Jar Jar should have a big, goofy smile as he holds a spoon in one hand and a bowl of miso soup in front of him. The bowl should have steam rising to indicate it''s hot. Around the table, include playful Japanese elements like a pair of chopsticks resting beside the bowl, a small soy sauce bottle, and maybe a sushi roll plate nearby. The background should be light and cheerful with subtle hints of a Star Wars-themed diner, like a starship window showing space outside. Overall, the tone is fun and lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing Jar Jar''s silly charm and his unexpected favorite meal, miso soup.'),
 (3226, 'Food Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'KKWH: Annie. Annie who? Annie body seen the turkey?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a family dining table decorated for Thanksgiving. In the center, an empty serving platter with a small note or napkin reading ''Missing Turkey!'' is prominently displayed. Around the table, several family members with exaggerated confused and surprised expressions look around the room as if searching for something. One person, likely a child, is standing with their hands cupped around their mouth, calling out ''Annie! Annie who? Annie body seen the turkey?'' The background includes typical Thanksgiving decorations like autumn leaves and a pumpkin centerpiece. The mood is light-hearted and silly, with exaggerated facial features to emphasize the pun and confusion.'),
 (2702, 'Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Celery: what a concept. Food with built-in dental floss.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon showing a lively stalk of celery personified with a big friendly smile and eyes. The celery is holding a giant smiling piece of floss stretched between two stalks, as if it’s dental floss naturally integrated into the vegetable. Around the celery, a few comical characters (such as a happy tooth and a toothbrush) are looking impressed or applauding. The background is light and simple, perhaps a kitchen setting with a countertop and a bowl of other vegetables in the background. The style is playful and bright, emphasizing the pun on celery being ‘food with built-in dental floss.’'),
 (2865, 'Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'For a REAL sponge cake, BORROW all the ingredients.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a confused baker standing in a bright, colorful kitchen cluttered with various baking ingredients scattered everywhere, some clearly labelled such as eggs, flour, sugar, and butter. The baker is scratching their head and holding an empty mixing bowl while several mischievous-looking kitchen utensils - a whisk, a spatula, a measuring cup - sneak away carrying packets and boxes of ingredients as if ‘borrowing’ them. Above the baker, a thought bubble says, ''For a REAL sponge cake… BORROW all the ingredients.'' The kitchen should have exaggerated expressions on the utensils to add humor. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with playful, exaggerated facial features and bright colors, creating a funny and innocent atmosphere without any negativity or violence.'),
 (2993, 'Food Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I had a job at a bakery once - I kneeded some dough', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a bakery. Show a cheerful baker wearing a white apron and a traditional baker''s hat, standing behind a wooden countertop covered in flour. The baker is energetically kneading a big lump of dough with both hands, with visible motion lines to emphasize the kneading action. On the counter nearby, place a mixing bowl with some dough inside and a rolling pin leaning against it. In the background, include a bakery oven with some bread loaves inside and a shelf filled with freshly baked bread. Add a playful banner or sign hanging above the scene that reads ''Kneeded Some Dough.'' Use bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions on the baker''s face to convey the pun humor. The overall style should be lighthearted and whimsical, suitable for all ages, emphasizing the pun on ''kneaded'' and ''needed'' related to bread dough and money (dough).'),
 (2926, 'Food Humor, Pun, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'Hershey''s Kisses are called that because the machine that makes them looks like it''s kissing the conveyor belt.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene depicting a chocolate factory conveyor belt. The belt is moving small, shiny Hershey''s Kisses chocolates down the line. Above the conveyor belt, a quirky, vintage-style machine is shown with two mechanical parts facing each other with puckered ''lips'', clearly mimicking the act of kissing. The machine parts look cartoonishly exaggerated, with eyes closed and little heart symbols floating around to emphasize the ''kissing'' motion. In the background, a factory worker in a chef’s hat and apron looks on amused, scratching their head with a playful smile. Include conveyor belts, chocolate pieces shaped like Hershey’s Kisses, and factory elements like gears and pipes to establish the setting. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors and rounded shapes to make it visually appealing and funny.'),
 (2934, 'Food Humor, Pun, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'Hors d''oeuvres--a ham sandwich cut into forty pieces.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large ham sandwich on a wooden platter, cut into about forty tiny, bite-sized pieces. The sandwich is layered with ham and a slice of bread, exaggeratedly cut into numerous small squares arranged neatly on the platter like fancy hors d''oeuvres. Nearby, a fancy party setting is suggested with elegant tablecloth, a few cocktail glasses, and a person dressed in semi-formal clothing looking surprised or amused while pointing at the platter. The style is light-hearted and whimsical, emphasizing the contrast between the simplicity of a ham sandwich and the fancy presentation implied by the term ''hors d''oeuvres.'' No people are depicted as stressed or confused, just amused and appreciating the joke visually.'),
 (2828, 'Food Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Ever wonder why there are Pop Tarts, but no Mom Tarts? I think it''s because of the pastryarchy', NULL, 'A colorful humorous cartoon scene inside a kitchen. On the left, there''s a smiling box of Pop Tarts with a cartoon face, arms, and legs, standing proudly on the counter. On the right side of the counter are a few plain-looking muffins or pastries labeled ''Mom Tarts'' looking confused or sad with little arms and faces. Above them is a thought bubble originating from the Pop Tart with the word ''pastryarchy'' in a playful font. The kitchen background includes typical elements like a toaster, a stove, and a refrigerator with a magnet shaped like a star. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated with bold outlines and bright colors to accentuate the humor. No people are present, just anthropomorphic pastries emphasizing the joke about ''Pop Tarts'' vs ''Mom Tarts'' and the pun on ''patriarchy.'' The overall tone is whimsical and fun.'),
 (3263, 'Food Humor, Pun, What do you call...', 'What do you call cheese that isn''t yours? Nacho Cheese.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a wedge of cheese with a playful, mischievous face, wearing a sombrero to hint at the ''nacho'' pun. The cheese wedge is standing on a small plate, looking proudly at the viewer. Next to it, include a cartoonish, confused character (human or animal) trying to reach for the cheese but holding a sign that reads ''Not Yours!'' or ''Keep Out!''. The background should be simple and colorful, with a festive, lighthearted vibe—maybe some decorative streamers or confetti to emphasize fun. The overall tone is cheerful and silly, emphasizing the pun without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (550, 'Food Humor, Puns', 'Nothing tops a plain pizza.', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon scene centered on a plain cheese pizza sitting proudly on a simple wooden pizza board. The pizza should have no toppings except melted cheese, with a golden-brown crust. Above the pizza, emphasize its ''plainness'' by drawing a little crown or spotlight to humorously suggest it is ''topping'' everything. Around the pizza, include several other typical pizza toppings like pepperoni, mushrooms, olives, and peppers, placed aside or looking jealous and defeated. The background should be a cozy pizzeria with a checkered tablecloth and a few plates with various elaborate pizzas to contrast the plain one. Use bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated, funny expressions on the toppings to create a lighthearted, cartoonish vibe. The overall feel should be playful and pun-filled without any people or violence.'),
 (551, 'Food Humor, Puns', 'Rule Of Thumb: Serving Wine: There are six glasses of wine in a bottle.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a partially opened wine bottle on a table with six empty wine glasses arranged around it. Each glass should be oversized and comically large compared to the bottle, emphasizing the joke''s exaggeration. A cheerful character, perhaps a waiter or a casual wine drinker, can be gesturing with one hand showing the number six, smiling confidently as if explaining the ''rule of thumb.'' The setting can be a cozy dining room or a casual party atmosphere with subtle wine-related decorations like corkscrews, a wine rack, or grapevines in the background. The style should be lighthearted and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke’s humor without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (552, 'Food Humor, Puns', 'Smoking will kill you, and bacon will kill you, but smoking bacon will cure it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful pig holding a partially cooked strip of bacon that is shaped like a large, crooked cigarette. The pig is smiling slyly as it smokes the bacon, with little puffs of smoke rising from the bacon-cigarette. Nearby, a classic old-fashioned cigarette lies extinguished on an ashtray, and a sizzling frying pan holds more bacon strips cooking. In the background, a vintage-style health warning poster reads, ''Smoking will kill you,'' and another sign says, ''Bacon will kill you.'' Above the pig, a thought bubble says, ''But smoking bacon will cure it!'' The setting is a cozy kitchen with a humorous, lighthearted atmosphere, bright colors, and exaggerated cartoon features on the pig. The scene emphasizes the pun and playful contradiction of the joke with a whimsical, fun tone.'),
 (553, 'Food Humor, Puns', 'Time-saving idea: pre-toasted bread - just heat and serve.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon kitchen scene featuring a loaf of pre-sliced bread labeled ''Pre-Toasted Bread'' sitting next to a regular toaster. The loaf has a smiling, confident face with steam rising from it, indicating it’s already toasted. A happy person, wearing an apron, is holding a plate with a perfectly toasted slice, looking pleasantly surprised. The toaster is unplugged and abandoned to the side, maybe with a small sign that says ''Not needed!''. The background is a bright, cheerful kitchen with a countertop, coffee mug, and a window showing morning sun rays. The overall style is playful and exaggerated with bold lines and vibrant colors, emphasizing the absurd convenience of the ''pre-toasted bread'' concept.'),
 (554, 'Food Humor, Puns', 'To me, ''drink responsibly'' means don''t spill it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a lively bar or party environment. In the center, a cheerful person is holding a glass of drink (could be beer, wine, or cocktail) with a big smile, focusing carefully on not spilling it. Nearby, drinks are precariously balanced, and someone in the background is accidentally spilling their drink, looking surprised or embarrassed. The setting includes a bar counter with bottles and glasses, colorful string lights, and a few other cartoon characters enjoying themselves. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the punchline about ''drink responsibly'' meaning ''don''t spill it.'' No violence or inappropriate content should be depicted.'),
 (555, 'Food Humor, Puns', 'Velveeta is so vegetarians can have Spam too.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters at a picnic table in a sunny park. One character is a cheerful vegetarian holding a big, shiny block of Velveeta cheese labeled clearly. The other character is looking surprised, holding a can of Spam with a puzzled expression. On the table, place sliced Velveeta cheese arranged to look like slices of Spam. Include a picnic basket nearby with typical picnic food like bread, fruit, and utensils. Add a small sign or speech bubble from one character saying, ''Velveeta is so vegetarians can have Spam too.'' The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s playful confusion about vegetarian substitutes. The overall tone is fun and silly, without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (556, 'Food Humor, Puns', 'What is the opposite of LadyFingers? Mentos', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring two anthropomorphized characters standing side by side. On the left, a tall, elegant ''Lady Finger'' biscuit character wears a fancy dress and a pearl necklace, smiling gently and waving a delicate hand. The biscuit should look long, slender, and golden brown, resembling the actual ladyfinger cookie. On the right, a pack of Mentos candies is personified as a cheerful, bubbly character with a big grin and shiny, round candy pieces visible through the clear pack. The Mentos character wears a playful hat or bowtie for added personality. Both characters stand on a simple flat surface with a softly colored background, possibly kitchen-themed or pastel-colored to emphasize playfulness. Above them, in a whimsical speech bubble or banner, the joke is written: ''What is the opposite of LadyFingers? Mentos.'' The tone is lighthearted and cute, with exaggerated, friendly expressions and soft outlines, perfectly suited for a cartoon comic panel or humorous greeting card style.'),
 (557, 'Food Humor, Puns, Relatable Humor, Steven Wright', 'The hardness of the butter is proportional to the softness of the bread.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon kitchen scene focusing on a loaf of bread and a butter stick on a counter. The loaf of bread looks soft and squishy, with a relaxed, happy facial expression and slightly sagging sides to emphasize softness. Beside it, a stick of butter appears very hard and solid, with a strained, determined facial expression, almost like it''s flexing muscles to show firmness. The butter could have little sweat drops, showing effort to remain hard. Above them or nearby, a simple balance scale tips to one side, with the bread on the soft side and the butter on the hard side, visually representing the proverb-like relationship between their textures. The background is a simple brightly colored kitchen setting with a toaster, a butter knife, and a plate nearby. Make sure the overall look is lighthearted, cheerful, and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features on the bread and butter to clearly convey the joke about their opposing textures.'),
 (558, 'Food Humor, Puns, Science', 'Support bacteria -- it''s the only culture some people have!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy kitchen or science classroom. Center a cheerful, anthropomorphic bacterium character with big friendly eyes, a wide smile, and tiny arms giving a thumbs-up. Surround the bacterium with petri dishes labeled ''Culture'' with colorful bacterial colonies growing inside. Nearby, depict a few puzzled or unimpressed human characters, showing confused or blank expressions, highlighting that they lack ''culture.'' Include shelves with jars of yogurt, cheese, and other fermented foods to subtly emphasize the word ''culture.'' Bright colors and exaggerated, playful expressions should be used for a lighthearted effect without any negativity or harm. Make the overall tone fun and witty, visually reinforcing the pun about bacteria being a form of culture for some people.'),
 (559, 'Food Humor, Puns, Science', 'The softness of the butter is inversely proportional to the softness of the bread.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon kitchen scene with a loaf of bread and a stick of butter on a counter. The bread looks very soft and fluffy, almost puffed up with a relaxed, sleepy expression on its face. The butter, by contrast, is rigid and firm, with a slightly annoyed or grumpy face, maybe even with a little sweat drop to emphasize it’s hard. Above the scene, a simple science chart or graph labeled "Softness Inverse Proportionality" shows a downward-sloping line connecting "Butter softness" on one axis and "Bread softness" on the other. The background is a bright kitchen with a table, some utensils, and a butter knife nearby. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, using exaggerated facial expressions on the bread and butter to convey the joke visually without any violence, politics, or inappropriate content.')
INSERT INTO @tmpJokes (JokeId, Categories, JokeTxt, Attribution, ImageTxt) VALUES
 (560, 'Food Humor, Puns, Science', 'The Universe is made up mainly of interesting things. (More beer please!)', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person sitting at a bar counter, holding up a frothy beer mug. The bar background is filled with celestial-themed decorations such as stars, planets, and swirling galaxies, blending into the bar''s ambiance. Behind the bar, a bartender in a friendly pose is pouring another beer from a tap. Above the bar, a whimsical sign reads ''The Universe is made up mainly of interesting things.'' The person looks excited and slightly amused, as if making a lighthearted toast. The setting should feel lively and fun, with a mix of cosmic elements and a casual pub atmosphere, emphasizing the playful link between the universe and beer without any violent or inappropriate content.'),
 (2951, 'Food Humor, Puns, Unknown', 'I accidentally rubbed ketchup in my eyes. Now I have Heintz-sight', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting on a kitchen stool at a counter. The person looks surprised and is rubbing their eyes with red hands smeared with ketchup. On the counter nearby, there should be a large bottle of Heinz ketchup prominently displayed, with a few ketchup splatters around. The person''s eyes are exaggeratedly red and watery, emphasizing the discomfort. In the background, include a simple kitchen setting with a fridge, a ketchup-stained napkin on the counter, and perhaps a plate of fries to hint at the cause. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor. A small thought bubble or caption near the character can read “Heintz-sight” to highlight the pun clearly without any text overtaking the image.'),
 (561, 'Food Humor, Puns, Wine Humor', 'Rule Of Thumb: Red wines should breathe two minutes for every year between  the vintage and the present date.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person holding a glass of red wine with a confused expression. Next to them is a large, exaggerated hourglass with red wine filling the top bulb and a calendar with years marked on it next to the bottom. A speech bubble from the person says, “Two minutes for every year?”, highlighting the time needed for the wine to breathe. In the background, a wine bottle labeled with a distant vintage year (e.g., 1990) sits on a table covered with several clocks and timers, emphasizing the concept of time. The setting is a cozy, playful wine cellar or kitchen with a whimsical style, bright colors, and cartoonish exaggeration of objects to emphasize humor without any violence or inappropriate content.'),
 (2132, 'Food Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Never ask a woman who''s eating ice cream straight from the carton what''s wrong.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a woman sitting comfortably on a couch, holding and eating ice cream directly from a large carton with a spoon. Her facial expression is a mix of frustration and mild sadness, but also a bit defensive, as if she doesn''t want to talk about it. Nearby, a person (off to the side) is leaning slightly forward, looking curious and about to ask a question, with a speech bubble beginning with ''What''s wrong?''. The setting is a cozy living room with a soft blanket on the couch, a small coffee table with a tissue box, and perhaps a dim lamp creating a relaxed atmosphere. The tone should be lighthearted, emphasizing the humor of the woman''s silent moodiness while eating ice cream, with exaggerated cartoon style expressions to enhance the comic effect.'),
 (2391, 'Food Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The toughest part of dieting isn''t watching what you eat - it''s watching what your friends eat.', 'Wilfred Beaver', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room where a person is sitting on a couch with a determined but slightly distressed expression, holding a small salad bowl. Nearby, three friends are happily eating large, delicious looking foods: one has a huge burger, another is enjoying a pile of fries, and the third is holding a big slice of cake. The dieter’s eyes are wide and focused, sneaking glances at the friends'' tempting meals. Include details like a coffee table with snacks, colorful plates, and maybe a motivational poster about dieting on the wall that looks ironic in the context. The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the struggle of resisting temptation while watching others indulge.'),
 (2393, 'Food Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The trouble with eating Italian food is that five or six days later you''re hungry again.', 'George Miller', 'A humorous cartoon scene in a cozy Italian restaurant setting. At the center, a cheerful, slightly hungry-looking person sits at a table with an empty plate and a forlorn expression, rubbing their stomach. The table holds a few Italian food remnants like a half-eaten slice of pizza, a small bowl of spaghetti with a stray noodle dangling off the fork, and an empty wine glass. Behind them is a calendar on the wall showing the passage of days: the dates are circled from the previous visit up to five or six days later, hinting at the joke about hunger returning after a while. The background includes charming Italian decor elements like a bottle of olive oil, a pasta display, and a small potted plant. The overall style is light, playful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the humor in how quickly hunger returns after enjoying delicious Italian food.'),
 (2428, 'Food Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'There is no sincerer love than the love of food.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a happy, chubby character sitting at a dining table filled with a variety of delicious foods like a large pizza, a burger, fries, a slice of cake, and a bowl of ice cream. The character is hugging a giant sandwich with an exaggerated loving expression—eyes closed, big smile, and heart symbols floating around their head. The background is simple and bright to keep focus on the character and food. On the wall behind them, a framed picture of a heart made out of different food items (like fruits, veggies, and sweets) adds a playful touch. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and cheerful, emphasizing the joy and sincerity of loving food.'),
 (3049, 'Food Humor, Tourism Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I went on a tour of the Coca Cola factory. Didn''t realize at the end there would be a pop quiz.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene inside a bright, colorful Coca-Cola factory tour. In the foreground, a happy tourist with a camera around their neck looks surprised and slightly confused. They are standing near a conveyor belt carrying classic glass Coca-Cola bottles and cans with the iconic red and white logo. A friendly tour guide wearing a Coca-Cola branded cap and shirt points to a large pop quiz board at the end of the tour. The quiz board humorously features multiple-choice questions about soda facts, with images of fizz bubbles and cola splashes. Other tourists in the background look puzzled or are scratching their heads. The setting includes factory machinery, large soda tanks labeled ''Coca-Cola,'' and posters of vintage Coke ads on the walls. The overall style is a lighthearted, bright, and humorous cartoon with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize surprise and confusion, avoiding any violence or negativity.'),
 (2864, 'Food Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Food for thought: There is no plural for grilled cheese.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style kitchen scene featuring a person looking thoughtfully at a grilled cheese sandwich on a plate. The grilled cheese is exaggeratedly golden and gooey, with melted cheese stretching out. Floating above the character''s head is a classic ''thought bubble'' showing a dictionary page where the word ''grilled cheese'' appears without a plural form. Surrounding the person are several other sandwiches, all clearly different types (like a club sandwich, a BLT), each labeled with plural forms to emphasize the joke. The kitchen has a cozy feel, with a toaster, cutting board, and a cheese block nearby. The overall tone is light, playful, and witty, with smiling expressions and bright colors to convey the pun''s cleverness.'),
 (562, 'Food Humor, Word Play', 'This cookie is void where prohibited, licensed, or taxed.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, oversized cookie sitting on a table with a serious official-looking stamp on it that reads ''Void Where Prohibited, Licensed, or Taxed'' as if it were legal fine print on a product. The cookie has a slightly perplexed but proud facial expression with cartoon eyes and a small smile. Around the cookie, place a few small signs that say ''Legal Notice,'' ''Tax Office,'' and ''License Required.'' In the background, an office clerk or government agent with glasses and a clipboard observes the cookie with a puzzled look. The setting is a simple, cheerful kitchen or a mix between a bakery and an office environment. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and exaggerated to emphasize the contrast between a tasty treat and legal jargon. No people look upset or angry—just amused and confused by the cookie’s unexpected legal status.'),
 (1972, 'Freedom Humor, Irony, Political Humor, Quotes', 'It is by the fortune of God that, in this country, we have three benefits: freedom of speech, freedom of thought, and the wisdom never to use either.', 'Mark Twain', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a typical town hall or country meeting setting with a diverse group of cheerful citizens gathered around a speaker''s podium. The speaker, wearing a suit and a slight smirk, holds a scroll labeled ''Rights & Freedoms.'' Behind him is a large banner that reads ''Freedom of Speech & Thought.'' Around the crowd, several people have exaggerated thought bubbles showing crazy or silly ideas, but they are all zipped shut by big cartoon zippers labeled ''Wisdom.'' Some citizens look nervous or hesitant to speak, with wide eyes and finger-on-lips gestures. The background includes symbols like a large open book titled ''Constitution'' and a statue of Lady Justice looking bemused. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing irony and gentle satire without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1418, 'Friendship Humor, Love Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'A hug warms the soul and places a smile in the heart.', NULL, 'A warm, colorful cartoon scene featuring two fluffy, smiling anthropomorphic hearts hugging each other tightly in the center. Around them, soft pastel colors radiate gentle light and tiny sparkles float, emphasizing the warmth. Both hearts have big, joyful eyes and wide smiles. Above them, a handwritten-style caption says, ''A hug warms the soul and places a smile in the heart.'' In the background, subtle, whimsical elements like cartoon-style sun rays or floating smiley faces enhance the feeling of warmth and affection. The overall style is simple, cute, and lighthearted, suitable for a cheerful greeting card or uplifting cartoon.'),
 (2387, 'Friendship Humor, Love Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'The supreme happiness of life is the conviction that one is loved; loved for oneself, or better yet, loved despite oneself.', 'Victor Hugo', 'A warm, humorous cartoon scene featuring a cozy living room with two characters: one is a person sitting comfortably in an armchair, looking content and happy, with a big smile and relaxed posture. Nearby, a friend or family member is playfully embracing or giving a gentle, affectionate hug, showing clear fondness. Their expressions convey genuine love and acceptance, despite some humorous flaws or quirks visible on the loved one (e.g., messy hair, quirky pajamas, or a funny expression). Around them, little heart symbols float in the air to emphasize love and happiness. The background shows personal and homely details like a framed picture on the wall, a small plant on a side table, and a warm lamp casting a soft glow. The style should be simple, colorful, and exaggerated for a lighthearted, endearing feel without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (1703, 'Friendship Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Friendships are fragile things, and require as much handling as any other fragile and precious thing.', 'Randolph S. Bourne', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two friends carefully carrying an oversized, transparent glass object shaped like a heart, symbolizing their fragile friendship. Both friends are tiptoeing and holding the heart with great concentration, eyes wide with careful focus, as if it might break any second. Surrounding them are items labeled "Friendships," such as a delicate cake on a plate, a fragile bird''s nest balanced on a branch, and a wrapped gift with a fragile sticker on it. The background is light and cheerful, with soft pastel colors and whimsical details like cartoonish sparkles around the glass heart to emphasize its preciousness. The overall tone is lighthearted and gentle, with exaggerated expressions and movements typical of cartoon humor, clearly illustrating the idea that friendships need careful handling like precious fragile things.'),
 (1401, 'Friendship Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'A friend is somebody you want to be around when you feel like being by yourself.', 'Barbara Burrow', 'A humorous cartoon scene that shows two quirky characters sitting on a park bench. One character looks content and relaxed, with arms crossed enjoying solitude, wearing casual clothes and headphones, as if wanting to be alone. The other character is cheerfully leaning toward the first, smiling and casually chatting or just keeping company, also relaxed and happy. Around them, soft, comical thought bubbles appear: the first character’s bubble shows a cozy room with a book and a tea cup, symbolizing wanting to be by themselves; the second character’s bubble shows an image of a warm hug or happy company, representing the friend being there despite the other''s desire to be alone. The background includes a sunny day with a tree and birds, and a subtle humorous sign on the bench that reads ''Reserved for Unexpected Company.'' The style is light, friendly, and expressive, emphasizing the warm but ironic friendship dynamic without any aggression or discomfort.'),
 (2876, 'Friendship Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Friendship is the hardest thing in the world to explain.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two friends standing face-to-face. One friend looks really puzzled, scratching their head with a big question mark above it. The other friend is trying to explain friendship by holding a tangled ball of yarn or string labeled ''Friendship,'' looking equally confused but determined. Around them, include various items symbolizing friendship—like a shared cup of coffee, a heart floating over their heads, and little sticky notes with words like ''trust,'' ''laughter,'' and ''support.'' The background can be a simple park or living room setting to keep it cozy and relatable. The overall style should be lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the idea that explaining friendship is tricky and complex.'),
 (2060, 'Friendship, Love Humor, Music Humor, Quotes', 'Love is a friendship set to music.', 'E. Joseph Cossman', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two friends sitting on a park bench. The friends are smiling warmly at each other, with musical notes floating around them to represent ''music''. One friend holds a small guitar and the other holds a microphone, as if they are serenading each other. The background shows a sunny day with birds happily singing and a few whimsical floating hearts mixed with musical notes. The bench is simple but inviting, and there’s a small boombox nearby playing tunes. Emphasize a lighthearted and cheerful atmosphere that visually combines friendship and music.'),
 (2547, 'Friendship, Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'What sweetness is left in life, if you take away friendship? Robbing away the friendship is like robbing the world of sun.', 'Cicero', 'A colorful, lighthearted cartoon scene showing two cheerful characters sitting together on a park bench under a radiant, smiling sun. The sun has a friendly face and warm rays that reach down toward the friends. One character is handing the other a small jar labeled ''Friendship'' filled with bright, glowing hearts or sparkles. Around them are flowers and butterflies, symbolizing happiness. In the background, a faint, open world globe glows warmly, illustrating the world being brightened by their bond. The overall tone is warm, inviting, and joyful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the sweetness and brightness friendship brings to life.'),
 (1871, 'Fun Facts, Quotes, Wit', 'If at first you don''t succeed, find out if the loser gets anything.', 'Bill Lyon', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple competition arena, like a game show stage or a school playground. Center the image on two characters: one clearly the winner, holding a big trophy or medal and smiling proudly; the other a disappointed loser, slouched and looking curious or hopeful. Above them, a large banner reads ''First Competition''. Between them, a game host or announcer stands with a microphone, wearing a suit and grinning mischievously, holding a clipboard titled ''Prize Rules''. Include subtle props like confetti, balloons, or a scoreboard showing the winner’s score and the loser’s score. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the joke’s punchline about checking if the loser receives a prize, rather than focusing on success or failure. Draw in bright, cheerful colors with exaggerated, cartoonish facial expressions to add to the comedy.'),
 (2289, 'Funny Advice, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The bitterest tears shed over graves are for words left unsaid and deeds left undone.', 'Harriet Beecher Stowe', 'A humorous cartoon-style graveyard scene at twilight with gentle, soft colors and a peaceful atmosphere. Several simple gravestones are visible, with one prominent stone in the center. A cartoon character with exaggerated sad eyes and a tear rolling down their cheek stands in front of it, holding a giant, old-fashioned speech bubble and a large to-do checklist titled ''Words & Deeds''. Behind the character, faint ghost-like speech bubbles and action icons (like a handshake or a helping hand) hover above other graves, representing words never said and deeds never done. The character’s face looks both regretful and puzzled, emphasizing the humor in the ''bitterest tears'' being about communication and unfinished acts, rather than overt tragedy. The setting includes soft, rolling hills and a few cute cartoon birds quietly observing, adding a lighthearted tone. The overall style is clean, colorful, and simple, with rounded shapes and expressive features making the scene feel gentle and amusing rather than morose.'),
 (2580, 'Funny Advice, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'Whenever you are asked if you can do a job, tell ''em, ''Certainly I can!'' Then get busy and find out how to do it.', 'Theodore Roosevelt', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with a confident character standing proudly before a boss or client who is asking if they can do a job. The confident character should be smiling broadly with an exaggerated thumbs-up gesture and a speech bubble saying, ''Certainly I can!'' In the background, depict the character at a desk cluttered with instruction manuals, a laptop with multiple tabs open showing tutorials, a coffee cup, and sticky notes, illustrating their frantic effort to figure out how to actually do the job. The setting is a casual office environment with lighthearted, bright colors and simple, exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the optimistic yet unprepared attitude. Include humorous small details like a confused or overwhelmed expression appearing on the character while reading a complicated manual, with scattered papers flying around to add to the comedic vibe. The overall tone is playful and encouraging, capturing the spirit of tackling challenges with enthusiasm even when unprepared.'),
 (1985, 'Future Humor, Philosophy, Quotes, Science Humor', 'It is the business of the future to be dangerous; and it is among the merits of science that it equips the future for its duties.', 'Alfred North Whitehead', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a futuristic scientist wearing a lab coat and safety goggles, standing proudly in a high-tech laboratory filled with quirky dangerous gadgets like bubbling test tubes, sparking robots, and a laser beam display. The scientist holds a glowing orb labeled ''Future'' while looking confidently into the distance. Around the lab, signs humorously warn ''Danger Ahead!'' and ''Future at Work!''. In the background, a playful robot assistant nervously tiptoes around a smoking machine. The overall tone is lighthearted and optimistic, emphasizing that science prepares the future for its ''dangerous duties'' in a fun way.'),
 (2963, 'Gambling, Humor, Irony, Unknown', 'I bet I could stop gambling if I wanted to.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a poker or casino table covered with poker chips and playing cards. The person has a confident, slightly mischievous grin, and is casually tossing chips in the air as if showing off. Around the table are scattered signs like ''Casino Night'' and a slot machine nearby with spinning reels. The background shows a clock on the wall indicating late night and a thought bubble above the person''s head with the words, ''I bet I could stop gambling if I wanted to.'' The art style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors, playful expressions, and minimal detail focusing on the character''s carefree attitude. No one else is at the table, emphasizing the individual''s confident yet ironic statement about gambling cessation.'),
 (1410, 'Games, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A good terminology is half the game.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene illustrating the phrase ''A good terminology is half the game.'' Show two characters playing a board game that resembles chess or a strategy game. One character confidently holds a large dictionary or glossary labeled ''Terminology'' like a valuable tool or weapon. The other character looks puzzled, staring at complicated game pieces labeled with confusing, jumbled words. The background shows a game board with pieces shaped like letters or words instead of traditional game pieces. The style is bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor — one player is smug, the other frustrated. Include speech bubbles; the confident player saying ''A good terminology is half the game,'' and the other scratching their head. The overall tone is lighthearted, emphasizing clever wordplay and the importance of knowing terms in strategy or games.'),
 (1182, 'Gaming Humor, Insults, Relatable Humor, Social Media Humor', 'May all your Facebook invites be game invites', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a computer desk at home. The computer screen displays a Facebook notifications pop-up window filled with multiple game invitations, like Candy Crush or FarmVille icons, piling up comically. The person has exaggerated wide eyes and a slightly annoyed smile, holding a phone or mouse in one hand. Around them are playful elements like colorful game characters creeping into the room or peeking from behind the furniture, emphasizing the overwhelming nature of game invites. The background is a casual home office with a coffee mug and a small plant, giving a lighthearted, everyday vibe without any negativity.'),
 (563, 'Gender Humor, Humor, Relatable', 'There are two theories to arguing with women. Neither one works.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man and a woman sitting at a small round table, both with exaggerated puzzled expressions. The man is holding a tiny book titled ''How to Argue with Women'' with question marks floating above his head. The woman sits calmly across from him with a slight amused smirk, arms crossed. Between them on the table are two visibly torn or crumpled papers labeled ''Theory 1'' and ''Theory 2'' to symbolize failed strategies. The background is simple, with soft pastel colors, and a clock on the wall showing time passing to imply long, unproductive debates. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing confusion and humorous futility without disrespect.'),
 (3094, 'Gender Humor, Humor, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, people would never talk about how fresh they felt.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a throne room or world leadership setting. In the center, a confident-looking man sits on a large throne labeled ''World Leader.'' Around him, confused or bored people stand and talk, looking tired, disheveled, and yawning, with speech bubbles showing phrases like ''I feel tired,'' ''Exhausted,'' or ''Could use a shower.'' On the side, a woman or mixed group of people observe with amused or knowing smiles, holding speech bubbles saying ''At least we talk about feeling fresh!'' The background includes a globe or map to suggest global leadership. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated tired expressions on the men and lively expressions on the others, highlighting that if men ran the world, nobody would discuss feeling fresh or energized.'),
 (3098, 'Gender Humor, Satire, Sports Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, the only show opposite ''Monday Night Football'' would be ''Monday Night Football from a Different Camera Angle.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a lively living room on a Monday night. Center stage is a large TV screen displaying a football game with players mid-action. Next to the TV, a remote control is held by a relaxed man with a big smile, wearing casual clothes like a T-shirt and jeans. The man is surrounded by typical football-watching snacks such as a bowl of popcorn, a beer bottle, and a plate of wings. In the background, a calendar is visible on the wall, clearly marking "Monday Night". The TV screen is split into two images showing the same football game from two slightly different angles, side by side, emphasizing the joke that the only alternative program is the same game from a different camera angle. The overall style is colorful and exaggerated with playful expressions, focusing on the humor of limited TV choices if men ran the world. No other characters or distracting elements included to keep the focus on the man, the TV, and the joke’s theme.'),
 (564, 'Geography Humor, Good Question!', 'Reno, Nevada is west of Los Angeles, California.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon map scene showing a very confused tourist standing at a signpost that points in multiple directions. The signpost has two big arrows: one labeled ''Los Angeles, CA'' pointing east, and another labeled ''Reno, NV'' pointing west. The tourist, wearing a hat and a fanny pack, is scratching their head with a puzzled expression. The background includes a simple cartoonish representation of the California and Nevada border with exaggerated mountains and desert scenery. A small airplane flies overhead carrying a banner that says ''Geography is tricky!'' The overall style is bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions and clear text on the signpost, emphasizing the mix-up about the relative west-east positions of Reno and Los Angeles.'),
 (565, 'Geography Humor, Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'Do people in Australia call the rest of the world ''up over''?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful Australian person, wearing a stereotypical Aussie hat with corks dangling and holding a boomerang, standing on a small globe or planet labeled ''Australia.'' The globe is tilted so Australia is shown at the bottom with a label ‘Down Under’ to emphasize position. Above, a group of diverse people representing the rest of the world look up curiously from a floating platform or cloud labeled ''Up Over.'' The Australian is pointing upward toward the group, with a puzzled but playful expression. The background is bright and cheerful with a simple blue sky, and arrows or dotted lines could show ''up'' and ''down'' directions humorously reversed. The style is light, cartoonish, and friendly with exaggerated features for comedy, avoiding any stereotypes beyond lighthearted Australian icons and globe representation. There are speech bubbles suggesting the question, but no text needed inside the drawing itself.'),
 (601, 'Geography Humor, Good Question!, Pun', 'What world capital has the fastest growing population? Ireland. The capital is Dublin every day.', NULL, 'A bright and colorful cartoon scene showing a map or globe focused on Ireland. In the center, there is a cheerful, animated city labeled ''Dublin'' with buildings that look like they''re physically growing taller and bigger right before the viewer’s eyes. Around the city, little stick-figure people are happily multiplying or multiplying in a playful, exaggerated way, like popping up every day. The scene has a humorous feel with a calendar on one side showing the word ''Dublin'' written across multiple days to visually emphasize the pun. The overall artwork should be lighthearted and fun, with smiling characters and a clear, bold lettering of ''Dublin Every Day'' to make the joke visually obvious and entertaining.'),
 (589, 'Geography Humor, Good Question!, Puns, Word Play', 'What has 4 eyes and still can''t see?  Mississippi', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a simple map or outline of the state of Mississippi, drawn with a happy, confused face. The key feature is that the word ''Mississippi'' is prominently written above or beside it, with all four letter ''i''s in the word clearly highlighted or exaggerated to look like big, googly cartoon eyes. Despite having these four ''eyes,'' the Mississippi character has a pair of eyes on its face that are crossed or looking in opposite directions, humorously implying that it still can''t see properly. The background is plain with a subtle suggestion of a classroom or quiz show setting, maybe a question mark floating nearby, to emphasize the joke''s riddle nature. The overall style is cheerful and playful, suitable for a lighthearted cartoon.'),
 (2902, 'Geography Humor, Music Humor, State Pride Humor, Unknown', 'Hang On Sloopy is the official rock song of Ohio.', NULL, 'Draw a cheerful cartoon map of the state of Ohio with animated features. Ohio should have a big smiling face and hands playing an electric guitar. Musical notes float around Ohio, with the title ''Hang On Sloopy'' appearing like a banner above. In the background, include a simple cityscape or countryside to represent Ohio''s diverse regions. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, resembling a playful mascot promoting the state’s ''official rock song.'' The scene should feel fun and musical, without people, focusing on Ohio as a character enjoying its own anthem.'),
 (2637, 'Golf Humor, Medical Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'A man lost three of his fingers in a tragic accident. While getting it treated he asked the doctor Will I be able to play golf with this hand? Doc: Maybe... but I wouldn''t count on it!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a doctor''s office. The central character is a man sitting nervously on an examination table, with three fingers visibly bandaged or missing on one hand. His other hand is intact, resting on his lap. The doctor, wearing a white coat and stethoscope, stands next to him holding a clipboard and giving a funny, slightly sarcastic expression. Include a framed picture of a golf course hanging on the wall behind them to hint at the man''s question. The setting is lighthearted with bright colors, and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s tone. The man looks anxious yet hopeful, while the doctor looks gently amused but doubtful. No elements appear violent or graphic; the missing fingers are simplified as clearly bandaged or just stub ends to keep it child-friendly and cartoonish.'),
 (566, 'Good Question!', 'How come in baseball when you strike out it''s bad, and in bowling it''s good?', NULL, 'Single-panel, split-scene cartoon with a vertical dividing line down the middle showing two contrasting sports moments side-by-side.Left side (baseball):- A dejected batter at home plate, shoulders slumped, helmet tipped forward over his eyes. His bat lies on the ground beside him.- The umpire behind the catcher has one hand raised and a stern expression; big red letters above read “STRIKEOUT” with a flashing X.- Background: a small, disappointed crowd with slumped faces and a concession-stand sign that says “Broken Dreams Hot Dogs.”- Color palette: classic baseball greens and muted tones to emphasize gloom.Right side (bowling):- A jubilant bowler mid-pose with fist pumped and a huge grin. The bowling ball has just hit the pocket; pins are exploding upward like confetti.- Above them, a scoreboard flashes “STRIKE!” in bright, celebratory letters with stars and confetti graphics.- Background: enthusiastic fans cheering, a banner reading “Perfect!” and a gutter decorated with party streamers.- Color palette: bright, warm colors (yellow, orange) to show celebration.Add exaggerated, cartoony expressions, motion lines (swing arc on left, pins flying on right), and a small caption at the bottom: “Same word. Different outcome.”'),
 (567, 'Good Question!', 'If you take life too seriously, it ceases to be amusing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person dressed in formal business attire sitting rigidly at a desk with a large, serious expression. The person is surrounded by stacks of paperwork, a computer, and a clock showing the passing of time. Hanging on the wall is a framed motivational poster that reads, ''Life is Serious Business!'' In contrast, next to the desk, there''s a small colorful clown juggling or a playful puppy with a silly hat, symbolizing amusement and fun. The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions on the serious character’s face to show stiffness and the playful elements standing out as bright and inviting. The style is simple, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between seriousness and amusement without any threatening or sensitive content.'),
 (568, 'Good Question!', 'If you think education is expensive, then try ignorance.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a simple classroom setting. On the left, a confident, well-dressed person is holding a large, shiny diploma or a big textbook labeled ''Education'' with dollar signs on it, looking proud but slightly stressed by the cost. On the right, a confused-looking character is standing next to a huge pile of bills labeled ''Ignorance Costs,'' looking overwhelmed and worried, with cartoonish sweat drops flying off their head. Between them, a small price tag hovers in the air reading ''Try Ignorance.'' The background can include a chalkboard with a math problem or alphabet letters, and a small piggy bank on a desk with coins scattered around. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s point about the cost of ignorance versus education.'),
 (660, 'Good Question!, Hardware Humor, Programming, Workplace', 'How many programmers does it take to change a lightbulb? None. It''s a hardware problem.', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a frustrated programmer sitting at a messy desk cluttered with computer parts, monitors, and coffee mugs. The programmer is wearing glasses and a hoodie, staring at a dark lightbulb screwed into a ceiling fixture above them. Nearby, a confused-looking person holding a screwdriver is trying to twist the lightbulb, while the programmer waves a hand dismissively or points toward a computer tower. The background should include tech gadgets, wires, and posters about coding. The mood is light and playful, emphasizing the stereotype that programmers don’t fix hardware issues, only software. The overall style should be exaggerated and cartoonish with bright colors and expressive faces to capture the humor without violence or negativity.'),
 (661, 'Good Question!, History Humor', 'Do you think that when they asked George Washington for ID that he just whipped out a quarter?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a modern-day convenience store or security checkpoint. George Washington, depicted in classic 18th-century attire with a powdered wig and colonial coat, stands at the counter holding up a large quarter coin prominently in front of a cashier or security guard who looks confused or surprised. The quarter shows George Washington''s face clearly, and the setting includes a small sign saying ''Please show ID''. The cashier is wearing a typical uniform and name tag, with a raised eyebrow expression. The background shows shelves with snacks or typical store items to place the scene in a present-day setting, contrasting with Washington''s historical appearance. The style should be light, colorful, and exaggerated in a friendly cartoon manner emphasizing the humor of using a quarter as ID.'),
 (662, 'Good Question!, History Humor', 'How do you write zero in Roman numerals?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an ancient Roman classroom. In the center, a Roman teacher in traditional toga stands at a large stone tablet easel, holding a piece of chalk. He looks puzzled or shrugging. Facing him, a group of cartoon Roman students dressed in tunics sit at stone desks, some scratching their heads or shrugging as well. The teacher is writing Roman numerals on the board: I, V, X, L, C, D, M. At the bottom of the board, there is a big question mark next to an empty space where ''zero'' would be. Around the classroom, classic Roman decorations like columns and laurel wreaths are visible. The mood is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the confusion about how to represent zero in Roman numerals. No one appears upset—just playfully puzzled by the concept of zero being absent in Roman numeral system.'),
 (663, 'Good Question!, History Humor', 'Leonardo da Vinci invented the scissors.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Leonardo da Vinci in a Renaissance workshop filled with sketches and inventions. Leonardo, wearing typical Renaissance clothes and a beret, is holding a pair of old-fashioned scissors with a proud smile. The scissors should look slightly exaggerated with large, ornate handles made of wood or metal. Around him on a wooden table are papers with rough sketches of scissors and other famous da Vinci inventions like the flying machine. The background could include shelves with tools, gears, and scrolls to emphasize the inventor''s workspace. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with a playful mood to match the joke''s tongue-in-cheek claim.'),
 (664, 'Good Question!, History Humor', 'Only two people signed the Declaration of Independence on July 4th, John Hancock and Charles Thomson. Most of the rest signed in August 2, but the last signature wasn''t added until 5 years later.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a colonial-era room with a large wooden table covered with an oversized, old parchment labeled ''Declaration of Independence.'' Two characters, John Hancock and Charles Thomson, are seated at the table confidently signing the document with large quill pens, both smiling and looking proud. Surrounding them are empty chairs with name tags labeled with other founders'' names, loosely scattered papers, and a large wall calendar showing July 4th. In the background, a comical timeline poster hangs on the wall showing dates July 4th, August 2nd, and a humorous ''5 years later'' marker with an old man sneakily adding a final signature with a huge quill, wearing a powdered wig and glasses, looking surprised or sheepish. The atmosphere is light and playful, emphasizing the delay in signing with exaggerated expressions and props, drawn in a colorful, cartoonish style with exaggerated features and bright colors.'),
 (665, 'Good Question!, History Humor, Military Humor', 'The Eisenhower interstate system requires that one mile in every five must be straight.  These straight sections are usable as airstrips in times of war or other emergencies.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a long stretch of highway with a perfectly straight section highlighted, resembling an airstrip runway. The highway is labeled ''Eisenhower Interstate System.'' On one side of the road, there is a small vintage airplane parked on the straight section as if it had just landed or is ready to take off. A few cars are nearby, looking surprised or curious. The surrounding landscape should be simple and slightly exaggerated for comedic effect, with green fields and road signs indicating mile markers and a sign that reads ''1 mile straight - usable as airstrip.'' The style is colorful and lighthearted, emphasizing the absurdity and cleverness of highways doubling as emergency runways without any tension or danger.'),
 (666, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'If a jogger runs at the speed of sound, can he still hear his walkman?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a jogger running at lightning speed, depicted by motion blur lines and speed streaks behind them. The jogger wears typical running clothes and a classic walkman with headphones. Around the jogger''s head, sound waves or musical notes are illustrated trying to catch up with him but trailing far behind. The background shows a park with trees and a winding path, emphasizing movement. The jogger has a slightly puzzled or amused expression, glancing back at the walkman. The colors are bright and playful to emphasize the humor and cartoon style. Include a speedometer hovering nearby showing an exaggerated speed labeled ''Speed of Sound.'' No violent or inappropriate elements, just lighthearted and imaginative.'),
 (667, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'If blind people wear dark glasses, why don''t deaf people wear earmuffs?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side in a bright, simple setting. On the left, a cheerful person with sunglasses on, representing a blind person, is smiling confidently. They wear classic dark sunglasses. On the right, a confused-looking person who appears deaf stands without earmuffs, scratching their head or shrugging. Around them, floating question marks emphasize the confusion or curiosity. The background is plain with a subtle suggestion of an indoor or outdoor casual environment, like a park or sidewalk. The style is light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor and the playful questioning of the joke. No text needed in the image; the visual contrast between sunglasses and absence of earmuffs should be clear and central to the humor.'),
 (668, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'If the funeral procession is at night, do folks drive with their lights off?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a nighttime funeral procession driving down a quiet road. The procession consists of a classic black hearse and several black cars following behind. The hearse has visible headlights on, but the other cars behind are humorously depicted with their headlights off, making it look like glowing taillights floating in the dark. The background shows a moonlit sky with a few stars, and some trees lining the road. A confused driver in one of the cars looks nervously at their dashboard, unsure if the lights should be on or off. Include small humorous details like a speech bubble above the confused driver saying, ''Should we turn them off?''. The overall tone should be light, silly, and playful with clean cartoon lines and exaggerated expressions on the drivers'' faces to convey the joke clearly without any dark or morbid elements.'),
 (669, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'If you had everything, where would you keep it?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing puzzled in a tiny, cluttered room that is crammed full of a wild assortment of objects, all labeled "everything." The room is bursting at the seams, with items overflowing from shelves, spilling from boxes, hanging from the ceiling, and stacked in towering piles nearly blocking the door. The person has a comical, exaggerated confused expression, scratching their head. Include a thought bubble above their head with the question "If you had everything, where would you keep it?" The scene should convey the visual joke about the impossibility of having and storing ''everything'' in one small space. Use bright and playful cartoon colors with exaggerated proportions to emphasize the overcrowded chaos humorously without any negativity or mess beyond comedic clutter.'),
 (670, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'If you think nobody cares about you, try missing a couple of payments.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room. In the center, show a person sitting on a couch looking sad and lonely, with a thought bubble above their head containing a small ghostly figure symbolizing ''nobody cares.'' Next to the couch, place a mailbox or a small stack of overdue payment bills clearly marked ''PAST DUE'' with big, bold letters. From the mailbox or bills, depict tiny, angry cartoon character-versions of the bills or a stern-looking creditor figure glaring at the person threateningly but comically. Add exaggerated facial expressions showing the person''s surprised or worried reaction as these ''billing characters'' loom over them. The style should be lighthearted, with bright colors and simple lines to emphasize the joke’s punchline without appearing harsh. Include details like a clock on the wall to imply time passing and a simple background to keep the focus on the interaction between the person, the ''nobody cares'' ghostly figure, and the payment bills.'),
 (671, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'If you want the rainbow, you gotta put up with the rain.', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene showing a rainbow brightly arcing across a partly cloudy sky. In the foreground, a happy character holding a large colorful umbrella is standing in the rain with big raindrops falling around. The character looks content and is smiling, enjoying the rain while looking up at the rainbow. There are simple cartoon clouds releasing rain, and sunlight breaking through to create the rainbow. The style is lighthearted and humorous, with soft colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the positive attitude toward enduring rain for the reward of a rainbow.'),
 (672, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'If you''re sitting in public and a stranger takes the seat next to you, just stare straight ahead and say, ''Did you bring the money?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a public park bench or in a busy waiting area, like a bus stop. The main character, a casually dressed person with a slightly confused but wary expression, is sitting on the bench looking straight ahead with a deadpan stare. A stranger, who looks like an ordinary passerby, is just sitting down right next to them, with a puzzled and slightly alarmed look. The main character’s mouth is open as if they have just said, ''Did you bring the money?'' The background shows subtle details like other benches, trees or a bus sign to emphasize the public setting. The style should be bright, simple, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the awkwardness and surprise of the moment, making the humor clear without any aggressive or negative vibes.'),
 (673, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'I''m most efficient when nobody is looking.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a cluttered desk with papers, a laptop, and a coffee cup. The individual is wearing casual clothes and has a sly, mischievous grin while stealthily typing or working. Behind them, a large window shows an empty room with a ''No Entry'' sign or a ''Help Wanted'' poster to emphasize solitude. In the background, a clock shows normal work hours to imply they''re being productive only when unobserved. The style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the exaggerated expression of secret efficiency without showing anyone else in the room.'),
 (674, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'I''m waiting for the Mothership. What are you waiting for?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing outside at night, looking up at the starry sky with an expectant expression. The person is casually dressed and has one hand shading their eyes, as if scanning the heavens. In the sky, a classic flying saucer-style UFO—silver and slightly glowing—is descending with a beam of light shining down. The background includes a simple landscape of rolling hills or a backyard with a few trees and maybe a fence. The mood is light-hearted and quirky, with exaggerated, cartoonish features for the character and the spaceship to emphasize the joke’s playful tone.'),
 (675, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'In case of doubt, make it sound convincing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person standing confidently at a podium or in a casual setting, speaking to an audience or another character. The speaker is gesturing with one hand, wearing a slightly mischievous smile, as if giving advice. Above or next to the person is a speech bubble containing the phrase, ''In case of doubt, make it sound convincing.'' The background is simple and uncluttered, maybe with a few question marks floating around to represent doubt. The audience or the other character looks uncertain or confused, emphasizing the humorous idea of bluffing one''s way through uncertainty. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic tone.'),
 (676, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'In Cleveland, Ohio, it''s illegal to catch mice without a hunting license.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon set outside a modest house in Cleveland, Ohio. Center the image on a nervous, slightly confused cartoon mouse wearing tiny glasses and holding a small sign that says ''Looking for a job.'' Nearby is a human character dressed like a hunter, complete with a big hunting hat, camouflage jacket, and a large hunting rifle slung over their shoulder. The hunter is solemnly holding up a piece of paper labeled ''Hunting License'' and pointing toward the mouse as if explaining the law. Behind them, a city sign reads ''Welcome to Cleveland, Ohio.'' Maybe include a whimsical courthouse building in the background with a banner saying ''Strict Mouse Hunting Laws.'' The overall style is playful and colorful with exaggerated expressions to highlight the absurdity of needing a license to catch mice.'),
 (677, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'In the words of the great philosopher and handyman Red Green:  ''...and remember, if the girls don''t find you handsome, at least let them find you handy''.', NULL, 'A cheerful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a middle-aged man resembling a handyman dressed in a red flannel shirt, worn jeans, and a tool belt packed with typical tools like a hammer, screwdriver, and wrench. He wears a baseball cap slightly askew and has an endearing, slightly goofy grin. The man is in a cozy workshop with wooden shelves holding tools and bits of hardware, including a saw and nails. A speech bubble above him shows the quote: ''...and remember, if the girls don''t find you handsome, at least let them find you handy.'' Nearby, two smiling women glance approvingly at his handiwork, which is a slightly crooked but charmingly built birdhouse on a workbench. The scene has bright colors with a warm, inviting atmosphere. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing humor and relatability without any offensive content.'),
 (678, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'It''s the little things that count.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large human hand with a tiny, comically small object being handed over between thumb and forefinger. The tiny object could be a miniature gift box, a tiny coin, or a small flower, emphasizing the phrase ''little things.'' The setting is simple, with a neutral background to keep focus on the hand and the tiny item. The hand is exaggerated in size compared to the small object to highlight the contrast. The style should be bright and cheerful, with exaggerated features to make the scene playful and funny, capturing the pun on ''small things'' mattering.'),
 (679, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'Laugh and you''ll burn up three and a half calories. No joke.', NULL, 'A lighthearted and cheerful cartoon scene showing a person sitting on a couch watching TV or holding a phone, laughing heartily. The character is mid-laugh with eyes closed and mouth wide open, with a cartoonish sweat drop or small puff of smoke rising from them to humorously indicate ''burning calories.'' Around the character, little calorie symbols (like tiny flames shaped like calories) float up playfully. The background is cozy and simple, such as a living room with a coffee table and a plant, emphasizing a relaxed atmosphere. The overall style is colorful, friendly, and whimsical to highlight the fun idea that laughter burns calories.'),
 (680, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'Laundry machines have a secret chamber where they hide single socks.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a typical laundry room with a washing machine and a dryer. The washing machine is slightly open, revealing a small hidden secret chamber inside, glowing softly with a few lonely single socks lounging around on tiny armchairs, sipping soda or playing cards. Some socks have funny facial expressions displaying boredom or mischief. Around the machines, piles of matching folded socks sit neatly, while one sock appears puzzled looking toward the secret chamber. The setting is bright, colorful, and playful with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the whimsical idea of socks having a secret hiding spot inside the machine.'),
 (681, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'LOTTERY: The equivalent of betting that the next pope will be from Duluth, or that the parrot in the pet store window speaks Flemish.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a lottery ticket counter looking confused and skeptical. Behind the counter, there is a colorful lottery poster featuring wildly unlikely predictions, such as a map pinpointing Duluth with a pope''s hat on it, and a bright pet store window with a cartoonish parrot wearing a little Flemish hat and speech bubble showing gibberish representing Flemish language. The customer holds a lottery ticket marked with question marks and raised eyebrows, emphasizing disbelief. The environment is light and playful with exaggerated facial expressions and a whimsical style, using vibrant colors and simple line art to enhance the joke''s absurdity.'),
 (682, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'Meditation is not what you think.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person sitting cross-legged in a typical meditation pose on a cushion in a peaceful, minimalistic room. Instead of looking calm and serene, the person''s face shows surprise or confusion with wide eyes and raised eyebrows. Above their head is a thought bubble depicting a chaotic jumble of random funny images like dancing cats, flying toasters, and question marks, illustrating how their mind is not at peace as they might expect during meditation. The background includes simple elements like a small indoor plant, a window with sunlight streaming in, and a small clock showing the passage of time. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the ideal of meditation and the reality of a busy, distracted mind.'),
 (683, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'My buddy can''t afford to pay his water bill, so I sent him a ''Get Well Soon'' card', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two friends in a living room. One friend looks worried, holding a water bill with a big red ''PAST DUE'' stamp on it. The other friend is cheerfully handing over a comical ''Get Well Soon'' card with a smiling water droplet character on the front. Include a kitchen sink or a dripping faucet in the background to emphasize the water theme. The setting is light and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the joke, capturing the irony of sending a ''Get Well Soon'' card for a water bill problem.'),
 (684, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'Nothing worth learning is learned quickly except parachuting.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a person mid-air, parachuting with a wide-eyed, surprised expression. The person should be wearing a simple parachute harness and helmet. Below, show a small cartoonish speedometer labeled "Learning Speed" stuck near zero, while a large arrow points to the parachuting person labeled "Fast Learning." In the background, include a few cloud puffs against a blue sky. Make the overall style light and whimsical, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke that parachuting is the only thing you learn quickly, while other learning takes more time.'),
 (685, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'Paul''s Law: You can''t fall off the floor.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a character named Paul standing confidently on the floor with a big smile. Paul is inside a simple room with a couch, a small table, and a few framed pictures on the wall to set a cozy home environment. Above Paul’s head is a whimsical thought bubble containing the phrase “Paul’s Law: You can’t fall off the floor.” Around him, a few playful elements emphasize the joke: a pair of shoes lying neatly by the door, a small rug, and perhaps a pet cat lounging calmly on the floor. The style is light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions, especially on Paul’s face, to capture the dry humor of stating something obvious as a ''law.'' No other characters are needed, but the overall tone should feel like a funny, simple everyday observation turned into a mock scientific rule.'),
 (686, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'Picture this: one-way elevators.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon depicting a tall, narrow elevator shaft with two separate glass elevators stacked vertically but facing opposite directions. One elevator is going only up, with a happy person inside pressing the ''Up'' button, and the other elevator below is going only down, with another cheerful person inside pressing the ''Down'' button. The building is shown from the side to emphasize the movement directions. A humorous sign next to the elevator buttons reads ''One-Way Elevators: Choose Your Fate!'' The style is playful and lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions of mild confusion and amusement on the passengers'' faces. The background is simple, perhaps inside an office building lobby with a floor number display next to each elevator shaft. Overall, the cartoon highlights the absurdity of having elevators that work only in a single direction in a whimsical manner.'),
 (687, 'Good Question!, Humor', 'Right-handed people live, on average, nine years longer than left-handed people do.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side-by-side on a timeline labeled ''Average Lifespan.'' On the left, a cheerful, right-handed person with a big smile is happily waving with their right hand, standing around an age marker of, say, 80 years. On the right, a slightly confused left-handed person is standing at a younger age marker, about 9 years less, with a puzzled look and scratching their left head. Above them, a large quirky sign reads, ''Right-handed people live 9 years longer!'' The background is simple with bright colors and playful font. Include details like a clock or calendar pages falling to emphasize time passing, and the characters should be cartoonish and friendly-looking, making the joke light-hearted and funny rather than serious.'),
 (688, 'Good Question!, Humor, Irony, Philosophy Humor', 'Do people who think they know everything really know everything?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing confidently with their arms crossed and a smug smile, wearing glasses and a casual outfit, in the middle of a simple room. Above their head is a big thought bubble filled with a jumbled mix of question marks, exclamation points, and random symbols to represent confusion and uncertainty. Surrounding the person are smaller floating question marks and light bulbs that are turned off, emphasizing doubt. The background is minimalistic with a bookshelf and a small table holding an open book titled ''Everything There Is To Know''. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the irony of someone who thinks they know everything but clearly doesn’t. The cartoon style should be vibrant and exaggerated, with expressive facial features and clean lines to highlight the comedic effect.'),
 (689, 'Good Question!, Humor, Irony, Social Commentary', 'Despite the cost of living, have you noticed how it remains so popular?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a lively, crowded supermarket named ''Cost of Living Mart.'' The entrance has a large, brightly colored sign with the store name. Inside, various shoppers of different ages and backgrounds happily browse aisles overflowing with everyday items like food, toiletries, and household goods. A cash register in the foreground shows an exaggeratedly high total amount, making a shopper gasp in mock surprise while still holding their full shopping basket. Nearby, a store employee gives a thumbs-up with a big smile, implying the store''s popularity despite high prices. The background includes price tags with comically inflated numbers, but the shoppers look cheerful and engaged. The overall style is cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the ironic humor of the cost of living still being ''popular'' or in demand, despite its expense. The tone is lighthearted and playful, with no violence or negativity.'),
 (690, 'Good Question!, Humor, Jobs', 'If you think talk is cheap, try hiring a lawyer.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a lawyer''s office desk looking shocked or surprised while holding a very large invoice or bill marked ''Legal Fees.'' The lawyer, dressed in a suit with a confident smile, is pointing at the bill. Around them, scattered papers, a clock showing time passing quickly, and a speech bubble from the person saying ''Talk is cheap? Try hiring a lawyer!'' make the joke clear. The scene should be bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the punchline, with no aggressive or negative vibes.'),
 (691, 'Good Question!, Humor, Life', 'My life has a superb cast, but I can''t figure out the plot.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing center stage like an actor in a theater. Around them are various caricatured figures representing their ''cast'' — friends, family, coworkers — all dressed in colorful, exaggerated costumes to highlight their distinctive personality traits. The person looks puzzled, scratching their head, holding a large, open script or plot outline that''s completely blank or filled with random question marks. The background suggests a whimsical stage setting with curtains, spotlights, and a cluttered director’s chair nearby. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, with speech bubbles or signs that say things like ''Great cast!'' and ''Where''s the plot?''. The characters and setting are drawn in a lively, cartoon style with exaggerated expressions to emphasize confusion mixed with amusement.'),
 (692, 'Good Question!, Humor, Life', 'Never miss a good chance to shut up.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a cheerful, slightly mischievous-looking character standing with a finger raised as if sharing advice. The character is surrounded by speech bubbles, one bubble contains the phrase: ''Never miss a good chance to shut up.'' In the background, a group of people listens. One person looks surprised, covering their mouth with one hand, trying not to speak, while another looks amused. The setting is a casual environment like a park or a living room, with simple details like a bench or a sofa. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of choosing silence wisely.'),
 (693, 'Good Question!, Humor, Life', 'Never say anything more predictive than ''Watch this!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently with a big grin, pointing at an object or situation about to go wrong. The person is mid-sentence saying, ''Watch this!'' Around them, a chaotic sequence is about to unfold—such as a cake teetering on the edge of a table, a dog eyeing the cake, or something obviously about to result in a funny mishap. The background is a casual living room or kitchen, with exaggerated expressions on onlookers'' faces showing a mix of anticipation and concern. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the irony of the phrase ''Watch this!'' being overly predictive of impending trouble, without showing the actual accident, just the build-up moment.'),
 (694, 'Good Question!, Humor, Life', 'On the keyboard of life, always keep one finger on the escape key.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a large computer keyboard labeled ''Keyboard of Life.'' The keyboard is oversized and colorful, resembling a computer keyboard but with whimsical keys, including a prominent ''Escape'' key glowing or highlighted. A cartoon character, appearing thoughtful but relaxed, is sitting or standing beside the giant keyboard with one finger gently resting on the glowing Escape key. Surrounding the keyboard are simple symbols representing life''s ups and downs, like small clouds, sunshine, a clock, and a heart, to suggest different life situations. The setting is lighthearted and vibrant, with soft pastel colors and exaggerated proportions to enhance the humor and visual appeal. The character should look casual and approachable, emphasizing the metaphor of having an ''escape option'' in life without any stress or negativity.'),
 (695, 'Good Question!, Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Ever stop to think, and forget to start again?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in the middle of a park with a confused and puzzled expression. The person is holding a large, exaggeratedly detailed thought bubble above their head, which contains a swirling spiral representing their thoughts getting lost. Around them are humorous visual clues: a small, forgotten to-do list floating in the air, a clock showing time passing, and a tiny cartoon bird perched on their shoulder looking equally bemused. The background is a simple, friendly park with a bench, a tree, and a winding path that loops back on itself, symbolizing the idea of forgetting to resume thinking. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the lighthearted, relatable nature of the joke.'),
 (696, 'Good Question!, Humor, Military Humor', 'If a stealth bomber crashes in a forest, will it make a sound?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a dense, lively forest with tall trees, bushes, and animals like birds, deer, and squirrels peeking out curiously. In the center, a sleek, black stealth bomber plane is humorously half-crashed into the ground or tangled in the trees, but it looks almost invisible or camouflaged with shadowy or transparent effects to suggest its stealthiness. The animals nearby have exaggerated confused or surprised expressions, some with tilted heads as if wondering if they heard anything. A question bubble floats above the scene asking, ''If a stealth bomber crashes in a forest, will it make a sound?'' The style is lighthearted and colorful, with soft outlines typical of cartoons to keep the tone funny and clean.'),
 (697, 'Good Question!, Humor, Money Humor', 'Real faith is sending the IRS your tax return and two Lotto tickets.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person nervously mailing their tax return envelope at a post office mailbox labeled ''IRS''. The character is a middle-aged individual with raised eyebrows and a hopeful but anxious smile. Peeking out from the envelope are two bright, colorful Lotto tickets alongside the tax return papers. Behind the person, a post office clerk watches with a knowing, slightly amused expression. The background shows a typical post office interior with a ''Tax Season'' sign and a calendar marked April 15. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the mix of anxiety and hope tied to the joke, without any dark or intense elements.'),
 (698, 'Good Question!, Humor, Pessimistic', 'If you must fall on your face, then do it in bed.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of a person tripping and about to fall, but instead of falling onto a hard floor, they land face-first onto a cozy, fluffy bed with a big smile on their face. The bedroom is bright and cheerful, with soft pillows and a warm blanket on the bed. The person has exaggerated surprise and relief on their expression as they gently flop onto the bed. Around them, playful details like a startled alarm clock on the nightstand and a small cat watching curiously add to the lighthearted mood. The cartoon style is simple, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, focusing on the safe ''falling on your face'' scenario in bed rather than a painful one.'),
 (699, 'Good Question!, Humor, Pessimistic, Quotes', 'If you can smile when things go wrong, you have someone in mind to blame.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person (gender-neutral) standing in a cluttered room where a series of small mishaps have just happened: a spilled cup of coffee on the floor, a broken picture frame hanging crookedly on the wall, and a computer screen displaying an error message. The person is smiling slyly, with one hand behind their back holding a finger pointed subtly as if blaming someone else. In the background, a shadowy silhouette of another character (just an outline with a surprised or worried expression) peeks from around a doorway. The overall atmosphere is light-hearted with exaggerated facial expressions. The style should be clean and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon proportions to emphasize the humor in calmly smiling despite chaos.'),
 (700, 'Good Question!, Humor, Philosophy', 'It''s never too late to be early.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person with a big, cheerful smile standing confidently in front of a large, old-fashioned clock that shows an early hour, like 7:00 AM. The person is dressed casually with a sense of pride, maybe wearing a wristwatch as well. Surrounding the character, there''s a subtle background showing a sunrise to reinforce the idea of ''early''. Nearby, a calendar on the wall shows a page being flipped backward or a date in the past, symbolizing ''never too late''. The style is colorful and playful, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the upbeat and optimistic mood of the phrase. The overall tone is lighthearted and motivational, without any complex background elements, focusing on the character and the clock as central objects.'),
 (701, 'Good Question!, Humor, Philosophy', 'It''s not reality that''s important, but how you perceive things.', NULL, 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing in front of two windows. Through the left window, depict a plain, gray rainy day with a frown on the person''s face. Through the right window, show a bright, sunny park with flowers, children playing, and a rainbow, with the person smiling brightly there. The person is holding a large magnifying glass up to the right window, symbolizing ''perception.'' Above their head, floating like a thought bubble, is a small, colorful brain with sparkles around it, emphasizing the idea of mental perspective. The overall style should be light and humorous with exaggerated expressions and bright colors for the positive scene, and duller, muted colors for the negative side. Add a small sign on a wall behind the person that reads: ''Perception is everything,'' to reinforce the joke''s message in a playful way.'),
 (702, 'Good Question!, Humor, Philosophy', 'Originality is the art of concealing your sources.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in an artist''s studio or writer''s workspace. In the center, a person (the artist or writer) sits at a cluttered desk, looking slyly at a canvas or a piece of paper. Surrounding them are several paintings, sketches, or notes pinned on the wall, each styled in very different artistic ways but clearly borrowing elements from famous works or common ideas—a Mona Lisa smile, a famous cartoon character, and a classic storybook image. The person holds up a brush or pen with a cheeky grin, as if proud of their ''original'' work. Nearby, a cartoonish detective character with a magnifying glass peers suspiciously at the artwork, trying to identify the sources. The overall tone is lighthearted, with playful facial expressions and exaggerated cartoon features. Include speech bubbles or a sign that says: "Originality is the art of concealing your sources." The background is a bright, creative workspace with paint tubes, sketchpads, and quotes about creativity pinned to the walls. No violence or inappropriate content.'),
 (703, 'Good Question!, Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'Have you ever imagined a world with no hypothetical situations?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a whimsical, colorful imaginary world. In the foreground, show a thought bubble coming from a puzzled person sitting on a bench, looking confused and scratching their head. The thought bubble contains various quirky, abstract sketches of ''hypothetical situations,'' such as a flying pig, a talking clock, and a dragon riding a bicycle, all crossed out with big red ''X'' marks. Behind the person, depict a dull, gray, and overly plain cityscape symbolizing a world without imagination or hypotheticals—empty streets, identical gray buildings, and no signs of inventive or creative ideas. The overall tone should be lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions and fantasy elements that emphasize the contrast between a lively imaginative world and the dull reality without hypothetical situations. Use bright colors for the imaginative bubble and muted tones for the background to increase the comedic effect.'),
 (704, 'Good Question!, Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'Is sloppiness in speech caused by ignorance or apathy?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting at a small café table outside. One character is a neatly dressed person holding a notepad and pointing thoughtfully as if asking a serious question. The other is a very casual, sloppily dressed person with messy hair, slouched posture, and a casual, indifferent expression, lazily sipping a coffee. Above them, a comic speech bubble displays the question: "Is sloppiness in speech caused by ignorance or apathy?" The café scene has whimsical details like exaggerated coffee cups and a menu board with silly items. The background is a simple city street with a couple of pedestrians looking amused. The art style is colorful and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humorous contrast between the diligent and careless characters.'),
 (640, 'Good Question!, Humor, Photography Humor, Relatable', 'Why do we look so good in a mirror, and yet so lousy in a photograph?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split in half vertically. On the left side, a person stands confidently in front of a large, shiny mirror with a bright smile and perfect posture, admiring their reflection. The reflection looks vibrant, glowing, and very flattering. On the right side, the same person is seated awkwardly in front of an old-fashioned camera on a tripod, with their expression frustrated and slouched, looking displeased at the resulting photograph. The photo on a small easel next to the camera shows a comically exaggerated unflattering image of them with messy hair and a goofy face. The background is simple and cheerful, with soft colors, to keep the focus on the contrast between the two images of the same person. Incorporate lighthearted, exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and irony of how we perceive ourselves differently in mirrors versus photos.'),
 (705, 'Good Question!, Humor, Police Humor, Word Play', 'If the cops arrest a mime, do they tell him he has the right to remain silent?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a city street with a police officer standing next to a mime who is in classic mime attire: white face paint, black beret, striped shirt, suspenders, and white gloves. The mime is in a typical exaggerated ''silent'' pose with hands framing his face or pretending to be inside an invisible box. The police officer is holding a notepad and speaking, with a speech bubble that says, ''You have the right to remain silent!'' The background includes a police car with flashing lights and a few amused onlookers chuckling or pointing. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions on the characters to emphasize the joke''s irony and playful misunderstanding of the mime''s silent nature. No violence or tension, just a funny interaction.'),
 (706, 'Good Question!, Humor, Pop Culture', 'When confronted by a seemingly difficult problem, it is easier solved by reducing it to the question ''How would the Lone Ranger have handled this?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a cluttered desk filled with papers, books, and a complicated-looking problem on a whiteboard behind them. The person scratches their head thoughtfully while imagining a heroic figure dressed as the Lone Ranger, complete with a white cowboy hat, mask, bandana, and horseback, confidently tipping his hat and holding a clever solution note or tool. The background has subtle details like a clock, a coffee mug, and a small toy horse on the desk. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive faces emphasizing the contrast between the overwhelmed problem-solver and the calm, confident Lone Ranger inspiration floating in a thought bubble above.'),
 (580, 'Good Question!, Humor, Pop Culture, Pun', 'What do you call a Jedi with anxiety? P-anakin Skywalker', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a Jedi in traditional robes standing in a classic Star Wars-style desert landscape reminiscent of Tatooine. The Jedi should look visibly anxious and nervous, with wide eyes, shaky hands, and sweat droplets flying off his forehead. Incorporate a speech bubble above his head that says ''P-anakin Skywalker'' in a fun, playful font. Show the Jedi holding a lightsaber with a slightly trembling grip. Around him, add desert elements like twin suns in the sky, sand dunes, and a small moisture farm in the distance. To enhance the humor, include a small thought bubble showing a worried Anakin Skywalker''s face with exaggerated anxiety. Keep the style cartoonish and light-hearted, with bright colors and comical expressions, reflecting a pun linking anxiety to the character Anakin Skywalker from Star Wars.'),
 (707, 'Good Question!, Humor, Pop Culture, Word Play', 'If Barbie''s so popular, why do you have to buy all her friends?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a kid''s bedroom filled with various Barbie dolls. In the center, a slightly confused child is holding a Barbie doll in one hand and a price tag in the other. Surrounding the child are shelves cluttered with many Barbie friends—each doll with different hairstyles, outfits, and accessories. Above the child’s head is a thought bubble showing a big crowd of glamorous Barbie dolls smiling and waving, highlighting Barbie''s ''popularity.'' On a side table, scattered money bills or coins hint at the cost of all the extra dolls. The room should be colorful, playful, and exaggerated to accentuate the child''s baffled expression about why so many friends have to be bought, creating a lighthearted, cartoonish vibe without any negative or violent content.'),
 (708, 'Good Question!, Humor, Puns', 'Whoever invented air conditioning must have been really cool', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a cheerful inventor from the past, wearing old-fashioned clothing and round glasses, standing proudly next to a large, whimsical air conditioning machine. The machine looks a bit exaggerated with big vents blowing out icy cold air, shown with frosty effects and snowflakes. The inventor is surrounded by a few happy, relaxed people cooling off, wearing summer clothes and enjoying the breeze. The background is a sunny outdoor scene with a bright sun and a thermometer showing high temperatures, contrasting with the cold air coming from the machine. The overall tone is lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated, friendly expressions on the characters'' faces to emphasize the joke about the inventor being ''really cool.'''),
 (709, 'Good Question!, Humor, Puns, Steven Wright', 'How do you tell when you''re out of invisible ink?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person holding a pen labeled ''Invisible Ink'' and staring at a completely blank white sheet of paper on a desk. The person is scratching their head in puzzlement, eyebrows raised, with a small question mark above their head. The background is a light, cheerful office or study room with a bookshelf, a cup of coffee, and some colorful stationery scattered around. To emphasize the joke, a faint outline of invisible writing can be shown on the paper, slightly shimmering or glowing to hint that there was supposed to be words but none are visible. The style should be bright, simple, and playful, highlighting the irony that invisible ink leaves no visible trace, and hence it is impossible to tell when it''s empty. No people or expressions should appear frustrated or angry, just lighthearted confusion.'),
 (710, 'Good Question!, Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'Can you buy an entire chess set in a pawn-shop?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a quaint pawn shop with a cluttered interior. In the foreground, show a customer holding up a box labeled ''Chess Set'' looking confused and asking the shopkeeper a funny question. The shopkeeper is behind the counter, slightly amused, wearing a nametag and gesturing toward a display on a shelf. On that shelf, draw oversized chess pawns and other chess pieces scattered around, with some items resembling traditional pawnshop goods like old watches, guitars, or jewelry. To add humor, include a literal pawn piece (from chess) wearing a hat or glasses to anthropomorphize it playfully. The setting should feel lighthearted with warm colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing the pun on ''pawn'' meaning both the chess piece and the pawn shop. Overall, keep the style whimsical and friendly without any harsh lines or dark elements.'),
 (648, 'Good Question!, Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'Why is it called lipstick if you can still move your lips?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a mirror applying bright red lipstick. The person has exaggeratedly large, animated lips that are clearly moving as they speak or smile. The mirror reflects their cheeky expression with lips in mid-motion. On the vanity table are scattered typical makeup items like lipstick tubes, brushes, and a compact mirror. A small speech bubble above the character reads the joke, "Why is it called lipstick if you can still move your lips?" The style is lighthearted and colorful, with playful line work emphasizing the lips and the motion, creating a fun and silly visual pun about the name "lipstick."'),
 (711, 'Good Question!, Humor, Puns, Workplace', 'Do cemetery workers prefer the graveyard shift?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a spooky but lighthearted cemetery at nighttime. In the foreground, two cemetery workers dressed in typical work clothes (reflective vests, work boots, and hats) stand near an open grave holding shovels. One worker looks tired, yawning and holding a coffee mug labeled ''Graveyard Shift.'' The other points to a nearby clock on a tombstone, showing a late night hour (around midnight). In the background, tombstones, trees, and a softly glowing full moon create a classic graveyard atmosphere. To add humor, a friendly ghost floats nearby, wearing a nightcap and holding a sign that says ''Welcome to the graveyard shift!'' The overall style is a lighthearted, colorful cartoon with exaggerated expressions on the workers'' faces to emphasize the pun on ''graveyard shift.'' No scary or scary elements, just a funny play on words in a whimsical setting.'),
 (615, 'Good Question!, Humor, Relatable', 'When was the last time you woke up from a nightmare laughing?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person waking up in bed with a big, surprised grin on their face. The room is cozy and softly lit by morning light coming through a window. The person is sitting up in bed, covers partly pulled down, with wide eyes and an open mouth laughing. Above their head, comic-style thought bubbles show a nightmarish scene that is actually funny—such as a silly monster slipping on a banana peel or a ghost tangled in bed sheets. The bed has a headboard and a pillow slightly askew. Beside the bed on a nightstand is an alarm clock showing early morning. The overall mood contrasts typical fear and funny surprise, emphasizing the unusual feeling of laughing right after a nightmare. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing exaggerated expressions and lively colors, with a gentle, cozy bedroom setting.'),
 (569, 'Good Question!, Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'Weekend, where are you?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a cluttered office desk looking tired and wistful. The person is glancing longingly out a window where the sun is shining brightly, symbolizing the weekend. Above their head is a thought bubble with the words ''Weekend, where are you?'' in playful, bold letters. On the desk are typical work items like a computer, papers, a coffee mug, and a calendar showing the days of the week, with the weekend days circled or highlighted but far away from the current day. The office environment looks dull and gray, contrasting with the bright, colorful outdoors seen through the window. The person’s expression and body language clearly convey impatience and longing. The artwork style is a light, cheerful cartoon, with exaggerated facial expressions to add humor and relatability without any negative or inappropriate content.'),
 (712, 'Good Question!, Humor, Science', 'If people evolved from monkeys, why are monkeys still around?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused human standing next to a monkey. The human looks puzzled scratching their head, wearing casual modern clothes. The monkey, sitting on a tree branch nearby, looks at the human with a raised eyebrow as if saying, ''Why are you asking me?'' In the background, there is a lush jungle setting with several other monkeys playing around or curiously observing the conversation. Above the human and monkey, a speech bubble contains the joke question: ''If people evolved from monkeys, why are monkeys still around?'' The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon features and bright colors to add humor and charm.'),
 (713, 'Good Question!, Humor, Science', 'The moon may be smaller than Earth, but it''s further away.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the Earth and the Moon personified as characters in a playful distance competition. Earth is drawn as a large, round, blue-and-green globe with a smug, confident face and arms crossed. The Moon is smaller, gray with crater features, looking slightly annoyed but determined, standing farther away on the right side of the image. Between them is a simple horizontal distance scale or measuring tape stretching across the scene, emphasizing the Moon is farther away. The background is a starry dark space with a whimsical feel. Both characters have exaggerated, friendly cartoon facial expressions to highlight the joke''s lighthearted nature. Include a small sign or speech bubble near Earth saying, "I’m bigger," and near the Moon "But I’m farther away!" The style should be clean, vibrant cartoon with bold outlines, making the concept clear and funny without any aggressive or intense elements.'),
 (714, 'Good Question!, Humor, Science', 'The reason lightning doesn''t strike twice in the same place is that the same place isn''t there the second time.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small patch of ground after a lightning strike; the first panel depicts a cartoon lightning bolt striking a particular spot on a grassy field with a surprised expression on a nearby animal, such as a squirrel. The second panel shows the same spot but comically shifted and transformed—a tree fallen, a crater formed, or ground visibly moved—indicating the original spot is no longer there. Above the panels, include a whimsical caption or thought bubble with the joke text. The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the playful impossibility of the ''same place'' existing twice due to the effects of the strike itself.'),
 (715, 'Good Question!, Humor, Science, Word Play', 'How is mercury a liquid at room temperature, yet a large solid when orbiting close to the sun?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon split scene with two panels side by side. On the left, show a small, shiny mercury thermometer personified as a quirky liquid character, lounging casually in a cozy living room labeled ''Room Temperature.'' The mercury liquid character should appear relaxed, maybe with sunglasses and a drink, sitting on a couch shaped like a thermometer. On the right panel, depict the planet Mercury near a blazing sun, but humorously exaggerated as a big, solid block of ice or a heavy ice cube wearing a sun hat and sweating nervously from the intense heat, standing on a small rocky terrain labeled ''Orbiting Close to the Sun.'' Add some humor by showing the sun frowning or looking puzzled at this paradox. The overall tone is light and funny, in a colorful, simple cartoon style with exaggerated facial expressions on both characters and objects to capture the joke about mercury''s different states in two contexts: the element and the planet.'),
 (716, 'Good Question!, Humor, Time Humor', 'Did you know that the next second is really only a second away?  OOPS - you missed it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a large, playful clock with a surprised face looking at its own ticking second hand. The second hand is just moving past the number one, symbolizing the next second that has just passed. Nearby, a cheerful character with wide eyes and an open mouth, as if they just realized something, looks slightly confused or shocked, pointing at the clock. The background is simple and colorful with floating, whimsical numbers around to emphasize the concept of time passing quickly. Include little motion lines around the second hand to show it just moved. The style should be lighthearted and funny, suitable for all ages, with no complex or abstract elements.'),
 (717, 'Good Question!, Humor, Travel Humor', 'The San Francisco Cable cars are the only mobile National Monuments.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classic San Francisco cable car climbing a steep hill in the city. The cable car is drawn with exaggerated features, such as a proud, smiling face on its front, and wearing a small, cartoonish statue-like pedestal underneath it as if it is a monument. Around the cable car, tourists are taking photos and looking amazed, some with cameras and phones. In the background, iconic San Francisco landmarks like the Golden Gate Bridge and downtown skyscrapers are visible. A signpost near the cable car reads ''National Monument'' with an arrow pointing to the cable car. The overall art style is lighthearted and colorful, with playful expressions on the characters and a bright, sunny day to emphasize the joke about the cable car being a ''mobile'' monument.'),
 (718, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'Can you be a closet claustrophobic?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person trying to squeeze into a small, overcrowded closet filled with clothes, boxes, and shoes. The person looks visibly uncomfortable, sweating and slightly panicked, with wide eyes and a nervous expression. The closet door is half-closed, just barely fitting the person inside. Around the closet, a neat bedroom background is visible to emphasize the contrast between the open space outside and the cramped space inside. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated expressions and simple, bright colors to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (719, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'Ever walk into a room full of mind readers playing charades?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room where a group of people are playing charades. The room has a round coffee table strewn with game cards and snacks. Around the table, multiple characters look confused and surprised, scratching their heads or wide-eyed, as if caught off guard by the game. One person is miming dramatically, while another nearby looks like they’re reading minds, with cartoon-style glowing eyes or a lightbulb above their head. A third character is holding their forehead as if struggling, and the background shows a playful atmosphere with a game scoreboard on the wall. The overall vibe is light, fun, with exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing the irony of mind readers playing a guessing game where reading minds would give an unfair advantage.'),
 (720, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'How can there be self-help ''groups''?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a small group of people sitting in a circle for a self-help meeting. Each person looks confused or puzzled, scratching their heads or shrugging. There is a large banner behind them that reads ''Self-Help Group'' with quotation marks around ''Help'' to hint at irony. In the center, one person raises their hand as if asking the question, ''How can there be self-help "groups"?'' The room is simple, with chairs arranged in a circle, a small table with a box of tissues, and a calming plant in the corner. The characters have exaggerated cartoon expressions of bewilderment. The style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the confusion around the oxymoron of a ''self-help group.'' No dark or serious tones.'),
 (721, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'How do you get off a non-stop flight?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a commercial airplane cabin. The airplane is shown mid-flight with clouds and sky visible through small oval windows. At the center aisle, a frustrated passenger is standing up, wearing casual clothes and looking confused or worried, as if trying to figure out how to get off the plane despite the flight being non-stop. Other passengers sit in their seats around them, some looking amused or puzzled. The flight attendant nearby is shaking their head or shrugging with a friendly smile, indicating that getting off isn''t possible yet. The airplane''s cabin should have typical details like overhead bins, seatbacks with tray tables, and the aisle carpet. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor of trying to exit a non-stop plane mid-flight, an obviously impossible task. No violent or inappropriate elements, just a funny visual of the literal interpretation of the joke question.'),
 (722, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'How many of you believe in telekinesis? Raise my hands...', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a casual setting, such as a small auditorium or classroom. A quirky, slightly nerdy character stands at the front, facing an audience of diverse people sitting in chairs. The character has a half-serious, half-smiling expression and is holding up both their own hands. The audience members, puzzled and looking around at each other, have their hands down, clearly not raising anyone else''s hands. To exaggerate the joke, a few people''s hands are awkwardly mid-air, but not coordinated, and some are just staring at the speaker. The setting includes details like a whiteboard behind the speaker with the words “Telekinesis Survey” written at the top. The tone is light and goofy, with exaggerated facial expressions showing confusion and mild amusement. Include playful speech bubbles: from the speaker saying “Raise my hands...” and from an audience member expressing bewilderment. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and simple, emphasizing the absurdity of expecting the audience to physically raise the speaker’s hands telekinetically.'),
 (723, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'If a book about failures doesn''t sell, is it a success?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bookstore with a large, prominently displayed book titled ''Failures'' on a stand. The book has a sad face drawn on its cover to personify failure. Around the stand, there are very few people, and the books have visible price tags with a downward arrow indicating poor sales. A cartoonish salesman or store clerk scratching their head with a puzzled expression while holding a sales report showing zero sales. Nearby, a big sign reads ''Bestseller?'' with a question mark, emphasizing the irony. The background is colorful and cheerful, contrasting with the pun in the joke. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions on the characters and the book to highlight the irony of the joke.'),
 (724, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'If you can''t drink and drive, why do bars have parking lots?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outside a lively bar with a bright neon sign reading ''The Tipsy Tavern.'' The bar has a large parking lot visible in the foreground, filled with various cars parked neatly. A few comical characters stand around: one looking puzzled, scratching their head, wearing casual clothes and holding a drink with a funny expression as if questioning the situation. Another character, a bartender inside, leans close to the open door and grins knowingly, holding a cocktail shaker. The scene highlights the irony: the parking lot is clearly meant for patrons, but the question about drinking and driving contrasts with it humorously. Include some whimsical details like a ''No Drinking & Driving'' sign near the parking lot entrance that seems slightly overlooked. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful with exaggerated cartoon features—big eyes, expressive faces, and vibrant colors—to emphasize the joke''s irony without any violent or inappropriate content.'),
 (725, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'Is it ethical to yell ''Movie!'' in a crowded firehouse?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a busy firehouse. Several firefighters wearing classic yellow firefighter uniforms and helmets are standing around inside a big garage filled with firefighting gear: hoses, axes, helmets on hooks, and a big red fire truck parked to the side. One firefighter stands in the middle with a surprised and confused expression, holding a megaphone and shouting ''Movie!'' loudly. Around him, other firefighters look startled or puzzled, some covering their ears or looking toward the shouting firefighter. The firehouse sign or wall clock is visible to set the indoor scene. The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated with cartoonish expressions to emphasize the humor and absurdity of yelling ''Movie!'' in a firehouse, playing on the double meaning of ''movie'' and ''move.'' No violence or danger should be depicted, keeping the joke lighthearted and silly.'),
 (726, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'Is the glass half empty, half full, or twice as large as it needs to be?', NULL, 'A cartoon scene featuring a large, exaggerated glass of water sitting on a simple table. The glass is clearly filled to the halfway point. Next to the glass, a cheerful, curious person with a questioning expression is scratching their head and looking at the glass. Above the glass, three floating cartoon thought bubbles show: one with a sad face and a half-empty glass, one with a happy face and a half-full glass, and one with a funny image of the same glass but comically oversized, dwarfing the person. The style is lighthearted and colorful with simple lines emphasizing the humor. The setting is minimalist with no distracting background, focusing on the glass, the person, and the thought bubbles to highlight the joke''s wordplay about perspective and size.'),
 (727, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'Is there an imaginary cure for hypochondria?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, slightly worried-looking character sitting in a cozy living room. The character is holding a huge, colorful book titled ''Imaginary Cures for Real Problems.'' Around them, floating in cartoonish thought bubbles, are playful, imaginary medicine bottles labeled with funny, made-up names like ''Placebo Potion'' and ''Fictional Fix.'' The character has wide eyes and an exaggerated questioning expression, scratching their head as if deeply puzzled. In the background, a wall calendar marks the date, and a small, cute pet (like a dog or cat) looks on curiously. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, illustrating the mental image of pondering an imaginary cure for hypochondria without any negativity or seriousness. The art style should be simple, colorful, and cartoony, with clear, exaggerated facial expressions and props to enhance the joke’s playful mood.'),
 (728, 'Good Question!, Humor, Word Play', 'The average person has one ovary and one testicle.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a diverse group of people standing in a line, each showing a comical, exaggerated body outline that highlights their reproductive organs. For each person, show one ovary clearly marked on one side and one testicle on the opposite side, like a quirky anatomy diagram. People should look puzzled or confused, glancing down at their own outline with exaggerated expressions. The background is simple, such as a friendly doctor''s office or classroom setting, with a large chart behind them titled ''Average Human Reproductive Organs'' showing one ovary and one testicle humorously circled. Use bright, cheerful colors and rounded shapes to keep it light and funny. Avoid any detailed or realistic anatomy; keep all features cartoonishly simplified and exaggerated for comedic effect. No violence or sensitive imagery, just fun confusion around a silly, false ''fact.'''),
 (729, 'Good Question!, Humor, Workplace', 'In case of fire, flee with the same reckless abandon that occurs each day at quitting time.', NULL, 'A busy office scene at quitting time depicted in a humorous cartoon style. Show a group of employees rushing out of the office door all at once with exaggerated expressions of excitement and urgency. Some people are half-running, others are leaping over desks or knocking over chairs. Papers and coffee mugs fly in the air to emphasize chaos. Near the door, a fire alarm is ringing with bright red lights flashing, and smoke is starting to appear coming from a small, harmless-looking fire in a trash bin. The scene should capture the similarity between the frantic quitting-time rush and an emergency fire escape, with an amusing and lighthearted tone. Include typical office elements like desks, computers, swivel chairs, and water coolers to set the workplace context.'),
 (730, 'Good Question!, Humor, Workplace', 'One person''s error is another person''s data.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two office coworkers at their desks, each looking at a computer screen. One person, appearing slightly frustrated, points at their screen showing a glaring mistake labeled ''ERROR!'' in big red letters. The second coworker, wearing glasses and looking amused, is holding a magnifying glass over what the first person calls an error, but on their screen it’s highlighted and labeled ''DATA!'' as if it''s a valuable find. The setting should be a light-hearted office with cubicles, desks cluttered with papers, coffee mugs, and office plants. The background can have a whiteboard with quirky graphs and charts to set the work vibe. The overall tone is playful and non-threatening, emphasizing the contrast in how the same information can be viewed differently as a mistake or useful data.'),
 (731, 'Good Question!, Humor, Workplace', 'Proof: you''re always losing paper clips, and there are always more coat hangers than expected in the closet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cluttered office closet. On the left side, a tired office worker is searching frantically through a pile of scattered paper clips on the floor and inside a small open box labeled ''Paper Clips'', looking puzzled and slightly frustrated. To the right, the closet rack is overloaded with many clothes hangers, some tangled and spilling over, far more than what would be expected for the number of coats present. The worker wears office attire, and above them, a small caption or thought bubble reads: ''Proof: Always losing paper clips and too many coat hangers.'' The overall vibe is lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the chaotic abundance of coat hangers and the mysterious disappearance of paper clips, with bright colors and simple cartoon lines to enhance the humor.'),
 (624, 'Good Question!, Irony, Life, Relatable', 'Why can''t life''s big problems come when we are twenty and know everything ?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident 20-year-old person standing proudly with a big grin, wearing casual clothes like a T-shirt and jeans, hands on hips, radiating an aura of ''knowing everything.'' On the right side of the image stands an older adult, looking tired and worried, dressed in work or casual clothing, holding a stack of papers labeled ''Life''s Big Problems.'' Over the head of the 20-year-old is a shiny lightbulb symbolizing overconfidence. Behind the older adult, shadowy, exaggeratedly large, menacing symbols that represent major life problems—such as bills, work stress icons, relationship troubles (like a broken heart), and a clock showing late hours—loom in the background. The setting is a simple, generic room with a wall clock and a calendar showing the current date. The cartoon style is light-hearted with expressive faces and exaggerated expressions to emphasize youthful arrogance vs. adult challenges. The overall mood is playful and ironic, visually highlighting the humor in the contrast between youthful certainty and adult reality.'),
 (610, 'Good Question!, Jobs, Puns, Word Play', 'What''s the difference between a jeweler and a jailer? One sells watches and one watches cells', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters side by side. On the left, a cheerful jeweler behind a glass display case filled with shiny watches and jewelry. He wears a magnifying loupe on one eye and holds a sparkling watch, smiling proudly. On the right, a stern jailer standing next to a prison cell door with metal bars, holding a large set of keys and peering inside the cell. The jailer wears a classic uniform with a badge and a hat. Above them, a playful sign reads ''Jeweler'' on the left and ''Jailer'' on the right. The background should be simple and bright, emphasizing the contrast between the two professions. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated features and cheerful expressions to highlight the pun between ''watches'' and ''watching cells.'' No violent or negative elements—focus on the wordplay humor.'),
 (732, 'Good Question!, Language, Objects Humor', 'If tin whistles are made out of tin, what do they make fog horns out of?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing by the water''s edge on a misty day. One character is holding a shiny tin whistle and looking curiously at it. The other character is pointing towards a giant foghorn mounted on a pier or dock, which is emitting visible, thick fog clouds shaped like waves or musical notes. The background shows a soft, foggy atmosphere with water and a few distant boats barely visible through the fog. Both characters have exaggerated puzzled or amused expressions. Include a playful detail like a musical note floating from the tin whistle and a larger, comical sound wave or cartoon-style fog puff coming out of the fog horn. The art style is colorful, light-hearted, and cartoonish with clean lines and simple shapes to emphasize the joke without any harsh or realistic details.'),
 (602, 'Good Question!, Language, Pun, Word Play', 'What''s another word for thesaurus?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk with a big open book titled ''Thesaurus'' in front of them. The person looks puzzled, scratching their head with a pen in hand. Above their head is a thought bubble containing a jumble of synonyms flying around, but none of them making sense—some words are crossed out or fading away. Nearby on the desk is a dictionary and a speech bubble from the book saying, "What''s another word for thesaurus?" to add a playful paradox. The background is a cozy room with a bookshelf full of various books and a quirky pet, like a cat, looking equally confused. The entire scene is drawn in a lighthearted, cartoonish style with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s ironic question about synonyms and words themselves.'),
 (620, 'Good Question!, Language, Pun, Word Play', 'Which letter is silent in the word Scent - the S or the C?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon style drawing of a large, colorful dictionary book opened to the word ''Scent''. The letters ''S'' and ''C'' are exaggerated and animated, each with expressive faces looking at each other suspiciously or quizzically. The letter ''S'' appears calm and smug, while the letter ''C'' looks confused and shy. A thought bubble above them shows the question: ''Which letter is silent in "Scent" - the S or the C?'' The background is a simple indoor setting, like a cozy study with a desk, lamp, and a steaming cup of tea nearby. The overall tone is light and playful, with bright colors and soft lines that emphasize the silly debate between the letters.'),
 (652, 'Good Question!, Language, Puns, Word Play', 'Why is the letter W called double U? Shouldn''t it be called double V?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two anthropomorphic letters: a large blue uppercase ''W'' and two smaller purple uppercase ''V''s standing side by side. The ''W'' has a puzzled facial expression with raised eyebrows and a question mark above its head. The two ''V''s are next to each other, looking confident and slightly smug, as if making a point. They are on a simple white background with a playful caption above them reading: ''Why is W called double U? Shouldn’t it be double V?'' The letters have arms and legs, with simple cartoon gloves and shoes. The style is colorful and exaggerated, reminiscent of classic animated letter characters, emphasizing the humor of the letter shape and name confusion. No additional objects or background elements are needed to keep focus on the letters and the joke.'),
 (733, 'Good Question!, Life', 'It is the climbing of the mountain that makes the view from the top so breathtaking.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful hiker standing at the peak of a tall mountain. The hiker is wearing classic climbing gear: a bright colored jacket, a backpack, and hiking boots. The background features a panoramic view of distant snow-capped mountains and a clear blue sky with a shining sun. The hiker is catching their breath, looking slightly exhausted but happy, with a big smile. Nearby, there is a signpost that reads ''Mount Breathtaking Peak.'' A playful detail could be a pair of binoculars hanging off their neck and some small clouds drifting below the mountain peak to exaggerate the height. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the triumph and joy of the climb without any complex or serious elements.'),
 (734, 'Good Question!, Life, Philosophy', 'Measuring wealth: count the things that you have for which you would not accept money.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing next to a large, overflowing treasure chest filled not only with traditional riches like gold coins and jewels but also with everyday meaningful items. The person is holding up a photo album, a pet cat sitting beside them, a family portrait, and a blooming flower, all sparkling or glowing slightly to highlight their value. Around the chest, various objects like a handmade gift, a favorite book, and a pair of worn-out but treasured shoes are visible. The background is bright and whimsical, with floating dollar signs crossed out or with a red ''no'' symbol over them, emphasizing that these items can''t be bought. The overall tone is lighthearted and warm, celebrating sentimental value over money in a playful cartoon style.'),
 (735, 'Good Question!, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'Water is never truly yours - it’s just your turn to drink it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing next to a large, clear water dispenser or water cooler with a big label that reads ''Water.'' The person is holding a glass of water and grinning broadly, as if proudly claiming the water. Around them, a subtle flow of water continues downstream or around a curved water pipe, visually indicating that the water is constantly moving or flowing elsewhere. In the background or as a small thought bubble above the person''s head, depict a clock or a line of people waiting to have their turn, suggesting the water is shared and only momentarily theirs. The style should be colorful and light-hearted, with exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the joke’s theme that water is never permanently owned but just temporarily used. Include some simple elements like a river, a faucet dripping, or other containers to reinforce the idea of water''s ongoing flow and shared nature.'),
 (736, 'Good Question!, Music Humor', 'Rule Of Thumb: Tuning A Musical Instrument: A stringed instrument is less apt to slip out of pitch if the strings are tuned up from flat than it is if the strings are tuned down from sharp.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a stringed musical instrument, such as a violin or guitar, with exaggerated facial features showing it ''worrying'' or ''relaxing.'' One side shows the strings being tuned up from flat with an enthusiastic character confidently tightening tuning pegs, and the instrument smiling or looking stable. On the other side, show strings being tuned down from sharp, with a nervous or stressed character carefully loosening tuning pegs, and the instrument looking shaky or about to ''slip.'' Include musical notes floating around to emphasize tuning, and a cartoon-style hand with a thumb prominently pointing upwards near the ''tuned up'' side to play on the ''rule of thumb.'' The background is a cozy music room or stage, with humorous small details like a metronome bobbing worriedly and a tuner device displaying tuning status. Keep the style light, colorful, and playful with simple, exaggerated expressions and clear visual cues about tuning direction and the ''rule of thumb.'''),
 (579, 'Good Question!, Objects Humor, Puns', 'What do you call a boomerang that doesn''t come back to you?  A stick', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters outdoors on a sunny day. One character is holding a boomerang and looking confused while staring at a plain wooden stick lying on the ground a few feet away. The stick should be clearly simple and unremarkable, contrasting with the typical curved shape of a boomerang visible in the other character''s hand or on their shoulder. The background shows a park or backyard setting with green grass, a tree or two, and a clear blue sky. The characters should be drawn with exaggerated puzzled expressions to emphasize the joke''s punchline about the ''boomerang that doesn''t come back.'' No violence or offense, just lighthearted confusion and fun.'),
 (737, 'Good Question!, Pessimistic, Politics, Quotes', 'If voting changed anything, they''d make it illegal.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused and skeptical voter standing in front of a voting booth. The voter is scratching their head while holding a ballot paper with a big red ''X'' on it. Behind the booth, there''s a large, exaggerated government official or politician sneaking away with a mischievous smirk, holding a rulebook labeled ''Laws'' with a page flipped open to ''Make Voting Illegal.'' In the background, a large sign hangs above the voting area that says, ''Voting Day,'' but it looks slightly crooked or worn out. The style is bright and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the irony and cynicism of the joke. No violence or aggression, just playful cynicism portrayed in a friendly way.'),
 (738, 'Good Question!, Philosophy', 'Integrity has no need for rules.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cartoon character standing confidently with a bright, glowing aura labeled ''Integrity'' around them. The character is in a simple room with a large, old-fashioned book titled ''Rules'' sitting closed on a table nearby. The character is ignoring the book, perhaps with a relaxed smile or a knowing wink. You can show a few floating symbols representing rules (like stop signs, lines, or do-not symbols) around the book, but they are comically deflated or floating away. The background should be light and cheerful with simple geometric shapes and pastel colors to keep it lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the idea that the character doesn’t need these symbols or rules to guide them. The style should be cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and clean lines to highlight the humor in the phrase ''Integrity has no need for rules.'''),
 (739, 'Good Question!, Philosophy', 'It is better to light a candle than to curse the darkness.', NULL, 'A bright and simple cartoon scene featuring a person standing in a small dark room with a gloomy atmosphere. The person is holding a lit candle that casts a warm, glowing light around them, pushing back the surrounding darkness which looks like creeping shadows or a black mist retreating. The person has a calm, hopeful expression and wears casual, approachable clothing. In one corner of the room, there is an unlit candle lying on the floor, symbolizing missed chances. The cartoon style should be colorful but not overly detailed, with exaggerated light contrast between the candle''s glow and the darkness, emphasizing the hopeful message. The background is minimal and uncluttered to keep the focus on the candle and the darkness. A faint smiling face could be imagined in the candle’s flame for an added touch of warmth and humor.'),
 (740, 'Good Question!, Philosophy Humor', 'The facts, although interesting, are irrelevant.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or lecture hall. In the center, a bored or unimpressed student with exaggeratedly crossed arms and a skeptical expression sits at a desk piled with books and papers labeled ''Facts.'' The teacher or lecturer at the front gestures towards a large blackboard filled with numerous detailed facts and scientific formulas written in neat handwriting. Around the student, funny little visual icons like question marks or an eye-roll symbol show disinterest. The overall style should be bright and colorful with clean lines and expressive, exaggerated facial features that highlight boredom and irrelevance. No violent or sensitive elements—just a lighthearted critique of how sometimes knowing facts doesn’t impact the bigger picture.'),
 (741, 'Good Question!, Philosophy Humor, Steven Wright', 'OK, so what''s the speed of dark?', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon scene showing a curious person, looking puzzled while holding a speedometer. The person should be standing in a dark room where one side is fully illuminated and the other side is completely dark. The speedometer''s needle is spinning wildly as if trying to measure something invisible. Include a thought bubble above the person''s head that says, ''OK, so what''s the speed of dark?''. The style should be lighthearted and whimsical with bright colors on the lit side and deep blues or blacks on the dark side, emphasizing the humorous confusion over an impossible concept.'),
 (742, 'Good Question!, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'Does killing time damage eternity?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a giant hourglass labeled ''Time'' with some grains of sand personified as little characters inside. One tiny character is holding a pickaxe, chipping away at the sand inside the hourglass as if ''killing time.'' Outside the hourglass, a relaxed and slightly confused-looking figure representing ''Eternity'' is standing or floating with an exaggeratedly calm expression, unaffected, surrounded by an infinite starry sky or a never-ending looping symbol (like an infinity sign). The setting is surreal and playful, emphasizing the absurd idea of harming something infinite by messing with something finite, with bright colors and simple, exaggerated shapes to enhance the cartoon effect. No violence, just whimsical interaction between time and eternity.'),
 (743, 'Good Question!, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'If you try to fail, and succeed, which have you done?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing at a crossroad with two signposts labeled ''Fail'' pointing left and ''Succeed'' pointing right. The person is scratching their head in puzzlement while holding a large oversized checklist titled ''Try to Fail.'' Behind them is a smiling thought bubble with a trophy, and behind the other side a broken pencil on the ground. The background is bright and cheerful with a few simple trees and clouds. The art style is playful and exaggerated to emphasize the person''s bewilderment at the paradox of trying to fail but succeeding.'),
 (744, 'Good Question!, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'Is it possible to be totally partial?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a crossroads labeled with two opposing signs: one saying ''Totally'' and the other saying ''Partial.'' The character looks confused and puzzled, scratching their head and with exaggerated wide eyes. Behind them, a thought bubble shows a silly imaginary scale balancing ''Total'' on one side and ''Partial'' on the other, teetering humorously. Include bright colors and simple, playful lines to emphasize the joke''s philosophical wordplay. Avoid any text beyond the signs and the thought bubble symbols. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, focusing on the play on words around ''totally'' and ''partial.'''),
 (581, 'Good Question!, Pun', 'What do you call a woman with one leg?  Eileen', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a confident woman standing on one leg, playfully balancing. She should have a big smile and be wearing casual, colorful clothes. Beside her, show a playful pun written in a speech bubble or caption that says, ''What do you call a woman with one leg? Eileen.'' The background should be simple, like a park or a plain color, to keep focus on the character and the joke. The atmosphere is light and cheerful, emphasizing the wordplay without any negative or insensitive elements.'),
 (655, 'Good Question!, Pun, Word Play', 'Why is the word abbreviation so long?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large dictionary open on a table with the word "abbreviation" highlighted in big, bold letters taking up most of a dictionary page. Next to the dictionary is a confused cartoon character scratching their head while looking at the long word. Above the character''s head is a thought bubble showing the irony of the word "abbreviation" being so long, perhaps with the word spelled out in an exaggeratedly long way. The setting is lighthearted, with bright colors, exaggerated expressions, and a simple background to emphasize the joke.'),
 (745, 'Good Question!, Puns, Science', 'Does the name Pavlov ring a bell?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a man standing next to a large bell. The man looks thoughtful and slightly confused, scratching his head. Behind him is a simple classroom or laboratory setting with a chalkboard that has a simple drawing of a dog and a bell, referencing Pavlov''s classical conditioning experiment. The bell is large, shiny, and prominently displayed to emphasize the pun. Include a small, happy cartoon dog sitting nearby, looking expectantly at the bell. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to convey the pun''s humor visually.'),
 (746, 'Good Question!, Puns, Science, Space Humor', 'How does NASA organize a party? They planet', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene depicting an outer space party organized by NASA. In the foreground, a friendly astronaut stands next to a large, round table shaped like a planet with rings, resembling Saturn. The table is decorated with party items like cups, snacks, balloons, and a banner that says ''Party Time!'' floating in zero gravity. Around the table are small planets with faces, wearing party hats and holding tiny cups, as if attending the party. In the background, a rocket ship with NASA logos hovers and emits festive lights and confetti. Stars and other celestial bodies sparkle against a dark space backdrop. The astronaut holds a clipboard labeled ''Plan-et Party Checklist'' with a checklist showing checkmarks. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright, cheerful colors emphasizing the pun on ''planet'' and ''plan it.'''),
 (572, 'Good Question!, Puns, Sports Humor', 'What can you serve but you can never eat?  A pickle ball!', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a cheerful kitchen or dining room where a smiling person is presenting a pickleball on a fancy serving tray as if it were food. The pickleball should be bright yellow-green with small holes, clearly resembling the sport''s ball. The person is dressed in casual clothes and stands by a table that has typical serving items like plates, utensils, and maybe a napkin. In the background, a confused pet or a hungry-looking cartoon character is sitting nearby, eyeing the pickleball suspiciously as if expecting to eat it. Use exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize humor, such as the person’s proud smile and the pet’s puzzled or disappointed look. The style should be light-hearted and colorful, suitable for a general audience, with no violence or suggestiveness.'),
 (747, 'Good Question!, Puns, Word Play, Workplace', 'If a train station is where the train stops, what is a work station?', NULL, 'A colorful, funny cartoon scene showing two contrasting ''stations'' side by side. On the left, a classic train station with a cartoon train stopped at the platform, steam puffing and a big station sign saying ''Train Station.'' On the right, a humorous take on a ''work station'' — a cluttered office desk with a computer, keyboard, coffee mug, papers, and an overwhelmed, tired-looking cartoon person sitting in an office chair, surrounded by piles of documents and sticky notes, maybe with a clock showing late hours. The office space should look busy and chaotic, contrasting with the calm train platform. Both scenes are connected by an imaginary dotted line to emphasize the wordplay between ''train station'' and ''work station.'' Style: cheerful, bright colors, exaggerated expressions, friendly and lighthearted cartoon style.'),
 (748, 'Good Question!, Quotes', 'If you tell the truth, you don''t have to remember anything.', NULL, 'A simple humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk with a thought bubble above their head. Inside the bubble, there are two contrasting images: on one side, a tangled, complicated web of different storylines symbolizing lies and confusion, with question marks and sticky notes; on the other side, a clear, straight path labeled ''Truth'' leading to a relaxed, smiling brain wearing glasses, indicating ease and clarity. The person at the desk looks relaxed and confident, smiling as they point at the clear path in the thought bubble. The background is minimal, focusing attention on the thought bubble and the character''s expression, with light pastel colors to keep it friendly and playful.'),
 (641, 'Good Question!, Relatable Humor, Sports Humor, Word Play', 'Why do we sing ''Take me out to the ball game ''when we are already there?', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene set inside a lively baseball stadium filled with cheerful fans. In the foreground, a group of people are sitting in the stands holding snacks like popcorn and baseball gloves, clearly at a baseball game. Some fans are standing and singing enthusiastically with smiling, animated faces, mouths wide open as musical notes float above their heads. A scoreboard in the background displays the game progress, adding context that they are indeed watching the game live. The atmosphere is fun and light-hearted, capturing the humorous irony that everyone is ''singing'' about going to the game when they are already there. Include some small details like a hotdog stand, flags, and a mascot somewhere visible to give the setting an authentic ballpark vibe. The characters should be diverse in age and gender, drawn in a playful, exaggerated cartoon style emphasizing their joy and the silly contradiction of the song lyrics.'),
 (749, 'Good Question!, Religion Humor, Word Play', 'If Catholics only have mass on Sundays, do they cease to exist the rest of the week?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a puzzled person standing outside a church on a sunny weekday. The church is clearly marked with a big sign reading ''Catholic Church'' and a schedule board that shows ''Mass: Sundays only.'' The person is scratching their head with a confused expression, looking down at their smartphone that displays a calendar with all days except Sunday marked as ''No Mass.'' To add humor, a ghost-like transparent figure representing the church''s ''existence'' is shown faintly fading away outside the church during the other days of the week. The style is light-hearted and cartoony, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s play on existence and weekly mass timing. The background shows common weekday elements like people walking dogs, cars driving by, and a calendar floating above the character''s head to highlight the concept of time passing during the week.'),
 (750, 'Good Question!, School, Word Play', 'The name of all the continents end with the same letter that they start with.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly, slightly puzzled teacher standing in front of a classroom blackboard. On the blackboard are the names of the continents: Africa, Asia, Europe, Antarctica, Australia, South America, and North America. The teacher is pointing to the words with a pointer, highlighting the first and last letter of each continent name. The last and first letters are circled in bright colors (for example, ''A'' circled in Africa and Asia, ''E'' in Europe). The students, a diverse group of children, look surprised and amused, with one scratching their head in confusion. The setting is a simple classroom with posters of a world map and a globe on a desk. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions showing curiosity and amusement.'),
 (751, 'Good Question!, Science', 'If ice floats, why is Antarctica at the bottom of the earth?', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon showing a simple, colorful globe of the Earth. The globe should have a visibly exaggerated bottom labeled ''Antarctica,'' colored with large blocks of ice. On top of the globe, depict floating ice cubes bobbing in water with little cartoonish faces looking confused or surprised. Add a curious cartoon character (human or animal) standing next to the globe scratching their head or holding a question mark above their head, pondering the apparent contradiction. The style should be lighthearted and fun, with clear labels on the globe and ice cubes to emphasize the joke''s question about ice floating and Antarctica''s position at the bottom of the Earth. Avoid any violent or controversial elements—focus on a playful, educational, and silly scene that captures the joke''s confusion and curiosity.'),
 (752, 'Good Question!, Science', 'In reality, everything is less than zero. It just depends where your zero is.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on a large number line spread out on the ground. The person looks puzzled or contemplative, scratching their head, while pointing at the zero point on the line. Around them, there are other numbers, both positive and negative, depicted as big colorful digits stretching to the left and right. In the background, a whimsical thought bubble shows two scenarios: one where zero is at sea level with negative numbers below and positive numbers above, and another where zero is set higher on a mountain, so everything below is less than zero. The style is lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated expressions and clear labeling on the number line to emphasize the concept that "everything is less than zero depending on where your zero is." The scene should feel educational yet silly, like a visual pun playing on perspective and relative positions on a line.'),
 (753, 'Good Question!, Science', 'The human heart creates enough pressure when it pumps out to the body to squirt blood 30 feet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a cartoon human heart with exaggerated angry eyes and arms flexing muscles, standing on a small podium labeled ''World''s Strongest Pump.'' From its main artery, a dramatic, high-pressure red stream of blood shoots out like a powerful water fountain, arching in the air and stretching about 30 feet. Nearby, a few surprised cartoon characters (people or animals) react in astonishment, some shielding their eyes or holding umbrellas to avoid the ''blood spray.'' The background is a simple lab or anatomy classroom setting with a blackboard illustrating a heart diagram, emphasizing a playful educational tone.'),
 (754, 'Good Question!, Science, Word Play', 'How many weeks are there in a light year?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a confused scientist or student standing in front of a large blackboard filled with complex math and physics formulas related to light speed and time. The character scratches their head, looking puzzled and holding a ruler or calendar. Floating nearby is a playful lightbulb with legs and a face, walking along a path marked with weeks and calendars, symbolizing the pun on a ''light year'' confused as weeks. The background should have stars and outer space elements to hint at astronomy, but the setting is clearly a classroom or study with humorous, exaggerated expressions and props to highlight the joke''s confusion between ''light year'' as a distance and ''weeks'' as a time measurement. The overall style is colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated features and lighthearted vibe, making the pun approachable and visually funny without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (755, 'Good Question!, Space Humor', 'If space is a vacuum, who changes the bags?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in outer space featuring an astronaut floating next to a giant space vacuum cleaner shaped like a classic household vacuum but with a clear, oversized bag labeled ''Space Vacuum Bag''. The astronaut, wearing a traditional spacesuit with a visible name tag, is scratching their helmet in confusion. The vacuum floats amongst stars, planets, and small space debris. Nearby, a confused-looking alien with multiple eyes peeks from behind a small asteroid holding a replacement vacuum bag, looking equally unsure. The background is a colorful starry cosmos with Earth visible in the distance. The mood is light and comical, emphasizing the absurdity of the question about who changes the ‘vacuum bags’ in space.'),
 (758, 'Good Question!, Word Play', 'If shoelaces always untie and headphone always tangle, why don''t we use headphone cables in shoes and shoelaces in headphones?', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person holding up a shoe with tangled headphone wires as shoelaces and a pair of headphones with long, untied shoelaces instead of regular cables. The shoe is oversized with bright, comically twisted headphone cables sticking out where the laces should be, and the headphones look puzzled as long, colorful shoelaces dangle messily from the ear cups. The setting is a casual room with a small table holding a tangled mess of regular shoelaces and headphone wires. The person has a playful, puzzled expression, scratching their head as they wonder about the swap. Exaggerate the twists and loops in both the headphone wires and shoelaces to emphasize their problematic nature, in a lighthearted cartoon style with bold lines and bright colors, avoiding any complexity or realistic detail to keep the humor clear and accessible.'),
 (759, 'Good Question!, Word Play', 'If you jog backwards, will you gain weight?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person jogging backwards on a sidewalk or park path. The jogger looks puzzled, glancing over their shoulder as they run backwards, with exaggerated wide eyes and a question mark above their head. Behind them, a floating, oversized scale hovers midair showing weight numbers, while a few crumbs or snacks like a donut and an apple float nearby, adding to the playful confusion. The background shows a simple park setting with a tree, a bench, and a squirrel watching curiously. The style is colorful and lighthearted, emphasizing the silly idea of gaining weight by jogging backwards.'),
 (760, 'Good Question!, Word Play', 'I''m not sure why the call child birth delivery... shouldn''t it be called takeout?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cozy, brightly colored hospital room. In the center, a pregnant woman lies in a hospital bed, looking amused and holding a takeout menu in one hand while her other hand rests on her belly. Next to the bed, a cheerful nurse or doctor holds a large takeout food container with a newborn baby peeking out, wrapped in a tiny blanket like a ''delivered order.'' Above them, a big speech bubble from the woman says, "Shouldn''t childbirth be called takeout?" In the background, typical hospital details like an IV stand, heart monitor, and baby crib are visible. The overall mood is light, funny, and playful, with exaggerated cartoonish expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke about childbirth resembling a food takeout experience.'),
 (761, 'Good Question!, Word Play', 'My book on the history of clocks just arrived. It''s about time.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person holding a freshly delivered book titled ''The History of Clocks.'' The person should be smiling widely and giving a thumbs-up gesture. In the background, show an exaggeratedly large, old-fashioned grandfather clock and a modern digital clock on the wall to emphasize the theme of time. Include a delivery box on the floor beside the person with a shipping label reading ''Just arrived.'' Add light rays or sparkles around the book to highlight it as special or long-awaited. The style should be bright and playful with simple lines and exaggerated expressions to enhance the joke''s pun on ''about time.'' Avoid any violent or sensitive content, focusing on a warm and funny atmosphere.'),
 (762, 'Good Question!, Word Play', 'The word swims upside-down is still swims.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the word "swims" written on a bright white pool float drifting in a clear blue swimming pool. The pool float is flipped upside-down in the water, with the letters still legible and spelled correctly as "swims" despite being inverted. Around the pool, a smiling cartoon character in sunglasses and a sunhat points at the float in surprise, admiring the quirky fact. Nearby, a small rubber duck floats, also upside-down but obviously a duck. The scene conveys lighthearted fun under a sunny sky with cartoon-style water ripples and sparkles to emphasize the pool setting.'),
 (638, 'Good Question!, Word Play', 'Why do the signs that say ''Slow Children'' have a picture of a running child?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a street sign that reads ''Slow Children'' prominently displayed next to a neighborhood sidewalk. The sign includes a comically exaggerated picture of a child in mid-run, with wide eyes, messy hair flying backwards, and exaggerated running motion lines to emphasize speed, contrasting with the ''Slow Children'' text. Nearby, a few children are playing—one child is blissfully slow and relaxed, sitting on the curb with a lollipop, while another is running energetically past the sign. The background shows typical suburban houses with trees and bushes. The overall style should be light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the irony between the words and the picture on the sign in a bright, cheerful color palette typical of classic cartoons.'),
 (1469, 'Government Humor, Irony, Quotes, Workplace', 'A taxpayer is someone who works for the government but doesn''t have to take a civil service exam.', 'Ronald Reagan', 'In a humorous cartoon style, depict two characters side by side. On the left, a taxpayer is shown sitting at a cluttered desk at home or a casual office space, looking relaxed and holding cash or a bill labeled ''Tax Payment.'' They wear everyday clothes, maybe a simple shirt, and have a slightly confused or bemused expression. On the right, a government employee standing in a formal government office wearing a suit and glasses, holding a clipboard or test paper titled ''Civil Service Exam,'' looking serious or stressed. Between them, place a symbol such as an arrow or a dashed line with a prohibition sign that visually says the taxpayer ''skipped'' the exam. The background could include a government building with a clear sign. The overall tone should be light and playful, highlighting a contrast with funny exaggerations but no aggression or negativity.'),
 (1620, 'Government Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Democracy is a form of government that substitutes election by the incompetent many for appointment by the corrupt few.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two characters in a government office. One character is an ordinary citizen, looking confused or frustrated, holding a ballot paper labeled ''Election.'' This character is surrounded by a crowd of diverse people depicted as silly or goofy-looking to imply incompetence, all eagerly participating in voting. Facing them is a small, smug group of well-dressed officials seated behind a large desk, marked with a plaque that says ''Corrupt Few.'' These officials exchange sly glances and smirk knowingly, holding briefcases stuffed with money or shaking hands behind a curtain labeled ''Backroom Deals.'' In the background, a large sign or banner reads ''Democracy'' above the scene. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with slightly caricatured facial expressions and vibrant colors, emphasizing the irony of the quote without being harsh or negative.'),
 (1704, 'Grammar Humor, Language, Quotes, Word Play', 'From now on, ending a sentence with a preposition is something up with which I will not put.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a strict-looking grammar teacher (wearing glasses and a tweed jacket with elbow patches) standing in front of a classroom blackboard. On the blackboard, the sentence "Something up with which I will not put." is written in large, neat letters. The teacher is pointing sternly at the sentence with a long wooden pointer and has an exaggeratedly disapproving facial expression. Around the teacher, several cartoon students sit at desks, looking confused or amused. One student raises a hand slightly, scratching their head. The classroom is cheerful and colorful, with posters of grammar rules and a large open book on the teacher''s desk. The scene should feel light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the humor in the formal, awkward sentence construction, poking fun at the old grammar rule about not ending sentences with prepositions.'),
 (2895, 'Grammar Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Grammar Fumblerule: Proofread carefully to see if you any words out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk, looking confused and scratching their head while holding a pencil. On the desk is an open book or notebook with a sentence written on it: ''Proofread carefully to see if you any words out.'' The sentence is obviously missing the word ''left'' or ''left out'', causing the confusion. Above the person, a large thought bubble shows a jumble of floating, scrambled words or letters to represent their struggle to find the missing word. The room is simple, with a lamp, a small potted plant, and some scattered papers to emphasize a writing or studying environment. The overall tone is light, funny, and relatable to anyone who has made or noticed a proofreading mistake. The style is bright and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions typical of cartoons to emphasize confusion and humor.'),
 (3237, 'Halloween, Holiday Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'What''s Frankenstein''s favorite Thanksgiving dish? Monster mash potatoes and grave-y.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Frankenstein''s monster sitting at a Thanksgiving dinner table. The monster looks friendly and goofy with green skin, flat head with bolts in the neck, stitches, and big square body. In front of him is a large white plate piled high with mashed potatoes shaped like a monster face, complete with eyes and a mouth made of small vegetables. Next to the mashed potatoes is a gravy boat labeled ''Grave-y'' with ghostly wisps coming off it, implying it''s spooky or eerie. The table has a classic autumn setting with fall leaves, a pumpkin centerpiece, candles, and typical Thanksgiving side dishes like cranberry sauce and corn. The background shows a cozy dining room with warm lighting and a window revealing a dark, starry night. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and details to emphasize the pun and humor.'),
 (794, 'Halloween, Humor, Puns', 'What happens if you don''t pay your exorcist? You get re-possessed', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a spooky, slightly messy haunted house. In the center, a surprised person is halfway faded and ghostly, showing they are being ''re-possessed'' by a ghost or spirit. Nearby, an exorcist character with a cross necklace, holding a big unpaid invoice labeled ''Unpaid Bill'', looks annoyed but playful. Ghostly wisps swirl around the person and the exorcist. In the background, typical haunted house elements such as cobwebs, a creaky old chair, a flickering candle, and a hovering spirit add to the spooky, comical vibe. The style should be colorful and lighthearted, emphasizing the pun on ''re-possessed'' without being scary.'),
 (766, 'Halloween, Love Humor, Pun', 'What did the ghost bring his girlfriend? A Boo-quet', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cute, friendly ghost and his ghost girlfriend. The ghost boyfriend is holding out a ''boo-quet''—a bouquet made of charming little ghost shapes or white puffballs with tiny smiling ghost faces, maybe with some faint glowing or floating effect. Both ghosts should look happy and affectionate. The background can be simple, like a softly glowing haunted house or a night sky with a full moon. Add light-hearted details like floating hearts or stars around them to emphasize the romantic and playful mood. The style should be bright, clean, and cartoony, emphasizing cuteness and whimsy without any spooky or scary elements.'),
 (795, 'Halloween, Movies, Pop Culture', 'The mask used by Michael Myers in the original ''Halloween'' was actually a Captain Kirk mask painted white.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two masks side by side on a dark shelf in a spooky Halloween setting. On the left is a classic Michael Myers mask—plain, white, and expressionless, slightly eerie. On the right is a well-known Captain Kirk mask from Star Trek, recognizable by its distinctive facial features and hair, but painted entirely white to mimic the Michael Myers mask. Include a small paintbrush and white paint can nearby to suggest the repainting. The background should have subtle Halloween decorations like a jack-o''-lantern and cobwebs to set the mood but keep the tone light and funny, not scary. Maybe add a speech bubble from the Captain Kirk mask saying something cheeky like ''To boldly scare,'' playing on his famous catchphrase. The style should be colorful, simple lines, and exaggerated facial features to emphasize humor and contrast between the two iconic characters.'),
 (789, 'Halloween, Pun, Word Play', 'Why do witches look angry? She have resting witch face', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a witch with traditional witch attire: a tall, pointed black hat, a dark robe, and a broomstick leaning against a nearby tree. The witch is standing outdoors in a spooky, slightly whimsical forest setting under a crescent moon. Her expression is serious and grumpy, with furrowed brows and a slight scowl, perfectly embodying the ''resting witch face'' pun. Around her, a few small, cute black cats and fluttering bats add a lighthearted, funny atmosphere. The scene emphasizes her grumpy face but in an amusing and exaggerated cartoon style. The background should be colorful and playful rather than scary, highlighting the joke''s wordplay rather than any dark themes.'),
 (796, 'Halloween, Puns, School', 'What was the witch''s favorite subject in school? Spelling', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a friendly, classic witch sitting at a wooden school desk in a classroom. The witch is wearing a traditional tall pointy hat and has a big grin on her face. On the desk in front of her is an open book titled ''Spelling''. In the background, a chalkboard shows letters and words written neatly, with magical sparkles around the word ''Spelling''. Other students at desks (non-witch children or cartoon animals) look amused or curious. The classroom has whimsical Halloween-themed decorations like a small black cat perched on a shelf and a broomstick leaning against the wall. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright, cheerful colors emphasizing the pun on ''Spelling'' as both a school subject and magical spell casting.'),
 (1573, 'Health Humor, Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Attention to health is life greatest hindrance.', 'Plato (427-347 B.C.)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person relaxing on a couch in casual clothes, looking happy and carefree. Around them are various health-related items like a salad bowl, a pair of running shoes, a dumbbell, a water bottle, and a heart rate monitor, all placed on a nearby table or scattered around in a humorous disorganized manner. The person''s smartphone displays a health app with alerts and reminders popping up comically. The background is a cozy living room with bright colors and exaggerated facial expression on the person showing a mix of slight frustration and amusement at the constant health reminders. The overall vibe should convey the irony that focusing too much on health can get in the way of enjoying life, with a lighthearted cartoon style emphasizing exaggerated expressions and playful details.'),
 (2232, 'Health Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'Seven days without laughter makes one weak.', 'Mort Walker', 'A cheerful cartoon scene showing a calendar hanging on a wall. The calendar prominently displays the seven days of the week, each day marked with a small smiley face except for one day which has a sad or neutral face indicating no laughter. In front of the calendar is a cartoon character slouched and looking tired or weak, with exaggerated droopy eyes and a faint frown. Nearby, a speech bubble floats above the character with the phrase ''Seven days without laughter makes one weak'' in playful, bold letters. The background is bright and colorful, emphasizing the humor and lighthearted tone, and the character wears casual clothes to keep the mood fun and relatable. Overall, the image should have a simple, friendly cartoon style with a touch of whimsy to express the pun clearly, without any harsh or negative visuals.'),
 (1198, 'Historical Humor, Insults, Political Humor, Wit', '''Sir, if you were my husband, I would poison your drink.''  --Lady Astor to Winston Churchill.  ''Madam, if you were my wife, I would drink it.'' --His reply', 'Winston Churchill', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a classic, elegant 1940s drawing room with rich wood paneling and a vintage chandelier. On the left, depict Lady Astor, an aristocratic woman dressed in a refined, old-fashioned dress and pearl necklace, holding a delicate teacup with a sly, challenging expression. On the right, show Winston Churchill, a stout, stout man with round glasses, a bow tie, and a cigar in his mouth, sitting confidently in a high-backed chair, smirking knowingly while gesturing toward Lady Astor''s teacup as if acknowledging the poison threat. Both should have exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing their witty exchange. Include a small table between them with a tea set and a bottle marked "Poison?" in a humorous, non-threatening style. The background features classic portraits and a cozy fireplace to set the period tone. Overall, the style should be light-hearted and playful, resembling a vintage political cartoon with clear, bold lines and warm colors highlighting the clever repartee without any harsh or offensive elements.'),
 (1778, 'Historical Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'I am become death, shatterer of worlds.  (Citing from the Bhagavadgita, after witnessing the world''s first nuclear explosion)', 'Robert J. Oppenheimer (1904-1967)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set outdoors during daytime. In the center, depict a startled, slightly bewildered scientist wearing a lab coat and safety goggles, standing with arms raised as if reacting to something shocking. In the background, show a large nuclear mushroom cloud rising impressively into the sky, with exaggerated swirls and a bright fiery glow at its base. The scientist should look small compared to the giant cloud. Include a simple lab table nearby cluttered with typical lab equipment like beakers and test tubes. The scientist''s expression should be a mix of awe and mild panic, reflecting the iconic quote. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bold outlines and bright colors. Avoid any dark or violent imagery — the humor comes from the scientist''s dramatic reaction to the explosion, referencing the famous quote from the Bhagavadgita in a historic context. Add a small speech bubble near the scientist with the quote written inside for clarity and comedic effect.'),
 (1546, 'History Humor, Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'Any event, once it has occurred, can be made to appear inevitable by a competent historian.', 'Lee Simonson', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy, old-fashioned study room filled with history books and scrolls. In the center, a confident historian, wearing round spectacles and a tweed jacket with elbow patches, is sitting at a large wooden desk cluttered with papers and an open book titled ''History Facts.'' He is holding a magnifying glass in one hand and pointing dramatically at a timeline on the wall behind him, which shows a series of wildly exaggerated and improbable historical events, all connected by arrows leading to one inevitable conclusion. Around him, faint ghostly silhouettes of famous historical figures like Napoleon and Cleopatra look on, some scratching their heads or shrugging as if perplexed by how the historian twists the story. The overall tone is light and funny, with lots of little details like a quill pen, inkpot, and a steaming cup of coffee to evoke the mental image of a scholarly but playful environment. The drawing style is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor about making any event seem inevitable after the fact.'),
 (801, 'History Humor, Humor, Philosophy', 'Puritanism: The haunting fear that someone, somewhere may be happy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a gloomy, stern-looking Puritan man in traditional 17th-century attire, including a tall black hat with a buckle, a white collar, and dark clothing. He is peeking anxiously and suspiciously from behind a large wooden door or corner of a building. Through a window or slightly open door nearby, show a small cheerful scene with bright colors, such as a few happy people dancing, laughing, or enjoying a sunny picnic with balloons or musical instruments. The contrast between the Puritan''s dark, fearful expression and the joyful scene visible through the window highlights his ''haunting fear'' that someone may be happy. Add exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize humor, with the Puritan appearing almost haunted or shocked. Background should be simple, with a hint of a colonial village, wooden houses, or a church to set the historical mood without overcrowding the image.'),
 (802, 'History Humor, Humor, Politics', 'Taxation with representation isn''t so hot, either.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a colonial-era character from the American Revolution period sitting at a simple wooden table. The character looks frustrated and is holding a scroll labeled ''Taxation Without Representation.'' Opposite him, a modern-day person in casual clothing sits at the same table holding a paper labeled ''Taxation With Representation,'' also looking unhappy but resigned. Above their heads, include speech bubbles: the colonial character saying, ''Taxation without representation is terrible!'' and the modern character replying, ''Taxation with representation isn''t so hot, either.'' The setting should exaggerate the contrast between the two eras by showing a colonial-style room on one side and a modern office-like setting on the other, both blending humorously. Keep the expressions exaggerated and cartoonish to emphasize frustration and irony. The overall scene should evoke humor about the woes of taxes across time without any negativity beyond mild grumbling.'),
 (803, 'History Humor, Humor, Pop Culture', 'The first toilet ever seen on television was on ''Leave It To Beaver''.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a vintage 1950s living room with classic mid-century furniture and decor. Place a large, old-fashioned television set with big dials and rabbit ear antennas in the center. On the TV screen, show a cartoonishly exaggerated toilet bowl with water inside, making it obvious it’s a toilet. Add a small caricature of Beaver from the show "Leave It To Beaver" standing beside the TV, looking surprised or curious. Include details like the show''s logo or a retro TV screen border to emphasize the era. The overall tone should be light-hearted and nostalgic, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions for a funny and wholesome vibe. No violence or anything inappropriate should be included.'),
 (804, 'History Humor, Humor, Word Play', 'VIRGIN: A young innocent who in former times was sacrificed to the gods but who now merely lives in disgrace.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene divided into two panels. In the first panel, depict an ancient setting with a young, wide-eyed innocent person (labeled ''Virgin'') tied to a stone altar, surrounded by cartoonish angry gods with thunderbolts, dramatic fire, and gods looking displeased but not scary. The setting should be outdoors with temple columns and some tropical plants to suggest an ancient civilization. In the second panel, show the same young person in modern clothes, sitting alone on a park bench looking awkward and embarrassed, with people nearby whispering or giving side glances. Include modern urban elements like a city skyline, a lamppost, and a dog walker passing by. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated with big expressive eyes to emphasize innocence and shame without being mean. Add a caption under the panels reading: ''Virgin: A young innocent who in former times was sacrificed to the gods but who now merely lives in disgrace.'''),
 (2518, 'History Humor, Irony, Music Humor, Quotes', 'We don''t like their sound, and guitar music is on the way out.  (Said when rejecting the Beatles in 1962)', 'Decca Recording Co.', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a 1960s-style music industry office. Two stern-looking record executives, dressed in early 60s suits with skinny ties and slicked-back hair, sit behind a large wooden desk cluttered with papers and an old-fashioned microphone. One executive holds a rejection letter that reads, ''Sorry, no thanks.'' Opposite them stand the four members of the Beatles in their early mop-top hairstyles and matching suits, looking disappointed but hopeful. Behind them, a simple poster on the wall shows a guitar with a red ''X'' over it and a faded notice that says ''Guitar music is on the way out.'' The room has vintage decor with a rotary phone and a vinyl record player in the corner. The overall style is bright and exaggerated with large expressive faces to capture the irony and humor of missing out on a future musical phenomenon.'),
 (2018, 'History Humor, Irony, Quotes, War Humor', 'John Dalton''s records, carefully preserved for a century, were destroyed during the World War II bombing of Manchester. It is not only the living who are killed in war.', 'Isaac Asimov', 'Create a humorous cartoon scene set in a vintage museum room with old wooden shelves and walls adorned with framed portraits and historical documents. Center the image around a large, aged, glass-covered display case labeled ''John Dalton''s Records - 19th Century Scientist.'' Inside the case, show a mix of papers, notebooks, and charts with atomic symbols and colorful sketches. Outside, a small WWII-era airplane is seen in the distance dropping a cartoonish bomb marked with classic explosive visuals (but harmless, like a lit fuse with smoke). The bomb is moments from hitting the building. Add a ghostly, semi-transparent figure of John Dalton looking sad or disappointed, hovering near the display with a speech bubble saying, ''It is not only the living who are killed in war.'' The overall art style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors, emphasizing the irony and sadness humorously without any violence or gore.'),
 (805, 'History Humor, Lawyer Humor, Word Play', 'The phrase ''rule of thumb'' is derived from and old English law which stated that you couldn''t beat your wife with anything wider than your thumb.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused looking medieval English judge in traditional robes and a curly white wig sitting on a high wooden bench inside a courtroom. The judge is holding an oversized cartoonish thumb ruler (like a ruler shaped as a giant thumb) up to a small, worried-looking man standing in front of him. The man is holding a wooden stick, narrowly avoiding it being crushed or measured by the giant thumb ruler. In the background, a scroll labeled ''Old English Law'' hangs on the stone wall. The courtroom setting is exaggerated with exaggerated wooden beams, an old-fashioned balance scale, and a quill and inkpot on the judge''s bench. The overall tone is light and silly, emphasizing the absurdity of measuring with thumbs in a legal context. No violence depicted, just confused faces and comically oversized thumb measuring tool.'),
 (1757, 'History Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'History never looks like history when you are living through it.', 'John W. Gardner', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person living a mundane, somewhat hectic everyday moment such as dealing with a messy kitchen or waiting in a long line. The person appears slightly stressed or confused, looking at their watch or calendar. In the background, a large thought bubble shows the same scene, but aged and framed like a golden historical painting or museum exhibit with an ornate plaque titled ''History.'' Around this frame are old-fashioned historical objects like scrolls, statues, and vintage books. The contrast between the busy, real-time moment and the calm, celebrated ''history'' version is clear and humorous. The style is lively and colorful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the difference between living history and looking back at it.'),
 (1755, 'History Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'History is a set of lies agreed upon.', 'Napoleon Bonaparte', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of people from different historical periods sitting around a large round table like they are in a secret meeting. Each character is dressed distinctly: one in ancient Roman toga, one in medieval knight armor, another as a Victorian-era gentleman or lady, and one in 20th-century clothing. They are all smiling slyly and shaking hands as if they''ve just struck a deal. On the table lies a big, open ancient-looking book labeled ''History,'' with cartoonish, exaggerated scribbles and crossed-out words visible. In the background, a chalkboard or scroll on the wall reads the phrase ''History is a set of lies agreed upon.'' The overall style is light and playful, with exaggerated expressions and lively colors to emphasize the joke’s irony without any negativity or offense.'),
 (2176, 'History Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'One of the lessons of history is that nothing is often a good thing to do and always a clever thing to say.', 'Will Durant', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking professor or historian standing in front of a large chalkboard filled with various historical dates and events scattered randomly. The professor has an exaggerated thoughtful expression, holding a pointer and looking slightly amused. The chalkboard has the phrase “Nothing is often a good thing to do and always a clever thing to say” written prominently in playful, bold letters. Surround the professor with small visual symbols of history like a scroll, an old quill pen, a globe, and a clock showing time passing. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with soft, bright colors and exaggerated facial features to enhance the comedic tone, making the scene feel like a funny classroom moment about the paradoxical nature of history and clever sayings.'),
 (2542, 'History Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'What is history but a fable agreed upon?', 'Napoleon Bonaparte', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting at a wooden table under a large old-fashioned parchment scroll titled ''HISTORY.'' One character is an ancient, scholarly-looking person in a toga with a laurel wreath, holding a quill pen and looking thoughtfully at the scroll. The other character is a modern-day casual person in jeans and a t-shirt, scratching their head in confusion. Above them floats a whimsical thought bubble containing a book labeled ''FABLES'' with small, amusing illustrations of dragons, talking animals, and castles. The background features a classic classroom or library setting with shelves of books, historical artifacts like a globe and an old helmet. The overall mood is lighthearted, showing the contrast between the seriousness of history and the playful idea of it being just an agreed-upon story, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s irony. The style is colorful, cartoonish, and slightly exaggerated to highlight humor without any harsh or serious tones.'),
 (1529, 'History Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'America has had gifted conservative statesmen and national leaders. But with few exceptions, only the liberals have gone down in history as national heroes.', 'Gunnar Myrdal', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of historical American figures standing on a podium labeled ''National Heroes.'' On the left, a small, modest group of figures wearing traditional conservative-style clothing, looking a bit underwhelmed and standing slightly off to the side. On the right, a larger, more colorful and dynamic group dressed as liberals, with vibrant clothing and big smiles, striking heroic poses under a bright spotlight. The background shows a large book or monument titled ''History,'' emphasizing the idea of who gets remembered. Thought bubbles above the conservative group show phrases like ''Gifted conservative statesmen,'' while the liberal group has butterflies, stars, and celebration icons around them. The style is lighthearted and playful with exaggerated facial expressions and cartoonish features, no political symbols or violence, just a comedic portrayal of the contrasting legacies and recognition in history.'),
 (2206, 'History Humor, Politics, Quotes, Satire', 'Politics I supposed to be the second-oldest profession. I have come to realize that it bears a very close resemblance to the first.', 'Ronald Reagan', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two cavemen sitting around a small fire in a prehistoric setting. The first caveman is holding a spear and has a sly grin, while the second caveman is dressed like a modern politician in a suit and tie but still with a caveman style beard and hair. They are both gossiping or scheming with exaggerated sly expressions. Nearby, a rock with ''First profession: Hunting'' carved into it stands beside a simple wooden sign that says ''Second profession: Politics'' with a question mark. The background has basic elements like a few trees, rocks, and a distant volcano to emphasize the Stone Age era. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated facial features to amplify the joke’s playful comparison between ancient hunting and modern politics as professions.'),
 (2177, 'History Humor, Programming Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'One of the main causes of the fall of the Roman Empire was that, lacking zero, they had no way to indicate successful termination of their C programs.', 'Robert Firth', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an ancient Roman setting with classical Roman elements such as columns, togas, and Roman soldiers. In the center, a frustrated Roman programmer dressed in a toga and laurel wreath sits at a crude, stone-carved computer terminal made to look like Roman architecture. On the screen, there is ancient Roman numerals (I, V, X, L, C, D, M) displayed like code lines, but no zero anywhere. The programmer is scratching his head, holding a stylus or quill, looking confused and annoyed. Nearby, a scroll labeled ''C Programs'' lies on a pedestal, with some kind of error marks or question marks floating above it. Surrounding details include a small chalkboard or wax tablet with the phrase ''No Zero - No Success'' written in ancient script. The atmosphere is light and silly, with exaggerated cartoon expressions and slightly exaggerated Roman clothing and props, emphasizing the absurdity of mixing ancient Rome and modern programming concepts.'),
 (806, 'History Humor, Puns, Science', 'Wernher von Braun settled for a V-2 when he coulda had a V-8.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Wernher von Braun, an early rocket scientist, dressed in mid-20th-century attire with a rocket blueprint in one hand, standing next to a large rocket labeled ''V-2''. Nearby, there is a sleek, shiny red V-8 engine car with a confused or wistful expression on its face, symbolizing the missed opportunity. Von Braun looks contemplative, glancing between the rocket and the car. The background is a simple rocket launch pad with smoke or steam puffs, and a signpost humorously pointing in two directions: one labeled ''Rocket Science'' toward the V-2, and the other labeled ''Luxury Cars'' toward the V-8. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated in classic cartoon format, with expressive faces and bright colors to emphasize the pun about the V-2 rocket and V-8 car engine.'),
 (807, 'History Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'Shakespeare invented the word ''assassination'' and ''bump''.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene with a playful medieval writer, styled like Shakespeare, sitting at a wooden desk cluttered with old scrolls and a quill pen. He has a jovial, slightly mischievous smile as he holds up two scrolls: one with the word ''assassination'' in an elegant, dramatic font, and another with the word ''bump'' in big, simple, cartoonish letters. The background shows a cozy Elizabethan study, with shelves of books and parchment. Nearby, a small animated speech bubble shows a tiny dagger next to the word ''assassination'' and a little comic bump (like a bump on the head) next to ''bump,'' emphasizing the contrast between the serious and silly words. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, focusing on the witty contrast of the two invented words by Shakespeare.'),
 (2619, 'History Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'You want scary, I have more electronic processing power in my home than the Pentagon did in 1945.', 'David Harris', 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a modern living room filled with several electronic devices: a large flat-screen smart TV, a sleek laptop, a smartphone, a smart speaker, a game console, and other gadgets all glowing with bright lights and digital screens. In the center, depict a person (looking slightly amused or smug) holding a phone or tablet, glancing at the electronic setup. Above them, include a small ghostly, vintage-looking Pentagon building (1940s style) appearing faint and outdated with old-fashioned computers inside visible through windows or as ghostly impressions. The contrast shows the huge difference in technology between the past and present in a funny, non-threatening way. Keep the art style bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the exaggerated number and brightness of modern devices. Avoid any scary or violent imagery; focus on the humorous comparison of tech power through the visual contrast between past and present computing.'),
 (1758, 'History Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'History will be kind to me for I intend to write it.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident, smiling historical figure dressed in old-fashioned clothing reminiscent of the 19th century, sitting at a large vintage wooden desk cluttered with stacks of papers, an inkwell, and a quill pen. The figure is dramatically writing in a large, open book labeled ''History'' with a prominent feather quill. Around the desk, ghostly faint images of famous historical events and figures float as comic thought bubbles showing scenes such as battles, famous speeches, or ancient landmarks, implying the person is ''writing'' history themselves. The background is a cozy study room with bookshelves packed with thick history books and a globe. Bright warm colors and exaggerated facial expressions and gestures emphasize the humor. The style is clearly cartoonish and lighthearted, with a slight wink or smirk on the writer''s face, suggesting cleverness and self-awareness about controlling the narrative of history.'),
 (808, 'History Humor, School, Word Play', 'What''s the worst thing about ancient history class? The teachers tend to Babylon.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a colorful ancient history classroom. The classroom has stone walls decorated with hieroglyphics and ancient artifacts like a small pyramid, a clay pot, and scrolls on shelves. Several students with exaggerated, confused expressions sit at desks looking at an animated teacher who is dressed like an ancient Babylonian with a typical beard, a striped robe, and a tall, tiered hat. The teacher is shown yawning widely, leaning back in his chair, clearly bored or sleepy. Behind him, a chalkboard or stone tablet displays the phrase ''Babylon'' with doodles of zzz''s floating above to emphasize his boredom or tendency to nod off. The scene should have bright and cheerful colors with slightly exaggerated cartoonish proportions to enhance the humor without any violence or politics. Include speech bubbles or cartoon-style text showing the pun: ''Teachers tend to Babylon,'' to highlight the joke visually in the scene.'),
 (809, 'History Humor, Word Play', 'Joseph Stalin''s grave was a Communist Plot.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cemetery featuring a simple gravestone labeled ''Joseph Stalin.'' Surrounding the grave are classic communist symbols like a red hammer and sickle flag planted in the ground. In front of the grave, a small group of burly, stereotypical Soviet-style cartoon characters (wearing ushankas and military coats) are gathered, some whispering and looking conspiratorial. The gravestone itself has a subtle cartoonish glow or aura, implying it''s part of a literal ''Communist Plot.'' The background shows some trees and a quaint fence, with lighthearted, exaggerated expressions on the characters to emphasize the joke without menace. The overall tone is playful and satirical, with bright colors, simple lines, and exaggerated features to enhance the comedic effect without depicting anything violent or serious.'),
 (3225, 'Holiday Humor, Pun, Thanksgiving', 'How does Thanksgiving always end? With a ''g''.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a Thanksgiving dinner table with a big roasted turkey, plates, and autumn decorations like pumpkins and fall leaves. At the end of the table, a giant red lowercase letter ''g'' is sitting or standing prominently, perhaps looking proud or mischievous. Around the table, happy and slightly puzzled family members are looking at the ''g'' with amused expressions. The setting is warm and cozy, emphasizing the holiday theme with a banner or sign saying ''Happy Thanksgiving''. The cartoon style should be light-hearted and colorful to enhance the pun''s humor.'),
 (1969, 'Honesty Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'It is annoying to be honest to no purpose.', 'Ovid [43B.C. - A.D.18]', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a podium or desk with a speech bubble saying something long and overly detailed, while the audience around them looks visibly confused, bored, or disinterested. The speaker looks earnest and serious, but the audience members are looking at their watches, yawning, or whispering to each other. The setting could be a meeting room or a casual gathering, with a mix of people showing a lack of engagement despite the speaker''s honesty. The overall vibe is light-hearted, emphasizing the frustration of speaking honestly when no one cares.'),
 (810, 'Humor', 'I''m as confused as a baby in a topless bar.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a very cute, wide-eyed baby sitting in the middle of a colorful, lively topless bar. The baby looks utterly puzzled with raised eyebrows and a small open mouth, clearly overwhelmed. Around the baby, cheerful adults are dancing and socializing, some holding drinks, but the bar is cartoonish and light-hearted with decorations like neon signs, bar stools, and a jukebox in the background. The lighting is playful, with exaggerated expressions on the adults to highlight the baby''s confusion. The baby could be wearing a simple diaper and maybe a pacifier hanging from its neck, emphasizing innocence and contrast with the bar setting.'),
 (811, 'Humor', 'My wife just opened the car door for me. Would''ve been a nice gesture if we hadn''t been going 70mph', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a car speeding down a road at about 70 mph with exaggerated motion lines and a speedometer visible inside the car showing the speed. The wife is outside the car on the passenger side, leaning into the open car door with a polite, cheerful smile, as if she just opened the door for her husband. The husband is inside the car, looking surprised and wide-eyed, holding the steering wheel tightly. The scene should be lighthearted and funny, highlighting the absurdity of opening a car door at high speed. The background could be a simple roadside with a few trees or a stretch of highway to emphasize motion. No one should appear hurt or in danger, and the artwork should be cartoonish and playful, avoiding anything violent or serious.'),
 (812, 'Humor about Gender, Word Play', 'The average woman would rather have beauty than brains, because the average man can see better than he can think.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters: a man and a woman standing side by side. The woman is styled in a classic beauty look, with exaggeratedly perfect makeup, shining hair, and a confident smile. The man is depicted with cartoonishly large eyes that are humorously exaggerated to indicate strong visual perception; his thinking bubble above his head is small or nearly empty, implying limited thinking ability. The background is simple with soft pastel colors, emphasizing the characters. The woman might be holding a mirror or a beauty-related object, while the man wears glasses or squints with overly focused eyes. Both characters have exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor: the woman is proud and self-assured, the man is mildly clueless but visually attentive. No violence or negativity is shown, keeping the tone light and funny.'),
 (1897, 'Humor, Inspirational, Motivational, Quotes', 'If you can imagine it, you can achieve it. If you can dream it, you can become it.', 'William Arthur Ward', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a whimsical dream-like setting. On the left side, a person sits in a comfy chair, eyes closed, imagining a bright, colorful thought bubble above their head containing various imaginative objects like a rocket, a trophy, and a light bulb. On the right side, the same person is depicted as an animated dream version of themselves, confidently standing on a small podium wearing a superhero cape and a laurel wreath, smiling proudly. Between the two versions is a soft gradient or magical swirl representing the transition from imagination and dreaming to achievement and becoming. The background is light and cheerful with fluffy clouds and stars to enhance the dreamy, inspirational tone. The overall style is playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the theme of imagination turning into reality with a positive and uplifting vibe.'),
 (813, 'Humor, Insults', 'I''m not being rude. You''re just insignificant.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing face-to-face. The first character looks calm and polite, with a slight, innocent smile, raising one hand in a gentle, reassuring gesture. The second character appears surprised and slightly offended, eyes wide and mouth open mid-reaction. The setting is simple, with a plain background to keep focus on the interaction. Above the calm character is a speech bubble that reads, "I''m not being rude. You''re just insignificant." The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive facial features to highlight the humor without being mean-spirited. No violent or aggressive body language; the mood is playful sarcasm.'),
 (814, 'Humor, Insults', 'I''m really easy easy to get along with, once you people learn to worship me.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident person standing proudly on a small pedestal or stage, with a bright spotlight shining down on them. The person is dressed in casual, slightly exaggerated ‘royal’ attire—like a crown slightly askew and a flowing cape—striking a boastful pose with arms crossed and a smug smile. Around them, a small group of diverse people stand looking puzzled or slightly annoyed, glancing sideways or whispering to each other, clearly unsure about the person’s demanding attitude. The background is simple, maybe a plain wall or an office breakroom setting to keep the focus on the characters. The mood is lighthearted and playful, with cartoonish, exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s ironic tone about wanting to be ‘worshipped’ to get along with someone.'),
 (815, 'Humor, Insults', 'Never argue with an idiot. They drag you down to their level then beat you with experience.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing on a simple flat ground. On the left, a clean-cut, slightly annoyed person wearing a shirt and jeans, holding their hands up as if trying to explain or argue. On the right, a goofy-looking character with a silly grin, messy hair, mismatched clothes, and barefoot, clearly representing the ''idiot.'' The goofy character is happily holding a wooden stick labeled ''Experience'' and is playfully tapping the other person''s head with it. Both characters should be drawn with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor — the annoyed person looks frustrated and surprised, while the silly character looks gleefully mischievous. The background is minimal, perhaps a simple park or street setting with a tree and bench to keep the focus on the interaction. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish, leaning into the playful insult of the joke without any aggression or negativity in tone.'),
 (1191, 'Humor, Insults, Internet Humor, Relatable Humor', 'May your article load that extra little bit, so just as you''re about to click a link you click an ad instead', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated internet user sitting at a desk with a laptop. The laptop screen displays a slow-loading web article with a visible loading bar almost at 100%. The user''s hand hovers above the mouse or trackpad, about to click. Nearby, a brightly colored and annoyingly flashy online ad pops up overlapping the article content, with a big, exaggerated ''Click Me!'' button. The user''s expression should be a mix of anticipation and annoyance, eyebrows raised and eyes wide, clearly about to click the article but accidentally about to click the ad instead. Include comic-style movement lines around the hand to show the imminent clicking action. The room is simple, maybe with a coffee cup and a small plant to add everyday life context. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the common internet frustration with slow loads and intrusive ads without exaggerating negativity.'),
 (1159, 'Humor, Insults, Social Commentary', 'Any fool can criticize, condemn, and complain -- and most fools do.', 'Dale Carnegie', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large group of silly-looking people standing together outdoors in a park. Each character has exaggerated foolish expressions like crossed eyes, sticking tongues out, or scratching their heads. Some hold signs or speech bubbles with phrases like ''I criticize!'', ''I condemn!'', and ''I complain!'' above them. In the foreground, a calm, wise-looking person with a gentle smile observes the crowd with mild amusement. The background includes trees and a sunny sky to create a lighthearted, everyday setting. The overall tone is playful and non-threatening, emphasizing the foolishness of constant criticism with bright, vibrant colors and exaggerated caricatures.'),
 (1163, 'Humor, Insults, Technology Humor, Word Play', 'Artificial Intelligence usually beats real stupidity.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a sleek, shiny robot with a friendly digital face and glowing eyes stands confidently, perhaps holding a small trophy labeled ''AI Champion.'' On the right, a human with a puzzled, confused expression is scratching their head, wearing oversized glasses and a crooked tie, looking slightly frazzled. The background is simple, like an office or lab setting, with a whiteboard behind them showing a mix of complex math equations on the AI side and doodles or question marks on the human side. A banner overhead reads "Artificial Intelligence vs. Real Stupidity." The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke without any negativity.'),
 (816, 'Humor, Insults, Word Play', 'MUGGER: A benevolent citizen of the streets who frequently spares the lives of total strangers in exchange for any cash and valuables in their possession.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a busy city street corner. The central figure is a cartoon mugger who looks surprisingly friendly and kind, wearing casual clothes but with a big goofy smile. Instead of a threatening pose, the mugger is holding out an open palm kindly or tipping an imaginary hat. Around him, surprised pedestrians are handing over their wallets, watches, and jewelry cheerfully with relieved or amused expressions. The background shows urban details like street lamps, a trash can, and a few passersby looking shocked yet unafraid. Above the scene, a playful sign or thought bubble reads: ''Benevolent citizen of the streets'' in a whimsical font. The style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the ironic contrast between typical mugger expectations and this funny portrayal.'),
 (817, 'Humor, Insults, Word Play', 'People who think they know it all really annoy those of us who do.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a casual setting, perhaps a coffee shop or a park bench. One character appears smug, with a slight smirk, arms crossed confidently, dressed in neat, slightly pretentious clothing, suggesting they believe they know everything. The other character, standing nearby or sitting opposite, looks even more confident and slightly amused, with a knowing smile and one eyebrow raised, as if silently mocking the first. Include a speech bubble above the second character that reads, "People who think they know it all really annoy those of us who do." The background should be simple and cheerful, with light colors and unobtrusive details like a potted plant or a bookshelf to keep the focus on the two characters. The style should be a clean, light-hearted cartoon, emphasizing facial expressions and body language to convey the joke’s ironic tone without any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (818, 'Humor, Irony', 'Someone who thinks logically is a nice contrast to the real world.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a chaotic, exaggeratedly messy office or living room representing the ''real world.'' Papers, books, and random objects are scattered everywhere. In the middle stands a calm, neatly dressed character labeled ''Logical Thinker,'' depicted as serene and composed, holding a neatly stacked set of papers or a clipboard. Around them, cartoonish characters and objects behave wildly—one person frantically juggling phones and coffee cups, another tangled in headphones, and a cat knocking over a plant. The background features a clock spinning fast and a calendar with pages flying away to emphasize the chaos. The logical thinker’s calm demeanor and neat appearance stand out as a sharp and amusing contrast to the hectic, disorganized surroundings. All characters have exaggerated, comedic expressions to emphasize humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (819, 'Humor, Irony', 'STATE-OF-THE-ART: Soon-to-be-obsolete.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a futuristic gadget labeled ''STATE-OF-THE-ART'' on a pedestal with a big spotlight shining on it, as if on display in a museum. The gadget looks sleek and shiny but is already covered in cobwebs and small dust clouds, humorously highlighting its obsolescence. Nearby, a confused-looking person (wearing casual clothes) scratches their head while holding a manual titled ''Instructions for the Future.'' The background features a sign that says ''Future Tech Museum'' with a small calendar showing the current year, emphasizing the irony. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and light-hearted details like a small clock ticking fast to suggest time passing quickly. No violence, politics, or mature themes.'),
 (820, 'Humor, Irony', 'Tell me what you need, and I''ll tell you how to get along without it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room. On the left, a person with a friendly, slightly sarcastic smile is leaning forward in a comfortable armchair, gesturing with one hand as if giving advice. On the right, another person stands with a puzzled expression, holding a shopping list titled ''What I need.'' The room has a simple setting: a small coffee table with a cup of tea, a bookshelf in the background, and a window showing a sunny day outside. Above the seated person, a speech bubble reads: ''Tell me what you need, and I''ll tell you how to get along without it.'' The overall style is light and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the sarcastic humor of the advice given in the joke.'),
 (821, 'Humor, Irony', 'To get maximum attention, it''s hard to beat a good, big mistake.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing in the middle of a busy office or classroom with exaggerated, comedic expressions of surprise on everyone''s faces. The central character has a big, exaggerated facial expression of shock or realization, pointing to a giant, obvious mistake nearby, such as a massive, misspelled sign or a huge paper mess labeled ''Mistake.'' Around the character, other people stare wide-eyed or lean forward with curiosity, emphasizing the ''maximum attention'' concept. The setting is lighthearted with fun details like floating question marks, exclamation points, and cartoonish sweat drops to add humor. The style should be playful and exaggerated, making the mistake appear ridiculously large and the reactions overly dramatic, all done in a friendly, funny cartoon style without harsh lines or negativity.'),
 (822, 'Humor, Irony, Life', 'Some make it happen, some watch it happen, and some say, ''What happened?''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring three characters standing side by side with distinct expressions and actions. On the left, a confident person actively holding a large wrench or tool, clearly ''making it happen'' with a machine or project that is working perfectly. The middle character is casually sitting on a bench or leaning against a wall, watching the first person work with a relaxed, mildly interested look, representing ''watching it happen.'' The third character stands to the right, looking confused and scratching their head, with cartoon question marks floating above, clearly saying, ''What happened?'' The background is a simple workshop or outdoor setting with humorous small details like spilled coffee or scattered plans to add charm. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated in classic cartoon style, with bright colors and expressive faces emphasizing the difference in attitudes toward action and observation.'),
 (823, 'Humor, Irony, Life', 'Success is a matter of luck; ask any failure.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon featuring two characters standing side by side, labeled ''Success'' and ''Failure.'' ''Success'' is depicted as a confident, well-dressed person holding a trophy or medal with a lucky rabbit''s foot hanging from their wrist. ''Failure'' is slouching, looking frustrated or bewildered, wearing worn-out clothes and holding a broken horseshoe. Both stand under a sky filled with cartoonish lucky symbols like four-leaf clovers, falling horseshoes, and shooting stars. A thought bubble above ''Failure'' reads, ''It’s all just luck…'' while ''Success'' looks smug, maybe shaking the rabbit’s foot. The background can be a simple park or plain with bright colors to keep the mood light and funny, emphasizing the irony of the quote. The style should be cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor of blaming luck for success or failure, without any negativity towards either character.'),
 (824, 'Humor, Irony, Life', 'When faced with a crisis, take the inevitable and turn it around to make it look like a conscious decision.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in the middle of a chaotic situation, such as a small room where something clearly went wrong (like a spilled cup of coffee, papers flying everywhere, or a broken object). The person stands confidently and proudly holding a large sign or a speech bubble saying, ''I totally meant for this to happen!'' Their expression is smug and calm, as if they have a clever plan. Around them, friends or colleagues look surprised or confused, glancing at the mess but unsure whether the person’s explanation is true. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and rounded shapes to emphasize the humor and avoid any serious or negative tone.'),
 (825, 'Humor, Irony, Life', 'While money can''t buy happiness, it certainly lets you choose your own form of misery.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a large display board titled ''Choose Your Misery.'' The board is divided into sections, each labeled with different types of typical stressful situations or problems, such as ''Work Stress,'' ''Health Issues,'' ''Relationship Drama,'' ''Bills & Expenses,'' and ''Traffic Jam.'' The person is holding a big bag of money and looking thoughtfully at the options, with a slight smirk on their face. Around the character, little symbolic icons represent each misery type—like a dripping faucet for bills, a ringing phone for work stress, a broken heart for relationships, a traffic cone for traffic jams, and a pill bottle for health issues. The background is bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the person’s face to emphasize the ironic twist of having money only to pick the kind of unhappiness they want. The scene should evoke a lighthearted, ironic feel without being dark or gloomy.'),
 (3194, 'Humor, Irony, Mental Health Humor, Steven Wright', 'Depression is merely anger without enthusiasm.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene with two characters side by side. On the left, a gloomy character slouched on a plain couch, looking visibly depressed with a grayish tone to their clothes and face. On the right, an angry character with a red face, furrowed brows, and steam coming out of their ears, standing rigidly with clenched fists. Both characters share the same outline and general facial features to imply they are versions of each other. Above them, a big thought bubble with the words: ''Depression is merely anger without enthusiasm.'' The background is simple, with minimal objects like a small coffee table and a lamp to keep focus on the characters’ expressions and postures. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated in typical cartoon fashion, emphasizing the contrast between anger and depression in a visually funny way without being dark or heavy.'),
 (2224, 'Humor, Irony, Motivational, Quotes', 'Remove failure as an option, and your chances for success are infinitely greater.', 'Joan Lunden', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person standing at a crossroads with two visible signs. One path is labeled ''Failure'' and shows a messy, chaotic scene: a banana peel, spilled paint, and a broken trophy. The other path is labeled ''Success,'' bright and shining, but with a large ''Dead End'' sign blocking the way. The person, scratching their head with a puzzled yet determined look, is holding a big eraser and is actively erasing the ''Failure'' sign while looking at the blocked ''Success'' path. The scene is colorful and light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions and cartoonish details to emphasize the irony of removing failure yet being stuck. Include a thought bubble above the character saying, ''Hmm... This feels off.'' The background contains playful elements like a frustrated bird watching from a tree and a smiling sun, adding to the humorous tone.'),
 (826, 'Humor, Irony, Philosophy Humor', 'There never was a good war or a bad peace.', NULL, 'A simple, humorous cartoon featuring two contrasting panels side by side. On the left panel, depict a chaotic, exaggerated battlefield scene showing confused soldiers scrambling around with silly expressions rather than intense fighting—no realistic violence. There are cartoon explosions made of colorful puffs of smoke and flying hats. On the right panel, show an overly peaceful, yet comically boring scene: a sleepy village with people napping in hammocks, reading newspapers, and having a dull conversation on a park bench, looking bored but content. Include a big, friendly dove with an olive branch flying above the peaceful scene. Above or between the two panels, have a speech bubble or banner with the text: ''There never was a good war or a bad peace.'' The overall style should be lighthearted, simple line art with bright colors and smiling or humorous facial expressions to reflect the irony in the statement without any negativity.'),
 (2307, 'Humor, Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The function of genius is not to give new answers, but to pose new questions -- which time and mediocrity can solve.', 'Hugh Trevor-Roper', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classical, slightly eccentric professor with wild, frazzled hair and round glasses standing at a chalkboard filled with complex equations and question marks. The professor is holding a pointer, gesturing excitedly at a big question mark drawn prominently on the board. In the foreground, two average-looking, plain characters, representing ‘time and mediocrity,’ are casually sitting in folding chairs, looking relaxed and holding a large hourglass and a simple checklist respectively. The setting is a modest classroom or study filled with stacks of books and papers scattered around, emphasizing intellectual effort. The facial expressions contrast: the professor appears passionate and intense, while the other two look unimpressed but confident as if solving problems in a slow, methodical, and unremarkable way. The overall style should be light, exaggerated, and cartoonish to emphasize the humor in the contrast between the genius’ deep questions and mediocrity’s slow solutions.'),
 (1630, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes', 'Disclaimer: If anyone disagrees with anything I say, I am quite prepared to not only retract it, but also to deny under oath I ever said it.', 'T. Lehrer', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person sitting at a desk in a simple office or living room setting. The person looks slightly mischievous and relaxed, leaning back in their chair with fingers steepled as if plotting or smugly confessing. On the desk is a large, official-looking document titled “Disclaimer.” Next to the person is a stack of papers and a quill or pen. Behind them, on the wall, there is a framed certificate or courtroom-style document with a scale of justice symbol. Above the scene is a speech bubble with the full joke text. The overall tone is lighthearted and clever, with exaggerated cartoon features (big eyes, expressive face, casual posture) to emphasize the humor in the legal-sounding, contradictory nature of the statement. No other people or complex backgrounds are included, focusing on the single character and their cheeky disclaimer.'),
 (1518, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Always be sincere, whether you mean it or not.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring a well-dressed person standing at a podium giving a speech to an audience. The speaker is smiling broadly with exaggerated sincerity, yet a small subtle thought bubble shows a cheeky or mischievous face, implying they don’t truly mean what they’re saying. The audience looks a bit puzzled but polite, with a couple of cartoonish expressions raising eyebrows. In the background, include a banner or sign that reads “Always Be Sincere!” to highlight the message. Use bright colors and playful, round character designs to keep the tone light and funny without any negativity or controversy.'),
 (2369, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes, Social Humor', 'The problem with people who have no vices is that generally you can be pretty sure they''re going to have some pretty annoying virtues.', 'Elizabeth Taylor', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters having a conversation in a casual setting like a coffee shop or park bench. One character looks very serious and overly proper, dressed in neat clothing with a halo or a shining glow to symbolize ''virtue.'' This character holds a checklist labeled ''Virtues'' with boxes ticked for qualities like ''Politeness,'' ''Honesty,'' and ''Punctuality.'' The other character, more relaxed and slightly amused, is holding a sign or thought bubble that reads, ''No vices? Hope you can handle my virtues!'' Around them, small visual cues highlight the ''annoying virtues,'' such as watches with multiple alarm clocks, ribbons for ''best behavior,'' and an overly neat and tidy environment. The style is bright, playful, and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony and light sarcasm of the joke without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (1959, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes, Wit', 'Intellectual brilliance is no guarantee against being dead wrong.', 'David Fasold', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a very serious-looking professor or intellectual figure with wild, messy hair, thick glasses, and a tweed jacket with elbow patches. The professor is standing confidently at a blackboard filled with complex equations, charts, and ideas, proudly pointing at it with a chalk in hand. However, there is a big obvious mistake on the blackboard, like a silly math error or a nonsensical diagram, and a small cartoon ghost or skeleton casually floating nearby, looking unimpressed or facepalming. The background could include a few confused or amused students sitting at desks, watching the professor with raised eyebrows or smirks. The overall style should be colorful, light-hearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the humor of intellectual confidence paired with clear error, but avoid any scary or violent elements. Make the scene feel playful and ironic, capturing the contrast between intelligence and being wrong in a fun way.'),
 (2294, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes, Wit', 'The cynics are right nine times out of ten.', 'Henry Louis Mencken (1880-1956)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of people labeled as ''Cynics'' standing confidently on a large, oversized dartboard. Out of ten dart holes on the board, nine have darts perfectly stuck in, while one hole remains empty. The cynics are portrayed with smirks and crossed arms, looking very sure of themselves. Around the board, a few other characters who represent optimists or hopeful people look surprised or frustrated at the success of the cynics. The background is simple, maybe an office or casual social setting, emphasizing that the cynics’ prediction about being right most of the time is being humorously highlighted. The style should be colorful, exaggerated facial expressions, and clear focus on the dartboard metaphor to visually represent the phrase "nine times out of ten." No violence or negativity—just playful irony.'),
 (2379, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes, Wit', 'The secret of life is honesty and fair dealing. If you can fake that, you''ve got it made.', 'Groucho Marx', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, slightly mischievous character standing confidently at a simple wooden podium giving a speech. The character is smiling with a twinkle in their eye, dressed in casual smart clothing (like a blazer over a T-shirt). Behind them is a large banner that reads ''The Secret of Life''. To the side of the podium, an open book titled ''Honesty & Fair Dealing'' lies on a small table. Around the podium are a few cartoonish, diverse audience members looking intrigued but slightly puzzled or amused. The setting is a brightly lit community hall or small conference room with simple decorations. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the ironic twist of the joke that honesty can be faked to succeed.'),
 (1782, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes, Word Play', 'I am opposed to millionaires, but it would be dangerous to offer me the position.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a single character, a well-dressed person with an amused or mischievous expression, sitting comfortably in a large, plush armchair. Around the character are subtle symbols of wealth such as a shiny briefcase or a gold watch, but nothing overtly flashy. The scene is indoors, with elegant but understated décor—a framed picture of a piggy bank on the wall or a small stack of cash on a side table. The character is holding a paper or sign that reads ''Millionaire Position Offered'' crossed out or with a caution sign next to it. The atmosphere is lighthearted and ironic, visually emphasizing the contradiction of opposing millionaires but acknowledging the temptation or risk if personally offered to become one. The style should be colorful, clear, and friendly, with exaggerated facial expressions to convey the humor and internal conflict.'),
 (1597, 'Humor, Irony, Quotes, Workplace', 'By working faithfully eight hours a day, you may eventually get to be a boss and work twelve hours a day.', 'Robert Frost', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office environment. On the left, a cheerful employee wearing casual office attire sits at a cluttered desk with a clock showing 9:00 AM and a calendar emphasizing ''8-hour workday.'' The employee happily types on a computer, surrounded by stacks of paperwork, coffee mug, and a small plant. To the right, a boss character looks tired and stressed, dressed in a suit, with disheveled hair and dark circles under eyes. The boss stands near a wall clock showing 9:00 PM, indicating a 12-hour workday. The boss holds a large stack of files and a ringing office phone, while gesturing with one hand. In the background, a banner or motivational poster reads "Work Hard, Move Up!" The scene humorously contrasts the happy worker’s eight-hour shift with the boss’s exhausting long shift, emphasizing the irony of job progression increasing workload. The style is light-hearted and cartoony, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the joke’s irony, no violent or sensitive content.'),
 (827, 'Humor, Irony, Relatable', 'Two can live as cheaply as one, for half as long.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two quirky characters sharing a single tiny, rundown apartment to cut costs. One character is lounging on a shabby couch looking relaxed and frugal, while the other is peeking from behind a door with a worried expression. The room should look cramped and old-fashioned, with minimal furniture such as a small table, a single lamp, and a bare light bulb hanging from the ceiling. A large calendar on the wall highlights the passage of time with pages flying off to emphasize the idea of short time. The atmosphere is lighthearted and kitschy, with exaggerated expressions to capture the humor about living cheaply but only for a short duration. Include small details like an empty wallet, a shared cup of instant noodles, and a clock showing time ticking fast to reinforce the joke’s theme of economy versus longevity. The style should be colorful, simple, and playful to enhance the cartoonish comedy of the scene.'),
 (2848, 'Humor, Irony, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Exhilaration is that feeling you get just after a great idea hits you, and just before you realize what''s wrong with it. [Unknown]', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene capturing the moment of sudden inspiration followed by doubt. In the center, show a character with a lightbulb above their head, eyes wide with excitement and a big smile, representing the ''great idea'' moment. The character’s body language should be energetic and hopeful. Next to them, depict a thought bubble or a faded secondary image showing the same character with a confused or worried expression, scratching their head or facepalming, illustrating the moment when they realize the flaw in their idea. The background should be simple and bright to convey energy and mental activity, with swirling lines or sparkles around the lightbulb to emphasize the idea ''hitting''. Use exaggerated cartoon features and expressions to heighten the humor, keeping the tone light, playful, and relatable. No complex setting—focus on the character and their mental/emotional contrast between excitement and doubt.'),
 (3192, 'Humor, Irony, Steven Wright', 'Ambition is a poor excuse for not having enough sense to be lazy.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cozy living room with a comfortable armchair at the center. Sitting in the armchair is a relaxed, slightly chubby cartoon character wearing pajamas and slippers, leaning back with a blissfully content smile. One hand holds a remote control, and the other rests on an armrest with a bowl of popcorn nearby. A thought bubble above their head depicts a medal or trophy labeled ''Ambition'' with a red cross over it, suggesting rejection. Around the character, there are lazy-related items like a half-finished book, an unplugged laptop, and a small pile of unfinished tasks. The background includes a clock showing mid-morning, implying leisure time. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the idea that laziness is preferred over ambition or hard work. The art style should be simple and cartoonish, with bright, warm colors to enhance the humorous yet relatable vibe of choosing laziness over ambition.'),
 (2785, 'Humor, Irony, Unknown, Workplace', 'Don''t assume malice for what stupidity can explain.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a casual office setting. Character A looks frustrated, pointing accusingly at Character B, who appears bewildered and sheepish. Above Character A’s head is a large thought bubble with a devilish figure symbolizing ''malice.'' Above Character B’s head is a second, smaller thought bubble showing a cartoonishly silly, goofy face representing ''stupidity.'' The office has typical elements like desks, computers, coffee mugs, and scattered papers, emphasizing a mundane workplace environment. A caption at the bottom reads: “Don’t assume malice for what stupidity can explain.” The art style is light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the comedic contrast between blame and innocent mistake.'),
 (828, 'Humor, Irony, Word Play', 'Some people wouldn''t recognize subtlety if it hit them on the head.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person obliviously standing in the middle of a comical situation illustrating ''subtlety'' hitting them on the head. The ''subtlety'' is depicted as a cartoonish, light and fluffy cloud or a gentle breeze personified with cute eyes and a smiling face, gently tapping the person''s head with a soft feather or small pillow. The person is wide-eyed and confused, perhaps scratching their head or looking around cluelessly. The background is simple with a park bench or a streetlamp to give context but keep focus on the interaction. Use exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor: the cloud has a playful and innocent look, while the person looks puzzled but unharmed. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and rounded shapes to emphasize a non-threatening, funny tone.'),
 (829, 'Humor, Irony, Word Play', 'Those who live by the sword, get shot by those who don''t.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of people in a medieval-meets-modern setting. On one side, there are several knights in shining armor holding swords, looking confident and ready for battle. On the other side, a group of modern-day people dressed in casual clothes are holding guns, aiming playfully but carefully. The swordsmen have startled, worried expressions as they see the opponents with guns. The background could be a simple blend of a castle wall on one side and a contemporary cityscape behind the people with guns. Include a humorous street sign or banner above that reads, ''Those who live by the sword,'' and below it, another sign near the gun-holders saying, ''get shot by those who don’t.'' The overall color scheme should be bright and playful, with exaggerated, cartoon-style caricatures and expressions emphasizing the irony and humorous contrast between old and new weaponry.'),
 (830, 'Humor, Irony, Workplace', 'Tell your boss what you think of him, and the truth shall set you free.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in an office setting. Centered is an employee standing confidently in front of a boss’s desk. The employee has a cheeky, mischievous grin, mid-speech, clearly speaking their mind. The boss looks caught off guard with wide eyes, slightly startled but not angry. The office includes common items like a desk with papers, a computer, and a nameplate that reads ''Boss''. Nearby, a window shows a sunny sky, symbolizing the phrase ''the truth shall set you free.'' Add a small freedom bird flying outside the window as a visual pun. The style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the humor of telling the boss the truth setting someone free rather than resulting in trouble.'),
 (831, 'Humor, Jobs', 'If your boss calls tomorrow, do you want me to find out his name?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple office environment. In the foreground, a casual employee is on the phone with a wide-eyed, surprised expression. The employee is holding a smartphone to their ear with one hand while the other hand gestures as if asking a question. Nearby, a coworker leans in, smirking mischievously, as if they just delivered the punchline. The office background includes a desk with scattered papers, a computer monitor, and a coffee mug. A calendar on the wall shows the day marked as ''Tomorrow.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the awkwardness of the question about the boss’s name in a funny, non-threatening way. The characters are drawn with exaggerated expressions and rounded features to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (832, 'Humor, Jobs', 'Improve mail delivery -- mail the postal workers their pay.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a mailroom with a group of cheerful postal workers. In the foreground, one postal worker is handing an oversized envelope labeled ''Paycheck'' to another worker who looks surprised and delighted. Around them, there are mailbags, letters, and parcels scattered about, emphasizing the mail delivery theme. On the wall behind them, a sign reads ''Improve Mail Delivery!'' with a smaller note underneath saying ''Mail the postal workers their pay.'' Everyone is depicted with exaggerated, friendly expressions to add a light-hearted, comedic tone. The style is simple and playful, suitable for a fun, workplace-related joke without any negative or stressful elements.'),
 (833, 'Humor, Jobs', 'People are usually shocked when they find out I''m not a very good electrician', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing next to a lamp post that is bent and sparking, with several live wires loosely hanging around him. The man looks sheepish and embarrassed, scratching his head, wearing a tool belt filled with electrical tools like pliers and screwdrivers. In the background, a small crowd of neighbors or bystanders are looking surprised or shocked, with exaggerated wide eyes and open mouths. The setting is a suburban street with houses, trees, and a clear sky to keep it light and friendly. The overall tone should be playful and non-threatening, emphasizing the man''s ineptitude in a funny way.'),
 (834, 'Humor, Jobs', 'What was Bob the Builder called after he retired? Bob', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an older man named Bob the Builder, wearing a faded yellow hard hat pushed back on his head and casual clothes instead of work gear. He is sitting comfortably on a porch rocking chair with a cup of tea or coffee in hand, smiling contentedly. Around him are retired worker items: a small toolbox closed and put aside, a pair of worn-out work boots beside the chair, and a calendar on the wall behind him marked ''Retired!''. The setting is a cozy home outdoors with a garden in the background. Above Bob’s head is a simple speech bubble that says, ''They just call me Bob now.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and ironic, emphasizing that after retirement, he no longer has a special job title—he''s simply Bob. The style is colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish to enhance the joke’s simplicity and charm without any violent, sexual, or political elements.'),
 (835, 'Humor, Jobs, Life', 'JOB: A state of employment everyone wants but few look forward to on a Monday morning.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office on a Monday morning. The focus is a tired-looking worker sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer, coffee mug, and piles of paperwork. The worker has disheveled hair, half-closed eyes, and a slightly slouched posture, clearly not enthusiastic about starting the day. In the background, a large wall clock shows early morning time. Nearby, a motivational poster ironically reads ''Love Your Job!'' The office environment should have cubicles, fluorescent lights, and a window with a dreary sky outside. A small calendar on the desk prominently displays Monday. The overall style should be light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the worker’s Monday morning dread and the contradictory desire versus reluctance about having a job.'),
 (836, 'Humor, Jobs, Word Play', 'Manual Writer''s Creed:  Garbage in, gospel out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person sitting at a cluttered desk labeled ‘Manual Writer.’ The person looks frustrated but diligent, wearing glasses and holding a pen over a large open manual or instruction book. Around them are piles of crumpled papers and garbage bins overflowing with trash. In the background, there''s a whiteboard or poster with the phrase: ''Garbage in, gospel out'' written in bold, playful letters. The scene should show a mix of seriousness and silliness, with exaggerated facial expressions and cartoonish mess to emphasize the idea that poor input leads to blindly accepted output. Include small humorous details like spilled coffee and a clock showing late hours to capture the writer’s ongoing struggle.'),
 (1249, 'Humor, Knock Knock, Pun, Word Play', 'Whoever invented the knock knock joke should get a no bell prize', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at the front door of a cheerful, colorful house. Show a person standing just outside the door, holding a small trophy labeled ''No Bell Prize'' with a big, silly smile. The door has a big, old-fashioned brass doorbell with a big ''X'' crossing it out or taped over to imply ''no bell''. The person might be wearing a shirt with a lightbulb icon, symbolizing invention or an idea. On the doorstep, a classic wooden plank with the words “Knock Knock Joke Inventor” engraved. A few playful sound lines or comic-style action lines emphasize the knocking gesture of the person’s free hand. The overall art style should be cartoonish, colorful, and lighthearted, emphasizing the pun visually by highlighting the ''no bell'' or ''knock'' elements without any background distractions or negativity.'),
 (1252, 'Humor, Knock Knock, Pun, Word Play', 'Why don''t knock knock jokes never get old?  They always have a fresh opening.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a classic wooden door set in a bright, cheerful hallway. The door has exaggerated, smiling eyes and a big friendly mouth that is slightly open as if speaking. A small comic-style speech bubble emerges from the door, with the words: ''I''ve got a fresh opening!'' Around the door, there are several cartoonish knock knock joke symbols, like a little bell, a hand knocking, and a comic burst with the words ''Knock Knock!''. To emphasize freshness, the door frame is decorated with sparkling stars and fresh green leaves or tiny flowers growing around it. The background is simple and warm-toned to keep focus on the door, giving it an inviting and lively personality. The overall style is whimsical and playful, with bold outlines and vibrant colors to create a humorous cartoon atmosphere without any violence, politics, or inappropriate content.'),
 (837, 'Humor, Language', 'Never use a long word when a diminutive one will do.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a classroom where a teacher stands at the blackboard, pointing to a complicated, long word written in big letters. Next to the teacher is a small cartoon character—a cute, tiny creature labeled ''Diminutive''—holding a much smaller, simpler word on a sign. The teacher looks serious but puzzled, while the tiny character looks confident and cheeky. The classroom has typical school elements: desks, a globe, a chalkboard with some scribbles, and a window showing a sunny day. The style is lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of using long versus short words.'),
 (838, 'Humor, Language', 'PSYCHOPHOBIA: n. The compulsion, when using a host''s bathroom, to peer behind the shower curtain and make sure no one is waiting for you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a small, slightly cramped bathroom of a guesthouse. The central character is a wide-eyed, nervous-looking person standing in front of a closed bathroom door, slightly ajar, holding a roll of toilet paper. They are peeking cautiously behind a colorful shower curtain with exaggerated eyes looking around, as if expecting someone to jump out. The shower curtain should have playful patterns like ducks or bubbles. The bathroom has typical elements: a sink with a mirror, a towel rack, a toilet, and a small window showing a hint of bright sunlight outside to indicate daytime. The character’s body language shows wariness mixed with awkwardness, one hand clutching toilet paper, the other pulling the curtain back slightly with fingers. A small speech bubble or thought bubble might contain the word "Psychophobia?" or a question mark to highlight the joke. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor and anxiety of the moment, avoiding any scary or aggressive elements.'),
 (839, 'Humor, Language, Philosophy Humor', 'Qvid me anxivs svm? -- Alfredo E. Neumanus.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style scene featuring a Roman senator or scholar dressed in a traditional toga, standing in a grand ancient Roman forum with classical columns and a large stone scroll in his hand. The character looks puzzled and slightly anxious, scratching his head as he studies the scroll that bears the phrase ''Qvid me anxivs svm?'' in stylized Latin letters. In the background, a small group of toga-clad citizens whisper and point at him with amused expressions. The overall tone is light and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing confusion and mild worry. The setting includes Roman architecture, stone benches, and some scrolls scattered around to reinforce the ancient theme. Bright colors and clear lines give it a comical, cartoon feel without any harsh or serious elements, capturing the humor of an ancient-style philosopher humorously expressing existential anxiety in Latin.'),
 (840, 'Humor, Language, Philosophy Humor', 'Tact: the unsaid part of what you are thinking.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual conversation. One character is speaking with a thought bubble above their head showing a blunt or rude comment. The other character listens with a polite smile but has a transparent bubble near their head labeled ''Tact'' that mutes or hides part of the thought bubble. The background is a simple living room or coffee shop setting with a few chairs and a table. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between the harsh thought and the softened spoken words to represent tact as the unsaid part of what you are thinking.'),
 (841, 'Humor, Language, Philosophy Humor', 'What you''re saying is too vague to be inconsistent.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters having a conversation. One character, looking slightly confused and holding a speech bubble with vague, scribbled lines representing unclear speech, is saying something indistinct. The other character looks puzzled with a raised eyebrow and scratchs their head, responding with the line: ''What you''re saying is too vague to be inconsistent.'' The setting is a simple indoor room with a casual, friendly atmosphere, such as a couch or a coffee table between them. The style is light, playful, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing confusion and bemusement. The focus is on their interaction and the speech bubbles to convey the joke about vagueness and inconsistency in communication.'),
 (842, 'Humor, Language, Puns', 'What''s the difference between a cat and a complex sentence? A cat has claws at the end of its paws. A complex sentence has a pause at the end of its clause.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two side-by-side panels. In the left panel, a cute, slightly mischievous cartoon cat sits proudly with its tail curled around its paws. The cat''s paws show exaggerated, sharp, shiny claws extended. In the right panel, a giant book or paper scroll is open, labeled ''Complex Sentence.'' At the end of the sentence is a large, visible comma or semicolon, personified as a small pause symbol with sleepy eyes and a relaxed pose. Above the panels is a playful title that reads, ''What''s the difference between a cat and a complex sentence?'' The background should be light and simple, with soft colors and a friendly cartoon style. The focus is on the contrast between the physical claws of the cat and the punctuation mark representing the pause in the sentence, emphasizing the wordplay visually and humorously.'),
 (2029, 'Humor, Language, Quotes', 'Language is a wonderful thing. It can be used to express thoughts, to conceal thoughts, but more often, to replace thinking.', 'Kelly Fordyce', 'A humorous cartoon scene in a simple office or classroom setting. At the center, a character sits at a desk with a goofy, slightly confused expression, holding a speech bubble coming from their mouth. The speech bubble contains scribbles or whimsical symbols indicating ''talking nonsense'' or ''replacing thinking.'' Surrounding the character are floating thought bubbles: one shows clear, neat ideas (like a light bulb or brain icon), another is clouded or crossed out, and a third one, very large, is filled with tangled words or symbols showing the act of ''using language instead of thinking.'' The room includes a simple desk with a few papers and a pencil, perhaps a small bookshelf in the background labeled ''Language'' with a few open books. The overall tone is light and playful, emphasizing the wit behind language sometimes being a substitute for actual thought, in a visual pun style typical of cartoons. The colors are bright and the lines are simple, enhancing the comic effect without overwhelming detail.'),
 (1763, 'Humor, Language, Quotes, Word Play', 'How often misused words generate misleading thoughts.', 'Herbert Spencer', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person reading a book with a puzzled expression, surrounded by floating word bubbles with misused words inside them. Each bubble shows a word humorously misunderstood, causing funny, exaggerated mental images above the person''s head. For example, the word ''dessert'' is mistaken for ''desert,'' so above the bubble is a tiny person stranded on a desert island holding a cake. Another bubble might say ''stationary'' with a confused figure trying to write on a standstill bike. The background is a simple room with a cozy chair, a small bookshelf with slightly crooked books, and a cat looking confused at the floating words. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoony to emphasize the lighthearted nature of confusion caused by misused words.'),
 (843, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'In which level of metalanguage are you now speaking?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk looking confused, surrounded by floating speech bubbles filled with words inside other words, like a series of nested boxes or Russian dolls illustrating layers of language. The person is scratching their head, with question marks above them. In front of the person, there''s a computer screen displaying a chat window or text conversation with increasingly complex overlapping dialogue bubbles, each labeled ''metalanguage level 1,'' ''metalanguage level 2,'' etc. The setting is a casual office or home workspace with a coffee mug and books titled ''Linguistics'' and ''Language Theory'' scattered on the desk. The color palette is bright and cheerful, enhancing the lighthearted, intellectual humor of the scene.'),
 (844, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'No word in the English language rhymes with month, orange, silver, and purple.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a confused dictionary character with arms and eyes, holding a large magnifying glass over a page titled ''Words That Rhyme''. Around it are four colorful word bubbles shaped like comic clouds, each containing one of the words: ''month'', ''orange'', ''silver'', and ''purple''. In each bubble, illustrate the word looking sad or frustrated, maybe with small frowns or slumped posture. The setting is a cozy study room with bookshelves full of word books and a desk lamp shining light. The dictionary character is scratching its head, looking puzzled. The overall style should be lighthearted and funny, with simple, vibrant colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the rhyming struggle.'),
 (845, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'Pronoun: a noun that turned professional.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a talking dictionary or grammar book character with eyes and a big smile. Next to it, show a confident-looking pronoun character dressed in a business suit, standing tall with a briefcase or a name badge that says ''Professional''. Include small speech bubbles with simple examples like ''he'', ''she'', ''they'' floating around to emphasize that it is a pronoun. The background could be a simple office environment with desks, computers, and paperwork to reinforce the ''professional'' theme. The style should be playful and light-hearted, with exaggerated friendly facial expressions and bright colors to make the scene amusing and approachable.'),
 (846, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'Stewardesses is the longest word typed with only the left hand.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person sitting at a desk typing on a classic QWERTY keyboard. The person looks surprised and amused, pointing at the screen where the word ''Stewardesses'' is boldly displayed in large, colorful letters. Around the keyboard, only the left-hand side keys are highlighted or glowing to emphasize the joke. The setting is light and fun, with a bright office or home office background including a coffee mug and a small smiling airplane model on the desk to hint at the airline theme. The person''s right hand rests idly, while the left hand is actively typing. The overall style should be playful and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expression and clear visual focus on the keyboard and word on screen, reinforcing the idea that ''Stewardesses'' uses only the left hand keys while typing.'),
 (847, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'The quantity of consonants in the English language is constant.  If omitted in one place, they turn up in another. When a Bostonian ''pahks'' his ''cah,'' the lost r''s migrate southwest, causing a Texan to ''warsh'' his car and invest in ''erl wells.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels side by side. On the left, depict a stereotypical Boston man with a thick accent, wearing a casual jacket, standing proudly next to his vintage car, labeled ''cah.'' He''s saying ''pahks my cah,'' emphasizing the missing ''r'' sounds. Thought bubbles or wavy lines illustrate the letter ''r''s flying out of Boston and heading southwest as small red letter ''R''s with tiny wings. On the right side, a cheerful Texan wearing a cowboy hat and boots is washing his car, shown with large soap bubbles. He says, ''warsh my car,'' emphasizing his added ''r''s and Southern accent. Near him, an ''erl wells'' oil well cartoonishly pumps oil in the shape of the letter ''R.'' The background can include subtle region markers or small map-like icons showing Boston in the northeast and Texas in the southwest. The overall style is light-hearted, colorful, and exaggerated to highlight the accents and the migration of the letter ''R''s in a charming, educational way.'),
 (848, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'The word racecar and kayak are the same whether they are read left to right or right to left.', NULL, 'Draw a colorful cartoon scene showing two objects side by side on a simple white background. On the left, depict a shiny red racecar with cartoonish eyes on its windshield, smiling. On the right, show a bright blue kayak floating on a small pond with a friendly, slightly exaggerated face on its front tip. Above both, in large bold letters, write the words ''racecar'' and ''kayak'' respectively, each styled so they look symmetrical or mirrored from left to right. Include subtle arrows on each word pointing from left to right and right to left, emphasizing the palindrome nature. The overall style should be cheerful and simple, with thick outlines and bright colors to highlight the humorous idea that these words read the same forwards and backwards. No background details besides the pond under the kayak, and no people should be included.'),
 (849, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'TYPEWRITER is the longest word that can be made using the letters only on one row of the keyboard.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classic QWERTY keyboard viewed from above, emphasizing the top row of letters (QWERTYUIOP). Above the keyboard, a large, playful word bubble shows the word ''TYPEWRITER'' in big, colorful letters, clearly made up entirely from the top row keys. A cheerful cartoon character, perhaps a quirky writer or typist, is pointing excitedly at the keyboard with a big smile, wearing round glasses and a slightly exaggerated clicky typing finger. On the desk nearby, there are crumpled papers and a vintage typewriter (to humorously hint at the word''s meaning). The background is simple with pastel colors to keep focus on the keyboard and the character. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the cleverness of the fact that ''TYPEWRITER'' fits only on one keyboard row. Avoid any violent or political elements; focus on a fun, educational, and slightly nerdy vibe.'),
 (850, 'Humor, Language, Word Play', 'Wanna hear a word I just made up? Plagiarism', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon featuring a person standing on a small stage holding a microphone. The person looks enthusiastic and confident, as if about to share a joke or a fact. Above them, a large comic-style speech bubble reads: ''Wanna hear a word I just made up? Plagiarism.'' In the background, the audience looks puzzled or amused, some scratching their heads or whispering to each other. The setting is a simple comedy club or classroom with a spotlight on the speaker. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor of the punchline about copying a word called plagiarism, which ironically means copying others'' work.'),
 (851, 'Humor, Language, Workplace', 'Jargon is used as a means of succeeding by not simplifying.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an office meeting room where a confident businessperson stands at a presentation board filled with complex, confusing jargon-filled charts and graphs. The presenter is smiling smugly, pointing at the overly complicated text that clearly doesn''t simplify anything, while the audience around the table looks baffled, scratching their heads or exchanging confused glances. Include exaggerated thought bubbles above the listeners showing question marks and swirling lines to emphasize confusion. The overall style should be light-hearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humorous contrast between the complicated jargon and the struggling audience.'),
 (852, 'Humor, Laundry Humor, Puns', 'Remember, if you lose a sock in the dryer, it comes back as a Tupperware lid that doesn''t fit any of your containers.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a laundry room with a front-loading dryer door wide open. Emerging from the dryer is a confused, mismatched sock floating mid-air, looking surprised, while next to it, a bright red Tupperware lid with a puzzled face (cartoon eyes and mouth) is slightly warped and clearly too large for a nearby plastic container sitting on the floor. The laundry room has a basket full of socks with some missing pairs, and containers of various shapes and sizes scattered around, emphasizing the mystery. The background should be simple with light colors and a washing machine next to the dryer, and the floor has a few random socks and lids strewn about. The overall tone is whimsical and playful, emphasizing the joke about lost socks turning into mismatched lids from the dryer.'),
 (853, 'Humor, Lawyer Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'The problem with any unwritten law is that you don''t know where to go to erase it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a confused character standing in front of an enormous, old-fashioned stone tablet labeled ''Unwritten Law.'' The tablet is blank but glowing slightly to emphasize the irony that it''s an unwritten law. The character, looking puzzled, is holding a giant eraser comically oversized for the tablet and searching around nervously for an eraser board or any place to rub off the law. Around the scene, there are whimsical elements like question marks floating above the character''s head and a signpost with directions like ''To the Law Library,'' ''Erase Here,'' and ''Unwritten Law Department'' all with arrows pointing in different, conflicting directions. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the character''s frustration and confusion.'),
 (1552, 'Humor, Lawyer Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Any society that needs disclaimers has too many lawyers.', 'Erik Pepke', 'A cartoon scene showing a quirky, chaotic public place like a park or a busy street with a large, colorful billboard or signboard in the center reading multiple absurdly long legal disclaimers. The disclaimers are comically detailed and cover the entire sign in tiny print. Around it, several confused and overwhelmed people look at the sign with exaggerated puzzled expressions. In the background, there is a small office labeled ''Lawyer''s Office'' with a cartoonish lawyer sitting inside, smiling slyly and counting money. The scene should have a light, humorous tone with exaggerated characters for comedic effect. Emphasize the ridiculous length and complexity of the disclaimers versus the simple environment, highlighting the joke about excessive legal warnings in society. A few birds or animals looking baffled at the sign can add to the humor. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and playful in a comic style.'),
 (854, 'Humor, Lawyer Humor, Word Play', 'Where there''s a will, there''s a probate.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cluttered lawyer''s office. On the left, an elderly person with a mischievous smile is signing a large, official-looking document labeled ''Last Will and Testament.'' On the right, a stern-looking probate judge in robes is holding a big rubber stamp with the word ''PROBATE'' on it, ready to stamp another document. In the center, a long scroll-like paper flows from the will to the judge''s desk, visually connecting the two characters, symbolizing the legal process. The office is filled with law books, a gavel on the desk, a clock showing late afternoon, and a potted plant with droopy leaves to add humor. Both characters have exaggerated, cartoonish expressions to emphasize the joke’s play on words. The background wall features a framed diploma and a humorous motivational poster saying "Where there''s a will, there''s a probate." The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, suitable for a legal pun without any dark or serious undertones.'),
 (2431, 'Humor, Leadership Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'There is nothing more difficult to take in hand, more perilous to conduct, or more uncertain in its success, than to take the lead in the introduction of a new order to things.', 'Machiavelli', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a nervous character standing at the center, sweating and fidgeting while holding a large scroll titled ''New Order of Things.'' Around them are several other characters with skeptical and confused expressions, some whispering among themselves. The setting is a whimsical office or meeting room with a large banner behind the speaker that reads ''Introduction Meeting.'' The nervous character looks overwhelmed, and one curious character is raising a hand with a puzzled smile. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the anxiety and uncertainty of leading change. Bright colors and expressive faces create a humorous, relatable atmosphere about the challenges of innovation and leadership.'),
 (855, 'Humor, Life', 'I''m trying to hide from reality but it always seems to find me.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person hiding behind a small tree or a big bush in a park or backyard. The person looks comically anxious or worried, peeking out cautiously with wide eyes. Nearby, a tall, looming figure labeled ''Reality'' is casually strolling toward them with a friendly but inevitable expression, as if it’s about to gently tap the person on the shoulder. The figure can be drawn like a large, shadowy character wearing casual clothes and a small briefcase, symbolizing life responsibilities. The background is simple and cheerful, with a few clouds and birds to keep a lighthearted tone. The overall style is colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of trying to hide but being found anyway.'),
 (856, 'Humor, Life', 'In any household, junk accumulates to fill the storage space available.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene set inside a cluttered house storage room or attic. The room is small and cramped with boxes, old furniture, bags, and odd household items stacked neatly but overflowing to completely fill every inch of the available shelf space, floor, and even spilling into the doorway. A confused or mildly exasperated person (gender-neutral, casual clothes) stands in the middle holding a measuring tape or ruler, looking at the jam-packed shelves with wide eyes or a raised eyebrow. Include a calendar or a clock on the wall to subtly imply the passage of time. The humor comes from showing the junk precisely filling all possible storage spots perfectly, as if the clutter magically expanded to fit the room exactly. The overall style should be colorful and exaggerated in a lighthearted, cartoonish way to emphasize the chaos without making it messy or unpleasant.'),
 (857, 'Humor, Life', 'It doesn''t matter how many times you fall off the horse, what matters is how fast you get back on it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person dressed in casual horseback riding attire who has just fallen off a horse. The rider is lying on the ground with a surprised but determined expression, looking up at a horse standing nearby patiently. The horse looks calm and slightly amused, with a subtle smile. The background is a simple outdoor setting with green grass, a few scattered flowers, and a blue sky with a couple of fluffy clouds. Next to the fallen rider, a stopwatch or timer is shown, emphasizing the importance of speed in getting back on. The overall art style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with vibrant colors and clear facial expressions to convey humor and encouragement.'),
 (858, 'Humor, Life', 'It''s best to start each day with a nap.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a cozy bedroom in the morning. The room has soft sunlight streaming through a window with curtains slightly fluttering. A person, wearing pajamas and a sleep mask pushed up on their forehead, is comfortably snuggled in a big, fluffy bed with a huge pillow. Their bedside table has an alarm clock showing an early hour, but the person is blissfully napping with a content smile. Nearby, a cup of coffee is untouched and steam is gently rising from it. The scene should emphasize relaxation and humor, with warm colors and exaggerated, cute features to highlight the joke about starting the day with a nap rather than morning activity. Include a small, playful cat curled up at the foot of the bed, also napping.'),
 (859, 'Humor, Life', 'It''s lonely at the top, but you eat better.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a mountain peak with a content, slightly plump character sitting at the very top eating a lavish feast—like a huge turkey leg, a bowl of fruits, and a cake—all on a fancy picnic blanket. The character wears a simple crown or laurel wreath symbolizing ''being at the top.'' Below the mountain, at the base, a sad and scruffy climber or hiker looks up with an empty plate and a forlorn expression. The background includes a bright sunny sky, a few fluffy clouds, and a trail winding up the mountain. The overall feel is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between loneliness at the top and the abundance of food there.'),
 (860, 'Humor, Life', 'It''s not as easy as people think to get a parking ticket - first you have to find somewhere to park.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a busy urban street lined with parallel parking spots. A frustrated driver, exaggeratedly scratching their head or looking confused, is standing next to an overfilled parking lot sign. Multiple cars are cramped together, some double-parked or awkwardly squeezed in. Show a clearly visible parking meter with a ticket stuck to a windshield of one car, but instead of focusing on the fine, emphasize the scarcity of empty spots. Include a street sign reading ''No Parking'' or ''Full Parking'' nearby for context. The overall mood should be light-hearted and comical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions illustrating the irony that getting a parking ticket requires actually finding a parking space first. Avoid any aggressive or negative portrayal of tickets or enforcement officers.'),
 (861, 'Humor, Life', 'It''s not the waiting, it''s the time between now and then that concerns me!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person anxiously sitting on a park bench, repeatedly checking a large wristwatch with an exaggerated worried expression. Around them, time is visually represented by several floating clocks showing different times and calendars fluttering in the wind. The background is a simple park setting with a tree, a couple of birds looking curiously at the person, and a distant horizon suggesting a long wait ahead. The style is colorful and lighthearted, with playful exaggeration in the character''s expression and body language to emphasize impatience and concern about the time passing rather than the actual waiting moment.'),
 (862, 'Humor, Life', 'Laugh alone and the world thinks you''re an idiot.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a single person in the center, sitting on a park bench or at a café table. The person is laughing heartily all alone, maybe with their head thrown back and eyes closed in amusement. Around them, several other people nearby are looking at them with puzzled, confused, or slightly judgmental expressions, with some whispering to one another or raising eyebrows. The setting is light and casual, with a sunny day and simple background such as trees, a lamppost, or café chairs to keep it relatable. A visible thought bubble above the laughing person shows a little cartoon world to symbolize ''the world thinks.'' The overall tone is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the social awkwardness of laughing alone in public without any indication of the person being self-conscious or lonely.'),
 (863, 'Humor, Life', 'Life is too short to waste time matching socks.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing in front of an open laundry basket overflowing with colorful, mismatched socks. The person, wearing casual home clothes, has a relaxed, carefree expression and is tossing one sock over their shoulder. Around them, socks of various bright colors and patterns are scattered on the floor and some even float in the air, emphasizing the chaotic mismatch. The background is a cozy, simple laundry room with a washing machine and a clothesline. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, highlighting the theme of not stressing over matching socks and enjoying life.'),
 (864, 'Humor, Life', 'Lord give me patience......but hurry!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person kneeling with clasped hands in a classic prayer pose, eyes closed, and a slightly impatient expression on their face. Above their head, a speech bubble reads, "Lord give me patience......but hurry!" The setting is simple, like a cozy living room with a small table nearby holding a clock with its hands spinning fast, emphasizing the urgency. The person’s exaggerated facial expression, with raised eyebrows and a slightly open mouth, conveys a mix of earnestness and impatience. The overall style is clean, bright, and lighthearted with rounded lines and soft colors, emphasizing the comedic and relatable tone of the joke without any religious symbols or darker tones.'),
 (865, 'Humor, Life', 'Monday is a terrible way to spend 1/7 of your life.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at an office desk looking tired and miserable with a calendar prominently displayed that shows Monday circled in red. The background is an exaggeratedly gloomy Monday morning office setting with a clock showing early morning time, a coffee mug labeled ''Survival Juice'', and a stack of paperwork towering over the person. On the wall behind, a large poster humorously displays ''1/7 of life spent here!'' with a sad face emoji. The person slouches in their chair, wearing messy hair and wrinkled clothes, clearly dreading the start of the week. The overall tone is lighthearted and slightly exaggerated to emphasize the universal dread of Mondays.'),
 (866, 'Humor, Life', 'Money can''t buy happiness...But it sure makes misery easier to live with.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting on a simple wooden bench looking somewhat gloomy or stressed. The setting is a park with green grass and a few trees in the background. Next to the person on the bench is a big, overflowing bag labeled with a dollar sign ($), brimming with money such as cash and coins spilling out slightly. The person is holding a cup of coffee in one hand, with a small smile suggesting a slight comfort despite the misery. Above the scene, a thought bubble shows a happy face crossed out and replaced with a money bag, indicating the conflict between happiness and money. The colors should be bright and cheerful to contrast the person''s mixed emotions, and the overall style is lighthearted with exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing irony rather than sadness or despair.'),
 (867, 'Humor, Life', 'My mind''s made up . . . don''t confuse me with facts.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cartoon character standing stubbornly with arms crossed and a determined, slightly annoyed expression. Their eyebrows are furrowed and mouth is set in a firm line. Around their head are thought bubbles with scribbled question marks and simple symbols representing confusion or contradiction, like a light bulb with a big red ''X'' over it, or question marks. In the background, a friendly cartoon figure labeled ''Facts'' is holding out an open book or paper towards the main character, trying to get their attention. The scene is lighthearted and colorful, using soft lines and exaggerated facial expressions to show the clash between stubbornness and reason without any hostility. The setting can be simple, like a plain room or outdoor park, making the characters and their interaction the focus. The overall tone is playful, illustrating the mental image of someone refusing to change their mind despite clear evidence or logic presented to them.'),
 (868, 'Humor, Life', 'Never mistake endurance for hospitality.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cozy living room. A tired but polite guest, wearing casual clothes and holding a small suitcase, is sitting on a shabby-looking couch that’s clearly past its prime. Their facial expression shows exhaustion mixed with awkward politeness. Across from them, a weary but welcoming host stands near the door, smiling awkwardly while holding a tray with a barely half-full teacup and a lone cookie. The host’s home looks a bit crowded, with mismatched furniture and visible signs that the guest has been there a long time (maybe a pair of slippers on the floor, a sleep mask on the coffee table). A small clock on the wall shows late evening time. The overall vibe implies the guest is enduring a lengthy stay rather than feeling genuinely welcome, capturing the joke’s essence about confusing endurance with true hospitality. The art style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, focusing on exaggerated expressions and cozy but slightly tired atmosphere without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (869, 'Humor, Life', 'Never test the depth of the water with both feet.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at the edge of a small pond or river, looking hesitant and worried. The person has one foot confidently stepping into the water while holding a shoe in their hand, and the other foot is kicking backward, already submerged and splashing water dramatically. Their facial expression should be wide-eyed and panicked, as if they''ve just realized the water is unexpectedly deep. Around them, include reeds, a few fish peeking out, and maybe a surprised frog on a rock. The background is a bright outdoor setting with a sunny sky and trees. Emphasize the splash and water depth to highlight the joke''s message about the dangers of testing water depth with both feet. Use a colorful, playful cartoon style with exaggerated expressions and motion lines for comedic effect.'),
 (870, 'Humor, Life', 'No good deed goes unpunished.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy neighborhood park. In the center, a well-meaning character wearing a friendly smile is handing a small gift—like a flower or a sandwich—to another character, who looks slightly surprised but grateful. However, just as the giver turns away, a series of comic mishaps occur: the gift unexpectedly springs to life or causes a minor chaos, like a bee buzzing out from the flower or sandwich crumbs attracting a swarm of ants, leading the giver to accidentally trip or get tangled. The background shows other cartoonish onlookers with exaggerated expressions of shock or amusement. The overall vibe is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the ironic twist of "no good deed goes unpunished." Include speech bubbles or small visual cues (like cartoon stars around a head or tiny flies) to enhance the humor without any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (871, 'Humor, Life', 'No matter what goes wrong, there is always somebody who knew it would.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a chaotic office or family living room where things are clearly going wrong: a spilled cup of coffee on a laptop, papers flying in the air, a broken lamp, and a frazzled person looking surprised and upset. Meanwhile, in the background or off to the side, another character is smirking knowingly with crossed arms or a finger to their temple, as if they predicted the disaster all along. The setting should be colorful and exaggerated in style, emphasizing the contrast between the chaos and the calm person who ''knew it would happen.'' Include small humorous details like a calendar with the word ''Disaster Day'' marked or a wall clock running backward, reinforcing the inevitability theme. The overall tone should be light, funny, and relatable, capturing the idea that there''s always someone who anticipated the problem.'),
 (872, 'Humor, Life', 'Nothing is so smiple that it can''t get screwed up.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person confidently holding a simple, basic object—like a plain wooden chair—looking proud and ready to complete a straightforward task. Nearby, another character, looking confused and overwhelmed, is trying to assemble the chair but has screws scattered everywhere, some falling to the floor and others stuck in wrong places. The chair is partially assembled but clearly messed up, with legs crooked or backrest tilted. The background is a typical living room or workshop setting with a toolbox open on a table, and a small sign or thought bubble above the confused character saying, ''How did this get so complicated?'' The overall tone should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the irony that even the simplest things can be complicated to mess up.'),
 (873, 'Humor, Life', 'Nothing will dispel enthusiasm like a small admission fee.', NULL, 'A cheerful person stands at the entrance of a small event or festival with a big, excited smile, eagerly holding a ticket in hand. Just in front of them is a friendly but slightly awkward attendant at a tiny booth, holding up a hand to indicate a small admission fee, with a price sign reading ''$1 Admission'' clearly visible. Behind the attendee, the excited crowd’s smiles quickly fade to confused or disappointed expressions as they realize they have to pay. The scene should be drawn in bright, colorful, cartoon style with exaggerated facial expressions showing enthusiasm turning into mild dismay. Include balloons or festive decorations in the background to emphasize the initial excitement of the event. The overall vibe is humorous and lighthearted without any negativity.'),
 (874, 'Humor, Life', 'Nothing''s impossible for those who don''t have to do it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side. One character looks confident and relaxed, leaning against a wall with a satisfied smile, arms crossed. This character has a thought bubble that depicts an impossible task, like juggling flaming swords, or walking on water, illustrated clearly but in an exaggerated, silly way. The other character is scrubbing a giant, dirty pile of dishes or struggling to carry a heavy box, looking exhausted and stressed. Both characters are in a simple domestic setting such as a kitchen or backyard, with everyday objects like a sink, dishes, boxes, and household furniture visible. The overall tone is lighthearted and comedic, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the contrast between ''not doing'' a task versus the difficulty of ''doing'' it.'),
 (875, 'Humor, Life', 'Oh, no! Not another learning experience!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated, overwhelmed character sitting at a desk cluttered with books, papers, and a computer, indicating they''re in the middle of studying or working. The character has a stressed expression and is holding their head with one hand while looking at an open book or a laptop screen with a speech bubble above them saying: ''Oh, no! Not another learning experience!'' In the background, there are motivational posters and a coffee mug with steam rising. The overall style is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the comic frustration of facing continuous challenges or lessons.'),
 (876, 'Humor, Life', 'Some days you are the bug, other days you are the windshield.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a car speeding down a road with a large bug hitting its windshield. The bug looks surprised, its eyes wide open and legs spread out as if squished against the glass. On the other side of the scene, the same bug is depicted on a day when it’s the one driving a tiny bug-sized car, confidently crashing into a huge windshield-shaped wall labeled ''windshield.'' The background is simple with a sunny sky and a road, emphasizing the contrast between the bug being smashed and the bug doing the smashing. The art style is light-hearted, with exaggerated facial expressions on the bug and the car being cartoonish and fun, no violence or harm depicted, just comically illustrating the phrase ''some days you are the bug, other days you are the windshield.'''),
 (877, 'Humor, Life', 'Thank you for your attention. We now return to regular programming.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a vintage black-and-white TV set with rabbit ear antennas in the center. The TV screen displays the text ''Thank you for your attention. We now return to regular programming.'' The background is a cozy living room setting with colorful, slightly exaggerated furniture such as a comfy armchair, a side table with a lamp, and a curious cat or dog watching the TV. The overall mood is lighthearted and amusing, emphasizing the sudden transition from something important back to normal everyday TV shows. The style is simple and playful with expressive characters and slightly exaggerated proportions to bring out the comic effect of the announcement.'),
 (878, 'Humor, Life', 'The amount of sleep required by the average person is just five minutes more.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sleepy person trying to measure their sleep with a giant, exaggerated analog clock. The person, looking tired and disheveled with messy hair and pajamas, is lying in bed but has one eye slightly open, holding a giant alarm clock that clearly shows 5 minutes past an hour. The background depicts a cozy bedroom setting with a bedside table holding a lamp, a cup of coffee, and an eyelid-shaped pillow. A calendar on the wall humorously shows days passing by quickly, emphasizing the minimal sleep time. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with soft colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the ridiculousness of needing ''just five minutes more'' of sleep. The humor focuses on the universal feeling of always wanting more sleep, despite how impossible that often is.'),
 (879, 'Humor, Life', 'The first three minutes of your life can be dangerous ... The last three can be pretty dodgy too!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a baby in a crib on the left side, looking freshly born with a surprised face, surrounded by three large, ticking clocks labeled ''First 3 minutes.'' On the right side, an elderly person with a mischievous smile is sitting in an armchair, wrapped in a blanket, with another set of three clocks labeled ''Last 3 minutes.'' Both sides are separated by a big, central clock with exaggerated, oversized hands. The background is light and cheerful with soft pastel colors. The baby wears a little bonnet and has a slightly frazzled look, while the elderly person looks relaxed but cheeky, holding a cup of tea. The style is playful, with exaggerated expressions and cartoonish lines to emphasize the humor about the potential dangers at the very beginning and end of life. No scary or dark imagery, just lighthearted and funny.'),
 (880, 'Humor, Life, Marriage Humor', 'My wife isn''t talking to me. The funny part is - she thinks she''s punishing me!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a husband and wife in a living room. The wife is sitting comfortably on a couch with her arms crossed and a slight smirk, clearly silent but feeling victorious. The husband stands nearby looking confused and slightly worried, scratching his head or shrugging with a puzzled expression. Show a small comic bubble above the wife''s head with a light bulb to indicate she thinks she''s clever, and a small speech bubble near the husband with a question mark to show his confusion. Around them, objects like a TV, a coffee table with a remote and a cup, and light colors add a cozy home atmosphere. The style is simple and friendly, emphasizing the humor in the silent ''punishment.'' No aggressive or violent imagery, just a funny domestic scenario.'),
 (881, 'Humor, Life, Mental Health Humor', 'There is a fine line between ''hobby'' and ''mental illness.''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person enthusiastically engaging in an unusual hobby that looks a bit eccentric. The person could be surrounded by an exaggeratedly cluttered workspace filled with quirky and odd items—like stacks of colorful, oddly shaped crafts, strange gadgets, wild plants, or piles of notes. The person wears a big, enthusiastic smile and holds a magnifying glass or a whimsical tool, clearly obsessed with their hobby. Nearby, a friend or family member looks on with a mix of amusement and bewilderment, maybe scratching their head or giving a hesitant thumbs-up. The background should be a cozy room or garage filled with creative chaos, highlighting the fine line between passion and eccentricity in a light-hearted, non-offensive way. Use bright, cheerful colors and expressive, cartoon-style characters to enhance the humor without suggesting anything negative or harmful.'),
 (882, 'Humor, Life, Money Humor', 'Shopper''s bumper sticker: Broke but not broken.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the rear end of a car with a large, colorful bumper sticker that reads ''Broke but not broken.'' Around the car, depict a cheerful shopper standing next to some shopping bags, looking optimistic despite an empty wallet visible in their hand or pocket. The background can be a simple parking lot outside a shopping mall with a few other cars and shoppers for context. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions on the shopper to highlight determination and good spirit despite financial strain. Include small humorous details like a cartoon wallet with a sad face or coins escaping from it, and maybe a few funny price tags floating around the bags to emphasize the ''broke'' theme without sadness.'),
 (883, 'Humor, Life, Motivational', 'Love like you''ve never been hurt, dance like nobody is watching, sing like nobody is listening and live like heaven on earth.', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene set in a bright, open meadow under a sunny sky with fluffy clouds. In the center, a joyful person is dancing freely with eyes closed and a big smile, wearing casual, colorful clothes. Around them, musical notes float in the air to show singing, while a small audience of diverse cartoon characters (animals and people) nearby look either playfully distracted or genuinely happy but not directly watching the dancer. In the background, a peaceful idyllic landscape with a few birds flying and flowers blooming suggests a ''heaven on earth'' vibe. The overall mood is lighthearted, carefree, and uplifting, with soft pastel colors and exaggerated happy expressions for humor and positivity.'),
 (884, 'Humor, Life, Motivational', 'Strive always for your goals, but choose those goals with care. Every choice has a cost, and balance is the key.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a cheerful character standing on a tightrope stretched across a canyon. The character is wearing a determined expression and holding a balancing pole labeled ''Balance.'' On one side of the canyon is a treasure chest labeled ''Goals,'' glowing and enticing, while on the other side is a giant weight marked ''Costs.'' Below the tightrope are fluffy clouds and a bright, sunny sky. The scene emphasizes the theme of carefully balancing ambitions versus consequences in a lighthearted way, with exaggerated expressions and playful colors to keep the tone fun and positive.'),
 (885, 'Humor, Life, Motivational', 'The time is right to make new friends.', NULL, 'A cheerful, colorful cartoon scene showing a friendly clock character with a big smiling face and arms, pointing at its watch face which displays the time as exactly 12:00. Surrounding the clock are diverse, happy cartoon characters representing different people—some waving, some shaking hands. The background is bright and welcoming, perhaps with a park setting including benches, trees, and flowers to suggest a social, pleasant atmosphere. The overall mood is upbeat and inviting, emphasizing the idea that now is a perfect moment to start new friendships. The style is simple, rounded, and playful, suitable for a lighthearted, humorous cartoon.'),
 (886, 'Humor, Life, Motivational', 'Things turn out best for people who make the best of the way things turn out.', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene with a smiling person standing at a crossroads in a simple countryside setting. The crossroads has two signposts: one pointing left labeled ''Plan A'' and the other pointing right labeled ''Plan B.'' The person is wearing casual clothes, has a positive expression, and is shrugging with open arms as if saying, ''Oh well!'' Around them are bright green grass, a few flowers, and a blue sky with fluffy clouds. In the background, a winding path continues beyond the signs, symbolizing the journey ahead regardless of the choice made. The overall tone is lighthearted and optimistic, drawn in a colorful, humorous cartoon style to emphasize making the best of whatever happens.'),
 (887, 'Humor, Life, Motivational', 'Unless you try to do something beyond what you have already mastered, you will never grow.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at the edge of a small cliff or stepping off a diving board labeled ''Comfort Zone.'' Behind them are various trophies and certificates on a shelf labeled ''What I Have Mastered.'' The person looks hesitant but determined, dressed in casual clothes with a small backpack labeled ''Growth.'' In the background, a bright sun is rising, symbolizing new opportunities. Nearby, a friendly cartoon character (a wise owl wearing glasses) points encouragingly toward a path leading uphill labeled ''New Challenges.'' The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to convey cautious optimism and the idea of stepping beyond familiar limits to grow.'),
 (888, 'Humor, Life, Motivational', 'What you can be is more important than what you have been.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a cozy living room setting. On the left, a slightly scruffy but cheerful person is proudly looking forward, wearing casual, slightly mismatched clothes and holding a medal labeled ''Future Potential.'' On the right, a dusty old photo frame sits on a small table, featuring the same person but looking tired and worn out, wearing outdated clothes. Between them floats a large, glowing speech bubble stating, ''What you can be is more important than what you have been.'' The background includes a comfy armchair, a small bookshelf with a few quirky books, and a potted plant. The style is colorful and exaggerated with big eyes and expressive faces to highlight the hopeful, forward-looking humor of the message.'),
 (1713, 'Humor, Life, Motivational, Quotes', 'Get busy livin'' or get busy dyin''.', 'Shawshank Redemption', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a lively, energetic character on the left side energetically jumping out of bed, surrounded by bright sunlight, birds chirping outside the window, and an alarm clock ringing with motion lines. On the right side, a contrasting character slouched on a couch looking tired, grayish, and holding a TV remote with a thought bubble showing a snooze button. Between them, a big, bold caption saying "Get busy livin'' or get busy dyin''" in fun, exaggerated lettering. The background is split into two: vibrant colors with sun and nature on the left, and dull, muted colors with dark clouds and a wilted plant on the right. The style is bright, exaggerated cartoon with clear comedic expression on the characters’ faces to emphasize the choice between an active life or passive lethargy. No violence or negativity, just a playful presentation of the phrase as a humorous life decision dilemma.'),
 (2166, 'Humor, Life, Motivational, Quotes', 'Obstacles are those frightening things you see when you take your eyes off your goal.', 'Henry Ford', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a determined person jogging toward a shining, glowing trophy labeled ''Goal'' in the distance. The runner has big focused eyes looking straight ahead at the trophy. Behind and around the runner are exaggerated, comical obstacles like large cartoonish rocks, cones, puddles, and banana peels, all looking scary or menacing but ignored by the runner because their eyes are fixed on the goal. The runner’s body language shows concentration and determination. The background is bright and simple, with a clear path toward the trophy but cluttered with obstacles only visible behind or beside the runner, emphasizing that they appear only when the runner looks away. The style is colorful and light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions and shapes for comedic effect, making the obstacles look silly rather than dangerous.'),
 (2413, 'Humor, Life, Motivational, Quotes', 'There are no shortcuts to any place worth going.', 'Beverly Sills', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person traveling on a winding path up a scenic mountain. The path has many twists, turns, and small obstacles like rocks and tree roots, emphasizing the difficulty and length of the journey. The traveler, a cheerful and slightly determined character with a backpack and walking stick, pauses to look at a whimsical signpost that reads "No Shortcuts" with a smiling sun and birds around. In the background, there is a peak with a shining flag labeled "Worth Going" symbolizing the successful destination. The sky is bright and clear with a few fluffy clouds. The overall style should be playful and light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions and cartoonish nature elements to reinforce the idea that the journey, while challenging, is rewarding and fun.'),
 (2853, 'Humor, Life, Motivational, Unknown', 'Faith makes all things possible, not easy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a steep, rocky mountain path. At the bottom, a cheerful character wearing hiking gear looks up with a hopeful smile, clutching a walking stick. Above them, a large, whimsical sign reads "Faith Makes All Things Possible" with an arrow pointing up the mountain. The path is shown as rugged and difficult, with exaggerated obstacles like big boulders, slippery rocks, and tangled roots. Further up, the same character is depicted struggling, slipping, or sweating, yet still determined to climb. The sky above is bright and sunny, emphasizing optimism despite the challenge. The scene uses bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the contrast between hopeful faith and the reality of difficulty, in a light, non-threatening way. No harsh elements or negativity.'),
 (2019, 'Humor, Life, Optimism Humor, Quotes', 'Just because something doesn''t do what you planned it to do doesn''t mean it''s useless.', 'Thomas Edison', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene where a person is holding a bizarre invention that looks quirky and oddly put together. The invention could be a small, whimsical machine with blinking lights, gears, and antennas that is clearly not working as intended - for example, a toaster with a spray nozzle shooting water instead of popping out toast. The person wears a puzzled but optimistic expression, shrugging their shoulders. Around them, other people nearby look confused or amused, maybe pointing or scratching their heads. Include a sign or thought bubble with the phrase: ''Just because it doesn''t do what you planned doesn''t mean it''s useless.'' The background should be light and playful, with simple lab or workshop tools scattered around, like a wrench, blueprint, and gears. The overall style should be colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing the lighthearted and positive twist on failure and creativity.'),
 (889, 'Humor, Life, Parenting', 'Insanity is hereditary. You get it from your kids.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a tired-looking parent sitting on a couch with messy hair and dark circles under their eyes. Around them are three energetic children causing chaos: one child is jumping on the couch, another is drawing on the wall, and the third is yelling with a toy drum. The parent holds a cup of coffee, looking overwhelmed but resigned, with a speech bubble above reading, ''Insanity is hereditary. You get it from your kids.'' The room is messy with scattered toys, spilled juice, and a small family photo on a side table showing the same parent and kids all smiling peacefully, contrasting the current chaos. The overall art style is lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated to enhance the humor without any negativity or violence.'),
 (890, 'Humor, Life, Pessimistic', 'In a society of victims, nothing is anybody''s fault.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a courtroom without a judge or jury. Instead of people, there are exaggerated personifications of ''Victim'' characters scattered around, each looking overly dramatic with big, sad eyes and theatrical poses. The courtroom sign above reads ''Blame Court''. There are speech bubbles above the characters saying things like ''It''s not my fault!'' and ''Who could be to blame?'' In the center, there’s an empty spotlight or podium with a large question mark hovering above it, symbolizing no one is taking responsibility. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated with bright colors, clear outlines, and comical expressions to emphasize the irony of the situation. The background can include typical courtroom features like benches, a judge''s stand without anyone sitting, and scales of justice hanging crookedly, to reinforce the setting humorously.'),
 (891, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'It is better to die on your feet than to live on your knees.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with a character standing tall and proud on two upright legs, looking confident and heroic. Opposite them, show a comical character exaggeratedly living on their knees, perhaps wearing slippers and looking a bit lazy or timid. The scene should be simple, with a plain background and no violent or negative elements. Add a small speech bubble near the standing character with the quote: ''Better to die on your feet than live on your knees.'' The overall style should be lighthearted and fun, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the contrast between standing tall and living on knees.'),
 (892, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'It is easier to fight for one''s principles than to live up to them.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing proudly on a soapbox or small pedestal labeled ''Principles,'' holding a megaphone and passionately speaking to a small audience. The speaker looks confident, with an exaggerated determined expression. Next to them, show the same person struggling to carry a large, heavy sack labeled ''Living Up to Principles,'' visibly exhausted and sweating, trying to move forward. The setting is a simple park or street corner, with a few amused or confused onlookers observing both versions of the person. Use bright colors and caricature-style features to emphasize the contrast between the ease of fighting for principles versus the difficulty of living them. Avoid any violent, sexual, or political imagery; focus on the humorous struggle and irony of the situation.'),
 (893, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'It''s pretty hard to tell what does bring happiness; poverty and wealth have both failed.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting on opposite sides of a seesaw. One character is dressed in ragged clothes, holding a small pile of coins, looking confused but hopeful. The other character is wearing a fancy suit with a big bag of money, also looking puzzled and a bit frustrated. Above them, a whimsical thought cloud contains a simple smiley face symbol representing happiness, but it is floating just out of reach. The background is a sunny park with colorful trees, and some birds perched on the seesaw, adding to the lighthearted mood. The overall style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated, with friendly expressions on both characters emphasizing the joke that neither poverty nor wealth clearly brings happiness.'),
 (894, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'It''s sweet to be remembered, but it''s often cheaper to be forgotten.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing two characters at a birthday party. One character is holding a gift and smiling happily, surrounded by brightly colored balloons and a ''Happy Birthday'' banner. The other character stands off to the side looking a bit puzzled or blank, symbolizing being forgotten. Nearby is a table with a modest cake and a donation jar labeled ''Forget-Me-Not Fund'' with only a few coins inside, emphasizing the idea that being remembered often comes at a cost, while being forgotten might be ''cheaper.'' The setting is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humorous contrast between being sweetly remembered and the cost associated with it, all in a clean and friendly cartoon style.'),
 (895, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'Jealousy is all the fun you think they have.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side. One character is looking at the other with a greenish tint to their face and exaggeratedly large eyes filled with envy, possibly with tiny cartoon steam puffs or scribbles above their head to show jealousy. The other character is smiling widely and appears to be enjoying a fun activity, like eating a large ice cream cone or playing a party horn, surrounded by confetti to suggest they''re having a great time. The background is simple and cheerful, like a bright park or a casual party setting with balloons or streamers. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with rounded features and expressive faces to emphasize the humor and emotion without any violence or negativity.'),
 (896, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'Life is uncertain. Eat dessert first.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person sitting at a dining table with a fancy dinner setting (silverware, plate, napkin), but instead of the main course, the person is eagerly eating a big, colorful, delicious-looking dessert, like a slice of cake with bright icing and a cherry on top. The person has a wide smile and looks very satisfied. In the background, there is a clock showing time passing quickly, and a thought bubble above the person’s head with the words "Life is uncertain. Eat dessert first." The setting is cozy, with warm lighting and perhaps a window showing a sunny day outside to add a positive vibe. The cartoon style should be lighthearted, simple, and whimsical, and the scene emphasizes the playful idea of prioritizing dessert over the main meal in life.'),
 (897, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'Life isn''t fair, but neither is death.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a large, old-fashioned balance scale outdoors. On one side of the scale is a smiling, happy sun labeled ''Life,'' which is clearly lighter and higher up. On the other side is a grumpy-looking, dark cloud labeled ''Death,'' weighing heavier and lower. The person stands in the middle, wearing casual clothes, shrugging with an amused but resigned expression. Around the person are simple background elements like grass, a tree, and a few flowers to create a peaceful park-like setting. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the unfairness yet acceptance of both concepts.'),
 (898, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'No individual raindrop ever considers itself responsible for the flood.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, overflowing river or flooded street with lots of water. In the foreground, several cute, small raindrops with simple round shapes and expressive faces look oblivious and innocent, shrugging their ''arms'' or looking confused as if saying ''Not me!''. Some raindrops are mid-fall from a cloudy sky, others are already splashing into the flood below. The floodwater has little waves and maybe a floating rubber duck or a small boat to emphasize the size of the flood. The background could include houses or trees partially submerged to show the severity of the flood, but the raindrops themselves appear unaware or detached from the big problem. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, like a playful indictment of personal responsibility in a collective problem.'),
 (899, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'Not one shred of evidence supports the notion that life is serious.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene depicting a happy-go-lucky character walking through life on a sunny day. The character is smiling broadly, wearing casual, colorful clothes and sunglasses, with arms spread wide as if embracing the world. Around them, everyday life items—like a briefcase, a clock, a stack of papers, and a smartphone—are floating gently as if weightless or cartoonishly light, emphasizing the lightheartedness. Nearby, a serious-looking statue of Lady Justice holds scales, but the scales are humorously unbalanced with feathers and confetti instead of weights. In the background, a path winds through various simple signs that read ''Work,'' ''Bills,'' ''Deadlines,'' but these signs are playful and tilted, some with smiley faces drawn on. The overall tone is bright and cheerful, with exaggerated cartoon features and soft colors, highlighting the joke’s message that life should not be taken seriously at all.'),
 (900, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'Nothing is ever accomplished by a reasonable man.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side. On the left is a ''reasonable man'' depicted as very calm and proper, wearing a suit and glasses, holding a clipboard with checkmarks and a list titled ''Accomplishments.'' He looks mild and organized but somewhat bored. On the right is an ''unreasonable man,'' wild-eyed, with messy clothes and hair, holding a hammer and a paintbrush, energetically working on building or painting a crazy, odd-looking invention or project that is clearly unconventional and chaotic. Around them are tools, blueprints, and half-finished crazy inventions scattered about. The background shows a workshop or creative studio with a sense of lively chaos versus dull order. The style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between the dull, ''reasonable'' guy who gets nothing done and the messy, spirited ''unreasonable'' guy who creates wildly. Neither character is aggressive or violent—just a humorous contrast of personalities and productivity.'),
 (901, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy', 'People can be divided into three groups: those who make things happen, those who watch things happen and those who wonder what happened.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene divided into three distinct panels arranged horizontally. The first panel shows an active, energetic character confidently assembling a large, whimsical machine with tools in hand, surrounded by gears and bolts flying. The second panel illustrates a relaxed character casually sitting on a bench or chair, watching the first character work with a curious but passive expression, perhaps holding popcorn or a drink. The third panel features a confused character scratching their head with a thought bubble showing a swirling question mark, looking bewildered while the machine in the first panel is suddenly erupting in chaotic steam and sparks. The style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the personalities and contrasting attitudes, with clear labels above each panel: ''Make Things Happen,'' ''Watch Things Happen,'' and ''Wonder What Happened.'' No background distractions, just simple props like tools, a bench, popcorn, and the eccentric machine to keep focus on the characters and their actions.'),
 (902, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'Remember: No matter where you go, there you are.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing cheerfully in the middle of a variety of different, exaggerated, and contrasting locations all cramped together in one picture. For example, the left side features a tropical beach with a palm tree, the right side shows a snowy mountain peak, behind them is a city skyline with tall buildings, and in front a desert with a cactus. The person stands centered with a confident and slightly amused expression, pointing to themselves as if reminding the viewer of their presence amid all these places. The background can be whimsically split or blended to emphasize the variety of locations. Use bright colors and exaggerated features for each setting, with clear labels or simple iconic items (like a sun with sunglasses on the beach, a penguin in the snowy part, skyscrapers in the city, and a cartoon cactus in the desert). The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, capturing the philosophical joke that no matter where you go, you are always there.'),
 (903, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'The past is just a memory and the future is a guess. The point where they meet is the present, and it is the only place you exist.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at the intersection of two winding roads labeled ''Past'' and ''Future.'' The road labeled ''Past'' fades into a cloudy, misty memory bubble with faint images of clocks and old photographs. The road labeled ''Future'' disappears into a foggy question mark-shaped cloud filled with question marks and crystal balls. At the crossroads where these two roads meet, the person stands on a small brightly lit platform labeled ''Present,'' looking puzzled but content. Around the person, show floating icons representing time like hourglasses, calendars, and clocks, but all with a playful, exaggerated cartoon style. The whole scene should be lighthearted and whimsical, with soft colors and simple shapes emphasizing the abstract concept of time in a fun way.'),
 (904, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'The trouble with life is, you''re half way through it before you realize it''s a ''do it yourself'' thing.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a middle-aged person standing at a literal half-way point on a long, winding path labeled ''Life Journey.'' The character looks puzzled, holding an oversized instruction manual titled ''How to Live Your Life'' with a big question mark on the cover. Around the character, various life-related objects can be seen scattered: a toolbox with tools labeled ''choices,'' ''decisions,'' and ''effort,'' a calendar half-filled, a clock showing mid-day, and DIY project signs such as ''Build Your Dreams'' and ''Fix Your Future.'' The background should be bright and friendly, with whimsical elements like clouds shaped like light bulbs and thought bubbles. Everything should be drawn in a playful cartoon style with exaggerated expressions conveying surprise and realization. No violence or sensitive content, just a lighthearted and motivational tone emphasizing the idea of life being a self-driven project half-discovered too late.'),
 (1528, 'Humor, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Ambition is a poor excuse for not having sense enough to be lazy.', 'Charlie McCarthy', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person lounging comfortably in an oversized, fluffy armchair with a relaxed, smug expression. They are surrounded by snacks, a soft blanket, and a lazy cat napping on their lap. Behind them is a large window revealing a bright, sunny day with a jogging person visible outside, looking tired and energetic. The lounging person holds a cup of coffee or tea with a little thought bubble showing a motivational poster labeled ''Ambition'' crossed out, while a sign nearby reads: ''Pro laziness society.'' The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing comfort and laziness contrasted with ambition represented by the jogger outside. The setting should be indoors, cozy, with warm colors to underscore the humor about choosing laziness over ambition, drawing a visual pun on the idea that ambition is just an excuse to avoid being lazy.'),
 (905, 'Humor, Life, Programming', 'The fastest algorithm can freqently be replaced by one that is almost as fast and much easier to understand.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple office or study room. On one side, a stressed-out programmer or computer scientist is sitting at a desk cluttered with complex code printouts, a coffee cup, and a laptop displaying tangled, hard-to-read code labeled ''Fastest Algorithm.'' They look frustrated and overwhelmed. On the other side, a relaxed, cheerful character holds a neatly organized, much simpler flowchart or code labeled ''Almost as Fast Algorithm,'' smiling confidently. The two characters face each other, highlighting the contrast between complexity and simplicity. The background has math symbols and algorithm diagrams floating whimsically in the air. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the struggle with complexity versus ease of understanding. Keep the colors bright and friendly, avoiding any technical jargon on screen other than the simple labels.'),
 (906, 'Humor, Life, Psychology Humor', 'On average, people fear spiders more than they do death.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person sitting comfortably on a couch with a terrified expression, staring wide-eyed at a large, friendly-looking cartoon spider perched innocently on the armrest. The spider should have big, exaggerated eyes and a slight smile, appearing harmless and even a bit cute. In the background, a shadowy, cartoon-style grim reaper figure stands quietly behind the person, looking calm and non-threatening, holding a scythe lowered to the ground. The person’s gaze is firmly fixed on the spider rather than the grim reaper. The setting is a simple living room with a picture frame on the wall showing a little calendar page with the phrase ''On average...'' written on it, referencing the joke. Use bright colors and clean lines to emphasize the playful and lighthearted mood of the scene.'),
 (1688, 'Humor, Life, Quotes', 'Experience is that marvelous thing that enables you to recognize a mistake when you make it again.', 'F. P. Jones', 'A whimsical cartoon scene featuring a cheerful older character with a playful, slightly exaggerated expression of mild frustration and amusement. The character is scratching their head while standing next to a large, clearly labeled ''Mistake Log'' book sitting on a cluttered desk. On the desk is a large cup of coffee, a pair of round glasses, and a crumpled piece of paper. Behind the character is a wall with humorous framed certificates like ''Certified Expert in Mistakes'' and a calendar showing humorous dates crossed out. The background should be brightly colored and lighthearted, emphasizing a humorous take on learning from mistakes and the irony of repeating them. The overall tone is warm and cartoonish, with soft lines and exaggerated expressions to amplify the joke''s comedic effect.'),
 (2032, 'Humor, Life, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Laughter is the closest distance between two people.', 'Victor Borge', 'A cheerful, humorous cartoon scene featuring two people standing close together, both laughing heartily. They are surrounded by a bright, simple background with smiling cartoon faces floating around them to emphasize joy. Draw a playful, exaggerated measuring tape stretched between the two people, but instead of marking inches or centimeters, the tape is labeled ''Laughter'' and glows warmly. The characters should have exaggerated happy expressions with wide-open mouths and crinkled eyes. Include small comic lines or motion lines around their heads to show vigorous laughter. The scene should capture warmth, connection, and the humorous idea that laughter physically brings people closer in a lighthearted way.'),
 (1687, 'Humor, Life, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Experience is simply the name we give our mistakes.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful character standing proudly next to a large stack of oversized, comically labeled books titled ''Mistakes.'' The character wears casual clothes, maybe a lightbulb above their head to symbolize a bright idea or realization. The character''s expression is a confident smile, looking as if they''ve just learned an important lesson. Around them, there are scattered everyday objects that symbolize common mistakes, such as a spilled cup of coffee, a broken pencil, and a crumpled piece of paper. In the background, a simple chalkboard or sign reads the phrase: ''Experience is simply the name we give our mistakes.'' The overall style is light-hearted and friendly, with bright colors and exaggerated, cartoonish features to highlight the idea that mistakes are a natural and valuable part of learning.'),
 (1408, 'Humor, Life, Quotes, Wit', 'A good scare is better than good advice.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one giving advice and another reacting with a startled expression. The advisor is calm and friendly, holding a sign or a book labeled ''Advice.'' The other character is wide-eyed and jumping back in surprise, as if just frightened. Around them, include subtle spooky elements like a small ghost or a harmless creepy shadow in the background to suggest the ''scare'' part of the joke. The setting can be a simple living room or park bench to keep it casual. Emphasize exaggerated facial expressions to show that the scare is more impactful than the calm advice. The overall style should be lighthearted and fun, with bright colors and cartoonish proportions to highlight the humor without any threat or negativity.'),
 (2285, 'Humor, Life, Quotes, Word Play', 'The best remedy for a short temper is a long walk.', 'Jacqueline Schiff', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person with an obvious short temper—red face, steam coming out of their ears, furrowed eyebrows. They are standing at the edge of a small picturesque park or nature trail, about to set off on a long walk. Behind them is a short path labeled ''Short Temper Path'' with a tiny clock showing time passing quickly. In front is a winding, scenic path called ''Long Walk Trail'' that stretches far into the distance with trees, birds, and flowers alongside it. The character is putting on walking shoes and carrying a water bottle and a small backpack. The cartoon style should exaggerate the contrast between the angry expression and the calm, peaceful walking environment, emphasizing the idea that walking helps cool down a short temper with a lighthearted feel. Include a playful signpost showing ''Short Temper this way'' with a quick arrow backward and ''Long Walk that way'' pointing forward into the distance.'),
 (907, 'Humor, Life, Relatable', 'The only substitute for good manners is fast reflexes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people sitting at a dinner table. One person has just made a rude or awkward comment, and the other person is depicted with wide eyes and a quick motion blur on their hand as they rapidly move to catch a flying object (like a thrown napkin or a small food item) coming at them. The setting is a typical dining room with plates, utensils, and a centerpiece like a vase or candle. Include exaggerated facial expressions to show surprise and quick reaction, emphasizing the idea that fast reflexes are compensating for a lack of manners. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with clear, clean lines and playful exaggeration, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon strip or comic.'),
 (908, 'Humor, Life, Relatable', 'There comes a time when you should stop expecting other people to make a big deal about your birthday... around age 11.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a slightly awkward 11-year-old birthday kid standing in a modestly decorated living room. The kid looks mildly disappointed and holds a small, half-inflated balloon and a tiny cupcake with a single candle. Around the child, a few family members or friends stand casually, showing little excitement or attention toward the birthday. The decorations are simple: a small ''Happy Birthday'' banner that looks plain and a couple of sad-looking balloons floating at ceiling height. The background should suggest a normal home setting with a sofa, a table with minimal snacks, and a birthday card on the table. The overall mood is light and funny, capturing the moment where birthday expectations start to fizzle out at around age 11, making it a relatable and amusing scene without sadness or negativity.'),
 (909, 'Humor, Life, Relatable', 'Vital papers will demonstrate their vitality by moving from where you left them to where you can''t find them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cluttered home office or study room. On a wooden desk, a person looks puzzled and frustrated, searching through scattered papers and folders. Several sheets of paper are shown with cartoonish, lively arms and legs, tiptoeing or sneaking away from the desk toward a dark, mysterious corner or behind a couch. The papers have playful, expressive faces showing mischief and vitality, as if they are alive and deliberately hiding themselves. The room includes typical office objects such as a lamp, a computer, a cup of coffee, and a wastebasket. The lighting is warm and inviting, emphasizing the comical struggle of finding important documents that seem to have a mind of their own. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated with bright colors, appealing to a wide audience in a cartoon format.'),
 (910, 'Humor, Life, Relatable', 'We are born naked, wet and hungry.  Then things get worse.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a newborn baby lying on a changing table, looking a bit distressed. The baby is naked, with a little puddle of water around them to emphasize being wet, and a tiny milk bottle nearby to suggest hunger. Above the baby, a whimsical thought bubble shows a cartoonish downward spiral representing ''things getting worse,'' with funny mishaps: a diaper exploding, a crying toddler, spilled food, and messy toys. The background is a cozy nursery with pastel colors, a mobile hanging from the ceiling, and a tired-looking parent peeking in with a bemused expression. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated to capture the humor in the statement without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (911, 'Humor, Life, Relatable', 'What do you expect of a day that starts by getting out of bed?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a groggy person just waking up and reluctantly getting out of bed. The bedroom is a typical messy room with an unmade bed, a nightstand with a ringing alarm clock, and coffee mug on it. The person wears pajamas and slippers, rubbing their eyes with a tired, slightly annoyed expression. A calendar or wall clock shows early morning time. Around the character, subtle humorous details such as a sleepy, droopy-eyed pet (like a cat or dog) watching in sympathy, a slightly tilted picture frame, and an open window letting in bright sunlight exaggerate the idea of a difficult start to the day. The overall vibe is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the common experience of struggling with mornings that ''start by getting out of bed.'' The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and friendly, evoking relatable morning blues without negativity.'),
 (912, 'Humor, Life, Relatable', 'When I am right nobody remembers... When I am wrong nobody forgets!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in the middle with two thought bubbles above their head. One thought bubble to the left shows the person confidently giving a correct answer, but people around them are uninterested or distracted, looking away or checking their phones. The other thought bubble to the right shows the same person looking embarrassed or regretful after making a mistake, while a crowd around him points fingers, laughs, or holds up signs that say ''Never Forget!'' and ''Oops!''. The background is a simple setting like a park or office to keep focus on the characters. The person should be drawn in a lighthearted and relatable way, with exaggerated facial expressions for humor. Include diverse people in the crowd to represent bystanders. The style should be bright, colorful, and typical of friendly cartoon humor, without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (913, 'Humor, Life, Relatable Humor', 'The dream is the reward for finally getting to sleep.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tired person in bed surrounded by sleep-related items. The person looks exhausted but joyful, already half-asleep with a smile, snuggled under a cozy blanket with a pillow. Above them, a dream bubble floats, showing a shining golden trophy with the word ''Dream'' on it as if it were a grand prize. The background includes a simple bedroom setting with a nightstand holding a lamp and an alarm clock showing late night hours. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing relief and reward after a struggle to fall asleep without any intense or negative imagery.'),
 (3083, 'Humor, Life, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'If I had to do it all over again, I''d want to know WHY I had to do it all over again.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a cluttered desk with a large stack of papers, looking puzzled and scratching their head. A thought bubble above their head shows a smaller version of themselves replaying a confusing or boring task, symbolizing ''doing it all over again.'' The room has a clock showing time passing and a calendar on the wall flipped back to an earlier date. The overall mood is lighthearted confusion and mild frustration, with exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the irony of wanting to know the reason before repeating a task. The style is colorful and simple, with clean lines and playful exaggeration, suitable for a funny comic strip.'),
 (914, 'Humor, Life, Relatable, Steven Wright', 'When everything is coming your way, you''re in the wrong lane.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of a car on a two-lane road. The car is in the left lane, and multiple objects are flying or rolling directly toward the car from behind and ahead: a flying football, a rolling tire, a bouncing basketball, a dropped ice cream cone, and a paper airplane. The driver looks surprised and confused. On the right lane, another car calmly drives forward with no objects coming its way. The setting is a bright, simple countryside road with clear lane markings. The scene conveys the idea of ''everything coming your way'' but showing that the driver is in the wrong lane by visualizing all kinds of things headed toward them in traffic. The overall style should be lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and motion lines to show the incoming objects.'),
 (915, 'Humor, Life, Shopping Jokes', 'It''s easy to identify people who can''t count to ten. They''re always in front of you at the express checkout line.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene set in a supermarket checkout area. In the foreground, there is an express checkout lane clearly marked with a bright sign that reads ''Express Checkout: 10 Items or Less.'' In front of this lane, a cheerful cashier is scanning items. Standing just ahead of the line is a customer with a shopping cart overflowing with dozens of items, looking somewhat clueless or sheepish. Behind this customer, a frustrated or amused person waits with only a few items. The background includes other shoppers and grocery store shelves. The scene should be colorful and exaggerated in a humorous way, emphasizing the irony of the person who can’t count to ten blocking the express lane. The expressions on the characters'' faces and the visible quantity of items in the cart help deliver the punchline visually.'),
 (916, 'Humor, Life, Social Commentary', 'No matter what happens, somebody will find a way to take it too seriously.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a casual, lighthearted setting like a small gathering or a party where one person makes a playful joke or silly gesture. In the background, a second person is shown reacting with exaggerated seriousness—arms crossed, frowning deeply, perhaps wearing a suit and tie to exaggerate their overly serious demeanor. Other people around them are laughing or smiling relaxedly, highlighting the contrast. Add a speech bubble coming from the serious person with something like ''This is not a laughing matter,'' while the jokester has a cheerful expression. Include subtle details like a party banner, snacks on a table, and casual clothing on the majority of the people to enhance the lighthearted atmosphere. The overall tone is playful and friendly, without any aggression or negativity, emphasizing that someone always finds a reason to get overly serious about something that should be fun or minor.'),
 (917, 'Humor, Life, Technology Humor', 'Real Techs don''t have nice looking lawns. This is for the same reason they don''t have tans. Besides, why mow grass when it''s just going to grow out again?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a tech professional relaxing in a backyard. The lawn is wildly overgrown with tall, unruly grass and some weeds poking through. The tech person is sitting comfortably in a lawn chair with a laptop on their lap, wearing casual tech-style clothes like a hoodie and glasses, showing no concern for the messy lawn. Nearby, there is an old, unused lawnmower left forgotten, covered partly by the growing grass. In the background, a bright sun shines in the sky, but the tech person has very pale skin with no tan, emphasizing their indoor lifestyle. Small elements like a coffee mug with a tech logo and a Wi-Fi router or antenna on a nearby table add to the tech vibe. The overall scene is lighthearted and emphasizes a techie’s relaxed attitude towards traditional yard work and outdoor activities, drawn in bright colors with simple shapes and exaggerated features for comedic effect.'),
 (918, 'Humor, Life, Traffic Jokes', 'Making eye contact with another driver revokes your right of way.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a busy intersection with two cars stopped opposite each other. The drivers, a man in one car and a woman in the other, are exaggeratedly making intense eye contact through their windshields, each looking suspicious and determined. Small sweat drops or cartoonish tense expression lines emphasize their serious stares. Above their heads, a cartoonish ''Right of Way'' sign with a red crossed circle symbol appears, indicating it''s been ''revoked.'' Around the cars, other vehicles wait impatiently, with one driver tapping the steering wheel or honking lightly in frustration. The background shows typical street elements like traffic lights and crosswalks, but the focus remains on the staring drivers and the humorous moment of silent negotiation over who proceeds first. The style should be light, colorful, and playful, capturing the funny awkwardness of the situation without any aggression.'),
 (2795, 'Humor, Life, Unknown, Workplace', 'Don''t mistake activity for achievement.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in an office environment. One character is frantically busy, surrounded by piles of paperwork, multiple ringing phones, and a computer with dozens of open tabs, looking overwhelmed but active. The other character, calm and relaxed, is holding a single completed document labeled ''Achievement'' and pointing at it with a confident smile. The background features a whiteboard with a big checkmark under the word ''Success'' and sticky notes scattered around the frantic character''s desk labeled ''Busy Work.'' Include exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the difference between mere activity (busy but unproductive) and real achievement (calm and successful). Cartoon style with bright colors and clear, simple lines to emphasize the humor and contrast between the two states.'),
 (2906, 'Humor, Life, Unknown, Workplace', 'Hard work pays off in the future, laziness pays off now.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, show a tired but happy person working hard: they are wearing a sweatband, holding a shovel or briefcase, surrounded by symbols of effort like a clock showing late hours and stacks of papers or a small pile of coins growing into a treasure chest labeled ''Future Rewards.'' On the right side, depict a relaxed person lounging comfortably on a fluffy couch or hammock, wearing sunglasses, eating snacks, and watching TV or playing video games, with a big smile and a pile of money or treats piled up next to them labeled ''Immediate Rewards.'' Include bright colors, exaggerated facial expressions, and a lighthearted vibe with background details like a calendar flipping pages on the left and a clock showing daytime on the right to emphasize the contrast between future and now. The overall style should be cartoonish and playful, emphasizing the humor in choosing between hard work delayed gratification and laziness immediate gratification.'),
 (919, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'In general, people who have the most birthdays live the longest.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly person with a big, joyful smile surrounded by a large pile of birthday cakes stacked high like a tower. The person wears party hats of different colors and holds a calendar showing many marked birthdays. Around them, colorful balloons float, and confetti fills the air. The background could be a simple party room with a banner that reads "Happy Birthday!" emphasizing the idea of celebrating numerous birthdays. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to enhance the humor of ''having the most birthdays means living the longest.'''),
 (920, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Indecision is the key to flexibility.', NULL, 'A simple cartoon scene featuring a person standing at a crossroads with multiple signposts pointing in different directions. The person looks confused, scratching their head with a puzzled expression. Around them, several transparent thought bubbles show the person imagining different possible paths, each with humorous elements like a relaxing beach, a mountain hike, a cityscape, and a quiet home. In the background, a large key labeled ''Flexibility'' floats above the crossroads, glowing softly. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the theme of indecision leading to adaptability.'),
 (921, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Jaywalker: A person who walks when you are driving.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon street scene with a frustrated driver sitting in a small car at a red traffic light. The driver wears a puzzled or annoyed expression, clearly staring at a pedestrian confidently crossing the street outside the crosswalk, without paying attention to the traffic signals. The pedestrian is happily walking right in front of the car with a casual, oblivious smile. Include a traffic light showing red and a visible street sign or mark indicating a crosswalk nearby, to emphasize the jaywalking aspect. Add a cityscape background with simple buildings and other pedestrians waiting politely on the sidewalk. The style should be bright and colorful with exaggerated expressions to bring out the humor of a driver internally labeling the pedestrian as a "jaywalker" because they’re walking when the driver wants to go.'),
 (922, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Laugh, and the world laughs with you. Snore and you sleep alone.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two contrasting panels side by side. On the left panel, a cheerful character is laughing joyfully, surrounded by a crowd of smiling, laughing people who are all enjoying the moment together outdoors in a bright, sunny park. Everyone looks friendly and happy. On the right panel, the same character is lying in bed at night, snoring loudly with exaggerated Z’s floating above their head. The room is dimly lit by a small bedside lamp. Nearby, a partner or roommate is wide awake, looking annoyed and covering their ears with a pillow, highlighting the loneliness caused by snoring. The style is lighthearted and playful with expressive facial features and bold colors, emphasizing the humorous contrast between shared laughter and isolated snoring.'),
 (923, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Living on Earth is expensive, but it does include a free trip around the sun.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a smiling, cartoon-style Earth character wearing sunglasses and holding a suitcase labeled ''Life Journey.'' The Earth is standing on a small patch of grass, with a price tag hanging from its side showing a high cost in dollars. Beside the Earth, a friendly, cartoon Sun wearing a cheerful face and a sunhat is orbiting around the Earth, depicted by a dotted circular path with arrows indicating the orbit. Above the scene, include a playful banner that reads ''Living on Earth is expensive...'' and below, a caption reading ''...but it does include a free trip around the sun.'' The overall style should be bright, colorful, and lighthearted, emphasizing humor without any people or complex backgrounds, focusing on the personified Earth and Sun as main characters.'),
 (924, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Love is blind. And when you get married you get your eyesight back.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene shows a happy couple standing side by side. The husband is wearing thick, comically oversized glasses with lenses fogged up, looking surprised but relieved. The wife is playfully holding a giant pair of binoculars aimed at him. Above them is a heart-shaped speech bubble or banner with the phrase, “Love is blind. And when you get married you get your eyesight back.” The background is a simple cozy home setting with a window showing a sunny day outside. The couple''s expressions are lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the joke’s irony. The style is colorful, cheerful, and clearly cartoonish with soft outlines and exaggerated facial features to enhance the humor.'),
 (925, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Ole and Sven are on opposite sides of a river. Ole: How do I get to the other side of the river? Sven: You ARE on the other side of the river!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters, Ole and Sven, standing on opposite banks of a calm river. Ole, looking puzzled and scratching his head, is on the left side of the river, holding a walking stick and glancing toward Sven. Sven, on the right side of the river, is smiling and pointing at Ole''s side. Both men are dressed in simple Scandinavian-style clothing with sweaters and caps. The river runs horizontally across the middle of the image, clearly separating the two characters. The background includes a few trees and bushes on each riverbank, with a bright blue sky overhead. A small wooden sign next to Ole reads ''You ARE on the other side!'' in playful lettering to emphasize the joke. The overall tone is lighthearted and friendly, drawn in a colorful, exaggerated cartoon style with expressive faces to highlight the confusion and humor of the situation.'),
 (926, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'One big difference between men and women is that if a woman says ''Smell this'', it usually smells nice.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters: a man and a woman standing side by side in a bright, cheerful room. The woman is holding a small, fancy perfume bottle near her wrist, smiling confidently as she gestures toward it with the phrase ''Smell this!'' above her. The man, looking curious but a bit hesitant, leans in with a slightly puzzled or skeptical expression, holding his nose with one hand as if preparing for a surprise. Around them, subtle details hint at gender stereotypes in a playful way, such as the woman’s neatly styled hair and fashionable outfit and the man’s casual, slightly disheveled look, like a t-shirt and jeans. The background is simple with a dresser or table holding a few more perfume bottles and maybe a small flower vase. The cartoon style is light-hearted with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to amplify the humor without being offensive or political.'),
 (927, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'One-seventh of your life is spent on Monday.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a cheerful weekly calendar character personified as a smiling paper sheet with arms and legs. Each day of the week is a square section on the calendar''s body. The Monday section is brightly highlighted and exaggerated to take up exactly one-seventh of the calendar’s surface, perhaps glowing or shining. The calendar character is pointing to the Monday section with a proud or exaggerated expression, conveying the joke that Monday consumes one-seventh of your life. In the background, a clock or hourglass can emphasize the passing of time. The overall tone should be lighthearted and fun, with bold outlines and simple colors suitable for a humorous cartoon style. There should be no violent or inappropriate elements, just a friendly, relatable depiction of time and the dread or prominence of Monday in a week’s cycle.'),
 (928, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'PHONESIA (fo nee'' zhuh) n. The affliction of dialing a phone number and forgetting whom you were calling just as they answer.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in a bright, cozy living room holding a smartphone up to their ear. Their face expresses a mix of surprise and confusion, with wide eyes and a small open mouth. Above their head is a classic ''thought bubble'' with a question mark and tiny swirly lines indicating forgetfulness. In the background, a phone screen shows the call is connected (green bar or ringing icon). Nearby is a table with a forgotten notepad and pen, symbolizing their lapse in memory. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated features to emphasize the humorous moment of dialing without remembering the recipient.'),
 (929, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Plan to be spontaneous tomorrow.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person standing with a puzzled but excited expression, holding a handwritten calendar marked ''Tomorrow'' in big letters. Behind them is a thought bubble with a zigzag arrow and a checklist titled ''Spontaneity Plan'' with checkmarks next to ''Wake up on time'', ''Decide what to do'', and ''Be spontaneous!'' The setting is a simple living room with a clock and a window showing daylight. The style is light-hearted and whimsical, emphasizing the irony of planning spontaneity with exaggerated expressions and fun details like scattered notes labeled ''Ideas?''.'),
 (930, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Procrastinate NOW', NULL, 'A single-panel humorous cartoon featuring a laid-back character sitting comfortably in an armchair with a calendar and clock prominently displayed nearby. The calendar page shows a big, bold date circled with the words "Deadline" or "Due Date" visible, but the character is clearly relaxed, with feet up on a coffee table and a casual smile. The clock’s hands point to a time suggesting the deadline is near, but the character holds a coffee mug with the phrase "Procrastinate NOW" on it. Around the room, subtle humorous details, like a cluttered desk with papers stacked haphazardly and a sticky note saying "Start tomorrow," emphasize the irony of urging to procrastinate immediately. The style is bright and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to enhance the comic effect, ensuring it feels lighthearted and fun without any negative or violent elements.'),
 (931, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'PROCRASTINATION: The art of kee... (I think I''ll finish this thought tomorrow...)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a cluttered desk littered with papers, a coffee cup, and a clock showing late afternoon. The person looks distracted and relaxed, leaning back in their chair with a half-smile, gazing off into the distance. Above their head is a speech bubble that starts with the phrase ''PROCRASTINATION: The art of kee...'' but trails off with a smaller bubble saying ''(I think I''ll finish this thought tomorrow...)''. The room has casual elements like a calendar on the wall showing an overdue date, and a small growing plant on the windowsill symbolizing time passing. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing a whimsical and relatable atmosphere about putting off tasks.'),
 (932, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'Two rules for a very successful life:   1. Never tell everything that you know   2. (This space intentionally left blank)', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a quirky, smiling character standing next to a large whiteboard or poster titled ''Two Rules for a Very Successful Life.'' The board shows: 1. ''Never tell everything that you know'' written clearly, and 2. ''(This space intentionally left blank)'' written below with a large empty space around it. The character is holding a marker and gesturing proudly towards the board, with a playful smirk or wink, suggesting they are in on a clever secret. Around the character, add a few lighthearted elements like a thinking bubble with an exaggerated secret (e.g., a treasure chest or a lightbulb with a lock), and a classroom or office background with subtle details like a small plant, a clock, or motivational posters, creating a friendly, humorous atmosphere. Use bright colors and simple cartoon styling to emphasize the joke''s irony and wit without any tension or negativity.'),
 (933, 'Humor, Life, Word Play', 'UNEMPLOYMENT ISN''T WORKING', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person lounging on a couch in casual, slightly rumpled clothes, looking completely relaxed with a content smile. Beside them is a coffee table cluttered with snacks, a remote control, and an empty coffee cup. Behind the couch, a calendar on the wall clearly shows a month with many days crossed out, indicating a long period of unemployment. The room has a messy, lived-in feel, with slippers kicked off near the couch and a sleeping cat curled up nearby. A thought bubble above the person reads ''Unemployment isn''t working,'' adding a clever visual pun. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the irony and wordplay in a friendly, non-serious atmosphere.'),
 (934, 'Humor, Life, Workplace', 'Many people quit looking for work when they find a job.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a busy job seeker in casual clothes holding a large magnifying glass, looking intensely at a ''Help Wanted'' sign on a shop window. Behind them, another character wearing work clothes is cheerfully walking away from a cluster of job listings with a briefcase in hand, smiling and waving goodbye to the hunting phase. The background includes a city street with other shops and a few puzzled pedestrians watching the worker leave the hunt behind. The style is light and playful with exaggerated expressions highlighting the contrast between searching and having a job.'),
 (935, 'Humor, Life, Workplace', 'No one is listening until you make a mistake.', NULL, 'A cartoon office or classroom setting where a person is trying to explain something to a group of people or colleagues. The group looks bored, uninterested, or distracted—some are looking at phones, others have sleepy expressions. Suddenly, the speaker makes a small, obvious mistake in their speech or writing (like a visible spelling error or stumbling over words). In the next panel or nearby scene, the entire group’s heads snap up, eyes wide with surprise and focus, mouths open as if all are paying intense attention for the first time. The setting should be light and humorous with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize disinterest turning into sudden alertness. Include details like a whiteboard, desk, or presentation materials to situate the scene in a learning or work environment. The style should be colorful, simple, and cartoonish with clear visuals emphasizing the change in attention triggered by the mistake.'),
 (936, 'Humor, Life, Workplace', 'Nothing makes a person more productive than the last minute.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a messy desk cluttered with papers, a laptop, coffee cups, and a clock on the wall showing just one minute to a deadline time. The person''s eyes are wide open with a panicked but determined expression, frantically typing on the laptop and scribbling notes. Around the desk, speech bubbles or action lines emphasize rapid movement and urgency. The background is a typical office or home workspace, with a calendar or sticky notes hinting at a looming deadline. The overall tone is light and funny, capturing the idea that extreme productivity kicks in only at the last possible moment.'),
 (937, 'Humor, Life, Workplace', 'Quality: If you don''t have time to do it right, when will you have time to do it over?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stressed-out character sitting at a cluttered desk surrounded by stacks of papers, tools, and a ticking clock prominently displayed on the wall. The character looks frazzled, with wild hair and sweat drops, holding a checklist with a big red question mark. A thought bubble above the character''s head shows two images: one of the character carefully and slowly completing a task with a happy, content expression, and another of the character rushed, making mistakes, then having to redo the work in frustration. The room should have a humorous, exaggerated style with bright colors to emphasize the contrast between doing it right the first time and having to redo it. Include a calendar on the wall showing tight deadlines and a coffee cup to add to the busy work atmosphere. Make sure the tone is light, playful, and clearly expresses the dilemma of rushed work versus quality work and redoing tasks.'),
 (938, 'Humor, Life, Workplace', 'The learning curve is steep for the first n years, then flattens out. Typical quote from those with n years experience.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two characters standing next to a large, exaggerated line graph on a whiteboard. The graph''s y-axis is labeled ''Learning'' and the x-axis is labeled ''Years of Experience.'' The graph starts with a very steep upward slope for the first segment labeled ''n years,'' then suddenly flattens out into a straight horizontal line. One character, wearing glasses and holding a pointer stick, is confidently explaining the graph to the other character, who looks skeptical or puzzled. Around them are office or classroom elements like a desk with a coffee cup, a stack of books titled ''Experience'' and ''Skills,'' and a clock showing time passing. The overall style is lighthearted with clear, bold cartoon lines, bright colors, and exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the humor in the idea that after some ''n'' years, learning stops or plateaus completely.'),
 (2404, 'Humor, Love Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'The ultimate test of a relationship is to disagree but to hold hands.', 'Alexandra Penney', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a couple standing side by side with contrasting expressions. The woman looks frustrated or annoyed, arms crossed, while the man looks equally frustrated but is holding her hand tightly. Their bodies face slightly away from each other as if they are in a disagreement, but their fingers remain intertwined with exaggerated emphasis on their holding hands. Above them, a simple heart symbol or a small banner that reads ''The Ultimate Test'' adds context. The background is a cozy living room setting with a sofa and a small table with a single flower vase, emphasizing an intimate environment. The overall style is light-hearted and playful with clear, bold outlines and vibrant colors to match the positive yet ironic tone of the joke. No violence or negative elements are included, focusing on the affectionate contrast of disagreement and connection.'),
 (939, 'Humor, Love Humor, Word Play', 'There''s so much to say but your eyes keep interrupting me.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting across from each other at a small table. One character is trying to speak, with a speech bubble filled with many words trying to come out, but in front of their mouth, large, exaggerated cartoon eyes hover and cover the words, blocking the speech. The eyes should be big, bright, and animated with playful expressions, as if ''interrupting'' or ''talking over'' the person. The setting can be casual—a coffee shop or park bench—with a few simple background details like a coffee cup or tree. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the playful interruption of the eyes to the speaker’s attempt to talk, visualizing the metaphor in the joke.'),
 (940, 'Humor, Marriage Humor', 'Never trust a man who says he''s the boss at home. He probably lies about other things too.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy home living room. Center the image on a man sitting comfortably in an armchair with a confident, slightly smug expression, wearing casual clothes and holding a remote control. Nearby, a woman stands with her arms crossed, sporting a knowing smile or amused smirk, clearly skeptical of the man''s claim. A speech bubble from the man reads, "I''m the boss at home!" while a smaller thought bubble above the woman says, "He probably lies about other things too." The background should include everyday home items like a couch, a coffee table with magazines, a lamp, and family photos on the wall. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions typical of cartoon humor.'),
 (2119, 'Humor, Marriage Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'My advice to you is get married: if you find a good wife you''ll be happy; if not, you''ll become a philosopher.', 'Socrates (470-399 B.C.)', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels. On the left panel, a happy man is joyfully holding hands with a smiling woman, both surrounded by pink hearts and a bright sunny background symbolizing happiness in marriage. On the right panel, the same man is alone but thoughtfully stroking his beard, wearing glasses and sitting at a desk cluttered with books titled Philosophy, Wisdom, and Life. There is a lamp illuminating a thought bubble with question marks and abstract symbols, showing his transformation into a philosopher due to an unhappy marriage. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive facial features to highlight the contrast between happiness and wisdom gained through struggle. The setting is indoors for the philosopher side and outdoors for the happy couple side, emphasizing two different life paths humorously.'),
 (2496, 'Humor, Marriage Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Two things are necessary to keep one''s wife happy. First, let her think she''s having her own way. And second, let her have it.', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon scene showing a husband and wife sitting comfortably side by side on a cozy living room couch. The wife has a confident, pleased expression and is leaning slightly forward as if she’s just made a decision or stated what she wants. The husband, smiling sheepishly but happily, is holding an object (like a remote control, a shopping bag, or a dinner menu) with a cheerful, accepting attitude, as if he is fully agreeing and letting her have her way. The background includes a warm home setting with simple, humorous details like a framed picture on the wall with a heart, a small plant on a side table, and maybe a funny caption on a decorative pillow. The style is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the playful, affectionate tone of the joke, focusing on mutual respect and humor without conflict.'),
 (941, 'Humor, Marriage Humor, Social Commentary', 'People seldom think alike, until it comes to buying wedding presents.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene at a wedding gift table filled with many identical, identical-looking presents wrapped in the same paper, such as dozens of toasters, blenders, or identical coffee makers all stacked neatly. A diverse group of guests, each with a quirky expression showing surprise or amusement, is gathered around the table, some holding matching gifts in their hands as they look at each other bewildered. The background shows a festive wedding reception with balloons and streamers. The scene should emphasize uniformity in the gifts contrasting with the individuality of the guests, using bright and cheerful colors to keep it lighthearted and funny.'),
 (942, 'Humor, Marriage Humor, Word Play', 'My wife and I always argued about which way to hang the toilet paper, so our therapist suggested we try it the other persons way for a week. You know... roll reversal.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bathroom where a man and a woman stand near a toilet paper holder, each looking at the toilet paper roll with exaggerated facial expressions of mild confusion and surprise. The toilet paper roll is hanging in the ''wrong'' direction from each person''s perspective — one side showing the paper coming over the top, and the other side under the bottom. The bathroom has a simple playful design with a small framed picture on the wall, a plant on a shelf, and a typical toilet. Nearby, a cheerful therapist, holding a clipboard, is smiling and pointing toward the toilet paper roll, symbolizing the suggestion of ''roll reversal.'' The couple seems to be reacting to the therapist''s advice on resolving their argument in a lighthearted way. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the humor in the everyday domestic disagreement about toilet paper orientation without any harsh emotions or conflict.'),
 (943, 'Humor, Math Humor', 'MATH ANXIETY: An intense lifelong fear of two trains approaching each other at speeds of 60 and 80 mph.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two trains on the same track heading directly towards each other. One train is labeled ''60 mph'' and is colored blue, the other labeled ''80 mph'' and is red. Both trains have exaggerated scared facial expressions with wide eyes and sweat drops on their faces. In the middle between the trains, a cartoon person stands with a frightened expression, clutching a math book titled ''Math Anxiety.'' The background is a simple countryside with railroad tracks continuing into the distance and a few trees. The overall mood should be lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the ''fear'' element with cartoon-style over-the-top emotions and a math-related twist, without any violence or danger depicted explicitly.'),
 (944, 'Humor, Math Humor, School', 'When aiming for the common denominator, be prepared for the occasional division by zero.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a classroom or math lecture hall. At the front, a friendly-looking teacher stands next to a large blackboard filled with mathematical symbols and equations. The teacher is pointing at an equation labeled ''common denominator'' that humorously shows a fraction with a denominator of zero, causing a big, comical ''ERROR'' or ''DIVISION BY ZERO'' sign to flash above it. The teacher has a slightly surprised or worried expression, scratching their head. In the foreground, a few students sit at desks with puzzled or amused faces, some raising their eyebrows or whispering to each other. The classroom has typical school elements like desks, chairs, and a clock on the wall. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the math joke in a cartoon style with exaggerated expressions and clean, simple lines, avoiding any negativity or complexity.'),
 (945, 'Humor, Mechanics, Steven Wright, Word Play', 'My mechanic told me, ''I couldn''t repair your brakes, so I made your horn louder.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a small auto repair shop. In the foreground, a cheerful mechanic wearing a work jumpsuit and a name tag is speaking with a customer standing beside a car. The customer looks both surprised and amused. The car has a visible extra-large, comically loud horn attached to the front bumper, maybe painted bright red with sound waves drawn coming out of it to show it''s booming. The brake area of the car is either visibly broken or has a small ''Out of Order'' sign on it. The background shows typical garage elements: toolboxes, tires, and a lift. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive characters to emphasize the joke.'),
 (2911, 'Humor, Medical Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'He is not dead, he is electroencephalographically challenged.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a doctor standing beside a hospital bed. On the bed lies a person who looks very still and comically expressionless, with a brainwave monitor nearby showing a flat EEG line. The doctor, wearing a white coat and a stethoscope, holds an EEG printout with a puzzled but non-serious expression. Include a speech bubble from the doctor saying, ''He is not dead, he is electroencephalographically challenged.'' The hospital room should have a simple background with a window showing a sunny day outside to keep the tone light and funny, not somber. Use bright, friendly colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the playful misunderstanding of medical jargon.'),
 (946, 'Humor, Mental Health Humor', 'Of all the things I''ve lost, I miss my mind the most.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a middle-aged person standing in a messy living room looking slightly puzzled and scratching their head. Around them, various everyday items like keys, glasses, a wallet, and a phone are scattered or misplaced. Above their head is a thought bubble showing a little animated brain wearing a tiny suitcase and walking away as if it’s leaving them. The setting should be light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the comedic loss of the brain rather than anything serious. The style should be simple and playful, like a classic comic strip character.'),
 (947, 'Humor, Mental Health Humor', 'Psychiatrists say that 1 of 4 people are mentally ill.  Check 3 friends.  If they''re OK, you''re it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene with four friends sitting together on a park bench. Three of the friends look visibly calm and relaxed, smiling and chatting. The fourth friend looks wide-eyed, confused, and slightly worried, realizing they might be the ''mentally ill'' one. Above them, a thought bubble from the worried friend says, ''If these three are okay... then I’m it!'' In the background, a small sign reads ''Psychiatrist says 1 in 4 people are mentally ill.'' The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke. No violent or sensitive content.'),
 (1378, 'Humor, Mental Health Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'A clear conscience is usually a sign of a poor memory.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person lounging comfortably in an armchair, smiling with a relaxed and carefree expression. Above their head is a thought bubble showing a series of crossed-out and erased memories or notes, symbolizing forgotten events or mistakes. Surrounding the person are several floating sticky notes or reminder papers with scribbled, partially erased words and drawings. The background is simple and bright, with playful colors to emphasize a lighthearted mood. The style is exaggerated and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between the person’s innocent smile and the jumbled, disappearing memories to illustrate the idea that their clear conscience comes from forgetting important things.'),
 (948, 'Humor, Mental Health Humor, Word Play', 'My memory is so bad.. (how bad is it?) How bad is what?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters having a conversation. Character A looks confused and scratches their head, with a puzzled expression and a thought bubble showing a jumbled mess of symbols or question marks to represent forgetfulness. Character B stands nearby, leaning in slightly with an inquisitive face and raised eyebrows. The background is a simple indoor setting, such as a living room with a couch and a small table. Above Character A, the speech bubble reads, ''My memory is so bad...''. Character B''s speech bubble responds, ''(how bad is it?)''. The punchline is delivered with Character A looking baffled, having an empty or very confused speech bubble, and Character B asks in a final speech bubble, ''How bad is what?''. The overall style is colorful and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize confusion and forgetfulness. This cartoon should be lighthearted and family-friendly, visually emphasizing the comic misunderstanding caused by bad memory.'),
 (949, 'Humor, Mental Health Humor, Word Play', 'Schizophrenia: human version of cross-link files!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon showing a person depicted as a computer file folder labeled ''Human Brain.'' This folder is shown trying to organize colorful sticky notes and small digital files visibly tangled and connected by chaotic, glowing lines labeled ''cross-links.'' The person looks slightly confused but curious, scratching their head while holding two files that are connected by a bright, jumping ''cross-link'' line. In the background, other folders labeled with various brain functions like ''Memory,'' ''Thoughts,'' and ''Emotions'' are also connected by similar glowing lines, some neatly and some tangled, with a sparkle effect to emphasize connections. The setting is a lighthearted, playful office or computer desktop environment emphasizing the concept of files and digital data organization rather than anything clinical or serious. The style is simple, cartoonish, and friendly, with exaggerated expressions for humor without depicting illness harshly or insensitively.'),
 (2683, 'Humor, Money Humor, Pessimism Humor, Unknown', 'Borrow money from pessimists. They don''t expect it back.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters. One character is happily handing over a stack of money to the other, who looks gloomy and pessimistic with slouched shoulders and a frown. The pessimistic character is crossing their arms or shaking their head, clearly not expecting to return the money. They stand outdoors near a simple bank or lending office with a sign that says ''Pessimist Lending''. The happy character has a confident, sly grin, while the pessimistic character wears a sweater with a small cloud raining over their head, emphasizing their gloomy attitude. The background is light and colorful to keep a lighthearted tone, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor. The overall style is a cheerful, playful cartoon with bold outlines and bright colors, suitable for a joke about borrowing money with low or no expectations of repayment.'),
 (2440, 'Humor, Money Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'There was a time when a fool and his money were soon parted, but now it happens to everybody.', 'Adlai Stevenson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of diverse people—young, old, rich, poor—all standing together looking puzzled or frustrated while holding empty wallets and coins slipping through their fingers. In the background, a large, old-fashioned proverb scroll reads ''A fool and his money are soon parted'' with a bright, modern neon sign flickering beside it that says ''Now it happens to everybody.'' The setting is a casual, everyday urban environment like a street corner or park bench with subtle humor in their expressions showing they all experience financial loss regardless of wisdom or status. The characters should be drawn in a light, playful cartoon style with exaggerated faces and body language to emphasize the universal and ironic nature of the joke.'),
 (950, 'Humor, Money Humor, Word Play', 'NEGOTIATING: The art of persuading your opponent to take the nice shiny copper penny and give you the wrinkled old paper money.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters at a negotiation table. One character is enthusiastically holding out a bright, shiny copper penny with a big smile, while the other looks skeptical, holding crumpled, wrinkled paper money (like old dollar bills) in their hand. The setting is simple, with a plain table between them, a small stack of coins on one side, and worn-out paper money on the other. Both characters have exaggerated expressions: the penny-holder looks persuasive and hopeful, the paper-holder looks unsure and wary. The background is minimalistic to focus on the exchange, perhaps with a small sign above the table that says “Negotiations”. The style should be lighthearted and playful, like a typical cartoon strip with bold lines and bright colors to emphasize the humor in the situation.'),
 (951, 'Humor, Motivational', 'Just close your eyes, fall asleep. Next time you open your eyes you''ll be in your future!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person lying in bed with their eyes closed, snuggled under a blanket. Above their head is a thought bubble depicting two panels: the first panel shows the person peacefully sleeping with ''Zzz'' symbols; the second panel shows the same person waking up, but in a funny future scenario—perhaps wearing futuristic clothes, surrounded by flying gadgets or robots, or standing next to a calendar labeled with a future year. The bedroom should look cozy and simple, with a nightstand holding an alarm clock and a lamp. The overall style should be lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated expressions of calm sleep and surprise or curiosity upon waking. The colors should be bright and cheerful to emphasize optimism and humor about the concept of ''sleeping into the future.'''),
 (952, 'Humor, Motivational', 'Never let your fears stand in the way of your dreams.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon shows a character standing at a fork in a path labeled ''Fears'' on one side and ''Dreams'' on the other. The ''Fears'' path is cluttered with comically exaggerated obstacles such as tiny monsters, jagged rocks, and silly pitfalls. The ''Dreams'' path is bright and inviting, with fluffy clouds, stars, and a shining sun. The character, looking determined but slightly nervous, wears casual clothes and is stepping confidently toward the ''Dreams'' path, while behind them a shadowy, oversized fear figure perhaps shaped like a cartoon monster tries to block the way but looks harmless and goofy rather than scary. The overall tone is uplifting and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions emphasizing overcoming silly fears to reach big dreams.'),
 (953, 'Humor, Motivational', 'Some succeed because they are destined to. Most succeed because they are determined to.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene split into two halves side by side. On the left side, a character stands on a simple podium labeled ''Destiny,'' looking relaxed and content with a glowing aura or stars above their head, suggesting they are naturally fated to succeed. On the right side, another character is climbing a tall, steep mountain labeled ''Determination,'' sweating but smiling with effort, carrying a backpack full of tools like a rope and pickaxe. The background shows the mountain peak with a flag at the top that says ''Success.'' Both characters are cartoonish, friendly-looking, and dressed in casual clothes. The sky is bright and cheerful on both sides. The overall tone is optimistic and humorous, highlighting the contrast between destiny and determination in a lighthearted way.'),
 (954, 'Humor, Motivational', 'The task ahead of us is never as great as the power behind us.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small group of people standing before a huge mountain labeled ''The Task'' which looks very tall and intimidating. Behind them is a giant, exaggeratedly large muscle arm symbolizing ''The Power'' supporting and lifting them up. The people look determined and hopeful, some with sweat on their brows, others flexing their arms confidently. The background is simple with a clear sky and some light clouds to keep focus on the metaphorical mountain and the powerful arm. Text above or below the image reads the joke: ''The task ahead of us is never as great as the power behind us.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and motivational, drawn in vibrant, colorful cartoon style with smiling faces and exaggerated expressions.'),
 (955, 'Humor, Motivational, Philosophy', 'It''s your attitude, not your aptitude, that determines your altitude in life.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a whimsical simple mountain landscape. In the foreground, a cheerful character wearing a business suit and a pilot''s hat is standing on a stack of large books labeled ''Attitude'' and ''Aptitude.'' The character is smiling confidently with arms raised as if ready to take off. Above the character, a cartoon airplane shaped like an upward arrow is soaring upward into the sky labeled ''Altitude.'' The sky is bright with a few fluffy clouds and a sun shining. Around the character, small motivational signs or symbols like smiley faces and light bulbs float to emphasize positive attitude, while the book labeled ''Aptitude'' looks a bit dusty and less colorful. The style should be playful and colorful, using exaggerated expressions and simple shapes to create a humorous and uplifting vibe.'),
 (956, 'Humor, Motivational, Philosophy', 'POSITIVE THINKING: Self-improvement through self-deception.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person looking at themselves in a bedroom mirror. The person is smiling confidently and wearing casual clothes. Behind the person is a wall with motivational posters, one prominently reads ''Positive Thinking!'' with bright, cheerful colors. On a nearby table are self-help books stacked messily with titles like ''Self-Improvement'' and ''Mindset Magic.'' Nearby, a little floating cartoon cloud above the person’s head shows a thought bubble with the words ''Self-deception'' crossed out and replaced by ''Self-improvement'' in bold letters. The overall mood is light and playful, emphasizing the irony of the phrase, with exaggerated cheerful colors and a playful font for all text elements. No other people or animals are included in the scene.'),
 (1994, 'Humor, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It takes as much courage to have tried and failed as it does to have tried and succeeded.', 'Anne Morrow Lindbergh', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side on a stage with a spotlight. On the left, a character stands proudly on a small podium labeled ''Success,'' smiling confidently and holding a trophy. On the right, another character looks equally brave and determined, standing on a similar podium labeled ''Failure,'' holding a crumpled certificate or a broken medal but smiling with pride. The background features encouraging banners that say ''Courage Counts!'' and ''Try Again!'' Both characters wear heroic capes and have cheerful expressions, highlighting that courage is the same regardless of outcome. The style is colorful and lighthearted with exaggerated facial expressions, emphasizing humor and encouragement rather than competition or disappointment.'),
 (1915, 'Humor, Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'If you want to be successful, it''s just this simple: Know what you''re doing. Love what you''re doing. And believe in what you''re doing.', 'Will Rogers', 'A cheerful and colorful cartoon scene showing a confident person standing in the center with a giant checklist titled "Success Steps" floating above their head. The checklist has three big, bold checkmarks next to the items: "Know what you''re doing," "Love what you''re doing," and "Believe in what you''re doing." The person is smiling brightly, wearing casual clothes and holding a large pencil in one hand as if they just checked off the list. Around them are simple symbolic objects: a light bulb representing ideas/knowledge, a heart symbolizing love/passion, and a shining star symbolizing belief/confidence. The background is lively but not crowded, with some playful swirls or sparkles to show positive energy and inspiration. The style is friendly and upbeat, with exaggerated facial expressions and bold lines to emphasize humor and motivation without being serious or intense.'),
 (1644, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes', 'Don''t lose the dreams inside your head, they''ll only be there till you''re dead, so dream.', 'Dave Matthews Band', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person''s silhouette with a large, whimsical thought bubble above their head. Inside the thought bubble are colorful, playful doodles representing dreams: a flying pig, a rocket, a castle on a cloud, and a sleeping moon wearing a nightcap. The person, smiling gently, is looking up at the bubble as if treasuring the images. The background is simple and bright, with soft clouds and stars to emphasize a dreamy atmosphere. Below the person is a tombstone with a date far in the future, humorously hinting at the limited time to keep dreams alive. The overall tone is light-hearted and encouraging, combining visual elements of dreams and life in a funny but warm cartoon style.'),
 (957, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes', 'The price of greatness is responsibility.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, muscular trophy character standing tall on a pedestal labeled ''Greatness''. The trophy has arms and legs and is holding a huge, heavy-looking clipboard labeled ''Responsibility''. It looks both proud and slightly overwhelmed. Around the base of the pedestal, scattered papers marked with tasks and duties fly about chaotically, emphasizing the burden. The background is a simple stage with curtains to highlight the ''award'' moment. The style is lighthearted with exaggerated expressions and bright, cheerful colors to keep the tone funny and uplifting.'),
 (1645, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes, Relatable', 'Don''t measure yourself by what you have accomplished, but by what you should have accomplished with your ability.', 'John Wooden', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of two scoreboards. The first scoreboard titled ''What You’ve Accomplished'' has a modest number, while the second scoreboard titled ''What You Should Have Accomplished'' shows a much larger, exaggerated number. The person looks confused or overwhelmed, scratching their head with one hand and holding a pencil and paper labeled ''Self-Assessment'' in the other. Around the person are small items symbolizing ability and potential, like a trophy, a brain icon, and a chart with upward arrows. The setting is simple, like a casual office or home workspace, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions for humor. The overall tone is witty and lighthearted without any negativity.'),
 (1360, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes, Science Humor', '...I have not failed. I''ve just found 10,000 ways that won''t work.', 'Thomas Edison', 'Create a humorous cartoon scene showing an enthusiastic inventor in a cluttered workshop filled with quirky, failed inventions. The inventor is a cheerful character with glasses and messy hair, holding a lightbulb turned off in one hand and scratching their head with the other. Around them are scattered objects like a broken robot, a malfunctioning flying machine with bent wings, a bucket catching leaking water, and a blueprint pinned on the wall titled ''10,000 Attempts.'' A chalkboard or whiteboard nearby displays the phrase: ''Not failed, just 10,000 ways that won’t work!'' The setting has a comical, colorful vibe with exaggerated expressions and lots of small details showing inventive failure, to emphasize persistence and optimism in a funny way.'),
 (2536, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'What are you waiting for? You''re faster than this. Don''t think you are, know you are. Come on. Stop trying to hit me and hit me.', 'Morpheus', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing in a simple, brightly colored boxing ring. One character is looking frustrated and slightly confused, mid-motion with their hands raised as if ready to punch but hesitating. The other character is confidently poised, sporting a playful smirk and holding up a finger in a ''come on'' gesture, as if encouraging the first to attack. Both characters wear exaggerated boxing gloves and headgear that looks cartoonish and oversized for comedic effect. The background is minimal, focusing on the ring ropes and a few simple crowd silhouettes cheering subtly. A speech bubble from the confident character contains the motivational and somewhat ironic lines: ''What are you waiting for? You''re faster than this. Don''t think you are, know you are. Come on. Stop trying to hit me and hit me.'' The overall tone is lighthearted, mixing sports and motivational coaching with a playful rivalry vibe.'),
 (1709, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Genius is perseverance in disguise.', 'Mike Newlin', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a lightbulb wearing glasses and a graduation cap, sweating and working hard at a cluttered desk piled high with books, papers, and coffee cups. The lightbulb character is trying to look smart but is visibly tired and determined, with a small sign on the desk that reads ''Perseverance Station.'' Around the desk, faint ghost-like outlines of various inventions and ideas float, symbolizing hidden genius. The background is a cheerful office or study room with posters that say ''Keep Going!'' and ''Almost There!'' The style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the notion that what looks like genius is actually hard work and persistence in disguise.'),
 (2145, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes, Wise Sayings', 'No one can make you feel inferior without your consent.', 'Eleanor Roosevelt', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a confident character standing tall with a big smile, radiating positive energy. Surround this character are several small, cartoonish shadowy figures trying to look imposing or mean, but they are bouncing off an invisible shield labeled ''Consent'' that glows brightly around the confident character. The background can be simple and cheerful, with light rays emphasizing the shield''s power. Include a small caption or banner above that reads: ''No one can make you feel inferior without your consent.'' The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing empowerment and humor without violence or negativity.'),
 (2140, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes, Word Play', 'Never, never, never, never, never give up.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a determined character climbing an impossibly steep mountain made up of giant letters spelling out the word ''GIVE UP.'' The character looks exhausted but resolute, gripping onto the letters with a face of focused perseverance. At the top, a bright shining sun emphasizes triumph and hope. The sky is clear with a few fluffy clouds. To add a touch of humor, a small motivational poster stuck in the ground reads ''Never, never, never, never, never give up!'' The style is colorful and exaggerated with bold outlines, emphasizing the character''s struggle in a lighthearted, playful way.'),
 (1980, 'Humor, Motivational, Quotes, Workplace', 'It is no use saying, ''we are doing our best''; you have got to succeed in doing what is necessary.', 'Sir Winston Churchill', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in an office or classroom. In the center, show a stern, slightly exaggerated boss or teacher figure standing in front of a whiteboard. The whiteboard displays the sentence: ''It is no use saying, "we are doing our best"; you have got to succeed in doing what is necessary.'' Around the boss/teacher are a group of cartoon characters sitting at desks or around a table. Their expressions range from nervous to puzzled, some glancing at each other as if unsure what to do next. Include items like laptops, papers, coffee mugs, and a clock showing time passing to emphasize urgency. The style should be bright and colorful with clear, simple lines and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor in the serious advice being given. The overall mood is lighthearted yet earnest, highlighting the clash between trying hard and actual success in a playful way.'),
 (958, 'Humor, Motivational, Word Play', 'The door of opportunity won''t open unless you do some pushing!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, ornate door labeled ''Opportunity'' in big letters. The door is closed and slightly ajar, set in a bright and inviting hallway or entranceway. In front of the door stands a cheerful cartoon character with a friendly expression, using both hands to push against the door with visible effort. The character''s body is leaning forward slightly to emphasize the pushing action, and small sweat droplets or motion lines can show exertion. Behind the character, scattered thought bubbles or signs with motivational words like ''Push!'' or ''Try!'' add to the encouragement theme. The background is simple and lighthearted, with warm colors to keep the tone positive and funny but not intense. The overall style is playful, with exaggerated expressions and simple lines to enhance the joke''s message that the door (opportunity) only opens when you push (take action). No violent or political elements.'),
 (959, 'Humor, Motivational, Workplace', 'Pros are people who do jobs well even when they don''t feel like it', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a simple office setting. One character, looking tired and unenthusiastic with messy hair and slouched posture, is sitting at a desk cluttered with papers and a computer. A second character, bright-eyed and energetic, stands beside them with a thumbs-up and a friendly smile. A caption bubble above the standing character reads, ''Pros are people who do jobs well even when they don''t feel like it.'' The background includes an office clock showing late hours and a coffee cup with steam rising, emphasizing fatigue. The style is light-hearted with exaggerated expressions to convey both exhaustion and determination in a playful manner.'),
 (960, 'Humor, Movies, Word Play', 'Sequels we''ll never see: The Duplicate Bridge over the River Kwai', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing the original famous Bridge over the River Kwai with a cheeky twist. Draw two identical wooden bridges side by side stretching across a river labeled ''River Kwai.'' One bridge looks old-fashioned and war-themed, resembling the classic movie setting, complete with a few surprised or curious tourists taking photos. Right next to it, the second bridge is exactly the same in every detail, as if it’s a perfect duplicate, with a large sign overhead that says ''Duplicate Bridge over the River Kwai.'' Make both bridges colorful and a bit exaggerated, with comically large planks and rope railings. Include a small boat with puzzled people looking up at the two identical bridges, scratching their heads with question marks above their heads. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions on the characters to emphasize the joke about a never-to-exist sequel involving duplication and the famous bridge.'),
 (961, 'Humor, Music Humor, Word Play', 'SFB: Song Fragment Buildup. Little bits of songs that you can''t get out of your head. Often the last song you heard on the radio before getting out of the car. Example: Day-O! Daylight''s comin'' an'' me wanna go home!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a car with a person sitting in the driver''s seat looking slightly annoyed but amused. Musical notes are floating around their head representing a catchy tune stuck in their mind. A small radio on the dashboard displays a song title or musical notes, indicating the source of the tune. The background through the car windows shows a simple street or parking lot, suggesting the person just got out of the car. Above the person, a speech bubble contains the text: “Day-O! Daylight''s comin'' an'' me wanna go home!” The overall style is light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the feeling of a catchy song stuck in the head. The scene should evoke the common relatable experience of an earworm or a song fragment that won’t go away after leaving the car or radio environment. No people other than the driver, no violence or anything inappropriate.'),
 (962, 'Humor, Music Humor, Word Play', 'They say if you play rap music backwards, you hear Satanic messages. And even worse - if you play it forwards, you hear rap music!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene in a living room. A curious character with exaggerated surprised eyes is sitting on a cozy armchair wearing oversized headphones connected to a vintage-looking turntable playing a vinyl record labeled ''Rap Music.'' The character holds the record, which has a visible arrow indicating ''Play Backwards.'' Around their head are quirky musical notes and tiny flames shaped like tiny devils floating, suggesting ''Satanic messages.'' On the coffee table, there''s a speech bubble from another character, looking horrified and pointing at a large poster on the wall that says ''Rap Music'' with crazy, chaotic scribbles symbolizing unpleasant noise. The other character looks dismayed, covering their ears because the music is playing forward. The overall art style is bright and exaggerated, with cartoonish expressions and clear visual cues highlighting the joke''s punchline that playing rap forwards is worse than backwards. No violent or offensive elements present.'),
 (963, 'Humor, Nostalgia, Word Play', 'They don''t make nostalgia like they used to.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene depicting an elderly person sitting on a cozy old-fashioned armchair, holding a dusty photo album with a smile. Surrounding them are nostalgic items: an old rotary phone, a vintage radio, a classic TV set showing a black-and-white show, and faded posters on the wall featuring retro styles. The character looks fondly at the album, with a thought bubble showing a faded scene from the past, like children playing outside with classic toys. The overall mood is warm and humorous, emphasizing fond memories. The scene is drawn in a lighthearted, cartoon style with exaggerated, friendly features on the character and slightly exaggerated proportions of the vintage items to enhance the nostalgic feel.'),
 (1811, 'Humor, Optimism Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'I find that the harder I work, the more luck I seem to have.', 'Thomas Jefferson (1743-1826)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person dressed in casual work clothes, energetically carrying multiple tools like a hammer, wrench, and paintbrush, with sweat flying off their forehead. The background is a cluttered workspace with half-finished projects: a ladder, a toolbox, and scattered nails. Above the character’s head, typical comic-style luck symbols float around – like a four-leaf clover, a horseshoe, and a lucky coin – glowing or shining to indicate ''luck''. The character has a determined and happy expression, conveying a mix of hard work and unexpected good fortune. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated motion lines to emphasize activity and fortune symbols glowing for contrast. The setting should be indoors in a workshop or garage to clearly illustrate the work environment.'),
 (964, 'Humor, Parenting', 'Learn from your parents'' mistakes - use birth control!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a teenager sitting with a thoughtful expression while looking at a family photo album. In the album, the images of quirky-looking parents are exaggerated with comical features, such as glasses slipping down the nose and slightly disheveled hairstyles. Next to the teen is a large, clearly labeled pack of birth control pills, highlighted with a glowing aura to emphasize its importance. The background is a cozy living room with a framed picture on the wall that says ''Learn from your parents!'' The overall tone is lighthearted and cheeky, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the joke''s playful warning.'),
 (965, 'Humor, Parenting, Philosophy', 'No one ever really finds out what he believes until he begins to instruct his children.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a parent trying to explain a lesson to two curious children sitting cross-legged in front of them. The parent looks slightly confused or thoughtful, scratching their head while holding a book or a chalkboard with some simple words or pictures. The children look eager but puzzled, mirroring the parent''s uncertainty. The background is a cozy living room or a classroom with playful colors and simple decorations like a clock, family photos, or educational posters. The overall style is light-hearted, with exaggerated expressions emphasizing the parent''s moment of self-discovery and the children''s questioning faces.'),
 (3150, 'Humor, Parenting, Relatable, Unknown', 'Young people should learn to take criticism, they may become parents someday.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a young adult looking nervously at an older, stern-faced parent holding a long list labeled ''Criticism List.'' The parent is pointing at the list with a finger, delivering advice, while the young adult has a worried expression, sweating slightly. Around them are subtle background elements like a messy living room with toys scattered, a crying baby in a crib, and maybe a tired-looking partner sitting on a couch. The setting emphasizes a home environment with warmth but also slight chaos. The style is colorful and exaggerated, cartoonish faces with big eyes and expressive mouths to highlight the humor in the generational advice about criticism.'),
 (2841, 'Humor, Parenting, Unknown', 'Everyone is a child psychologist until they become a parent.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of adults standing confidently in a circle, each wearing glasses and holding a clipboard labeled ''Child Psychologist.'' They look calm, collected, and are smiling as if they know exactly how to handle children''s behavior. In front of them, a frazzled-looking new parent is holding a crying toddler who is throwing a tantrum, with toys scattered on the floor and colorful scribbles on the wall. The new parent looks overwhelmed, hair messy, sweat drops on their face, and a thought bubble above saying, ''Wait... this is harder than it looks!'' The background is a living room with a couch, some children’s books, and a baby monitor. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated to emphasize the contrast between confident adults and the struggling parent.'),
 (3193, 'Humor, Pessimism Humor, Steven Wright, Word Play', 'Borrow money from pessimists -- they don''t expect it back.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters. One character, looking hopeful and slightly awkward, is handing a stack of money to another character who is slouched with a gloomy expression, wearing a shirt labeled ''Pessimist.'' The pessimist character has crossed arms and an unamused face, clearly expecting not to see the money again. The hopeful character has a thought bubble showing a smiling banknote with wings flying away. The background is simple, suggesting a casual outdoor setting with a bench near them. The style is colorful and exaggerated with big expressive eyes to emphasize the humor and mood contrast between hopeful lender and pessimistic borrower. Include a witty caption under the scene: ''Borrow money from pessimists — they don’t expect it back.'''),
 (966, 'Humor, Pessimistic', 'In a million years, it won''t make any difference.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing next to a giant, ancient-looking hourglass filled with tiny grains of sand. The person has a clueless or indifferent expression, shrugging their shoulders with palms up. Around them is a vast landscape that looks unchanged through different eras: a dinosaur faintly visible in the background, a futuristic city poking up on the horizon, and a stone age campfire to one side. The hourglass stands prominently in the center, exaggerated in size to emphasize the passage of an enormous amount of time. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon-style features to emphasize the joke’s irony about time making no difference.'),
 (967, 'Humor, Pessimistic', 'People think I go out of my way to piss them off. Trust me, it''s not out of my way at all.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a grumpy person walking along a sidewalk with a mischievous smirk on their face. The person should be casually strolling but clearly taking a deliberate detour around an annoyed group of people standing nearby with crossed arms and angry expressions. The background is a simple urban scene with houses or shops in soft pastel colors to keep it lighthearted. Include visual cues that the person effortlessly and happily avoids going straight on their path, taking an exaggeratedly longer route to pass right in front of the irritated people. The style is playful and exaggerated with bold lines and expressive faces to emphasize the humor in intentionally annoying others without extra effort.'),
 (968, 'Humor, Pessimistic, Social Commentary', 'Never underestimate the power of stupid people in large groups.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, diverse crowd of people standing together in a public place like a park or town square. The people are portrayed in exaggerated, silly poses with confused or goofy expressions—some scratching their heads, some looking bewildered. The crowd is so large that it spills beyond the edges of the picture. In the foreground, a single character (looking thoughtful or wise) stands apart from the group, holding a sign or placard that reads "Never underestimate the power of stupid people in large groups." The background can include simple cityscape elements or trees to imply a communal gathering. The style should be lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the playful absurdity of the idea without being mean-spirited or offensive. No aggressive or negative actions, just an amusing look at crowd mentality.'),
 (969, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'It is not enough to succeed; others must fail.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a corporate office. In the foreground, a confident-looking character stands on a podium labeled ''Success'' with a big trophy in hand and a wide grin. In the background, several other characters wearing business attire look dejected, sitting or slumped over desks with papers scattered around, showing clear signs of failure. Above them, a thought bubble from the main character shows a sneaky smirk with the phrase ''It is not enough to succeed; others must fail.'' The office should have typical items like a water cooler, computer monitors, a clock on the wall, and motivational posters, but one of the posters ironically says ''Teamwork makes the dream work.'' The style is colorful, simple, and exaggerated for comic effect, with expressive facial features to highlight the competitive and slightly mean-spirited tone of the joke without violence or negativity.'),
 (970, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'It may be that your sole purpose in life is simply to serve as a warning to others.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on a small pedestal labeled ''Warning.'' The person looks awkward and sheepish, rubbing the back of their neck nervously. Around the pedestal are several other people pointing and whispering, looking surprised or amused. In the background, a large, colorful warning sign with exclamation marks and bold letters saying ''BEWARE!'' floats above. The setting is a simple park or city square with a few trees and benches, emphasizing that this is an ordinary place where the ''warning'' person stands out humorously as a living cautionary example.'),
 (971, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Let a fool hold his tongue and he will pass for a sage.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting on a park bench. One character is a cheerful, naive-looking person with wide eyes and a big smile, clearly a fool, holding his own tongue gently with both hands as if to keep it from speaking. The other character is an older, wise figure, perhaps an elderly person with glasses, a long beard, and a thoughtful expression, nodding approvingly at the fool''s silence. Around them, there are speech bubbles with silly nonsense from the fool when he speaks, but now the bubbles are empty to indicate silence. The background is simple, with trees and a sunny sky. The setting is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the humor of the situation where silence makes the fool appear wise.'),
 (972, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Many are called, few are chosen. Fewer still get to do the choosing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a celestial or mystical environment. In the foreground, a large group of diverse, eager people stand with hopeful expressions, looking up toward a glowing heavenly figure or figure on a throne symbolizing ''the chooser.'' This figure is depicted with a thoughtful or slightly overwhelmed expression, holding a golden clipboard or a list labeled ''Chosen List.'' Around this figure are a handful of individuals standing confidently or celebrating, wearing little stars or badges that say ''Chosen.'' The background has soft clouds, beams of light, and maybe faint outlines of other groups waiting for their turn, emphasizing the idea of many being called, fewer chosen, and even fewer choosing. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated to emphasize the humor and hierarchy, with cartoonish expressions and gentle colors suitable for all ages. No violent or political imagery.'),
 (973, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Memories are a gift for the mind to open.', NULL, 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing in front of a giant, ornate gift box labeled ''Memories.'' The box is partly open, and instead of typical presents inside, glowing, colorful brain-shaped items float out like magical sparks. The background is bright and cheerful, with soft clouds and sparkles emanating from the open gift box. The person has a delighted, surprised expression as they reach out to catch one of the glowing brain souvenirs. Around them, faint, playful illustrations of past happy moments (like a small heart, a smiling sun, or a simple family stick figure) float gently nearby, emphasizing warmth and nostalgia. The style is light-hearted, cartoonish, and inviting, with exaggerated features and vibrant colors to emphasize the whimsical nature of the metaphor.'),
 (974, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Modesty is a vastly overrated virtue.', NULL, 'A humorous, colorful cartoon scene showing a confident person standing proudly on a small podium labeled ''Most Modest Award.'' The person is smiling broadly with their chest puffed up and arms folded proudly. Around their feet, there are several discarded modesty-related items like a folded shirt labeled ''Modesty'' or a book lying open titled ''How to Be Modest''. In the background, a few cartoonish onlookers have puzzled or skeptical expressions, scratching their heads or whispering to each other. The setting is light and playful with simple, rounded shapes and bright colors to emphasize the joke about modesty being overrated without any aggressive or negative tones.'),
 (975, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Never make anything simple and efficient when it can be complex and wonderful.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a cluttered desk with papers, gears, wires, and colorful contraptions surrounding them. The person looks both proud and amused, holding a ridiculously complicated gadget full of unnecessary buttons, levers, and flashing lights. Nearby, a simple and plain object, like a basic light switch or simple tool, lies untouched and ignored. The background should be a cozy room filled with quirky inventions and sketches pinned on the wall. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, highlighting the joy and absurdity of complexity over simplicity.'),
 (976, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Never say never unless you''re lying.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing confidently while saying the phrase ''Never say never.'' The person has a playful smirk, and a small mischievous cartoon speech bubble pops out with the word ''Lying!'' inside it to highlight the joke. Surround the character with lighthearted thought bubbles or doodles, such as crossed-out words and big question marks, to visually represent the irony of the phrase. Keep the background simple and colorful, like a casual everyday setting (a park bench or sidewalk), so the focus stays on the character and the speech bubbles. Use exaggerated cartoon features and expressions to emphasize humor without any elements of violence, politics, or negativity.'),
 (977, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'No person was ever honored for what he received.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a simple awards ceremony stage with a podium and a big banner that says ''Honors Ceremony.'' Standing at the podium is a quirky, smiling announcer holding a microphone. In front of the stage, a person looks confused, holding an oversized gift box wrapped with big shiny ribbon, clearly expecting applause for receiving it. Nearby, a trophy display case is empty except for plaques labeled ''Honored for Giving, Achievements, Excellence.'' The audience consists of cartoon people clapping and cheering, but no one is applauding the gift-holder. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, using bright colors and expressive faces to highlight the irony that people are honored for what they give or accomplish, not for what they receive. The setting is indoors with a few balloons and streamers for festive atmosphere, emphasizing the comedic contradiction in the joke’s message.'),
 (978, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Nostalgia isn''t what it used to be.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an elderly person sitting in a cozy armchair, holding a photo album open on their lap. The person looks slightly puzzled or disappointed, scratching their head, with a thought bubble above them containing a simple retro symbol like an old cassette tape or vintage TV. Around the room, nostalgic items are scattered: a rotary phone on a side table, a vinyl record player, and a poster of a classic movie on the wall. The caption ''Nostalgia isn''t what it used to be'' is prominently displayed either above or below the scene, emphasizing the joke. The overall style is warm and lighthearted with exaggerated, friendly facial features to highlight the playful irony of the phrase.'),
 (979, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'Nothing in life is to be feared. It is only to be understood.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a curious little child with wide eyes and a thoughtful expression, holding a magnifying glass up to a cute, slightly confused-looking cartoon monster. The monster is harmless-looking with big, friendly eyes and goofy features, standing in a bright, colorful room with bookshelves full of science and nature books. A light bulb floats above the child''s head to symbolize understanding. In the background, a clock shows no urgency, suggesting calm exploration. The overall vibe is playful and encouraging, emphasizing curiosity overcoming fear with humor and warmth.'),
 (980, 'Humor, Philosophy', 'OBITUARY: A final summation of our lives that, for most of us, occupies about three inches of space in what will shortly become cage liner for your neighbor''s parakeet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small birdcage with a lively, colorful parakeet inside perched on a stand. Beneath the cage, the floor is lined with bird cage liner paper. On top of the cage liner, a tiny, crumpled obituary notice is visible, just about three inches long, with obvious but exaggerated text and a small black border like a real obituary. Nearby, a cartoonish, confused or indifferent neighbor stands holding the birdcage door open, glancing at the small obituary with mild surprise. The setting is a casual, cozy living room with simple furniture and a potted plant, making it clear this is a neighbor’s home. The style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the humor in the idea that a meaningful life summary is reduced to tiny scraps repurposed as bird cage lining.'),
 (981, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'Remember, you''re unique, just like everybody else.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of diverse people standing side by side in a bright, cheerful setting such as a park or a casual outdoor gathering. Each person has distinctive traits emphasizing their uniqueness—different clothing styles, hairstyles, expressions, and accessories. Above the group, a colorful banner reads, ''Remember, you''re unique!'' Below or beside the group, a thought bubble or a quirky sign humorously adds, ''Just like everybody else.'' The characters smile knowingly, adding to the lighthearted irony of the message. The style is simple and playful, with exaggerated cartoon features and bold outlines to emphasize the humor without any threatening or controversial elements.'),
 (982, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'Tact is the art of making a point without making an enemy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room. In the center, a well-dressed, friendly-looking character is speaking to another person who looks a bit surprised but not angry. The first character is holding a large, old-fashioned paintbrush labeled ''Tact'' and is gently painting a speech bubble above the second person''s head that contains the phrase ''making a point''. The second character has a small, cartoonish enemy (depicted as a tiny, grumpy cloud with arms crossed) trying to approach but is being stopped by an invisible barrier labeled ''without making an enemy''. The background includes a comfy sofa, a potted plant, and a framed motivational poster on the wall that says ''Speak Kindly''. The overall mood is light, friendly, and clever, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize humor and warmth.'),
 (983, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Psychology Humor', 'The careful application of terror is also a form of communication.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a living room setting. A person stands nervously with wide eyes and raised eyebrows, holding a pet cat that looks alarmed with its fur puffed up. Nearby, another person sits on a couch with a knowing smirk, holding a small remote control labeled ''Terror Device.'' The background features simple furniture like a sofa, a coffee table with a cup of coffee, and a couple of framed pictures on the wall. The expression on the smirking person''s face should clearly convey the idea that the ''terror'' they are applying is intentional and playful, emphasizing the joke that terror can be a way of communicating. The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with clean lines and bright colors to enhance the comedic effect without any menace or fear.'),
 (1545, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Psychology Humor, Quotes', 'Any emotion, if it is sincere, is involuntary.', 'Mark Twain', 'Draw a simple, humorous cartoon of a person whose facial expression is wildly changing to depict different sincere emotions rapidly. The character should be in the center with exaggerated features showing surprise, joy, sadness, anger, and confusion, all blending into one another. Around the character’s head, include small cartoon-like swirls or emotive symbols like hearts, teardrops, lightning bolts, and question marks to illustrate the involuntary nature of these feelings. The background should be plain or softly gradient to keep the focus on the character’s expressive face. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the uncontrollable burst of feelings rather than any detailed setting or props.'),
 (1783, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'I am ready to meet my Maker. Whether my Maker is prepared for the great ordeal of meeting me is another matter.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident, slightly mischievous person standing at the gates of heaven. The person has a smug, self-assured grin and is dressed in casual clothes, arms crossed with a relaxed posture. On the other side of the pearly white gates, an angelic figure (the Maker) looks nervously surprised and a bit overwhelmed, wiping sweat from their forehead. The background shows fluffy clouds, a bright golden glow, and a classic ''Heaven'' sign above the gates. The contrast between the confident person and the anxious Maker creates a funny, lighthearted mood. The style is caricatured and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor, no dark or serious tones.'),
 (2317, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'The greatest conflicts are not between two people but between one person and himself.', 'Garth Brooks', 'A cartoon scene depicting a single person standing in front of a mirror, but with a twist: his reflection is looking grumpy and arms crossed, while he looks confused and frustrated. The person and his reflection are facing each other like they are in a tense standoff or argument. Around them, subtle visual cues like small lightning bolts or squiggly lines can show the ''conflict'' mood. The setting is a simple bathroom or bedroom with a visible mirror, a sink or dresser, and some everyday objects like a toothbrush, comb, or clothes strewn about to keep it relatable and lighthearted. The style should be colorful and exaggerated with humorous facial expressions to emphasize the inner personal conflict in a funny, non-threatening way.'),
 (2056, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religious Humor', 'Lord, grant that I may always desire more than I accomplish.', 'Michelangelo', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a peaceful, quaint church or a humble home prayer corner. A person kneels at a prayer bench or small altar with hands clasped, looking up with hopeful eyes. Above them, a whimsical thought bubble shows a somewhat mischievous or cheeky angel holding a large scroll labeled ''Desire List'' that extends way beyond a shorter ''Accomplishment List'' pinned on a nearby wall or board. The room is simple, with soft warm colors and religious symbols like a cross, a candle, and an open book. The contrast of overly ambitious goals with modest actual achievements is highlighted in a lighthearted, playful style. The character''s expression combines earnestness and slight irony, capturing the joke''s ironic wish of always wanting more than actually doing.'),
 (2192, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'People are fickle by nature; and it is simple to convince them of something, but difficult to hold them in that conviction.', 'Machiavelli', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a group of people standing on a large, colorful spinning carousel labeled ''Beliefs.'' The people are all looking confused, some moving from one brightly colored segment to another, with expressions showing hesitation, curiosity, and doubt. A character in the middle, depicted as a smooth talker with a sly smile and holding a giant megaphone labeled ''Persuasion,'' is trying to convince the group. Around the carousel, signs read ''Easy to Convince'' at the entrance side and ''Hard to Keep'' near the exit. The background is simple and cheerful, emphasizing the comical nature of people easily jumping onto new ideas but struggling to stay firmly committed. The style is lighthearted, exaggerated, and cartoonish, focusing on expressing the fickleness and difficulty of holding onto beliefs with friendly and playful visuals.'),
 (2523, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'We know what we are, but know not what we may be.', 'William Shakespeare', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing in front of a large, whimsical mirror labeled ''The Future.'' The first character is looking at their clear reflection with a thoughtful, slightly puzzled expression. The second character peers curiously but their reflection in the mirror is shown as a playful, exaggerated version of what they might become (for example, a superhero costume, wizard robes, or a fanciful inventor with wild gadgets). The setting is light and imaginative, with soft clouds and stars around the mirror, suggesting possibility and potential. Include speech bubbles above the characters with the quote: ''We know what we are, but know not what we may be.'' The overall style should be colorful, friendly, and cartoonish, emphasizing hope and mystery rather than seriousness.'),
 (2199, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Pessimism never won any battle.', 'Dwight D. Eisenhower', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a medieval battlefield where two armies face off. On one side, soldiers look determined, with lively expressions, carrying flags and weapons, ready to fight. On the other side, a single gloomy character representing pessimism stands alone, slumped and looking discouraged, maybe with a frown and a dark rain cloud above his head. The battlefield background includes a simple castle or tents. Above the pessimistic figure, depict a small sign or thought bubble saying ''I guess we won''t win…'' to emphasize negativity. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated emotions to highlight the contrast between optimism and pessimism without any violence or harm.'),
 (2209, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Prediction is very difficult, especially about the future.', 'Niels Bohr', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a quirky fortune teller with a crystal ball sitting at a small round table draped with colorful cloths and mystical symbols. The fortune teller, wearing a turban and oversized round glasses, has a puzzled expression while scratching their head. In the crystal ball, instead of a clear vision, there is a confusing swirl of question marks and clocks flying around. Around the table, scattered papers labeled ''Predictions'' are crumpled or torn, emphasizing the difficulty. In the background, a calendar with rapidly flipping pages and a comic-style thought bubble coming from the fortune teller says, "Especially about the future!" The whole setting should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize humor without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (1756, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'History is made at night. Character is what you are in the dark.', 'John, Lord Whorfin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene divided vertically down the middle into two contrasting halves. On the left half, depict a cheerful, lively daytime setting with a bright sun, blue sky, and a confident person smiling in broad daylight—wearing casual, neat clothes and standing tall. On the right half, illustrate the same person in a dark, nighttime environment with a dim moon, stars, and shadows. In this dark half, the person''s facial expression changes to show their true character—either thoughtful, mischievous, or contemplative. The person is illuminated only by a soft, mysterious light that highlights their face, leaving the rest in shadow. Include subtle elements to represent ''history made'' on the left side (like a book or calendar page marked today) and ''character'' on the right side (like a mirror or faint reflection revealing the inner self). Make the style playful and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between light/day and dark/night in a visually funny and clear way, without any scary or intense elements.'),
 (1981, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'It is not enought to be wicked to prosper.', 'Victor Hugo', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky, mischievous character trying various silly ways to ''prosper.'' The character should look playful and a bit sneaky, with exaggerated facial expressions showing determination but also a hint of struggle. They could be holding a bag of money or a golden trophy just out of reach, symbolizing prosperity. Around them are humorous obstacles or symbols of wickedness, like a devilish pitchfork, a mischievous grin, or tiny cartoon flames or sparks representing ''wickedness.'' The background is lighthearted and colorful, with a simple office or home setting to contrast the character''s antics. Include a thought bubble above the character''s head containing the text: "It''s not enough to be wicked to prosper." The overall style should be cartoonish and fun, avoiding anything threatening, and focusing on the comedic effort to succeed despite just being ''wicked.'''),
 (984, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Relatable', 'The worst thing about the worst thing that could happen is that we know that the worst thing could happen.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a small table with a cup of coffee, looking puzzled and stressed. Their thought bubble should contain a dramatic swirling dark cloud labeled ''The Worst Thing'' with exaggerated lightning bolts and cartoonish eyes to personify the ''worst thing.'' Around the person, subtle smaller thought bubbles show different possible disasters, each increasingly absurd but all labeled ''worst thing.'' The background is a simple room with a calendar on the wall showing a marked day, emphasizing anticipation. The person''s expression is a mix of worry and irony, capturing the endless loop of worrying about the worst possible outcome. The art style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors to keep the mood funny rather than gloomy.'),
 (985, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Space Humor', 'The meek shall inherit the Earth. The rest of us shall go the the Stars!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon split into two halves. On the left side, depict a meek-looking person—timid, small, with wide eyes—standing on green Earth, holding a little plant or flower, symbolizing inheriting the Earth peacefully. The Earth should be bright and cheerful, with a few trees and animals to show a hospitable environment. On the right side, show a group of confident, adventurous-looking people wearing space suits or casual space traveler outfits, happily boarding or floating around a large spaceship labeled ''Stars.'' The background is a starry, deep-space scene with twinkling stars, planets, and a shining spaceship ready to take off. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions showing calm contentment on the Earth side and excitement or ambition on the Stars side. Make sure the scene is clear, friendly, and humorous, emphasizing the contrast between the meek inheriting Earth and the others aiming for the stars, without any negative or aggressive elements.'),
 (2793, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Don''t let your mind wander. It''s too little to be out there alone.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, anthropomorphized brain wearing sneakers and a tiny backpack, looking nervously lost and wandering in a large, open landscape like a wide park or empty field. The brain has eyes wide open and tiny hands holding a map upside down. In the background, there is a signpost pointing in several confusing directions with arrows labeled ''Thoughts,'' ''Memories,'' and ''Ideas.'' On the side, a smiling person watches the brain with a speech bubble saying, ''Don''t let your mind wander. It''s too little to be out there alone.'' The style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and clear outlines, emphasizing the contrast between the small wandering brain and the vast surroundings.'),
 (986, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'Seeing is believing - so you can close your eyes and be in Kansas.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing with their eyes closed, smiling peacefully, with a large thought bubble above their head. Inside the thought bubble is a colorful, whimsical depiction of Kansas, featuring iconic imagery like wide open fields, sunflowers, a flying tornado with a friendly face, and a small farm with a red barn. The person is casually dressed and standing in a simple, nondescript room. The caption or text on a sign nearby reads: ''Seeing is believing – so you can close your eyes and be in Kansas.'' The overall style is light-hearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the surreal, imaginative feel of ''being in Kansas'' while closing eyes.'),
 (987, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'The difference between genius and stupidity is that genius has its limits.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters side by side. On the left, a person labeled ''Genius'' has a large, glowing brain visible above their head, wearing glasses and a thoughtful expression. They are surrounded by books, math equations, or scientific symbols floating in the air, indicating intelligence and limits. On the right, a person labeled ''Stupidity'' looks confused or silly with a goofy, exaggerated facial expression, scratching their head with question marks circling above it, with an endless road or path stretching behind them to symbolize ''no limits.'' The background is light, with a simple classroom or office setting to keep a casual, friendly mood. The style should be colorful, whimsical, and exaggerated without any negativity, emphasizing the playful contrast between intelligence and foolishness in a light-hearted manner.'),
 (988, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'The future isn''t what it used to be... it never was.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple living room with a person sitting in an old-fashioned armchair, looking thoughtfully into the distance. Above their head is a classic thought bubble with a whimsical, blurry illustration of a futuristic city that is half-built and half-disintegrated, with uncertain shapes and question marks floating around it. The person looks a bit confused and slightly amused, with one eyebrow raised. Around them are some retro objects, like an old radio, a calendar on the wall showing a past year, and a clock with loose numbers falling off. The style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and rounded, soft lines for a classic cartoon feel. No violence or controversial elements present.'),
 (989, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'The meek shall inherit the earth... if that''s o.k. with the rest of you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors with a small group of diverse, exaggeratedly confident characters standing on a globe representing Earth. In the center, a very meek-looking character (timid posture, glasses, a book labeled ''Meekness 101'') is raising a hand hesitantly and looking worried. Surrounding this character are several louder, bolder characters — one with crossed arms and a skeptical expression, another pointing at the meek character with a smirk, and a third rolling their eyes or shrugging. The globe beneath them is colorful and detailed with continents and oceans, emphasizing ''the Earth.'' The style is lighthearted and playful, with expressive faces showing disbelief or annoyance. A speech bubble above the meek character says, "The meek shall inherit the earth... if that''s o.k. with the rest of you." The background is simple, perhaps with a few clouds or sun to keep focus on characters and the globe. The overall tone is comedic and ironic, highlighting the meek character’s uncertainty and the others’ resistance in a non-threatening, funny way.'),
 (990, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'The only reason some people get lost in thought is because it''s unfamiliar territory.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing at the edge of a small cliff labeled ''Thought Territory.'' The person looks confused and lost, holding a map upside down with a question mark above their head. Behind them is a familiar, cozy-looking town labeled ''Reality,'' with smiling people going about their day. The landscape around the cliff is whimsical and abstract, with floating clouds shaped like various symbols representing ideas (light bulbs, question marks). The style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and clean lines to emphasize the humor of being ''lost in thought'' as if it''s a physical place one can get lost in.'),
 (991, 'Humor, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'What do you get when you cross a Mafia don with a deconstructionist?  Somebody who makes you an offer you can''t understand.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring two main characters combining traits of a Mafia don and a deconstructionist philosopher. On one side, depict a classic Mafia don: a portly man wearing a pinstriped suit, fedora hat tilted, with a cigar in his mouth and a stern expression. On the other side, show an academic-looking man with glasses, messy hair, and holding a thick book labeled ''Deconstruction Theory.'' Between them, show a confused person scratching their head, wearing casual clothes, surrounded by question marks and speech bubbles with fragmented, complex words and confusing symbols. The setting should look like a dimly-lit office with a desk and an old-fashioned rotary phone. Include a large sign on the wall that says, ''An Offer You Can’t Understand'' in bold letters. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features to emphasize confusion and humor, avoiding any violent or threatening imagery.'),
 (992, 'Humor, Philosophy, Programming', 'Life would be so much easier if we could just look at the source code.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting comfortably at a desk with a big, exaggerated computer monitor in front of them. The monitor displays complex, colorful, and tangled lines of code, with some humorous snippets like function names: lifeProblems(), happiness(), and love(). The person has a curious and slightly puzzled expression, scratching their head as if wishing they could understand the code of life. Around them, everyday objects like a coffee mug, a calendar marked with chaotic events, and a thought bubble showing a simplified, happy life flowchart add to the scene. The background is a cozy home office with playful details such as post-it notes saying ''If only...'' and ''debug life()''. The style is cheerful, cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated features to emphasize humor and relatability without any violent or controversial content.'),
 (993, 'Humor, Philosophy, Quotes', 'It is better to keep your mouth shut and have people think you are a fool, than to open it and remove all doubt.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting quietly on a park bench with a calm and thoughtful expression. Their mouth is gently closed, and a light bulb above their head glows softly to indicate a clever idea or thought. Nearby, a small group of people are whispering and looking puzzled, as if unsure about the quiet person''s intelligence. To the right, the same person is shown in a separate circular inset, now with their mouth wide open, animatedly speaking, and exaggeratedly silly expressions that confuse the onlookers, who now laugh or raise their eyebrows in amusement. The background is a simple park with a few trees, bushes, and a clear sky, drawn with vibrant colors to keep the cartoon light and friendly. The whole image plays on the contrast between silence implying mystery and speaking revealing foolishness in a comedic way, without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (994, 'Humor, Philosophy, Science', 'Maybe oxygen is a very lethal poison that just takes 75-100 years to work', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a playful personified oxygen molecule wearing a mischievous grin, holding a small hourglass dripping sand slowly. The oxygen molecule stands next to an elderly smiling human cartoon character sitting in a rocking chair, wearing comfy clothes and glasses, looking relaxed and unaware. Around them are subtle symbols of aging, like a birthday cake with many candles and a calendar showing many years passing. The setting is bright and cheerful, maybe in a cozy living room or a park bench, emphasizing the long timespan. The style is light, colorful, and whimsical with exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke that oxygen is a slow-acting poison.'),
 (995, 'Humor, Philosophy, Science', 'Men love to wonder, and that is the seed of science.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of men gathered around a large plant pot labeled ''Science.'' From the pot, a whimsical seedling with exaggerated light bulbs as leaves is sprouting, symbolizing ideas and knowledge growing. The men have curious and thoughtful expressions, some stroking their chins or pointing at the seedling. The background is simple, with a lab table holding beakers and books titled ''Wonder'' and ''Curiosity.'' The overall style is light-hearted and colorful, emphasizing the connection between wonder and the birth of science without being serious or technical.'),
 (996, 'Humor, Philosophy, Word Play', 'Life is like an analogy.', NULL, 'Draw a light-hearted cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, slightly confused character standing at a blackboard or flip chart. The blackboard or chart has the phrase ''Life is like an analogy'' written prominently. The character, a simple stick-figure or cartoon person with exaggerated puzzled eyebrows and a playful smile, is holding a pointer stick or chalk, as if explaining the phrase. Around the character, include whimsical thought bubbles illustrating confusing but related items—for example, a clock, a fruit, a puzzle piece, and a question mark—to visually show the abstract and humorous concept of comparing life to an analogy. The style should be colorful, simple, and playful, evoking a light, philosophical humor without any complexity or negativity.'),
 (997, 'Humor, Philosophy, Word Play', 'My opinions may change, but not the fact that I am right.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident person standing on a small stage or platform with their arms crossed and a smug smile. The person is surrounded by floating speech bubbles showing changing opinions, like a thumbs up, a question mark, a lightbulb, and a shrug emoji, illustrating the idea of shifting viewpoints. Despite the changing speech bubbles, a large bold sign behind or above them reads clearly, ''I AM RIGHT.'' The setting should look lighthearted and colorful, avoiding any negativity, with a few laughing or puzzled audience characters watching the person. The style is simple and exaggerated, with big expressive eyes and playful lines to emphasize the humor in stubborn self-assurance despite changing opinions.'),
 (998, 'Humor, Physical Comedy, Relatable', 'They say dance like nobody is watching so I did, but someone was watching - they thought I was having a seizure and called an ambulance!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a living room. In the center, a person is enthusiastically dancing wildly with exaggerated, awkward movements, arms flailing and legs bent in odd angles. Their eyes are closed, completely absorbed in the dance, unaware of anything around them. Nearby, through a large window or an open door, a neighbor or passerby looks on with wide, concerned eyes, holding a phone to their ear as if calling an ambulance. The neighbor’s facial expression shows worry and confusion. The room is cozy and well-lit, with simple furniture like a couch, a coffee table with a small plant, and a framed picture on the wall. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with playful exaggeration to emphasize the awkward dancing and the misunderstanding. Speech or thought bubbles can be included if desired: the dancer thinking “Dance like nobody’s watching!” and the neighbor thinking “Is that a seizure?”'),
 (999, 'Humor, Physical Comedy, Relatable Humor', 'The severity of the itch is proportional to the reach.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person trying desperately to scratch an itch on their back. The person should be exaggeratedly stretching their arm and body in an awkward, almost impossible pose to reach the itchy spot. Their face should show a mix of frustration and determination. Include subtle visual humor like sweat drops or little red scratch marks appearing where they are trying to reach. The background can be simple, such as a plain room or outdoor setting, emphasizing the person’s struggle. Optionally, add a measuring tape or a graph next to the person showing a comical ''proportional relationship'' between the length of the reach and the intensity of the itch as a funny visual metaphor.'),
 (1000, 'Humor, Poker Humor', 'Never do card tricks for the group you play poker with.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a poker table with four players sitting around it. The main focus is on one player in the middle of performing a flashy card trick, holding cards fanned out dramatically. The other three players have unimpressed, annoyed, or suspicious expressions. The poker table is cluttered with poker chips, cards, and drinks. One player is crossing their arms, another is sighing heavily, and the last is giving a side-eye glance. The setting should be bright and lively but with a comic sense of tension. Include a thought bubble or small speech bubble from one player saying something like ''Focus on the game!'' to emphasize the joke, but keep it light and playful. The style should be colorful and exaggerated, with cartoonish facial expressions to highlight the humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2143, 'Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'No man''s life, liberty or property are safe while the legislature is in session.', 'Gideon J., Judge Tucker', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a traditional legislative chamber, with a large wooden podium and desks arranged in a semicircle. At the center, depict a mischievous-looking group of legislators in suits and ties, some with playful smirks, holding oversized pens or stacks of papers like bills. In the foreground, a confused and worried common man stands looking at a chart labeled ''Life, Liberty & Property'' that comically shows these items slowly disappearing or shrinking. Maybe include whimsical elements such as a liberty statue on one desk with its torch lowered or a property deed flying out of a window. Use exaggerated, cartoonish expressions to emphasize the man’s concern and the legislators’ sly intent, giving the overall image a lighthearted, satirical tone without any negativity or hostility. The background should include classic legislative details like flags or a clock to set the official mood.'),
 (2207, 'Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Politics is far too important to leave in the hands of politicans.', 'Patrick Stewart', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a group of stereotypical politicians in a chaotic office, looking confused and bumbling while frantically trying to manage a giant, complex machine labeled ''Politics.'' Nearby, an ordinary person watches with a skeptical, unimpressed expression, arms crossed. The background should include typical political symbols, such as a podium, campaign posters, and stacks of papers. The exaggerated facial expressions and body language of the politicians should emphasize their ineptitude, while the onlooker embodies the idea that politics is too important for such people to handle alone. The style should be colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated features to enhance the humor and keep the tone light and playful.'),
 (1384, 'Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'A conservative is a man who does not think that anything should be done for the first time.', 'Frank Vanderlip', 'A humorous cartoon showing a middle-aged man labeled ''Conservative'' standing stubbornly with his arms crossed in front of a large, old-fashioned, creaky door labeled ''New Ideas.'' Behind the door, bright light and colorful signs say ''First Time Ever!'' and ''Innovations Inside!'' The man wears a suit and tie, has a slightly perplexed but determined expression, and is surrounded by cobwebs and traditional objects like a classic clock and an old rotary phone. Near him is a younger character holding a blueprint or gadget enthusiastically, trying to convince him to open the door. The background has a simple indoor setting with a small plant and a picture frame showing historical scenes to emphasize tradition. The overall tone is light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the hesitation to try anything new.'),
 (1449, 'Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Workplace', 'A motion to adjourn is always in order.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a formal meeting room with a round table and several characters sitting around it. One character, depicted as a slightly overwhelmed but cheerful chairperson or moderator holding a gavel, is raising a hand while saying, ''A motion to adjourn is always in order.'' Around the table, people look relieved, happy, or excited, as if they are eager for the meeting to end. Include simple details like stacks of papers, nameplates, water glasses, and a clock on the wall showing late hour. The setting should exaggerate the formality of meetings with comically serious faces but with a lighthearted, friendly vibe. The style is colorful cartoon with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor about the common meeting phrase.'),
 (1001, 'Humor, Political Humor, Relatable', 'The state of the world can be accurately gauged by the numbers of cars in the Pentagon parking lot on any given midnight.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at midnight outside the Pentagon building, which is clearly labeled with a large sign reading ''PENTAGON'' on its facade. The background is dark with a moon and stars visible in the sky. The foreground shows a large, well-lit parking lot filled with cars, highlighting an excessive number of vehicles parked there at such an unusual hour. A couple of characters (maybe two friends or coworkers) stand at the edge of the parking lot looking surprised or puzzled while pointing at the sheer volume of parked cars. To add humor, one character could be holding a giant, exaggerated stopwatch or a world globe to symbolize ''gauging the state of the world.'' The overall style is light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish with simple, exaggerated expressions to emphasize the witty commentary on world affairs and government activity at odd hours. No violence, political bias, or complex elements—just a funny, clear visual metaphor for the joke''s message about secretive or intense government involvement.'),
 (1002, 'Humor, Political Humor, Technology Humor', 'The reason the government thinks you''re a number is because it''s just a machine.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, old-fashioned, bulky government machine with various blinking lights, levers, and a classic typewriter-style printout coming out the front. The machine has a simplistic, slightly anthropomorphic face with tired eyes, emphasizing it as just a cold, unfeeling device. Next to the machine stands an ordinary person looking confused or frustrated while holding up a sign with their name and a big digit ''7'' printed on it. The background is an office setting with filing cabinets and paperwork piled high, with a subtle joke atmosphere. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated in a cartoon style, focusing on the idea that the government processes people impersonally, as if they are just numbers for a machine.'),
 (1003, 'Humor, Politics, Social Commentary', 'Now and then an innocent man is sent to the Legislature.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a slightly confused, nervous man wearing simple everyday clothes standing at the entrance of a large, grand government building labeled ''Legislature.'' The man looks out of place among several slick, scheming-looking politicians inside, who are depicted with exaggerated sly grins and shifty eyes. The setting should look like a classic legislative chamber with rows of desks, microphones, and flags, all drawn in a lighthearted, exaggerated manner to emphasize the surreal idea of an "innocent man" entering this environment. The innocent man’s expression contrasts sharply with the sly, cunning politicians, highlighting his naivety. Use bright, cheerful colors to keep the tone funny and non-threatening, and include speech bubbles with question marks or sweat drops to reflect the man''s confusion or nervousness. The style should clearly be cartoonish and playful, without any hints of violence or negativity.'),
 (1004, 'Humor, Politics, Social Commentary', 'Taxes are not levied for the benefit of the taxed.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a confused, slightly frustrated taxpayer sitting at a cluttered desk covered in paperwork labeled ''Taxes.'' The taxpayer is holding a form and looking at a large, looming, shadowy figure in the background labeled ''Government'' or ''Tax Authority.'' The figure is happily counting money bags or throwing money into a giant vault, clearly benefiting from the taxes. The taxpayer’s speech bubble reads, ''Taxes are not levied for my benefit?!'' In the foreground, piles of money flow from the taxpayer’s desk toward the vault, emphasizing the one-sided benefit. The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive faces and bright colors to emphasize humor without any aggression or political symbols.'),
 (1005, 'Humor, Pop Culture', 'Internationally, Baywatch is the most popular TV show in history.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a sunny, busy beach with golden sand and bright blue water. In the foreground, a group of lifeguards wearing classic red Baywatch swimsuits and holding rescue buoys are standing proudly on the shore. They have big, exaggerated smiles and confident poses as if they are celebrities. Around them, tourists from various countries are excitedly taking photos, holding international flags, and wearing T-shirts with worldwide landmarks like the Eiffel Tower and the Statue of Liberty. A large television screen on the beach plays the Baywatch show, with oversized ON AIR-style text above it. The sign reads: ''Internationally, Baywatch is the most popular TV show in history.'' Palm trees, beach umbrellas, and seagulls add to the lively, fun seaside atmosphere. The overall tone is bright, cheerful, and clearly pokes fun at the global fame of the show in a lighthearted, cartoonish style.'),
 (1006, 'Humor, Pop Culture', 'National Enquirer headline we''ll never see:  Elvis Is Dead', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a front page of a tabloid newspaper displayed on a newsstand with the headline ''Elvis Is Dead''. The newspaper has exaggerated, flashy fonts and eye-catching colors typical of sensational tabloids. Surrounding the newsstand are caricatured people reacting with surprise and confusion—two elderly fans wearing Elvis-style sunglasses and leather jackets, a reporter looking shocked, and a bystander with a raised eyebrow. In the background, there’s a subtle ghostly silhouette or shadow of Elvis Presley with his iconic hairstyle and sideburns, giving a playful nod to the joke’s implication that such a headline would never be printed. The overall tone is lighthearted and humorous, drawn in a classic comic strip style with bright colors and exaggerated expressions.'),
 (1007, 'Humor, Pop Culture', 'Princess Leia is technically a Disney princess now', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing Princess Leia standing in the center dressed in her iconic white robes and signature cinnamon bun hairstyle. She''s holding a small Disney castle model in one hand, with a playful, slightly surprised expression on her face. Around her are subtle references to both Star Wars and Disney: a faint magical sparkle effect around the castle, a background blend of a galaxy with stars and a Disney theme park castle silhouette. A few other classic Disney princesses like Cinderella or Snow White peek from behind the castle, looking amused or surprised to see Leia with them. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and whimsical, emphasizing the playful merger of the two worlds without any tension or conflict. No violent or political imagery, focusing purely on imagination and fun crossover vibes.'),
 (1008, 'Humor, Pop Culture, Puns', 'What are terminators called when they retire? Exterminators', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of Terminator-style robots in a retirement home setting. The robots have a metallic, humanoid appearance with glowing red eyes, but instead of looking menacing, they appear relaxed and cheerful, engaging in leisure activities like playing cards or knitting. One robot is wearing reading glasses and holding a newspaper with the headline ''Retirement Tips for Terminators.'' Another robot is reclining in a rocking chair with a cup of tea. In the background, include a sign that says ''Exterminators Retirement Community.'' The overall mood should be lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the pun ''Exterminators'' by showing these tough robots now taking it easy in retirement. Use bright, cartoonish colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (1636, 'Humor, Pop Culture, Quotes, Star Wars Humor', 'Do not underestimate the power of the Force.', 'Darth Vader', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small, ordinary object unexpectedly radiating a glowing mystical aura representing ''the Force.'' Place a cardboard box or a simple kitchen lamp in the center, glowing with bright blue and white energy swirls around it. Nearby, a surprised person, drawn in a lighthearted cartoon style, stares wide-eyed and mouth-open at the object. They wear casual clothes and stand in a living room setting with minimal furniture, like a couch and a coffee table with a cup of coffee. Add whimsical sparkles and floating small stars around the object to emphasize its ''Force'' power. The overall tone is playful and magical, with exaggerated expressions but no intensity, suitable for a family-friendly audience. The background is simple with soft pastel colors to keep focus on the glowing object and the person''s reaction.'),
 (1009, 'Humor, Pop Culture, Science', 'Reality is for people who can''t face science fiction.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side. On the left, a person dressed in everyday casual clothes is holding a newspaper titled ''Today’s Reality'' and looking somewhat bored or unimpressed. On the right, another character is dressed in a futuristic sci-fi outfit with glowing gadgets, a hoverboard at their feet, and a small robot companion. This sci-fi character looks confident and excited, pointing towards a bright, imaginative background filled with flying cars, alien landscapes, and starships. Between them, a speech bubble from the sci-fi character says, "Reality is for people who can''t face science fiction." The style should be lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing the contrast between mundane reality and exciting sci-fi fantasy. The setting can be a neutral simple background fading from a dull urban area near the reality character to a vibrant sci-fi world near the other character.'),
 (1010, 'Humor, Pop Culture, Science Fiction Humor', 'To hell with the Prime Directive - let''s kill something.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style scene set on the bridge of a starship, clearly inspired by classic sci-fi, with a diverse crew of colorful aliens and humans in futuristic uniforms. In the center, a captain with a confident, mischievous grin is dramatically throwing down a large, old-fashioned book titled ''Prime Directive'' onto a console. Around the captain, the crew reacts with surprised, shocked, or excited expressions. The background shows futuristic control panels, blinking lights, and viewscreens displaying outer space with distant planets and stars. Emphasize exaggerated cartoonish features and lively expressions to highlight the humor of breaking a well-known serious rule for a ridiculous reason. No violence should be depicted—just the playful mood of wanting to do something rebellious in a sci-fi setting.'),
 (1011, 'Humor, Pop Culture, Star Wars', 'Look! There''s a Klingon vessel, Mr. Chekov!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set on the bridge of the Starship Enterprise from Star Trek. In the foreground, a surprised and slightly confused Russian crewmember, Mr. Chekov, wearing a classic Starfleet uniform with a distinctive golden shirt, points excitedly out a large curved window. Outside the window, visible in space, is a brightly colored Klingon bird-of-prey spaceship with exaggerated, cartoonish features such as large wings, sharp angles, and menacing eyes on its hull to make it look funny rather than threatening. The setting should look like a sci-fi spaceship interior with control panels, blinking lights, and futuristic screens in the background. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, capturing the moment of Mr. Chekov excitedly announcing the Klingon vessel to his crewmates, but with a smile or smirk from nearby characters to imply the joke is appreciated. The style is simple, colorful, and exaggerates facial expressions for comedic effect.'),
 (1012, 'Humor, Pop Culture, Star Wars', 'Why did Star Wars 4,5,6 come before 1,2,3? Because in charge of scheduling, Yoda was.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring Yoda sitting behind a large, cluttered office desk labeled ''Scheduling Department.'' Yoda is wearing oversized round glasses and looking thoughtfully at a big calendar that shows movie release schedules. The calendar humorously lists Star Wars episodes with ''4, 5, 6'' scheduled in the earlier months and ''1, 2, 3'' booked later. In the background, posters of Star Wars movies (episodes 1-6) hang on the wall with the numbers out of order. Yoda holds a pen in one hand and scratches his head with the other in a puzzled and funny manner. Add a small sign on the desk saying ''Master Scheduler Yoda.'' The style should be colorful, cartoony, and lighthearted, emphasizing Yoda''s quirky personality and the joke about his confusing, backwards speech affecting movie release order. Include subtle Star Wars themed items like a lightsaber leaning against the desk and a small spaceship model on the shelf behind him to enhance the setting.'),
 (1013, 'Humor, Pop Culture, Word Play', 'STAR: A performer who makes more than his or her agent.  SUPERSTAR: A performer who makes more than Guatemala.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a brightly lit stage, featuring a confident performer dressed in flashy, over-the-top superstar attire (sparkly jacket, sunglasses, exaggerated hair). The performer is holding a large bag of money with a dollar sign on it, smiling proudly. To the side, a small, somewhat grumpy-looking person wearing a business suit and holding a contract represents the agent, looking surprised or bewildered as they see the performer''s earnings. In the background, a small, simple outline or tiny map of Guatemala with a dollar sign next to it emphasizes the comparison. The stage has spotlights and a shiny star symbol overhead. The overall tone is lighthearted and comedic, using exaggerated expressions and cartoonish proportions to emphasize the joke without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1711, 'Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Genius not only diagnoses the situation but supplies the answers.', 'Robert Graves', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person wearing oversized glasses and a lab coat labeled ''Genius.'' They stand confidently next to a thought bubble showing a messy problem—a tangled ball of yarn or a complicated knot labeled ''situation.'' The Genius is holding a bright glowing light bulb in one hand (representing ideas/answers) and pointing to a neat, untangled ball of yarn next to them labeled ''answers.'' The setting is simple, like a clean whiteboard or chalkboard backdrop with some scribbles, charts, or question marks to indicate complexity. The Genius character wears a satisfied grin, and maybe a little sparkle or shine around their head to emphasize intelligence. The overall tone is light-hearted and clever, with bold, clear lines and exaggerated cartoonish expressions, emphasizing the idea of diagnosing and solving problems in a smart, playful way. No other characters or backgrounds should distract from this central humorous concept.'),
 (2539, 'Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'What I''m looking for is a blessing that''s not in disguise.', 'Kitty O''Neill Collins', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing outdoors, looking hopeful and holding a large magnifying glass up to the sky. Around them are various comical ''blessings'' cleverly disguised as ordinary objects. For example, a cloud shaped like a gift box, an angel wing hidden behind a tree branch, a sunbeam partially blocked by a pair of sunglasses, and a smiling rabbit with a rabbit’s foot hanging from its neck like a necklace. The person is scanning these disguised blessings with a perplexed, yet determined expression, as if trying to find a blessing that is straightforward and obvious. The sky is bright with fluffy clouds, a few birds flying, and a rainbow faintly visible in the distance. The style is colorful, playful, and exaggerated in typical humorous cartoon fashion, with warm tones and friendly faces on some objects to emphasize the joke’s lightheartedness. No violence or anything inappropriate is present.'),
 (1014, 'Humor, Pranks, Science', 'Professor Eppendorf''s Laboratory Novelties and Practical Jokes: REMOTE-CONTROLLED GEIGER COUNTER: Looks and acts like a real geiger counter but you can make the needle jump at the press of a button. Hide the remote control in your pocket and make the needle move when people check themselves for radiation. They''ll go into hysterics thinking thay have received a lethal dose! Yuks galore!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a quirky science laboratory labeled ''Professor Eppendorf''s Laboratory''. On a cluttered wooden table, there is a classic-looking Geiger counter with a needle gauge prominently displayed. The Geiger counter looks old-fashioned but functional. Nearby, a mischievous scientist with wild hair, glasses, and a lab coat holds a small remote control with a big grin on his face. The remote is clearly pointed toward the Geiger counter. In front of the table, a worried-looking person is holding the Geiger counter to their chest, eyes wide with panic as the needle jumps wildly. Around them, scientific glassware, beakers, test tubes filled with colorful liquids, and scattered papers add to the lab atmosphere. Emphasize exaggerated cartoonish expressions: the scientist is gleefully sneaky, and the person testing themselves is comically alarmed, amplifying the joke’s playful prank vibe. The overall color scheme should be bright and lively to enhance the whimsical mood, and a little sign in the background reads ''Novelties and Practical Jokes''.'),
 (1327, 'Humor, Programmers, Programming, Pun', '!false (it''s funny because it''s true!)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a computer screen displaying a very simple code snippet: "!false" in large, clear font. Next to the screen, a cheerful programmer character with a knowing smile points at the code. The background shows a cozy home office with typical programmer items: a coffee mug labeled ''Code Fuel,'' a keyboard, and some scattered sticky notes. The expression on the programmer''s face conveys a mix of pride and amusement, emphasizing the simple truth behind the joke. The scene should be colorful and light-hearted to match the clever and witty tone, with exaggerated cartoon features for the programmer, such as big glasses and a casual T-shirt with a funny slogan related to coding or logic.'),
 (1331, 'Humor, Programmers, Pun, Relationship Humor', 'Arguing with a woman is like a software license agreement. To get to the end, you ignore everything and say ''I agree''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man and a woman sitting across from each other at a simple table. The man looks slightly confused but resigned, holding a computer mouse in one hand and looking towards a large computer screen in front of him. On the screen is a visible pop-up window styled like a software license agreement, with a long block of small text and a big button labeled ''I Agree.'' The woman is animatedly talking or gesturing, appearing slightly amused or emphatic. The setting should feel casual, like a living room or home office. Include subtle comedic details like the man sweating lightly or scratching his head, and the woman holding a speech bubble with multiple lines representing her argument. Draw in a bright, playful color palette with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize humor and lightheartedness. The style should be a clean, modern cartoon without anything offensive or inappropriate.'),
 (1015, 'Humor, Programming', 'Meets quality standards:  Compiles without errors.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon shows a computer programmer sitting at a desk cluttered with typical coding paraphernalia: multiple computer monitors displaying lines of colorful code, a keyboard, a coffee mug labeled ''Code Fuel,'' and sticky notes on the desk and monitor. The programmer is smiling proudly with a speech bubble that says, ''Meets quality standards: Compiles without errors.'' Around the desk, there are small cartoon-style celebratory elements like confetti or little stars to emphasize the joy of a successful compile. The background is a simple office or home workspace with minimal details to keep the focus on the programmer and the code. The overall mood is light-hearted and playful, highlighting the satisfaction programmers feel when their code compiles error-free.'),
 (1016, 'Humor, Programming', 'The effort required to correct a programming error increases with time.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered programmer''s workspace. On the left, a developer with exaggeratedly frazzled hair and wide eyes sits at a desk, staring at a computer screen showing a glowing red error message. Near the developer, a calendar on the wall shows days getting crossed off rapidly, emphasizing the passage of time. To the right, a large staircase or mountain labeled ''Effort'' rises steeply upward, with the programmer struggling to carry an increasingly heavy-looking error bug as they climb. The bug should look like a cartoonish beetle with a sad or mischievous face. The overall tone is lighthearted and cartoonish, with whimsical expressions and bright colors. The background includes coding symbols floating around to reinforce the programming context. No violence or inappropriate content, just a funny visual metaphor for how fixing bugs gets harder over time.'),
 (1017, 'Humor, Programming, Puns', 'Testing can show the presence of bugs, but not their absence.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon featuring a quirky software tester in a casual office setting cluttered with computers and coding books. The tester is holding a magnifying glass up to a computer screen filled with visible cartoon bugs (small, colorful insects with funny faces) crawling over lines of code. The tester looks puzzled, scratching their head. In the background, a whiteboard has the phrase ''Testing can show the presence of bugs but not their absence'' written in playful letters. Around the room, small whimsical details like a coffee mug labeled ''Bug Hunter'' and sticky notes with code jokes add to the lighthearted tech atmosphere. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with the bugs looking more mischievous than scary, emphasizing the joke''s pun on software bugs rather than real insects.'),
 (1018, 'Humor, Programming, Puns', 'The determined programmer can write a FORTRAN program in any language.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a programmer sitting confidently at a cluttered desk filled with multiple monitors, keyboards, and coffee mugs. The programmer has a focused and slightly smug expression, wearing casual techie clothes and glasses. Displayed on one monitor is code written in FORTRAN, but the surrounding screens show code snippets in various human languages (like English, French, Chinese characters, and Spanish) mixed with programming elements. A speech bubble above the programmer reads: "I can write FORTRAN in any language!" The background includes typical programmer items like sticky notes, a small plant, and a clock showing late hours. The overall style is light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the programmer''s determination and skill humorously without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1019, 'Humor, Programming, Puns', 'The value of a program is proportional to the weight of its output.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a programmer sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer. The programmer looks puzzled and is staring at the printer next to the desk. The printer is comically overloaded and struggling to spit out a huge stack of printed paper that is so tall it almost reaches the ceiling. The papers are plain sheets with random code snippets and lines of text. Nearby, a scale is placed underneath the paper stack, clearly showing a large weight number on its display. In the background, a whiteboard with some programming sketches and lines of code hangs on the wall. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and an emphasis on the heavy output paper stack as the ''weight'' representing program value. No violence or offensive content.'),
 (1020, 'Humor, Programming, Technology Humor', 'To understand a program you must become one with the machine and the program.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person half-transformed into a robot sitting at a desk with a computer. The human side looks curious and slightly confused, while the robot side has mechanical features like a metal arm with wires and a screen for an eye. The computer screen shows lines of code. Around the desk, include scattered programming books and a coffee cup labeled ''Fuel.'' Have subtle steam or blinking lights around the person to emphasize the process of becoming ''one'' with the machine. The setting is a quirky, colorful office space with typical programmer items such as a keyboard, mouse, and sticky notes with funny reminders. The overall style should be lighthearted and whimsical, highlighting the funny idea of literally merging with a machine to understand a program better.'),
 (1021, 'Humor, Programming, Word Play', 'My unix programmer got sick. It was a case of grep throat.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a Unix programmer sitting at a desk cluttered with computer screens displaying code and command lines. The programmer looks unwell, with a red, irritated throat and a sad expression, possibly holding a thermometer or a cup of tea. A speech bubble or sign near the programmer says ''grep throat'' in a playful font. Around the desk, include visual puns: maybe a magnifying glass highlighting the word ''throat'' on a monitor, referencing the ''grep'' command used to search text. The overall style should be lighthearted and colorful, with computer and programming elements clearly visible, emphasizing the joke about a Unix-specific ''sore throat''. Avoid any harsh or graphic imagery; keep it simple, cute, and geeky in style.'),
 (1022, 'Humor, Programming, Word Play', 'Newton''s Law of Programming: For every neat enhancement there is an equally neat bug.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered programmer''s workspace. At the center, a cheerful programmer is sitting at a desk filled with two computer monitors, keyboard, coffee mug, and scattered code papers. One monitor displays a neat, colorful ''enhancement'' window with a big green checkmark, while the other screen shows a bug report or an error message with a red warning symbol. Above the programmer, a playful cartoon thought bubble shows Newton''s Law of Programming written like a scientific law, perhaps with little arrows pointing between a neat enhancement and an equally neat bug, illustrated as a tiny cartoon bug holding a ruler. The background can feature sticky notes with code snippets and a poster humorously combining Isaac Newton''s apple with software icons. The overall tone is light and witty, emphasizing the programmer’s resigned but amused acceptance of bugs appearing after improvements. The style is friendly and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor in the contradiction.'),
 (1023, 'Humor, Programming, Word Play', 'Profanity is the one language all programmers know best.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stressed programmer sitting at a cluttered desk covered with multiple computer monitors, keyboards, and empty coffee cups. The programmer looks frustrated, with a furrowed brow and hands raised in exasperation. Around the programmer''s head are little comic-style speech bubbles filled with typical symbols representing swear words (like @#!%&*). The computer screens display lines of messy, error-filled code. Behind the programmer, a whiteboard features diagrams and notes mixed with colorful profanity symbols. The setting is a typical office or home workspace with tech gadgets and sticky notes scattered about. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the universal frustration and humorous language all programmers share when debugging or coding.'),
 (1024, 'Humor, Programming, Word Play', 'Some programming languages manage to absorb change but withstand progress.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a group of programming language characters personified as quirky robots or computer icons. One robot labeled ''Legacy Language'' looks worn-out, patched up with duct tape and bandages, symbolizing it absorbing changes but looking tired and old-fashioned. Another sleek, shiny robot labeled ''Modern Language'' is confidently walking forward with a futuristic vibe, carrying a briefcase labeled ''Progress.'' In the background, a puzzled crowd of smaller, neutral characters watches this interaction, representing programmers or users. The setting is a simple office space with code snippets on screens and a whiteboard showing arrows labeled ''Change'' pointing toward the Legacy Language robot, which tries to absorb these arrows, while arrows labeled ''Progress'' bounce off it, causing some comic confusion. Overall, the scene is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions on the robots, emphasizing the joke''s play on adaptation to change but resistance to progress in programming languages.'),
 (1025, 'Humor, Programming, Word Play', 'Structured Programming supports the law of the excluded muddle.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a confused programmer sitting at a cluttered desk filled with open books and computer screens showing tangled, messy code. The programmer is scratching their head, looking puzzled. Above them, depict a playful sign or chalkboard that says ''Law of the Excluded Muddle'' instead of the usual ''Law of the Excluded Middle.'' Around them, add symbols representing structured programming, like neat flowcharts and simple code blocks, but tangled lines and question marks mixed in to emphasize confusion and muddle. The overall tone should be lighthearted and silly, capturing the irony of a logical programming concept becoming mixed up and perplexing.'),
 (1026, 'Humor, Programming, Word Play', 'There are two ways to write error-free programs; only the third one works.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a programmer sitting at a cluttered desk with multiple computer screens. On one screen, a document titled ''Error-Free Programs'' is open, displaying two crossed-out methods labeled ''Method 1'' and ''Method 2'' with big red X marks. The programmer looks puzzled but amused, scratching their head. Above the desk, a thought bubble reads, ''There are two ways to write error-free programs; only the third one works.'' Nearby, an open notebook or whiteboard humorously shows a blank space or question marks where the ''third method'' should be, suggesting it’s unknown or mysterious. The environment includes typical programmer items like coffee mugs, code snippets on paper, and a small plant to add charm. The overall style is light and comical, emphasizing the irony and frustration programmers face with bugs and errors, in a non-threatening, funny way.'),
 (1027, 'Humor, Programming, Word Play', 'To be, or not to be, those are the parameters.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused Shakespeare character holding a large scroll or script with the famous line, but altered: ''To be, or not to be, those are the parameters.'' Shakespeare should be standing in a classic Elizabethan setting, perhaps in a dimly lit study or on a small stage with wooden floorboards. Around him, instead of the usual philosophical props, include some modern elements associated with programming or math – such as lines of code or parameter boxes floating in the air, question marks, and maybe a speech bubble with binary numbers or function arguments. Shakespeare’s facial expression should be puzzled but comedic, scratching his head or furrowing his brow. The overall style should be light, colorful, and exaggerated like a classic cartoon, capturing the playfully nerdy twist on the famous Shakespeare quote.'),
 (1028, 'Humor, Programming, Workplace', 'One day I''m going to write a user-friendly program that will still respect me in the morning.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a cluttered desk with a computer, looking tired but determined. The computer screen displays code with friendly icons and messages like ''Good Morning!'' and ''Respecting User Preferences''. The person has a hopeful smile, coffee mug nearby with steam rising. Behind them, a calendar on the wall shows early morning hours, hinting they stayed up late. The setting should feel light and playful, with bright colors, simple lines, and exaggerated expressions that emphasize the mix of exhaustion and ambition. Include little details like crumpled paper balls, a clock showing morning time, and motivational posters about programming on the wall to add humor and context.'),
 (1029, 'Humor, Programming, Workplace', 'Real programmers... don''t dress for success unless they are trying to convince others that they are going on job interviews.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two programmers sitting in a casual office environment. One programmer is wearing a messy t-shirt with code symbols, jeans, and slippers, working comfortably at his computer surrounded by coffee cups, snack wrappers, and multiple monitors displaying lines of code. The other programmer is standing up in the foreground, wearing a sharp business suit and tie, holding a briefcase and looking slightly awkward or out of place. A wall clock and some tech posters or sticky notes are visible in the background. The environment clearly looks like a relaxed tech workspace that contrasts with the dressed-up programmer, highlighting the joke that programmers usually dress down unless they are preparing for a job interview. The overall tone should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the contrast between casual and formal attire in a humorous way.'),
 (1030, 'Humor, Psychology Humor', 'My therapist says I have trouble expressing emotions.  I can''t say I''m surprised.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a person sitting on a comfy armchair in a therapist''s office. The person looks slightly awkward or uncomfortable, with a blank or deadpan facial expression, mouth closed as if unable to speak. Across from them, a friendly therapist sits with a clipboard and glasses, leaning slightly forward as if listening carefully, wearing a calm expression. The setting includes a framed diploma on the wall, a small potted plant, and a box of tissues on a side table. The scene should visually emphasize the difficulty of expressing emotions: the patient appears silent and unexpressive, while the therapist shows understanding. A speech bubble from the therapist reads, "You have trouble expressing emotions," and a second smaller speech bubble near the patient reads, "I can''t say I''m surprised." The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with clean lines and bright colors, creating a relatable and funny mental image of therapy and emotional expression struggles without seriousness or gloominess.'),
 (2079, 'Humor, Psychology Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Man tends to root for the underdog, because he fears that he will find himself in that same position far too often.', 'Michael S. Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting on a couch watching a sports game on TV. The TV screen displays a tiny, scrappy underdog team or competitor clearly losing or struggling. The man''s expression is a mix of nervousness and sympathy, subtly worried as he leans forward, eyes wide, rooting intensely for the underdog. Around the room, small visual clues hint at his personal fears or challenges, like a calendar marked with setbacks or a small plant wilting on a table. The overall atmosphere combines sports enthusiasm with a touch of self-awareness and anxiety, rendered in bright, friendly colors with exaggerated, comical facial expressions. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, capturing both the humor and the emotion behind rooting for the underdog out of personal fear of being in that tough spot.'),
 (2514, 'Humor, Psychology Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'We confess our little faults to persuade people that we have no large ones.', 'L. Rochefoucauld', 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting on a park bench in a peaceful outdoor setting. One character is nervously confessing small, silly mistakes with exaggerated expressions—like spilling coffee, tripping over shoelaces, or forgetting to water a plant—while the other character listens with a skeptical but intrigued look. Above them, include a lighthearted thought bubble showing a giant, shadowy, mysterious figure (representing a large fault) lurking in the background just out of clear sight, hinting at hidden big faults. Keep the style bright and playful with soft colors, using simple, rounded character designs to enhance the humor and relatability of admitting small faults to hide bigger ones.'),
 (1031, 'Humor, Psychology Humor, Word Play', 'My superiority complex is better than your superiority complex.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two quirky characters standing face-to-face, both with exaggerated confident expressions and puffed-up chests. Each character wears a t-shirt with the phrase ''Superiority Complex'' printed on it. Above their heads are speech bubbles: one says, ''My superiority complex is better than yours!'' The background is simple and colorful, emphasizing the playful rivalry. One character might be slightly taller or wearing glasses to add contrast, and both have comically smug smiles. The scene should be lighthearted and playful, with cartoon-style bold outlines and vibrant colors, capturing the ironic and self-contradictory tone of the joke.'),
 (1937, 'Humor, Pun, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Improve your odds by increasing your wisdom.', 'J. A. Agnew', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise old owl wearing round spectacles perched on top of a large stack of books titled ''Wisdom,'' ''Philosophy,'' and ''Life Lessons.'' In front of the owl, a character—in a playful, slightly exaggerated cartoon style—holds a pair of dice and looks thoughtfully at them, as if trying to ''improve their odds.'' The character should have a curious expression, eyebrows raised, and a slight smile. Surrounding the character are floating question marks and lightbulbs symbolizing thinking and ideas. The setting is a cozy, bright study room with a window showing a sunny day outside. A small table holds a cup of tea, more books, and a crystal ball, adding a mystical yet funny vibe. The overall tone is lighthearted and smart, blending the idea of gaining wisdom to ''improve your odds'' with the imagery of gambling or chance, making the joke clear without any violence or controversy.'),
 (1370, 'Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A brilliant smile will get you fan mail from lighthouses.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a charming, confident person standing on a rocky coastline at night. The person has an exaggeratedly bright, dazzling smile that literally shines like a spotlight. Nearby, several classic lighthouses on cliffs are animated with happy, blushing faces, holding letters or envelopes labeled ''Fan Mail'' and eagerly looking towards the smiling person. The sky is dark with stars, and waves gently crash around the lighthouses, enhancing the maritime atmosphere. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, with playful expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke.'),
 (1398, 'Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A fool and his money are soon partying.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a jovial, carefree fool character celebrating wildly at a lively party. The fool is a comical figure, wearing mismatched clothes and a silly hat, holding an open wallet with money flying out. Surrounding him are party elements like balloons, confetti, a punch bowl, and a disco ball hanging from the ceiling. In the background, a few amused party guests watch or dance, some holding drinks, smiling or laughing. The setting is a colorful, festive room with upbeat energy, emphasizing the lightheartedness of spending money quickly on fun rather than wisely saving it. The overall tone is playful and exaggerated to highlight the pun that a fool and his money ''are soon partying,'' as if the money itself is joining the party along with the fool.'),
 (1502, 'Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'Aibohphobia: the fear of palindromes.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon-style scene featuring a nervous, wide-eyed character standing in front of a large sign or book titled ''Palindromes''. The character is visibly worried, biting their nails or sweating comically, holding a flyer or dictionary page that highlights examples of palindromes like ''madam'', ''racecar'', and ''level''. Above their head, a thought bubble contains the palindrome word ''Aibohphobia'' mirrored forwards and backwards. Around the character, little visual palindrome symbols can appear (such as ''121'', ''ABA'') to emphasize the theme. The setting is lighthearted and colorful, with simple, exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor of fearing a linguistic curiosity. No dark or negative elements, just a playful take on an unusual phobia related to wordplay.'),
 (1816, 'Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'I hate quotations.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated person sitting at a cluttered desk, surrounded by stacks of books and papers filled with quotation marks everywhere. The person has an exaggeratedly annoyed expression, with steam coming out of their ears. Floating above their head are large, bold quotation marks looking like tiny mischievous characters, smirking and playfully poking or whispering to the person. The background is a simple office or study room with a bookshelf labeled ''Quotes,'' filled with books having visible quotation marks on spines. The style is colorful and exaggerated, emphasizing the person’s irritation and the overwhelming presence of quotation marks all around.'),
 (3180, 'Humor, Pun, Star Wars', 'What is the internal temperature of a taun-taun? Luke-warm', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a taun-taun, the furry, camel-like creature from Star Wars, standing calmly on a snow-covered icy planet reminiscent of Hoth. The taun-taun has a slightly puzzled or relaxed expression. Next to it, a cartoon Luke Skywalker dressed in his iconic white Hoth outfit is holding a large, old-fashioned meat thermometer inserted into the side of the taun-taun. The thermometer’s reading clearly shows a lukewarm temperature (around room temperature, 70°F/20°C) with wavy heat lines to exaggerate the pun. Both characters are drawn in a simple, colorful, exaggerated cartoon style with soft outlines. The background should have snowy hills, some sci-fi elements like Rebel base buildings or starships partially visible, and a clear sky. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful without any violence or threat, emphasizing the pun on “luke-warm.”'),
 (3123, 'Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Yesterday a clown held the door open for me. I thought it was a nice jester.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a clown standing at an open door, holding it wide open with a cheerful smile. The clown is dressed in traditional bright and oversized clown clothes: a big red nose, oversized shoes, colorful wig, and a polka-dot or striped outfit. The clown''s expression is friendly and welcoming. On the other side of the door, a casually-dressed person with a slightly amused or surprised look is about to walk through. Above or below them, a pun text bubble reads: ''I thought it was a nice jester.'' The background is simple and bright, suggesting a playful, everyday environment like a school, theater, or circus entrance. The overall style is lighthearted, cartoonish, and exaggerated to emphasize the clown’s silliness and the pun, without any dark or inappropriate elements.'),
 (2761, 'Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Did you hear about the new restaurant called Karma? There’s no menu: You get what you deserve.', NULL, 'Draw a cartoon-style scene inside a quirky, cozy restaurant named ''Karma'' with a bright, colorful sign above the entrance showing the name prominently. Inside, instead of a traditional menu on the wall or table, there is a large, blank chalkboard with the phrase ''No Menu - You Get What You Deserve!'' written in playful, bold letters. A cheerful waiter stands by a table, holding a covered silver platter, raising an eyebrow with a knowing smile. Seated at the table is a surprised-looking customer, opening their mouth in disbelief or curiosity. Around them, other diners have humorous dishes on their plates that clearly match their personalities or actions (e.g., a very healthy person gets a big salad, while a messy eater has spaghetti all over). Include some fun details like a small karma wheel or symbols of balance and justice subtlety in the background. The overall tone is lighthearted and humorous, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke’s irony and the idea of poetic justice being served as food.'),
 (2802, 'Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Don''t sweat petty things....or pet sweaty things.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters: one character is looking stressed and sweating profusely, holding their forehead with a worried expression; above their head is a small cloud symbolizing ''petty things'' with tiny annoying symbols like bugs, clocks, and papers floating inside it. Nearby, a second character is holding a small, funny-looking pet (could be a dog or cat) that is visibly sweaty, exaggerated by sweat drops dripping from its fur. The pet looks innocent but silly, with its tongue hanging out. The background is simple and cheerful, with bright colors and a few sweat droplets around to emphasize the theme. A speech bubble with the text "Don''t sweat petty things... or pet sweaty things." appears above them. The overall drawing style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with rounded shapes and expressive faces to highlight the pun and humor without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2916, 'Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'He who buries talent is making a grave mistake.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small graveyard with several gravestones. In the center, a cartoon character, looking a bit worried but comical, is burying a big, shiny gold coin labeled ''Talent'' in an open grave. The grave has a simple wooden sign that reads ''Talent''. Nearby, a confused crow looks on, tilting its head. The background has a sunny sky with a few fluffy clouds and a tree to one side, creating a lighthearted atmosphere. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and playful to emphasize the pun and humor without any dark or serious tone.'),
 (3001, 'Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I have to stop now. My fingers are getting hoarse.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk frantically typing on a computer keyboard with exaggerated speed and intensity. The person''s fingers are shown as tired and strained, with small cartoon sweat droplets flying off them. Above the desk, a speech bubble or caption reads, "I have to stop now. My fingers are getting hoarse." Around the desk, include a computer screen with text flying off like musical notes or cartoon wavy lines to represent loud typing sounds. The background is simple and light-hearted. The overall style is playful and exaggerated to emphasize the pun that fingers can get ''hoarse'' like a sore throat, not tired fingers.'),
 (1032, 'Humor, Puns', 'Thank you for holding your breath while I smoke.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a public place like a small elevator or a waiting room. There''s a person standing, holding their breath with puffed cheeks and cheeks turning slightly red, clearly struggling to keep from breathing. Nearby, another character is casually smoking a cigarette or a cigar, looking apologetic but relaxed. Include subtle smell lines (wavy lines) rising from the smoker to visually represent smoke. The background should be simple, with a clock on the wall and a few chairs to set the scene. Both characters should have exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor: the holder of breath looks uncomfortable but polite, while the smoker looks sheepish but amused. Make the style lighthearted and cartoonish, avoiding anything aggressive or unpleasant.'),
 (1033, 'Humor, Puns', 'When the missionaries visited the tribe of cannibals, they got their first taste of religion', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of friendly missionaries visiting a tribe of cannibals in a tropical jungle clearing. The missionaries, dressed in typical explorer or missionary clothing with hats and backpacks, appear nervous but polite. Nearby, a tribal chief and several tribe members with traditional colorful attire and feathered headdresses look at them curiously. The focus is on a large cooking pot over a fire, with a cartoonish speech bubble from the chief saying, ''Here, try the religion!'' Inside the pot, instead of anything scary, there are floating symbolic religious items like a small cross, a Bible, and a pair of glasses, humorously implying the ''taste of religion.'' The background includes palm trees, jungle plants, and a bright blue sky. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on all characters to emphasize the joke''s pun on ''taste of religion.'''),
 (1034, 'Humor, Puns', 'Which is the non-smoking lifeboat?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a lifeboat floating on calm seas near a large ship. The lifeboat is labeled clearly, and next to it stands a cheerful anthropomorphic cigarette with a sad or disappointed face, looking at the lifeboat. The lifeboat itself is wearing a big no-smoking sign (a cigarette crossed out) on its side. In the background, a few seagulls fly with speech bubbles, one pointing to the lifeboat and announcing, “This one doesn’t smoke!” The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bright, vivid colors and exaggerated, friendly character designs for the cigarette and lifeboat. The scene should feel like a classic cartoon, with expressive faces and simple ocean waves underneath.'),
 (2223, 'Humor, Puns, Quotes, Word Play', 'Remember: I''m with you, win or tie!', 'Floyd B. Buchanan', 'A humorous cartoon scene of two characters playing a game of tic-tac-toe on a piece of paper. One character, confidently smiling, points to the game board where there is a clear win for them, but they say, ''Remember: I''m with you, win or tie!'' The other character looks confused but slightly encouraged. The setting is a casual table with simple items like pencils and a coffee mug. The style is bright and cartoony, with exaggerated facial expressions showing friendly rivalry and good-natured support. The tic-tac-toe grid is clearly visible, and the overall mood is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the pun on “win or tie.”'),
 (1035, 'Humor, Puns, Science', 'The 2 most common elements in the universe are hydrogen and stupidity', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in outer space. Show a colorful, whimsical depiction of the universe with stars, galaxies, and planets scattered in the background. In the center, depict two large, smiling, and cartoonish characters representing the elements mentioned: one as a bubbly, happy hydrogen atom with a big ''H'' on its body, and the other as a goofy, silly-looking character symbolizing ''stupidity''—for example, a funny creature with crossed eyes, a silly grin, and a little thought bubble showing a question mark or light bulb dimmed out. The hydrogen atom should look smart and scientific, wearing little glasses and maybe holding a tiny beaker, while the ''stupidity'' character contrasts by looking simple-minded and goofy. Both should be floating side by side in space, emphasizing they are the ''most common elements.'' The cartoon style should be light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor without any negative or offensive connotations.'),
 (1036, 'Humor, Puns, Science, Steven Wright', 'The problem with the gene pool is that there is no lifeguard.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a gene pool literally depicted as a swimming pool labeled ''Gene Pool.'' The pool is filled with various cartoonish double-helix DNA strands swimming or floating around like people relaxing in a pool. There is no lifeguard chair or lifeguard present anywhere around the pool, emphasizing the joke. Around the poolside, goofy characters representing different genetic traits (like a character with oversized glasses, another with wild hair, and one with a quirky hat) are casually lounging or splashing. The background shows playful poolside details, such as a beach ball, a sun umbrella, and pool floaties in shapes referencing biology or genetics (like a microscope-shaped floatie). The art style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with smiling DNA strands and relaxed atmosphere. The whole setup visually plays on the pun of a ''gene pool'' and the absence of a lifeguard in a swimming pool setting to communicate the joke clearly and humorously, without any offensive or inappropriate elements.'),
 (2884, 'Humor, Puns, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'Give a man a gun and he''ll rob a bank. Give a man a bank and he''ll rob everyone.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with two panels side by side. The left panel shows a man holding a large cartoonish gun, looking excited and slightly nervous, standing outside a bank building with a classic ''BANK'' sign overhead. The right panel shows the same man now dressed as a banker wearing a suit, tie, and glasses, sitting comfortably behind a large desk piled high with money and smiling slyly. Around him are smaller cartoon characters looking worried or shocked, representing the people being ''robbed'' by the bank. Emphasize the contrast between the overt robbery in the first panel and the sly, corporate robbery in the second panel. Use bright colors, simple shapes, exaggerated facial expressions, and clean lines to keep it light and funny, not serious or threatening.'),
 (1037, 'Humor, Puns, Technology Humor', 'Warning: do not use your toaster as an alternate diskette reader.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy kitchen. On the left side, a confused, slightly frazzled person (gender-neutral) stands with a computer diskette in hand, staring at a toaster on the kitchen counter. The toaster has two slots on top, and instead of toast, a old-fashioned floppy disk (diskette) is halfway inserted into one slot, humorously ill-fitted. The toaster''s lever is halfway down, as if someone just tried to use it. Around the toaster, a few pieces of burnt toast with smoke rising comically form a small cloud above it. The background includes typical kitchen items: a coffee mug, a fruit bowl, and some cabinets. The person’s expression is exaggeratedly puzzled, with wide eyes and a raised eyebrow, capturing the confusion about using a toaster as a diskette reader. The overall style is bright, cartoonish, with slightly exaggerated proportions and simple, clean lines to emphasize the absurdity and humor of the situation. No text bubbles, just visual storytelling with a whimsical, lighthearted tone.'),
 (1038, 'Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'Scrambo - the meanest word-tile game on the market!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene inside a living room. On a small table sits a Scrabble-style word game with tiles scattered in a chaotic mess, some tiles even appearing to have angry faces or little frowns. The game box is prominently displayed with the label ''Scrambo'' in big, bold, playful letters. The subtitle on the box reads ''the meanest word-tile game on the market!'' Nearby, a frustrated player—exaggerated expression with furrowed brows and gritted teeth—is dramatically throwing their tiles up in the air in mock anger. Another player sits opposite, smirking mischievously while holding a tile, as if ready to unleash a ''mean'' word. The background is simple but cheerful, with a few cartoon-style speech bubbles showing silly words or letters clashing. The overall vibe is lighthearted and funny, capturing the chaos and competitive spirit of a family game night turned vicious, all in a playful way.'),
 (1039, 'Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'To be Frank, I''d have to change my name.', NULL, 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a person named Steve standing in front of a mirror, looking at his reflection. The mirror clearly shows his name tag on his shirt that reads ''Steve.'' A thought bubble above his head contains the text: ''To be Frank, I''d have to change my name.'' The background is simple, inside a cozy room with a dresser and a door visible. The character has a playful, slightly puzzled expression, and the overall style is colorful, cheerful, and exaggerated to emphasize the pun humor. No other people or complicated details, keeping the focus on the character and the pun about names.'),
 (1040, 'Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'What does a house wear? Address', NULL, 'Draw a funny cartoon scene showing a simple house standing upright like a person. The house should have eyes and a smiling face on the front, making it look friendly and alive. Instead of clothes, it is wearing a big, colorful name tag or badge with the word ''Address'' clearly printed on it, hanging around its ''neck'' area like a necklace or lanyard. Around the house, include a few street signs or a mailbox to emphasize the idea of an address. The background should be a cute neighborhood with other houses but without characters or people to keep focus on the main house figure. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated features, like the house’s windows acting as eyes and a door as the mouth to add humor to the concept that a house ''wears'' an address like an outfit.'),
 (1041, 'Humor, Puns, Workplace', 'Watch out, buddy! You break it, you buy it! (Moral: Don''t Press Break.)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a mischievous character about to press a big red button labeled ''BREAK'' on a large, old-fashioned machine. The setting is a workshop or a store with various gadgets around, some slightly cracked or broken. Another character stands beside him with an exaggerated worried expression, pointing a finger and shouting, ''Watch out, buddy! You break it, you buy it!'' The scene should be colorful and lighthearted, with cartoonish exaggerated facial expressions and body language showing the warning and impending trouble. The broken gadgets and the big red button are central elements, with a sign above the machine humorously reading ''Don''t Press Break!'''),
 (1042, 'Humor, Quotes', 'Ignorance is a lack of knowledge. Stupidity is ignorance with pride.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a person looks confused and clueless, scratching their head with question marks floating above them, representing ignorance as a lack of knowledge. On the right, another person looks overly confident or smug, with their chest puffed out proudly and a big, goofy grin, representing stupidity as ignorance with pride. Both characters are in a simple office or classroom setting with a whiteboard behind them that reads the quote: ''Ignorance is a lack of knowledge. Stupidity is ignorance with pride.'' The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the difference in attitudes between the two characters without any hostility or negativity. Include bright, cheerful colors and cartoonish expressions to keep the tone funny and approachable.'),
 (2225, 'Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'Research is what I''m doing when I don''t know what I''m doing.', 'Wernher Von Braun (1912-1977)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a cluttered desk filled with open books, papers scattered everywhere, a laptop displaying graphs and charts, and several coffee mugs. The person looks puzzled and slightly overwhelmed, scratching their head with a pen in one hand, staring intently at a magnifying glass examining a random object on the desk. Above them is a thought bubble that reads: "Research is what I''m doing when I don''t know what I''m doing." The background includes a bookshelf overflowing with books titled ''Science,'' ''Data,'' and ''Experiments,'' and a calendar with random dates circled. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, showing the confusion and trial-and-error nature of research in an exaggerated, cartoon style with vibrant colors and expressive facial features to emphasize the humor.'),
 (2163, 'Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Nothing makes your sense of humour disappear faster than having someone ask where it is.', 'Ivern Ball', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a living room. Center stage is a person with a baffled, slightly uncomfortable expression, looking directly at the viewer. Near them stands another person, cheerfully accusing or inquisitive, pointing a finger in a playful manner as if asking a question. To emphasize the joke''s theme, place a small ''thought bubble'' above the first person''s head with a faint fading smile or a small cartoonish ''sense of humor'' figure slipping away like a ghost or puff of smoke. The overall mood should be lighthearted and silly, using exaggerated facial expressions and body language to highlight the awkwardness of being asked where one''s sense of humor has gone. Include simple and colorful furniture such as a couch, a small side table with a lamp, and framed pictures on the wall to create a cozy, relatable home environment. The artistic style should be bold lines with vibrant colors, suitable for a funny comic strip or casual cartoon panel.'),
 (2335, 'Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Social Humor', 'The man who can smile when things go wrong has thought of someone else he can blame it on.', 'Robert Bloch', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man with a slightly mischievous smile standing amid a comical mess: spilled coffee, a toppled plant, scattered papers, and a knocked-over chair. The man is looking sideways with a sly expression, as if he''s just had a clever thought. Nearby, a cartoonish, innocent-looking character or object (like a pet dog or a small robot) looks up at him, seemingly unaware that it might be the scapegoat. The setting is a casual office or home workspace with a desk, computer, and bookshelves in the background. Bright, exaggerated facial features and vibrant colors highlight the man''s confident grin and the chaotic environment around him. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the joke about blame-shifting as a humorous coping mechanism.'),
 (1830, 'Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Self-Love', 'I never loved another person the way I loved myself.', 'Mae West', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person gazing lovingly at a mirror reflection of themselves. The character has a big, exaggerated smile and dreamy eyes, perhaps with little heart symbols floating around their head to show affection. They are holding their own hands, as if about to hug themselves, emphasizing self-love. The background is simple and cheerful, with soft pastel colors. Include a small heart-shaped frame or decoration near the mirror to reinforce the theme of affection. Overall, the style should be lighthearted and playful with clear cartoonish exaggeration to highlight the joke''s ironic self-centeredness.'),
 (1374, 'Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Wit', 'A child of five would understand this. Send someone to fetch a child of five.', 'Groucho Marx', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an adult looking utterly confused while holding a complicated math book or puzzle with exasperated expression. Nearby, a little five-year-old child is happily playing or holding a simple toy, looking innocent and smart. The adult points towards the child, as if asking for help, with a speech bubble saying, "A child of five would understand this. Send someone to fetch a child of five." The background is a casual living room or classroom setting with books and toys scattered around. The style is bright and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between the confused adult and the confident child.'),
 (1742, 'Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Word Play', 'He can compress the most words into the smallest idea of any man I know.', 'Abraham Lincoln (1809-1865)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing confidently with a thought bubble above his head. Inside the thought bubble is a tiny, tightly packed cluster of words representing his idea — the words are compressed together like letters squeezed into a very small space, almost unreadable. The man has a smirk or proud expression, wearing casual clothes, perhaps glasses. Around him, other people look baffled or overwhelmed, holding longer speech bubbles filled with many simple words that stretch out widely to contrast his tiny dense bubble. The setting is informal, like a casual office or coffee shop, with some chairs, a table, and maybe a laptop or books nearby to indicate conversation or ideas. The style is colorful, cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and playful proportions to emphasize the humor in ''compressing many words into a tiny idea.'' No violence or offensive elements.'),
 (2127, 'Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'My toughest fight was with my first wife.', 'Muhammad Ali', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man and a woman in a lighthearted, exaggerated pose typical of a playful argument. The man is holding up a white flag of surrender while the woman has her hands exaggeratedly on her hips, with a slight smirk on her face. They stand in a simple living room with a cozy couch, a small table with a vase of flowers, and a framed picture on the wall. Both characters are drawn with comically expressive faces, emphasizing the ''toughest fight'' as more of a humorous or verbal disagreement rather than physical. The overall style should be bright and cheerful, with clear, bold outlines and cartoonish proportions to emphasize humor and avoid any sense of real conflict or violence.'),
 (1701, 'Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wise Sayings', 'Forgive your enemies, but never forget their names.', 'John F. Kennedy (1917-1963)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, friendly-looking person sitting at a cozy desk with a big open book titled ''Enemy Roll Call.'' The person is smiling, holding a quill pen mid-air, as if writing down names carefully. Around the desk are little name tags scattered that read humorous enemy names like ''Mr. Forgetful'' and ''Captain Nuisance.'' Above the person’s head is a large thought bubble showing a funny but clear list of enemies with their bright names written prominently. The setting should be lighthearted, with bright colors and a warm tone conveying a mix of forgiveness and playful caution. Include small, exaggerated details like a calendar on the wall with the word ''Remembrance Day'' circled, and a cheeky but harmless ''No Grudges'' poster behind the desk for added humor. The overall feel is that forgiveness is being done with a good memory and a wink.'),
 (1402, 'Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wit', 'A gentleman can disagree without being disagreeable.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two well-dressed gentlemen standing face-to-face in a cozy, elegant room with classic decor such as framed pictures, a small bookshelf, and a potted plant. Both men wear suits and bow ties—one with a slight frown and arms folded, the other with a gentle smile and hands open in a peaceful gesture. Above them, a speech bubble from the smiling man says, ''A gentleman can disagree without being disagreeable.'' To add humor, one gentleman has a tiny, friendly cloud of ''disagreement symbols'' like small lightning bolts and question marks instead of angry symbols, highlighting a calm disagreement. The overall tone is lighthearted and polite, with warm colors and rounded character designs to convey a charming and witty atmosphere without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2089, 'Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Word Play', 'Marriage is the result of the longing for the deep, deep peace of the double bed after the hurly-burly of the chaise lounge.', 'Mrs. Patrick Campbell', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy bedroom. On one side, a disheveled chaise lounge is shown in a lively, chaotic state: cushions are askew, a book and a remote control are tossed haphazardly, and a person lounges there looking somewhat restless or overwhelmed. On the opposite side, a large, inviting double bed with neat, smooth blankets and fluffy pillows exudes calm and serenity. A relaxed couple is peacefully sleeping or resting together in the double bed, smiling contentedly. The background shows soft lighting with warm colors to emphasize the contrast between the chaotic chaise lounge and the peaceful double bed. Include subtle humorous details like a clock showing late night or a cat snoozing calmly on the bed to enhance the sense of tranquility versus the hectic chaise lounge. The overall style is bright, friendly, and cartoonish to highlight the humor without any darkness or negativity.'),
 (1723, 'Humor, Quotes, Religious Humor, Science Humor', 'God runs electromagnetics by wave theory on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday, and the Devil runs them by quantum theory on Tuesday, Thursday, and Saturday.', 'Sir William Bragg', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, depict a benevolent, kindly-looking God figure with a flowing white beard and robes, standing in a bright, orderly laboratory filled with classical wave diagrams on blackboards and oscillating sine waves represented as rolling ocean waves or smooth curves. God is holding a clipboard with ''Wave Theory Lab Schedule'' marked Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. On the right side, show a mischievous yet playful Devil figure with small horns and a tail, working in a slightly chaotic, dimmer lab filled with quirky quantum symbols like particles popping out of boxes and wavy lines turning into particle clouds. The Devil’s calendar shows Tuesday, Thursday, and Saturday highlighted. Both characters look focused but contrastingly styled to emphasize the difference in their scientific approaches. The background can subtly suggest a heavenly setting on God''s side and a quirky underworld on Devil''s side without being scary or dark. Include a calendar hanging overhead that clearly marks the days these theories are run. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s playful tone.'),
 (1875, 'Humor, Quotes, Religious Humor, Word Play', 'If God created us in his own image, we have more than reciprocated.', 'Voltaire', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters facing each other in a whimsical art studio. On the left, a dignified figure representing God is looking at a large mirror, showing a classical, idealized image of Himself—glowing halo, gentle smile, and radiant light. On the right side, a modern human is holding a paintbrush and standing proudly in front of a canvas where a comically exaggerated, quirky self-portrait is painted. The human’s self-portrait is filled with fun exaggerations—mismatched eyes, a big goofy grin, wild messy hair, and quirky features that clearly differ from the holy image opposite. The studio is filled with playful artistic chaos—paint splatters, colorful palettes, easels, and sketches of imaginative faces pinned on the wall. Both figures have amused expressions, and the setting conveys a lighthearted, witty take on the idea that humans have creatively ''returned the favor'' of being created in God''s image by making highly imperfect, personalized versions of themselves. The style is bright, cartoonish, and friendly with rounded shapes and expressive faces to emphasize humor and charm without any negativity or offense.'),
 (1722, 'Humor, Quotes, Satire, School', 'God made the Idiot for practice, and then He made the School Board.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a lighthearted depiction of God in a white robe with a playful smile, holding a small, silly-looking character labeled ''Idiot'' in one hand. Nearby, God is pointing to a large group of serious-looking, slightly overwhelmed adults labeled ''School Board,'' who appear to be reviewing complicated papers and looking confused or stressed. The background is a bright, simple sky with soft clouds, and a cartoon-style divine glow surrounds God, emphasizing the humorous contrast between the playful ''Idiot'' and the more serious ''School Board.'' The scene should be colorful, exaggerated, and playful, avoiding anything mean-spirited, with clear labels on the characters to convey the joke visually.'),
 (1799, 'Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Word Play', 'I don''t have any solution, but I certainly admire the problem.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon-style scene featuring a person standing thoughtfully in front of a large, complex math or science problem written on a chalkboard or whiteboard. The problem should look complicated with lots of equations, diagrams, or symbols. The person has an admiring, impressed expression, perhaps with a hand stroking their chin or a slight smile, clearly fascinated by the problem. Nearby, a small bottle labeled ''Solution'' sits unopened on a desk or shelf, emphasizing that the solution is not present. The setting is a casual, lighthearted classroom or study room environment with some scattered books and papers to add to the academic vibe. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions for comedic effect but keep the mood light and friendly.'),
 (1677, 'Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'Every private citizen has a public responsibility.', 'Myra Janco Daniels', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an ordinary person standing between two contrasting areas: on one side, their ''private'' space showing a cozy living room with personal belongings like a couch, books, and a TV; on the other side, a public area resembling a busy town square with people watching and the person holding a small megaphone or wearing a badge labeled ''Public Responsibility.'' The character has a slightly puzzled but determined expression, as if realizing their personal life unexpectedly requires public duties. Include lighthearted details like a calendar on the wall with a reminder saying ''Public Duty Today!'' and a mailbox marked ''Private Mail.'' The overall style should be bright, simple, and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the irony of a private citizen juggling private comforts and public responsibilities simultaneously.'),
 (1806, 'Humor, Quotes, Social Humor, Word Play', 'I drink to make other people interesting.', 'George Jean Nathan', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a bar counter with a slightly amused yet tired expression. The person holds a large cocktail or beer glass, mid-drink, with a casual posture. Around them, several other characters sit or stand who look extremely dull, boring, or uninterested—perhaps one is yawning, another staring blankly, one checking their watch, and another scrolling on a phone. The dull characters have exaggerated, bland appearances: simple clothing, droopy eyes, and slumped posture to emphasize their lack of interest. The bar setting includes stools, a wooden counter, background shelves with bottles, and a neon sign that humorously reads "Making Others Interesting Bar." The style is light-hearted cartoon with lively colors and exaggerated facial expressions to bring out the dry wit in the scene. No violence or negativity, just playful exaggeration of social boredom and drinking as a humorous coping mechanism.'),
 (1873, 'Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor, Wit', 'If computers take over (which seems to be their natural tendency), it will serve us right.', 'Alistair Cooke', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of anthropomorphic computers, laptops, and smartphones standing upright on a city street like robots taking over. These devices have eyes and mouths, looking a bit smug or mischievous. Around them, humans are walking away looking surprised and slightly worried. Above the scene, a large billboard reads, ''Computers Taking Over!'' One human, pointing at the machines, is saying to another, ''It will serve us right.'' The overall look is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions on the devices and people to emphasize the joke. The background shows a typical urban environment with buildings, streetlights, and some tech gadgets plugged in or charging on the sidewalks. The style should be cartoonish and playful, emphasizing the idea that the computers are ''taking over'' in a comedic, non-threatening way.'),
 (1749, 'Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'He who hesitates is a damned fool.', 'Mae West (1892-1980)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters: one is confidently striding forward with a big grin, symbolizing decisiveness, while the other stands hesitating at a crossroads with exaggeratedly nervous and confused facial expressions. The hesitant character scratches his head, looking back and forth at two opposite signposts labeled ‘Go’ and ‘Wait.’ The confident character has a speech bubble above him that reads, ''He who hesitates is a damned fool.'' The setting is lighthearted with bright colors, a simple path splitting into two, and playful exaggerated features on both characters to emphasize the humor in hesitation versus confidence. No violence or negativity is depicted, just a comical contrast of attitudes.'),
 (1970, 'Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'It is better to be quotable than to be honest.', 'Tom Stoppard', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing on a small stage with a microphone, dressed like a casual speaker or comedian. They have a confident, cheeky smile and are holding a large, oversized quotation mark symbol in one hand like a trophy. Around the stage are several speech bubbles floating in the air with witty, funny quotes inside. In the background, there''s a small crowd laughing and clapping, enjoying the performance. The setting is bright and playful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing the contrast between being quotable and honest. No one looks upset or serious; the tone is light and comedic.'),
 (2600, 'Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'You can observe a lot by just watching.', 'Yogi Berra', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person intently staring through a large pair of binoculars. The person is standing in a park or garden, surrounded by birds, squirrels, and a pond with ducks. The person’s eyes are exaggeratedly wide as if deeply focused, and their whole body is leaning forward as if trying to observe something very carefully. Nearby, a signpost reads ''Observation Point'' to emphasize the theme. Subtly in the background, a cat is watching the person, adding a playful element. The style is bright and colorful with clear, simple lines to keep a lighthearted, fun atmosphere.'),
 (2603, 'Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'You can pretend to be serious; you can''t pretend to be witty.', 'Sacha Guitry (1885-1957)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a casual setting like a small café or a park bench. One character looks very serious, wearing a suit and glasses, with a stern expression and arms crossed, perhaps scowling or staring off thoughtfully. The other character next to them is clearly trying to be witty: they have a playful smile, a raised eyebrow, and are holding a small joke book or a thought bubble with a pun or funny quote inside. Despite their efforts, their expression looks a bit forced or awkward, showing that their wit is not quite natural. The background should be light and cheerful, with warm colors and soft lines to keep it friendly and funny. Include simple props like coffee cups, a newspaper, or a small plant on the table to make the scene cozy. The overall mood captures the contrast between the genuine seriousness that can be put on and the more elusive, natural charm of wit, emphasizing the joke’s point with an amusing visual contrast.'),
 (1388, 'Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A cynic is a man who, when he smells flowers, looks around for a coffin.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a middle-aged man with a skeptical, suspicious expression standing in a vibrant flower garden full of colorful blossoms. The man is holding a large bouquet of flowers close to his nose, sniffing them, but instead of looking pleased, his eyes are wide and darting nervously as he glances over his shoulder. In the background, hidden partially behind bright flower bushes, is a cartoonish, slightly exaggerated wooden coffin with a subtle, humorous aura—not scary or creepy, just clearly visible enough to emphasize the joke. The setting is bright and cheerful, contrasting with the man''s cynical demeanor. The style is lighthearted, with bold lines and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor, avoiding anything dark or unsettling.'),
 (1432, 'Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A lie gets halfway around the world before the truth has a chance to get its pants on.', 'Sir Winston Churchill (1874-1965)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters representing a ''lie'' and the ''truth.'' The ''lie'' appears as a playful, fast-moving person or creature, already halfway around a simplified globe, depicted mid-run with exaggerated speed lines behind it. The ''truth'' is nearby, still at the starting point, hurriedly trying to pull on a pair of oversized pants, with one leg halfway in and the other leg stuck. The ''truth'' should have a slightly embarrassed or flustered expression, glancing anxiously at the speeding ''lie.'' The globe in the background is simple and colorful, showing continents in a stylized, cartoonish way. Make the characters visually distinct: perhaps the ''lie'' looks sly and confident, wearing a mischievous grin, and the ''truth'' looks earnest but struggling. Include lighthearted, bright colors and bold outlines to emphasize the comedic and whimsical tone of the joke.'),
 (1451, 'Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A narcissist is someone better looking than you are.', 'Gore Vidal', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people standing side by side. One person is looking into a handheld mirror with an exaggeratedly smug and self-admiring expression, clearly a narcissist. Their hair is perfectly styled, and they strike a confident pose. The other person looks toward the viewer with a slightly annoyed or skeptical expression, arms crossed. The background is simple with a few lighthearted details such as a vanity table with makeup and a comb scattered around to emphasize self-obsession. The style is vibrant and playful, with exaggerated facial features to highlight the humor without any harshness or negativity. The caption or thought bubble from the second person can read, "A narcissist is someone better looking than you are." The overall tone should be lighthearted and cartoonish, focusing on the concept of vanity and self-love in a funny way.'),
 (1663, 'Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Egotist: a person more interested in himself than in me.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring two characters engaged in conversation outdoors, perhaps in a park or casual café setting. One character is confidently speaking, with a smug smile and chest puffed out, clearly the ''egotist.'' The other character looks surprised or slightly annoyed, reacting to the egotist''s self-focused statement. To emphasize the joke, include a thought bubble over the egotist''s head showing a small mirror reflecting just his own face. Meanwhile, the other character has a speech bubble saying the punchline: "Egotist: a person more interested in himself than in me." Keep the style lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors, large expressive eyes, and simple backgrounds to keep attention on the interaction. Avoid any harsh expressions or negativity; the humor should come from the playful rivalry and irony of the definition itself.'),
 (1828, 'Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I may not be totally perfect, but parts of me are excellent.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful cartoon character with a big, friendly smile, standing proudly with one hand on their hip and the other pointing to themselves. The character''s body is depicted as a patchwork quilt or segmented into different parts (like arms, legs, torso, head) with some parts gleaming or sparkling brightly to emphasize their ''excellent'' quality while other parts look ordinary or plain. Around the character, small sparkles or stars highlight the excellent body parts. The background is simple and colorful, keeping attention on the character. Above or near the character is a playful speech bubble containing the joke text: "I may not be totally perfect, but parts of me are excellent." The overall style is lighthearted and cartoony, emphasizing self-acceptance with a funny twist and no harshness or negativity.'),
 (2035, 'Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Legend -- a lie that has attained the dignity of age.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly personified book or scroll sitting comfortably in an armchair, wearing reading glasses and looking wise with a gentle smile. The book or scroll should have subtle wrinkles or gray hair to symbolize old age. Beside the chair, include a small side table with a cup of tea and a calendar showing many years passed. Above the book or scroll, have a speech bubble that reads: ''Legend -- a lie that has attained the dignity of age.'' The setting is cozy and warm, like a quiet library or study room, emphasizing respect and dignity. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with soft, warm colors and simple, cartoon-style lines to make the visual inviting and funny rather than serious.'),
 (2297, 'Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'The difference between pornography and erotica is lighting.', 'Gloria Leonard', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two side-by-side indoor rooms separated by a thin wall. On the left side, dim red or pink lighting with a humorous, exaggeratedly sleazy setup: a couple awkwardly posed in front of a poorly lit camera, with some tacky decorations like heart-shaped balloons and a feather boa hanging. On the right side, bright soft white or golden lighting illuminating a classy, romantic environment: a couple comfortably and tastefully sitting on a couch or bed, dressed nicely, perhaps reading a book or holding hands, creating an elegant, warm atmosphere. Both scenes should be caricatured for comedic effect, featuring facial expressions that exaggerate the awkwardness on the ''pornography'' side and the relaxed charm on the ''erotica'' side. Include a simple light switch on the dividing wall with a label humorously reading ''Lighting.'' The overall tone is light, playful, and cheeky, avoiding any explicit or inappropriate content.'),
 (1043, 'Humor, Relatable', 'The more that you hate a song, the more difficult it is to get out of your head.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person with a frustrated expression, sitting at a desk or on a couch with music notes and a cartoonish, ugly-looking song symbol (like a speech bubble with a jagged musical note) floating above their head. The person''s head is slightly exaggerated and enlarged to emphasize the idea of the song being stuck inside. Around them, faint ghostly musical notes swirl uncontrollably, emphasizing the ''stuck'' effect. The person is holding their hands to their temples or trying to block their ears. The background is simple, with a light color and maybe a small clock indicating time passing to show the annoyance lasting. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features and bright colors to make the frustration funny and relatable without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (1044, 'Humor, Relatable', 'The only way to amuse some people is to slip and fall on an icy pavement.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set on a snowy, icy pavement outside a city park. In the foreground, a person is slipping dramatically on a thin patch of ice, arms flailing in the air and eyes wide with surprise, about to fall backward. Nearby, a group of people are watching and laughing heartily, showing clearly amused expressions. One person might be holding a hot coffee cup spilling a little due to laughter. The environment should be simple with some snow-covered trees or benches in the background, emphasizing a cold, wintry day. Use bright, lively colors and exaggerated facial expressions and body poses to emphasize the humor and lighthearted tone of the moment.'),
 (1045, 'Humor, Relatable', 'The opposite of talking isn''t listening. It''s waiting.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting side by side. One character is animatedly talking, smiling and gesturing with their hands, clearly enthusiastic. The second character appears visibly bored, with droopy eyes and a half-smile, staring blankly ahead, holding a clock or tapping their fingers impatiently, symbolizing ''waiting.'' Between them is a speech bubble coming from the talker filled with lots of words, while the listener''s speech bubble is empty with just a small hourglass or clock icon representing impatience. The setting is casual, like a simple living room or coffee shop, with a small table and chairs. The overall tone is lighthearted and relatable, emphasizing the idea that the listener is just waiting their turn rather than actively listening.'),
 (1046, 'Humor, Relatable', 'The trouble with doing something right the first time is that nobody appreciates how difficult it was.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated, tired person standing next to a perfectly completed project—a neatly assembled, complicated-looking puzzle or machine. The character has sweat drops on their forehead and is holding their hands up in an ''I did it!'' gesture, looking both proud and exhausted. Nearby, three other people are standing nonchalantly with blank or mildly indifferent expressions, completely ignoring the hard work that was just done. The background can be a simple room with a table where the project rests. Include small visual cues like a clock showing a long time passed, scattered tools or puzzle pieces around, and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the contrast between the effort and the lack of appreciation. The overall color scheme should be light and playful, fitting a cartoon style with clear, bold outlines and simple shading.'),
 (1047, 'Humor, Relatable', 'There are times my greatest achievement is keeping my mouth shut.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting in a cozy living room, looking proud and triumphant. The person is smiling with exaggerated satisfaction, maybe a little chest puffed out, and has their finger pressed gently against their lips in a ''shushing'' gesture. Around them are thought bubbles or floating icons like a trophy or medal that say ''Greatest Achievement.'' The setting should be light-hearted, with bright colors and simple, rounded shapes. Include a small clock on the wall to imply everyday life, and perhaps a couch with a pet (like a cat or dog) looking up curiously. The overall mood is playful and self-congratulatory without being boastful.'),
 (1048, 'Humor, Relatable', 'To not see these messages all the time, close your eyes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk cluttered with a computer, smartphone, and several sticky notes with notifications or message icons on them. The person has a mildly frustrated but playful expression and is closing their eyes tightly, as if trying to escape the barrage of messages around them. Around their head, small cartoon message bubbles with exclamation marks, email icons, and chat symbols float in the air to represent constant notifications. The background shows a window with light coming in, and a clock on the wall indicating daytime. The overall style is bright and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial features and simple shapes to emphasize the comic mood without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (1049, 'Humor, Relatable', 'Waking a person unnecessarily should not be considered a capital crime. For a first offense, that is.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a sleepy person in bed, wearing pajamas and a nightcap, with heavy eyelids and a big yawn. Next to the bed, a mischievous character—depicted as a smiling person or cartoon animal—leans over, about to poke or shake the sleeper to wake them up. The bedroom should feel cozy, with a bedside table holding a lamp, an alarm clock showing an early morning time, and maybe a window showing dawn outside. The sleeping person looks annoyed or startled but not angry, emphasizing comedy rather than frustration. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive faces and simple lines, capturing the silly idea of treating waking someone up as a serious crime. Include a small sign or thought bubble near the mischievous character that says something like "First offense" to link to the joke text humorously. The overall tone is playful and whimsical, without any aggressive or dark elements.'),
 (1050, 'Humor, Relatable', 'When someone asks what I did over the weekend, I squint and ask, ''Why, what did you hear?''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing casually in a living room setting. The character has a playful, mischievous smile and is slightly squinting their eyes as if suspicious or teasing. Their body language should convey a sense of slyness, with one eyebrow raised and a slight lean forward. Include a thought bubble with a stylized ear or sound waves emerging to hint at overhearing gossip. Surround the character with subtle weekend-related items like a couch, a coffee mug, maybe a weekend newspaper or a TV remote nearby to set the casual weekend vibe. The colors should be bright and cheerful to match the lighthearted tone of the joke. Avoid complex backgrounds; keep the focus on the character''s facial expression and gesture conveying their funny, cheeky response to the question, ''What did you hear?''.'),
 (1051, 'Humor, Relatable', 'When someone says, ''That''s a good question'', you can bet that the question will be better than the answer.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a casual office or classroom. In the foreground, a confident person is raising their hand with a big smile and a speech bubble that says, ''That''s a good question!'' Behind a desk, a teacher or presenter looks slightly nervous or puzzled, scratching their head as if unsure how to answer. Around them, several cartoon thought bubbles show exaggerated, complex questions with question marks, while the answer bubble from the presenter is small, simple, and unimpressive. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize that while the question is exciting, the answer disappoints in comparison. Include typical office or classroom items like a whiteboard, papers, and a water cooler in the background for context, and make the characters cartoonish with rounded features and expressive faces to heighten the humor without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1052, 'Humor, Relatable', 'When you ask me what I am doing today, and I say ''nothing,'' it does not mean I am free. It means I am doing nothing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person lounging comfortably on a couch at home, wearing casual clothes like sweatpants and a t-shirt. The person has a relaxed, slightly guilty expression while scrolling on a phone or tablet. Around them are items that suggest laziness rather than availability: a messy stack of unopened mail, a coffee cup with steam rising, a half-eaten snack, and a clock on the wall indicating early afternoon. The speech bubble above the person says, "I''m doing nothing," while a nearby phone shows an incoming call or message asking, "Are you free today?" The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the idea that doing "nothing" is an activity in itself. The background is a simple living room setting with a plant on a small table and a window letting in daylight.'),
 (1053, 'Humor, Relatable', 'Whoever snores loudest falls asleep first.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people in a bedroom at night. Both are lying in separate beds side by side, clearly ready to sleep. One person is wide awake with a big smile, eyes open, looking amused. The other person is already asleep, mouth wide open, exaggeratedly snoring with large comic-style ''Zzz'' symbols emerging. The snore lines are visually loud and almost filling the room, while the awake person appears relaxed and amused. Include little details like a bedside lamp, a clock showing nighttime hours, and a window with a moon outside for context. The overall style should be lighthearted and simple, with exaggerated facial expressions and sound effects to bring out the joke''s punchline about snoring indicating who falls asleep first.'),
 (1054, 'Humor, Relatable Humor', 'Sometimes I feel like I''m telling 6 foot tall jokes and everybody in the room is 5 foot 10 inches', NULL, 'A cartoon drawing of a person standing on a small wooden stool or ladder, looking confident and animated as if telling a joke to a group. The person appears taller than everyone else in the scene. Around them, a group of people stand or sit, all noticeably shorter—visibly about 5''10"—looking slightly puzzled or unimpressed, with some scratching their heads or glancing sideways. The setting is a casual comedy club or living room with a microphone stand nearby and a simple backdrop. The style is colorful and humorous, emphasizing the height difference exaggeration for comedic effect without being mean-spirited.'),
 (1055, 'Humor, Relatable Humor', 'Sometimes I wake up Grumpy; Other times I let him sleep', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels side-by-side. In the first panel, a person is waking up in bed early in the morning, eyes half-open with a big scowl on their face, clearly grumpy. The background shows a messy bedroom with a tired-looking alarm clock ringing loudly on the nightstand. In the second panel, the same person is seen asleep again under the covers, with a peaceful smile, completely relaxed. Above their head is a small cartoon ''Grumpy'' character (a tiny grumpy-faced figure with crossed arms) curled up and sleeping, complete with a little sleep bubble indicating Zzz. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions for comic effect, emphasizing the mood difference between the two panels. The style should be lighthearted and cartoony, conveying humor without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1056, 'Humor, Relatable Humor', 'That must be wonderful! I don''t understand it at all.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters engaged in conversation. One person is speaking enthusiastically with a bright smile and wide-open eyes, perhaps holding a book or pointing to a complex chart or diagram. The other character looks utterly confused, scratching their head, eyebrows furrowed, with a puzzled expression. They might be holding their chin or shrugging. The background should be a simple indoor setting, like a cozy living room or a casual office, with minimal distractions. The contrast between enthusiasm and confusion should be emphasized, using exaggerated facial expressions and body language to highlight the humor of misunderstanding. Optional small speech bubbles can show a jumble of indecipherable symbols or words behind the speaker and question marks around the listener’s head to further convey confusion.'),
 (1057, 'Humor, Relatable Humor', 'The difference between antiques and junk is who''s running the garage sale.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a lively, colorful garage sale in a suburban driveway. On one side, an elderly individual with glasses and a proud smile is carefully displaying elegant, polished old items labeled as ''Antiques'' on a vintage tablecloth. These include a classic vase, an ornate clock, and an old-fashioned lamp. On the other side, a younger person with casual clothes and a slightly messy appearance is throwing a bunch of random, worn-out-looking items onto a folding table with a sign that says ''Junk''. Around them are a few confused buyers looking puzzled but curious. The background shows a cozy house and some balloons tied to the tables for a festive feel. The sky is bright and sunny to keep the tone light and friendly. The overall style is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor of the difference being just ''who’s running the garage sale''.'),
 (2980, 'Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I don''t suffer from stress. I''m a carrier.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in the center looking slightly frazzled but with a cheeky smile. The character is surrounded by different stylized ''stress carriers''—such as a large backpack labeled ''Stress,'' a shirt printed with the word ''Stress Carrier,'' and virus-like cartoon stress particles floating around them like germs. The character should be shrugging or holding up their hands as if saying ''It''s not me, it''s the stress I carry.'' Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated features, such as wild hair or squiggly lines around the head to show stress. The background can be a simple office or home setting with a clock showing a busy hour. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, emphasizing the wordplay on ''carrier'' as if stress is something contagious they carry around like a cold or virus.'),
 (1058, 'Humor, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'STAY TUNED: I could say something brilliant at any moment.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a relaxed character sitting comfortably on a couch in a cozy living room. The character has a playful, slightly mischievous smile, and is holding a TV remote in one hand while a speech bubble above their head reads, ''STAY TUNED: I could say something brilliant at any moment.'' The TV in front of them displays a static or loading screen with the words ''Stay Tuned...'' The room includes classic cozy elements like a floor lamp, a small side table with a cup of coffee, and a quirky framed poster on the wall that says ''Brilliance Loading...''. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated cartoon expressions and rounded shapes to emphasize humor and anticipation without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (1059, 'Humor, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'TELECRASTINATION (tel e kras tin ay'' shun) n. The act of always letting the phone ring at least twice before you pick it up, when you''re only six inches away.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room. A person is sitting comfortably on a couch, half-turned away from a ringing smartphone lying on a coffee table just six inches away. The phone screen shows incoming call with animated ringing lines or sound waves around it. The person has an exaggerated, amused expression, looking casually disinterested yet intentionally delaying picking up the call. Include a clock on the wall showing a couple of seconds passing, and maybe a thought bubble above the person reading: ''I''ll let it ring twice…'' The overall style should be light, colorful, and quirky with simple exaggerated features to highlight the playful procrastination of answering the phone.'),
 (1060, 'Humor, Relatable, Science', 'Who me? I just wander from room to room. It might look like I am doing nothing, but at a cellular level I am quite busy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy, slightly messy home showing a person casually wandering from one room to another with a nonchalant expression. The person is depicted in mid-step between a living room and a kitchen, wearing comfortable clothes and slippers. Around them, several rooms are visible through open doorways. To visualize the ''cellular activity,'' the person''s body is semi-transparent, revealing a colorful, exaggerated cartoon view of busy, animated cells inside—some running on tiny treadmills, others lifting weights, and a few using computers. The cells have happy, determined faces, emphasizing their ''busyness.'' The background is lighthearted and warm, with simple furniture like a couch, a small table with a cup of coffee, and a few houseplants. No violent, sexual, or political elements are included, and the style is bright, simple, and playful to bring out the contrast between external stillness and internal energy.'),
 (2661, 'Humor, Relatable, Self-Deprecation, Unknown', 'At least I have a positive attitude about my destructive habits.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting comfortably on a couch with a big, exaggerated grin, clearly trying to show they have a ''positive attitude.'' Around them, various signs of destructive habits are depicted in a lighthearted way: an overflowing ashtray with several burnt-out cigarettes, an empty junk food bag crumpled on the floor, a spilled cup of coffee or soda on a messy table, and a video game controller left carelessly nearby. The person is giving a thumbs-up with one hand while holding a half-empty bottle labeled as something humorous but innocent, like ''Energy Juice.'' The background should be a typical messy living room with scattered magazines, a tilted picture frame, and some empty snack wrappers. The overall tone is playful and self-deprecating, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the ironic positivity in the face of bad habits, but without any dark or harmful imagery.'),
 (2653, 'Humor, Relatable, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'April Fool''s Day is the only day of the year that people critically evaluate news articles before accepting them as true', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a busy living room on April Fool''s Day. A person sits on a couch holding a newspaper or tablet, eyebrows raised and eyes wide in a skeptical expression, clearly scrutinizing the news. Around them, friends or family look puzzled or amused, some holding smartphones showing exaggerated or silly news headlines with quirky images or obvious fake news cues (like flying pigs or outrageous claims). A calendar on the wall prominently shows the date ''April 1'' with funny doodles around it. The setting is cozy and colorful, with light-hearted caricature style and exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing disbelief and critical thinking, capturing the essence of questioning news only on this specific day. No violence or anything offensive, just a playful take on people''s unusual behavior on April Fool''s Day.'),
 (1061, 'Humor, Relatable, Technology Humor', 'This has got to be the worst dream I''m ever having. I think I''m a computer...', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a person lying in bed asleep with a worried or confused expression on their face, eyes twitching under closed lids as if dreaming. Above the bed or near the person''s head, show a thought bubble filled with comical computer-related imagery: a desktop monitor displaying an error message or loading bar, a keyboard with some keys popping out, and maybe a mouse cursor floating around. The bedroom should be cozy but simple, with a nightstand holding an alarm clock and a small lamp. The overall style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the oddity and frustration of dreaming oneself as a computer rather than a pleasant or normal dream. Include soft colors and cartoonish proportions to enhance the humor and absurdity of the mental image.'),
 (1062, 'Humor, Relatable, Time Humor', 'When I say, ''The other day'', I could be referring to any time between yesterday and 15 years ago.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing with a confused and slightly exaggerated pondering expression, holding a calendar in one hand and pointing to an imaginary timeline with the other. The timeline above their head stretches from a date labeled ''Yesterday'' on the left, gradually extending all the way to ''15 Years Ago'' on the right, marked with playful icons like a smartphone for recent times and floppy disks for the past. Around the person, small thought bubbles contain small, funny memories or objects scattered along the timeline to emphasize the wide range of possible times ''the other day'' could refer to. The background is simple and colorful, with clock faces and calendar pages swirling humorously to highlight the confusion about time. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated features and lively expressions to convey the joke visually without any violence, politics, or adult themes.'),
 (3015, 'Humor, Relatable, Unknown, Workplace', 'I like my job. It''s the work I hate.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon-style office scene is depicted. In the center, a cheerful-looking employee sits at a cluttered desk with a big smile, wearing casual office attire. Around him, the desk is piled high with paperwork, a tired coffee cup, a ringing phone, and a blinking computer screen displaying a long to-do list. Behind him, a whiteboard lists two sections: one labeled ''Job'' with a big heart symbol and the other labeled ''Work'' with a chaotic scribble of tasks, deadlines, and warning signs. The character gestures with one hand towards the ''Job'' section, looking pleased, and with the other apparently overwhelmed by the ''Work'' section. The overall mood blends contentment with comic frustration. Include bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the contrast between liking the job and hating the work, making the contrast visually clear and funny. The setting should be a lighthearted, modern office environment with typical elements like a swivel chair, desk lamp, sticky notes, and a motivational poster on the wall that ironically says ''Love Your Job!''.'),
 (1063, 'Humor, Relatable, Weather Humor', 'The most delightful advantage of being bald - you can hear snowflakes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set outside on a snowy winter day. In the center is a bald man with a big, friendly smile, his shiny scalp clearly visible. Snowflakes are gently falling around him, and several large, distinct snowflakes are shown close to his head, as if making a soft sound. The man has his eyes closed and a peaceful, delighted expression, with one hand cupped behind an ear to ''hear'' the snowflakes. Around him, a simple snowy landscape with a few bare trees and a light blue sky. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the funny idea that being bald allows him to hear the delicate sound of snow falling. The style should be colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions, no text needed in the image.'),
 (1064, 'Humor, Relatable, Weather Humor', 'Washing your car to make it rain doesn''t work.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene outside a suburban house on a sunny day, depicting a person enthusiastically washing their car with a big sponge and a bucket of soapy water. The car, shiny and wet, reflects the bright sun. Above, a clear blue sky with no clouds is visible, and a small, exaggerated cartoon sun wearing sunglasses beams down. The person looks hopeful but puzzled, glancing upward at the dry sky. Nearby, a calendar on the wall or post shows the date, emphasizing the moment. Include humorous details such as water splashing comically or a bird watching with a skeptical expression. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the futility of the idea that washing a car could affect the weather.'),
 (1065, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'The right side of the street should be wider than the left, since that''s the side that we drive on.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of a simple street scene viewed from above, split down the middle. The right side of the street is exaggeratedly wide, with broad lanes, while the left side is very narrow, barely enough for a car. On the right side, several cars drive happily and confidently, maybe one car with a smiling face or eyes on the windshield to add personality. On the left side, a tiny car comically squeezed into a narrow lane or even trying to navigate a space too small for it, looking confused or frustrated. The street signs indicate that driving is on the right side. The background is light and colorful with simple buildings and trees lining both sides of the street. The overall style is playful and cartoonish with clean lines and bright colors emphasizing the absurdity of making one side wider just because we drive on it. Include a sun in the sky with a friendly face to add to the cheerful mood.'),
 (1066, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'There''s too much blood in my caffeine system.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a person sitting wide-eyed and jittery at a kitchen table cluttered with multiple coffee cups and a big empty coffee pot. The character looks frazzled and wired, with sweat drops and shaky hands holding a coffee cup. Around them, little red droplets shaped like tiny blood cells bounce comically away from the coffee cups as if they''re being overwhelmed or pushed out. A thought bubble above the person reads, ''There''s too much blood in my caffeine system.'' The kitchen is bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to amplify the humor of someone who has had way too much caffeine and is confusing the body’s systems. Include humorous details like a ticking clock showing early morning and an overfilled coffee mug about to spill.'),
 (1067, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'Things to do today: 1) Stop the arms race. 2) Floss.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person standing in front of a large chalkboard or list board titled ''Things to do today.'' The board has two items: ''1) Stop the arms race'' and ''2) Floss.'' The person is scratching their head, looking both puzzled and amused, holding a large, comically oversized dental floss container in one hand. Behind them, faintly illustrated or as a background element, are two large muscular robot arms facing each other, as a silly representation of an ''arms race.'' The setting is a simple, bright room with a casual vibe, emphasizing the absurd contrast between the serious global issue and the mundane personal task. The style should be colorful and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor in the juxtaposition of epic and trivial tasks.'),
 (1068, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'Total strangers need love too - and I''m stranger than most!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, eccentric-looking character standing alone on a busy city street. The character should have a wide grin and be dressed in mismatched, colorful clothes to emphasize their oddball nature. Around this character, there are small groups of people clearly ignoring each other, highlighting the concept of strangers. Include subtle heart-shaped symbols floating above the character’s head to show their desire for love. The background should show everyday elements like street lamps, benches, and a few pedestrians walking by without paying attention. The overall style should be light-hearted and fun, with exaggerated expressions to convey the character’s self-aware and playful attitude about being “stranger than most.”'),
 (1069, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'Two wrongs are only the beginning.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a series of two comic mistakes happening one after the other. The first part of the image depicts a character, looking puzzled, holding two incorrect items (for example, a broken map and a misspelled sign). The second part shows the same character making a second blunder based on the first one, like getting lost further or accidentally heading toward trouble, with exaggerated confused expressions and question marks above their head. The background can be a city street or a wilderness trail with signs pointing in conflicting or wrong directions, emphasizing the phrase ''two wrongs are only the beginning.'' The style should be colorful, playful, and emphasize the escalating nature of errors without implying any harm. Thought bubbles or caption boxes can be used to highlight the idea that one mistake leads to another.'),
 (1070, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'Warning: Dates in Calendar are closer than they appear.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a close-up of a traditional wall calendar. The calendar is open to a month with the days clearly visible. The numbers for each date seem to be comically squished or crowded together, almost overlapping, conveying the idea that the dates are physically closer to each other than usual. At the top of the calendar page, in big bold letters, is a warning sign that reads: ''Warning: Dates in Calendar are closer than they appear.'' In the background, a confused person or character with a raised eyebrow and wide eyes stares at the calendar, scratching their head as if puzzled by how tightly packed the dates are. The scene should have bright colors and exaggerated cartoonish expressions to enhance the humor and lightheartedness of the concept. The style is clean and simple with a focus on the calendar and the character''s reaction, capturing the joke’s play on words about the perception of dates approaching rapidly.'),
 (1071, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'We have enough youth, how about a fountain of SMART?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a park with a whimsical, sparkling fountain labeled ''Fountain of SMART'' in large, playful letters. Nearby, a group of diverse teenagers hang out looking playful and carefree, representing ''youth.'' An older, wise-looking figure (such as a professor or a cartoonish elder with glasses and a book) stands beside the fountain, holding a scroll or clipboard that says ''Intelligence Requests'' with an exaggerated hopeful expression. The background includes green grass, trees, and a clear blue sky, with some birds or butterflies to add lightness. The fountain should have sparkling water shooting up in a fun, exaggerated way, perhaps with little light bulbs or brains floating in the water to symbolize intelligence. The overall tone is lighthearted and clever, with characters drawn in a friendly, cartoon style with expressive faces to emphasize the joke’s ironic longing for more smarts rather than more youth.'),
 (1072, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'What''s the difference between ignorance and apathy? I don''t know and I don''t care', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side. The first character looks confused, scratching their head with a questioning expression, symbolizing ''ignorance.'' The second character stands next to them, arms crossed and wearing a bored or indifferent face, symbolizing ''apathy.'' Above their heads is a simple caption with the joke text: ''What''s the difference between ignorance and apathy? I don''t know and I don''t care.'' The background is plain or minimal to keep focus on the characters and the text. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated with cartoonish facial expressions for clear humor, avoiding any harsh lines or details. The characters can be casually dressed and set in a neutral indoor or outdoor environment, such as a park bench or sidewalk, emphasizing the universal nature of the joke.'),
 (1073, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'When I''m not in my right mind, my left mind gets pretty crowded.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a human brain split into two sides labeled ''Right Mind'' and ''Left Mind.'' The ''Right Mind'' side is empty or very sparse, looking calm and quiet. The ''Left Mind'' side is overcrowded with little cartoon characters or tiny people pushing and shoving, trying to fit in, with some comically squeezed into small spaces. The brain has a friendly face with raised eyebrows, looking slightly overwhelmed but amused. The background is simple and colorful, emphasizing the contrast between the empty and crowded sides. Add visual elements like small thought bubbles or symbols (like lightbulbs or question marks) above the left side to show busy thinking. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, drawn in a bright, friendly cartoon style suitable for all ages.'),
 (1074, 'Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'When there''s a will, I want to be in it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person holding a legal document titled ''Last Will and Testament.'' The person is smiling broadly and pointing at the document. Nearby, a group of people—family members or friends—look surprised or confused. In the background, a judge or lawyer sits at a desk, looking amused. The setting is a bright, simple office with a few plants and framed certificates on the walls. A playful sign on the wall reads ''Estate Planning Made Fun!'' The overall style is colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun on the word ''will'' with lighthearted expressions and exaggerated features without any dark or morbid elements.'),
 (1075, 'Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'The ''Oops'' attitude - get it done quick and bring it back if you have to.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person working hurriedly at a cluttered desk with papers flying everywhere and a big clock showing time ticking down. The person looks slightly frazzled but determined, holding a wrench or some work tool in one hand and a half-finished project on the desk. Nearby, a speech bubble from the person says, ''Oops attitude - get it done quick and bring it back if you have to.'' In the background, a confused coworker or friend watches with raised eyebrows, holding a checklist or a manual. The scene conveys a funny ''rush now, fix later'' vibe in a lighthearted office or workshop setting, emphasizing quick, imperfect work rather than perfection.'),
 (1076, 'Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'The part you least suspect to be the problem is, and is usually the most expensive, AND they''re out of stock.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a brightly lit auto repair shop. A frustrated customer stands beside a car with its hood open, looking bewildered and scratching their head. The mechanic, wearing a slightly stained uniform and a name tag, points dramatically to a tiny, obscure car part (like a small sensor or bolt) on a workbench labeled ''The Culprit.'' Nearby, a large sign on a shelf reads ''Out of Stock'' with empty hooks and dusty boxes. The customer holds a long receipt with a ridiculously high price highlighted. Around them, exaggerated details include a calendar with circled days waiting for the part, a thought bubble above the customer showing a big question mark, and scattered tools emphasizing the chaos and confusion. The overall style is colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions and comedic proportions to emphasize the frustration and irony of the situation without any negativity.'),
 (1077, 'Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'There is absolutely no substitute for a genuine lack of preparation.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an office or classroom environment. In the foreground, a person is sitting at a desk looking utterly frazzled and disorganized—papers scattered everywhere, a coffee cup tipped over, and a messy pile of books and notes around them. Their hair is wild and their expression shows panic and exhaustion. Behind them, a clock on the wall shows it''s late or just before a deadline. On the side, another character stands calmly, smiling knowingly with arms crossed, as if delivering the punchline. A speech bubble above this calm character contains the joke text: ''There is absolutely no substitute for a genuine lack of preparation.'' The overall tone is light-hearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions and clutter to highlight the chaos of being unprepared. The style is simple, bright, and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between calm acceptance and chaotic stress without any negativity or aggression.'),
 (1078, 'Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'There is always one more imbecile than you counted on.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a busy, chaotic office. At the center is a frustrated character (wearing casual office attire) looking surprised and slightly exasperated while counting on their fingers. Around them, several quirky, silly-looking coworkers act in absurd or goofy ways—one accidentally spills coffee, another typewrites nonsense, and a third is tangled in wires. In the background, a whiteboard or flip chart shows a neat list with a number, but an extra coworker stands behind it grinning mischievously, representing "one more imbecile" than expected. The office has simple desks, computers, coffee mugs, and scattered papers to emphasize the setting. The overall style is colorful and playful with exaggerated facial expressions and comically silly poses to highlight the joke''s meaning without any negativity.'),
 (1079, 'Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'UNEMPLOYMENT: The usual alternative to overwork.', NULL, 'A simple cartoon scene depicting two contrasting sides to illustrate the joke about unemployment as an alternative to overwork. On the left side, draw a stressed-out worker slumped over a desk piled high with paperwork, clock showing late hours. The worker looks tired, with disheveled hair and dark circles under their eyes. On the right side, show the same character relaxed at home in casual clothes, lounging comfortably on a couch with feet up, watching TV or playing video games, looking content and carefree. Include a calendar on the wall with workdays crossed out on the left side and blank or relaxed symbols like smiley faces on the right. The overall style should be light, bright, and humorous, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize fatigue versus relaxation, in a clean, colorful cartoon format without any violence or political themes.'),
 (1080, 'Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'When I look around at all the turmoil and strife, the power struggles and wars and injustice, I can''t help but think ...  Why do I keep working here?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon office scene with a stressed-out employee sitting at a cluttered desk covered in paperwork, a computer, and a coffee mug. Around them, depict subtle chaotic elements symbolizing turmoil: coworkers arguing in the background, a bulletin board with pinned headlines like ''Power Struggles,'' ''Wars,'' and ''Injustice.'' Include a clock on the wall showing late hours and an overflowing trash bin to emphasize workplace overwhelm. The employee should have a weary, puzzled expression, scratching their head, clearly questioning why they remain in this hectic environment. The style should be playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and expressive facial features to enhance the comic tone without any violence or harshness.'),
 (1081, 'Humor, Relatable, Workplace', 'Whoever decided beards are unprofessional probably couldn''t grow one.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two men in a simple office setting. On the left, a clean-shaven man dressed in a suit and tie looks somewhat uncomfortable or annoyed, holding a clipboard labeled ''Professionalism Standards.'' On the right, a confident man with a thick, well-groomed beard wearing casual office attire (a button-up shirt and jeans) leans back in his chair with a smug smile. Behind them is a whiteboard showing a checklist with ''Beard = Unprofessional?'' with a big red X next to it. The background includes typical office elements like a desk with a computer, a coffee mug that has a small beard logo, and a potted plant. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between the two men’s appearances and attitudes about beards in a professional environment. The expressions and body language clearly communicate the joke’s punchline — the clean-shaven man’s probable inability to grow a beard, contrasted with the bearded man’s pride and relaxed demeanor.'),
 (3090, 'Humor, Relationship Humor, Social Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, hallmark would make ''Sorry, what was your name again?'' cards.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a stereotypical handsome man standing confidently at a greeting card store aisle labeled ''Hallmark Cards.'' The man is holding a card awkwardly with the front cover reading ''Sorry, what was your name again?'' in playful, elegant font. Around him, other greeting cards on shelves have typical categories like ''Birthday,'' ''Thank You,'' and ''Love,'' but the man’s card humorously stands out. The man should look a bit clueless but proud, with a slight smirk. The background includes a sign above reading ''Hallmark'' and some shoppers glancing at him with amused expressions. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the comedic effect, ensuring a lighthearted and friendly vibe without any aggressive or insensitive elements.'),
 (1082, 'Humor, Riddles, Word Play', 'What starts with E, ends with E, and has only one letter in it?  An envelope!', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a large, friendly-looking envelope standing upright with a big smile and wide cartoon eyes. The envelope should have human-like arms and hands, one hand holding a small letter (a tiny paper with a visible letter symbol) prominently in front of it. Around the envelope, little animated letter symbols (like ''A'', ''B'', ''C'') float playfully. The background is simple and cheerful, like a light blue sky with a few white clouds. To the side, a puzzled cartoon character (person) scratches their head, looking at the envelope with a questioning expression. A speech bubble above the person says, "What starts with E, ends with E, and has only one letter in it?" while the envelope seems to be playfully presenting the answer. The overall tone is light, clean, and whimsical, suitable for all ages.'),
 (3220, 'Humor, Satire, Steven Wright, Words Humor', 'To steal ideas from one person is plagiarism; to steal from many is research.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a mischievous character sitting at a cluttered desk piled high with crumpled papers, books, and notebooks. The character has a sly grin and is holding a magnifying glass over one of the papers filled with scribbles and lightbulb sketches. Around the desk are thought bubbles depicting multiple different people with little idea icons floating above their heads, implying the character is ''stealing'' ideas from many sources. In the background, a wall labeled ''Research Vault'' with papers pinned everywhere is visible. The overall tone is light and comedic with exaggerated expressions and bright colors.'),
 (3097, 'Humor, Satire, Unknown, Workplace', 'If men ran the world, the funniest guy in the office would get to be CEO.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon office scene with a group of men gathered around a conference table. One man stands confidently at the head of the table dressed in a CEO suit, wearing a big, goofy clown nose and a wide grin, clearly the ''funniest guy.'' The other men are watching him with mixed expressions—some amused, others skeptical. The office has typical elements like a whiteboard with charts, a large potted plant, and cubicles visible in the background. A small sign on the wall reads ''World Headquarters.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the joke that the CEO position is based on who is the funniest, rather than traditional qualifications.'),
 (1083, 'Humor, School, Word Play', 'Study art and logic - learn to draw your own conclusions.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a student sitting at a traditional school desk. The student holds a pencil and a sketchpad, drawing a funny, exaggerated picture of a logical diagram (like a flowchart or Venn diagram) that is clearly labeled ''Conclusions.'' Around the student are two posters on the classroom wall: one labeled ''Art'' with paintbrushes and colorful strokes, and another labeled ''Logic'' with symbols such as syllogisms or math symbols. The student’s expression is sheepish but proud, suggesting they are literally ''drawing conclusions.'' The classroom setting is bright and playful, with a chalkboard in the background showing the phrase ''Study art and logic'' written neatly. The overall tone is lighthearted and clever, emphasizing the pun with visual elements combining art and logical reasoning.'),
 (1084, 'Humor, School, Word Play', 'Teachers have class.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a bright, cheerful classroom. In the center stands a smiling teacher with a confident pose, wearing glasses and holding a book titled ''Class.'' Around the teacher are cartoonish floating objects symbolizing ''class''—such as a little top hat, a monocle, and a fancy teacup—floating lightly in the air like magical icons. The chalkboard behind the teacher has the words ''Teachers have class'' written in playful, bold letters, with doodles of students clapping or giving thumbs-up. The room contains typical classroom elements: desks with notebooks, a globe, a clock on the wall, and colorful posters. The overall mood is lighthearted and witty, emphasizing the pun on ''class'' as both a group of students and having elegance or style. The cartoon style should be fun and exaggerated, with happy expressions and vibrant colors to capture the double meaning of the joke without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (1085, 'Humor, Science', 'If you yelled for 8 years, 7 months and 6 days, you will have produced enough sound energy to heat one cup of coffee.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a tired, cartoonish person standing in a cozy kitchen. The person looks exhausted, with messy hair and cheeks puffed out as if they''ve been yelling non-stop for a very long time. Surround them with speech bubbles filled with sound waves or exclamation marks to represent yelling. Nearby on a counter or table, place a steaming cup of coffee with visible rising steam. To emphasize the time span, include a large calendar or clock in the background showing the passage of "8 years, 7 months, and 6 days." The kitchen environment should be light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to add humor. The overall tone is funny and slightly absurd, highlighting the idea that yelling for such a long time could generate enough energy to heat a cup of coffee.'),
 (1086, 'Humor, Science', 'It has recently been discovered that research causes cancer in rats.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cluttered laboratory filled with typical research equipment: microscopes, beakers, test tubes, charts, and a whiteboard with complicated formulas. In the foreground, a cute, slightly confused cartoon rat wearing tiny glasses is holding a small research paper titled ''Cancer Studies''. The rat is surrounded by scientists wearing white lab coats, who are intently observing it and taking notes. In the background, there is a poster on the wall that reads ''Warning: Research Causes Cancer in Rats'' with a humorous emphasis. The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated facial expressions on both the rat and the scientists to emphasize the irony of research causing cancer in the very subject being studied. The style is colorful, simple, and consistent with a classic cartoon comic strip look, with rounded shapes and expressive eyes on the characters to enhance humor and approachability.'),
 (1087, 'Humor, Science', 'Mr. Interesting says: Imagine if water were magnetic! Drink some and walk through a strong magnetic field...', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a quirky character labeled ''Mr. Interesting'' wearing a bright ''Mr. Interesting'' name tag, holding up a glass of water with a curious and mischievous smile. Around him, there’s a playful, visible magnetic field illustrated by large, wavy red and blue magnetic lines or waves emanating from a giant magnet shaped like a horseshoe. The magnet is positioned nearby, and the character is shown slightly lifting off the ground or being pulled towards the magnet as if the water inside him is magnetic. The setting is a simple lab or science classroom with a chalkboard in the background featuring a simple drawing of a magnet and water molecules. The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the absurdity of magnetic water manipulation. The scene should evoke a fun “what-if” science vibe with humor and imagination clearly conveyed.'),
 (1088, 'Humor, Science', 'Our eyes are always the same size from birth, but our nose and ears never stop growing.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a baby, a young child, and an elderly person standing side by side. Each character has exaggerated features to emphasize the joke: all three have almost identical-sized eyes (large and round for clarity), but progressively larger noses and ears as they age. The baby has small nose and ears, the child has medium-sized nose and ears, and the elderly person has very large, long ears and a big nose. They all look cheerful and slightly surprised, with the elderly person possibly holding a mirror or magnifying glass to emphasize the growth. The background is simple and bright, like a light pastel color, with minimal props, focusing on the characters'' facial features. The style is playful and cartoonish, with bold outlines and expressive faces to highlight the joke humorously and clearly.'),
 (1089, 'Humor, Science Fiction Humor, Word Play', 'Travel to the future in the blink of an eye!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person standing in front of a large, old-fashioned clock face with exaggeratedly large eyes wide open, mid-blink. The clock’s hands are spinning rapidly, and around the person, there are small cartoonish futuristic elements like flying cars, robots, and holograms appearing as if they''ve popped up instantly. The character is frozen in the blink, with a surprised or puzzled expression, emphasizing the idea of ''traveling to the future'' literally by blinking. The background should be simple and colorful, playing up the contrast between the ordinary present time and the futuristic world. Include humorous details like a calendar flipping pages or a newspaper headline changing from ''Today'' to ''Future News.'' The style is light, playful, and suitable for all audiences, with round shapes and vibrant colors to keep the mood fun and whimsical.'),
 (1090, 'Humor, Science, Word Play', 'If you''re not part of the solution, you''re part of the precipitate.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple chemistry lab. In the foreground, a scientist character wearing a white lab coat and safety goggles looks slightly puzzled while holding a test tube with bubbling liquid. On the lab table in front of them, there is a clear glass beaker labeled ''Solution'' containing a blue liquid, sparkling and looking active. Next to it is a small pile of solid, grainy material labeled ''Precipitate'' with tiny particles clumping together. Above the scene floats a comic-style speech bubble with the joke text: ''If you''re not part of the solution, you''re part of the precipitate.'' The background has typical lab elements like shelves with colorful chemicals and periodic table posters, drawn in bright, cheerful cartoon style to emphasize the pun and lightheartedness of the joke.'),
 (1091, 'Humor, Science, Word Play', 'Inanimate objects are classified scientifically into three major catergories:', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a classroom or laboratory setting with a cheerful professor or scientist standing beside a large, old-fashioned chalkboard. On the chalkboard, the title reads: ''Classification of Inanimate Objects.'' Below this, there are three large cartoon drawings of everyday objects arranged in three columns. The objects are exaggerated and lively-looking: a grumpy old clock with arms crossing, a dumbfounded toaster with a popping slice of bread, and a confused rubber duck sitting on a lab table. The scientist, wearing a lab coat and glasses, is pointing at the objects with a big smile, as if explaining their scientific categories, while a group of amused students or other scientists watch, some taking notes and others chuckling. The whole scene has bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the joke''s playful tone. The setting should be light and funny, with no text beyond the chalkboard heading and simple arrows/labels pointing to the objects to hint at their ''classification.'' The overall mood is educational parody with a silly twist.'),
 (1092, 'Humor, Science, Word Play', 'Infinity is far out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of a cosmic scene where a cool, laid-back infinity symbol (8) is floating in space wearing retro sunglasses and a relaxed smile, surrounded by stars and planets. The infinity sign is depicted as a character with arms and legs, one arm casually pointing outward as if saying ''far out,'' and a speech bubble above it saying ''Infinity is far out.'' The background should have vibrant colors with whimsical stars and a swirling galaxy to emphasize the ''far out'' space vibe. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated for comedic effect, suitable for a fun science or math-themed cartoon.'),
 (1093, 'Humor, Science, Word Play', 'Quantum Particles: the dreams that stuff is made of.', NULL, 'A colorful, whimsical cartoon scene featuring a cozy bedroom with a child tucked into bed, their head resting on a pillow shaped like an atom. Above the bed floats a translucent thought bubble filled with tiny, smiling quantum particles depicted as cute, glowing orbs with eyes and tiny limbs, performing various dream-like activities such as bouncing around, forming patterns, and creating sparkles. The room contains scientific elements like a poster of an atom on the wall, a telescope by the window, and a bookshelf labeled ''Physics for Kids.'' Soft pastel colors dominate the scene, giving it a dreamy, imaginative atmosphere. The style is playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the joke''s pun that quantum particles are the ''dreams'' that make up matter, blending science with fantasy humor.'),
 (1094, 'Humor, Science, Word Play', 'There''s no future in time travel.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a slightly confused scientist standing next to a classic, comical time machine (think a quirky contraption with flashing lights, dials, and a big clock face). The scientist is scratching their head while holding a calendar showing the current date. A speech bubble above reads, "There''s no future in time travel." In the background, there is a long timeline displayed as a wavy line with past dates fading on the left and the present date marked clearly where the scientist stands. The timeline ends abruptly before reaching any ''future'' dates. The overall tone is lighthearted and silly, with exaggerated facial expression on the scientist emphasizing the ironic punchline.'),
 (2784, 'Humor, Self-Deprecation Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'Don''t ask me; I was hired for my looks.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person at an office job interview. The candidate is sitting across a desk from a serious-looking interviewer. The candidate is dressed very casually, smiling confidently, with exaggerated good looks—perfect hair, perfect clothes, and a charming expression. On the desk is a sign that reads ''Hiring Manager'' and another sign that says ''Position: Whatever''. Behind the interviewee is a large mirror reflecting their attractive appearance. The candidate is shrugging with an innocent smile, as if to say ''Don''t ask me; I was hired for my looks.'' The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial features to emphasize humor and charm without any negativity or political tone.'),
 (1095, 'Humor, Shopping Jokes', 'People will buy anything that''s one to a customer.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a quirky market stall labeled ''One-to-a-Customer Shop.'' The shopkeeper is standing behind a counter with a friendly grin, holding up a silly assortment of odd items each clearly marked with a small sign saying ''One Per Customer.'' Items on display include a single banana, a lone sock, a single shoe, a solitary carrot, and a single rubber duck. In front of the counter, a diverse line of eager, quirky customers is waiting, some holding baskets or shopping bags. Each customer is selecting exactly one item, looking amused or excited. The background should be colorful and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke about how people buy anything if limited to one each. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bold outlines and bright colors, emphasizing the whimsical nature of the joke without any threatening or sensitive content.'),
 (1096, 'Humor, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'Polite conversation is rarely either.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a fancy tea party with several well-dressed characters sitting around a table, all speaking to each other with overly formal and polite expressions but with obvious signs of awkwardness or tension. Some characters have raised eyebrows, forced smiles, or slightly uncomfortable body language. Speech bubbles show polite but awkward phrases like ''Oh, such a delightful weather, isn’t it?'' and ''Your hat is... quite unique!'' The background is an elegant parlor with fancy wallpaper, a chandelier, and delicate china cups on the table. The overall mood is comically stiff, suggesting that while everyone is being polite, the conversation is clearly not lively or genuinely friendly. The style is light and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the irony.'),
 (1097, 'Humor, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'Sometimes, someone unexpected comes into your life out of nowhere, makes your heart race, and changes you forever. We call those people cops.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a surprised person on a city sidewalk, mid-stride, with a very exaggerated, wide-eyed, and heart-racing expression. Above their head should be a comic-style heart pounding symbol with motion lines to emphasize a racing heart. Suddenly, a friendly police officer unexpectedly appears out of nowhere, stepping onto the scene with a cheerful smile and a gesture like raising a hand in greeting or holding a ticket book. The setting is urban with a few simple street details: a streetlamp, a park bench, and a distant cityscape. The style is lighthearted and playful with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to show shock and sudden change. The overall mood is funny, capturing the surprise and impact the officer has on the person’s life as if they suddenly appeared like a love interest, but humorously it’s a cop instead.'),
 (1098, 'Humor, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'The worst thing about censorship is XXXXXXXXXXXXXX.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk or computer, trying to write or speak the sentence: ''The worst thing about censorship is XXXXXXXXXXXXXX.'' The person looks frustrated and confused, scratching their head or shrugging, with a speech bubble or text box containing the line with the Xs clearly blocking out the rest of the sentence. Around the person, include visual symbols representing censorship, such as big red ''censored'' stamps, black bars covering words on papers, or a giant pair of scissors floating above ready to cut words. The background should be simple and lighthearted, emphasizing the absurdity and irony of being unable to express themselves fully due to censorship. Make the art style bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for humor but non-threatening and family-friendly overall.'),
 (3201, 'Humor, Social Humor, Statistics Humor, Steven Wright', 'Half the people you know are below average.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a casual social gathering in a park or backyard with a diverse group of about eight people chatting and mingling. Each character wears exaggerated facial expressions and body language indicating varying levels of confidence or self-awareness. Above the scene, a playful graph or scale hovers showing a line dividing the group into two halves labeled ''Above Average'' and ''Below Average.'' Half the people are clearly placed on each side, with some happily on the top half and others sheepishly on the bottom half. Include lighthearted details like a confused character scratching their head and another shrugging as if puzzled by the unexpected fact. The overall style should be colorful and cartoonish with simple, rounded characters to emphasize the humor and friendly tone of the joke.'),
 (1099, 'Humor, Star Wars', 'There is much Obi-Wan did not tell you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a Star Wars-like desert landscape reminiscent of Tatooine. In the foreground, a confused-looking young Jedi, dressed in simple robes with a lightsaber hanging from his belt, scratches his head. Facing him is an older, mysterious Jedi master with a wise, knowing expression who is deliberately holding his finger over his lips as if keeping a secret. Around them, iconic Star Wars elements like twin suns in the sky and a small moisture farm in the background subtly enhance the scene. Above the characters, a speech bubble from the older Jedi reads, "There is much Obi-Wan did not tell you." The overall art style is colorful and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and mystique of hidden information, all drawn in a lighthearted cartoon format.'),
 (1100, 'Humor, Star Wars', 'Very funny, Scotty.  Now beam down my clothes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on the bridge of a starship with a cheerful, uniformed captain addressing a small, stout engineer named Scotty, who is standing next to a large, futuristic teleportation device. The captain is depicted with a playful smile, pointing toward an empty hanger or a clothes rack that is humorously floating in midair, indicating missing clothes. Scotty looks slightly puzzled or amused as he operates the teleportation controls. The background shows typical sci-fi elements like blinking consoles and a starry window view of outer space. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, capturing the joke about teleporting clothes rather than people.'),
 (1101, 'Humor, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs are born without a biological clock. If they aren''t near a window they can''t tell if it''s night or day. Unless someone tells them dinner''s ready, they forget to eat.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a cluttered, dimly lit tech workshop filled with computer parts, monitors, cables, and gadgets scattered around. In the middle, a distracted technician with messy hair and glasses is sitting in front of multiple screens glowing brightly, unaware of the time. Behind him, a window shows a clear contrast with bright daylight outside on one side and nighttime stars on the other, emphasizing confusion about day and night. Nearby, a colleague or family member stands holding a plate with a steaming dinner, waving and calling out cheerfully. The technician looks puzzled and somewhat surprised as he glances up from his work. The overall mood is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and details like a clock with no hands on the wall to visually reinforce the joke about lacking a biological clock. Include subtle tech-themed decorations like a “Real Techs” mug or a poster that humorously says “Biological Clock Not Found.”'),
 (1102, 'Humor, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs can''t explain their job to anyone but another Real Tech. This is because the explanation is both too complicated and too boring.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two tech people standing in an office filled with computers, wires, and tech gadgets. One tech person is enthusiastically explaining something complicated with tangled speech bubbles full of confusing symbols, code snippets, and math formulas. The other person looks completely lost and bored, eyes half-closed and slumped posture, holding a coffee cup. Nearby, a third person (non-tech) is trying to listen but is clearly overwhelmed and about to fall asleep, with a thought bubble showing a simple smiley face to indicate confusion. The background has amusing details like a whiteboard with indecipherable graphs, a stack of programming books, and a clock showing late hours to emphasize the boring and complex nature of the explanation. The overall style is light-hearted, exaggerated, and cartoonish, focusing on the comedic disconnect between tech people and non-tech listeners.'),
 (1103, 'Humor, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs don''t do status reports or work to schedules. Brilliance arrives when it arrives.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon office scene featuring a laid-back tech worker at their cluttered desk. The tech is casually dressed, maybe with a t-shirt and hoodie, leaning back in their swivel chair with feet up on the desk, hands behind their head and a relaxed, confident smile. On the desk are typical tech gadgets: a laptop with code visible on the screen, empty coffee cups, scattered sticky notes labeled ''Brilliance Ideas'' and ''Maybe Tomorrow.'' Nearby, a wall clock shows an unusual random time like 3:17. The background features a whiteboard with the sarcastic note: ''No Status Reports, No Deadlines – Brilliance Arrives When It Arrives.'' Add a calendar flipped to a month but with no dates marked, emphasizing no schedule. The overall style should be bright and cartoonish with exaggerated relaxed posture and playful decor to underline the joke’s humor about informal work culture among tech professionals.'),
 (1104, 'Humor, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs haven''t seen their desks for at least two years. They know something''s holding up all that paper, but they''re not sure what it looks like.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside an office workspace. The foreground shows a very messy desk completely buried under an enormous, chaotic pile of paper stacks reaching well above the height of a seated person. A tired-looking tech worker wearing casual office attire—such as a T-shirt, hoodie, and glasses—is standing beside the desk with a confused expression, scratching his head while peering at the mountain of papers. The background includes typical tech office elements: a computer monitor on the side partially visible behind the stacks, a coffee mug with steam rising, some scattered cables, and maybe a small potted plant wilting under the paper''s shadow. The overall room is dimly lit to suggest neglect and disuse. The style should be cartoonish with exaggerated features to emphasize the absurd height and clutter of the paper pile, as well as the tech''s puzzled expression. Include a small caption or thought bubble above the tech reading, ''Not sure what’s holding all this up...'''),
 (1105, 'Humor, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs know what firmware is but can''t explain it to anyone else.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confused person (a ''customer'') standing in front of a tech technician. The technician wears a shirt or badge labeled ''Tech Support'' and is holding a small, glowing microchip labeled ''Firmware.'' The technician has a thoughtful, slightly puzzled look, as if struggling to explain, with speech bubbles showing a jumble of technical symbols and question marks. Behind them, a large computer or gadget with flashing lights sits on a desk. The customer scratches their head looking utterly baffled. Background is a simple tech support office with posters of computers and wires, drawn in bright, playful colors to keep the tone light and funny.'),
 (1106, 'Humor, Traffic Jokes', 'Never use directional signals when changing lanes. They only warn other drivers to speed up and not let you in.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a congested multi-lane highway with several cars. In the foreground, one car is trying to change lanes. The driver inside looks mischievous, cheekily grinning while deliberately not using the turn signal. Other nearby cars have exaggerated expressions of annoyance and frustration, speeding up with motion lines behind them to indicate acceleration. Above the lane changer, a comic-style thought bubble reads, ''Why warn them?'' The setting is daytime, with clear skies and simple roadside elements like streetlights and signs. Overall, the style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor of the joke about not using signals causing other drivers to speed up and block the lane change.'),
 (1107, 'Humor, Word Play', 'If you''re ever attached by a group of clowns, go for the juggler', NULL, 'Draw a colorful, humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of clowns standing together, looking mischievous and somewhat silly. In the foreground, show a slightly surprised person (with wide eyes) encountering the clowns. Among the clowns, highlight one juggling bright, bouncing balls or clubs. The setting is cheerful and circus-themed with balloons, juggling pins scattered on the ground, and a big red nose on each clown. The person in the scene is preparing to ''go for the juggler'' by pointing at or stepping toward the juggling clown with a confident but playful expression. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, focusing on exaggerated clown costumes, big shoes, colorful wigs, and face paint to emphasize the joke’s playful tone. No violence is shown, just an amusing encounter full of lively energy.'),
 (1108, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Ignorance is when you don''t know anything and somebody finds it out.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a simple classroom or living room setting. In the center, a character with a confused, clueless expression is shrugging their shoulders. Around them are floating question marks and empty thought bubbles to emphasize ignorance. Nearby, another character is holding a magnifying glass, leaning in with a curious and amused expression as if they have just discovered the clueless person''s ignorance. Add a subtle, lightbulb-shaped sign above the discoverer''s head to indicate the moment of realization. The style is playful and exaggerated, with bright colors and rounded shapes to keep the tone light and funny, no detail should be harsh or negative.'),
 (1109, 'Humor, Word Play', 'I''m immortal - so far.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a cheerful ghost standing confidently in the middle of a simple, bright background. The ghost has a friendly smile and thumbs up, wearing a casual ''I''m Immortal'' T-shirt. Around the ghost are little cartoon-style hourglasses and calendar pages fluttering away, indicating the passage of time. A small tombstone with the word ''So Far'' humorously written on it is placed next to the ghost, emphasizing the joke’s cautious optimism. The style is light, clean, and colorful, evoking a playful and humorous atmosphere without any darkness or spookiness.'),
 (1110, 'Humor, Word Play', 'I''m not breaking the rules - I''m just testing their elasticity.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in casual clothes stretching a large rubber band labeled ''rules'' between their hands. The person has a playful grin and exaggeratedly stretched arms, with the rubber band extending and twisting in a way that looks elastic and flexible. Around them is a setting like an office or classroom with a few simple desks and chairs, and a small stack of rulebooks or a sign that says ''Rules'' nearby. The background is light and simple, focusing on the stretchy rubber band and the person''s animated effort to stretch it. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the idea of flexible rule-breaking without any confrontation.'),
 (1111, 'Humor, Word Play', 'I''m not in good enough shape to exercise.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person, slightly out of shape, sitting on a couch surrounded by various exercise equipment like dumbbells, a yoga mat, and a jump rope. The person looks tired and is holding a remote control in one hand and a bag of chips in the other. A thought bubble above their head shows a tired, sweaty version of themselves struggling to lift a weight, emphasizing their lack of motivation or energy to exercise. The room is cozy with a TV in front, displaying a fitness workout program that the person clearly isn''t engaging with. The overall tone is lighthearted and relatable, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke about not being in ''good enough shape'' to exercise.'),
 (1112, 'Humor, Word Play', 'I''m not indecisive, am I?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of two open doors, both looking identical and equally appealing. The person has a puzzled expression, scratching their head, clearly unsure which door to choose. Above their head, two thought bubbles show conflicting ideas: one with a question mark and the other with an exclamation mark. The background is simple, perhaps an office or hallway setting, to emphasize the indecision. The style is light and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to highlight the comedic confusion.'),
 (1113, 'Humor, Word Play', 'I''m not unemployed. I''m a consultant.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a casually dressed person sitting at a small desk in a messy home office or living room. They have a relaxed, slightly smug expression while typing on a laptop, with a coffee mug next to them labeled ''World''s Best Consultant.'' Around them, scattered papers and a calendar marked with sparse appointments suggest a lack of actual work. The room includes a couch with a few video game controllers and a TV in the background, emphasizing a laid-back atmosphere. A speech bubble above the person reads, "I''m not unemployed. I''m a consultant." The overall style should be lighthearted and comical, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the irony of calling unemployment "consulting." No stressful or serious elements, just a playful take on the phrase.'),
 (1114, 'Humor, Word Play', 'I''m out of my mind, but please leave a message.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly disheveled cartoon brain character standing next to a classic office answering machine. The brain has wide, friendly eyes and a goofy smile. Beside it, there''s a phone on a desk with a note that says ''Please leave a message.'' The background is a simple, bright office setting with a calendar and a small potted plant on the desk. The brain character looks as if it has just stepped away, leaving a humorous ''message'' sign with an empty speech bubble above it. The style should be lighthearted and whimsical, with bold outlines and vibrant colors to emphasize the silly, playful nature of the phrase ''I''m out of my mind, but please leave a message.'''),
 (1115, 'Humor, Word Play', 'In the US we call it an elevator, but in the UK they call it a lift. I guess we''re all just raised differently.', NULL, 'A lighthearted, colorful cartoon set in the middle of a city street with an elevator and a lift next to each other. The elevator is a typical American-style elevator with shiny metal doors and buttons visible inside, labeled ''Elevator.'' The lift is a classic British-style red telephone booth turned into a lift, with the word ''Lift'' on the top sign. Two characters stand in front of each: an American person on the elevator side wearing casual clothes with a friendly smile, and a British person on the lift side wearing a bowler hat and holding a teacup with a smirk. Above them is a speech bubble from each, one saying, ''In the US we call it an elevator,'' and the other, ''In the UK they call it a lift.'' The background includes subtle landmarks like a small American flag and Big Ben for the UK to clarify the location humorously. The overall style is a cheerful, simple cartoon emphasizing cultural differences with a friendly tone.'),
 (1116, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Intentionally losing a game of rock paper scissors is just as hard as trying to win', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two friends sitting across from each other at a small table, playing rock paper scissors. One player has a conflicted, exaggerated facial expression, scratching their head and hesitating with a hand hovering mid-gesture, as if struggling to intentionally lose. The other player is confidently showing a ''rock'' hand sign with a sly, knowing smile. Above them, a playful floating thought bubble shows a cartoon rock, paper, and scissors with tiny sweat drops, emphasizing the difficulty of the task. The background is simple with cheerful, bright colors to keep the tone light and funny. Both characters are drawn in a friendly, exaggerated cartoon style with big eyes and expressive faces to show the internal struggle humorously.'),
 (1117, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Invest in the Miracle Chair Company today!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a bright, cheerful office or living room with a large, luxurious, and obviously comfortable armchair in the center, gleaming as if it''s magical. The chair has sparkles or stars around it to emphasize the ''miracle'' aspect. A person standing nearby, dressed in business casual, is holding a briefcase labeled ''Investments'' and looking excitedly at the chair as if plotting to invest in the company. A small sign next to the chair reads ''Miracle Chair Co.'' in bold, playful letters. The background includes charts or posters that humorously suggest huge growth or profits, but with exaggerated, funny graphics like upward arrows shaped like couches. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to convey optimism and humor related to the idea of investing in a miraculous chair product.'),
 (1118, 'Humor, Word Play', 'It''s good to keep an open mind - just don''t let your brains fall out.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a friendly-looking human head with the top of the skull opened like a hinged lid, tilted back as if ''open,'' revealing a few humorous, slightly exaggerated brains inside. The brains look surprised or alarmed, some depicted as trying not to fall out, with little cartoon hands holding on or grabbing the edge. The head wears glasses and has a gentle smile, capturing the idea of ''keeping an open mind'' literally. The background is simple, pastel-colored, with maybe a small floating speech bubble above the head saying, ''Keep your brains inside!'' The overall tone is light and funny, with simple line art and bright colors to emphasize the pun without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1119, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Lately I''ve found that every time I want to rest on my laurels, I need wider laurels.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person reclining comfortably on a small laurel wreath acting like a recliner chair. The person looks relaxed but slightly cramped and is reaching out to a much larger laurel wreath nearby, shaped like a bigger recliner chair, illustrating the idea of needing more space to rest. The setting is light and playful, with perhaps a few trophies or medals on a nearby shelf to reinforce the concept of ''resting on laurels'' as resting on past achievements. The overall style is colorful and simple, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of wanting bigger laurel wreaths to rest on.'),
 (1120, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Law of Probability Dispersal: Whatever it is that hits the fan will not be evenly distributed', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classic fan mounted on a table blowing air. In front of the fan, a large pile of various messy items (representing ''whatever hits the fan'') like mud, papers, paint splatters, and a pie are flying toward the fan. Instead of being evenly spread behind the fan, the mess is scattered wildly and unevenly—one corner has a huge splatter on the wall, another patch on the floor, and some dripping on a nearby character’s surprised face. The character, cartoonishly wide-eyed and wearing casual clothes, is ducking or trying to shield themselves with a newspaper. The background is simple, focusing on the fan, the flying mess, and the uneven splatter patterns to emphasize the joke. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize humor without any mess being scary or dirty—just silly and exaggerated splats and drips.'),
 (1121, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Legalize mental telepathy? I knew you were going to say that.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing two people facing each other in a casual setting, such as a park bench or coffee shop. One person says the phrase, ''Legalize mental telepathy?'' with an inquisitive look, as if proposing a new idea. The other person immediately replies with a knowing smile and hand raised in acknowledgment, responding, ''I knew you were going to say that.'' To emphasize the telepathy joke, small playful wavy lines or a faint glowing outline could be drawn between their heads, suggesting communication without words. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions portraying surprise and amusement. The background is simple but cheerful, with minimal details so the focus remains on the interaction between the two characters.'),
 (1122, 'Humor, Word Play', 'LOOTING: A public shopping spree generously sponsored by local merchants in the wake of a riot.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a chaotic outdoor street market just after a riot. Local shop owners stand bewildered behind their colorful storefronts with ''Sale'' signs, scratching their heads or shrugging. In front of the shops, groups of cartoonish cartoon people excitedly dash around grabbing merchandise off shelves and from displays, holding shopping bags overflowing with goods. Some shoppers look gleeful and others confused, as if mistaking looting for a public shopping spree. Smoke and broken windows in the background suggest recent unrest, but the atmosphere remains lighthearted with exaggerated expressions. Bright colors, exaggerated motion lines, and comical facial expressions emphasize the joke’s ironic tone about looting being a ‘shopping spree sponsored by local merchants.’ No one appears angry or violent; instead, everyone is caught in comedic disbelief or merriment.'),
 (1123, 'Humor, Word Play', 'METHYLPHOBIA: n. The fear that you are going to have to pay the one cent you over-pumped at the self-service station.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene at a busy self-service gas station. In the foreground, a nervous-looking person stands next to a gas pump with a wide-eyed expression of anxiety. The gas hose is still hooked to the car, and a small digital meter on the pump shows a price ending with an extra 1 cent. Behind the character is a thought bubble displaying a tiny, scary-looking, but funny cartoon monster labeled ''Methylphobia'' with a worried expression holding a tiny coin. Include the gas station surroundings with signs that say ''Self-Service'' and a price board showing gas prices. The overall tone is light-hearted and comical, with exaggerated facial expressions and a bright color palette to convey the silly fear of having to pay an extra cent at the pump.'),
 (1124, 'Humor, Word Play', 'My friend David had his ID stolen recently. Now we just call him Dave.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two male friends standing together outside. One friend, looking slightly smug and wearing casual clothes, is pointing at the other who looks confused and slightly annoyed. The annoyed friend is holding an empty wallet with a visible ''ID Missing'' label on it. Above them is a small floating caption showing a torn or disappearing ID card icon. The environment is simple, maybe a park or street background with light colors to keep it bright and funny. The style should be playful and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the joke about the stolen ID and the nickname change from ''David'' to ''Dave.'' No violence or negativity, just light-hearted and witty banter vibes.'),
 (1125, 'Humor, Word Play', 'My friend Rick has CDO - it''s just like OCD but it''s in alphabetical order', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person named Rick standing proudly next to a large clipboard or poster. On the clipboard, the letters ''CDO'' are neatly written in perfect alphabetical order, with the letters ''OCD'' jumbled or crossed out nearby. Rick should have a cheerful, slightly nerdy expression, wearing casual clothes with maybe glasses. Around him, include little visual hints of neatness and order: perfectly stacked books, color-coded folders, or labeled jars arranged alphabetically on shelves. The style should be bright, clean, and light-hearted, emphasizing neatness and the joke about OCD being alphabetized.'),
 (1126, 'Humor, Word Play', 'My reality check just bounced.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a bank teller''s window looking surprised and slightly confused. The person holds out a large, oversized check labeled ''Reality Check'' in bright, bold letters. The bank teller behind the counter has raised eyebrows and holds up a rubber stamp marked ''Bounced,'' stamping it across the check. Around them, the bank environment is cheerful and exaggeratedly colorful, with a sign that says ''Reality Bank.'' Include small humorous details like a wall poster offering ''Loans for Dreams'' and a tiny calendar showing the date. The person’s expression and body language should convey disbelief and irony, emphasizing the joke about a ''reality check'' literally bouncing like a bad bank check.'),
 (1127, 'Humor, Word Play', 'NEONPHANCY (ne on'' fan see) n. A fluorescent light bulb struggling to come to life.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a single fluorescent light bulb mounted on a ceiling fixture. The bulb has a face with exaggerated sleepy eyes and a slightly frowning mouth, as if it is struggling to wake up. Tiny sweat droplets can be added around its ''forehead'' to emphasize effort. The bulb glows faintly with dim bluish neon light, flickering intermittently. Around the bulb, whimsical squiggly lines and subtle spark effects illustrate the struggling to come to life. Below, a room with a cozy interior and a person staring up at the bulb in mild frustration or confusion, scratching their head. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to convey the humorous concept of a bulb ''waking up'' like a groggy human. No violent or offensive elements, just playful and fun.'),
 (1128, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Nerves of steel, Body of iron, Brain of stone.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a superhero character striking a triumphant pose. The superhero is wearing a shiny metallic suit made partly of steel and iron, emphasizing the ''nerves of steel'' and ''body of iron''. Their expression looks dazed or confused, with a comically oversized stone for a brain visible through a transparent helmet or open head section, illustrating ''brain of stone''. The background is simple and bright, with comic-style action lines radiating outward to highlight the character''s exaggerated qualities. Include subtle humorous details like a steel nerve-shaped guitar string or iron muscles with bolts, and a large rock labeled ''brain'' sitting loosely inside the head cavity. The overall tone is light and funny, without any threatening or inappropriate elements.'),
 (1129, 'Humor, Word Play', 'No matter what you hear, the words are usually different.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of two characters standing next to each other, both wearing rabbit ear headbands and holding large cartoonish ears to symbolize listening. There are colorful speech bubbles above the characters showing the same phrase but with each bubble containing jumbled, slightly different words to visually represent misunderstanding. The setting is a simple park bench or living room couch to imply casual conversation. Include subtle visual cues like a smashed tin can phone or slightly crossed telephone wires between them to enhance the theme that messages are altered when transmitted. The style should be playful, with exaggerated expressions of confusion and amusement on their faces, to capture the irony of the joke.'),
 (1130, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Nobody is in control of their own elevator.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a small elevator with three diverse people looking slightly confused or surprised. The elevator buttons are prominently displayed with some buttons glowing, but there is also a quirky, oversized “Control Panel” that is humorously complex and comically labeled with random knobs, levers, and a big red ''Do Not Touch'' button. None of the people are pressing the buttons; instead, a small, playful robotic hand or a tiny, cheeky cartoon character (like a mischievous elevator sprite) is pressing a button from the corner, illustrating that nobody inside actually controls the elevator. The elevator''s background shows typical elevator features like floor numbers, a floor indicator with moving arrows, and a small mirror reflecting the puzzled expressions. The style is light-hearted, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the joke’s playful nature without any negativity.'),
 (1131, 'Humor, Word Play', 'On a beautiful day like this, it is hard to believe that anyone can be  unhappy - but we''re working on it.', NULL, 'A cheerful outdoor park scene on a bright, sunny day with clear blue skies and fluffy white clouds. In the foreground, a smiling person in casual, colorful clothing holds a large sign that reads, ''Hard to believe anyone can be unhappy today!'' Nearby, a small group of cartoon-style workers wearing construction hats and overalls are humorously trying to ''work on'' making people unhappy. They might be carrying comically oversized tools like giant paintbrushes painting frowns on flowers or holding a blueprint labeled ''Unhappiness Plan''. Around them, happy people are enjoying the sunny weather: kids playing, birds singing, and flowers blooming. The overall feel is lighthearted and ironic, capturing the joke''s clever twist with exaggerated, playful expressions and a cartoon vibe, avoiding any negativity or harm.'),
 (1132, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Once, I thought I made a mistake. But I was wrong.', NULL, 'Draw a simple, colorful cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a large whiteboard or chalkboard. The person looks confused but then suddenly realizes something, with a light bulb glowing above their head. On the board is written the phrase ''I made a mistake'' with a big red X over it, and underneath it the corrected phrase ''But I was wrong.'' The person''s expression changes from worried to amused, shrugging with a smile. The background should be minimal, indoors, with perhaps a desk and a small plant nearby. The overall tone is light and humorous, emphasizing the play on words and the unexpected twist.'),
 (1133, 'Humor, Word Play', 'One good turn gets all the blankets.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people in bed at night. One person is happily wrapped up snugly in multiple blankets while the other looks chilly and annoyed, with only a thin sheet barely covering them. The person with all the blankets is smiling slyly, having clearly pulled the blankets over for themselves with a cheeky grin. The bed is drawn simply with a headboard and pillows. In the background, a window shows a starry night sky to emphasize bedtime. Use exaggerated expressions and warm colors for the person hogging blankets, and cool colors or shivers to emphasize the other person''s discomfort. The overall tone is light and silly, capturing the classic blanket-stealing scenario in a friendly, cartoonish style.'),
 (1134, 'Humor, Word Play', 'One picture is worth a thousand words. See diagram below.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a simple framed picture hung on a wall labeled ''Diagram.'' The framed picture is minimalist, like a child’s drawing or a stick figure scene, with a few squiggly lines and simple shapes suggesting a basic message. Below the picture, a small caption reads: ''One picture is worth a thousand words.'' In the foreground, a confused cartoon character with exaggerated raised eyebrows and a puzzled look stands holding a speech bubble filled with tiny words and letters overflowing around them, emphasizing the idea of many words. The overall style is light-hearted and whimsical with bright colors, clean lines, and playful expressions, suitable for a family-friendly comic panel.'),
 (1135, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Pedestrian: A person who walks when you are walking.', NULL, 'A colorful humorous cartoon scene showing two characters walking side by side on a sidewalk in a city setting. One character looks slightly annoyed and is walking with an exaggerated slouch and arms swinging, dressed in casual clothes. The other character is walking right beside them, cheerfully matching their pace, smiling and unaware of the annoyance. The sidewalk is clearly visible with a few street signs, a tree, and a bench in the background. A small caption above them reads: ''Pedestrian: A person who walks when you are walking.'' The style is lighthearted and playful, with simple bright colors and rounded shapes to emphasize the humor without any harsh lines or details.'),
 (1136, 'Humor, Word Play', 'People say I''m condescending. (That means I talk down to people)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing on a small step ladder or a box, looking down at a group of people below with a smug or confident expression. The person is speaking, with a speech bubble that says, ''People say I''m condescending. (That means I talk down to people)''. The group below looks up with mixed expressions of confusion and mild annoyance. The setting is simple, like a minimalistic indoor room or a park. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated with vibrant colors and expressive faces to highlight the joke’s sarcastic tone.'),
 (1137, 'Humor, Word Play', 'PETROPHOBIC (pet ro fob'' ik) adj. One who is embarrassed to undress in front of a household pet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a shy person standing partially undressed in a cozy living room. The person is blushing and nervously clutching a robe or towel tightly around themselves as they look down modestly. Nearby, a household pet—a curious dog or cat—is staring directly at the person with an innocent but attentive expression. The room includes typical home elements like a couch, a small table with a lamp, and a framed picture on the wall. The pet’s eyes are wide and focused, adding to the humor of the situation. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing exaggerated facial expressions for both the person (embarrassed) and the pet (curious). The setting conveys the awkward yet funny moment someone feels embarrassed undressing around their pet, captured with playful colors and simple, clear lines.'),
 (1138, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Poise: The act of raising the eyebrows instead of the roof.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a stylish person standing confidently with perfectly arched eyebrows raised high. Instead of raising the roof of a house behind them, the roof appears perfectly flat and unchanged, contrasting with their exaggerated eyebrow lift. The person''s facial expression is elegant and composed, highlighting the concept of ''poise.'' Around them, subtle comic elements like a confused neighbor looking up at the unchanged roof add humor. The background should be simple, with a cartoon-style house and clear sky, emphasizing the contrast between the raised eyebrows and the unlifted roof.'),
 (1139, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Smile, it''s the second best thing you can do with your lips.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person smiling widely in the foreground, showing shiny, prominent lips. Next to them, a large, colorful speech bubble says: ''Smile, it''s the second best thing you can do with your lips.'' Nearby, a pair of lips cartoonishly puckered up as if about to give a kiss, winking playfully. The background is simple and bright with a lighthearted, friendly atmosphere, using soft pastel colors. The characters are drawn with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize humor, and the style is clean, fun, and inviting without any complex backgrounds or distractions.'),
 (1140, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Someone stole my Scrabble game - I''m at a loss for words', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cheerful living room. In the center, show a person standing with a confused and frustrated expression, holding an empty Scrabble game box with nothing inside. Scattered around the floor are a few random Scrabble tiles, emphasizing that the game pieces are missing. Above the person’s head, include a visible thought bubble with quirky, jumbled letters floating inside, symbolizing ‘at a loss for words.’ Nearby, a suspicious cat or sneaky-looking cartoon thief with a bag labeled ''Scrabble tiles'' peeks around the corner to add a playful element. The background includes a cozy couch, bookshelf, and a small table with a Scrabble board visibly absent, highlighting the missing game. Use bright, vibrant colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor and light-heartedness of the situation.'),
 (1141, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Sometimes too much drink is not enough.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a lively bar. In the center, a cheerful, slightly disheveled character holds an overflowing glass of a colorful drink with bubbles and garnish. Around them, several empty glasses and bottles are scattered on the table, implying they''ve already had many drinks. The character looks both amused and frustrated, scratching their head with one hand while holding the drink with the other, as if saying, ''I still need more!'' The background shows fellow patrons enjoying themselves, some laughing, some watching the character with raised eyebrows. The bar has typical details: stools, a bartender wiping a glass, shelves lined with bottles, and funny small signs like ''Drink Responsibly'' with a wink emoji. The style is bright, cartoonish, and exaggerated to emphasize the humorous struggle of wanting more despite already having too much.'),
 (1142, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Suggestions Welcome:  They''re good for a lot of laughs', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room. In the center, a cheerful, somewhat quirky-looking character sits on a comfy armchair with a notebook or suggestion box labeled ''Suggestions'' on their lap. Around them are several laughing friends or family members, some pointing at the character while chuckling. On a nearby coffee table, there are a few playful items like funny hats, joke books, and a rubber chicken to hint at humor. The room has bright, colorful walls with framed comic strips or funny posters. The overall mood is lighthearted and fun, emphasizing the idea that suggestions (or the suggestion box) bring lots of laughter. The style is cartoonish with exaggerated, expressive faces and warm colors to enhance the comedic vibe.'),
 (1143, 'Humor, Word Play', 'The direct approach is the best approach.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two characters in a casual conversation outdoors. One character is holding a large, comically oversized arrow pointed straight towards the other character, emphasizing the ''direct approach.'' The other character looks surprised but amused. The background is simple with a few trees and a park bench to set a casual, friendly environment. Both characters wear casual clothes and have exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor. The oversized arrow should look funny and exaggerated, almost like a cartoon prop, reinforcing the idea of being very direct. The style should be light-hearted and colorful to match the joke tone, with clean lines and expressive body language.'),
 (1144, 'Humor, Word Play', 'The guy who coined the term ''coined the term'', coined the term ''coined the term''.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, slightly confused-looking man sitting at an old-fashioned desk cluttered with papers and a large, vintage dictionary opened in front of him. Above his head is a large, glowing light bulb indicating he has just had an idea. On the desk, there is a small plaque or nameplate that reads ''Mr. Wordsmith.'' Around him, in a playful visual effect like comic-style echo bubbles, the phrase ''coined the term'' is repeated multiple times, each bubble shaped like a speech balloon with little quotation marks. The background shows a cozy, book-filled study with a large bookshelf packed with thick books titled with various linguistic or phrase-related labels. The overall style is colorful, cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the man''s pride and slight bewilderment about the phrase he created. No other characters are present, keeping focus entirely on the man and his catchy phrase being ''coined.'''),
 (1145, 'Humor, Word Play', 'They also surf who only stand on waves.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters at the beach. One character is energetically surfing on a big, dynamic ocean wave, confidently standing on a surfboard. The other character is casually standing upright on a smaller, tiny wave near the shore, holding the surfboard loosely or just standing on the water as if surfing, but with a relaxed, almost lazy expression. The waves are exaggerated and playful, with smiling faces on the water for added whimsy. The beach is sunny with a few palm trees in the background and some seagulls flying above. The style is colorful and lighthearted, emphasizing the contrast between the serious surfer and the laid-back ''stand-only'' surfer, highlighting the twist in the joke.'),
 (1146, 'Humor, Word Play', 'To the thief who took my anti-depressants - I hope you''re happy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing next to an open medicine cabinet with an empty bottle labeled ''Anti-Depressants''. The person has a sarcastic, slightly annoyed expression and is shaking their fist upward. In the background, a shadowy, sneaky thief is tiptoeing away, sneaking off with a small sack or bag looking pleased and humming, clearly happy. The setting is a cozy, everyday bathroom with a sink, a mirror reflecting the frustrated owner, and some quirky details like a rubber duck and a towel rack. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the irony of the statement with exaggerated facial expressions and body language in a cartoon style.'),
 (1147, 'Humor, Word Play', 'Two guys are fighting and one draws a line on the ground and says ''if you cross that line I''ll punch you''. <pause and look puzzled> uh, that was the punch line.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two guys standing face-to-face outdoors on a simple dirt or pavement ground with a clearly drawn straight line between them. One guy, with a serious but slightly puzzled expression, is drawing the line on the ground with a stick or finger. The other guy is standing just behind the line looking confused or thoughtful, scratching his head or raising an eyebrow. Above them, there''s a speech bubble from the first guy saying, ''If you cross that line I''ll punch you.'' The second guy then has a speech bubble with a pause or dots ''...uh, that was the punch line.'' The background is simple, emphasizing the focus on the characters, the line on the ground, and their comedic misunderstanding. The style is clean, bright, and cartoony with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke''s wordplay.'),
 (1148, 'Humor, Word Play', 'What''s the least spoken language in the world? Sign language', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side in a simple park-like setting with a few trees and a bench. One character is speaking excitedly with a speech bubble containing question marks, representing the question, ''What''s the least spoken language in the world?'' The other character is responding with a large smile and hands raised mid-sign, clearly using sign language. Above them, a floating thought bubble shows a comical depiction of the word ''SILENCE'' in big letters with little ''sound waves'' fading away to emphasize that sign language isn''t spoken aloud. The characters should be drawn with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke: the first character looks curious and puzzled, while the second is confident and cheerful. The art style should be colorful, simple, and playful, with bold lines, suited for a lighthearted cartoon comic strip. No violent, sexual, or political elements. Background details minimal but enough to suggest a casual everyday environment.'),
 (1149, 'Humor, Word Play', 'What''s the number one rule of vegan fight club? Tell everybody', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of quirky animals and a few humans gathered together in a lighthearted ''fight club'' setting. There is a big banner overhead that reads ''Vegan Fight Club.'' The characters include a friendly cow, a carrot with boxing gloves, a lettuce leaf, a tofu block with a headband, and a few smiling humans in workout clothes. Everyone is standing around chatting and laughing in a bright, cheerful gym or community hall with mats on the floor. In the center, a person with a megaphone is enthusiastically announcing, "Remember: Rule number one – tell everybody!" The overall mood is playful and ironic, capturing the idea that vegan fight club is about outspoken openness instead of secrecy. The style is colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish with expressive faces and body language that emphasize humor and approachability.'),
 (1150, 'Humor, Word Play', 'What''s the tallest building in the world? The library - it has the most stories.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a very tall building shaped like a classic library: large, with big windows and a sign that says ''Library'' at the top. The building has multiple visible floors stacked high, each floor is represented as an open book shelf lined with oversized books labeled as ''Story 1'', ''Story 2'', etc. Sitting on top of the building is a cheerful librarian character holding an oversized book and waving. The sky is bright and clear with a few light, fluffy clouds. Nearby, a few small, modern skyscrapers look up in amazement, looking tiny compared to the towering library. Include a playful banner or caption at the bottom that says, ''The tallest building – it has the most stories!'' The overall tone should be lighthearted and whimsical, in a bright cartoon style with exaggerated proportions and expressive characters.'),
 (1151, 'Humor, Word Play', 'When I''m around Hispanics, I say ''Mucho'' all the time - it means a lot to them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a smiling person standing in the center, casually chatting with a diverse group of friendly Hispanic people around them. The person is cheerfully saying the word ''Mucho'', with comic-style speech bubbles showing this word repeatedly. The Hispanic group looks amused and pleased, with warm, friendly expressions. The background is simple and colorful, perhaps with festive decorations like colorful papel picado banners to subtly hint at a Hispanic cultural setting. Include subtle visual cues such as a taco stand or maracas nearby to set the tone without stereotypes. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with clear, bold lines and bright colors to emphasize the fun and wordplay of the joke, avoiding any caricature or offense.'),
 (1152, 'Humor, Word Play, Workplace', 'To steal ideas from one person is plagiarism, to steal from many is research.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a quirky, cluttered office or study room filled with books, papers, and quirky inventions. In the center, a character is comically holding a giant, overflowing net labeled ''Idea Catcher,'' capturing floating light bulbs (representing ideas) from several other characters around him who look surprised or annoyed. Each of these characters is standing by desks or chairs cluttered with papers and notebooks, some labeled ''Original Idea.'' The main character wears glasses and a mischievous grin, confidently sorting ideas into a big folder labeled ''Research.'' The background includes whimsical details like inspirational posters, a coffee mug, and a chalkboard with crossed-out copyrights and scribbled notes. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and playful to highlight the witty contrast between plagiarism and research without any negativity.'),
 (1153, 'Humor, Word Play, Workplace', 'We do precision guesswork.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in an office setting featuring a group of professionals in lab coats and glasses standing around a large conference table covered with blueprints, rulers, calculators, and computers. They have confused, uncertain facial expressions as they try to measure something, but comically, their measuring tools are all wildly inaccurate or absurd (e.g., a ruler bent like a snake, a calculator displaying random symbols, a giant protractor mismatched to the drawing). One person is scratching their head, another is shrugging, and a third is marking a blueprint with a big question mark. In the background, a whiteboard says in large letters: ''PRECISION GUESSWORK'' with a wavy underline, emphasizing the ironic nature of the phrase. The overall tone is light and fun, with exaggerated expressions reflecting the contradiction between ''precision'' and ''guesswork.'' The style is simple, colorful, and playful, evoking classic cartoon humor without any harsh or negative elements.'),
 (1154, 'Humor, Workplace', 'Look deeeeep into the monitor..... you''re getting sleeeeeeeeepy.  As usual.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a tired person sitting at a desk staring at a computer monitor. The monitor screen should have exaggerated, hypnotic swirling spirals or concentric circles glowing softly in blue and purple hues. The person has droopy eyelids starting to close, a slight yawn, and a sleepy expression. Around the desk are typical office items like a coffee mug labeled ''Need Coffee,'' scattered papers, and a desk lamp dimly lit. The room looks dim to emphasize late-night fatigue. The caption near the monitor reads in a wavy font: ''Look deeeeep into the monitor..... you''re getting sleeeeeeeeepy. As usual.'' The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated sleepy features and whimsical colors to enhance the humor of feeling tired from screen time without any threat or negativity.'),
 (1155, 'Humor, Workplace', 'Please solve your problems in advance so I can help you quicker.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in an office or help desk setting. A friendly-looking person, drawn in a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon style, sits behind a desk with a computer and a phone. They wear a name tag and have a slightly amused expression. In front of them stands a frustrated or confused person holding a long scroll or list labeled ''Problems.'' The key visual joke: the person behind the desk is holding a calendar or planner opened to a page marked ''Solve problems in advance,'' with a big smile, as if implying the caller should have already solved their issues before asking for help. Around them are humorous details like a clock showing busy hours, sticky notes with reminders, and colorful problem-themed icons (light bulbs, question marks) floating above. The overall tone is light, whimsical, and clearly shows impatience mixed with good humor, emphasizing the absurdity of expecting problems to be solved before they even arise, in a clever cartoon style.'),
 (1156, 'Humor, Workplace', 'Preudhomme''s Law of Window Cleaning: It''s on the other side.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person cleaning a large window from the inside of a house. The person is holding a squeegee and has a puzzled, slightly frustrated expression. Outside the window, another person is standing on the opposite side of the glass, also holding a squeegee, equally puzzled. The window spans the center of the image, showing clear reflections, emphasizing that both are trying to clean the same window but each from their respective side. The background inside the house shows a simple cozy room with a potted plant and a small table, while outside there is a bright sunny day with a tree and some clouds. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the confusion and humor of the situation where the dirt or streaks are always ''on the other side.'' Avoid any violent or political imagery, keeping it friendly and family-appropriate.'),
 (1803, 'Individuality, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'I don''t like to do what people expect. Why should I live up to other people''s expectations instead of my own?', 'Julia Stiles', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a confident person standing at a forked path signposted ''Other People''s Expectations'' pointing to one side and ''My Own Expectations'' pointing to the other. The character is cheerfully striding confidently towards the ''My Own Expectations'' direction, with a carefree smile and a relaxed posture. The setting is bright and simple with a clear sky, a few fluffy clouds, and some greenery around. Around the character’s feet are small symbols representing typical expectations (like a briefcase, a clock, and a checklist) being left behind. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the subject''s confident and independent attitude. No other characters are present, focusing on this individual’s choice to follow their own path rather than conforming.'),
 (2085, 'Inspirational, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Many people die with their music still in them. Why is this so? Too often it is because they are always getting ready to live. Before they know it, time runs out.', 'Oliver Wendell, Jr. Holmes', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a person sitting on a bench in a sunny park, holding an unopened music box or a sealed vinyl record titled ''My Music.'' Around them, musical notes float in the air, but the person''s eyes look distracted, focused on a checklist or calendar labeled ''Plans'' and ''To-Do.'' In the background, a large whimsical clock shows time passing quickly, with its hands spinning fast. Nearby, a ghostly silhouette or shadow of the same person is joyfully dancing with a boombox playing music, representing the ''life'' they never quite started. The setting is bright, colorful, and peaceful, emphasizing the theme of unfulfilled potential with a gentle, humorous touch, no violence or negativity.'),
 (1614, 'Inspirational, Life, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Dance as though no one is watching you, love as though you''ve never been hurt before, sing as though no one can hear you, live as though heaven is on earth.', 'Souza', 'A cheerful, bright, cartoon-style scene featuring a joyful person in the center, depicted as mid-dance with exaggerated happy movements and a carefree expression. Around them are several subtle transparent outlines of imaginary onlookers with puzzled or amused faces, implying the person is dancing like no one is watching. Nearby, a heart hovering above their head glows warmly to symbolize loving without fear. Off to one side, a whimsical bird is shown singing loudly with musical notes floating around, unaware of anyone hearing it. The background is an idyllic, colorful park or garden setting with smiling flowers and a radiant sun shining, evoking the feeling of heaven on earth. Overall, the style is lighthearted and inspiring, with each aspect illustrating the lines from the joke in a playful, exaggerated cartoon format without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (2320, 'Inspirational, Motivational Humor, Quotes', 'The greatest pleasure in life is doing what people say you cannot do.', 'Walter Bagehot', 'A cheerful cartoon character stands triumphantly on top of a small hill or podium with arms raised in victory. Around them, various other characters look surprised or doubtful, some shaking their heads or crossing their arms, representing people who said it couldn''t be done. The victorious character is smiling confidently, with a subtle sparkle or glow to emphasize their pleasure. Background is simple and bright, with a clear blue sky and a few fluffy clouds. Include subtle speech bubbles from the doubters with phrases like ''You can''t do that!'' and one from the winner saying ''Watch me!'' The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and humorously celebratory.'),
 (1982, 'Inspirational, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It is not on the stars to hold our destiny but in ourselves.', 'Shakespeare', 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently on an open field under a starry night sky. The stars are bright and numerous, scattered across the sky, looking down at the person. The person is depicted with a cheerful smile and a determined stance, with one fist on their hip and the other hand pointing at themselves, symbolizing self-empowerment. Large, glowing stars float in the sky, but a subtle path or ribbon coming from the stars leads nowhere, while another glowing path emanates from the person’s chest, symbolizing destiny originating inside. The background is simple to keep focus on the person and stars, with soft grassy hills underfoot. The overall tone is uplifting and humorous, emphasizing the idea that destiny is self-determined rather than written in the stars. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, using bright but calming colors to evoke hope and self-reliance without any sense of conflict or negativity.'),
 (2386, 'Inspirational, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The stories of past courage...can teach, they can offer hope, they can provide inspiration. But they cannot supply courage itself. For this each man must look into his own soul.', 'JFK, Profiles in Courage, 1956.', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a medieval knight standing in front of a large, ornate mirror. The knight is wearing classic shining armor but with a slightly puzzled expression, leaning forward to peer deeply into his reflection. Behind him, framed pictures hang on a stone castle wall, each depicting famous heroic figures from history or legend (like a lion-hearted king, a dragon-slayer, and a fearless explorer). The knight’s reflection looks confident and brave, but the knight himself appears uncertain as if searching for courage within. Include a glowing or shimmering effect around the mirror, giving it a magical or inspirational aura. The setting is warm and inviting, with a light-hearted tone achieved through exaggerated facial expressions and soft colors. On a nearby wooden stand, an open book titled ''Stories of Past Courage'' rests, reinforcing the message. Overall, the scene humorously illustrates the idea that while stories inspire, true courage must come from within oneself.'),
 (1511, 'Inspirational, Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'All meaningful change starts in the imagination and works its way out. Therefore, dream often and dream big.', 'Dan Zadra', 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring a person sitting cross-legged on the ground with their eyes closed, smiling peacefully as they imagine a glowing, colorful thought bubble above their head. Inside the thought bubble are various whimsical and inspiring images: a lightbulb, a sprouting plant, a soaring rocket, and a rainbow. The background is bright with soft clouds and rays of sunshine emphasizing creativity and optimism. Around the person, small, floating stars and sparkles suggest imagination and magic. The style is playful and uplifting, with rounded, friendly shapes and vibrant colors, illustrating the idea of dreams starting in the mind and spreading outward into the world.'),
 (2282, 'Inspirational, Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'The best and most beautiful things in the world cannot be seen or even touched. They must be felt with the heart.', 'Helen Keller', 'A colorful, warm cartoon scene featuring a smiling person sitting peacefully on a grassy hill under a bright blue sky with fluffy white clouds. The person’s eyes are closed and they have a gentle, content smile, holding their hands over their chest where a large, radiant glowing heart symbol floats above their hands. Around the person, floating sparkles or soft light swell to visually represent feelings and emotions. In the background, subtle silhouettes of beautiful things like flowers, stars, and a distant rainbow hint at beauty that is not the main focus, emphasizing the idea that true beauty is felt, not seen or touched. The whole image is cheerful, uplifting, and simple, using soft pastel colors and rounded shapes to create a heartfelt cartoon mood.'),
 (2617, 'Inspirational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'You must be the change you wish to see in the world.', 'Mahatma Gandhi', 'A cartoon scene showing a smiling person standing happily in front of a globe, holding a watering can and watering a small plant growing out of the globe. The person wears casual clothes and has a friendly, hopeful expression. The background has a bright blue sky with a few fluffy clouds, and the globe sits on a simple wooden podium labeled ''The World.'' Around the person, small illustrated symbols of positive change float in the air—like hearts, peace signs, and lightbulbs. The overall tone is cheerful and inspiring, with vibrant colors and playful, exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize optimism and personal responsibility for making a difference.'),
 (2265, 'Inspirational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'Technology is a gift of God. After the gift of life it is perhaps the greatest of God''s gifts. It is the mother of civilizations, of arts and of sciences.', 'Freeman Dyson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person standing proudly on a small hill, holding a glowing smartphone like a prized gift. Behind them is a radiant beam of light shining down from fluffy clouds shaped vaguely like hands, symbolizing a divine gift. Around the hill are playful symbols representing civilizations, arts, and sciences: a tiny ancient pyramid, a paintbrush with splashes of color, and a beaker bubbling with colorful liquid. The person is smiling broadly, wearing casual modern clothes, and the atmosphere is bright and optimistic. The style is colorful and lighthearted, with simple lines and exaggerated, joyful expressions to emphasize the humorous reverence for technology as a ''gift of God.'' The background is a clear blue sky with a few birds, enhancing the uplifting feeling of the scene.'),
 (2544, 'Inspirational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'What lies behind us and what lies before us are small matters compared to what lies within us.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson', 'A colorful, lighthearted cartoon scene set in a peaceful park. In the foreground, a smiling person stands with their chest open wide like a treasure chest, revealing a glowing light or a small, charming scene inside their chest symbolizing ''what lies within us.'' Behind the person is a short, winding path leading into a distant horizon with a bright sunrise, representing ''what lies before us.'' Behind the path are hills and a slightly cloudy sky. On the ground nearby, a small signpost or plaque has the words ''Behind Us'' pointing backward and ''Before Us'' pointing forward. The overall atmosphere is warm and inspiring, with soft greens, blues, and yellows, and the style is whimsical and cartoonish, emphasizing the positive message rather than literal interpretation.'),
 (2308, 'Inspirational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'The future belongs to those who believe in the beauty of their dreams.', 'Eleanor Roosevelt', 'A bright, whimsical cartoon scene featuring a cheerful young person standing on a small hill at sunrise. The person is gazing dreamily at a vibrant, colorful sky filled with stars and soft glowing clouds shaped like various dreams—such as a flying book, a musical note, and a shining trophy. Around the hill, small flowers and butterflies add a hopeful, uplifting atmosphere. The background has gentle rolling hills and a rising sun casting warm golden light. The cartoon style should be light-hearted and inspirational, with exaggerated expressions of wonder and hope on the person''s face. The overall feel is optimistic and imaginative, emphasizing the theme of believing in one''s dreams and a promising future. No text is needed in the image, just the visual metaphor of dreams and future.'),
 (2453, 'Inspirational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Think of all the beauty still left around you and be happy.', 'Anne Frank, Diary of a Young Girl', 'Draw a cheerful cartoon scene in a bright, sunny park filled with colorful flowers, butterflies, chirping birds, and smiling trees with faces. In the center, a relaxed person sits on a bench, eyes closed, smiling contentedly while soaking in the beautiful surroundings. Nearby, a small dog wags its tail happily, and a rainbow arches gently in the sky. The overall vibe is peaceful, uplifting, and whimsical, emphasizing the idea of appreciating nature''s beauty and feeling happiness from it. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with vibrant colors and expressive characters to enhance the positive mood.'),
 (2517, 'Inspirational, Positive Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'We don''t know who we are until we see what we can do.', 'Martha Grimes', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a person standing in front of a mirror with a surprised and curious expression. The person is wearing casual clothing and striking a pose as if testing their ability—maybe balancing on one foot or trying to juggle. Around them, small playful visual elements like stars, question marks, and sparkles emphasize self-discovery and amazement. In the reflection, the mirror subtly shows the same person performing a small, quirky feat (like juggling or bending into a funny shape) to symbolize seeing ''what we can do.'' The background is simple, indoors with soft colors, and maybe a motivational poster on the wall that reads, "Discover Yourself!" The style is lighthearted and cartoony with exaggerated facial expressions to capture the theme of self-realization and fun exploration of potential, avoiding anything serious or dramatic.'),
 (2475, 'Inspirational, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'To laugh often and much; to win the respect of intelligent people and the affection of children... This is to have succeeded.', 'Emerson', 'A cheerful, cartoon-style scene featuring a smiling adult figure standing proudly at the center, holding a trophy labeled ''Success'' with one hand. Surrounding the adult are two distinct groups: on one side, a diverse group of children giggling and hugging the adult, showing affection and joy; on the other side, a few adults with glasses and thoughtful expressions nodding in respect and applauding. The background is bright with balloons and confetti to convey celebration. The style is light-hearted and colorful with exaggerated, friendly facial expressions to emphasize warmth, respect, and happiness. Include a banner or sign above saying ''True Success'' to highlight the theme. The overall mood is uplifting and humorous in a gentle way, capturing the essence of achieving meaningful success through laughter, respect, and affection.'),
 (2528, 'Inspirational, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'We must be willing to get rid of the life we''ve planned, so as to have the life that is waiting for us.', 'J. Campbell', 'A cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing at a literal crossroads shaped like a large life plan chart with boxes and arrows labeled ''The Life We''ve Planned.'' The person is holding a giant eraser and smiling as they erase part of the chart titled ''Plans.'' Nearby, a bright and colorful path labeled ''The Life Waiting for Us'' stretches forward with happy symbols like a sun, flowers, and birds. The background is light and uplifting with a few fluffy clouds and a rainbow hinting at optimism. The character wears casual, everyday clothes and has a hopeful expression. The overall style is simple and humorous, with bold lines and vibrant colors, emphasizing the metaphor of letting go of rigid plans to embrace unexpected positive opportunities.'),
 (3212, 'Inspirational, Steven Wright, Weather Humor', 'If you want the rainbow, you got to put up with the rain.', 'Steven Wright', 'A cheerful cartoon scene showing a person standing outside holding a colorful umbrella, with raindrops falling around them. Above, a bright, vibrant rainbow arcs across the sky peeking through the clouds. The person looks content, smiling and looking up at the rainbow despite the rain. In the background, there are simple cartoon-style grassy hills and trees with drops of rain falling from the clouds. The overall mood is positive and lighthearted, capturing the idea that enduring rain leads to the reward of a rainbow. The style is playful and bright, with exaggerated expressions and simple bold outlines for a humorous cartoon effect.'),
 (1206, 'Insults, Irony, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'You are impossible to underestimate.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a casual setting, such as a living room or coffee shop. One character, with an exaggerated puzzled expression, is looking at the other with raised eyebrows. The second character stands confidently with arms crossed and a sly grin. Above them, a speech bubble from the first character says, ''You are impossible to underestimate.'' The scene should emphasize the playful sarcasm in the phrase, perhaps by showing subtle visual irony—like a small trophy labeled ''Most Underestimated'' on a nearby table, or a thought bubble from the second character picturing themselves as a giant or superhero but clearly humbled by the comment. The style should be lighthearted and cartoony, with rounded edges, bright colors, and expressive faces to enhance the wit of the statement. Avoid any elements of aggression or negativity; the focus is on the clever twist of the phrase itself.'),
 (1168, 'Insults, Irony, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'I don''t have an attitude problem. You have a perception problem.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing confidently with crossed arms and a slight smirk on their face, clearly exuding attitude. The setting is simple, like a plain office or home living room. Opposite them, another character looks mildly frustrated or confused, holding a pair of glasses at the bridge of their nose as if scrutinizing carefully. Above the confident person is a bold speech bubble that reads, ''I don''t have an attitude problem.'' The frustrated character has a speech bubble that says, ''You have a perception problem.'' Both characters are drawn in a friendly cartoon style with exaggerated facial expressions: one self-assured, the other bewildered. The background is minimal to keep focus on their interaction. The overall style is colorful and playful, capturing the comedic misunderstanding between attitude and perception in a lighthearted way.'),
 (1173, 'Insults, Literary Humor, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'I wish we could become better strangers (from Shakespeare ''As You Like It'')', 'Shakespeare', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two people standing awkwardly on opposite sides of a street or park path. Both characters look uncomfortable and avoid eye contact, with exaggerated body language showing closed-off poses like crossed arms and looking away. Between them, a comically large speech bubble contains the text: "I wish we could become better strangers." Around them, subtle Shakespearean elements are included, such as a flowing parchment scroll with the words ''As You Like It'' at the top corner or a small, whimsical Shakespearean hat hanging on a nearby lamppost. The style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and simple, expressive facial features to emphasize the ironic humor of wanting to get to know someone even less. The overall mood is ironic and clever, capturing the paradoxical idea of improving a relationship by being more disconnected.'),
 (1165, 'Insults, Math Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'As far as the laws of mathematics refer to reality, they are not certain; and as far as they are certain, they do not refer to reality.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a classroom or study room where a quirky professor or mathematician stands at a blackboard full of complex math formulas and diagrams. The professor has a puzzled yet amused expression, scratching their head with one finger while holding a piece of chalk in the other hand. Next to the chalkboard is a transparent glass globe or a realistic miniature Earth model that looks slightly distorted or cartoonishly skewed to represent ''reality.'' Around the room, scattered books titled ''Math Theories,'' ''Reality,'' and ''Philosophy'' lie open. The blackboard shows a funny illustration where math symbols float above the Earth''s head but do not quite touch it, visually implying a disconnect between math and reality. The style should be light, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the irony and humor in the quote. No violence, political or sensitive content.'),
 (1166, 'Insults, Relatable Humor, Religion Humor, School', 'As long as there are tests, there will be prayer in public schools', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a lively public school classroom. At the front, a teacher stands by a blackboard with a large, challenging test titled ''Big Test Day!'' written prominently. The teacher looks slightly stressed but hopeful. Around the teacher, several students sit at desks with exaggerated worried expressions, some nervously glancing at their papers. Hovering above the classroom, a whimsical angel or cartoonish praying hands are depicted, symbolizing prayer in the school setting—make it lighthearted and symbolic rather than religiously doctrinal. Perhaps include small doodles around the angel like a halo, cartoon stars, or a thought bubble showing a student silently praying. The overall tone should be playful and convey the idea that students rely on prayer or hope when facing difficult tests, without implying any endorsement or critique of religion. Keep the style colorful, cheerful, and clearly cartoonish.'),
 (1169, 'Insults, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'I don''t know what your problem is, but I am sure it is hard to announce.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters having a conversation. One character is speaking with a puzzled or slightly amused expression, holding a megaphone awkwardly pointed away from their mouth as if unsure how to ''announce'' something difficult. The other character looks confused or concerned, listening intently. The setting is simple, such as a park bench or a casual indoor space, with no background distractions. Include a speech bubble coming from the speaking character with the text: "I don''t know what your problem is, but I am sure it is hard to announce." The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the irony of having a ''problem'' that must be announced out loud, portrayed through exaggerated facial expressions and posture.'),
 (1170, 'Insults, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'I envy people who haven''t met you.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side in a simple outdoor setting like a park. One character looks cheerful and friendly, while the other character looks awkward, uncomfortable, or slightly annoyed. The cheerful character is smiling widely and speaking the line, "I envy people who haven''t met you." The background includes trees, a park bench, and soft clouds to keep the scene light and casual. The style should be bright and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the awkwardness and humor. Both characters should have simple, cartoonish features, with the focus on their contrasting reactions to the humorous insult wrapped in a compliment.'),
 (1179, 'Insults, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'I''ve just learned about his illness. Let''s hope it''s nothing trivial.', 'Irvin S. Cobb', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing next to each other in a cozy living room. One character, looking worried, is holding a piece of paper labeled ''Medical Report'' with a big red stamp that says ''TRIVIAL?'' On the paper. The other character is leaning in curiously, eyes wide with anticipation. Both have exaggerated facial expressions — the worried character frowning slightly with raised eyebrows, and the curious character looking hopeful and attentive. The background includes a comfy armchair, a small side table with a cup of tea, and a calendar on the wall showing a random date. The overall tone is light and funny, capturing the irony of hoping that an illness is ''nothing trivial,'' as the word itself suggests it might be unimportant or minor. The style is cartoonish with bright colors and rounded shapes emphasizing the characters'' emotions and the humor of the statement.'),
 (1171, 'Insults, Science Fiction Humor, Television, Word Play', 'I take it you weren''t burdened with an overabundance of schooling (Firefly)', 'Mal Reynolds, Firefly', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in the futuristic sci-fi spaceship interior from the show Firefly. In the center, a casually dressed character with a sly, playful expression is speaking to another character who looks slightly confused or taken aback. The speaker has an exaggeratedly large book labeled ''Schooling'' strapped awkwardly to their back, as if it were a heavy burden or backpack. The listener stands with a light shrug and a puzzled look, clearly implying they didn’t carry such a weight. The background shows typical spaceship elements: metal walls, control panels with blinking lights, and a small window looking out into space. The style should be playful, with cartoonish exaggeration of expressions and props to emphasize the joke about not having too much schooling as a burden. Bright, clear colors and bubbly speech bubbles complete the humorous tone.'),
 (1244, 'Internet Humor, Knock Knock, Pun, Word Play', 'KK/WT: Echo ? Bless you', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two speech bubbles to represent a conversation. The first bubble shows ''KK/WT'' as if someone is typing or texting these letters. The second bubble replies with ''Echo ? Bless you,'' playing on the idea that ''KK'' sounds like a sneeze trigger or similar to an echo of a sneeze. The background is simple and uncluttered, maybe a minimalistic chat interface on a smartphone or computer screen. Around the speech bubbles, small cartoon-style sound wave lines illustrate the echo effect. Include a tiny cartoon character in the corner with a confused but amused expression, scratching their head. The overall tone is light and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s wordplay on ''echo'' and ''bless you.'' No other people or complex backgrounds are needed to keep focus on the chat bubbles and the pun.'),
 (3024, 'Invention Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I recently invented a thought-controlled air freshener. I know - it sounds strange, but it make scents when you think about it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky inventor in a cluttered, colorful workshop filled with gadgets and tools. The inventor, a cheerful character with wild hair and glasses, is holding a small, sleek air freshener device with a glowing blue light. Around the air freshener, little cartoon thought bubbles of flowers, fresh lemons, and pine trees float, indicating different scents. The inventor is pointing to the device with a proud smile. A comic-style banner above reads, ''Thought-Controlled Air Freshener!'' The background includes shelves with typical inventor paraphernalia like gears, light bulbs, and blueprints. The mood is playful and whimsical, capturing the pun about the freshener that “makes scents when you think about it.” No violence or political elements, clear focus on the silly invention and its concept in a bright, exaggerated cartoon style.'),
 (1878, 'Inventors, Irony, Quotes, Science Humor', 'If I had thought about it, I wouldn''t have done the experiment. The literature was full of examples that said you can''t do this. (on the work that led to the unique adhesives for 3M Post-Its)', 'Spencer Silver', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple laboratory. In the center, a quirky scientist with slightly messy hair and round glasses looks surprised but proud, holding a brightly colored sticky note in one hand. On the desk in front of the scientist are various lab equipment like beakers, test tubes, and papers scattered with scribbles and diagrams of sticky notes. Behind the scientist, a chalkboard or wall chart displays several large printed pages titled ''Literature'' with big red X marks over images illustrating ''You can''t do this.'' The sticky notes on the desk and wall should be prominent and colorful, clearly tied to the idea of the Post-It note invention. The overall style should be bright, cartoonish, and whimsical, emphasizing the humor in ignoring warnings and accidentally inventing something famous and useful. The scientist''s expression combines slight regret and amazement, capturing the ironic tone of the joke.'),
 (2287, 'Inventors, Motivational, Quotes, Science Humor', 'The best way to predict the future is to invent it.', 'Alan Kay', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky inventor in a cluttered workshop filled with whimsical inventions and gadgets. The inventor, wearing oversized goggles and a lab coat with patchwork, is excitedly holding a glowing lightbulb labeled ''Future Idea.'' Around him, futuristic objects like a small flying robot, a console with blinking buttons, and a blueprint titled ''Tomorrow'' are scattered. In the background, a chalkboard displays the phrase ''Best way to predict the future... invent it!'' with quirky doodles of clocks, robots, and rockets. The room has a playful, cartoonish style with bright colors and exaggerated features to enhance the cheerful, inventive atmosphere, emphasizing creativity and forward-thinking with a lighthearted vibe.'),
 (2689, 'Irony, Kids Humor, Parenting, Unknown', 'Buy a kid an unbreakable toy, and he will use it to break other toys.', NULL, 'Draw a colorful and humorous cartoon scene of a young child standing proudly in the middle of a playroom. The child is holding a bright, shiny, indestructible toy shaped like a hammer or bat. Around the child, several other toys lie broken or damaged—such as a teddy bear with a loose arm, a toy car with missing wheels, and a building block tower partially collapsed. The child has a mischievous but innocent smile, showing they''re unaware of the chaos around them. The playroom should be cozy, with a rug, a few shelves of toys, maybe a window with sunlight coming in, emphasizing a happy yet funny atmosphere. The broken toys should look clearly damaged but in a lighthearted, cartoonish way without any sadness or violence implied. The overall vibe is playful and ironic, capturing the paradox of giving a tough toy that ends up used as a tool for breaking other toys.'),
 (2744, 'Irony, Legal Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Criminal Lawyer is a redundancy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a courtroom with a judge sitting behind a bench, looking amused. In the foreground, a slick-looking lawyer wearing a suit and tie stands confidently next to a defendant who looks nervous in handcuffs. The lawyer is holding a briefcase labeled ''Criminal Lawyer'' with a big, exaggerated label. A thought bubble above the judge’s head shows a cheeky idea: a second briefcase labeled ''Criminal Lawyer'' bursting with rogue criminals trying to break free, emphasizing the joke that ''criminal lawyer'' itself is redundant. The courtroom has typical features like an American flag, a courtroom clock, pillars, and a witness stand. The style should be light and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the irony and humor of the phrase being a redundancy, implying that lawyers and criminals are closely linked.'),
 (1794, 'Irony, Life, Optimism Humor, Quotes', 'I don''t believe in pessimism. If something doesn''t come up the way you want, forge ahead. If you think it''s going to rain, it will.', 'Clint Eastwood', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person confidently walking forward on a path labeled ''Life Journey.'' The sky above shows two halves: one side sunny and bright, the other dark with heavy rain clouds. The person wears casual clothes and carries a small umbrella closed in one hand, clearly unused. Behind them, there is a signpost with arrows; one says ''Pessimism'' pointing toward stormy clouds, the other says ''Forge Ahead'' pointing toward the sunny side. The figure has a determined smile, showing optimism despite the looming rain clouds overhead. In the background, subtle rain is falling on the ''Pessimism'' side while the ''Forge Ahead'' side remains dry and welcoming. The style is colorful, light-hearted, and cartoon-like with exaggerated expressions to emphasize determination and humor without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (1212, 'Irony, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'The less you risk, the more you lose when you win.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a character standing at the edge of a gambling table or game board with a very cautious, nervous expression. The character is holding a small stack of chips or tokens close to their chest, hesitating to place a bet. On the opposite side of the table, a confident, playful dealer or another character is smiling knowingly, gesturing toward a big pile of chips or prizes labeled ''WIN''. Include thought bubbles above the cautious character showing images of ''risk'' as a cliff or a dice roll, and ''reward'' as a big treasure chest or jackpot. The setting should be bright and colorful with exaggerated features to emphasize the mental tension between risk and reward, but the style is light-hearted and cartoonish, without any gambling encouragement or negativity. There should be a clear contrast between the small risk taken and the large potential prize, visually reinforcing the joke’s message: the less you risk, the more you lose when you win.'),
 (1213, 'Irony, Life, Philosophy Humor', 'To win you sometimes have to concede.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene with two cartoon-styled characters sitting at a negotiation table. One character looks serious and determined, confidently pointing at a contract or chessboard labeled ''Victory.'' The other character is smiling slyly, holding a white flag or a small flag that reads ''I concede.'' Both characters are in a simple office or game room with a playful atmosphere, bright colors, and exaggerated expressions. The background should be minimal to keep the focus on the interaction and the concept of conceding as a form of winning. The overall tone is lighthearted and clever, emphasizing the irony of winning by giving up.'),
 (2415, 'Irony, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'There are only two tragedies in life: one is not getting what one wants, and the other is getting it.', 'Oscar Wilde (1854-1900)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side, each representing one of the ''tragedies.'' On the left, a character looks sad and disappointed, standing with slumped shoulders in front of a display window showing an object they desire but cannot have (like a shiny new gadget or a delicious cake just out of reach). On the right, another character looks equally unhappy, holding that same coveted item awkwardly or with dismay, unsure whether to smile or frown. Both characters exaggerate their emotions in a playful, exaggerated cartoon style. The background is simple, with a sign overhead that says ''Life''s Tragedies.'' Between them is a small shrugging emoji or a comic-style thought bubble filled with question marks, adding to the ironic humor of the situation. The overall tone is light, funny, and relatable, with bright colors and clean lines typical of a modern cartoon.'),
 (2553, 'Irony, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Whatever you want too much you can''t have, so when you REALLY want something, try to want it a little less.', 'Joel Rosenberg', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a small table, staring longingly at a delicious-looking cake on a plate. The person''s eyes are wide and full of desire. Nearby, there is a thought bubble showing a shrinking cake, implying ‘wanting it a little less’. The background is simple and light-hearted, with soft pastel colors. The character’s exaggerated expression conveys a mix of craving and puzzlement as they try to ''want it a little less.'' Include a small sticky note or thought bubble on the table with the text: ''Try wanting a little less!'' The overall tone is whimsical and playful, emphasizing the ironic advice of the joke without any negativity.'),
 (2598, 'Irony, Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'You can live to be a hundred if you give up all the things that make you want to live to be a hundred.', 'Woody Allen', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an elderly person sitting in a comfortable armchair next to a window, looking somewhat bored and gloomy. Around them are scattered objects that symbolize life''s pleasures: a cake with candles on a small table, a laid-back dog with a frisbee, a guitar leaning on the chair, a TV remote, a book, and a small bottle of wine. The elderly person looks at these items wistfully but also a bit defeated, wearing reading glasses and a cozy sweater. Above their head is a thought bubble showing a vibrant, younger version of themselves enjoying these things with energy and joy. The overall atmosphere is lighthearted with bright colors, exaggerated expressions, and a clean, simple cartoon style emphasizing the irony of giving up what makes life worth living to reach old age.'),
 (2409, 'Irony, Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'The worst part of success is trying to find someone who is happy for you.', 'Bette Midler', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing on top of a podium labeled ''1st Place'' with a big smile holding a trophy. Around them are several people in the background showing skeptical or jealous expressions—one crossing arms, another whispering to a friend, and one looking sideways with envy. Include a thought bubble above the winner’s head that says, ''Is anyone really happy for me?'' The setting should be simple, like at an awards ceremony or competition, with confetti falling but the mood clearly mixed. Use bright, cheerful colors on the winner and duller tones for the others to emphasize contrast. The overall style is lighthearted and friendly, without hostility, focusing on the ironic loneliness of success.'),
 (2332, 'Irony, Life, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'The longer I live the more I see that I am never wrong about anything, and that all the pains that I have so humbly taken to verify my notions have only wasted my time.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene of an elderly person sitting comfortably in an armchair, looking very confident and content, with a slight smirk as if proud of being always right. Around them are scattered papers, books, and a magnifying glass symbolizing past efforts to verify ideas, all appearing neglected or tossed aside. Above their head is a whimsical thought bubble showing checkmarks turning into little clocks or hourglasses to represent time wasted. The background is a cozy living room with a clock on the wall showing the passage of time, and perhaps a cat or small pet curled up at their feet, adding to the relaxed vibe. The style is light and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the self-assured attitude mixed with ironic humor about wasted efforts.'),
 (1700, 'Irony, Life, Quotes, Wisdom', 'For every problem, there is one solution which is simple, neat and wrong.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing confused in front of a giant whiteboard filled with messy equations, diagrams, and notes, representing ''problems.'' The person holds a large, oversized, humorously labeled ''SIMPLE SOLUTION'' box that is neat, shiny, and perfectly wrapped, but with a big red ''WRONG'' stamp slapped across it. The person''s expression is puzzled yet hopeful. Around the character, scattered tools like a wrench, calculator, and lightbulb icons emphasize problem-solving attempts. The background should look like a casual office or workshop to suggest problem-solving context but keep the style playful and exaggerated. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the irony that simple and neat solutions are often incorrect despite their appeal.'),
 (1780, 'Irony, Life, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'I am not young enough to know everything.', 'Oscar Wilde (1854-1900)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a middle-aged person sitting comfortably in an armchair surrounded by piles of open books, scrolls, and notes scattered all around. The person has a playful, slightly smug expression and is scratching their head as if pondering, wearing casual clothes and glasses perched on their nose. A thought bubble above their head reads, "I am not young enough to know everything." In the background, a younger person peers in with a confused or surprised expression, holding a phone or tablet as if seeking knowledge quickly. The room should look like a cozy study or library, with a few quirky details like a globe, a coffee mug labeled "World''s Not-So-Young Expert," and a small cat sleeping on some papers. The overall style is bright, lighthearted, and cartoonish, emphasizing the ironic wisdom and humorous contradiction expressed by the joke.'),
 (2550, 'Irony, Life, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'What we anticipate seldom occurs; what we least expected generally happens.', 'Benjamin Disraeli', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side, each reacting to unexpected events. The first character, labeled ''What We Anticipate,'' is holding a large, folded event plan or calendar marked with a big star, looking confidently expectant but surprised to see nothing happening around them. The second character, labeled ''What We Least Expected,'' depicts a chaotic or whimsical scene happening nearby—like a random object, such as a rubber chicken or a small UFO, amusingly interrupting the calm. The background is a simple park or street setting to keep the focus on the contrast between expectation and surprise, with exaggerated facial expressions (disappointment vs. shock/delight) to emphasize the irony of the statement. The style should be light, colorful, and cartoonish, with speech bubbles or a caption reinforcing the joke’s message about unpredictability in life.'),
 (1440, 'Irony, Life, Quotes, Wit', 'A man cannot be too careful in his choice of enemies.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a confident, slightly smug man standing proudly with his arms crossed. Around him, depict a few comical villains or enemies looking annoyed or frustrated, perhaps sulking with exaggerated angry or defeated expressions. The setting is a casual outdoor park or street, with simple trees and a bench in the background to keep it lighthearted. Add small speech bubbles or visual cues that emphasize the man''s careful scrutiny or selection, such as a checklist in his hand labeled ''Enemies List'' with some names ticked off and others crossed out. The overall tone is playful and ironic, highlighting the idea that even enemies are ''chosen'' carefully as if they were friends or business partners. Use bright colors and caricature-style faces to enhance the humor without anything threatening or violent.'),
 (1214, 'Irony, Life, Relatable', 'Things that come to those who wait are what''s left behind by those who got their first.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with two characters standing side by side in a setting that looks like a group waiting in a line for something desirable, such as a food truck or amusement ride. The first character is happily walking away with a big plate of delicious food or a fun prize, smiling confidently and ignoring the second character. The second character is left behind looking disappointed and holding only a few scraps or an empty plate, symbolizing "what’s left behind." Include clear visual contrast: the first character is bright and fulfilled, while the second character appears duller and frustrated. Add a queue sign or a clock showing elapsed time to emphasize waiting. The overall tone is lighthearted and exaggerated to capture the irony of the phrase, without any violence or negativity. Make the style colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor of missing out because of waiting.'),
 (1215, 'Irony, Life, Relatable Humor', 'Success always occurs in private, and failure in full view.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two panels side by side. On the left panel, a person is quietly celebrating alone in a cozy room, smiling modestly while sitting at a desk with a small trophy or certificate subtly displayed. The room is dimly lit with a single lamp, giving a private and calm vibe. On the right panel, the same person is in a busy public park or street, dramatically tripping over their own feet while juggling papers or objects, watched by a crowd of surprised and amused onlookers. People are pointing and laughing, some taking pictures with their phones. The contrast between the two scenes highlights the joke: quiet, private success vs. very public failure. Keep the characters cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions for humor and clearly different lighting for private vs. public settings. No violence or negativity, just a lighthearted and relatable depiction.'),
 (3210, 'Irony, Life, Relatable, Steven Wright', 'If everything seems to be going well, you have obviously overlooked something.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a relaxed person sitting comfortably in a living room, smiling and looking satisfied as if everything is perfect. Around them, subtle but funny visual clues hint at overlooked problems, such as a small fire starting quietly in the corner behind the couch, a leaky pipe dripping slowly with tiny puddles growing on the floor, and a mischievous cat knocking over a vase but the person remains blissfully unaware. The room is cozy and well-lit, with a clock on the wall showing time passing, and a checklist on a table with all tasks checked except one scribbled as ''forgotten''. The overall atmosphere is bright and lighthearted, emphasizing the irony that all seems well but clearly something is amiss.'),
 (3211, 'Irony, Life, Relatable, Steven Wright', 'If everything seems to be going well, you have obviously overlooked something.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a cheerful person confidently walking along a path labeled ''Smooth Sailing.'' The person is smiling and relaxed, wearing casual clothes, eyes closed in optimism. Behind them, partially hidden by a bush or around a corner, is a large, obvious but comically exaggerated trap or obstacle (like a big banana peel, a hole in the ground, or a slipping banana peel), suggesting trouble that the person has not noticed. The setting is bright and sunny, with a few details like scattered papers flying or a loose nail on the path to hint at hidden problems. The overall style is humorous and lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions and simple cartoon lines, emphasizing the irony of the situation without any violence or negativity.'),
 (3199, 'Irony, Life, Steven Wright, Wisdom Humor', 'Experience is something you don''t get until just after you need it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple living room. In the center is a confused person (could be a young adult) scratching their head with a puzzled expression, holding a broken or malfunctioning object, such as a toaster or a flat bicycle tire. Nearby, an older version of the same person (distinguished by subtle age lines, gray hair or glasses) appears behind them, smiling knowingly while holding a book titled "Experience". The older figure is pointing at the book as if offering advice. Around them are small details like a clock showing time has passed and a calendar with pages flipping or torn off to emphasize the passage of time. The setting should emphasize the contrast between youthful cluelessness and the wisdom that arrives only after the moment it was needed has passed. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the comic effect, using bright colors and simple lines to keep it cheerful and accessible.'),
 (2889, 'Irony, Life, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'Good judgement comes from bad experience, and a lot of that comes from bad judgement.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking owl wearing round spectacles perched on a tree branch, holding an open book titled ''Good Judgement.'' Below the owl, a confused-looking cartoon character with a helmet labeled ''Bad Judgement'' is stumbling over various obstacles like banana peels, open manholes, and spilled paint cans labeled ''Bad Experience.'' The background is a sunny park with a few other animals watching the scene, laughing. A thought bubble from the owl reads: ''Good judgement comes from bad experience...'' and a speech bubble from the character says: ''...and a lot of that comes from bad judgement!'' The art style is colorful and playful, emphasizing the irony and circular nature of the joke in a lighthearted, non-threatening way.'),
 (2918, 'Irony, Life, Unknown, Wit', 'He who hesitates is probably right.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a timid character at a fork in a forest path. The character looks unsure and hesitant, scratching their head with a puzzled expression. One path is clearly smooth and safe, the other bumpy and risky, but faint shadows on the ground hint that the risky path leads to trouble. Nearby, a wise old owl perched on a tree branch watches the character knowingly, as if approving their hesitation. The scene should be light-hearted and colorful, emphasizing the character’s indecision and the subtle suggestion that hesitation might be the smarter choice. Include simple details like signposts with confusing arrows and a bright, friendly forest background.'),
 (1216, 'Irony, Marriage Humor, Relationship Humor', 'Whenever you meet a man who would make a good husband, you will usually find that he does already.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two women standing at a party or social gathering. One woman is whispering or talking to the other with a knowing smile, while the other woman looks surprised or thoughtfully nodding. In the background, show a few men mingling; one man stands out, depicted as a charming, well-dressed gentleman with a wedding ring clearly visible on his finger. The setting should be bright and cheerful with typical party decorations like balloons or streamers. Emphasize the irony with a subtle visual cue: a small thought bubble from the surprised woman imagining a single man looking lonely or out of place. The style should be lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated facial expressions for comedic effect, with no violent or sensitive content.'),
 (1916, 'Irony, Military Humor, Quotes', 'If your attack is going too well, you''re probably walking into an ambush.', 'US Army Infantry Journal', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a forest clearing. In the foreground, a confident, cartoon-style soldier or adventurer is tiptoeing exaggeratedly forward with a big grin, looking overly pleased with himself, holding a sword or weapon loosely. Behind a bush nearby, several mischievous cartoon enemies or bandits are hiding, peeking out with sly, exaggerated expressions and holding simple weapons like spears or slingshots. The forest is drawn whimsically with bright green trees, bushes, and some flowers. The expressions should emphasize the unsuspecting joy of the attacker contrasted with the hidden, playful danger of the ambush. Include subtle visual cues like a few comic question marks or exclamation marks above the characters to emphasize the humor and surprise. The style is light, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon strip.'),
 (2353, 'Irony, Military Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'The object of war is not to die for your country but to make the other bastard die for his.', 'General George S. Patton (1885-1945)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two soldiers facing each other on a battlefield. Each soldier is shown with exaggerated expressions and cartoonish gear—helmets slightly askew, wide eyes, and playful grimaces. One soldier is nervously pointing a cartoonish rifle at the other, who looks equally wary. Between them is a simple cartoon landscape with rolling hills, a few doodle-style trees, and a bright, comical sun smiling down. Above them is a thought bubble from one soldier thinking, "The goal isn’t to die for your country but to make the other guy die." The scene is lighthearted with bright colors and no violence, focusing on the ironic and clever nature of the quote rather than any real combat. The overall style is friendly and silly, reminiscent of classic comic strips or editorial cartoons that emphasize wit over action.'),
 (2512, 'Irony, Military Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'We are not retreating - we are advancing in another direction.', 'General Douglas MacArthur (1880-1964)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a group of determined-looking soldiers or explorers on a battlefield or in a forest. Instead of running away or fighting, they are all turning around or walking sideways with confused but optimistic expressions. One leader in the front is confidently pointing forward with a speech bubble saying, "We are not retreating - we are advancing in another direction." Add playful elements like a winding path behind them with footprints showing backward movement, but the characters look proud and motivated. The background can include simple hills, trees, and a small flag being carried by one of the group. Keep the characters exaggerated and cartoonish with expressive faces to highlight the humor of spin on retreating as a form of progress.'),
 (1855, 'Irony, Money Humor, Quotes', 'I''d give $1000 to be a millionaire.', 'Lewis Timberlake', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing with a big mischievous grin holding a giant bag labeled "$1000" in one hand. Around them are thought bubbles illustrating their dream of being a millionaire, with a huge pile of money stacks, sparkling gold coins, and a fancy sports car. The setting is colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated cartoon dollar signs floating in the air and the person looking hopeful yet slightly puzzled. The background could be a simple cityscape or a bank to emphasize money themes. The overall tone is playful and whimsical, capturing the irony of wanting to be a millionaire but only having $1000.'),
 (2476, 'Irony, Money Humor, Quotes', 'To make a small fortune, invest a large fortune.', 'Bruce Cohn', 'A humorous cartoon showing a wealthy-looking character sitting at a fancy desk counting a huge pile of money. On the desk is a large, overflowing sack labeled ''Large Fortune''. The character looks puzzled and stressed, rubbing their temple. Behind them is a whiteboard or chart with a downward trending arrow labeled ''Fortune''. Next to the desk is a small, comically tiny pile of coins labeled ''Small Fortune''. The scene is colorful and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony that investing a large fortune results in only a small fortune, poking fun at the idea of losing money in investments.'),
 (1508, 'Irony, Money Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'All I ask is a chance to prove that money can''t make me happy.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly scruffy person standing next to a giant pile of money bags and gold coins stacked high. The person wears casual clothes and has a hopeful, eager expression with one hand raised slightly as if making a point or request. Around them are thought bubbles depicting happy, fun activities like travel, parties, and laughing with friends. The background is light and colorful, with no dark or negative tones. The overall style is playful and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony that the person wants a chance to prove money can''t buy happiness—suggesting they haven''t had the chance yet. Include a small sign in the corner that reads "Prove it!" to add humor and context, making it clear the character is asking for the chance to test the saying rather than denying it outright.'),
 (2111, 'Irony, Money Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Money isn''t everything, according to those who have it.', 'Malcolm Forbes', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a wealthy-looking person sits relaxed in a large armchair surrounded by piles of money, gold coins, and valuables—yet they have a bored or unimpressed expression. On the right, a person with empty pockets turned inside out looks frustrated or worried. Above them, a thought bubble emerges from the wealthy character with the phrase ''Money isn''t everything.'' The setting is simple, with bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the irony of the statement. Include classic cartoon elements such as sparkling coins, dollar signs floating around, and a humorous contrast between the two characters'' emotions. The style should be light and playful, suitable for a family-friendly cartoon joke.'),
 (2144, 'Irony, Money Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'No one can earn a million dollars honestly.', 'William Jennings Bryan (1860-1925)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a messy desk piled high with paperwork, calculators, and empty coffee cups, looking exhausted and disheartened. Behind them is a large, comically overflowing money bag labeled ''1 Million Dollars'' just out of their reach on a high shelf. The person''s expression is exaggeratedly tired and frustrated, eyebrows raised, with a thought bubble above their head containing a crossed-out honesty badge or a sticky note reading ''Honest Work.'' Nearby, a sign on the wall says ''Honest Millionaire Wanted.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated facial features to emphasize the irony that earning a million dollars through honest means feels impossible or out of reach. The style should be simple and cartoonish, with no violence or sensitive content.'),
 (2115, 'Irony, Money Humor, Quotes, Word Play', '''More often I wish that I had less'' is not the same as ''Less often I wish that I had more'', nor is it normally true, unless we''re talking about income tax.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a middle-aged person sitting at a cluttered desk, looking thoughtful with a slightly puzzled expression. Above their head are two large, colorful thought bubbles. The first bubble reads: ''More often I wish that I had less'' and shows a pile of excessive clutter, like stacks of papers, boxes, a broken clock, and a mountain of clothes. The second bubble reads: ''Less often I wish that I had more'' and shows a tiny, half-empty wallet with a few coins spilling out and some tax forms with big red letters ''INCOME TAX'' stamped on them. The person is scratching their head in confusion. Around the desk are humorous details like a coffee cup labeled ''World''s Okayest Earner'' and a small calendar flipped to April. The style should be bright, cartoonish, and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony and humor in the contradictory wishes about having more or less, ending with a wink toward the taxing nature of income tax.'),
 (1217, 'Irony, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Steven Wright', 'The sooner you fall behind, the more time you''ll have to catch up.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person running on a winding race track. The runner looks both worried and slightly hopeful, glancing back over their shoulder with exaggerated wide eyes. Behind them, a humorous finish line is visible far in the distance. Several clocks and timers float in the air above the track, each showing different times, symbolizing the passing time. Nearby, a quirky, smiling tortoise wearing running shoes is casually strolling the path, representing the idea of slow progress. The track is lined with funny motivational signs saying things like ''Keep Up!'' and ''Catch Up Zone Ahead!'' The background is bright and lively with simple trees, a clear blue sky, and a few cartoon-style clouds. Ensure the expression and body language of the runner capture the irony with a mix of anxiety and optimism. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, suitable for a clean and funny comic panel without any harsh or negative elements.'),
 (1218, 'Irony, Motivational, Workplace', 'We have done so much for so long with so little, we can now do anything with nothing.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a tired but determined office worker sitting at a cluttered desk piled high with old, broken gadgets and empty coffee cups. The worker is smiling wryly, holding up empty hands as if proudly showing they have nothing. In the background, show a barely functioning, outdated computer with a flickering screen. Include motivational posters on the wall with irony, such as one reading ''Do More With Less'' and another saying ''Innovation from Nothing.'' The overall tone should be light and playful, emphasizing the idea of making do with very little but having a can-do attitude.'),
 (1219, 'Irony, Music Humor, Puns', 'There is a CD out entitled ''The Worst of Jefferson Airplane''. If you buy this, take it home, play it, and enjoy it, should you take it back and demand a refund?', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room. In the center, a person stands holding a CD case titled ''The Worst of Jefferson Airplane'' with a puzzled but amused expression. The CD cover should have a playful, retro design featuring a cartoon airplane looking a bit distressed or crooked, hinting at the band''s name. Nearby, a stereo or record player is prominently displayed, playing music notes that visually look odd or twisted, to represent ''worst'' music. Include subtle visual cues like a thought bubble above the person''s head with a question mark and an ironic shrugging emoji or tiny refund receipt to show their dilemma. The room should feel lighthearted and colorful, with minimal background detail such as a comfy armchair, a small plant, and a poster of a classic rock band on the wall to set the tone. The style should be lively and exaggerated, emphasizing the joke’s irony about enjoying bad music and questioning a refund, without any harmful or negative imagery.'),
 (3065, 'Irony, Office Humor, Programming Humor, Unknown', 'If a program is useless, it must be documented.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a disorganized office programmer''s desk cluttered with papers, coffee cups, a computer displaying messy code with lots of red errors, and sticky notes all over the monitor and desk. A frustrated-looking programmer wearing glasses and a wrinkled shirt sits at the desk, scratching their head in confusion. Behind them, on the wall, hangs a framed certificate titled ''Documentation Award'' with a comically exaggerated ribbon. The computer screen has a speech bubble saying, ''If it''s useless, at least it''s documented!'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with cartoonish exaggeration to emphasize the silly contradiction of useless programs being meticulously documented.'),
 (1220, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor', 'The basis of optimism is sheer terror.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful-looking person standing on a cliff edge with an exaggeratedly terrified expression, eyes wide and hair standing on end. Behind them, dark storm clouds swirl ominously, but instead of looking worried, the person wears an overly bright smile, almost forced. Emphasize the contrast between their scared demeanor and their optimistic grin. Include a small speech bubble above their head that says, "This is great!" to highlight ironic optimism. The cliff is detailed with cracks and loose rocks to enhance the danger, but the overall style should be lighthearted and comical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to maintain a funny and non-threatening tone.'),
 (1221, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor', 'The chief cause of problems is solutions.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a giant, exaggeratedly complicated Rube Goldberg machine labeled ''Solution Machine,'' with lots of gears, levers, and pipes. In the foreground, a frustrated-looking person in casual clothes, scratching their head while looking at the mess. Around the machine, small signs say ''Problem #1,'' ''Problem #2,'' and silly unintended side effects, like a bucket of water spilling or a toy robot malfunctioning. The background is a simple office or workshop with scattered tools and papers, emphasizing a chaotic but comical atmosphere. The style is lighthearted, bright colors, round shapes, and exaggerated expressions to capture the irony that solutions often cause more problems.'),
 (1222, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor', 'To laugh at men of sense is the privilege of fools.', NULL, 'A simple humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one clearly a wise, older man with glasses and a thoughtful expression, dressed in scholarly clothing, and the other a young foolish-looking character laughing exaggeratedly. The wise man stands calmly with a slight smirk, holding a book titled ''Sense & Wisdom.'' The fool wears a colorful jester hat and oversized shoes, giggling loudly with tears of laughter, pointing at the wise man. The background is minimalistic with a small podium labeled ''Privilege.'' The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the fool''s amusement and the wise man''s calm demeanor.'),
 (2078, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Psychology Humor, Quotes', 'Man is a rational animal who always loses his temper when he is called upon to act in accordance with the dictates of reason.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting at a desk cluttered with papers labeled ''Reason'' and ''Logic.'' The man has a frustrated, angry expression and is throwing up his hands in exasperation. Nearby, a small, cute anthropomorphic brain character wearing glasses stands with a clipboard labeled ''Dictates of Reason,'' looking calm and slightly annoyed. Behind the man, a thought bubble depicts a chaotic storm of emotions—comic symbols like lightning bolts, sweat drops, and angry red marks—contrasting with the neat clipboard. The setting is an office-like room with a wall calendar reading ''Rational Animal Club Meeting,'' and motivational posters about staying calm and thinking clearly. The tone is light and exaggerated to emphasize the irony of a ''rational'' man losing his temper when asked to be rational, with bright colors and expressive cartoonish features.'),
 (1611, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Criticism is prejudice made plausible.', 'Henry Louis Mencken (1880-1956)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing next to each other. One is an older, stern-looking person holding a large magnifying glass over a tiny speech bubble containing a very small comment or opinion. The speech bubble is labeled ''Criticism.'' The other character is a whimsical figure wearing a judge''s wig and robes, holding a gavel and looking skeptically at the magnified speech bubble. Around them are scattered papers labeled ''Opinions'' and ''Prejudices,'' giving a visual metaphor that the magnifying glass is turning vague prejudices into seemingly serious criticism. The background is simple with a light color to keep the focus on the characters and props. Make the style exaggerated and cartoonish to emphasize the absurdity of turning prejudice into plausible criticism, with their facial expressions being both ironic and bemused. Include humorous details like tiny dust particles labeled ''bias'' floating around the magnifying glass to add whimsy without clutter.'),
 (2354, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The only thing necessary for the triumph of evil is for good men to do nothing.', 'Edmund Burke (1729-1797)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of three good-looking but clearly unmotivated men standing idly side by side. They are dressed like classic heroes (e.g., capes, simple heroic costumes) but are completely relaxed and doing nothing—one is checking his phone, another is slouching with arms crossed, and the third is yawning. In front of them is a tiny, comically exaggerated evil character—small, devilish with horns and a mischievous grin—holding a small flag that reads ''Victory.'' This evil character is triumphantly standing atop a small podium or pedestal labeled ''Evil Wins.'' The background is simple, with a sunny sky and some light-hearted buildings or trees. The overall tone is light, fun, and cartoonish to emphasize the irony of the quote about passivity leading to evil''s triumph without any threatening or violent imagery.'),
 (1951, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'In theory, there is no difference between theory and practice. But, in practice, there is.', 'Jan L.A. van de Snepscheut', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two side-by-side panels. The left panel is labeled ''Theory'' and depicts a calm, neat scientist or professor at a desk with neat stacks of papers and books titled ''Theories''. The scientist is smiling confidently while holding a chalkboard with complex equations or diagrams, looking very assured. The right panel is labeled ''Practice'' and shows the same character in a comically chaotic workshop or messy lab. The character looks frazzled with wild hair and a slightly disheveled outfit, surrounded by broken gadgets, spilled liquids, scattered tools, and tangled wires. A machine or experiment is clearly malfunctioning, emitting smoke or sparks. The contrast between the two panels visually represents the gap between the neatness of theory and the messy reality of practice. The overall style is colorful, playful, and lighthearted, emphasizing the irony and humor of the joke without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (1999, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'It''s discouraging to think how many people are shocked by honesty and how few by deceit.', 'Noel Coward', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of diverse, exaggeratedly shocked people standing together, each with wide eyes and jaws dropped in astonishment as a plainly dressed character confidently speaks with a speech bubble containing a shining golden word ''HONESTY''. Nearby, another group of people is shown with indifferent or bored expressions as a sneaky-looking character waves slyly with a speech bubble labeled ''DECEIT''. The setting is a simple park or town square with a bench, some trees, and a lamppost to give context, all drawn in bright, cheerful colors with playful cartoonish exaggeration on facial expressions for comedic effect. The overall mood contrasts the surprise at honesty versus the blasé attitude toward deceit.'),
 (2530, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Theater Humor', 'We participate in a tragedy; at a comedy we only look.', 'Aldous Huxley', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two groups of people at two different entertainment events side by side. On the left, a small theater stage shows actors dramatically performing a serious tragedy, with the audience actively participating—some are crying, others cheering, some even standing and reacting emotionally, clearly involved. On the right, a comedy show stage features a stand-up comedian telling jokes, but the crowd is simply sitting quietly, passively watching, displaying mild smiles but no real engagement or participation. Include clear visual contrasts: expressive, involved audience on the tragedy side versus calm, reserved audience on the comedy side. The setting is indoors with simple stage backgrounds, spotlighting each performer. Use exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize emotional involvement versus passive observation. Make sure the humor comes from the difference in audience behavior in the two adjacent scenes, with signs labeling ''Tragedy'' and ''Comedy'' above each stage to clarify the joke.'),
 (1877, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'If history repeats itself, and the unexpected always happens, how incapable must Man be of learning from experience.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a crossroads labeled ''History'' and ''Experience.'' The person looks confused and frustrated, scratching their head while looking at a large, old scroll titled ''History Repeats Itself'' on one side and a mysterious box labeled ''The Unexpected'' on the other. Behind the person, a repeating shadow or faded ghostlike figures represent past mistakes marching in a loop around them, suggesting history continuously repeats. The setting is a simple outdoor scene with a clear blue sky and a few fluffy clouds, emphasizing the ironic inevitability of human error. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated with vibrant colors and playful expressions to convey the irony without negativity or complexity.'),
 (2160, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Nothing is so good for an ignorant man as silence; and if he was sensible of this he would not be ignorant.', 'Saadi', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused, cartoonish man with a puzzled expression, scratching his head while standing next to a large, giant mute button or a big sign that says ''SILENCE'' with a finger pressed against it like a button. The man is surrounded by question marks floating above his head to signify ignorance. The background is simple and bright with soft colors to keep the tone light and comical. A thought bubble from the man shows a tiny version of himself being silent and calm, indicating the idea that staying quiet would benefit him. The overall style is whimsical with exaggerated features to emphasize cluelessness and the irony that the man does not realize silence would help him.'),
 (2330, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The little I know I owe to my ignorance.', 'Sacha Guitry', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a small desk cluttered with books and papers labeled ''Knowledge'' and ''Learning.'' The character looks puzzled but amused, scratching their head with a big, silly grin. Above their head, a thought bubble reads: ''The little I know I owe to my ignorance.'' Around them, question marks and lightbulbs float, mixing confusion with sudden ideas. The room is simple—a cozy study with a window showing a sunny day outside, a plant on the windowsill, and a cat watching the person curiously from a chair. The overall style is light, colorful, and playful, emphasizing the irony and humor in the statement without any harsh or serious elements.'),
 (1436, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'A little sincerity is a dangerous thing, and a great deal of it is absolutely fatal.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a charming but overly serious character, perhaps a middle-aged man in a suit, standing on a stage delivering a speech with exaggerated enthusiasm. Around him, the audience members display a range of reactions: some are nervously sweating, others look shocked or overwhelmed, while one or two are fainting or dramatically clutching their chest as if ''sincerity'' is physically harming them. The background should be a simple auditorium or conference room with a podium and a microphone. Include a speech bubble coming from the speaker that reads, ''A little sincerity is a dangerous thing, and a great deal of it is absolutely fatal.'' The tone should be light and playful, emphasizing the absurdity of sincerity being portrayed as lethal. Use bright colors and expressive, cartoon-style faces to elicit humor without any negativity or violence.'),
 (1525, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Always remember you''re unique, just like everyone else.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or a seminar room where a quirky, cheerful teacher is standing in front of a whiteboard. The whiteboard shows the phrase: ''Always remember you''re unique, just like everyone else.'' The teacher has a big smile, glasses, and is pointing with a pointer stick at the phrase, emphasizing it comically. Around the teacher are several students sitting at desks or chairs, looking either confused or amused, highlighting the irony of the statement. The room has minimal details: a clock on the wall, a few books stacked on a desk, and a motivational poster ironically stating ''Be Yourself!'' The overall tone is bright and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor without any hint of negativity or sarcasm, keeping it lighthearted and funny.'),
 (2545, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'What passes for optimism is most often the effect of an intellectual error.', 'Raymond Aron', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy office or study filled with books and papers. In the center, a thoughtful-looking character sits at a desk cluttered with open books and notes, scratching their head in confusion or mild frustration. Above the character’s head, a large thought bubble shows a whimsical, somewhat distorted idea of optimism—like a bright, shining light bulb malfunctioning or flickering erratically. The character’s expression hints at irony or realization, suggesting that their idea of optimism is actually a mistake or intellectual error. The background includes details like a small chalkboard or whiteboard scribbled with complicated equations and crossed-out ideas, implying deep thinking gone slightly wrong. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and an inviting atmosphere, emphasizing the humor of confusing optimism with an error of thinking rather than genuine hope or positivity.'),
 (2231, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Self-sacrifice enables us to sacrifice other people without blushing.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a simple living room. One character, looking proud and noble, is holding a tiny flag or badge labeled ''Self-Sacrifice''. This character is confidently stepping back, pointing toward the other character with a sly smirk. The second character looks surprised and slightly annoyed, standing next to a pile of comically oversized, exaggeratedly difficult tasks or chores labeled ''Sacrifices''. The setting is light and colorful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions emphasizing the irony of the statement. Include a small thought bubble above the first character reading, ''Self-sacrifice means someone else does the hard work!'' or a similar punchline vibe to reinforce the humor without words. The overall tone is playful and non-threatening, with simple detailing focused on the characters’ expressions and body language to highlight the joke’s ironic twist on self-sacrifice.'),
 (2838, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Religious Humor, Unknown', 'Everybody wants to go to heaven, but nobody wants to die.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two contrasting halves. On the left side, a bright, cheerful, inviting ''Heaven'' gate gleams with clouds, soft light, and angels smiling and welcoming with open arms. People eagerly stand in a line, looking excited and hopeful, reaching towards the gate. On the right side, the same people are shown nervously backing away from a large, scary, dark door labeled ''Death'' with exaggerated fearful expressions, sweating or hiding behind one another. The expressions clearly show they all want to reach heaven but dread going through death. The style should be light-hearted and cartoony with exaggerated facial expressions, bright colors on the heaven side, and darker tones on the death side for comedic contrast. Include small humorous details like a person holding a ''Heaven or Bust'' sign and another peeking nervously from behind the death door.'),
 (1223, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Social Commentary', 'REVOLUTIONARY: An oppressed person waiting for the opportunity to become an oppressor.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a single character standing anxiously on a sidewalk, looking up at a large, towering statue labeled ''OPPRESSOR'' holding a big baton. The character has humble clothes and a hopeful yet nervous expression. Behind the character, a crowd of other everyday people wait in line, some whispering excitedly, as if waiting for their turn. Above them is a billboard reading ''Revolutionary Training Center: From Oppressed to Oppressor!''. The style is colorful and exaggerated, with caricatured figures to highlight the humor. The setting is a city square with a few protest signs folded in the background to hint at past struggles. The overall tone is light and funny, using visual irony to depict the cycle of oppression in a non-violent, witty way.'),
 (2852, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'Facts do not cease to exist because they are ignored.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk with a large stack of papers labeled ''Facts'' teetering dangerously. The person is wearing glasses, looking away while covering their ears and closing their eyes tightly, as if trying to block out or ignore the facts. The desk is cluttered with books and a coffee cup. Behind them, an animated speech bubble shaped like a fact bubble floats with bold text saying, ''Facts do not cease to exist because they are ignored.'' The background is a simple office or study room, with a calendar on the wall showing a serious date, emphasizing the persistence of facts despite avoidance. The overall style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to convey denial and humorous irony, but no violence or offensive content.'),
 (3154, 'Irony, Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Wit', 'Your reasoning is silly, illogical, irrational, and it''s beginning to make sense.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters engaged in a conversation. One character is an older, wise-looking person with glasses, holding a book titled ''Logic for Beginners'' and looking slightly frustrated. The other character is younger with a mischievous grin, shrugging their shoulders as if admitting to silliness. Floating above their heads is a thought bubble showing a jumbled mix of symbols, question marks, exclamation points, and lightbulbs, representing the mix of silly, illogical, irrational, yet somehow sensible ideas. The background is a simple room with a chalkboard that has random spirals and question marks drawn on it, humorously implying chaotic yet clever thinking. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors emphasizing the ironic contradiction of the statement.'),
 (1387, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes', 'A conservative is one who admires radicals centuries after they''re dead.', 'Leo C. Rosten', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a modern-day conservative person, dressed in typical conservative attire such as a blazer and glasses, standing in front of a large framed portrait gallery on a wall. The portraits are of famous historical radicals—think wild-haired philosophers, revolutionaries with passionate expressions, or colorful 18th-century figures—each labelled with old-fashioned nameplates and dates long ago. The conservative is gazing admiringly at one of these portraits with a thoughtful smile and hands clasped behind their back. The setting is cozy and old-fashioned, like a small museum or study room, with a polished wooden floor and warm lighting. In the background, a small plaque reads: "Radicals of the Past." The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing a contrast between the modern conservative’s calm demeanor and the fiery, dramatic radical portraits. No violent or political imagery, just a witty depiction of admiration across time.'),
 (1807, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes', 'I either want less corruption, or more chance to participate in it.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A cartoon scene featuring a confused-looking person standing at a street corner labeled ''Corruption Blvd.'' The person is dressed in casual clothes, scratching their head while looking at two brightly colored signs pointing in opposite directions. One sign says ''Less Corruption'' with clean, shining buildings and happy people in the background. The other sign says ''More Chance to Participate'' with sneaky-looking characters exchanging briefcases behind bushes. The person has a thought bubble showing a scale tipping between a big ''No'' symbol and a pile of money, illustrating indecision. The whole scene is drawn in a lighthearted, humorous cartoon style with exaggerated facial expressions and clear labels on the signs. No violence or negative imagery is present; the tone is ironic and playful.'),
 (2405, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes', 'The warning message we sent the Russians was a calculated ambiguity that would be clearly understood.', 'Alexander Haig', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two people in a cozy, modern office or war room. One person, looking serious and wearing glasses, stands next to a whiteboard covered in complicated math formulas and diagrams labeled ''Calculated Ambiguity.'' The other person looks puzzled, scratching their head while holding a phone or radio. Nearby, a computer screen displays a vague, cryptic message with question marks floating above it. In the background, a small map pinned on the wall shows Russia marked with a question mark and unclear symbols, adding to the confusion. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing earnestness and bemusement. The overall atmosphere conveys the irony and humor about a message intended to be both ambiguous and clearly understood, avoiding any direct references to conflict or alarm.'),
 (1618, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Democracy encourages the majority to decide things about which the majority is ignorant.', 'John Simon', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a town meeting in a simple, brightly colored community hall. There is a large round table with a diverse group of cartoon characters sitting around it, with puzzled and confused expressions. Some characters are scratching their heads, others looking at papers or whispering to each other uncertainly. In the center of the table is a large ballot box labeled ''Democracy Votes.'' Behind the characters, a whiteboard reads ''Decisions for Today'' with scribbles and question marks. Include humorous details like one person holding a tiny book titled ''Expert Guide'' looking overwhelmed, another character trying to open a giant book labeled ''Everything You Need to Know,'' and a bored cat sleeping under the table. The overall tone is lighthearted and witty, emphasizing the irony of voting without knowledge, all depicted in a colorful, cartoon style with simple lines and exaggerated facial expressions.'),
 (1973, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'It is dangerous to be right when the government is wrong.', 'Voltaire', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on a street corner, holding a large speech bubble sign that says ''I''m right!'' Meanwhile, in the background, a cartoonish government building with an exaggeratedly stern and grumpy face is glaring at the person. The government building has human-like eyes and arms crossed to show disapproval. Around them, small bystanders look nervously at the person holding the sign. The setting should be a bright, simple city street with some trees and benches, drawn in a colorful, lighthearted cartoon style. The overall tone is humorous but non-threatening, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the tension between the individual and the government figure.'),
 (2187, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Our elections are free -- it''s in the results where eventually we pay.', 'Bill Stern', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a voting booth labeled ''Elections'' in bright, cheerful colors, with a diverse group of happy voters lining up, smiling and casting their ballots. In the foreground, a large, exaggerated ballot box is seen clearly marked ''Free to Vote.'' Behind the scene, a shadowy, slightly exaggerated giant hand (symbolizing government or consequences) is reaching into people''s wallets overflowing with money, with dollar bills flying out, symbolizing the ''paying in the results.'' The scene is lighthearted and playful, using exaggerated expressions and cartoonish proportions to keep a non-serious tone. Include speech bubbles from the voters or signs emphasizing ''Free elections!'' to contrast with the sneaky giant hand, visually enforcing the joke''s meaning.'),
 (1992, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'It only takes 20 years for a liberal to become a conservative without changing a single idea.', 'Robert Anton Wilson', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left is a younger person dressed in typical ''liberal'' attire—perhaps colorful clothes, holding a peace sign flag or wearing a t-shirt with a progressive slogan. On the right is the same character, now older, dressed more conservatively, maybe in a suit or formal wear with a red tie or American flag pin, holding a traditional symbol like an eagle or a ballot box. Both characters have identical facial expressions and posture, emphasizing that their ideas haven’t changed, just their appearance. The background can be a simple park or cityscape, with a subtle timeline or clock showing 20 years passing, like a calendar flipping or an hourglass halfway empty. The overall style is cartoonish and lighthearted, with exaggerated features and bright colors to emphasize the joke’s ironic twist without hostility or political judgment.'),
 (1430, 'Irony, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A liberal is a man too broadminded to take his own side in a quarrel.', 'Robert Frost', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two men in a friendly quarrel or debate. One man is labeled as a ''liberal'' either by a badge, name tag, or a small sign nearby. He appears confused and conflicted, looking slightly torn between two opposing viewpoints symbolized by a speech bubble split in half, with contradictory statements on each side. Both men are standing in a casual setting, like a park bench or a café patio. Around them, items that suggest an everyday argument context—like coffee cups or newspaper headlines—are visible. The liberal man has an exaggeratedly large brain or an oversized head to visually emphasize broadmindedness, but he looks unsure and hesitant, literally holding up both his own sides, as if unable to pick one. The other man watches with a smirk or amused expression, adding to the lighthearted tone. The style is bright and cartoonish, with simple facial expressions and clear labels, no violence or anything controversial, aiming to play on the idea of being so open-minded it causes internal contradiction.'),
 (1551, 'Irony, Programming Humor, Quotes', 'Any program that runs right is obsolete.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an old-fashioned computer (like a bulky desktop from the 1980s) sitting on a cluttered desk. On the computer screen, there is a big error message with a red ''X'' and a pop-up that says ''Program Running…'' but the computer looks unusually calm and pristine — almost suspiciously perfect. Nearby, a frazzled cartoon programmer is scratching their head, holding a large coffee mug labeled ''Debug Juice.'' Around the desk, scattered papers have scribbled bug reports and error codes. The background features a whimsical ''obsolete'' sign hanging on the wall behind the computer. The overall tone is playful and light-hearted, capturing the irony that if a program runs correctly, it’s considered outdated or useless. The cartoon style should be colorful with exaggerated expressions and simple lines, emphasizing the comedic contradiction without any negativity.'),
 (3064, 'Irony, Programming Humor, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'If a program is useful, it must be changed.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a software development office. In the foreground, a cheerful programmer is sitting at a cluttered desk with a laptop displaying lines of code and a big green checkmark labeled ''Useful Program.'' The programmer is scratching their head and holding a wrench hesitantly, looking at the screen. Behind them, a mischievous robot assistant or a small technical-looking character (like a bug with glasses) is gently pushing a big red button labeled ''CHANGE.'' In the background, other programmers are either face-palming, laughing, or frantically typing. On the wall, a whiteboard shows a flowchart with ''Useful Program → Must Change!'' written humorously as a rule. The overall vibe is lighthearted, focusing on the ironic idea that no program stays useful without constant modification. The art style is cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors, emphasizing the playful irony of software development culture.'),
 (1640, 'Irony, Project Management, Quotes, Workplace', 'Doing it right is no excuse for not meeting the schedule.', '(Actual Dilbert Manager Quotes)', 'A humorous cartoon office scene showing a stressed project manager standing next to a large wall calendar with many crossed-out dates and a looming deadline circled in bright red. The manager has a clipboard and is pointing at a worker sitting at a cluttered desk, working meticulously on a large blueprint or detailed report with a focused, serious expression. The worker wears round glasses and is surrounded by piles of papers, rulers, and sticky notes. On the wall behind them is a poster that says ''Do it right!'' but below it is a sticky note attached that reads ''Schedule First!''. The atmosphere combines a sense of urgency with the comedic contrast between careful perfectionism and looming deadlines. The style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing mild frustration and determination without any aggressive or negative tones.'),
 (2579, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Whenever people agree with me I always feel I must be wrong.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing confidently in the center, with a puzzled and slightly worried expression as they look around. Surrounding the person are several other characters nodding enthusiastically and giving thumbs-up or smiling broadly in agreement. The central figure should have a thought bubble showing a question mark and a small, quirky image of themselves looking doubtful. The setting is a simple, neutral background like a park or an office breakroom, to emphasize the interaction. Characters should be drawn with exaggerated, friendly cartoon features, adding to the humor of the situation where agreement ironically causes the main character’s uncertainty. No aggressive or negative body language or environment elements.'),
 (2277, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Social Humor', 'The average person thinks he isn''t.', 'Father Larry Lorenzoni', 'A humorous cartoon showing a crowd of diverse, cartoon-style people standing together on a street or in a park. Each person has a quirky, confident facial expression, with arms crossed or hands on hips, clearly looking very self-assured. Over the crowd, a large floating thought bubble reads, "I’m not average!" in playful, bold lettering. The scene captures a lighthearted, ironic mood where everyone is convinced they are special and unique. The background is simple with some trees or buildings softly drawn to keep focus on the characters. The characters should be relatable everyday people of various ages, styles, and appearances to emphasize the universal humor in the idea that everyone thinks they are above average. The overall style is colorful, friendly, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (1641, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'Don''t be so humble - you are not that great!', 'Golda Meir', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a character standing in front of a mirror. The character is looking at their reflection with a slightly puzzled and amused expression. Around the character are faint, exaggerated sparkles or stars indicating confidence or self-importance, but the mirror reflection looks modest and unspectacular, creating a funny contrast. The character is dressed casually and the setting is a simple bedroom or bathroom with a plain wall and a framed mirror hanging on it. Above the mirror or as a speech bubble, include the phrase: ''Don''t be so humble - you are not that great!'' The overall style is light and cartoonish with soft colors and expressive facial features to emphasize the ironic tone of the joke without being mean-spirited.'),
 (1394, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'A fanatic is one who can''t change his mind and won''t change the subject.', 'Winston Churchill', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person labeled ''Fanatic'' sitting stubbornly at a small round table with a speech bubble full of tangled words and symbols, showing a refusal to change their opinion. Across from them, another person looks frustrated, holding a sign that says ''Let''s talk about something else!'' The background is simple, with a few scattered topics floating as small icons (like a sports ball, a book, a music note) that the fanatic ignores. The fanatic wears a headband with the word ''Fixed'' on it to emphasize their unchanging mindset. The style is lighthearted, expressive, and colorful, capturing the stubbornness and comedic tension without conflict or aggression. The overall mood is playful and witty, with exaggerated facial expressions for both characters to underline the joke''s idea.'),
 (1405, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'A good man gone wrong is usually a bad man found out.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: one labeled ''Good Man'' depicted as a well-dressed, friendly-looking gentleman with a halo slightly slipping off his head and a worried expression. The second character is labeled ''Bad Man'' and appears disheveled with a suspicious look, holding a magnifying glass as if investigating or discovering something. They stand opposite each other on a simple street or sidewalk, with a signpost in the background reading ''Truth Lane'' to hint at revelation. The ''Good Man'' is tipping his hat awkwardly, and the ''Bad Man'' looks triumphant as if just uncovered the truth. Include lighthearted, exaggerated facial expressions and cartoon elements like question marks or exclamation marks around their heads. The overall style is clean, colorful, and playful to emphasize the ironic twist that a ''good man gone wrong'' becomes a ''bad man found out.'' No violence or threatening gestures.'),
 (1491, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'Accomplishing the impossible means only that the boss will add it to your regular duties.', 'Doug Larson', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office environment. In the foreground, a tired but determined employee sits at a cluttered desk covered with stacks of paper, a computer, and a coffee mug. The employee, drawn with exaggeratedly weary eyes and a slight grimace, is reaching out to hand a large, shiny trophy labeled ''Impossible Accomplished'' to a grinning boss. The boss, standing confidently behind the employee''s desk, points with a smirk toward a large whiteboard or bulletin board behind them titled ''Regular Duties,'' which now has a long list of tasks including the recently added ''Impossible Task'' written in bold. The office background includes humorous details like motivational posters with funny slogans, a clock showing late hours, and coworkers peeking in with surprised or sympathetic expressions. The overall tone is light-hearted and relatable, capturing the frustration and irony of workplace expectations in a playful, cartoon style.'),
 (1533, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'An authority is somebody who can tell you more about something than you really care to know.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene in an office or lecture room. A person in formal attire with glasses, a pointer stick, and a stack of papers stands in front of an audience, enthusiastically explaining something. The audience looks bored or overwhelmed, with some people yawning, glancing at their watches, or drifting off to sleep. Include a whiteboard behind the speaker filled with excessively detailed notes, charts, and confusing diagrams to emphasize information overload. The overall tone should be lighthearted and playful, focusing on exaggerating the contrast between the speaker’s enthusiasm and the listeners’ disinterest.'),
 (2458, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'This project is so important, we can''t let things that are more important interfere with it.', '(Actual Dilbert Manager Quotes)', 'A humorous cartoon scene in a modern office environment. Center the image on a stressed-looking project manager sitting at a cluttered desk filled with papers, sticky notes, a computer, and a large calendar marked with deadlines. The project manager is pointing determinedly at a whiteboard with the project title written at the top and notes reading "MOST IMPORTANT" in bold letters. Around the manager, two interruptions are humorously depicted: on one side, a ringing phone with a big label saying "More Important Calls" and on the other, a coworker holding a coffee cup and a huge stack of documents labeled "More Important Work" looking hopeful to get the manager’s attention. The manager''s expression is one of frantic seriousness, as if unable or unwilling to let either interruption distract them, even though the interruptions clearly carry signs of higher priority. The style is bright and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the absurdity of the statement and situation. No violence or negativity; just a lighthearted portrayal of misplaced priorities and workplace irony.'),
 (1840, 'Irony, Quotes, Relatable, Workplace', 'I think our No. 1 problem is that nobody wants to take responsibility for anything, but don''t quote me.', 'Randy Glasbergen', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of four office workers standing around a large meeting table cluttered with papers, coffee cups, and a laptop. Each person is shrugging their shoulders with exaggerated puzzled or indifferent expressions, avoiding eye contact or looking away. One worker is scratching their head, another is nervously glancing at a paper. Above the table, a big speech bubble shows the quote: "I think our No. 1 problem is that nobody wants to take responsibility for anything, but don''t quote me." The office background includes a wall clock showing mid-afternoon and a whiteboard with vague charts labeled ''Project Status''. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the irony of the statement. The style is colorful, simple, and cartoonish, with clear expressions and body language focused on avoidance and non-commitment.'),
 (1847, 'Irony, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'I waited and waited, and when no message came, I knew it must have been from you.', 'Ashleigh Brilliant', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters texting each other on their smartphones. One character is sitting impatiently on a couch, looking at their phone with an exaggerated expression of hopeful anticipation mixed with slight frustration. The other character, slightly offscreen or hinted at, is shown with a mischievous or deadpan face holding their phone but ignoring it, clearly intentionally not replying. Around the first character are visual symbols of waiting—like a clock with the hands spinning rapidly, sweat drops on their forehead, and perhaps a growing pile of unopened messages or sticking notes saying ''No reply.'' The setting is casual and modern, like a cozy living room with a coffee table and a lamp. The overall tone is light and playful, emphasizing the irony that the lack of a message itself is the message.'),
 (1605, 'Irony, Quotes, Religion Humor', 'Christian: One who believes that the New Testament is a divinely inspired book admirably suited to the spiritual needs of his neighbor. One who follows the teachings of Christ in so far as they are not inconsistent with a life of sin.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly-looking man labeled ''Christian'' holding a large, glowing New Testament Bible. His expression is thoughtful with a slight smirk. Around him, a faint halo or light suggests inspiration from the book. In the background, there are subtle visual contrasts: a small devil’s tail poking out from behind him or playful little symbols representing ''sin'' such as a party hat, a bottle, or a mischievous grin on his face, hinting at a life of imperfection. The setting is simple and clear, maybe a park or a street corner, with neighbors looking on curiously and warmly. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features to emphasize the blend of reverence and playful irony in the joke.'),
 (1963, 'Irony, Quotes, Religion Humor', 'It ain''t the parts of the Bible that I can''t understand that bother me, it''s the parts that I do understand.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon showing a middle-aged person sitting in an armchair with a large open Bible resting on their lap. The person has a perplexed but subtly worried expression, scratching their head as if troubled by what they just read. Around them are floating cartoon-style thought bubbles containing simple iconic Bible images, like a rainbow, a burning bush, and a pair of tablets with commandments. The background suggests a cozy living room with a bookshelf, a lamp, and a small window showing a peaceful, sunny day outside. The overall tone is light and comic, emphasizing the irony of the person being less confused by complex sections and more unsettled by the understandable parts.'),
 (2004, 'Irony, Quotes, Religion Humor', 'It''s hard to be religious when certain people are never incinerated by bolts of lightning.', 'Calvin, Calvin and Hobbes comic strip by Bill Watterson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a sunny park with two people standing side by side. One person looks puzzled and slightly frustrated, holding a small open book labeled ''Religion''. Above them, in the bright blue sky, a clearly unlucky cartoon character with a big goofy smile stands under a storm cloud that''s raining lightning bolts, but none of the lightning bolts hit him—they comically miss or bounce off with little ''zap'' sound effects. Nearby, another character (the puzzled one) is looking at the sky with a skeptical expression, scratching their head as if questioning their beliefs. The setting is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and playful expressions to emphasize the irony of the joke, without any dark or violent overtones. The overall mood is funny and slightly absurd, focusing on the irony of lightning striking some people but not others despite the religious expectation implied by the joke.'),
 (2566, 'Irony, Quotes, Religious Humor, Social Humor', 'When it''s a question of money, everybody is of the same religion.', 'Voltaire', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of diverse people from different religions and cultural backgrounds standing together in a semi-circle. Each person is wearing clear traditional or religious attire — for example, a priest with a collar, a person in a turban, someone in a yarmulke, another wearing a hijab, and a monk in robes. In the center, they all reach into a large, communal piggy bank labeled ''Money,'' smiling and eagerly holding out coins and bills. Their facial expressions are cheerful and friendly, emphasizing unity despite differing backgrounds. The setting is light and simple, with a plain park bench or outdoor setting in the background, and cartoon-style bright colors. The focus is on the shared eagerness toward the money rather than their religious differences, highlighting the joke''s point about money uniting all beliefs. The overall tone is playful and non-offensive, with exaggerated but respectful caricatures of the characters.'),
 (1921, 'Irony, Quotes, Satire, Workplace', 'Ignorance is no obstacle to advancement.', 'Abraham Lincoln (1809-1865)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an office environment. Show a cheerful, oblivious office worker confidently climbing over a large obstacle labeled ''Ignorance.'' The obstacle can be a big colorful wall or barrier. The worker is gleefully holding a briefcase and wearing office attire, but clearly unaware of the difficulty or importance of the barrier. Around the worker, other coworkers look surprised or bewildered. Include typical office elements like desks, computers, and a motivational poster on the wall ironically saying ''Knowledge is Power.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to emphasize the irony of advancing despite ignorance.'),
 (2620, 'Irony, Quotes, Science Humor', 'You will be able to appreciate the influence of such an Engine on the future progress of science. I live in a country which is incapable of estimating it.', 'Charles Babbage', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a vintage-style science lab featuring a quirky, oversized steam engine with exaggerated gears and pipes puffing little clouds of smoke, labeled ''Engine of Progress.'' Nearby stands a frustrated, cartoonish scientist in a lab coat scratching his head and holding a scroll labeled ''Future of Science.'' In the background, a dull, gray country map on a wall with a frowning face and a big question mark above it, symbolizing the country''s failure to appreciate the engine''s value. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated expressions and clean lines to emphasize the scientist''s earnest hope contrasted with the country''s cluelessness.'),
 (2569, 'Irony, Quotes, Science Humor, Social Commentary', 'When the lay public rallies round to an idea that is denounced by distinguished but elderly scientists and supports the idea with great fervor and emotion, the distinguished but elderly scientists are then, after all, right.', 'Isaac Asimov', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a lecture hall. On one side, a group of elderly scientists with grey hair, glasses, and lab coats look grumpy and skeptical, holding old-fashioned clipboards and pointing at charts showing complex scientific formulas. On the other side, a lively, diverse crowd of enthusiastic laypeople cheer, wave banners, and hold signs supporting a bold, unconventional idea (represented by a large quirky lightbulb symbol). Above them, a thought bubble from one elderly scientist shows a smiling version of themselves with a trophy labeled ''Right all along.'' The overall style is bright and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between the solemn, serious scientists and the energetic, emotional crowd. The setting is light-hearted and non-confrontational, with both groups clearly visible to highlight the irony of the joke.'),
 (2331, 'Irony, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor, Workplace', 'The longer I am out of office, the more infallible I appear to myself.', 'Henry Kissinger', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting comfortably in a cozy home office or living room, surrounded by typical work items like a laptop, desk, and papers. The person has a relaxed, slightly smug expression, gazing confidently into a mirror or a thought bubble that shows a shining halo or golden aura around their head, symbolizing their growing self-importance. In the background, a calendar on the wall marks several days off with big colorful X''s or ''Out of Office'' notes. The overall atmosphere is light-hearted, with warm colors and playful details like a coffee mug labeled ''Best Employee'' and a small plant on the desk. The style should be cartoonish and friendly, emphasizing the irony of someone becoming more convinced of their own infallibility the longer they stay away from work.'),
 (2364, 'Irony, Quotes, Social Humor', 'The penalty of success is to be bored by the people who used to snub you.', 'Nancy, Lady Astor', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a successful-looking person standing on a small podium or stage, dressed in sharp business or celebrity attire with a confident smile. Around the person, a mix of two groups of caricatured people. One group is approaching eagerly and excitedly, dressed in casual clothes and holding small gifts or autograph books, clearly former snubbers turned admirers. The other group is standing off to the side looking bored or uninterested, with crossed arms and yawns, representing the person''s old circle who once ignored them. The background is simple and bright, maybe with a subtle spotlight on the successful figure to emphasize the ''success'' theme. Include visual exaggerations like shining stars, little hearts or sparkle effects near the eager crowd, and muted gray tones or clouds over the bored group for contrast. The overall style should be lighthearted, playful, and cartoonish, highlighting the irony of changing social dynamics after success without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (1965, 'Irony, Quotes, Social Humor, Technology Humor', 'It has become appallingly obvious that our technology has exceeded our humanity.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of people completely absorbed by their smartphones and gadgets, with exaggerated blank or robotic expressions on their faces. Some have their heads lowered, eyes glued to screens, typing or swiping. In the background, a robot or futuristic AI stands looking confused or disappointed, symbolizing technology "overtaking" humanity. Include small comedic details like a person trip-walking into a streetlamp because they’re distracted by their phone or a dog trying to get attention that nobody notices. The setting should be in a modern urban park or street, highlighting the contrast between natural humans and cold technology. Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the irony and humor in the cartoon style.'),
 (2243, 'Irony, Quotes, Social Humor, Workplace', 'Some people have so much respect for their superiors they have none left for themselves.', 'Peter McArthur', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office environment. In the foreground, a sad-looking employee stands slouched at their desk, looking tired and deflated, with a small thought bubble showing a tiny version of themselves looking sad. On the other side of the desk, a large, proud boss figure with an exaggeratedly tall hat labeled ''Superior'' stands confidently, possibly receiving a bouquet of flowers or applause from several other employees in the background. The room has typical office elements: a computer, paperwork stacked on the desk, a coffee cup, and motivational posters on the walls. The employee''s desk is noticeably empty of any kind of personal decoration, contrasting with the decorated area around the boss. The cartoon style is colorful and exaggerated, emphasizing the difference in energy and spirit between the overly respectful employee and the proud superior, with a lighthearted and playful tone that captures the irony of the joke without any negativity.'),
 (1818, 'Irony, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'I have learned silence from the talkative, toleration from the intolerant, and kindness from the unkind; yet, strange, I am ungrateful to these teachers.', 'Kahlil Gibran', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a thoughtful person sitting cross-legged in the center, looking slightly puzzled and confused. Around them are three character figures that represent the ''teachers'': one very chatty person with a big open mouth and animated gestures to symbolize talkativeness; another person frowning with arms crossed, clearly showing intolerance; and a third character with an annoyed or grumpy expression representing unkindness. Each teacher should have a small schoolteacher-like attribute, such as a blackboard, pointer, or book, to indicate their ''teaching'' role. The main character’s expression should convey irony or conflicted emotions to emphasize their ungratefulness despite learning from these difficult sources. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions in a friendly cartoon style to keep the tone light and humorous without any negative or harmful imagery. The background should be simple, maybe a classroom or plain park bench setting to keep focus on the characters and their interaction.'),
 (1743, 'Irony, Quotes, Wit', 'He has all of the virtues I like, and none of vices I admire.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters having a casual conversation in a park setting. One character is speaking with a sly smile and a raised eyebrow, while the other listens with a puzzled or amused expression. The speaker is gesturing toward a third character standing a little apart, who looks quirky with exaggerated traits suggesting a mix of virtues and vices—perhaps wearing angel wings on one side and devil horns on the other, but in a playful, non-threatening way. Include simple trees and a park bench as background objects to set the scene. The atmosphere should be light-hearted and comical, emphasizing irony rather than any conflict.'),
 (1974, 'Irony, Quotes, Wit', 'It is dangerous to be sincere unless you are also stupid.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side. The first character looks very earnest and sincere, with wide, serious eyes, a hand-on-heart pose, and a small speech bubble with a heart symbol to represent sincerity. The second character stands next to them looking carefree and slightly silly, with a goofy smile, perhaps sticking out their tongue or crossing their eyes playfully. Above the scene, the joke text ''It is dangerous to be sincere unless you are also stupid'' is written in a playful font. The setting is simple, like a park or a sidewalk, with minimal background details such as a bench and a tree to keep focus on the characters and the contrast between their expressions and body language. The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated cartoonish to emphasize the humor without any negativity or offense.'),
 (2577, 'Irony, Quotes, Wit, Workplace', 'When your work speaks for itself, don''t interrupt.', 'Henry J. Kaiser', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in an office. In the center, show a confident worker sitting at a desk with papers, a laptop, and a coffee mug. The worker looks calm and satisfied. Emerging from the laptop screen or stacks of paperwork, depict cartoon-style speech bubbles made of tiny tools, graphs, and briefcase icons to symbolize ''work speaking.'' Nearby, a second character, perhaps a curious coworker or manager, is about to interrupt with an open mouth and raised finger but pauses, looking surprised or thoughtful. The room should have typical office elements like a desk plant, a clock on the wall, and motivational posters. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated with bright colors and expressive faces to emphasize the irony that the work itself communicates the message, and the interruption is unwanted. No violence or negativity—just a funny, relatable office moment.'),
 (3071, 'Irony, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'If at first you do succeed, try to hide your astonishment.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a surprised person standing in the middle, their eyes wide open and mouth hanging slightly agape in astonishment. The person should be drawn in a comical, exaggerated style with raised eyebrows, hands partly covering their mouth, and a few sweat drops to emphasize their surprise. Surrounding the character are subtle success symbols like a gold trophy on a pedestal nearby, confetti falling, and a small banner overhead reading ''Success!''. The background is bright and cheerful with simple shapes showing an informal setting, such as a small podium or stage to hint they''ve just succeeded in something. Include a thought bubble above the person’s head with a humorous text reading: ''Wait, I actually did it...?''. Ensure the scene captures the mix of pride and disbelief in a light-hearted, friendly cartoon style suitable for all ages.'),
 (2854, 'Irony, Relatable, Social Humor, Unknown', 'Fame: When you dominate the conversation and you''re not there.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set at a party or social gathering. In the foreground, a group of 3-4 people are animatedly talking to each other, laughing and gesturing excitedly. None of them look like the person being talked about. In a faded or ghostly bubble or thought cloud above them, an image of a single person appears, looking clueless or surprised, clearly not present in the scene. The background should show a casual party setting with drinks and snacks on a table, subtle decorations, and people mingling. The overall tone is light and playful, emphasizing the idea that someone is being talked about as if they are the center of attention, but they are not actually present. The style is simple, colorful cartoon with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor of dominating a conversation while absent.'),
 (2724, 'Irony, Relatable, Unknown, Workplace', 'Cooperation is doing with a smile what you have to do anyhow.', NULL, 'A cheerful office scene in a humorous cartoon style. Show an employee at a desk with a big, exaggerated smile plastered on their face. The employee is surrounded by piles of paperwork, a computer, and a coffee cup, clearly overwhelmed but still smiling. Nearby, a boss or coworker is pointing to a long ''To-Do'' list on a whiteboard labeled ''Must Do Tasks,'' indicating all the unavoidable chores. Include a subtle clock showing late afternoon to emphasize the feeling of a long day. The overall vibe is light-hearted, highlighting the irony of pretending happiness while doing obligatory work.'),
 (1224, 'Irony, Relatable, Workplace', 'The trouble with being punctual is that nobody''s there to appreciate it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing alone in front of a closed door labeled ''Meeting Room'' with a clock on the wall clearly showing an early time (e.g., 8:00 am). The person looks confused and a bit disappointed, glancing around to see that the hallway and doorway are completely empty. Include small details like a watch on the person''s wrist and a calendar or notice board nearby indicating the meeting time is later. The setting is an office hallway with bright, simple colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the loneliness and irony of being the first and only one present.'),
 (1225, 'Irony, Relatable, Workplace', 'The unwilling, led by the unqualified, doing the impossible for the ungrateful.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small group of office workers struggling to carry a giant, oddly shaped, heavy object labeled ''Impossible Task.'' The workers look reluctant, with exaggerated expressions of exhaustion and frustration. Leading them is a boss figure confidently pointing forward but with a clueless, confused expression, wearing a suit slightly too big or crooked. Around them, other people (the ''ungrateful'') stand casually with crossed arms or indifferent faces, some taking selfies or checking phones, ignoring the effort happening. The setting is a typical bland office hallway with cubicles and motivational posters ironically saying ''Teamwork!'' and ''You Can Do It!''. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated emotions, bright colors, and simple line work to emphasize the humor of unwilling people being led by an unqualified leader to do impossible work for unappreciative onlookers.'),
 (1226, 'Irony, Shopping Jokes', 'Whatever you spend a fortune on today will be on sale tomorrow.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a brightly colored, busy shopping mall. The main focus is a frustrated shopper standing in front of a large store window, looking at an expensive item like a flashy gadget or designer handbag with a price tag labeled ''Full Price $999''. The shopper has a comically exaggerated sad expression, scratching their head or holding their empty wallet. Behind them, a store employee cheerfully points to a big sign outside the store that says ''Sale Tomorrow! 50% OFF'' in bold, colorful letters with little stars and arrows. Add a calendar on the wall showing today''s date with an arrow pointing to tomorrow''s date, marked with a big red circle and a ''SALE'' sticker. Include some humorous small details like a confused pet dog dragging a shopping bag, or a price tag slipping off the item to emphasize the joke. The overall style should be playful and exaggerated with bright colors and clear, expressive characters to highlight the irony that what you buy expensive today drops in price just tomorrow.'),
 (1227, 'Irony, Sports Humor', 'The object of golf is to play the least amount of golf.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a bright, sunny golf course with green rolling hills and a clear blue sky. In the foreground, depict a cheerful, slightly confused golfer in classic golf attire (polo shirt, cap, golf glove) holding a golf club upside down, looking at a scorecard with a puzzled expression. Around him, show several golf balls scattered very close to the tee, some barely hit. Nearby, a golf cart is parked, with a flagstick standing in a hole not far from the player. Add a thought bubble above the golfer’s head with a playful text saying, "The less I play, the better my score!" The overall vibe should be light and whimsical, emphasizing the ironic statement that in golf, doing the least amount of playing can be the goal. The style is cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to highlight the joke’s humor.'),
 (1228, 'Irony, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs expect it to work the first time. They fix it when it doesn''t, but they don''t like it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a tech repair shop or a small office. At the center, a frustrated but determined-looking technician, wearing a shirt with a small ''Tech Support'' logo, sits at a cluttered desk filled with various gadgets like a laptop, smartphone, and tangled wires. The technician is staring at a computer screen with an error message or a broken device in front of them. Behind them, a thought bubble shows a smiling version of the same technician imagining everything working perfectly on the first try, with green check marks and a thumbs-up. The background includes posters with funny tech-related sayings like ''Expect it to work the first time!'' or ''We fix it when it breaks.'' The overall tone is light-hearted and funny, focusing on the contrast between expectations and reality in tech work, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comic effect.'),
 (2869, 'Irony, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'Forgive your enemies but don''t ever forget their names.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a cheerful, wise-looking old man sitting on a park bench with a notebook and pen. He is smiling kindly but has a quirky look as he writes down names on a long scroll labeled ''Enemies List.'' Nearby, a small mischievous cartoon devil with a notepad is peeking over his shoulder, looking curious. The background is a sunny park with trees and birds. The man is dressed in casual clothes with glasses and a friendly expression, emphasizing forgiveness but the act of remembering. The overall tone is lighthearted and amusing, capturing the humor of forgiving but keeping track of enemies'' names.'),
 (1513, 'Jewelry Humor, Puns, Quotes, Science Humor', 'All that glitters has a high refractive index.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a shiny, sparkling gemstone resting on a simple velvet display cushion. Above it, show a bright light source shining down, causing exaggerated, colorful light beams and sparkles to radiate from the gem. Nearby, a scientist or jeweler character wearing thick glasses and a lab coat examines the gem with a large magnifying glass, looking both intrigued and amused. Include a simple background of a jewelry shop or a lab with charts of optical properties pinned to the wall (e.g., diagrams of light bending or refraction). The overall tone should be light and fun, emphasizing the ''scientific sparkle'' joke without any harsh detail. Use bold outlines, bright colors, and an expressive, cartoonish style to enhance the humor and make the refractive index pun visually clear.'),
 (2641, 'Jobs, Programming Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'A programmer lost three of his fingers in a tragic accident. While getting it treated he asked the doctor ''Will I be able to type with this hand?'' Doc: ''Maybe... but I wouldn''t count on it!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a simple doctor''s office. A programmer sits on an exam table looking worried but slightly hopeful. His right hand is prominently shown with three fingers obviously missing, bandaged or in a medical glove covering the stumps humorously. The doctor, wearing a white coat and glasses, stands next to him holding a clipboard and giving a dry, slightly skeptical look. In the background, typical medical posters and an anatomy chart hang on the wall, adding to the clinic setting. On the programmer''s desk nearby, there is a laptop with code visible on the screen to emphasize his profession. Both characters have exaggerated cartoon facial expressions: the programmer hopeful and the doctor deadpan. The scene should have bright colors and clear outlines, emphasizing the comic and lighthearted tone without any dark or disturbing elements.'),
 (2945, 'Jobs, Pun, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'How many optometrists does it take to change a light bulb? 1 or 2? 1... or 2?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy, well-lit optometrist''s office. The main character is an optometrist standing on a small step stool, holding a light bulb and trying to screw it into a ceiling light fixture. Nearby, a second optometrist is peeking around the corner, wearing thick-rimmed glasses and holding an eye chart. Above them, the ceiling light is half lit, flickering slightly, creating an unclear illumination. Add a wall chart with letters in different sizes and an eye exam chair to set the scene clearly as an optometrist’s clinic. Both optometrists appear puzzled, glancing at each other with indecision, as if both are unsure whether one or two optometrists are needed for the simple task. Use expressive faces with raised eyebrows and small sweat drops to enhance the comedic uncertainty. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and playful with exaggerated cartoon features to match the joke’s light-hearted nature.'),
 (1235, 'Jobs, Pun, Word Play', 'I want a job cleaning mirrors. It''s a job I can see myself doing.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful person holding a large window squeegee in one hand and a spray bottle labeled ''Mirror Cleaner'' in the other. They are standing proudly in front of a giant mirror that reflects their smiling face clearly. The person is dressed in casual cleaning attire with gloves and an apron. The background is a simple room with shiny, spotless mirrors on the walls to emphasize their job. Add a thought bubble above the person''s head with the pun ''It''s a job I can see myself doing.'' The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated cartoonish to capture the lighthearted, pun-based humor without any violence or inappropriate elements. The overall mood is optimistic and playful, focusing on the pun about seeing oneself in a mirror-cleaning job.'),
 (1233, 'Jobs, Pun, Workplace', 'I used to work at a calendar factory, but I got fired cuz I took a couple of days off', NULL, 'Draw a cheerful cartoon factory building labeled ''Calendar Factory'' with a big sign out front. Outside, show a frustrated but funny-looking worker in factory attire holding a calendar with several date pages torn off or scattered around him on the ground. The worker looks sheepish or surprised. Nearby, a stern but comical boss character stands with arms crossed, pointing at the missing calendar pages like they’re evidence. The setting should be colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the pun—no one looks angry or mean, just playfully annoyed. Include a conveyor belt inside the factory transporting large calendar pages or stacks of paper with dates, emphasizing the ''calendar factory'' concept. The style is a humorous cartoon with clean lines and bright colors, suitable for a light joke about taking days off at work.'),
 (1250, 'Knock Knock, Patriotic Humor, Pun, Word Play', 'Why are there no knock-knock jokes about ''Merica? \nCuz Freedom Rings', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a door with a large, comically oversized doorbell shaped like a golden liberty bell. The door has stars and stripes painted on it to resemble the American flag. Standing next to the door is a smiling, cartoonish character dressed in red, white, and blue, looking triumphant as they press the big freedom bell doorbell. Around the character are subtle sound waves or comic-style ''RING!'' text emanating from the bell to emphasize the pun. The background is simple, maybe with a few fireworks or a waving American flag, to reinforce the patriotic theme. The style is playful and exaggerated, clearly conveying the joke about ''Merica and the phrase ''Freedom Rings'' visually without any elements of violence or offense.'),
 (1248, 'Knock Knock, Word Play', 'KK/WT: Spell ? (spell who?) : W H O', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters engaged in a playful conversation. Character 1 is holding a piece of paper or a small chalkboard with a question mark (?) on it, looking confused and curious. Character 2, with a cheeky smile, is pointing to the word ''WHO'' spelled out boldly in large, colorful letters floating whimsically in the air between them. The style is simple and exaggerated, emphasizing the wordplay and confusion. The background is minimalistic, maybe a classroom or casual setting, to keep focus on the interaction and the spelled word. Both characters should have expressive faces showcasing the joke’s pun effect.'),
 (2599, 'Language, Math Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'You can not apply mathematics as long as words still becloud reality.', 'Hermann Weyl', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a puzzled person sitting at a cluttered desk filled with open math textbooks, papers with complex equations, and a large question mark hovering over their head. The person''s face should show confusion and frustration. Around them, floating above the desk, are translucent speech bubbles filled with vague, jumbled words and abstract phrases, visually ''beclouding'' the area. The background should be a simple classroom or study room with a blackboard covered in messy scribbles combining words and math symbols that merge confusingly together. The style should be light and cartoonish, emphasizing the clash between clear math formulas and unclear, foggy language, evoking the joke’s theme that unclear words obstruct applying clear mathematical logic.'),
 (2516, 'Language, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'We dissect nature along lines laid down by our native language. Language is not simply a reporting device for experience but a defining framework for it.', 'Benjamin Whorf', 'A humorous cartoon showing a group of animals and plants arranged neatly on a giant, colorful map that looks like a language chart. The map is divided into segments labeled with different linguistic categories like ''colors,'' ''shapes,'' ''actions,'' and ''emotions.'' In the foreground, a cheerful human scientist or explorer in casual clothing holds a large magnifying glass over the map, thoughtfully examining a flower that is partially colored and shaped differently depending on the segment it crosses. Around the scene, floating word bubbles contain simple words from various languages illustrating how they label parts of nature differently. The background is a sunny outdoor setting with a blue sky, trees, and some curious animals peeking at the map, adding a playful vibe. The overall tone is light and whimsical, emphasizing the idea that language frames how we ''slice'' and understand nature, as if nature is shaped by linguistic boundaries rather than just physical ones.'),
 (2030, 'Language, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Language is not only the vehicle of thought, it is a great and efficient instrument in thinking.', 'Humphrey Davy', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a brain sitting in the driver''s seat of a vintage car shaped like a large speech bubble. The brain is wearing aviator goggles and a scarf, looking confidently ahead as if driving. The car''s wheels are illustrated as letters and punctuation marks rolling on a road made of an open book''s pages. Around the car, small floating thought bubbles contain symbols like question marks, light bulbs, and scribbled lines to suggest thinking and ideas. The background is bright and cheerful with a clear sky, emphasizing movement and mental activity. The overall style is playful, colorful, and exaggerated to create a fun and imaginative portrayal of language and thought working together as a vehicle and tool for thinking.'),
 (1901, 'Language, Programming Humor, Puns, Quotes', 'If you can''t write it down in English, you can''t code it.', 'Peter Halpern', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated programmer sitting at a cluttered desk. The programmer is scratching their head with one hand, holding a pencil in the other, staring at a computer screen filled with confusing code made up of random symbols and foreign characters (like Chinese, Arabic, or Cyrillic letters). Around the desk are scattered paper sheets filled with scribbled notes in various unreadable scripts. A thought bubble above the programmer''s head displays an English sentence written neatly, symbolizing the idea that clear English is needed. The room has a playful, colorful tech vibe, with a coffee cup, keyboard, and a simple motivational poster on the wall that says "Code in English!" in bright letters. The overall tone should be light-hearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the humor of struggling to code when the instructions are not in English.'),
 (1517, 'Language, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'Always and never are two words you should always remember never to use.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly, slightly confused-looking person standing in front of a large, colorful chalkboard. The chalkboard has the words ''Always'' and ''Never'' written in big, bold letters, each with a red circle and a line crossing through them, as if they are forbidden. The person is holding a giant, oversized dictionary or grammar book open, with a thoughtful expression, scratching their chin. Around the character, there are playful visual cues like question marks floating in the air and a small calendar with the words ''Always'' and ''Never'' scribbled on it and crossed out. The background is simple, classroom-like, with a few scattered papers and a clock on the wall. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with vibrant colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the pun and irony in the joke.'),
 (3009, 'Language, Pun, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'I just learned sign language - it''s really handy', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing next to a large, exaggerated sign language book or a giant hand making a clear sign language gesture (like the ''thumbs up'' or ''OK'' sign). The person is smiling confidently and giving a playful thumbs-up with one hand while holding the book or pointing to the hand symbol with the other. Around them, floating little comic-style icons symbolize both hands and small tools like hammers and wrenches, playing on the pun of ''handy.'' The background is simple, with a bright, friendly color palette to emphasize the lighthearted mood. The style is light and cartoonish, with bold lines and expressive features to enhance the joke''s pun about sign language and being ''handy.'' No complex background or other characters needed.'),
 (1668, 'Language, Quotes, Relatable, Word Play', 'Even if you do learn to speak correct English, whom are you going to speak it to?', 'Clarence Darrow', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing alone in the middle of a quiet park or urban street, looking slightly puzzled or thoughtful. The person is dressed casually, holding an English grammar book titled ''Correct English'' in one hand. Around them are groups of diverse people chatting in casual, informal, or slang-heavy speech bubbles, clearly not paying attention to or understanding formal, perfect grammar. Some speech bubbles show informal language or slang with smiley faces. The background includes typical city elements like benches, trees, a streetlamp, and a distant cafe or bookstore to set a relaxed, everyday setting. The expression on the person''s face conveys bemusement, capturing the essence of the question: if you master perfect English, who is really going to understand or appreciate it? The style is light-hearted, bright, and colorful with exaggerated, cartoonish facial expressions to emphasize humor and social awkwardness rather than serious or academic tone.'),
 (2961, 'Language, Science Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I before E has been disproved by science', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a classroom or lab setting where a quirky scientist in a white lab coat and oversized glasses holds a chemistry flask bubbling with colorful liquids. Behind the scientist is a large blackboard with the phrase ''I before E'' written in big letters, crossed out boldly with a big red X. Around the blackboard are funny examples of words breaking the rule, like ''science'', ''weird'', and ''neighbor'', with little comic-style bursts indicating confusion or surprise. The scientist looks excited and triumphant, as if they''ve just made a groundbreaking discovery disproving the famous spelling rule. The style is playful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the humor and absurdity of treating a spelling rule like a scientific law. The scene includes some books, a periodic table poster twisted humorously to illustrate letters instead of elements, and maybe a confused cartoon student taking notes.'),
 (2334, 'Law Humor, Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes', 'The man for whom law exists -- the man of forms, the Conservative, is a tame man.', 'Henry David Thoreau', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a well-dressed man symbolizing a ''Conservative'' standing confidently holding a giant stack of legal forms and documents. He should be wearing a neat suit with a conservative tie, glasses, and have a calm, composed demeanor. Around him, place various law-related items like a large law book, a gavel resting on a desk, and a scale of justice. The background can include a simple courtroom or office setting with a neatly organized bookshelf. The man looks very orderly and ''tame,'' maybe with a subtle smile, to emphasize the joke''s idea that law exists for someone who is methodical and restrained. The overall tone should be light and intellectual with clear cartoon exaggeration on the stacked papers and the man’s tidy appearance to keep it funny and charming without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2021, 'Law Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'Justice is incidental to law and order.', 'J. Edgar Hoover', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a courtroom setting. Center stage is a judge sitting behind a large bench, wearing classic robes and a gavel in hand, looking slightly bewildered or indifferent. In the foreground, a police officer stands confidently next to a black-and-white police car labeled ''Law & Order'' in bold letters. The officer looks proud but somewhat oblivious to the concept of justice. On the judge''s bench, an old-fashioned scale of justice is present but tipped heavily to one side with a large pile of paperwork labeled ''Law & Order'' weighing it down, while the smaller side labeled ''Justice'' barely has anything. The courtroom audience appears confused or uninterested. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the contrast between justice and law & order as concepts. No violence or political symbols are shown.'),
 (2924, 'Lawyer Humor, Legal Humor, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'Hell hath no fury like the lawyer of a woman scorned.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an angry female lawyer standing resolutely in a courtroom. She wears a sharp business suit and glasses, holding a legal brief in one hand and pointing sternly with the other. In front of her, a visibly nervous man sits at the defendant''s table, surrounded by stacks of papers and legal documents. The courtroom background includes a judge''s bench with a bemused judge watching the scene, and a gallery with a few spectators whispering and reacting with surprise. Above or behind the lawyer, a playful, stylized flame or aura shaped like a heart with spiky edges lightly glows to symbolize ''fury'' mixed with the idea of being ''scorned.'' The overall tone is light and exaggerated to emphasize the pun in the phrase "Hell hath no fury like the lawyer of a woman scorned," blending legal seriousness with comedic heat.'),
 (1254, 'Lawyer Humor, Politics, Workplace', 'LAWYER: A professional advocate hired to bend the law on behalf of a paying client; for this reason considered the most suitable background for entry into politics.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a lawyer standing confidently in a courtroom. The lawyer is dressed in a suit with a briefcase labeled ''Law Books'' and is smiling slyly. Behind the lawyer, there is a scale of justice that is noticeably tipped heavily to one side, humorously implying imbalance. In the background, a large open door labeled ''Politics'' is shown with a red carpet leading from the courtroom to the door. A few shadowy figures dressed in suits stand near the door, welcoming the lawyer with outstretched hands. The courtroom has typical elements like judge''s bench, witness stand, and spectators, but exaggerated and whimsical in style for comedic effect. The overall mood is light, playful, and ironic, emphasizing the joke’s commentary on lawyers often entering politics because of their skill at ''bending the law.'''),
 (1427, 'Lawyer Humor, Pun, Quotes, Workplace', 'A lawyer''s opinion is worth nothing unless paid for.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a lawyer sitting confidently behind a large wooden desk in a typical office setting. The lawyer is sharply dressed in a classic suit and tie, with a smug but friendly expression, holding a neatly stacked pile of paperwork labeled ''Legal Opinions.'' On the opposite side of the desk stands a client, looking surprised and slightly confused, holding out an empty wallet. A speech bubble above the lawyer reads, ''A lawyer''s opinion is worth nothing unless paid for.'' The office walls have framed law diplomas and a clock showing mid-afternoon. Include subtle humor details like a ''Bill Me Later'' sign on the desk and a gold pen holder shaped like a dollar sign. The overall style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s punchline about the value of paid legal advice.'),
 (3188, 'Lawyer Humor, Pun, Steven Wright, Word Play', '99% of lawyers give the rest a bad name.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene set outside a courthouse. In the foreground, a group of cartoonish lawyers is gathered, looking proud and confident. Behind them, a single lawyer stands apart, with a slightly sheepish or bad-guy look, wearing a suit with an exaggeratedly large price tag or a ''shady'' aura, to represent the ''rest'' giving lawyers a bad name. The courthouse building is visible in the background with a big, classic columned facade and a sign reading ''Lawyers'' Association.'' Include a few whimsical details, like a briefcase overflowing with law books and a gavel leaning against a bench. The overall style should be playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the joke’s pun on reputation without any negativity or hostility.'),
 (1428, 'Leadership Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A leader in the Democratic Party is a boss, in the Republican Party he is a leader.', 'Harry Truman', 'A humorous cartoon split into two panels side-by-side. On the left panel, depict a bustling, chaotic office labeled ''Democratic Party'' with a bossy-looking character standing on a desk. This character should have an exaggerated, somewhat impatient expression, pointing a finger downwards while giving orders to employees who look overwhelmed or juggling papers and phones. Include elements like a messy desk, papers flying, and stressed workers. On the right panel, show a calm, confident character labeled ''Republican Party'' standing in front of a group of attentive followers with hands relaxed by their sides or gesturing inspirationally. The scene should convey respect and leadership without any hostility. Background details like flags or party symbols can be subtle and stylized to avoid political bias. The overall style is lighthearted, cartoonish, and exaggerated for comic effect, focusing on the contrast between ''boss'' and ''leader'' without negativity or conflict.'),
 (1416, 'Life, Marriage Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'A happy marriage is a long conversation which always seems too short', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an elderly couple seated comfortably on a cozy living room couch. Both are smiling warmly, engaged in animated conversation. They’re leaning slightly towards each other, with speech bubbles containing little symbols like hearts, musical notes, and small clock icons to symbolize the joy and the fleeting feeling of time. The background features a warm fireplace, framed family photos on the walls, and a small coffee table with tea cups and a clock showing time moving quickly. The overall mood is lighthearted and peaceful, emphasizing connection and laughter without any exaggeration or harm, all rendered in a clean, friendly cartoon style with bright, cheerful colors.'),
 (1255, 'Life, Money Humor, Philosophy', 'Money wouldn''t be so important if everybody didn''t want some.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a diverse group of cartoon characters standing in a queue, all reaching eagerly toward a large, shiny coin or stack of bills floating just out of reach in the air. The coin is exaggerated in size and glowing to emphasize its importance. Characters vary in appearance; some look desperate, others greedy or hopeful, with comical exaggerated expressions like wide eyes and extended hands. In the background, a sign reads ''Money Here!'' with an arrow pointing toward the coin. The overall mood is lighthearted, with bright colors and playful details, such as one character holding an empty wallet and another counting coins with a puzzled look. The scene captures the universal idea that money is coveted by everyone because everyone wants some.'),
 (1426, 'Life, Money Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'A large income is the best recipe for happiness I ever heard of.', 'Jane Austin', 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person in casual clothes holding a large, overflowing cooking pot labeled ''Happiness.'' Instead of food, the pot is filled with dollar bills and coins sparkling in the air. Around the person, utensils like a wooden spoon and whisk lie on a kitchen counter, and recipe books with titles like ''Happiness Cookbook'' and ''Life Recipes'' are stacked nearby. The background is a bright kitchen setting with whimsical details like framed pictures on the wall showing smiley faces and dollar signs. The person is smiling widely, as if proud of their unconventional recipe. The overall atmosphere is playful and light-hearted, emphasizing the pun between a ''recipe'' and ''income'' without any negativity.'),
 (1905, 'Life, Money Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'If you had your life to live over again -- you''d need more money.', 'Construction Digest', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a middle-aged person sitting at a simple kitchen table, looking wistfully at a large, old-fashioned calendar labeled ''Life.'' On the table are scattered bills, coins, and an empty wallet. Behind them, a thought bubble shows a younger version of themselves dressed in casual clothes, but holding an absurdly large bag overflowing with money. The younger self looks cheerful yet puzzled as if learning an important, ironic lesson. The kitchen background is cozy but modest, with a clock on the wall and a window letting in daylight. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the idea of wishing for more money if life could be done over, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (1256, 'Life, Money Humor, Workplace', 'Nothing puts a man deeper in debt than a small raise in his salary.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing on one side of a giant balance scale. On the scale''s left side, labeled ''Salary Raise,'' there is a small, shiny coin stack. On the scale''s right side, labeled ''Debt,'' there is a towering, comically large pile of bills, credit cards, and IOUs towering up several times higher than the man. The man looks puzzled and slightly worried, scratching his head while staring at the imbalance. Around him, various everyday items like a car, house, and shopping bags with price tags emphasize expenses. The background is simple and bright, with an office clock on the wall to hint that he just got a raise at work. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated to highlight how a small salary raise ironically leads to a much bigger debt.'),
 (2567, 'Life, Motivational Humor, Optimism Humor, Quotes', 'When one door closes another door opens; but we so often look so long and so regretfully upon the closed door, that we do not see the ones which open for us.', 'Alexander Graham Bell', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a character standing in front of two doors inside a cheerful, colorful room. One door on the left is clearly closed, with the character staring at it longingly and looking sad or regretful, maybe with a little thought bubble showing a missed opportunity or something closed off. To the right, another door is wide open, brightly lit with beams of light shining through, revealing a bunch of fun objects like balloons, a party hat, or a treasure chest inside, symbolizing new opportunities. The character is oblivious to the open door, still facing the closed one. The background should be simple and bright, focusing on the contrast between the closed and open doors for a visually funny and relatable effect, emphasizing the idea of missing opportunities by fixating on what’s gone.'),
 (2384, 'Life, Motivational Humor, Quotes, Self-Improvement Humor', 'The sooner you make your first five thousand mistakes the sooner you will be able to correct them.', 'Kimon Nicolaides', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a young person standing proudly at the start line of a race track labeled ''Mistake Marathon.'' In front of them are five large, comically exaggerated obstacles labeled ''Mistake #1,'' ''Mistake #2,'' up to ''Mistake #5,'' each with visible signs of damage like dents, cracks, or band-aids. The character wears running shoes, a determined expression, and a sweatband, ready to dash through and ''make'' these mistakes. Behind the finish line, a cheerful coach or mentor holds a clipboard labeled ''Correction Zone,'' smiling and giving a thumbs-up. The background is bright and cheerful, with colorful banners saying ''Keep Going!'' and small cartoonish clouds shaped like question marks and light bulbs to signify learning and thinking. The style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions and rounded shapes to emphasize the humor and positivity of the message.'),
 (2407, 'Life, Motivational Humor, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'The will to win is useless without the will to prepare.', 'Thoreau', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a sports context. On the left, a confident athlete is standing relaxed with arms crossed and a smug smile, wearing a medal or sportswear, representing ''will to win.'' On the right, a tired but focused athlete is seen surrounded by preparation tools: a checklist, water bottles, training gear, and open books or manuals about training. This character looks determined and busy practicing or studying, sweat drops visible to emphasize effort. The setting is a sports field or gym with a scoreboard in the background showing a zero or empty score to indicate no results yet. The caption above reads, ''The will to win is useless without the will to prepare,'' emphasizing the contrast between wishful thinking and hard work. The style should be light, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor without any aggressive or negative tone.'),
 (2616, 'Life, Motivational Humor, Quotes, Sports Humor', 'You miss 100 percent of the shots you don''t take.', 'Wayne Gretzky', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a basketball court with a single character standing, looking slightly confused but determined. The character is holding a basketball but hesitating to shoot. Around them, exaggerated visual elements emphasize the concept of missing shots they don''t take: numerous basketballs scattered on the ground marked with big red Xs, while a scoreboard in the background shows 0 for missed shots and 0 for made shots. The basketball hoop is visible with the net swaying gently, as if inviting a shot. The character''s thought bubble says the quote: ''You miss 100 percent of the shots you don''t take.'' The overall style is light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish with rounded lines and expressive features on the character to emphasize indecision and motivation.'),
 (2460, 'Life, Motivational Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Thorough preparation makes its own luck.', 'Joe Poyer', 'A humorous cartoon showing a person dressed like a classic detective (hat, trench coat) standing very confidently in front of a table covered with organized items: a detailed map, a crystal ball, a lucky rabbit''s foot, and a notebook labeled ''Plans.'' Around the detective are symbols of chance and luck, like four-leaf clovers, horseshoes, and dice, but hilariously ignored. The character wears a big grin, holding a magnifying glass over their perfectly prepared notes and seemingly shaking hands with a cartoonish anthropomorphic ''Luck'' character — a smiling green four-leaf clover with eyes and arms. The background is simple and light, enhancing focus on the character and items, emphasizing that solid preparation is what conjures ''luck.'' The overall style is bright, cheerful, and exaggerated for comic effect, reminiscent of classic detective cartoons but with a playful twist on the concept of luck versus preparation.'),
 (2532, 'Life, Motivational Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Well done is better than well said.', 'Benjamin Franklin (1706-1790)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side to represent the contrast between ''well said'' and ''well done.'' On the left, a character dressed in a suit and tie holds a microphone confidently, clearly delivering a speech or lecture, with animated speech bubbles showing fancy words and phrases. On the right, a worker character wearing casual clothes and a tool belt is actively building or fixing something, such as assembling a wooden chair or painting a wall, with tools in hand. Above them, a banner displays the text ''Well done is better than well said'' in playful lettering. The background should be simple and bright, with lighthearted expressions on both characters’ faces. The cartoon style should exaggerate the difference in action versus talk, emphasizing the idea that actions speak louder than words in a fun and engaging way. Include small props like a clock or calendar to subtly hint at time passing as the worker gets things accomplished while the speaker is still talking.'),
 (1257, 'Life, Motivational, Philosophy Humor', 'The greatest use of life is to spend it on something that will outlast it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person planting a large, vibrant tree labeled ''Life''s Legacy.'' The person is watering the tree with a watering can while smiling proudly. In the background, smaller trees and saplings are visible, representing things that outlast a single life. Above the scene, a sunny sky with a clock subtly blending into a sun symbolizes the passage of time. The style is lighthearted and colorful with exaggerated, friendly facial expressions and rounded shapes to emphasize positivity and longevity, avoiding any violence or negativity.'),
 (2048, 'Life, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Life was meant to be lived, and curiosity must be kept alive. One must never, for whatever reason, turn his back on life.', 'Eleanor Roosevelt', 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a cheerful character standing at a scenic crossroads in life, with a winding path leading into a bright, lively landscape filled with vibrant flowers, butterflies, and sunshine. The character is looking forward with a curious and eager expression, holding a magnifying glass in one hand symbolizing curiosity. Behind the character, a shadowy but non-threatening figure labeled ''Turning Your Back on Life'' tries to gently pull at the character''s jacket from behind, but the character steadfastly faces forward, ignoring it. The overall style is lighthearted and motivational with exaggerated features and bright, uplifting colors to emphasize energy and positivity. Include cartoon-style speech bubbles or signs near the path with uplifting words like ''Live Fully'' and ''Stay Curious.'' The tone is hopeful and humorous without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2049, 'Life, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Life without goals is like a race without a finish line.', 'Anonymous Sheng Choua Vang', 'A cartoon depicts a comical race track stretching infinitely into the horizon, with no visible finish line in sight. Several exaggerated, funny runners are on the track looking confused and tired, some scratching their heads or checking their watches. Around the track, signs show motivational words like ''Keep Going!'' and ''Almost There!'' but the finish line remains nowhere to be seen. The sky is bright and cheerful to keep a lighthearted tone, and there’s a whimsical banner overhead reading ''The Never-Ending Race.'' One runner is panting and slumped over, while another looks hopeful but puzzled. The overall style is playful and colorful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor in running a race with no goal or endpoint.'),
 (2508, 'Life, Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Watch your thoughts; they become words. Watch your words; they become actions. Watch your actions; they become habits. Watch your habits; they become character. Watch your character; it becomes your destiny.', 'Frank Outlaw', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky wise philosopher character standing at the center, holding an oversized magnifying glass labeled ''Watch.'' Around the character, a playful visual progression is depicted in a circle or flowing line: first, a thought bubble filled with small symbols (like light bulbs and question marks), then a speech bubble with words coming out, next a cartoonish figure taking an action like stepping forward, followed by rows of repetitive actions forming a habit (like brushing teeth repeatedly), then an outline silhouette labeled ''Character,'' and finally a winding road or path labeled ''Destiny'' leading off into the distance. Each element is drawn with exaggerated, fun cartoon style and bright colors, with small humorous details like animated eyes on the objects and quirky expressions on the philosopher. The background is simple and cheerful, emphasizing the flow from thoughts to destiny without any text bubbles apart from the magnifying glass label and path sign. The overall tone is light-hearted and visually engaging, illustrating the evolution of thoughts to destiny in an amusing, clear sequence.'),
 (1676, 'Life, Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Every passing moment is another chance to turn it all around.', 'Penelope Cruz', 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring a person standing at a literal crossroads in a bright, sunny park. The crossroads signposts show one direction labeled ''Past Mistakes'' with a gloomy, slightly overgrown path, and the other labeled ''Fresh Start'' with a bright, flower-lined path. The person looks optimistic, mid-step towards the ''Fresh Start'' path, with a hopeful smile and arms slightly raised. Above, floating in the sky like a friendly cloud, are whimsical words that read, ''Every passing moment is another chance to turn it all around.'' The background includes lighthearted elements like birds, butterflies, and a few playful squirrels to add charm and a sense of new beginnings. The style is colorful, simple, and exaggerated in a humorous cartoon format, emphasizing positivity and opportunity without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (1853, 'Life, Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'I would rather attempt and fail than to regret something I never did.', 'Katie McGregor', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a character standing at a fork in the road. One path is labeled ''Attempt'' and is rocky and steep, with a small mountain or obstacle in the distance. The other path is labeled ''Regret'' and is smooth but ends abruptly at a cliff or a sign that says ''Dead End.'' The character looks determined yet slightly nervous, wearing casual clothing and holding a backpack with some gear visibly sticking out (like a rope or map). Above the character''s head is a thought bubble showing two mini-scenes: one of them climbing or struggling on the rocky path, and another of them standing sadly at the cliff edge. The background should be bright and colorful with exaggerated cartoon trees and clouds, emphasizing a lighthearted and motivational mood without any darkness or intensity. The style should be simple, friendly, and playful, with smiling faces and clear, bold labels on the signs and thought bubble.'),
 (2333, 'Life, Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'The longer I live, the more I realize the impact of attitude on life I am convinced that life is 10 percent what happens to me and 90 percent how I react to it.', 'Chuck Swindoll', 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring an older person standing on a small hill with a bright sun shining behind them. The individual has a slight smile and an open, positive posture, looking upward. Around them are two thought bubbles: one small bubble showing a minor mishap like a spilled coffee cup; another large, dominant bubble illustrating a radiant sunbeam or a glowing heart symbol, representing their positive reaction. The background is simple with a few fluffy clouds and some green grass, emphasizing a peaceful, uplifting mood. The art style is colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions to convey optimism and the power of attitude in life.'),
 (1952, 'Life, Motivational, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'In times like these, it helps to recall that there have always been times like these.', 'Paul Harvey', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a calm, wise-looking character—perhaps an elderly person or a philosopher-like figure—sitting on a park bench in a peaceful setting. The character should appear relaxed and smiling gently, holding an old, oversized book titled ''History of Troubled Times.'' Around the bench, subtle elements hint at various challenging moments from the past, like a faded newspaper on the ground with headlines about past crises, a weathered calendar showing different years, and a small clock symbolizing passing time. The backdrop is a bright, cheerful park with trees, birds, and a clear sky to contrast the seriousness of the statement. The overall tone is lighthearted and reassuring, with simple, colorful lines and exaggerated expressions typical of a friendly cartoon style.'),
 (2286, 'Life, Motivational, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The best way to escape from a problem is to solve it.', 'Alan Saporta', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person faced with a large, tangled ball labeled ''Problem'' blocking their path. The person, drawn with a confident, smiling expression, is actively unraveling or dismantling the ball using oversized cartoon tools like a giant pair of scissors or a comically large key labeled ''Solution.'' Behind them, the path is clear and sunny, representing freedom or escape. The background is simple and bright with a road or path leading away from the ball. The style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the idea of ''escaping'' by actually solving the problem rather than running away. No threatening or negative elements are present, keeping the tone cheerful and optimistic.'),
 (1258, 'Life, Motivational, Thanksgiving', 'There is always something for which to be thankful.', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon scene set around a Thanksgiving dinner table. In the center, a large roasted turkey with steam rising, surrounded by classic side dishes like mashed potatoes, corn, and cranberry sauce. Around the table, a diverse group of smiling family members of varying ages, all holding hands or raising glasses in a toast. Above them, a warm glowing banner or speech bubble that reads, ''There is always something for which to be thankful.'' The background shows cozy home decorations like autumn leaves, pumpkins, and soft lighting to emphasize warmth and gratitude. The overall style is bright, colorful, and lighthearted, with exaggerated happy expressions to convey a joyful, grateful mood in cartoon form.'),
 (1259, 'Life, Motivational, Workplace', 'There is nothing greater than the moment you realize that you''re free and the whole world is waiting to be explored. Quit your job and go!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a joyful person standing at the open door of an office cubicle. The person is mid-step, with one foot already outside, carrying a small suitcase or backpack, symbolizing readiness for adventure. The office is drab and gray, with a computer, stacks of paperwork, and a coffee mug on the desk. Outside the cubicle, a bright, vibrant outdoors scene bursts in through the doorway: green rolling hills, a clear blue sky with a shining sun, birds flying, and a winding path leading off into the distance. The person’s face expresses a mix of excitement and relief. Include a subtle calendar on the cubicle wall with crossed-out workdays, emphasizing the end of work, and tiny details like a clock showing quitting time. The overall style is colorful, light-hearted, and uplifting, capturing the freedom and thrill of leaving work to explore the world.'),
 (1642, 'Life, Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Don''t ever become a pessimist, Ira; a pessimist is correct oftener than an optimist, but an optimist has more fun -- and neither can stop the march of events.', 'Robert A. Heinlein', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in conversation. One character, labeled ''Ira,'' looks gloomy and wears slightly droopy clothes with a pessimistic frown. The other character is more cheerful and carefree, smiling broadly with bright, colorful clothes suggesting optimism. They stand side by side on a simple outdoor path symbolizing the ''march of events,'' with little footprints or motion lines illustrating movement forward. In the background, playful icons float in the air: a cloud raining on Ira’s head and a shining sun above the optimist. Above the scene, a banner or thought bubble states the joke’s punchline emphasizing the contrast between the pessimist being often right versus the optimist having more fun. The overall art style is light, cartoonish, and expressive, with exaggerated facial expressions highlighting the mood differences. The setting is minimal but cheerful to reflect the humor and message without distraction.'),
 (1792, 'Life, Optimism Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'I do the very best I know how - the very best I can; and I mean to keep on doing so until the end.', 'Lincoln', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a determined person, smiling confidently with a thumbs-up, standing firmly on a path that stretches straight ahead toward a bright horizon. The person should look earnest and optimistic, wearing simple casual clothes. Behind them, a signpost reads ''The End'' with an arrow pointing down the path. Around the person, lighthearted symbols like little stars or sparkles emphasize their good intentions. The background should be cheerful and simple, perhaps with a sun rising or shining brightly. The overall tone is positive and uplifting with a touch of gentle humor, capturing the idea of persevering and doing one''s best until the very end.'),
 (1968, 'Life, Optimism Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'It is a funny thing about life; if you refuse to accept anything but the best, you very often get it.', 'W. Somerset Maugham', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing proudly on a podium labeled ''Best.'' Around them are several other podiums labeled ''Average'' and ''Poor,'' both empty. The person is wearing a crown and holding a shiny golden trophy with a big smile. In the background, a conveyor belt delivers various comical, exaggerated items like a diamond, a trophy, and a gold medal, all labeled ''Best.'' Two puzzled, less fortunate cartoon characters look on from the side, holding smaller, duller objects like a crumpled paper and a wilted flower. The setting is bright and colorful with floating stars and confetti to emphasize the ''best'' theme. The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical to match the optimistic humor of the joke.'),
 (1260, 'Life, Philosophy Humor', 'We are always the same age inside.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters, one elderly person and one child, standing side by side inside a giant transparent birthday cake decorated with colorful candles. Both characters have the same vibrant, youthful expression and wide, excited eyes as if they feel equally young on the inside. The elderly person is wearing glasses and slightly wrinkled clothes, while the child is dressed in casual, bright clothing. Around them are festive decorations like balloons and streamers. The background is simple and cheerful, emphasizing the contrast between their outward appearances and their shared inner youthfulness. The style is playful and exaggerated to highlight the joke’s message visually, with thought bubbles above each character showing a smaller version of themselves happily playing or dancing.'),
 (2370, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'The question is not whether we will die, but how we will live.', 'Joan Borysenko', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a lively, colorful park setting bathed in warm sunlight. In the foreground, a cheerful elderly person with a big smile is sitting on a bench, holding a life-sized, metaphorical blueprint or guidebook titled ''How to Live Well.'' Around them, a group of animated characters of various ages and styles engage in joyful activities: dancing, gardening, playing an instrument, painting, and sharing laughter. Above the scene, a whimsical thought bubble emerges from the elderly person’s head containing two contrasting images: a simple tombstone labeled ''We all die'' alongside vibrant icons representing ''How we live'' such as a heart, sunshine, smiley face, and connected hands. The overall tone is lighthearted and uplifting, emphasizing the message to focus on living fully rather than fearing death. The style is bright, cartoony, and exaggerated with expressive faces and exaggerated poses to capture humor and positivity.'),
 (1859, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'I''d rather be a failure at something I enjoy than be a success at something I hate.', 'George Burns', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two contrasting panels side by side. On the left panel, a relaxed person is happily painting on a canvas with a big smile, surrounded by paint splashes and art supplies; the painting looks messy but the person is clearly enjoying themselves. On the right panel, the same person is sitting at a desk piled high with papers, looking stressed, tired, and unhappy while dressed in a formal business suit. Above the painting panel, show a small, golden trophy labeled ''Success at Something I Hate'' with a frown face on it, and above the painting panel, a simple, colorful sign saying ''Failure but Fun!'' with happy little stars around it. The background is bright and vibrant on the failure/enjoyment side and dull gray and boring on the success/hate side. This visual contrast humorously illustrates the idea of choosing happiness over conventional success. The overall style should be bright, cheerful, and exaggerated, like a lighthearted, expressive cartoon.'),
 (1898, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'If you can spend a perfectly useless afternoon in a perfectly useless manner, you have learned how to live.', 'Lin Yutang', 'A whimsical cartoon scene featuring a person lounging comfortably in a cozy armchair in a bright, sunny room. The person looks completely relaxed and content, smiling peacefully with their feet propped up on a small ottoman. Around them are various objects that emphasize leisure and ''useless'' activities: a half-finished jigsaw puzzle, an open book face down, a clock showing time passing but with no rush, a simple cup of tea or coffee on a side table, a lazy cat snoozing nearby, and a window showing a calm, peaceful garden outside with birds casually flying. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated, playful lines to emphasize the carefree, easygoing vibe of spending a useless, perfectly wasted afternoon doing nothing important, but enjoying it fully.'),
 (2045, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'Life is something to do when you can''t get to sleep.', 'Fran Lebowitz', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a tired person lying in bed, eyes wide open and staring at the ceiling in frustration. Around the bed, whimsical elements illustrate the joke: floating clocks showing late night hours, a thought bubble above the person''s head filled with playful images representing random life activities like a book, a coffee cup, a bicycle, and a calendar. The room is cozy but dimly lit with a small night lamp casting a soft glow. The person’s pajamas are cozy, and the bed looks inviting but the person clearly can''t sleep. A cute alarm clock on the bedside table wears a sleepy face, suggesting the irony. The overall art style is light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the irony of life being a ''time filler'' when sleep is elusive.'),
 (2047, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'Life moves pretty fast. If you don''t stop and look around once in awhile, it might pass you by.', 'Ferris Bueller', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly frantic character riding a scooter or skateboard zooming quickly along a winding path in a lively park. Surrounding the character are vibrant, exaggerated details: colorful trees swaying, birds flying, flowers blooming, and a few smiling animals. Ahead, there''s a large, whimsical clock with arms and legs, running away as if escaping. The character looks back with wide eyes, almost about to miss the beautiful scenery. In the background, a bench with an elderly person leisurely reading a newspaper and a child feeding ducks adds to the theme of pausing to appreciate life. The overall style is playful, bright, with exaggerated expressions and dynamic motion lines emphasizing speed and urgency, all in a lighthearted, cartoonish vibe without any negative or dark elements.'),
 (2596, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'You begin your life at last when you can live for someone other than yourself.', 'Einstein', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in two panels side by side. On the left, the person is drawn very self-centered, with crossed arms, a grumpy face, and a speech bubble saying, "Me, me, me!" In the background, they''re surrounded by mirrors and personal items like selfies, snacks, and video games. On the right panel, the same person is shown happily caring for someone else—maybe holding a baby, feeding a pet, or helping a friend. They have a big smile, hearts floating around, and a speech bubble that says, "You matter too!" The setting is bright and cheerful. Both panels are connected with a playful arrow or timeline that contrasts ''before'' and ''after'' living for others. Keep the style lighthearted with exaggerated facial expressions and simple, colorful backgrounds to emphasize the transformation without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (2171, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'One can be instructed in society, one is inspired only in solitude.', 'Goethe', 'A cartoon-style scene split into two halves. On the left side, depict a cheerful group of diverse people standing close together in a park or city square, all looking engaged and listening attentively to a teacher or guide who is pointing at a large open book or a sign labeled ''Society Lessons.'' Everyone is smiling, taking notes, or interacting. On the right side, show a single person sitting comfortably alone on a small hill or by a tree in nature, looking peaceful and inspired. This person is holding an illuminated light bulb above their head or has a glowing aura around them to symbolize inspiration. The background on the solitary side is calm and serene with soft pastel colors, while the group side is lively and colorful. Use exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the contrast between social learning and solitary inspiration. Include small humorous touches such as a bird on the solo person''s shoulder and a stack of books next to the group scene.'),
 (1558, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Anything that is given can be at once taken away. We have to learn never to expect anything, and when it comes it''s no more than a gift on loan.', 'John McGahern', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room. In the center, a cheerful character stands with open arms as if presenting a glowing gift box labeled ''Anything.'' The box is brightly colored and slightly transparent, showing it’s sparkling or glowing inside. Nearby, a mischievous, playful cartoon hand reaches out from offscreen or behind the gift to gently snatch the gift away, highlighting the ''taken away'' concept. The character’s expression shifts from happy to surprised or puzzled, emphasizing the humor of receiving something only to lose it immediately. Around them, subtle visual cues like floating question marks or small clocks suggest the passage of time and the idea of ''on loan.'' The background includes a comfy chair, a small table with a teacup, and a window letting in warm light, creating a warm but ironic atmosphere. The overall style should be light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and simple, clean lines to keep it humorous and relatable without any violence or negative tone. The scene visually communicates the philosophical idea of expecting nothing because gifts can be temporary, with a playful twist.'),
 (1737, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Happiness is good health and a bad memory.', 'Ingrid Bergman (1917-1982)', 'A cheerful, cartoon-style elderly person with a big smile, looking relaxed and content. They are outdoors in a sunny park setting, with a picnic blanket, a basket labeled ''Healthy Food,'' and a few scattered pills or vitamins nearby to symbolize good health. Above their head is a whimsical, lightbulb-style thought bubble showing a jumbled, cartoon-style memory cloud with random, incomplete, or silly images inside, like a forgotten shopping list or a mismatched pair of socks, emphasizing a ''bad memory'' in a humorous way. The overall mood is lighthearted and positive, with vibrant colors and simple, exaggerated facial expressions to bring out the humor in achieving happiness through good health and forgetting life''s troubles.'),
 (1764, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'How vain it is to sit down to write when you have not stood up to live.', 'Thoreau', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a desk, eagerly writing on a piece of paper with a quill or pen. The person looks intent but slightly bored or uninspired. In the background or to one side, the same character is shown standing outside enjoying vibrant life activities—perhaps stretching, looking at a bright sun, surrounded by nature, birds, flowers, or people jogging and playing. The contrast between the seated writer indoors and the lively standing figure outdoors highlights the joke''s message about living actively before creating. The style is lighthearted with exaggerated expressions and clear division between the two parts of the scene, emphasizing the irony humorously.'),
 (2309, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'The future is no place to place your better days.', 'Dave Matthews Band', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person looking wistfully into the distance, standing at a crossroads sign labeled ''Future.'' The person is holding a small, glowing box labeled ''Better Days'' with a confused and slightly sad expression. Around them, the landscape is split: one side bright and sunny representing the present, with flowers and birds, and the other side misty and uncertain, symbolizing the future. The signpost looks a bit crooked, with an arrow pointing into an unclear, foggy area. Include subtle elements like a clock showing ''now'' and a calendar flipped to today. The style should be light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated features to emphasize the emotional mix of hope and confusion about when to enjoy good moments.'),
 (2001, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'It''s good to have an end to journey toward; but it is the journey that matters in the end.', 'Ursula K. LeGuin', 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a cheerful traveler walking on a long winding path that stretches from the foreground into the distance. The path should have colorful signs pointing forward with words like ''Journey'' and ''Adventure'' on them. The traveler, dressed in casual, slightly exaggerated explorer clothes (like a hat, backpack, and boots), is looking content and curious rather than fixated on a distant mountain labeled ''The End.'' Around the path, small playful elements like quirky animals or friendly landmarks (a smiling tree, a quirky rock) emphasize the joy along the way. The background should show both the path''s inviting twists and turns and a faint, small destination far away, subtle and not dominating the scene. The overall mood is lighthearted, emphasizing that while the end maybe visible, the focus is on the lively and fun journey itself.'),
 (2005, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'It''s hard to detect good luck - it looks so much like something you''ve earned.', 'Frank A. Clar', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a person in casual clothes looks confused, scratching their head while holding a four-leaf clover and looking at it suspiciously. On the right, another person, wearing a graduation cap and holding a diploma, looks proud and confident. Between them, have a large, playful magnifying glass hovering over them both, emphasizing the idea of ''detecting'' luck. The background should be simple, maybe a park or an outdoor setting with bright colors. Include subtle visual contrasts: the lucky character surrounded by whimsical sparkles or shamrocks and the earned character with books or certificates stacked nearby. The overall tone is lighthearted and clever, highlighting the joke about the difficulty distinguishing luck from hard work, without any negativity or complexity.'),
 (1363, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', '90% of being smart is knowing what you''re dumb at.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk surrounded by books, notebooks, and a laptop. The person looks thoughtfully puzzled, scratching their head, with a lightbulb above indicating a moment of realization. Behind them, a large, comically oversized brain wearing glasses looms, looking wise but also slightly bemused. On the desk, there is a sticky note that reads ''Know what you don''t know.'' The background includes a wall with a simple chart labeled ''Smartness Scale,'' showing 90% highlighted next to ''Knowing what you''re dumb at.'' The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and simple lines to emphasize the concept of self-awareness in intelligence without any aggressive or negative imagery.'),
 (1648, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Don''t take life too seriously. You''ll never get out alive.', 'Bugs Bunny', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, slightly quirky character standing on a small patch of grass or simple ground. The character, drawn in a lighthearted style, is wearing casual clothes and holding a large, colorful balloon shaped like a smiley face. Around them, subtle life symbols like a clock showing time passing, a smiling sun in the sky, and a few floating question marks or whimsical items symbolize life''s unpredictability. In the background, a simple exit door or gate labeled ''Life'' with a humorous ''No One Gets Out Alive'' sign hangs slightly open but with a playful, non-threatening vibe. The overall mood is cheeky and optimistic, conveying the message not to take life too seriously because no one escapes it anyway. Bright colors and an expressive face on the character add to the lighthearted and approachable tone of the cartoon.'),
 (1948, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'In the fight between you and the world, back the world.', 'Frank Zappa', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small person standing on the left side looking determined but clearly overwhelmed, facing a huge, smiling globe representing the world on the right. The globe is personified with eyes, a big friendly grin, and arms crossed confidently. The background is a simple outdoor setting with a clear sky, a few trees, and grass to set a lighthearted mood. The small character is wearing casual clothes and clenched fists, showing readiness to ''fight,'' while the globe towers over, relaxed and unbothered. A playful tension is conveyed with concerned cartoon sweat drops on the small person and a calm, knowing expression on the globe. Include a small caption bubble above the person that says, "I''m ready to fight!" and above the globe, a speech bubble saying, "Back me instead!" The overall style is colorful and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the absurdity of challenging the entire world alone.'),
 (1261, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Relatable', 'There is much more to life than having everything.', NULL, 'Draw a simple, lighthearted cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting on a park bench under a tree. One character looks content and peaceful, admiring a small flower growing nearby, while the other character is surrounded by oversized bags and boxes labeled ''Everything.'' The character with the bags looks tired and overwhelmed, while the peaceful character smiles gently, enjoying the simplicity of life around them, such as birds, sunshine, and a butterfly. The backdrop is a sunny day in the park, with a few clouds and a sign that reads ''Life’s More Than Stuff.'' The style should be colorful, friendly, and whimsical, emphasizing the contrast between material abundance and simple joy in a non-judgmental, humorous way.'),
 (1262, 'Life, Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'The best laid plans of mice and men are usually about equal.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a small mouse and a man side by side, both looking frustrated but determined. The mouse is wearing tiny, old-fashioned overalls with a small blueprint rolled out in front of it, filled with complex little designs (like tiny traps or cheese wheels). The man, dressed in casual clothes, holds a similar-sized but much bigger blueprint showing a grand plan involving houses or machines. Both are sitting at a picnic table or simple drafting table outdoors, perhaps in a park, to emphasize equality despite size difference. Their expressions are comically serious as if their plans are equally complicated and likely to fail. Around them, subtle chaos like spilled coffee near the man, and a small fallen piece of cheese near the mouse suggests the plans might not work out. The background is bright and cheerful, reinforcing the light-hearted, ironic tone of the joke.'),
 (1263, 'Life, Philosophy, Workplace', 'Nothing is really work unless you''d rather be doing something else.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a relaxed person lounging comfortably in a cozy living room on a big armchair, smiling peacefully with a book in one hand and a cup of coffee on a side table. In the background, a clock on the wall shows typical working hours, and an open laptop with documents and graphs sits neglected on a desk, looking boring and tedious. Above the person, a thought bubble shows them happily envisioning doing their favorite hobby (like gardening or playing a guitar). The overall vibe is light and cheerful, emphasizing the contrast between enjoyable leisure and dreaded work, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to capture the humorous mental message of the joke.'),
 (1707, 'Life, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'From what we get, we can make a living; what we give, however, makes a life.', 'Arthur Ashe', 'A bright and cheerful cartoon scene featuring two characters: one is holding a small bag of money looking content but simple, standing near a modest home or workplace to symbolize ''making a living.'' The other character, with a warm smile, is shown giving a heart or gift (like a wrapped present, a flower, or a helping hand) to another person or perhaps a group including a child and an elderly person, symbolizing kindness and generosity. The background should have soft, uplifting colors like light blue sky and green grass. Include subtle symbols of life and connection, such as a tree with blooming leaves and small hearts floating around the giving character to emphasize ''making a life.'' The overall style is cartoonish, friendly, and humorous yet heartwarming without any harsh lines or shading. No violence or negative elements, just an uplifting and positive depiction of the message.'),
 (2526, 'Life, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'We make a living by what we get; we make a life by what we give.', 'Winston Churchill', 'A cheerful, cartoon-style outdoor scene with two characters. One character, looking a bit focused and content, is holding a bunch of bills and coins with a small smile, representing ''what we get.'' The other character is happily handing over a brightly wrapped gift box or a flower to a third person, embodying ''what we give.'' The background has a sunny sky with fluffy clouds and a simple house or park setting to suggest everyday life. Both characters have exaggerated, friendly facial expressions emphasizing kindness and generosity. There should be a subtle contrast—one side showing the first character counting money, the other side showing the act of giving something personal and meaningful. No violent or negative elements; overall a warm, lighthearted, and inspiring cartoon tone.'),
 (2920, 'Life, Positive Humor, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'He who laughs, lasts.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a peaceful park. In the foreground, a cheerful, cartoonish character is laughing heartily with tears of joy streaming from their eyes. The character looks lively and happy, sitting on a bench or standing with arms wide open. Surrounding them are several cartoonized hourglasses or clocks with smiling faces, implying the passage of time. In the background, a clever visual pun: a tombstone with a grin engraved on it, symbolizing ''lasting'' or longevity related to laughter. The colors are bright and vibrant to emphasize positivity and good health. The overall style is lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize joy and longevity.'),
 (3074, 'Life, Pragmatic Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'If at first you don''t succeed, try, try again. Then quit. There''s no point in being a damn fool about it.', 'W.C. Fields', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a determined but increasingly frustrated character trying repeatedly to complete a simple task, such as assembling a small piece of furniture or trying to untangle a mess of wires. The character should appear hopeful and focused in early frames but gradually looks more tired, puzzled, and exasperated in subsequent frames. In the last frame, the character throws up their hands and walks away with a resigned expression. Include a small motivational poster in the background with the words ''If at first you don''t succeed, try, try again.'' Near the character’s exit, a speech bubble or sign reads: ''Then quit. There''s no point in being a damn fool about it.'' The art style should be cartoonish and lighthearted, emphasizing facial expressions and body language to convey the character’s emotional journey from determination to pragmatic acceptance without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (2288, 'Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'The best way to win is to follow the advice you give others.', 'God''s Little Instruction Book', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual living room. One character, looking confident and slightly smug, is giving advice with a raised index finger, like a teacher or mentor. The other character looks skeptical but curious. In the background, a large poster on the wall displays a scroll or chalkboard with the phrase: ''Best way to win? Follow your own advice!'' Floating above their heads are thought bubbles illustrating the advice being given—like a simple trophy, a lightbulb for ideas, and a checkmark for success. The overall style is colorful and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the irony and humor in the saying. The setting includes comfy furniture, maybe a small plant, and a coffee cup on a side table to add warmth and casual atmosphere. The tone is friendly, visualizing the concept that wisdom often lies in practicing what you preach, framed as an amusing, relatable moment.'),
 (2490, 'Life, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Trust takes a long time to build up, but is quick to tear down.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a casual setting, such as a park bench or office break room. One character is carefully stacking colorful building blocks labeled ''TRUST'' into a tall tower, showing dedication and patience with a smile. The other character is standing nearby with a mischievous grin, holding a small hammer or a finger ready to knock down the tower. The tower is partially built and looks delicate, with a few blocks wobbling. Around them, add subtle visual cues like a clock or calendar on the wall to emphasize the slow build-up of ''trust.'' Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated facial expressions for comedic effect, making sure the scene looks lighthearted and non-threatening. The setting should be simple, focusing on the characters and the trust tower, with the expression and interaction highlighting the contrast between slow building and fast destruction of trust.'),
 (2585, 'Life, Quotes, Relatable, Wisdom Humor', 'Wisdom is the reward you get for a lifetime of listening when you''d have preferred to talk.', 'Doug Larson', 'Draw a cartoon scene featuring an elderly person sitting comfortably in a cozy armchair, with a gentle and knowing smile. They are surrounded by speech bubbles filled with lines representing others talking, while the elderly person listens attentively with a calm demeanor. Include elements like a softly glowing lamp, a bookshelf filled with books, and a clock on the wall indicating the passage of time. Nearby, a younger person with a chatty expression is eagerly talking, showing enthusiasm and energy. The scene should highlight the contrast between the talkative youth and the patient listener, illustrating the idea that wisdom comes from listening rather than talking. The style is light-hearted and humorous, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor without any negativity.'),
 (2477, 'Life, Quotes, Relatable, Workplace', 'To many people quit looking for work when they find a job.', 'God''s Little Instruction Book', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a crowded job fair where many people are eagerly searching for jobs, holding resumes and looking hopeful. In the foreground, a character has just found a job and happily sits down with a relaxed, contented smile, completely ignoring the job fair chaos behind them. Around this character, other job seekers are actively looking—some frantically waving resumes, others talking to representatives at desks. The background shows colorful booths with signs like ''Jobs Here'' and ''Hiring Now.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the active seekers and the one person who has stopped searching after landing a job.'),
 (2360, 'Life, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wisdom', 'The only way to make a man trustworthy is to trust him.', 'Henry L. Stimson', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters. The first character is a cheerful woman standing with arms open wide, smiling encouragingly at the second character, a man who looks a bit nervous but hopeful. Between them is a large, oversized sign or banner that reads, ''Trust me!'' The background is bright and simple, with soft colors to emphasize a lighthearted mood. The man has a slight sweat drop to show his surprise or uncertainty, and the woman’s body language is open and confident. Include a subtle visual metaphor, like a small bridge labeled ''Trust'' connecting the two characters, symbolizing the bridge of trust that must be crossed. The style should be playful and exaggerated, typical of a light cartoon with expressive faces and simple, clean lines. Avoid any negativity or sternness, keeping the mood warm and encouraging.'),
 (1684, 'Life, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Experience is a good school, but the fees are high.', 'Heinrich Heine', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a whimsical open-air school labeled ''Experience School.'' The building looks like a quirky, slightly exaggerated schoolhouse made of books and coins stacked into walls. In front, a cheerful teacher wearing glasses and a mortarboard stands beside a large old-fashioned chalkboard that reads ''Experience is a good school, but the fees are high.'' Around the school, several students of various ages look slightly worried or tired, holding oversized, comically heavy piggy banks or giant coins, symbolizing the high fees. One student tries to hand a massive coin to the teacher, who smiles knowingly. The background includes a sunny sky with a few fluffy clouds and subtle hints of a playground made up of items representing life lessons, like a seesaw shaped like a balance scale and textbooks labeled ''Mistakes'' and ''Lessons.'' The overall style is bright and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of learning through costly experience without depicting anything violent or inappropriate.'),
 (1686, 'Life, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Experience is a revelation in the light of which we renounce our errors of youth for those of age.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene with two characters side by side. On the left, a younger person looking confident but slightly clueless, wearing casual youthful clothes and maybe a silly hairstyle or expression to show youthful mistakes, holding a crumpled piece of paper labeled "Youthful Mistakes." On the right, an older person with a slight amused or resigned smile, wearing glasses and a cardigan, holding a similar crumpled paper labeled "Mistakes of Age." Between them, a glowing light bulb or a bright spotlight labeled "Experience" illuminating both characters. The background is simple and cheerful, with a few humorous elements illustrating learning or growth, such as books, a graduation cap tossed aside, or a wall clock showing the passing of time. The overall vibe should be lighthearted, showing how old age brings a new kind of error as a result of gained experience.'),
 (2053, 'Life, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Live as if you were to die tomorrow. Learn as if you were to live forever.', 'Mahatma Gandhi', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, a lively character is energetically enjoying life—dancing, eating cake, and laughing, with a bright sun overhead and a calendar page showing ''Tomorrow.'' On the right side, the same character is sitting quietly at a desk surrounded by towering books, glasses on, deep in study, with a clock showing late night and a starry sky visible through a window. The background colors should contrast: warm and bright on the left, cool and calm on the right. The character looks identical in both halves but expresses enjoyment in both ways. Include thought bubbles above the character: on the left, ''Live like today is your last!''; on the right, ''Learn like you''ll live forever!''. The cartoon style is playful and lighthearted with exaggerated facial expressions to show enthusiasm and focus respectively, emphasizing the balance between living fully and learning continuously.'),
 (2551, 'Life, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Whatever is begun in anger ends in shame.', 'Benjamin Franklin (1706-1790)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person who has just angrily started something but now feels embarrassed. The scene shows two comic panels side by side. In the first panel on the left, the character is visibly angry: red cheeks, clenched fists, steam coming out of their ears, maybe a broken object like a vase slipping from their hand. In the second panel on the right, the same character appears ashamed and red-faced, looking down with slumped shoulders and a small sweat drop on their head. Around them are scattered signs of the earlier anger—a broken vase on the floor, scrap papers, or a spilled drink. The background is simple but emphasizes mood by shifting from fiery orange/red in the first panel to dull grey/blue in the second. The setting is a typical home living room or simple office environment to keep it relatable. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and body language to clearly convey anger transitioning into shame without anything violent or mean.'),
 (1995, 'Life, Quotes, Wisdom, Workplace', 'It takes less time to do a thing right than explain why you did it wrong.', 'Henry Wadsworth Longfellow', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a frustrated person standing next to a half-finished or clearly done wrong project (like a crooked picture frame on the wall or an uneven stack of books). The person holds their hands up in exasperation or mid-explanation, while a clock on the wall shows the passing of time quickly. In the background, a thought bubble shows the same person working efficiently and finishing the task correctly. The setting is a simple, cozy room with minimal furniture, emphasizing the contrast between the wrong work and the time wasted explaining. Use bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor and make the scenario immediately relatable and funny.'),
 (1264, 'Life, Relatable Humor', 'The first parking space you see will be the last parking space you see.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene in a parking lot. In the foreground, a frustrated driver sits inside a small car, gripping the steering wheel tightly with a worried expression. The car is stopped just before the first available parking space, which is clearly open and empty. Behind the car, the parking lot is shown with dozens of cars tightly parked and no other open spots visible. Above the scene, a whimsical caption bubble reads: ''The first parking space you see will be the last parking space you see.'' The parking lot should have light humor style details like a ''No Parking'' sign on the far side, a distant clock tower or tree for background, and a little trickle of sweat on the driver''s forehead to show impatience. The style should be colorful, exaggerated cartoon with clear expressions emphasizing the irony of finding a spot early but knowing it''s the only one.'),
 (2890, 'Life, Relatable, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'Good judgement comes from experience. Experience comes from poor judgement.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing confidently with a thoughtful expression on their face, perhaps stroking their chin. Around them are comic-style bubbles illustrating two stages: one bubble shows the same person making a silly, exaggerated mistake (like slipping on a banana peel or wearing mismatched shoes), representing ''poor judgment.'' Another bubble shows the person looking wiser and more experienced, wearing glasses and holding a book or checklist, representing ''good judgment.'' The background is simple and bright, with lighthearted elements to emphasize the connection between learning from mistakes and gaining wisdom. The style should be cartoonish, colorful, and playful, evoking a sense of learning and growth through humor without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (3198, 'Life, Steven Wright, Wisdom Humor', 'Experience is something you don''t get until just after you need it.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a crossroads or in front of a tricky situation, looking confused or hesitant. Behind them, a transparent ghostly version of the same person wearing glasses and holding a book labeled ''Experience'' is floating just out of reach, smiling knowingly. The setting could be an office or a simple home environment with a clock showing the time late, emphasizing that the ''experience'' arrives too late. The living person looks puzzled and frustrated, while the ghostly experienced self gestures as if saying ''I should have been here earlier!'' The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive faces and simple background details like a calendar with the date circled, a spilled coffee cup, and a thought bubble showing a missed chance or a mistake, reinforcing the idea that experience comes only after it''s needed.'),
 (3048, 'Life, Unknown, Visual Humor, Word Play', 'I used to have a handle on life, then it broke.', NULL, 'A cartoon-style image showing a cheerful, slightly quirky character standing next to a large, oversized life-sized boiler or machine labeled ''Life.'' The machine has a prominent old-fashioned door handle on it, which is humorously broken off with jagged edges. The character is scratching their head with one hand and shrugging with a sheepish grin. Around the character, small objects like a calendar, clock, and sticky notes float or lie scattered, representing attempts to get life organized. The background is simple and bright with whimsical clouds or stars to emphasize a light-hearted tone. The overall mood is playful and humorous, capturing the metaphor of losing control in a fun, relatable way.'),
 (1265, 'Life, Workplace', 'Nobody notices what I do until I don''t do it.', NULL, 'A cartoon office scene showing a single worker sitting at a cluttered desk with a tired but content expression. Around the worker, various tasks are depicted humorously: a coffee machine brewing coffee, a printer spitting out paper, a filing cabinet with papers neatly stacked, and a plant being watered by a small automatic sprinkler. The worker is surrounded by colleague characters each looking worried or confused, glancing around and checking their watches, implying something is off. In the background, a calendar shows the current day marked with a big red X. The style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the humor of quiet contributions going unnoticed until they stop happening. The scene should feel relatable and amusing, without any harsh or negative expressions.'),
 (2827, 'Light Humor, Motivational Humor, Objects Humor, Unknown', 'Even the smallest candle burns brighter in the dark.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon showing a tiny candle with a big, confident smile standing upright on a dark, shadowy surface. The candle''s flame should be unusually bright and exaggeratedly large compared to the candle''s small size, lighting up a significant area around it. Surrounding the candle are tall, dark silhouettes of larger candles that are unlit or barely glowing, looking surprised or dim in comparison. The background should be pitch black, emphasizing the brightness of the little candle’s flame. Include subtle cartoonish facial expressions on the candles to add humor and personality, focusing on the contrast of size versus brightness.'),
 (2203, 'Literary Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Poetry begins in delight and ends in wisdom.', 'Robert Frost', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful poet character standing on the left side, holding a quill pen and a scroll with flowing lines of whimsical poetry written on it. Their facial expression shows delight and inspiration, with sparkling eyes and a bright smile. On the right side, the same character is now older and wiser, wearing glasses and holding a thicker book titled ''Wisdom,'' with a slightly more serious, thoughtful expression. Between the two characters is a gradient background transitioning from bright and colorful on the left (representing delight) to calm and refined on the right (representing wisdom). Include whimsical decorative elements like floating musical notes, stars, and thought bubbles around the poet to emphasize creativity turning into insight. The style should be light and playful, with exaggerated, friendly cartoon features and clean lines to highlight the contrast between youthful delight and mature wisdom in poetry''s journey. No violence or complex backgrounds, focus on the character and symbolic elements representing the transformation.'),
 (2480, 'Literary Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'To sleep perchance to dream, ay there''s the rub.', 'Hamlet', 'A cartoon scene featuring a tired person lying in bed at night under a simple blanket, eyes half-closed with a worried or puzzled expression. Above their head is a classic thought bubble showing a whimsical scene of someone trying to sleep but being gently poked or ''rubbed'' by a literal small rubber made of wood to play on the word ''rub''. The bedroom is cozy with a moon and stars visible through a window. The style is light-hearted and humorous, with soft colors and exaggerated expressions emphasizing the pun on ''the rub''. No darkness or fear, just playful confusion about sleep and dreaming.'),
 (2054, 'Logic Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Logic is in the eye of the logician.', 'Gloria Steinem', 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a logician, depicted as a thoughtful character wearing glasses and a tweed jacket with elbow patches, standing contemplatively. The logician holds a magnifying glass up to one eye, with the lens comically enlarged and emphasizing the eye. Instead of the human eye, the magnifying glass shows a small piece of a wooden log with wood grain and growth rings clearly visible inside the eye. Around the logician''s head are cartoon thought bubbles with small logic symbols like arrows, syllogisms, and question marks. The background is simple, light blue with subtle math formulas floating faintly to suggest intellectual activity. The overall tone is whimsical and clever, with a light-hearted cartoon style emphasizing the pun on "eye of the logician" and "log." There should be no violent, sexual, or political elements, just a playful visual pun involving a log and the logician’s eye.'),
 (1266, 'Love Humor, Marriage Humor, Word Play', 'Love may be blind, but marriage is a real eye-opener.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a newlywed couple standing side by side. The wife looks lovingly at her husband with heart-shaped eyes and a dreamy smile, symbolizing ''love may be blind.'' The husband wears very thick, oversized eyeglasses with exaggeratedly wide-open eyes, glasses slipping down his nose to highlight ''marriage is a real eye-opener.'' Around them, wedding decorations like balloons, flowers, and a ''Just Married'' sign. The background is cheerful but includes subtle details like a messy pile of bills or a misbehaving pet to gently hint at marriage realities. Both characters are drawn in a lighthearted and playful style with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the joke. Bright colors and simple lines keep the tone fun and friendly.'),
 (1267, 'Love Humor, Marriage Humor, Word Play', 'Make love, not war; get married and do both!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful couple standing side by side. The couple is in wedding attire: the bride wearing a flowing white dress and the groom in a tuxedo. Above them, a playful banner reads ''Make Love, Not War.'' Surrounding the couple are whimsical symbols combining love and conflict imagery in a lighthearted way: hearts floating around the couple, but also small cartoonish peace signs and tiny, harmless cartoon bombs with smiley faces. The husband is holding a bouquet of flowers in one hand and a tiny white flag in the other. The background is bright and colorful, with a simple outdoor garden wedding setup featuring a decorated arch. Include subtle humorous cues like the bride giving a playful smirk and the groom looking slightly surprised, hinting at the joke''s punchline about marriage involving a mix of love and conflict in a fun, non-offensive way. The style should be cartoonish and cheerful with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor.'),
 (2066, 'Love Humor, Math Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'Love is like pi -- natural, irrational, and VERY important.', 'Lisa Hoffman', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful mathematician character standing next to a large, whimsically drawn pie labeled with the Greek letter π (pi). The mathematician is holding a heart-shaped balloon or has heart symbols floating around their head to symbolize love. The pie looks delicious but also has mathematical symbols and numbers swirling around it to emphasize the ''pi'' concept. The background is simple and bright, with a lighthearted and playful vibe. Include a speech bubble from the mathematician saying, ''Love is like pi — natural, irrational, and VERY important.'' The overall style should be colorful, fun, and exaggerated to enhance the humor, without any violent or political elements.'),
 (2062, 'Love Humor, Metaphor Humor, Quotes', 'Love is a hole in the heart.', 'Ben Hecht', 'A humorous cartoon drawing of a cute human heart character with a surprised or puzzled expression. The heart has a small, clearly visible hole right in its center. Around the heart, floating love-related symbols like small red hearts, cupid’s arrow, and sparkles add to the theme. Maybe show a tiny bandage or patch near the hole to emphasize ''love is a hole.'' The background is simple and cheerful, with soft colors like pink or light red to suggest affection, but the heart’s expression humorously reflects the ''hole'' concept rather than happiness. Keep features exaggerated and playful to create a lighthearted, funny vibe without any sadness or negativity.'),
 (2058, 'Love Humor, Metaphor Humor, Quotes, Spiritual Humor', 'Love in its essence is spiritual fire.', 'Swedenborg', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring two characters personifying love as a literal ''spiritual fire.'' In the center, depict a small, whimsical campfire with glowing flames shaped like a heart, floating just above the ground. Surrounding the fire are two cartoon people: one looking amazed and lovingly at the fire, and the other gently fanning it with a symbolic angel’s wing. The background should be simple and cheerful, possibly a serene night sky with twinkling stars to emphasize spirituality. Include faint wisps or sparkles rising from the heart-shaped flame to suggest warmth and spiritual energy. Make the characters expressive and light-hearted, with exaggerated facial expressions of affection, wonder, and enthusiasm. The overall tone is warm, charming, and playful, without any complex or dark elements.'),
 (1268, 'Love Humor, Money Humor, Puns', 'Someone with money to burn will always find a perfect match.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a wealthy-looking person with a sparkling crown and fancy clothes standing next to a bonfire made of money bills and coins literally burning in the fire. The rich person holds a box of oversized wooden matchsticks labeled ''Perfect Match'' with a big smile on their face, ready to light one. The background is cheerful and bright with a few gold coins floating in the air and little heart-shaped sparks rising from the fire, playfully suggesting both money being set aflame and the idea of finding a romantic or ideal match. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize the pun.'),
 (1269, 'Love Humor, Philosophy', 'Of all forms of caution, caution in love is the most fatal.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a nervous-looking person tiptoeing very cautiously toward a large, heart-shaped object labeled ''Love.'' The heart is surrounded by warning signs like ''Beware,'' ''Handle with care,'' and ''Caution.'' The person is wearing comically oversized caution gear: a helmet, knee pads, and holding an exaggeratedly big magnifying glass to examine the heart. Around them are scattered items that represent typical warnings or obstacles in love, like a broken arrow, a spilled love potion, and a caution tape wrapped loosely around the heart. The background is light and playful with pastel colors, emphasizing a whimsical rather than serious tone. The facial expression of the character should be a mix of anxiety and exaggerated care, highlighting the joke that being overly cautious in love can be dangerous or ''fatal.'''),
 (2061, 'Love Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Love is a gross exaggeration of the difference between one person and everybody else.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two people standing apart on either side of the frame. One person, on the left, is smiling dreamily with hearts floating around their head, wearing casual, everyday clothes. The other person, on the right, looks almost identical but slightly faded or outlined in a dull gray tone to symbolize ''everybody else.'' Between them is an exaggeratedly large, comically oversized speech bubble or banner reading: ''Love is a gross exaggeration of the difference between one person and everybody else.'' The background is simple and light, with a soft pink or red gradient to evoke the idea of love. Add subtle visual cues like giggling butterflies or tiny sparks around the smiling person for whimsical effect. The style should be lighthearted, playful, and caricature-like, avoiding any realistic or serious art style, to emphasize the joke''s witty observation about love being an overstatement of human difference.'),
 (2071, 'Love Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Love is the triumph of imagination over intelligence.', 'H.L.Mencken', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a couple sitting at a small café table outdoors. The woman is daydreaming with hearts floating around her head, eyes closed and smiling blissfully, while the man next to her looks puzzled or slightly concerned, scratching his head and holding a book titled ''Logic for Beginners.'' Above their heads is a large thought bubble showing a whimsical flying unicorn or an imaginative, colorful fantasy scene. On the table are two coffee cups, a small vase with a single flower, and a tiny brain with wings trying to take off but weighed down by a heavy book labeled ''Intelligence.'' The setting is light and cheerful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions to enhance the contrast between imagination and intelligence in a playful way.'),
 (2609, 'Love Humor, Physical Comedy, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'You have to walk carefully in the beginning of love; the running across fields into your lover''s arms can only come later when you''re sure they won''t laugh if you trip.', 'Jonathan Carroll', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a young person carefully tiptoeing across a grassy field toward another person standing with open arms, smiling but also holding back a small chuckle. The tiptoeing character looks cautious and slightly nervous, with one foot raised mid-step and wide eyes focused on the other person. The field is open, dotted with a few whimsical flowers and gentle rolling hills under a clear sky. In the background, faintly outlined, show a future scene (like a thought bubble or faded image) of the same two characters joyfully running into each other''s arms with big grins, emphasizing the contrast between careful approach and carefree running. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to capture the nervousness and playfulness of early love. Avoid any harsh or intense elements to keep it sweet and funny.'),
 (1514, 'Love Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'All you need is love.', 'The Beatles', 'A simple, charming cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly exaggerated heart character with big eyes and a wide smile, standing at the center. The heart is surrounded by a few smaller, smiling characters representing love: a couple holding hands, a friendly dog wagging its tail, and a smiling flower with heart-shaped petals. Above them float cartoon-style words in playful, bubbly letters saying, ''All you need is love.'' The background is soft pastel colors, with a few cartoon-style clouds and sunshine, emphasizing warmth and happiness. The art style is lighthearted and whimsical, with smooth lines and expressive but simple faces on all characters to convey joy and affection without complexity or clutter.'),
 (1424, 'Love Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'A kiss is a rosy dot over the ''i'' of loving.', 'Cyrano de Bergerac', 'A lighthearted, whimsical cartoon scene featuring the word ''loving'' written in large, playful cursive letters across the image. Over the lowercase letter ''i'' in the word ''loving'', a bright red, shiny, slightly three-dimensional kiss mark (lipstick imprint) is placed exactly where the dot should be, making it look like a ''rosy dot''. The kiss mark should appear exaggerated and cartoonish, with a little sparkle or shine to emphasize its vivid color. The background is simple and cheerful, with soft pastel colors, maybe a faint heart or two floating around to accentuate the theme of love. The letters are bold and curved with friendly expressions or subtle smiley faces incorporated into the word to highlight warmth and affection. The overall mood is cute, romantic, and humorous without being overly sentimental or serious.'),
 (2063, 'Love Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Relationship Humor', 'Love is always having to say I''m sorry.', 'Bob Irwin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a couple sitting on a couch in a cozy living room. One partner looks sheepish and is holding a small bouquet of flowers with a slightly embarrassed smile. The other partner is crossing their arms with an amused but slightly forgiving expression. Include thought bubbles: the embarrassed partner''s bubble says "I''m sorry" while the other’s shows a heart symbol. Surround them with lighthearted details like a coffee table, a potted plant, and a picture frame of their happy moments to emphasize their relationship. The style should be bright and cheerful, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor and affection in always needing to apologize in love. Avoid anything serious or negative; keep it playful and warm-hearted.'),
 (1532, 'Love Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'Among those whom I like or admire, I can find no common denominator, but among those whom I love, I can: all of them make me laugh.', 'W. H. Auden', 'Draw a warm, cozy living room scene with a person sitting comfortably in an armchair, smiling and laughing as they look at a group of three close friends or family members nearby. Each person has a joyful expression, causing the main character to laugh heartily. Around them, small symbols of affection and connection float subtly—like hearts and laughing emoji-style bubbles. The background should be simple but inviting, with a bookshelf, a lamp, and a small table with a mug to create an intimate, friendly atmosphere. The art style is cartoonish and lighthearted, with exaggerated happy faces to emphasize the laughter and love connection, conveying the idea that love is linked with shared joy and laughter rather than shared interests or traits.'),
 (2068, 'Love Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'Love is not blind -- it sees more, not less. But because it sees more, it is willing to see less.', 'Rabbi Julins Gordon', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in love, standing close together and gazing at each other with big exaggerated eyes. Around them are floating visual icons representing things commonly noticed in relationships—like a messy room, a pile of dirty dishes, a quirky worn-out sock, and a humorous odd habit symbolized by a little cartoon thought bubble showing a funny bad habit (e.g., someone snoring). One character holds a magnifying glass, looking intently and humorously at these flaws, while the other character is playfully covering or turning a blind eye to these same flaws with a wink or a smile, indicating willingness to overlook them. The setting should be warm and affectionate, like a cozy living room with heart-shaped decorations or soft lighting to emphasize love and acceptance. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to bring out the funny side of seeing "more but willing to see less." No violence or offensive elements, just playful and sweet humor about love''s perspective.'),
 (2084, 'Love Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Word Play', 'Many a man in love with a dimple makes the mistake of marrying the whole girl.', 'Stephen Leacock', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man happily staring at a smiling woman, with a large, exaggerated dimple clearly highlighted on her cheek, maybe glowing or sparkling to emphasize his fascination. The man has hearts over his head and a dreamy, lovestruck expression. In the background, there is a humorous sign or thought bubble showing the man looking overwhelmed or surprised by the woman''s other characteristics, such as her quirky personality traits or everyday habits illustrated with small icons (like a messy pile of books, a cooking pot steaming, and a dog tugging her clothes). The woman stands confidently and cheerfully with her hands on her hips, unaware that the man is only focused on her dimple. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, drawn in a bright and colorful cartoon style with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke''s meaning about overlooking someone''s whole person because of one appealing feature.'),
 (2064, 'Love Humor, Quotes, Romance Humor, Word Play', 'Love is an irresistable desire to be irresistably desired.', 'Robert Frost', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing face-to-face in a whimsical setting. One character is looking adoringly at the other with big, sparkling eyes and a dreamy smile; hearts float around their head to show affection. The second character looks confident and slightly smug, with a hand on their hip, radiating an aura of being ''irresistibly desired.'' Between them, a large, playful banner or thought bubble displays the phrase ''Love is an irresistible desire to be irresistibly desired'' in fun, curly lettering. The background is simple and cheerful, with bright colors and soft shapes like clouds or flowers to keep the mood light and romantic. The style is exaggerated and cartoonish, emphasizing facial expressions and body language that convey mutual attraction and playful flirtation.'),
 (2072, 'Love Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Love. . . She is Blind, No?', 'Pepe LePew', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters: a man and a woman. The woman is wearing a large pair of comically oversized sunglasses that completely cover her eyes, emphasizing the ''blind'' aspect. The man stands beside her with a puzzled or amused expression, scratching his head or shrugging. Above them, a simple speech bubble contains the words: ''Love... She is Blind, No?'' The background is light and minimal, perhaps a park bench or a simple street setting to keep focus on the characters. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with simple lines and bright colors to create a playful and funny mood.'),
 (2091, 'Marriage Humor, Music Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Marriage should be a duet - when one sings, the other claps.', 'Joe Murray', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a married couple on a small stage or in a living room set up like a stage. One partner is holding a microphone and singing enthusiastically, with musical notes floating around their head, eyes closed and fully into the performance. The other partner is sitting or standing next to them, clapping with a big smile but clearly not singing, maybe wearing casual home clothes. Include a simple backdrop with a few musical decorations like a music stand or speakers. The overall vibe should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing teamwork in marriage through music and clapping rather than both singing. Make the characters look friendly and relatable, avoiding exaggeration or caricature. The style should be a colorful, cheerful cartoon with clean lines and expressive faces to highlight the joke''s humor about marriage dynamics.'),
 (1594, 'Marriage Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'By all means marry; if you get a good wife, you''ll be happy. If you get a bad one, you''ll become a philosopher.', 'Socrates', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a man standing at a wedding altar with a wide, cheerful smile holding his bride''s hand. To one side, a small thought bubble shows the man happily lounging on a couch with a heart symbol above his head, representing a good wife making him happy. On the other side, another thought bubble shows the same man sitting cross-legged with a long beard and thoughtful expression, surrounded by philosophy books with question marks floating above, indicating he has become a philosopher due to a bad wife. The background is a simple church or wedding hall setting, with a joyful crowd in the distance. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated cartoon expressions. The focus is the contrast in the two thought bubbles visualizing the joke’s punchline without any negative or violent imagery.'),
 (2087, 'Marriage Humor, Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Marriage is give and take. You''d better give it to her or she''ll take it anyway.', 'Joey Adams', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a married couple at home. The wife is standing confidently with a sly smile, holding a large sack labeled ''Your Things'' while playfully looking at her husband. The husband looks surprised and a bit worried, holding out empty hands as if pleading or trying to give something. The setting is a cozy living room with a couch, a small table with a lamp, and a few household items scattered around, suggesting a typical domestic environment. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated, with expressive faces emphasizing the wife''s assertiveness and the husband''s apprehension, capturing the playful ''give and take'' dynamic in marriage without any negativity.'),
 (2104, 'Marriage Humor, Puns, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Men who have pierced ears are better prepared for marriage. They''ve experienced pain and bought jewelry.', 'Rita Rudner', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing confidently with one ear clearly pierced and a fancy earring visible. The man looks slightly proud but with a subtle wince to hint at the pain he endured. Next to him is a happy woman with a wedding ring, smiling and holding a small box of jewelry or a ring. In the background, a thought bubble above the man''s head shows two simple images: one of an ear with a piercing needle causing a small exaggerated expression of hurt and a sparkling jewelry box. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon-style facial expressions to emphasize both the pain and the purchase of jewelry as symbolic preparation for marriage. No other people are in the scene, and the setting is a simple neutral background to keep focus on the characters and the symbolic elements.'),
 (1270, 'Marriage Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'SHOTGUN WEDDING:  A case of wife or death.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a classic ''shotgun wedding.'' In the center, a nervous-looking groom in a tuxedo stands beside a cheerful bride in a wedding dress. Behind the groom, a large, slightly oversized cartoon shotgun is being held by a grinning father of the bride, pointing it comically over the groom''s shoulder but not menacingly—more like a playful warning. The setting is a simple wedding venue decorated with flowers, balloons, and a ''Just Married'' sign in the background. The groom appears caught between two exaggeratedly large objects: a heart-shaped wedding bouquet in one hand and a cartoonish skeleton or Grim Reaper figure with a scythe positioned on the other side, symbolizing ''death.'' The expressions should reflect humor and lighthearted tension to convey the joke''s pun: the groom chooses between marrying the wife or facing death. The style is colorful, exaggerated facial expressions and proportions typical of a funny comic strip, suitable for all ages.'),
 (2134, 'Marriage Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Self-Deprecation', 'Never laugh at your wife''s choices - you are one of them', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a husband and wife standing side by side in their cozy living room. The wife has a playful smirk on her face, arms folded with a mix of amusement and mock sternness. The husband looks sheepishly at her, with a slightly embarrassed smile and a slight blush on his cheeks. The husband is pointing at himself, indicating he is one of her "choices." The setting includes a comfy couch behind them, a small table with a vase of flowers, and a framed family photo on the wall that subtly hints they are a happy couple. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the warmth and humor in the joke without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (2448, 'Marriage Humor, Quotes, Weather Humor, Word Play', 'They say marriage is made in heaven, but so is thunder and lightning', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful couple getting married in a beautiful heavenly setting. They stand under a fluffy cloud backdrop with a bright shining sun and angelic figures in the distance. Above them, there’s a large, partly cloudy sky where dramatic thunderclouds form, complete with visible lightning bolts zig-zagging across the sky and colorful cartoon thunder sounds (''BOOM!'') illustrated. The couple is smiling nervously, with one of them looking slightly wide-eyed toward the thunder and lightning above. The wedding arch is decorated with flowers and ribbons, and a small cherub is holding a wedding ring. The overall scene contrasts the romantic wedding moment with the amusing ominous nature of the thunder and lightning happening simultaneously in the same heavenly place, emphasizing the joke’s witty take on marriage and nature. Light pastel colors and exaggerated expressions make the cartoon funny, lively, and family-friendly.'),
 (1271, 'Marriage Humor, Word Play', 'Marriage is a democracy -- one woman, one vote.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a husband and wife sitting at a small table that looks like a voting booth with a ballot box labeled ''Marriage Elections.'' The wife is smiling confidently and holding a single large ballot paper or a big checkmark, while the husband looks slightly puzzled or resigned with a small voting slip or empty hand. The setting is a cozy living room with a picture frame on the wall that shows a heart or wedding ring symbol. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and cheerful expressions to emphasize the joke that in marriage, the wife has the decisive or sole vote.'),
 (1272, 'Marriage Humor, Word Play', 'My wife and I had a big argument about which is the best vowel. I won.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon depicting a husband and wife standing in a brightly colored living room. The husband is smiling confidently, holding up a large letter ''I'' like a trophy, symbolizing his ''win'' in the argument about the best vowel. The wife looks slightly annoyed or surprised, with her arms crossed. Around them are playful visual hints emphasizing vowels: floating large colorful letters A, E, I, O, and U in the background. The scene is lighthearted and fun, with simple, friendly cartoonish characters and no harsh expressions. The atmosphere conveys a playful debate rather than a serious fight.'),
 (1554, 'Math Humor, Philosophy Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'Anyone who considers arithmetical methods of producing random digits is, of course, in a state of sin.', 'John von Neumann (1903-1957)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a mathematician standing in front of a chalkboard filled with complicated equations and random numbers scattered around. The mathematician looks worried or guilty, holding a calculator in one hand and a large book titled ''Random Number Generation'' in the other. Above their head is a thought bubble with a golden halo slightly tilted, symbolizing the ''state of sin'' joke. Around the mathematician, error symbols or question marks float to emphasize confusion about randomness. The background should be a cozy, slightly cluttered study or office with a coffee mug, papers, and math-related posters on the wall. The style is playful and exaggerated with bold lines and bright colors, emphasizing the cartoonish and lighthearted tone without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2340, 'Math Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The mathematician lives long and lives young; the wings of his soul do not early drop off, nor do its pores become clogged with the earthy particles blown from the dusty highways of vulgar life.', 'James Joseph Sylvester', 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a cheerful mathematician standing upright, looking youthful and energetic despite his age. His head is surrounded by glowing, transparent angelic wings shaped like mathematical symbols (like infinity signs, pi symbols, and geometric shapes) fluttering lightly behind him. The mathematician wears a quirky professor outfit with round glasses, a bow tie, and a pocket protector filled with colorful pens. Around his feet, tiny clouds of dust labeled “dusty highways of vulgar life” are blowing past but failing to settle on him. The background is a bright, clean environment, representing mental freshness, with subtle chalkboard formulas floating subtly in the air. The mathematician’s face exudes wisdom and vitality, with a smile that suggests timeless youthfulness. The style is a lighthearted, humorous cartoon, with exaggerated expressions and playful visual metaphors emphasizing the “winged soul” and resisting the grime of ordinary life.'),
 (2434, 'Math Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'There is nothing that can be said by mathematical symbols and relations which cannot also be said by words. The converse, however, is false. Much that can be and is said by words cannot successfully be put into equations, because it is nonsense.', 'C. Truesdell', 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a classroom or study room. In the foreground, a friendly-looking professor or mathematician stands beside a chalkboard filled with complex mathematical symbols and equations. The professor holds a pointer and looks smugly at a student. The student holds a large open book labeled ''Words'' with scribbles and nonsensical phrases spilling out in whimsical lettering that floats around in a chaotic way. The student looks frustrated and confused. Nearby, a speech bubble above the professor shows neat, clean equations with a checkmark, while a speech bubble above the student shows tangled words and question marks turning into a jumbled cloud labeled ''nonsense.'' The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor of how math can say everything words do, but words often fail in math. Include classic classroom props like desks, notebooks, and a globe for ambiance, but keep the focus on the contrast between exact math symbols and the chaotic words cloud.'),
 (3117, 'Math Humor, Political Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'With all the talk of adding Puerto Rico as the 51st state, I feel like we should add two more to be 53 - a prime number. You know how it goes - ''One nation, indivisible''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of diverse, cheerful people standing in front of a large map of the United States on a wall. The map has the usual 50 states outlined clearly. Next to it, there is a small empty space labeled ''Puerto Rico'' with a friendly-looking character representing Puerto Rico holding a suitcase, smiling and ready to join. Nearby, two other smaller characters (personified states) stand, looking eager and excited, each with a number badge: 51 and 52. Above the map, a banner reads ''The United States of America'' with the subtitle ''Now at 53 – A Prime Number!'' On the floor by the map is a large chalkboard with the phrase ''One nation, indivisible'' written in big letters, with a little math equation illustrating the number 53 as a prime number (perhaps a small thought bubble showing ''53 = ?'' with a big check mark). The mood is lighthearted and fun, emphasizing unity and math humor. The style is colorful, friendly, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and no political symbols or controversies.'),
 (1577, 'Math Humor, Pun, Quotes', 'Base 8 is just like base 10, if you are missing two fingers.', 'Tom Lehrer', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. One character is holding up all ten fingers, clearly counting in base 10. The other character is holding up only eight fingers, with two fingers playfully missing or folded down, representing base 8. Both characters have friendly, amused expressions. Above them, floating speech bubbles show the number systems: ''Base 10'' over the character with ten fingers, and ''Base 8'' over the one with eight fingers. The background is simple and colorful, maybe with a chalkboard or thought bubble illustrating numbers 0 to 9 for base 10 and 0 to 7 for base 8. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, ensuring the scene is clean, funny, and easily understandable without any complexity.'),
 (2174, 'Math Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'One man''s constant is another man''s variable.', 'Perlis', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two men standing side by side by a chalkboard filled with math symbols and simple algebra. One man is confidently holding a large constant number ''5'' on a clipboard, smiling proudly. The other man is looking confused or thoughtful at a big question mark drawn on the board labeled ''Variable x''. The setting is a casual classroom or office with a playful vibe, including doodles of numbers, math symbols, and a light bulb above their heads to symbolize thinking. Both men wear casual clothes and have expressive faces to emphasize the difference in how each perceives ''constant'' and ''variable''. The style is lighthearted and colorful to convey the pun in the joke visually without any complexity or seriousness.'),
 (1273, 'Math Humor, Puns', 'There''s a fine line between a numerator and a denominator. (and only a fraction of you will get this..)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, hand-drawn blackboard filled with a simple fraction like 1/2 written in big chalk writing. On the top half of the fraction, a cheerful cartoon character labeled ''Numerator'' with a smiling face stands on the top line of the fraction bar, and on the bottom half, another cartoon character labeled ''Denominator'' looks similar but stands below the fraction line. Between them, a thin, clearly visible line acts as the fraction bar or ''fine line.'' The two characters look playful and friendly, maybe with tiny arms and legs. To the side, a cartoon audience (various diverse characters) reacting with puzzled or amused expressions. In the corner of the board, a small caption reads, ''Only a fraction of you will get this...'' The style should be bright, colorful, and light-hearted, clearly emphasizing the pun on ''a fine line'' and the math fraction theme without any complex background elements—just a classroom or simple setting to keep the focus on the fraction and characters.'),
 (1498, 'Math Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'After a number of decimal places, nobody gives a damn.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a giant chalkboard, covering most of the background, filled with an absurdly long and complicated decimal number, stretching off the edges. In front of the board stands a frustrated-looking math teacher or scientist scratching their head, holding a long pointer at the decimal number. Nearby, a group of bored students or people in casual clothes look increasingly uninterested—some yawning, others doodling or looking away. One person waves their hand dismissively. The setting is a classroom or lecture hall with desks and chairs scattered. The mood is light and comic, emphasizing the idea that after a certain point, the precision or length just doesn’t matter anymore. The style should be Cartesian cartoon with exaggerated expressions and a playful color palette, no harsh lines or dark tones.'),
 (1274, 'Math Humor, Word Play', 'Long computations that yield zero are probably all for naught.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered home office or study room filled with math books, papers, and a computer on a desk. A person with a puzzled or slightly frustrated expression is sitting at the desk, staring at a long scroll of printed calculations that curl all the way to the floor. The scroll ends with a giant zero circled in red. On the wall behind the person, whimsical mathematical symbols and formulas float in thought bubbles, emphasizing complex math work. The person’s hand is raised in a shrugging gesture, conveying the meaning of ''all for naught.'' The overall style is lighthearted and playful, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect of the futile long calculation resulting in zero.'),
 (1275, 'Math Humor, Word Play', 'One Bazillion = A one with a Bunch of zeroes following.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon featuring a large, exaggerated number ''1'' standing upright in the center of the scene. Behind it stretches a comically long string of zeroes that extends off the page, looping and curling whimsically to emphasize its enormous length. The number ''1'' has animated, expressive eyes and a big smile, giving it a cheerful personality. The background is simple and bright, with a subtle gradient to keep focus on the numbers. Optionally, a small character (like a curious child or a confused mathematician) stands at the start of the zeroes, scratching their head or looking amazed, adding to the joke''s playful tone. No other complex objects are needed, keeping the scene light, clear, and fun. The overall style is cartoonish with bold outlines and vibrant colors, suitable for a family-friendly visual pun about large numbers.'),
 (2093, 'Mathematics, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Mathematics transfigures the fortuitous concourse of atoms into the tracery of the finger of God.', 'Herbert Westren Turnbull', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a whimsical, cosmic environment. At the center, depict a large, friendly finger labeled ''Finger of God'' made out of intricate mathematical symbols, equations, and geometric shapes (like fractals or spirals) glowing softly. Around this finger, colorful atoms and particles (simple circles with electron orbits) float and converge toward the finger’s tip in a swirling, magical pattern, symbolizing the ''fortuitous concourse of atoms.'' In the background, include faint stars, subtle math formulas floating in the air, and a subtle glow emphasizing the mystic mathematical transformation. The overall style is lighthearted and playful rather than serious or mystical, with smiling atoms or little sparkling effects to keep it humorous and imaginative.'),
 (2994, 'Medical Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I had my patience tested. I''m negative.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting in a doctor''s office, looking a bit frustrated but calm. The doctor, wearing a white coat and holding a clipboard, is smiling politely as they give the test results. The person’s thought bubble shows a cracked hourglass or a stopwatch to imply ''patience running out.'' On the wall behind them, a sign reads ''Patience Testing Center'' with a cartoonish gauge or meter labeled ''Patience Level.'' The doctor says, ''Your patience test came back negative,'' with a small humorously exaggerated medical chart in the background displaying a simple ''Positive / Negative'' scale related to patience. The mood is light and the style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, aiming to visually represent the pun on ''patience tested'' like a medical test for a virus or illness but applied to patience instead.'),
 (3159, 'Medical Humor, Puns, Science, Word Play', 'Doctor: I''m afraid your DNA is backwards Me: ''AND...?''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a doctor and a patient in a brightly lit medical office. The doctor is standing next to an exam table, wearing a white coat and holding a clipboard, looking slightly puzzled but professional. Above the doctor, display a speech bubble saying, "I''m afraid your DNA is backwards." The patient, sitting on the edge of the exam table with a curious and slightly confused expression, responds with a speech bubble that says, "''AND...?" To emphasize the joke, include a simple DNA double helix diagram on a wall poster behind the doctor, but the helix is shown reversed or mirrored. The setting should be light-hearted and clean, with minimal medical equipment like a stethoscope on a desk and a plant in the corner. Use bright colors and exaggerated, expressive cartoon characters to highlight the play on words in a funny, family-friendly style.'),
 (1276, 'Mental Health Humor, Philosophy Humor', 'Sadness is rarely an illusion.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene featuring a sad-faced character standing in front of a large, whimsical magician''s hat from which colorful, sparkling illusions or magical swirls are emerging. The character looks puzzled and melancholic, with a small rain cloud hovering directly above their head, creating a contrast between the bright illusions and their real sadness. Around the character, there are faint translucent images of illusions or shiny magical objects floating in the air, but the character''s droopy posture and facial expression clearly show genuine sadness that stands apart from the illusions. The setting is simple with a plain background to emphasize the character. The style is lighthearted and humorous despite the serious theme, with exaggerated, rounded features and expressive eyes to highlight the emotional difference between illusion and actual sadness.'),
 (1277, 'Mental Health Humor, Philosophy Humor, Relatable', 'There is no such thing as pure pleasure; some anxiety always goes with it.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person reclining on a comfy armchair with a content smile, holding a tray with a slice of cake and a steaming cup of tea. Around the person, subtle visual cues of anxiety are present: small cartoonish sweat drops, a tiny worried face hovering like a thought bubble above their head, or a small clock showing time ticking. The background should be cozy, like a living room with a bookshelf and a window showing a peaceful day outside. The overall vibe mixes comfort and slight tension to visually represent the idea that even in moments of pleasure, a bit of anxiety lingers. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humorous contrast.'),
 (1278, 'Mental Health Humor, Philosophy, Word Play', 'NEUROTIC: Sane but unhappy about it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a character with a slightly frazzled appearance—disheveled hair and wide, nervous eyes—sitting at a desk with a cup of coffee spilled beside a notebook. The character is slouched, looking both tired and frustrated. Above their head is a thought bubble with the word "Sane" crossed out and replaced with "Unhappy." The background is a simple office or home workspace with a clock showing late hours, emphasizing the mental state. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated features to highlight the neurotic nature without any negativity or distress, incorporating a subtle smile to imply the irony of being ''sane but unhappy.'''),
 (1279, 'Mental Health Humor, Word Play', 'Kiss me twice. I''m schizophrenic.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene shows two identical cartoon characters standing very close to each other. Both look exactly alike, with the same hairstyle, clothes, and facial expressions. One character leans forward puckering lips, ready to give a kiss, while the other character, slightly behind but mirrored, also leans in with puckered lips. Above them is a speech bubble from one character saying, ''Kiss me twice. I''m schizophrenic.'' The background is simple and cheerful, maybe a park bench or neutral interior to keep focus on the characters and the punchline. The style is light and playful, emphasizing the idea of two versions of the same person interacting in a funny way without anything scary or overly serious.'),
 (1280, 'Mental Health Humor, Word Play', 'Watch out for Borderline psychotics - they tend to repeat things.  They tend to repeat things. Watch out for those borderline psychotics.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky psychiatrist''s office. In the center, a cheerful psychiatrist with glasses and a clipboard is pointing nervously toward the office door. The door has a sign above it that reads ''Borderline Psychotic Waiting Room''. Outside the door, a slightly confused patient is pacing back and forth, repeating the same sentence twice with a speech bubble that loops over itself, saying: ''They tend to repeat things... They tend to repeat things.'' In the background, a wall chart titled ''Psychological Terms'' humorously highlights the word ''Borderline'' with a blinking light. The overall color palette is bright and lively, and all characters have exaggerated cartoon features for comedic effect. The scene should evoke a lighthearted, playful mood without any negativity or distress.'),
 (1486, 'Metaphor Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Absence is to love what wind is to fire; it extinguishes the small, it enkindles the great.', 'Comte DeBussy-Rabutin', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two contrasting campfires in a forest clearing. On one side, a tiny, flickering flame is being blown out by a gusty, exaggeratedly strong wind, with scared-looking small flames trying to hold on. On the other side, a large, strong bonfire blazes brightly, with the wind dramatically fanning its flames higher and making it grow bigger. The wind is portrayed as a playful, cartoonish character with a mischievous face, puffing air towards both fires. Around the fires, simple trees and a starry night sky set a peaceful outdoor atmosphere. The mood is light and whimsical, emphasizing the metaphor about absence and love by visually showing how wind (absence) weakens small fires (small love) but strengthens large fires (great love). No people or animals are necessary, and the overall style is colorful and cartoony with clear, exaggerated expressions on the flames and wind.'),
 (2654, 'Military Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Army Law: If it moves, salute it; If it doesn''t move, pick it up; If you can''t pick it up, paint it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a military base with a cheerful soldier in uniform standing at attention. In the foreground, various objects are shown illustrating the joke: a walking soldier moving past, who the main soldier is saluting; a large, immobile cannon or heavy equipment that the soldier is trying to lift with exaggerated effort; and finally, a big, immovable tank or vehicle that the soldier is painting bright green with a large paintbrush. The scene is lighthearted with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, showing the soldier''s determination and slight strain. Background elements can include other soldiers watching or reacting with mild amusement, a military tent, and flags to set the army environment. The style is a clean, funny cartoon suitable for all ages with no violence or negativity.'),
 (2976, 'Money Humor, Political Humor, Satire, Unknown', 'I don''t blame Congress. If I had $600 billion at my disposal, I''d be irresponsible too.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a wealthy personified dollar bill or a giant bag of money labeled "$600 billion" sitting comfortably in a lavish armchair, wearing sunglasses and a smug grin. Next to it, a typical government building labeled "Congress" looks small and somewhat powerless, with a few comically confused or worried-looking cartoon politicians standing around it scratching their heads. The setting is a simple office or legislative chamber background with a large window showing a sunny day outside. The overall tone is light and playful, using bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize irresponsibility associated with having too much money.'),
 (1422, 'Money Humor, Pun, Quotes, Travel Humor', 'A journey of a thousand miles usually begins with a cash advance.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a travel agency counter. The person looks excited and is holding a large wad of cash, handing it to a smiling travel agent behind the desk. Behind the agent, a big colorful poster reads ''Journey of a Thousand Miles'' with a winding road leading to a distant mountain or city. The person has a small suitcase or backpack nearby, suggesting they are about to start a trip. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on both characters’ faces. The setting includes travel-related items like maps, globes, postcards on the wall, and some travel brochures on the counter. Bright cheerful colors and simple shapes emphasize the cartoon and humorous tone of the scene.'),
 (1281, 'Money Humor, Puns', 'The quickest way to double your money is to fold it in half and put it back in your pocket.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a person standing happily with a big grin, holding a folded dollar bill in one hand. The person is folding a single dollar bill neatly in half, clearly amused by their ''money doubling'' method. Nearby, their empty wallet or pocket is visible, open or extended, as they are about to put the folded bill inside. The background is simple and colorful, emphasizing the character and the dollar bill. There can be some light motion lines around the folded money to suggest the action of folding, and a small sparkle or shine on the bill to highlight its ''doubling.'' The style should be lighthearted and playful, capturing the clever but silly literal interpretation of ''doubling money.'''),
 (1282, 'Money Humor, Puns, Workplace', 'We all like praise, but a hike in our pay is the best kind of ways.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two colleagues standing side by side in an office break room. One person, dressed in casual business attire, is giving a thumbs-up and handing over a large paycheck with a big smile. The other person looks delighted, eyes wide and grinning, clearly preferring the paycheck over the verbal praise. Behind them, a whiteboard on the wall displays the words “Praise” with applause emojis and “Pay Raise” with dollar signs and upward arrows. The office setting includes a water cooler, a potted plant, and a coffee machine in the background. The characters have exaggerated facial expressions, emphasizing the joy over the pay raise, with a subtle humorous tone highlighting the pun “hike in pay” sounding like a “hike” walk in nature but referring to money increase instead.'),
 (2110, 'Money Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wit', 'Money couldn''t buy friends, but you get a better class of enemy.', 'Spike Mulligan', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a well-dressed person standing in the middle, holding a large bag of money with a dollar sign on it. Around this person, there are two groups: on one side, a few sad or disappointed figures labeled ''Friends'' looking far away and uninterested; on the other side, a group of flashy, slightly sneaky-looking characters labeled ''Enemies'' with sharper clothes and smug faces, standing closer and appearing more engaged. The setting is an abstract environment with a simple background, like a park or street, to focus on the contrasts between the groups. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated, with expressive facial features emphasizing the joke''s idea that while money doesn''t buy friends, it does attract more refined or prominent enemies. Include some whimsical signs or speech bubbles with playful expressions, but no violence or negativity.'),
 (2643, 'Money Humor, Relatable, Shopping Jokes, Unknown', 'A rich man is one who isn''t afraid to ask the clerk to show him something cheaper.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a fancy boutique or luxury store. In the foreground, show a wealthy-looking man dressed in an expensive suit, wearing a monocle and holding a designer handbag or watch, looking slightly amused and confident. Opposite him, a store clerk with a polite but slightly surprised expression, holding an elegant item (like a watch, handbag, or shoes) in one hand and gesturing with the other, as if inviting the rich man to consider a less expensive alternative. Include a few shelves or display cases filled with very fancy, high-end products to set the upscale shop setting. The man’s speech bubble says, ''Can you show me something cheaper?'' Make sure the style is light-hearted and playful, featuring exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the humor without being aggressive or offensive.'),
 (1283, 'Money Humor, Tech Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs don''t believe in budgets. A good idea is a good idea no matter what it costs.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a modern tech company office. In the center, a confident tech worker wearing glasses and casual clothes (like a T-shirt with a circuit pattern) is standing next to a whiteboard with a chaotic flowchart full of expensive-sounding tech buzzwords and dollar signs. The tech worker is holding a glowing lightbulb above their head, symbolizing a ''good idea.'' Nearby, a stressed-out finance person with a calculator and a big budget spreadsheet labeled ''Company Budget'' looks bewildered and worried. Around them, items like high-end computers, gadgets, and floating dollar signs emphasize cost concerns. The office background shows desks cluttered with coffee cups, cables, and sticky notes. The mood is playful, highlighting the contrast between the carefree tech mindset and the strict budget limitations, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance the humor.'),
 (1284, 'Money Humor, Word Play', 'Nothing in the known universe travels faster than a bad check.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a bad check personified as a tiny character zipping across the universe at incredible speed. Imagine the bad check as a paper check with eyes, arms, and legs, wearing running shoes and a determined expression. The background should be outer space with stars, planets, and comets to emphasize the vastness of the universe. Other cosmic objects, like a spaceship or aliens, can be looking surprised or amazed as the bad check speeds past them in a blur. Include speed lines and motion effects to show the extreme velocity of the bad check, making it clear it''s faster than anything else in space.'),
 (1285, 'Money Humor, Workplace', 'Waste not; your budget will get cut next year.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of an office budget meeting. Show a stressed-out office worker sitting at a desk covered with papers and a small calculator. The worker is looking worriedly at a big, scary budget chart on the wall with a downward arrow and the words ''Next Year Budget Cuts'' in bold. The scene has a large wastebasket overflowing with crumpled paper labeled ''Waste''. Add a speech bubble from the worker saying the joke: ''Waste not; your budget will get cut next year.'' The office environment should have a whiteboard and a clock showing late afternoon. Use bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize humor and mild panic, avoiding anything violent or political.'),
 (2341, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The mind has exactly the same power as the hands: not merely to grasp the world, but to change it.', 'Colin Wilson', 'A colorful cartoon-style scene showing a human character with exaggeratedly large, expressive hands and an oversized brain visible inside a transparent head. The character is standing confidently on a small globe representing the world. One hand is physically holding or grasping a miniature version of the Earth firmly. The other hand is not touching the Earth but instead is illustrated emitting sparkles or magical swirls symbolizing ''changing'' the world, like shaping or molding it. Around the globe, subtle visual effects indicate transformation, such as gears turning, blooming flowers, or tiny buildings rising up. The background is bright and cheerful with soft clouds, emphasizing creativity and power. The character has a playful smile, symbolizing empowerment and wisdom, and the scene overall is drawn in a lighthearted, humorous cartoon style without any threatening or serious elements.'),
 (2372, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The real tragedy is the tragedy of the man who never in his life braces himself for his one supreme effort, who never stretches to his full capacity, never stands up to his full stature.', 'Arnold Bennett', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man of average height standing in a small gym or home workout space. The man looks relaxed and slightly slouched, wearing casual workout clothes but clearly not preparing for any effort. In front of him is a large motivational poster on the wall that reads: ''Brace Yourself for Your Supreme Effort!'' Around him are gym props like a yoga mat, dumbbells, and a stretching strap unused and sitting idle. The room has a playful, lighthearted vibe: a clock showing time passing, an open window with a gentle breeze, and a small cheering cartoon muscle figure encouraging the man, but the man is ignoring all to stay seated or casually standing with no effort. The art style is colorful, cartoonish, and exaggerated for humor, with big eyes and expressive faces emphasizing the man’s lack of readiness contrasted with the motivational message around him. The scene captures the irony of never summoning the strength or stretching to full capacity despite all resources and encouragement being present.'),
 (2301, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religious Humor', 'The first and greatest commandment is, ''don''t let them scare you.''', 'Elmer Davis', 'A humorous cartoon depicting a person standing calmly in front of a large, exaggeratedly scary, shadowy monster with glowing eyes and sharp teeth, but the person is nonchalantly holding a big sign that says, "Don''t Let Them Scare You." The setting is simple—a slightly spooky background with twisted trees and fog to emphasize the ''scary'' vibe. The person''s expression is confident and relaxed, showing no fear. Around them, smaller frightened characters or creatures are looking nervously at the scary monster, while the main character stands firm, defying the fear. The scene should be colorful and playful, with exaggerated features on both the monster and characters to keep it lighthearted and fun.'),
 (2515, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'We could never learn to be brave and patient, if there were only joy in the world.', 'Helen Keller', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene showing a cheerful, colorful world split into two halves. On the left side, depict bright sunshine, vibrant flowers, smiling people, and playful animals to represent ''only joy.'' The right side contrasts with a few small, gentle challenges — like a person waiting patiently at a bus stop in the rain, a child trying to climb a tree looking determined, and a slightly worried but hopeful character standing near a small, harmless obstacle like a fallen branch. Both sides flow seamlessly into each other, illustrating balance. The overall style is friendly and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing patience and bravery on the right side and pure happiness on the left. Include soft clouds and simple backgrounds to keep the focus on the characters'' emotions. The tone should be warm and inspiring without harshness or negativity.'),
 (2380, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The secret of success is to know something nobody else knows.', 'Aristotle Onassis (1906-1975)', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy, bright study room. In the center, a cheerful character (gender-neutral) sits at a cluttered wooden desk filled with books, notes, and a glowing light bulb overhead symbolizing an idea. The character is holding a large, old-fashioned key labeled "Secret of Success." Behind them, a bookshelf is packed with books, some humorously titled like ''Top Secrets'' and ''Unlock Your Potential.'' There is a big thought bubble above the character showing mysterious symbols and question marks, implying knowledge that no one else has. To add humor, a sneaky little cartoon mouse with glasses is peeking from behind a book, looking curious. The scene should be colorful, light-hearted, and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor behind the idea of having a secret nobody else knows as the key to success.'),
 (2583, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Whether you think that you can, or that you can''t, you are usually right.', 'Henry Ford (1863-1947)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two identical characters standing on opposite sides of a large signpost labeled ''Can'' on one side and ''Can''t'' on the other. Both characters look like the same person but dressed slightly differently: the ''Can'' character is confident, smiling, standing tall with arms crossed; the ''Can''t'' character looks unsure, scratching their head nervously. Above them, a thought bubble extends from both heads merging into one that shows a lightbulb (idea) half-glowing. The background is simple with a bright blue sky and a few cartoon-style fluffy clouds. Nearby, a motivational poster on a wall reads: ''Believe in Yourself!'' Emphasize friendly expressions and a clear visual contrast between confidence and doubt to humorously represent the mental states in the joke. The art should be colorful, simple, and cheerful, styled as a light-hearted motivational comic.'),
 (2669, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown', 'Be interested in the future - you will spend the rest of your life there.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a crossroad split into two paths labeled ''Present'' and ''Future.'' The person looks both intrigued and slightly puzzled, scratching their head while looking down the ''Future'' path. The ''Future'' path has whimsical elements like floating clocks, stars, and question marks to suggest uncertainty and possibility. Nearby, a small calendar on the ground shows today''s date with a tiny clock ticking. The background is bright and colorful, with a cheerful sky and some comical directional signs pointing the way. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing curiosity about what lies ahead rather than anxiety.'),
 (2741, 'Motivational Humor, Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Courage is your greatest present need.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a gift box sitting on a table labeled ''PRESENT.'' Instead of a typical gift inside, there is a small, brave-looking character personified as ''Courage'' — a tiny cartoon figure with a superhero cape and a determined expression. Around the box are other typical gift items like bows, wrapping paper, and ribbons, but the focus is on the tiny ''Courage'' figure standing confidently inside the open gift box. A smiling person reaches toward the box with an expression of hopeful anticipation, emphasizing that courage is the most important gift needed right now. The background is simple and cheerful to enhance the lighthearted mood of the scene without any violent or sensitive elements.'),
 (1781, 'Motivational Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'I am only one, but still I am one. I cannot do everything, but still I can do something. And because I cannot do everything, I will not refuse to do the something that I can do.', 'Helen Keller', 'A cheerful cartoon character stands confidently in the center of the image. The character is smiling warmly, with one hand raised as if making a promise or a declaration. Around them are small, whimsical objects representing achievable tasks: a watering can next to a sprouting plant, a single book on the ground, and a paintbrush with a tiny splash of paint. The background is simple and bright with a sunny sky and a few fluffy clouds. Above the character, a speech bubble shows the text of the joke''s key message in a friendly font. The overall tone is positive and encouraging, designed to inspire rather than overwhelm, in a colorful and lighthearted cartoon style.'),
 (2318, 'Motivational Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'The greatest glory in living lies not in never falling, but in rising every time we fall.', 'N. Mandela', 'Draw a cartoon scene of a cheerful character climbing up a small hill made of soft colorful cushions. The character should look happy and determined, with arms outstretched as if they have just gotten up from falling. Around the base of the hill, several cushions are scattered, showing previous ''falls.'' The character is wearing casual clothes, and there is a bright sun in the background with smiling clouds. Include a simple inspiring banner floating overhead with the phrase, ''Rise Every Time You Fall.'' The overall style is lighthearted, positive, and motivational, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the humor and encouragement without any aggression or negativity.'),
 (2299, 'Motivational Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'The difference between the impossible and the possible lies in a person''s determination.', 'Tommy Lasorda', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing at the base of a steep, impossibly high mountain labeled "Impossible" on the left side and "Possible" on the right side. The path on the impossible side looks jagged, with giant boulders and seemingly no way forward. The possible side has a winding but clear path leading up the mountain. The character on the impossible side looks frustrated and ready to give up, while the character on the possible side is confidently striding up the path with a big smile and a determined expression. Above them, a large, whimsical sign hanging on a post reads: "Determination Bridge" connecting the two sides, suggesting the bridge is the key to crossing from impossible to possible. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor and motivational aspect of the joke.'),
 (2622, 'Motivational Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'You''ll never find a better sparring partner than adversity.', 'Walt Schmidt', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a determined cartoon character, depicted as a boxer with gloves and shorts, standing in a simple boxing ring. Instead of an opponent, the boxer faces a large, anthropomorphic cloud or mist labeled ''Adversity'' with a playful but challenging expression. The cloud is positioned in a fighting stance, shadowboxing in place, puffing small angry steam puffs. The background is a lighthearted gym or arena environment with a cheering audience of various silly, supportive caricatures like animals and objects holding banners that say ''Keep Fighting!'' and ''Never Give Up!''. The scene should be colorful and vibrant, with exaggerated, friendly facial expressions, creating a comedic but motivational atmosphere.'),
 (2573, 'Motivational Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Sports Humor', 'When you are not practicing, remember, someone somewhere is practicing, and when you meet him he will win.', 'Ed Macauley', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a simple competition setting, like a race or a martial arts showdown. On the left side, one character is casually lounging on a bench, looking relaxed and distracted, maybe eating a snack or scrolling on a phone, clearly ''not practicing.'' On the right side, the other character is energetically practicing with intense focus — perhaps doing stretches, lifting dumbbells, or punching a training bag. In the middle or foreground, both are facing each other about to compete. The focused character looks confident and ready, while the lounging one looks surprised and worried. The background can be a simple gym or outdoor training area with minimal props like cones, dumbbells, or a stopwatch. Use bright colors and exaggerated expressions for a lighthearted and funny vibe, emphasizing the contrast between the two attitudes.'),
 (2325, 'Motivational Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The intelligent man is one who has successfully fulfilled many accomplishments, and is yet willing to learn more.', 'Ed Parker', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly nerdy-looking man with glasses and a stack of diplomas, trophies, and certificates piled up beside him, symbolizing his many accomplishments. He is seated at a desk cluttered with books and a laptop, eagerly reading a new book titled ''More to Learn.'' Around him, lightly floating question marks and lightbulbs emphasize curiosity and continuous learning. The man''s expression is enthusiastic and open-minded. The background is a cozy study room with motivational posters on the wall reading ''Never Stop Learning'' and ''Knowledge is Power.'' The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated features to enhance humor and warmth, making the intellect and eagerness to learn visually obvious and charming.'),
 (2233, 'Motivational Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Shoot for the moon. Even if you miss, you''ll land among the stars.', 'Les Brown', 'A cheerful cartoon scene showing a person in a space suit standing on a small cartoonish moon cratering the lunar surface. The person is aiming a slingshot or bow and arrow labeled ''Dreams'' up towards a bright, smiling crescent moon in the starry night sky. Around the person and moon, there are numerous twinkling, playful stars with happy faces, scattered across a dark blue background. The person has an optimistic expression, and the scene has a whimsical, light-hearted feel, emphasizing inspiration and hope. Cartoon style with vibrant colors, simple shapes, and exaggerated expressions to enhance humor and positivity.'),
 (2259, 'Motivational Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Success is a dream. Dream success.', 'J. Clarke', 'A humorous cartoon featuring a person sleeping peacefully in bed with a big smile on their face and a thought bubble above their head. Inside the thought bubble, the word ''Success'' appears as a shining, sparkling trophy or medal. Around the person’s bed, whimsical dream-like elements float, such as stars, clouds, and tiny doodles of money and awards. In the background, a dreamy sky with soft pastel colors suggests the boundary between sleep and waking. Below the sleeping person, the phrase ''Dream success.'' is written in playful, bold letters, complementing the overall lighthearted and uplifting mood of the scene. The style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for humor and positivity.'),
 (3151, 'Motivational Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Your ''I Will'' is more important than your ''IQ''.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing two characters facing each other in a friendly and humorous way. On the left, a character with a big brain glowing or sparkling cartoonishly above their head, labeled ''IQ''. On the right, a determined character flexing their muscles or striking a confident pose, with a large scroll or contract in hand labeled ''I Will''. The background is simple and bright, emphasizing the contrast between intelligence (IQ) and determination (I Will). Both characters have exaggerated cartoon expressions: the IQ character looks thoughtful or smug, while the I Will character looks enthusiastic and resolute. Add subtle motion lines around the determined character to suggest energy and drive. The style should be lighthearted, humorous, and suitable for a family-friendly cartoon panel or a motivational comic strip.'),
 (2007, 'Motivational, Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'It''s kind of fun to do the impossible.', 'Walt Disney', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful character standing triumphantly on top of a small mountain or mound labeled ''Impossible.'' The character is mid-jump with arms raised in celebration, wearing casual, colorful clothes and a big smile. Around the base of the mountain are whimsical, exaggerated obstacles like giant clocks, floating question marks, and a signpost pointing in confusing directions labeled ''Impossible Road,'' ''No Way Out,'' and ''Maybe Never.'' The sky is bright with a few fluffy clouds, and a playful sun with sunglasses beams down. The scene is light-hearted and imaginative, emphasizing fun and positivity in achieving what seems impossible rather than anything serious or daunting. No other people or animals are needed, focusing on the single joyful figure and metaphorical obstacles to illustrate the joke''s abstract concept visually.'),
 (1286, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor', 'The important thing is not to stop questioning.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a curious young child and a friendly-looking adult sitting together at a kitchen table. The child eagerly holds a magnifying glass up to a cookie on a plate, examining it closely with wide eyes and raised eyebrows. The adult, wearing glasses and a slight smile, gestures encouragingly with one hand as if nurturing the child''s curiosity. On the table are scattered question marks floating above as if arising from their conversation. The background shows a cozy kitchen with a window letting in sunlight and a bookshelf filled with books and a small globe. The overall vibe is warm, lighthearted, and emphasizes the theme of continuous questioning and curiosity, with playful exaggerated expressions on both characters’ faces to enhance the humor and inspiration of the quote.'),
 (1287, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor', 'To believe you can is everything.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a cheerful, eager character standing at the starting line of a race track labeled ''Life Challenge.'' The character is in mid-lean, ready to sprint, eyes bright with determination. Above their head is a glowing, large, inspirational thought bubble containing the phrase ''To believe you can is everything.'' Around the track are simple, encouraging signs like ''You got this!'' and ''Keep going!'' The background is bright and optimistic with a clear blue sky and a few fluffy clouds. The overall mood is motivational and light-hearted, drawn in a colorful, exaggerated cartoon style emphasizing positive energy and self-confidence.'),
 (1494, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Action may not always bring happiness, but there is no happiness without action.', 'Benjamin Disraeli', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful character standing at a crossroads. One path is labeled ''Action'' and looks vibrant, filled with lively colors, flowers, and a bright sun overhead. The other path, labeled ''No Action,'' appears dull and gray with wilting plants and a gloomy sky. The character is mid-step towards the ''Action'' path with a big smile, arms raised in excitement, showing determination and happiness. Add thought bubbles above the character’s head: one showing a happy face linked to action, and another with a sad face linked to inaction. The overall style should be lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and colorful surroundings. Include a signpost with the quote written neatly on it: "Action may not always bring happiness, but there is no happiness without action." The background should be simple, focused on the crossroads and the character’s choice, ensuring the message of the quote is clear and visually engaging without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1464, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'A second chance is an opportunity with experience.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing at a large open door labeled ''Second Chance.'' The door is shiny and inviting, with a bright light shining through. On the right side of the door, a shadowy figure representing ''Experience'' is waiting outside, wearing glasses and holding a briefcase filled with documents entitled ''Lessons Learned.'' The person looks excited but slightly curious, glancing at Experience with a smile. Behind the person, a faint outline of a previous version of themselves is walking away, looking less confident and a bit clumsy, symbolizing past mistakes. The background should be simple and colorful, emphasizing the theme of opportunity and growth with a lighthearted, cartoonish style. No harsh lines or dark elements—just playful and encouraging imagery.'),
 (1730, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Great spirits always encounter violent opposition from mediocre minds.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene depicting an energetic lightbulb character labeled ''Great Spirit'' trying to shine brightly on the left side of the image. On the right side, several dull, gray-minded characters with flat, uninspired faces and crossed arms stare skeptically at the lightbulb. These ''mediocre minds'' can be shown as small, gray clouds with simple, unimpressed eyes and mouths, symbolizing closed thinking or negativity. The background should be simple and uncluttered, with a contrast between the bright glow around the lightbulb and the dull gray tint surrounding the mediocre minds. Include a playful facial expression on the lightbulb character showing determination and enthusiasm. The overall style should be whimsical and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between brightness and dullness without any aggression or negativity—just a visual metaphor of opposition between inspiration and mediocrity.'),
 (1863, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'If a man does his best, what else is there?', 'General George S. Patton (1885-1945)', 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing proudly with a big smile, wearing casual clothes, looking slightly flushed as if he just finished a challenging task. Surrounding him are various completed efforts—a finished painting on an easel, a neatly made bed, a cooked meal on the table, and a tidy workshop with tools organized. Above the man, a speech bubble contains the words: ''If a man does his best, what else is there?'' The background is cheerful, with soft pastel colors and a subtle sunbeam shining down on the man as if highlighting his achievement. The overall tone is lighthearted and uplifting, emphasizing the humor in the rhetorical question about doing one''s best being enough.'),
 (1858, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I''d rather be a could-be if I cannot be an are; because a could-be is a maybe who is reaching for a star. I''d rather be a has-been than a might-have-been, by far; for a might-have-been has never been, but a has was once an are.', 'Milton Berle', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting three whimsical characters representing the words ''are,'' ''could-be,'' and ''has-been.'' At center stage is a confident, shiny gold star with eyes and a smile labeled ''are.'' Nearby, a hopeful character labeled ''could-be'' is a charming, eager figure reaching upward toward a bright, twinkling star in the sky showing aspiration. To the side, a relaxed, slightly older character labeled ''has-been'' wears vintage clothing and lounges comfortably on a plush armchair, holding a cup of tea, smiling knowingly. In the background, a faded, ghostly figure labeled ''might-have-been'' is slightly transparent and looks wistful, gazing longingly at the others. The setting is a lightly whimsical, theatrical stage with curtains drawn back, symbolizing life''s roles. The expressions and body language emphasize hope, achievement, and nostalgia in a playful, light-hearted way, with bright colors and soft lines enhancing the cartoon format without any harsh or negative themes.'),
 (1288, 'Motivational, Philosophy Humor, School', 'Teachers aren''t the ''enemy.'' Other students aren''t the ''enemy.'' The only real ''enemy'' is what we believe we cannot accomplish.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon classroom scene. At the center, a confident student stands facing a large, friendly blackboard with the phrase ''The only real enemy is what we believe we cannot accomplish'' written boldly. Surrounding the student are smiling classmates who look supportive, and the teacher is giving a thumbs up, showing encouragement. Instead of traditional intimidation, the ''enemy'' is depicted as a silly, small, and goofy-looking shadow labeled ''Self-Doubt'' that is comically sneaking away, defeated. The classroom setting should be bright and optimistic with posters about learning and success on the walls. Keep the style playful and lighthearted, emphasizing the positive message that challenges come from within, not from others in the environment.'),
 (1628, 'Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Difficulties are meant to rouse, not discourage.', 'William Ellery Channing', 'A humorous cartoon scene set outdoors with a determined cartoon character standing at the base of a steep, slightly exaggerated mountain labeled ''Difficulties.'' The character is wearing casual hiking clothes and has a comically oversized backpack filled with symbolic objects like a light bulb (ideas), a book (knowledge), and a heart (motivation) poking out. The character looks lively and excited, with wide eyes and a confident smile, as if ready to climb. At the mountain''s peak, a bright sunrise is breaking through clouds, symbolizing hope and success. Around the base of the mountain are small signs or rocks with words like ''Discouragement'' discarded or trampled on by the character. The overall style is colorful and playful, with bold lines and exaggerated expressions to capture the positive, uplifting mood of the quote in a lighthearted way.'),
 (1650, 'Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Dreams and dedication are a powerful combination.', 'William Longgood', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful, energetic person climbing a steep mountain labeled ''Dreams'' while holding a giant flag labeled ''Dedication.'' The mountain is exaggeratedly tall and jagged, with whimsical clouds and sun shining in the background. At the base of the mountain, a signpost points upward reading ''Success.'' The climber is wearing casual adventure gear, with a big smile, showing determination. Around the mountain are small, humorous elements like motivational sticky notes stuck on rocks, and tiny cartoon birds cheering. The overall colors are bright and uplifting, creating a lighthearted, positive vibe emphasizing the power of combining dreams and dedication.'),
 (1719, 'Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Go confident in the direction of your dreams. Live the life you''ve imagined.', 'Thoreau', 'A cheerful cartoon scene showing a confident person walking along a path labeled ''DREAMS'' that stretches toward a bright, shining sunset on the horizon. The character has a big smile, chest out proudly, and is casually dressed with a backpack and a map rolled up sticking out of it. Along the path are whimsical signs pointing in encouraging directions like ''Live Your Best Life'', ''Imagination Station'', and ''Positive Vibes''. The sky is colorful with warm tones, fluffy clouds, and birds flying. In the background are faint outlines of abstract dream symbols, such as stars, lightbulbs, and hearts floating gently above the path. The overall mood is uplifting and inspiring, drawn in a simple, friendly cartoon style with rounded shapes and vivid colors to emphasize optimism and motivation.'),
 (2133, 'Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Never frown, even when you are sad, because you never know who is falling in love with your smile.', 'Justin Milton', 'A cheerful cartoon scene featuring a smiling person standing in the center, brightly illuminated by a sunny, warm background. The person should have a big, genuine smile and eyes sparkling with happiness. Around them, several characters in the background (two or three) are subtly depicted looking at the smiling person with hearts or sparkles over their heads, indicating admiration or falling in love. The setting should be simple and pleasant, like a park or a street on a sunny day, with a few trees or flowers to create a happy atmosphere. The smiling person should be in everyday casual clothes, and their expression should clearly convey warmth and positivity. The style should be light-hearted and humorous, with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize friendliness and attraction. Avoid dark or sad elements—focus on the uplifting mood of the quote.'),
 (2075, 'Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'Make the most of yourself, for that is all there is of you.', 'Ralph Waldo Emerson', 'A lighthearted cartoon scene featuring a person looking into a small, handheld mirror with a bright smile. The character is standing in front of a backdrop that subtly resembles a stage or spotlight setting, emphasizing self-focus. Around them, exaggerated reflections of themselves are playfully shown doing different activities like juggling, reading, and dancing, symbolizing making the most of their abilities and personality. The overall tone is cheerful and motivational, using soft pastel colors and simple, rounded shapes to emphasize a humorous and uplifting vibe without any harsh lines or complicated details.'),
 (1632, 'Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Do not commit the error, common among the young, of assuming that if you cannot save the whole of mankind you have failed.', 'Jan de Hartog', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a young person standing on a small hilltop, looking somewhat overwhelmed but determined. The young person wears casual clothes and carries a big, oversized globe labeled ''Mankind'' that looks too heavy and cumbersome for them to hold or carry properly. Around them are tiny groups of cartoon-style people representing ''mankind'' scattered all over a vast landscape stretching into the distance. The sky is clear with a bright sun, and a friendly-looking wise old character (perhaps an older mentor or philosopher with spectacles, a book in hand, and a gentle smile) stands nearby offering encouragement. The mentor gestures toward the distant people, implying that saving even a small part is meaningful. The overall tone is lighthearted and optimistic, showing the young person’s struggle mixed with hope, without any threatening or negative elements. The art style is colorful, exaggerated, and playful to emphasize the message humorously and warmly.'),
 (2022, 'Motivational, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom', 'Keep the faith and it will keep you.', 'C.W. Treacy', 'A cheerful, cartoon-style scene showing a person standing peacefully in a sunny, pleasant outdoor setting. The person is holding a glowing, oversized candle labeled ''Faith'' that emits a soft, warm light surrounding them. In the background, faint outlines of clouds part to reveal a bright blue sky with rays of sunlight. The person’s expression is calm and hopeful, with gentle, uplifted eyebrows and a slight smile. Nearby, small whimsical elements like floating sparkles or tiny hearts emphasize positivity and reassurance. The overall mood is comforting and encouraging, depicted in bright, friendly colors and smooth, rounded lines to enhance a lighthearted, inspirational feel.'),
 (2184, 'Motivational, Pun, Quotes, Workplace', 'Opportunity is missed by most people because it is dressed in overalls and looks like work.', 'Thomas Alva Edison', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person encountering ''Opportunity'' as a lively, cheerful character wearing blue denim overalls, a tool belt, and a hard hat, holding a hammer and paintbrush. The setting is a sunny backyard or construction site with a ''Work Zone'' sign and some building materials like wooden planks, a ladder, and paint cans scattered around. The person looks hesitant or uncertain, standing nearby in casual clothes (shirt and pants), scratching their head or stepping back as if unsure about approaching. In the background, a bright shining sun or light glows subtly around ''Opportunity'' to hint its importance. The overall style is playful and vibrant with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the humor and the metaphor that opportunity often comes disguised as hard work.'),
 (1289, 'Motivational, Puns', 'Success is not the result of spontaneous combustion. You must light yourself on fire.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky character, perhaps a cheerful person wearing casual clothes, standing outdoors with a big smile. The person holds a giant matchstick, striking it against a big matchbox labeled ''Motivation.'' Flames subtly but comically start to flicker on the person''s feet or hands (clearly cartoon fire, not painful or scary). Around them, motivational posters or signs hang on a fence or wall, with slogans like ''Light Up Your Life!'' and ''Ignite Your Passion!'' The background shows a sunny day in a park or backyard, with cartoonish trees and a bench, creating a light-hearted and positive atmosphere. The character''s expression should be confident and funny, emphasizing the pun on ''light yourself on fire'' as an energetic metaphor for self-motivation rather than literal burning. Overall, the artwork should be vibrant, exaggerated, and playful to capture the clever wordplay of the joke.'),
 (1635, 'Motivational, Quotes, Religious Humor', 'Do not settle for mediocrity. The kingdom of heaven is for those determined to enter it.', 'Pope John Paul II', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a narrow, brightly lit golden gate labeled ''Kingdom of Heaven'' at the top center. In front of it stands a cheerful, cartoon-style character wearing simple, everyday clothes, determinedly pushing a large wooden sign that says ''Mediocrity'' backwards away from the gate, symbolizing rejecting mediocrity. Around the gate, show a crowd of characters in bland, gray attire looking confused or hesitant at a fork in the path, with one path leading to the majestic golden gate and the other path fading into a dull, gray fog labeled ''Mediocrity.'' The background should be simplistic with fluffy white clouds and a heavenly glow behind the gate to emphasize the uplifting, positive theme. The overall style is light-hearted and funny, using exaggerated expressions to highlight determination and the contrast between mediocre and excellence without any violent or sensitive elements.'),
 (2135, 'Motivational, Quotes, Wisdom Humor, Workplace', 'Never mistake motion for action.', 'Ernest Hemingway (1899-1961)', 'A humorous cartoon showing two characters in an office setting. On the left, a person is wildly running on a treadmill labeled ''Busy Work'' with exaggerated motion lines, sweat flying, and a frantic expression, symbolizing ''motion.'' On the right, another character calmly sits at a desk, focused and checking off tasks on a clipboard labeled ''Action,'' with a satisfied smile. The background is simple, with an office desk, chair, a clock on the wall showing time passing, and a small plant for decoration. The contrast between frantic movement and calm productivity creates a funny but clear visual metaphor for the joke.'),
 (1290, 'Motivational, Sports Humor, Word Play', 'The most important quality of a champion is the burning desire to be a champion.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a determined, energetic character standing on a winner''s podium labeled ''Champion.'' The character has flames comically rising from their head and shoulders to represent the ''burning desire.'' The character is wearing a gold medal and sports attire, striking a confident pose with clenched fists and a big smile. Around the podium are cheering cartoon spectators holding signs that say ''Go Champion!'' The background is a colorful stadium with bright lights, emphasizing a competitive sports atmosphere. The scene should be lighthearted and exaggerated in style to highlight the pun on ''burning desire,'' with the flames looking more like playful cartoon fire rather than anything dangerous.'),
 (1348, 'Movie Humor, Programmers, Pun, Word Play', 'What''s Forrest Gump''s password? 1forest1', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene showing a cheerful Forrest Gump sitting at a simple wooden desk typing on a classic computer keyboard. The computer screen clearly displays a password field with the typed password: ''1forest1''. Forrest is smiling widely, wearing his iconic white running outfit and red baseball cap. Behind him, there is a simple background hinting at the outdoors with a small forest of green trees visible through a window. To emphasize the humor, a thought bubble above Forrest''s head shows a running trail and an exclamation mark, suggesting the pun on his name combined with a common password style. The overall style is lighthearted, playful, and exaggerated in a fun cartoon format with bright, cheerful colors and expressive features on Forrest’s face.'),
 (3171, 'Movies, Pun, Science Fiction Humor, Star Wars', 'I just watched a great documentary about how the Death Star was built. It was riveting', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy living room where a person sits comfortably on a couch holding a remote control and watching TV. On the TV screen, an illustrated documentary-style image shows the construction of the Death Star from Star Wars, with small engineers and construction machines working on the giant spherical space station. The TV frame has the title ''Death Star: How It Was Built'' at the top. The person on the couch looks amused and engaged, smiling with wide eyes. Around the room, sci-fi themed decorations like a Star Wars poster, a lightsaber lamp, and a cardboard cutout of Darth Vader add to the atmosphere. The style is light and cartoonish, emphasizing the playfulness of watching a serious documentary about a fictional, iconic space weapon described as ''riveting.'''),
 (1450, 'Music Humor, Occupational Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A musicologist is a man who can read music but can''t hear it.', 'Sir Thomas Beecham', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a slightly confused man labeled as a ''musicologist'' sitting at a desk covered with open music sheets and books about music theory. The man is wearing glasses and holding a magnifying glass over the sheet music, intently studying the notes. Around him, musical notes float in the air but appear silent—depicted as notes without any sound waves or musical effects. His ears have little sound-proof earmuffs or cartoon zzz''s above them to show he can’t hear the music. The background can be a cozy study or library filled with stacks of music books and a framed diploma on the wall. The expression on his face is focused but puzzled, emphasizing the joke that he can read music perfectly but cannot actually hear it. The overall style is light, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, making the scene friendly and funny without any references to violence, politics, or anything controversial.'),
 (2471, 'Music Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', '''TO DO IS TO BE''. Jean Paul Sartre.  ''TO BE IS TO DO''. Bertrand Russell. ''DO BE DO BE DO''. Frank Sinatra.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing three characters who represent the three quotes. On the left, Jean Paul Sartre is depicted as a classical philosopher figure with timeless scholar attire (a tweed jacket, round glasses, and a thoughtful pose), holding a small chalkboard that reads ''TO DO IS TO BE''. In the middle, Bertrand Russell is drawn as a serious, older philosopher with neat hair and a suit, holding a book titled ''Philosophy'' and a speech bubble with ''TO BE IS TO DO''. On the right, Frank Sinatra is a lively, playful character in a flashy suit and fedora, singing into a vintage microphone with musical notes swirling around him and a speech bubble saying ''DO BE DO BE DO''. The scene takes place on a simple stage with a spotlight shining on the three men. The style is colorful, cartoonish, exaggerated faces for humor, and a lighthearted atmosphere emphasizing the playful progression from deep philosophical quotes to a jazzy song lyric. Include subtle background elements like a philosophy book on a stool near Sartre and Russell and a music stand near Sinatra to highlight their distinct worlds.'),
 (3047, 'Music Humor, Physical Comedy, Pun, Unknown', 'I tripped and hit my head on a snare drum. Now I think I have a percussion.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person who has just tripped and is stumbling forward toward a large snare drum on the floor. The person has a surprised, dizzy expression, with cartoon stars or small birds circling around their head to show they are dazed. The snare drum should be large and clearly identifiable with drumsticks lying nearby. The setting can be a simple stage or music room with a few musical notes floating in the air to emphasize the musical context. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated for comedic effect, with bright colors and clear, simple lines.'),
 (1342, 'Music Humor, Programmers, Technology Humor, Word Play', 'There''s a new band called 1023MB. They haven''t had any gigs yet.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky rock band named ''1023MB''. Show a small group of cartoon characters on a simple stage with musical instruments like a guitar, drums, and microphone stands. The band members look hopeful but a bit confused or disappointed. In front of the stage, instead of a typical audience, draw a few empty chairs or a small crowd of pixelated computer icons with speech bubbles showing data symbols (like bits and bytes) looking indifferent. Include a colorful banner or sign above the stage that reads ''1023MB'' in playful tech-style font. Add a humorous touch by depicting a digital loading bar or a computer progress circle hovering above them, stuck just short of ''full'' to emphasize the joke about not having any gigs (gigs = concerts and gigabytes). The background should be a simple music venue with cartoonish spotlights shining down. The style is light-hearted, bright, and exaggerated for comedic effect without any violent or inappropriate elements.'),
 (2730, 'Music Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'Country and Western Song Titles: If You Keep Checkin'' Up on Me (I''m Checkin'' Out on You)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a classic country and western singer standing on a small wooden stage under a cowboy hat. The singer is holding a microphone and looking slightly dramatic with a twangy expression, wearing a plaid shirt, jeans, and cowboy boots. Behind him is a large, illustrated song title sign reading: ''If You Keep Checkin'' Up on Me (I''m Checkin'' Out on You)''. On the side of the stage, a small audience of smiling country fans wearing cowboy hats and boots laugh and tap their feet. The overall style is colorful, warm, and exaggerated with big smiles and expressive faces to amplify the pun. Elements like a guitar leaning against an amp and a rustic wooden backdrop complete the country music vibe. The tone is lighthearted and playful, capturing the double meaning of ''checkin'' out'' as both monitoring and leaving.'),
 (2969, 'Music Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I can''t reach the brakes on this piano!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a grand piano with an exaggeratedly long keyboard stretching far beyond the usual size. The person looks frustrated and is trying to reach down towards the piano pedals on the floor, but their arms are stretched awkwardly, unable to reach. The piano has three pedals clearly visible and oversized piano keys. The background is simple and light-colored to keep focus on the character and piano. Include a small speech bubble above the person saying, ''I can''t reach the brakes on this piano!'' Make the artistic style playful and lighthearted, with cartoonish proportions and expressive facial features emphasizing the comedic struggle.'),
 (1567, 'Music Humor, Puns, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Are part-time band leaders semi-conductors?', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a small group of musicians arranged like a band or orchestra. In the center, a quirky character dressed as a band leader stands on a podium holding a baton, but looking casual and slightly confused, wearing a badge or sign that reads ''Part-Time Band Leader.'' Surrounding the leader are various cartoon-style musical instruments such as trumpets, drums, guitars, and a keyboard. The band leader''s clothing subtly incorporates electronic circuit motifs or glowing semiconductor chips to hint at the pun. The background is a simple stage with a banner that says ''Semi-Conductor Band'' in playful lettering. The style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated, with smiling characters and a lighthearted atmosphere, emphasizing the wordplay between a band leader and semiconductor electronics without any technical or overly complex elements.'),
 (2871, 'Music Humor, Puns, Unknown, Word Play', 'Found on a door in the MSU music building: This door is baroquen, please wiggle Handel. (If I wiggle Handel, will it wiggle Bach?)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a wooden door labeled "MSU Music Building" with an ornate, baroque-style handle shaped like a classical musical instrument, such as a violin scroll or a fancy old-fashioned doorknob. A person stands next to the door, looking confused but amused, wiggling the door handle with a slight smile. Above the door, a whimsical sign reads: "This door is baroquen, please wiggle Handel." In the background, musical notes and subtle references to famous classical composers (like portraits or sheet music labeled ''Handel'' and ''Bach'') decorate the walls. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun on "baroquen" (baroque), "Handel" (the composer and the handle pun), and "Bach." The mood is light and fun, highlighting the clever wordplay.'),
 (1291, 'Music Humor, Word Play', 'Rap music is my second favorite type of music. Every other form of music is tied for #1.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful person with headphones enjoying music. They stand in front of a large colorful scoreboard divided into two sections: one reads ''Second Favorite: Rap Music'' with a single star, and the other shows a crowded tie with many music genres all jumbled together under ''First Favorite: All Other Music.'' Around the person are musical notes floating in the air, with little icons representing different genres like rock guitars, classical violins, jazz saxophones, and pop microphones, all grouped equally on the ''First Favorite'' side. The character has a playful smirk and is shrugging as if proud of their quirky ranking system. The background should be bright and vibrant to keep the mood light and funny, emphasizing the joke''s wordplay about music preferences.'),
 (1850, 'Nature Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'I would feel more optimistic about a bright future for man if he spent less time proving that he can outwit Nature and more time tasting her sweetness and respecting her seniority.', 'E. B. White', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful man sitting relaxed on a grassy hill under a large, wise-looking ancient tree with a face (like a friendly elder). The man is holding and tasting a shiny ripe fruit from the tree with an appreciative smile. Around them, various playful elements represent ''Nature'': flowers, bees, butterflies, and a small stream flowing nearby. In the background, a complicated and bizarre array of human inventions like a complex maze of gadgets, books, and scientific tools are cluttered, gathering dust and ignored by the man. The tree’s expression is kindly but slightly amused, hinting at its wisdom and seniority over man. The overall tone is light and gentle, with vibrant colors and exaggerated cartoonish proportions to accentuate the humor about respecting nature rather than trying to outsmart it.'),
 (2255, 'Nature Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Seasonal Humor', 'Spring is nature''s way of saying, ''Let''s Party!''', 'Robin Williams', 'A bright and cheerful outdoor spring scene in cartoon style. The setting shows blossoming flowers, green grass, and trees with fresh leaves under a sunny sky. In the center, anthropomorphic flowers and animals like butterflies, bees, and birds are depicted having a lively party. The flowers have smiling faces and are dancing with party hats and streamers, bees are buzzing around with tiny instruments like drums or trumpets, and birds are perched on branches singing joyfully. Colorful balloons and confetti float gently in the air. The overall mood is festive and playful, emphasizing a joyful celebration of spring as if nature itself is throwing a party.'),
 (2948, 'Nature Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'How much do rainbows weigh? Not much - they''re actually pretty light.', NULL, 'A colorful cartoon scene featuring a bright, vibrant rainbow arching softly across a cheerful blue sky dotted with fluffy white clouds. At one end of the rainbow, a cute, smiling scale with large, friendly eyes is tilted slightly as if weighing the rainbow itself. Nearby, a small cartoon character, like a curious child or a whimsical creature, is looking up at the rainbow holding a tiny feather in one hand, symbolizing ''lightness.'' The overall mood is playful and lighthearted, with exaggerated features and pastel colors to enhance the humor. The setting is simple with green rolling hills below and the sun shining gently to keep the scene bright and joyful. No people or objects look distressed or heavy—everything is in a humorous, gentle cartoon style.'),
 (1292, 'Nature Humor, Relatable, Word Play', 'Weeds always grow like weeds.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a suburban backyard garden. In the foreground, there is a patch of various garden plants with a few big, scraggly weeds growing tall and wild among them. The weeds are personified with silly faces and exaggerated features like wild, unkempt leaves and crooked stems, looking proud and mischievous. A gardener with a slightly puzzled or bemused expression is standing to the side, holding a watering can, looking at the weeds almost admiringly. Behind the gardener, a small sign stuck in the ground reads ''Garden''. The overall style should be lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the weeds’ uncontrolled and unruly growth as if they are happily doing exactly what weeds do best. No harmful or aggressive elements, just playful chaos of nature overruling human intent.'),
 (2943, 'Nature Humor, Seasonal Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'How does a tree feel on the first day of spring? Relieved', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly-looking tree in a park setting on a sunny early spring day. The tree has a big smile on its face and slightly raised ''eyebrows'' made from branches to show relief. Around the tree, fresh green leaves are just starting to sprout, and a few colorful spring flowers bloom at its base. Small animals like a couple of birds or a squirrel are nearby, looking cheerful. The background shows patches of melting snow and bright sunshine with a clear blue sky. Include a subtle visual cue like a small calendar page or sign reading ''First Day of Spring'' placed near the tree to emphasize the context. The overall style should be cartoonish and lighthearted, with vibrant colors and exaggerated facial expressions on the tree to convey the feeling of relief and happiness.'),
 (1328, 'Nerd Humor, Programmers, Programming, Pun', '[''hip'',''hip''] (hip hip array!)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of computer programmers or mathematicians standing around a large whiteboard. The whiteboard displays a simple array or list that has two elements labeled ''hip'' and ''hip'' as text strings in square brackets: [''hip'', ''hip'']. One character, smiling widely and confidently, is pointing at the array and saying ''Hip hip array!'' as if it''s a clever pun. The other characters look amused or chuckling. The setting is a casual office or classroom with simple desks, laptops, coffee mugs, and coding posters on the walls. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and playful, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun''s humor. The overall mood is fun and geeky, capturing the pun on the traditional ''hip hip hooray'' phrase but cleverly twisted with programming/array humor.')
INSERT INTO @tmpJokes (JokeId, Categories, JokeTxt, Attribution, ImageTxt) VALUES
 (1293, 'Nerd Humor, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Real Techs have no blank paper on which to write. They were brought up writing on scraps and the backs of octal dumps. It was good enough for their teachers and it''s good enough for them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered, slightly chaotic workspace of a computer technician. The tech is a quirky-looking person wearing glasses and a T-shirt with a pixelated computer icon. Around them are scattered scraps of paper filled with handwritten notes and strange octal number dumps (strings of zeros and ones or digits 0-7) on the back sides of papers, old floppy disks, and coffee-stained notebooks. The technician holds a tiny torn piece of paper in one hand and a pencil in the other, looking both determined and slightly amused. In the background, you see a whiteboard with a complex, nerdy diagram, and a vintage computer monitor displaying hexadecimal or octal code. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, using cartoon exaggeration like animated question marks or light bulbs around the tech’s head to symbolize problem-solving and nostalgia. The environment looks busy but cozy, emphasizing a humorous embrace of old-school, resourceful tech habits rather than neat organization.'),
 (1316, 'Objects Humor, Pirates, Pun', 'Where do pirates buy their hooks? At the second hand store', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a friendly pirate standing outside a quaint second-hand store designed to look old-fashioned with a wooden sign above the door reading ''Second Hand Store.'' The pirate has a typical pirate outfit, including a tricorn hat, eye patch, striped shirt, and a wooden hook for a hand. He is happily holding a shiny new hook in the other hand, as if he just purchased it. Around the pirate, display racks outside show various items like old clothes, hats, and antique objects. Include a humorous detail like another hook dangling from a hanger, labeled with a small price tag. The backdrop suggests a cheerful seaside town with a few seabirds flying, and the pirate has a big smile, adding to the lighthearted atmosphere. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun without any violence or threatening elements.'),
 (2910, 'Objects Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'Have you heard about the new corduroy pillow? It''s making headlines!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a fluffy pillow made out of corduroy fabric placed on a newspaper. The pillow has a big smiley face and is wearing tiny glasses, holding a mini microphone, as if it is a reporter. The newspaper headline reads, ''Corduroy Pillow Making Headlines!'' Around the pillow, several other pillows made of different fabrics (silk, cotton) look surprised or amused. The setting is a cozy bedroom with a bed, a nightstand with a lamp, and maybe a small stack of newspapers to emphasize the ''headlines'' pun. The overall style should be bright, cheerful, and comical, with exaggerated expressions and clear reference to the pun about ''making headlines'' and corduroy’s ridged texture resembling lines or ''headlines'' on paper.'),
 (2965, 'Objects Humor, Pun, Unknown, Word Play', 'I built a wooden car. It had wooden doors, wooden wheels, wooden seats, even a wooden key. Guess what? It wooden start.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a small wooden car made entirely out of wood. The car has visible wooden textures and grain on every part: wooden chassis, wooden wheels with visible wood grain and knots, flat wooden doors with simple wooden handles, wooden seats with plank-like appearance, and a large wooden key sticking out of the ignition. The car is parked on a simple road or driveway with a puzzled-looking person standing next to it, scratching their head or shrugging in confusion. The background is simple with a clear sky and a few cartoon-style trees or bushes. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features on the car to emphasize that everything is made of wood. The key might be comically oversized to highlight the joke. The expression on the person''s face is bemused but friendly, enhancing the pun about why the car ''wooden start.'''),
 (2936, 'Objects Humor, Puns, Unknown, Word Play', 'How can you get four suits for a dollar? Buy a deck of cards.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a store counter looking surprised and delighted. In front of them is a cashier holding a deck of playing cards with four visible suits (hearts, clubs, diamonds, spades) clearly shown on the card faces. The person is holding a single dollar bill, smiling with wide eyes. The background is a simple store interior with shelves faintly stocked with unrelated items, emphasizing that the focus is on the dollar and the deck of cards. The art style is light, colorful, and exaggerated to enhance the humor, with little motion lines to express the person''s excitement or realization. The overall mood is playful and punny, highlighting the wordplay between the suits of cards and clothing suits, without showing any literal clothing suits or formal wear.'),
 (1294, 'Objects Humor, Puns, Word Play', 'What''s the difference between a tuna, a piano, and a jar of glue? You can tuna piano, but you can''t piano a tuna (what about the glue?) I knew you''d get stuck there', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into three panels side by side. The first panel shows a cheerful person holding a large tuna fish, looking confused but trying to ''tune'' it with a giant old-fashioned piano tuning hammer. The second panel depicts the same person next to a grand piano, tuning the instrument with a smile, clearly focused and happy. The third panel shows the person staring perplexedly at a jar of glue on a table, scratching their head, with a small speech bubble containing a question mark. Around the jar are sticky notes or little cartoon squiggles showing the person ''stuck'' in thought. The background is simple and clean with light colors, emphasizing the playful confusion between the words and objects. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated typical cartoon, with expressive faces and clear labeling or signposts on each object to enhance clarity and humor.'),
 (2668, 'Occupational Humor, Psychology Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'Be a better psychiatrist and the world will beat a psychopath to your door.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly psychiatrist sitting in a cozy office with diplomas and brain models on the walls. The psychiatrist is smiling confidently and holding a clipboard. Outside the office door, wildly colorful and exaggerated cartoon psychopaths line up eagerly, with silly, over-the-top expressions like manic grins and wide eyes, as if competing to get in. One psychopath is tapping their foot impatiently, another is holding a sign that says ''Next!'', and a third is balancing nervously on one foot. The atmosphere is light and comical, with bright colors and exaggerated features to keep the tone playful. The door has a sign that reads ''Dr. Mind’s Office'' and there is a welcome mat shaped like a brain. The psychiatrist looks amused and slightly overwhelmed but in a friendly way, emphasizing the joke that if the psychiatrist improves, the crazier clients will come rushing over.'),
 (1341, 'Office Humor, Programmers, Technology Humor, Word Play', 'Someone sent me a message recently in an encrypted Teams channel, but the only word I could understand was ’eggs’. I think the message was scrambled.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene inside an office setting with two coworkers chatting by a computer screen displaying a Microsoft Teams chat window. The chat bubble on the screen shows a jumbled, scrambled message with mixed-up letters and symbols, except one clear word: ''eggs'' in bold or highlighted font. One worker, looking confused and scratching their head, points at the word ''eggs'' on the screen. The other worker grins mischievously as if sharing a joke. The office background includes typical elements like desks, chairs, a potted plant, and a coffee mug with a little smiley face. The style should be colorful and lighthearted with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the confusion and humor of the scrambled message and the pun on "scrambled eggs." The overall tone is playful and cartoonish without any negative or serious elements.'),
 (3063, 'Office Humor, Programming Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'If a listener nods his head when you are explaining your program, wake him up.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside an office meeting room. At the center, show a person standing confidently with a pointer or remote, explaining a complex flowchart or computer program displayed on a screen. Seated in front of them is a listener wearing office attire, slumped slightly in their chair with eyes closed, clearly dozing off. Their head is nodding up and down comically, indicating they are asleep but mimicking agreement. Include typical office elements like a round table, coffee mugs, a laptop, and a whiteboard. The presenter looks slightly confused or amused, glancing at the sleepy listener. Use exaggerated facial expressions and poses to emphasize the humor in the listener nodding off during the explanation. The scene should be colorful, bright, and in a lighthearted cartoon style.'),
 (1523, 'Office Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'Always postpone meetings with time wasting morons.', 'Dilbert', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an office setting with a large round meeting table. Around the table sits several exaggerated characters clearly labeled as ''time wasting morons'' by small nameplates or humorous labels, depicted with silly or clueless expressions—one fiddling with a phone, another yawning, one doodling nonsense on a notepad. In the foreground, a confident, slightly sarcastic professional figure (maybe wearing business casual clothes and holding a calendar or planner) is shown looking at the clock, smiling slyly while pressing a big red button on a giant delaying device labeled ''Meeting Postponer.'' The background includes a wall clock showing time passing quickly, and a calendar with days crossed off, emphasizing the postponement theme. The overall style is vibrant and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and comic-style bubble text above the main character reading, ''Always postpone meetings with time wasting morons.'' No violence or negativity; just lighthearted office satire.'),
 (2149, 'Office Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'No one will believe you solved this problem in one day! We''ve been working on it for months. Now, go act busy for a few weeks and I''ll let you know when it''s time to tell them.', '(Actual Dilbert Manager Quotes)', 'A humorous cartoon office scene showing two coworkers. One is a relaxed employee leaning back in their chair with a big satisfied smile, hands behind their head, clearly done with their work early. The other coworker, a middle manager type, is standing nearby with a sly grin and finger pointing as if giving a secret order. Behind them are desks with computer screens, stacks of paperwork, and a whiteboard with ''Problem-solving Project'' written on it and lots of complex charts and notes. In the background, other employees look stressed and busy with lots of papers and coffee cups scattered around. The manager''s speech bubble says: ''No one will believe you solved this problem in one day! We''ve been working on it for months. Now, go act busy for a few weeks and I''ll let you know when it''s time to tell them.'' The overall style is lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon with bright colors and smiling characters, emphasizing office culture and playful deception.'),
 (1698, 'Office Humor, Quotes, Satire, Sports Humor', 'Football combines the two worst features of American life: violence and committee meetings.', 'George Will', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a football field during a game. On one side, a group of football players wearing helmets and pads are clashing in a rough, comic fight, with exaggerated angry faces and action lines showing violence. On the sidelines, there is a large, round table with a handful of people in business attire sitting around it with papers, clipboards, and coffee cups, looking bored or frustrated as if in a long committee meeting. Maybe include a scoreboard showing ''Violence 0 - Committee Meetings 0'' for added humor. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between the chaotic physicality of the players and the dullness of the committee meeting participants. Bright colors and expressive faces make the scene feel lively yet clearly comedic and non-threatening.'),
 (1448, 'Office Humor, Quotes, Wit, Workplace', 'A memorandum is written not to inform the reader, but to protect the writer.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office environment. An office worker, dressed in business casual, is sitting at a cluttered desk with a worried, slightly mischievous expression. The worker holds a long, official-looking memo with stacks of paper behind them. The memo is titled ''Memorandum'' in bold letters at the top. Nearby, a large clear shield or bubble labeled ''PROTECTION'' surrounds the worker, symbolizing how the memo is a shield rather than an informative tool. A co-worker peeks over a cubicle wall in the background with a puzzled or bemused look, holding a coffee cup. The office contains common items like a computer, a coffee mug, some filing cabinets, and a clock on the wall showing mid-morning. The overall tone is lighthearted, with exaggerated expressions and features that enhance the joke about memos serving to protect their writers rather than inform readers.'),
 (2362, 'Optimism Humor, Pessimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'The optimist thinks this is the best of all possible worlds. The pessimist fears it is true.', 'Robert Oppenheimer', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left, depict an optimistic character, bright and cheerful, wearing a big smile and colorful clothes, looking at a sunny, vibrant world full of flowers, happy animals, and smiling people. On the right, show a pessimistic character, frowning with a worried expression, in muted, darker clothes, looking at the exact same world but seeming stressed and anxious, with subtle comic exaggerations like a small raincloud only over their head or exaggerated worried faces on the animals. The background is the same on both sides, emphasizing the contrast in perception but showing the world itself is unchanged. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor in their opposing views.'),
 (1653, 'Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'Dum spiro, spero (While I breathe, I hope).', 'South Carolina state motto', 'A cheerful, cartoon-style elderly person sitting peacefully in a cozy armchair by a sunlit window, gently smiling while taking a deep breath. Around them are simple signs of hope and optimism: a small blooming plant on a side table, a framed inspirational quote on the wall, and a little heart-shaped pillow on the chair. Soft sunlight streams through the window, emphasizing a calm and hopeful atmosphere. The background is warm and inviting, with gentle colors and no clutter, highlighting the phrase ‘Dum spiro, spero’ hovering softly in elegant, handwritten text above the character’s head like a thought or mantra. The overall tone is light-hearted and uplifting, drawn in a humorous but tender cartoon style.'),
 (2510, 'Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes', 'We are all in the gutter, but some of us are looking at the stars.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing in a filthy, dark gutter filled with mud, leaves, and some trash like a crumpled can and a broken bottle. One character is looking down, scraping their shoe in the dirty water, with a gloomy expression. The other character is slightly elevated on the edge of the gutter, smiling and gazing upward toward a clear night sky filled with bright, twinkling stars and a glowing crescent moon. The contrast between the dirty gutter and beautiful sky above highlights the joke. Both characters are simple, cartoon-style humans with exaggerated expressions to emphasize mood: the first is grumpy and discouraging, the second hopeful and dreamy. The backdrop includes a simple city street with a lamppost casting some light. The scene should look playful and lighthearted, with vibrant colors in the sky contrasting the muddy gutter below.'),
 (1454, 'Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'A pessimist sees the difficulty in every opportunity; an optimist sees the opportunity in every difficulty.', 'Sir Winston Churchill (1874-1965)', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, show a pessimistic character standing in front of a tall ladder leaning against a wall with broken, uneven rungs. The character looks worried and frustrated, arms crossed, with a gloomy cloud over their head. They see the huge obstacle (the broken ladder) and focus on it. On the right side, show an optimistic character standing in front of the same ladder but with a bright sun shining, smiling and confidently reaching up to climb the ladder despite the broken rungs. There are small sparkles or stars around them emphasizing positivity. Both characters should be wearing casual clothes and positioned facing the ladder. The background is simple and bright to keep focus on the contrast of attitudes. Include a signpost in the middle labeled “Opportunity” pointing toward the ladder. Overall style should be colorful, lighthearted, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions showing pessimism vs optimism clearly and humorously.'),
 (1501, 'Optimism Humor, Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Ah, but a man''s reach should exceed his grasp -- or what''s a heaven for?', 'Robert Browning', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing on a small hill or mound, reaching upward with an exaggeratedly long arm or a comically extended ladder. Above him, there is a shiny, glowing cloud labeled ''Heaven,'' just out of his grasp. The man looks determined but slightly frustrated, wearing casual modern clothes. The background should be simple with a clear blue sky and a few fluffy clouds. Include a subtle visual metaphor, such as a dotted line or sparkles, indicating the unreachable ''heaven'' floating above him. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with friendly, rounded lines and bright colors that emphasize the optimistic but ironic spirit of the quote.'),
 (1429, 'Optimism Humor, Political Humor, Quotes', 'A liberal is a man or a woman or a child who looks forward to a better day, a more tranquil night, and a bright, infinite future.', 'Leonard Bernstein', 'A cheerful, colorful cartoon scene showing three characters side by side: a man, a woman, and a child. Each character looks optimistically toward the horizon with bright, hopeful expressions. The background features a radiant sunrise symbolizing a better day, calm blue skies for a tranquil night, and a starry sky morphing into an infinite galaxy to represent a bright, infinite future. The style is light, whimsical, and humorous, with soft pastel colors and simple, friendly lines to emphasize positivity and hopefulness. Include minimal details like birds flying, some flowers, and gentle hills to enhance the peaceful, uplifting atmosphere.'),
 (2037, 'Philosophy Humor, Poetry, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Let your life lightly dance on the edges of time like dew on the tip of a leaf.', 'Tagore', 'Draw a whimsical cartoon scene showing a single delicate green leaf extending from a slender branch. At the very tip of the leaf, depict a small, shimmering droplet of dew, sparkling in the soft morning light. The droplet should appear almost weightless, gently perched as if it might dance or slide off at any moment. Surround this focal image with an ethereal, dreamy background of soft pastel colors like pale blue, lavender, and light pink to evoke a calm, peaceful atmosphere. Include subtle motion lines or tiny sparkles around the dew to emphasize its lightness and fleeting nature. The overall style should be gentle and uplifting, capturing the poetic and metaphorical essence of life''s delicate beauty and transience in a humorous cartoon manner without any characters or complex objects.'),
 (2344, 'Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'The modern conservative is engaged in one of man''s oldest exercises in moral philosophy; that is, the search for a superior moral justification for selfishness.', 'John Kenneth Galbraith', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cozy living room styled like a philosophy classroom mixed with modern décor. In the center, a well-dressed man labeled “Modern Conservative” is sitting on a throne-like chair with a smug expression, holding a large, ancient-looking book titled "Moral Philosophy" open on his lap. Around him float ghostly thought bubbles showing old philosophers like Socrates and Aristotle, depicted humorously with exaggerated thinking poses and question marks. The man is surrounded by luxury items symbolizing selfishness—gold coins, gadgets, and fancy food—while a confused or amused crowd of assorted people in casual clothing watches him, some whispering or raising eyebrows. The background has a chalkboard with the phrase “Search for superior moral justification” scribbled humorously, with some moral-sounding but clearly selfish reasons crossed out. The overall tone is light and witty, with expressive, exaggerated cartoon characters and vibrant colors to amplify the satire but keep it friendly and approachable.'),
 (1617, 'Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Democracy does not guarantee equality of conditions - it only guarantees equality of opportunity.', 'Irving Kristol', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side at the starting line of a race track labeled ''Opportunity Race.'' Both are ready to start running, wearing exaggeratedly large running shoes, but behind them the terrain quickly changes. One character''s track is smooth, flat, and clear, while the other''s track is filled with obstacles like rocks, mud puddles, and small hills. A large banner overhead reads ''Democracy: Equality of Opportunity'' in bold letters. The background shows a cheering crowd holding signs like ''Fair Start!'' and ''Good Luck!'' The style is bright, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated expressions on the racers—one confident, the other frustrated but determined. Include a scoreboard in the corner labeled ''Conditions'' showing uneven scores to emphasize unequal conditions despite the same starting line. The overall tone is light-hearted and cartoonish without any negativity or harshness.'),
 (1624, 'Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Democracy is the recurrent suspicion that more than half of the people are right more than half of the time.', 'E. B. White', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, round ballot box at the center with a crowd of diverse, cartoon-style people gathered around it. The people should look confused, suspicious, and somewhat skeptical, with exaggerated expressions such as raised eyebrows, crossed arms, and thoughtful gestures. Above the crowd, include a large thought bubble containing half of a pie chart marked “Right” in bright colors and the other half marked “Wrong” in dull colors. Somewhere in the background, show a simple, classic voting booth with a character hesitating in front of it, scratching their head. The overall atmosphere is light-hearted and non-threatening, emphasizing the idea of democratic doubt and the humorous suspicion that the majority might actually be correct about half the time. Use lively colors and expressive, cartoonish characters to enhance the comedic effect without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2039, 'Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Liberalism is trust of the people tempered by prudence; Conservatism is distrust of the people tempered by fear.', 'William E. Gladstone', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two sides, left and right, each representing Liberalism and Conservatism respectively. On the left, a friendly-looking, smiling figure labeled ''Liberalism'' is holding a large, overflowing jar labeled ''Trust of the People.'' Next to them is a smaller bottle labeled ''Prudence,'' which they are carefully pouring into the large jar to balance it. The environment is bright and inviting, with cheerful colors. On the right side, a cautious, slightly worried figure labeled ''Conservatism'' is clutching a jar labeled ''Distrust of the People,'' which looks half-full and guarded. They are nervously adding a bottle labeled ''Fear'' into the jar, with shaking hands. The background here uses more muted, anxious tones. Between them in the middle is a thin, wavy line symbolizing the contrast between the two ideologies. The overall style is a lighthearted, exaggerated cartoon without any harsh or aggressive elements, emphasizing the metaphor of mixing emotional qualities in jars as a visual pun.'),
 (2167, 'Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'Of all the varieties of virtues, liberalism is the most beloved.', 'Aristotle', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a variety of personified ''virtues'' gathered together like characters at a party or social event. Each virtue is depicted as a whimsical character wearing a simple name tag: ''Patience,'' ''Kindness,'' ''Honesty,'' ''Liberalism,'' etc. Liberalism stands out in the center, glowing or sparkling, with hearts or smiles floating around it, to emphasize that it is the most ''beloved.'' The other virtues look on admiringly or cheerfully. The setting is light and festive with balloons, confetti, and a banner reading ''The Virtue Gala.'' The style is colorful, playful, and caricatured without any aggressive or serious tones.'),
 (2541, 'Philosophy Humor, Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'What is conservativism? Is it not the aherence to the old and tried against the new and untried?', 'Abraham Lincoln (1809-1865)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an elderly person standing at a crossroads labeled ''Old'' and ''New.'' The ''Old'' path has cobblestone pavement with vintage objects like an old-fashioned clock, a classic rotary phone, and a well-worn book. The ''New'' path is modern but slightly shaky with bright, futuristic items like a drone, a tablet, and a hoverboard, some of which look unstable or uncertain. The elderly person is dressed in slightly exaggerated old-fashioned clothing, holding a walking cane, and looking skeptically at the ''New'' path, with a thought bubble that reads, ''Why fix what isn’t broken?'' Nearby, a signpost titled ''Conservativism'' has the quote from the joke written on a wooden plank. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with expressive characters and playful exaggeration to highlight the humor about preferring the tried and true over the new and unproven.'),
 (2500, 'Philosophy Humor, Pop Culture, Quotes', 'Unfortunately, no one can be told what the Matrix is. You have to see it for yourself.', 'Morpheus', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inspired by the famous quote about The Matrix. Show a curious person standing in front of a large, glowing computer screen or a futuristic-looking portal labeled ''The Matrix.'' The person looks puzzled and excited, wearing casual modern clothes. Next to them, an older, wise-looking character dressed like a quirky mentor (similar to a professor or a streetwise guide) is gesturing dramatically but trying to explain something impossible to fully grasp. The background is a blend of a normal room morphing into a digital grid pattern with floating code symbols and green cascading numbers, reminiscent of The Matrix movie effects. Emphasize the confusion and the mysterious vibe, with cartoonish facial expressions showing awe and bewilderment. Include no violence or anything that can be interpreted as scary, just playful curiosity and mild bewilderment.'),
 (1902, 'Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'If you carry your childhood with you, you never become older.', 'Abraham Sutzkever', 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing an adult happily walking along a path with a bright, joyful expression. The adult carries a large, colorful backpack labeled ''Childhood'' that is overflowing with playful, nostalgic items like a teddy bear, a jump rope, a comic book, a toy car, and a small kite. Around the adult, the environment appears lively and youthful: birds chirping, flowers blooming, a sunshine with a smiling face in the sky, and butterflies fluttering. The adult’s clothes are casual and lighthearted, such as a t-shirt with a childish graphic. In the background, a calendar with pages flipping but showing no signs of aging or worries. The overall tone is light, cheerful, and imaginative, emphasizing the idea that holding onto childhood keeps one feeling young at heart. The style is a colorful, exaggerated cartoon with rounded, friendly shapes and expressive characters.'),
 (2220, 'Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes', 'Recall it as often as you wish, a happy memory never wears out.', 'Libbie Fudim', 'A cheerful, nostalgic cartoon scene featuring a smiling person sitting comfortably in an armchair, reminiscing. Above their head, a thought bubble contains a bright, colorful memory depicted as a sparkling, joyful moment—such as a sunny picnic, a joyful hug, or playing with friends. The memory is vibrant and glowing, visually contrasting with the muted but cozy surroundings of the person’s room. The person’s expression is warm and content, with light, happy eyes. Around the room, small, subtle symbols of time passing appear, such as a softly ticking clock and a calendar with pages gently fluttering, emphasizing that time goes by but the memory remains fresh. The overall tone is light-hearted and uplifting, with smooth lines and exaggerated facial expressions typical of humorous cartoons. The scene avoids any negativity and focuses on the positive, timeless nature of happy memories.'),
 (1484, 'Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'Above all nations is humanity.', 'Goldwin Smith', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a globe with various national flags pinned around its surface representing different countries. Above the globe, a large, smiling anthropomorphic character labeled ''Humanity'' floats wearing a superhero cape, standing proudly above all the flags. The superhero humanity is drawn in a friendly, lighthearted style, with open arms and a glowing aura. The globe is placed on a simple office desk with papers and a small plant, emphasizing the theme of unity above divisions. The mood is cheerful and uplifting, using bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features to highlight the idea of ''Humanity'' being above all nations.'),
 (1984, 'Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'It is our choices that show what we truly are, far more than our abilities.', 'J.D. Rowling, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets', 'A humorous cartoon-style scene showing two characters standing side by side on a stage labeled ''Talent Show.'' One character looks confident, holding a trophy labeled ''Abilities,'' but with a somewhat indifferent or smug expression. The other character looks less capable, holding a small sign that reads ''Choices,'' but is smiling warmly and receiving applause from a quirky cartoon audience with exaggerated happy faces. The background should be simple with bright colors and spotlight effects to emphasize the stage. Include silly details like a banner overhead that reads ''What Truly Defines Us'' and a judge holding a scorecard with big question marks. The overall tone is cheerful and lighthearted, emphasizing that what truly matters is the choices one makes rather than raw abilities, without any dark or serious elements.'),
 (2416, 'Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'There are only two ways to live your life. One is as though nothing is a miracle. The other is as though everything is a miracle.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A whimsical cartoon scene split into two halves down the middle. On the left side, a person is walking through a dull, gray cityscape with a neutral or skeptical expression, surrounded by ordinary, everyday objects like a bus stop, traffic lights, and a cup of coffee on a bench. Nothing stands out as amazing. On the right side, the same person is in a bright, colorful version of the same setting, with vibrant flowers growing on the sidewalk, butterflies fluttering around, and rays of sunshine sparkling off everything. The person looks wide-eyed and delighted, with sparkling eyes and a big smile. Above the entire scene, a softly glowing text banner reads: "Two Ways to Live Life". The overall style should be light, playful, and exaggerated with round shapes typical of a humorous cartoon, emphasizing the contrast in perception between the two outlooks on life, without any dark or negative elements.'),
 (2390, 'Philosophy Humor, Positive Humor, Quotes, Wise Sayings', 'The time is always right to do what is right.', 'Martin Luther King Jr.', 'Draw a cheerful, round-faced clock with arms and legs standing upright like a friendly cartoon character. The clock''s hands point at an ambiguous time, like 10:10, to avoid stressing a specific hour. The clock character wears a big, warm smile and holds a shining heart symbol in one hand, symbolizing doing the right thing. Around the clock, rays or sparkles emphasize its positivity and timeless wisdom. In the background, include a simple outdoor park scene with a few trees and a bench, suggesting a pleasant, everyday setting. The overall style is bright, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated, friendly features to give it a humorous cartoon vibe. Avoid any text or complex backgrounds, focusing on the clock as the main character conveying the message that it''s always the right time to do good.'),
 (1944, 'Philosophy Humor, Pun, Quotes, Romance Humor', 'In the arithmetic of love, one plus one equals everything, and two minus one equals nothing.', 'Mignon McLaughlin', 'A whimsical cartoon scene illustrating a playful metaphor for love as arithmetic. The scene is divided into two halves. On the left, a cheerful cartoon couple stands close together, smiling warmly at each other, surrounded by glowing plus signs and hearts floating above their heads. Above them is a large, hand-drawn math equation: ''1 + 1 = Everything,'' with the word ''Everything'' whimsically filling the space around them in colorful, lively letters. On the right side, the same couple stands apart, each looking slightly sad or lonely, with a big minus sign between them and only one person remaining. Above this side is the equation ''2 - 1 = Nothing,'' with the word ''Nothing'' fading or disappearing in a gentle, playful font. The background is soft pastel colors, and the characters are drawn in an exaggerated, humorous cartoon style with big eyes and expressive faces. The scene should feel light, thoughtful, and emotionally sweet rather than overly sentimental.'),
 (1689, 'Philosophy Humor, Pun, Quotes, Science Humor', 'Experience is the mother of science.', 'Henry George Bohm', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful middle-aged scientist wearing a white lab coat and thick glasses, standing in a cluttered laboratory. Surrounding the scientist are typical lab items such as test tubes filled with colorful liquids, a microscope, and scientific charts on the wall. Above the scientist''s head is a large floating thought bubble shaped like a mother holding a baby, where the baby is symbolically labeled ''Science.'' The mother figure is drawn humorously, slightly exaggerated and smiling warmly, representing ''Experience.'' The overall art style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and playful expressions to emphasize the pun and the idea that experience ''gives birth'' to science in a literal, visual metaphor. No harsh or intimidating elements are included, just a fun and imaginative depiction of the phrase.'),
 (2326, 'Philosophy Humor, Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'The investigator should have a robust faith -- and yet not believe.', 'Claude Bernard', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an investigator (detective) standing at a crime scene. The investigator is holding a magnifying glass in one hand and a small Bible or book titled ''Faith'' in the other hand. The investigator has a puzzled, thoughtful expression, looking confused by the contradiction. Behind the investigator is a chalk outline on the ground, evidence markers, and a signpost labeled ''Belief'' pointing one way and ''Skepticism'' pointing the other. The sky above shows a whimsical blend of two contrasting symbols: a shining cross and a question mark, visually representing faith and doubt. The style is lighthearted, exaggerated, and playful, with cartoonish proportions and bright colors to emphasize the irony of needing ''robust faith'' but ''not to believe.'' No violent or serious elements, just a silly detective puzzling over a philosophical paradox.'),
 (1295, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'To be great is to be misunderstood.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on a small stage or pedestal, looking proud but confused, with question marks and puzzled faces around them. The person is surrounded by various people who are reacting with funny expressions: some scratching their heads, some whispering to each other, and one person holding a dictionary upside down. Above the person on stage, a big speech bubble contains the phrase ''To be great is to be misunderstood.'' The background is colorful with simple shapes, and the style is lighthearted and exaggerated, focusing on the contrast between the confident individual and the baffled crowd. No violent or sensitive elements should be included.'),
 (1296, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable', 'Wherever you go, there you are.', NULL, 'A simple, humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in the middle of a small town square or park. The person looks mildly confused but calm. Around the person, on signposts, walls, and shop windows, there are identical directional signs or sticky notes all stating ''You Are Here.'' The background includes a few buildings, trees, and a bench. The character is scratching their head in a funny way as if realizing no matter where they move, the signs keep pointing to ''You Are Here.'' The mood is light-hearted and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions highlighting the irony of the phrase.'),
 (2106, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'Millions long for immortality who do not know what to do with themselves on a rainy Sunday afternoon.', 'Susan Ertz', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cozy living room on a rainy Sunday afternoon. Outside the window, rain pours steadily, with gray clouds and raindrops on the glass. Inside, a person (looking bored and restless) sits slouched on a couch holding a TV remote and staring blankly at a turned-off television. Nearby, there’s a table with scattered items suggesting failed attempts to pass time: an unfinished puzzle, an open book lying face down, and an untouched cup of tea steaming. A clock on the wall shows mid-afternoon. The overall tone is light and exaggerated, emphasizing the person’s impatience and confusion about how to spend the day. The artwork should be bright and colorful with exaggerated facial expressions for comedic effect, capturing the contrast between the rainy gloom outside and the person’s restless, aimless mood inside.'),
 (2430, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Self-Reflection Humor', 'There is nothing like returning to a place that has remained unchanged to find ways in which you yourself have altered.', 'Nelson Mandela', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person returning to their childhood home. The house looks exactly the same as it did years ago—classic design, a familiar porch, and perfectly unchanged garden with flowers and a swing on a large tree. The person stands outside in the foreground, wearing casual clothes, holding a photo of their younger self in front of the same house. Their expression is a mix of surprise and reflection. Behind them, subtle visual hints like wrinkles, gray hair, or posture differences emphasize personal aging and change, while everything around remains static and untouched. Optional funny detail: a small calendar or clock stuck in time on the wall to reinforce unchanged surroundings. The overall tone should be lighthearted and nostalgic, with bright colors and exaggerated cartoon features to enhance humor and relatability, avoiding any serious or melancholic mood.'),
 (1568, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wisdom', 'Are you not ashamed of caring so much for the making of money and for fame and prestige, when you neither think nor care about wisdom and truth and the improvement of your soul?', 'Socrates', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person dressed in formal business attire standing on a stage or podium, holding a large sack of money in one hand and a shining trophy labeled ''Fame'' in the other. The person has an exaggerated proud and boastful expression. Behind them, a ghostly, wise-looking figure or philosopher with a long beard and flowing robe shakes their head disapprovingly, holding a scroll labeled ''Wisdom & Truth.'' Around the stage are scattered symbols of soul improvement such as a glowing book titled ''Soul Improvement,'' a heart symbol with sparkles, and a small plant growing. The background shows a crowd of people watching, some looking confused or unimpressed. The setting is lighthearted, colorful, and clearly a cartoon style with exaggerated features to emphasize the contrast between material success and deeper values, but no violence or negativity.'),
 (2522, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'We judge ourselves by what we feel capable of doing, while others judge us by what we have already done.', 'Henry Wadsworth Longfellow', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a person looks thoughtful and enthusiastic, imagining themselves climbing a tall mountain or achieving something ambitious, with a dreamy expression and a thought bubble above their head illustrating a mountain peak with a flag. On the right, a different person is looking at the first person with a clipboard or checklist, marking off completed tasks symbolized by small trophies or medals floating around the first person’s torso, representing achievements they''ve already finished. The setting is simple, with a neutral background and exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the contrast between self-expectation and outside judgment. Include smiling faces and lighthearted body language to keep the tone positive and funny, capturing the irony of differing perspectives on capability versus accomplishment.'),
 (1539, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'An optimist is a man who has never had much experience.', 'Don Marquis', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful man labeled ''Optimist'' standing confidently with a bright smile on his face. Around him are a series of small, faintly drawn sketches or ghost-like outlines showing past mishaps or unlucky experiences (like slipping on a banana peel, a burnt toast, a broken umbrella). These sketches are subtle and semi-transparent, indicating limited or no actual experience. The scene should have a light, playful atmosphere with bright colors and simple lines emphasizing the optimistic attitude despite weak or no evidence of adversity. Include a thought bubble above the man''s head showing a sunny, perfect day with clear skies and no troubles, reinforcing his hopeful outlook. The background can be a simple park or street scene to keep focus on the character and the concept of optimism versus experience.'),
 (1710, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'Genius may have its limitations, but stupidity is not thus handicapped.', 'Elbert Hubbard', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side by side. On the left, a person depicted as a stereotypical ''genius'' with wildly messy hair like Einstein, glasses, and holding a large open book or complex scientific formula on a chalkboard behind them. This character looks thoughtful but slightly frustrated, symbolizing intellectual limitation. On the right, a second character is portrayed as comically clueless: with crossed eyes, tongue sticking out slightly, and making a silly face. Their surroundings are chaotic—papers flying around, a bucket on their head, or a banana peel on the floor—to emphasize unrestrained foolishness. The background should be simple and bright, enhancing the comedic contrast between controlled genius and limitless stupidity. Speech bubbles over each character can emphasize the joke, but not necessary to write exact text. The style should be colorful, exaggerated cartoon with clean lines and lighthearted tone.'),
 (1977, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'It is good to be without vices, but it is not good to be without temptations.', 'Walter Bagehot', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, clean-cut person standing confidently with arms crossed, surrounded by a bright, spotless environment symbolizing ''being without vices.'' Nearby, whimsical, colorful cartoon temptations float around teasingly—like a slice of cake, a shiny casino slot machine, a bottle labeled ''mystery potion,'' and a mischievous little devil character holding a sign saying ''Come on!''. The person looks amused but firm, both resisting and acknowledging these temptations. The background should be light and playful, using soft, bright colors to emphasize the positivity of virtue alongside the inevitable presence of tempting options. Include small visual cues like sparkles around the person to imply virtue and playful swirls or spark-like effects around the temptations to show their alluring nature. The overall tone is lighthearted and humorous without tension or conflict.'),
 (2359, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wit', 'The only way to get rid of a temptation is to yield to it.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing in front of a large, colorful box labeled ''Temptations.'' The box is overflowing with tempting items like donuts, chocolate, and a big shopping bag. The person looks conflicted at first but then happily reaches inside the box, smiling as they pull out a giant donut. In the background, a faint ghostly figure labeled ''Willpower'' shrinks away, looking defeated. The setting is lighthearted with soft pastel colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the struggle and eventual surrender to temptation without any negativity or harm. The style is playful and cartoonish, with rounded lines and cheerful tones to evoke amusement rather than seriousness.'),
 (2011, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Wit', 'It''s not what you look at that matters; it''s what you see.', 'Henry David Thoreau', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing side by side, both looking at the same object—a simple picture frame on the wall showing an abstract image or pattern. One character squints with a confused expression, seemingly only seeing random shapes. The other character gazes thoughtfully, with a lightbulb above their head, clearly seeing a clear image or a meaningful scene within the abstract picture. The background is a cozy living room with a couch, a small table holding a book titled ''Perception,'' and a window showing a sunny day outside. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the contrast between the two characters'' interpretations to visually express the joke''s meaning about perception versus observation.'),
 (2582, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Word Play', 'Wherever you go, there you are.', 'Harlan Cornell', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person standing in different locations, but always looking exactly the same and pointing at themselves. The character should be shown in a series of three small panels or frames arranged horizontally. In the first panel, they stand at a beach with palm trees and sand, looking surprised and pointing at themselves. In the second panel, the same character is on a mountain peak with an alpine background, same pose and expression. In the third panel, the character stands in a busy city street, again pointing at themselves with a knowing smile. Each location should be clearly distinct but simple, with bright, colorful, and cheerful cartoon style. The focus is on the repeated presence of the character in all settings with the gesture highlighting the phrase, "Wherever you go, there you are." No other characters or text bubbles are needed.'),
 (1538, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relatable, Words of Wisdom', 'An idea is not responsible for the people who believe in it.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a light bulb character with a face, arms, and legs standing confidently. The light bulb is shrugging its shoulders in a carefree manner. Around the light bulb, several quirky people are shown enthusiastically holding colorful signs, banners, and books with various ideas written on them (e.g., ''Flat Earth,'' ''Time Travel,'' ''Invisible Cats''). Some people look excited, others confused or overly serious. The setting is an open park or town square with a gentle, bright sky, emphasizing a friendly and non-threatening atmosphere. Include small, playful details like birds wearing glasses and a dog reading a sign to add whimsy. Overall, the cartoon should clearly illustrate that the idea (the personified light bulb) is indifferent to the diverse crowd of beliefers, highlighting the joke''s meaning in a light, funny way without any negativity or conflict.'),
 (2195, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wit', 'People think love is an emotion. Love is good sense.', 'Ken Kesey', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting at a small café table with coffee cups. One character has a dreamy, romantic expression with heart-shaped eyes and is holding a heart-shaped balloon labeled ''Love (Emotion)''. The other character, looking practical and thoughtful, holds a large book titled ''Common Sense'' and points to it confidently while saying, ''Love is good sense.'' The setting is bright and cheerful with light pastel colors, a few hearts floating around the dreamy character, and a clear contrast between the whimsical and the rational. Include speech bubbles for the dialogue and exaggerate the characters’ contrasting expressions to emphasize the joke’s play on defining love as common sense rather than just emotion.'),
 (2437, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religion Humor, Social Humor', 'There is only one religion, though there are a hundred versions of it.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of diverse people standing in a circle, each holding a different version of the same book titled ''The One Religion.'' Each person looks slightly different—varied clothing styles, ages, and ethnicities—to emphasize diversity. Above their heads is a large thought bubble divided into many smaller bubbles, each containing a unique, colorful symbol representing one of the many versions of the religion (e.g., different icons, colors, and shapes), illustrating the many interpretations. In the center of the circle, the original book is glowing softly, indicating the singular origin. The background is simple with a soft gradient to keep the focus on the characters and bubbles. The overall style is lighthearted and whimsical, with expressive faces showing curiosity and friendliness. No intense or controversial imagery.'),
 (2125, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religion Humor, Spiritual Humor', 'My religion consists of a humble admiration of the illimitable superior spirit who reveals himself in the slight details we are able to perceive with our frail and feeble mind.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person with an awestruck expression looking up at a vast, glowing, abstract spirit figure made of swirling light and subtle, tiny sparkling details. The spirit figure is ethereal and majestic but portrayed with soft, gentle curves to emphasize kindness and a superior presence. The person is standing on a small hill or simple ground, depicted with a frail and slightly exaggerated tiny body and big head to show their ‘frail and feeble mind.’ Around them, small detailed objects like a leaf, an insect, or a tiny flower are highlighted to represent the ''slight details'' that the person can perceive. The background should be a starry, expansive sky to enhance the infinite and illimitable nature of the spirit. The overall style is colorful, light-hearted, and whimsical, emphasizing wonder and admiration without any text or symbols tied to specific religions.'),
 (1791, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religion Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'I do not feel obliged to believe that the same God who has endowed us with sense, reason, and intellect has intended us to forgo their use.', 'Galileo Galilei', 'A cartoon-style scene with a thoughtful person sitting at a wooden desk cluttered with books, a glowing light bulb above their head to symbolize an idea. The person, wearing glasses and a contemplative expression, is pointing at an open book titled ''Sense, Reason, and Intellect'' with one hand, while the other hand gestures as if making a point. Above the character, a gentle cloud shaped like a classical god figure with a kind face looks down approvingly but with a raised eyebrow, suggesting curiosity or skepticism. The background shows shelves filled with more books and a window letting in natural light, adding an atmosphere of study and reflection. The overall tone is warm and humorous, capturing the mental image of using intellect in matters of faith without confrontation or negativity.'),
 (1866, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religion Humor, Word Play', 'If a person wants to be atheistic it''s his God-given right to be an atheist.', 'Michael Patton', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing proudly on a small podium styled like a book titled ''Rights and Freedoms.'' Above the person is a shining spotlight with a halo-like glow, symbolizing the phrase ''God-given.'' The person looks confident and cheerful, holding a sign that says ''Atheist'' with a big smile. Around the podium, various symbolic items float: a cloud with light rays shining down, a small angel with a confused expression scratching its head, and a cartoonish deity figure peeking from the corner scratching its chin thoughtfully. The setting is bright and whimsical, with soft pastel colors and gentle details like floating stars and sparkles to keep the mood light and funny. The style is exaggerated, with expressive faces and simple, bold outlines typical of a playful cartoon.'),
 (1667, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religious Humor, Word Play', 'Even God cannot change the past.', 'Agathon', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a gentle, cartoonish representation of God sitting at an old-fashioned wooden desk with a large, open book labeled ''Past'' in front of Him. God looks thoughtfully at the pages, holding a golden quill pen poised above the book but unable to write or erase anything. Around God, ethereal clouds float, with clocks displaying different times in the background. A celestial chalkboard nearby shows a timeline with past dates crossed out with a red ''X''. The expression on God''s face is mild but slightly puzzled, indicating the impossibility of altering what has already happened. The scene is lighthearted with soft colors, rounded shapes, and a few whimsical details like little angel helpers shrugging or scratching their heads beside God. The overall mood is funny and contemplative without any drama or negativity, emphasizing the joke’s concept that even an all-powerful figure cannot change the past.'),
 (1716, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Religious Humor, Word Play', 'Give me chastity and continence, but not yet.', 'Saint Augustine (354-430)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful young person standing at a crossroads with two large signs. One sign on the left says ''Chastity & Continence'' with a serious, almost angelic glow, while the other sign on the right says ''Not Yet'' and is colorful, playful, and inviting. The character looks conflicted but mischievous, scratching their head with a slight smile. Around them are little floating symbols of temptation like a heart, a slice of cake, and a party hat, illustrating distraction from the serious path. The background is bright and simple, emphasizing the comic contrast between the moral high road and the tempting delay. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and clear, bold text on the signs to make the joke''s punchline visually obvious and funny without any violence or offense.'),
 (2065, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Romance Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Love is but the discovery of ourselves in others, and the delight in the recognition.', 'Alexander Smith', 'A cheerful, whimsical cartoon scene showing two characters facing each other, each holding a large, ornate mirror that reflects the other person''s face. The mirrors glow softly to emphasize the idea of recognition. The characters wear simple, colorful clothing and have friendly, expressive eyes showing delight and surprise. Around them, subtle heart shapes float gently in the air to signify love. The background is light and airy with soft pastel colors and a few whimsical clouds, giving a dreamy, introspective atmosphere. The overall style is playful and warm, with exaggerated expressions to highlight the joy of discovering oneself through another.'),
 (2070, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Romance Humor, Word Play', 'Love is the only way to grasp another human being in the innermost core of his personality.', 'Victor Frankel', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters: one labeled ''Love,'' depicted as a large, friendly, glowing heart with arms and eyes, gently holding a much smaller human figure in its hands. The small human looks surprised but happy, standing inside a transparent orb that represents the ''innermost core'' of their personality. Around them, symbols like musical notes, stars, and thought bubbles float to represent personality traits. The background is bright and cheerful, with soft pastel colors. The characters are drawn in a whimsical style with exaggerated, expressive faces. The heart character''s arms slightly wrap around the tiny person, showing care but also a funny sense of ''grasping'' someone deeply without being too literal or physical. The scene conveys warmth and affection with a clever visual pun on the idea of love ''grasping'' someone''s core personality.'),
 (1891, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Commentary', 'If the misery of the poor be caused not by the laws of nature, but by our institutions, great is our sin.', 'Charles Darwin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon of a courtroom scene set in a whimsical world. In the center, a judge with a large gavel looks dramatically solemn, wearing an exaggeratedly oversized wig. On one side, a sad, raggedly dressed character labeled "Poor" sits on the witness stand, looking miserable but innocent. On the other side, a confused group of bureaucrats or politicians—depicted as cartoonish people in suits with big glasses and stacks of paperwork labeled "Institutions"—shrug and look guilty. Behind them, a large, ancient book titled "Laws of Nature" lies closed collecting dust. Above them, a large banner or sign reads, "Great is Our Sin." The overall style is playful with exaggerated expressions, gentle lines, and bright but muted pastel colors to keep the tone light and humorous despite the serious theme.'),
 (2028, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Fiction Humor, Word Play', 'Language is a virus from outer space.', 'William S. Burroughs', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a quirky, colorful alien spaceship hovering just above Earth. From the spaceship, a playful, semi-transparent virus character shaped like a smiling, spiky microorganism with big eyes and little antennae is zipping toward an open book or a speech bubble. The virus is leaving a trail of letters, words, and symbols swirling around as if infecting language itself. On Earth below, a cartoon person looks up in surprise while holding a dictionary or smartphone showing words. The background includes a starry outer space setting with distant planets to emphasize the ''outer space'' origin. The overall tone is lighthearted and imaginative, with exaggerated, friendly characters and vibrant colors to convey the idea that language is comically being infected or influenced by this alien virus.'),
 (1881, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor', 'If it can''t be expressed in figures, it is not science; it is opinion.', 'Lazarus Long', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene set in a lighthearted science classroom or lab. In the foreground, depict a confident scientist or professor (wearing a lab coat and glasses) standing next to a large chalkboard or whiteboard covered with colorful graphs, charts, equations, and numbers. The scientist is holding a pointer stick, gesturing enthusiastically at the figures while making a clear, emphatic gesture to underline the point. To add humor, include a confused or skeptical student sitting at a desk with a thought bubble containing an abstract messy scribble or chaotic swirl to represent ''opinion.'' Around the room, include playful scientific props such as beakers, microscopes, and maybe a quirky robot or molecule model looking puzzled. The overall mood is fun and educational, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the difference between science (quantifiable figures) and opinion (no clear data). The style should be colorful, with bold outlines and expressive cartoon characters, making it approachable and amusing rather than serious.'),
 (2377, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Social Commentary', 'The saddest aspect of life right now is that science gathers knowledge faster than society gathers wisdom.', 'Isaac Asimov', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters side-by-side. On the left, a scientist in a white lab coat is excitedly holding up a beaker filled with bubbling, colorful liquid and a stack of thick books labeled ''Science''. Behind the scientist is a wall full of complex charts, formulas, and glowing screens symbolizing rapid knowledge gathering. On the right, a person wearing casual clothes sits on a park bench scratching their head, looking puzzled and confused, with question marks floating above their head. Around the bench are several old-fashioned wisdom symbols such as an owl, a thick dusty book labeled ''Wisdom'', and a slow-moving turtle trying to catch up. Between them, a dashed line or a gap represents the speed difference, with the scientist zooming forward on roller skates or a rocket and the puzzled person moving very slowly with a walking stick. The background is a simple city park with trees and clouds, rendered in a light, cheerful, exaggerated cartoon style to emphasize the contrast between fast science and slow societal wisdom.'),
 (2229, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Science is organized knowledge. Wisdom is organized life.', 'Immanuel Kant', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing an open book labeled ''Science'' on one side, with neat, precise diagrams, formulas, and a magnifying glass on the pages. On the other side, a friendly older person with a calm, wise expression is sitting cross-legged in a peaceful, natural setting with symbols of life around them—such as a small tree, a bird, a clock, and a heart-shaped thought bubble. Above the book and the person, a lightbulb shines, symbolizing insight. The scene is colorful and playful, with exaggerated, simple cartoon lines and a clear divide between the ''organized knowledge'' represented by the book and ''organized life'' represented by the person calmly embracing life. The background is simple, with soft warm colors to emphasize harmony and understanding. Both sides are connected by a curved arrow or a thought bubble linking science and wisdom, highlighting the contrast yet relation between them.'),
 (1463, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Wit', 'A science is any discipline in which the fool of this generation can go beyond the point reached by the genius of the last generation.', 'Max Gluckman', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of two characters representing different generations of scientists. On the left, depict an elderly, wise-looking scientist with glasses, messy white hair, and a lab coat, holding a thick stack of books or papers labeled ''Genius Research.'' On the right, show a younger, somewhat clueless-looking scientist in a lab coat, confidently using a telescope or microscope pointed beyond a far-off point on the horizon or an exaggerated distance marker labeled ''Next Level.'' The younger scientist should have a slightly goofy smile or an exaggerated expression of confidence. The background can include a cluttered laboratory with beakers, test tubes, and scientific instruments scattered around to emphasize the scientific setting. Add humorous details like a chalkboard with complex formulas crossed out and replaced by simpler, odd diagrams, highlighting the generational contrast. The overall style should be lighthearted, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the irony of the joke without any negativity or offense.'),
 (1721, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Science Humor, Word Play', 'God is the tangential point between zero and infinity.', 'Alfred Jarry', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a chalkboard with a large math diagram. On the board, there is a big circle representing infinity and a point labeled zero on a line. At the very spot where the two touch—called the tangent point—there is a cartoon character representing God. This character is drawn humorously as a friendly, wise figure with a long beard, flowing robes, and a halo, smiling and holding a pointer stick as if explaining the concept. Around the board are a few amused students or scientists with exaggerated puzzled and amazed expressions, maybe scratching their heads or holding notebooks. The setting is a classic classroom or lecture hall with desks, an overhead light, and some mathematical formulas scattered on the board. The whole image uses bright colors and clean lines to create a lighthearted, intellectual cartoon vibe, emphasizing the clever math pun in a fun way.'),
 (1606, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Help Humor, Wit', 'Circumstance does not make the man; it reveals him to himself.', 'James Allen', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man standing in front of a large magnifying mirror. The man looks thoughtful and a bit surprised as the mirror''s reflection humorously exaggerates his facial expression and personality traits, like revealing a confident superhero cape, a timid bunny, a clown nose, and a scholar''s hat all blending together. Around him, everyday objects such as a briefcase, casual shoes, and a coffee cup are scattered, symbolizing different life circumstances. The background is simple and light-hearted, with bright colors to keep the tone cheerful and comedic, emphasizing the idea that circumstances don''t create who he is, but the mirror reveals his true, sometimes funny, self to himself.'),
 (2043, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'Life is just a mirror, and what you see out there you must first see inside yourself.', 'Wally ''Famous'' Amos', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a large, ornate mirror. The person looks thoughtfully at their reflection. Instead of a normal reflection, the mirror shows a smaller, transparent version of the person''s mind above their head, filled with various imaginative images like a smiling sun, a heart, and a little scene of the person helping someone else. The background is simple, like a bedroom or hallway, to keep focus on the mirror and the person. Include subtle visual cues like a lightbulb above the person’s head, indicating an idea or realization. The overall tone is light-hearted and whimsical, highlighting the concept of self-reflection in a fun and clear way without being overly serious or deep.'),
 (2302, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'The first and greatest victory is to conquer yourself; to be conquered by yourself is of all things most shameful and vile.', 'Plato', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing in front of a large mirror. The person is dressed casually and looks determined, as if preparing for a challenge. In the reflection, an exaggerated, comical version of themselves stands back with crossed arms, wearing a sly smirk and holding a tiny white flag, symbolizing surrender. The setting is a simple bedroom or living room with a small rug and a plant nearby to keep the background lively but not distracting. Above the mirror, a motivational banner reads: ''Conquer Yourself!'' The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the internal struggle in a funny way without any seriousness or negativity.'),
 (2479, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor', 'To sit alone with my conscience will be judgment enough for me.', 'Charles William Stubbs', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a person sitting alone on a simple park bench at night under a glowing full moon. The person has a slightly worried but resigned expression, looking sideways at a small, personified character labeled ''Conscience'' sitting right next to them on the bench. The conscience character is a tiny, glowing, angelic figure with a halo and little wings, looking serious and stern, holding a tiny clipboard as if taking notes. The background should be minimal, focusing on the two characters, with a few trees and stars to emphasize quiet solitude. The style should be lighthearted and whimsical without any threatening or dark elements.'),
 (2052, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Listen to viewpoints different from your own. Conviction is strengthened by understanding all angles of a problem.', 'From Annie', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at the center of a round table, looking thoughtfully at several versions of themselves positioned around the table. Each version of the person has a slightly different expression and holds a speech bubble with different viewpoints or opinions symbolized by simple icons (e.g., a lightbulb for an idea, a question mark for doubt, a thumbs-up, a thumbs-down). The central figure is attentively listening with an exaggerated focused expression, perhaps rubbing their chin. The setting is a simple room with a whiteboard behind, labeled ''All Angles,'' with arrows pointing between the various selves. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with expressive faces to clearly convey the humor of ''thinking through all sides'' as if arguing with oneself to strengthen conviction. No violence or negative emotions, just playful introspection.'),
 (2181, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Only a brave person is willing to honestly admit, and fearlessly to face, what a sincere and logical mind discovers.', 'Rodan of Alexandria', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing proudly on a small stage or pedestal, holding a magnifying glass that shines a bright spotlight onto a large cartoon brain hovering nearby. The person looks confident and fearless, wearing simple but bold clothing, with a slightly exaggerated determined expression. Around the brain, are several thought bubbles showing complex and serious ideas (like math equations, philosophical symbols, and puzzle pieces) being uncovered. The background is simple, with rays radiating outwards to emphasize the ''discovery'' moment. The overall color palette is bright and playful to highlight the courage and clarity involved in facing one''s own logical thoughts.'),
 (2589, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor, Wit', 'Without you, what am I myself but a guide to my own downfall?', 'St. Augustine, The Confessions', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing at a crossroads or on a winding path. The person looks slightly confused and introspective, scratching their head or holding a small map. Around them, visual metaphors of ''downfall'' appear lightly and comically: for example, little cartoonish pitfalls, banana peels, or tiny cliffs on the path ahead. The environment is whimsical and slightly exaggerated, like a colorful outdoor setting with signposts pointing in different directions labeled "Success" and "Downfall." The character''s expression should be exaggerated to show a mix of self-awareness and comic despair. The overall style is light and playful, using bright colors and cartoonish proportions to emphasize humor without being dark or sad.'),
 (2116, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Wit', 'Most people are other people. Their thoughts are someone else''s opinions, their lives a mimicry, their passions a quotation.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a crowd of people walking in a city street, but each person looks like a puppet controlled by large strings held by shadowy, faceless figures above. The people have exaggerated blank expressions as if copying each other''s actions. Speech bubbles above some individuals contain identical thought bubbles or quotes with little attribution marks. In the background, a caricatured, oversized book or speech bubble labeled "Other People''s Opinions" floats above, emphasizing the theme. The overall mood is light-hearted and satirical, with bright colors and simple lines, highlighting mimicry and unoriginality in a playful, exaggerated way.'),
 (2193, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Wit', 'People demand freedom of speech to make up for the freedom of thought which they avoid.', 'Soren Aabye Kierkegaard (1813-1855)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters standing at a podium in front of a crowd. One character is speaking confidently into a microphone labeled ''Freedom of Speech.'' Around them, thought bubbles above the crowd''s heads are empty or show cartoonish images of people looking confused or distracted, clearly avoiding deep thinking. In contrast, a small sign near the speaker reads ''Freedom of Thought Area - No Entry,'' humorously suggesting the crowd is deliberately steering clear of thinking. The setting is a simple stage with a banner overhead stating ''Freedom Rally.'' The style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated to emphasize the irony that the crowd is eager to speak but uninterested in thinking. Cartoon facial expressions should show the speaker as smug and the crowd as eager yet vacant-minded to highlight the joke''s irony.'),
 (1537, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'An eye for an eye makes the whole world blind.', 'Gandhi', 'A cartoon-style global scene centered on a large, round Earth with exaggerated facial features to emphasize expression. The Earth has two big eyes with bandages over them, symbolizing blindness, and a slightly worried or sad expression. Surrounding the Earth are several cartoonish human characters of diverse backgrounds, all wearing thick, comical blindfolds that cover their eyes, indicating they cannot see. Above or beside the Earth, a large, stylized text bubble or banner reads "An eye for an eye makes the whole world blind." The background is simple with a clear sky and a few fluffy clouds to keep focus on the characters and Earth figure. The style is bright, colorful, and light-hearted, using soft outlines and exaggerated expressions to highlight the humor and the moral of the phrase without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (2210, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Humor', 'Pride gets no pleasure out of having something, only out of having more of it than the next man.', 'C. S. Lewis', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two men standing side by side, each holding a simple trophy or prize. Both men have exaggerated, proud expressions with puffed-up chests and smug smiles. Between them, a large measuring tape or ruler floats, showing one man’s prize is just a tiny bit bigger or taller than the other''s. The background is minimal, maybe a simple stage with a banner reading ''Who’s Got More?''. Add little visual cues of pride, like sparkles or shining stars around their heads. Keep the style light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the rivalry and competition to have ‘more’ rather than enjoying the prize itself. No violence or aggressive gestures, just friendly one-upmanship captured in a funny, cartoonish way.'),
 (2389, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Humor, Wit', 'The thermometer of success is merely the jealousy of the malcontents.', 'Salvador Dali', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene centered around a large, comically exaggerated thermometer labeled ''Success.'' The thermometer''s mercury level is bright red and rising, with small icons of trophies, money bags, stars, and thumbs-up inside it to represent success. Surrounding the thermometer are several cartoon characters looking enviously at it with exaggerated frowning faces, crossed arms, and puffed-up cheeks to symbolize jealousy and malcontent. One character might be glaring, another biting their lip nervously, and another with steam comically coming out of their ears to show frustration. The setting should be lighthearted and simple, like a small park or office break room with a bench or table nearby. Include speech bubbles over some of the envious characters with little green symbols (like tiny jealous eyes or scribbles) to emphasize their feelings. The overall tone is playful and witty, with bright colors and clean lines to give it a classic cartoon feel of irony about success and envy, without anything aggressive or dark.'),
 (2403, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Humor, Wit', 'The ultimate result of shielding men from the effects of folly, is to fill the world with fools.', 'Herbert Spencer', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two characters in a simple outdoor setting. On the left, a well-meaning character, dressed like a medieval knight wearing shining armor and holding an oversized, exaggerated shield labeled ''Shielding from Folly.'' This character looks serious and determined. On the right, multiple goofy-looking men with silly expressions, some tripping over their own feet, others scratching their heads confusedly. These men are dressed in casual, mismatched clothes to emphasize their foolishness. The background is a sunny grassy field with a few cartoonish trees and a clear blue sky. Above the characters, a bold caption banner reads: ''The ultimate result of shielding men from the effects of folly, is to fill the world with fools.'' The art style is colorful and exaggerated with big eyes and expressive faces for comic effect, emphasizing irony and silliness without any violence or offense.'),
 (2438, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Social Humor, Wit', 'There is only one thing in the world worse than being talked about, and that is not being talked about.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters at a small café table outside. One character looks slightly dejected and lonely sitting alone, glancing sideways with a sad expression. The other character nearby sits with an exaggeratedly large group of people animatedly gossiping and pointing in the direction of the lonely character with lively speech bubbles filled with chatter symbols (like lines or squiggles). Above the lonely character’s head, a thought bubble shows them imagining themselves as the center of attention, with a spotlight shining down. The café setting should include small tables with drinks, chairs, and cheerful background details like a sunny sky and a few trees. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing social interaction and the bittersweet irony of wanting to be talked about but also fearing it.'),
 (1893, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Sports Humor, Wit', 'If winning isn''t every-thing, why do they keep score?', 'Vince Lombardi', 'A humorous cartoon scene at a sports field depicting a scoreboard displaying a close game score. In the foreground, a puzzled character—perhaps a casual spectator or an athlete—scratches their head while looking up at the scoreboard. The character has a thoughtful, confused expression on their face. Nearby, a referee or coach stands holding a whistle and a clipboard, glancing toward the character with an amused smile. The background shows a simple sports setting, like a soccer or basketball court, with faint outlines of players in action and a few cheering spectators. The scoreboard is large, clearly visible, with brightly lit numbers emphasizing the score. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the irony and the mental contradiction expressed by the joke, without any aggressive or intense expressions.'),
 (1437, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Time Humor, Word Play', 'A lost ounce of gold may be found, a lost moment of time never.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene illustrating the concept of losing gold versus losing time. On one side, show a character kneeling and happily holding a shiny, detailed gold nugget they just found on the ground, surrounded by sparkles and little stars emphasizing its value. On the other side, depict the same character looking frustrated and confused while staring at a melting clock or an hourglass with sand slipping quickly through. The clock or hourglass should have exaggerated cartoon features like big eyes and a sad face, symbolizing the fleeting nature of time. The background is simple and light, with a clear division between the two scenes to highlight the contrast visually. Include small humorous details, like a lost ''map'' or magnifying glass next to the gold, and a calendar with days flying off near the hourglass. The style should be bright, colorful, and playful to emphasize the lighthearted yet thoughtful message of the joke.'),
 (2153, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Travel Humor, Wisdom', 'Not all those who wander are lost.', 'J.R.R. Tolkien', 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly quirky traveler walking through a colorful, exaggerated landscape filled with twisting paths, signposts pointing in multiple confusing directions, and a map upside down in their hands. The traveler wears a wide-brimmed hat, a backpack overflowing with camping gear, and brightly patterned clothes. In the background, other travelers look confused, scratching their heads or looking lost, while the main character confidently strides forward with a smile, clearly enjoying the journey. The sky is bright and sunny with a few fluffy clouds, and there are playful animals like a squirrel or bird nearby, observing curiously. A banner or caption overhead reads, “Not all those who wander are lost.” The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and vibrant colors to emphasize humor and joy in wandering without a clear destination.'),
 (2337, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Travel Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'The man who goes alone can start today; but he who travels with another must wait till that other is ready.', 'Henry David Thoreau (1817-1862)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting two travelers preparing for a journey. On the left, a cheerful man with a backpack and hiking boots is eagerly stepping forward onto a dirt path with a big smile, ready to start his adventure immediately. On the right, another man stands next to him, but he is distracted and comically tangled up trying to put on a large, oversized backpack, struggling with straps and looking frustrated. Between them is a signpost labeled ''Start of the Journey''. The background shows a bright, sunny day with green rolling hills and a distant mountain trail. The style should be colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the contrast between the ready solo traveler and the delayed duo waiting for the second person to get ready.'),
 (1920, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Ignorance is a voluntary misfortune.', 'Nicholas Ling', 'A humorous cartoon scene shows a cheerful, cartoonish character standing in front of two large signposts. One sign reads ''Knowledge'' and depicts a bright sun and open books, while the other sign points to ''Ignorance'' featuring a cozy armchair, TV remote, and snacks. The character is happily sitting in the armchair, wearing comfy pajamas, with a relaxed smile, eyes half-closed, clearly choosing comfort over effort. Surrounding the scene are floating light bulbs dimmed above the character''s head on the ''Ignorance'' side, and glowing bright light bulbs hovering over the ''Knowledge'' side far in the background. The overall setting is a bright, simple room with bookshelves near the ''Knowledge'' side, and a comfy living room setup on the ''Ignorance'' side. The style is colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between active learning and the voluntary choice of ignoring knowledge in a lighthearted, playful way.'),
 (2024, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Kindness consists in loving people more than they deserve.', 'Joseph Joubert', 'Draw a warm, humorous cartoon scene showing two characters interacting. One character is smiling kindly, offering a large heart glowing with light and warmth. The other character looks a bit surprised or undeserving, perhaps holding a scowl or an indifferent expression. Around them are small visual cues that show the kindness is going beyond what is expected: maybe the generous character is reaching past a ''deserved'' sign with a low score or thumbs down near the second character. The background should be simple, cheerful, and colorful, with soft rays or sparkles emanating from the heart to emphasize goodwill. Both characters should be friendly and expressive but caricatured in a fun, lighthearted cartoon style. Include some small humor in details, like a tiny angelic halo or a sign that says ''More than deserved'' floating above the generous character''s head, enhancing the playful, thoughtful message of the joke.'),
 (2027, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Knowledge is soon changed, then lost in the mist, an echo half-heard.', 'Gene Wolfe', 'Create a humorous cartoon scene depicting a whimsical library on a mountaintop shrouded in swirling mist. In the foreground, a small confused character in academic robes holds an oversized ancient book with question marks floating above their head. Behind them, ethereal ghostly echoes shaped like faint, blurred words drift away into the fog. The library building looks whimsical, with crooked shelves and dusty books whispering secrets into the mist. The sky is in soft pastel colors, suggesting dawn or dusk, enhancing the mysterious and fleeting nature of knowledge. Overall, the style is light and playful, capturing the idea that knowledge is ephemeral and elusive, like an echo fading away.'),
 (2217, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Real knowledge is to know the extent of ones ignorance.', 'Confucius', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking, cartoon character—perhaps an older person with glasses and a thoughtful, slightly amused expression—standing in front of a large blackboard. On the blackboard, write the phrase: ''Real knowledge is to know the extent of one''s ignorance'' in playful, bold letters. Around the character, show thought bubbles with question marks, small books with titles like ''What I Don''t Know,'' and a brain symbol to emphasize thinking. The background should be a cozy study or classroom setting with shelves of books, some tipped over to add light humor. The overall tone is lighthearted and playful, focusing on the irony and wisdom of understanding one’s own limits rather than showcasing anything serious or harsh. The style should be colorful, with exaggerated expressions and rounded shapes to keep it cartoonish and inviting.'),
 (2281, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The beginning of knowledge is the discovery of something we do not understand.', 'Frank Herbert', 'A cartoon scene featuring a curious-looking character, standing in front of a large, old-fashioned library filled with tall shelves of books stretching up to the ceiling. The character is scratching their head with one hand, holding an oversized magnifying glass in the other, peering at a floating glowing question mark hovering above an open book. The character''s expression is one of mild confusion mixed with intrigue. Around the character, a few whimsical question marks and light bulbs float in the air, symbolizing confusion and discovery. The background is warm and inviting, with vintage lamps illuminating the books. The style is colorful and lighthearted, with exaggerated features to emphasize humor and curiosity. No violence or controversial items, just a funny, thoughtful vibe.'),
 (2305, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The first step towards knowledge is to know that we are ignorant.', 'Richard Cecil', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at the base of a large colorful staircase labeled ''Knowledge.'' The person looks puzzled but determined, scratching their head with a thought bubble above showing the words: ''I know nothing!'' Around the person, floating question marks and light bulbs suggest curiosity and confusion. The background is simple and bright, with a few books and scrolls scattered near the staircase bottom. The overall vibe is lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the idea that recognizing one''s ignorance is the first step to gaining knowledge. The style should be cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright, bold lines to keep the tone friendly and funny.'),
 (2604, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'You cannot teach a man anything; you can only help him find it within himself.', 'Galileo', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters outdoors in a peaceful park. One person is a cheerful teacher, wearing glasses and holding an open book, gesturing encouragingly toward the other character, who is a confused-looking man scratching his head. Nearby, the man is looking into a treasure chest labeled ''Inner Wisdom'' that is slightly open and glowing softly, as if hinting at something valuable inside. Surround the treasure chest with whimsical thought bubbles containing small icons like a light bulb, a brain, a heart, and a key to symbolize self-discovery. The environment should be simple and colorful, with trees, grass, and a bright sky. The teacher''s expression is friendly and supportive, while the man’s face shows curiosity and slight bewilderment. Keep the style playful and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions for comedic effect.'),
 (2154, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor, Word Play', 'Not everything that can be counted counts, and not everything that counts can be counted.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking professor standing at a chalkboard. The chalkboard is divided into two halves. On the left side, there are many numbers and tally marks drawn, representing things that ''can be counted'' like apples, coins, and stars. On the right side, there are abstract symbols such as a heart, a smiley face, and a lightbulb glowing above, representing things that ''count'' but can''t be counted. The professor is pointing to both sides with a thoughtful, slightly amused expression. Around the professor are a few confused students scratching their heads, enhancing the playful, philosophical tone of the joke. The classroom setting includes desks, books, and a window showing a sunny day outside. The overall style is exaggerated and cartoonish, with bright colors and expressive characters to emphasize the humor and wisdom of the statement without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1745, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wisdom, Word Play', 'He is no fool who gives what he cannot keep to gain what he cannot lose.', 'Jim Elliot', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a wise-looking philosopher character dressed in simple ancient robes, standing thoughtfully on a small hill at sunset. He is holding an empty hand extended toward a glowing, floating treasure chest labeled ''What You Cannot Lose'' that shines with an ethereal light. Nearby, a small, locked wooden box labeled ''What You Cannot Keep'' is shown fading away in his other hand or vanishing like smoke. The background includes a peaceful landscape with a few fluffy clouds and birds to emphasize serenity and contemplation. The style is lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions to reflect clever wisdom rather than seriousness. The entire scene conveys the abstract idea of giving up something temporary to gain something permanent in a visually amusing way, without being dark or heavy.'),
 (2452, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wise Sayings, Word Play', 'Things are neither good nor bad, only thinking makes them so.', 'Shakespeare', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a relaxed person sitting cross-legged on a fluffy cloud in the sky, wearing simple, loose clothing and a peaceful smile. The person is holding a thought bubble above their head showing a split image: on one side, an angelic thumbs-up and a shining sun, and on the other side, a devilish thumbs-down and dark storm clouds. Around the cloud float various everyday objects—a spilled cup of coffee, a broken pencil, a blooming flower, and a buzzing bee—all neutral but drawn with expressive faces showing neither happiness nor sadness. The background is bright and cheerful, with soft pastel colors, emphasizing a whimsical and lighthearted atmosphere that visually represents the idea that things are neutral and only our thinking labels them as good or bad. The style should be simple and cartoony, with exaggerated expressions and gentle outlines to keep the mood playful and contemplative.'),
 (1383, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'A conclusion is where you got tired of thinking.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk cluttered with papers, books, and a brain-shaped lamp. The person looks exhausted and has their head resting on one hand, eyes half-closed, as if mentally drained. Above their head is a thought bubble with lots of scribbles and question marks transitioning into a speech bubble that says, “A conclusion is where you got tired of thinking.” The setting is a simple office or study environment, with a clock showing late hours and a crumpled piece of paper on the floor. The style should be light-hearted and exaggerated to enhance the comedic effect, emphasizing the person''s tiredness and confusion in a funny, relatable way.'),
 (1479, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'A witty saying proves nothing.', 'Voltaire', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a character standing confidently on a small stage holding a microphone, delivering a witty one-liner. The character has a confident smirk and exaggerated features to emphasize cleverness. In the foreground, an audience of various cartoon characters appears unimpressed or confused, some with raised eyebrows or scratching their heads. Include a sign on the stage background that reads "Witty Sayings Show." The scene should be light-hearted and comical, using bright colors and simple shapes to highlight the contrast between the speaker''s confidence and the audience''s reaction. No violence or sensitive elements; just playful expressions and body language to convey the joke''s irony that a witty saying alone doesn''t prove anything.'),
 (1485, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Above all, one must doubt.', 'Descartes', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a character standing at a crossroads with two identical signposts pointing in opposite directions, both labeled ''Truth.'' The character has a puzzled, exaggerated confused expression with wide eyes and scratching their head. The background shows a serene park with a few quirky details like a squirrel holding a tiny question mark and a thought bubble above the character''s head containing the phrase ''Above all, one must doubt.'' The scene is light and whimsical, with bright colors and simple, rounded shapes to emphasize the playful nature of the joke.'),
 (1718, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Glory is fleeting, but obscurity is forever.', 'Napoleon Bonaparte (1769-1821)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a flashy, radiant trophy or medal labeled ''Glory'' placed prominently on a pedestal, shining brightly with sparkles and beams of light. Nearby is a plain, dusty, and somewhat neglected box or bin labeled ''Obscurity,'' with cobwebs and shadows around it to emphasize its endless forgotten nature. The background is simple and clean, perhaps with a somber undertone around the ''Obscurity'' side and a vibrant glow around the ''Glory'' to contrast fleeting fame versus permanent anonymity. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, with expressive eyes on the trophy looking proud but also a little worried, and the box appearing calm and indifferent, creating a visual metaphor for the joke’s meaning.'),
 (2373, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'The reasonable man adapts himself to the world; the unreasonable man persists in trying to adapt the world to himself. Therefore all progress depends on the unreasonable man.', 'George Bernard Shaw (1856-1950)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two characters interacting in a park. The first character, labeled ''Reasonable Man,'' is calmly sitting on a bench, reading a newspaper and wearing neat, conventional clothes. Around him, everything is neat and orderly—a tidy tree, a paved path, and trimmed grass. The second character, labeled ''Unreasonable Man,'' is actively trying to reshape the world around him: he is pushing or pulling a large, exaggeratedly misshapen tree toward a different spot, or perhaps attaching strange inventions to the tree to change it. He looks enthusiastic and stubborn, with wild hair and a determined expression. In the background, other elements, like lamp posts or benches, are humorously distorted or being altered by the Unreasonable Man’s inventions. The overall mood is light, playful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, emphasizing the absurdity and creativity of insisting the world change instead of oneself. Include a small sign or plaque on the bench quoting the line: ''All progress depends on the unreasonable man.'''),
 (2408, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'The world is a tragedy to those who feel, but a comedy to those who think.', 'Horace Walpole', 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, an expressive character with large, teary eyes and a sad face is surrounded by gloomy, dark clouds, maybe shedding a single tear or looking overwhelmed, to represent ''those who feel'' viewing the world as a tragedy. On the right side, a different character with a sly, knowing smile and a thoughtful pose (hand on chin), wearing glasses or with a light bulb above their head to represent intelligence and thinking, stands in bright, sunny surroundings with cheerful birds or comedy masks floating around them, illustrating ''those who think'' seeing the world as a comedy. The middle should have a faint divide to show the contrast, but the style is whimsical and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions and simple, colorful backgrounds. No text is needed in the image.'),
 (2533, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Well-timed silence hath more eloquence than speech.', 'Martin Fraquhar Tupper', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters sitting opposite each other at a small café table outdoors. One character is animatedly talking with exaggerated hand gestures and a big smile, holding a steaming cup of coffee. The other character sits calmly, serene and composed, with lips sealed and a slight knowing smile, enjoying a quiet moment with a cup of tea. Above their heads, simple speech bubbles show the talking character’s many words spilling out as a jumble of letters and symbols, while the silent character’s bubble is empty except for a small elegant swirl or a musical note, symbolizing eloquence in silence. The background is bright and cheerful with other café tables, a friendly dog looking upwards, and a soft sun shining to add warmth to the setting. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, emphasizing the humor of silence speaking louder than words, drawn in a clear, colorful, and cartoonish style with expressive facial features to highlight the contrast between talkative and quiet.'),
 (2586, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Wise men make proverbs, but fools repeat them.', 'Samuel Palmer (1805-80)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters standing side by side. On the left, a wise-looking man with a long beard, glasses, and a thoughtful expression is writing or holding a scroll filled with proverbs. He wears a scholar''s robe and has an aura of intelligence, with light bulbs or stars around his head indicating wisdom. On the right, a silly-looking fool—wearing mismatched clothes, a dunce cap, and with a goofy smile—is holding an identical scroll as the wise man, but is obviously copying the wise man''s words without understanding. The fool is repeating the proverb aloud with a speech bubble saying, "Wise men make proverbs, but fools repeat them." In the background, a small audience (maybe animals or other villagers) watches and giggles. The setting is a simple village or classroom with a chalkboard or parchment on an easel showing simple proverbs. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggeratedly cartoonish with friendly expressions to keep the humor light and accessible.'),
 (1477, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Wit, Word Play', 'A wise man sees as much as he ought, not as much as he can.', 'Montaigne', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a calm, elderly wise man sitting cross-legged on a large rock at the top of a hill or mountain with a serene expression. He wears simple, flowing robes and holds a small scroll or ancient book in one hand. Surrounding him is a wide, exaggerated panoramic landscape showing distant mountains, forests, animals, and little villages far below, illustrating the vast scenery he can see. Place a whimsical telescope next to him on the rock, but it’s ignored and covered in dust. Add a thought bubble above his head with a small image of an eye symbol combined with a checkmark, humorously indicating he only sees what he should. The style should be soft and cartoonish with clear lines and warm colors, creating a peaceful yet lightly comedic atmosphere emphasizing wisdom over excessive curiosity or perception.'),
 (1442, 'Philosophy Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'A man may die, nations may rise and fall, but an idea lives on.', 'John F. Kennedy', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a thoughtful-looking man standing next to a large, glowing light bulb with a cheeky smile. The background shows stylized outlines of falling and rising nations portrayed by crumbling and newly built monuments such as a broken-down ancient pillar on one side and a fresh modern building on the other. The setting is bright and colorful, with the light bulb personified as the ''idea'' that remains steady and shining in the center, highlighting the persistence of ideas over time. The man wears casual modern clothes and has a pondering expression, while the monuments appear exaggerated and cartoonish to add humor. The composition focuses on the contrast between the transient nations and the enduring, lively idea in the middle, rendered in a clear, simple cartoon style appropriate for humorous illustration.'),
 (1297, 'Philosophy Humor, Relatable', 'To distinguish the real from the unreal, one must experience them both.', NULL, 'A whimsical cartoon scene split into two halves. On the left side, a cheerful person is holding a realistic-looking ice cream cone happily standing in a sunny park with trees, birds, and a bench. On the right side, the same person looks puzzled, now holding a melting, bizarre ice cream cone that looks unreal—perhaps with impossible shapes like floating scoops or glowing colors. The middle of the image shows a transparent mirror or glass dividing the two worlds, symbolizing the boundary between real and unreal. The person’s expression shifts from contentment on the real side to thoughtful curiosity on the unreal side. The overall style is lighthearted with bright colors and exaggerated, cartoonish features to emphasize the contrast and humorously illustrate the concept of distinguishing reality by experiencing both.'),
 (3190, 'Philosophy Humor, Relatable, Steven Wright, Word Play', 'A conclusion is the place where you got tired of thinking.', 'Steven Wright', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk cluttered with papers, books, and a coffee mug. The person is slumped over, resting their head on one hand with a tired, sleepy expression, eyes half-closed, clearly exhausted from thinking. Above their head is a thought bubble that contains a lightbulb that is dim or flickering, symbolizing fading ideas. Behind them is a large sign or poster on the wall that reads, ''Conclusion,'' styled like a destination sign or road sign, implying they have ''arrived'' there. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing mental fatigue rather than stress or frustration. The cartoon style is friendly and simple, with exaggerated facial expressions to enhance humor and relatability.'),
 (2844, 'Philosophy Humor, Science Humor, Unknown, Wit', 'Everything should be made as simple as possible, but no simpler.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a quirky, slightly disheveled professor or scientist standing next to a large, complicated-looking machine with lots of gears, buttons, and levers. The machine is clearly meant to perform a simple task, like making coffee or watering a plant, but it looks overly complex. The professor is holding a blueprint titled ''Simplify It!'' and has a thoughtful, slightly amused expression. Nearby, on a cluttered desk, there are scattered notes and discarded overly complicated diagrams crossed out. The setting is a bright, cluttered laboratory filled with shelves of books, test tubes, and scientific gadgets. Include a speech bubble from the professor that says, ''Everything should be made as simple as possible, but no simpler.'' The overall tone is light and playful, with exaggerated cartoonish proportions for the character and the machine, emphasizing the humor in overcomplicating simplicity.'),
 (1298, 'Philosophy Humor, Science, Word Play', 'Time is nature''s way of keeping everything from happening at once.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon showing a whimsical, exaggerated clock with human-like features (big eyes, a smiling face) standing in the middle of a busy natural scene. Around the clock are various events from nature happening, but spaced out in time. On one side, a flower is blooming with a happy face; on another, a bird is flying; nearby, a tree is growing slowly with little cartoons of roots and leaves popping up. In the background, the sun is rising on one side and setting on the other, emphasizing the passage of time. The clock holds a sign or points to a speech bubble saying, ''Time keeps everything from happening at once!'' The overall style is playful and light, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions on the clock and natural elements to emphasize the humor in the idea of time controlling events in nature.'),
 (1299, 'Philosophy Humor, Science, Word Play', 'What is wanted is not the will-to-believe, but the wish-to-find-out,  which are exact opposites.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a cozy library or study room. One character is holding a bright light bulb above their head, representing the ''wish-to-find-out,'' with an eager and curious expression. They are surrounded by open books, magnifying glasses, and scientific tools like a microscope and test tubes. The other character stands opposite, with their arms crossed, wearing a thought bubble with a heart symbol inside it, symbolizing the ''will-to-believe'' and looking confidently stubborn. Between them floats a signpost with arrows pointing in opposite directions labeled ''Will-to-Believe'' and ''Wish-to-Find-Out.'' The background includes shelves filled with books and curious objects, such as a globe and a telescope, adding to the theme of inquiry versus belief. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize their opposing stances in a friendly, non-serious debate.'),
 (3153, 'Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Your mind understands what you have been taught; your heart, what is true.', NULL, 'A whimsical cartoon scene showing a person standing with two exaggeratedly distinct characters emerging from their head and chest. From the head, a small scholarly-looking figure wearing glasses and holding a book labeled ''Lessons'' is intently pointing at a chalkboard filled with symbols and notes. From the heart area, a warm, glowing, friendly-looking figure with a big smile radiates light and holds a glowing gem labeled ''Truth.'' The background is simple, with soft pastel colors and subtle hearts and lightbulbs floating around. The person looks thoughtful, caught between the logical figure from the mind and the glowing figure from the heart, illustrating the contrast between learned knowledge and true feeling. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with round shapes and expressive faces, suitable for a humorous but gentle visual metaphor.'),
 (2674, 'Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'Better to understand a little than to misunderstand a lot.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters in a simple classroom or casual setting. On the left, a character is depicted confidently delivering a long, complicated speech or explanation, with large, tangled speech bubbles filled with confusing symbols and question marks to represent misunderstandings. On the right, a second character listens attentively but looks calm and thoughtful, holding a small book or just a simple speech bubble with a clear, short phrase demonstrating limited but accurate knowledge. The background can include a chalkboard with the phrase ''Better to understand a little than to misunderstand a lot'' written on it. Both characters should have friendly, exaggerated cartoon expressions to emphasize the humor in over-explaining versus knowing less but correctly. The style is light and playful with bright colors, mild exaggeration, and no violent or controversial elements.'),
 (2773, 'Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Wisdom Humor', 'Do not clog intellect''s sluices with bits of knowledge of questionable use.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a whimsical, old-fashioned water sluice gate labeled ''Intellect'' on a hillside. The sluice is made of wood and looks like a brain-shaped channel guiding water flowing smoothly through it. Nearby, a mischievous character resembling a scholar or librarian, wearing glasses and a tweed jacket with elbow patches, is holding a bucket filled with small, oddly shaped objects labeled ''Questionable Knowledge.'' The character is hesitating, about to dump the bucket onto the sluice, but the water is starting to clog and overflow. The background shows a peaceful countryside with a few quirky details like floating question marks in the air and a sign next to the sluice reading ''Use Wisely.'' The overall style is lighthearted and whimsical, with exaggerated facial expressions on the character showing concern and confusion. Add a speech bubble above the character saying, ''Maybe not all knowledge is meant to flow through!'''),
 (2787, 'Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Wit', 'Don''t believe everything you believe.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a person sitting comfortably in an armchair, thoughtfully stroking their chin with a slightly puzzled expression. Above their head is a large, colorful thought bubble filled with a jumble of symbols, question marks, and cartoonish icons representing beliefs (e.g., a light bulb, a heart, a book, a globe). The person is surrounded by smaller floating thought bubbles that show them doubting or questioning their own ideas (e.g., crossed-out checkmarks, question marks, and a speech bubble with the words ''Really?''). The setting is a cozy living room with a bookshelf and a window showing a sunny day outside. The overall style is simple, bright, and whimsical with exaggerated facial features to emphasize the moment of self-questioning. No violence or inappropriate content is included.'),
 (2880, 'Philosophy Humor, Unknown, Wit, Word Play', 'General notions are generally wrong.', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene set in a classroom or a lecture hall with a quirky professor at the front. The professor is standing beside a large blackboard or whiteboard with the phrase ''General notions are generally wrong'' written in big, playful letters. The professor is scratching their head with a puzzled but amused expression, wearing round glasses and a slightly disheveled suit. Around the professor, several students sit at desks, looking confused, surprised, or laughing. Include some scattered papers, books, and a globe on a stand to emphasize the educational setting. Use exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors typical of cartoons to highlight the irony and humor in the phrase. No text bubbles are necessary, just the written phrase on the board. The overall mood is light and witty, focusing on the contradiction in the statement itself to spark a smile.'),
 (1300, 'Philosophy Humor, War Humor, Word Play', 'War never decides who is right, only who is left.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a barren battlefield with a few scattered, tired-looking soldiers on both sides. The background shows damaged and abandoned flags, torn banners, and broken weapons strewn about. One soldier, standing in the center, looks puzzled and is holding a large sign with the words ''Who is right?'' on one side and ''Who is left?'' on the other. Another soldier nearby has an exaggeratedly confused expression, pointing to the ''Who is left?'' part of the sign. The atmosphere is light-hearted and comical, with no graphic violence, just a playful take on the wordplay. The scene uses bright colors and simple shapes to enhance the cartoon effect, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the silliness of the pun.'),
 (1301, 'Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'The best prophet of the future is the past.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple room with a large crystal ball resting on a small round table covered by a purple cloth. Behind the table, a cheerful fortune teller wearing a colorful robe and a turban is dramatically pointing at the crystal ball. Inside the crystal ball, instead of mystical swirls or visions, there is a clear and detailed depiction of an old-fashioned scroll labeled ''The Past'' with an ancient quill pen on top. The fortune teller has a speech bubble that says, "The best prophet of the future is the past!" Around the room, funny little details include a calendar on the wall showing yesterday''s date, and a history book lying open beside the crystal ball. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors, emphasizing the irony that to predict the future you just look at the past rather than magic or mystery.'),
 (1302, 'Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'The soul would have no rainbow had the eyes no tears.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large pair of cartoonish eyes with exaggerated tear drops streaming down. From the tears, a colorful, vibrant rainbow arches upward and outward, filling the space above with bright, cheerful colors. The eyes look slightly sad but there is a subtle smile to add a lighthearted feel. The background is simple and light, perhaps with a few fluffy clouds around the rainbow to enhance the contrast. The overall tone is uplifting and whimsical, capturing the idea that tears (sadness) produce something beautiful (a rainbow) from within the soul, but presented in a playful and exaggerated style.'),
 (1303, 'Philosophy Humor, Word Play', 'VUJA DE:  The strange feeling you get that nothing has ever happened before.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused person standing in the middle of a surreal landscape. The person has a puzzled expression, scratching their head with exaggerated confusion lines above their head. Around them, everyday objects like a coffee cup, clock, and calendar float in the air, but everything looks brand new and unfamiliar as if they''ve never been seen before. The background is whimsical and slightly surreal, with a twist on normal reality—trees with upside-down leaves and clocks with random numbers. A small caption near the person reads ''Vuja De: The strange feeling you get that nothing has ever happened before.'' The overall style is light-hearted, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the oddity of the feeling.'),
 (1304, 'Philosophy, Word Play', 'Old philosophers don''t die - they just don''t think therefore they aren''t.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in an ancient Greek-style agora with stone columns and scrolls scattered around. In the foreground, an elderly philosopher with a long white beard, toga, and round spectacles is sitting thoughtfully on a stone bench. He has a puzzled, slightly sleepy expression and a small thought bubble above his head with fading question marks. Nearby, a younger philosopher holds a scroll and points at the elder with a gentle smile, as if explaining the punchline. In the background, busts of famous philosophers with bemused faces are mounted on pedestals. The setting is bright and whimsical, with a subtle cloud in the shape of a faded brain floating above the elderly philosopher''s head to visually emphasize ''not thinking.'' The overall style is cartoonish and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and rounded features to keep the mood light and humorous.'),
 (3019, 'Photography Humor, Pun, Unknown', 'I once failed photography class --- I couldn''t focus...', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a student in a photography class. The student is holding a large camera with a confused and distracted expression, looking off in a random direction instead of through the camera lens. Around the student are blurred images and floating question marks, emphasizing a lack of focus. In the background, a classroom setting with a teacher pointing at an out-of-focus photograph displayed on a board labeled ''Photography 101''. Include cameras, photo prints, and a classroom desk with scattered books and notes. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun on ''focus'' with exaggerated confusion and visual blur effects around the student and photos.'),
 (2897, 'Physics, Pun, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Gravity isn''t easy, but it''s the law.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person tripping and falling flat on the ground with a surprised expression. Nearby, a large, friendly-looking book titled ''LAW'' is standing upright, with arms and legs, holding a gavel to emphasize it is a legal authority. Above the person, an exaggerated apple is falling straight down from a tree branch, referencing the classic gravity example. The setting is a simple park scene with grass, a tree, and a sunny sky. The style is lighthearted and comical, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to emphasize the pun between gravity as a physical force and law as a legal system.'),
 (2872, 'Physics, Puns, Science Humor, Unknown', 'Friction is a drag.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a piece of sandpaper personified with a tired, annoyed face dragging a heavy suitcase or bag labeled ''Friction'' behind it. The sandpaper has little arms and legs, exaggeratedly leaning backward as it struggles to pull the suitcase on a slightly rough surface that looks like a road made of wood or paper texture. The background is simple and bright, with a clear sky and maybe a small signpost that says ''Physics Road'' to hint at the scientific concept. Above or below the scene, include the caption ''Friction is a drag.'' The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on the sandpaper and suitcase to convey the pun and the concept of friction causing resistance or drag.'),
 (1332, 'Pirates, Programmers, Pun, Technology Humor', 'How did pirates collaborate before computers ? Pier to pier networking.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two classic pirates standing on separate wooden piers extending over calm blue water. Each pirate is holding a simple communication device resembling a tin can phone connected by a long string stretched taut between the two piers. Both pirates wear traditional pirate hats, eye patches, and striped shirts. One pirate is shouting into his can phone with a big smile, while the other listens intently, cupping his hand to his ear. The background includes a small pirate ship bobbing in the distance and a few seagulls flying overhead. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the pun “pier to pier networking” with visual elements representing both pirate culture and early, rudimentary communication methods. Bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated expressions highlight the joke’s friendly and absurd tone without any violence or negativity.'),
 (1308, 'Pirates, Pun', 'One pirate says to the other, ''Arrrgh, that be a fine looking hook and peg leg ye got for ye''self!'' The pirate replies, ''I would think so, it cost me and arm and a leg!''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two pirates standing on a wooden ship deck. The first pirate is excitedly looking at the other pirate’s prosthetics, pointing towards his wooden hook hand and peg leg. Both pirates wear classic pirate hats with skull-and-crossbones symbols, tattered shirts, and striped pants. The second pirate proudly shows off his hook and peg leg with a confident smile, emphasizing their quality. The background includes a bright blue sky with fluffy clouds and the ship’s mast with a waving pirate flag. Add some playful details like a parrot perched on the first pirate’s shoulder and a treasure chest in the corner to set a lighthearted pirate atmosphere. The style should be colorful and exaggerated with big expressive eyes and exaggerated features, capturing a cheerful and comical pirate interaction without any violence or threat.'),
 (1305, 'Pirates, Pun, Word Play', 'Did you know that Pirates were the first people to insulate their homes? They did it for the ''RRRR'' value.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a friendly pirate standing proudly in front of a small, cozy wooden pirate cabin. The pirate is wearing a classic pirate hat with a skull and crossbones, an eye patch, and a striped shirt. Around the cabin, visible insulation materials peek out from within the walls, with fluffy padding colored in light blue or white. Above or next to the pirate, a large comic-style speech bubble displays the phrase: "RRRR value" in bold, playful letters. The pirate is making a classic pirate growl face while holding a rolled-up insulation panel under one arm. The background is a sunny seaside scene with a pirate ship anchored nearby, decorated with the Jolly Roger flag fluttering. The overall style is bright, cheerful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun by creatively combining typical pirate imagery with home insulation elements, without any violence or dark themes.'),
 (1307, 'Pirates, Pun, Word Play', 'How much did the pirate pay for his piercings? A buck-an-ear!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful pirate with a classic pirate look: a tricorn hat, eye patch, striped shirt, and a big gold hoop earring in each ear. The pirate is standing proudly on a wooden pier that extends into the sea, holding up one hand near his face to show off several ear piercings, each adorned with small coins or bucks as earrings. The pirate has a big grin, showing off his gold teeth. Around him, seagulls fly and a wooden signpost reads ''Pier.'' To emphasize the pun, add a price tag or small price sign hanging off one ear saying ''A buck each!'' The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with caricatured features and cartoonish proportions to highlight the humorous wordplay without any violence or inappropriate content.'),
 (1311, 'Pirates, Pun, Word Play', 'What is a pirate''s favorite letter of the alphabet?? Ahhh.. yee''d think it''d be R, but me first love B the C!!!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a cheerful pirate standing on the deck of a classic wooden pirate ship. The pirate is dressed in stereotypical pirate attire, including a tricorn hat with a skull and crossbones, an eye patch, a striped shirt, a wide belt with a large buckle, and boots. The pirate is holding a large, playful parchment scroll with the alphabet letters written on it. He is grinning mischievously and pointing with one hand towards a big, bold letter ‘B’ that is stylized like a heart to signify ''love.'' Behind him, the ocean should be visible with light waves and a clear sky. Incorporate a speech bubble coming from the pirate with the joke punchline: “Ahhh.. yee''d think it''d be R, but me first love B the C!!!” Make the overall style bright, colorful, and exaggerated to emphasize the fun and pun. No violence or scary imagery; keep the pirate friendly and charming.'),
 (1317, 'Pirates, Pun, Word Play', 'Why are pirates so great? They just RRRRRrrrr!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful pirate standing on the deck of a wooden ship. The pirate is drawn in a classic style with a big smiling face, an eye patch, a pirate hat with a skull and crossbones, a striped shirt, and a large hook for a hand. The pirate''s mouth is open wide, as if shouting ''RRRRRrrrr!'', with large, playful letters in a speech bubble coming out of his mouth. Surrounding him, suggest a bright sunny ocean background with seagulls flying and a few barrels and ropes on the ship deck to set the pirate theme. The overall mood is light and playful, emphasizing the joke’s pun on the stereotypical pirate growl sounding like a simple expression of greatness. The cartoon style should be colorful, with exaggerated facial features for comedic effect.'),
 (1321, 'Pirates, Technology Humor, Travel Humor', 'We really used to print out pages from MapQuest and travel like pirates.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two modern-day travelers on a small boat dressed as pirates with eyepatches and pirate hats. One pirate is holding a big printed-out paper map with the MapQuest logo clearly visible, looking confused while trying to navigate. The other pirate is looking at a smartphone or GPS device, appearing amused or skeptical. The boat is whimsically decorated with a pirate flag, and the background shows a simple ocean with a tiny island in the distance. The overall tone is lighthearted, capturing the anachronism of using old-fashioned printed directions like pirates relying on treasure maps, contrasted with modern navigation technology.'),
 (1322, 'Police Humor, Word Play', 'Police are looking for criminals who stole the wheels of their cop car. They are working tirelessly to catch them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene outside a police station at night. A police car is parked with no wheels, resting awkwardly on stacks of colorful donuts or cinder blocks to emphasize the missing tires. Two cartoon police officers stand beside the car: one is scratching his head looking puzzled, while the other is energetically writing notes on a clipboard. Nearby, a sign labeled ''Police Station'' is visible. In the background, a full moon shines, and a small silhouette of fleeing thieves can be seen rolling away on stolen wheels, laughing mischievously. The style should be light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on the officers to highlight the joke about them ''working tirelessly.'' Keep the colors bright and the lines clean to give it a fun, cartoonish vibe without any violent or suggestive elements.'),
 (1411, 'Political Humor, Pun, Quotes, Satire', 'A government is the only vessel known to leak from the top.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, old-fashioned wooden ship labeled ''Government'' floating on calm water. The vessel has a wide deck with multiple government buildings and officials dressed in suits, looking busy or confused. At the very top of the ship’s mast, a faucet or pipe is dramatically leaking water down onto the officials below. The water leaking from the top contrasts with the idea that ships usually leak from the bottom. The officials appear surprised or trying to catch the leaking water with buckets. The background is simple, with a bright sky and a few clouds to keep the focus on the ship and the leak. The style should be lighthearted and exaggerated, emphasizing the irony of the leak coming from the top as a visual pun on the joke’s meaning, without any negativity toward individuals.'),
 (1453, 'Political Humor, Puns, Quotes, Satire', 'A penny saved is a Congressional oversight.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a large, exaggerated penny with a face, looking surprised or worried. Nearby, a few caricatured figures representing members of Congress are shown distracted or bumbling, perhaps flipping through stacks of paperwork or looking confused, highlighting their oversight. The setting is a congressional office or chamber with desks, papers, and American flags in the background. The penny is placed prominently in the foreground as the main focus, with some playful elements like dollar bills or coins scattered around to hint at finances. Everything should be drawn in a lighthearted, cartoon style with bright colors and expressive characters to emphasize the pun without any negativity.'),
 (1385, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'A conservative is a man who is too cowardly to fight and too fat to run.', 'Elbert Hubbard', 'A cartoon scene featuring a man depicted humorously as a conservative. He appears middle-aged, wearing a suit that is a bit too tight around his stomach to emphasize heaviness. His facial expression is timid, with wide eyes looking nervously over his shoulder. Around him are two symbolic elements: on one side, a boxing glove hanging loosely from one hand suggesting a reluctance to fight; on the other side, a running shoe barely tied and slipping off the foot, indicating an inability or unwillingness to run. The background is simple, perhaps showing a starting line for a race and a small boxing ring corner to represent the two actions. The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated features to emphasize humor and avoid offense, focusing on the gentle irony of the description rather than serious commentary.'),
 (2165, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire', 'Nothing would please the Kremlin more than to have the people of this country choose a second rate president.', 'Richard M. Nixon', 'A cartoon-style scene set outside a grand, ornate Kremlin building with its distinctive onion domes in the background. In the foreground, a group of cartoon Kremlin officials in stereotypical suits and Russian hats are huddled together with sly grins and rubbing their hands with anticipation. Nearby, a large ballot box labeled ''Presidential Election'' is overflowing with ballots scattered around, some marked with humorous ''second-rate'' check marks or simple doodles. The scene conveys a mischievous mood, emphasizing the Kremlin’s desire for an undesirable or incompetent leader to be elected elsewhere. The overall art style should be colorful and exaggerated with friendly, non-threatening characters, capturing the ironic humor of political incompetence desired by outsiders without any hostility or aggression. Thought bubbles with icons like confused voters or wobbly podiums may add to the humor.'),
 (2205, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Science Fiction', 'Politicians should read science fiction, not westerns and detective stories.', 'Arthur C. Clarke', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of politicians sitting in a cozy library or reading room. The politicians, depicted in exaggerated, caricatured style with suits and ties, are holding various books. One politician looks puzzled holding a thick western novel with a cowboy hat and horse on the cover, while another clutches a detective story with a magnifying glass and trench coat on the cover looking confused. Nearby, another politician is happily engrossed in a bright, colorful science fiction book featuring flying saucers and robots on the cover. Around them, shelves of books display clear labels like ''Westerns'', ''Detective Stories'', and ''Science Fiction''. The background should include humorous touches: a cowboy hat and a magnifying glass resting on a table and perhaps a futuristic robot toy peeking out from a bookshelf. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions showing confusion versus interest. No violence or politics, just a playful, satirical visual about reading choices among politicians.'),
 (1621, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Commentary', 'Democracy is a process by which people are free to choose the man who will get the blame.', 'Laurence J. Peter', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing a crowd of diverse, everyday people standing in front of a large voting booth shaped like a ballot box. Everyone looks slightly confused or indifferent but with a hint of amusement. In the foreground, an exaggeratedly serious-looking politician stands to one side, wearing a suit and looking nervously at a large, comically oversized blame target sign behind him. The sign reads ''Blame Here'' with an arrow pointing directly at the politician. Some people in the crowd hold ballot papers, but their expressions suggest they know the ''winner'' will just be the one blamed. The setting is simple with a clear focus on the group, the voting booth, and the politician and blame sign. Use bright, friendly colors and exaggerated facial expressions for a light-hearted, cartoonish effect. Avoid any political symbols or specific party references to keep it neutral and funny.'),
 (1625, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Commentary', 'Democracy is the theory that the common people know what they want and deserve to get it good and hard.', 'H. L. Mencken', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of diverse, ordinary citizens standing around a large voting ballot box in a town square. The people look eager and hopeful at first, holding ballots labeled with bright, simple symbols. Surrounding them are exaggeratedly large gears and levers marked ''Democracy Machine'' that are turning loudly and grinding harshly. From the machine’s output chute, a rough, oversized hammer or mallet labeled ''Hard Lesson'' drops with a comical ''thud'' onto a soft cushion shaped like the word ''Consequences.'' The expressions on the people''s faces shift from confident to surprised and slightly dismayed but still playful. The scene should be colorful, with cartoon-style exaggerated features, emphasizing quirky details like the oversized machine parts and comically intense expressions. The background shows a simple town hall and a cheerful sun, adding a lighthearted tone to the idea of democracy delivering something unexpectedly tough but deserved. Avoid any violent or aggressive imagery—focus on the metaphor with clear, funny visuals to accompany the idea that people get what they vote for, sometimes for better or worse.'),
 (1733, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Commentary', 'Half of the American people have never read a newspaper. Half never voted for President. One hopes it is the same half.', 'Gore Vidal', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a split crowd of American people divided into two groups on either side of the image. On the left side, a diverse group of people are casually holding or reading newspapers, some looking confused or uninterested. On the right side, another diverse group of people stand by a voting booth labeled ''Presidential Election,'' some clearly turning away or chatting instead of voting. Above them hovers a smiling, hopeful character holding their fingers crossed, representing the narrator''s wish that both groups are the same people. The background features subtle American symbols like a flag and a town hall, adding a civic context. The style should be bright and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor and irony of the message without any negativity or confrontation.'),
 (2339, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Commentary', 'The marvel of all history is the patience with which men and women submit to burdens unnecessarily laid upon them by their governments.', 'William H. Borah', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a long line of people dressed in various historical and modern clothes, each looking tired but patient. They are waiting outdoors in front of a large, imposing government building with pillars and a sign reading ''Government Office.'' Above them, exaggeratedly large and silly signs hang showing unnecessary burdens like giant stacks of paperwork, oversized taxes, complicated rules on scrolls, and long, winding red tape floating in the air. People carry heavy, comically oversized weights labeled ''Unnecessary Burdens.'' One person looks at their watch, another sighs dramatically, and yet another holds a protest sign humorously asking ''Why so much paperwork?'' The sky is bright and clear, and the building looks bureaucratic and slightly over-the-top to emphasize the humor in submission to pointless rules. The art style is playful, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions focusing on patience and mild frustration.'),
 (2345, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Commentary', 'The modern definition of ''racist'' is someone who is winning an argument with a liberal.', 'Peter Brimelow', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a lively debate between two characters seated at a café table outside. On one side, a casually dressed person labeled ''Liberal'' looks frustrated, scratching their head with several crumpled papers marked ''Points'' scattered around. On the other side, a smug-looking character labeled ''Winning Argument'' confidently holds a sign that says ''Modern Definition of Racist.'' The café table is cluttered with coffee cups, a laptop showing a debate forum, and a speech bubble from the ''Winning Argument'' character quoting the joke text. In the background, other patrons give puzzled or amused looks. The setting is light and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize humor and irony. No aggressive body language or harsh tones—just a funny portrayal of a verbal argument with humorous exaggeration.'),
 (2262, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Social Humor', 'Sure there are dishonest men in local government. But there are dishonest men in national government too.', 'Richard M. Nixon', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two politicians standing side by side in a simple office setting. The first politician is labeled ''Local Government'' and the second labeled ''National Government.'' Both are wearing suits but have exaggerated cartoonish expressions with sly grins and shifty eyes to suggest dishonesty. Between them is a large, overflowing trash bin labeled ''Promises'' filled with crumpled papers. The background includes typical office items like a flag, a wooden desk with nameplates, and a cityscape visible through a window behind the local politician, and a national parliament building visible through the window behind the national politician. The style is bright, colorful, and lighthearted, emphasizing the humor in the shared trait rather than negativity. The atmosphere is playful and satirical without being harsh or mean-spirited.'),
 (2368, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Television', 'The President has kept all of the promises he intended to keep. (Speaking on the Larry King Live show)', 'Clinton aide George Stephanopolous', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a TV studio resembling the Larry King Live show. The backdrop features a large banner with ''Larry King Live'' in bright colors. In the center, a confident-looking president, depicted with a big smile, stands at a podium or desk with a microphone. Nearby, a caricature of Larry King—wearing his signature suspenders, glasses, and holding a microphone—listens intently with a slightly amused expression. Floating above the president’s head is a thought bubble showing a checklist with a few boxes ticked and many left blank, symbolizing the promises. The studio audience in the background is subtly smirking or whispering to each other, reacting to the president’s statement. The overall tone is lighthearted and satirical but respectful, emphasizing the irony in the president''s claim in a friendly political humor style. The image uses bold lines and bright colors typical of cartoons, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor and subtle irony of the joke.'),
 (1964, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Word Play', 'It could probably be shown by facts and figures that there is no distinctly American criminal class except Congress.', 'Mark Twain', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of stereotypical American congress members caricatured as mischievous ''criminals.'' The setting is a classic congressional chamber with desks, microphones, and an American flag in the background. The congress members wear suits but have playful ‘criminal’ attributes like striped prisoner hats and oversized handcuffs hanging loosely from their wrists. Some are sneakily pocketing dollar bills or stacks of paperwork labeled ''Bills.'' In front, a large chart or whiteboard shows exaggerated statistics titled ''American Criminal Class'' with a dramatic arrow pointing exclusively to a silhouette labeled ''Congress.'' The atmosphere is lighthearted and satirical, with exaggerated facial expressions showing sly grins, winks, and finger-pointing, all in vibrant cartoon style. No violence; the focus is on the irony of the joke, making the politicians look comically guilty yet harmless.'),
 (2016, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Word Play', 'I''ve seen many politicians paralyzed in the legs as myself, but I''ve seen more of them who were paralyzed in the head.', 'George Wallace', 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of politicians standing on a stage or podium during a debate or speech. Draw most politicians with exaggerated, glassy, confused or silly expressions to symbolize being ''paralyzed in the head.'' Meanwhile, one or two politicians have visible leg braces or wheelchairs to subtly indicate ''paralyzed in the legs.'' The setting is lighthearted and colorful, with no harsh details. Include microphones, flags, or a simple backdrop suggesting a formal political event. Expressions should be playful and exaggerated rather than mean-spirited, emphasizing the joke''s wordplay on different types of ''paralysis.'' The overall tone is comical and satirical without being harsh or aggressive.'),
 (2040, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Word Play', 'Liberalism is, I think, resurgent. One reason is that more and more people are so painfully aware of the alternative.', 'John Kenneth Galbraith', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing at a crossroads with two large, clearly marked signposts. One signpost reads ''Liberalism'' and points toward a sunny, vibrant cityscape full of colorful buildings, happy people, and blooming trees. The other signpost reads ''Alternative'' and points toward a dull, bleak landscape with gray skies, dead trees, and unhappy figures trudging along. The person looks confused but thoughtful, scratching their head while facing the signs. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with cartoonish expressions and distinct contrasts between the two paths to emphasize the joke''s message without being aggressive or political. The background should keep the focus on the crossroads and signage, with clean, simple lines and bright colors for the liberal path and muted grays and browns for the alternative path.'),
 (2322, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Satire, Word Play', 'The illegal we do immediately. The unconstitutional takes a little longer.', 'Henry Kissinger', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters at a desk in a shady office labeled ''Government Operations.'' One character, dressed in a suit and looking sly, is holding a stack of papers labeled ''Illegal Actions'' and handing them over eagerly to an identical-looking but slightly older character sitting behind the desk. The second character holds a larger, dusty, cobweb-covered book titled ''Unconstitutional Actions'' and glances at it with a puzzled expression, as if it''s a complicated case needing time. The office is cluttered with exaggerated government-related props such as scales of justice, a clock showing fast-forward time on the ''illegal'' side, and a slow-moving hourglass labeled ''unconstitutional.'' The overall style is lighthearted and cartoonish, emphasizing the contrast between rapid illegal acts and slow unconstitutional processes, without any political or violent tones.'),
 (1431, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary', 'A liberal is a person whose interests aren''t at stake, at the moment.', 'Willis Player', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two groups of people at a town meeting or community boardroom. On one side, a group labeled ''Liberals'' is sitting relaxed, casually chatting, with a few looking bored or disinterested. They have documents or signs labeled ''Issues'' but seem unconcerned. On the other side, a diverse group of people showing various emotions—concern, frustration, or passion—are holding protest signs or papers with urgent topics like ''Environmental Change,'' ''Healthcare,'' or ''Economy.'' The room has a simple setting with chairs, a table, and a bulletin board showing different community issues pinned up. The style is lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions emphasizing the humor in how the ''liberals'' appear detached because their interests aren''t currently affected. No aggressive or political symbolism, just a funny take on perceived detachment at times of apathy, as a social observation.'),
 (1619, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Wit', 'Democracy is a form of government in which it is permitted to wonder aloud what the country could do under first-class management.', 'Senator Soaper', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a group of diverse people standing in a public square or town hall. They are all holding speech bubbles filled with question marks and lightbulbs, symbolizing wondering aloud and ideas. In the background, a large banner reads ''Democracy'' with a caricature of a government building or parliament behind it. Some characters look confused, others thoughtful or hopeful, representing a range of opinions. The setting is bright and colorful, with no tension or conflict—just lively discussion. Include subtle humorous details, like one person scratching their head while another points upward as if having a sudden thought. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, capturing the idea of people openly questioning and imagining better management without anger or aggression.'),
 (2099, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Wit', 'Men and nations behave wisely once they have exhausted all the other alternatives.', 'Abba Eban (1915-)', 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting a group of men and a globe-shaped character representing a nation sitting around a large round table labeled ''Decision Room.'' The men appear puzzled and contemplative, surrounded by scattered papers and charts showing various complicated options like graphs, maps, and strategy icons. The globe character looks wise but slightly weary, with glasses perched on its middle and a thoughtful expression. In the background, a large cartoon-style clock shows time passing, emphasizing delay. The scene captures the moment just before they choose the single remaining untried option, hinting at a reluctant acceptance. The style should be light-hearted with exaggerated expressions and simple lines for clarity, and bright colors to keep it playful and non-serious. No indication of conflict; instead, a whimsical take on patience and decision-making.'),
 (1549, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Social Commentary, Word Play', 'Any man who is under 30, and is not a liberal, has not heart; and any man who is over 30, and is not a conservative, has no brains.', 'Sir Winston Churchill (1874-1965)', 'A humorous cartoon scene divided into two halves side-by-side. On the left side, draw a young man under 30 with a cheerful, open heart visible as a literal red heart symbol glowing in his chest, wearing casual clothes and maybe a t-shirt with something suggesting liberal ideas (like a peace sign or a colorful activist badge). On the right side, show an older man over 30 with a large, visible brain glowing or shining inside a transparent skull or an open head, dressed in business casual or conservative-style clothing. Both characters should have puzzled or thoughtful expressions. Above each character, include a simple label: ''Under 30, Not Liberal = No Heart'' above the younger man but cross out or remove the heart, and ''Over 30, Not Conservative = No Brains'' above the older man but cross out or remove the brain. The setting is bright and simple with a white or neutral background. The style should be friendly and upbeat with exaggerated cartoon features to emphasize the joke’s playful political commentary without appearing harsh.'),
 (1785, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I belong to no organized party. I am a Democrat.', 'Will Rogers', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a confused-looking man standing between two large doors labeled ''Organized Party'' and ''Democrats.'' The ''Organized Party'' door is neatly painted, straight, and with a welcoming sign, while the ''Democrats'' door looks a bit crooked, with scattered papers and a mix of colorful campaign buttons pinned haphazardly around it. The man is shrugging with a puzzled expression, wearing casual clothes and holding a small flag that says ''No Party.'' The background is a simple outdoor setting with a few trees and a clear sky to keep the mood light and friendly. The style should be bright, whimsical, and playful, emphasizing the irony and wordplay of the joke in a clean, cartoon style without any political bias or negativity.'),
 (1928, 'Political Humor, Quotes, Word Play', 'I''m not a member of any organized political party, I''m a Democrat!', 'Will Rogers (1879-1935)', 'A humorous cartoon showing a man standing at a podium with a big smile, addressing an audience in a lively town hall or community center setting. The man is casually dressed, perhaps with a sticker or badge that says ''Democrat'' visibly pinned to his shirt. Around him are posters of political parties'' logos on the walls, but the man''s badge stands out humorously as the only ''organized'' symbol. The audience looks a mix of amused and confused, emphasizing the punchline that being a ''Democrat'' is ironically presented as an ''organized political party.'' The mood is lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the joke. Include a small sign on the podium with the words "Political Parties Meeting" for context.'),
 (2831, 'Political Humor, Satire, Social Commentary, Unknown', 'Every nation has the government it deserves.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing a globe in the center with tiny, stylized people of different nationalities standing on their countries, each looking up at a wobbly, comically mismatched government building labeled ''Government'' perched precariously atop their land. The buildings appear absurdly flawed, with one having a crooked roof, another with leaning walls, and one with a door barely hanging on its hinges. The globe''s expression is amused, with raised eyebrows and a smirk, as if judging the situation. Around the globe, various speech bubbles show the people saying things like ''Well, this is what we get!'' or shrugging with exaggerated gestures. The style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, capturing a light-hearted satire without harshness or negativity. The focus is on the playful representation of governance as a reflection of the people, avoiding any direct political or violent imagery.'),
 (3173, 'Pop Culture Humor, Science Fiction Humor, Star Wars, Word Play', 'Remember when Mandolorians were feared across the galaxy? Mandos were the days.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a galaxy far, far away with a playful nod to the Mandalorians from Star Wars. The foreground shows a confident Mandalorian warrior in iconic armor, helmet on, holding a blaster casually over one shoulder, standing proudly on a rocky alien planet. In the background, a bright, shining galaxy with stars and planets is visible. Nearby, a calendar or signpost labeled ''Remember When'' with cartoon-style dates flipping away, emphasizing nostalgia. The Mandalorian has a slight smirk or thumbs-up to convey pride and humor. Include a subtle, friendly boba fett-style helmet or emblem to hint at the Mandalorian culture without being too serious. The overall cartoon style is lighthearted, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with bold outlines and fun expressions. The mood should evoke a fond, joking memory of the Mandalorians’ once-feared reputation with a pun visualized by the calendar or signpost showing ''Mandos were the days.'''),
 (1323, 'Pop Culture, Puns, Science Fiction Humor', 'We''ve replaced the Dilithium with new Folgers Crystals!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on the bridge of a starship reminiscent of classic sci-fi shows. The captain, wearing a futuristic uniform with a confused but amused expression, is holding a small coffee jar labeled ''Folgers Crystals'' in one hand and pointing to a glowing, futuristic ''Dilithium Crystal'' power core next to a coffee machine on the console. Around him, colorful control panels and blinking lights typical of a spaceship bridge are visible. A crew member nearby is nervously holding a steaming coffee cup, looking hopeful. Above the scene, a whimsical thought bubble shows a spaceship zooming powered by coffee steam instead of energy beams, emphasizing the joke’s play on replacing a vital power source with coffee crystals. The style is bright, exaggerated, and cartoonish, capturing light-hearted sci-fi parody without any violence or political elements.'),
 (3179, 'Pop Culture, Puns, Star Wars', 'What is Jabba the Hutt’s middle name? The.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring Jabba the Hutt, the large slug-like alien from Star Wars, lounging on his usual throne. Jabba is depicted with an exaggerated, goofy smile, looking puzzled yet amused. A speech bubble from a nearby character, possibly a small droid or human, asks, ''What is Jabba the Hutt''s middle name?'' In the next panel or side-by-side, show Jabba''s full name humorously written as ''Jabba The Hutt,'' with emphasis on the word ''The'' as if it is his middle name. The background should be the dimly lit, exotic palace setting with alien decorations and familiar props like the chain around Jabba''s neck and the setting from the movies, but drawn in a playful cartoon style with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to highlight the joke''s pun on the middle name being ''The.'' No violence or dark elements involved, just a lighthearted sci-fi pun visually represented with fun character design and environment details.'),
 (1324, 'Pop Culture, Puns, Technology Humor', 'This morning, Siri said, ''Don''t call me Shirley.'' I accidentally left my phone in Airplane! mode', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person sitting at a kitchen table looking puzzled and holding a smartphone. The phone screen displays Siri’s speech bubble that reads, "Don''t call me Shirley." The person’s face shows a comical mix of confusion and surprise. Nearby on the table, an airplane mode icon on the phone screen is clearly visible. In the background, a small paper airplane toy rests on the table, adding a visual pun hinting at airplane mode. The setting is bright and cheerful, with exaggerated cartoon features to highlight the humor. Include playful details like small motion lines around the phone to suggest it just spoke, and a thought bubble above the person’s head with an airplane to reinforce the joke about airplane mode. The art style is light and fun, in bold colors, emphasizing the tech miscommunication theme with a witty nod to the classic “Don’t call me Shirley” line from the film Airplane!.'),
 (2457, 'Pop Culture, Quotes, Science Fiction Humor, Word Play', 'This is your last chance. After this, there is no turning back. You take the blue pill - the story ends, you wake up in your bed and believe whatever you want to believe. You take the red pill - you stay in Wonderland and I show you how deep the rabbit-hole goes.', 'Morpheus', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inspired by the iconic ''Matrix'' movie moment. Show a character resembling a modern, casually dressed person standing at a small table with an older, wise-looking person wearing a long coat and glasses, offering two oversized, colorful pills on a silver platter: one vibrant blue pill and one bright red pill. The background should be whimsical, mixing elements of a normal bedroom (like a bed with rumpled sheets and a nightstand) fading into a surreal, dreamlike landscape with twisting tunnels resembling a rabbit hole spiraling down from the table. Include subtle playful details like a small white rabbit peeking out from the shadows near the hole. Both characters should have exaggerated expressions: the older person confidently persuasive and the younger one wide-eyed and intrigued. The style is cartoonish, lighthearted, with bright colors and clear outlines, emphasizing the contrast between reality and fantasy without any dark or threatening tones.'),
 (1325, 'Pop Culture, Religious Humor, Science Fiction Humor', 'The Bible has been translated into Klingon.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy study room filled with bookshelves stacked with various colorful Bibles. In the center, a big open book labeled ''The Bible'' is displayed on a lectern. Next to it, a smaller book with the Klingon script on its cover is being held up proudly by a cheerful character wearing a Star Trek uniform, featuring the iconic Starfleet badge. Around them, a few characters dressed as Klingons—complete with ridged foreheads and warrior costumes—are enthusiastically reading copies of the Bible in Klingon. The background should have a mix of traditional religious objects, like candles and crosses, juxtaposed with sci-fi elements such as a warp drive console or a starship window showing space. The characters’ expressions are amused and pleased, creating a quirky blend of religion and science fiction humor in a lighthearted cartoon style.'),
 (1326, 'Pop Culture, Word Play', 'My favorite movie is Robin Williams, without a doubt, is Mrs. Fire', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting comfortably in a movie theater with popcorn, watching a movie. On the movie screen, instead of a movie title or scene, the words ''Mrs. Fire'' are displayed prominently. The person looks confused or amused, scratching their head as if mishearing or misunderstanding the movie title. Around the person, add subtle visual hints referencing Robin Williams, such as a stand-up microphone or a cartoonish mask resembling his face on a poster nearby, to connect the name ''Robin Williams'' with the joke. The theater is cozy with rows of seats and a classic movie screen, emphasizing the movie-watching setting in a light, funny way. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and cartoonish, with expressive facial features and playful details that highlight the confusion in the joke without any harsh or negative themes.'),
 (3168, 'Positive Humor, Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'You''re living, you occupy space, you have mass. You know what that means? You matter.', NULL, 'A cheerful cartoon character, smiling with wide eyes, standing confidently in the center of the frame. The character is drawn simply, like a friendly, round figure with exaggerated features for humor. Around the character, light beams or subtle sparkles emphasize their importance. The background shows simple physics-related elements: a small weight scale beside the character to represent mass, a transparent 3D box to represent occupying space, and a floating glowing word bubble above the character''s head with the text ''You matter!'' The overall color palette is bright and uplifting, with playful fonts and a clean layout to evoke a warm, punny vibe. The cartoon style should be lighthearted and accessible, suitable for a family-friendly comic strip or greeting card.'),
 (1739, 'Positive Humor, Quotes, Self-Help Humor', 'Have respect for yourself. Love yourself and realize that whatever you attempt to achieve in life is a direct reflection of you. Be proud!', 'Joe Greene', 'A cheerful, confident person stands in front of a full-length mirror, looking proudly at their reflection. The character is smiling broadly, with hands on hips, wearing casual but bright clothing. The mirror shows the same happy expression, symbolizing self-love and respect. Surrounding the character are uplifting elements like sparkles, hearts, and a glowing aura to emphasize positivity and pride. The background is simple and warm-toned, such as a cozy bedroom or a calm living room with motivational posters on the wall that say phrases like ''Love Yourself'' and ''Be Proud!''. The cartoon style is light-hearted and colorful with exaggerated joyful facial features to enhance the humor in the strong positive message as if it were a funny pep talk illustration.'),
 (2173, 'Positive Humor, Quotes, Winter Humor, Word Play', 'One kind word can warm three winter months.', 'Chinese proverb', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a snowy winter landscape with frosty trees and snow-covered ground. In the center, a cheerful character wearing a thick winter coat, hat, and scarf is smiling warmly while speaking. From their mouth, a whimsical speech bubble appears that visually transforms into three vertical icicles, each labeled as ''January,'' ''February,'' and ''March.'' The icicles appear to be melting near the character’s words, giving off a warm glow or steam that contrasts with the chilly surroundings. Around the character, other bundled-up figures look surprised and happier, as if feeling the warmth from that one kind word. The style is bright and colorful, with exaggerated, friendly expressions and simple, bold lines typical of cartoon humor. Include snowflakes gently falling in the background and a small thermometer showing below freezing to emphasize cold weather.'),
 (2023, 'Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Kind words can be short and easy to speak, but their echoes are truly endless.', 'Mother Theresa', 'Draw a cheerful, cartoon-style scene set in a sunny park. In the foreground, show a friendly character smiling and speaking, with simple speech bubbles containing kind words like ''Thank you!'' and ''You did great!'' Floating from the character''s mouth are colorful, glowing echoes represented as fading, translucent sound waves or tiny speech bubbles that stretch far into the background, looping and winding endlessly around trees, benches, and bushes to symbolize the ongoing impact of kind words. Include birds or squirrels happily listening nearby to add warmth and charm. Use bright, uplifting colors and soft, rounded shapes to maintain a gentle, humorous cartoon feel without suggestive or serious elements. The overall mood should evoke positivity and the lasting effect of kindness in a fun, visual metaphor.'),
 (2057, 'Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Love all, trust a few. Do wrong to none.', 'William Shakespeare', 'Draw a cheerful cartoon scene featuring a friendly person standing at the center with open arms, symbolizing ''love all.'' Around them, show two characters nearby with a subtle gesture of cautious nodding or holding a small sign that says ''trust a few.'' The main character should have a kind, warm smile while looking at these trusting few. In the background, include a simple peaceful setting, like a sunny park with trees and flowers, emphasizing positivity and goodwill. Also depict a clear path labeled ''Do wrong to none'' that has no obstacles, showing a smooth ethical journey. The overall style should be light-hearted and humorous, with gentle, exaggerated expressions to convey warmth, trust, and kindness without any threat or negativity.'),
 (2183, 'Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'Opportunities multiply as they are seized.', 'Sun Tzu', 'A light-hearted cartoon scene showing a cheerful person standing in the middle holding a basket labeled ''Opportunities''. Around them, small glowing orbs or shapes that represent ''opportunities'' are floating. As the person reaches out and grabs one orb, more similar orbs begin appearing and multiplying in the air, creating a whimsical effect of growth and abundance. The background is simple, maybe a park or open field with soft colors to keep the focus on the multiplying ''opportunity'' orbs. The person''s expression is excited and slightly surprised by how many orbs are appearing. The style is bright, colorful, and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and cartoonish proportions to highlight humor and positivity without any complexity or negative elements.'),
 (2346, 'Positive Humor, Quotes, Wisdom Humor', 'The more you like yourself, the less you are like anyone else, which makes you unique.', 'Walt Disney', 'A cheerful and colorful cartoon scene featuring a single person standing confidently on a small hilltop surrounded by a crowd of identical-looking cartoon characters. The main character is smiling broadly, radiating a glowing aura or sparkles to emphasize self-confidence and uniqueness. Around them on the hill are subtle signs of individuality, like a different hairstyle, colorful clothes, and quirky accessories (e.g., funky glasses or a hat), while the surrounding crowd all look exactly the same with neutral expressions and plain, matching clothing. The background is bright and sunny, reinforcing a positive and uplifting mood. The style is playful and exaggerated, with rounded shapes and simple lines to highlight humor and friendliness without any harsh or serious tones.'),
 (1581, 'Positive Humor, Quotes, Wit, Words of Wisdom', 'Be who you are and say what you feel because those who mind don''t matter and those who matter don''t mind.', 'Dr. Seuss', 'A cheerful, cartoon-style scene showing a diverse group of five people standing in a park-like setting. In the center, a confident person with an expressive face is happily speaking, with a little speech bubble showing a heart and a smiley face. Around this central figure, two groups of people are drawn distinctly: on one side, two individuals frowning and covering their ears or looking annoyed, representing "those who mind." On the other side, three people smiling warmly and giving thumbs up or nodding approvingly, representing "those who matter." The background is bright and colorful with trees, flowers, and a blue sky. The overall tone is lighthearted and supportive, illustrated with bold outlines and bright colors typical of humorous cartoons. No aggressive or unpleasant expressions—just a clear visual contrast between supportive and unsupportive reactions to the speaker’s honest feelings.'),
 (1337, 'Programmers, Programming Humor, Pun', 'Java truly is an OOP language As in: OOPs - I used Java!', NULL, 'Create a humorous cartoon scene featuring a programmer sitting at a cluttered desk in front of a computer screen displaying Java code. The programmer looks surprised and slightly embarrassed, with one hand on their forehead as if they''ve just realized a mistake. On the desk, include a coffee cup with the word ''Java'' printed on it, emphasizing the pun. Above the programmer, show a speech bubble or cartoon-style text that reads ''OOPs - I used Java!'' The background should be an office or home workspace with typical programmer items such as sticky notes, a keyboard, and a mouse. The style should be lighthearted and cartoonish, capturing the humor in messing up Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) while coding in Java, playing on the double meaning of ''OOP'' and ''OOPs.'' Avoid any harsh or negative expressions; keep the tone playful and relatable for anyone familiar with programming languages.'),
 (1344, 'Programmers, Programming Humor, Pun', 'Unfortunately these jokes only work if you git them.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a computer screen displaying a snippet of code with the word "git" prominently visible (as in the Git version control system). Next to the computer, show a programmer scratching their head with a puzzled yet amused expression. Around them, include subtle visual cues hinting at typical programming elements: a coffee mug labeled "Debug Juice," a sticky note with binary numbers, and a small open book titled "Git for Beginners." The setting is a cluttered desk with typical office or home workspace elements like a keyboard, mouse, and a desk lamp. The background can have lighthearted posters like "Keep Calm and Git Commit." The overall style should be playful and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun on "git" as both a version control system and the phrase "get them." No violence or negative expressions; friendly and nerdy humor vibe.'),
 (1330, 'Programmers, Programming Humor, Pun, Technology Humor', 'A SQL query goes into a bar, walks up to two tables and asks, ''Can I join you?''', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a cozy bar with a few tables scattered around. The main character is a personified SQL query depicted as a friendly, nerdy character holding a laptop or tablet, wearing glasses and a casual shirt. The SQL query character is walking up to two anthropomorphic tables sitting side by side, each with facial expressions and limbs, looking welcoming but slightly surprised. One table could have a coffee cup and a plate, the other maybe a small plant or a book. The SQL query character says, ''Can I join you?'' in a speech bubble. The background should include typical bar elements like a counter with bottles and stools, and warm lighting to give a casual, lighthearted atmosphere. The style is light, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the pun in a friendly tech bar setting.'),
 (1339, 'Programmers, Programming Humor, Pun, Workplace', 'Programming is like sex: One mistake and you have to support it for the rest of your life.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a programmer sitting at a cluttered desk with multiple computer screens displaying lines of colorful code. The programmer looks slightly worried and tired, scratching their head while staring at the screen. Next to the desk is a large, comically oversized calendar with the phrase ''Support Schedule'' highlighted in red repeatedly for many months into the future. In the background, a speech bubble from the programmer reads, ''One mistake and you have to support it for the rest of your life.'' The environment should be light-hearted and playful, with typical coder items like coffee cups, snacks, and sticky notes scattered around. The overall style is bright and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions to emphasize the humor without any inappropriate elements or references.'),
 (1350, 'Programmers, Programming Humor, Pun, Workplace', 'Why did the developer go broke? Because he used up all his cache', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a stressed-out software developer sitting at a cluttered desk in a small, messy office. The developer looks worried, hands on his head, with a sad expression. On the desk, there is a computer screen showing lines of code and a progress bar labeled ''Cache: 0%''. Around the developer, empty coffee cups and crumpled papers emphasize frustration. In the background, a piggy bank labeled ''Savings'' stands empty and cracked. The walls have tech-themed posters, one showing the word ''Cache'' with an arrow pointing to the empty piggy bank. The overall style is lighthearted and colorful, emphasizing the pun with visual elements tying ''cache'' (computer memory) to ''cash'' (money) running out, capturing the joke''s play on words without any violent or inappropriate content.'),
 (1588, 'Programmers, Pun, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'Beware of programmers who carry screwdrivers.', 'Leonard Brandwein', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a surprised or cautious person looking at a programmer. The programmer should be wearing casual office attire with glasses and holding a large screwdriver confidently like it’s a tool of power. Around the programmer, show typical computer or programming elements: a laptop or desktop with code on the screen, maybe some floating symbols like brackets and semicolons to emphasize programming. The background can be a simple office or tech workspace with a desk, chair, and some tech gadgets. The scene should have a light-hearted tone, with exaggerated facial expressions to underline the joke—perhaps the cautious person has wide eyes and a hesitant posture, while the programmer looks calm but slightly mischievous. Include a small warning sign next to the programmer that says “Beware of programmers with screwdrivers” in a playful font to visually reinforce the joke. The style should be colorful and cartoonish, with clear outlines and exaggerated features for comedic effect.'),
 (1351, 'Programmers, Pun, Technology Humor', 'Why do Java developers wear glasses? Because they can''t C#', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring two Java developers standing side by side. Both look quirky and stereotypical programmer-like, e.g., wearing casual hoodies and jeans. One developer is confidently wearing thick, comical glasses and holding a large coffee mug labeled ''Java''. The other developer is squinting, rubbing their eyes, and holding a laptop with a big green ''C#'' logo on the screen. To visually enhance the pun, show the ''C#'' symbol as a musical sharp sign hovering above the laptop, glowing slightly. The background is a simple office or tech workspace with computer monitors, code snippets on screens, and a whiteboard with some coding sketches like coffee cups and code symbols. The overall style is light, colorful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the play on words between the programming languages Java and C# and the visual punchline about eyesight and glasses. Avoid any violent or controversial elements; keep it cheerful and fun.'),
 (3077, 'Programming Humor, Pun, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'If debugging is the process of removing bugs, then programming must be the process of putting them in.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a bright, cluttered programmer''s office. On the left side, a stressed but comical programmer sits at a desk typing on a computer, surrounded by coffee mugs and scattered papers featuring code snippets. Small cartoon-style literal bugs (like ladybugs, beetles, and caterpillars) are crawling around the keyboard and monitor. Above the computer screen, a thought bubble shows the programmer imagining ''debugging''—depicted as an energetic cartoon character with a butterfly net catching bugs off a computer chip. On the right side, another thought bubble shows ''programming''—with the same programmer cheerfully releasing or dropping bugs onto the keyboard as if intentionally adding them. The bugs should look cute and non-threatening, emphasizing humor rather than fear. The overall style should be colorful and lighthearted with exaggerated expressions on the programmer’s face to highlight the irony and playfulness of the joke.'),
 (3075, 'Programming Humor, Pun, Unknown, Workplace', 'If at first you don''t succeed, you must be a programmer.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a stressed programmer sitting at a cluttered desk filled with multiple computer monitors displaying lines of confusing, error-filled code. The programmer looks tired and frustrated, rubbing their eyes or pulling at their hair. Behind them, a humorous motivational poster on the wall reads, ''If at first you don''t succeed, debug, debug, debug!'' On the desk are typical programmer goodies like coffee mugs, snacks, and scattered sticky notes covered in code snippets and bug reports. In the background, there is a clock showing late night hours to emphasize long coding sessions. The overall style is light-hearted cartoon with exaggerated expressions to capture the programmer''s struggle and persistence.'),
 (2017, 'Programming Humor, Puns, Quotes, Technology Humor', 'Joann''s ''PLOP'' theory of software development states that: Data that is ''PLOPPED'' from the database to the local variable may then be manipulated as neccessary.', 'Joann Gunderson', 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a simple office or home workspace with a computer on a desk. The computer screen displays a database window with a large, colorful button labeled ''PLOP''. Next to the screen, a big, exaggerated speech bubble comes out with the text: ''Data that is PLOPPED from the database to the local variable may then be manipulated as necessary.'' In front of the computer, a programmer character with a confused but amused expression is holding a small cartoonish bubble or blob labeled ''Data'' that''s literally falling or popping out of the screen and landing into a container labeled ''local variable'' on the desk. Around the desk are playful symbols, like curly braces {}, arrows, or code snippets, to emphasize programming. The style is light-hearted, bright, with exaggerated cartoon features to make the ''PLOP'' concept visually funny and memorable without any references to violence or controversial themes.'),
 (2463, 'Programming Humor, Quotes, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Though a program be but three lines long, someday it will have to be maintained.', 'The Tao of Programming', 'A humorous cartoon scene inside a simple office setting featuring a small desk with a computer showing a tiny code editor window displaying just three short lines of code. A worried-looking programmer, cartoon-styled with exaggerated expressions and casual office attire, is sitting in front of the computer scratching their head or looking stressed. Behind the programmer, a calendar on the wall humorously marked with futuristic dates to emphasize ''someday'' or ''in the future.'' Nearby on the desk, a big, dusty, thick manual or ''maintenance guide'' comically towers over the programmer, suggesting the eventual upkeep needed regardless of program size. The setting should feel light-hearted and relatable, using bright colors and exaggerated cartoon expressions to highlight the humor in needing maintenance on even the simplest software code. Include a speech bubble or caption above the programmer that hints at the inevitability of maintenance work, reinforcing the joke''s message.'),
 (3146, 'Programming Humor, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'You never finish a program, you just stop working on it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a programmer sitting at a cluttered desk filled with computer screens showing lines of code. The programmer looks tired and distracted, leaning back in their chair with a coffee mug in one hand and a half-eaten sandwich nearby. On one of the screens, the program is incomplete, with scattered lines and bugs highlighted. Above the programmer''s head is a light bulb dimly flickering, symbolizing a fading idea. In the background, a calendar on the wall shows multiple crossed-off days, emphasizing time passing. The mood is light and funny, showing the common programmer experience of never truly finishing code, just abandoning it.'),
 (1353, 'Programming, Word Play', 'Old programmers never die; they just branch to a new address.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring an elderly programmer character with white hair, glasses, and a cardigan, sitting at a vintage computer desk. On the screen, branching diagrams or code with arrows lead to a sign that reads ''New Address''. Around the desk, computer-related items like floppy disks, a coffee mug labeled ''Code'', and scattered papers with code snippets are present. In the background, a playful ghostly version of the same programmer floats gently upward, carrying a briefcase labeled ''Programmer''s Branch''. The overall tone is lighthearted, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun on branching and memory addresses in programming.'),
 (2190, 'Psychology Humor, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Social Humor', 'Paranoids are people, too; they have their own problems. It''s easy to criticize, but if everybody hated you, you''d be paranoid too.', 'D. J. Hicks', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting on a park bench. One character looks worried and suspicious, glancing over their shoulder nervously, with wide eyes and a furrowed brow, clearly paranoid. The other character, calm and smiling, is gently patting the paranoid character''s shoulder in reassurance. Around them, subtle hints of imagined threats float as faint, transparent thought bubbles showing exaggerated shadows or mysterious shapes to represent paranoia. The background is a sunny, peaceful park with trees, flowers, and a few harmless birds or squirrels. The overall mood is lighthearted and supportive, capturing the idea that even paranoid people are just like everyone else with their own problems.'),
 (1460, 'Psychology Humor, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Word Play', 'A psychiatrist asks a lot of expensive questions your wife asks for nothing.', 'Joey Adams', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting awkwardly on a psychiatrist''s couch in a cozy office setting. The psychiatrist, dressed in a professional suit with round glasses and a clipboard, is leaning forward, asking questions with a serious expression. Behind the man, a ghostly, smiling silhouette of his wife is depicted floating casually with crossed arms, looking relaxed and happy, implying she ''asks for nothing.'' The room has typical psychiatrist office items like framed Rorschach inkblots on the wall, a bookshelf filled with psychology books, a potted plant, and a clock. The style is light, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to emphasize humor without being harsh or aggressive.'),
 (2491, 'Psychology Humor, Quotes, Wit', 'Trust your hunches. They''re usually based on facts filed away just below the conscious level.', 'Joyce Brothers', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing thoughtfully with one hand on their chin and the other pointing to their belly area, where a small stack of cartoonish filing folders labeled ''Facts'' is tucked just beneath the skin, under their chest. The person''s brain is visible inside a translucent head, looking puzzled and peeking down curiously at the filing folders near the stomach. Above the person, a whimsical thought bubble contains a glowing light bulb and a winking cartoon brain giving a thumbs-up. The background is simple, with a soft gradient to keep focus on the character and their ''subconscious file cabinet.'' The style is light, clean, and playful, emphasizing the clever idea of ''hunches'' as subconscious factual memories stored in a filing system just below awareness.'),
 (3189, 'Psychology Humor, Steven Wright, Wit', 'A clear conscience is usually the sign of a bad memory.', 'Steven Wright', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly absent-minded person with a big, goofy smile and bright eyes, standing in a cozy living room. Around them, faint, cloud-like thought bubbles float above their head, each depicting funny forgotten events or silly mistakes—like a spilled coffee cup, a broken vase, or a missed appointment. To emphasize the ''clear conscience,'' the person is gleaming with a shiny halo or sparkle around their head, suggesting innocence or purity. The background includes simple furniture like a couch, a small table with a clock, and a few picture frames. The overall style is light-hearted and whimsical, with soft colors and exaggerated facial expressions to convey humor in the idea that forgetting mishaps keeps the conscience clear.'),
 (2634, 'Psychology Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'A Freudian slip is when you say one thing, but mean your mother', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing nervously in front of a speech bubble with a jumbled sentence showing a Freudian slip. The speech bubble contains two parts: first, the man says something clearly inappropriate or awkward, but below it is a corrected version in smaller text or a thought bubble indicating he meant ''your mother'' instead. To emphasize the joke, the man''s mother stands nearby with an unimpressed or raised eyebrow expression, arms crossed. The background is a simple living room setting with a couch and family photos on the wall, one photo humorously labeled ''Mother''. The style is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight awkwardness and the comedic misunderstanding of a Freudian slip.'),
 (1447, 'Pun, Quotes, Relatable Humor, Workplace', 'A meeting is an event at which the minutes are kept and the hours are lost.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene inside a typical office meeting room with a long rectangular table surrounded by bored-looking employees. Some are staring blankly at their laptops, some checking watches, and one person dozing off with a drool bubble. On the table, a large wall clock shows time passing clearly, with the hour hand moving exaggeratedly slow and the minute hand moving rapidly. In the background, a large flip chart or whiteboard displays the phrase ''Minutes are kept'' with a clipboard and pen resting on the table emphasizing the ''minutes.'' The clock and the people looking tired humorously highlight the idea that while official minutes are recorded, the actual hours spent feel wasted. The style should be bright, colorful, and in a lighthearted cartoon format without any harsh or sarcastic tones.'),
 (1904, 'Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Word Play', 'If you gave her a penny for her thoughts, you''d have change coming.', 'Buster Bunny in Tiny Toon Adventures', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a man and a woman sitting on a park bench. The man is holding a single shiny penny in his outstretched hand, looking expectant. The woman appears puzzled or slightly annoyed, with a small thought bubble above her head containing coins or change symbols. Around them, add subtle details like a park scene with trees, a walking path, and a few birds. The style should be light and playful, emphasizing the pun of ''penny for her thoughts'' and the idea that instead of one penny, there''s ''change coming''—represented by multiple coins floating in the thought bubble. Keep the characters friendly and expressive, capturing the joke’s clever wordplay without any negative or harsh undertones.'),
 (2559, 'Pun, Quotes, Relationship Humor, Word Play', 'When I eventually met Mr. Right, I had no idea that his first name was Always.', 'Rita Rudner', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a woman standing happily, holding a bouquet of flowers, looking hopeful and dreamy. In front of her is a man with a goofy smile, wearing a name tag that reads ''Always'' in bold letters. Above them, a large, whimsical sign says ''Mr. Right'' with an arrow pointing to the man named Always. The background is bright and cheerful with soft pastel colors, and small hearts float around the couple to emphasize romance. The woman’s expression shifts from surprise to exasperation as she realizes the pun in ''Mr. Right'' actually means ''Always Right.'' Include exaggerated cartoon expressions to highlight the joke''s playful irony. No other characters or complex background details are needed, keep it simple and focused on the two characters and the named sign for clarity and humor.'),
 (2051, 'Pun, Quotes, Science Humor, Word Play', 'Light year: Same as a regular year but with fewer calories.', 'Steve Martin in Roxanne', 'A humorous cartoon showing two characters standing in space near stars and planets. One character is holding a large calendar labeled ''1 Year'' with an exaggeratedly large slice of cake and a glass of soda on a table beside them, looking happily full. The other character, wearing a space helmet, stands nearby holding a much smaller slice of cake labeled ''Light Year'' with a tiny spoon, looking puzzled or confused. The background should suggest outer space with twinkling stars and a distant planet. The style should be bright, colorful, and exaggerated, capturing a playful contrast between the regular year with lots of food and the light year with a very small portion, emphasizing the joke''s pun on ''light'' as in fewer calories rather than a distance measure.'),
 (1845, 'Pun, Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor, Word Play', 'I used to be clueless, but I''ve turned that situation around 360°.', 'Dilbert', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confused-looking person standing in the center, looking puzzled. Around them, arrows form a large circular loop on the ground indicating a 360-degree turn, with the person starting on an arrow labeled ''Clueless'' and ending back in almost the same spot, but now smiling confidently. The background is simple and light with a few question marks above their head transitioning into light bulbs as they complete the circle. The person''s body language changes from confused at the beginning of the loop to self-assured at the end. The style is colorful and exaggerated with a playful, cartoonish vibe to emphasize the pun on turning cluelessness around 360 degrees, which humorously suggests they might actually be right back where they started.'),
 (1578, 'Pun, Quotes, Sports Humor, Word Play', 'Baseball is 90 percent mental and the other half is physical.', 'Yogi Berra', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a baseball player standing on a baseball field, looking confused and scratching his head. The player is dressed in a baseball uniform and holding a bat, wearing a cap slightly askew. Above him is a scoreboard with the phrase ''Baseball is 90 percent mental and the other half is physical'' written like a motivational quote. Around the player, thought bubbles depict exaggerated images: one bubble shows a brain doing push-ups, and another shows muscles lifting weights, visually mixing mental and physical aspects humorously. The field should have a simple cartoon background with bases and a pitcher''s mound, making it clearly a baseball setting. The overall tone is light and funny, with bright colors and cartoonish expressions emphasizing the silliness of the math in the joke.'),
 (2534, 'Pun, Quotes, Sports Humor, Word Play', 'We''re going to turn this team around 360 degrees. (Said upon his drafting to the Dallas Mavericks)', 'Jason Kidd', 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a basketball court outside a stadium labeled ''Dallas Mavericks Arena.'' In the center, a cartoon basketball player wearing a Dallas Mavericks jersey looks confused and slightly dizzy with swirly eyes. Next to him, a coach wearing a suit enthusiastically points to a large spinning arrow painted on the court that makes a full circle (360 degrees) around the player. Around the court, there are a few teammates watching with puzzled or amused expressions. The spinning arrow on the court should be exaggerated and colorful, emphasizing the idea of the full 360-degree turn. The style is lighthearted and fun, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor in the phrase ''turn this team around 360 degrees,'' illustrating the literal confusion of turning fully around rather than improving the team.'),
 (1627, 'Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'Denial ain''t just a river in Egypt.', 'Mark Twain (1835-1910)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cheerful river labeled ''Nile River'' flowing through a sunny Egyptian desert landscape with pyramids in the background. On the riverbank stands a confused cartoon character wearing explorer clothes, scratching their head. Above the river, a large, playful label floats reading ''Denial''. Nearby, a large signpost with two arrows points in different directions: one says ''Denial (the emotion)'', showing a sad face emoji, and the other says ''The River Nile'', pointing to the river. The overall style is colorful and lighthearted, emphasizing the pun by visually blending the emotional concept of denial with the famous geographical river, in a simple and friendly manner.'),
 (1750, 'Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'He who throws dirt loses ground.', 'God''s Little Instruction Book', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on a small patch of ground. The person is holding a small bucket of dirt and is tossing handfuls of dirt behind them. The ground beneath the person is visibly shrinking or eroding away, with little cracks or chunks of soil falling off the edge beneath their feet. The expression on the person''s face is a mix of surprise and frustration as they realize the ground they''re standing on is disappearing. The background is simple with a clear blue sky and a few tufts of grass around the patch of dirt. The overall style is lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the literal pun of ''throwing dirt'' causing the person to lose ground.'),
 (2006, 'Pun, Quotes, Word Play', 'It''s hard to make a comeback if you haven''t been anywhere.', 'El (Doug) o Serie', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person standing still in the middle of a simple setting with no travel signs, such as a closed airplane, parked car with flat tires, and a suitcase that is unopened and taped shut. The person looks puzzled and slightly frustrated, scratching their head as if wanting to make a comeback or return but clearly nowhere to come back from. Around them are speech bubbles or humorous signs: one says ''No exits,'' another ''No departures,'' and a third ''Return ticket expired.'' The background is minimal and simple to keep focus on the subject, with light, playful colors and exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the irony of the joke. Overall, it should have a lighthearted, cartoonish style that captures the play on words about ''comeback'' and ''being anywhere.'''),
 (2673, 'Pun, Relatable Humor, Unknown', 'Before you criticize someone, you should walk a mile in his or her shoes.  That way, when you criticize them, you''re a mile away... and you have their shoes.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people standing apart. One person is holding an exaggeratedly large pair of shoes, looking mischievous. The other person is far away, walking awkwardly in very oversized shoes that clearly belong to the first person, their feet comically slipping in the huge shoes. The background is a simple outdoor setting with a clear path or road to emphasize the "mile" walked. Both characters have exaggerated facial expressions: the walker looks frustrated but determined, while the shoe-holder grins slyly. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with emphasis on the oversized shoes and the distance between the two people to capture the punchline visually without any hint of violence or negativity.'),
 (3055, 'Pun, Relatable Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I won''t rise to the occasion, but I''ll slide over to it.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a person faced with a literal ''occasion'' shaped like a tall, fancy podium or stage with a spotlight beaming down on it. The person looks casual and relaxed, wearing everyday clothes, and instead of climbing up or standing on the podium, they are smoothly sliding sideways on the floor toward the base of the podium. Their expression shows a mix of cheeky determination and playful laziness, as if saying ''I won''t rise up, but I''ll still get close.'' Include some simple background elements like a curtain or event setting to convey a formal occasion. The overall style is light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated features and clean lines to emphasize the joke''s wordplay about ''rising to the occasion'' versus ''sliding over to it.'' No aggressive or inappropriate elements should be included.'),
 (2829, 'Pun, Relationship Humor, Unknown', 'Every day I tell my wife I''m going out jogging and then I don''t - it''s a running joke', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man in running gear (shorts, a T-shirt, running shoes) standing at the front door with one foot out, clearly about to jog. He has a nervous or sheepish smile. Inside, his wife is in the background looking amused or rolling her eyes, arms crossed. To emphasize the pun, there is a large, playful speech bubble overhead that says ''It''s a running joke!'' Around them, small visual hints like a calendar on the wall with multiple days circled and a jogging shoe left untouched on a shoe rack near the door. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated to enhance the joke''s play on words, with no violence or negative tone.'),
 (2940, 'Pun, Religious Humor, Unknown', 'How do you make holy water? You boil the hell out of it.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful kitchen with a large pot of boiling water on a stove. Over the pot, steam rises in the shape of little angelic halos and tiny crosses, symbolizing ''holy water.'' Next to the pot is a mischievous devil figure, looking frustrated and being figuratively ''boiled out'' of the pot with exaggerated cartoon steam and red heat waves. The kitchen background includes typical items like a teapot, spice jars, and a window with sunlight. The style is lighthearted and colorful with smiling characters and humorous visual cues emphasizing the pun.'),
 (3178, 'Pun, Robots, Science Fiction Humor, Star Wars', 'What happens to droids after they go defunct? They rust in peace.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a small group of droids standing in a peaceful cemetery designed for robots. The setting is outdoors with soft, rolling green hills and a clear blue sky. Each droid is cartoonish with simple geometric shapes like cylinders and spheres, some with antennae and glowing eyes. Several tombstones resemble metallic plates with humorous robot-related engravings (e.g., circuit patterns or a battery icon). One droid is slightly rusted, sitting or leaning against its tombstone with a calm, peaceful expression. A few other droids stand respectfully nearby, with one holding a small bouquet of oil cans or mechanical parts. A sign at the entrance reads "Rust In Peace Cemetery." The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to emphasize the pun humor without any dark or somber mood.'),
 (3175, 'Pun, Robots, Science Humor, Star Wars', 'What do droids dance to? Algorithms', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a futuristic dance floor or robot disco. In the center, a group of friendly-looking droids or robots are joyfully dancing with exaggerated dance moves like spinning, moonwalking, or breakdancing. The robots have simple, cute designs with antennas, screen faces showing smiles or musical notes, and mechanical limbs. Above them, a large colorful sign reads ''Robot Dance Party'' or ''Droid Disco.'' In the background, a DJ booth features a DJ robot manipulating a turntable or a music console, with digital waveforms and musical notes floating around. The dance floor lights are neon and vibrant, evoking a fun, lively robot party atmosphere. Emphasize playful, lighthearted energy with cartoonish proportions and bright colors to make the setting amusing and engaging without any references to violence or politics.'),
 (3110, 'Pun, Science Fiction Humor, Space Humor, Unknown', 'Why haven''t aliens visited our solar system yet? They looked at the reviews and we only had 1 star.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of three friendly-looking cartoon aliens standing outside a large glowing map or digital screen displaying the solar system. The aliens are holding clipboards and looking puzzled or disappointed. On the map, the Sun and planets are brightly illustrated, and next to the solar system, there is a giant review box with one big, shiny gold star and a text bubble or sign that says ''1 Star''. The background is a colorful outer space scene with stars and distant galaxies. The aliens should look whimsical and non-threatening, wearing simple futuristic outfits or helmets. This should be drawn in a light-hearted, playful cartoon style with exaggerated expressions to convey the joke''s punchline visually—aliens judging the solar system like a product with poor ratings.'),
 (3170, 'Pun, Science Fiction Humor, Star Wars, Star Wars Humor', 'Did you know Anakin''s first droid was invisible ?  C-through-PO', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a classic Star Wars setting on a desert planet with sand dunes and a twin sun in the sky. In the foreground, a young Anakin Skywalker stands with a curious and amused expression, looking at an invisible figure represented by an outline or sparkling air shape to indicate invisibility. Next to Anakin is a speech bubble with the joke text: ''Did you know Anakin''s first droid was invisible? C-through-PO.'' Nearby, depict a subtle shimmer shaped like a protocol droid (similar to C-3PO) but transparent or only outlined to emphasize the ‘invisible droid’ pun. The style should be light-hearted and cartoonish, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to keep the tone playful and fun.'),
 (3161, 'Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'I make bad science puns periodically', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a scientist in a white lab coat standing in front of a large blackboard filled with scientific formulas and periodic table elements. The scientist is smiling and holding up a beaker that has bubbles coming out of it, symbolizing a pun ''in action.'' Nearby, a periodic table poster on the wall has some of the element squares replaced with actual pun words or funny faces. The scientist has a light bulb above their head, representing a pun idea. Around the scene, small comic-style speech bubbles contain symbols like atoms, molecules, and puns made out of chemical element abbreviations, with a playful, lighthearted vibe. The setting is a bright, colorful laboratory filled with classic lab equipment like test tubes, microscopes, and flasks to emphasize the science theme without any complex or intimidating imagery.'),
 (3164, 'Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'Wanna hear a potassium joke? K', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a character with a playful expression holding up a giant, shiny potassium chemical element symbol tile with the letter ''K'' on it, like a game tile or a flashcard. The character should be mid-speech or showing a cheeky smile as if telling a joke. Around them on the floor or table are other elemental symbol tiles scattered playfully, hinting at chemistry. The background is simple and bright to keep focus on the character and the ''K'' tile. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated with bold lines and vibrant colors to enhance the humor and nerdy vibe of the joke.'),
 (3165, 'Pun, Science, Science Humor', 'Water is heavier than butane fluid because butane is a lighter fluid.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two cartoon-style bottles standing side by side on a kitchen counter. One bottle is labeled ''Water'' and looks plump and heavy, with sweat drops and a tired expression. The other bottle is labeled ''Butane Fluid'' and is slim and light, wearing sunglasses and a confident, relaxed smile. Above them is a simple scientific scale gently tipping to the water side, emphasizing that water is heavier. The background features a simple kitchen with a stove and a window, to keep it cozy and relatable. The overall style is bright, colorful, and exaggerated for comedic effect, with speech bubbles or signs indicating ''Water is heavier!'' and ''Butane is lighter fluid!'' to bring the pun across clearly and humorously.'),
 (3113, 'Pun, Sports Humor, Unknown', 'Why should you never date a tennis player? Love means nothing to them', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two people on a tennis court. On one side, a confident tennis player wearing tennis gear—headband, wristbands, tennis outfit—holds a racket and smirks. On the other side, a hopeful person stands holding a heart symbol above their head like a gift, looking slightly confused or disappointed. The tennis player''s speech bubble says, "Love means nothing to me!" The tennis court clearly features markings and a net, with a scoreboard in the background showing the tennis score with the word ''Love'' crossed out or replaced with a zero. Bright, colorful, and exaggerated cartoon style, emphasizing the pun on the word "love" as both a tennis score and romantic affection.'),
 (3054, 'Pun, Sports Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'I wondered why the football was getting bigger and bigger - and then it hit me.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person standing on the left side of the image with a confused or curious expression, looking toward a football that appears to be growing larger and larger as it rolls toward them from the right side. The football is exaggeratedly big, comically enormous in comparison to the person. The background is a simple grassy field to suggest a football setting. The motion of the football is emphasized with action lines indicating it''s rolling quickly toward the person. In the moment captured, the football is just about to make contact with the person, who has just realized the situation, shown by a light bulb or exclamation mark above their head. The style should be bright and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions to highlight the humor and surprise, in a playful cartoon style appropriate for all ages.'),
 (3174, 'Pun, Star Wars, Visual Humor', 'What did Luke think when the Emperor showed him the power of the dark side? He was shocked.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene depicting Luke Skywalker standing wide-eyed and with an exaggerated surprised expression in front of Emperor Palpatine, who is dramatically showing off his dark side powers with lightning crackling from his fingers. Luke''s face should clearly show shock and amazement. The background should be a simple, stylized Death Star interior with dark and ominous tones but drawn in a lighthearted, cartoony style. Include some lightning bolts from the Emperor’s hands, and Luke holding his lightsaber loosely at his side. The characters should be drawn with comically exaggerated features to emphasize the humor and surprise.'),
 (3028, 'Pun, Technology Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'I remember the first time I saw a universal remote controller. I thought to myself ''well, this changes everything...''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person in a cozy living room, holding a universal remote controller with a big, exaggerated amazed expression on their face. The person is mid-thought, with a large thought bubble above their head containing a playful illustration of a globe being literally flipped or turned by the remote''s buttons, symbolizing ''changing everything.'' Around the room, include typical living room elements like a TV, a couch, a coffee table with snacks, and maybe a pet looking curiously at the remote. The style should be lighthearted and colorful with caricature-style features to emphasize the joke''s fun and clever mental pun about the remote ''changing everything.'' No people or objects looking distressed; keep it cheerful and simple.'),
 (3247, 'Pun, Technology Humor, What do you call..., Word Play', 'What do you call a busy waiter? A server. \nWhat do you call an idle server? A waiter.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene with two panels side by side. In the first panel, show a busy restaurant waiter wearing a traditional white shirt and black vest, carrying a tray stacked with dishes, bustling eagerly between tables filled with happy diners. Above him, include the caption: ''What do you call a busy waiter? A server.'' In the second panel, depict a large, bulky computer server (like a standard server tower with blinking lights and wires) sitting idly on a table or platform with a relaxed, slightly bored expression (maybe with eyes and a mouth to personify it). Above this server, place the caption: ''What do you call an idle server? A waiter.'' Use bright, playful colors and exaggerated cartoon facial expressions to enhance the humor without any aggressive or offensive content. Backgrounds can be simple but clearly distinguish restaurant and tech environments respectively.'),
 (3120, 'Pun, Unknown, Visual Humor, Workplace', 'Work would be okay but it takes such a big chunk out of your day.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a large clock with a literal, oversized chunk missing from its face, as if bitten or cut out. Nearby, a tired-looking office worker sits slumped in a swivel chair at a desk cluttered with papers, a coffee mug, and a computer. The worker appears weary and slightly overwhelmed, glancing at the clock. The background is a simple office setting with cubicle walls and a calendar hanging. The missing chunk of the clock is shown as a huge puzzle-piece sized bite, emphasizing the phrase ''takes such a big chunk out of your day.'' The style is colorful and playful with exaggerated expressions to highlight the pun in the joke, emphasizing the cartoonish scale of the clock and the chunk taken out of it, without any violence or negativity.'),
 (2227, 'Puns, Quotes, Relationship Humor', 'Save a boyfriend for a rainy day -- and another, in case it doesn''t rain.', 'Mae West', 'A humorous cartoon showing a smiling young woman indoors looking out a window at a gray, rainy day. Outside, there''s rain pouring down with a visible puddle on the ground. Two cartoonish male characters stand under umbrellas nearby. One is standing directly under the rain with an umbrella labeled ''Boyfriend 1,'' looking slightly worried but hopeful. The other male figure, labeled ''Boyfriend 2,'' waits nearby holding a sunny umbrella, looking confident and ready in case ''Boyfriend 1'' doesn’t work out. The woman is holding a cup of tea, looking amused and relaxed, as if pleased to have both options available. The background is bright but clearly rainy outside, with cartoon raindrops and a cheerful home interior. The overall style is lighthearted, colorful, and playful, emphasizing a funny take on relationship preparedness without any aggression or offense.'),
 (2234, 'Puns, Quotes, Sports Humor, Workplace', 'Show me a man who is a good loser and I''ll show you a man who is playing golf with his boss.', 'Nebraska Smoke-Eater', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two men playing golf on a sunny, green golf course. One man, wearing a golf cap, polo shirt, and slacks, looks calm and mildly smiling as he holds a golf club, standing next to a golf ball near the hole. The other man, dressed similarly but with a slightly more stern expression, is identified as the boss by a subtle name tag or a small briefcase beside him on the grass. The calm man appears relaxed, showing good sportsmanship despite possibly losing. In the background, a small flag marks the hole, and a golf cart with golf bags is nearby. The overall tone is light-hearted and playful, capturing the idea that being a ''good loser'' in this context means trying to stay in your boss''s good graces during a round of golf. The style should be cartoonish with exaggerated expressions but not caricatured, with bright, cheerful colors and no aggressive or negative body language.'),
 (1354, 'Puns, Relatable, Technology Humor', 'When the inventor of USB dies, they''re going to lower him into the grave, raise him up, turn him over, then put him back in.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a graveyard with a tombstone labeled ''Inventor of USB.'' A group of funny-looking cartoon gravediggers (wearing simple hats and gloves) are lowering a coffin into the grave with ropes and pulleys. Next to the grave, the same gravediggers are shown lifting the coffin back up slightly, turning it 180 degrees in the air (with a comical exaggerated turning motion), and then carefully placing it back down. One gravedigger is scratching his head in confusion, while another holds a USB drive and points at the coffin as if explaining something. The sky is bright and clear with a few fluffy clouds, and there are some flowers and small bushes around the grave. The overall style is colorful, playful, and cartoonish, emphasizing the absurdity of the repeated raising, turning, and re-lowering of the coffin, mimicking the well-known fussiness of USB plugs needing to be turned before plugging in properly.'),
 (3160, 'Puns, Science, Science Humor', 'How does a scientist freshen his breath? With experi-mints', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon of a scientist in a white lab coat and safety goggles standing in a colorful chemistry lab. The scientist is holding a small mint candy shaped like a molecule or test tube with a big smile, as if proudly presenting it. On the lab table nearby are typical lab items like beakers, a Bunsen burner, test tubes filled with bubbling colorful liquids, and a sign that says ''Fresh Breath Science Lab.'' Around the scientist’s mouth, little fresh breath ''sparkle'' icons float to emphasize the minty freshness. The overall style is playful and cheerful, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors to enhance the joke''s pun on ''experiment'' and ''mints.'''),
 (1355, 'Puns, Science, Technology Humor', 'There are two major products to come out of Berkeley: LSD and UNIX. We don''t believe this to be a coincidence.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene set on a college campus labeled ''Berkeley.'' On one side, a whimsical scientist wearing round glasses and a lab coat is holding a large, swirling, psychedelic-looking molecule labeled ''LSD'' with a playful smile. On the other side, a quirky programmer with messy hair and thick glasses sits at an old-school computer terminal showing a UNIX command prompt on the screen. Between them, a large signpost points in two directions: one arrow toward a trippy, colorful, swirling background representing the psychedelic LSD culture, and the other toward a neatly organized server rack or computer stack symbolizing UNIX technology. In the background, iconic campus buildings with Berkeley banners should be visible. The style is bright and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions and funny details like floating binary numbers and colorful blobs around the scientist, and green command-line prompts glowing near the programmer. No violence or inappropriate content.'),
 (1356, 'Puns, Shopping Jokes, Word Play', 'VENI, VIDI, VISA (We came, we saw, we went shopping)', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon showing three characters in ancient Roman-style clothing but with a modern twist. They are standing in front of a shopping mall entrance with big glass doors labeled ''VISA Shopping Center.'' One character holds shopping bags overflowing with various colorful items, another is looking excitedly at a store window, and the third is checking a credit card (with VISA logo). Behind them is a large billboard on the mall showing the phrase ''VENI, VIDI, VISA'' in bold letters, with a subtitle underneath: ''We came, we saw, we went shopping.'' The background has a mix of ancient Roman columns and modern retail store signs. The style is bright, exaggerated, and playful, emphasizing the pun on the famous Latin phrase and the VISA credit card brand.'),
 (3029, 'Puns, Technology Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I Renamed my iPod The Titanic, so when I plug it in, it says, ''The Titanic is syncing.''', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a person holding an iPod with a big smile on their face. The iPod screen clearly displays the text: ''The Titanic is syncing.'' The iPod should look like a classic model with a click wheel, and a small cable is plugged into it, trailing off the edge of the image. In the background or nearby, a small, comical depiction of the Titanic ship, perhaps small and stylized as a toy or icon, can be floating next to or on the iPod screen for visual pun effect. The setting is simple, with the focus on the iPod and the syncing message, emphasizing the wordplay between ''syncing'' and the imagined sinking of the Titanic. The overall style is bright, colorful, and cartoonish, conveying lighthearted, clever humor without any dark or serious tones.'),
 (1357, 'Puns, Word Play', 'The cost of feathers has risen.... now even down is up!', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring a cozy bedroom with a large, fluffy down comforter on a bed. The comforter looks unusually dense and expensive, with small price tags hanging from the feathers and the word ''Feathers'' prominently displayed on a sign next to it. To emphasize the joke, show an arrow pointing upward above the comforter with the words ''Down is UP!'' in big, playful letters. Include a puzzled character (could be a person with an exaggerated confused expression, scratching their head) standing beside the bed, looking at the comforter and a receipt or price tag showing a high price. The room should feel warm and inviting, with light-hearted colors and cartoon-style exaggeration, like puffed-up pillows and a small bird looking shocked or surprised nearby. Avoid any aggressive or negative imagery, focusing on the playful absurdity of ''down'' (feathers) being ''up'' (expensive).'),
 (1358, 'Puns, Word Play', 'Time flies like an arrow, fruit flies like a banana.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene split into two parts. On the left side, depict a classic arrow flying swiftly through the air with motion lines, symbolizing the phrase ''Time flies like an arrow.'' The background shows a simple blue sky with a few clouds to emphasize speed and direction. On the right side, illustrate several small, cartoonish fruit flies with big eyes and wings happily gathering around and landing on a bright yellow banana that is lying on a wooden table. The fruit flies should look cheerful and animated, emphasizing the pun that these insects ''like a banana.'' The overall style should be light-hearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions on the flies and a clear visual contrast between the arrow in flight and the fruit flies interacting with the banana. Avoid any characters; focus on the arrow, the banana, and the flies to visually play on the dual meaning of the phrase.'),
 (1359, 'Puns, Word Play', 'What do you call a line of men waiting for a hair cut? A barber queue', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a barber shop exterior with a long line of men waiting patiently for their turn. The men should look similar but distinct in hairstyle and clothing to add variety, some with funny exaggerated hairdos like wild curly hair, bald spots, or comb-overs. The line stretches from the barber shop door, with a red and white barber pole spinning nearby. A small sign on the door reads "Barber Shop." One man at the front is sitting in the barber''s chair getting a haircut with scissors in the barber’s hand, smiling cheerfully. The overall mood is lighthearted and silly, emphasizing the play on words between "barber queue" and "barbecue." Use bright colors and simple, cartoonish lines to keep the image playful and inviting.'),
 (2336, 'Quotes', 'The man who does not read good books has no advantage over the man who cannot read them.', 'Mark Twain (1835-1910)', 'Cartoon scene, bright colors, exaggerated expressions. A city park bench centered in frame. Seated on the left is a tidy, bespectacled man in a suit who looks “bookish” but bored — he’s staring at his smartphone, thumbs busy, while a large, ornate hardcover labeled "GOOD BOOKS" sits closed and dusty on his lap (tiny dust lines). Seated on the right is a casual, friendly-looking man in a plaid shirt holding an identical book upside-down and squinting in confusion; a little spiral of letters (A B C) floats away from the page like mischievous fireflies. Above each man’s head is a cartoon thought bubble with a big question mark (same shape and size) to show equal confusion. Between them on the bench is a small stack of classic-looking books with a sign reading "CLASSICS" and a tiny sticker: "Free to read!" Add a cheerful park background (trees, pigeons), and a small dog at their feet wearing reading glasses and looking expectantly at the books (humorous touch). Draw in a light, playful cartoon style with bold outlines and expressive faces.'),
 (1798, 'Quotes, Relatable Humor', 'I don''t feel good.', 'The last words of Luther Burbank (1849-1926)', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a simple cartoon character standing in the middle of a plain room or outdoor setting, looking visibly unwell. The character should have exaggerated, tired eyes and a slumped posture, possibly holding their stomach or forehead to emphasize feeling sick. Around the character, include visual cues like wavy lines or little floating symbols (such as little clouds or tiny zigzags) above their head to indicate dizziness or discomfort. The background should be simple and uncluttered to keep focus on the character’s expression and body language. The overall style should be light, playful, and exaggerated to match a funny, relatable mood rather than anything serious or dark.'),
 (1966, 'Quotes, Relatable Humor, Science Humor, Word Play', 'It has been a bitter mortification for me to digest the conclusion that the ''race is for the strong'' and that I shall probably do little more but be content to admire the strides others made in science.', 'Charles Darwin', 'Draw a humorous cartoon featuring a person sitting at a dining table with a large, complicated science book open in front of them. The person looks defeated but thoughtful, holding a fork and knife awkwardly in one hand, as if trying to "digest" the knowledge. Around the table are several other characters confidently walking or running forward, representing scientists or researchers, each with exaggerated strides and lab coats, some holding test tubes or scientific instruments. The background suggests a race track labeled ''Science Race,'' with the other characters far ahead. The main character is at the starting line, looking wistfully at the others. Add a humorous element such as a thought bubble above the main person showing a digestive system, linking to the metaphor of ''digesting'' the conclusion. The overall style should be light, cartoonish, and playful, emphasizing the pun and the feeling of being left behind in the ''race for the strong'' in science without anything violent, sexual, or political.'),
 (1790, 'Quotes, Relatable Humor, Technology Humor', 'I do not fear computers.. I fear the lack of them.', 'Isaac Asimov', 'A humorous cartoon scene of a confused person standing in a vintage office setting filled with piles of messy paperwork, old-fashioned typewriters, and stacks of folders labeled ''To Do.'' The person looks anxious and overwhelmed, scratching their head and staring at a clock on the wall that is ticking slowly. In the background, there''s a large window showing a peaceful modern cityscape with people happily using laptops, tablets, and smartphones under sunny skies. The contrast emphasizes the person''s fear of the absence of computers. The style is light-hearted and exaggerated, with expressive eyes and comically exaggerated mouth shapes to convey worry but in a funny, non-threatening way.'),
 (1726, 'Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wisdom', 'Good instincts usually tell you what to do long before your head has figured it out.', 'Michael Burke', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a human head and a cartoonish, anthropomorphized stomach or gut side by side. The head looks puzzled and is scratching its head, with visible question marks floating above it. The gut, wearing a detective hat or a little superhero cape, is pointing forward confidently as if saying, ''Follow me!'' Around them, a simple office or decision-making setting such as a crossroads sign or a small desk with papers scattered. The gut should look wise and confident while the head looks unsure and slow to catch up. Soft, bright colors and exaggerated facial expressions emphasize the playful and lighthearted mood of the scene.'),
 (1509, 'Quotes, Relatable Humor, Wishful Thinking, Workplace', 'All I want is less to do, more time to do it, and more pay for getting it done.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a relaxed office worker sitting back in a swivel chair with legs kicked up on a desk. The desk is cluttered with unfinished paperwork and a clock on the wall shows plenty of time left in the workday. The worker has a satisfied, slightly smug expression, gazing dreamily at a thought bubble above their head that contains floating icons: a tiny to-do list with very few items, a large clock with plenty of time indicated, and a big dollar sign symbolizing high pay. Behind them, a calendar on the wall is marked with empty days suggesting no deadlines. The overall tone is light and funny, emphasizing the wish for less work, more time, and better pay simultaneously. The style should be bright, colorful, and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions to highlight the absurdity of these unrealistic desires in a workplace setting.'),
 (2014, 'Quotes, Relatable Humor, Word Play', 'It''s the good girls who keep diaries; the bad girls never have the time.', 'Tallulah Bankhead', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring two young women side by side. On the left, a ''good girl'' sits peacefully at a small desk in a bright, tidy room with soft colors, writing neatly in a diary labeled ''My Diary'' with a pen. She wears modest, simple clothing and has a gentle, calm expression. On the right, a ''bad girl'' is depicted in a lively, chaotic environment with energetic activity around her: she is multitasking, holding a phone in one hand, a skateboard at her feet, and a mischievous grin on her face. Her room is messier with posters, a buzzing alarm clock showing ''Too Busy!'', and a few open social media apps on a nearby tablet, symbolizing she doesn''t have time to write. The background highlights the contrast between calmness and busyness, emphasizing the joke’s punchline. The overall tone is light-hearted, playful, and cartoonish without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (2013, 'Quotes, Relatable, Self-Improvement Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'It''s so simple to be wise. Just think of some-thing stupid to say and then don''t say it.', 'Sam Levenson', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person sitting at a desk or table, looking thoughtful and a bit mischievous. The person has a lightbulb above their head to indicate an idea forming. Next to them, a little speech bubble is partially formed, but crossed out or fading away, suggesting the person is holding back from speaking. The background should be simple with soft colors to keep focus on the character. Add a small stack of books or a notepad on the desk to imply thinking or wisdom. The overall style is cartoonish and lighthearted, with exaggerated facial expressions of contemplation mixed with a hint of humor and restraint.'),
 (1867, 'Quotes, Relationship Humor, Sports Humor', 'If a woman has to choose between catching a fly ball and saving an infant''s life, she will choose to save the infant''s life without even considering if there are men on base.', 'Dave Barry', 'A colorful humorous cartoon scene at a baseball field. In the foreground, a smiling woman baseball player wearing a typical team uniform is sprinting toward a high, flying baseball, ready to catch it with her glove. Nearby, just off the field on the grass, a tiny infant is gently crawling or sitting, clearly in need of help. The woman’s eyes are focused not on the flying ball but on the infant, showing her prioritizing saving the baby. In the background, a scoreboard shows multiple men standing on different bases, casually watching the scene, surprised or confused. The style is lighthearted and playful, with exaggerated expressions on all characters’ faces to emphasize the humorous contrast between the baseball game and the life-saving choice. The scene should have bright colors and cartoonish proportions to keep the tone fun and non-serious, with no violence, just a clear visual of the joke’s punchline about priorities.'),
 (2226, 'Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'Sainthood emerges when you can listen to someone''s tale of woe and not respond with a description of your own.', 'Andrew V. Mason, M.D.', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing two characters sitting on a park bench. One character, looking very upset and animated, is telling a long, exaggerated story with expressive hand gestures and teary eyes. The second character listens patiently, with calm, serene facial expression, hands folded quietly in their lap, showing no urge to interrupt or respond with their own story. Around them is a peaceful park setting with trees, a walking path, and a few birds casually flying by. The overall style is lighthearted and exaggerated, with bright colors and soft outlines to emphasize the calmness of the listener contrasted with the dramatic narrator. Include a small glowing halo or subtle angel wings above the listener’s head to humorously indicate the idea of sainthood for their patience and restraint.'),
 (1744, 'Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wit', 'He has all the virtues I dislike and none of the vices I admire.', 'Sir Winston Churchill (1874-1965)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene featuring two characters in a casual conversation. One character looks visibly annoyed or unimpressed, crossing their arms with a slight frown. The other character stands confidently but with an awkward, overly perfect appearance—wearing a neat outfit, straight posture, and a big smile that seems slightly forced. Surround them with small symbolic objects illustrating virtues and vices: on one side near the annoyed character, include small icons or thought bubbles showing common vices like a cigarette, a bottle of alcohol, and a deck of cards. On the other side near the overly virtuous character, add icons or bubbles depicting virtues such as a halo, a book labeled "morals," and a shining star. The setting can be a simple park bench or a coffee shop table to keep it relatable. The style should be light-hearted and cartoonish with exaggerated facial expressions and clean lines to emphasize the ironic and humorous contrast the joke implies.'),
 (2402, 'Quotes, Relationship Humor, Wit', 'The two secrets to a good relationship: 1) You have to let the other person be themselves, and 2) You have to pretend they''re someone else.', 'Rita Rudner', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a couple sitting side-by-side on a cozy couch in a living room. The woman is looking at the man with a gentle smile, while the man is looking at her with a playful, slightly exaggerated expression of pretending or daydreaming. Above each of them are two thought bubbles: the woman''s thought bubble shows herself looking natural and happy, representing ''being themselves''; the man''s thought bubble shows the same woman but as a completely different, funny character—maybe wearing a superhero cape or a clown nose—symbolizing ''pretending they’re someone else.'' The room is warmly lit with simple furniture, a small coffee table with a plant, and a framed picture of hearts on the wall. The overall style is colorful and cartoonish, emphasizing the lighthearted and witty nature of the joke without any harshness or negativity.'),
 (1776, 'Quotes, Relationship Humor, Word Play', 'I am a marvelous housekeeper. Every time I leave a man I keep his house.', 'Zsa Zsa Gabor', 'A humorous cartoon showing a confident woman standing proudly outside a tidy, well-kept house. She is smiling with one hand on her hip and holding a small suitcase in the other, indicating she is leaving. Inside a window of the house, a surprised, slightly bewildered man is looking out as she walks away. The scene is bright and colorful, with a clean lawn, flowers, and the house looking neat and organized. The atmosphere is light and playful, clearly emphasizing the joke about ''keeping the house'' after leaving a man. No aggressive or negative emotions, just a funny, cheeky vibe.'),
 (1728, 'Quotes, Romance Humor, Science Humor, Word Play', 'Gravitation is not responsible for people falling in love.', 'Albert Einstein (1879-1955)', 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene showing two people (a man and a woman) awkwardly trying to resist the force pulling them toward each other, symbolizing ''falling in love.'' They are both standing on opposite sides of a large, exaggerated heart floating in the center, with a comically strong gravitational pull represented by cartoonish swirling lines or arrows drawing the two closer. The background is simple and cheerful, perhaps with a sunny park or cityscape. Include amusing details like one person holding a book titled ''Gravity'' while the other looks surprised, and a small, playful signpost nearby reading ''Not Gravity Zone.'' The style should be light and whimsical, emphasizing the absurdity that gravity isn’t responsible for love, with exaggerated facial expressions full of confusion and slight resistance to the pull toward each other.'),
 (2382, 'Quotes, Satire, Science Humor, Social Humor', 'The Social Sciences are good at accounting for disasters once they have taken place.', 'Claude T. Bissell', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of social scientists in an office filled with charts, graphs, books, and papers scattered everywhere. The scientists look calm and thoughtful, sitting at desks with calculators and laptops, analyzing a huge map on the wall labeled ''Recent Disasters.'' In the background, through a window, various ongoing minor disasters are clearly happening outside (e.g., a small flood, a minor fire, a toppled tree), but the scientists are ignoring them, focusing only on their notes and discussions. One scientist points seriously at the map, while another is jotting points on a whiteboard titled ''Post-Disaster Analysis.'' The overall look is light-hearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions of calm focus contrasted humorously with the chaos outside. No one appears panicked; the humor is in the scientists'' delay in reacting and their detailed study after the fact.'),
 (1461, 'Quotes, Satire, Social Commentary, Wit', 'A satirist is a man who discovers unpleasant things about himself and then says them about other people.', 'Peter McArthur', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a man sitting comfortably in an armchair, holding a large magnifying glass up to his own reflection in a nearby mirror. His face shows a mock-serious expression as if he’s discovering something unpleasant about himself. Behind him is a wall with framed pictures of various people, each looking surprised or shocked—as if hearing these negative traits being told about them. The man’s clothing should be slightly exaggerated, like a classic satirist with round glasses and a tweed jacket, to emphasize the intellectual stereotype. The background is a cozy room with bookshelves filled with books titled ''Truths'' and ''Satire.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and whimsical, emphasizing the irony of self-reflection versus telling others’ faults. Include playful speech bubbles above the man that contain simple phrases like ‘I’m flawed...’ and ‘...but so are you!’ to illustrate the joke''s concept visually.'),
 (2427, 'Quotes, Satire, Social Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'There is no cause so right that one cannot find a fool following it.', 'Niven''s Law #16', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a colorful protest or rally with a large crowd of diverse characters holding signs and banners supporting a cause. Among them, an obviously silly-looking character stands out—wearing mismatched clothes, a dunce cap, and looking confused or dazed while eagerly following the group. The silly character is slightly exaggerated with big googly eyes, a wide grin, and perhaps tripping over or holding a completely unrelated or silly object like a rubber chicken or a whoopee cushion, highlighting their folly. The background includes happy protestors marching forward with determined expressions, reinforcing the idea of a righteous cause. The tone is lighthearted and cartoonish with bright colors and exaggerated expressions, ensuring a funny but respectful depiction of the joke’s meaning about fools following even good causes.'),
 (1489, 'Quotes, School, Sports Humor, Word Play', 'Academy: A modern school where football is taught.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a building with a sign that says ''Academy'' above the door. In front of the building is a group of school-age children dressed in football gear (helmets, jerseys, cleats) practicing football plays and throwing a football. The building looks like a traditional school with brick walls and windows, but instead of classrooms, inside are visible football goalposts and sports equipment. A teacher wearing glasses and holding a clipboard is enthusiastically coaching the kids, as if teaching a class. The sky is clear and the scene is bright and cheerful, emphasizing the playful mix-up of schooling and sports. The style is lighthearted and cartoonish, with exaggerated expressions of determination on the children''s faces and a comical seriousness from the coach.'),
 (2319, 'Quotes, Self-Reflection Humor, Wisdom Humor', 'The greatest of all faults is to be conscious of none.', 'Thomas Carlyle', 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person confidently standing with a big, proud smile on their face and their eyes closed. Their posture is upright, hands on hips, radiating an exaggerated sense of self-satisfaction. Surrounding them are thought bubbles showing little cartoon faults or quirks—like a missing sock, a spilled coffee cup, or crooked picture frames—but the person is completely ignoring these. In the background, a small mischievous cartoon character labeled ''Conscience'' (a tiny figure with glasses and a little pointer stick) is trying to get their attention, waving and looking frustrated. The setting is a simple, colorful living room with a couch, a houseplant, and a picture on the wall slightly off-center to emphasize unnoticed faults. The overall style is light, playful, and exaggerated to emphasize the joke’s message about not being aware of one''s own mistakes.'),
 (1591, 'Quotes, Social Commentary, Wit, Word Play', 'Bigot: One who is obstinately and zealously attached to an opinion that you do not entertain.', 'Ambrose Bierce (1842-1914)', 'A humorous cartoon scene in a public park setting with two characters. One character labeled ''Bigot'' is depicted as an overly stubborn person with crossed arms, a frown, and steam puffing out of their ears to emphasize obstinacy and zealotry. The other character, more relaxed and open-minded, is standing next to them holding a large, old-fashioned dictionary open to the word ''Bigot'' with the comedic dictionary definition visible: "One who is obstinately and zealously attached to an opinion that you do not entertain." The background includes a bench, trees, and a clear sky to keep it light and friendly. The style should be colorful, exaggerated, and clearly cartoonish, with speech or thought bubbles used to highlight the definition as if it’s a humorous dictionary entry rather than a spoken sentence. No violence or negativity, just playful exaggeration of the stubborn attitude and the irony in the definition.'),
 (1829, 'Quotes, Social Humor, Word Play', 'I must decline your invitation owing to a subsequent engagement.', 'Oscar Wilde', 'A cartoon scene showing two characters in a humorous social setting. One character is politely turning down an invitation from another. The character declining is dressed in formal attire, holding a fancy invitation card, and speaking with a slightly exaggeratedly formal and stiff posture. The other character looks puzzled or mildly surprised. A small clock is visible in the background showing a later time appointment. The setting looks like a casual party or gathering with balloons and a table with snacks. The style is light, bright, and playful with exaggerated facial expressions to emphasize the overly formal refusal. No dark or violent elements included.'),
 (2230, 'Quotes, Social Humor, Workplace', 'Science may never come up with a better office communications system than the coffee break.', 'Earl Wilson', 'A humorous cartoon scene set inside a typical office break room. The focal point is a diverse group of office workers gathered around a shiny, modern coffee machine labeled ''Ultimate Office Communication Device.'' Some employees hold coffee mugs, smiling and chatting animatedly, while others point at the machine as if it''s a high-tech invention. In the background, a clock on the wall shows break time. The room includes common office elements like a small table with cookies or snacks, a bulletin board with lighthearted posted notes, and a window showing a bright day outside. The overall style is light, cheerful, and exaggerated to emphasize the humor of coffee breaks being the best communication system, blending office life with a playful twist on technology and social interaction.'),
 (1561, 'Quotes, Software Development, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'Applications can no longer be built to last - they must be built to change.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a software developer sitting at a cluttered desk with multiple computer monitors. On one screen, a crumbling, ancient-looking, rock-solid building labeled ''Legacy Application'' is falling apart with cracks and pieces breaking off. On another screen, a modern, flexible, vibrant-looking structure made of LEGO bricks labeled ''Adaptive Application'' is actively being rebuilt and changed by the developer using LEGO pieces in hand. Around the desk, scattered papers and sticky notes read ''Requirements Change'' and ''Client Feedback.'' The developer wears a slightly frustrated but amused expression, scratching their head while looking back and forth between the two screens. The atmosphere is light-hearted with exaggerated cartoon style, bright colors, and clear depiction of contrast between rigidity and adaptability in software building. No background distractions, just the developer''s workspace emphasizing the joke about software development philosophy that apps shouldn''t be built to last forever but to easily evolve and change over time.'),
 (1761, 'Quotes, Software Development, Technology Humor, Workplace', 'How long is this Beta guy going to keep testing our stuff?', '(Actual Dilbert Manager Quotes)', 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a frustrated software development team in a typical office environment. The focus is on three cartoonish characters: a stressed-out project manager with hands in the air and a furrowed brow, a developer sitting at a cluttered desk full of computer monitors showing error messages and bugs, and a Beta tester nervously typing on a laptop that has a visible sticker labeled ''BETA TESTER''. The room has comic-style speech bubbles: the project manager is saying, ''How long is this Beta guy going to keep testing our stuff?'' with an exasperated expression. The background should include a whiteboard with bugs and features listed, stacks of coffee cups to imply overtime, and maybe a calendar showing a long stretch of testing days. The overall style is light-hearted and playful, with exaggerated facial expressions and bright colors emphasizing the chaotic yet funny nature of software testing and Beta testing rituals.'),
 (2962, 'Relatable Humor, Self-Deprecation Humor, Unknown', 'I believe that I smell as good as most people.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a confident person standing in front of a group of diverse people in a casual setting like a park or office corridor. The person has a relaxed smile and is confidently sniffing their own armpit with a thought bubble above their head that says, ''I believe that I smell as good as most people.'' Around them, the other people sniff the air with curious or amused expressions, some pleasantly surprised and others slightly confused. The background should be simple and cheerful, emphasizing the light-hearted tone. Include small details like subtle scent lines wafting from the main character to visually represent the smell, and friendly body language among all characters to keep the mood playful and non-offensive.'),
 (2984, 'Relatable Humor, Sleep Humor, Unknown', 'I finally got eight hours of sleep. It took me three days, but whatever.', NULL, 'A cartoon scene showing a tired-looking person slumped over a desk with a calendar behind them showing three consecutive days marked off. The person looks sleepy but relieved, with droopy eyes and messy hair, yawning or rubbing their eyes. On the desk are a mug of coffee, a clock showing 11 PM, and scattered papers. The calendar clearly highlights three days, with a big green checkmark on the third day labeled ''8 hours sleep achieved!'' The overall style is lighthearted and humorous, with exaggerated sleepy features on the character and bright colors to keep the mood upbeat and funny.'),
 (2843, 'Relatable Humor, Social Humor, Unknown', 'Everyone seems normal until you get to know them.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of people standing together casually, all with normal, smiling faces and typical everyday clothing. Behind the front row, the backs of some characters reveal quirky, odd, or surprising features: for example, one person has mismatched shoes, another has a pet parrot perched on their shoulder whispering secrets, another person’s shirt displays strange symbols or a hidden quirky tattoo peeking out. The background is a simple park or café setting to suggest an everyday social gathering. The overall vibe should be lighthearted and playful, emphasizing the contrast between the normal outward appearance and the unusual, funny details glimpsed once you ''get to know them.'' The style is colorful and cartoonish with exaggerated expressions of mild surprise and amusement on some characters'' faces.'),
 (3059, 'Relatable Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'I''d be unstoppable if I could only get started.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cartoon character standing at the base of a starting line on a race track. The character looks motivated but is frozen in place, with one foot hovering just above the ground as if ready to run but not moving. The stopping block behind their foot is oversized and looks like a large, literal anchor or a giant stop sign labeled ''START''. Around the character, small whimsical signs or objects hint at distractions or hesitation, such as a clock with spinning hands and cartoon birds chirping and pointing at the character. The background shows a cheering crowd and an unrolling finish line far ahead, emphasizing the irony of being ''unstoppable if only I could get started.'' The overall tone is lighthearted and funny, with exaggerated expressions and bright colors typical of classic comic strips.'),
 (3018, 'Relatable Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'I never bring my problems to work--I have enough here already.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a cluttered office. In the center, a stressed-looking office worker sits at a messy desk piled with mountains of paperwork, overflowing inbox trays, and a ringing phone. The worker has a weary expression, rubbing their temples. Behind or beside the desk, show a large thought bubble filled with little cartoonish ''problem'' icons like broken clocks, spilled coffee, tangled cables, and alarm bells—symbolizing the worker''s existing problems at work. The office surroundings should include typical elements like a computer, coffee mug, file cabinets, and motivational posters sarcastically saying ''Keep Calm'' or ''No Problem Too Big.'' The overall style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated in a cartoon format to emphasize comedic stress, without any threats or sensitive content.'),
 (3157, 'Relatable, Sleep Humor', 'Wake me in time for the weekend.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a person lying in bed with a cozy blanket, eyes closed, and a peaceful smile, clearly deep in sleep. The room is softly lit with a bedside lamp. On the nightstand next to the bed, there is an old-fashioned alarm clock showing some random weekday time. Above the sleeping person, a thought bubble contains the words, ''Wake me in time for the weekend.'' The wall behind the bed has a small calendar with the current day highlighted, emphasizing the wait for the weekend. The overall style is lighthearted and simple, with bright, cheerful colors and exaggerated expressions to convey the concept of longing to skip ahead in time. No other characters or complex background details are needed.'),
 (3100, 'Relationship Humor, Sports Humor, Technology Humor, Unknown', 'If men ran the world, when your girlfriend really needed to talk to you during the game, she''d appear in a little box in the corner of the screen during a time-out.', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a living room with a TV screen prominently displayed. On the TV, a basketball game is on, paused for a time-out. In the bottom corner of the screen, there is a small picture-in-picture box showing a woman looking slightly annoyed but trying to get attention. She looks like she’s trying to talk to the man comfortably seated on a couch nearby, wearing casual sports fan attire with a foam finger and a drink in hand, looking surprised and caught off guard by the little box. The room includes typical fan gear like a snack bowl, team banners, and a remote control. The mood is light and funny, highlighting the absurd idea that a girlfriend could appear digitally on the TV during a sports break to get attention.'),
 (3080, 'Religious Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor, Word Play', 'If God had not meant us to write on walls, he would never have given us an example.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a large, ancient stone wall with Old Testament-style biblical murals painted on it. The murals depict a whimsical scene where God, portrayed as a jolly figure with a flowing beard and robe, is painting or carving on the wall. Below, a modern-day person with a surprised but amused expression is holding a can of spray paint or a marker, looking up at the divine example. The setting is outdoors with fluffy clouds and rays of sunlight shining down, emphasizing a lighthearted divine approval. The overall tone is playful and bright, with exaggerated, friendly character designs and simple, clear lines to highlight the joke that writing on walls is inspired by a divine precedent rather than mischief.'),
 (3078, 'Road Humor, Traffic Jokes, Unknown, Visual Humor', 'If everything is coming your way, you''re in the wrong lane!', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene of a two-lane road with clear lane markings. In the foreground, a confused driver sits inside a small car, looking perplexed and scratching their head. The car is facing the camera but positioned in the left lane, with a visible road sign nearby showing an arrow pointing straight ahead for both lanes. All the traffic, including several cartoonish cars, bikes, and a bus, is shown moving directly toward the driver in the same lane, with surprised expressions drawn on the front windows to emphasize the absurdity. A bright blue sky and simple roadside elements like trees and streetlights frame the scene. The overall style is colorful, exaggerated, and playful to highlight the joke’s idea that the driver is in the wrong lane since everything is coming at them instead of moving away.'),
 (3183, 'Science Fiction Humor, Star Wars, Star Wars Humor, Word Play', 'What’s R2-D2’s favorite game? Hide and beep.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring R2-D2, the iconic small astromech droid from Star Wars, partially hidden behind a large, cartoon-style bush or a piece of futuristic machinery. R2-D2''s circular eye is peeking out as if he is playing hide and seek. Around him, sound effect text bubbles appear with the word ''Beep!'' to emphasize R2-D2''s characteristic sounds. The background is a simple, bright sci-fi setting with stars or spaceship elements to set the context. The style is lighthearted and colorful, with exaggerated expressions on R2-D2 to convey playful mischief.'),
 (3169, 'Science, Word Play', 'People get sucked into black hole schemes all the time, I bet.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a cosmic setting with a large, exaggerated black hole in the center. Around the black hole, various confused and comically worried people are being gently pulled toward it as if caught in an invisible vacuum. The people are cartoonish and diverse, wearing everyday clothes and looking surprised or puzzled. Some hold wallets, phones, or shopping bags labeled with words like ''Investments'' or ''Schemes.'' The black hole itself has a swirling, spiraling pattern with a sly face, smirking mischievously to emphasize the ''scheme'' aspect. A small sign nearby reads ''Black Hole Schemes - Enter at Your Own Risk!'' The background shows stars and distant planets to set the space environment. The overall tone is light-hearted and funny, with bright colors and exaggerated expressions to enhance the comedic effect.'),
 (2931, 'Sign Humor, Unknown, Visual Humor, Word Play', 'Honk if you love obscene gestures.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing the back of a car on a street with a clearly visible rear bumper sticker that reads, ''Honk if you love obscene gestures.'' Around the car, other vehicles are honking exaggeratedly, indicated by large comic-style ''HONK!'' sound effects. The driver of the car, visible through the rear window, is a cheerful, slightly mischievous-looking person smiling or grinning proudly. To add humor, one or two nearby drivers in other cars are reacting with confused or shocked expressions as they glance at the bumper sticker. The background is a simple city street with a few trees and light traffic. The overall style is playful and colorful, with exaggerated facial expressions and clear, bold text for the bumper sticker and sound effects. No actual obscene gestures are shown, only the suggestion and reactions to the sign.'),
 (3067, 'Software Development, Technology Humor, Unknown, Workplace', 'If a system is of sufficient complexity, it will be built before it is designed, implemented before it is tested, and obsolete before it is debugged.', NULL, 'Draw a humorous cartoon scene of a chaotic software development office. In the foreground, show a frazzled programmer at a cluttered desk with multiple computer screens displaying confusing code and numerous sticky notes labeled ''To Do'', ''Debug'', and ''Test''. The programmer looks overwhelmed, scratching their head while staring at a large whiteboard behind them filled with tangled flowcharts and crossed-out design plans. A calendar on the wall humorously shows a past deadline date labeled ''Design Complete'' in red, and a clock shows late hours. Nearby, a half-built robot or gadget sits on a workbench covered with tools and a sign that reads ''Obsolete Prototype''. Include exaggerated expressions to emphasize the irony of the system being built before properly designed or tested. The overall style should be light and cartoonish, emphasizing the irony and complexity mess in a comedic way without any harsh or aggressive visuals.'),
 (2944, 'Sports Humor, Unknown, Word Play', 'How many Minnesota freshman football players does it take to change light bulb? None. That''s a sophomore course', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene showing a group of young football players standing inside a dimly lit room. One player, wearing a Minnesota football jersey labeled ''Freshman,'' looks puzzled and holds a light bulb. Another player, labeled ''Sophomore,'' confidently points toward a light fixture with a lit bulb, smiling smugly. The room is simple with a ceiling light fixture and a small football poster on the wall. The freshman players appear confused and uninterested, while the sophomore looks knowledgeable and relaxed. A humorous caption bubble above the sophomore says, ''That''s a sophomore course.'' The style is colorful, exaggerated cartoon with playful facial expressions and team jerseys for clear identification.'),
 (3186, 'Star Wars, Word Play', 'Klingon Wessel Destroyed, Keptin.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set on a simple spaceship bridge styled like a classic sci-fi starship. In the center, a cartoonish Klingon captain with exaggerated forehead ridges and a proud mustache stands perplexed, looking at a large computer console screen. The screen displays a big red flashing message: ''Wessel Destroyed, Keptin.'' Nearby, a messed-up spelling correction bubble pops up over the console saying, ''Wessel? You mean vessel!'' The captain looks both annoyed and confused, scratching his head. Around him, typical starship controls and blinking lights add to the sci-fi atmosphere. The style is colorful, lighthearted, and exaggerated, emphasizing the joke about Klingon English pronunciation and spelling mistakes in a playful manner.'),
 (3104, 'Unknown', 'When all other means of communication fail, try words.', NULL, 'Cartoon scene: a small chaotic rooftop or park clearing where every nonverbal method of communication has hilariously failed. Center foreground: a calm, slightly exasperated person holding a giant, literal white speech bubble sign that reads in bold block letters: “WORDS.” Their posture is triumphant but sheepish. Around them in a semi-circle are other characters, each showing a failed attempt:- Left: someone waving two semaphore flags frantically while a confused pigeon sits on their head, holding a tiny “Nope” sign.- Next: a person with a smoking campfire sending “smoke signals” — puffs form question marks and one tiny cloud shaped like a phone with an “X.”- Center-left: a broken megaphone cracked open with cartoonish sparking, a smartphone with a gigantic red “NO SIGNAL” bubble.- Center-right: a person trying elaborate sign language, but the listener has tangled headphones and a puzzled face.- Far right: someone tapping Morse code on a tin can, with musical notes turning into squiggly lines.Background: simple city skyline or park, bright colors, exaggerated expressions (confusion, frustration, relief). Add small caption banner at top: “When all other means fail…” Humorous, clean, friendly cartoon style.'),
 (2938, 'Unknown, Word Play', 'How do you make a goldfish age? Take away the g.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a cute, smiling goldfish swimming inside a classic round fishbowl filled with water. The fishbowl is sitting on a simple table with a towel underneath. Above the bowl, a playful hand (wearing a cartoonish sleeve) is shown reaching down to pluck the letter ''g'' out of the air, as if the letter was floating just above the goldfish. The goldfish looks slightly puzzled but still content, with small bubbles rising to the surface. Behind the bowl, there''s a calendar on the wall with a big arrow pointing to aging or time passing, hinting at the joke''s meaning. The whole image is done in a bright, colorful cartoon style with exaggerated expressions and clean lines to emphasize the humor without being complex or violent.'),
 (2946, 'Unknown, Word Play', 'How many seconds are in a year? 12. January 2nd, February 2nd, March 2nd, April 2nd.... etc', NULL, 'A colorful, humorous cartoon scene showing a cheerful, slightly confused cartoon character (could be a generic adult) standing next to a large calendar hanging on a wall. The calendar pages have months clearly labeled (January, February, March, etc.). Each month’s page prominently displays a big number “2” on the second day, with sparkles or emphasis marks around the date to highlight it. Above the character, a speech bubble reads: "How many seconds are in a year?" and below the calendar, the punchline is humorously illustrated as “January 2nd, February 2nd, March 2nd…” with arrows pointing from month to month. The character is scratching their head or looking amused, and the background is simple and cheerful, with maybe a clock on the wall to hint at the ‘seconds’ pun. The overall style is lighthearted, cartoonish, and suitable for a family-friendly comic strip.'),
 (3265, 'Word Play', 'If you think the way to a man''s heart is through his stomach you''re aiming too high.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene featuring a man standing with a slightly puzzled and worried expression while holding a large heart-shaped target above his head. Below him, a small plate of food (like a hamburger or a slice of pizza) lies on the ground looking tiny and insignificant compared to the big red heart target. Around the man, arrows aimed at the heart target are flying wildly but missing completely, some hitting the plate on the floor. The background is simple and cheerful, with light pastel colors. The scene visually represents the saying "the way to a man''s heart is through his stomach" but highlights the joke by showing the heart being set much higher than the plate of food, emphasizing the idea that aiming at the stomach (food) is aiming too high. The cartoon style is exaggerated and playful with clean lines and expressive faces, making it clear that this is a light-hearted pun.'),
 (3266, 'Word Play', 'I''m going to try on my reversible jacket now and see how it turns out', NULL, 'Cartoon-style image of a person standing in front of a full-length mirror in a brightly lit bedroom. The person is halfway through putting on a large, comically oversized reversible jacket, with one side already on and the other side inside out but clearly visible. They have a puzzled and curious expression as they try to see how the jacket looks. The jacket should appear exaggerated with big reversible zippers and contrasting colors or patterns on each side, making it obvious it can be flipped inside out. The room includes simple furniture like a chair with clothes on it, a small plant, and a poster on the wall to add life, but the focus remains on the person and the jacket. The style should be lighthearted and humorous, emphasizing their playful experimentation with the jacket.'),
 (3267, 'Word Play, Workplace', 'Never tell your boss that you work better under pressure.', NULL, 'A humorous cartoon scene set in a typical office environment. The main character is an employee nervously talking to their boss, who is standing with crossed arms and a stern expression. The employee''s speech bubble says, ''I work better under pressure.'' To illustrate the phrase literally, the background shows a large, exaggerated pressure gauge labeled ''Work Pressure'' with the needle dangerously close to the red zone. Nearby, a stack of papers is visibly being squished by an oversized hand labeled ''Pressure.'' The office has typical items like a desk with a computer, a coffee mug, and a calendar on the wall. The style is lighthearted and exaggerated to bring out the humor of the double meaning of ''pressure.'' No one looks hurt or upset beyond office stress.')
